Object.assign(ANNOTATIONS_RAW, {
  "Grapevine_Phenological_Process": {
  "definition": "A Grapevine_Phenological_Process is a process (<a href=\"http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000015\" target=\"_blank\">BFO_0000015</a>) comprising the ordered developmental progression of Vitis vinifera L. through morphologically distinct stages classifiable according to the BBCH extended scale for grapevine.",
  "alternative_term": "grapevine developmental process | grapevine phenophase | vine phenological event | grapevine growth stage process |+ Phänologischer Prozess der Weinrebe | Rebenphänologischer Prozess | Entwicklungsprozess der Rebe | Phänophase der Weinrebe",
  "example_of_usage": "The progression of Riesling through BBCH principal growth stages 0 (sprouting/bud development) to 9 (senescence/dormancy) in the Rheingau over a single vintage year represents a complete annual sequence of Grapevine_Phenological_Processes, where each principal stage comprises subordinate phenological processes such as bud swelling (BBCH 01), wool stage (BBCH 03), green tip (BBCH 05), full bloom (BBCH 65), veraison onset (BBCH 81), and harvest maturity (BBCH 89).",
  "editor_note": "Grapevine_Phenological_Process is the root class for all 463 phenology classes in VVO. It aligns with BFO_0000015 (process) and references BBCH staging (Lorenz et al. 1995) as the primary temporal framework. ||Subclasses model individual phenophases and their sub-stages using n-ary causal relations that capture the interaction of environmental drivers (temperature, photoperiod, water status) with genotype-specific response thresholds. ||Each subclass is cross-referenced to BBCH codes and, where applicable, to Plant Ontology growth stage terms. 1995), spanning the full annual cycle from winter dormancy through bud burst, shoot growth, flowering, fruit set, berry development, veraison, ripening, leaf senescence, and return to dormancy.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0007033 ## whole plant development stage | 0.95" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH, Eichhorn KW, Bleiholder H, Klose R, Meier U, Weber E (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine (Vitis vinifera L. ssp. vinifera) - Codes and descriptions according to the extended BBCH scale, Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1(2): 100-103 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp.: 59-155 || Coombe BG (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1(1): 100-110 || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp.: 81-146"
},

  "Bud_Burst": {
  "definition": "A Bud_Burst is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the developmental transition from dormant bud to emerging green shoot through bud scale separation and shoot tissue protrusion.",
  "alternative_term": "bud break | budbreak | bud sprouting | spring bud burst |+ Austrieb | Knospenaustrieb | Knospenaufbruch | Frühjahrsaustrieb",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy initiates bud burst at BBCH 01-09 in early April after accumulating 850-950 chilling hours and 150-200 growing degree days base 10°C, with process completion requiring 15-21 days under typical spring conditions of 12-16°C mean temperature and increasing from 12 to 14 hours daylength, representing critical frost-risk period for this early-bursting cultivar in continental climate",
  "editor_note": "Bud_Burst encompasses the entire dormancy-to-growth transition including Bud_Swelling and Bud_Breaking as constituent processes. ||Distinguished from Shoot_Growth which begins after BBCH 09 when leaves separate from shoot axis. ||Timing relative to other phenological events determines frost risk, pest pressure, and growing season duration. ||Regional terminology varies with some sources using \"bud break\" specifically for BBCH 07 while others apply it to the entire 00-09 period. || This critical developmental process spans BBCH stages 00-09, typically occurring when sustained temperatures exceed 10°C and accumulated chilling requirements have been met. ||The process initiates with bud swelling as dormant meristematic tissues resume metabolic activity, progresses through scales separating and protective tissues breaking, and culminates with green tissue emergence and first leaf unfolding. ||Bud burst timing fundamentally determines growing season length, frost exposure risk, and harvest timing. ||The process involves coordinated activation of cell division and expansion in apical and axillary meristems, mobilization of stored carbohydrate reserves from permanent woody structures, resumption of vascular cambium activity connecting bud to cane, and establishment of bidirectional nutrient transport. ||Water uptake increases dramatically as cells expand, creating turgor pressure that mechanically forces protective bud scales apart. ||Hormonal regulation centers on declining abscisic acid levels from dormancy and rising cytokinin and gibberellin concentrations promoting growth. ||Environmental triggers include cumulative heat accumulation measured as growing degree days, photoperiod lengthening providing developmental cues, and soil temperature affecting root activity and water uptake. ||The process exhibits substantial cultivar variation, with early-bursting varieties like Chardonnay and Pinot Noir initiating growth 7-14 days before late-bursting varieties like Riesling and Cabernet Sauvignon under identical conditions. ||This variation reflects genetic differences in chilling requirements ranging from 200-1400 hours below 7°C and base temperature thresholds for heat accumulation. ||Regional timing varies from late March in warm climates to mid-May in cool regions, with spring frost risk inversely related to burst timing. ||Viticultural management critically depends on accurate burst prediction, as protective measures against spring frost, early-season pest and disease management, and canopy management operations must be timed relative to developmental stage. ||Bud burst uniformity within vineyards affects subsequent crop load management and harvest decisions. ||Climate change has advanced burst timing by 1-2 weeks in many regions over recent decades, increasing frost exposure in some areas while extending growing seasons in others. ||Research applications include phenological modeling for climate adaptation, molecular analysis of dormancy release mechanisms, and breeding for optimized burst timing relative to regional climate patterns.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0025532 ## bud burst stage | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 157-189 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 63-89 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Fennell A & Hoover E (1991) Photoperiod influences growth, bud dormancy, and cold acclimation in Vitis species, J Am Soc Hort Sci 116:270-273"
},

  "Bud_Swelling": {
  "definition": "A Bud_Swelling is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the volumetric expansion of dormant buds with bud scales remaining attached.",
  "alternative_term": "bud swell | swollen bud stage | winter bud swelling |+ Knospenschwellung | Knospenquellung | Schwellphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Riesling in Mosel initiates bud swelling at BBCH 01-03 in mid-April after 1100-1300 chilling hours and 180-220 growing degree days base 10°C, with swelling phase requiring 12-15 days under spring conditions averaging 11-14°C mean temperature and 60-75% relative humidity, representing later burst timing characteristic of this cool-climate cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Bud_Swelling precedes Bud_Breaking and represents expansion phase before protective scales actually separate fully. ||Distinguished by bud remaining closed with scales touching while overall bud volume increases measurably. ||Further subdivided into Early_Bud_Swelling, Advanced_Bud_Swelling, and Late_Bud_Swelling based on progression. ||Temperature and water availability are primary rate-limiting factors. || This process corresponds to BBCH stages 01-03, marking the transition from endodormancy to active growth as winter buds increase 15-30% in volume over 7-14 days. ||The process initiates when sustained temperatures above 10°C trigger hormonal signals releasing growth inhibition, with abscisic acid concentrations declining in bud tissues while cytokinin levels increase through root-to-shoot transport. ||Water uptake drives initial expansion as osmotic potential increases in bud cells through starch hydrolysis to soluble sugars and protein synthesis from stored nitrogen compounds. ||Cell walls soften through expansin activity and loosening of cellulose-hemicellulose networks, allowing turgor-driven expansion without cell division at this stage. ||Vascular reconnection between bud and supporting cane tissue establishes functional xylem for water transport and phloem for nutrient delivery from storage reserves. ||The outer bud scales begin separating at margins as internal tissues expand, creating visible gaps between protective scales while green tissue remains concealed. ||Metabolic reactivation includes elevated respiration rates consuming stored carbohydrates, protein synthesis supporting cell structure and enzyme production, and lipid mobilization from storage membranes. ||Temperature sensitivity at this stage is high, with development rate approximately doubling for each 10°C increase between 10-25°C base temperatures. ||The process exhibits three distinguishable phases based on swelling progression and bud scale separation, progressing from initial barely-visible expansion through clearly enlarged buds to late swelling where scale tips separate revealing first hints of internal green tissue. ||Cultivar variation in swelling rate and duration reflects genetic differences in dormancy depth and temperature response thresholds. ||Early cultivars like Chardonnay may complete swelling in 7-10 days while later varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon require 12-16 days under identical temperature regimes. ||Regional timing varies from late March in Mediterranean climates to late April or early May in continental regions, with accumulated growing degree days providing more reliable prediction than calendar dates. ||Viticultural significance includes serving as first visible indicator for timing protective frost measures, determining optimal pruning completion deadlines, and providing developmental reference for early-season pest monitoring. ||Frost damage during swelling causes bud mortality through ice crystal formation in expanding cells with high water content, requiring replacement growth from secondary or basal buds with reduced crop potential. ||Research applications focus on modeling temperature responses for phenology prediction, analyzing molecular mechanisms of dormancy release and growth resumption, and evaluating climate change impacts on growing season initiation timing across viticultural regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 157-172 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 63-78 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Early_Bud_Swelling": {
  "definition": "An Early_Bud_Swelling is a Bud_Swelling comprising volumetric increase of 5–10% in dormant buds with bud scales intact and closed.",
  "alternative_term": "initial bud swelling | beginning bud expansion | first bud enlargement |+ erste Knospenschwellung | beginnende Knospenquellung | initiale Schwellung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows early bud swelling at BBCH 01 in late March after 800-900 chilling hours and 120-150 growing degree days base 10°C, with buds increasing 5-8% in volume over 3-4 days under conditions of 11-13°C mean temperature and 13-hour photoperiod, representing initial growth resumption in this early-bursting cultivar typical of cool maritime climate",
  "editor_note": "Early_Bud_Swelling is the first of three Bud_Swelling subphases, distinguished by subtle expansion with fully closed scales and no visible gaps. ||Transitions to Advanced_Bud_Swelling when scale margins begin separating. ||Most difficult stage to identify consistently requiring close observation. ||Temperature fluctuations commonly cause progression-regression cycles at this developmental point. || This developmental stage corresponds to BBCH 01, occurring when winter buds first show visible enlargement though scales remain tightly appressed and green tissue is completely concealed. ||The process initiates when accumulated growing degree days trigger metabolic reactivation in meristematic tissues, with cells resuming protein synthesis and starch mobilization providing soluble sugars for osmotic water uptake. ||At this earliest phase, expansion results primarily from cell expansion rather than division, with turgor pressure increasing through osmotic potential changes as stored reserves mobilize. ||The bud profile changes from winter's compressed ellipsoid to slightly rounded form, with the most noticeable change occurring at bud tip where apical meristem drives initial expansion. ||Bud scales remain brown and appear dry with tight overlap between adjacent scales showing no visible gaps, distinguishing this stage from more advanced swelling where scale margins begin separating. ||Hormonal changes include declining abscisic acid from winter dormancy levels and initial cytokinin accumulation transported from root systems resuming activity with soil warming. ||Respiration rates increase 3-5 fold from dormancy baselines as mitochondrial activity escalates to support growth, creating measurable temperature elevation in bud tissues through metabolic heat production. ||Vascular tissues between bud and supporting cane begin differentiating to establish functional xylem for water transport, critical for sustaining turgor-driven expansion. ||Water content in bud tissues increases from winter's 35-40% to 45-50% fresh weight as hydration supports cellular metabolism and physical expansion. ||The process requires sustained temperatures above 10°C for 3-5 consecutive days to maintain development, with cooler periods temporarily slowing but not reversing expansion. ||Cultivar differences appear in minimum temperature thresholds triggering this initial swelling, ranging from 8-9°C for early varieties like Chardonnay to 11-12°C for later varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon. ||Duration of early swelling phase varies from 2-4 days in warm spring conditions to 5-8 days when temperatures fluctuate near threshold values. ||Regional timing follows chilling requirement completion and heat accumulation patterns, occurring late March in warm climates, mid-April in temperate regions, and late April to early May in cool continental areas. ||Viticultural significance includes providing first visible confirmation of dormancy release for timing completion of dormant-season vineyard operations like pruning, serving as developmental marker for initiating early-season pest monitoring programs, and indicating need to prepare frost protection measures as increasingly vulnerable tissues develop. ||Frost damage at this stage causes cell death through ice crystal formation in hydrating tissues, resulting in bud mortality requiring compensatory growth from secondary buds. ||Research applications include phenological modeling incorporating early swelling as first observable response to heat accumulation, microscopic analysis of cellular changes accompanying dormancy exit, and molecular profiling of gene expression changes initiating growth resumption in perennial woody plants.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## viticulture-specific; no equivalent granularity in PO/PPO" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 157-165 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Jones GV & Davis RE (2000) Climate influences on grapevine phenology, grape composition, and wine production and quality for Bordeaux, France, Am J Enol Vitic 51:249-261"
},

  "Advanced_Bud_Swelling": {
  "definition": "An Advanced_Bud_Swelling is a Bud_Swelling comprising volumetric expansion with bud scales separated at margins and green tissue not yet visible, corresponding to BBCH 03.",
  "alternative_term": "pronounced bud swelling | obvious bud expansion | mid-stage swelling |+ fortgeschrittene Knospenschwellung | deutliche Knospenquellung | mittlere Schwellphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux exhibits advanced bud swelling at BBCH 03 in early April after 950-1050 chilling hours and 200-250 growing degree days base 10°C, with buds showing 20-25% volume increase and 0.8-1.2 mm scale separation over 4-5 days under conditions of 13-16°C mean temperature and 65-70% relative humidity, representing typical oceanic climate pattern for this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Advanced_Bud_Swelling is the second of three Bud_Swelling subphases, distinguished by prominent expansion and visible scale margin separation but no exposed green tissue. ||Transitions to Late_Bud_Swelling when green tissue becomes faintly visible through scale gaps. ||Represents optimal developmental reference point for vineyard operation timing due to clear visual distinction. || This stage occurs after early swelling has established basic metabolic activity and vascular connection, characterized by buds enlarging 15-25% beyond winter dimensions over 3-6 days as cell expansion accelerates and water content increases substantially. ||The bud profile transitions from slightly enlarged to markedly swollen with noticeably rounded form, creating obvious visual change from dormant appearance. ||Scale separation begins at margins where adjacent scales no longer overlap completely, creating visible gaps of 0.5-1.0 mm though brown scale surfaces still dominate visual appearance and no green tissue is exposed. ||This margin separation results from continued turgor-driven expansion of internal meristematic and primordial tissues pushing outward against mechanical resistance of protective scales. ||The underlying shoot primordium and first leaf primordia expand rapidly through both cell division and cell enlargement, with cell cycle activation producing new cells while existing cells extend through water uptake and wall loosening. ||Metabolic activity intensifies markedly with respiration rates 8-12 fold above winter dormancy levels, consuming stored carbohydrates at measurable rates that can be detected through starch depletion in supporting cane tissues. ||Hormonal regulation shows elevated cytokinin and gibberellin concentrations promoting cell division and expansion respectively, with auxin production initiating in developing shoot apex to coordinate growth polarity. ||Vascular reconnection approaches completion with differentiated xylem vessels establishing functional water transport pathway from cane to expanding bud tissues, critical for maintaining turgor as expansion accelerates. ||Water content in bud tissues reaches 55-65% fresh weight compared to 35-40% during winter dormancy, reflecting both cell expansion and increased metabolic hydration requirements. ||Protein synthesis escalates dramatically to support new cell production and enzyme activity, drawing on nitrogen reserves mobilized from storage proteins in woody tissues. ||Temperature sensitivity remains high with development rate approximately doubling for each 10°C increase between 10-25°C, making this stage particularly responsive to spring temperature variability. ||The process requires sustained favorable conditions with 3-5 consecutive days above 12°C for reliable progression, with cool periods temporarily slowing development but not causing regression unless freeze damage occurs. ||Cultivar variation in progression rate reflects genetic differences in cell division rates and expansion responsiveness, with early varieties like Pinot Noir completing advanced swelling in 3-4 days while late varieties like Mourvèdre require 5-7 days under identical conditions. ||Regional timing follows early swelling by 5-8 days, occurring early April in Mediterranean climates, mid-April in temperate regions, and late April in continental areas. ||Viticultural management implications include marking time point for completing pruning operations as delayed pruning beyond this stage risks damaging expanding tissues, establishing reference for initiating early-season disease management particularly against powdery mildew, and providing developmental marker for frost protection preparedness as tissue vulnerability increases substantially. ||Frost damage at advanced swelling causes widespread cell death through ice formation in highly hydrated expanding tissues, typically killing primary buds and forcing reliance on secondary or basal buds with reduced fruitfulness. ||Research applications include quantitative analysis of cell division and expansion rates during dormancy exit, hormonal profiling documenting growth regulation transitions, and thermal time modeling for phenology prediction across diverse climatic conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## viticulture-specific; no equivalent granularity in PO/PPO" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 165-172 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 70-78 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Late_Bud_Swelling": {
  "definition": "A Late_Bud_Swelling is a Bud_Swelling comprising maximum volumetric expansion with bud scales widely separated at margins and green tissue visible through inter-scale gaps.",
  "alternative_term": "final bud swelling | pre-breaking swelling | maximum bud expansion |+ späte Knospenschwellung | maximale Knospenquellung | Vorbruchschwellung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley demonstrates late bud swelling at BBCH 03 in mid-April after 850-950 chilling hours and 270-320 growing degree days base 10°C, with buds showing 30-35% volume increase and 1.5-2.0 mm scale separation revealing pale green tissue over 3-4 days under conditions of 15-18°C mean temperature and increasing photoperiod to 13.5 hours, representing typical Mediterranean climate progression for this mid-to-late season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Late_Bud_Swelling is the third and final Bud_Swelling subphase, distinguished by maximum expansion with wide scale gaps and faintly visible green tissue that has not yet emerged beyond scales. ||Transitions directly to Bud_Breaking when green tissue actively emerges. ||Represents most frost-vulnerable stage of entire bud burst sequence. ||Brief duration makes field observation timing-dependent. || This developmental phase occurs after advanced swelling has established prominent expansion, with buds reaching 25-35% enlargement beyond winter dimensions as internal shoot primordium and leaf primordia achieve sufficient size to mechanically force scale separation. ||The bud profile shows maximum rounded swelling with scale tips spread apart creating gaps of 1-2 mm where pale green shoot tissue can be glimpsed without yet emerging beyond protective scales, representing the culmination of turgor-driven expansion before structural breaking occurs. ||Scale separation extends from tip toward base as internal pressure increases, with brown outer scales maintaining structural integrity while being mechanically pushed apart by expanding internal tissues rather than actively growing or retracting. ||The underlying shoot primordium reaches 3-5 mm length with first leaf primordia 2-3 mm in size, both expanding rapidly through coordinated cell division in meristematic zones and cell enlargement through water uptake creating turgor pressure of 0.3-0.8 MPa. ||Metabolic activity reaches peak levels for bud burst period with respiration rates 15-20 fold above winter baseline, consuming stored carbohydrates at maximum rate before photosynthetic leaves emerge to provide new carbon sources. ||Cell division rates peak in apical and axillary meristems with cell cycle duration reduced to 18-24 hours compared to days or weeks during early development, producing new cells that will form shoot axis, leaves, tendrils and inflorescence structures. ||Vascular connection between bud and supporting cane achieves full functionality with mature xylem vessels conducting water at rates sufficient to support rapid expansion and phloem transporting stored reserves mobilized from woody tissues to support growth. ||Water content in bud tissues reaches 65-75% fresh weight approaching levels found in actively growing tissues, requiring continuous water uptake to maintain turgor driving expansion and prevent wilting. ||Protein synthesis operates at maximum capacity producing structural proteins for new cells, enzymes supporting rapid metabolism, and regulatory proteins coordinating developmental progression toward breaking and shoot emergence. ||Hormonal regulation shows peak cytokinin and gibberellin concentrations promoting cell production and expansion, with auxin gradients establishing apical dominance and organ differentiation patterns in developing shoot. ||Temperature responsiveness continues with development rate doubling per 10°C increase between 10-25°C, making progression timing highly dependent on spring temperature patterns and variability. ||The process requires sustained favorable conditions with temperatures consistently above 12°C for 2-4 days to complete late swelling, with cooler conditions extending duration but warm conditions above 20°C accelerating transition to breaking. ||Cultivar variation in late swelling duration reflects genetic differences in force required to separate scales and size threshold triggering breaking, with some varieties showing brief late swelling of 2-3 days while others maintain this stage for 4-6 days. ||Regional timing follows advanced swelling by 4-7 days, occurring mid-April in warm climates, late April in temperate areas, and early May in cool regions. ||Viticultural significance includes marking final opportunity for completing dormant-season operations before active growth initiates, establishing critical reference for frost protection deployment as tissue vulnerability reaches maximum before breaking, and serving as timing reference for early-season pest management applications targeting newly active insects. ||Frost damage at late swelling causes complete primary bud mortality through ice formation in highly hydrated tissues with maximum water content, necessitating total reliance on secondary or basal buds resulting in delayed development and reduced crop potential. ||Research applications include microscopic documentation of cellular and tissue changes preceding shoot emergence, molecular profiling of gene expression patterns transitioning from dormancy to active growth, and biomechanical analysis of forces involved in scale separation and shoot emergence from protective structures.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## viticulture-specific; no equivalent granularity in PO/PPO" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 170-175 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Schultz HR (2000) Climate change and viticulture: A European perspective on climatology, carbon dioxide and UV-B effects, Aust J Grape Wine Res 6:2-12"
},

  "Bud_Breaking": {
  "definition": "A Bud_Breaking is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising bud scale separation and emergence of green shoot tissue.",
  "alternative_term": "bud break | budbreak | green tip emergence | shoot emergence |+ Knospenaufbruch | Austriebsbeginn | Grünspitzenstadium | Triebaustrieb",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows bud breaking at BBCH 07-09 in mid-April after 1050-1200 chilling hours and 320-380 growing degree days base 10°C, with green shoot tip emerging and extending 15-25 mm over 9-11 days under conditions of 16-20°C mean temperature, 50-60% relative humidity, and 14-hour photoperiod, representing typical warm-climate timing for this late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Bud_Breaking follows Bud_Swelling and represents active emergence phase rather than expansion phase. ||Distinguished by green tissue extending beyond protective scales. ||Encompasses Initial_Bud_Breaking, Active_Bud_Breaking, and Complete_Bud_Breaking as progression subphases. ||Transitions to Shoot_Growth after BBCH 09 when leaves separate from axis. ||Most frost-vulnerable period of entire growing season. || This fundamental developmental process corresponds to BBCH stages 05-09, occurring when internal shoot primordium achieves sufficient size and turgor pressure to mechanically force scales apart and extend beyond protective structures. ||The process progresses from initial emergence of green shoot tip through scales at BBCH 07 to complete separation of first leaves from shoot axis at BBCH 09, typically requiring 7-12 days depending on temperature and cultivar. ||Breaking initiates when expanding shoot primordium reaches 5-8 mm length with first leaf primordia 3-5 mm, generating mechanical force of 0.5-1.2 MPa sufficient to overcome resistance of bud scale attachments. ||The green shoot tip, often called \"green tip,\" first appears at bud apex where scales spread widest, initially showing pale yellow-green coloration due to limited chlorophyll in enclosed tissues. ||As emergence progresses, shoot extends 10-20 mm beyond scales with increasing chlorophyll synthesis producing characteristic green coloration and photosynthetic capacity beginning to develop. ||The protective bud scales separate progressively from tip toward base, eventually falling away or remaining attached at bud base as dry brown remnants while shoot continues elongating. ||Cell division rates remain high in shoot apical meristem producing new cells at 18-24 hour intervals, while cells behind meristem undergo rapid expansion through water uptake and wall loosening, creating visible shoot elongation of 2-5 mm per day. ||First true leaves unfold from their compressed primordia state, initially remaining appressed to shoot axis then progressively spreading away to establish characteristic palmate leaf configuration. ||Vascular tissues extend through elongating shoot establishing continuous xylem and phloem connections from permanent woody structures through new shoot tissues to emerging leaves, enabling water transport and nutrient distribution. ||Metabolic transition occurs from dependence on stored carbohydrate reserves to beginning photosynthetic carbon fixation as leaf area develops, though stored reserves remain primary carbon source until several leaves fully expand. ||Respiration rates remain elevated at 12-18 fold above dormancy levels supporting rapid growth, while photosynthetic capacity increases gradually as chloroplasts develop and leaf area expands. ||Hormonal regulation shows sustained high cytokinin and gibberellin concentrations promoting continued cell division and expansion, with auxin production in shoot apex establishing apical dominance suppressing lateral bud activation and coordinating leaf and shoot development. ||Temperature remains primary rate-determining factor with development doubling for each 10°C increase between 10-25°C base temperatures, making spring temperature patterns critically important for breaking progression rate. ||Water availability becomes increasingly important as transpiring leaf area develops, with water stress potentially slowing or arresting breaking process if root uptake cannot meet shoot demand. ||Light quality affects breaking progression with red: far-red ratios influencing elongation rate and leaf expansion, though light intensity effects are minimal until photosynthetic capacity develops. ||The process exhibits substantial cultivar variation in duration and environmental sensitivity, with early varieties like Chardonnay and Pinot Noir completing breaking in 7-9 days while late varieties like Riesling and Mourvèdre require 10-14 days under identical conditions. ||Regional timing follows late bud swelling by 3-5 days, occurring mid-to-late April in warm climates, late April to early May in temperate regions, and mid-May in cool continental areas. ||Viticultural management considerations include completing all dormant-season vineyard operations before breaking as mechanical damage risk increases substantially with fragile emerging tissues, deploying frost protection measures as breaking represents period of highest freeze vulnerability with tender tissues highly susceptible to cold damage, implementing early-season pest and disease management programs targeting newly available host tissues, and monitoring breaking uniformity within blocks to assess crop potential and identify areas requiring adjusted management. ||Frost damage during breaking causes immediate tissue death through ice formation in highly hydrated cells, killing primary shoots and forcing compensatory growth from secondary or basal buds with 2-3 week delays and substantially reduced fruitfulness. ||Research applications include phenological modeling incorporating breaking as key developmental milestone for growing season initiation, molecular analysis of genes regulating shoot emergence and organ differentiation, cellular and developmental biology studies of meristem activity and organ formation, biomechanical analysis of forces involved in scale separation and shoot emergence, and climate change impact assessment examining historical trends and future projections for breaking timing across viticultural regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 175-189 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 78-89 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Jones GV & Davis RE (2000) Climate influences on grapevine phenology, grape composition, and wine production and quality for Bordeaux, France, Am J Enol Vitic 51:249-261"
},

  "Initial_Bud_Breaking": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Bud_Breaking is a Bud_Breaking comprising green shoot tissue emergence through maximally separated bud scales, corresponding to BBCH 07.",
  "alternative_term": "green tip | green tip stage | first shoot emergence | beginning bud break |+ initiales Knospenaufbrechen | Grünspitze | beginnender Austrieb | erste Triebspitze",
  "example_of_usage": "Sauvignon Blanc in Marlborough shows initial bud breaking at BBCH 07 in early October (Southern Hemisphere) after 950-1050 chilling hours and 280-330 growing degree days base 10°C, with 2-3 mm pale green shoot tip visible through separated scales over 2-3 days under conditions of 14-17°C mean temperature and 12.5-hour photoperiod, representing typical cool maritime climate pattern for this early-to-mid season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Bud_Breaking is the first of three Bud_Breaking subphases, distinguished by first appearance of green tissue through scales with <30% shoot exposed. ||Transitions to Active_Bud_Breaking as shoot elongates and more tissue emerges. ||Represents most standardized phenological observation point (BBCH 07) for regional comparisons and historical records. ||Maximum frost vulnerability point. || This critical developmental stage occurs when expanding shoot primordium reaches sufficient size and mechanical force to breach protective scale barrier, with green tip first becoming visible at bud apex where scale separation is widest. ||The emerging shoot tip measures 2-4 mm in visible length extending beyond scale margins, appearing pale yellow-green due to limited chlorophyll synthesis in tissues previously enclosed within protective scales. ||At this initial phase, shoot tissue remains largely covered by scales with only apical 10-30% exposed, creating characteristic \"green tip\" appearance that gives this stage its descriptive terminology in both scientific and viticultural contexts. ||The shoot primordium beneath scales has reached 5-8 mm total length with apical meristem actively producing new cells through divisions every 18-24 hours, while cells in elongation zone behind meristem expand rapidly through turgor pressure of 0.5-0.8 MPa driving observable emergence. ||First leaf primordia measure 3-5 mm length remaining tightly folded against shoot axis within protective scales, not yet visible externally but prepared for rapid expansion once shoot elongates further. ||Bud scales reach maximum separation at tips with gaps of 2-3 mm, maintaining structural connection at base while being mechanically forced apart by internal tissue pressure rather than actively growing or dehiscing. ||The mechanical force driving emergence results from coordinated cell expansion through osmotic water uptake, with shoot cells importing solutes including sugars mobilized from cane storage reserves and ions transported through developing vascular system. ||Vascular connection between emerging shoot and permanent woody structures achieves full functionality with mature xylem vessels conducting water at rates of 0.5-1.5 mg per second to support expanding tissues and beginning transpiration from exposed surfaces. ||Chloroplast development initiates in emerging shoot cells with chlorophyll synthesis beginning though photosynthetic capacity remains negligible, requiring several days and additional leaf area before net carbon fixation approaches respiration losses. ||Metabolic activity remains at peak levels with respiration consuming stored carbohydrates at 15-20 fold above winter baseline, supporting rapid cell division and expansion before photosynthetic capacity develops. ||Protein synthesis continues at maximum rates producing structural proteins for new cells, enzymes supporting growth metabolism, and regulatory proteins coordinating developmental progression toward shoot elongation and leaf expansion. ||Hormonal regulation maintains high cytokinin and gibberellin concentrations promoting cell production and expansion, with auxin synthesis in shoot apex establishing polarity gradients coordinating upward shoot growth and suppressing lateral bud activation. ||Temperature sensitivity persists with development rate doubling per 10°C increase between 10-25°C, making emergence timing and rate highly responsive to spring temperature conditions. ||Water requirement increases substantially as exposed tissues begin transpiring, requiring functional xylem to transport water from roots through cane to emerging shoot to maintain turgor and prevent wilting. ||Light exposure affects emerging tissues with chlorophyll synthesis responding to light intensity and quality, though full photosynthetic capacity requires additional development time and leaf expansion. ||The process typically requires 2-4 days from first green tip visibility to progression toward active breaking under favorable spring conditions, with cooler temperatures extending duration to 4-6 days. ||Cultivar variation in initial breaking appears in shoot emergence rate and extent, with vigorous varieties showing rapid 1-2 mm per day emergence while less vigorous types emerge 0.5-1.0 mm per day. ||Regional timing follows late bud swelling by 2-4 days, occurring mid-April in Mediterranean climates, late April in temperate areas, and early May in cool continental regions. ||Viticultural significance includes marking the definitive point when dormant-season operations must cease to avoid damage, establishing critical reference for deploying frost protection as tissues reach maximum vulnerability to freeze damage, serving as developmental marker for initiating pest and disease management targeting newly available host tissues, and providing standardized phenological reference point for regional comparisons and historical tracking. ||Frost damage at initial breaking causes immediate tissue death through ice formation in exposed shoot tip and enclosed developing leaves, killing primary bud and requiring compensatory growth from secondary buds with 2-3 week delay and substantial fruitfulness reduction. ||Research applications include precise phenological monitoring for climate studies, molecular profiling of genes regulating shoot emergence and meristem activity, microscopic analysis of cellular differentiation during organ formation, and thermal time modeling for predicting breaking timing across diverse climatic conditions and future climate scenarios.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 175-180 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Buttrose MS (1974) Climatic factors and fruitfulness in grapevines, Hort Abstr 44:319-325"
},

  "Active_Bud_Breaking": {
  "definition": "An Active_Bud_Breaking is a Bud_Breaking comprising green shoot extension beyond bud scales with first leaves partially separated from the shoot axis.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive bud break | shoot elongation phase | advancing shoot emergence |+ aktives Knospenaufbrechen | fortschreitender Austrieb | Triebstreckung | Blattspreizung",
  "example_of_usage": "Grenache in Châteauneuf-du-Pape exhibits active bud breaking following BBCH 07 in mid-April after 800-900 chilling hours and 350-400 growing degree days base 10°C, with shoot extending 8-12 mm beyond scales and first leaves beginning to separate over 4-5 days under conditions of 17-21°C mean temperature, 45-55% relative humidity, and 14-hour photoperiod, representing typical Mediterranean climate progression for this late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Active_Bud_Breaking is the second of three Bud_Breaking subphases, distinguished by substantial shoot emergence with 30-60% exposed and beginning leaf unfolding. ||Transitions to Complete_Bud_Breaking when leaves fully separate from shoot axis. ||Represents transition from mechanical emergence to active shoot growth. ||Frost vulnerability remains very high though slightly reduced from initial breaking. || This intermediate breaking stage occurs after initial emergence has breached scale barrier, with exposed shoot tissue extending 5-15 mm beyond scale margins representing 30-60% of total shoot emergence from protective structures. ||The shoot shows bright green coloration as chlorophyll synthesis proceeds actively in light-exposed tissues, creating visible contrast with pale yellow-green of newly emerging portions still transitioning from enclosed environment. ||Shoot elongation proceeds at 2-5 mm per day through coordinated cell division in apical meristem and cell expansion in elongation zone immediately behind meristem, with cell production maintaining 18-24 hour division cycles while expansion proceeds rapidly through turgor-driven cell wall extension. ||The apical meristem remains protected at shoot tip continuing to produce new cells that will form additional shoot axis, leaves, and other organs, while cells produced earlier enter expansion and differentiation phases creating observable elongation. ||First true leaves begin unfolding from their tightly compressed primordia configuration, initially remaining appressed along shoot axis then progressively spreading perpendicular to axis as cell expansion and differential growth patterns establish characteristic leaf orientation. ||Leaf primordia expand from their 3-5 mm initial size toward 10-15 mm length during active breaking, with leaflets of compound grapevine leaf beginning to separate from each other though full palmate configuration is not yet achieved. ||Bud scales progressively separate further and begin falling away from base upward, with some cultivars showing scales dropping completely while others maintain dry brown scale remnants attached at bud base throughout growing season. ||Vascular tissues extend through elongating shoot with new xylem and phloem cells differentiating continuously to maintain functional connection from permanent woody structures through expanding shoot to developing leaves, enabling sustained water transport for growth and beginning transpiration from increasing surface area. ||Chloroplast development progresses in leaf cells with chlorophyll accumulating and photosynthetic machinery assembling, though photosynthetic rate remains below respiration rate meaning net carbon balance is still negative and growth depends primarily on stored carbohydrate reserves mobilized from woody tissues. ||Metabolic activity transitions gradually from peak respiration toward increasing photosynthetic contribution, with respiration remaining at 10-15 fold above dormancy baseline while photosynthetic capacity increases from negligible toward 20-30% of mature leaf rates. ||Stored carbohydrates continue flowing from woody tissue reserves through phloem to support rapid shoot growth, with starch and sugar concentrations declining measurably in canes as reserves mobilize to developing shoots. ||Protein synthesis continues at high rates producing structural components for new cells, enzymes supporting rapid metabolism, membrane proteins for expanding cells, and regulatory proteins coordinating complex developmental processes. ||Hormonal regulation maintains elevated cytokinin and gibberellin supporting continued cell division and expansion, with auxin concentration highest at shoot apex establishing apical dominance and coordinating leaf and tendril differentiation through concentration gradients. ||Temperature remains primary rate-determining factor with development doubling per 10°C between 10-25°C base temperatures, creating strong temperature dependence in progression rate through active breaking phase. ||Water demand increases substantially as transpiring leaf area expands, requiring adequate soil moisture and functional root water uptake to prevent water stress that could slow or temporarily arrest development. ||Light intensity begins affecting development as chloroplasts become functional, with higher light promoting leaf expansion and chlorophyll synthesis though shade does not prevent progression at this stage. ||The process typically requires 3-5 days under favorable spring conditions with consistent temperatures above 15°C, with cooler or fluctuating conditions extending duration to 5-8 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in shoot elongation rate and leaf expansion timing, with vigorous varieties showing 4-6 mm per day elongation while less vigorous types achieve 2-3 mm per day progression. ||Regional timing follows initial breaking by 2-4 days, occurring late April in warm climates, early May in temperate regions, and mid-May in cool areas. ||Viticultural management considerations include maintaining frost protection readiness as vulnerable tissue amount increases substantially with expanding shoot and leaves, avoiding mechanical operations that could damage elongating shoots, initiating canopy positioning preparations for eventual shoot training, and implementing pest monitoring for insects and mites colonizing expanding leaf area. ||Frost damage during active breaking kills exposed shoot and developing leaves through ice formation, forcing compensatory growth from secondary or basal buds resulting in 1-2 week delays and reduced fruitfulness. ||Research applications include quantifying cell division and expansion rates during rapid shoot growth, analyzing metabolic transitions from stored reserve dependence to photosynthetic independence, documenting gene expression changes during organ differentiation and chloroplast development, and evaluating cultivar and environmental effects on breaking progression rates for phenological modeling.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 180-185 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 82-89 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Complete_Bud_Breaking": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Bud_Breaking is a Bud_Breaking comprising the full separation of first true leaves from the shoot axis, corresponding to BBCH 09.",
  "alternative_term": "full bud break | leaves unfolded | shoot established | completed breaking |+ vollständiger Austrieb | Blattentfaltung | abgeschlossener Knospenaustrieb | etablierter Trieb",
  "example_of_usage": "Tempranillo in Rioja completes bud breaking at BBCH 09 in early May after 1100-1250 chilling hours and 420-480 growing degree days base 10°C, with shoot measuring 20-25 mm exposed length and first leaves spread 15-20 mm from axis over 3-4 days under conditions of 18-22°C mean temperature, 40-50% relative humidity, and 14.5-hour photoperiod, representing typical continental climate timing for this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Bud_Breaking is the third and final Bud_Breaking subphase, distinguished by full leaf separation from shoot axis marking bud burst completion. ||Transitions directly to Shoot_Growth as primary developmental process. ||Represents definitive end of dormancy period and beginning of vegetative growth phase. ||Frost vulnerability begins declining but remains elevated for next 7-10 days. || This culminating developmental stage occurs when shoot has extended sufficiently that first leaves no longer remain appressed to axis but instead spread perpendicular establishing characteristic grapevine leaf orientation and beginning substantial photosynthetic contribution. ||The shoot typically measures 15-30 mm exposed length with apical meristem continuing active cell production while elongation zone cells complete expansion creating visible daily growth increments of 3-7 mm under favorable conditions. ||First true leaves expand to 10-20 mm length with leaflets of palmate leaf structure clearly separated from each other, creating recognizable grapevine leaf form though still representing juvenile configuration smaller than mature leaf dimensions. ||Leaf surfaces show bright green coloration indicating substantial chlorophyll accumulation, with stomata becoming functional enabling gas exchange for photosynthesis and transpiration though stomatal density and control mechanisms are not yet fully mature. ||Protective bud scales have fallen away completely or remain only as dry brown remnants at shoot base, no longer providing any protective function as shoot and leaves are fully exposed to environmental conditions. ||The apical meristem maintains high cell division rates producing new cells for continued shoot elongation and initiating additional leaf and tendril primordia, with meristem structure showing characteristic layered organization of tunica and corpus zones producing organs in regular phyllotactic pattern. ||Vascular system extends throughout exposed shoot length with functional xylem providing water transport capacity of 1-3 mg per second supporting expanding tissues and increasing transpiration from developing leaf area, while phloem continues transporting stored reserves though beginning to carry photosynthate from expanding leaves. ||Chloroplasts in leaf cells achieve substantial though not complete development with thylakoid membranes organized for light capture and Calvin cycle enzymes assembled for carbon fixation, enabling photosynthetic rates reaching 40-50% of mature leaf capacity. ||The metabolic balance transitions toward net positive carbon fixation as photosynthetic rate in expanding leaves begins approaching and occasionally exceeding respiration rate, though shoots remain net carbon consumers for several more days until additional leaf area develops. ||Stored carbohydrate reserves continue supporting growth with starch concentrations in canes declining to 40-50% of winter maximum levels, while new photosynthate begins contributing measurably to growth carbon requirements. ||Protein synthesis continues at elevated rates producing structural and functional proteins for expanding tissues, with nitrogen demand high as amino acids support protein production for new cells and enzyme systems. ||Hormonal regulation shows sustained cytokinin and gibberellin promoting continued growth, with auxin concentration highest at shoot apex maintaining apical dominance and coordinating differentiation of leaves, tendrils, and beginning inflorescence primordia in nodes being produced by meristem. ||Temperature continues driving development rate with doubling per 10°C between 10-25°C, though increasing leaf area creates beginning canopy microclimate effects moderating temperature exposure of apical meristem. ||Water demand increases substantially with functional leaf area creating transpirational water loss of 10-30 mg per hour per shoot depending on environmental conditions, requiring adequate soil moisture and root uptake capacity to prevent water stress affecting development. ||Light intensity increasingly affects development as photosynthetic capacity develops, with high light promoting rapid leaf expansion and shoot growth while shade begins creating measurable growth rate reductions. ||The process typically requires 2-4 days from active breaking to complete breaking under favorable conditions with consistent temperatures above 16°C, with cooler conditions extending duration to 4-7 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in final shoot length and leaf size at complete breaking, with vigorous varieties showing 25-30 mm shoot length and 18-22 mm leaf length while less vigorous types achieve 15-20 mm shoot and 12-15 mm leaf dimensions. ||Regional timing follows active breaking by 2-4 days, occurring late April to early May in warm climates, early to mid-May in temperate areas, and mid-to-late May in cool continental regions. ||Viticultural management considerations include transitioning from frost protection focus to shoot training and canopy management planning, implementing pest management programs for insects and diseases colonizing expanding tissues, monitoring shoot growth uniformity to assess crop potential and identify management requirement variations, and planning irrigation scheduling as water demand increases with transpiring canopy development. ||Frost damage at complete breaking kills exposed shoot and leaves though damage severity may be slightly reduced compared to earlier stages as tissues begin hardening, still requiring compensatory growth from secondary or basal buds causing 7-14 day delays and fruitfulness reductions. ||Research applications include documenting transition from heterotrophic to autotrophic carbon balance in developing shoots, quantifying photosynthetic capacity development in expanding leaves, analyzing hormonal regulation of organogenesis and differentiation in active meristems, evaluating environmental effects on breaking completion timing across cultivars and regions, and assessing climate change impacts on growing season initiation and subsequent developmental timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 185-189 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 86-89 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Green_Tip_Emergence": {
  "definition": "A Green_Tip_Emergence is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the first visibility of green shoot tissue through separating bud scales.",
  "alternative_term": "green tip | green tip stage | green tip visible | tip emergence |+ Grünspitze | Grünspitzenstadium | Spitzenaustrieb | sichtbare Grünfärbung",
  "example_of_usage": "Riesling in Mosel shows green tip emergence at BBCH 07 in mid-April after 1200-1350 chilling hours and 320-380 growing degree days base 10°C, with 3-5 mm green shoot tip visible through separated scales over 4-5 days under conditions of 12-15°C mean temperature, 65-75% relative humidity, and 13.5-hour photoperiod, representing typical cool-climate timing for this late-bursting cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Green_Tip_Emergence focuses specifically on visibility milestone of green tissue appearance, overlapping temporally with Initial_Bud_Breaking through Active_Bud_Breaking but emphasizing observation-based phenological marker rather than developmental process. ||Subdivided into First_Green_Tip_Visible, Green_Tip_Extended, and Green_Shoot_Tip_Visible based on visibility and extension. ||Serves as universally recognized phenological reference point across viticultural regions. || This critical developmental milestone corresponds primarily to BBCH 07, occurring when expanding shoot primordium breaches protective scale barrier and green tissue becomes visible at bud apex. ||The process encompasses the progression from barely detectable green coloration through scales to clearly visible green shoot tip extending beyond scale margins, typically requiring 3-6 days depending on temperature regime and cultivar characteristics. ||Green tip emergence serves as universally recognized phenological marker across viticultural regions worldwide, providing standardized observation point for comparing seasonal timing, assessing frost risk, and tracking long-term climate impacts on growing season initiation. ||The visible green tissue represents the shoot apical meristem and immediately surrounding cells that have accumulated sufficient chlorophyll to create characteristic coloration, transitioning from pale yellow-green of newly emerged tissues to brighter green as chloroplast development proceeds and light exposure increases. ||Scale separation at bud apex creates viewing opportunity for enclosed tissues, with gaps of 2-4 mm allowing observation of green shoot tip that measures 2-8 mm visible length depending on progression stage within emergence process. ||The shoot primordium beneath visible tip has reached 5-10 mm total length with actively dividing apical meristem producing new cells every 18-24 hours, while cells in subapical elongation zone expand through turgor pressure generating mechanical force pushing shoot through scale opening. ||Emergence timing depends on accumulated heat units from dormancy release, with most cultivars requiring 250-400 growing degree days base 10°C from initial bud swelling to green tip visibility. ||Temperature remains primary controlling factor with emergence rate doubling approximately every 10°C increase between 10-25°C, creating strong temperature dependence in timing and progression rate. ||The process shows three distinguishable phases based on visibility and extension of green tissue, progressing from first barely visible green coloration through clearly extended green tip to prominent green shoot tip with beginning leaf tissue visibility. ||Chlorophyll synthesis accelerates in light-exposed tissues creating increasingly intense green coloration, with chlorophyll concentrations reaching 0.3-0.5 mg per gram fresh weight in emerged tissues compared to negligible levels in enclosed portions. ||Photosynthetic capacity begins developing as chloroplasts assemble light-harvesting complexes and Calvin cycle enzymes, though photosynthetic rate remains below 20% of mature leaf capacity and respiration continues exceeding carbon fixation making shoots net carbon consumers. ||Vascular connection between emerging shoot and permanent structures achieves full functionality with xylem conducting water at 0.5-2.0 mg per second supporting turgor-driven growth and beginning transpiration from exposed surfaces. ||Metabolic activity maintains peak levels with respiration 15-20 fold above winter baseline supporting rapid cell division and expansion, consuming stored carbohydrates mobilized from woody tissue reserves through phloem transport. ||Protein synthesis operates at maximum capacity producing structural proteins for new cells, enzymes supporting metabolism, and regulatory proteins coordinating development. ||Hormonal regulation shows elevated cytokinin and gibberellin promoting cell production and expansion, with auxin concentration highest at shoot apex establishing apical dominance. ||Cultivar variation in emergence timing reflects genetic differences in chilling requirements, base temperature thresholds, and developmental rates, with early cultivars like Chardonnay and Pinot Noir showing green tip 7-14 days before late cultivars like Riesling and Mourvèdre under identical conditions. ||Regional timing varies from late March in warm Mediterranean climates through mid-April in temperate regions to early May in cool continental areas, with accumulated heat units providing better prediction than calendar dates across diverse climatic zones. ||Viticultural significance includes providing standardized observation point for regional phenology monitoring and historical comparisons, marking critical reference for deploying frost protection as tissue vulnerability reaches maximum, establishing developmental marker for initiating pest and disease management programs, and serving as regulatory milestone for vineyard operation restrictions in some appellations. ||Green tip stage represents period of maximum frost vulnerability with tender emerging tissues highly susceptible to freeze damage, requiring protection when temperatures approach -2°C compared to -5°C or lower tolerance during dormancy. ||Frost damage at green tip causes complete primary bud mortality through ice formation in hydrated tissues, necessitating compensatory growth from secondary or basal buds with 2-3 week delays and 40-60% fruitfulness reduction. ||Research applications include long-term phenological monitoring documenting climate change impacts on growing season timing, thermal time modeling for predicting emergence across regions and climate scenarios, molecular analysis of genes regulating shoot emergence and meristem activity, and standardized observations supporting viticulture decision support systems and climate adaptation strategies.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 175-180 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Jones GV & Davis RE (2000) Climate influences on grapevine phenology, grape composition, and wine production and quality for Bordeaux, France, Am J Enol Vitic 51:249-261"
},

  "First_Green_Tip_Visible": {
  "definition": "A First_Green_Tip_Visible is a Green_Tip_Emergence comprising the initial appearance of green shoot tissue through maximally separated bud scales.",
  "alternative_term": "first green visible | initial green tip | barely visible green | faint green tip |+ erste Grünspitze sichtbar | kaum sichtbare Grünfärbung | initiale Grünspitze | schwache Grünfärbung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows first green tip visible at early BBCH 07 in early April after 850-950 chilling hours and 280-320 growing degree days base 10°C, with 1-2 mm pale green tissue faintly visible through 2-3 mm scale opening over 1-2 days under conditions of 13-15°C mean temperature and variable spring weather typical of continental climate, representing early-bursting pattern for this cultivar",
  "editor_note": "First_Green_Tip_Visible is the first of three Green_Tip_Emergence subphases, distinguished by subtle initial visibility of green tissue with minimal extension. ||Transitions to Green_Tip_Extended as shoot elongates and visibility becomes unambiguous. ||Represents earliest possible field observation point but requires careful inspection. ||Most challenging stage for consistent identification across observers. || This subtle developmental stage occurs at the onset of BBCH 07 when expanding shoot primordium first breaches protective scale barrier, with green coloration faintly visible at bud apex where scale separation creates narrow viewing aperture. ||The visible green tissue measures 1-3 mm in observable length, appearing pale yellow-green due to limited chlorophyll accumulation in tissues recently emerged from enclosed environment within protective scales. ||At this initial visibility stage, green coloration may be intermittently visible depending on viewing angle and lighting conditions, requiring careful observation to detect particularly in overcast conditions or when viewing from non-optimal angles relative to scale opening. ||The shoot apex has reached 5-7 mm total length beneath scales with apical meristem actively producing cells through divisions every 20-24 hours, while subapical cells expand creating turgor pressure of 0.4-0.6 MPa sufficient to maintain position at scale opening but not yet generating force for rapid extension beyond scales. ||Bud scales maintain separation of 2-3 mm at apex creating viewing gap, with scales remaining structurally intact and providing continued protection to majority of developing shoot tissues beneath. ||Chlorophyll synthesis has recently initiated in shoot apex cells with concentrations reaching 0.1-0.2 mg per gram fresh weight, sufficient to create visible green coloration but representing early stage of chloroplast development. ||Photosynthetic capacity remains negligible at less than 10% of mature tissue rates, with respiration greatly exceeding any carbon fixation making shoots entirely dependent on stored carbohydrate reserves mobilized from woody tissues. ||Vascular connection between shoot and permanent structures has established functional xylem vessels conducting water to support turgor maintenance and beginning cellular metabolism, with water transport rate of 0.3-0.8 mg per second supporting current developmental stage. ||Cell division continues actively in apical meristem initiating new cells for shoot axis elongation and organ primordia, with cell production rate maintaining consistent 20-24 hour cycle characteristic of early emergence phase. ||Metabolic activity operates at elevated levels with respiration 12-15 fold above winter dormancy baseline, consuming stored sugars and mobilizing stored proteins to support rapid growth processes. ||Hormonal regulation maintains high cytokinin and gibberellin concentrations promoting continued meristem activity and cell expansion, with auxin synthesis in apex establishing developmental polarity. ||Temperature sensitivity remains high with development rate doubling per 10°C increase between 10-25°C, making progression highly dependent on spring temperature stability. ||Water availability must be adequate to support turgor maintenance in expanding tissues, with water stress potentially slowing visibility stage if uptake cannot meet demand. ||Light quality affects chlorophyll synthesis rate with red light promoting chloroplast development, though visibility stage occurs regardless of light conditions once developmental threshold is reached. ||The process typically requires 1-2 days from first faint visibility to progression toward extended green tip under favorable spring conditions above 14°C mean temperature, with cooler conditions extending duration to 2-4 days. ||Cultivar variation in first visibility appears in shoot apex size and chlorophyll synthesis rate at emergence, with some varieties showing brighter green at first detection while others remain pale yellow-green. ||Regional timing follows late bud swelling by 2-3 days, occurring mid-April in Mediterranean climates, late April in temperate areas, and early May in cool regions. ||Viticultural significance includes providing earliest possible observation point for confirming dormancy exit and growth initiation, enabling maximum lead time for frost protection deployment, serving as initial reference for beginning phenological monitoring programs, and establishing earliest marker for regulatory restrictions on vineyard operations in some regions. ||Frost damage at first green tip visible stage causes complete primary bud death through ice formation in tender emerging tissues, requiring compensatory growth from secondary buds with substantial delays and fruitfulness reduction. ||Field observation challenges include subtle visibility requiring careful inspection, variable detectability under different lighting conditions, and potential confusion with bud scale coloration changes that can mimic green tissue appearance. ||Research applications include precise determination of dormancy exit timing for phenological models, establishing earliest observation point for climate change monitoring studies, documenting cultivar variation in emergence characteristics, and evaluating prediction accuracy of thermal time models for green tip timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 175-177 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Green_Tip_Extended": {
  "definition": "A Green_Tip_Extended is a Green_Tip_Emergence comprising the extension of green shoot tissue beyond bud scales with unambiguous tip visibility.",
  "alternative_term": "extended green tip | prominent green tip | elongated shoot tip | clear green tip |+ verlängerte Grünspitze | deutliche Grünspitze | gestreckte Triebspitze | ausgeprägte Grünfärbung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows green tip extended at mid-BBCH 07 in mid-April after 1100-1250 chilling hours and 380-430 growing degree days base 10°C, with 5-7 mm bright green shoot tip clearly visible through 4-5 mm scale opening over 2-3 days under conditions of 16-19°C mean temperature, 50-60% relative humidity, and 14-hour photoperiod, representing typical warm-climate timing for this late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Green_Tip_Extended is the second of three Green_Tip_Emergence subphases, distinguished by clear unambiguous visibility and measurable shoot extension beyond scales. ||Transitions to Green_Shoot_Tip_Visible when shoot elongation reveals additional structures beyond simple tip. ||Represents most reliable observation stage with minimal inter-observer variability. ||Standard reference point for many phenological studies. || This developmental stage occurs during mid-progression of BBCH 07 when shoot primordium has achieved sufficient growth to extend 4-8 mm visible length beyond protective scales, with bright green coloration clearly distinguishable under all normal viewing conditions. ||The extended green tip shows characteristic conical or cylindrical shape tapering toward apex where apical meristem remains enclosed by youngest leaf primordia, with shoot tissue displaying smooth surface texture and uniform green coloration indicating active chlorophyll synthesis and chloroplast development. ||Scale separation has progressed to 3-5 mm at bud apex with scales beginning to separate further down bud structure as internal pressure from expanding tissues continues forcing mechanical separation, though scales maintain structural connection at base and continue providing protection to enclosed developing structures. ||The shoot primordium beneath visible tip has reached 8-12 mm total length with apical meristem maintaining active cell production every 18-22 hours, while elongation zone cells expand rapidly through turgor pressure of 0.6-0.9 MPa driving observable shoot extension of 1-3 mm per day. ||Chlorophyll concentration in extended tip tissues reaches 0.4-0.7 mg per gram fresh weight creating bright green coloration characteristic of actively growing vegetative tissues, with chloroplasts achieving 30-40% of structural development toward mature configuration. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases to 15-25% of mature leaf rates as chloroplasts become functional, though respiration continues exceeding carbon fixation meaning shoots remain net carbon consumers dependent on stored reserves. ||Vascular tissues extend through elongating shoot with functional xylem conducting water at 1.0-1.8 mg per second supporting expansion and increasing transpiration from exposed surfaces, while phloem continues transporting stored carbohydrates mobilized from woody tissue reserves. ||Cell division maintains high rates in apical meristem producing cells for continued shoot elongation and initiating additional organ primordia including leaves and tendrils, with mitotic activity creating zone of actively dividing cells 100-200 micrometers behind apex. ||Metabolic activity continues at elevated levels with respiration 15-18 fold above winter baseline, consuming stored sugars at rates creating measurable starch depletion in supporting cane tissues. ||Protein synthesis operates at high capacity producing structural proteins for new cell walls and membranes, enzymes supporting rapid metabolism, and regulatory proteins coordinating developmental progression. ||Hormonal concentrations maintain elevated cytokinin and gibberellin promoting continued growth, with auxin gradients from shoot apex coordinating upward growth orientation and beginning to establish patterns for lateral organ differentiation. ||Temperature remains primary rate-determining factor with development doubling per 10°C between 10-25°C, creating strong thermal dependence in extension rate and subsequent developmental timing. ||Water demand increases substantially as exposed tissue area expands and transpiration from green surfaces accelerates, requiring adequate soil moisture and functional root uptake to maintain turgor supporting extension. ||Light intensity begins affecting development as photosynthetic capacity increases, with higher light promoting chlorophyll synthesis and shoot extension though development continues in reduced light. ||The process typically requires 2-3 days progression from first visibility to extended tip under favorable spring conditions with consistent temperatures above 15°C, with cooler conditions extending duration to 3-5 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in extension rate and final tip length at this stage, with vigorous varieties showing 2-3 mm per day extension achieving 7-9 mm total visible length while less vigorous types extend 1-2 mm per day reaching 4-6 mm length. ||Regional timing follows first green tip visible by 1-3 days, occurring mid-April in warm climates, late April in temperate areas, and early May in cool regions. ||Viticultural significance includes providing clear unambiguous observation point for phenological monitoring with minimal observer variability, serving as reliable reference for frost risk assessment and protection deployment decisions, marking developmental stage for beginning early-season pest monitoring programs, and establishing standardized phenological marker for research studies and climate monitoring. ||Frost damage at extended green tip stage causes primary bud mortality through ice formation in exposed tissues, requiring secondary bud compensation with 2-3 week delays and 40-60% fruitfulness reduction. ||Research applications include standardized phenological observations for climate studies, validation of thermal time models for development prediction, analysis of cultivar variation in emergence patterns, and documentation of environmental effects on shoot extension rates during early development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 177-180 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Buttrose MS (1974) Climatic factors and fruitfulness in grapevines, Hort Abstr 44:319-325"
},

  "Green_Shoot_Tip_Visible": {
  "definition": "A Green_Shoot_Tip_Visible is a Green_Tip_Emergence comprising the extension of elongated shoot tissue beyond bud scales with compressed first leaves visible at the tip.",
  "alternative_term": "visible shoot structure | shoot tip with leaves | emerging shoot visible | recognizable shoot |+ sichtbare Triebstruktur | Triebspitze mit Blättern | erkennbarer Trieb | Triebaufbau sichtbar",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Barossa Valley shows green shoot tip visible at late BBCH 07 in late April after 800-900 chilling hours and 450-500 growing degree days base 10°C, with 12-15 mm shoot visible including compressed first leaves along axis over 2-3 days under conditions of 18-21°C mean temperature, 45-55% relative humidity, and 13-hour photoperiod, representing typical warm-climate pattern for this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Green_Shoot_Tip_Visible is the third of three Green_Tip_Emergence subphases, distinguished by substantial shoot extension revealing shoot structure including compressed leaves. ||Transitions toward First_Leaf_Unfolding as leaves begin separating from axis. ||Represents advanced emergence stage approaching BBCH 09. ||Marks point where shoot architecture becomes assessable for uniformity evaluation. || This developmental stage occurs during late BBCH 07 progression toward BBCH 09 when shoot has extended 10-20 mm visible length beyond protective scales, with shoot structure showing not only apical tip but also beginning differentiation of shoot axis and enclosed leaf primordia. ||The visible shoot displays bright green coloration throughout with characteristic grapevine shoot morphology becoming apparent, including slightly angular cross-section reflecting vascular bundle arrangement and subtle nodes marking positions where leaf primordia attach to developing axis. ||Shoot apex remains conical or rounded at tip where apical meristem continues active growth enclosed by youngest primordia, with older leaf primordia visible as compressed structures along shoot axis though not yet unfolded or separated from axis. ||Scale separation has progressed extensively with gaps of 5-8 mm at widest point and scales beginning to fall away from shoot base, transitioning from functional protective role to vestigial remnants that will completely detach as shoot continues elongating. ||The shoot primordium beneath visible portion has reached 15-25 mm total length including sections still enclosed by loosened scales, with apical meristem producing new cells every 18-20 hours and elongation zone expanding at 2-4 mm per day. ||First leaf primordia along visible shoot axis measure 5-10 mm length remaining tightly appressed against shoot but showing beginning separation preparation, with leaf surfaces displaying characteristic grapevine leaf texture including developing trichomes and beginning venation patterns. ||Chlorophyll concentration in shoot and leaf tissues reaches 0.6-0.9 mg per gram fresh weight creating intense green coloration, with chloroplasts achieving 50-60% structural development and beginning substantial photosynthetic activity. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases to 30-40% of mature rates as functional chloroplasts accumulate and leaf area begins expanding, though respiration still exceeds carbon fixation keeping shoots as net carbon consumers for several more days. ||Vascular system extends through entire visible shoot length with xylem conducting water at 1.5-2.5 mg per second supporting expansion and increasing transpiration, while phloem continues primary role of transporting stored reserves though beginning to carry limited photosynthate from developing leaves. ||Cell division continues actively in apical meristem and in young leaf primordia, with mitotic zones producing cells for continued shoot elongation and leaf expansion while older cells behind meristem complete expansion and begin differentiation into specialized tissue types. ||Metabolic activity maintains elevated levels with respiration 12-16 fold above dormancy baseline supporting rapid growth, drawing on stored carbohydrates though beginning transition toward photosynthetic carbon contribution. ||Protein synthesis continues at high rates producing components for expanding tissues, with particular emphasis on photosynthetic proteins as chloroplast development accelerates in expanding leaf primordia. ||Hormonal regulation maintains elevated cytokinin and gibberellin supporting continued growth, with auxin concentration highest at apex and declining basipetally establishing polarity for shoot orientation and coordinating leaf and tendril positioning. ||Temperature continues as primary rate factor with development doubling per 10°C between 10-25°C, though increasing shoot size begins creating microclimate effects that moderate temperature exposure. ||Water demand increases substantially as transpiring surface area expands to 20-40 square mm per shoot, requiring adequate soil moisture and functional root systems to prevent water stress slowing development. ||Light intensity increasingly affects development with photosynthetic capacity enabling response to light availability, with high light promoting rapid shoot and leaf expansion while shade begins measurably reducing growth rates. ||The process typically requires 2-3 days progression from extended green tip to visible shoot tip under favorable conditions above 16°C mean temperature, with cooler conditions extending duration to 3-5 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in shoot structure visibility and leaf primordium development at this stage, with some varieties showing earlier leaf structure definition while others maintain compressed configuration longer. ||Regional timing follows extended green tip by 2-3 days, occurring late April in warm climates, early May in temperate regions, and mid-May in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes marking transition point where shoot structure becomes apparent enabling assessment of shoot density and uniformity, providing developmental reference for beginning canopy management planning, serving as observation point for detecting shoot abnormalities or damage, and establishing marker for transitioning pest monitoring focus from buds to shoots and developing leaves. ||Frost damage at this stage kills exposed shoot and developing leaves, forcing secondary bud growth with 1-2 week delays and reduced fruitfulness. ||Research applications include documenting shoot morphological development during emergence, analyzing leaf initiation and early expansion processes, evaluating photosynthetic capacity development in young tissues, and assessing cultivar differences in early shoot architecture affecting subsequent canopy development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 180-185 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 82-86 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "First_Leaf_Unfolding": {
  "definition": "A First_Leaf_Unfolding is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the separation and expansion of the first true leaf from the shoot axis.",
  "alternative_term": "first leaf spreading | leaf expansion initiation | leaf unfolding stage | opening leaves |+ erste Blattentfaltung | Blattspreizung | Blattöffnung | Blattexpansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows first leaf unfolding at BBCH 09-11 in early May after 1000-1100 chilling hours and 480-550 growing degree days base 10°C, with first true leaves separating from axis and expanding to 18-25 mm over 6-8 days under conditions of 17-20°C mean temperature, 60-70% relative humidity, adequate soil moisture, and 14.5-hour photoperiod, representing typical oceanic climate pattern for this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "First_Leaf_Unfolding follows Complete_Bud_Breaking and represents transition from bud burst to active shoot growth. ||Distinguished by leaf separation from axis and progressive expansion. ||Subdivided into First_Leaf_Separation, First_Leaf_Expansion, and Multiple_Leaf_Unfolding based on progression. ||Marks beginning of significant photosynthetic contribution and transition toward autotrophic growth. ||Critical phase for establishing shoot photosynthetic capacity. || This fundamental process corresponds to BBCH 09-11, occurring when shoot has elongated sufficiently that first leaves no longer remain compressed against axis but instead spread perpendicular establishing characteristic grapevine leaf positioning and beginning substantial contribution to carbon assimilation. ||The process encompasses progression from initial leaf separation through partial expansion to establishment of multiple unfolding leaves, typically requiring 5-10 days depending on environmental conditions and cultivar growth characteristics. ||First leaf unfolding marks definitive transition from heterotrophic growth depending entirely on stored reserves to beginning autotrophic capacity as expanding leaves develop photosynthetic function, though shoots remain net carbon consumers until 3-5 leaves fully expand. ||The unfolding leaves expand from compressed primordia configuration measuring 5-10 mm to partially expanded leaves of 15-30 mm length, with characteristic palmate grapevine leaf form becoming clearly recognizable as leaflets separate and spread from central rachis. ||Leaf surfaces transition from pale yellow-green of enclosed tissues to bright green as chlorophyll accumulates and chloroplasts mature, with upper leaf surface typically developing darker green than lower surface reflecting chloroplast distribution differences. ||Leaf expansion proceeds through coordinated cell division in marginal and plate meristem zones producing new cells, and cell expansion throughout leaf blade through turgor-driven growth increasing individual cell volumes 10-50 fold. ||Stomata develop and become functional enabling gas exchange for photosynthesis and transpirational cooling, with stomatal density on lower leaf surface reaching 150-250 per square mm compared to 50-100 per square mm on upper surface. ||Trichomes characteristic of grapevine leaves emerge from epidermal cells creating varying degrees of leaf hairiness depending on cultivar, with density ranging from sparse to dense coverage affecting leaf reflectance and transpiration rates. ||Vascular system extends throughout expanding leaf blade establishing network for water delivery and photosynthate export, with primary veins forming structural framework and secondary and tertiary veins creating reticulated pattern for resource distribution. ||Chloroplast development accelerates in leaf cells with chlorophyll concentration increasing to 1.2-2.0 mg per gram fresh weight, thylakoid membranes organizing into grana stacks for light capture, and Calvin cycle enzymes assembling for carbon fixation. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases progressively as leaves expand, reaching 50-70% of mature rates when leaves achieve 40-50% final size, with full photosynthetic capacity developing as expansion completes and chloroplasts mature. ||The metabolic balance transitions from net carbon consumption to approaching neutral and eventually positive as photosynthetic rate increases with leaf area expansion, with crossover point typically occurring when 3-4 leaves have substantially expanded. ||Shoot elongation continues with apical meristem producing new leaf primordia every 2-3 days while older leaves unfold and expand sequentially, creating characteristic pattern of progressively larger leaves from shoot base toward apex. ||Stored carbohydrate reserves continue supporting growth during unfolding phase with cane starch concentrations declining to 30-40% of winter maximum, while new photosynthate increasingly supplements stored reserves as leaf area develops. ||Protein synthesis continues at elevated rates supporting leaf tissue development, with particular emphasis on photosynthetic proteins including Rubisco comprising up to 50% of total leaf protein in mature tissues. ||Hormonal regulation maintains elevated cytokinin and gibberellin promoting continued leaf expansion, with auxin from shoot apex coordinating leaf positioning and establishing patterns for additional organ differentiation including tendrils and inflorescence primordia. ||Temperature continues affecting development rate with leaf expansion approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 10-25°C, though optimal temperature for maximum expansion rate is 20-25°C with higher temperatures potentially reducing expansion through increased respiration and water stress. ||Water availability becomes critically important as transpiring leaf area increases exponentially, with adequate soil moisture and root function essential to maintain turgor supporting expansion and preventing water stress that arrests development. ||Light intensity strongly affects leaf expansion rate and final size with high light promoting rapid expansion and larger final dimensions while shade reduces expansion rate and ultimate leaf size, with adaptation beginning whereby shaded leaves develop thinner blades with higher specific leaf area. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects expansion rate and photosynthetic capacity development, with adequate nitrogen supporting protein synthesis for both structural and photosynthetic components. ||The process shows three distinguishable phases based on leaf separation and expansion progression, advancing from initial first leaf separation through first leaf expansion to multiple leaves unfolding creating developing shoot canopy. ||Cultivar variation appears in leaf unfolding rate, final leaf size, and timing of photosynthetic capacity development, with vigorous cultivars showing rapid expansion to large final dimensions while less vigorous types develop more slowly to smaller leaf sizes. ||Regional timing follows complete bud breaking by 2-4 days, occurring late April to early May in warm climates, early to mid-May in temperate regions, and mid-to-late May in cool areas. ||Viticultural management considerations include transitioning from frost protection focus to shoot positioning and canopy management, implementing nutrient management particularly nitrogen to support rapid leaf development, establishing irrigation scheduling as water demand increases dramatically, monitoring for pest colonization of expanding leaf area including mites and leafhoppers, and assessing shoot growth uniformity for crop load and canopy management decisions. ||Frost damage during leaf unfolding kills expanded leaf tissue though growing point may survive if sufficiently protected, causing growth delays and reduced photosynthetic capacity affecting subsequent development. ||Research applications include quantifying transition from heterotrophic to autotrophic carbon balance, analyzing photosynthetic capacity development in expanding leaves, evaluating environmental effects on leaf expansion rates and final sizes, documenting hormonal regulation of leaf development, and assessing cultivar differences in early canopy development affecting light interception and photosynthetic capacity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 189-205 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 89-105 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "First_Leaf_Separation": {
  "definition": "A First_Leaf_Separation is a First_Leaf_Unfolding comprising the initial spreading of the first true leaf away from the shoot axis.",
  "alternative_term": "first leaf spreading | initial leaf separation | beginning leaf unfolding |+ erste Blattspreizung | beginnende Blattentfaltung | initiale Blattseparation | Blattablösung vom Trieb",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows first leaf separation at BBCH 09 in late April after 900-1000 chilling hours and 420-480 growing degree days base 10°C, with first leaf petiole angling 30-45 degrees from axis and blade spreading to 12-16 mm over 2-3 days under conditions of 15-18°C mean temperature, 65-75% relative humidity, and 14-hour photoperiod, representing typical cool maritime climate progression for this early-bursting cultivar",
  "editor_note": "First_Leaf_Separation is the first of three First_Leaf_Unfolding subphases, distinguished by initial spreading of first leaf from compressed position along axis. ||Transitions to First_Leaf_Expansion as blade continues enlarging and spreading. ||Represents beginning of significant photosynthetic contribution to shoot carbon balance. ||Standard BBCH 09 observation point. || This developmental stage occurs at BBCH 09 when shoot elongation has progressed sufficiently that mechanical constraints maintaining leaf compression are released, allowing leaf petiole to angle away from axis and leaf blade to begin expanding perpendicular to shoot. ||The separating first leaf measures 10-15 mm length at separation initiation, having developed from 5-8 mm compressed primordium through continued cell production in marginal meristems and beginning cell expansion in blade tissues. ||Leaf blade shows beginning spread of palmate leaflet configuration with leaflets starting to separate from each other though remaining partially folded, creating transitional form between compressed primordium and fully expanded leaf architecture. ||The leaf petiole angles 20-40 degrees from shoot axis at initial separation, progressively increasing to 60-90 degrees as separation advances and cell expansion in petiole abaxial side creates upward bending establishing characteristic leaf orientation. ||Leaf coloration transitions from pale yellow-green of recently uncompressed tissue to brighter green as chlorophyll synthesis accelerates with light exposure, with chlorophyll concentration increasing from 0.4-0.6 mg per gram to 0.8-1.2 mg per gram fresh weight during separation phase. ||Chloroplast development progresses rapidly in expanding blade cells with thylakoid membranes organizing into grana stacks, photosystem complexes assembling for light capture, and Calvin cycle enzymes accumulating for carbon fixation capability. ||Photosynthetic capacity begins developing as chloroplasts mature though rates remain below 30% of mature leaf capacity during initial separation, with light saturation point low and photosynthetic efficiency suboptimal compared to fully developed leaves. ||Stomata complete development and become functional during separation, with stomatal apertures responding to environmental conditions including light intensity, CO2 concentration, and leaf water status to regulate gas exchange for photosynthesis and water loss through transpiration. ||Leaf surface features including trichomes and epicuticular waxes develop during separation creating characteristic cultivar-specific leaf appearance and affecting optical properties including reflectance and light penetration to photosynthetic tissues. ||Cell division continues in marginal and plate meristems at leaf edges and throughout blade respectively, producing new cells that will expand to create final leaf dimensions, with cell production rates highest during early separation phase. ||Cell expansion begins throughout leaf blade through water uptake creating turgor pressure that drives cell wall extension, with expansion rate initially limited by wall properties and increasing as wall-loosening enzymes accumulate and allow plastic deformation. ||Vascular system extends throughout separating leaf establishing primary veins forming structural framework and beginning development of secondary vein network for resource distribution, with xylem vessels differentiating to transport water and phloem sieve elements forming to export beginning photosynthetic products. ||Water content in separating leaf increases to 75-85% fresh weight typical of actively growing tissues, requiring continuous water uptake through shoot xylem to maintain turgor supporting expansion and prevent wilting. ||The shoot continues elongating at 3-5 mm per day with apical meristem producing additional leaf primordia while first leaf separates, creating sequential pattern of leaf development along shoot axis. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated in separating leaf with respiration 8-12 fold above mature leaf levels supporting rapid growth processes, consuming both stored carbohydrates transported from woody tissues and beginning to use photosynthate produced by developing photosynthetic capacity. ||Protein synthesis operates at high rates producing structural proteins for cell walls and membranes of expanding cells, photosynthetic proteins including Rubisco and other Calvin cycle enzymes, and regulatory proteins coordinating development. ||Hormonal regulation involves cytokinin promoting cell division in meristematic zones, gibberellin supporting cell expansion throughout blade, and auxin establishing polarity patterns affecting leaf shape and orientation relative to axis. ||Temperature affects separation rate and subsequent expansion with optimal range 18-24°C for maximum development rate, higher temperatures potentially reducing efficiency through increased respiration and water stress while lower temperatures slow all processes. ||Water availability critically affects separation and expansion with adequate soil moisture essential to maintain turgor driving cell expansion, while water stress arrests development and can cause permanent size reduction even after stress relief. ||Light intensity influences separation rate and subsequent photosynthetic development with high light promoting rapid chloroplast maturation and full photosynthetic capacity while shade reduces development rate and ultimate capacity. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects protein synthesis capacity supporting both structural and photosynthetic protein production required for full leaf development. ||The process typically requires 1-3 days from initial separation to obvious spreading under favorable conditions above 18°C, with cooler temperatures extending duration to 3-5 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in separation timing relative to shoot elongation and in separation angle and rate, with some varieties showing rapid perpendicular spreading while others separate more gradually to acute angles. ||Regional timing follows green shoot tip visible by 2-4 days, occurring late April to early May in warm climates, early to mid-May in temperate areas, and mid-to-late May in cool regions. ||Viticultural significance includes marking beginning of rapid leaf area development requiring adequate water and nutrient availability, establishing point where photosynthetic capacity begins contributing to carbon balance affecting subsequent growth potential, providing developmental reference for monitoring shoot growth uniformity across vineyard blocks, and serving as marker for intensifying pest monitoring as leaf area increases colonization opportunity. ||Damage during separation from mechanical injury, pests, or diseases reduces photosynthetic capacity affecting shoot growth potential and fruit development. ||Research applications include analyzing cellular and molecular mechanisms of leaf separation and unfolding, quantifying photosynthetic capacity development during early leaf expansion, evaluating environmental effects on leaf development rates and final characteristics, and assessing hormonal regulation coordinating leaf positioning and expansion processes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 189-195 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 89-95 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "First_Leaf_Expansion": {
  "definition": "A First_Leaf_Expansion is a First_Leaf_Unfolding comprising the enlargement of the first true leaf toward mature dimensions through cell expansion.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf expansion phase | expanding first leaf | growing leaf | enlarging leaf |+ erste Blattexpansion | wachsendes Erstblatt | expandierendes Blatt | Blattwachstum",
  "example_of_usage": "Tempranillo in Rioja shows first leaf expansion following BBCH 09 in early May after 1150-1300 chilling hours and 520-580 growing degree days base 10°C, with first leaf expanding from 18 mm to 35-45 mm over 4-5 days under conditions of 18-22°C mean temperature, 50-60% relative humidity, adequate soil moisture, and 14.5-hour photoperiod, representing typical continental climate pattern for this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "First_Leaf_Expansion is the second of three First_Leaf_Unfolding subphases, distinguished by rapid enlargement of separated first leaf approaching functional dimensions. ||Transitions to Multiple_Leaf_Unfolding as additional leaves begin separating and expanding. ||Represents critical phase establishing shoot photosynthetic capacity. ||Final leaf size at this stage strongly affects subsequent shoot growth potential. || This developmental stage follows initial separation with leaf blade expanding from 15-20 mm to 30-50 mm length over 3-5 days, developing characteristic palmate grapevine leaf morphology with clearly separated leaflets spreading from central rachis establishing recognizable cultivar-specific leaf form. ||Leaf expansion proceeds through coordinated processes including continued cell division in marginal and plate meristems producing new cells particularly at leaf margins, and rapid cell expansion throughout blade through turgor-driven cell wall extension increasing individual cell volumes 20-100 fold from meristematic dimensions. ||The expanding leaf displays intensifying green coloration as chlorophyll concentration increases to 1.5-2.5 mg per gram fresh weight approaching mature leaf levels, with upper leaf surface typically darker green than lower surface reflecting differential chloroplast distribution between palisade and spongy mesophyll tissues. ||Leaflets separate progressively from each other with sinuses deepening between lobes creating characteristic leaf outline, with final sinus depth varying substantially among cultivars from shallow creating nearly entire leaves to deep producing highly dissected configurations. ||Leaf surface texture develops characteristic features including trichome density varying from glabrous to densely tomentose depending on cultivar genetic programming, with trichome development affecting leaf optical properties including light reflectance and absorption. ||Stomata achieve full functional capacity with stomatal apertures responding dynamically to environmental conditions including light intensity providing photosynthetic substrate CO2, atmospheric vapor pressure deficit affecting transpirational water loss, and internal CO2 concentration reflecting photosynthetic activity. ||Chloroplast development approaches completion with thylakoid membranes fully organized into grana and stroma lamellae, photosystem complexes assembled and functional for light capture and electron transport, and Calvin cycle enzymes including Rubisco accumulated to concentrations supporting substantial carbon fixation. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases rapidly during expansion reaching 60-80% of mature rates when leaf achieves 70-80% final size, with light saturation point increasing and photosynthetic efficiency approaching mature tissue values. ||The expanding leaf transitions from net carbon consumer to approaching carbon neutrality as photosynthetic rate increases with area expansion and chloroplast maturation, with crossover to net production typically occurring when leaf reaches 80-90% final dimensions. ||Vascular system extends throughout expanding blade with primary veins providing structural framework and transport pathways, secondary veins forming reticulated network connecting primary veins, and tertiary veins developing fine network ensuring all photosynthetic cells have access to water and export pathway for photosynthate. ||Water content maintains 80-85% fresh weight typical of actively expanding tissues, requiring continuous water uptake through shoot xylem with transpirational water loss from expanding leaf area increasing to 15-40 mg per hour depending on environmental conditions and leaf size. ||Cell wall composition changes during expansion with initial walls rich in pectin allowing plastic deformation, transitioning toward walls with increased cellulose and hemicellulose content providing structural rigidity as expansion completes, determining final cell and leaf mechanical properties. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated with respiration 6-10 fold above mature leaf levels supporting growth processes and photosynthetic infrastructure development, gradually declining as expansion completes and maintenance requirements decrease. ||Protein synthesis continues at high rates producing structural proteins for expanding cells, photosynthetic proteins approaching mature leaf concentrations with Rubisco accumulating to 40-50% total leaf protein, and regulatory proteins coordinating development and establishing metabolic capacity. ||Hormonal regulation maintains cytokinin and gibberellin supporting continued expansion, with auxin concentration declining from separation levels as expansion proceeds and polarity patterns become established. ||Temperature strongly affects expansion rate with optimal range 20-25°C for maximum rate, temperatures above 28-30°C reducing expansion through increased respiration and water stress while temperatures below 15°C slowing all processes substantially. ||Water availability critically affects expansion rate and final size with adequate soil moisture essential for maintaining turgor driving cell expansion, while water stress arrests expansion causing permanent size reduction even after recovery affecting photosynthetic capacity. ||Light intensity influences expansion rate and photosynthetic capacity development with high light promoting rapid chloroplast maturation to high capacity while shade reduces capacity though may increase specific leaf area through thinner blades. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects expansion rate and final photosynthetic capacity, with adequate nitrogen supporting protein synthesis for both structural and photosynthetic components while deficiency reduces expansion and limits photosynthetic potential. ||The process typically requires 3-5 days under favorable conditions with consistent temperatures 18-22°C and adequate resources, with suboptimal conditions extending duration to 5-8 days or causing incomplete expansion to reduced final dimensions. ||Cultivar variation appears in expansion rate, final leaf dimensions ranging from small 50-80 mm leaves to large 150-200 mm leaves, leaflet number and sinus depth creating diverse leaf shapes, and trichome density affecting leaf appearance and microclimate. ||Regional timing follows first leaf separation by 2-3 days, occurring early May in warm climates, mid-May in temperate regions, and late May in cool areas. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate water availability particularly during rapid expansion phase when stress severely impacts final size, providing sufficient nitrogen supporting protein synthesis for photosynthetic capacity, monitoring for pest colonization including leafhoppers and spider mites preferring young expanding leaves, and assessing expansion uniformity indicating shoot vigor and resource availability affecting canopy development. ||Damage during expansion from pests, diseases, or environmental stress permanently reduces photosynthetic capacity affecting shoot growth potential and subsequent fruit development. ||Research applications include analyzing cellular mechanisms of coordinated division and expansion, quantifying photosynthetic capacity development relative to leaf age and size, evaluating environmental factor effects on expansion rates and final characteristics including size and photosynthetic capacity, documenting hormonal and genetic regulation of leaf form development, and assessing implications of early leaf development for subsequent shoot growth and crop potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 195-205 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 95-105 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Multiple_Leaf_Unfolding": {
  "definition": "A Multiple_Leaf_Unfolding is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the sequential separation and expansion of second and subsequent leaves from the shoot axis.",
  "alternative_term": "sequential leaf unfolding | progressive leaf development | canopy development |+ multiple leaves spreading | mehrfache Blattentfaltung | sukzessive Blattexpansion | fortschreitende Blattentwicklung | Bestandesentwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Sauvignon Blanc in Marlborough shows multiple leaf unfolding at BBCH 12-15 during May after 1000-1100 chilling hours and reaching 650-850 growing degree days base 10°C, with second through fifth leaves unfolding sequentially at 3-4 day intervals reaching dimensions of 40-80 mm over 15-20 days under conditions of 16-20°C mean temperature, 60-70% relative humidity, adequate soil moisture and nutrition, and 13-14 hour photoperiod, representing typical cool maritime climate canopy development for this vigorous early-to-mid season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Multiple_Leaf_Unfolding is the third of three First_Leaf_Unfolding subphases, distinguished by sequential development of additional leaves creating expanding canopy. ||Transitions to Shoot_Growth as primary developmental designation once leaf unfolding pattern is established. ||Represents critical phase establishing shoot photosynthetic capacity and carbon balance. ||Encompasses BBCH 11-15 and beyond as shoot continues developing throughout growing season. || This developmental stage corresponds to BBCH 11-15 as sequential leaves unfold with each new leaf designated by number in BBCH system, progressing from two leaves unfolded at BBCH 12 through five leaves unfolded at BBCH 15 and continuing beyond as shoot elongation proceeds. ||The unfolding leaves show characteristic pattern of size progression with each successive leaf typically larger than previous reflecting increasing shoot vigor and resource availability as photosynthetic capacity develops, with second leaf reaching 80-120% dimensions of first leaf, third leaf 100-140% of first, and subsequent leaves continuing expansion to eventual maximum dimensions determined by cultivar genetics and environmental conditions. ||Sequential leaf unfolding follows regular timing pattern with new leaves separating at approximately 3-5 day intervals under favorable conditions, creating progressively developing canopy with leaves at various developmental stages from recently separated to approaching mature dimensions and full photosynthetic capacity. ||The apical meristem maintains active cell production initiating new leaf primordia every 2-3 days in regular phyllotactic pattern, typically alternating positions approximately 180 degrees around shoot axis creating characteristic distichous leaf arrangement, with each new primordium developing through stages from multicellular initiation to recognizable leaf form over 10-15 days before separation from axis. ||Shoot elongation continues at 5-15 mm per day depending on temperature and resource availability, with internodes between successive leaves extending through cell division in intercalary meristems and cell expansion throughout internode tissues creating visible daily shoot growth. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases progressively as leaf area accumulates with each unfolding leaf, transitioning shoot from net carbon consumer dependent on stored reserves to net carbon producer with positive carbon balance typically achieved when 3-4 leaves have substantially expanded to functional dimensions. ||The metabolic transition from heterotrophic to autotrophic growth represents critical developmental milestone with shoots becoming self-supporting for carbon requirements while continuing to import nitrogen, minerals, and initially some carbon from permanent structures. ||Stored carbohydrate reserves show progressive depletion during multiple leaf unfolding with cane starch concentrations declining to 20-30% of winter maximum by time 4-5 leaves have unfolded, while newly produced photosynthate increasingly supplies carbon for continued growth. ||Water demand increases substantially with each additional unfolding leaf as transpiring surface area expands exponentially, with shoot water use increasing from 20-30 mg per hour with one leaf to 100-200 mg per hour with four to five leaves depending on leaf size, environmental conditions, and stomatal conductance. ||Vascular system extends continuously through elongating shoot with xylem differentiation maintaining functional water transport capacity and phloem development enabling bidirectional transport of resources including nitrogen and minerals imported from roots and photosynthate exported from expanding leaves. ||Nutrient demand intensifies during multiple leaf unfolding particularly for nitrogen supporting protein synthesis in expanding leaf tissues, with nitrogen concentration in young expanding leaves 3-5% dry weight declining to 2-3% as leaves mature and structural carbohydrates dilute nitrogen-rich proteins. ||Cell division continues in apical meristem and expanding leaf primordia with high mitotic activity producing cells for continued shoot and leaf growth, while older leaves complete cell production and expansion approaching mature dimensions and beginning transition to fully differentiated functional state. ||Chlorophyll concentration increases in each successive unfolding leaf following characteristic developmental pattern reaching mature levels of 2.0-3.5 mg per gram fresh weight as expansion completes and chloroplasts mature, with variation among cultivars in final chlorophyll concentration affecting leaf color intensity. ||Photosynthetic capacity per unit leaf area increases in each leaf as it expands and chloroplasts mature, reaching maximum rates of 10-20 micromoles CO2 per square meter per second at light saturation when leaves approach mature dimensions, with whole shoot photosynthetic capacity increasing proportionally to total expanded leaf area. ||Hormonal regulation continues with cytokinin and gibberellin supporting growth, auxin coordinating developmental patterns and establishing positions for lateral organs including tendrils and inflorescence primordia that begin appearing in nodes as shoot develops, with first inflorescence primordia typically visible microscopically by 5-7 leaf stage though not externally apparent. ||Temperature remains primary factor controlling unfolding rate and shoot elongation with development rate doubling approximately per 10°C increase between 10-28°C optimal range, with higher temperatures potentially reducing growth efficiency through excessive respiration and water stress. ||Water availability critically affects unfolding rate, leaf expansion, and final sizes with adequate soil moisture essential for maintaining turgor supporting rapid expansion, while water stress slows or arrests development and permanently reduces leaf dimensions affecting photosynthetic capacity and subsequent growth. ||Light intensity strongly affects leaf expansion rates, final sizes, and photosynthetic capacity development with high light promoting rapid expansion to large dimensions with high photosynthetic capacity, while shade reduces expansion rates and final sizes but may increase specific leaf area through thinner blades adapting to light limitation. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen and phosphorus affects unfolding rate and leaf development with adequate nutrition supporting rapid expansion to large dimensions with high photosynthetic capacity, while deficiencies reduce expansion rates, final sizes, and photosynthetic potential limiting subsequent growth. ||The process continues throughout shoot growth season with new leaves unfolding until shoot apex transitions to tendril or inflorescence production or until environmental limitations or management practices arrest growth, typically producing 12-20 leaves per shoot depending on vigor, cultivar, and management. ||Cultivar variation appears in leaf unfolding rate, final leaf number and sizes, leaf morphology including shape and dissection, and photosynthetic characteristics affecting canopy productivity. ||Regional timing shows continuous progression following first leaf stages, with rapid development during May-June in Northern Hemisphere warm climates, May-July in temperate regions, and June-July in cool areas. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate water and nutrient availability during rapid leaf development, managing shoot positioning and canopy architecture to optimize light interception, monitoring for pest and disease colonization of expanding canopy, implementing shoot thinning or trimming operations to control vigor and improve fruit microclimate, and assessing canopy development rates informing irrigation and nutrition management. ||Damage to multiple unfolding leaves from pests, diseases, hail, or other factors reduces photosynthetic capacity potentially severely limiting shoot growth, fruit development, and reserve accumulation affecting current season productivity and subsequent season potential. ||Research applications include quantifying canopy development rates and leaf area expansion patterns, analyzing photosynthetic capacity development and carbon balance transitions, evaluating environmental and management effects on shoot growth patterns and final canopy characteristics, assessing hormonal regulation of shoot architecture and organ differentiation, and documenting cultivar variation in growth patterns affecting vineyard productivity and management requirements.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 205-235 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 105-128 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Shoot_Growth": {
  "definition": "A Shoot_Growth is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the development of shoot architecture through internode extension and sequential leaf production.",
  "alternative_term": "vegetative growth | shoot development | shoot extension | canopy growth |+ Triebwachstum | Triebentwicklung | Triebstreckung | vegetatives Wachstum | Bestandeswachstum",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows shoot growth from early May through late July spanning BBCH 15-35 over 12-14 weeks, with shoots elongating from 150 mm at 5 leaves unfolded to 1200-1800 mm final length through growth phases progressing from 10-15 mm per day early elongation through 30-50 mm per day peak growth declining to cessation, under conditions of 18-28°C temperature range, adequate irrigation maintaining soil moisture, and moderate nitrogen fertility supporting balanced vegetative-reproductive development typical of this vigorous late-season cultivar in warm climate",
  "editor_note": "Shoot_Growth represents sustained vegetative development phase following Bud_Burst and First_Leaf_Unfolding. ||Distinguished by active internode elongation and sequential leaf production. ||Encompasses Shoot_Elongation as major constituent process along with Internode_Development, Leaf_Emergence, Tendril_Formation, and Shoot_Lignification. ||Transitions eventually to reproductive development focus and growth cessation. ||Critical phase establishing canopy architecture and photosynthetic capacity. || This fundamental developmental process follows bud burst completion and continues throughout the growing season, typically spanning 8-16 weeks depending on cultivar vigor, environmental conditions, and management practices. ||Shoot growth encompasses internode elongation creating visible daily shoot extension of 10-50 mm during peak growth periods, continued leaf initiation and expansion adding photosynthetic area, tendril and inflorescence development establishing reproductive structures, and progressive shoot maturation through lignification and reserve accumulation. ||The process shows characteristic sigmoid growth pattern with initial slow growth during early shoot establishment transitioning to rapid exponential growth as photosynthetic capacity develops, reaching maximum linear growth rate during mid-season optimal conditions, then declining as environmental limitations, resource competition, or developmental programming reduce growth rate, and eventually terminating as shoot apex ceases meristematic activity. ||Shoot elongation results from cell division in apical and intercalary meristems producing new cells, and cell expansion in subapical zones where cells increase length 20-100 fold through turgor-driven wall extension creating visible shoot extension. ||The apical meristem maintains organized structure with tunica and corpus cell layers producing organs in regular phyllotactic pattern, initiating new leaf primordia every 2-3 days during active growth, with primordia developing through predictable sequence from multicellular initiation to recognizable leaf form requiring 10-15 days before emergence. ||Internodes between successive leaves extend through intercalary meristem activity and cell expansion creating shoot length increments, with internode length varying from 20-40 mm during slow growth to 80-150 mm during rapid growth depending on vigor, environment, and developmental stage. ||Leaves continue unfolding and expanding sequentially with each shoot typically producing 12-20 leaves during growth period, with leaf size generally increasing from shoot base toward middle nodes then declining toward apex reflecting changing resource availability and developmental stage. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases progressively as leaf area accumulates, with shoots transitioning from net carbon consumers during early development to net carbon producers once 3-4 leaves fully expand, ultimately achieving positive carbon balance supporting both shoot growth and contribution to whole-plant assimilate pool. ||Carbon allocation shifts during shoot growth from exclusive vegetative growth during early phases to increasingly supporting reproductive development and reserve accumulation as fruit load develops and growth rate declines. ||Water demand increases substantially during shoot growth as transpiring leaf area expands and metabolic activity remains high, with vigorous shoots consuming 200-500 mg water per hour during peak growth depending on environmental conditions and canopy development. ||Vascular system extends continuously through elongating shoots with xylem differentiation maintaining functional water transport and phloem development enabling bidirectional resource movement including water and minerals upward and photosynthate and hormones both directions. ||Nutrient requirements intensify during rapid shoot growth particularly for nitrogen supporting protein synthesis in expanding tissues, phosphorus supporting energy metabolism and nucleic acid synthesis, and potassium supporting cell expansion and enzyme activation. ||Shoot lignification begins in basal internodes during active growth, progressing acropetally as growth rate declines with lignified tissues providing mechanical support, creating perennial woody structures for subsequent seasons, and accumulating carbohydrate reserves in parenchyma cells. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin from shoot apex maintaining apical dominance and coordinating growth polarity, cytokinins promoting cell division and delaying senescence, gibberellins supporting cell expansion and internode elongation, and ethylene and abscisic acid eventually contributing to growth cessation and maturation. ||Temperature strongly affects growth rate with optimal range 20-28°C for maximum elongation, with development rate approximately doubling per 10°C increase within physiological range while temperatures above 32°C or below 12°C substantially reduce growth. ||Light intensity affects growth rate and pattern with high light supporting rapid growth and shorter internodes with thicker shoots, while shade promotes elongated internodes with thinner shoots as etiolation response seeking improved light exposure. ||Water availability critically affects growth rate and duration with adequate soil moisture essential for maintaining turgor supporting cell expansion, while water stress rapidly arrests growth and can prematurely terminate shoot development affecting final canopy size and productivity. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen strongly affects growth rate, duration, and final shoot size with adequate nutrition supporting vigorous extended growth while deficiency reduces growth rate and causes early growth cessation limiting canopy development. ||The process shows five distinguishable phases based on growth rate progression, advancing from early shoot elongation during canopy establishment through rapid exponential growth, reaching peak linear growth during optimal mid-season conditions, declining as limitations develop or developmental programming engages, and terminating as apical meristem ceases activity. ||Cultivar variation appears in growth habit including vigor determining final shoot length, internode length patterns affecting architecture, growth duration from short 8-10 week to extended 14-16 week periods, and responsiveness to environmental conditions and management. ||Regional timing shows shoot growth active from late April through July-August in warm climates, May through August-September in temperate regions, and June through September in cool areas, with duration varying based on temperature accumulation, water availability, and cultivar characteristics. ||Viticultural management considerations include providing adequate water and nutrition supporting desired growth, implementing shoot positioning and canopy management optimizing light interception and air movement, controlling excessive vigor through appropriate crop load and root zone management, timing shoot trimming operations managing canopy size and directing resources toward fruit development, and monitoring growth uniformity assessing vineyard conditions and management effectiveness. ||Excessive shoot growth creates dense shaded canopy reducing fruit quality through poor light exposure and air movement increasing disease pressure, while insufficient growth limits photosynthetic capacity reducing fruit development and reserve accumulation affecting current and subsequent season productivity. ||Research applications include quantifying environmental and management effects on growth patterns and final canopy characteristics, analyzing carbon allocation between vegetative and reproductive growth affecting productivity and quality, evaluating hormonal and genetic regulation of growth habit and architecture, modeling growth responses to environmental conditions for management decision support, and assessing climate change impacts on growth patterns across viticultural regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0048367 ## shoot system development | 0.85", "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010016 ## shoot system morphogenesis | 0.80" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 205-265 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 128-178 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Schultz HR (2000) Climate change and viticulture: A European perspective on climatology, carbon dioxide and UV-B effects, Aust J Grape Wine Res 6:2-12"
},

  "Shoot_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Shoot_Elongation is a Shoot_Growth comprising shoot length increase through internode extension driven by apical meristem activity.",
  "alternative_term": "shoot extension | shoot stretching | internode elongation | axis elongation |+ Triebstreckung | Triebverlängerung | Internodienstreckung | Achsenstreckung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows shoot elongation from late April through early August over 14-15 weeks, with shoots extending from 120 mm at 4-5 leaves to 900-1400 mm final length through elongation rate progression from 8-12 mm per day early phase through 25-40 mm per day peak mid-June declining to cessation late July-early August, under continental climate conditions of 15-25°C temperature range, variable precipitation requiring supplemental irrigation, and moderate fertility typical of this moderate-vigor early-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Shoot_Elongation represents primary mechanism of Shoot_Growth through internode extension and apical activity. ||Distinguished by focus on length increase rather than broader growth encompassing leaf development and lignification. ||Subdivided into Early, Rapid, Peak, Declining, and Terminal phases based on elongation rate trajectory. ||Critical process determining final shoot length and canopy architecture. || This fundamental developmental process constitutes the primary mechanism of shoot growth, occurring continuously from early development through growth cessation over 8-16 week period depending on vigor and conditions. ||Elongation results from cell production in apical meristem initiating new cells for shoot axis and organ primordia, intercalary meristem activity in developing internodes adding cells to internode tissues, and cell expansion in subapical elongation zones where cells increase length dramatically through turgor-driven wall extension. ||The apical meristem maintains dome structure typically 100-200 micrometers diameter with organized cell layers including outer tunica producing surface tissues and inner corpus generating internal tissues, with cell division rates during active growth producing new cells every 18-24 hours maintaining meristem size while contributing cells to developing organs and shoot axis. ||Subapical elongation zone extends 10-30 mm behind apex depending on growth rate, containing cells undergoing rapid expansion through water uptake creating turgor pressure of 0.4-0.8 MPa driving cell wall extension, with expansion rate highest immediately behind meristem declining toward mature tissues as cell walls rigidify. ||Internode extension contributes most directly to visible shoot elongation with developing internodes elongating through intercalary meristem activity near nodes and general cell expansion throughout internode length, creating internode lengths varying from 20-40 mm during slow growth to 80-150 mm during rapid growth. ||Cell expansion involves water uptake increasing cell volume 20-100 fold from meristematic dimensions, wall loosening through expansin proteins and other wall-modifying enzymes allowing plastic deformation under turgor pressure, and wall synthesis adding new material maintaining structural integrity while allowing continued expansion. ||Elongation rate shows characteristic temporal pattern following sigmoid curve with initial slow rate during early shoot establishment at 5-15 mm per day, accelerating to rapid exponential growth at 20-40 mm per day as photosynthetic capacity develops, reaching peak linear growth at 30-50 mm per day during optimal mid-season conditions, then declining to 10-20 mm per day as limitations develop, and eventually ceasing as growth terminates. ||Daily elongation rate varies substantially with environmental conditions particularly temperature driving metabolic rates and water availability maintaining turgor, with favorable conditions supporting maximum rates while stress rapidly reduces or arrests elongation. ||Vascular differentiation proceeds continuously in elongating tissues with procambial strands differentiating into xylem vessels for water transport and phloem sieve elements for assimilate distribution, establishing functional connections between developing leaves and permanent structures. ||Cell wall composition changes during elongation with initial thin plastic walls rich in pectins allowing expansion, transitioning toward walls with increased cellulose and hemicellulose providing structural rigidity as expansion completes, determining final cell and tissue mechanical properties. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated in elongation zones with respiration rates 8-15 fold above mature tissue levels supporting growth processes, consuming both stored reserves during early growth and photosynthate from expanding leaves as photosynthetic capacity develops. ||Protein synthesis operates at high rates producing structural proteins for expanding cells including cell wall proteins and membrane proteins, enzymes supporting metabolism including wall-modifying enzymes enabling expansion, and regulatory proteins coordinating developmental processes. ||Hormonal regulation centrally involves auxin from shoot apex maintaining elongation through promoting cell expansion and coordinating growth polarity, gibberellins supporting internode elongation particularly through promoting cell expansion, cytokinins from roots promoting cell division in meristems, and brassinosteroids enhancing cell expansion and vascular differentiation. ||Temperature strongly affects elongation rate with optimal range 22-28°C for maximum rate approximately doubling per 10°C increase within 15-30°C physiological range, with temperatures above 32°C reducing efficiency through excessive respiration and water stress while temperatures below 15°C substantially slow all processes. ||Light quality affects elongation pattern with red: far-red ratio influencing internode length through phytochrome-mediated responses, with shade conditions promoting elongated internodes as etiolation response while high light supports shorter stouter internodes. ||Water availability critically affects elongation through direct effects on cell turgor driving expansion and indirect effects on photosynthesis supplying assimilates and energy, with water stress rapidly arresting elongation through turgor loss and can prematurely terminate growth affecting final shoot size. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects elongation rate and duration through effects on protein synthesis supporting growth and photosynthesis providing carbon skeletons and energy, with adequate nutrition supporting vigorous sustained elongation while deficiency reduces rate and causes early cessation. ||The process shows five distinguishable phases based on elongation rate trajectory, progressing from early elongation during establishment through rapid exponential growth, peak linear growth during optimal conditions, declining growth as limitations engage, and terminal phase as elongation ceases. ||Cultivar variation appears in elongation rate patterns, maximum elongation rates during peak growth, total elongation duration determining final shoot length, internode length characteristics affecting shoot architecture, and environmental responsiveness in growth patterns. ||Regional timing shows active elongation from May through July-August in warm climates, late May through August-September in temperate regions, and June through September in cool areas, with duration varying based on temperature accumulation and water availability. ||Viticultural management considerations include providing adequate resources supporting desired elongation patterns, managing vigor through appropriate irrigation and nutrition balancing vegetative and reproductive development, implementing shoot positioning optimizing canopy light interception, timing shoot trimming operations controlling excessive elongation and directing resources toward fruit, and monitoring elongation rates assessing vine health and management effectiveness. ||Excessive elongation creates overly vigorous canopies with dense shade reducing fruit quality while insufficient elongation limits photosynthetic capacity reducing productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing cellular and molecular mechanisms of elongation processes, quantifying environmental and hormonal effects on elongation rates and patterns, modeling elongation responses for management decision support, evaluating genetic variation in elongation characteristics affecting architecture and productivity, and assessing climate change impacts on elongation patterns and final canopy development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0007089 ## stem elongation stage | 0.95" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 205-235 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 128-152 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Early_Shoot_Elongation": {
  "definition": "An Early_Shoot_Elongation is a Shoot_Elongation comprising shoot length increase at low elongation rate sustained by stored reserves and developing photosynthetic capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "initial shoot extension | beginning elongation phase | establishment growth | early vegetative growth |+ frühe Triebstreckung | beginnende Längenwachstum | Etablierungsphase | initiale Triebverlängerung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows early shoot elongation from late April through mid-May at BBCH 15-19 over 3-4 weeks, with shoots extending from 180 mm at 5 leaves to 550-650 mm at 9 leaves through elongation rates progressing from 10-14 mm per day initially to 16-20 mm per day as photosynthetic capacity develops, under cool maritime climate conditions of 14-18°C mean temperature, adequate spring rainfall, and moderate fertility typical of this moderately vigorous early-bursting cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Early_Shoot_Elongation is first of five Shoot_Elongation subphases, distinguished by modest elongation rates and transition from stored reserves to photosynthetic carbon sources. ||Transitions to Rapid_Shoot_Elongation as photosynthetic capacity becomes established and growth accelerates. ||Represents critical establishment phase determining subsequent growth potential. ||Carbon balance transition during this phase fundamentally affects growth capacity. || This developmental stage occurs during late April through May in temperate regions corresponding approximately to BBCH 15-19 as shoots develop 5-9 unfolded leaves, with elongation rate typically 8-18 mm per day creating total shoot length increase from 150-200 mm to 400-700 mm over 2-4 week period. ||Early elongation shows progressive acceleration as each additional expanding leaf contributes photosynthetic capacity, with shoots transitioning from net carbon consumers during initial phase to approaching carbon neutrality and eventually positive carbon balance when 4-5 leaves achieve substantial expansion and photosynthetic function. ||The apical meristem maintains high activity producing new leaf primordia every 2-3 days and contributing cells to shoot axis, with meristem structure showing organized tunica-corpus organization and cell division rates of 20-24 hour cycles characteristic of active growth. ||Internode lengths during early elongation typically range 25-45 mm reflecting moderate growth rate and developing resource availability, with internodes progressively lengthening as growth accelerates toward rapid elongation phase. ||Cell expansion in subapical zones proceeds through water uptake and wall loosening, with expansion zone extending 15-25 mm behind apex containing cells increasing from meristematic dimensions to final lengths of 100-300 micrometers depending on internode position and growth conditions. ||Leaves continue unfolding and expanding sequentially with new leaves separating from axis every 3-5 days, with leaf sizes progressively increasing from basal leaves toward middle shoot positions reflecting improving resource status as photosynthetic area accumulates. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases progressively during early elongation as leaf area expands and chloroplasts mature, with whole-shoot net photosynthesis transitioning from negative to positive typically around 4-5 leaf stage when photosynthetic carbon fixation begins exceeding respiratory carbon consumption. ||Carbon sources during early elongation include primarily stored carbohydrates mobilized from woody tissues in declining amounts as reserves deplete, and increasingly photosynthate from expanding leaves as photosynthetic capacity develops, with transition from stored to current assimilate occurring progressively over 2-3 week period. ||Vascular system extends through elongating shoot with xylem differentiation maintaining functional water transport capacity of 1-3 mg per second supporting expansion and transpiration, and phloem development enabling import of stored reserves initially and bidirectional transport as photosynthetic production begins. ||Water demand increases substantially during early elongation as transpiring leaf area expands from 100-200 square mm with 4-5 leaves to 500-1200 square mm with 8-9 leaves, requiring shoot water uptake rates increasing from 30-60 mg per hour to 100-200 mg per hour depending on environmental conditions. ||Nutrient requirements intensify particularly for nitrogen supporting protein synthesis in rapidly expanding tissues, with nitrogen concentration in young leaves 3-5% dry weight and substantial nitrogen import from storage reserves and root uptake supporting growth demands. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated with respiration rates in expanding tissues 10-15 fold above mature levels supporting growth processes, with respiratory carbon loss declining as proportion of photosynthetic gain as carbon balance improves. ||Protein synthesis continues at high rates producing structural proteins for expanding cells, photosynthetic proteins accumulating in developing leaves reaching 40-50% total leaf protein as Rubisco and other Calvin cycle enzymes concentrate in chloroplasts, and enzymes supporting rapid metabolism. ||Hormonal regulation maintains elevated auxin from shoot apex coordinating elongation and apical dominance, gibberellins supporting cell expansion and internode elongation, and cytokinins from roots promoting cell division in meristematic tissues and leaf expansion. ||Temperature strongly affects early elongation rate with development approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C optimal range, with cool spring conditions often limiting early growth while warm conditions accelerate development. ||Light intensity affects early elongation through effects on photosynthetic capacity development, with high light promoting rapid photosynthetic maturation supporting accelerating growth while shade reduces photosynthetic gain potentially prolonging early elongation phase. ||Water availability must be adequate to support turgor maintaining cell expansion, with spring water stress potentially limiting early elongation rate and delaying transition to rapid growth impacting final canopy development. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects early elongation rate through effects on protein synthesis capacity and photosynthetic development, with adequate nutrition supporting rapid acceleration toward peak growth while deficiency prolongs slow early phase. ||The process typically spans 2-4 weeks under favorable conditions with consistent temperatures above 16°C and adequate moisture and nutrition, with suboptimal conditions extending duration or limiting acceleration toward rapid elongation. ||Cultivar variation appears in early elongation rate reflecting inherent vigor differences, with vigorous cultivars showing more rapid acceleration toward peak growth while less vigorous types maintain modest rates longer. ||Regional timing shows early elongation occurring late April through May in warm climates, May through early June in temperate regions, and late May through mid-June in cool areas, with duration depending on spring temperature patterns and resource availability. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate water availability during early elongation supporting transition to rapid growth, providing sufficient nitrogen supporting protein synthesis and photosynthetic capacity development without excessive promotion of vigor, monitoring shoot development uniformity assessing vine health and resource distribution, and planning canopy management operations based on elongation progression. ||Limitations during early elongation including water stress, nutrient deficiency, or pest damage can permanently reduce final canopy size affecting productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing transition from heterotrophic to autotrophic growth documenting carbon balance dynamics, quantifying photosynthetic capacity development relative to growth requirements, evaluating environmental effects on early growth patterns affecting final canopy development, and assessing hormonal regulation coordinating transition from establishment to rapid growth phase.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 205-220 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 128-140 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Rapid_Shoot_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Shoot_Elongation is a Shoot_Elongation comprising shoot length increase at accelerated elongation rate establishing the major portion of final canopy architecture.",
  "alternative_term": "exponential elongation | accelerating growth phase | maximum elongation rate | rapid vegetative growth |+ rapide Triebstreckung | exponentielle Wachstumsphase | Beschleunigungsphase | maximale Streckungsrate",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows rapid shoot elongation from late May through late June at BBCH 19-31 over 4-5 weeks, with shoots extending from 750 mm at 9 leaves to 1600-1900 mm at flowering through elongation rates accelerating from 22-28 mm per day to peak 38-48 mm per day mid-phase, under temperate maritime conditions of 18-24°C mean temperature, adequate rainfall or irrigation, high solar radiation, and moderate-high fertility typical of this vigorous mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Shoot_Elongation is second of five Shoot_Elongation subphases, distinguished by accelerating exponential growth rate and strongly positive carbon balance. ||Transitions to Peak_Shoot_Elongation as maximum linear growth rate is achieved. ||Represents phase of maximum canopy establishment and photosynthetic capacity development. ||Critical phase determining final shoot length and productive capacity. || This developmental stage typically occurs during May-June in temperate regions corresponding approximately to BBCH 19-31 as shoots develop 9 leaves through flowering, with elongation rate accelerating from 20-30 mm per day to 35-50 mm per day creating total shoot length increase from 600-800 mm to 1200-2000 mm over 3-5 week period depending on vigor and conditions. ||Rapid elongation represents exponential growth phase of sigmoid growth curve where rate increases progressively as each additional expanding leaf contributes photosynthetic capacity and favorable temperature and water availability support maximum metabolic activity. ||The apical meristem maintains maximum activity producing new leaf primordia every 2 days and contributing high cell production rate to shoot axis, with mitotic activity creating zone of dividing cells extending 100-200 micrometers behind apex supplying cells for continued elongation. ||Internode lengths during rapid elongation typically range 60-120 mm reflecting high growth rate and abundant resource availability, with longest internodes typically occurring during this phase when conditions and developmental state optimize for maximum expansion. ||Cell expansion in subapical zones proceeds at maximum rates through abundant water uptake and active wall loosening, with expansion zone extending 20-35 mm behind apex containing cells rapidly increasing to final lengths of 200-500 micrometers creating visible daily shoot extension. ||Leaves continue unfolding and expanding with new leaves emerging every 2-3 days and expanding rapidly to large dimensions, with leaf area accumulation rate highest during rapid elongation contributing progressively to whole-plant photosynthetic capacity. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases dramatically during rapid elongation as leaf area expands exponentially and mature leaves achieve full photosynthetic function, with whole-shoot net photosynthesis strongly positive producing substantial excess assimilate beyond shoot growth requirements contributing to whole-plant carbon economy. ||Carbon allocation during rapid elongation directs substantial photosynthate to shoot growth supporting high cell production and expansion rates, with shoots consuming 60-80% of their photosynthetic production for growth while contributing excess to developing fruit, other vegetative growth, and beginning reserve accumulation. ||Vascular system extends rapidly through elongating shoots with xylem differentiation maintaining high water transport capacity of 3-6 mg per second supporting rapid expansion and increasing transpiration, and phloem development enabling bidirectional transport moving photosynthate to growth zones and excess production to sinks. ||Water demand increases dramatically during rapid elongation as transpiring leaf area expands from 1000-1500 square mm to 3000-5000 square mm, requiring shoot water uptake rates increasing from 200-300 mg per hour to 400-700 mg per hour depending on environmental conditions and shoot size. ||Nutrient requirements peak during rapid elongation particularly for nitrogen supporting high protein synthesis rates, phosphorus supporting energy metabolism and nucleic acid synthesis for new cells, and potassium supporting cell expansion and enzyme activation throughout rapidly growing tissues. ||Metabolic activity operates at maximum levels with respiration rates in expanding tissues 12-18 fold above mature levels providing energy and carbon skeletons supporting rapid growth, though declining as proportion of photosynthetic production as carbon balance becomes strongly positive. ||Protein synthesis operates at maximum capacity producing structural proteins for rapidly expanding cells, photosynthetic proteins in developing leaves, regulatory proteins coordinating complex developmental processes, and enzymes supporting high metabolic activity. ||Hormonal regulation shows peak auxin production from active shoot apex maintaining elongation and strong apical dominance, elevated gibberellins supporting maximum cell expansion and internode elongation, and high cytokinins from active roots promoting cell division and leaf expansion. ||Temperature during rapid elongation strongly affects growth rate with optimal range 22-28°C supporting maximum elongation approximately doubling per 10°C within physiological range, with warm spring-early summer conditions typically occurring during this phase promoting maximum growth potential. ||Light intensity affects rapid elongation through photosynthetic capacity and internode length responses, with high light supporting maximum photosynthetic rate providing assimilates for growth and promoting moderate internode lengths, while shade reduces photosynthetic capacity limiting growth potential though may promote elongated internodes through etiolation. ||Water availability critically affects rapid elongation as high transpiration rates and growth water requirements demand continuous adequate supply, with water stress rapidly arresting elongation through turgor loss and can prematurely transition to declining growth phase permanently limiting final canopy size. ||Nutrient availability must be adequate to support high growth rates particularly nitrogen for protein synthesis, with deficiency during rapid elongation causing premature transition to declining phase limiting canopy development and subsequent productivity. ||The process typically spans 3-5 weeks under favorable conditions with consistent temperatures 20-26°C, adequate soil moisture and nutrition, and sufficient light, with vigorous cultivars showing extended duration while less vigorous types show briefer rapid phase. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum elongation rate during rapid phase ranging from 30-40 mm per day in moderate vigor cultivars to 45-60 mm per day in highly vigorous types, duration of rapid phase, and responsiveness to environmental conditions and management. ||Regional timing shows rapid elongation occurring May-June in warm climates, late May through July in temperate regions, and June-July in cool areas, with timing relative to flowering varying but typically encompassing pre-bloom through early fruit set period. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate water availability maintaining turgor and photosynthetic capacity supporting maximum growth, providing sufficient but not excessive nitrogen supporting rapid growth while avoiding over-stimulation, implementing shoot positioning operations managing canopy development for optimal light interception and air movement, monitoring vigor uniformity assessing resource distribution and vine health, and planning timing of trimming operations relative to flowering and fruit set to optimize reproductive success while managing excessive vegetative vigor. ||Excessive rapid elongation creates overly vigorous dense canopies reducing fruit quality through shading and disease pressure, while limited rapid elongation reduces photosynthetic capacity potentially limiting fruit development and reserve accumulation. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms of exponential growth including hormonal and metabolic regulation, quantifying carbon balance dynamics and assimilate partitioning patterns, evaluating environmental and management effects on growth patterns affecting canopy architecture and productivity, modeling growth responses for decision support systems, and assessing genetic variation in growth characteristics affecting vineyard management requirements and wine quality potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 220-235 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 140-152 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Peak_Shoot_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Shoot_Elongation is a Shoot_Elongation comprising shoot length increase at maximum sustained elongation rate.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum elongation | sustained rapid growth | linear growth phase | peak vegetative growth |+ maximale Triebstreckung | Höchststreckungsphase | lineare Wachstumsphase | Spitzenvegetation",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Barossa Valley shows peak shoot elongation from mid-December to early January at BBCH 31-35 over 3 weeks, with shoots extending from 1400 mm at flowering to 2100-2400 mm following fruit set through sustained elongation rate of 42-52 mm per day, under warm climate conditions of 24-30°C mean temperature, irrigation maintaining adequate soil moisture, high solar radiation, and moderate fertility typical of this vigorous mid-to-late season cultivar in Southern Hemisphere warm region",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Shoot_Elongation is third of five Shoot_Elongation subphases, distinguished by maximum sustained linear growth rate occurring typically during flowering through early fruit set. ||Transitions to Declining_Shoot_Elongation as environmental limitations or developmental programming reduce growth rate. ||Represents critical phase where vegetative-reproductive competition is highest. ||Timing and duration strongly affect final canopy architecture and fruit development balance. || This developmental stage typically occurs during mid-June to early-July in temperate regions corresponding approximately to BBCH 31-35 encompassing flowering through early fruit set, with elongation rate maintaining maximum of 40-60 mm per day for vigorous cultivars and 30-45 mm per day for moderate vigor types over 2-3 week period creating shoot length increase of 600-1200 mm. ||Peak elongation represents linear growth phase of sigmoid growth curve where rate remains at maximum for extended period as photosynthetic capacity, favorable environmental conditions, and developmental state combine to optimize growth resource availability. ||The apical meristem continues maximum activity producing new leaf primordia and contributing cells to shoot axis at consistent high rate, maintaining organized structure with active cell division cycles of 18-22 hours supplying cells for sustained rapid elongation. ||Internode lengths during peak elongation achieve maximum dimensions typically 80-150 mm reflecting optimal resource availability and growth conditions, with individual internode length varying based on position and microenvironmental conditions but generally remaining consistent during peak phase. ||Cell expansion in subapical zones operates at maximum sustainable rate with abundant water uptake and active wall loosening, expansion zone extending 25-35 mm behind apex with cells reaching final lengths of 300-600 micrometers depending on internode position and vigor characteristics. ||Leaves continue emerging and expanding at maximum rate with new leaves appearing every 2 days and rapidly expanding to large final dimensions, with mature leaf photosynthetic capacity fully established contributing strongly positive net carbon balance. ||Photosynthetic capacity operates at seasonal maximum with full canopy area developed and mature leaves functioning at peak efficiency, producing substantial excess assimilate beyond shoot growth requirements available for fruit development, root growth, and reserve accumulation. ||Carbon allocation during peak elongation shifts progressively from predominantly shoot growth toward increasing fruit development as reproductive demand accelerates following fruit set, with shoots consuming 40-60% their photosynthetic production for growth while contributing substantial excess to developing clusters and beginning significant reserve accumulation in permanent structures. ||Vascular system maintains maximum functionality with xylem conducting water at 4-8 mg per second supporting high transpiration and growth water requirements, and phloem transporting large assimilate quantities to multiple competing sinks including shoot growth, developing fruit, and storage tissues. ||Water demand reaches seasonal maximum during peak elongation as full canopy transpires under typically warm conditions, with shoot water use of 500-900 mg per hour requiring continuous adequate root uptake and soil moisture availability maintaining turgor and photosynthetic function. ||Nutrient demand continues at high levels particularly nitrogen supporting continued protein synthesis though declining as proportion of total demand as fruit development creates competing nutrient sink, phosphorus supporting energy metabolism in rapidly growing tissues, and potassium critical for fruit development quality attributes. ||Metabolic activity maintains elevated levels with respiration supporting growth processes though declining as proportion of photosynthetic production as mature leaves operate at maximum efficiency, creating favorable carbon balance supporting multiple growth processes simultaneously. ||Protein synthesis continues at high rates supporting shoot growth requirements while increasingly producing proteins for fruit development and reserve accumulation in permanent structures. ||Hormonal regulation maintains auxin from shoot apex supporting continued elongation though effects begin declining as reproductive hormones from developing fruit increasingly influence assimilate partitioning, gibberellins continue supporting cell expansion, and cytokinins promote continued cell division though root production may decline as root growth becomes limited by above-ground demands. ||Temperature during peak elongation typically remains in optimal 22-28°C range with mid-summer conditions, though excessive heat above 32°C can begin limiting growth efficiency through increased respiration and water stress. ||Light intensity remains high during long summer days supporting maximum photosynthetic production, with full canopy creating shading patterns affecting lower canopy leaves and potentially limiting whole-canopy photosynthetic efficiency if excessive density develops. ||Water availability becomes critical during peak elongation as maximum transpiration and growth demands coincide with typically warm dry conditions in many regions, requiring irrigation in water-limited regions maintaining adequate soil moisture preventing stress that rapidly arrests growth. ||Nutrient availability must remain adequate though excessive nitrogen during peak elongation can promote excessive vegetative vigor competing with fruit development, requiring balanced nutrition supporting both vegetative and reproductive growth. ||The process typically spans 2-3 weeks under favorable conditions with consistent optimal temperatures, adequate moisture, and balanced nutrition, with duration varying based on cultivar vigor characteristics and environmental limitations. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum sustained elongation rate during peak phase, duration of peak elongation period, and sensitivity to environmental limitations or reproductive demand affecting transition to declining growth. ||Regional timing shows peak elongation occurring mid-June to early July in warm climates, late June to mid-July in temperate regions, and July in cool areas, typically spanning flowering through early fruit set developmental period when both vegetative and reproductive demands are high. ||Viticultural management considerations include maintaining adequate but not excessive water availability supporting growth while promoting moderate water stress initiating growth decline and improved fruit development, managing nitrogen availability avoiding excessive late vegetative growth competing with fruit quality development, implementing shoot trimming operations at appropriate timing removing excessive length while maintaining adequate leaf area for fruit maturation, monitoring canopy density managing excessive growth creating unfavorable fruit microclimate, and assessing growth uniformity across vineyard blocks identifying management requirement variations. ||Excessive peak elongation extending too long creates overly vigorous canopies with dense shading reducing fruit quality, while premature limitation of peak elongation reduces photosynthetic capacity potentially limiting fruit development and reserve accumulation. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms maintaining sustained maximum growth rate, quantifying assimilate partitioning between vegetative and reproductive sinks during competition period, evaluating environmental and management effects on peak elongation duration and transition to declining phase affecting canopy architecture, modeling growth dynamics for decision support optimizing vegetative-reproductive balance, and assessing genetic and environmental variation in growth patterns affecting productivity and quality potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 235-248 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 152-165 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Declining_Shoot_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Declining_Shoot_Elongation is a Shoot_Elongation comprising shoot length increase at decelerating elongation rate below peak values.",
  "alternative_term": "decelerating growth | slowing elongation phase | growth reduction phase | declining vegetative growth |+ abnehmende Triebstreckung | verlangsamte Wachstumsphase | Wachstumsrückgang | Verlangsamungsphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows declining shoot elongation from early July through early August at BBCH 35-38 over 4-5 weeks, with shoots extending from 1800 mm following fruit set to 2200-2500 mm final length through elongation rate declining from 28-35 mm per day to 12-18 mm per day as berry development progresses, under oceanic climate conditions of 22-26°C mean temperature, decreasing precipitation requiring supplemental irrigation, and moderate fertility with nitrogen becoming redistributed to fruit typical of this moderately vigorous mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Declining_Shoot_Elongation is fourth of five Shoot_Elongation subphases, distinguished by progressive reduction in growth rate from peak levels as limitations engage. ||Transitions to Terminal_Shoot_Elongation as growth approaches cessation. ||Represents critical phase where resource allocation shifts decidedly toward fruit development. ||Timing and management of decline substantially affect fruit quality outcomes through effects on canopy-fruit balance. || This developmental stage typically occurs during July in temperate regions corresponding approximately to BBCH 35-38 as fruit develops from pea-size through beginning of berry touch, with elongation rate declining from 30-50 mm per day to 10-25 mm per day over 3-5 week period creating shoot length increase of 400-800 mm before growth largely ceases. ||Declining elongation represents deceleration phase of sigmoid growth curve where growth rate progressively reduces as multiple factors including high fruit demand for assimilates, possible water or nutrient limitations, increasing temperature stress, or developmental signals engage processes reducing meristematic activity and cell expansion rates. ||The apical meristem continues producing new leaf primordia but at reduced frequency of 3-4 days between new primordia initiation, with cell division rates slowing and meristem size potentially reducing as growth regulatory signals shift developmental priorities. ||Internode lengths during declining elongation progressively shorten from 60-100 mm early in phase to 30-60 mm later reflecting reducing resource availability for elongation and changing hormonal environment, with final internodes before growth cessation typically quite short 15-30 mm. ||Cell expansion in subapical zones operates at progressively reducing rates as turgor pressure declines through increased tissue water stress or hormonal signals reducing cell wall extensibility, with expansion zone potentially shortening to 15-25 mm behind apex and cells achieving smaller final dimensions of 150-400 micrometers. ||Leaves continue emerging but at slower rate and expanding to progressively smaller final dimensions, with late-season leaves typically 50-70% size of mid-season leaves reflecting reducing resource availability and changing developmental state. ||Photosynthetic capacity maintains high levels in mature leaves though proportion of production allocated to shoot growth declines substantially as fruit demand dominates assimilate partitioning, with reproductive sink strength typically exceeding vegetative demand creating competition that contributes to growth decline. ||Carbon allocation during declining elongation shifts dramatically from approximately equal vegetative-reproductive partitioning to 70-85% fruit allocation as developing clusters exert dominant sink strength, with shoot growth consuming only 20-30% photosynthetic production and remainder supporting fruit development, root growth, and increasing reserve accumulation. ||Vascular system maintains functionality though new vessel and sieve element production slows, with water transport capacity of 3-5 mg per second adequate for reduced growth requirements and maintained transpiration from mature canopy. ||Water demand remains substantial at 400-600 mg per hour from mature canopy though growth component declines, with tissue water status often declining during this period in many regions as mid-summer heat and possible water limitation create moderate water stress contributing to growth reduction. ||Nutrient demand shifts predominantly to fruit with nitrogen particularly redirected from vegetative to reproductive tissues, with shoot growth nitrogen requirements declining while fruit accumulates nitrogen for protein synthesis and other developmental processes. ||Metabolic activity in shoot apical regions remains elevated though declining from peak levels, with respiration in expanding tissues 6-10 fold above mature levels declining as growth rate reduces, while mature leaf photosynthesis maintains high efficiency supporting fruit development. ||Protein synthesis continues in apical growing zones though at reduced rates, with declining production of cell cycle proteins and wall synthesis enzymes reflecting reduced growth while maintenance proteins and reserve storage proteins increase in mature tissues. ||Hormonal regulation shows declining auxin production from slowing shoot apex reducing growth-promoting signals, increasing abscisic acid from water-stressed tissues or fruit development promoting growth reduction, possible declining cytokinin supply from roots under stress or developmental change, and ethylene potentially increasing promoting growth cessation processes. ||Temperature during declining elongation typically includes warmest conditions of growing season with means often 24-30°C in many regions, with high temperatures contributing to growth reduction through increased respiration reducing carbon balance efficiency and exacerbating water stress effects. ||Light intensity remains high during mid-summer though increasing canopy density may reduce light penetration to lower leaves limiting whole-canopy photosynthetic efficiency, while high light on exposed tissues can create photo-inhibition stress. ||Water availability often becomes limiting during declining elongation in many regions as mid-late summer typically coincides with reduced precipitation and high evaporative demand, with moderate water stress contributing beneficially to growth reduction while severe stress risks premature leaf senescence and compromised fruit development. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen becomes redistributed with mobile nutrients moving from vegetative tissues toward fruit, with continued excessive nitrogen availability potentially prolonging vegetative growth undesirably competing with fruit maturation. ||The process typically spans 3-5 weeks under normal conditions with progressive environmental stress and fruit sink development, with duration varying based on severity of limiting factors and cultivar growth habit characteristics. ||Cultivar variation appears in rate of decline from peak growth, final shoot length achieved before cessation, timing of growth cessation relative to fruit development stages, and sensitivity to environmental stresses affecting decline rate. ||Regional timing shows declining elongation occurring July in warm climates, July-August in temperate regions, and August in cool areas, typically spanning early berry development through beginning color change period when fruit demands are increasing substantially. ||Viticultural management considerations include using moderate water stress to promote timely growth decline improving fruit development conditions, avoiding excessive late nitrogen maintaining vegetative growth competing with fruit quality, implementing shoot trimming removing excessive length and lateral growth managing canopy density, monitoring canopy condition assessing stress levels and fruit development progress, and adjusting irrigation and nutrition management based on growth decline patterns and fruit development requirements. ||Premature severe growth decline from excessive stress risks insufficient photosynthetic capacity for fruit maturation and reserve accumulation, while prolonged excessive growth from over-supply of resources creates unfavorable fruit microclimate and delays maturation. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms of growth decline including hormonal regulation and source-sink dynamics, quantifying assimilate partitioning shifts during vegetative-reproductive competition, evaluating management strategies optimizing growth cessation timing for quality outcomes, modeling growth patterns for decision support systems, and assessing genetic variation in growth habit affecting management requirements and fruit quality potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 248-258 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 165-175 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Terminal_Shoot_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Terminal_Shoot_Elongation is a Shoot_Elongation comprising the final shoot length increase at near-zero elongation rate with apical meristem activity ceased.",
  "alternative_term": "growth cessation | shoot maturation | terminal growth phase | apical growth arrest |+ Wachstumsabschluss | Triebausr eifung | Terminalphase | apikaler Wachstumsstillstand",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows terminal shoot elongation from late July through mid-August at BBCH 38-41 over 3 weeks, with shoots reaching 2400-2800 mm final length through elongation rate declining from 15-20 mm per day to cessation, shoot apex becoming necrotic, under warm climate conditions of 26-32°C mean temperature, moderate water stress from limited irrigation, and nutrient redistribution to developing fruit typical of this vigorous late-season cultivar achieving growth cessation as veraison initiates",
  "editor_note": "Terminal_Shoot_Elongation is fifth and final Shoot_Elongation subphase, distinguished by growth approaching and reaching zero as apical meristem activity ceases. ||Marks definitive end of vegetative elongation phase. ||Transitions focus to Shoot_Lignification and fruit maturation processes. ||Timing relative to fruit development critically affects fruit quality potential through effects on photosynthetic capacity duration and resource allocation patterns. || This developmental stage typically occurs during late July through August in temperate regions corresponding approximately to BBCH 38-41 as berries reach full size and begin color change, with elongation rate declining from 10-20 mm per day to <5 mm per day and eventually ceasing over 2-3 week period adding final 100-300 mm shoot length. ||Terminal elongation represents asymptotic approach to zero growth of sigmoid growth curve as multiple limiting factors combine with developmental programming to arrest meristematic activity and cell expansion, with shoot apex typically transforming from active vegetative meristem to senescent or necrotic terminal structure. ||The shoot apex ceases producing new leaf primordia with apical meristem losing organized structure, cells losing division capacity, and apex often becoming necrotic or senescing creating characteristic appearance of growth cessation, though some cultivars may maintain green non-growing apex. ||Final internodes produced during terminal elongation show markedly reduced length typically 15-40 mm reflecting minimal resource allocation to elongation and changed hormonal environment strongly favoring reproductive over vegetative development. ||Cell expansion in subapical zones operates at minimal rates as severe water stress or hormonal signals nearly eliminate cell wall extensibility, with expansion zone reduced to <15 mm behind apex and cells achieving small final dimensions of 100-250 micrometers in terminal internodes. ||Final leaves emerging show substantially reduced size typically 30-50% dimensions of mid-season leaves and may show reduced expansion or development indicating resource limitation and changed developmental priorities, with terminal leaves sometimes failing to fully expand before growth ceases. ||Photosynthetic capacity in mature canopy remains substantial supporting fruit development and reserve accumulation though new photosynthetic area addition ceases with growth termination, with assimilate production directed almost entirely toward reproductive development and storage with negligible vegetative growth demand. ||Carbon allocation during terminal elongation shows 85-95% fruit and reserve accumulation with only 5-15% supporting minimal remaining shoot growth, with cessation of elongation redirecting all photosynthetic production toward fruit maturation, root growth, and substantial reserve accumulation in woody tissues. ||Vascular system in shoot apex may show incomplete differentiation as growth arrests before full maturation, with functional xylem and phloem in mature shoot portions maintaining resource transport for fruit development and reserve movement though no longer supporting shoot growth. ||Water demand from mature canopy continues at 300-500 mg per hour though growth component essentially zero, with tissue water status often at seasonal minimum in many regions as late summer conditions and fruit transpiration create high demand, with moderate to severe water stress typical and contributing to growth cessation. ||Nutrient demand shifts entirely to fruit with nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium and other nutrients moving predominantly toward berries, with shoot apex and young leaves potentially showing nutrient deficiency symptoms as mobile nutrients redistribute, contributing to growth cessation and terminal leaf senescence. ||Metabolic activity in shoot apex declines substantially with respiration approaching mature tissue levels as growth ceases, while mature leaf photosynthesis maintains efficient operation supporting fruit development though possibly declining slightly as water stress or nutrient redistribution affects function. ||Protein synthesis in apical tissues nearly ceases with growth arrest, while mature tissues increasingly produce reserve storage proteins and enzymes involved in reserve accumulation and tissue maturation processes. ||Hormonal regulation shows minimal auxin production from ceased apex eliminating growth promotion, elevated abscisic acid from water stress and developmental signals promoting growth cessation, possible increased ethylene from stress or fruit ripening contributing to senescence processes, and depleted cytokinins as root production declines. ||Temperature during terminal elongation includes continued warm to hot conditions typical of late summer with means often 24-30°C in many regions, with high temperatures contributing to growth cessation through water stress and metabolic efficiency reduction though not typically limiting fruit maturation processes. ||Light intensity begins declining from summer maximum as day length shortens and solar angle lowers, though generally remaining adequate for photosynthesis and not limiting factor in growth cessation. ||Water availability often at seasonal minimum during terminal elongation in many regions with late summer drought conditions, with moderate water stress beneficial for fruit quality development while severe stress risks premature senescence and incomplete fruit maturation. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen largely depleted from vegetative tissues as mobile nutrients redistribute to fruit, with shoot tissues showing declining nitrogen concentrations and possible deficiency symptoms in young tissues as growth ceases. ||The process typically spans 2-3 weeks with progressive growth rate reduction to zero, with final cessation timing varying based on environmental stress severity, fruit load and developmental stage, and cultivar growth habit characteristics. ||Cultivar variation appears in timing of growth cessation relative to fruit development stages, whether apex maintains viable appearance or necrotizes, final shoot length achieved, and sensitivity to environmental factors affecting cessation timing. ||Regional timing shows terminal elongation and cessation occurring late July-August in warm climates, August-September in temperate regions, and August-September in cool areas, typically spanning berry development completion through beginning ripening when fruit demands are maximum. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring growth cessation timing relative to fruit development ensuring adequate vegetative development for fruit maturation while avoiding excessive late growth, managing water stress promoting timely cessation and fruit quality development without excessive stress causing premature senescence, assessing post-cessation canopy condition for fruit maturation and reserve accumulation capacity, planning late-season leaf removal and cluster thinning operations based on canopy function, and evaluating year's vegetative growth outcomes informing subsequent season management adjustments. ||Premature growth cessation from excessive stress reduces photosynthetic capacity and duration potentially limiting fruit maturation and reserve accumulation, while delayed cessation from excessive resources maintains vegetative growth competing with fruit quality development. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms of growth cessation including hormonal regulation and developmental programming, quantifying final assimilate partitioning patterns during fruit maturation, evaluating management effects on cessation timing and fruit quality outcomes, modeling seasonal growth patterns for cultivar characterization and management decision support, and assessing climate change impacts on growth duration and cessation timing affecting productivity and quality across regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 258-265 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 175-178 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Internode_Development": {
  "definition": "An Internode_Development is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the formation, elongation, and maturation of stem segments between successive nodes.",
  "alternative_term": "stem segment development | internode formation | stem development | axis development |+ Internodienentwicklung | Stängelgliedbildung | Achsenentwicklung | Stammabschnittbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows internode development from late April through July over 12-14 weeks at BBCH 15-38, producing 14-18 internodes ranging from 35-45 mm in basal positions to 70-95 mm during peak growth declining to 25-40 mm terminally, creating final shoot length of 900-1300 mm with progressive lignification from base upward under continental climate conditions of 15-26°C temperature range, variable moisture, and moderate fertility typical of this moderate-vigor cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Internode_Development represents structural axis formation process within Shoot_Growth, occurring coordinately with Shoot_Elongation but focusing on segmental structure rather than overall length. ||Subdivided into First_Internode_Formation, Sequential_Internode_Formation, Internode_Elongation, and Internode_Maturation based on progression. ||Distinguished from Shoot_Elongation which emphasizes length increase while Internode_Development emphasizes segmental structure and maturation. ||Critical process determining shoot architecture and mechanical properties. || This essential developmental process occurs continuously during shoot growth from early elongation through growth cessation, typically spanning 8-16 weeks producing 12-20 internodes per shoot depending on vigor and conditions. ||Internode development encompasses initiation of new internode segments at shoot apex through intercalary meristem establishment, progressive elongation through cell division and expansion creating visible shoot extension, and maturation through lignification and vascular differentiation establishing permanent woody structure. ||The process shows coordinated progression along shoot axis with basal internodes completing development and lignifying while apical internodes continue forming and elongating, creating developmental gradient from mature lignified base to actively elongating apex to meristematic summit. ||Internode formation initiates at shoot apex immediately behind apical meristem where leaf primordia emergence defines nodal positions, with intercalary meristem establishing between successive nodes containing cells that will contribute to internode length through division and subsequent expansion. ||Cell division in intercalary meristems continues for limited period adding cells to internode, with division typically ceasing when internode reaches 5-15 mm length depending on ultimate dimensions, followed by extended expansion phase where cells increase length 10-50 fold creating final internode dimensions. ||Internode elongation proceeds through coordinated cell expansion in central elongation zone where cells undergo turgor-driven wall extension, with expansion rate and duration determining final internode length ranging from 20-40 mm in slow-growing shoots to 80-150 mm during rapid elongation periods. ||Vascular differentiation proceeds acropetally through developing internodes with procambial strands differentiating into functional xylem vessels for water transport and phloem sieve elements for assimilate distribution, establishing continuous vascular connection from permanent structures through shoot to developing apex. ||Lignification begins in basal internodes while apical regions continue elongating, with secondary wall deposition and lignin incorporation creating rigid woody structure providing mechanical support, with lignification front progressing acropetally at approximately same rate as elongation creating mature lignified shoot base while apex remains herbaceous. ||Internode structure includes epidermis providing protective surface, cortex containing photosynthetic and storage parenchyma, vascular bundles arranged in characteristic pattern conducting water and assimilates, and pith providing structural core with storage function. ||Internode length variation along shoot reflects changing growth conditions and resource availability, with basal internodes typically shorter reflecting slower early growth, middle internodes longest corresponding to peak elongation phase, and apical internodes progressively shorter as growth declines toward cessation. ||Mechanical properties develop progressively during maturation with young expanding internodes showing low tensile strength and flexibility from thin primary walls, transitioning to rigid strong structure as secondary walls develop and lignification proceeds providing self-supporting shoot architecture. ||Metabolic activity varies dramatically along developmental gradient with high respiration in expanding internodes supporting growth at 10-15 fold mature tissue rates, declining in maturing regions to maintenance levels, with photosynthetic activity in green cortex contributing modestly to carbon balance. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin from apex promoting elongation and coordinating vascular differentiation in acropetal pattern, gibberellins supporting cell expansion particularly affecting internode length, cytokinins from roots promoting cell division in intercalary meristems, and ethylene potentially affecting lignification and maturation processes. ||Temperature strongly affects internode development rate with elongation approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C optimal range, influencing both cell division rates in meristems and expansion rates in elongation zones. ||Light quality affects internode elongation through phytochrome-mediated responses with red: far-red ratio influencing length, with shade promoting elongated internodes through etiolation response seeking improved light exposure while high light supports shorter stouter internodes with enhanced photosynthetic capacity in cortex. ||Water availability critically affects internode elongation through direct effects on cell turgor driving expansion and indirect effects on photosynthesis providing assimilates, with water stress rapidly arresting elongation and can permanently limit internode length affecting final shoot architecture. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects development through effects on protein synthesis supporting growth and photosynthesis, with adequate nutrition supporting maximum internode production and elongation while deficiency reduces both number and length limiting final shoot size. ||The process shows four distinguishable phases based on developmental progression, advancing from internode formation at apex through sequential formation of multiple internodes, elongation creating shoot length, and maturation establishing permanent structure. ||Cultivar variation appears in internode number produced per season, length characteristics affecting shoot architecture with some varieties producing numerous short internodes creating compact structure while others produce fewer longer internodes creating open architecture, and lignification timing affecting shoot mechanical properties. ||Regional timing shows internode development active throughout growing season from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with duration corresponding to shoot growth period. ||Viticultural management considerations include understanding internode development patterns informing shoot positioning and training operations, recognizing that internode length reflects growth conditions providing diagnostic information about vine status, managing factors affecting elongation to achieve desired canopy architecture, timing mechanical operations considering maturation state avoiding damage to unlignified tissues, and evaluating final internode patterns assessing seasonal growth outcomes and planning subsequent season management. ||Excessive internode elongation particularly in shade creates weak shoots with poor lignification susceptible to damage, while insufficient development limits photosynthetic capacity through reduced canopy size. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating internode length including hormonal and environmental controls, evaluating genetic variation in internode characteristics affecting architecture and training requirements, quantifying developmental timing and progression patterns informing growth models, assessing environmental and management effects on development affecting final shoot structure, and documenting anatomical and structural development supporting understanding of woody tissue formation in perennial plants.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:narrowMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0007091 ## SE.01 one node or internode visible stage | 0.75" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 205-235 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 128-152 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "First_Internode_Formation": {
  "definition": "A First_Internode_Formation is an Internode_Development comprising the formation of the stem segment between cotyledonary node and first true leaf node.",
  "alternative_term": "basal internode formation | first stem segment | initial internode development | primary internode |+ erstes Internodium | basale Internodienbildung | primäres Stängelglied | Grundinternodium",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows first internode formation from late April to mid-May at BBCH 09-11 over 12-14 days, developing internode of 18-25 mm length between cotyledonary node and first true leaf, with elongation rate of 1.2-2.0 mm per day under cool maritime climate conditions of 13-17°C mean temperature, adequate spring moisture, and complete dependence on stored carbohydrate reserves typical of this early-bursting moderate-vigor cultivar",
  "editor_note": "First_Internode_Formation is first of four Internode_Development subphases, distinguished by representing initial axis segment following bud burst. ||Shorter than subsequent internodes reflecting limited early resource availability. ||Transitions to Sequential_Internode_Formation as additional internodes develop. ||Critical for establishing stable shoot base. ||Timing coordinated with First_Leaf_Unfolding processes. || This developmental stage occurs during late April to May in temperate regions corresponding to BBCH 09-11 as first leaves unfold, with first internode initiating at shoot apex immediately behind apical meristem once first leaf primordium establishes nodal position defining proximal boundary. ||First internode formation proceeds through intercalary meristem establishment in axis tissue between cotyledonary position and first leaf attachment point, with meristematic cells undergoing divisions adding cells to developing internode segment over 7-14 days until cell production phase completes. ||Cell division in first internode intercalary meristem produces cells through organized divisions in longitudinal files, with division rates initially high at 20-24 hour cycles declining as meristem activity transitions from proliferation to expansion, typically producing 500-2000 cells along internode length depending on cultivar and final dimensions. ||The developing first internode shows procambial strand differentiation establishing vascular connection between permanent structures and developing shoot, with xylem vessels beginning to differentiate providing water transport capacity and phloem sieve elements forming enabling assimilate movement both upward from reserves and eventually downward from photosynthesizing leaves. ||Elongation of first internode begins while cell division continues, with cells in central zones initiating expansion through water uptake and wall loosening while marginal zones near nodes continue divisions, creating developmental gradient along internode length. ||First internode elongation typically produces final length of 15-35 mm substantially shorter than subsequent internodes, reflecting limited resource availability during early shoot development when photosynthetic capacity is minimal and growth depends entirely on stored reserves. ||The first internode shows characteristic anatomical structure including epidermis with developing cuticle providing protection, cortex with chloroplast-containing parenchyma contributing photosynthetic function, vascular bundles arranged in ring pattern characteristic of dicot stems, and central pith providing structural support and potential storage function. ||Mechanical properties of first internode develop progressively from soft herbaceous tissue during expansion to increasing rigidity as primary walls thicken and lignification initiates earlier than more apical internodes, providing stable base for developing shoot. ||Vascular connection through first internode is critical for shoot establishment, with xylem capacity of 0.5-1.5 mg per second adequate for supporting first leaf transpiration and growth water requirements, and phloem enabling initial upward movement of stored reserves and later bidirectional transport as photosynthesis initiates. ||Metabolic activity in developing first internode remains high with respiration 10-15 fold above mature tissue levels supporting growth processes, consuming stored carbohydrates transported through developing phloem until first leaf photosynthetic production begins supplementing energy supply. ||Cortical chloroplasts in first internode contribute modestly to carbon fixation once tissue is exposed to light, with stem photosynthesis potentially contributing 5-10% total shoot carbon gain though respiration in growing tissues typically exceeds local photosynthetic production. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin from shoot apex promoting elongation and coordinating acropetal vascular differentiation pattern, gibberellins supporting cell expansion influencing final internode length, and cytokinins from roots promoting cell division in intercalary meristem. ||Temperature affects first internode development rate with elongation approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 12-25°C, influencing both cell production duration in meristem and subsequent expansion rate and duration. ||Light intensity and quality begin affecting development once internode emerges from bud scales, with high light promoting chloroplast development in cortex and potentially affecting elongation through photomorphogenic responses, while shade might promote slight elongation through etiolation response. ||Water availability must be adequate to support turgor maintaining cell expansion, with water stress during first internode development potentially permanently limiting length affecting subsequent shoot architecture through reduced basal internode stability. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects development through effects on protein synthesis supporting cell division and expansion, with adequate nutrition supporting normal development while deficiency can reduce cell production and expansion limiting internode formation. ||The process typically requires 10-16 days from initiation to completion of elongation under favorable spring conditions, with cool temperatures or resource limitations extending duration. ||Cultivar variation appears in first internode length ranging from 12-20 mm in compact varieties to 25-40 mm in vigorous types, affecting basal shoot architecture and mechanical stability. ||Regional timing shows first internode formation occurring late April to early May in warm climates, May in temperate regions, and late May to early June in cool areas, following initial leaf unfolding and during continued bud burst progression. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing structural foundation for shoot development with adequate first internode length providing mechanical stability for shoot positioning operations, while insufficient development may create weak basal region susceptible to breakage during training. ||Damage to first internode during formation from mechanical injury, pests, or diseases can compromise shoot stability and vascular function affecting entire shoot development. ||Research applications include analyzing earliest stages of vegetative axis development documenting transition from embryonic to adult structure, evaluating cellular and molecular mechanisms of internode initiation and elongation, quantifying vascular differentiation patterns establishing shoot hydraulic architecture, and assessing environmental effects on early development affecting subsequent shoot growth patterns.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## first internode formation as ordinal-position-specific phenological event; no equivalent in PO/GO at this granularity." ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 205-215 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 128-138 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Sequential_Internode_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Sequential_Internode_Formation is an Internode_Development comprising the continuous initiation of successive stem segments at the shoot apex through cell division at apical meristematic regions.",
  "alternative_term": "continuous internode formation | progressive internode development | successive stem segment formation |+ fortlaufende Internodienbildung | sukzessive Stängelgliedentwicklung | progressive Internodienentwicklung | kontinuierliche Segmentbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows sequential internode formation from early May through late July at BBCH 11-38 over 12-14 weeks, initiating new internodes every 2-3 days during peak June growth and every 3-5 days during July decline, producing 16-20 total internodes creating final shoot length of 2200-2800 mm under warm climate conditions of 18-30°C temperature range, adequate irrigation, and moderate-high fertility typical of this vigorous late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Sequential_Internode_Formation is second of four Internode_Development subphases, distinguished by continuous production of successive internodes throughout growth period. ||Encompasses entire formation sequence from first through final internode. ||Transitions focus to Internode_Elongation and Internode_Maturation as individual segments progress through development. ||Represents fundamental axis segmentation process determining final shoot structure. || This fundamental developmental process occurs throughout active shoot growth from early May through July-August in temperate regions corresponding to BBCH 11-38, with new internodes initiating at shoot apex every 2-3 days during peak growth producing total of 12-20 internodes per shoot over 8-16 week growing period. ||Sequential formation proceeds through continuous apical meristem activity producing new leaf primordia in regular phyllotactic pattern, with each successive leaf primordium emergence defining nodal position and simultaneously establishing boundaries for new internode segment between successive nodes. ||Intercalary meristem initiation occurs in axis tissue immediately behind each developing node, with meristematic cells establishing in zone that will form internode through activation of cell division capacity and organization into longitudinal files characteristic of intercalary meristem structure. ||Cell division in each successive intercalary meristem produces cells contributing to internode length, with division phase typically lasting 10-20 days adding cells through organized divisions creating longitudinal cell files, then transitioning to expansion phase where cell production ceases but cells undergo dramatic elongation. ||The shoot apex maintains production of new internodes through sustained apical meristem activity, with meristem structure showing organized tunica-corpus arrangement producing organs in regular pattern, initiating new leaf primordia and associated internode segments every 2-3 days during active growth declining to 3-5 day intervals as growth slows. ||Sequential formation creates characteristic developmental gradient along shoot with basal internodes in maturation phase undergoing lignification, middle internodes in elongation phase actively expanding, and apical internodes in formation phase with active intercalary meristems producing cells. ||Internode number produced per shoot varies substantially with cultivar vigor and growing conditions, ranging from 10-14 internodes in less vigorous cultivars or limited conditions to 16-22 internodes in vigorous cultivars with optimal conditions and extended growing period. ||Timing between successive internode initiations reflects shoot growth rate and apical meristem activity level, with most rapid initiation of 2-day intervals during peak exponential growth phase, extending to 3-4 day intervals during declining growth, and ceasing when apical meristem activity terminates with growth cessation. ||Vascular differentiation proceeds acropetally through sequentially forming internodes, with procambial strands differentiating into functional xylem and phloem in coordinated pattern connecting each new segment into continuous vascular system extending from permanent structures through developing shoot to apex. ||The sequential formation process shows coordination with other developmental processes including leaf emergence with each internode associated with specific leaf at proximal node, tendril or inflorescence development at nodes following cultivar-specific patterns, and overall shoot elongation resulting from summed contributions of sequentially forming and elongating internodes. ||Internode length variation among sequentially formed segments reflects changing resource availability and growth conditions during formation and elongation phases, with early internodes typically shorter from limited early resources, middle internodes longest corresponding to peak growth conditions, and late internodes shorter as growth declines and resources become limiting. ||Cell number produced in intercalary meristems varies among sequential internodes correlating with final length, with shorter internodes containing fewer cells from reduced division duration or rate while longer internodes contain more cells from extended or accelerated division phase. ||Metabolic activity in sequentially forming internodes shows high levels in active meristems and early elongation zones with respiration supporting cell production and expansion, declining as internodes mature and transition from growth to maintenance metabolism. ||Hormonal regulation coordinating sequential formation involves auxin from apical meristem maintaining overall shoot growth and coordinating vascular differentiation pattern, gibberellins affecting internode elongation with effects varying among sequential positions, and cytokinins promoting cell division in intercalary meristems with availability potentially varying through season. ||Temperature affects sequential formation rate through effects on apical meristem activity determining initiation frequency and on cell division rates in intercalary meristems affecting cell production, with optimal 22-28°C supporting maximum formation rate declining at lower or higher temperatures. ||Light intensity and quality affect formation through effects on photosynthetic production providing resources for growth and through photomorphogenic responses potentially affecting internode length characteristics, with shade promoting elongated internodes while high light supports stouter structure. ||Water availability affects sequential formation through effects on turgor maintaining meristem activity and cell expansion, with water stress potentially reducing formation rate through slowed apical meristem activity and limiting internode elongation affecting final dimensions. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects formation rate and internode development through effects on protein synthesis supporting cell division and growth, with adequate nutrition supporting maximum formation rate and normal development while deficiency reduces rate and limits development. ||The process continues throughout shoot growth period showing characteristic temporal pattern of increasing formation rate during early accelerating growth, maximum rate during peak growth, and declining rate during decelerating growth before cessation. ||Cultivar variation appears in total internode number produced per season reflecting inherent differences in growth duration and vigor, spatial pattern of internode lengths along shoot affecting architecture, and timing of formation cessation relative to fruit development stages. ||Regional timing shows sequential formation active from May through July-August in warm climates, May through August-September in temperate regions, and June through September in cool areas, with duration corresponding to total shoot growth period. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing that internode formation pattern reflects growth progression providing diagnostic information about vine status and growing conditions, understanding that management affecting shoot growth including irrigation and nutrition influences formation patterns determining final canopy architecture, and timing canopy management operations considering developmental state of forming internodes. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms coordinating sequential organ formation at shoot apex, evaluating temporal patterns of formation and their regulation by internal and environmental factors, quantifying developmental gradients along shoot axis documenting simultaneous processes at different stages, and assessing genetic variation in formation patterns affecting shoot architecture and growth characteristics.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 215-230 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 138-150 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Internode_Elongation": {
  "definition": "An Internode_Elongation is an Internode_Development comprising the length increase of stem segments through cell expansion following cell division.",
  "alternative_term": "stem extension | internode stretching | axis elongation | stem segment expansion |+ Internodienstreckung | Stängelgliedverlängerung | Achsenstreckung | Stielexpansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows internode elongation throughout May-July at BBCH 15-38, with individual internodes requiring 2-3 weeks to complete elongation from 5-10 mm initial length to final dimensions ranging 35-50 mm basally, 75-105 mm in middle positions during peak June growth, and 40-65 mm apically, under oceanic climate conditions of 16-26°C temperature range, variable precipitation with supplemental irrigation, and moderate fertility typical of this moderately vigorous mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Internode_Elongation is third of four Internode_Development subphases, distinguished by cell expansion phase following cell division creating final internode length. ||Occurs in each internode after Sequential_Internode_Formation cell production phase. ||Transitions to Internode_Maturation as expansion completes and lignification initiates. ||Primary determinant of final shoot length and architecture. ||Highly responsive to environmental conditions during expansion period. || This fundamental developmental process occurs in each internode following formation with cell division phase, typically spanning 2-4 weeks per internode from initiation of elongation to completion, with multiple internodes elongating simultaneously creating developmental gradient along shoot from actively elongating subapical zones to recently completed basal regions. ||Elongation proceeds through cell expansion in intercalary zones between nodes where cells increase length dramatically through turgor-driven wall extension, with cells expanding from meristematic dimensions of 10-20 micrometers to final lengths of 150-500 micrometers representing 10-50 fold increase in length. ||Cell expansion involves water uptake increasing cell volume creating turgor pressure of 0.4-0.8 MPa driving cell wall extension, wall loosening through expansin proteins and other wall-modifying enzymes allowing plastic deformation under pressure, and wall synthesis adding new material to maintain structural integrity during expansion. ||The elongation zone in each internode extends throughout internode length during early expansion phase, becoming progressively restricted to central region as cells near nodes complete expansion earlier than central cells, creating elongation pattern proceeding from ends toward middle then completing throughout. ||Elongation rate varies substantially among internodes along shoot reflecting changing resource availability and growth conditions, with basal internodes showing modest rates of 1-2 mm per day during early slow shoot growth, middle internodes showing maximum rates of 4-8 mm per day during peak growth, and apical internodes showing declining rates of 2-4 mm per day as growth decelerates. ||Final internode length results from combined effects of cell number produced during division phase and extent of cell elongation during expansion phase, with variation in both factors contributing to characteristic internode length pattern along shoot. ||Internode position affects final length with typical pattern showing basal internodes 25-45 mm from limited early resources, middle internodes 70-120 mm corresponding to peak conditions, and apical internodes 30-60 mm from declining late-season resources and accelerated maturation. ||Vascular tissues continue differentiating during elongation with procambial cells in longitudinal strands undergoing coordinated divisions and differentiation into functional xylem vessels with secondary wall thickening and lignification, and phloem sieve elements with specialized wall structures enabling translocation function. ||Water transport capacity through elongating internodes increases progressively as vessel diameter and number increase, with functional xylem maintaining adequate capacity for supporting transpiration from developing leaves and water requirements for continued elongation in more apical zones. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated during elongation with respiration rates 8-15 fold above mature levels providing energy for active transport supporting expansion, wall synthesis, and protein production, consuming carbohydrates from photosynthesis in mature leaves and stored reserves mobilized from permanent structures. ||Cell wall composition changes during elongation from thin primary walls rich in pectin allowing expansion to thickening walls with increased cellulose and hemicellulose providing progressive structural rigidity, with wall modification processes regulated by pH changes, enzyme activities, and hormonal signals coordinating expansion with wall strengthening. ||Protein synthesis operates at high rates during elongation producing structural proteins for expanding cell walls and membranes, enzymes including wall-modifying proteins enabling expansion, and beginning accumulation of photosynthetic proteins if cortex cells contain developing chloroplasts. ||Hormonal regulation centrally involves auxin from shoot apex promoting elongation through effects on cell wall extensibility and coordinating elongation pattern along shoot, gibberellins strongly affecting elongation with higher concentrations promoting increased cell expansion and longer final internode length, brassinosteroids enhancing cell expansion and vascular differentiation, and ethylene potentially limiting elongation as maturation processes initiate. ||Temperature strongly affects elongation rate with approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C optimal range, influencing both rate of individual cell expansion and duration of elongation period before maturation processes dominate. ||Light quality affects elongation through phytochrome-mediated responses to red: far-red ratio, with shade conditions promoting enhanced elongation through etiolation response creating longer thinner internodes seeking improved light exposure, while high light conditions support normal to reduced elongation with stouter structure. ||Water availability critically affects elongation through direct effects on cell turgor driving expansion, with adequate moisture essential for maintaining pressure supporting wall extension, while water stress rapidly arrests elongation through turgor loss and can permanently limit final length even after stress relief. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects elongation through effects on protein synthesis supporting wall expansion and enzyme production, with adequate nutrition supporting maximum elongation achieving genetic potential while deficiency reduces expansion rate and limits final dimensions. ||The process shows variation in timing and rate among internodes creating characteristic pattern along shoot, with basal internodes completing elongation early in season during slow growth phase, middle internodes elongating during peak growth achieving maximum length, and apical internodes elongating during declining growth showing progressive length reduction. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum internode elongation rate and final lengths achieved, with vigorous cultivars showing rapid elongation to long dimensions 100-150 mm while less vigorous types show moderate elongation to shorter lengths 40-80 mm, affecting overall shoot architecture and training requirements. ||Regional timing shows internode elongation occurring throughout shoot growth period from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with individual internodes requiring 2-4 weeks for complete elongation depending on conditions and position. ||Viticultural management considerations include understanding that internode elongation pattern reflects growth conditions with length providing diagnostic information about resource availability during formation period, managing factors affecting elongation including water, nutrition, and light to achieve desired canopy architecture, recognizing that excessive elongation from shade or over-fertilization creates weak shoots requiring additional support, and timing canopy operations considering elongation state of target internodes. ||Research applications include analyzing cellular and molecular mechanisms of cell expansion including wall modification and hormonal regulation, quantifying environmental and genetic factors affecting elongation rates and final dimensions, evaluating relationships between elongation patterns and overall shoot growth characteristics, modeling elongation processes for predicting shoot development under varying conditions, and assessing implications of internode length variation for mechanical properties and canopy function.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 220-235 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 140-152 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Internode_Maturation": {
  "definition": "An Internode_Maturation is an Internode_Development comprising the structural conversion of stem segments to woody tissue through lignification and secondary wall deposition.",
  "alternative_term": "stem lignification | internode ripening | shoot maturation | wood formation |+ Internodienreifung | Stängelverholzung | Triebausreifung | Holzbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Riesling in Mosel shows internode maturation from June through September at BBCH 31-43, with basal internodes initiating lignification in early June completing by late July, middle internodes maturing July-August, and apical internodes beginning maturation late August potentially incomplete by dormancy, accumulating starch reserves reaching 18-22% dry weight in mature tissues under cool climate conditions of 15-22°C temperature range, adequate late moisture, and declining nitrogen availability typical of this moderate-vigor late-season cultivar requiring thorough maturation for winter survival",
  "editor_note": "Internode_Maturation is fourth and final Internode_Development subphase, distinguished by lignification and reserve accumulation transforming herbaceous growth to woody permanent structure. ||Follows Internode_Elongation completion. ||Progresses acropetally from base to apex during late season. ||Critical for winter survival and subsequent season resource availability. ||Incomplete maturation creates hardiness and vigor concerns. || This fundamental developmental process begins in basal internodes during active shoot growth and progresses acropetally following elongation completion, typically spanning 4-8 weeks per internode from maturation initiation to full lignification, with mature lignified basal regions coexisting with elongating middle zones and forming apical sections creating developmental gradient along shoot. ||Maturation initiation follows completion of elongation when cells achieve final dimensions and growth transitions from expansion to differentiation and secondary wall synthesis, with timing varying along shoot from early June for basal internodes to August for apical sections in temperate regions. ||Lignification represents central maturation process involving secondary wall deposition with lignin incorporation creating rigid woody structure, proceeding through increased cellulose and hemicellulose synthesis forming secondary wall framework, lignin monomer synthesis and polymerization creating hydrophobic matrix binding wall polysaccharides, and progressive wall thickening particularly in vascular tissues and structural support cells. ||Secondary xylem development accompanies maturation with vascular cambium initiating activity between primary xylem and phloem, producing additional xylem elements internally increasing water transport capacity and phloem elements externally enhancing assimilate translocation, establishing secondary growth pattern that continues in subsequent seasons in older permanent structures. ||Periderm formation begins in basal internodes replacing epidermis as protective surface, with cork cambium initiating in subepidermal layers producing cork cells externally providing protection against water loss and pathogen entry, and phelloderm cells internally contributing to cortex structure, creating characteristic brown bark appearance of mature stems. ||Metabolic changes during maturation include declining respiration from growth levels toward maintenance rates 2-4 fold above completely dormant tissue, shifting protein synthesis from growth-related proteins to storage and defense proteins accumulating in parenchyma cells, and beginning carbohydrate accumulation with starch synthesis converting excess photosynthate to storage form in cortex and pith parenchyma. ||Reserve accumulation intensifies during late maturation as shoot growth ceases and photosynthate allocation shifts from growth to storage, with starch concentrations in mature internodes increasing from negligible during active growth to 15-25% dry weight by dormancy entry, providing crucial carbon reserves for subsequent season bud burst and early growth. ||Mechanical properties change dramatically during maturation from flexible herbaceous tissue in elongating internodes with tensile strength 5-15 MPa to rigid woody structure in mature lignified internodes with strength 40-80 MPa, providing self-supporting architecture and resistance to wind loading and mechanical damage. ||Cell wall composition shifts during maturation from primary walls dominated by pectin and hemicellulose allowing expansion to mature walls with high cellulose content 40-50% providing tensile strength, lignin content 15-25% providing compressive strength and hydrophobicity, and modified pectin providing cross-linking and matrix properties. ||Vascular tissue maturation includes secondary wall thickening and lignification in xylem vessels creating functional water transport elements persisting into subsequent seasons, sieve element and companion cell differentiation in phloem establishing long-distance assimilate transport capacity, and fiber development in vascular bundles providing mechanical support. ||Water content declines during maturation from 75-85% fresh weight in expanding tissues to 55-65% in mature lignified internodes, reflecting reduced metabolic activity, increased wall material deposition, and beginning preparation for winter dormancy in perennial structures. ||Photosynthetic activity in cortex chloroplasts declines during maturation as lignification and periderm formation reduce light penetration and gas exchange capacity, with stem photosynthesis contribution to carbon balance declining from modest levels during active growth to negligible in fully mature internodes. ||Hormonal regulation of maturation involves declining auxin and gibberellin from reduced apical production and transport affecting growth promotion, increasing abscisic acid promoting maturation processes and stress tolerance, ethylene potentially involved in lignification and senescence processes, and jasmonates possibly affecting secondary metabolism and defense compound synthesis. ||Temperature affects maturation rate with warm conditions promoting rapid lignification progression while cool conditions slow processes, though maturation proceeds across wide temperature range unlike growth which shows narrower optimal conditions. ||Light intensity affects maturation through effects on photosynthetic carbon availability for reserve accumulation and possible direct effects on lignification through photomorphogenic responses, with high light supporting rapid thorough maturation while shade may result in incomplete lignification creating weaker shoot structure. ||Water availability affects maturation timing and completeness with moderate water stress potentially promoting earlier maturation initiation and enhanced reserve accumulation, while severe stress may cause premature incomplete maturation affecting tissue quality and reserve storage. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects maturation with adequate but not excessive nitrogen supporting normal maturation and good reserve accumulation, while nitrogen excess may delay maturation prolonging herbaceous state and reducing lignification, and deficiency may cause premature maturation limiting final shoot development and reserve accumulation. ||The process shows characteristic progression along shoot from base to apex with basal internodes completing maturation by mid-summer, middle internodes maturing during late summer, and apical internodes potentially incomplete maturation by growth cessation particularly in vigorous shoots or late-season growth. ||Cultivar variation appears in maturation timing and completeness with some varieties showing early thorough maturation creating well-lignified shoots while others maintain herbaceous state longer potentially creating winter hardiness concerns in cold regions. ||Regional timing shows maturation beginning June-July in warm climates, July-August in temperate regions, and August-September in cool areas for basal internodes, with progression continuing through late summer and early autumn approaching dormancy entry. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate but not excessive late-season growth allowing proper maturation before dormancy, managing water and nitrogen avoiding excessive late vegetative growth interfering with maturation, assessing maturation adequacy for winter survival particularly in cold regions where incomplete lignification creates freeze damage risk, and recognizing that good maturation with substantial reserve accumulation benefits subsequent season bud break and early growth. ||Incomplete maturation from excessive late growth or inadequate resources creates winter injury risk and reduces reserve availability for next season. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating lignification and secondary wall formation, quantifying reserve accumulation patterns and their regulation by source-sink dynamics, evaluating environmental and management effects on maturation affecting shoot quality and perennial structure development, assessing relationships between maturation and cold hardiness in grapevine adaptation to cold climates, and documenting transition from annual herbaceous shoot to perennial woody structure in woody plant development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 248-265 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 165-178 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Leaf_Emergence": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Emergence is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the developmental progression of leaf primordia from apical initiation to expanded functional photosynthetic organ.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf development | leaf formation | foliar development | leaf ontogeny |+ Blattentwicklung | Blattbildung | Laubentwicklung | Blattontogenese",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows leaf emergence from May through July at BBCH 11-38 over 12-14 weeks, producing 15-18 leaves ranging from 80-120 mm dimensions with moderate lobing and sparse trichomes, achieving photosynthetic capacity of 12-16 micromoles CO2 per square meter per second at maturity, under Mediterranean climate conditions of 18-28°C temperature range, limited summer precipitation requiring irrigation, high solar radiation, and moderate fertility typical of this vigorous mid-to-late season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Emergence represents fundamental organ development process within Shoot_Growth establishing photosynthetic capacity. ||Occurs coordinately with Shoot_Elongation and Internode_Development but focuses on leaf organ formation and function. ||Subdivided into Leaf_Primordium_Initiation, Sequential_Leaf_Emergence, Leaf_Primordium_Expansion, and Leaf_Maturation based on developmental progression. ||Distinguished from broader shoot growth processes by focus on individual leaf development. ||Critical process determining canopy photosynthetic capacity and productivity. || This essential developmental process occurs continuously during shoot growth from early elongation through growth cessation, typically producing 12-20 leaves per shoot over 8-16 week period depending on vigor and conditions. ||Leaf emergence encompasses primordium initiation at shoot apical meristem, sequential emergence of multiple leaves in regular phyllotactic pattern, expansion from compressed primordia to functional photosynthetic structures, and maturation establishing full photosynthetic capacity and structural characteristics. ||The process begins with primordium initiation at shoot apex where apical meristem produces new leaf primordia every 2-3 days during active growth in alternating positions approximately 180 degrees around shoot axis, with each primordium arising as localized cell proliferation on meristem flank creating multicellular bulge that will develop into complete leaf structure. ||Primordium development proceeds through coordinated cell division in marginal meristems at leaf edges and plate meristem throughout blade establishing leaf form, differentiation of adaxial upper and abaxial lower surfaces with distinct cellular characteristics, and initiation of procambial strands that will develop into leaf venation system. ||Leaf expansion follows primordium formation with dramatic size increase from 1-2 mm primordia to 50-150 mm mature leaves through continued cell division producing new cells particularly at margins and continued cell expansion throughout blade increasing individual cell volumes 50-100 fold. ||Photosynthetic capacity develops progressively during expansion as chloroplasts differentiate in mesophyll cells, chlorophyll accumulates creating characteristic green coloration, thylakoid membranes organize for light capture, and Calvin cycle enzymes accumulate enabling carbon fixation. ||Mature leaves achieve photosynthetic rates of 10-20 micromoles CO2 per square meter per second at light saturation, with whole-canopy photosynthesis integrated across leaves at various developmental stages providing assimilates for shoot growth, fruit development, and reserve accumulation. ||Leaf morphology development establishes characteristic grapevine palmate form with major lobes and sinuses, venation pattern with primary veins from petiole attachment and reticulated secondary and tertiary vein network, trichome distribution varying among cultivars from glabrous to densely tomentose, and stomatal distribution with higher density on abaxial surface enabling gas exchange for photosynthesis and transpiration. ||Leaf lifespan from emergence to senescence typically spans 12-20 weeks depending on position and environmental conditions, with basal leaves emerging early in season persisting through summer until senescence in autumn, while apical leaves emerging late in season may have abbreviated lifespan before dormancy entry. ||Carbon balance transitions during leaf development from net carbon consumer during early expansion requiring 10-15 days to reach carbon neutrality where photosynthesis equals respiration, to net carbon producer contributing excess assimilate to shoot growth and other sinks, with mature leaves potentially producing 5-10 times their own carbon requirements enabling support of other organs. ||Water relationships evolve during emergence with developing leaves showing high water content 80-85% fresh weight and high transpiration rates per unit area relative to mature leaves, declining to 70-75% water content in mature leaves with regulated transpiration through stomatal control responding to environmental conditions and plant water status. ||Nutrient requirements particularly nitrogen remain high in emerging leaves supporting protein synthesis for both structural and photosynthetic components, with nitrogen concentration 3-5% dry weight in young leaves declining to 2-3% in mature leaves as structural carbohydrates accumulate diluting protein nitrogen. ||Vascular development establishes connection between leaf and shoot axis with xylem providing water delivery from roots through stem to transpiring leaf surfaces, and phloem initially importing assimilates to support leaf growth then transitioning to export as photosynthetic capacity develops and production exceeds local requirements. ||Hormonal regulation coordinates leaf emergence with auxin from shoot apex affecting primordium positioning and expansion polarity, cytokinins promoting cell division in primordia and expanding leaves, gibberellins affecting cell expansion and final leaf size, and abscisic acid potentially involved in maturation and stress responses. ||Temperature strongly affects emergence rate with primordium initiation frequency, expansion rate, and maturation all approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C optimal range, influencing total leaf number produced per season and final leaf sizes achieved. ||Light intensity affects emergence through photosynthetic capacity development with high light promoting rapid chloroplast maturation and maximum photosynthetic capacity, and through morphological effects on leaf size, thickness, and structure with high light producing smaller thicker leaves with higher photosynthetic capacity per unit area compared to shade leaves. ||Water availability affects emergence rate and final leaf characteristics with adequate moisture supporting rapid expansion to large dimensions and full photosynthetic development, while water stress reduces expansion rate, limits final size, and may reduce photosynthetic capacity affecting canopy productivity. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects emergence rate and photosynthetic capacity development with adequate nutrition supporting rapid leaf production and expansion with high photosynthetic potential, while deficiency reduces emergence rate, limits final sizes, and reduces photosynthetic capacity through protein synthesis limitation. ||The process shows four distinguishable phases based on developmental progression, advancing from primordium initiation at apex through sequential emergence of multiple leaves, expansion creating functional leaf area, and maturation establishing full photosynthetic capacity and structural characteristics. ||Cultivar variation appears in total leaf number produced per season, final leaf dimensions ranging from small 50-80 mm to large 150-200 mm, leaf shape including lobe number and sinus depth, trichome density affecting leaf appearance and microclimate, and photosynthetic characteristics affecting productivity. ||Regional timing shows leaf emergence active throughout shoot growth from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with individual leaves requiring 2-4 weeks from separation to functional maturity. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate water and nutrient availability during leaf emergence supporting canopy development, managing light environment optimizing leaf photosynthetic capacity without excessive shading, monitoring pest and disease colonization of emerging leaves, implementing canopy management optimizing leaf exposure and air movement, and assessing canopy development adequacy for fruit maturation requirements. ||Damage to emerging leaves from pests, diseases, hail, or other factors reduces photosynthetic capacity potentially severely limiting productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms coordinating leaf initiation, expansion, and photosynthetic development, quantifying environmental effects on leaf development affecting canopy characteristics and photosynthetic capacity, evaluating genetic variation in leaf morphology and function affecting vineyard productivity, modeling leaf emergence and canopy development for management decision support, and assessing climate change impacts on leaf development patterns across viticultural regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0001050 ## leaf development stage | 0.75" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 235-265 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 152-178 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Leaf_Primordium_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Primordium_Initiation is a Leaf_Emergence comprising the production of new leaf primordia at the shoot apical meristem through localized cell proliferation.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf initiation | primordium formation | leaf organogenesis | foliar primordium development |+ Blattprimordienbildung | Blattanlagebildung | Blattinitiierung | Blattorganogenese",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows leaf primordium initiation from May through July at BBCH 11-35 over 10-12 weeks, initiating new primordia every 2-3 days during June peak growth and every 3-4 days during July decline, producing total of 14-17 primordia establishing maximum leaf number potential under cool climate conditions of 16-24°C temperature range, adequate moisture, and moderate fertility typical of this moderate-vigor early-to-mid season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Primordium_Initiation is first of four Leaf_Emergence subphases, distinguished by organogenesis at apical meristem establishing new leaf structures. ||Represents earliest stage of leaf development occurring at microscopic scale at shoot apex. ||Transitions to Sequential_Leaf_Emergence as primordia continue developing and separating from axis. ||Determines maximum leaf number potential for shoot. ||Critical developmental process establishing canopy capacity. || This essential developmental process occurs continuously at shoot apex during active growth from early shoot elongation through growth cessation, with new primordia initiating every 2-3 days during peak growth producing total of 12-20 primordia per shoot over 8-16 week period depending on cultivar vigor and environmental conditions. ||Primordium initiation begins with localized increase in cell division activity on apical meristem flank at position determined by phyllotactic patterning, with cells in initiation zone undergoing accelerated divisions creating multicellular bulge protruding from meristem surface marking first visible stage of leaf formation. ||The initiation site occurs in regular pattern around shoot axis typically alternating approximately 180 degrees between successive primordia creating characteristic distichous leaf arrangement of grapevine, with positioning controlled by auxin concentration patterns and mechanical forces in meristem dome influencing where new primordia can form. ||Primordial cells undergo oriented divisions establishing three-dimensional structure with adaxial-abaxial polarity defining upper and lower leaf surfaces, proximal-distal axis defining petiole-blade orientation, and medio-lateral axis defining central midrib and lateral lobes, with these fundamental polarities established early in initiation through gene expression patterns and hormonal gradients. ||Cell division patterns during initiation show activity concentrated in peripheral zones that will form marginal meristems responsible for blade expansion, and in central zones that will form plate meristem contributing cells throughout blade interior, establishing organizational framework that will guide subsequent leaf development. ||Primordium size at initiation measures approximately 50-100 micrometers diameter containing 50-200 cells, increasing to 500-1000 micrometers with several thousand cells by time primordium is clearly recognizable as leaf structure rather than simple protrusion, requiring approximately 3-5 days from first division acceleration to recognizable leaf form. ||Procambial strand initiation occurs early in primordium development establishing vascular connection between developing leaf and shoot axis, with procambial cells forming continuous strand from primordium base through shoot cortex connecting to main vascular system, providing pathway for water delivery and eventually assimilate export critical for leaf development and function. ||Gene expression patterns during initiation include activation of leaf identity genes specifying organ type and suppressing alternative developmental fates like shoot apex or floral meristem, polarity genes establishing adaxial-abaxial identity and coordinating with hormonal signals, and morphogenesis genes controlling cell division patterns and growth orientation establishing three-dimensional leaf form. ||Marginal meristem establishment represents critical initiation event with cells at primordium edges maintaining division capacity longer than internal cells, creating zones that will produce majority of blade area through sustained cell production at margins extending into lobes characteristic of palmate grapevine leaf form. ||Early primordium development shows differentiation between petiole and blade regions with cells near attachment point developing into petiole with vascular strand and supportive tissue, while distal cells form blade with characteristic morphology including lobes, sinuses, and expanded photosynthetic surface. ||Hormonal regulation of initiation involves auxin concentration patterns at meristem apex with local auxin maxima marking sites where primordia will initiate and auxin transport directing polarity establishment, cytokinins from roots promoting cell division supporting primordium growth, and brassinosteroids potentially affecting primordium outgrowth and expansion. ||Timing between successive primordium initiations reflects shoot growth rate and apical meristem activity, with most rapid initiation of 2-day intervals during peak exponential growth when apical meristem operates at maximum capacity, extending to 3-4 day intervals during declining growth as meristem activity reduces, and ceasing when apical growth terminates. ||Temperature affects initiation frequency through effects on meristem cell division rates, with optimal 22-28°C supporting maximum initiation frequency approximately doubling per 10°C increase within physiological range, influencing total primordium number produced per season determining maximum potential leaf number. ||Light intensity and quality affect apical meristem activity influencing initiation through effects on photosynthetic production providing resources for growth and possible photomorphogenic responses affecting meristem developmental state, though initiation occurs across wide light range unlike expansion which shows strong light dependency. ||Water availability affects initiation through effects on cell division requiring adequate turgor and metabolic function, with severe water stress potentially reducing initiation frequency though moderate stress has minimal effect as meristem maintains preferential resource allocation. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects initiation through effects on protein synthesis supporting cell division and growth, with adequate nutrition supporting maximum initiation frequency while severe deficiency may reduce frequency limiting final leaf number potential. ||The process continues throughout shoot growth showing characteristic temporal pattern of increasing initiation frequency during accelerating growth, maximum frequency during peak growth producing 2-3 primordia per week, and declining frequency during decelerating growth before cessation when apical meristem activity terminates. ||Cultivar variation appears in total primordium number initiated per season reflecting differences in growth duration and apical meristem activity patterns, with vigorous long-season cultivars initiating 18-22 primordia producing potential for high leaf numbers while less vigorous or shorter-season types initiate 10-14 primordia limiting leaf number. ||Regional timing shows primordium initiation active from May through July-August in warm climates, May through August-September in temperate regions, and June through September in cool areas, corresponding to shoot growth period with initiation ceasing when growth terminates. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing maximum leaf number potential for developing shoot with actual emerged leaf number determined by primordium number initiated at apex, recognizing that environmental conditions during initiation period affect total leaf number affecting ultimate canopy size and photosynthetic capacity, and understanding that management affecting shoot growth including irrigation and nutrition influences initiation patterns determining canopy potential. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of organogenesis including gene regulatory networks controlling leaf identity and patterning, evaluating hormonal regulation of initiation timing and positioning including auxin transport and signaling, quantifying environmental effects on initiation frequency affecting final leaf number, investigating cellular mechanisms of polarity establishment and morphogenesis, and assessing evolutionary and developmental biology of leaf form in vascular plants using grapevine as model for compound leaf development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 235-242 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 152-162 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Sequential_Leaf_Emergence": {
  "definition": "A Sequential_Leaf_Emergence is a Leaf_Emergence comprising the concurrent development of multiple leaf primordia at staggered stages along the shoot axis with mature basal leaves and emerging apical primordia.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive leaf development | continuous leaf emergence | successive foliar development |+ fortlaufende Blattentwicklung | sukzessive Blattbildung | kontinuierliche Blattentfaltung | progressive Laubentwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Tempranillo in Rioja shows sequential leaf emergence from May through August at BBCH 11-38 over 14-15 weeks, with successive leaves separating at 3-4 day intervals during peak June-July growth producing total of 15-18 emerged leaves ranging from 65-90 mm basal dimensions to 95-130 mm mid-shoot maximum declining to 55-80 mm apically, under continental climate conditions of 16-28°C temperature range, moderate summer precipitation, and moderate-high fertility typical of this moderately vigorous mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Sequential_Leaf_Emergence is second of four Leaf_Emergence subphases, distinguished by continuous progression of multiple leaves through developmental stages creating gradient along shoot. ||Encompasses entire emergence sequence from initiation through separation and early expansion. ||Transitions focus to Leaf_Primordium_Expansion and Leaf_Maturation as individual leaves progress through development. ||Represents fundamental canopy development process determining photosynthetic capacity and architecture. || This fundamental process occurs throughout shoot growth period from early elongation through growth cessation, typically encompassing 12-20 leaves at various stages from microscopic primordia to fully expanded mature leaves over 8-16 week period. ||Sequential emergence proceeds through regular timing pattern with successive leaves separating from shoot axis at approximately 3-5 day intervals during active growth, reflecting both primordium initiation frequency at apex and development time required from initiation through separation, creating continuous leaf production throughout growing season. ||The developmental progression shows characteristic stages advancing along shoot axis from apical meristem producing new primordia, through subapical zones containing developing primordia attached to axis, to regions where primordia separate and begin expanding away from shoot, and finally basal zones with mature expanding to fully developed functional leaves. ||Leaf separation from shoot axis represents critical transition in emergence process occurring when primordium development reaches stage where petiole angles away from compressed position against axis and blade begins spreading perpendicular to shoot, typically requiring 10-15 days from primordium initiation to separation depending on growth rate and environmental conditions. ||Each successive leaf shows progressive size increase from small basal leaves emerging during slow early growth to largest middle leaves emerging during peak growth, then declining size in apical leaves emerging during decelerating growth, reflecting changing resource availability and growth conditions during emergence period. ||The sequential pattern establishes characteristic canopy architecture with leaves positioned in alternating pattern approximately 180 degrees around shoot axis, creating two rows of leaves along shoot when viewed from side providing good light interception while allowing air movement through canopy interior. ||Developmental timing shows coordination with internode formation with each leaf associated with specific node position, emerging at proximal end of internode that develops between current and previous leaf position, creating integrated shoot structure with consistent organ relationships. ||Photosynthetic capacity develops progressively in sequentially emerging leaves with each new leaf contributing additional area and carbon fixation capability, with shoot photosynthetic capacity increasing in stepwise manner as each leaf reaches functional status typically 10-15 days after separation. ||Carbon balance transitions in developing shoot from net consumption during early emergence when few leaves have functional photosynthetic capacity to net production once 3-5 leaves have substantially expanded and matured, with positive balance increasing as sequential emergence adds photosynthetic area through mid-season. ||Water demand increases progressively with sequential emergence as each additional leaf contributes transpiring surface area, with shoot water use rising from 30-50 mg per hour with 2-3 leaves to 400-700 mg per hour with 12-15 leaves depending on leaf sizes, environmental conditions, and stomatal conductance. ||Nutrient demand particularly nitrogen intensifies during sequential emergence period as each new leaf requires protein synthesis for structural and photosynthetic components, with nitrogen import from root uptake and possibly mobilization from older leaves supporting continued leaf production through season. ||Vascular development extends continuously through shoot connecting sequentially emerging leaves into integrated transport system, with xylem providing water delivery from roots to all transpiring leaves and phloem enabling assimilate distribution from photosynthesizing leaves to growth sinks and storage tissues. ||Leaf position along shoot affects development timing and final characteristics with basal leaves emerging earliest having longer potential lifespan but slower development during early low-resource period, middle leaves emerging during peak growth developing rapidly to large dimensions with maximum photosynthetic capacity, and apical leaves emerging latest showing accelerated development to smaller sizes before growth cessation. ||Hormonal coordination of sequential emergence involves auxin from shoot apex affecting emergence timing and development rate, cytokinins from roots promoting cell division in developing primordia, gibberellins affecting expansion rate and final leaf size, and possible abscisic acid effects during stress conditions influencing development rate and final characteristics. ||Temperature affects sequential emergence through effects on development rate with each stage from primordium initiation through separation to expansion approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C, determining both timing between successive emergences and development time for individual leaves. ||Light intensity affects development of sequentially emerging leaves with high light promoting rapid photosynthetic maturation and maximum capacity development while shade reduces photosynthetic development and may alter leaf morphology through shade avoidance responses including increased specific leaf area. ||Water availability affects sequential emergence rate and leaf development with adequate moisture supporting rapid emergence and expansion creating large well-developed leaves, while water stress slows emergence rate, reduces expansion, and limits final sizes affecting canopy development and productivity. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects emergence rate and leaf characteristics with adequate nutrition supporting maximum emergence frequency and rapid development to large dimensions with high photosynthetic potential, while deficiency reduces emergence rate and limits leaf development affecting canopy capacity. ||The process continues throughout shoot growth period showing temporal variation in emergence rate corresponding to shoot growth phases, with most rapid sequential emergence during exponential growth phase producing 2-3 leaves per week, declining during decelerating growth to 1-2 leaves per week, and ceasing when apical meristem activity terminates with growth cessation. ||Cultivar variation appears in total leaf number emerging per season ranging from 10-14 leaves in less vigorous cultivars to 16-22 leaves in highly vigorous types, timing pattern of emergence reflecting growth habit, and final leaf characteristics including size, shape, and photosynthetic capacity affecting canopy productivity. ||Regional timing shows sequential emergence active throughout shoot growth from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with emergence pattern reflecting seasonal temperature and resource availability progression. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing that sequential emergence pattern reflects shoot growth progression and environmental conditions providing diagnostic information about vine status, understanding that management affecting shoot growth including irrigation and nutrition influences emergence determining final canopy characteristics, ensuring adequate resources during emergence period supporting full canopy development, and monitoring emergence uniformity across vineyard assessing vine health and resource distribution. ||Research applications include analyzing regulation of sequential organ emergence including hormonal and developmental controls, quantifying emergence patterns and their environmental responsiveness informing growth models, evaluating canopy development dynamics integrating sequential emergence with shoot growth patterns, and assessing implications of emergence pattern for light interception, photosynthetic capacity, and vineyard productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 242-255 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 162-172 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Leaf_Primordium_Expansion": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Primordium_Expansion is a Leaf_Emergence comprising the size increase of compressed primordia to full leaf dimensions with palmate morphology through cell division and expansion.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf expansion | leaf growth | blade expansion | leaf enlargement | Blattexpansion |+ Blattwachstum | Blattvergrößerung | Blattspreitung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows leaf primordium expansion from late May through August at BBCH 15-38, with individual leaves requiring 2-3 weeks to expand from 3-5 mm separated primordia to final dimensions of 85-140 mm depending on position, achieving expansion rates of 6-10 mm per day during peak growth under temperate maritime conditions of 17-25°C temperature range, adequate moisture, high light availability, and moderate fertility typical of this vigorous mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Primordium_Expansion is third of four Leaf_Emergence subphases, distinguished by dramatic size increase from millimeter primordia to functional photosynthetic structures. ||Follows Sequential_Leaf_Emergence separation phase. ||Transitions to Leaf_Maturation as expansion completes and full photosynthetic capacity develops. ||Primary determinant of final leaf size and photosynthetic area. ||Highly responsive to environmental conditions during expansion period. || This critical developmental process follows primordium initiation and separation from axis, typically requiring 2-4 weeks per leaf from expansion initiation to near-final dimensions, with multiple leaves at various expansion stages creating developmental gradient along shoot. ||Expansion proceeds through continued cell division in marginal and plate meristems producing new cells particularly at leaf edges and throughout blade interior, and progressive cell expansion throughout developing blade where cells increase from meristematic dimensions to final sizes representing 50-200 fold volume increase. ||Cell division during expansion shows highest activity in marginal meristems at leaf edges producing cells that will form blade extent and lobe structures, with division continuing for 7-14 days in marginal zones after minimal division in interior regions has ceased, establishing size potential through cell number production. ||Cell expansion follows and overlaps with division phase with cells throughout blade undergoing water uptake creating turgor pressure driving cell wall extension, increasing individual cell dimensions from 10-20 micrometers in meristematic zones to 30-80 micrometers in mature blade representing 10-40 fold linear increase and 1000-64000 fold volume increase. ||Leaf area increase shows characteristic rapid exponential phase during early expansion when both cell production and expansion operate at maximum rates, transitioning to declining rate as cell division ceases and expansion completes, with total expansion from 2-4 mm separated primordium to 50-150 mm mature leaf representing 625-5600 fold area increase. ||Expansion rate varies substantially among leaves along shoot reflecting resource availability and growth conditions, with basal leaves showing modest rates of 3-6 mm per day during early slow shoot growth achieving final dimensions of 50-90 mm, middle leaves showing maximum rates of 8-15 mm per day during peak growth reaching 100-150 mm, and apical leaves showing declining rates of 4-8 mm per day achieving smaller 60-100 mm final sizes. ||Morphological development during expansion establishes characteristic palmate leaf form with major lobes separated by sinuses, with lobe number typically 3-5 and sinus depth varying from shallow creating nearly entire leaves to deep producing highly dissected forms depending on cultivar genetics and development conditions. ||Venation pattern develops during expansion with primary veins extending from petiole attachment point into major lobes providing structural framework and main transport pathways, secondary veins branching from primaries creating reticulated network, and tertiary veins forming fine network ensuring all photosynthetic cells have vascular access. ||Trichome development occurs during expansion with hair-like structures emerging from epidermal cells, with trichome density, length, and branching characteristics varying substantially among cultivars from glabrous leaves with minimal trichomes to densely tomentose leaves with extensive covering affecting leaf optical properties and transpiration characteristics. ||Stomatal development completes during expansion with stomatal complexes differentiating from epidermal progenitor cells, achieving final density typically 150-250 per square mm on abaxial lower surface and 50-100 per square mm on adaxial upper surface, with stomata becoming functional during late expansion enabling gas exchange for photosynthesis and transpiration. ||Chloroplast development proceeds during expansion transforming proplastids in young cells to functional chloroplasts with organized thylakoid membranes for light capture and assembled Calvin cycle enzymes for carbon fixation, with chlorophyll accumulation creating progressive greening from pale yellow-green in young expanding tissues to dark green in nearly mature leaves. ||Photosynthetic capacity develops progressively during expansion with photosynthetic rate per unit area increasing from negligible in early expansion to 40-60% mature rates when leaf reaches 50% final area to 80-90% mature rates approaching final dimensions, with whole-leaf carbon balance transitioning from net consumption to net production typically when leaf achieves 70-80% final area. ||Cell wall composition changes during expansion from thin primary walls dominated by pectin allowing plastic deformation to progressively thickening walls with increased cellulose and hemicellulose providing structural rigidity as expansion completes, determining final leaf mechanical properties and resistance to wilting under water stress. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated during expansion with respiration rates 8-15 fold above mature leaf levels providing energy for growth processes including cell division, expansion, wall synthesis, and protein production, declining progressively as expansion completes and maintenance requirements dominate. ||Protein synthesis operates at maximum capacity during expansion producing structural proteins for cell walls and membranes, photosynthetic proteins accumulating in chloroplasts with Rubisco reaching 40-50% total leaf protein supporting carbon fixation, and regulatory proteins coordinating complex developmental processes. ||Hormonal regulation coordinating expansion involves cytokinins promoting cell division in marginal and plate meristems, gibberellins supporting cell expansion and affecting final leaf size with higher concentrations promoting larger leaves, auxin from developing veins coordinating expansion patterns, and brassinosteroids enhancing cell expansion and vascular development. ||Temperature strongly affects expansion rate with development approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C optimal range, influencing both cell division duration and expansion rate affecting time required for expansion completion and potentially final dimensions achieved. ||Light intensity critically affects expansion with high light promoting rapid expansion to moderate final dimensions and thick leaf structure with high photosynthetic capacity per unit area, while shade reduces expansion rate and promotes larger final area with thin structure adapted to light limitation creating high specific leaf area. ||Water availability critically affects expansion through direct effects on cell turgor driving expansion, with adequate moisture essential for maintaining pressure supporting cell wall extension, while water stress rapidly arrests expansion permanently limiting final dimensions even after stress relief affecting photosynthetic capacity. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects expansion through effects on protein synthesis supporting both cell division and expansion, with adequate nitrogen supporting maximum expansion rate and large final dimensions while deficiency reduces expansion limiting final area and photosynthetic potential. ||The process shows variation in timing and rate among leaves creating characteristic pattern along shoot with basal leaves requiring longer expansion periods during slow early growth, middle leaves expanding rapidly during favorable peak growth conditions, and apical leaves showing abbreviated rapid expansion before growth cessation. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum expansion rate, final leaf dimensions ranging from small 50-80 mm in compact varieties to large 150-200 mm in vigorous types, leaf shape characteristics including lobe number and sinus depth, trichome density affecting leaf appearance, and expansion responsiveness to environmental conditions. ||Regional timing shows leaf expansion occurring throughout growing season from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with individual leaves requiring 2-4 weeks for expansion depending on position and conditions. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate water availability during expansion supporting full development of functional photosynthetic area, providing sufficient nitrogen supporting protein synthesis without excessive promotion, managing light environment optimizing expansion and photosynthetic development, monitoring for pest and disease damage during expansion as young tissues are particularly vulnerable, and assessing expansion patterns across vineyard evaluating vine health and resource availability. ||Limitations during expansion permanently reduce final leaf size affecting photosynthetic capacity and productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing cellular and molecular mechanisms of cell division and expansion during organ development, quantifying environmental and hormonal effects on expansion affecting final leaf characteristics, evaluating genetic variation in expansion patterns affecting leaf morphology and function, modeling expansion processes for predicting canopy development under varying conditions, and assessing developmental biology of compound leaf form using grapevine as model system.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 255-265 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 172-178 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Leaf_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Maturation is a Leaf_Emergence comprising the structural and functional completion of expanded leaves with fully differentiated anatomy and maximum photosynthetic capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf maturity | fully developed leaf | functional leaf development | mature foliage | Blattreife |+ Blattausreifung | funktionelles Blatt | ausgereiftes Laub",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows leaf maturation following expansion completion across May-August period at BBCH 15-38, with individual leaves requiring 1-2 weeks to achieve full photosynthetic capacity of 11-15 micromoles CO2 per square meter per second and complete structural development including stomatal control system and vascular function, under oceanic climate conditions of 18-26°C temperature range, adequate moisture, and moderate fertility typical of this moderately vigorous mid-season cultivar producing mature canopy supporting fruit development through véraison and ripening",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Maturation is fourth and final Leaf_Emergence subphase, distinguished by completion of structural and functional development achieving maximum photosynthetic capacity. ||Follows Leaf_Primordium_Expansion. ||Establishes productive mature canopy supporting vine growth and reproduction. ||Timing and completeness critically affect photosynthetic capacity and productivity. ||Mature characteristics persist until senescence. || This essential developmental process follows expansion completion, typically requiring 1-2 weeks per leaf from expansion completion to full functional maturity, with leaves at various maturation stages creating developmental gradient along shoot from immature recently expanded apical leaves to fully mature basal leaves. ||Maturation encompasses completion of chloroplast development achieving maximum photosynthetic enzyme concentrations and membrane organization, final cell wall thickening establishing mechanical properties, stomatal regulation system maturation enabling responsive control of gas exchange, vascular tissue completion establishing full transport capacity, and metabolic adjustment transitioning from growth to maintenance and production. ||Chloroplast maturation represents critical aspect with thylakoid membranes achieving final organization into grana stacks for light capture and stroma lamellae for electron transport, photosystem complexes reaching maximum concentration and functional efficiency, and Calvin cycle enzymes including Rubisco accumulating to final concentrations of 3-5 mg per square cm leaf area supporting maximum carbon fixation rates. ||Photosynthetic capacity increases during maturation from 60-80% maximum rates in recently expanded leaves to full capacity of 10-20 micromoles CO2 per square meter per second at light saturation in mature leaves, with light response curves showing maximum quantum efficiency, high light saturation points 1200-1800 micromoles per square meter per second, and minimal photo-inhibition at high light intensities. ||Stomatal control system matures during this phase with guard cells achieving full responsiveness to environmental signals including light intensity, atmospheric vapor pressure deficit, internal CO2 concentration, and plant water status through abscisic acid signaling, enabling dynamic regulation of gas exchange optimizing carbon gain while controlling water loss. ||Cell walls complete thickening during maturation with increased cellulose deposition providing tensile strength, lignification in vascular tissues establishing rigid transport structures, and cuticle development on epidermal surfaces providing protection against water loss and pathogen entry, determining final leaf mechanical properties and stress tolerance. ||Leaf water relations achieve mature characteristics with water potential typically -0.8 to -1.5 MPa under well-watered conditions, pressure-volume relationships reflecting cell wall elasticity and osmotic adjustment capacity, and hydraulic conductance from petiole through blade to stomata determining transpiration capacity and drought sensitivity. ||Vascular tissues complete functional development with xylem vessels achieving full water transport capacity supporting maximum transpiration rates and phloem sieve elements enabling efficient assimilate export from photosynthesizing mesophyll to growth sinks and storage tissues, with vascular density and architecture affecting resource transport efficiency. ||Metabolic transition during maturation involves declining respiration from growth levels to maintenance rates 2-4 fold above dark-adapted values, shifting protein synthesis from growth-related to photosynthetic and maintenance proteins, and adjusting carbon metabolism toward maximum net carbon export supporting other organs. ||Nitrogen concentration declines during maturation from 3-5% dry weight in young leaves to 2-3% in mature leaves as structural carbohydrates accumulate diluting protein nitrogen, with nitrogen distribution showing highest concentrations in photosynthetic apparatus particularly Rubisco in chloroplasts. ||Carbon balance achieves maximum positive status in mature leaves with net photosynthetic rate typically 8-15 micromoles CO2 per square meter per second during mid-day optimal conditions, supporting leaf's own maintenance requirements consuming approximately 10-20% photosynthetic production while exporting 80-90% to support other organs. ||Water use efficiency develops mature characteristics with photosynthetic rate per unit transpiration typically 2-4 micromoles CO2 per millimole H2O in mature leaves under favorable conditions, reflecting optimization of stomatal control balancing carbon gain and water loss. ||Mature leaf lifespan following maturation typically spans 8-16 weeks depending on leaf position and environmental conditions, with basal leaves persisting longer having more extended productive period while apical leaves maturing late in season may have abbreviated lifespan before senescence or dormancy entry. ||Environmental stress responses become established during maturation with mature leaves showing capacity for photosynthetic down-regulation under water stress protecting photosystems while reducing carbon fixation, osmotic adjustment maintaining turgor under moderate drought, and possible photo-protective mechanisms including xanthophyll cycle operation preventing photo-damage under stress conditions. ||Secondary metabolite accumulation may occur during maturation particularly in cultivars with anthocyanin pigmentation developing red coloration in leaves, phenolic compounds accumulating for defense against herbivory and disease, and volatile organic compounds potentially serving signaling or defense functions. ||Hormonal status transitions during maturation with declining growth-promoting hormones and possible increasing abscisic acid establishing stress-responsive state, with cytokinin concentrations particularly important for maintaining photosynthetic function and delaying senescence. ||Temperature affects maturation rate with warm conditions promoting rapid completion while cool conditions extend maturation period, though final photosynthetic capacity may be higher in leaves maturing under moderate rather than high temperatures through optimization of photosynthetic apparatus to prevailing conditions. ||Light intensity during maturation affects final photosynthetic characteristics with high light promoting maximum photosynthetic capacity per unit area and thick leaf structure, while shade reduces capacity though may increase chlorophyll concentration per unit area as adaptation to light limitation. ||Water availability during maturation affects final leaf characteristics with adequate moisture supporting normal maturation and maximum function while stress during maturation may result in reduced photosynthetic capacity and increased stress sensitivity. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen during maturation affects final photosynthetic capacity with adequate nitrogen supporting maximum enzyme concentrations and high photosynthetic rates while deficiency reduces capacity limiting leaf productivity. ||The process shows variation in timing and final characteristics among leaves with basal leaves maturing earliest and potentially achieving highest photosynthetic capacity having developed under favorable early-to-mid season conditions, middle leaves maturing during peak season achieving maximum function, and apical leaves maturing latest potentially showing reduced capacity if environmental conditions deteriorate late season. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum photosynthetic capacity in mature leaves ranging from moderate 8-12 micromoles per square meter per second in some varieties to high 15-20 micromoles per square meter per second in others, drought tolerance characteristics, and photosynthetic temperature optimum affecting performance in different climate zones. ||Regional timing shows leaf maturation occurring throughout growing season offset from expansion by 1-2 weeks, with basal leaves maturing June-July, middle leaves July-August, and apical leaves August-September in temperate regions. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing that mature leaf photosynthetic capacity determines canopy productivity supporting fruit development and reserve accumulation, maintaining leaf health during functional period maximizing productivity through pest and disease management, providing adequate water and nutrients supporting maximum photosynthetic function, and assessing mature canopy characteristics evaluating vineyard productivity potential. ||Factors limiting leaf maturation or reducing mature leaf function significantly impact whole-vine productivity and fruit quality. ||Research applications include quantifying photosynthetic capacity development and its environmental and genetic regulation, analyzing mechanisms of photosynthetic optimization to prevailing growth conditions, evaluating stress response capabilities in mature leaves affecting drought tolerance, modeling leaf carbon balance and its contribution to whole-plant productivity, and assessing implications of leaf functional characteristics for vineyard productivity across diverse environmental conditions and management systems.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 262-282 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 175-195 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Tendril_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Tendril_Formation is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the development of tendrils, lateral structures homologous to inflorescences functioning as climbing organs.",
  "alternative_term": "tendril development | climbing structure formation | tendril organogenesis |+ Rankenbildung | Rankenentwicklung | Kletterorganbildung | Rankenorganogenese",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows tendril formation from May through July at BBCH 15-35, producing tendrils at every third node in pattern of two tendril nodes followed by one inflorescence node, with individual tendrils developing bifurcated structure over 2-3 weeks reaching 80-120 mm length and coiling around trellis wires within 24-36 hours of contact under warm climate conditions of 18-28°C temperature range, providing essential support for vertical shoot positioning in VSP training system typical of this vigorous late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Tendril_Formation represents specialized lateral organ development within Shoot_Growth, producing attachment structures enabling climbing growth habit. ||Distinguished from Leaf_Emergence and Inflorescence_Development though sharing developmental homology with latter. ||Subdivided into Tendril_Primordium_Initiation, Tendril_Elongation, Tendril_Branching, and Tendril_Coiling based on developmental progression. ||Critical for vine architecture in both wild and cultivated contexts. ||Pattern regularity provides diagnostic information about shoot structure. || This distinctive developmental process occurs at regular intervals along shoot during active growth, typically producing tendrils at every third node in alternating pattern with inflorescences following cultivar-specific architectural programs, with tendril development spanning 2-4 weeks from primordium initiation to functional coiling structure. ||Tendril formation encompasses primordium initiation at shoot apex in positions homologous to inflorescence primordia, elongation through coordinated cell division and expansion creating tendril axis and branches, branching establishing bifurcated or multifurcated structure characteristic of grapevine tendrils, and coiling through differential growth responses enabling attachment to supports. ||The developmental origin of tendrils reflects evolutionary modification of inflorescence structures, with tendrils representing sterile inflorescence homologs that have lost reproductive function while maintaining developmental program for producing branched structures, evident in occasional tendril-inflorescence intermediates showing partial flower development. ||Tendril positioning follows regular architectural pattern along shoot axis with typically two successive nodes bearing tendrils followed by one node bearing inflorescence in fruiting shoots, or continuous tendril production at every third node in sterile shoots, creating predictable structural organization. ||Primordium initiation occurs at shoot apex in lateral positions opposite leaves following phyllotactic pattern similar to inflorescence positioning, with primordia arising as multicellular protrusions from meristem flank developing through similar early stages as inflorescence primordia before diverging toward tendril-specific development. ||Tendril structure typically shows bifurcated or trifurcated branching pattern with main axis dividing into 2-3 branches, each potentially subdividing creating total of 3-6 terminal segments, with branching architecture affecting attachment efficiency and mechanical strength. ||Elongation proceeds through cell division in apical regions and cell expansion throughout tendril axis creating slender flexible structure typically 50-150 mm total length at functional maturity, with elongation rate coordinated with shoot growth ensuring tendril availability for attachment as shoot extends. ||Tendril anatomy shows central vascular core providing water and nutrient transport, surrounding parenchyma and collenchyma tissues providing flexibility and strength, and epidermis with specialized cells enabling coiling responses, with anatomical structure optimized for combining flexibility during searching with strength after coiling attachment. ||Coiling mechanism involves differential growth responses with cells on one side of tendril expanding more than opposite side creating curvature, triggered by contact stimulation through mechanoreceptors detecting physical contact with support structures, with response developing over hours to days creating tight coils securing attachment. ||The coiling response shows two distinct phases including initial contact coiling where tendril portion touching support coils around support creating primary attachment within 12-24 hours, and subsequent free tendril coiling where unsupported portions between shoot and support coil creating spring-like structure that provides mechanical stability and shock absorption. ||Tendril functionality provides critical support enabling vertical shoot growth reaching canopy heights of 2-4 meters in trained systems or climbing into tree canopies reaching 10-20 meters in wild populations, with attachment strength sufficient to support shoot weight and resist wind loading. ||Mechanical properties develop during maturation with young tendrils showing high flexibility enabling searching movements, transitioning to increased rigidity after coiling attachment through lignification in coiled regions providing permanent structural support. ||Lignification proceeds in attached coiled tendrils creating woody persistent structures that remain functional for multiple seasons, while unattached tendrils typically senesce and abscise having failed to fulfill attachment function. ||Metabolic activity in developing tendrils shows elevated respiration supporting growth processes, declining to maintenance levels in mature attached tendrils, with photosynthetic contribution negligible due to limited chlorophyll content and small surface area. ||Water transport through tendrils contributes minimally to shoot hydraulic system as small vascular capacity relative to main shoot axis, though maintaining tendril turgor may be important for coiling function and attachment maintenance. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin affecting elongation and possibly coiling responses, ethylene potentially involved in coiling mechanism and senescence of unattached tendrils, and jasmonates possibly affecting touch-induced coiling responses through mechanotransduction pathways. ||Temperature affects tendril development rate with elongation approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C, influencing timing of tendril availability for attachment relative to shoot growth progression. ||Light intensity affects tendril development with adequate light supporting normal elongation and function while extreme shade may reduce tendril production or vigor affecting climbing ability. ||Water availability affects tendril turgor and function with adequate moisture maintaining flexibility and coiling capability while severe water stress may impair coiling responses affecting attachment success. ||The process shows characteristic progression through distinct developmental phases advancing from primordium initiation at apex through elongation creating structure, branching establishing architecture, and coiling enabling functional attachment. ||Cultivar variation appears in tendril production pattern with some varieties showing consistent every-third-node pattern while others show variation, branching architecture affecting attachment efficiency, and coiling vigor affecting climbing ability with implications for training requirements. ||Regional timing shows tendril formation occurring throughout shoot growth from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with formation rate corresponding to shoot growth rate and node production frequency. ||Viticultural management considerations include understanding tendril positioning pattern informing node counting for reproductive structure prediction, recognizing that vigorous tendril production indicates healthy shoot growth, utilizing tendril attachment for shoot positioning and training in vertical systems, monitoring tendril function assessing support system adequacy, and removing excessive tendrils in some training systems reducing shoot entanglement and improving canopy management. ||Research applications include analyzing evolutionary developmental biology of organ modification from reproductive to vegetative function, investigating molecular mechanisms of tendril identity specification and coiling responses, quantifying mechanical properties and attachment strength affecting vine architecture, evaluating coiling mechanotransduction pathways and signal integration, and assessing tendril function in wild grapevine ecology and implications for cultivated vine architecture.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 265-278 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 195-210 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Tendril_Primordium_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Tendril_Primordium_Initiation is a Tendril_Formation comprising the production of lateral primordia at the shoot apical meristem at positions homologous to inflorescence primordia.",
  "alternative_term": "tendril initiation | tendril primordium formation | tendril organogenesis initiation |+ Rankenprimordienbildung | Rankenanlagebildung | Rankeninitiierung | Rankenorganogenese-Beginn",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows tendril primordium initiation from May through July at BBCH 15-35 at shoot apex, initiating new tendril primordia every 6-8 days at every third node position following two-tendril-one-inflorescence architectural pattern, with primordia developing from 50-100 micrometer initial bulges to 400-500 micrometer recognizable tendril structures over 5-7 days under continental climate conditions of 16-26°C temperature range and moderate fertility typical of this moderate-vigor early-to-mid season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Tendril_Primordium_Initiation is first of four Tendril_Formation subphases, distinguished by organogenesis at apical meristem establishing tendril structures. ||Represents earliest microscopic stage occurring at shoot apex. ||Transitions to Tendril_Elongation as primordia continue developing. ||Shares early developmental stages with inflorescence primordia reflecting evolutionary homology. ||Critical for establishing regular architectural pattern along shoot. || This fundamental organogenesis process occurs at shoot apex during active growth following every-third-node pattern in most cultivars, with new tendril primordia initiating every 6-9 days corresponding to three leaf primordium initiations, producing total of 4-8 tendril primordia per shoot over growing season. ||Primordium initiation begins with localized increase in cell division activity on apical meristem flank at lateral position opposite developing leaf primordium, with cells in initiation zone undergoing accelerated divisions creating multicellular protrusion marking first visible stage of tendril formation. ||The initiation site occurs in regular architectural pattern with typically two successive nodes producing tendril primordia followed by one node producing inflorescence primordium in reproductive shoots, or continuous tendril production at every third node in sterile shoots, with positioning controlled by genetic developmental programs and possibly hormonal signals. ||Tendril primordium initiation shares early developmental stages with inflorescence primordium formation showing similar multicellular protrusion and initial cell division patterns, with divergence toward tendril versus inflorescence fate occurring through differential gene expression suppressing floral meristem identity genes and activating tendril-specific developmental programs. ||The molecular basis of tendril versus inflorescence specification involves transcription factors regulating meristem identity with mutations in key regulatory genes capable of converting tendrils to inflorescences or vice versa, demonstrating close developmental relationship and evolutionary origin of tendrils from modified inflorescence structures. ||Primordial cells undergo oriented divisions establishing elongated axis structure characteristic of tendril rather than compact branching structure of inflorescence, with longitudinal growth dominating over radial growth creating slender primordium form. ||Primordium size at initiation measures approximately 50-100 micrometers diameter similar to other lateral organ primordia, increasing to 300-500 micrometers with several hundred cells by time primordium is clearly recognizable as tendril structure rather than simple protrusion or potential inflorescence, requiring approximately 4-7 days from first division acceleration to recognizable tendril form. ||Vascular strand initiation occurs early in primordium development establishing connection between developing tendril and shoot axis, with procambial cells forming continuous strand from primordium base through shoot cortex connecting to main vascular system, providing pathway for water delivery and nutrient transport supporting tendril development. ||Gene expression patterns during initiation include activation of lateral organ identity genes specifying formation of lateral structure, expression of tendril-specific genes suppressing inflorescence development programs, and morphogenesis genes controlling cell division patterns and growth orientation establishing elongated tendril form. ||Early primordium development shows establishment of apical-basal polarity defining tip and base regions with apical zone maintaining division capacity longer supporting elongation growth characteristic of tendril development. ||Branching point determination may occur during initiation phase with cells at specific positions along developing primordium establishing zones where branches will subsequently emerge, though branch development itself occurs later during elongation phase. ||Hormonal regulation of initiation involves auxin concentration patterns at meristem apex with local auxin distributions possibly affecting tendril versus inflorescence fate determination, cytokinins from roots supporting cell division in initiating primordia, and gibberellins potentially affecting tendril elongation programming. ||Timing of tendril primordium initiation relative to leaf primordium initiation follows architectural program with tendril initiation occurring at every third node position, coordinated through developmental signals ensuring regular pattern maintenance along shoot axis. ||Environmental conditions during initiation period may influence tendril versus inflorescence determination with stress conditions potentially promoting tendril production over reproductive structures in some developmental contexts, though genetic programs predominantly control organ identity. ||Temperature affects initiation timing through effects on apical meristem activity with optimal 22-28°C supporting regular initiation frequency maintaining every-third-node pattern, while suboptimal temperatures may slow meristem activity affecting timing though typically maintaining positional pattern. ||Light intensity and quality during initiation may influence developmental programs with high light supporting normal development while extreme shade potentially affecting organ identity determination in some cases. ||Water availability affects meristem function with adequate moisture maintaining normal initiation patterns while severe water stress potentially disrupting regular development and organ identity specification. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects meristem activity and organ initiation with adequate nutrition supporting normal initiation frequency and organ development while severe deficiency may reduce initiation or affect organ identity. ||The process shows regular temporal pattern corresponding to leaf initiation frequency with new tendril primordium initiating after every third leaf primordium, creating predictable sequence of organs along developing shoot axis. ||Cultivar variation appears in regularity of every-third-node pattern with some varieties showing consistent pattern while others show occasional variation, tendril versus inflorescence determination with some cultivars showing higher proportion of reproductive structures, and possibly branching architecture programming during early primordium development. ||Regional timing shows tendril primordium initiation occurring throughout shoot growth period from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with initiation frequency corresponding to apical meristem activity and shoot growth rate. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing tendril positioning pattern that informs shoot structure prediction and node counting for crop estimation, recognizing that initiation reflects normal shoot development and meristem function, and understanding that environmental or genetic factors affecting initiation may alter shoot architecture affecting training and management. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of organ identity specification and tendril versus inflorescence determination, investigating evolutionary developmental biology of organ modification and function change, evaluating genetic and environmental factors affecting developmental fate decisions, documenting cellular mechanisms of primordium formation and polarity establishment, and assessing architectural programs controlling regular organ positioning patterns in shoot development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 265-270 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 195-202 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Tendril_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Tendril_Elongation is a Tendril_Formation comprising the length increase of tendril primordia through cell division and expansion into slender flexible structures.",
  "alternative_term": "tendril extension | tendril growth | tendril stretching |+ Rankenstreckung | Rankenwachstum | Rankenverlängerung | Rankenexpansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows tendril elongation from late May through July at BBCH 15-35, with individual tendrils requiring 8-12 days to elongate from 5-10 mm primordia to functional length of 60-90 mm through elongation rate of 5-8 mm per day during peak growth, under cool maritime climate conditions of 15-20°C temperature range, adequate moisture, and moderate fertility typical of this moderately vigorous early-bursting cultivar producing tendrils supporting shoot positioning in vertical training systems",
  "editor_note": "Tendril_Elongation is second of four Tendril_Formation subphases, distinguished by length increase creating functional tendril structure. ||Follows Tendril_Primordium_Initiation. ||Transitions to Tendril_Branching as branch points develop and Tendril_Coiling as contact with supports occurs. ||Primary determinant of final tendril dimensions and attachment potential. ||Critical phase establishing functional searching structure. || This critical developmental process follows primordium initiation, typically requiring 7-14 days per tendril from elongation initiation to functional length, with multiple tendrils at various elongation stages creating developmental gradient along shoot corresponding to regular tendril positioning pattern. ||Elongation proceeds through continued cell division in apical growth zone producing new cells contributing to tendril length, and progressive cell expansion throughout tendril axis where cells increase length creating visible elongation of 3-8 mm per day during active growth. ||Cell division during elongation shows highest activity in apical zone behind tendril tip maintaining meristem-like characteristics, with division continuing for 5-10 days producing cells arranged in longitudinal files characteristic of unidirectional growth, then transitioning to expansion phase where cell production ceases but existing cells undergo dramatic elongation. ||Cell expansion occurs throughout elongating tendril with cells increasing from meristematic dimensions of 10-20 micrometers to final lengths of 100-300 micrometers representing 10-30 fold increase, through water uptake creating turgor pressure driving cell wall extension and progressive wall thickening maintaining structural integrity. ||Tendril length increase shows characteristic pattern with rapid elongation during early-mid phase at 5-10 mm per day when both cell division and expansion operate actively, declining to 2-4 mm per day during late phase as division ceases and expansion completes, with final functional length typically 50-150 mm depending on cultivar, position along shoot, and environmental conditions. ||Elongation rate varies among tendrils reflecting shoot growth conditions with tendrils forming during peak shoot growth showing maximum elongation rates and achieving longest dimensions, while tendrils forming during declining growth show reduced rates and shorter final lengths. ||Anatomical development during elongation establishes characteristic tendril structure including central vascular strand with xylem vessels for water transport and phloem sieve elements for assimilate distribution, surrounding parenchyma providing flexibility and storage capacity, peripheral collenchyma providing mechanical strength while maintaining flexibility, and epidermis with specialized cells capable of detecting contact stimulation. ||Vascular differentiation proceeds basipetally from connection with shoot axis toward tendril tip, with procambial cells differentiating into functional xylem vessels and phloem elements establishing continuous transport pathway supporting tendril growth and eventual coiling responses. ||The elongating tendril shows negative gravitropism growing upward and positive thigmotropism enabling growth toward potential support structures through touch-induced directional responses, with combination of growth orientations positioning tendril optimally for encountering supports. ||Tendril surface cells develop mechanoreceptor capabilities during elongation enabling detection of contact with support surfaces that will trigger subsequent coiling responses, with mechanoreceptor distribution particularly concentrated on tendril ventral surfaces that will contact supports. ||Mechanical properties during elongation emphasize flexibility enabling searching movements and exploration of spatial environment for support structures, with young elongating tendrils showing low tensile strength and high flexibility from thin primary cell walls. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated during elongation with respiration 8-12 fold above mature tissue levels supporting growth processes including cell division, expansion, vascular differentiation, and wall synthesis. ||Protein synthesis operates at high rates producing structural proteins for expanding cells, enzymes supporting metabolism and wall modification, and potentially beginning accumulation of proteins involved in mechanoreception and signal transduction for coiling responses. ||Circumnutation movements may occur during elongation with tendril tip describing circular or elliptical path through space enhancing probability of encountering support structures, driven by differential growth rates on opposite sides of tendril coordinated through internal oscillatory developmental program. ||Hormonal regulation coordinating elongation involves auxin promoting elongation and coordinating vascular differentiation pattern, gibberellins supporting cell expansion affecting final tendril length, and possible brassinosteroid effects on cell expansion and mechanoreceptor development. ||Temperature strongly affects elongation rate with development approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C optimal range, influencing both cell division duration and expansion rate determining time required for functional length achievement. ||Light intensity affects elongation with adequate light supporting normal development while shade may promote enhanced elongation through etiolation-like response seeking improved light exposure, potentially affecting final tendril length and functionality. ||Water availability critically affects elongation through direct effects on cell turgor driving expansion, with adequate moisture essential for maintaining pressure supporting cell wall extension while water stress arrests elongation limiting final dimensions affecting attachment potential. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects elongation through effects on protein synthesis supporting cell division and expansion, with adequate nutrition supporting maximum elongation while deficiency reduces elongation rate and limits final dimensions. ||The process shows variation in timing and rate among tendrils creating pattern along shoot with early-season tendrils requiring longer elongation periods during slower shoot growth, mid-season tendrils elongating rapidly during peak conditions achieving maximum length, and late-season tendrils showing abbreviated rapid elongation before growth cessation. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum elongation rate, final tendril length ranging from short 40-80 mm in some varieties to long 120-180 mm in vigorous types affecting climbing ability, and possibly circumnutation vigor affecting support encounter probability. ||Regional timing shows tendril elongation occurring throughout growing season from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas offset from initiation by 1-2 weeks, with individual tendrils requiring 7-14 days for elongation depending on conditions. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing that vigorous tendril elongation indicates healthy shoot growth and adequate resources, understanding that elongation timing affects availability for shoot attachment and training operations, monitoring elongation patterns assessing vine vigor and resource status, and considering tendril development in timing of shoot positioning and wire attachment operations. ||Research applications include analyzing cellular and molecular mechanisms of unidirectional organ elongation, investigating circumnutation mechanisms and their ecological function in support location, evaluating mechanoreceptor development and mechanotransduction pathways, quantifying environmental effects on elongation affecting tendril functionality, and assessing biomechanics of tendril searching behavior and attachment efficiency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 270-275 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 202-207 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Tendril_Branching": {
  "definition": "A Tendril_Branching is a Tendril_Formation comprising the production of lateral branches from the main tendril axis into a bifurcated or multifurcated structure.",
  "alternative_term": "tendril bifurcation | tendril subdivision | tendril ramification | branch formation |+ Rankenverzweigung | Rankengabelung | Rankenaufgliederung | Rankenramifikation",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows tendril branching from June through August at BBCH 19-35, with main tendril axes reaching 15-25 mm length before producing typically bifurcated branch structure dividing into two branches of 40-60 mm length over 8-12 days, creating total tendril structure of 80-120 mm with 4-6 terminal segments under oceanic climate conditions of 17-24°C temperature range and adequate resources typical of this moderately vigorous mid-season cultivar producing well-branched tendrils supporting shoot attachment",
  "editor_note": "Tendril_Branching is third of four Tendril_Formation subphases, distinguished by lateral branch development creating characteristic bifurcated or multifurcated structure. ||Occurs during or after Tendril_Elongation. ||May overlap with Tendril_Coiling if contact occurs during branch development. ||Establishes architectural complexity affecting attachment efficiency. ||Cultivar-specific patterns provide diagnostic characters. || This distinctive developmental process occurs during or following elongation, with branch initiation typically beginning when main axis reaches 10-20 mm length and branch development continuing over 7-14 days producing final bifurcated structure with 2-4 primary branches each potentially subdividing creating total of 3-8 terminal segments. ||Branching initiation occurs at specific positions along main tendril axis where localized cell division establishes lateral branch primordia, typically at one or two positions creating characteristic bifurcated or trifurcated primary branch structure, with branch positioning determined during early tendril development through developmental programs establishing branch point locations. ||Branch primordia develop through similar processes as main tendril axis with localized cell proliferation creating lateral protrusion, followed by coordinated cell division and expansion creating branch axis, and vascular connection establishment linking branch to main tendril vascular system. ||Branch elongation proceeds through cell division in branch apical zones and cell expansion throughout branch length creating branches typically 60-80% length of main axis distal portion, with elongation rate generally similar to main axis elongation though total length development time shorter due to later initiation. ||Branching architecture shows cultivar-specific patterns with some varieties producing predominantly bifurcated structure with single branch point dividing main axis into two equal branches, others showing trifurcated pattern with main axis producing two lateral branches while continuing apical growth, and some producing more complex branching with secondary subdivisions creating 6-8 terminal segments. ||The adaptive significance of branching includes increasing total tendril surface area and number of terminal segments available for encountering support structures, providing multiple independent attachment points increasing attachment reliability and mechanical strength, and creating architectural form optimized for wrapping around diverse support structures including wires, branches, and other plant stems. ||Terminal segment number affects attachment efficiency with more segments providing increased probability of support contact and successful coiling, though excessive branching may reduce individual segment length potentially limiting coiling effectiveness. ||Branch development shows coordination with main axis growth ensuring branches develop during period of active tendril elongation when resources are available and growth conditions favorable, with branch initiation and elongation typically completing before main axis growth cessation. ||Vascular architecture in branched tendril establishes connections from main axis strand into each branch providing water transport for turgor maintenance and coiling function, and enabling assimilate import during development transitioning to potential limited export from any photosynthetic tissue though tendril photosynthetic contribution is minimal. ||Mechanical properties of branched structure provide both flexibility during searching phase enabling exploration of spatial environment and strength after coiling attachment with multiple coiled segments distributing mechanical loads and providing redundancy if individual segments fail. ||Branch angles relative to main axis typically range 30-60 degrees creating spreading structure that increases spatial coverage during searching movements and provides advantageous geometry for encountering supports in various orientations. ||Anatomical structure in branches mirrors main axis with central vascular strand, surrounding flexible parenchyma, peripheral collenchyma, and epidermis with mechanoreceptor capabilities, though branches may show slightly smaller dimensions reflecting later initiation and shorter development period. ||Metabolic activity in developing branches shows elevated respiration supporting growth similar to main axis elongation, declining to maintenance levels as branch development completes and structure becomes functional. ||Hormonal regulation of branching involves auxin from main tendril apex potentially affecting branch outgrowth through apical dominance mechanisms similar to shoot branching, with lower auxin concentrations in branch initiation zones permitting lateral growth, and cytokinins possibly promoting branch initiation and outgrowth. ||Temperature affects branching development rate with branch elongation approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C similar to main axis elongation, influencing timing of branch development relative to main axis growth. ||Light intensity affects branch development with adequate light supporting normal branching while extreme shade may reduce branch number or vigor though branching shows less light dependency than photosynthetic leaf development. ||Water availability affects branching through effects on cell turgor supporting branch elongation and development, with adequate moisture essential for normal branching pattern achievement. ||Nutrient availability affects branching through effects on protein synthesis and growth processes supporting branch development, with adequate nutrition supporting normal branching architecture while severe deficiency may reduce branch number or development. ||The process typically completes within 7-14 days after initiation producing functional branched structure ready for support searching and coiling attachment, with timing varying based on environmental conditions and position along shoot. ||Cultivar variation appears in branching architecture with some varieties consistently producing bifurcated structure while others show trifurcated or more complex patterns, branch number ranging from 2 primary branches to 4-6 in highly branched types, and branch length relative to main axis affecting overall tendril dimensions and attachment potential. ||Regional timing shows tendril branching occurring throughout growing season corresponding to tendril formation period from May-July in warm climates, May-August in temperate regions, and June-September in cool areas, with individual tendrils requiring 7-14 days for branching development. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing that branching architecture affects attachment efficiency and reliability, understanding that vigorous branching indicates healthy tendril development and adequate resources, monitoring branching patterns across vineyard assessing vine development uniformity, and considering tendril branching architecture in selecting training systems and support structures. ||Research applications include analyzing developmental mechanisms of branch initiation and positioning in lateral organs, investigating genetic and environmental regulation of branching architecture, evaluating functional morphology of branched tendril structure and attachment mechanics, quantifying relationship between branching pattern and attachment success, and assessing evolutionary ecology of tendril architecture in climbing plant adaptation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 275-278 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 207-210 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Tendril_Coiling": {
  "definition": "A Tendril_Coiling is a Tendril_Formation comprising the differential growth of tendril tissues producing helical curvature wrapping around support surfaces.",
  "alternative_term": "tendril wrapping | tendril curling | helical coiling | attachment formation |+ Rankeneinrollung | Rankenwicklung | Rankenumschlingung | Spiralbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows tendril coiling from June through August at BBCH 19-35, with contact with trellis wires triggering coiling response initiating within 10-20 minutes producing 4-6 tight coils around 2.5mm wire within 18-24 hours followed by free coiling in unattached tendril portions creating characteristic spring structure over following 36-48 hours, with subsequent lignification over 10-14 days creating permanent woody attachment supporting vertical shoot growth under Mediterranean climate conditions of 20-28°C temperature range typical of this vigorous mid-to-late season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Tendril_Coiling is fourth and final Tendril_Formation subphase, distinguished by functional attachment response following support contact. ||Represents culmination of tendril development converting structure to function. ||May occur during or after Tendril_Elongation and Tendril_Branching depending on contact timing. ||Critical functional process enabling climbing growth habit. ||Unsuccessful coiling results in tendril senescence and abscission. || This critical functional process occurs following tendril elongation when contact with suitable support surface triggers coiling response, typically requiring 12-48 hours from initial contact to complete primary coiling around support and additional 24-72 hours for secondary free coiling between shoot and support attachment point. ||Coiling mechanism involves differential cell expansion on opposite sides of tendril with cells on outer convex side elongating more than cells on inner concave side creating curvature, driven by touch-induced signal transduction activating differential growth responses through hormonal and biomechanical mechanisms. ||Contact detection occurs through mechanoreceptors in tendril epidermal cells sensing physical pressure or friction from support surface contact, transducing mechanical stimulus into biochemical signals including calcium influx, electrical signals propagating through tendril tissues, and hormonal responses triggering differential growth. ||The coiling response shows two distinct spatial phases including contact coiling where tendril portion touching support coils tightly around support creating primary attachment with multiple coils providing grip, and free coiling where unsupported tendril length between shoot attachment and support contact point coils creating spring-like helical structure. ||Contact coiling typically produces 3-8 tight coils around support with coil diameter corresponding to support diameter ranging from 3-30 mm, with coiling direction variable though often showing consistent right-handed or left-handed helicity within individual tendrils. ||Free coiling creates characteristic spring structure with larger diameter coils typically 10-30 mm and variable handedness often reversing direction creating perversions where handedness switches providing mechanical properties of bidirectional spring, enabling tension and compression responses to wind loading and shoot movement. ||Coiling initiation time after contact shows temperature dependence with responses beginning within 5-15 minutes of contact at optimal 22-28°C, slowing substantially at lower temperatures, and potentially accelerating at higher temperatures within physiological range. ||Coiling rate during active response shows vigorous differential growth creating visible curvature increasing at 10-30 degrees per hour during peak response 4-12 hours after contact, with complete primary coiling around thin supports achieved within 12-24 hours and coiling around thicker supports requiring 24-48 hours. ||Cellular mechanisms underlying differential growth include asymmetric auxin distribution with higher concentrations on outer expanding side driven by polar auxin transport, differential cell wall loosening through expansin and other wall-modifying enzyme activities responding to hormonal signals, and asymmetric turgor pressure potentially contributing to immediate response preceding growth-based curvature. ||Lignification proceeds in coiled tendril portions following completion of coiling response, with secondary wall deposition and lignin incorporation creating rigid permanent attachment structure from initially flexible herbaceous tissue, typically requiring 1-2 weeks for substantial lignification providing long-term mechanical stability. ||Mechanical strength develops during and after coiling with initial attachment depending on friction and geometric constraint as tender coils wrap support, increasing substantially with lignification creating rigid structure capable of supporting shoot weight and resisting substantial tensile forces from wind loading. ||Attachment strength in mature lignified coiled tendrils can exceed 10-50 Newtons depending on tendril thickness, number of coils, support diameter, and lignification completeness, providing reliable anchorage for shoots with typical weights of 0.5-2.0 Newtons bearing additional fruit load. ||Free coil spring function provides mechanical benefits including shock absorption dampening sudden loading from wind gusts, accommodation of shoot growth allowing vertical extension without excessive tension on attachment points, and multi-directional response capacity enabling shoots to move in various directions while maintaining attachment. ||Vascular function in coiled tendrils maintains water transport capacity through coiled regions supporting distal branch portions that may contact additional supports, though overall hydraulic contribution to shoot water supply is minimal given small vascular dimensions relative to main shoot axis. ||Tendril longevity after successful coiling extends through multiple growing seasons with lignified coiled tendrils persisting as permanent woody structures, while unattached tendrils failing to contact supports typically senesce and abscise within 2-4 weeks representing unsuccessful development. ||Metabolic activity in coiling tendrils shows elevated respiration during active coiling response supporting differential growth processes, declining substantially after coiling completion and lignification to minimal maintenance levels in mature woody coiled structures. ||Hormonal regulation of coiling involves ethylene potentially mediating mechanoreceptor signal transduction and triggering differential growth response, auxin redistribution creating differential expansion on opposite tendril sides, and possibly jasmonates involved in touch signal transduction and response coordination. ||Temperature affects coiling response rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid vigorous coiling completing within 12-24 hours, cool temperatures below 15°C substantially slowing response potentially requiring 48-96 hours, and very high temperatures above 32°C potentially reducing response vigor through stress effects. ||Light intensity shows minimal effect on coiling response as mechanically triggered process operates in light or dark, though photosynthetic production supporting overall plant vigor indirectly affects tendril development and function. ||Water availability affects coiling response through effects on turgor maintaining cell expansion capacity, with adequate moisture essential for normal vigorous coiling while water stress may reduce response rate or vigor affecting attachment success. ||The process shows cultivar variation in coiling vigor affecting response rate and attachment strength, sensitivity to contact stimulation affecting coiling initiation threshold, and possibly coiling directionality preferences though most cultivars show variable handedness. ||Regional timing shows tendril coiling occurring throughout growing season corresponding to tendril development period from May-August in temperate regions, with individual coiling responses requiring 12-72 hours depending on support type and environmental conditions. ||Viticultural management considerations include providing appropriate support structures with suitable dimensions for tendril coiling typically 3-20 mm diameter, timing shoot positioning operations allowing tendrils to attach before requiring shoot adjustment, monitoring attachment success assessing support system adequacy, recognizing that vigorous coiling indicates healthy tendril function and adequate resources, and managing excessive tendril attachment that may complicate shoot repositioning or removal operations. ||Research applications include investigating mechanoreception and mechanotransduction pathways mediating touch responses, analyzing cellular and molecular mechanisms of differential growth creating curvature, evaluating biomechanics of coiling attachment and spring function, quantifying environmental effects on coiling responses affecting attachment success, and assessing evolutionary ecology of coiling mechanisms in climbing plant adaptation and support utilization strategies.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 275-282 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 207-215 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Shoot_Lignification": {
  "definition": "A Shoot_Lignification is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the conversion of herbaceous shoot tissues to woody tissues through secondary wall deposition and lignin incorporation.",
  "alternative_term": "shoot maturation | shoot woodification | cane lignification | wood formation | shoot hardening |+ Triebverholzung | Triebausreifung | Triebverholzung | Holzbildung | Stockausreifung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Bordeaux shows shoot lignification from June through October at BBCH 31-47, initiating in basal internodes in early June progressing acropetally through shoot reaching apical regions by September-October, accumulating starch reserves to 20-28% dry weight creating brown woody mature shoots with complete lignification before dormancy entry under oceanic climate conditions of 18-24°C summer declining to 10-15°C autumn, with management promoting moderate late-season water stress supporting timely thorough maturation typical of this vigorous late-season cultivar requiring complete lignification for adequate winter hardiness",
  "editor_note": "Shoot_Lignification represents maturation process within Shoot_Growth converting annual herbaceous growth to perennial woody structure. ||Distinguished from Shoot_Elongation and other growth processes by focus on maturation and lignin deposition. ||Subdivided into Basal_Shoot_Lignification, Progressive_Shoot_Lignification, Midshoot_Lignification, and Complete_Shoot_Lignification based on spatial-temporal progression. ||Critical for winter survival and subsequent season resource availability. ||Timing and completeness determine cold hardiness and reserve status. || This essential developmental process begins in basal shoot regions during active growth and progresses acropetally following shoot elongation, typically spanning 8-14 weeks from initiation in basal internodes through completion in apical regions by dormancy entry, establishing permanent woody architecture from annual shoot growth. ||Lignification encompasses secondary cell wall synthesis in vascular tissues, fibers, and parenchyma cells, lignin monomer biosynthesis and polymerization creating hydrophobic matrix binding wall polysaccharides, progressive tissue rigidification through wall thickening and cross-linking, and metabolic transition from active growth to maintenance and storage functions. ||The process shows characteristic basipetal-to-acropetal progression with basal internodes initiating lignification during early-mid summer while shoot apex continues active growth, middle internodes lignifying during mid-late summer, and apical internodes completing maturation during late summer-autumn before dormancy. ||Lignification initiation occurs when internode elongation completes and cells transition from expansion to differentiation and secondary wall synthesis, with timing varying along shoot from early June in basal regions to August-September in apical regions in temperate climates. ||Secondary wall deposition represents central lignification process involving cellulose and hemicellulose synthesis forming secondary wall framework layers designated S1, S2, and S3 with specific microfibril orientations, followed by lignin monomer synthesis producing p-coumaryl, coniferyl, and sinapyl alcohols from phenylalanine through phenylpropanoid pathway, and lignin polymerization through oxidative coupling creating three-dimensional polymer network. ||Lignin content increases progressively during maturation from negligible in actively growing tissues to 15-25% dry weight in fully lignified mature shoots, with lignification proceeding from vascular tissues outward through adjacent fiber and parenchyma cells creating progressive rigidification. ||Cell types showing most extensive lignification include xylem vessel elements requiring rigid walls for water transport under tension, xylem fibers providing mechanical support, and interfascicular fibers between vascular bundles contributing to shoot rigidity. ||Mechanical properties change dramatically during lignification from flexible herbaceous tissue with tensile strength 5-15 MPa and high flexibility in unlignified shoots, to rigid woody structure with strength 40-80 MPa and minimal flexibility in fully lignified mature shoots, enabling self-supporting architecture and resistance to mechanical loading. ||Vascular tissue maturation accompanies lignification with secondary xylem development from vascular cambium activity producing additional vessels increasing water transport capacity, secondary phloem formation enhancing assimilate translocation, and progressive primary tissue compression as secondary tissues develop. ||Periderm formation proceeds during lignification replacing epidermis with cork tissue providing protection, developing from cork cambium in subepidermal layers producing cork cells externally creating brown bark appearance and phelloderm internally contributing to cortex structure. ||Carbohydrate accumulation intensifies during lignification as growth cessation redirects photosynthate from growth to storage, with starch concentration increasing from negligible during active growth to 15-30% dry weight in fully mature lignified shoots by dormancy entry, providing critical reserves for subsequent season bud burst and initial growth. ||Reserve accumulation timing shows basipetal-acropetal pattern corresponding to lignification progression with basal regions accumulating reserves earliest and most thoroughly, while apical regions show later abbreviated accumulation particularly in vigorous shoots where late growth delays maturation. ||Metabolic changes during lignification include declining respiration from growth levels to maintenance rates 2-4 fold above completely dormant tissue, shifting protein synthesis from growth-related to storage and defense proteins, and activating phenylpropanoid pathway enzymes supporting lignin biosynthesis. ||Nitrogen dynamics during lignification involve declining nitrogen concentration from 2-3% in mature leaves and growing shoots to 1-1.5% in lignified shoots as structural carbohydrates accumulate and mobile nitrogen remobilizes to storage tissues or senescing leaves, with nitrogen conservation important for resource economy. ||Water content declines during lignification from 70-80% fresh weight in herbaceous tissues to 50-60% in lignified mature shoots, reflecting reduced metabolic activity, increased cell wall material deposition, and beginning dehydration preparing for winter dormancy. ||Hormonal regulation involves declining auxin and gibberellin from reduced apical production affecting growth promotion, increasing abscisic acid promoting maturation processes and stress tolerance development, ethylene potentially involved in senescence and maturation coordination, and jasmonates possibly affecting secondary metabolism and lignification processes. ||Temperature affects lignification rate with warm conditions promoting rapid progression while cool conditions slow processes, though lignification proceeds across wide temperature range unlike growth which requires narrow optimal conditions. ||Light intensity affects lignification through effects on photosynthetic carbon availability for reserve accumulation and possibly direct photomorphogenic effects, with high light supporting thorough rapid lignification while shade may result in incomplete lignification particularly in apical regions. ||Water availability affects lignification with moderate water stress potentially promoting earlier initiation and enhanced progression, while severe stress may cause incomplete lignification or premature growth cessation affecting tissue quality. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects lignification with adequate but not excessive nitrogen supporting normal maturation, while excess may delay lignification prolonging herbaceous state, and deficiency may cause premature incomplete maturation. ||The process shows four distinguishable phases based on spatial progression along shoot advancing from basal shoot lignification in earliest maturing regions through progressive lignification moving acropetally, midshoot lignification in middle regions, and complete shoot lignification extending to apical zones. ||Cultivar variation appears in lignification timing and completeness with early-maturing varieties showing rapid thorough lignification while late-maturing types may show incomplete apical lignification particularly in vigorous growth, affecting winter hardiness in cold climates. ||Regional timing shows basal shoot lignification beginning June-July in warm climates, July-August in temperate regions, and August in cool areas, with progression continuing through late summer and autumn toward dormancy entry. ||Viticultural management considerations include ensuring adequate late-season growth cessation allowing proper maturation before winter, managing water and nitrogen avoiding excessive late growth interfering with lignification, assessing lignification completeness particularly in cold regions where inadequate maturation creates freeze damage risk, recognizing that thorough lignification with substantial reserve accumulation benefits subsequent season development, and understanding that incomplete lignification reduces winter survival and next-season vigor. ||Research applications include analyzing regulation of lignin biosynthesis and deposition, quantifying environmental and management effects on lignification affecting shoot quality, evaluating relationships between lignification and cold hardiness in climate adaptation, assessing carbohydrate partitioning between growth and storage affecting reserve accumulation, and documenting developmental transitions from annual herbaceous to perennial woody growth in grapevine as model woody perennial.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009699 ## phenylpropanoid biosynthetic process | 0.70" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 282-305 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 215-235 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Basal_Shoot_Lignification": {
  "definition": "A Basal_Shoot_Lignification is a Shoot_Lignification comprising the conversion to woody tissue at the basal shoot regions through secondary wall deposition and lignin incorporation.",
  "alternative_term": "basal maturation | lower shoot lignification | shoot base woodification |+ basale Triebverholzung | Triebbasisausreifung | basale Holzbildung | Grundtriebverholzung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows basal shoot lignification from late June through late July at BBCH 31-35 spanning 4-5 weeks, initiating in lowest 3-4 internodes when elongation completes with lignin content increasing to 14-18% dry weight and starch accumulating to 12-16% dry weight creating brown woody basal structure under cool climate conditions of 18-24°C mean temperature, adequate moisture, and moderate fertility typical of this moderate-vigor early-to-mid season cultivar requiring timely maturation for winter survival",
  "editor_note": "Basal_Shoot_Lignification is first of four Shoot_Lignification subphases, distinguished by lignification in oldest shoot regions establishing initial woody structure. ||Represents earliest maturation occurring during mid-summer active growth period. ||Transitions to Progressive_Shoot_Lignification as maturation extends acropetally. ||Critical for establishing stable shoot base and initiating reserve accumulation. ||Timing indicator of vine development status and resource adequacy. || This critical developmental stage occurs in lowest 3-5 internodes of shoot during mid-summer corresponding approximately to flowering through early fruit set period at BBCH 31-35, typically beginning 4-6 weeks after bud burst when basal internodes have completed elongation and cells transition to differentiation and secondary wall synthesis. ||Basal lignification initiation occurs when internode elongation in basal regions completes typically by late May-early June in temperate climates, with cells in vascular tissues, fibers, and adjacent parenchyma beginning secondary wall deposition and lignin biosynthesis transforming primary walled herbaceous tissue to secondary walled woody structure. ||Secondary wall synthesis begins in xylem vessel elements requiring rigid walls for water transport function, with S1, S2, and S3 wall layers depositing with characteristic microfibril orientations providing tensile and compressive strength, followed by lignin monomer synthesis through phenylpropanoid pathway producing p-coumaryl, coniferyl, and sinapyl alcohols. ||Lignin polymerization proceeds through oxidative coupling reactions catalyzed by peroxidases and laccases, creating three-dimensional polymer network that cross-links wall polysaccharides and provides hydrophobic character, with lignin content in basal internodes increasing from negligible to 12-18% dry weight over 3-4 week initial lignification period. ||Lignified tissue extent in basal regions shows progressive expansion from initial vascular tissue lignification extending into surrounding fibers and parenchyma cells, creating increasingly rigid internode structure with brown coloration replacing green as chlorophyll degrades and phenolic compounds accumulate. ||Mechanical property changes during basal lignification include increasing tensile strength from 8-15 MPa in recently completed elongation to 35-60 MPa in substantially lignified tissue, declining flexibility as rigid secondary walls prevent bending, and increasing resistance to compression providing stable base supporting developing shoot. ||Vascular tissue maturation in basal regions includes vascular cambium initiation between primary xylem and phloem, secondary xylem production internally increasing vessel number and water transport capacity to 3-5 mg per second per basal internode, and secondary phloem formation externally enhancing assimilate translocation from photosynthesizing canopy. ||Periderm initiation begins in basal internodes during lignification with cork cambium forming in subepidermal layers, producing cork cells externally creating protective brown bark replacing green epidermis, establishing protective surface layer reducing water loss and providing pathogen barrier. ||Reserve accumulation initiates in basal internodes as lignification proceeds with starch synthesis converting excess photosynthate to storage form, increasing starch concentration from negligible during growth to 10-18% dry weight in basal regions by mid-summer when lignification substantially completes. ||Metabolic transition in basal regions involves declining respiration from growth levels 10-15 fold above dormancy to early maturation levels 4-6 fold above dormancy as growth ceases and maintenance requirements dominate, with continued decline toward dormancy levels as maturation completes. ||Protein composition shifts during basal lignification from growth-related proteins including cell cycle regulators and wall synthesis enzymes to maintenance proteins, storage proteins accumulating in parenchyma cells, and defense proteins providing pathogen resistance. ||Water content in basal internodes declines during lignification from 75-80% fresh weight in recently elongated tissue to 60-65% in substantially lignified tissue, reflecting increased wall material deposition, reduced metabolic activity, and beginning dehydration associated with maturation. ||Nitrogen dynamics show declining concentration in basal tissues from 2.0-2.5% dry weight after elongation to 1.2-1.8% as structural carbohydrates accumulate diluting nitrogen-rich proteins, with mobile nitrogen potentially remobilizing toward active growth regions or storage tissues. ||Hormonal regulation of basal lignification involves declining auxin from reduced apical production and transport as basal regions distance from apex, increasing abscisic acid promoting maturation processes and beginning stress tolerance development, and ethylene possibly involved in coordinating metabolic transitions. ||Temperature affects basal lignification rate with warm mid-summer conditions 22-28°C promoting rapid progression completing substantial lignification within 3-4 weeks, while cooler conditions extend duration though typically not limiting as process proceeds across wide temperature range. ||Light intensity affects basal lignification through effects on whole-shoot photosynthetic production providing carbon for lignin synthesis and reserve accumulation, with adequate light supporting normal progression while extreme shade may limit carbon availability slowing maturation. ||Water availability affects basal lignification with moderate water stress potentially promoting earlier initiation and enhanced progression as stress signals trigger maturation responses, while severe stress may impair processes through limiting photosynthetic production and metabolic function. ||Nutrient availability affects basal lignification with adequate nitrogen supporting normal progression as growth in basal regions has completed and nitrogen requirements shift toward upper shoot zones, while excessive nitrogen may slow lignification prolonging metabolic activity. ||The process typically requires 3-5 weeks from initiation to substantial lignification in basal 3-5 internodes depending on environmental conditions and cultivar characteristics, with warm conditions and moderate stress promoting rapid complete lignification. ||Cultivar variation appears in basal lignification timing with early-maturing varieties showing earlier initiation and rapid progression while late-maturing types show delayed initiation, extent of lignification in basal regions with some varieties showing thorough complete lignification while others maintain less complete maturation, and reserve accumulation intensity affecting basal tissue starch concentrations. ||Regional timing shows basal shoot lignification initiating June-July in warm climates, July in temperate regions, and late July-early August in cool areas, with progression corresponding to summer temperature patterns and shoot growth stage. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing basal lignification as indicator of normal shoot development and resource adequacy, understanding that inadequate basal lignification indicates problems with vine health or excessive late vegetative growth, monitoring lignification progress assessing vine maturation status and dormancy preparation, and ensuring management promotes timely basal maturation through appropriate water and nitrogen management. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms initiating lignification including developmental and environmental signals, quantifying lignin biosynthesis and deposition patterns during maturation, evaluating carbon partitioning between growth and storage during transition periods, assessing environmental effects on maturation timing affecting reserve accumulation and dormancy preparation, and documenting cellular and molecular changes during herbaceous-to-woody tissue transformation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 282-290 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 215-222 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Progressive_Shoot_Lignification": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Shoot_Lignification is a Shoot_Lignification comprising the acropetal advancement of woody conversion from basal through middle shoot regions.",
  "alternative_term": "advancing lignification | upward shoot maturation | acropetal woodification |+ fortschreitende Triebverholzung | aufsteigende Ausreifung | akropetale Holzbildung | progressive Triebausreifung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows progressive shoot lignification from mid-July through early September at BBCH 35-38 over 7-8 weeks, with lignification front advancing at 25-35 mm per week through middle shoot internodes 6-12 achieving lignin content of 18-24% dry weight and starch accumulation of 20-26% dry weight under oceanic climate conditions of 20-26°C temperature range, moderate summer precipitation, and declining nitrogen availability typical of this moderately vigorous mid-season cultivar showing steady maturation progression coordinated with fruit development",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Shoot_Lignification is second of four Shoot_Lignification subphases, distinguished by systematic acropetal advancement of maturation through middle shoot regions. ||Follows Basal_Shoot_Lignification and overlaps with ongoing shoot growth. ||Transitions to Midshoot_Lignification as middle regions complete maturation. ||Represents period of most active maturation progression requiring adequate resources. ||Critical phase determining final extent of thorough lignification and reserve accumulation. || This essential developmental phase occurs during mid-late summer corresponding approximately to fruit set through mid-berry development at BBCH 35-38, typically spanning 6-8 weeks as maturation front progresses from basal completion through middle shoot regions covering internodes 6-12 depending on total shoot length. ||Progressive lignification proceeds through systematic acropetal advancement with each successive internode initiating lignification 3-7 days after previous internode reflecting both temporal sequence of internode formation and developmental program coordinating maturation with resource availability and environmental conditions. ||The lignification front progresses at rate typically 20-40 mm per week corresponding to approximately one internode per week during mid-summer conditions, with rate varying based on temperature, water status, shoot growth rate, and fruit development stage affecting resource partitioning. ||Secondary wall deposition and lignin incorporation in progressively lignifying internodes follows same cellular mechanisms as basal lignification with xylem vessel and fiber lignification proceeding first followed by parenchyma lignification, creating progressive rigidification moving up shoot from brown woody base through transitional zones to green herbaceous apex. ||Lignin content in progressively lignifying internodes increases from negligible to 15-25% dry weight over 2-4 weeks depending on internode position and environmental conditions, with middle internodes often achieving highest lignin concentrations reflecting favorable development conditions during their formation and maturation. ||Mechanical properties develop progressively along shoot creating gradient from fully rigid basal regions through progressively more flexible middle zones to herbaceous apex, with tensile strength increasing from 10-20 MPa in recently lignified regions to 40-80 MPa in fully mature woody tissue. ||Vascular tissue maturation continues in progressively lignifying regions with secondary xylem development from vascular cambium activity increasing vessel number and diameter, enhancing water transport capacity supporting continued shoot function and fruit development, and secondary phloem formation improving assimilate translocation efficiency. ||Periderm development progresses acropetally following lignification with cork cambium formation and cork production creating protective bark layer replacing epidermis, with periderm extent corresponding closely to lignification extent creating visible demarcation between mature brown woody base and immature green herbaceous apex. ||Reserve accumulation intensifies in progressively lignifying regions with starch synthesis converting photosynthate to storage form, increasing starch concentration from 5-10% during early lignification to 18-25% dry weight as lignification completes and growth cessation redirects carbon allocation, with middle internodes often accumulating highest starch concentrations reflecting optimal timing of maturation and resource availability. ||Metabolic transition during progressive lignification shows declining respiration in successively maturing internodes from growth levels to maturation levels 3-5 fold above dormancy then toward maintenance levels 2-3 fold above dormancy, creating metabolic gradient along shoot corresponding to developmental gradient. ||Carbon allocation shifts progressively during this phase from substantial vegetative growth consumption early in period to declining vegetative demand as growth slows, increasing fruit demand as berry development intensifies, and increasing storage allocation as maturation proceeds and growth cessation approaches. ||Shoot water status often shows moderate stress development during progressive lignification period as summer conditions create water limitation, with moderate stress potentially beneficial for promoting maturation and fruit quality development while severe stress risks incomplete lignification and inadequate reserve accumulation. ||Nitrogen dynamics show continuing decline in tissue concentrations as structural carbohydrates accumulate, with nitrogen remobilization from senescing lower leaves potentially supporting fruit development and storage protein synthesis in maturing woody tissues. ||Hormonal regulation involves progressively declining auxin as apical production decreases with growth slowing, increasing abscisic acid from water stress and developmental programming promoting maturation, and possible ethylene involvement in coordinating metabolic transitions and beginning senescence processes. ||Temperature during progressive lignification shows warm mid-late summer conditions generally promoting rapid maturation progression, with optimal 24-28°C supporting efficient lignification and reserve accumulation, while excessive heat above 32°C may stress vines limiting maturation quality. ||Light intensity affects progressive lignification through effects on photosynthetic production supporting both lignin biosynthesis and reserve accumulation, with adequate light essential for complete maturation while canopy shading may limit carbon availability in shaded shoots reducing lignification and storage. ||Water availability shows moderate stress typically developing during this period potentially promoting enhanced maturation through stress-induced developmental responses, while severe sustained stress may impair photosynthetic production limiting lignification completeness and reserve accumulation. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen shows declining requirements as shoot growth slows with adequate but declining availability supporting maturation, while excessive continued nitrogen availability may prolong growth delaying maturation, and severe deficiency may cause premature incomplete maturation. ||The process typically spans 6-8 weeks progressing through middle shoot regions with individual internodes requiring 2-3 weeks for substantial lignification depending on position and conditions, with warm conditions and moderate stress promoting steady progression. ||Cultivar variation appears in progression rate with early-maturing varieties showing rapid steady progression while late-maturing types show slower or interrupted progression, extent of lignification achieved in middle regions with some varieties showing complete thorough lignification while others maintain less complete maturation, and reserve accumulation intensity affecting tissue starch concentrations. ||Regional timing shows progressive shoot lignification occurring July-August in warm climates, July-September in temperate regions, and August-September in cool areas, with progression rate affected by summer temperature patterns and water availability. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring progression rate and extent assessing vine maturation status and resource adequacy, managing water providing moderate stress promoting maturation without excessive limitation impairing function, controlling nitrogen avoiding excessive late availability prolonging growth and delaying maturation, assessing progression uniformity across vineyard identifying areas with inadequate maturation requiring management attention, and recognizing that proper progressive lignification is essential for adequate reserve accumulation supporting subsequent season productivity. ||Research applications include quantifying spatial-temporal patterns of maturation progression and their environmental regulation, analyzing coordination between vegetative maturation and reproductive development affecting resource partitioning, evaluating management strategies optimizing maturation timing and completeness, modeling maturation progression for predicting vine status and dormancy preparation, and assessing implications of maturation patterns for productivity and longevity in perennial grapevine cultivation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 290-298 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 222-230 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Midshoot_Lignification": {
  "definition": "A Midshoot_Lignification is a Shoot_Lignification comprising the complete conversion to woody tissue of internodes in the middle shoot regions.",
  "alternative_term": "middle shoot lignification | peak shoot maturation | central region woodification |+ mittlere Triebverholzung | Mitteltriebausreifung | zentrale Holzbildung | Haupttriebverholzung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows midshoot lignification from early August through mid-September at BBCH 38-41 over 5-6 weeks, with middle internodes 7-11 achieving lignin content of 24-28% dry weight and starch accumulation of 28-32% dry weight representing maximum values along shoot axis under temperate maritime conditions of 19-25°C temperature range declining to 15-20°C by maturation completion, moderate precipitation, and declining nitrogen availability typical of this vigorous mid-season cultivar achieving thorough midshoot maturation supporting strong subsequent season development",
  "editor_note": "Midshoot_Lignification is third of four Shoot_Lignification subphases, distinguished by maturation in middle regions achieving maximum lignification and reserve accumulation. ||Follows Progressive_Shoot_Lignification and may overlap with Complete_Shoot_Lignification in apical regions. ||Represents most critical maturation phase for reserve storage and mechanical support. ||Extent and completeness strongly predict subsequent season vigor and productivity. || This important developmental stage occurs in middle shoot internodes typically positions 6-12 during late summer corresponding to mid-late berry development at BBCH 38-41, with maturation in these regions often achieving most complete lignification and highest reserve concentrations due to favorable timing of development. ||Midshoot internodes often represent longest internodes along shoot reflecting formation during peak growth conditions, requiring proportionally extended maturation period to achieve complete lignification throughout large internode volume, typically 3-4 weeks from lignification initiation to substantial completion. ||Lignification in midshoot regions achieves highest completion levels with lignin content reaching 20-30% dry weight in fully mature middle internodes compared to 15-20% in basal regions and potentially lower concentrations in apical regions depending on maturation timing and environmental conditions. ||Secondary wall deposition shows maximum extent in midshoot regions with vessel elements, fibers, and parenchyma cells all achieving thick secondary walls with extensive lignin incorporation, creating most rigid woody structure along shoot axis providing primary mechanical support and resistance to loading. ||Mechanical properties in fully lignified midshoot regions achieve maximum values with tensile strength 60-100 MPa exceeding basal and apical regions, modulus of elasticity indicating maximum rigidity, and resistance to compression and torsion providing robust mechanical performance. ||Vascular tissue development reaches maximum extent in midshoot regions with secondary xylem production creating numerous large-diameter vessels providing high water transport capacity, and extensive secondary phloem formation supporting efficient bidirectional assimilate movement, with vascular development reflecting importance of middle regions for hydraulic and translocation functions. ||Periderm development achieves complete maturation in midshoot regions with well-developed cork layer providing robust protection, brown bark appearance indicating complete epidermis replacement, and potentially lenticels for gas exchange through otherwise impermeable cork layer. ||Reserve accumulation reaches maximum levels in midshoot regions with starch concentration increasing to 25-35% dry weight in fully mature middle internodes by late summer-autumn, representing highest storage levels along shoot axis and reflecting optimal timing of carbohydrate accumulation when photosynthetic production is high and competing growth demands have ceased. ||Storage lipids also accumulate in parenchyma cells of midshoot regions with oil bodies forming in ray parenchyma cells adjacent to vascular tissues, providing additional energy-dense reserves complementing starch storage. ||Protein storage shows accumulation of storage proteins in parenchyma cells with concentrations reaching 8-12% dry weight in mature woody tissue, providing nitrogen reserves for subsequent season protein synthesis demands during bud burst and early growth. ||Water content in fully lignified midshoot regions declines to 50-55% fresh weight representing lowest levels along shoot axis, reflecting maximum cell wall material deposition, minimal metabolic water requirements, and advanced dehydration in preparation for dormancy. ||Metabolic activity in mature midshoot regions declines to near-maintenance levels with respiration 2-3 fold above completely dormant tissue, minimal protein synthesis focused on maintenance and defense functions, and virtually no growth-related metabolism. ||Cell viability maintains high levels in parenchyma cells of midshoot regions providing living tissue for storage and mobilization functions, while lignified vascular elements are dead at functional maturity serving purely structural and transport roles. ||Bark characteristics in midshoot regions often show distinctive features including color patterns, lenticel distribution, and texture providing cultivar identification characters, with middle shoot bark most representative of variety-specific characteristics. ||Mechanical importance of midshoot regions for shoot architecture includes providing primary bending resistance preventing shoot sagging, torsional resistance preventing twisting under wind loading, and load distribution transferring forces from distal shoot portions and fruit load to proximal attachment points. ||Reserve importance of midshoot regions for subsequent season development includes providing substantial portion of total shoot reserve carbohydrate available for bud burst and early growth, with middle regions often contributing 40-60% of mobilizable starch due to high concentrations and substantial tissue volume. ||Hormonal status in mature midshoot regions shows minimal auxin and gibberellin reflecting complete growth cessation, elevated abscisic acid maintaining maturation and dormancy preparation, and possible accumulation of defense-related hormones including jasmonates and salicylates supporting pathogen resistance. ||Temperature during midshoot lignification typically represents late summer conditions with warm days promoting rapid maturation and cool nights enhancing carbohydrate accumulation, with optimal conditions supporting maximum lignification extent and reserve storage. ||Light intensity affects midshoot lignification through canopy position effects with well-exposed shoots showing complete thorough maturation while shaded shoots may show reduced lignification and reserve accumulation affecting subsequent productivity. ||Water availability shows moderate late-summer stress typically beneficial for promoting complete maturation and enhanced reserve accumulation through stress-induced resource partitioning, while severe stress may limit photosynthetic production reducing storage potential. ||Nutrient availability shows declining nitrogen levels appropriate for maturation with remobilization from senescing leaves providing nitrogen for storage protein synthesis, while excessive nitrogen would impair maturation and reduce reserve accumulation. ||The process typically requires 3-5 weeks for individual midshoot internodes to achieve complete maturation from lignification initiation to maximum reserve accumulation depending on environmental conditions and cultivar characteristics. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum lignification extent achieved in midshoot regions with some varieties showing complete thorough lignification to 28-32% lignin content while others maintain lower levels, maximum reserve concentrations ranging from moderate 20-25% starch to high 30-35% in elite storage cultivars, and timing of maturation completion affecting subsequent dormancy depth and cold hardiness. ||Regional timing shows midshoot lignification occurring late July-August in warm climates, August-September in temperate regions, and September in cool areas, with timing critical for achieving complete maturation before dormancy entry. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing midshoot regions as most important for reserve storage and mechanical support, monitoring maturation completeness in middle zones as indicator of overall vine preparation for dormancy, ensuring management promotes thorough midshoot lignification through appropriate late-season water and nitrogen management, assessing midshoot reserve status through tissue testing informing subsequent season vigor predictions, and understanding that inadequate midshoot maturation severely compromises subsequent productivity and survival. ||Research applications include analyzing regulation of maximum lignification and reserve accumulation including hormonal and metabolic controls, quantifying relationships between maturation extent and subsequent season development capacity, evaluating management effects on midshoot maturation affecting productivity and quality, assessing mechanical properties of mature woody tissue supporting architectural understanding, and documenting reserve dynamics during accumulation and mobilization cycles in perennial plant resource management.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 298-305 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 230-235 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Complete_Shoot_Lignification": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Shoot_Lignification is a Shoot_Lignification comprising woody conversion throughout the entire shoot length from base to apex including apical regions.",
  "alternative_term": "full shoot maturation | total shoot lignification | complete woodification | shoot maturation completion |+ vollständige Triebverholzung | komplette Triebausreifung | totale Holzbildung | Ausreifungsabschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "Riesling in Mosel shows complete shoot lignification from late August through early October at BBCH 41-43 over 5-6 weeks, achieving lignification extending to apical regions with final 3-4 internodes showing lignin content of 14-20% dry weight and starch of 18-24% dry weight, creating fully mature brown woody shoots necessary for winter survival under cool climate conditions of 15-20°C declining to 10-15°C by maturation completion, declining precipitation, and minimal nitrogen availability typical of this moderate-vigor late-season cultivar requiring complete maturation for adequate cold hardiness in continental climate",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Shoot_Lignification is fourth and final Shoot_Lignification subphase, distinguished by maturation extending to apical regions achieving woody structure throughout shoot. ||Represents culmination of entire maturation process. ||Completeness critically determines winter survival, reserve status, and subsequent season vigor potential. ||Timing relative to dormancy entry and first freezes critical in cold climates. ||Assessment of completion status essential management activity at season end. || This culminating developmental stage occurs during late summer-autumn corresponding to late berry development through harvest at BBCH 41-43, with apical regions completing maturation 8-14 weeks after basal initiation depending on cultivar, vigor, and environmental conditions. ||Complete lignification achievement requires successful progression of maturation through all shoot regions including apical internodes that formed latest and had shortest growing season, with apical maturation often most challenging particularly in vigorous cultivars or favorable growing conditions promoting extended late growth. ||Apical shoot lignification proceeds through same cellular processes as earlier regions with secondary wall deposition and lignin incorporation, though apical regions often achieve lower lignin content 12-20% dry weight compared to middle regions 20-30%, reflecting abbreviated maturation period before dormancy entry. ||Lignification extent along shoot shows characteristic gradient from thorough complete lignification in basal regions through maximum values in middle zones to progressively less complete lignification in apical regions, with most apical 2-4 internodes potentially showing incomplete lignification particularly in vigorous shoots or late-season growth. ||Mechanical properties in apically lignified regions show adequate rigidity for winter survival with tensile strength 30-60 MPa sufficient for supporting shoot weight and resisting snow loading, though lower than middle region values reflecting less extensive secondary wall development. ||Reserve accumulation in apical regions proceeds during final maturation period with starch concentrations reaching 15-25% dry weight in successfully matured apical internodes, representing important contribution to whole-shoot reserves though lower than middle region concentrations 25-35%. ||Complete shoot maturation assessment involves evaluating lignification extent typically requiring brown woody appearance throughout shoot with minimal green tissue remaining, adequate rigidity resisting bending with finger pressure, and periderm development complete or nearly complete over entire length. ||Incomplete apical lignification represents common maturation failure particularly in vigorous cultivars, excessive late-season growth, or unfavorable conditions, with unlignified or poorly lignified apical tissue showing green coloration, high flexibility, and susceptibility to winter freeze damage. ||Cold hardiness relationship with lignification shows critical importance of complete maturation for winter survival, with unlignified or poorly lignified apical tissues susceptible to freeze damage at temperatures as mild as -5 to -10°C while fully lignified tissues survive -15 to -25°C depending on cultivar and acclimation, making complete lignification essential in cold-climate viticulture. ||Reserve status at complete lignification represents maximum carbohydrate accumulation for season with whole-shoot starch content 18-28% dry weight in well-matured shoots, providing reserves essential for subsequent season bud burst, initial shoot growth before photosynthesis develops, and root growth resumption. ||Dormancy preparation accompanies complete lignification with metabolic downregulation toward maintenance levels, cold acclimation processes developing freeze tolerance, and water content reduction to 50-60% fresh weight approaching winter dormancy levels. ||Leaf senescence timing shows coordination with shoot lignification completion with leaves typically senescing and abscising during or shortly after final lignification in apical regions, representing coordinated transition to dormancy with nitrogen remobilization from senescing leaves supporting storage protein accumulation in woody tissues. ||Pruning wound healing capacity declines with complete lignification as cambial activity ceases and metabolic activity declines, with pruning ideally delayed until dormancy establishment after complete maturation to minimize disease infection risks. ||Cane quality for subsequent season pruning depends critically on complete lignification with well-matured canes showing brown color throughout length, adequate rigidity, plump appearance from good reserve status, and appropriate diameter 6-12 mm indicating balanced vigor. ||Maturation failure consequences include inadequate reserve accumulation reducing subsequent season bud burst vigor and early growth, increased winter freeze damage risk particularly in cold climates creating bud mortality and cane dieback, delayed spring development from limited reserve availability, and potentially reduced crop potential from winter damage. ||Environmental conditions during final maturation period critically affect completion with warm late summer-autumn promoting continued maturation progression, adequate soil moisture maintaining photosynthetic function supporting reserve accumulation, and moderate water stress promoting growth cessation and enhanced maturation. ||Temperature during complete lignification shows importance of warm conditions for final maturation progression with optimal 18-24°C during September-October in temperate regions, declining temperatures promoting growth cessation and dormancy transition, and absence of early freezes allowing maturation completion before cold damage occurs. ||Light intensity remains important through final maturation period with adequate late-season light supporting continued photosynthetic production for reserve accumulation, canopy management ensuring apical shoot exposure promoting thorough maturation. ||Water availability shows moderate stress beneficial for promoting growth cessation and final maturation without excessive stress limiting photosynthetic reserve production, with irrigation management in late season targeting moderate stress promotion. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen shows declining levels appropriate for maturation with nitrogen management avoiding late-season application that would prolong growth and delay or prevent maturation completion. ||The process timing varies substantially with cultivar maturity characteristics, vigor levels, and environmental conditions, with early-maturing cultivars completing lignification by late August-early September while late-maturing types requiring September-October for completion. ||Cultivar variation appears in maturation timing with early-maturing varieties showing rapid progression to complete lignification while late-maturing types show extended maturation period, apical lignification completeness with some varieties consistently achieving thorough apical maturation while others frequently show incomplete apical lignification affecting winter hardiness, and reserve accumulation capacity affecting dormancy reserve status and subsequent season vigor potential. ||Regional timing shows complete shoot lignification occurring August-September in warm climates, September-October in temperate regions, and September-early October in cool areas with critical importance of completing maturation before significant freezes in cold regions. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring maturation progress through late season assessing completion likelihood before dormancy, implementing management promoting timely growth cessation and complete maturation including water stress management and nitrogen control, assessing maturation completion status at dormancy entry predicting winter survival and subsequent season development potential, selecting cultivars with maturation characteristics appropriate for climate ensuring reliable complete maturation, and understanding that incomplete maturation represents major limitation in cold-climate viticulture requiring management attention. ||Research applications include analyzing factors determining final maturation completeness including genetic and environmental controls, quantifying relationships between maturation extent and winter hardiness across cultivars and climates, evaluating management strategies ensuring reliable complete maturation, modeling maturation progression for predicting completion timing and dormancy preparation, and assessing climate change impacts on maturation patterns affecting winter survival and productivity across viticultural regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 300-315 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 230-245 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Inflorescence_Development": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Development is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the production of inflorescences through primordium initiation in latent buds and post-dormancy elaboration to flowering.",
  "alternative_term": "inflorescence formation | cluster development | reproductive structure development |+ Blütenstandsentwicklung | Gescheinbildung | Infloreszenzenbildung | reproduktive Strukturentwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows inflorescence development spanning two seasons with primordium formation June-August Year N at BBCH 19-35 during active shoot growth establishing architectural framework with 20-35 primary branches per inflorescence under conditions of 22-30°C temperature, adequate light exposure, moderate water stress, followed by winter dormancy requiring 800-1000 chilling hours, and emergence May Year N+1 at BBCH 53-57 producing visible inflorescences that will flower early June, with Year N management critically affecting Year N+1 crop potential in this moderately fruitful late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Development represents fundamental reproductive process spanning two growing seasons from primordium formation through emergence. ||Distinguished from Flowering which represents anthesis and fertilization processes. ||Subdivided into Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation occurring Year N and Inflorescence_Emergence occurring Year N+1. ||Critical determinant of yield potential requiring two-season perspective in management. ||Year N conditions during primordium formation fundamentally affect Year N+1 productivity. || This fundamental reproductive process encompasses primordium formation during previous season typically May-August Year N establishing inflorescence architecture within developing buds, winter dormancy maintaining primordia in arrested state, emergence during bud burst April-May Year N+1 as inflorescences become externally visible, and continued development through flowering preparation. ||Inflorescence development determines crop potential for subsequent season with primordium initiation frequency, branching architecture, and flower number established during Year N affecting yield capacity in Year N+1, making environmental conditions and vine management during primordium formation critically important for subsequent productivity. ||The developmental program follows predictable architectural pattern in most cultivars with inflorescences forming at nodes following two-tendril pattern, typically producing inflorescence at every third node in alternating sequence with tendrils, though pattern varies among cultivars and with vine vigor affecting reproductive versus vegetative allocation. ||Primordium formation begins at shoot apex during active growth in Year N when lateral meristems that could form tendrils instead differentiate toward inflorescence identity, initiating as undifferentiated meristematic protrusions that will elaborate into complex branched structures bearing hundreds to thousands of flower primordia. ||Inflorescence architecture establishment during Year N involves primary axis formation creating main rachis structure, primary branch primordium initiation establishing first-order lateral branches typically 15-40 per inflorescence, secondary branch primordium formation on primary branches creating second-order branching, and flower primordium initiation on branch tips establishing potential flower number. ||Architectural elaboration follows basipetal sequence with apical regions of developing inflorescence primordium initiating structures first and basal regions forming later, creating developmental gradient within primordia that persists through dormancy into emergence and flowering phases. ||Dormancy entry in autumn preserves inflorescence primordia within buds as structured meristematic tissues with architectural organization established but organs incompletely differentiated, with primordia maintaining developmental potential through winter in arrested metabolic state. ||Chilling requirement satisfaction during winter represents essential developmental prerequisite for normal inflorescence development, with inadequate chilling causing poor inflorescence emergence, irregular flowering, and reduced fruit set affecting productivity. ||Emergence phase following bud burst in spring Year N+1 reveals inflorescence structures developing within buds, with inflorescences becoming externally visible as small compact clusters initially enclosed by expanding leaves, then elongating and expanding as flowering approaches. ||Inflorescence position within shoot architecture shows consistent pattern with typically first two nodes producing inflorescences in fruitful shoots following architectural program, though fruitfulness varies with cultivar, bud position, vine vigor, and previous season conditions affecting primordium formation. ||Developmental timing shows characteristic two-season progression with primordium formation requiring 6-12 weeks during Year N vegetative growth, dormancy spanning 4-6 months maintaining primordia in arrested state, and emergence-to-flowering requiring 4-6 weeks during Year N+1 spring depending on temperature accumulation. ||Environmental conditions during both seasons critically affect development with Year N conditions during primordium formation determining inflorescence number, architecture, and flower number potential, and Year N+1 conditions during emergence affecting developmental success, uniformity, and flowering quality. ||Temperature represents primary environmental factor affecting development with optimal 22-28°C during Year N primordium formation supporting maximum inflorescence initiation and architectural elaboration, chilling accumulation during winter affecting dormancy release and subsequent development, and spring temperatures in Year N+1 determining emergence rate and flowering timing. ||Light intensity during Year N primordium formation affects inflorescence initiation with adequate light promoting reproductive development while shade reduces fruitfulness shifting allocation toward vegetative growth, affecting subsequent season yield potential. ||Water availability during Year N affects inflorescence formation with moderate water stress potentially promoting reproductive allocation while severe stress reduces primordium formation, and Year N+1 water status affecting emergence and development quality. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen during Year N affects reproductive versus vegetative allocation with moderate nitrogen supporting good inflorescence formation while excessive nitrogen promotes vegetative growth reducing fruitfulness, affecting yield potential. ||Hormonal regulation involves gibberellins with low concentrations promoting reproductive development and high concentrations favoring vegetative growth affecting inflorescence versus tendril determination, cytokinins potentially promoting inflorescence initiation and flower number, and other hormones coordinating developmental transitions. ||The process shows multiple distinguishable phases based on developmental stage and season, progressing from inflorescence primordium formation in Year N through dormancy maintenance to emergence in Year N+1, with each phase critical for successful development. ||Cultivar variation appears in fruitfulness with number of inflorescences per shoot ranging from 0-1 in low-fruitfulness varieties to 2-3 in highly fruitful types, inflorescence architecture affecting cluster size and structure, flower number per inflorescence determining berry number potential, and chilling requirements affecting development success in different climates. ||Regional timing shows primordium formation during June-August in warm climates, July-September in temperate regions, and July-August in cool areas of Year N, with emergence occurring April-May in warm climates, May in temperate regions, and May-June in cool areas of Year N+1. ||Viticultural management considerations include understanding that current season conditions affect next season productivity requiring forward-looking management, maintaining adequate but not excessive vigor during primordium formation optimizing reproductive allocation, ensuring sufficient light exposure promoting inflorescence initiation, managing water and nitrogen supporting balanced vegetative-reproductive development, and recognizing that primordium formation represents critical determinant of subsequent yield potential. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating reproductive versus vegetative organ identity determination, investigating environmental and hormonal controls of inflorescence architecture affecting yield components, evaluating management effects on primordium formation influencing subsequent productivity, quantifying relationships between Year N conditions and Year N+1 yield outcomes, and assessing genetic variation in inflorescence development affecting productivity across environments.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0048281 ## inflorescence morphogenesis | 0.85" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 315-345 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 245-275 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation is an Inflorescence_Development comprising the differentiation of lateral meristems within latent buds toward inflorescence identity and the elaboration of branched architecture establishing flower number potential.",
  "alternative_term": "inflorescence initiation | cluster primordium formation | inflorescence organogenesis |+ Blütenstandsprimordienbildung | Gescheinsanlagebildung | Infloreszenzinitiierung | Blütenstandsorganogenese",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows inflorescence primordium formation during July-August Year N at BBCH 19-35 within developing latent buds over 8-10 weeks, initiating 1-2 inflorescence primordia per bud with 18-28 primary branches per inflorescence and 200-400 flower primordia under conditions of 20-26°C temperature, adequate light exposure in well-managed canopy, moderate water stress, and balanced nitrogen fertility typical of this moderately fruitful early-to-mid season cultivar, establishing architectural framework determining Year N+1 crop potential",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation is first major subphase of Inflorescence_Development, occurring entirely during Year N vegetative growth period. ||Distinguished by primordium elaboration within latent buds establishing architectural framework. ||Subdivided into Initial_Inflorescence_Primordium, Inflorescence_Meristem_Differentiation, Primary_Branch_Primordium_Formation, and Secondary_Branch_Primordium_Formation. ||Followed by dormancy then Inflorescence_Emergence in Year N+1. ||Critical determinant of subsequent crop potential. || This critical developmental process occurs within developing latent buds during summer Year N, typically spanning 6-12 weeks from initial primordium initiation through architectural elaboration to dormancy entry, establishing inflorescence structures that will remain dormant through winter and emerge during bud burst Year N+1. ||Primordium formation begins at shoot apex in primary bud meristems during active vegetative growth typically June-August in temperate regions Year N, when lateral meristems at positions following architectural pattern differentiate toward reproductive rather than vegetative tendril identity. ||Inflorescence identity determination involves suppression of tendril developmental program and activation of reproductive meristem identity genes, with environmental signals including light quality and quantity, water status, nitrogen availability, and hormonal balance particularly gibberellin concentrations affecting reproductive versus vegetative fate decisions. ||Initial primordium development shows undifferentiated meristematic protrusion emerging from primary bud axis in lateral position opposite leaf primordium, similar in early stages to tendril primordium but diverging through differential gene expression activating inflorescence-specific developmental programs. ||Inflorescence meristem differentiation transforms initial undifferentiated primordium into organized inflorescence meristem with distinct zones including apical zone maintaining indeterminate growth capacity and lateral zones producing branch primordia, establishing architectural organization that will guide subsequent development. ||Primary branch primordium formation proceeds basipetally from inflorescence apex with lateral meristems initiating along primary axis in regular phyllotactic pattern, typically producing 15-40 primary branch primordia per inflorescence depending on cultivar and development conditions, with branch initiation establishing first-order architectural framework. ||Secondary branch primordium formation occurs on primary branch primordia creating second-order branching structure, with secondary branches varying from absent in simple inflorescence architectures to numerous in highly compound structures, determining inflorescence complexity and ultimate flower number capacity. ||Flower primordium initiation begins on branch tips during late primordium formation phase, with individual flower primordia developing as small meristematic protrusions that will differentiate into complete flowers during following season, with flower number per inflorescence ranging from 100-200 in small clusters to 500-1500 in large compound inflorescences. ||Architectural organization within developing primordium shows basipetal gradient with apical regions most advanced in development containing initiated flower primordia while basal regions show progressively earlier stages with recently formed branch primordia, creating developmental heterogeneity persisting through dormancy into emergence and flowering. ||Developmental timing within season shows progression from inflorescence identity determination occurring as early as node formation at shoot apex, through rapid primordium elaboration over 4-8 weeks as architectural elements initiate, to final maturation and dormancy entry as shoot growth declines in late summer-autumn. ||Cell division rates during active primordium formation show high mitotic activity supporting rapid organ initiation, with divisions occurring every 24-48 hours in meristematic zones producing cells for expanding primordial structures. ||Vascular connection establishment between developing inflorescence primordium and bud axis occurs early in formation providing pathway for nutrient and hormone delivery supporting primordium development, though transport is minimal during dormancy maintaining primordia through stored reserves. ||Metabolic activity during primordium formation shows elevated respiration supporting growth processes, declining to minimal maintenance levels as primordia mature and enter dormancy. ||Hormonal regulation centrally involves gibberellins with low endogenous concentrations or exogenous application of anti-gibberellins promoting inflorescence formation while high gibberellin levels favor tendril formation, cytokinins potentially promoting inflorescence initiation and branching affecting architecture, and auxin coordinating meristem activity and organ positioning. ||Environmental factors during formation critically affect developmental outcomes with light intensity and quality strongly affecting reproductive allocation through photosynthetic production and photomorphogenic signaling, with shade reducing fruitfulness shifting toward vegetative growth. ||Temperature during primordium formation shows optimal range 22-28°C supporting maximum inflorescence initiation and architectural elaboration, with suboptimal temperatures reducing reproductive allocation. ||Water status affects primordium formation with moderate water stress during formation period potentially enhancing reproductive allocation as stress response promoting reproduction, while severe stress reduces primordium formation through limitation of metabolic resources. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen shows complex effects with moderate nitrogen supporting good primordium formation providing resources for development, while excessive nitrogen promotes vegetative growth reducing reproductive allocation, requiring balanced nutrition for optimal fruitfulness. ||Carbon availability from photosynthesis affects primordium formation with adequate carbohydrate production supporting reproductive development, while carbon limitation from excessive crop load, disease, or stress reduces formation affecting subsequent productivity. ||Canopy microclimate affects primordium formation with well-exposed shoots showing higher fruitfulness through favorable light environment promoting reproductive development, while shaded interior shoots show reduced inflorescence formation shifting toward vegetative growth. ||Shoot vigor affects primordium formation with moderate vigor supporting optimal reproductive allocation, while excessive vigor promotes vegetative growth reducing fruitfulness and insufficient vigor limits formation through resource constraints. ||Node position affects primordium formation with basal nodes typically most fruitful having optimal development conditions, middle nodes moderately fruitful, and apical nodes often unfruitful formed late under declining conditions. ||The process shows four distinguishable developmental phases progressing from initial inflorescence primordium initiation establishing reproductive identity, through inflorescence meristem differentiation organizing architectural framework, primary branch formation establishing first-order structure, to secondary branch formation completing architectural elaboration. ||Cultivar variation appears in fruitfulness with inflorescence initiation frequency at nodes ranging from low fruitfulness producing inflorescences at few nodes to high fruitfulness at most nodes, inflorescence architecture ranging from simple with few branches to highly compound with extensive branching, and flower number per inflorescence determining berry number potential. ||Regional timing shows inflorescence primordium formation during June-August in warm climates, July-September in temperate regions, and July-August in cool areas corresponding to active vegetative growth period when conditions favor primordium formation. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing that current season management affects next season crop potential requiring forward planning, maintaining moderate balanced vigor optimizing reproductive allocation, ensuring adequate light exposure through canopy management promoting inflorescence formation, managing water and nitrogen supporting reproductive development without excessive vegetative growth, controlling crop load allowing adequate resources for primordium formation, and understanding that conditions during primordium formation represent critical determinant of subsequent yield. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of reproductive versus vegetative organ identity specification, investigating environmental and hormonal regulation of inflorescence architecture, evaluating management effects on primordium formation affecting yield outcomes, quantifying developmental processes within primordia documenting architectural elaboration, and assessing genetic variation in inflorescence development affecting productivity potential across cultivars and environments.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 315-328 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Srinivasan C & Mullins MG (1981) Physiology of flowering in the grapevine, Am J Enol Vitic 32:47-63"
},

  "Initial_Inflorescence_Primordium": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Inflorescence_Primordium is an Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation comprising the first commitment of an undifferentiated lateral meristem at the bud apex to inflorescence identity and its emergence as a distinct meristematic protrusion.",
  "alternative_term": "primordium initiation | initial inflorescence meristem | early inflorescence formation | reproductive primordium emergence |+ initiales Blütenstandsprimordium | Primordieninitiierung | frühe Gescheinsanlage | reproduktives Primordium",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows initial inflorescence primordium formation during early July Year N at BBCH 19-31 at shoot apex within developing latent buds, with undifferentiated meristematic protrusions of 40-60 micrometers emerging at 2-3 basal node positions over 10-14 days under conditions of 20-24°C temperature, adequate light exposure in managed canopy, balanced nitrogen fertility, and moderate water availability typical of this moderately-to-highly fruitful early-bursting cultivar, establishing reproductive commitment for Year N+1 productivity",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Inflorescence_Primordium is first of four Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation subphases, distinguished by earliest recognizable reproductive primordium emergence before architectural elaboration. ||Represents commitment to reproductive rather than vegetative tendril development. ||Transitions to Inflorescence_Meristem_Differentiation as architectural organization develops. ||Critical stage determining formation frequency and fruitfulness. ||Highly sensitive to environmental conditions and hormonal signals. || This critical developmental stage occurs at shoot apex during active growth Year N typically June-July in temperate regions, representing first 7-14 days of inflorescence development from identity determination through initial protrusion formation before architectural elaboration begins. ||Primordium initiation occurs at lateral position on primary bud axis opposite developing leaf primordium, following architectural pattern with inflorescence primordia forming at positions alternating with tendril primordia in regular sequence. ||Inflorescence identity determination involves molecular switches suppressing tendril developmental genes and activating reproductive meristem identity genes including homologs of LEAFY, APETALA1, and other floral identity genes, with identity commitment representing irreversible developmental decision under normal conditions. ||Initial primordium appearance shows small meristematic protrusion measuring 30-80 micrometers diameter emerging from bud axis, containing 50-200 actively dividing cells with organized meristem structure including peripheral zone producing organ primordia and central zone maintaining stem cells. ||Cell division during initial primordium stage shows high mitotic activity with cycles of 24-36 hours producing cells contributing to primordium growth and preparing for subsequent architectural elaboration, with division rates highest in peripheral zones where branch primordia will initiate. ||Morphological characteristics at this stage show undifferentiated dome or cone-shaped structure lacking recognizable architectural features that will develop during subsequent stages, appearing similar to early tendril primordia requiring molecular markers or developmental tracking for definitive identification. ||Gene expression patterns during initial primordium stage show activation of reproductive identity genes suppressing vegetative tendril program, expression of meristem maintenance genes sustaining stem cell populations, and beginning expression of architectural patterning genes that will guide branching development. ||Hormonal environment during initiation shows low gibberellin concentrations permitting or promoting reproductive identity with exogenous gibberellin application or high endogenous levels capable of converting inflorescence primordia to tendrils demonstrating hormonal control of organ identity, while cytokinin presence supports meristematic activity and initial growth. ||Environmental signals affecting initiation include light quality with high red: far-red ratio and adequate light intensity promoting reproductive development, photoperiod potentially affecting reproductive allocation in some genotypes, and temperature within optimal growth range supporting active meristem function. ||Carbon availability affects initiation with adequate photosynthetic production providing resources for primordium formation, while carbon limitation from stress or excessive sink competition reduces initiation frequency affecting fruitfulness. ||Nitrogen status influences initiation with moderate nitrogen supporting primordium formation while excessive nitrogen promotes vegetative tendril formation, requiring balanced nutrition for optimal reproductive allocation. ||Water status may influence initiation with moderate water stress during this period potentially promoting reproductive development as adaptive response, while severe stress inhibits meristem activity reducing formation. ||Vascular connection initiation begins during early primordium stage with procambial cells establishing strand connecting primordium base to bud vascular system, providing pathway for nutrient and hormone delivery though transport is minimal at this early stage. ||Developmental commitment during initial primordium stage establishes trajectory toward inflorescence development that normally proceeds through subsequent architectural elaboration stages, though severe stress or experimental manipulation can cause abortion or reversion affecting final primordium number. ||Timing within season shows initial primordium formation occurring relatively early during shoot growth typically when shoot has 10-15 nodes and continues active elongation, with primordium formation in basal bud positions preceding apical positions following basipetal bud maturation sequence. ||Developmental duration of initial primordium stage spans approximately 7-14 days from first recognizable emergence to transition toward architectural elaboration with branch primordium initiation, with duration varying based on temperature and growth rate. ||Position effects show basal node buds initiating inflorescence primordia earliest and most reliably showing highest fruitfulness, while middle node buds form primordia during mid-season with moderate fruitfulness, and apical node buds may fail to form or show delayed reduced primordia reflecting declining conditions. ||Metabolic activity during initial primordium stage shows elevated respiration supporting cell division and growth, high protein synthesis producing cell cycle proteins and regulatory factors, and active nucleic acid synthesis supporting rapid cell proliferation. ||Temperature during initiation shows optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum formation frequency and rapid development, with suboptimal temperatures reducing formation or slowing development affecting subsequent architectural elaboration. ||The process represents first distinguishable stage of inflorescence primordium formation marking commitment to reproductive development, transitioning to inflorescence meristem differentiation as architectural organization develops. ||Cultivar variation appears in initiation frequency determining fruitfulness with highly fruitful cultivars forming primordia at most bud positions while low fruitfulness types show sparse formation, timing of initiation affecting developmental window, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting formation reliability. ||Regional timing shows initial inflorescence primordium formation during late June-July in warm climates, July-early August in temperate regions, and July-August in cool areas corresponding to active shoot growth period when conditions support reproductive allocation. ||Viticultural significance includes representing first commitment to reproductive development with management during this period critically affecting formation frequency, understanding that conditions promoting balanced growth without excessive vigor favor initiation, and recognizing that stress or resource limitations during initiation can reduce fruitfulness affecting subsequent yield. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of reproductive identity determination and commitment, investigating hormonal and environmental regulation of inflorescence versus tendril fate decisions, documenting earliest stages of reproductive organogenesis through microscopic and molecular techniques, evaluating factors affecting initiation frequency and their implications for fruitfulness, and assessing genetic variation in reproductive commitment affecting productivity across cultivars.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Srinivasan C & Mullins MG (1981) Physiology of flowering in the grapevine, Am J Enol Vitic 32:47-63"
},

  "Inflorescence_Meristem_Differentiation": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Meristem_Differentiation is an Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation comprising the development of an organized inflorescence meristem with distinct functional zones from the initial primordium.",
  "alternative_term": "meristem organization | inflorescence meristem structuring | reproductive meristem patterning |+ Blütenstandsmeristem-Differenzierung | Meristemorganisation | reproduktive Meristemstrukturierung | Infloreszenzmeristem-Musterbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows inflorescence meristem differentiation during mid-July Year N at BBCH 25-31 within developing latent buds over 10-12 days, with initial 60-80 micrometer primordia developing organized meristem structure with distinct zonal organization reaching 180-220 micrometers establishing framework for 22-32 primary branches under conditions of 22-26°C temperature, adequate light in well-exposed canopy, balanced fertility, and moderate water status typical of this moderately fruitful mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Meristem_Differentiation is second of four Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation subphases, distinguished by establishment of organized meristem structure with functional zoning. ||Follows Initial_Inflorescence_Primordium. ||Transitions to Primary_Branch_Primordium_Formation as branch initiation begins. ||Establishes architectural framework determining subsequent elaboration capacity. ||Critical organizational stage affecting ultimate inflorescence complexity. || This critical organizational stage occurs within developing latent bud during mid-summer Year N typically 1-2 weeks after initial primordium emergence, spanning approximately 7-14 days as meristem structure and zoning patterns establish before branch primordium initiation begins. ||Meristem organization development involves establishment of distinct zones within growing primordium including apical central zone maintaining indeterminate meristematic identity and stem cell populations, peripheral zone producing lateral organ primordia including branch initiation sites, and rib zone generating primary axis tissues extending primordium length. ||Central zone establishment maintains population of slowly dividing stem cells expressing meristem identity genes including WUSCHEL and CLAVATA homologs, providing reservoir of uncommitted cells sustaining continued meristem activity during architectural elaboration. ||Peripheral zone organization shows higher cell division rates producing cells that will form lateral branch primordia, with spatial patterning establishing regular arrangement of initiation sites along developing primary axis determining ultimate branch number and distribution. ||Meristem shape transitions from initial rounded or dome structure to increasingly elongated form as primary axis extends, creating characteristic inflorescence primordium morphology distinguishing reproductive from vegetative organ development. ||Cell division patterns show highest rates in peripheral zones where branch primordia will initiate at 24-36 hour cycles, moderate rates in central zone maintaining meristem at 36-48 hour cycles, and lower rates in maturing rib zone tissues forming primary axis at 48-72 hour cycles. ||Gene expression patterns during differentiation include sustained expression of reproductive identity genes maintaining inflorescence character, activation of meristem organization genes establishing zonal structure including SHOOTMERISTEMLESS and KNOTTED1 homologs, and beginning expression of auxin response genes involved in lateral organ positioning. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin gradients establishing positions where branch primordia will initiate with local auxin maxima marking future branch sites, cytokinins maintaining meristem activity and supporting cell division, and low gibberellin levels permitting reproductive development rather than reverting to vegetative tendril formation. ||Morphological landmarks appearing during differentiation include elongation of primordium from initial 80-120 micrometers to 150-250 micrometers establishing primary axis framework, beginning surface irregularities marking future branch initiation sites though distinct branch primordia not yet emerged, and increased primordium complexity distinguishing from simpler tendril primordium structure. ||Vascular tissue development begins within differentiating meristem with procambial strands extending through developing primary axis, establishing vascular framework that will supply developing branches and eventually flowers, though actual differentiation to functional xylem and phloem occurs later. ||Developmental rate during differentiation shows temperature dependence with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid progression completing differentiation within 7-10 days, cooler temperatures extending duration to 12-16 days, affecting overall developmental window available for architectural elaboration. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated during differentiation supporting high cell division rates and growth, with respiration 10-15 fold above mature tissue levels providing energy for rapid development. ||Protein synthesis operates at high capacity producing cell cycle regulators, transcription factors controlling zonal organization, and structural proteins supporting primordium growth and organization. ||Architectural commitment during differentiation establishes framework determining ultimate inflorescence structure with meristem organization patterns affecting branch number potential, though actual branch formation occurs in subsequent stage. ||Environmental conditions during differentiation affect organizational quality with adequate light supporting normal meristem differentiation, appropriate temperature maintaining optimal developmental rate, and sufficient resources enabling complete organization establishing robust architectural framework. ||Canopy position affects differentiation with exposed shoots showing more robust meristem organization supporting higher branch numbers, while shaded shoots may show reduced differentiation limiting architectural complexity. ||Stress during differentiation can impair organizational processes reducing subsequent branching potential or causing developmental abnormalities affecting inflorescence architecture and flower number. ||Cultivar differences in meristem organization may affect subsequent architectural development with some varieties showing early establishment of numerous branch initiation sites supporting compound inflorescence architecture while others show fewer sites determining simpler structure. ||The process represents second distinguishable stage of inflorescence primordium formation following initial primordium emergence and preceding branch primordium formation, establishing organized reproductive meristem structure. ||Timing within season shows differentiation occurring mid-late summer approximately July-August in temperate regions following initial primordium formation and during continued active shoot growth, with timing varying based on cultivar and environmental conditions. ||Duration of differentiation stage spans approximately 7-14 days from beginning of zonal organization to emergence of first branch primordia, with duration varying based on temperature and developmental rate. ||Regional timing shows inflorescence meristem differentiation during July-August in warm climates, August in temperate regions, and late July-August in cool areas corresponding to mid-summer period following primordium initiation. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing organizational framework determining subsequent architectural elaboration potential, understanding that conditions during differentiation affect ultimate inflorescence complexity and flower number capacity, and recognizing that stress during differentiation can permanently limit reproductive potential. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of meristem organization and zonal patterning, investigating gene regulatory networks controlling inflorescence meristem identity and structure, documenting cellular and developmental processes during meristem differentiation through microscopy and molecular techniques, evaluating environmental effects on meristem organization affecting architectural outcomes, and assessing genetic variation in meristem organization affecting inflorescence structure across cultivars.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Srinivasan C & Mullins MG (1981) Physiology of flowering in the grapevine, Am J Enol Vitic 32:47-63 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Primary_Branch_Primordium_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Primary_Branch_Primordium_Formation is an Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation comprising the initiation of first-order lateral branch primordia from the organized inflorescence meristem establishing the compound architecture characteristic of the grapevine inflorescence.",
  "alternative_term": "primary branch initiation | first-order branch formation | primary branching |+ Primärzweig-Primordienbildung | Erstordnungsverzweigung | primäre Blütenstandsverzweigung | Hauptzweigbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows primary branch primordium formation during late July-August Year N at BBCH 27-35 within developing latent buds over 3-4 weeks, with organized inflorescence meristems initiating 24-34 primary branch primordia in basipetal sequence along elongating axis reaching 500-700 micrometers length under conditions of 24-28°C temperature, high light exposure in well-managed canopy, moderate water stress, and balanced nutrition typical of this moderately-to-highly fruitful mid-to-late season cultivar establishing compound inflorescence architecture",
  "editor_note": "Primary_Branch_Primordium_Formation is third of four Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation subphases, distinguished by first-order branch initiation establishing major architectural framework. ||Follows Inflorescence_Meristem_Differentiation. ||May overlap with Secondary_Branch_Primordium_Formation as early-formed primary branches begin producing secondary branches. ||Primary determinant of inflorescence complexity and flower number capacity. ||Critical phase requiring adequate resources and favorable conditions. || This essential developmental stage occurs within developing latent bud during mid-late summer Year N following meristem differentiation, typically spanning 2-4 weeks as primary branch primordia initiate sequentially along elongating inflorescence axis producing 15-40 primary branches depending on cultivar and developmental conditions. ||Branch initiation proceeds basipetally from inflorescence apex with branch primordia emerging from peripheral zone of inflorescence meristem in regular phyllotactic pattern, typically spiral arrangement with divergence angles of 135-140 degrees creating characteristic branching geometry. ||Primary branch primordium emergence shows local cell division acceleration in peripheral meristem zone creating meristematic protrusion 20-40 micrometers diameter, with each primordium containing 20-50 actively dividing cells that will elaborate into branch structure bearing secondary branches and flowers. ||Branch number determination depends on inflorescence meristem activity duration and axis elongation rate, with longer activity period and greater elongation producing more branch initiation sites increasing total primary branch number, while shortened development reduces branch number affecting cluster architecture. ||Temporal sequence shows branch initiation beginning at inflorescence apex when primordium reaches 150-200 micrometers length, proceeding basipetally as axis elongates with successive branches initiating at 1-2 day intervals during peak development, continuing for 2-4 weeks until axis elongation ceases and basal branch initiation completes. ||Developmental gradient within elaborating inflorescence shows most advanced development at apex where early-formed branches begin developing their own secondary branching, intermediate development in middle regions with recently formed primary branches, and least development at base where final primary branches are just initiating. ||Branch primordium development following initiation involves continued cell division increasing primordium size to 50-100 micrometers over 5-10 days, beginning establishment of branch meristem organization, and preparation for subsequent secondary branch formation or flower initiation depending on position and architecture. ||Inflorescence axis elongation accompanies primary branch formation extending from initial 200-300 micrometers to final 400-800 micrometers by completion of primary branching, with elongation creating spatial framework distributing branch attachment points along axis length. ||Cell division rates during active primary branch formation show highest activity in branch initiation zones with cycles of 20-30 hours, moderate activity in elongating axis with 30-40 hour cycles, and maintained activity in apical meristem with 24-36 hour cycles. ||Gene expression patterns include sustained reproductive identity genes maintaining inflorescence character, auxin response genes showing local maxima at branch initiation sites, and meristem maintenance genes in developing branch primordia establishing branch identity. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin transport establishing concentration patterns that mark and drive branch initiation sites with polar auxin transport creating spatial organization, cytokinins supporting cell division in initiating branches and maintaining meristem activity, and continued low gibberellins permitting reproductive development. ||Environmental factors affecting primary branch formation include light intensity with adequate light supporting maximum branch initiation frequency producing highly compound inflorescences while shade reduces branching creating simpler architecture, temperature within optimal 24-28°C range supporting rapid sequential branch initiation, and adequate resources enabling complete branching pattern development. ||Canopy microclimate strongly affects branching with well-exposed shoots showing robust primary branch formation producing 25-40 branches creating large compound inflorescences, while shaded interior shoots show reduced branching with 10-20 branches producing smaller simpler clusters. ||Metabolic demands during primary branch formation intensify as multiple developing structures require resources simultaneously, with respiration increasing to support elevated cell division rates throughout elaborating inflorescence primordium. ||Carbon availability affects branching with adequate photosynthetic production supporting full branching potential while limitation reduces branch number affecting ultimate cluster size and flower number. ||Nitrogen availability influences branching with moderate nitrogen supporting good branch formation while deficiency may reduce branching and excess may alter development through effects on overall plant vigor. ||Water status may affect branching with moderate stress potentially acceptable though severe stress during this critical elaboration period can reduce branching affecting yield potential. ||Architectural diversity among cultivars reflects differences in primary branch formation with highly compound varieties producing 30-40 primary branches creating large dense clusters, moderately compound types producing 20-30 branches with intermediate structure, and simply branched varieties showing 10-20 branches creating loose small clusters. ||The process represents third distinguishable stage of inflorescence primordium formation following meristem differentiation and preceding secondary branch formation, establishing primary architectural framework determining cluster structure. ||Duration spans approximately 2-4 weeks depending on developmental rate and cultivar branching characteristics, with warm conditions promoting rapid completion while cooler temperatures extend period. ||Completion timing shows primary branch formation finishing typically late July-August in temperate regions Year N as shoot growth declines and developmental activity in buds decreases preparing for dormancy entry. ||Regional timing shows primary branch primordium formation during late July-August in warm climates, August-early September in temperate regions, and August in cool areas corresponding to mid-late summer period when adequate resources remain available for inflorescence elaboration. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing primary architectural framework determining cluster size and structure affecting yield capacity and quality attributes, understanding that conditions during branch formation critically affect subsequent productivity, recognizing that management supporting adequate but not excessive vigor promotes optimal branching, and appreciating that stress during branching can permanently reduce cluster size affecting yield. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating branch initiation frequency and spatial patterning, investigating hormonal and genetic control of inflorescence branching architecture, quantifying environmental effects on branching affecting yield components, evaluating relationships between primary branching and ultimate flower number, and assessing genetic variation in branching patterns affecting cluster architecture and productivity across cultivars.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Srinivasan C & Mullins MG (1981) Physiology of flowering in the grapevine, Am J Enol Vitic 32:47-63"
},

  "Secondary_Branch_Primordium_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Secondary_Branch_Primordium_Formation is an Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation comprising the initiation of second-order lateral branch primordia from primary branch primordia, establishing the higher-order compound architecture of the grapevine inflorescence.",
  "alternative_term": "secondary branch initiation | second-order branch formation | higher-order branching |+ Sekundärzweig-Primordienbildung | Zweitordnungsverzweigung | sekundäre Blütenstandsverzweigung | höhere Verzweigungsordnung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows secondary branch primordium formation during late August-early September Year N at BBCH 33-38 within developing latent buds over 2-3 weeks, with 20-30 primary branch primordia initiating 2-5 secondary branches each particularly on distal primary branches producing total flower primordium number of 400-800 per inflorescence before dormancy entry under conditions of 18-24°C declining temperature, adequate late-season moisture, maintained canopy function, and balanced fertility typical of this moderately-to-highly compound mid-season cultivar establishing complex architecture determining Year N+1 yield capacity",
  "editor_note": "Secondary_Branch_Primordium_Formation is fourth and final Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation subphase, distinguished by second-order branching completing architectural elaboration. ||Follows or overlaps with Primary_Branch_Primordium_Formation. ||Represents final developmental stage before dormancy entry. ||Major determinant of inflorescence complexity and flower number. ||Vulnerable to late-season stress or premature dormancy induction. ||Completion critical for maximum yield potential. || This final architectural developmental stage occurs within developing latent bud during late summer-early autumn Year N following or overlapping with primary branch formation, typically spanning 2-3 weeks as secondary branch primordia initiate on progressively maturing primary branches before dormancy entry arrests development. ||Secondary branch initiation proceeds on primary branch primordia beginning with earliest-formed apical branches and progressing basipetally as successive primary branches mature to appropriate developmental stage, creating temporal and spatial gradient of secondary branching development within elaborating inflorescence primordium. ||Branch initiation mechanism on primary branches resembles primary branch formation from inflorescence axis, with local cell division acceleration in peripheral zone of primary branch meristem creating meristematic protrusion 15-30 micrometers diameter that will develop into secondary branch bearing flower primordia. ||Secondary branch number per primary branch varies substantially with cultivar architecture and developmental conditions, ranging from 0-2 in simply branched varieties creating relatively simple loose clusters to 3-8 in highly compound varieties producing large dense clusters, with secondary branching representing major determinant of cluster complexity. ||Architectural diversity among cultivars reflects differences in secondary branching with some varieties showing minimal or no secondary branching producing primary-branch-only architecture, others showing moderate secondary branching on distal primary branches creating intermediate complexity, and highly compound types showing extensive secondary branching throughout inflorescence creating maximum complexity. ||Flower primordium initiation begins on branch tips during or following secondary branch formation, with individual flower primordia emerging as small meristematic protrusions 10-20 micrometers that will remain undifferentiated through dormancy and complete flower development during Year N+1, with flower number determined by total number of branch tips established during architectural elaboration. ||Total flower number potential per inflorescence results from multiplicative architecture with primary branch number multiplied by average secondary branch number per primary branch multiplied by average flower number per branch tip, typically yielding 100-400 flowers in small simple architectures to 500-1500 flowers in large compound structures. ||Developmental timing shows secondary branch formation occurring relatively late in primordium elaboration typically late August-September in temperate regions Year N, with timing constrained by need to complete before dormancy entry as declining temperatures and photoperiod trigger growth cessation. ||Completion urgency creates vulnerability with late-season stress or early dormancy induction potentially interrupting secondary branch formation before completion, reducing final branching extent and flower number affecting yield capacity. ||Inflorescence primordium size at completion of secondary branching reaches maximum dimensions of 600-1200 micrometers length and 300-600 micrometers width depending on cultivar architecture, representing fully elaborated structure containing complete branching framework and initial flower primordia though organs remain undifferentiated. ||Cell division activity declines progressively during secondary branch formation as developmental program approaches completion and dormancy preparation begins, with final cell divisions occurring in latest-forming branch primordia and flower initiation sites before complete arrest. ||Gene expression changes during late primordium elaboration show declining reproductive development genes as architectural program completes, increasing dormancy-related genes preparing for winter arrest including DORMANCY ASSOCIATED genes and cold acclimation genes, and maintained meristem identity genes preserving developmental potential through dormancy. ||Hormonal regulation during late elaboration shows declining growth-promoting hormones including auxin and cytokinin as activity reduces, increasing abscisic acid promoting dormancy preparation, and maintained low gibberellins preserving reproductive identity through dormancy. ||Metabolic transition during completion shows declining respiration from peak elaboration levels toward dormancy maintenance levels, reduced protein synthesis shifting from growth-related to storage and protective proteins, and beginning carbohydrate accumulation in bud scales and axis tissues supporting dormancy survival. ||Dormancy entry arrests development with primordium in state of complete architectural elaboration but incomplete organ differentiation, with branch framework established, flower primordia initiated but undifferentiated, and tissues dehydrating and accumulating protective compounds preparing for winter survival. ||Environmental conditions during secondary branch formation critically affect completion with warm late summer-early autumn supporting full elaboration, adequate late-season resources enabling complete branching, and absence of early stress or premature dormancy induction allowing developmental completion. ||Canopy management effects show importance of maintaining adequate late-season photosynthetic capacity with early defoliation or disease reducing resources impairing secondary branching completion, while well-maintained canopy supports full elaboration. ||Late-season stress effects can reduce secondary branching with severe water stress arresting development prematurely, excessive crop load diverting resources limiting branching, or disease reducing photosynthetic capacity impairing completion. ||Temperature effects show warm late summer promoting complete secondary branching while cool conditions may limit elaboration, and timing of autumn cooling relative to completion stage affecting whether full branching achieves before dormancy arrest. ||The process represents fourth and final stage of inflorescence primordium formation completing architectural elaboration before dormancy entry, with completed primordia representing Year N+1 yield potential established during Year N. ||Regional timing shows secondary branch primordium formation during late August-September in warm climates, September-early October in temperate regions, and late August-September in cool areas, requiring completion before dormancy entry timing which varies geographically. ||Viticultural significance includes representing final determinant of inflorescence architecture and flower number capacity, understanding that late-season conditions critically affect completion and subsequent yield, recognizing importance of maintaining vine health and resources through late season supporting elaboration, and appreciating that incomplete secondary branching permanently reduces yield potential. ||Research applications include analyzing regulation of higher-order branching and architectural complexity, investigating environmental and resource effects on late-season primordium elaboration, quantifying relationships between secondary branching and ultimate yield capacity, evaluating timing constraints and dormancy interactions affecting completion, and assessing genetic variation in inflorescence architecture affecting productivity and cluster characteristics across cultivars.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Srinivasan C & Mullins MG (1981) Physiology of flowering in the grapevine, Am J Enol Vitic 32:47-63"
},

  "Inflorescence_Emergence": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Emergence is an Inflorescence_Development comprising the post-dormancy resumption of inflorescence primordium development with external visibility following bud burst.",
  "alternative_term": "inflorescence visibility | cluster emergence | inflorescence expression |+ Blütenstandsaustritt | Gescheinssichtbarkeit | Infloreszenzemergenz | Traubenerscheinen",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows inflorescence emergence from late April through late May Year N+1 at BBCH 53-57 over 4-5 weeks, with dormant primordia resuming development and becoming visible as 3-5 mm compact clusters within opening buds, elongating to 25-35 mm and expanding with distinguishable branches and flower buds approaching flowering readiness under oceanic spring climate conditions of 12-18°C mean temperature, adequate moisture, accumulated 1000-1200 chilling hours during winter, supporting transition from dormant primordia to functional reproductive structures in this moderately fruitful mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Emergence is second major subphase of Inflorescence_Development, occurring during spring Year N+1 following winter dormancy. ||Distinguished by resumption of development and external visibility of inflorescence structures formed during previous season. ||Subdivided into Inflorescence_Visibility, Inflorescence_Elongation, Inflorescence_Expansion, and Rachis_Development. ||Follows Inflorescence_Primordium_Formation that occurred Year N. ||Precedes Flowering phase. ||Critical period for frost protection and establishing reproductive success. || This critical reproductive phase occurs during April-May in temperate regions following winter dormancy and chilling requirement satisfaction, typically spanning 3-5 weeks from first inflorescence visibility within opening buds through complete emergence and expansion as compact clusters approaching flowering readiness at BBCH 53-57. ||Emergence initiation follows bud burst when swelling buds expose developing shoot apex and enclosed organs including leaves and inflorescences that have remained dormant through winter, with inflorescences becoming visible as small compact structures initially enclosed by expanding leaves. ||Dormancy release enabling emergence requires adequate chilling accumulation during winter typically 800-1400 hours below 7°C depending on cultivar, with insufficient chilling causing poor emergence, erratic development, and potentially reduced flowering affecting yield. ||Development resumption involves metabolic reactivation in dormant primordium tissues with respiration increasing from minimal dormancy levels, protein synthesis resuming to support growth, and cell division and expansion initiating in meristematic regions driving visible enlargement. ||Inflorescence visibility marks first external observation of reproductive structures within opening buds at BBCH 53, with small clusters 2-5 mm length visible between separating bud scales and emerging leaves, confirming successful inflorescence formation during previous season and dormancy survival. ||Inflorescence elongation proceeds through coordinated rachis extension and branch elongation increasing cluster size from initial 5-10 mm to 20-40 mm over 2-3 weeks, with elongation rate temperature-dependent doubling approximately every 10°C increase within 10-25°C range. ||Inflorescence expansion involves branch spreading and flower primordium enlargement transforming compact undifferentiated structure into recognizable cluster form with distinguishable branches and enlarging flower buds, though flowers remain closed as green buds during emergence phase with anthesis occurring subsequently. ||Rachis development establishes main cluster axis structure through cell division and expansion in rachis tissues, with primary and secondary branch rachis similarly elongating and thickening providing structural framework supporting developing flowers and eventually fruit. ||Flower development during emergence shows continuation from primordial state with floral organ primordia differentiating into recognizable sepals, petals, stamens, and carpels though organs remain small and enclosed, with full flower development and opening occurring during subsequent flowering phase. ||Inflorescence position relative to shoot structure shows characteristic pattern with first inflorescence typically at node 3-4 on fruitful shoots becoming visible as shoot has 3-5 unfolded leaves, and second inflorescence if present at node 5-6 emerging slightly later as shoot continues elongating. ||Developmental coordination with vegetative growth shows inflorescences emerging concurrently with leaf unfolding and shoot elongation, with all processes drawing on stored carbohydrate reserves mobilized from woody tissues until developing leaves achieve photosynthetic capacity. ||Resource demand during emergence creates competition between vegetative and reproductive development for limited reserves, with adequate reserve status supporting vigorous concurrent development while depleted reserves may limit emergence affecting reproductive success. ||Vascular connection between emerging inflorescence and shoot establishes functional xylem and phloem providing water delivery supporting turgor-driven growth and enabling nutrient import supporting rapid development, with vascular capacity adequate for emergence needs but requiring further development supporting subsequent fruit growth. ||Metabolic activity during emergence shows progressively increasing respiration as tissues reactivate and growth intensifies, reaching 8-12 fold above dormancy levels by peak emergence supporting rapid cell division and expansion. ||Hormonal regulation involves gibberellins with moderate concentrations supporting rachis elongation and flower development, cytokinins promoting cell division and delaying senescence, and auxin coordinating growth and vascular development. ||Environmental conditions during emergence critically affect development with temperature as primary factor determining rate, with optimal 15-22°C supporting rapid uniform emergence while cool conditions delay development and excessive heat may cause abnormalities. ||Light intensity affects emergence indirectly through effects on whole-plant photosynthesis and resource availability, with adequate light supporting vigorous development while severe shade may limit emergence vigor. ||Water availability affects emergence through effects on cell turgor supporting expansion and on overall vine function, with adequate moisture essential for normal development while stress may reduce vigor or cause developmental abnormalities. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects emergence with adequate nutrition supporting vigorous development, though emergence primarily depends on stored reserves with current uptake becoming important later during rapid growth. ||Frost risk during emergence represents major concern with developing reproductive tissues highly vulnerable to freeze damage at temperatures below -2°C, requiring protection measures in frost-prone regions during this critical period. ||The process shows four distinguishable developmental phases progressing from inflorescence visibility within opening buds, through inflorescence elongation extending cluster structure, inflorescence expansion spreading branches and enlarging flowers, to rachis development establishing structural framework. ||Cultivar variation appears in emergence timing with early-bursting varieties showing early inflorescence emergence while late types emerge later, emergence vigor affecting cluster development rate, and architectural expression of primordium structure determined during previous season. ||Regional timing shows inflorescence emergence during April-May in warm climates, May in temperate regions, and May-June in cool areas, with timing relative to bud burst and vegetative development consistent across regions. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring emergence progress assessing reproductive development status, protecting developing inflorescences from frost damage through active or passive protection measures, ensuring adequate vine reserves supporting vigorous emergence through appropriate previous season management, recognizing that emergence represents realization of previous season primordium formation, and understanding that abnormal emergence indicates problems with either primordium formation, dormancy, or current season conditions. ||Research applications include analyzing developmental transitions from dormancy to active growth, investigating environmental regulation of emergence timing and rate, evaluating relationships between emergence characteristics and subsequent flowering and yield, quantifying resource requirements and limitations during emergence, and assessing cultivar variation in emergence patterns affecting phenological timing and adaptation across climates.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 328-345 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 260-275 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Inflorescence_Visibility": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Visibility is an Inflorescence_Emergence comprising the first external observability of inflorescence primordia within swelling buds, corresponding to BBCH 53.",
  "alternative_term": "inflorescence appearance | first cluster visible | inflorescence detection |+ Blütenstandssichtbarkeit | erstes Geschein sichtbar | Infloreszenzerscheinung | Traubenansatzerkennung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows inflorescence visibility at BBCH 53 in early May Year N+1 when shoots have 3-4 unfolded leaves, with 2-3 mm pale green compact inflorescences becoming visible between expanding leaves within opened buds after accumulating 900-1000 chilling hours during winter and reaching 180-220 growing degree days base 10°C in spring under cool maritime conditions of 11-15°C mean temperature, enabling early fruitfulness assessment showing typically 2 inflorescences per shoot in this highly fruitful early-bursting cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Visibility is first of four Inflorescence_Emergence subphases, distinguished by initial external appearance of inflorescences within opening buds. ||Corresponds to BBCH 53 phenological stage. ||Transitions rapidly to Inflorescence_Elongation as development proceeds. ||Critical observation point for crop assessment and management decisions. ||Vulnerable period for frost damage requiring protective measures in susceptible regions. || This critical observational milestone occurs during late April-early May in temperate regions shortly after bud burst when separating bud scales expose developing shoot contents including leaves and enclosed reproductive structures, providing first opportunity for assessing reproductive development status. ||Initial visibility shows small compact inflorescence structures 2-5 mm length appearing between expanding leaves within opening buds, with clusters showing dense undifferentiated form consisting of compressed rachis and tightly packed flower buds in early developmental state. ||Visibility timing relative to vegetative development typically occurs when shoot has 3-5 leaves unfolded corresponding to BBCH 13-15, with first inflorescence becoming visible at basal shoot positions as bud scales separate sufficiently to expose enclosed organs. ||Inflorescence appearance at visibility shows pale green coloration from enclosed development within bud lacking light exposure for chlorophyll synthesis, compact compressed structure from confined bud environment constraining expansion, and undifferentiated form with individual flowers not yet distinguishable requiring magnification for architectural details. ||Developmental state at visibility represents resumption from winter dormancy with meristematic tissues reactivating, cells beginning division and expansion driving initial enlargement, and metabolic processes resuming supporting growth though development remains early with substantial elaboration required before flowering. ||Observation requirements for reliable visibility assessment include careful inspection within opening buds as structures remain partially enclosed by leaves and scales, appropriate lighting enabling detection of small pale structures, and possible magnification for definitive identification distinguishing inflorescences from other bud contents. ||Inflorescence number assessment at visibility provides critical information about fruitfulness and potential yield, with count of visible inflorescences per shoot determining crop load potential guiding management decisions about thinning or crop adjustment. ||Visibility reliability depends on successful previous season primordium formation, adequate winter chilling satisfaction enabling normal dormancy release, winter survival without severe freeze damage, and appropriate spring conditions supporting development resumption. ||Abnormal visibility patterns indicate developmental problems with absence of expected inflorescences suggesting primordium formation failure during previous season, delayed visibility indicating inadequate chilling or cool spring conditions, or malformed structures suggesting developmental abnormalities or frost damage. ||Frost damage assessment at visibility enables early detection of injury with damaged inflorescences showing brown discoloration, necrotic tissues, or failure to resume growth, providing information for crop adjustment decisions. ||Developmental progression from visibility proceeds through continued enlargement and differentiation with inflorescences rapidly elongating and expanding over following 2-3 weeks, transitioning from compressed barely visible structures to recognizable clusters approaching flowering readiness. ||Metabolic state at visibility shows recently reactivated metabolism with respiration increasing from dormancy levels to 5-8 fold above baseline supporting resumed growth, protein synthesis recommencing producing enzymes and structural proteins, and mobilization of stored reserves from woody tissues providing energy and building materials. ||Resource dependence at visibility emphasizes stored carbohydrate importance with emergence drawing primarily on reserves accumulated during previous season, with inadequate reserves potentially limiting emergence vigor affecting subsequent development. ||Vascular connection at visibility maintains functional status with xylem conducting water from permanent structures through emerging shoot to developing inflorescences supporting turgor-driven growth, and phloem importing mobilized reserves and nutrients supporting rapid development. ||Hormonal status at visibility shows increasing cytokinin from root production promoting cell division and growth, moderate gibberellin supporting elongation processes, and auxin from developing organs coordinating growth and differentiation. ||Temperature during visibility period critically affects development rate with optimal 12-18°C supporting rapid visibility and continued development, cool conditions delaying emergence and progression, and warm conditions accelerating development advancing toward flowering. ||Light intensity during visibility affects overall vine vigor and resource availability indirectly though direct light effects on inflorescences are minimal at this early enclosed stage, with adequate light supporting vigorous shoot and inflorescence development. ||Water availability affects visibility through effects on cell turgor supporting expansion and overall vine function, with adequate moisture essential for normal resumption of growth enabling visibility. ||Protective measures during visibility period focus on frost protection as newly emerged tissues show high vulnerability to freeze damage with temperatures below -2°C causing tissue mortality, requiring active or passive protection in frost-prone regions. ||The process represents first of four distinguishable inflorescence emergence phases marking initial external appearance before subsequent elongation and expansion, providing critical early assessment opportunity. ||Duration from first visibility to transition toward elongation typically spans 3-7 days depending on temperature with warm conditions promoting rapid progression and cool conditions extending visibility period. ||Cultivar variation appears in visibility timing relative to bud burst with some varieties showing early inflorescence visibility while others show delayed appearance, and in ease of observation with compact varieties requiring careful inspection while loose-budded types show obvious visibility. ||Regional timing shows inflorescence visibility during late April-early May in warm climates, early-mid May in temperate regions, and mid-late May in cool areas, consistently occurring shortly after bud burst across climatic zones. ||Viticultural significance includes providing first definitive assessment of reproductive development status enabling crop load evaluation, representing critical observation point for fruitfulness assessment informing thinning decisions, enabling early detection of frost damage allowing timely crop adjustment, and confirming successful completion of previous season primordium formation and winter dormancy. ||Research applications include documenting precise emergence timing for phenological studies, evaluating environmental effects on dormancy release and development resumption, quantifying fruitfulness variation among cultivars and conditions, assessing relationships between visibility timing and subsequent flowering and yield, and developing prediction models for emergence timing supporting management decision-making.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 328-335"
},

  "Inflorescence_Elongation": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Elongation is an Inflorescence_Emergence comprising the size increase of clusters from 5–10 mm to 20–40 mm through rachis extension and branch elongation, corresponding to BBCH 55.",
  "alternative_term": "rachis extension | cluster elongation | inflorescence stretching |+ Blütenstandsstreckung | Gescheinsstreckung | Spindelstreckung | Traubenstrecku ng",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows inflorescence elongation from early-mid May Year N+1 at BBCH 55 over 12-14 days, with compact 6-8 mm visible inflorescences elongating to 22-30 mm extended clusters through rachis and branch extension at 1.5-2.5 mm per day under cool climate spring conditions of 13-18°C mean temperature, adequate moisture, developing photosynthetic capacity from expanding leaves, typical of this moderate-vigor early-to-mid season cultivar producing medium-sized clusters approaching flowering readiness",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Elongation is second of four Inflorescence_Emergence subphases, distinguished by primary size increase through rachis and branch extension. ||Follows Inflorescence_Visibility. ||Transitions to Inflorescence_Expansion as spatial extension completes and architectural spreading begins. ||Corresponds to BBCH 55. ||Primary determinant of cluster size and flower spacing. ||Highly temperature-dependent process critical for proper cluster development. || This critical developmental phase occurs during early-mid May in temperate regions following initial visibility, typically spanning 10-14 days as coordinated rachis and branch elongation proceeds at temperature-dependent rates transforming compressed clusters into extended structures. ||Elongation mechanism involves cell division in intercalary meristems within rachis and branch tissues producing new cells contributing to axis length, and progressive cell expansion throughout elongating axes where cells increase length 10-30 fold through turgor-driven wall extension creating visible growth. ||Rachis elongation proceeds through primary axis extension from initial 3-8 mm to final 15-30 mm depending on cultivar and conditions, with elongation rate typically 1-3 mm per day at optimal temperatures providing main cluster axis structure. ||Primary branch elongation occurs simultaneously with rachis extension as branches lengthen from initial 2-5 mm to final 8-18 mm, with branch elongation creating spatial separation between flower clusters distributed along rachis and branch axes. ||Secondary branch elongation where present creates additional architectural complexity with second-order branches extending from primary branches, contributing to compound cluster structure in highly branched cultivars. ||Flower bud spacing increases during elongation as rachis and branch extension separates attachment points, transitioning from tightly packed appearance at visibility to distinguishable individual flowers arranged along elongating axes. ||Elongation rate shows strong temperature dependence with development approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 10-25°C optimal range, with warm spring conditions promoting rapid elongation completing within 8-10 days while cool conditions extend period to 14-18 days. ||Cell division during elongation shows activity concentrated in intercalary meristem zones within rachis and branches with cycles of 24-36 hours producing cells arranged in longitudinal files contributing to axis elongation. ||Cell expansion follows and overlaps division phase with cells throughout elongating axes undergoing water uptake creating turgor pressure of 0.4-0.7 MPa driving cell wall extension, with expansion zone extending throughout much of rachis and branch length during peak elongation. ||Vascular differentiation proceeds during elongation with procambial strands differentiating into functional xylem vessels and phloem sieve elements establishing continuous vascular connection from shoot through rachis and branches to developing flowers, with vascular capacity increasing to support growing tissue mass and approaching anthesis demands. ||Mechanical properties during elongation show flexible herbaceous structure from thin primary cell walls allowing bending and positioning, with rigidity increasing progressively as walls thicken though final strength development awaits fruit set and berry development. ||Metabolic activity during elongation remains elevated with respiration 10-15 fold above mature tissue levels supporting rapid growth processes, with energy demands met through continued mobilization of stored reserves and increasingly from photosynthesis as leaf area develops. ||Protein synthesis operates at high capacity producing structural proteins for expanding cells, enzymes supporting rapid metabolism and wall modification, and beginning accumulation of proteins involved in flowering processes. ||Carbohydrate sources during elongation include declining dependence on stored reserves as shoots transition toward autotrophic growth, with photosynthesis from expanding leaves beginning to contribute though stored reserves remain important until several leaves fully expand. ||Hormonal regulation involves gibberellins supporting rachis and branch elongation with moderate concentrations promoting normal extension while very high or low levels may cause abnormalities, auxin from developing flowers coordinating rachis development and positioning, and cytokinins supporting cell division in meristematic zones. ||Environmental conditions during elongation critically affect development with temperature as primary factor determining rate and final dimensions, with optimal 15-22°C supporting maximum elongation while cool conditions reduce rate and extent, and warm conditions may accelerate development but risk stress effects. ||Light intensity affects elongation indirectly through effects on whole-plant vigor and photosynthetic capacity, with adequate light supporting vigorous elongation while shade may reduce vigor affecting cluster development. ||Water availability affects elongation through direct effects on cell turgor supporting expansion and on overall vine function, with adequate moisture essential for normal elongation while water stress reduces rate and final dimensions affecting cluster size. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects elongation with adequate nutrition supporting vigorous development, though elongation depends substantially on stored reserves with current uptake becoming more important during rapid later growth. ||Frost vulnerability remains high during elongation with developing tissues highly susceptible to freeze damage at temperatures below -1°C, requiring continued protection in frost-prone regions through this critical period. ||Developmental coordination with vegetative growth shows concurrent shoot elongation and leaf expansion providing increasing photosynthetic capacity, with vegetative-reproductive balance determining resource allocation between shoot growth and inflorescence development. ||Cluster architecture expression during elongation reveals branching pattern established during previous season primordium formation, with highly branched types showing extensive primary and secondary branch elongation creating compound structures while simply branched types show limited branching producing loose small clusters. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster shows slight gradient with apical portions typically slightly more advanced reflecting basipetal primordium elaboration pattern, though elongation tends to reduce within-cluster heterogeneity preparing for synchronized flowering. ||The process represents second of four distinguishable inflorescence emergence phases focusing on size increase before architectural spreading and flower maturation, providing critical cluster development establishing framework for flowering. ||Duration typically spans 10-14 days from initial visibility through completion of major elongation depending on temperature, with warm conditions accelerating and cool conditions slowing progression. ||Cultivar variation appears in elongation rate with vigorous varieties showing rapid extension while less vigorous types show slower development, final rachis and branch lengths determining cluster size ranging from small compact 15-25 mm to large loose 30-45 mm structures, and elongation responsiveness to environmental conditions affecting development plasticity. ||Regional timing shows inflorescence elongation during early-mid May in warm climates, mid-May in temperate regions, and late May-early June in cool areas, with timing relative to fixed calendar dates varying but progression relative to thermal time accumulation consistent. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring elongation progress assessing development uniformity and timing predictions for flowering, maintaining frost protection through elongation period as tissues remain highly vulnerable, ensuring adequate resources supporting vigorous elongation without excessive vegetative competition, recognizing that elongation determines spatial cluster framework affecting subsequent fruit development, and understanding that stress during elongation can reduce final cluster size affecting yield. ||Research applications include quantifying environmental effects particularly temperature on elongation rate and final dimensions, analyzing hormonal regulation of rachis and branch elongation, evaluating relationships between elongation characteristics and ultimate yield components, modeling elongation processes for phenology prediction supporting management timing, and assessing genetic variation in elongation patterns affecting cluster architecture across cultivars.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 335-340 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 265-270"
},

  "Inflorescence_Expansion": {
  "definition": "An Inflorescence_Expansion is an Inflorescence_Emergence comprising the lateral separation of branches and enlargement of flower buds with individual flowers becoming distinguishable, corresponding to BBCH 57.",
  "alternative_term": "cluster spreading | inflorescence opening | flower cluster expansion |+ Blütenstandsentfaltung | Gescheinsspreizung | Infloreszenzerweiterung | Traubenöffnung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows inflorescence expansion from mid-late May Year N+1 at BBCH 57 over 8-10 days, with elongated 25-35 mm clusters spreading branches from compressed to 50-65 degree angles and flower buds enlarging from 1.5-2.0 mm to 3.0-4.0 mm approaching flowering readiness under warm spring Mediterranean conditions of 17-23°C mean temperature, adequate moisture, full photosynthetic capacity from developed canopy, typical of this moderately-to-highly fruitful mid-to-late season cultivar expressing compound cluster architecture before anthesis",
  "editor_note": "Inflorescence_Expansion is third of four Inflorescence_Emergence subphases, distinguished by architectural spreading and flower maturation. ||Follows Inflorescence_Elongation. ||Transitions to Rachis_Development final maturation and directly toward Flowering phase. ||Corresponds to BBCH 57. ||Critical preparatory phase establishing flowering readiness. ||Important period for disease management protecting susceptible tissues. || This critical preparatory phase occurs during mid-late May in temperate regions following rachis elongation, typically spanning 7-10 days as coordinated branch spreading and flower maturation proceed transforming elongated but compact clusters into fully expanded structures ready for flowering. ||Expansion mechanism involves branch angle increase from compressed acute angles to spreading obtuse angles creating open architecture, continued branch elongation contributing to separation, and flower bud enlargement from small 1-2 mm primordia to plump 3-4 mm buds approaching cap fall. ||Branch spreading proceeds through differential growth on branch abaxial versus adaxial sides creating angular change, with primary branches moving from 20-30 degree angles to 45-70 degrees relative to rachis axis, and secondary branches similarly spreading creating three-dimensional open structure. ||Flower bud enlargement represents major developmental change with flower organs completing differentiation and expansion within enclosing calyptra cap, with sepals remaining fused as cap, petals, stamens, and pistil enlarging substantially as anthesis approaches. ||Flower development during expansion includes stamen filament elongation positioning anthers for pollen release, anther maturation with pollen completing development becoming viable, pistil enlargement with ovary expanding and style-stigma developing receptivity, and nectary development preparing for nectar secretion. ||Cluster appearance transitions from compact elongated structure with indistinct flowers to fully expressed architecture with clearly visible individual flower buds arranged in characteristic pattern, with cluster form revealing branching complexity established during previous season primordium formation. ||Flower number becomes definitively countable during expansion as individual buds separate and become distinct, providing accurate assessment of potential berry number though actual berry set will depend on successful pollination and fertilization during subsequent flowering. ||Metabolic activity remains elevated during expansion supporting continued growth and flower maturation, with respiration 8-12 fold above mature tissue levels providing energy for developmental processes. ||Photosynthetic contribution increases during expansion as shoot leaf area expands and matures, with developing leaves beginning to supply significant photosynthate supplementing declining stored reserves, though clusters remain net carbon consumers requiring import. ||Vascular development continues during expansion with vessel diameter and number increasing in rachis and branches enhancing water transport capacity to 4-8 mg per second adequate for supporting full cluster and approaching berry demands, and phloem development increasing assimilate import capacity. ||Sugar concentration in rachis and flower tissues during expansion shows minimal levels as structures remain in growth phase consuming imported assimilates rather than accumulating storage products, with sugar dynamics changing dramatically after fruit set when berries begin accumulating photosynthate. ||Hormonal regulation during expansion involves gibberellins maintaining growth promotion though concentrations may begin declining as flowering approaches, auxin from developing flowers coordinating development, and possibly ethylene beginning involvement in maturation processes. ||Environmental conditions during expansion affect development with temperature continuing as primary factor though optimal range shifts slightly higher to 16-24°C supporting maximum expansion and flower maturation, with cool conditions delaying progression and very warm conditions potentially accelerating development. ||Light intensity affects expansion through photosynthetic effects supporting vigorous development, with well-exposed shoots showing robust expansion while shaded shoots may show reduced vigor affecting cluster quality. ||Water availability remains critical during expansion with adequate moisture essential for turgor supporting branch spreading and flower enlargement, while water stress reduces expansion vigor potentially affecting flower development and subsequent fruit set. ||Nutrient availability particularly nitrogen affects expansion with adequate nutrition supporting vigorous development, with nitrogen from both current uptake and remobilization from storage supporting rapid tissue growth and protein synthesis. ||Pest pressure begins increasing during expansion as developing reproductive tissues attract insects including grape berry moth, leafhoppers, and thrips requiring monitoring and possible management interventions. ||Disease pressure also intensifies with expanding clusters creating favorable microclimate for powdery mildew development requiring protective fungicide applications particularly in susceptible varieties or conducive conditions. ||Frost vulnerability declines during expansion as tissues mature and temperatures typically rise reducing freeze risk, though late spring frosts remain possible in some regions requiring vigilance. ||Developmental coordination with vegetative growth shows continued concurrent shoot elongation and leaf expansion with shoots typically having 10-15 leaves at expansion completion, with balanced vegetative-reproductive development supporting subsequent flowering and fruit set. ||Cluster position relative to canopy architecture becomes established during expansion with shoot positioning operations determining cluster exposure affecting microclimate during critical flowering period. ||Within-cluster developmental uniformity increases during expansion as flower maturation proceeds synchronously preparing for coordinated anthesis, with well-developed clusters showing good flowering synchrony supporting uniform fruit set. ||The process represents third of four distinguishable inflorescence emergence phases focusing on architectural spreading and flower maturation preparing for anthesis, completing transformation from dormant primordium to functional reproductive structure. ||Duration typically spans 7-10 days depending on temperature and conditions, with warm favorable conditions promoting rapid progression while cool conditions or stress may extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in expansion vigor affecting final cluster openness with some varieties showing tight compact architecture while others show very loose open structure, flower size at expansion affecting visual appearance and possibly pollination efficiency, and expansion rate affecting timing progression toward flowering. ||Regional timing shows inflorescence expansion during mid-late May in warm climates, late May-early June in temperate regions, and early-mid June in cool areas, with timing relative to thermal accumulation consistent though calendar dates vary geographically. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring expansion progress for flowering timing predictions, implementing pre-flowering disease management protecting expanding susceptible tissues, positioning shoots optimizing cluster exposure for favorable flowering microclimate, assessing cluster uniformity and architecture affecting disease pressure and quality potential, and recognizing expansion as final preparatory phase before critical flowering period. ||Research applications include analyzing developmental processes during flower maturation, evaluating environmental effects on expansion affecting flowering readiness, quantifying relationships between expansion characteristics and flowering uniformity, assessing pest and disease colonization during expansion informing management thresholds, and documenting genetic variation in cluster architecture expression affecting fruit quality potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 340-345 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 270-275"
},

  "Rachis_Development": {
  "definition": "A Rachis_Development is an Inflorescence_Development comprising the differentiation of cluster axis tissues into mechanical framework and vascular pathways supporting flower and fruit development.",
  "alternative_term": "cluster axis development | rachis formation | peduncle development | cluster stem maturation |+ Gescheinsachsenentwicklung | Rhachisentwicklung | Stielgerüstbildung | Traubenstielentwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows rachis development from late April through late May Year N+1 during inflorescence emergence at BBCH 53-59, with rachis tissues differentiating and expanding from 0.6-0.8 mm initial diameter to 2.0-2.8 mm at flowering, establishing vascular capacity of 3-5 mg per second water transport, moderate lignification creating flexible but strong structure, under warm climate conditions supporting cluster development in this vigorous large-clustered late-season cultivar producing robust rachis architecture supporting 200-400 gram clusters through development and harvest",
  "editor_note": "Rachis_Development is fourth aspect of Inflorescence_Emergence, distinguished by focus on structural framework rather than overall cluster. ||Occurs throughout emergence period concurrently with Visibility, Elongation, and Expansion but emphasizes support function. ||Critical for cluster integrity and function through anthesis, berry development, and harvest. ||Rachis quality affects mechanical properties, transport capacity, and quality characteristics. || This foundational developmental process occurs throughout inflorescence emergence spanning 3-5 weeks from initial visibility through flowering preparation, with rachis tissues progressively differentiating, thickening, and lignifying establishing permanent cluster structure. ||Rachis structure includes primary axis extending from peduncle attachment to cluster apex providing main structural support, primary branch rachis extending laterally from main axis to flower attachment points, and secondary branch rachis where present in compound architectures creating higher-order framework, with complete rachis system determining cluster mechanical properties and resource distribution. ||Anatomical development involves establishment of central vascular core with xylem vessels differentiating to provide water transport capacity of 2-5 mg per second per cluster adequate for flower and developing berry demands, phloem sieve elements forming enabling bidirectional assimilate transport, surrounding parenchyma providing storage capacity and maintaining live tissue function, peripheral cortex and strengthening tissues providing flexibility during development transitioning to rigidity at maturity, and epidermis with cuticle providing protection and controlling water loss. ||Cell division in developing rachis shows activity concentrated in intercalary meristems contributing to elongation during emergence, and in cambial zones producing vascular tissues and secondary growth, with division rates declining as maturation proceeds and elongation completes. ||Cell expansion throughout rachis contributes to thickness increase from initial 0.5-1.0 mm diameter at visibility to 1.5-3.0 mm at flowering depending on cultivar and cluster size, with expansion establishing final dimensions before lignification creates permanent structure. ||Lignification begins in rachis tissues during late emergence as secondary walls deposit with lignin incorporation creating mechanical strength, proceeding from base toward apex in basipetal pattern, with lignification extent at flowering variable among cultivars affecting rachis brittleness and breakage susceptibility. ||Mechanical properties develop progressively from flexible herbaceous structure during early emergence to increasingly rigid framework at flowering, with tensile strength increasing from 10-20 MPa in elongating tissues to 30-60 MPa in mature rachis providing resistance to fruit load and handling. ||Vascular capacity increases during development as vessel number and diameter increase enhancing water transport, with final capacity at flowering adequate for supporting anthesis water demands and prepared for substantial increases required during berry expansion. ||Resource transport through rachis includes upward water movement through xylem from shoot to flowers and berries, bidirectional assimilate movement through phloem with import during development and export during late berry ripening as seeds senesce, and hormone transport coordinating cluster development including auxin from developing seeds affecting fruit growth. ||Rachis function during flowering includes structural support maintaining cluster position and flower orientation facilitating pollination, water delivery to flowers supporting turgor during anthesis and stigma receptivity, and nutrient supply supporting active metabolism during reproductive processes. ||Rachis importance after fruit set intensifies as structure must support increasing berry weight reaching 100-500 grams per cluster depending on size, provide water delivery supporting berry expansion consuming 80-95% cluster water use, enable assimilate import during berry growth accumulating sugars and supporting metabolism, and maintain integrity through harvest preventing berry loss from rachis detachment or breakage. ||Rachis browning or necrosis represents physiological disorder reducing rachis function with tissue death interrupting transport causing berry shriveling and reduced quality, with disorder associated with calcium deficiency, water stress, or excessive berry load exceeding rachis capacity. ||Rachis lignification extent affects brittleness with highly lignified rachis showing rigidity and brittleness increasing shattering risk during harvest, while less lignified flexible rachis shows toughness reducing shattering but potentially increasing breakage under load. ||Rachis color development shows green coloration during active growth from chlorophyll in cortex tissues, transitioning toward brown as maturation proceeds and chlorophyll degrades, with final color at harvest ranging from green in some varieties to brown or reddish in others affecting visual cluster appeal. ||Rachis phenolic content affects browning with high polyphenol oxidase activity causing rapid oxidative browning when tissues damaged, with browning affecting appearance though not necessarily function unless extensive necrosis develops. ||Temperature during rachis development affects differentiation and maturation rate with optimal 15-24°C supporting normal development, cool conditions slowing progression, and very warm conditions accelerating development potentially causing incomplete differentiation. ||Water availability affects rachis development with adequate moisture supporting normal cell expansion and differentiation establishing robust structure, while water stress limits development producing smaller weaker rachis susceptible to dysfunction. ||Nutrient availability particularly calcium affects rachis quality with adequate calcium supporting strong cell walls and reducing browning susceptibility, while deficiency increases disorder risk affecting berry quality. ||The process represents fourth aspect of inflorescence emergence focusing on structural framework rather than overall cluster development, occurring concurrently with other emergence phases but emphasizing architectural support function. ||Duration spans entire emergence period from visibility through flowering preparation approximately 3-5 weeks, with continued rachis function required throughout berry development until harvest. ||Cultivar variation appears in final rachis dimensions and strength with vigorous large-clustered varieties showing thick strong rachis while small-clustered types show thin delicate structure, lignification extent affecting mechanical properties, and browning susceptibility affecting appearance and quality. ||Regional timing shows rachis development throughout spring emergence period from April-May in warm climates, May-June in temperate regions, and May-June in cool areas, with continued function through summer berry development and harvest. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing rachis as critical support structure determining cluster handling quality, ensuring adequate calcium availability reducing browning risk, managing water and crop load preventing rachis stress and dysfunction, understanding that rachis capacity ultimately limits cluster size potential, and appreciating that rachis quality affects harvest efficiency and fruit quality. ||Research applications include analyzing rachis anatomical development and mechanical properties, investigating physiological basis of rachis browning disorders, evaluating management effects on rachis quality affecting fruit quality and handling characteristics, quantifying transport capacity and limitations in rachis affecting berry development, and assessing genetic variation in rachis characteristics affecting cluster architecture and quality potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 340-355 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 270-280 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Flower_Cluster_Separation": {
  "definition": "A Flower_Cluster_Separation is an Inflorescence_Emergence comprising the differentiation of compact inflorescence regions into distinct flower groups through localized spacing, corresponding to BBCH 55–57.",
  "alternative_term": "cluster group separation | flower group definition | inflorescence compartmentalization |+ Blütengruppenseparation | Gescheinsgliederung | Blütenstandskompartimentierung | Teilblütenstandsseparation",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows flower cluster separation during mid-late May Year N+1 at late BBCH 55-early 57 over 6-7 days, with 22-30 primary branches separating along rachis creating 2-4 mm spacing between branch attachment points, secondary branches where present separating 1-2 mm on primary branches, establishing compound cluster architecture with distinguishable flower groups under oceanic spring conditions of 16-20°C mean temperature, adequate moisture, developed photosynthetic capacity, typical of this moderately compound mid-season cultivar approaching flowering readiness",
  "editor_note": "Flower_Cluster_Separation represents organizational phase within Inflorescence_Development distinguishing flower groups before individual flower separation. ||Follows Inflorescence_Expansion. ||Subdivided into Primary_Cluster_Separation, Secondary_Cluster_Separation, Cluster_Spacing_Development, and Individual_Cluster_Definition. ||Transitions to Individual_Flower_Separation as flowers individualize. ||Important for establishing cluster microenvironment affecting disease and quality. ||Architectural expression reveals previous season primordium formation pattern. || This important organizational phase occurs during mid-May in temperate regions Year N+1 following initial inflorescence elongation, typically spanning 5-7 days as coordinated differential growth creates spatial separation between flower groups revealing underlying architectural pattern established during previous season primordium formation. ||Cluster separation mechanism involves differential branch elongation with primary branches extending at varying rates creating unequal spacing, localized rachis elongation between branch attachment points generating gaps, and beginning secondary branch spreading where present establishing hierarchical spatial organization. ||Primary cluster separation proceeds through primary branch differentiation from main rachis with branches elongating and angling away from axis creating first-order spatial organization, with branch spacing along rachis typically 2-5 mm reflecting primordium formation pattern from previous season. ||Secondary cluster separation occurs in compound architectures where secondary branches separate from primary branches creating second-order spatial organization, with secondary branch spacing typically 1-3 mm establishing fine-scale architectural pattern. ||Developmental progression shows basipetal-acropetal gradient with apical regions often showing earlier separation reflecting advanced development in earlier-formed structures, while basal regions show progressive separation as development proceeds, creating temporal heterogeneity within inflorescence. ||Cluster definition emerges during separation as grouped flowers on branch tips become visually distinguishable from neighboring groups, with separation creating perceptual organization of continuous inflorescence into discrete clusters facilitating observation and assessment. ||Spacing development creates microenvironmental variation within inflorescence with separated regions showing improved air circulation reducing disease pressure potential, enhanced light penetration affecting flower development uniformity, and differential temperature exposure potentially affecting developmental timing within cluster. ||Architectural pattern expression during separation reveals branching structure established during previous season primordium formation, with highly branched compound architectures showing complex hierarchical separation pattern while simply branched types show straightforward primary branch separation. ||Branch angle development accompanies separation with branches moving from acute compressed angles toward more obtuse spreading positions, creating three-dimensional spatial organization enhancing resource distribution and later fruit exposure. ||Flower bud development continues during cluster separation with buds enlarging from 1.5-2.5 mm to 2.5-3.5 mm as flower organs mature within enclosing calyptra, preparing for subsequent individual flower separation and anthesis. ||Vascular differentiation proceeds during separation with branch vascular traces differentiating from main rachis establishing independent transport pathways, enabling localized resource delivery to separated flower groups supporting development and subsequent fruit growth. ||Metabolic activity during separation maintains elevated levels supporting continued growth processes, with respiration 8-12 fold above mature tissue levels providing energy for differential expansion, cell division, and organ differentiation. ||Photosynthetic contribution increases during separation as shoot canopy develops providing substantial assimilate production, transitioning from early emergence dependence on stored reserves toward current photosynthetic support, though inflorescences remain net carbon consumers requiring import. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin from developing flowers affecting rachis and branch development through polar transport establishing growth gradients, gibberellins maintaining elongation promotion though concentrations may begin declining, and cytokinins supporting continued cell division in active growth zones. ||Environmental conditions during separation affect development with temperature continuing as primary factor with optimal 16-24°C supporting rapid uniform separation, cool conditions slowing progression potentially causing compressed cluster development, and warm conditions accelerating separation though excessive heat may cause stress effects. ||Light intensity affects separation through photosynthetic effects on whole-plant vigor with adequate light supporting robust development, though direct light effects on inflorescence are modest at this stage with structures still partially shaded by developing leaves. ||Water availability affects separation through effects on cell turgor supporting expansion and overall vine function, with adequate moisture essential for normal spacing development while water stress reduces growth limiting separation and potentially creating compact cluster architecture. ||Nutrient availability affects separation with adequate nitrogen supporting vigorous development, phosphorus supporting energy metabolism, and balanced nutrition enabling optimal architectural expression without excessive vegetative growth competition. ||Disease pressure during separation includes powdery mildew colonization risk with developing inflorescence tissues susceptible to infection, requiring protective fungicide applications particularly in favorable disease conditions or susceptible varieties. ||Pest monitoring during separation includes grape berry moth larval presence potentially affecting flower development, leafhoppers feeding on tender tissues, and thrips colonization affecting flower quality. ||Within-inflorescence developmental uniformity improves during separation as flower groups individualize at similar rates preparing for coordinated flowering, with well-separated clusters showing good flowering synchrony supporting uniform fruit set. ||The process shows four distinguishable developmental aspects progressing from primary cluster separation establishing first-order organization, through secondary cluster separation creating hierarchical structure, cluster spacing development enhancing separation, to individual cluster definition completing group organization before individual flower separation. ||Duration typically spans 5-7 days depending on temperature and cultivar characteristics, with warm conditions promoting rapid separation while cool conditions extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in separation extent with loose-clustered varieties showing substantial spacing creating well-separated flower groups while tight-clustered types show minimal separation maintaining compact architecture, branching complexity affecting hierarchical separation pattern, and separation rate affecting developmental timing toward flowering. ||Regional timing shows flower cluster separation during mid-May in warm climates, late May in temperate regions, and late May-early June in cool areas, occurring during late inflorescence emergence preparing for flowering. ||Viticultural management considerations include recognizing separation as indicator of approaching flowering enabling preparation for critical bloom period, understanding that separation pattern affects cluster microenvironment influencing disease pressure and fruit quality, monitoring separation uniformity assessing development synchrony affecting flowering timing predictions, implementing pre-bloom disease management protecting susceptible tissues during separation, and appreciating that architectural expression during separation reflects previous season primordium formation quality. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating differential growth creating spatial separation, investigating environmental effects on separation affecting cluster architecture and microenvironment, quantifying relationships between separation patterns and disease susceptibility, evaluating architectural diversity among cultivars and its functional implications, and assessing developmental coordination between separation processes and approaching anthesis.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 340-350 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Primary_Cluster_Separation": {
  "definition": "A Primary_Cluster_Separation is a Flower_Cluster_Separation comprising the differentiation of primary branches from the main rachis through elongation and angular positioning into first-order flower groups.",
  "alternative_term": "primary branch separation | first-order cluster division | main branch differentiation |+ Primärcluster-Separation | Hauptzweigseparation | erste Gescheinsgliederung | Erstordnungs-Blütentrennung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows primary cluster separation during mid-May Year N+1 at late BBCH 55 over 4-5 days, with 24-32 primary branches elongating to 10-15 mm length and spreading to 50-65 degree angles creating 2.5-4.0 mm spacing along 25-35 mm rachis under temperate maritime conditions of 15-19°C mean temperature, adequate resources, typical of this moderately loose-clustered vigorous mid-season cultivar establishing well-separated primary cluster architecture",
  "editor_note": "Primary_Cluster_Separation is first of four Flower_Cluster_Separation subphases, distinguished by first-order spatial organization through primary branch differentiation. ||Establishes coarse-scale cluster architecture. ||Transitions to or overlaps with Secondary_Cluster_Separation in compound architectures. ||Primary determinant of cluster density and microenvironment. ||Extent reflects genetic architecture program and developmental conditions. || This fundamental organizational stage occurs during mid-May in temperate regions Year N+1 as part of cluster separation process, typically requiring 3-5 days as primary branches achieve sufficient extension and angular divergence to create perceptible separation from rachis and neighboring branches. ||Separation mechanism involves primary branch elongation extending branches 8-18 mm from rachis attachment points creating spatial projection, branch angle increase from compressed acute positions toward 45-70 degree angles establishing lateral spreading, and rachis elongation between branch attachment points creating 2-5 mm spacing along primary axis. ||Primary branch differentiation shows each branch unit containing cluster of flower buds at distal positions, with branch serving as structural support and transport pathway connecting flowers to main cluster vascular system through rachis. ||Branch number along rachis determines number of primary clusters with typical range 15-40 primary branches per inflorescence creating 15-40 first-order flower groups, reflecting primordium formation during previous season with cultivar variation in branching frequency. ||Spatial organization created by primary separation establishes coarse-scale cluster architecture with widely-spaced first-order units in loose-clustered varieties showing 4-6 mm between branches, moderately-spaced intermediate types showing 2-4 mm spacing, and tightly-spaced compact varieties showing 1-2 mm spacing affecting overall cluster density. ||Branch elongation mechanism involves cell division in intercalary meristems at branch base adding cells to branch length, and cell expansion throughout branch tissues increasing cell dimensions through turgor-driven growth, with elongation rate typically 0.5-1.5 mm per day at optimal temperatures. ||Branch angle development proceeds through differential growth on abaxial versus adaxial sides creating angular change, with abaxial side showing enhanced expansion driving branch outward from rachis, establishing spreading three-dimensional architecture. ||Vascular development in separating primary branches shows continued xylem and phloem differentiation establishing functional transport capacity, with vascular trace connecting branch to main rachis vascular system enabling water delivery and assimilate distribution to flowers on branch. ||Mechanical properties during separation show flexible structure from thin-walled tissues allowing positioning adjustments, with progressive wall thickening increasing rigidity though final strength development awaits fruit set and berry growth. ||Flower bud development on primary branches continues during separation with buds enlarging as flower organs mature, preparing for subsequent individual flower separation within each primary cluster unit. ||Metabolic activity in separating primary branches maintains high levels supporting elongation and angle development, with respiration elevated providing energy for growth processes. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin affecting branch elongation and positioning through effects on cell expansion and growth orientation, with auxin gradients potentially coordinating spatial organization among branches. ||Environmental effects on primary separation include temperature as primary factor with optimal 16-22°C supporting rapid uniform separation, cool conditions slowing elongation reducing separation extent, and warm conditions accelerating development though potentially causing stress if excessive. ||Resource availability affects separation with adequate photosynthetic production supporting vigorous branch elongation creating well-separated clusters, while limitation reduces elongation maintaining compact architecture. ||Developmental gradient within inflorescence shows apical primary branches often separating earlier reflecting advanced development in earlier-formed structures, while basal branches show progressive separation as development proceeds. ||Within-branch uniformity shows similar developmental stage among flowers on each primary branch preparing for coordinated anthesis within branch unit, supporting synchronous flowering and fruit set. ||The process represents first of four flower cluster separation aspects establishing coarse-scale spatial organization before finer-scale secondary separation and individual flower separation, providing primary architectural framework. ||Duration typically spans 3-5 days from initiation to substantial completion depending on temperature and genetic elongation characteristics, with rapid progression under favorable conditions. ||Cultivar variation appears in separation extent with loose-clustered varieties showing substantial primary branch elongation and spreading creating 4-6 mm spacing while tight-clustered types show minimal elongation maintaining 1-2 mm spacing, affecting cluster compactness and microenvironment. ||Regional timing shows primary cluster separation during mid-May in warm climates, late May in temperate regions, and late May-early June in cool areas, occurring as part of late inflorescence emergence approaching flowering. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing primary cluster structure affecting disease pressure with well-separated clusters showing better air circulation and reduced infection risk, influencing later fruit exposure and quality characteristics, and revealing architectural pattern established during previous season primordium formation. ||Research applications include quantifying genetic and environmental variation in primary branch separation affecting cluster architecture, analyzing mechanisms regulating branch elongation and angular positioning, evaluating relationships between primary separation and disease susceptibility, and assessing implications of separation patterns for fruit quality outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 340-345 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Secondary_Cluster_Separation": {
  "definition": "A Secondary_Cluster_Separation is a Flower_Cluster_Separation comprising the differentiation of secondary branches from primary branches through elongation and positioning into sub-clusters within primary branch units.",
  "alternative_term": "secondary branch separation | second-order cluster division | hierarchical branching |+ Sekundärcluster-Separation | Nebenzweigseparation | hierarchische Gescheinsgliederung | Zweitordnungs-Blütentrennung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows secondary cluster separation during late May Year N+1 at early BBCH 57 over 3-4 days in moderately compound architecture, with 2-4 secondary branches per distal primary branch elongating to 5-8 mm and spreading 35-45 degrees creating 1.5-2.5 mm spacing establishing sub-cluster organization under Mediterranean conditions of 18-22°C temperature, typical of this moderately-to-highly compound mid-to-late season cultivar producing 400-700 flowers per inflorescence through hierarchical branching",
  "editor_note": "Secondary_Cluster_Separation is second of four Flower_Cluster_Separation subphases, distinguished by second-order spatial organization through secondary branch differentiation. ||Occurs only in compound architectures. ||Follows Primary_Cluster_Separation. ||Major determinant of cluster complexity and berry number. ||Highly variable among cultivars reflecting genetic architectural programs. ||Creates hierarchical nested structure characteristic of grapevine inflorescence. || This advanced organizational stage occurs during mid-late May in temperate regions Year N+1 following or overlapping with primary cluster separation, typically requiring 2-4 days as secondary branches achieve sufficient development to create perceptible separation from primary branch axis and neighboring secondary branches. ||Separation mechanism involves secondary branch elongation extending branches 4-10 mm from primary branch attachment creating spatial projection, angular positioning with branches spreading 30-50 degrees from primary branch axis establishing sub-cluster distribution, and localized primary branch elongation between secondary branch attachments creating 1-3 mm spacing along primary branch. ||Secondary branch presence and development varies substantially among cultivars with highly compound architectures showing 3-8 secondary branches per primary branch creating complex hierarchical structure, moderately compound types showing 1-3 secondary branches on distal primary branches creating intermediate complexity, and simply branched varieties showing absent or minimal secondary branching producing relatively simple architecture. ||Architectural complexity created by secondary separation substantially increases flower number and cluster density with highly compound types producing 500-1500 flowers per inflorescence through extensive secondary branching, compared to 100-400 flowers in simply branched varieties lacking secondary elaboration. ||Flower group organization within primary clusters shows subdivision through secondary branching with each secondary branch unit containing group of flowers at distal positions, creating hierarchical nested structure characteristic of compound grapevine inflorescence architecture. ||Vascular organization in secondary branches establishes independent transport pathways branching from primary branch vascular system, enabling localized resource delivery to flower groups on secondary branches supporting coordinated development within sub-clusters. ||Secondary branch elongation mechanism resembles primary branch elongation with cell division in intercalary zones adding cells and cell expansion throughout tissues increasing dimensions, though secondary branches typically achieve smaller final dimensions reflecting later initiation and shorter development period. ||Mechanical properties in secondary branches show flexible herbaceous structure adequate for supporting flowers and small developing berries, with progressive strengthening as tissues mature though secondary branches often represent weakest structural links in mature clusters potentially creating shattering locations during harvest. ||Flower development on secondary branches continues during separation with buds enlarging preparing for individual flower separation and anthesis, with flowers on secondary branches typically synchronized with flowers on primary branch supporting coordinated flowering within entire primary cluster unit. ||Metabolic activity in developing secondary branches shows elevated respiration supporting growth, though total metabolic demand is lower than primary structures reflecting smaller size. ||Developmental timing shows secondary separation occurring later than primary separation reflecting hierarchical development sequence, with delay typically 2-3 days between primary and secondary separation initiation. ||Within-cluster architectural pattern shows spatial distribution of secondary branches with distal primary branch regions often showing more extensive secondary branching while basal regions show reduced or absent secondary branches, creating compound-to-simple gradient along primary branch length. ||Genetic control of secondary branching represents major determinant of cluster architecture with cultivar-specific programs establishing branching extent, with mutations or environmental effects affecting secondary branching substantially altering cluster structure and berry number. ||Environmental effects on secondary separation include temperature affecting elongation rate with optimal conditions supporting full secondary branch development while suboptimal conditions may limit elongation or reduce secondary branch expression. ||Resource availability affects secondary branching with adequate resources supporting full architectural elaboration while limitation may reduce secondary branch development creating simpler architecture than genetic potential. ||Previous season conditions during primordium formation fundamentally determine secondary branching potential established in bud, with current season affecting expression of established potential rather than creating new branches. ||The process represents second of four flower cluster separation aspects creating hierarchical fine-scale organization in compound architectures, following primary separation and preceding final spacing and individual flower separation. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 days depending on cultivar branching characteristics and temperature, with warm conditions promoting rapid completion. ||Cultivar variation represents most prominent feature with highly compound varieties showing extensive secondary separation creating 6-12 mm branch extensions with numerous secondary branches, moderately compound types showing selective secondary branching on 30-50% primary branches, and simply branched varieties showing minimal to absent secondary branching maintaining simple architecture. ||Regional timing shows secondary cluster separation during mid-late May in warm climates, late May-early June in temperate regions, and early June in cool areas, occurring late in inflorescence emergence approaching flowering. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing fine-scale cluster architecture affecting berry number and density, influencing cluster microenvironment with highly compound types showing dense architecture potentially increasing disease pressure, affecting mechanical properties with secondary branches representing potential weak points in mature clusters, and expressing architectural diversity among cultivars affecting management requirements and quality potential. ||Research applications include analyzing genetic regulation of hierarchical branching determining architectural complexity, investigating developmental coordination between primary and secondary branching establishing nested structure, quantifying relationships between secondary branching and berry number, evaluating environmental effects on secondary branch expression affecting architectural plasticity, and assessing functional implications of architectural diversity for disease susceptibility and fruit quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 345-350"
},

  "Cluster_Spacing_Development": {
  "definition": "A Cluster_Spacing_Development is a Flower_Cluster_Separation comprising the enhancement of branch separations through differential elongation and positioning into the final cluster architecture.",
  "alternative_term": "spacing refinement | cluster architecture optimization | final spacing adjustment |+ Abstands-Entwicklung | Gescheinsraumoptimierung | Feinabstimmung der Gliederung | architektonische Verfeinerung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows cluster spacing development during late May Year N+1 at BBCH 57 over 2-3 days, with rachis adding 3-5 mm final length distributing spacing to 2.5-3.5 mm between 16-22 primary branches, branch angles adjusting 8-12 degrees optimizing distribution, under continental conditions of 16-20°C temperature, typical of this moderately loose-clustered early-to-mid season cultivar completing architectural refinement before individual flower separation",
  "editor_note": "Cluster_Spacing_Development is third of four Flower_Cluster_Separation subphases, distinguished by refinement of established separations rather than initial establishment. ||Follows Primary and Secondary Cluster Separation. ||Transitions to Individual_Cluster_Definition completing group organization. ||Represents final architectural adjustments before individual flower separation. ||Optimizes cluster microenvironment for flowering and development. || This fine-tuning developmental phase occurs during late May in temperate regions Year N+1 following initial cluster separations, typically spanning 2-3 days as coordinated growth adjustments complete spatial organization preparing for individual flower separation and anthesis. ||Spacing enhancement mechanism involves continued rachis elongation between branch attachment points increasing inter-branch distances, progressive branch angle adjustment through differential growth refining spatial positioning, and localized branch elongation at specific positions correcting irregularities in flower distribution. ||Rachis growth during spacing development typically adds 2-5 mm total length distributing increment across inter-branch regions, with growth rate declining from earlier elongation phase as maturation approaches but sufficient to enhance established separations. ||Branch repositioning involves subtle angular adjustments typically 5-15 degrees refining three-dimensional cluster architecture, with adjustments creating more uniform spatial distribution and optimizing light penetration and air circulation within cluster structure. ||Localized elongation in specific branches showing compressed spacing provides corrective growth enhancing separation in tight regions, creating more uniform flower group distribution improving microenvironmental uniformity within cluster. ||Flower bud enlargement continues during spacing development with buds reaching 3-4 mm preparing for individual separation and anthesis, with flower organ maturation within enclosing calyptra approaching completion. ||Spatial optimization during this phase creates cluster architecture balancing competing requirements including adequate separation for air circulation reducing disease pressure, sufficient compactness for mechanical protection and harvest efficiency, and appropriate exposure for successful pollination and fruit development. ||Microenvironmental consequences of spacing include light penetration patterns with well-spaced clusters showing good light distribution to interior flowers supporting uniform development, air circulation characteristics with adequate spacing promoting rapid drying reducing infection risk, and temperature distribution with exposed regions showing higher temperatures potentially advancing development. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster improves during spacing development as flower groups achieve similar maturation states, with good spacing supporting synchronized flowering across cluster promoting uniform fruit set and ripening. ||Mechanical properties of cluster structure show progressive strengthening as rachis and branch tissues mature, with spacing pattern affecting load distribution affecting cluster mechanical performance under fruit weight and handling stresses. ||Vascular maturation continues during spacing development with vessels achieving functional capacity adequate for flowering water demands and prepared for substantial increases during berry expansion, with spacing pattern affecting vascular network geometry influencing transport efficiency. ||Metabolic activity during spacing development shows declining growth-related respiration as elongation slows approaching maturation, transitioning toward maintenance levels though remaining elevated relative to mature vegetative tissues. ||Resource allocation during spacing development shows continued inflorescence demand competing with vegetative growth and other reproductive structures, with balanced allocation supporting adequate spacing development without excessive vegetative competition. ||Hormonal regulation during spacing development involves declining gibberellins as elongation processes complete, sustained auxin from developing flowers coordinating final adjustments, and possibly increasing ethylene as maturation processes initiate. ||Environmental conditions during spacing development include temperature effects continuing with optimal 17-23°C supporting final adjustments, cool conditions potentially limiting refinements maintaining somewhat compressed architecture, and warm conditions accelerating maturation potentially truncating spacing development. ||Light exposure begins having more direct effects during spacing development as clusters emerge from leaf enclosure, with adequate light supporting robust final development while excessive shade may limit growth reducing spacing achievement. ||Water availability continues affecting development with adequate moisture supporting turgor-driven adjustments while stress limits growth maintaining established spacing without refinement. ||Disease management during spacing development becomes increasingly critical as susceptible flowering tissues develop with powdery mildew representing primary concern requiring protective fungicide coverage, with spacing pattern affecting infection risk through microenvironmental effects. ||The process represents third of four flower cluster separation aspects focusing on refinement rather than establishment, following primary and secondary separations and preceding individual cluster definition and individual flower separation. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing final adjustment period before individual flower separation initiation, with warm conditions promoting rapid completion. ||Cultivar variation appears in spacing adjustment extent with some varieties showing substantial refinement creating notably improved uniformity while others show minimal adjustment maintaining initial separation pattern, reflecting genetic regulation of final architectural elaboration. ||Regional timing shows cluster spacing development during late May in warm climates, late May-early June in temperate regions, and early June in cool areas, occurring in final days before individual flower separation begins. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final cluster microenvironment affecting disease pressure and fruit quality, completing architectural expression revealing previous season primordium formation pattern and current season environmental effects, preparing cluster for critical flowering period requiring adequate exposure and air circulation, and finalizing structural framework that will support fruit development through season. ||Research applications include quantifying spatial optimization processes during final cluster development, analyzing environmental effects on spacing refinement affecting final architecture, evaluating relationships between spacing patterns and disease susceptibility, and assessing functional consequences of architectural variation for fruit quality outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 348-352 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Individual_Cluster_Definition": {
  "definition": "An Individual_Cluster_Definition is a Flower_Cluster_Separation comprising the achievement of distinct visual and functional demarcation between adjacent flower groups within the inflorescence architecture.",
  "alternative_term": "cluster unit recognition | definitive cluster organization | flower group consolidation |+ individuelle Cluster-Definition | Gescheinseinheitserkennung | Blütengruppenverfestigung | Teilblütenstandsabgrenzung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows individual cluster definition during late May Year N+1 at late BBCH 57 over 1-2 days, with 18-25 primary branch units showing clear 2.5-3.5 mm spacing, flower buds enlarged to 3.0-3.5 mm creating visible flower mass within each unit, establishing recognizable cluster architecture in this moderately-to-highly compound early-bursting cultivar under cool maritime conditions of 16-19°C temperature preparing for flowering early June",
  "editor_note": "Individual_Cluster_Definition is fourth and final Flower_Cluster_Separation subphase, distinguished by achieving clear recognizable cluster unit identity. ||Follows and completes Primary, Secondary separation and Spacing Development. ||Transitions to Individual_Flower_Separation as flowers individualize within cluster units. ||Represents culmination of group-level organization before flower-level development. ||Marks readiness for flowering processes. || This final group-level organizational stage occurs during late May in temperate regions Year N+1 completing cluster separation process, typically spanning 1-2 days as final spatial adjustments and flower development create definitive cluster unit recognition. ||Definition achievement involves completion of spatial separation with final inter-cluster spacing established, flower bud enlargement to 3-4 mm creating visible flower mass within each cluster unit, and architectural stabilization with growth rates declining as structure approaches flowering readiness. ||Cluster unit recognition emerges through combined effects of spatial separation creating inter-group gaps, flower mass creating visual density within groups, and structural definition with branch units clearly distinguishable as discrete organizational elements. ||Visual demarcation between adjacent clusters shows clear spacing typically 2-5 mm in well-separated architectures enabling easy perceptual distinction, while compact architectures show minimal 1-2 mm spacing creating somewhat ambiguous boundaries though structural branch units remain identifiable. ||Functional cluster units represent coordinated developmental domains with flowers within each unit showing similar developmental stage supporting synchronized anthesis, creating temporal organization with individual cluster units flowering coordinately though entire inflorescence may show slight developmental gradient. ||Microenvironmental characteristics within defined cluster units show localized conditions including light exposure, air circulation, and temperature that will affect flowering success and subsequent fruit development, with well-defined separated clusters showing favorable microenvironment supporting uniform development. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster units improves during definition phase as flowers approach anthesis readiness, with good within-unit synchrony supporting coordinated flowering and uniform fruit set creating consistent berry development within cluster. ||Flower bud maturation during definition phase approaches completion with flower organs fully differentiated within enclosing calyptra, anthers mature with viable pollen, pistils developed with receptive stigmas, and nectaries functional preparing for nectar secretion, creating flowering readiness. ||Architectural framework established through definition determines cluster structure that will persist through anthesis, fruit set, berry development, and harvest, affecting disease pressure, fruit quality characteristics, and mechanical properties influencing handling and processing. ||Branch structural maturation during definition includes progressive wall thickening and beginning lignification particularly in rachis and primary branch bases establishing mechanical support adequate for flower weight and preparing for substantially greater berry loads. ||Vascular system completion during definition establishes transport capacity adequate for flowering water demands of 2-4 mg per second per cluster, with capacity prepared for increases to 8-15 mg per second during peak berry expansion supporting substantial water transport requirements. ||Metabolic transition during definition shows declining respiration from growth levels toward maintenance and flowering function levels, with energy allocation shifting from growth processes toward reproductive metabolism supporting anthesis and fertilization. ||Resource allocation during definition emphasizes inflorescence demands preparing for flowering with adequate carbohydrate reserves ensuring energy availability for anthesis processes, nitrogen concentrated in developing reproductive organs supporting protein synthesis, and mineral nutrients particularly boron positioned for supporting pollen germination and tube growth. ||Hormonal status during definition shows declining growth promoters as elongation completes, sustained auxin from developing flowers coordinating final maturation, possible increasing ethylene involved in senescence of calyptra cap preparing for cap fall, and other hormones coordinating transition toward flowering. ||Environmental conditions during definition include temperature approaching optimal flowering range with 18-24°C supporting final maturation and preparing for anthesis occurring optimally at 20-30°C, adequate moisture maintaining turgor supporting tissue function, and favorable weather supporting approaching critical flowering period. ||Disease pressure during definition intensifies as susceptible flowering tissues fully expose with powdery mildew infection risk high requiring final protective fungicide applications before flowering, botrytis potentially establishing infections that will remain latent through development expressing during ripening, and downy mildew threatening in wet conditions. ||Pest monitoring during definition includes grape berry moth adults present potentially ovipositing on inflorescences, leafhoppers reaching populations requiring management in some regions, and thrips colonization affecting flower quality potentially impacting pollination and fruit set. ||The process represents fourth and final flower cluster separation aspect completing group-level organization before individual flower separation, establishing recognizable cluster units that will function as developmental domains. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days representing brief culminating phase as definition emerges from completed spacing and maturation, with rapid transition toward individual flower separation. ||Cultivar variation appears in cluster unit clarity with loose-clustered varieties showing well-defined clearly separated units while tight-clustered types show less distinct units with ambiguous boundaries, affecting management assessment of flowering progress and disease intervention requirements. ||Regional timing shows individual cluster definition during late May in warm climates, late May-early June in temperate regions, and early June in cool areas, occurring immediately before individual flower separation and anthesis. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing recognizable organizational units facilitating cluster assessment and management, completing architectural framework affecting disease pressure and fruit quality throughout season, preparing cluster for critical flowering period with adequate exposure and appropriate microenvironment, and marking transition point from structural development to reproductive function. ||Research applications include analyzing perceptual and functional aspects of cluster organization, evaluating architectural effects on within-cluster developmental uniformity, quantifying relationships between cluster definition and flowering success, and assessing implications of cluster architecture for disease management and fruit quality outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 350-355 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Individual_Flower_Separation": {
  "definition": "An Individual_Flower_Separation is an Inflorescence_Emergence comprising the differentiation of compact flower buds into distinguishable individual flowers through pedicel elongation and inter-flower spacing, corresponding to BBCH 57–59.",
  "alternative_term": "flower bud separation | individual flower spacing | pedicel development |+ Einzelblütenseparation | Blütenknospentrennung | Blütenstielentwicklung | individuelle Blütenaufteilung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows individual flower separation during late May-early June Year N+1 at BBCH 57-59 over 4-5 days, with pedicels elongating from 0.8-1.2 mm to 2.5-4.0 mm creating flower spacing of 4-7 mm, flower buds enlarging to 4.0-4.5 mm with loosening caps preparing for anthesis, under oceanic conditions of 17-22°C temperature, adequate moisture, approaching optimal flowering conditions typical of this moderately spaced mid-season cultivar completing pre-anthesis preparation",
  "editor_note": "Individual_Flower_Separation represents final pre-anthesis phase within Inflorescence_Development focusing on flower-level individualization. ||Follows Flower_Cluster_Separation. ||Subdivided into Flower_Bud_Separation, Pedicel_Elongation, Individual_Flower_Visibility, and Flower_Spacing_Completion. ||Transitions directly to Flowering phase as anthesis initiates. ||Critical preparatory phase establishing conditions for successful pollination and fruit set. ||Completion marks flowering readiness. || This critical preparatory phase occurs during late May-early June in temperate regions Year N+1 following cluster separation, typically spanning 3-5 days as coordinated pedicel elongation and flower bud maturation transform compact undifferentiated flower masses into arrays of individual flowers ready for anthesis. ||Separation mechanism involves pedicel elongation extending flower attachment stalks from initial 0.5-1.5 mm to final 2-5 mm creating spatial projection, flower bud enlargement from 3-4 mm to 4-5 mm as organs complete maturation, and slight branch elongation distributing flower attachment points along branch length. ||Pedicel function includes structural support maintaining flower position and orientation, vascular connection providing water and nutrient delivery to flower and developing fruit, and mechanical flexibility allowing flower movement facilitating pollination and later accommodating berry expansion. ||Individual flower visibility emerges progressively during separation as pedicels extend projecting flowers away from compact positions, creating recognizable individual flower units arranged along branches rather than undifferentiated masses. ||Flower spacing completion establishes final pre-anthesis flower arrangement with inter-flower distances typically 3-8 mm depending on cluster architecture, supporting adequate separation for air circulation around flowers, pollen transfer between flowers, and accommodation of expanding berries after fruit set. ||Flower bud maturation during separation approaches completion with all flower organs fully developed and functional, calyptra cap loosening in preparation for detachment, anthers positioned for dehiscence and pollen release, pistils mature with receptive stigmas, and nectaries active producing nectar attracting potential insect pollinators. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster increases during individual separation as flowers achieve similar readiness states, supporting synchronized anthesis with coordinated cap fall and pollen release across cluster promoting effective pollination and uniform fruit set. ||Pedicel elongation mechanism involves cell division in pedicel meristem zones adding cells to pedicel length particularly during early separation, and cell expansion throughout pedicel tissues increasing cell dimensions through turgor-driven growth, with elongation rate typically 0.3-0.8 mm per day at optimal temperatures. ||Vascular differentiation in elongating pedicels establishes functional xylem and phloem connecting flower to branch vascular system, enabling water delivery supporting flower turgor and function, nutrient import supporting metabolism and organ growth, and preparing for post-fertilization assimilate import during berry development. ||Mechanical properties of pedicels show flexible structure from thin-walled tissues allowing flower movement and positioning adjustments, with progressive strengthening as walls thicken though major lignification occurs later during fruit development when mechanical demands increase. ||Flower positioning during separation establishes spatial orientation affecting pollination efficiency with flowers typically oriented upward or laterally exposing stigmas for pollen deposition, with positioning also affecting post-anthesis berry orientation and cluster geometry. ||Metabolic activity during individual separation maintains elevated levels supporting continued development with respiration 8-12 fold above mature tissue levels, though beginning to shift from growth to reproductive function supporting approaching anthesis. ||Resource demands during separation emphasize carbohydrate requirements for continued growth and preparing energy reserves for anthesis processes, nitrogen for final protein synthesis in reproductive organs, and minerals particularly boron critical for pollen germination and tube growth. ||Hormonal regulation during separation involves auxin from developing flowers affecting pedicel elongation and positioning, gibberellins potentially affecting elongation though concentrations declining toward flowering, and ethylene possibly involved in cap loosening preparing for cap fall. ||Environmental conditions during separation critically affect development with temperature approaching flowering optimum with 18-26°C supporting final separation and maturation, adequate moisture maintaining turgor supporting elongation and flower function, and favorable weather conditions supporting approaching anthesis. ||Light exposure increases during separation as flowers extend from cluster interior toward exterior, with adequate light supporting robust flower development though excessive exposure potentially causing stress effects. ||Water stress during separation impairs development through effects on turgor limiting pedicel elongation and potentially affecting flower viability, requiring adequate soil moisture and favorable evaporative conditions minimizing stress. ||Disease pressure during separation focuses on powdery mildew with fully exposed flowers highly susceptible requiring final protective applications before anthesis, with infection during flowering potentially causing berry infection affecting fruit development. ||Developmental coordination between separation and approaching anthesis shows tight coupling with separation completing as flowers achieve anthesis readiness, creating seamless transition from structural preparation to reproductive function. ||Within-flower organ maturation proceeds during separation with final anther dehiscence preparation including connective tissue development enabling anther opening, pollen maturation completing with viable pollen grains containing developed gametophytes, pistil maturation with ovules prepared for fertilization containing mature megagametophytes, and stigma surface development establishing receptivity for pollen germination. ||The process shows four distinguishable developmental aspects progressing from flower bud separation beginning individualization, through pedicel elongation creating spatial projection, individual flower visibility establishing recognition, to flower spacing completion achieving final pre-anthesis arrangement. ||Duration typically spans 3-5 days depending on temperature and cultivar characteristics, with warm conditions promoting rapid completion while cool conditions extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in final pedicel length affecting flower spacing with long-pedicelled varieties showing 4-6 mm creating well-separated flowers facilitating air circulation while short-pedicelled types showing 2-3 mm maintaining compact flower arrangement, separation rate affecting timing toward flowering, and flower size at separation affecting visual impact. ||Regional timing shows individual flower separation during late May-early June in warm climates, early June in temperate regions, and early-mid June in cool areas, occurring immediately before anthesis with separation completing as flowering initiates. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final flower arrangement affecting pollination efficiency and fruit set uniformity, completing pre-anthesis development preparing flowers for critical reproductive processes, creating favorable microenvironment for flowering with adequate air circulation reducing disease pressure, and marking final preparation stage before flowering requiring optimal management and conditions. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating pedicel elongation and flower spacing, investigating environmental effects on separation affecting flowering readiness, quantifying relationships between flower spacing and pollination efficiency, evaluating coordination between separation completion and anthesis initiation, and assessing genetic variation in flower separation characteristics affecting fruit set and yield.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 352-360 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Flower_Bud_Separation": {
  "definition": "A Flower_Bud_Separation is an Individual_Flower_Separation comprising the initial differentiation of clustered flower buds into distinguishable units through pedicel elongation onset and bud expansion.",
  "alternative_term": "bud loosening | initial flower separation | beginning flower individuation |+ Blütenknospentrennung | Knospenlockerung | beginnende Einzelblütenisolierung | initiale Blütenseparation",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows flower bud separation during late May Year N+1 at BBCH 57 over 1-2 days, with tightly packed 3.2-3.6 mm flower buds beginning to separate as pedicels elongate from 0.6-0.8 mm to 1.2-1.8 mm creating initial gaps between buds under warm climate conditions of 19-24°C temperature, approaching optimal flowering conditions typical of this late-season cultivar initiating pre-anthesis flower individuation",
  "editor_note": "Flower_Bud_Separation is first of four Individual_Flower_Separation subphases, distinguished by initial flower individuation before substantial pedicel elongation. ||Represents beginning of transition from compact cluster to separated flowers. ||Transitions rapidly to Pedicel_Elongation as separation proceeds. ||Brief phase marking initiation of critical pre-anthesis development. ||Indicates imminent flowering requiring preparation and protection. || This critical initiation stage occurs during late May-early June in temperate regions Year N+1 as part of individual flower separation process, typically requiring 1-2 days as initial pedicel growth and bud enlargement create perceptible flower individuation. ||Separation initiation shows flower buds loosening from extremely tight packing where buds physically contact neighbors creating compressed undifferentiated appearance, toward beginning separation with small gaps appearing between adjacent buds as pedicels start extending. ||Initial pedicel elongation during bud separation extends flower attachment stalks from very short 0.5-1.0 mm initial length to 1.0-2.0 mm as first separation increment, with elongation creating minimal but perceptible spatial projection beginning to isolate flowers. ||Flower bud enlargement from 3.0-3.5 mm to 3.5-4.0 mm diameter contributes to separation as expanding buds require more space, with expansion resulting from continued flower organ growth within enclosing calyptra approaching final pre-anthesis dimensions. ||Bud surface characteristics during separation show smooth green calyptra tightly enclosing flower organs with seam between fused petal tips potentially becoming slightly more apparent as cap loosening begins, though cap remains firmly attached during separation with detachment occurring during subsequent anthesis. ||Spatial positioning of separating buds shows transition from chaotic compressed arrangement with random bud orientations to beginning organized array with buds showing more consistent upward or lateral orientation as pedicels establish positioning. ||Flower organ status within separating buds shows continued maturation with anthers completing pollen development, pistils achieving final size with ovary expansion and stigma development, and nectaries becoming functional, all occurring while enclosed within protective calyptra. ||Mechanical properties of separating flower structures show delicate fragile nature with thin-walled tissues easily damaged by physical contact, rain impact, or pest feeding, requiring gentle handling and protective conditions. ||Vascular function in beginning-to-elongate pedicels shows developing transport capacity with xylem vessels differentiating to enable water delivery and phloem elements forming to support nutrient import, though capacity remains limited at this early separation stage. ||Metabolic activity during bud separation maintains elevated levels supporting continued growth and maturation, with respiration providing energy for pedicel elongation, organ expansion, and approaching reproductive function. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster during bud separation shows flowers at similar stages with synchronized separation initiation across cluster supporting coordinated anthesis, though slight developmental gradient may persist with distal flowers sometimes slightly advanced. ||Resource requirements during separation emphasize carbohydrate demand for continued growth and energy storage for anthesis, nitrogen for final protein synthesis particularly in anthers and pollen, and boron critical for pollen viability and approaching germination and tube growth. ||Hormonal regulation during bud separation involves auxin affecting pedicel initiation and early elongation, possible declining gibberellins as reproductive maturation proceeds, and beginning ethylene involvement in cap loosening processes. ||Environmental conditions during bud separation include temperature nearing flowering optimum with 18-24°C supporting separation and continued maturation, adequate moisture maintaining turgor supporting elongation, and favorable weather protecting delicate developing structures. ||Disease vulnerability during bud separation emphasizes powdery mildew with susceptible tissues fully exposed and infection potential high, requiring protective fungicide coverage particularly in conducive humid conditions or susceptible varieties. ||Developmental progression from bud separation proceeds rapidly toward continued pedicel elongation and full flower individuation, with separation representing brief initial phase in 3-5 day individual flower separation process. ||Within-bud organ positioning shows anthers positioned centrally within calyptra cap preparing for cap fall and pollen release, pistil extending upward with stigma approaching cap apex positioning for early exposure at anthesis, and nectaries at flower base preparing for nectar secretion. ||The process represents first of four individual flower separation aspects marking beginning of flower individuation, transitioning rapidly toward pedicel elongation and complete flower separation. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days representing brief initiation phase as separation begins, with warm conditions promoting rapid progression toward elongation. ||Cultivar variation appears in separation initiation timing with some varieties showing early coordinated bud separation while others show more gradual progressive separation, affecting synchrony of subsequent flowering. ||Regional timing shows flower bud separation during late May-early June in warm climates, early June in temperate regions, and early-mid June in cool areas, occurring 2-4 days before anthesis initiation. ||Viticultural significance includes marking beginning of final pre-anthesis development, establishing vulnerability period requiring disease protection and favorable conditions, indicating imminent flowering requiring preparation for bloom management, and representing point where flower number becomes definitively countable for yield prediction. ||Research applications include documenting earliest stages of flower individuation, analyzing coordination of separation initiation across cluster, evaluating environmental effects on separation affecting flowering uniformity, and assessing developmental readiness markers for anthesis prediction.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 352-355 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pedicel_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Pedicel_Elongation is an Individual_Flower_Separation comprising the length increase of flower attachment stalks producing spatial separation between flowers.",
  "alternative_term": "pedicel extension | flower stalk elongation | peduncle development |+ Blütenstielstreckung | Stielchenverlängerung | Blütenansatzverlängerung | Pedizelexpansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows pedicel elongation during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 57-59 over 2-3 days, with flower pedicels extending from 1.2-1.5 mm to 3.5-4.5 mm at rate of 0.9-1.3 mm per day creating flower spacing of 5-8 mm under warm Mediterranean conditions of 21-26°C temperature, adequate moisture, typical of this moderately loose-clustered mid-to-late season cultivar completing spatial flower separation before anthesis",
  "editor_note": "Pedicel_Elongation is second of four Individual_Flower_Separation subphases, distinguished by active stalk extension creating primary spatial separation. ||Follows Flower_Bud_Separation. ||Represents main mechanism of flower individuation. ||Transitions to Individual_Flower_Visibility and Spacing_Completion. ||Primary determinant of flower spacing and cluster density. ||Highly temperature-dependent process. ||Genetic pedicel length variation fundamentally affects architecture. || This critical separation process occurs during late May-early June in temperate regions Year N+1 as main component of individual flower separation, typically spanning 2-3 days as coordinated pedicel extension creates 2-5 mm final stalk lengths projecting flowers away from branch attachment points. ||Elongation mechanism involves cell division in pedicel intercalary meristem zones adding cells to pedicel length particularly during early rapid elongation at 24-36 hour cycles, and cell expansion throughout pedicel tissues with cells increasing length 10-30 fold through turgor-driven wall extension creating visible daily growth of 0.5-1.2 mm. ||Pedicel structure includes central vascular core with xylem vessels differentiating to conduct water at 0.1-0.3 mg per second per flower adequate for flower function and prepared for berry expansion demands, phloem sieve elements forming to enable nutrient import, surrounding parenchyma providing flexibility and storage capacity, and epidermis with cuticle providing protection. ||Elongation rate shows strong temperature dependence with development approximately doubling per 10°C increase between 15-28°C range, with optimal 20-26°C supporting maximum elongation rate of 0.8-1.2 mm per day completing elongation within 2-3 days. ||Final pedicel length varies among cultivars affecting flower spacing with long-pedicelled varieties achieving 4-6 mm creating well-separated loose flower arrangement enhancing air circulation, moderate-pedicelled types reaching 3-4 mm producing intermediate spacing, and short-pedicelled varieties attaining 2-3 mm maintaining relatively compact flower clustering. ||Pedicel positioning establishes flower orientation with most flowers angled upward or laterally exposing stigmas for pollen deposition, with positioning resulting from phototropic and gravitropic responses and possibly mechanical constraints from neighboring structures. ||Mechanical properties during elongation show flexible herbaceous structure from thin primary cell walls allowing bending and movement, with progressive wall thickening increasing strength though major mechanical development awaits fruit set when pedicel must support berry weight. ||Vascular maturation during elongation establishes functional transport capacity with vessel differentiation proceeding basipetally from flower toward branch connection, creating continuous water pathway from branch through pedicel to flower supporting turgor and metabolic function. ||Cell wall composition changes during elongation from thin plastic walls allowing expansion to progressively thickening walls with increased cellulose deposition providing structural strength, though walls remain relatively thin compared to mature fruit-bearing pedicels. ||Flower bud development continues during pedicel elongation with buds enlarging to 4-5 mm final pre-anthesis size as flower organs complete maturation, calyptra cap progressively loosening preparing for detachment, and reproductive organs achieving functional readiness. ||Metabolic activity during elongation maintains elevated respiration supporting growth processes, with energy demands met through photosynthetic assimilate import as shoot canopy provides substantial production capacity. ||Protein synthesis continues at high rates producing structural proteins for expanding cells, enzymes supporting rapid metabolism and wall modification, and preparing enzymes for reproductive processes. ||Resource requirements during elongation emphasize carbohydrate demand for cell wall synthesis and energy, nitrogen for protein synthesis, and minerals particularly calcium for wall structure and boron critical for upcoming pollen germination. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin promoting elongation through effects on cell expansion and wall loosening, declining gibberellins as reproductive transition proceeds, and possible brassinosteroid effects on cell expansion. ||Environmental conditions critically affect elongation with temperature as primary factor determining rate, adequate moisture essential for turgor supporting expansion, and favorable weather protecting delicate elongating structures from damage. ||Water stress during elongation impairs development through turgor loss limiting expansion, potentially resulting in shortened pedicels reducing flower spacing affecting pollination and fruit development accommodation. ||Disease pressure during elongation continues with powdery mildew representing primary concern requiring protective coverage, with elongating pedicels themselves relatively resistant but attached flowers highly susceptible. ||Developmental coordination shows pedicel elongation proceeding synchronously across cluster flowers supporting uniform spatial arrangement, with good uniformity promoting coordinated anthesis and fruit set. ||Within-flower organ positioning changes during pedicel elongation as elongating stalk projects flower away from branch, affecting relative positioning of flower structures and preparing spatial relationships for anthesis. ||The process represents second of four individual flower separation aspects providing primary mechanism for spatial individuation, following bud separation and preceding full flower visibility and spacing completion. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing main active elongation period, with warm conditions promoting rapid completion while cool conditions extend period. ||Cultivar variation represents major feature with genetically determined final pedicel length ranging from short 2-3 mm in compact types to long 5-6 mm in loose types fundamentally affecting cluster architecture, elongation rate affecting timing, and elongation uniformity affecting developmental synchrony. ||Regional timing shows pedicel elongation during late May-early June in warm climates, early June in temperate regions, and early-mid June in cool areas, occurring 1-3 days before anthesis initiation. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing flower spacing affecting pollination efficiency with adequate spacing improving pollen transfer, creating cluster microenvironment affecting disease pressure with good separation enhancing air circulation, preparing structural support for berry development with pedicel strength affecting fruit attachment, and determining final cluster density affecting fruit quality and harvest characteristics. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating pedicel elongation including hormonal and biomechanical controls, quantifying environmental effects particularly temperature on elongation affecting flower spacing, evaluating genetic variation in pedicel characteristics affecting cluster architecture, and assessing functional relationships between pedicel length and pollination efficiency and fruit quality outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 355-358 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Individual_Flower_Visibility": {
  "definition": "An Individual_Flower_Visibility is an Individual_Flower_Separation comprising the projection of flowers on elongated pedicels to a configuration in which each flower is distinguishable as a separate unit.",
  "alternative_term": "distinct flower appearance | individual flower recognition | flower counting stage |+ einzelne Blütensichtbarkeit | deutliche Blütenerkennung | Blütenzählstadium | Einzelblütenerkennbarkeit",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows individual flower visibility during early June Year N+1 at late BBCH 59 over 1-2 days, with 200-350 individual flowers per cluster clearly distinguishable on pedicels of 2.5-3.5 mm length, flower buds 4.0-4.5 mm showing slight cap loosening in earliest flowers, under cool climate conditions of 17-21°C temperature approaching flowering, enabling accurate flower counting for yield prediction in this moderately compact early-to-mid season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Individual_Flower_Visibility is third of four Individual_Flower_Separation subphases, distinguished by achievement of clear perceptual distinction of individual flowers. ||Follows Pedicel_Elongation as recognition milestone. ||Overlaps with or transitions to Flower_Spacing_Completion as final arrangements establish. ||Represents practical assessment stage for flower counting and yield prediction. ||Marks flowering readiness with anthesis imminent. || This important recognition milestone occurs during early June in temperate regions Year N+1 as pedicel elongation nears completion, typically representing 1-2 day period when individual flowers achieve definitive visual distinction corresponding to late BBCH 57-59 stages immediately preceding anthesis. ||Visibility achievement involves completion of substantial pedicel elongation projecting flowers 2-4 mm from branch attachment creating spatial separation, flower bud enlargement to 4-5 mm final pre-anthesis size establishing visible flower mass, and flower positioning with most flowers oriented upward or laterally creating recognizable spatial array. ||Visual distinction criteria include clear inter-flower spacing enabling perception of individual flowers rather than undifferentiated masses, recognizable flower bud morphology with calyptra cap shape distinguishable, and spatial positioning allowing viewing of individual flowers from multiple angles confirming independent status. ||Flower countability emerges during visibility phase as individual flowers can be reliably enumerated providing accurate assessment of potential berry number, supporting yield prediction calculations and crop adjustment decisions based on desired crop load. ||Cluster appearance transitions from compressed flower masses at separation initiation to clearly defined arrays of individual recognizable flowers at visibility achievement, revealing final pre-anthesis cluster architecture including branching pattern, flower density, and spatial organization. ||Flower bud characteristics at visibility show 4-5 mm green calyptra caps with smooth surface, fused petal seams potentially visible indicating enclosed corolla, slight cap loosening detectable in some flowers approaching earliest anthesis, and overall plump appearance indicating mature flower organs within. ||Flower positioning patterns show majority of flowers oriented upward 30-60 degrees above horizontal or laterally near horizontal, with positioning affecting stigma exposure for pollen deposition and reflecting phototropic, gravitropic, and mechanical influences. ||Pedicel characteristics at visibility include final or near-final length of 2-5 mm depending on cultivar, green herbaceous appearance with smooth surface, flexible structure allowing flower movement in wind, and functional vascular connection visible as slight ridge along pedicel length. ||Spatial flower distribution along branches shows characteristic pattern with flowers distributed according to branching architecture, inter-flower spacing reflecting pedicel length and branch elongation, and overall density determined by flower number per unit branch length. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster at visibility shows most flowers at similar maturation stage with synchronized cap loosening and approaching anthesis, supporting coordinated flowering across cluster promoting uniform pollination and fruit set. ||Microenvironmental characteristics within visible flower arrays include air circulation patterns with adequate flower spacing promoting rapid drying after rain or dew reducing disease infection risk, light exposure with flowers emerging from leaf shade toward better illumination, and temperature distribution with exposed flowers experiencing warmer conditions potentially advancing development. ||Flower organ status at visibility shows complete maturation with anthers containing viable pollen, pistils with receptive stigmas prepared for pollen germination, nectaries functional and beginning nectar production, and all structures positioned for imminent anthesis. ||Resource status at visibility shows accumulated carbohydrate reserves in flowers providing energy for anthesis processes, nitrogen concentrated in reproductive organs supporting continued protein synthesis, and critical minerals particularly boron positioned for pollen germination and tube growth. ||Hormonal environment at visibility involves declining growth promoters as elongation completes, sustained auxin from flowers, increasing ethylene potentially involved in cap abscission triggering, and other hormones coordinating transition from development to reproductive function. ||Environmental conditions at visibility approach optimal flowering requirements with temperature typically 19-26°C supporting final maturation and approaching anthesis optimum 22-30°C, adequate moisture maintaining flower turgor and function, and favorable weather protecting delicate structures and supporting approaching pollination. ||Disease assessment at visibility enables evaluation of powdery mildew infection presence with visible mycelial growth indicating infection requiring immediate intervention, though fully protective fungicide applications must precede visibility due to application restrictions during flowering. ||Pest presence at visibility may include grape berry moth larvae on inflorescences potentially affecting flower survival, leafhoppers feeding causing stippling damage, and thrips affecting flower quality potentially impacting pollination efficiency. ||Developmental progression from visibility proceeds immediately toward anthesis with cap fall initiating within 1-2 days in earliest flowers, creating seamless transition from structural preparation to reproductive function. ||The process represents third of four individual flower separation aspects marking achievement of clear flower recognition, following bud separation and pedicel elongation and preceding final spacing completion. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day period when visibility definitively achieves though flowers have been progressively becoming more distinct during elongation. ||Cultivar variation appears in visibility clarity with loose-clustered well-spaced varieties showing obvious early visibility while tight-clustered compact types show less distinct visibility requiring careful inspection, affecting assessment ease and management timing precision. ||Regional timing shows individual flower visibility during late May-early June in warm climates, early June in temperate regions, and early-mid June in cool areas, occurring 1-2 days before anthesis initiation with visibility representing flowering readiness indicator. ||Viticultural significance includes enabling accurate flower counting for yield prediction, confirming cluster architecture affecting disease risk and quality potential, indicating imminent flowering requiring final preparations and optimal conditions, providing assessment reference for flowering uniformity predictions, and marking transition point from developmental to reproductive management focus. ||Research applications include documenting precise timing relationships between visibility achievement and anthesis initiation, evaluating environmental effects on visibility clarity affecting assessment reliability, quantifying flower counting accuracy as function of architectural clarity, and developing automated computer vision systems for flower counting leveraging visibility characteristics.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 358-360 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Flower_Spacing_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Flower_Spacing_Completion is an Individual_Flower_Separation comprising the achievement of definitive inter-flower distances within the inflorescence preceding anthesis.",
  "alternative_term": "final flower spacing | completed flower arrangement | pre-anthesis positioning |+ Blütenabstandsabschluss | finale Blütenanordnung | Vorblüten-Positionierung | abgeschlossene Blütenverteilung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows flower spacing completion during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 59 over 1-2 days, with 300-550 individual flowers per cluster achieving final spacing of 4-7 mm on pedicels of 3.0-4.5 mm, flower buds 4.5-5.0 mm showing advanced cap loosening preparing for anthesis initiation within 24-36 hours, under temperate maritime conditions of 19-23°C temperature, 50-65% relative humidity, favorable for imminent flowering in this moderately loose-clustered vigorous mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Flower_Spacing_Completion is fourth and final Individual_Flower_Separation subphase, distinguished by achievement of final pre-anthesis spatial arrangement. ||Follows Flower_Bud_Separation, Pedicel_Elongation, and Individual_Flower_Visibility. ||Represents culmination of entire Inflorescence_Development spanning two growing seasons. ||Transitions immediately to Flowering phase as anthesis initiates. ||Critical milestone indicating flowering readiness and requiring optimal conditions for successful bloom. || This culminating organizational stage occurs during early June in temperate regions Year N+1 as individual flower separation concludes, typically representing final 1-2 days of development before anthesis initiation at BBCH 59 immediately preceding flowering. ||Completion achievement involves cessation of pedicel elongation at final lengths of 2-5 mm establishing permanent flower attachment dimensions, finalization of flower positioning with stable spatial orientations, and cluster architecture stabilization with growth processes declining as structure transitions from development to reproductive function. ||Final spacing characteristics show inter-flower distances typically 3-8 mm depending on cultivar architecture and pedicel length, with spacing adequate for air circulation around individual flowers promoting rapid drying and reducing disease pressure, sufficient for pollen transfer between flowers during wind-assisted self-pollination, and appropriate for accommodating berry expansion after fruit set without excessive crowding. ||Spatial optimization during completion may involve minor positioning adjustments through differential pedicel growth or branch repositioning, creating more uniform flower distribution and improved microenvironmental conditions within cluster. ||Flower arrangement pattern at completion reveals complete architectural expression reflecting previous season primordium formation with branching hierarchy fully realized, current season environmental effects on elongation and spacing development integrated, and genetic architectural program completely manifested in final cluster structure. ||Microenvironmental characteristics in completed flower arrays include favorable air circulation with adequate spacing enabling rapid evaporation of surface moisture reducing powdery mildew and botrytis infection risks, appropriate light exposure with flowers positioned for moderate illumination supporting function without excessive heat stress, and temperature distribution with exposed flowers experiencing conditions near ambient promoting normal development. ||Flower organ final maturation during spacing completion shows anthers fully developed with mature pollen grains containing bicellular or tricellular male gametophytes, pistils with receptive stigmas showing papillate surface cells and active exudate production, ovaries containing mature ovules with developed megagametophytes, and nectaries producing nectar in 30-50% flowers attracting potential insect pollinators. ||Calyptra cap loosening advances during completion with connection between fused petals and receptacle weakening through abscission zone development, preparing for cap detachment during imminent anthesis with cap fall typically initiating within 12-24 hours of completion. ||Pedicel structural maturation at completion includes cessation of elongation growth with cells achieving final dimensions, progressive wall thickening particularly in vascular tissues preparing for berry support function, and beginning subtle lignification in basal pedicel regions establishing permanent structural properties. ||Vascular function at completion shows fully developed transport capacity with xylem conducting water at rates adequate for flower function and prepared for substantial increases during berry expansion, phloem enabling bidirectional transport with current import supporting flower metabolism and prepared for future export during late berry ripening. ||Mechanical properties at completion show flexible yet adequate strength for supporting flowers during anthesis and small developing berries immediately after fruit set, with major mechanical development awaiting berry expansion when loads increase substantially requiring pedicel strengthening. ||Resource status at completion emphasizes stored energy reserves in flowers providing carbohydrates for anthesis processes particularly anther dehiscence and pollen tube growth, nitrogen concentrated in reproductive organs supporting protein synthesis for reproductive function, and critical minerals especially boron essential for pollen germination positioned for utilization. ||Metabolic transition at completion shows declining growth-related respiration as elongation ceases, increasing reproductive metabolism preparing for anthesis including elevated respiration in anthers supporting pollen maturation and dehiscence, and active sugar metabolism in nectaries producing nectar. ||Hormonal environment at completion involves low growth promoters as developmental processes complete, sustained reproductive hormones supporting flower function, increasing ethylene triggering or coordinating cap abscission, and integrated signals preparing flowering initiation. ||Environmental conditions at completion should approach flowering optimum with temperature 20-28°C ideal for anthesis supporting cap fall and pollen release, relative humidity 40-70% adequate for pollen viability without excessive moisture causing issues, and calm to light wind conditions facilitating pollination without physical damage. ||Weather sensitivity increases at completion as flowers become maximally vulnerable with rain or high humidity potentially delaying anthesis or reducing pollen viability, cool temperatures slowing or preventing normal flowering progression, and excessive heat potentially causing pollen sterility or stigma dysfunction. ||Disease pressure reaches critical stage at completion with powdery mildew infection potential highest on fully exposed susceptible flower tissues, requiring that protective fungicide coverage be established before completion as applications during flowering are restricted, and botrytis potentially establishing latent infections that will remain dormant through development expressing during ripening. ||Pest presence at completion may include thrips reaching maximum abundance affecting flower quality and potentially interfering with pollination, grape berry moth adults present potentially ovipositing during or immediately after flowering, and leafhoppers at varying populations depending on region and management. ||Developmental uniformity at completion shows high synchrony with most flowers at similar maturation state supporting coordinated anthesis across cluster, with synchronized flowering promoting effective pollination through overlapping pollen availability and receptive stigmas, and uniform fruit set creating consistent berry development within cluster. ||The process represents fourth and final individual flower separation aspect completing all pre-anthesis spatial organization, following bud separation, pedicel elongation, and flower visibility achievement. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day culminating period as final adjustments complete and structure stabilizes before flowering, with rapid transition to anthesis initiation. ||Cultivar variation appears in final spacing characteristics with loose-clustered types achieving 6-10 mm inter-flower distances creating very open architecture while tight-clustered varieties maintaining 3-5 mm spacing producing compact structure, affecting disease pressure, pollination efficiency, and fruit quality potential. ||Regional timing shows flower spacing completion during early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-June in cool areas, occurring immediately before anthesis with flowering typically initiating within 24-48 hours of completion. ||Viticultural significance includes marking definitive flowering readiness enabling precise bloom timing predictions, establishing final cluster architecture determining disease pressure, pollination conditions, and fruit development potential throughout season, representing culmination of two-season inflorescence development from previous season primordium formation through current season emergence and separation, and indicating critical transition point requiring optimal conditions and management for successful flowering and fruit set. ||Research applications include documenting precise spatial relationships in completed flower arrays, analyzing environmental effects on final spacing affecting functional outcomes, quantifying relationships between spacing characteristics and pollination efficiency and fruit set uniformity, evaluating microenvironmental consequences of architectural variation for disease susceptibility and fruit quality, and assessing coordination mechanisms synchronizing spacing completion with anthesis initiation across diverse genotypes and environments.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 358-365 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Flowering": {
  "definition": "A Flowering is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising flower opening through cap shedding, pollen release and transfer to receptive stigmas, and fertilization producing zygotes.",
  "alternative_term": "bloom | anthesis period | flowering period | reproductive phase |+ Blüte | Blühphase | Blütezeit | reproduktive Phase | Anthese",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows flowering during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-69 over 8-10 days, progressing from first flowers opening June 5-7 through peak anthesis June 8-12 with 60-80% flowers open simultaneously to late anthesis completing June 14-16, achieving 45-60% fruit set under oceanic climate conditions of 18-25°C temperature, 50-70% relative humidity, light winds, and no significant rain during bloom, typical of this mid-season moderately productive cultivar producing 300-450 berries per cluster",
  "editor_note": "Flowering represents critical reproductive phase within Grapevine_Phenological_Process determining yield and quality. ||Distinguished from Inflorescence_Development which establishes structure and from Fruit_Set which follows successful fertilization. ||Subdivided into Anthesis covering flower opening and pollination, and subsequent fertilization and early berry development phases. ||Environmental conditions during flowering critically affect success. ||Timing represents major phenological marker. ||Corresponds to BBCH 60-69. || This essential reproductive period occurs during early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1 following inflorescence development, typically spanning 7-14 days from first flower opening through completion of anthesis across cluster depending on environmental conditions and developmental uniformity. ||Flowering encompasses cap shedding where fused petal calyptra detaches exposing reproductive organs, pollen release through anther dehiscence liberating mature pollen grains, pollination through wind-assisted self-pollination transferring pollen to stigmas, pollen germination on receptive stigma surfaces, pollen tube growth through style tissues delivering sperm cells to ovules, and fertilization with sperm-egg fusion initiating embryo development and endosperm formation. ||The process shows characteristic progression beginning with sporadic early flower opening, accelerating through peak anthesis when maximum flowers open simultaneously, and declining during late anthesis as final flowers complete opening, with entire cluster typically requiring 5-10 days to complete flowering depending on developmental synchrony. ||Grapevine flowers show distinctive morphology with pentamerous organization having five sepals fused into calyptra cap, five petals fused and coherent with calyptra forming cap that sheds as unit, five stamens with anthers producing pollen, and superior bicarpellate ovary containing typically four ovules though only 0-4 develop into seeds. ||Cap shedding mechanism involves abscission zone development at junction between fused petals and receptacle, with zone cells degrading middle lamella through enzymatic activity creating separation plane, and mechanical stresses from expanding reproductive organs and potentially turgor changes driving physical detachment. ||Anther dehiscence proceeds through specialized stomium zones in anther walls where cells undergo programmed breakdown creating longitudinal slits, with dehiscence triggered by humidity decrease causing anther wall dehydration and mechanical opening releasing pollen through slits. ||Pollen characteristics include small spheroidal grains 25-35 micrometers diameter with three-colporate aperture pattern, tricellular maturity state at release containing vegetative cell and two sperm cells, and limited longevity remaining viable only hours to few days depending on environmental conditions. ||Pollination mechanism in grapevine involves predominantly self-pollination with wind assistance transferring pollen from anthers to stigmas within same flower or neighboring flowers on same vine, with occasional insect visitation attracted by nectar but playing minor role compared to wind. ||Stigma receptivity develops progressively showing papillate surface cells producing adhesive exudate capturing pollen grains, with receptivity peaking 1-3 days after flower opening and persisting 4-7 days depending on conditions. ||Pollen germination on receptive stigma occurs within 1-4 hours under favorable conditions with pollen grain hydrating from stigma exudate, producing pollen tube that penetrates stigma surface growing through transmitting tract tissues in style toward ovary. ||Pollen tube growth proceeds at rate of 1-3 mm per hour requiring 12-36 hours to traverse 15-30 mm style length reaching ovary, with tube guided by chemotactic signals from ovules growing through micropyle into embryo sac. ||Double fertilization characteristic of angiosperms occurs with one sperm cell fusing with egg forming diploid zygote initiating embryo development, and other sperm cell fusing with two polar nuclei forming triploid endosperm nucleus initiating nutritive tissue development. ||Fruit set following successful fertilization shows developing seeds producing hormones particularly auxin and gibberellins triggering berry development, with successful fertilization preventing flower abscission and initiating berry expansion from initial 2-3 mm ovary to mature berry dimensions. ||Environmental conditions critically affect flowering success with temperature representing primary factor with optimal 20-30°C supporting rapid coordinated anthesis and effective pollination, cool conditions below 15°C delaying flowering and reducing pollen viability, and excessive heat above 35°C potentially causing pollen sterility or stigma dysfunction. ||Water status affects flowering with moderate water stress potentially beneficial for concentrating carbohydrate reserves supporting reproductive processes, while severe stress impairs function potentially causing poor fruit set. ||Humidity affects pollen function with moderate 40-70% relative humidity optimal for pollen viability and dehiscence, while high humidity above 80% delays dehiscence and promotes fungal infection, and very low humidity below 30% causes rapid pollen desiccation reducing viability. ||Rain during flowering represents major concern with water washing pollen from anthers and stigmas, preventing dehiscence, promoting fungal infection particularly botrytis, and physically damaging delicate reproductive structures, potentially severely reducing fruit set. ||Wind during flowering shows dual effects with light-moderate wind facilitating pollination through pollen dispersal, while strong wind may damage flowers or excessively dry tissues reducing function. ||Light intensity during flowering affects overall vine vigor and photosynthetic support for reproductive processes, with adequate light supporting robust flowering though direct effects on individual flowers are modest. ||Nutrient requirements during flowering emphasize boron critical for pollen germination and tube growth with deficiency causing poor fruit set, adequate nitrogen supporting protein synthesis in reproductive tissues, and balanced nutrition supporting overall vine function. ||Carbohydrate availability affects flowering success with adequate reserves supporting energy-demanding reproductive processes, while limitation from excessive crop load, disease, or previous season stress may reduce flowering vigor affecting fruit set. ||Hormonal regulation involves auxin from developing seeds triggering berry development and preventing abscission, gibberellins affecting flowering and early berry development with applications sometimes used to manipulate berry size and seedlessness, cytokinins supporting cell division in developing berries, and ethylene potentially involved in cap abscission and flower senescence. ||Fruit set percentage varies substantially among cultivars and conditions ranging from 10-30% in varieties with poor set or unfavorable conditions creating loose clusters, to 40-70% in good-setting varieties under favorable conditions producing compact clusters, with fruit set determined by successful fertilization frequency among total flowers. ||Developmental coordination shows flowering synchronized with vegetative growth with shoots typically having 15-20 leaves at flowering providing photosynthetic capacity supporting reproductive metabolism, and balanced vegetative-reproductive allocation supporting both canopy development and successful flowering. ||Disease pressure during flowering includes botrytis bunch rot with flowers highly susceptible to Botrytis cinerea infection establishing latent infections that remain dormant through development expressing during ripening, and powdery mildew continuing as threat requiring protective management though fungicide applications are restricted during flowering. ||Pest management during flowering includes monitoring grape berry moth oviposition on clusters potentially affecting berry development, and managing other pests that might interfere with flowering processes or damage developing structures. ||The process shows two major phases progressing from anthesis encompassing flower opening and pollination, through fertilization establishing seed development and fruit set, with successful flowering determining yield and berry number for the season. ||Duration typically spans 7-14 days from first to last flower opening depending on temperature, developmental uniformity, and environmental conditions, with warm favorable conditions promoting rapid coordinated flowering within 7-10 days while cool variable conditions may extend period to 12-16 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in flowering timing with early-flowering varieties showing anthesis in late May-early June while late types flower mid-late June, flowering duration with some varieties showing compressed 5-7 day bloom period while others show extended 10-14 day period, fruit set percentage affecting cluster density and yield, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting flowering success reliability. ||Regional timing shows flowering during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, with timing critical for frost avoidance and favorable weather window. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring flowering progress for timing management operations, protecting flowering period from adverse weather through site selection and possible protective measures, managing canopy optimizing light exposure and air circulation for flower function, ensuring adequate vine nutrition particularly boron supporting successful pollination and fruit set, avoiding stressful conditions during flowering supporting reproductive success, and recognizing flowering as critical determinant of yield and quality requiring optimal conditions and management. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating flowering including hormonal and environmental controls, investigating pollination biology including pollen-stigma interactions and fertilization processes, evaluating environmental effects on flowering success affecting fruit set and yield, quantifying genetic variation in flowering characteristics affecting productivity and adaptation, and assessing climate change impacts on flowering phenology and success across viticultural regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0007616 ## flowering | 0.95" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 275-295 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Anthesis": {
  "definition": "An Anthesis is a Flowering comprising flower opening through cap shedding with reproductive organ exposure and pollen release.",
  "alternative_term": "flower opening | bloom period | flowering phase | cap shedding period |+ Anthese | Blütenöffnung | Blühphase | Kalyptra-Abwurf",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows anthesis during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65 over 7-9 days, with first flowers opening June 4-6 followed by peak anthesis June 7-11 showing 50-70% simultaneous opening and completing June 12-14, under warm climate conditions of 22-28°C temperature, 45-65% relative humidity, light winds, no rain during bloom, supporting efficient pollination and 50-65% fruit set typical of this late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Anthesis is first major phase of Flowering, distinguished by flower opening and pollination processes. ||Subdivided into Early_Anthesis and Peak_Anthesis based on temporal progression and flowering intensity. ||Followed by fertilization and fruit set processes. ||Corresponds to BBCH 60-65. ||Environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity critically affect success. ||Duration and timing major determinants of fruit set and yield. || This fundamental reproductive stage occurs during early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 5-10 days from first flower opening through completion across cluster depending on developmental synchrony and environmental conditions, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 stages. ||Anthesis progression shows characteristic temporal pattern beginning with sporadic opening of earliest-maturing flowers typically at cluster apex corresponding to earliest primordium formation, accelerating through peak anthesis when maximum 40-70% flowers open simultaneously within 2-3 days, and declining during late phase as final 20-30% flowers complete opening, creating overall flowering duration of 5-10 days under favorable conditions. ||Cap shedding represents distinctive grapevine flowering mechanism with fused petal calyptra detaching as unit from receptacle base, lifting away from flower through combined forces of expanding reproductive organs pushing upward, turgor changes potentially creating mechanical pressure, and wind or gravity causing final detachment and fall. ||Calyptra detachment shows characteristic appearance with cap initially loosening at base showing slight gap, progressively lifting upward as abscission zone cells separate, and ultimately detaching completely falling away from flower typically within minutes to hours of abscission initiation. ||Abscission zone development involves enzymatic degradation of middle lamella in specialized cell layers at calyptra-receptacle junction, with cellulase and pectinase enzymes breaking down cell wall polysaccharides creating separation plane, under hormonal regulation possibly involving ethylene promoting abscission and auxin potentially regulating timing. ||Reproductive organ exposure following cap shedding reveals functional flower structures with five stamens surrounding central pistil, anthers positioned above stigma in close proximity facilitating self-pollination, nectary disc at flower base secreting nectar in some flowers, and overall flower diameter 3-5 mm depending on cultivar. ||Anther dehiscence proceeds rapidly after cap shedding with specialized stomium zones in anther walls breaking down creating longitudinal slits along anther length, dehiscence triggered by humidity decrease causing anther wall dehydration creating mechanical tension opening slits and releasing pollen. ||Pollen release occurs through anther slits with mature pollen grains liberating from anther locules, initially adhering in small masses then dispersing as individual grains, with release facilitated by flower movement from wind creating agitation dislodging pollen. ||Pollen dispersal proceeds primarily through wind transport with light pollen grains 25-35 micrometers diameter easily becoming airborne, traveling distances from centimeters within same flower to meters between vines depending on wind conditions, with pollen cloud visible surrounding flowering vines under favorable dry windy conditions. ||Pollen capture on stigmas occurs when airborne pollen grains contact receptive stigma surfaces, adhering to sticky exudate produced by stigma papillate cells, with pollen capture efficiency affected by stigma position, exudate production, and environmental conditions. ||Stigma receptivity develops progressively with papillate surface cells elongating and secreting proteinaceous exudate creating adhesive surface, receptivity typically peaking 1-3 days after flower opening and persisting 4-7 days though declining progressively, with receptive period affected by temperature and humidity. ||Flower longevity after opening shows stamens remaining functional 1-3 days with viable pollen production declining rapidly after initial release, stigma remaining receptive 4-7 days providing extended opportunity for pollination, and overall flower structure persisting 5-10 days before senescence if fertilization fails or longer if successful fertilization initiates fruit development. ||Pollination efficiency in grapevine shows high success with self-pollination within individual flowers through close proximity of anthers and stigma enabling direct pollen transfer, supplemented by wind-assisted pollination between neighboring flowers on same cluster or adjacent clusters, with cross-pollination between vines playing minor role. ||Nectary function shows variable activity among flowers with some producing modest nectar quantities potentially attracting insect visitors including honeybees, though insect contribution to pollination is minimal compared to dominant wind-assisted self-pollination mechanism. ||Flower scent production varies among cultivars with some producing subtle floral fragrance potentially attracting insects, while many commercial cultivars show minimal scent, with scent consisting of volatile organic compounds including terpenoids and aromatics. ||Environmental conditions critically affect anthesis with temperature as primary factor with optimal 20-30°C supporting rapid synchronized opening and effective pollination, cool conditions below 15°C substantially delaying opening and reducing pollen viability, and excessive heat above 35°C potentially causing pollen sterility or incomplete cap shedding. ||Humidity affects anthesis with moderate 40-70% relative humidity optimal for cap shedding and anther dehiscence, high humidity above 80% delaying dehiscence and potentially preventing pollen release, and low humidity below 30% causing rapid pollen desiccation reducing viability though facilitating release and dispersal. ||Rain during anthesis represents critical threat with water preventing cap shedding by maintaining high humidity and physical interference, washing pollen from anthers and stigmas preventing pollination, promoting botrytis and other fungal infections on wet flowers, and potentially physically damaging delicate reproductive structures, with rain timing particularly detrimental during peak anthesis. ||Wind affects anthesis showing beneficial effects through facilitating pollen dispersal and enhancing pollination efficiency, though excessive wind may cause flower damage or overly rapid pollen desiccation, with light-moderate wind 5-15 km per hour generally optimal. ||Light intensity shows modest direct effects on anthesis though adequate light supports overall vine vigor and photosynthetic capacity providing resources for reproductive processes, with shaded flowers showing similar opening patterns though potentially reduced vigor. ||Metabolic activity during anthesis shows elevated respiration particularly in anthers supporting pollen maturation and dehiscence, active sugar metabolism in nectaries producing nectar in functional flowers, and maintained metabolism in stigmas supporting receptivity and exudate production. ||Resource requirements during anthesis emphasize carbohydrate demand for energy-intensive processes including anther dehiscence, pollen tube growth after pollination, and initiating fruit development, with adequate reserves supporting successful reproduction while limitation potentially reducing fruit set. ||Hormonal regulation involves declining gibberellins as reproductive transition completes, ethylene potentially triggering or coordinating cap abscission, auxin from successfully fertilized ovaries preventing flower abscission and initiating berry development, and other hormones coordinating reproductive processes. ||Developmental uniformity within cluster affects anthesis duration with highly synchronized development producing compressed 5-7 day flowering period facilitating uniform fruit set, while heterogeneous development extends period to 10-14 days potentially creating variable berry development and extended vulnerability to adverse conditions. ||The process shows two distinguishable phases progressing from early anthesis with initial flower opening establishing reproductive function, through peak anthesis when maximum flowers open simultaneously creating optimal pollination window. ||Duration typically spans 5-10 days depending on developmental synchrony and environmental conditions, with warm stable conditions promoting rapid coordinated anthesis while variable cool conditions extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in anthesis timing with early varieties flowering late May-early June while late types flower mid-late June, anthesis duration with some showing compressed 5-7 day period while others show extended 8-12 day period, cap shedding efficiency with some varieties showing clean complete shedding while others show retained caps causing coulure, and pollen production and viability affecting fruit set success. ||Regional timing shows anthesis during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, with timing critical for frost avoidance and favorable weather window. ||Viticultural management considerations include monitoring anthesis progress for timing management operations and interventions, protecting flowering from adverse weather particularly rain through site selection and training systems, avoiding canopy operations during anthesis preventing physical disturbance of delicate flowers, ensuring adequate vine nutrition particularly boron supporting pollen function, recognizing anthesis as critical period determining fruit set and yield, and understanding weather during anthesis fundamentally affects season outcomes. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating cap abscission and anther dehiscence, investigating environmental controls of anthesis timing and duration, evaluating pollen biology including production, dispersal, and viability, quantifying pollination efficiency under varying conditions, and assessing genetic variation in anthesis characteristics affecting reproductive success and adaptation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0007616 ## flowering stage | 0.85" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-375 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 275-285 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Early_Anthesis": {
  "definition": "An Early_Anthesis is an Anthesis comprising flower opening with 10–20% of flowers open within the cluster, corresponding to BBCH 61–62.",
  "alternative_term": "flowering onset | initial bloom | beginning anthesis | early flower opening |+ frühe Anthese | Blühbeginn | beginnende Blüte | initiale Blütenöffnung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows early anthesis during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 61-62 over 2-3 days June 3-5, with 10-20% flowers opening initially in apical cluster regions, caps shedding exposing reproductive organs, stigmas developing receptivity with exudate production, under continental climate conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 55-70% relative humidity, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar initiating flowering before mid-June",
  "editor_note": "Early_Anthesis is first of two major Anthesis subphases, distinguished by initial flower opening establishing reproductive onset. ||Corresponds to BBCH 61-62 with 10-20% flowers open. ||Subdivided into First_Flowers_Opening, Initial_Cap_Shedding, and Stigma_Receptivity_Onset. ||Transitions to Peak_Anthesis as flowering intensity increases. ||Critical period for weather sensitivity and management preparation. ||Timing represents major phenological marker. || This critical initiation stage occurs during early June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 2-3 days as earliest-maturing flowers begin opening creating foundation for subsequent mass flowering, with timing representing major phenological marker for vineyard management and climate studies. ||Initial flower opening shows sporadic pattern with earliest flowers typically in apical cluster regions reflecting most advanced development from earliest primordium formation, with 5-10% flowers opening on first day increasing to 15-25% by end of early anthesis period, establishing progressive opening pattern. ||Cap shedding initiation in earliest flowers shows characteristic sequence with calyptra loosening visible as slight gap appearing at base between cap and receptacle, progressive lifting as abscission zone cells separate, upward movement driven by expanding reproductive organs and turgor forces, and complete detachment with cap falling away exposing reproductive structures. ||Reproductive organ exposure in early-opening flowers reveals functional structures with five stamens positioned around central pistil, anthers beginning to show color change from green to yellow-brown indicating approaching maturity, stigma surface developing papillate cells and exudate production, and overall flower structure delicate and vulnerable. ||Anther maturation in early-opening flowers shows final preparation for dehiscence with pollen completing maturation to tricellular state, anther walls undergoing structural changes preparing stomium zones for opening, and anthers positioned for effective pollen release and transfer to stigma. ||Stigma development in early-opening flowers shows receptivity onset with papillate surface cells elongating creating increased surface area, exudate secretion initiating producing adhesive proteinaceous coating capturing pollen, and stigma surface showing characteristic glistening appearance indicating functional receptivity. ||Pollen release timing shows variable pattern with some early-opening flowers releasing pollen within hours of cap shedding under favorable dry conditions, while others may delay release 12-24 hours if humidity is elevated, with initial pollen release establishing first opportunity for pollination within cluster. ||Pollination opportunity in early anthesis remains limited as relatively few flowers are open simultaneously, with successful pollination depending on overlap between pollen availability from early-opening flowers and stigma receptivity in same or neighboring flowers, creating first window for fruit set though majority of pollination occurs during subsequent peak anthesis. ||Flower appearance at early anthesis shows opened flowers with exposed stamens and pistil contrasting with majority of unopened buds still enclosed in calyptra caps, creating mixed developmental appearance within cluster with clear visual distinction between opened and closed flowers. ||Cluster-level progression shows characteristic basipetal-acropetal pattern with apical flowers often opening earliest, followed by middle region flowers, and basal flowers typically opening latest, though pattern shows variation among cultivars and environmental conditions affecting developmental uniformity. ||Environmental sensitivity intensifies during early anthesis with opened flowers highly vulnerable to adverse conditions including rain causing cap retention or washing pollen, excessive heat or cold affecting pollen viability or stigma function, and high humidity delaying anther dehiscence. ||Weather monitoring becomes critical during early anthesis as conditions during this period affect not only early-opening flowers but indicate likely conditions during subsequent peak anthesis, with unfavorable early anthesis weather potentially portending problems for entire flowering period. ||Temperature requirements for early anthesis show optimal 20-28°C supporting normal cap shedding and organ function, with cool conditions below 15°C substantially delaying opening and reducing organ vigor, and excessive heat above 32°C potentially causing organ dysfunction or accelerated senescence. ||Humidity effects on early anthesis show optimal 40-70% relative humidity supporting cap shedding and anther function, high humidity above 75% potentially preventing cap detachment or delaying dehiscence, and low humidity below 35% causing rapid tissue desiccation potentially affecting function. ||Metabolic activity in early-opening flowers shows elevated respiration supporting reproductive processes, active carbohydrate metabolism providing energy for organ function, and specialized metabolism in anthers supporting final pollen maturation and release. ||Hormonal status during early anthesis involves ethylene potentially involved in triggering cap abscission, declining growth hormones as reproductive transition completes, and preparing auxin system in ovaries ready for fertilization signal. ||Developmental coordination shows early anthesis occurring when shoot vegetative growth remains active with shoots typically having 12-18 expanded leaves, with concurrent vegetative-reproductive development requiring balanced resource allocation supporting both processes. ||Canopy microclimate effects become evident during early anthesis with well-exposed clusters showing earlier warmer conditions promoting earlier opening, while shaded interior clusters may show delayed opening creating within-vineyard heterogeneity. ||Management implications of early anthesis include providing indicator for subsequent peak anthesis timing enabling preparation of labor and operations, establishing critical period requiring weather monitoring and possible protective interventions, and representing final opportunity for pre-bloom disease management as fungicide applications become restricted once significant flowering begins. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from first flowers opening establishing reproductive onset, through initial cap shedding revealing organ function, to stigma receptivity onset creating first pollination opportunity. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing initiation period before peak flowering, with warm favorable conditions promoting rapid progression while cool conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in early anthesis timing with early-flowering varieties showing onset late May-early June while late types begin mid-late June, proportion of flowers opening during early phase with some showing gradual 10-15% early opening while others show more abrupt 20-30% opening, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting initiation reliability. ||Regional timing shows early anthesis during late May-early June in warm climates corresponding to heat accumulation of 900-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, early-mid June in temperate regions at 800-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 700-900 GDD, with timing critical for frost avoidance and favorable weather window. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive flowering onset enabling precise phenological tracking, providing early indicator of flowering conditions affecting subsequent peak bloom, establishing critical weather-sensitive period requiring monitoring and possible intervention, and marking transition point from pre-bloom to bloom management requiring operational adjustments. ||Research applications include documenting precise anthesis initiation timing for phenology studies, analyzing environmental controls of flowering onset affecting adaptation, evaluating developmental uniformity affecting anthesis duration and fruit set patterns, quantifying early pollination success contributing to overall fruit set, and assessing climate change impacts on flowering timing across regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-368 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "First_Flowers_Opening": {
  "definition": "A First_Flowers_Opening is an Early_Anthesis comprising the cap shedding of the earliest-maturing flowers within the cluster with reproductive organs exposed.",
  "alternative_term": "flowering start | first bloom | anthesis initiation | initial flower opening |+ erste Blüten öffnen | Blütenbeginn | Anthesestart | initiale Blütenöffnung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows first flowers opening on June 4 Year N+1 at BBCH 61, with 5-8% flowers in apical cluster positions completing cap shedding exposing reproductive organs during morning hours, under cool maritime climate conditions of 18-22°C temperature, 60-75% relative humidity, after accumulating 880-920 growing degree days base 10°C, typical of this early-bursting cultivar establishing flowering onset for subsequent bloom progression",
  "editor_note": "First_Flowers_Opening is first of three Early_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by definitive flowering onset with first flowers achieving open state. ||Represents threshold phenological event corresponding to BBCH 61. ||Followed by progressive Initial_Cap_Shedding affecting more flowers and Stigma_Receptivity_Onset. ||Critical phenological marker for records and management. ||Timing highly sensitive to temperature and accumulated heat units. || This critical threshold event occurs during early June in temperate regions Year N+1 as part of early anthesis, typically representing single day or 1-2 day period when first 5-10% flowers achieve open state, corresponding to BBCH 61 phenological stage. ||Initial opening characteristics show first opened flowers typically in apical cluster positions reflecting earliest primordium formation and most advanced development, with flowers exhibiting freshly shed caps, newly exposed stamens and pistil showing delicate pristine appearance, and beginning anther color development from green toward yellow-brown indicating approaching pollen maturity. ||Flower identification at opening shows opened flowers clearly distinguishable from unopened buds through absence of calyptra cap exposing reproductive structures, visible stamens arranged around central pistil, and flower diameter expanded to 4-5 mm compared to 3-4 mm unopened buds. ||Cap detachment completion in first-opening flowers shows calyptra completely separated and fallen away, typically found on cluster surface or ground below, with detached caps showing characteristic intact fused petal structure and attachment scar where abscission occurred. ||Reproductive organ exposure reveals functional anatomy with five stamens showing anthers on short filaments positioned around pistil, anthers 0.8-1.2 mm length with bilocular structure containing pollen in two compartments separated by connective tissue, pistil centrally positioned with superior ovary, short style, and bilobed stigma surface. ||Anther status at flower opening shows approaching dehiscence readiness with anthers beginning color transition indicating pollen maturation, anther wall structure showing preparation for stomium opening, though actual pollen release typically occurs hours to days after flower opening depending on environmental conditions particularly humidity. ||Stigma appearance at opening shows developing receptivity with papillate surface cells visible under magnification, beginning exudate production creating slight glistening appearance, and stigma lobes positioned above anthers facilitating pollen capture from wind-dispersed pollen or direct contact with nearby anthers. ||Nectary visibility in opened flowers shows disc structure at flower base surrounding ovary, with some flowers showing active nectar secretion visible as small droplets though production is variable among flowers and cultivars. ||Flower timing shows first opening typically occurs during morning hours when temperature rises and humidity declines creating favorable conditions for cap shedding, with subsequent flowers throughout cluster following similar diurnal pattern with most opening occurring morning to mid-day. ||Developmental gradient within cluster shows earliest flowers opening 12-24 hours before neighboring flowers, creating progressive opening wave that will extend over subsequent 5-10 days encompassing entire cluster, with gradient reflecting primordium formation sequence from previous season. ||Environmental conditions at first opening indicate likely conditions during subsequent peak flowering, with favorable warm dry conditions at first opening suggesting good flowering potential, while unfavorable cool wet conditions may portend problems for bloom period. ||Temperature at first opening typically ranges 18-26°C supporting normal cap shedding and organ function, with opening delayed if temperatures remain below 15°C and potentially accelerated if temperatures exceed 28°C. ||Humidity at first opening preferably 40-70% relative humidity supporting cap detachment and organ function without excessive drying, with high humidity above 75% potentially preventing some caps from shedding cleanly and very low humidity below 35% causing rapid tissue desiccation. ||Weather sensitivity at first opening is extreme with opened flowers highly vulnerable to rain causing physical damage, preventing normal organ function, and promoting fungal infection particularly botrytis, making weather monitoring critical at this stage. ||Metabolic status at first opening shows elevated respiration in opened flowers supporting reproductive processes, active sugar metabolism providing energy for organ function and potential nectar production, and specialized anther metabolism completing final pollen maturation. ||Resource availability at opening requires adequate carbohydrate reserves supporting energy-intensive reproductive processes, with flowering success depending partially on vine reserve status affected by previous season crop load and current season photosynthetic production. ||Phenological significance of first flowers opening includes defining definitive flowering date used for heat summation calculations and phenological tracking, providing baseline for predicting subsequent peak anthesis timing typically 2-4 days later, and establishing critical management period requiring operational adjustments. ||Observational requirements for identifying first flowers opening include careful cluster inspection as initial opening may involve only few flowers at apical positions, appropriate timing with morning observations most likely to detect fresh opening, and distinguishing truly opened flowers with exposed organs from buds showing cap loosening but not yet detached. ||Documentation importance emphasizes recording precise first flower opening date as critical phenological marker for vineyard records, climate studies, and management planning, with date providing key reference for subsequent developmental predictions. ||The process represents first of three early anthesis aspects marking definitive flowering onset, followed by progressive cap shedding in additional flowers and stigma receptivity development. ||Duration represents threshold event occurring over 1-2 days as first 5-10% flowers open, with rapid transition toward increasing opening frequency during subsequent early anthesis. ||Cultivar variation appears in first opening timing with early varieties showing late May-early June opening while late types show mid-late June opening reflecting overall phenological differences, cluster position of first opening with some varieties showing consistent apical opening while others show more variable patterns, and environmental sensitivity affecting opening under marginal conditions. ||Regional timing shows first flowers opening during late May-early June in warm climates at approximately 950-1050 growing degree days base 10°C, early June in temperate regions at 850-950 GDD, and mid-June in cool areas at 750-850 GDD, with timing critical for frost avoidance and favorable weather. ||Viticultural significance includes defining flowering date for phenological records and management scheduling, providing early warning of flowering conditions affecting subsequent bloom success, establishing critical observation point requiring careful monitoring, and marking transition requiring operational adjustments including restricting fungicide applications and canopy operations. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering onset for phenology and climate studies, analyzing environmental triggers of first opening affecting phenological variation, evaluating developmental mechanisms determining first flower identity and timing, quantifying relationships between first opening and subsequent bloom progression, and assessing climate change impacts on flowering dates across regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-365"
},

  "Initial_Cap_Shedding": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Cap_Shedding is an Early_Anthesis comprising the progressive calyptra detachment of flowers within the cluster reaching 15–25% open flowers.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive cap detachment | calyptra shedding | early cap fall |+ beginnende Kalyptraablösung | progressive Kappenabwurf | früher Blütenkappenfall | initiale Kalyptralösung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows initial cap shedding during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 61-62 over 2-3 days June 4-6, with flowers progressively opening from initial 6-8% to 18-24% as caps detach exposing reproductive organs, showing clean efficient shedding under warm Mediterranean conditions of 23-28°C temperature, 50-65% relative humidity, light morning winds assisting detachment, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar showing rapid early anthesis progression",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Cap_Shedding is second of three Early_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by progressive calyptra detachment expanding bloom from initial opening. ||Follows First_Flowers_Opening. ||Overlaps with Stigma_Receptivity_Onset. ||Represents expansion phase increasing reproductive function within cluster. ||Efficiency critically affected by environmental conditions particularly humidity. ||Problems with retention indicate unfavorable conditions affecting fruit set potential. || This critical expansion phase occurs during early June in temperate regions Year N+1 spanning 2-3 days following first flower opening, as accelerating cap shedding creates increasing numbers of functional flowers preparing foundation for subsequent peak anthesis. ||Cap shedding progression shows characteristic pattern with increasing frequency of detachment events as more flowers reach appropriate maturity state, additional flowers throughout cluster particularly in middle regions completing abscission following initial apical opening, and daily increments of 3-8% additional flowers opening creating progressive expansion of bloom. ||Shedding mechanism involves abscission zone activation in calyptra base where specialized cells undergo programmed wall degradation, enzymatic breakdown of middle lamella through cellulase and pectinase activity creating separation plane, mechanical forces from expanding reproductive organs and turgor changes driving physical detachment, and final cap separation through combined enzymatic and mechanical processes. ||Cap lifting appearance shows characteristic sequence with initial loosening visible as narrow gap at base, progressive upward movement as abscission proceeds with cap elevating 0.5-2.0 mm above receptacle, continued lifting driven by expanding stamens and pistil pushing upward, and final detachment with cap falling away or sometimes remaining temporarily caught on adjacent structures. ||Detached cap characteristics show intact fused petal structure maintaining pentamerous form with five coherent petals visible as sections, attachment scar at base where abscission occurred showing clean separation plane, and occasional caps showing incomplete separation with partial retention requiring additional mechanical force for complete removal. ||Cap retention problems in some flowers show incomplete abscission with caps remaining partially attached, physical impediment preventing normal reproductive organ function affecting pollination and fruit set potential, with retention associated with unfavorable conditions including high humidity, cool temperature, or developmental abnormalities. ||Abscission zone anatomy shows specialized cell layers at calyptra-receptacle junction with smaller cells containing dense cytoplasm, thin walls particularly in middle lamella region susceptible to enzymatic degradation, and vascular traces disrupting at separation plane requiring coordinated breakdown. ||Enzymatic activity during shedding involves cellulase enzymes degrading cellulose components of cell walls, pectinase and polygalacturonase enzymes breaking down pectin in middle lamella, and possible xyloglucan endotransglycosylase activity modifying wall polysaccharides, creating coordinated wall dissolution enabling separation. ||Hormonal regulation of cap shedding involves ethylene potentially triggering or coordinating abscission with increased ethylene biosynthesis and sensitivity in abscission zone, auxin possibly regulating timing with declining auxin levels permitting abscission initiation, and abscisic acid potentially involved in coordinating developmental timing. ||Reproductive organ exposure following cap shedding reveals functional structures with stamens extending upward surrounding central pistil, anthers positioned at various angles typically 0.5-1.5 mm above stigma facilitating pollen release and capture, and pistil with bilobed stigma surface positioned to receive pollen from anthers or wind dispersal. ||Flower appearance during initial shedding shows increasing proportion of opened flowers contrasting with remaining unopened buds, creating characteristic mixed appearance with opened flowers showing yellow-brown anthers against green receptacle and unopened flowers showing green calyptra caps, and cluster taking on progressively more open appearance. ||Temporal pattern of shedding shows diurnal rhythm with most cap detachment occurring during morning hours as temperature rises and humidity declines creating favorable conditions, reduced shedding during afternoon and evening hours, and resumption following morning creating daily waves of opening. ||Environmental effects on shedding include temperature strongly affecting rate with optimal 22-28°C promoting rapid shedding while cool conditions below 15°C substantially delay shedding and warm conditions above 32°C may cause premature or incomplete shedding. ||Humidity critically affects shedding with moderate 45-65% relative humidity optimal for clean complete cap detachment, high humidity above 75% interfering with shedding through maintaining high turgor and possibly affecting enzymatic activity, and low humidity below 35% causing rapid desiccation potentially affecting tissue function though facilitating mechanical separation. ||Rain during initial shedding represents serious concern with water preventing normal cap detachment through elevated humidity and physical interference, causing caps to remain attached or shed incompletely affecting reproductive function, and promoting fungal infection on wet flowers particularly botrytis establishing latent infections. ||Wind effects show modest positive role with light air movement potentially assisting final mechanical cap detachment and removing detached caps from cluster vicinity, though excessive wind may cause damage to newly exposed delicate reproductive organs. ||Cluster position effects show well-exposed clusters typically showing earlier more uniform shedding while shaded interior clusters may show delayed or irregular shedding, creating within-vineyard spatial variation in flowering progression affecting fruit set uniformity. ||Developmental uniformity affects shedding pattern with highly synchronized flowers showing compressed rapid shedding over 2-3 days, while heterogeneous development extends shedding period to 4-6 days during early anthesis phase, affecting overall flowering duration and fruit set outcomes. ||Metabolic activity during shedding shows elevated respiration in abscission zone supporting enzymatic processes, active carbohydrate metabolism providing energy for controlled cell separation, and maintained metabolism in newly exposed reproductive organs supporting immediate function. ||Resource requirements during shedding emphasize carbohydrate demand for energy-intensive abscission and organ function, nitrogen for enzyme synthesis supporting abscission processes, and minerals particularly calcium affecting cell wall properties and separation mechanics. ||The process represents second of three early anthesis aspects focusing on progressive calyptra removal, following first flowers opening and overlapping with stigma receptivity onset as exposed organs develop function. ||Duration spans 2-3 days during early anthesis representing expansion period from initial 5-10% to 15-25% flowers open, with warm favorable conditions promoting rapid progression. ||Cultivar variation appears in shedding efficiency with some varieties showing clean complete cap detachment while others show frequent retention problems affecting fruit set, shedding rate affecting early anthesis duration, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting shedding under marginal conditions. ||Regional timing shows initial cap shedding during early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-June in cool areas, occurring during early anthesis phase 0-2 days after first flowers opening. ||Viticultural significance includes expanding reproductive function within cluster increasing pollination opportunity, revealing developmental uniformity affecting subsequent peak anthesis predictions, establishing period of heightened weather sensitivity requiring monitoring, and providing visual indicator of flowering progression enabling management assessment. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms regulating cap abscission including enzymatic and hormonal controls, evaluating environmental effects on shedding efficiency affecting reproductive success, quantifying developmental uniformity implications for shedding patterns, investigating causes of cap retention problems affecting fruit set, and assessing genetic variation in shedding characteristics affecting flowering reliability.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 365-370 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 278-282"
},

  "Stigma_Receptivity_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Stigma_Receptivity_Onset is an Early_Anthesis comprising the achievement of pollen capture and germination capacity by exposed stigmas in opened flowers.",
  "alternative_term": "stigma maturation | stigma functionality onset | receptivity initiation |+ Narbenrezeptivität | Narbenfunktionsbeginn | Empfängnisbereitschaft | Stigmareifung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows stigma receptivity onset during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 61-62 within 12-18 hours after flower opening, with stigma papillate cells elongating and exudate secretion initiating creating glistening appearance, developing peak receptivity 1-2 days after opening persisting 5-7 days, under oceanic climate conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 55-70% relative humidity supporting normal function typical of this mid-season cultivar establishing female reproductive capacity for pollination",
  "editor_note": "Stigma_Receptivity_Onset is third of three Early_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by functional female reproductive development. ||Develops concurrently with Initial_Cap_Shedding following flower opening. ||Represents essential functional requirement for fruit set. ||Timing relative to pollen availability critically affects pollination success. ||Environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity strongly affect development and function. ||Boron nutritional status critically important. || This essential functional milestone occurs during early anthesis in early June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically developing within 6-24 hours after flower opening as stigma tissues complete maturation and begin exudate secretion, corresponding to BBCH 61-62 stages. ||Receptivity development involves stigma papillate cell elongation increasing surface area 2-3 fold creating textured surface maximizing pollen capture potential, exudate secretion initiating with proteinaceous fluid production creating adhesive coating on stigma surface, and metabolic activation establishing capacity to support pollen hydration, germination, and tube growth. ||Papillate cell characteristics show specialized epidermal cells elongating to 40-80 micrometers length creating finger-like projections, cells containing dense cytoplasm with abundant organelles supporting active secretion, and cell walls remaining relatively thin facilitating pollen tube penetration after germination. ||Exudate composition includes proteins particularly lipid transfer proteins facilitating pollen-stigma recognition, carbohydrates providing hydration medium for pollen, lipids affecting surface properties, and various small molecules potentially serving signaling or nutritive functions. ||Exudate production shows progressive accumulation creating visible glistening appearance on stigma surface, with production rate affected by environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity, maximum accumulation typically occurring 1-3 days after flower opening when receptivity peaks. ||Stigma appearance at receptivity onset shows bilobed structure with two stigma lobes diverging at angle creating expanded capture surface, papillate surface texture visible under magnification appearing rough compared to smooth style tissue, and characteristic sheen from exudate coating indicating active secretivity. ||Pollen capture mechanism involves adhesive exudate trapping pollen grains contacting stigma surface, physical retention through papillate cell structure creating mechanical barriers preventing pollen loss, and possible electrostatic effects attracting charged pollen grains though evidence in grapevine is limited. ||Pollen-stigma interaction following capture involves pollen grain hydration from stigma exudate taking 15-60 minutes depending on pollen water status and environmental conditions, pollen recognition through molecular signals between pollen coat proteins and stigma exudate components, and germination initiation with pollen tube emerging through aperture penetrating stigma surface. ||Receptivity timing shows onset within 6-24 hours after flower opening with exact timing affected by environmental conditions particularly temperature, peak receptivity typically 1-3 days after opening when exudate production maximizes, and persistence 4-7 days though declining progressively as stigma senesces if pollination fails. ||Environmental effects on receptivity include temperature affecting metabolic rate with optimal 20-28°C supporting vigorous receptivity development, cool conditions below 15°C delaying receptivity onset and reducing function, and excessive heat above 35°C potentially impairing stigma function through protein denaturation or excessive desiccation. ||Humidity affects receptivity through effects on exudate properties with moderate 45-70% relative humidity maintaining appropriate exudate consistency for pollen capture and hydration, high humidity above 80% potentially diluting exudate reducing effectiveness, and low humidity below 35% causing rapid evaporation potentially desiccating stigma surface. ||Rain effects on receptivity are severely negative with water washing exudate from stigma surface eliminating pollen capture capacity, preventing pollen germination through excessive dilution, and promoting fungal growth on wet stigma tissues potentially interfering with function. ||Metabolic activity in receptive stigmas shows elevated respiration supporting active secretion and cellular function, protein synthesis producing exudate components and enzymes supporting pollen recognition and tube growth, and carbohydrate metabolism providing energy and secretory substrates. ||Nutritional requirements during receptivity development emphasize nitrogen for protein synthesis supporting exudate production, boron critically important for stigma function with deficiency causing poor receptivity and reduced fruit set, and adequate micronutrients supporting enzyme function in recognition and response pathways. ||Hormonal regulation of receptivity involves possible auxin effects on stigma development and secretory activity, cytokinins potentially maintaining stigma viability during receptive period, and ethylene possibly involved in stigma senescence terminating receptivity if pollination fails. ||Pollen availability timing relative to receptivity onset is critical with early-opening flowers showing slight delay between receptivity onset and pollen availability from own or neighboring anthers creating brief gap, while in peak anthesis abundant pollen becomes available immediately or precedes receptivity ensuring pollination opportunity. ||Pollination success dependence on receptivity shows strong positive relationship with vigorous receptive stigmas showing high fruit set 60-80% under favorable conditions, while impaired receptivity from environmental stress or nutritional deficiency shows reduced set 20-40% even with adequate pollen availability. ||Stigma position relative to anthers affects pollination efficiency with stigma typically positioned slightly below anthers in opened flower facilitating pollen capture from anthers in same flower or wind-dispersed pollen from neighboring flowers, with some flowers showing stigma exsertion above anthers affecting self versus cross pollination patterns. ||Receptivity assessment methods include visual observation of stigma exudate appearance providing qualitative indicator, controlled pollination experiments applying known pollen to stigmas at various times determining functional receptivity period, and molecular markers of receptivity-associated gene expression providing detailed developmental characterization. ||The process represents third of three early anthesis aspects establishing female reproductive function, developing concurrently with initial cap shedding as flowers open and expose organs. ||Onset typically occurs within 1 day of flower opening representing functional lag as stigma completes maturation, with rapid transition to receptive state. ||Cultivar variation appears in receptivity development timing with some varieties showing rapid onset within hours while others show delayed 24-48 hour onset, receptivity duration with some showing brief 3-4 day period while others maintain 6-8 day receptivity, and exudate production capacity affecting pollen capture efficiency. ||Regional timing shows stigma receptivity onset during early June in warm climates concurrent with first flowers opening, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-June in cool areas, with timing critical for ensuring overlap with pollen availability. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing functional female reproductive capacity essential for fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity for normal development, representing vulnerable period for weather-related fruit set failure, and interacting with pollen availability timing determining pollination success and yield. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of receptivity development including gene expression and protein synthesis, investigating environmental effects on receptivity affecting fruit set outcomes, evaluating nutritional requirements particularly boron for normal function, quantifying temporal dynamics of receptivity relative to pollen availability, and assessing genetic variation in receptivity characteristics affecting reproductive success.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 368-375 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 282-287 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Peak_Anthesis": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Anthesis is an Anthesis comprising flower opening at the maximum proportion of simultaneously open flowers within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "full bloom | flowering peak | maximum anthesis | peak flowering |+ volle Blüte | Blütenhöhepunkt | maximale Anthese | Hauptblüte",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows peak anthesis during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 over 3-4 days June 8-11, with 55-70% flowers open simultaneously, abundant pollen availability from widespread anther dehiscence, maximum stigma receptivity across cluster, under optimal warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature, 50-65% relative humidity, light winds, no rain, supporting efficient pollination and achieving 58-68% fruit set typical of this late-season cultivar under favorable conditions",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Anthesis is second and culminating major Anthesis phase, distinguished by maximum flowering intensity and optimal reproductive conditions. ||Follows Early_Anthesis. ||Corresponds to BBCH 63-65 with 40-70% flowers open. ||Subdivided into Maximum_Flower_Opening, Peak_Pollen_Availability, and Optimal_Pollination_Window. ||Represents most critical period for yield determination. ||Environmental conditions during peak fundamentally determine fruit set and season productivity. ||Weather sensitivity at absolute maximum. || This essential reproductive culmination occurs during early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1 typically 2-4 days after early anthesis initiation, spanning 2-4 days when 40-70% flowers achieve open state simultaneously, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 stages. ||Flowering intensity during peak shows characteristic maximum with 40-70% flowers open at any moment creating dense arrays of functional reproductive structures, daily addition of 10-20% new flowers opening maintaining high open flower proportion, and sustained intense reproductive activity across cluster establishing optimal pollination window. ||Flower distribution pattern at peak shows opened flowers throughout cluster with apical regions showing 70-90% open having initiated opening earliest, middle regions showing 60-80% open representing peak activity zone, and basal regions showing 30-60% open with opening continuing progressively, creating overall highly functional state. ||Reproductive organ functionality reaches maximum during peak with abundant viable pollen available from numerous anthers undergoing dehiscence, widespread stigma receptivity with 50-80% stigmas showing active exudate production and pollen capture capacity, and optimal spatial arrangement with opened flowers in close proximity facilitating efficient pollination. ||Pollen availability shows peak levels with anthers from recently opened flowers releasing fresh viable pollen, cumulative pollen from flowers opened over previous 1-2 days remaining partially viable, and continuous new pollen production from flowers opening during peak period, creating maximum pollen density in cluster atmosphere. ||Pollen viability during peak remains high with fresh pollen showing 70-90% germination capacity under optimal conditions, declining to 40-60% after 24 hours and 10-30% after 48 hours, creating 1-2 day window of maximum viability requiring effective pollination during this brief period. ||Pollen dispersal during peak creates visible pollen clouds surrounding flowering clusters under favorable dry windy conditions, with pollen grains becoming airborne readily when anthers dehisce, traveling centimeters to meters through wind transport, and settling on receptive stigmas within same cluster or neighboring clusters. ||Stigma receptivity distribution during peak shows maximum proportion of stigmas at optimal receptive state with fresh exudate production, providing widespread pollen capture capacity across cluster, with 60-80% stigmas showing peak receptivity creating abundant opportunities for successful pollination. ||Pollination activity intensifies during peak with high frequency of pollen-stigma contact events, rapid pollen germination on receptive stigmas typically within 1-4 hours, and extensive pollen tube growth initiating through style tissues toward ovaries, establishing conditions for high fruit set. ||Fertilization initiation begins during peak as earliest pollinated flowers complete pollen tube growth reaching ovaries typically 18-36 hours after pollination, with double fertilization occurring and embryo plus endosperm development beginning, triggering fruit set through hormonal signals preventing flower abscission. ||Cluster appearance at peak anthesis shows characteristic flowering appearance with numerous opened flowers showing yellow-brown anthers contrasting with green receptacles, remaining calyptra caps on unopened buds showing green color, detached caps accumulating on cluster surface and ground below, and overall cluster showing active reproductive state. ||Environmental conditions during peak critically determine flowering success with temperature optimally 22-30°C supporting maximum pollen and stigma function, cool conditions below 18°C substantially reducing pollen viability and stigma receptivity, and excessive heat above 33°C potentially causing pollen sterility or stigma dysfunction severely limiting fruit set. ||Humidity during peak preferably 45-65% relative humidity balancing pollen viability maintenance with anther dehiscence facilitation, high humidity above 75% preventing or delaying anther opening reducing pollen availability, and very low humidity below 35% causing rapid pollen desiccation reducing viability window. ||Weather stability during peak is critically important with favorable stable conditions enabling efficient pollination and high fruit set, while variable conditions create erratic pollination patterns and reduced set, with peak anthesis representing most weather-sensitive period of entire growing season. ||Rain during peak anthesis represents catastrophic risk with water preventing anther dehiscence eliminating pollen availability, washing pollen from anthers and stigmas preventing pollination, diluting or removing stigma exudate impairing pollen capture and germination, and promoting botrytis infection on wet flowers causing immediate tissue damage and establishing latent infections, with rain during peak potentially reducing fruit set to 10-30% compared to 50-70% under favorable conditions. ||Wind during peak shows beneficial effects with light-moderate wind 5-15 km per hour facilitating pollen dispersal and enhancing pollination efficiency, though strong wind above 25 km per hour may cause flower damage or excessive pollen loss reducing pollination success. ||Metabolic activity during peak shows maximum levels with elevated respiration in anthers supporting pollen maturation and release, active metabolism in stigmas maintaining receptivity and supporting pollen tube growth, and high energy demand across reproductive structures requiring adequate carbohydrate supply. ||Resource demand during peak emphasizes carbohydrate requirements for energy-intensive processes including pollen production, tube growth, and early embryo development, nitrogen for protein synthesis in reproductive tissues, and critical micronutrients particularly boron essential for pollen germination and tube growth. ||Hormonal status during peak involves active auxin and gibberellin production from successfully fertilized ovaries triggering berry development, ethylene possibly involved in coordinating flower senescence for unfertilized flowers, and other hormones coordinating transition from flowering to fruit development. ||Developmental coordination during peak shows concurrent vegetative and reproductive processes with shoot growth continuing though slowing, leaves expanding and maturing providing photosynthetic capacity, and tendrils developing and attaching supporting shoot positioning. ||Canopy management during peak should avoid disruptive operations with shoot positioning, hedging, or leafing operations suspended during flowering period preventing physical disturbance of delicate flowers, and disease management restricted due to fungicide application limitations during bloom. ||Disease pressure during peak focuses on botrytis with flowers highly susceptible to Botrytis cinerea infection particularly under wet conditions, establishing latent infections that remain dormant through berry development expressing during ripening, requiring protective fungicide applications before flowering due to application restrictions during bloom. ||Fruit set determination during peak with successful pollination and fertilization during this critical 2-4 day period determining 60-80% final berry number, with remaining 20-40% set during early and late anthesis periods, making peak anthesis outcomes dominant influence on seasonal yield. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from maximum flower opening establishing peak intensity, through peak pollen availability providing maximum pollination opportunity, to optimal pollination window encompassing ideal conditions for reproductive success. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 days representing brief intense period of maximum flowering, with warm favorable conditions producing compressed 2-3 day peak while variable conditions may extend peak to 4-5 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in peak intensity with some varieties showing sharp intense peak with 60-80% simultaneous opening while others show broader moderate peak with 40-60% opening, peak duration affecting pollination window and fruit set patterns, and environmental sensitivity affecting peak success reliability. ||Regional timing shows peak anthesis during early-mid June in warm climates at approximately 1000-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 900-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 800-900 GDD, with timing critical for favorable weather window. ||Viticultural significance includes representing most critical period for yield determination with peak outcomes dominating fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions for successful pollination and high fruit set, representing maximum weather vulnerability requiring monitoring and possible protective interventions, marking transition from structural development to reproductive function, and providing definitive reproductive outcome window affecting season productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing environmental controls of peak flowering intensity and duration, quantifying pollination dynamics including pollen production, dispersal, and capture, evaluating relationships between peak conditions and fruit set outcomes, developing models predicting fruit set from peak weather conditions, and assessing climate change impacts on peak anthesis conditions affecting viticultural productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 370-380 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 285-292 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Maximum_Flower_Opening": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Flower_Opening is a Peak_Anthesis comprising the simultaneous open state of the greatest absolute number and proportion of flowers within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "full bloom peak | maximum bloom | flowering maximum | peak flower opening |+ maximale Blütenöffnung | Vollblütehöhepunkt | Blütenmaximum | höchste Blühintensität",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows maximum flower opening on June 9 Year N+1 at BBCH 65, with 60-72% flowers simultaneously open creating full bloom appearance, abundant reproductive organs exposed throughout cluster, under cool climate conditions of 21-26°C temperature, 55-70% relative humidity, after accumulating 920-960 growing degree days base 10°C, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar reaching flowering intensity peak for optimal pollination opportunity",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Flower_Opening is first of three Peak_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by achieving highest proportion of simultaneously open flowers. ||Represents definitive peak bloom corresponding to BBCH 65. ||Followed by Peak_Pollen_Availability and Optimal_Pollination_Window creating reproductive opportunity. ||Brief 1-2 day period of maximum intensity. ||Critical phenological marker. ||Weather sensitivity absolute maximum. ||Visual assessment easily identifies maximum bloom state. || This critical intensity maximum occurs during mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1 as central event of peak anthesis, typically representing single day or 1-2 day period when 50-75% flowers show open state simultaneously, corresponding to BBCH 65 phenological stage. ||Opening intensity characteristics show maximum daily opening rate with 10-20% additional flowers opening per day during peak, cumulative effect of sustained opening over previous 2-3 days creating high proportion of simultaneously open flowers, and peak representing balance point between continuing opening of new flowers and beginning senescence of earliest-opened flowers. ||Flower distribution at maximum shows opened flowers throughout cluster creating dense reproductive display with apical regions showing 80-95% flowers open, middle regions showing 70-85% open representing highest density, and basal regions showing 40-70% open with opening continuing, creating overall highly functional reproductive state across cluster. ||Visual appearance at maximum bloom shows characteristic flowering display with numerous opened flowers exposing yellow-brown anthers and green-white stigmas creating distinctive color pattern, contrasting with remaining green calyptra caps on 20-40% unopened buds, scattered detached caps visible on cluster and ground surfaces, and overall appearance of active vibrant reproductive state. ||Cluster architecture visibility at maximum bloom clearly reveals branching pattern established during previous season primordium formation, with flower spacing and distribution patterns fully expressed, facilitating assessment of cluster structure and density affecting subsequent fruit development. ||Reproductive organ exposure at maximum shows abundant stamens and pistils throughout cluster creating maximum surface area for pollen production and capture, with anthers at various stages from newly dehisced to 1-2 days post-dehiscence, and stigmas ranging from newly receptive to peak receptivity providing widespread functional reproductive capacity. ||Pollen production at maximum reaches peak levels with numerous anthers simultaneously releasing pollen creating maximum pollen density in cluster atmosphere, fresh pollen showing optimal viability 70-90% germination capacity, and cumulative pollen from recently opened flowers supplementing current production, establishing optimal pollen availability conditions. ||Stigma receptivity distribution at maximum shows majority of stigmas at or approaching peak receptive state with active exudate production creating adhesive pollen capture surfaces, receptive stigmas distributed throughout cluster providing abundant pollination opportunity, and spatial arrangement facilitating efficient pollen transfer from anthers to stigmas within same flowers or neighboring flowers. ||Pollination opportunity at maximum reaches optimal level with highest probability of successful pollen-stigma contact through abundant pollen and widespread receptivity, favorable spatial arrangement with opened flowers in close proximity facilitating pollen dispersal and capture, and highest potential for efficient pollination supporting maximum fruit set. ||Temporal dynamics at maximum show brief peak period lasting 1-2 days as opening rate reaches maximum then begins declining, with individual flowers showing variable longevity creating continuous turnover maintaining high open proportion, and transition beginning toward declining phase as earliest flowers start senescence. ||Environmental conditions required for maximum opening include optimal temperature 24-30°C supporting rapid synchronized opening and maximum daily increments, moderate humidity 50-70% facilitating cap shedding without excessive desiccation, favorable weather stability enabling consistent opening progression without interruption, and absence of rain preventing interference with normal cap detachment and organ function. ||Diurnal pattern at maximum shows most intense opening during morning hours 8am-12pm as temperature rises and humidity declines, reduced opening during afternoon and evening, and resumption following morning creating daily peak opening periods, with pattern consistent throughout maximum bloom period. ||Metabolic status at maximum shows elevated activity across reproductive structures with high respiration supporting pollen maturation and release, active stigma metabolism maintaining receptivity, and substantial energy demand requiring adequate carbohydrate supply from photosynthesis and reserves. ||Resource allocation at maximum emphasizes reproductive demands competing with vegetative growth for available resources, with adequate supply supporting both processes and limitation potentially affecting reproductive success, highlighting importance of balanced vine vigor and resource status. ||Developmental uniformity implications show highly synchronized development producing sharp intense maximum with 60-75% simultaneous opening supporting concentrated efficient pollination, while heterogeneous development creates broader flatter maximum with 40-60% opening extending period and potentially reducing pollination efficiency. ||Phenological significance of maximum bloom includes defining peak flowering date used for phenological records and heat summation calculations, providing reference for predicting subsequent developmental timing including fruit set, berry development, and véraison, and establishing critical benchmark for management scheduling and climate studies. ||Observational assessment at maximum involves whole-cluster visual evaluation estimating proportion of opened flowers, random flower counts on representative clusters providing quantitative data, and photographic documentation capturing peak bloom appearance for records, with maximum bloom easily identifiable through dense flower display. ||Management implications at maximum include suspending canopy operations to avoid physical disturbance of flowers, restricting fungicide applications due to bloom application limitations, monitoring weather conditions for potential protective interventions if adverse conditions threaten, and assessing bloom uniformity across vineyard identifying areas with developmental variation. ||Weather sensitivity at maximum reaches absolute peak with opened flowers extremely vulnerable to adverse conditions including rain causing catastrophic pollination failure, excessive heat potentially causing organ dysfunction, and cold conditions impairing reproductive function, making weather monitoring and forecasting critical during maximum bloom period. ||Disease vulnerability at maximum emphasizes botrytis with abundant susceptible flower tissues providing infection opportunity particularly under wet conditions, requiring that protective fungicide coverage be established before bloom as applications during flowering are restricted or prohibited. ||The process represents first of three peak anthesis aspects establishing maximum flowering intensity, followed by peak pollen availability and optimal pollination window creating reproductive opportunity. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day period at flowering intensity peak, with rapid transition toward declining intensity as opening rate decreases. ||Cultivar variation appears in maximum intensity with some varieties showing very sharp peak with 65-80% simultaneous opening while others show broader peak with 50-65% opening, maximum duration with some showing brief 1-day peak while others show extended 2-3 day maximum, and timing relative to optimal environmental conditions affecting reproductive success. ||Regional timing shows maximum flower opening during early-mid June in warm climates at approximately 1050-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 950-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 850-900 GDD, with timing ideally coinciding with favorable weather window. ||Viticultural significance includes defining definitive peak bloom date for phenological records, representing moment of maximum yield determination potential with outcomes during this brief period dominating fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions for maximum reproductive success, marking most critical weather vulnerability period of entire season, and providing visual confirmation of flowering intensity and uniformity affecting management decisions. ||Research applications include documenting precise timing of maximum bloom for phenology studies, analyzing environmental controls of flowering intensity affecting peak characteristics, evaluating developmental uniformity implications for bloom patterns and fruit set, quantifying relationships between maximum bloom conditions and reproductive outcomes, and assessing climate change impacts on flowering intensity and timing across regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 372-378"
},

  "Peak_Pollen_Availability": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Pollen_Availability is a Peak_Anthesis comprising the maximum presence of viable pollen through widespread anther dehiscence within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum pollen production | peak pollen release | optimal pollen presence |+ maximale Pollenproduktion | höchste Pollenverfügbarkeit | Pollenmaximum | optimale Pollenpräsenz",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows peak pollen availability during mid-June Year N+1 during peak anthesis, with widespread anther dehiscence releasing abundant pollen creating visible pollen clouds under favorable conditions, fresh pollen showing 75-88% germination capacity, pollen density maximizing in cluster atmosphere, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, 48-62% relative humidity, light winds facilitating dispersal, supporting efficient pollination typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Pollen_Availability is second of three Peak_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by maximum male reproductive capacity through abundant viable pollen. ||Develops concurrently with or shortly after Maximum_Flower_Opening. ||Overlaps with Optimal_Pollination_Window. ||Represents critical male contribution to pollination success. ||Brief 1-2 day period of maximum viability requiring rapid pollination. ||Environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity critically affect viability. ||Boron nutrition essential for function. || This critical male function maximum occurs during peak anthesis in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically coinciding with or slightly following maximum flower opening, spanning 1-2 days when pollen density reaches maximum levels through cumulative production from recently opened flowers. ||Pollen production intensity shows maximum levels with numerous anthers simultaneously undergoing dehiscence releasing mature pollen grains, typical flower producing 20,000-60,000 pollen grains from five anthers representing substantial reproductive investment, and cluster-level production reaching millions of pollen grains creating dense pollen atmosphere in favorable conditions. ||Anther dehiscence pattern at peak shows widespread anther opening throughout cluster with apical regions showing 70-90% dehisced anthers from earliest-opened flowers, middle regions showing 60-80% active dehiscence representing peak activity zone, and basal regions showing 30-60% beginning dehiscence as opening continues, creating overall maximum dehiscence proportion. ||Pollen release mechanism involves anther wall dehydration creating mechanical tension opening longitudinal stomium slits, sudden rupture of anther locules liberating pollen grains from internal positions, and physical agitation from wind or flower movement dislodging pollen from anthers dispersing into atmosphere. ||Pollen characteristics at peak include optimal structural condition with intact exine wall and cytoplasmic contents, tricellular maturity state containing vegetative cell and two sperm cells ready for fertilization, and maximum viability with 70-90% pollen showing germination capacity under optimal laboratory conditions. ||Pollen viability timing shows peak immediately upon release from freshly dehisced anthers declining progressively over hours to days, with viability reducing to 50-70% after 6-12 hours exposure to ambient conditions, 30-50% after 24 hours, and 10-30% after 48 hours, creating critical 12-24 hour window of maximum functional viability. ||Environmental effects on viability include temperature with optimal 20-28°C maintaining viability while excessive heat above 35°C causes rapid viability loss through protein denaturation, humidity with moderate 40-70% maintaining pollen hydration and viability while very low humidity below 30% causes rapid desiccation reducing viability and very high humidity above 80% promotes fungal growth on pollen surfaces, and rain catastrophically destroying viability through excessive hydration and physical washing. ||Pollen dispersal at peak creates characteristic pollen clouds visible surrounding flowering clusters under favorable dry windy conditions, with light pollen grains 25-35 micrometers diameter easily becoming airborne through wind transport, traveling distances from centimeters within same flower to meters between adjacent vines, and settling on receptive stigma surfaces throughout cluster and neighboring clusters. ||Pollen density in cluster atmosphere reaches maximum during peak with estimated concentrations of 100-1000 pollen grains per cubic centimeter in immediate cluster vicinity under favorable conditions, declining with distance from source but remaining elevated 10-100 grains per cubic centimeter at vine scale, providing abundant pollen availability for pollination. ||Pollen-stigma contact frequency increases substantially during peak through high pollen density and widespread stigma receptivity, with individual receptive stigma potentially receiving 10-50 pollen grains during peak period though only 1-2 successful germinations required for fertilization, creating high-probability pollination opportunity. ||Pollen germination on receptive stigmas proceeds rapidly during peak with optimal conditions supporting germination initiation within 1-4 hours after contact, pollen grain hydrating from stigma exudate enabling metabolic activation, and pollen tube emergence through aperture penetrating stigma surface beginning growth toward ovary. ||Pollination efficiency during peak reaches maximum with abundant fresh viable pollen and widespread receptive stigmas creating optimal probability of successful pollen-stigma contact, favorable environmental conditions supporting pollen viability and germination, and high spatial density of reproductive structures facilitating efficient pollination within and between flowers. ||Self-pollination predominance shows characteristic pattern with majority of successful pollinations occurring within individual flowers or between flowers on same cluster through close proximity, wind-assisted transfer playing important role in distributing pollen among neighboring flowers, and limited cross-pollination between vines occurring but representing minor proportion of total successful pollinations. ||Atmospheric conditions affecting pollen dispersal include wind speed with light-moderate 5-15 km per hour optimal for pollen transport enhancing pollination efficiency, calm conditions below 3 km per hour reducing dispersal though self-pollination remains effective, and strong wind above 20 km per hour potentially dispersing pollen excessively reducing local availability or causing pollen desiccation. ||Temperature effects during peak show optimal 24-30°C supporting maximum pollen production, release, and viability, cool conditions below 18°C reducing anther dehiscence and pollen viability, and excessive heat above 33°C potentially causing pollen sterility through heat stress effects on developing pollen or reducing viability through rapid desiccation. ||Humidity during peak preferably 45-65% relative humidity balancing pollen viability maintenance with anther dehiscence facilitation, high humidity above 75% interfering with dehiscence preventing pollen release, and low humidity below 35% causing rapid pollen desiccation though facilitating dispersal. ||Metabolic activity in pollen and anthers shows maximum levels with elevated respiration in anthers supporting dehiscence processes, stored reserves in pollen grains providing energy for germination and initial tube growth, and metabolic activation upon hydration enabling rapid germination on receptive stigmas. ||Resource requirements for pollen production emphasize substantial carbohydrate investment with pollen containing high concentrations of storage compounds supporting germination and tube growth, protein content supporting cytoplasmic function and tube development, and specialized lipids in pollen coat affecting stigma interactions. ||Boron nutrition critically affects pollen function with adequate boron essential for pollen germination and tube growth, deficiency causing pollen sterility or poor germination severely reducing fruit set even with abundant pollen production, requiring sufficient boron availability during pollen development and germination phases. ||Anthesis synchronization implications show that peak pollen availability coinciding with peak stigma receptivity creates optimal pollination window, while temporal mismatch between pollen and stigma peaks reduces pollination efficiency affecting fruit set, highlighting importance of developmental synchrony for reproductive success. ||The process represents second of three peak anthesis aspects focusing on male reproductive capacity, developing concurrently with or shortly after maximum flower opening and overlapping with optimal pollination window. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day period of maximum pollen presence, with rapid viability decline necessitating efficient pollination during this window. ||Cultivar variation appears in pollen production quantity with some varieties producing abundant pollen supporting high fruit set while others show modest production potentially limiting set, pollen viability characteristics with some showing robust viability 80-95% while others show reduced 60-75% viability, and pollen release timing relative to stigma receptivity affecting pollination efficiency. ||Regional timing shows peak pollen availability during mid-June in warm climates, mid-June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with peak anthesis and requiring favorable weather for optimal function. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical determinant of pollination success and fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity for maximum pollen viability and function, emphasizing boron nutritional importance for pollen germination, representing period of maximum weather vulnerability with rain catastrophically affecting pollen availability, and establishing male reproductive capacity as potential fruit set limitation in unfavorable conditions. ||Research applications include analyzing pollen biology including production, viability dynamics, and germination characteristics, investigating environmental effects on pollen function affecting reproductive success, evaluating nutritional requirements particularly boron for normal pollen development and function, quantifying pollen dispersal patterns and pollination efficiency under varying conditions, and assessing genetic variation in pollen characteristics affecting reproductive success and fruit set.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 375-382 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-292 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Optimal_Pollination_Window": {
  "definition": "An Optimal_Pollination_Window is a Peak_Anthesis comprising the concurrent maximum of pollen availability and stigma receptivity within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "optimal flowering period | peak pollination opportunity | ideal reproductive window |+ optimales Bestäubungsfenster | ideale Blütephase | Hauptbestäubungsperiode | optimale Befruchtungszeit",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows optimal pollination window during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 over 2-3 days June 9-11, with 55-68% flowers simultaneously open, abundant fresh pollen available showing 76-85% viability, widespread stigma receptivity across cluster, under ideal oceanic climate conditions of 23-27°C temperature, 52-68% relative humidity, light winds 6-12 km per hour, stable weather without rain, enabling efficient pollination achieving 54-65% fruit set typical of this mid-season cultivar under favorable flowering conditions determining season yield potential",
  "editor_note": "Optimal_Pollination_Window is third and culminating Peak_Anthesis aspect, distinguished by integration of maximum male and female reproductive capacities creating ideal pollination conditions. ||Encompasses Maximum_Flower_Opening and Peak_Pollen_Availability phases. ||Represents most critical 2-3 day period determining 60-80% seasonal yield. ||Environmental conditions particularly weather during optimal window fundamentally determine fruit set and productivity. ||Weather sensitivity absolute maximum making this single most vulnerable period of entire growing season. ||Outcomes during optimal window dominant influence on vintage characteristics. || This essential reproductive opportunity occurs during peak anthesis in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 2-3 days encompassing maximum flower opening, peak pollen availability, and widespread stigma receptivity, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 stages. ||Window characteristics show simultaneous occurrence of key reproductive elements including 50-75% flowers open exposing reproductive organs, abundant fresh viable pollen available from widespread anther dehiscence, widespread stigma receptivity with active exudate production and pollen capture capacity, and favorable environmental conditions supporting reproductive organ function and pollination processes. ||Temporal overlap optimization shows critical coordination between pollen availability and stigma receptivity with peak pollen production coinciding with maximum proportion of receptive stigmas, temporal synchrony creating high probability of successful pollen-stigma contact, and brief overlap window requiring efficient pollination during limited favorable period. ||Pollination efficiency during optimal window reaches maximum levels with estimated successful pollination rates of 50-70% flowers under favorable conditions, compared to 20-40% during suboptimal early or late anthesis periods, and 10-30% or less if optimal window experiences adverse weather, demonstrating critical importance of favorable conditions during this brief period. ||Environmental requirements for optimal window include temperature ideally 24-30°C supporting maximum pollen and stigma function with pollen viability optimized, anther dehiscence proceeding efficiently, and stigma receptivity maintained at peak levels. ||Humidity optimally 45-65% relative humidity balancing pollen viability maintenance with anther dehiscence facilitation and stigma exudate properties, avoiding extremes that impair reproductive function. ||Weather stability critically important with consistent favorable conditions enabling sustained efficient pollination throughout optimal period, while variable conditions create erratic patterns reducing overall success. ||Wind conditions showing light-moderate breezes 5-15 km per hour optimal for pollen dispersal enhancing pollination efficiency without causing damage or excessive desiccation. ||Absence of rain absolutely critical with precipitation during optimal window catastrophically affecting pollination through preventing anther dehiscence, washing pollen from structures, eliminating stigma exudate, promoting fungal infection, and physically damaging delicate reproductive organs. ||Pollination mechanisms during optimal window emphasize wind-assisted self-pollination as dominant mode with pollen dispersing from anthers to stigmas within same flower through close proximity and slight air movement, between neighboring flowers on same cluster through short-distance wind transport, and occasionally between flowers on different clusters or vines through longer-distance dispersal, with self-compatibility enabling effective reproduction without requiring cross-pollination. ||Pollen-stigma interactions during optimal window proceed efficiently with receptive stigmas capturing airborne pollen grains through adhesive exudate, pollen hydrating rapidly from exudate enabling metabolic activation within 30-90 minutes, pollen recognition occurring through molecular signals between pollen coat proteins and stigma components, and pollen germination initiating within 1-4 hours producing pollen tube penetrating stigma surface. ||Pollen tube growth following pollination during optimal window proceeds rapidly with tubes elongating 1-3 mm per hour through style transmitting tract tissues, requiring 12-36 hours to traverse typical 15-30 mm style length reaching ovary, with tube growth guided by chemotactic signals from ovules directing growth through micropyle into embryo sac. ||Fertilization timing shows earliest successful fertilizations occurring 18-36 hours after pollination during optimal window, with double fertilization characteristic of angiosperms occurring with one sperm cell fusing with egg forming diploid zygote and other sperm fusing with polar nuclei forming triploid endosperm nucleus. ||Fruit set initiation begins immediately following successful fertilization with developing embryo and endosperm producing hormones particularly auxin and gibberellins triggering berry development, preventing flower abscission that would otherwise occur in unfertilized flowers, and initiating berry expansion from 2-3 mm ovary toward mature berry dimensions. ||Resource allocation during optimal window emphasizes reproductive demands with substantial carbohydrate consumption supporting pollen production, tube growth, and early embryo development, nitrogen requirements for protein synthesis in rapidly developing reproductive structures, and critical micronutrients particularly boron essential for pollen germination and tube growth with deficiency severely limiting pollination success. ||Hormonal coordination during optimal window involves declining growth promoters as flowering culminates, active auxin production from successfully fertilized ovaries triggering fruit development, possible ethylene involvement in unfertilized flower senescence, and integrated hormonal signals coordinating transition from flowering to fruit development. ||Developmental outcomes determined during optimal window include majority of final berry number 60-80% established through successful pollinations during this critical 2-3 day period, with remaining 20-40% set during suboptimal early and late anthesis periods, making optimal window conditions dominant influence on seasonal yield. ||Weather sensitivity during optimal window reaches absolute maximum with reproductive success extremely vulnerable to adverse conditions, minor weather perturbations potentially reducing fruit set by 10-30%, and severe events like rain reducing set by 50-80%, making weather during optimal window single most important determinant of seasonal productivity. ||Climate variability implications show that interannual variation in optimal window weather conditions creates substantial yield variation among seasons, favorable years with stable warm dry conditions during optimal window producing high set 60-75% and abundant yields, while unfavorable years with cool wet variable conditions producing poor set 20-40% and reduced yields, demonstrating critical role of flowering weather in determining vintage characteristics. ||Management implications during optimal window include maintaining minimal vineyard disturbance with all canopy operations suspended to avoid physical disruption of pollination, disease management restricted due to fungicide application prohibitions during bloom requiring protective applications completed before optimal window, weather monitoring intensified with forecasts critically important for anticipating potential problems, and possible protective interventions considered in high-value situations if adverse weather threatens though options are limited. ||The process represents third and culminating peak anthesis aspect integrating male and female reproductive capacities creating optimal reproductive opportunity, encompassing maximum flower opening and peak pollen availability phases. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing brief critical period determining majority of fruit set and yield, with warm stable conditions producing compressed 2-day window while variable conditions may extend to 3-4 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in optimal window timing with early varieties showing late May-early June window while late types show mid-late June timing, window duration with some varieties showing brief 2-day window while others show extended 3-4 day period, and sensitivity to environmental conditions with some varieties showing robust reproduction under variable conditions while others show high sensitivity requiring optimal conditions for adequate set. ||Regional timing shows optimal pollination window during early-mid June in warm climates at approximately 1050-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 950-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 850-900 GDD, with timing ideally coinciding with stable favorable weather period. ||Viticultural significance includes representing most critical period of entire growing season with outcomes during these 2-3 days determining 60-80% final yield, requiring optimal environmental conditions for successful pollination and high fruit set, emphasizing importance of site selection, vineyard design, and canopy management optimizing flowering conditions, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability necessitating risk management strategies, and illustrating fundamental challenge in viticulture of depending on brief weather-sensitive reproductive period for economic productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing temporal dynamics of reproductive capacity determining optimal window characteristics, quantifying environmental effects on pollination efficiency during optimal period, evaluating management practices affecting flowering conditions and fruit set outcomes, developing models predicting fruit set from optimal window weather conditions, assessing climate change impacts on optimal window timing and conditions affecting viticultural productivity, and investigating mechanisms of reproductive synchronization coordinating male and female functions during optimal window.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 378-390 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 290-298 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Late_Anthesis": {
  "definition": "A Late_Anthesis is an Anthesis comprising the opening of the final 20–30% of flowers concurrent with senescence of earlier-opened flowers and reduced pollen viability.",
  "alternative_term": "final bloom | concluding anthesis | late flowering | declining bloom |+ späte Anthese | Endblüte | auslaufende Blühphase | Blütenabschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows late anthesis during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 67-68 over 2-3 days June 12-14, with final 22-28% flowers opening predominantly in basal cluster regions, pollen viability declining to 35-55% in late-opening flowers, pollination success reducing to 28-38% compared to 52-62% during peak, under temperate maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, 60-75% relative humidity, variable weather, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing flowering with late anthesis contributing 18-24% final berry number",
  "editor_note": "Late_Anthesis is third major Anthesis phase following Early and Peak Anthesis, distinguished by declining flowering intensity and closing pollination window. ||Corresponds to BBCH 67-68 with 70-90% flowers opened. ||Subdivided into Final_Flowers_Opening, Declining_Pollen_Viability, and Pollination_Window_Closure. ||Transitions to Complete_Anthesis as final flowers open. ||Represents final 15-25% fruit set contribution. ||Weather sensitivity remains significant though reduced from peak. ||Flower abscission begins indicating fertilization outcomes. || This concluding reproductive phase occurs during mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1 following peak anthesis, typically spanning 2-3 days as remaining flowers open creating final pollination opportunities before anthesis completion, corresponding to BBCH 67-68 stages. ||Flowering intensity during late anthesis shows characteristic decline with decreasing daily opening rate dropping from 10-20% during peak to 3-8% during late phase, cumulative effect creating 70-90% flowers opened by late anthesis, and remaining 10-30% flowers completing opening during this final phase. ||Flower distribution pattern shows apical and middle regions predominantly showing opened or senescing flowers with 85-100% flowers past peak, while basal regions show final opening activity with 50-80% flowers opening during late phase, creating spatial gradient with most advanced development apically and latest development basally. ||Reproductive organ status during late anthesis shows mixed condition across cluster with earliest-opened flowers showing senescent organs including withered anthers depleted of pollen, declining stigma receptivity with reduced exudate production and beginning browning, and overall flower aging approaching abscission if unfertilized. ||Recently opened flowers in late anthesis show functional organs but suboptimal conditions with anthers dehiscing but pollen showing reduced viability compared to peak period, stigmas receptive but with lower exudate production and shorter functional period, and overall reduced reproductive capacity compared to earlier-opening flowers. ||Pollen availability during late anthesis shows substantial decline with remaining viable pollen from recently dehisced anthers representing final opportunity, cumulative pollen from earlier opening largely expired with viability reduced to 10-30% or less, and overall pollen density in cluster atmosphere declining substantially creating limited pollination opportunity. ||Pollen viability decline proceeds rapidly during late anthesis with fresh pollen from late-opening flowers showing 60-80% germination capacity compared to 70-90% during peak, and aged pollen from earlier opening showing minimal 5-20% viability, creating reduced pollination success potential for late-opening or previously unpollinated flowers. ||Stigma receptivity during late anthesis shows declining function with recently opened stigmas showing moderate receptivity 60-80% peak levels, stigmas from earlier-opened flowers showing substantially reduced receptivity 20-40% peak levels as exudate production declines and tissues begin senescence, and overall reduced female reproductive capacity across cluster. ||Pollination efficiency during late anthesis drops substantially with estimated successful pollination rates of 20-40% for late-opening flowers compared to 50-70% during optimal window, resulting from combined effects of reduced pollen availability, decreased pollen viability, diminished stigma receptivity, and potentially less favorable environmental conditions. ||Fertilization success from late anthesis pollinations shows reduced rates with longer time required for pollen tube growth potentially 24-48 hours due to suboptimal conditions, and higher probability of fertilization failure resulting in flower abscission, affecting final fruit set contribution from late anthesis period. ||Fruit set from late anthesis typically represents 15-25% total berry number established during this final phase, compared to 60-80% during peak anthesis, with late-set berries often showing slightly delayed development compared to earlier-set berries potentially affecting harvest uniformity. ||Developmental heterogeneity increases during late anthesis with wide range of flower states coexisting including newly opening flowers, recently pollinated flowers beginning fruit development, senescing unfertilized flowers preparing for abscission, and small developing berries from successful earlier pollinations, creating complex mixed developmental appearance. ||Environmental effects during late anthesis continue affecting reproductive success with optimal conditions 20-28°C maintaining adequate though declining organ function, while suboptimal cool or warm conditions further reduce reproductive capacity, and any adverse weather during late anthesis affecting final fruit set contribution. ||Cluster appearance during late anthesis shows transitional character with mixture of opened flowers, withering unfertilized flowers showing brown discoloration, small green developing berries 3-5 mm diameter from successful earlier fertilizations, and remaining unopened buds in basal positions, creating characteristic appearance of reproductive transition. ||Flower senescence becomes prominent during late anthesis with unfertilized flowers showing progressive deterioration including anther withering and browning, stigma desiccation and discoloration, petal remnant browning if not completely shed, and preparing for abscission through abscission zone activation at pedicel base. ||Flower abscission initiation begins during late anthesis with earliest unfertilized flowers developing abscission zones and detaching, creating visible flower drop that will continue through post-anthesis period, with successful fertilization preventing abscission through hormonal signals from developing embryo. ||Berry development visibility increases during late anthesis as successfully fertilized ovaries expand becoming recognizable as small berries distinguishable from unopened buds or unfertilized flowers, providing early indication of fruit set success and potential yield. ||Hormonal changes during late anthesis include increasing auxin production from successfully fertilized ovaries preventing flower abscission and triggering berry expansion, possible ethylene increase in unfertilized flowers promoting senescence and abscission, and declining reproductive hormones as flowering culminates. ||Metabolic transition during late anthesis shifts from reproductive to developmental focus with declining investment in flower function and increasing allocation to successfully fertilized ovaries initiating berry development, marking transition from flowering to fruit development as dominant process. ||Resource allocation changes during late anthesis redirect photosynthate from declining reproductive demands toward developing berries requiring substantial resources for early rapid growth, continuing vegetative growth with shoot elongation and leaf expansion, and beginning preparation for subsequent phenological stages. ||Weather sensitivity during late anthesis remains high though reduced compared to peak period, with adverse conditions affecting late-opening flowers but having minimal impact on successfully pollinated earlier flowers already initiating berry development, and rain during late anthesis causing less catastrophic effects than during peak though still reducing late pollination success. ||Disease pressure during late anthesis emphasizes botrytis with senescing flower tissues providing favorable substrate for fungal colonization, latent infections established during flowering remaining dormant in developing berries, and transition to berry protection becoming management priority. ||Management considerations during late anthesis include continuing restrictions on canopy operations and fungicide applications until flowering completion confirmed, monitoring flower abscission and small berry development assessing fruit set success, beginning preparations for post-bloom operations including disease management and canopy positioning, and evaluating flowering outcomes for yield predictions. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from final flowers opening completing cluster flowering activity, through declining pollen viability reducing late pollination success, to pollination window closure ending reproductive opportunity. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing concluding phase before complete anthesis, with warm conditions promoting rapid progression while cool conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in proportion of late-opening flowers with some varieties showing compressed flowering with only 10-15% late opening while others show extended 25-35% late opening affecting overall duration, late flower reproductive capacity with some maintaining adequate function while others show substantially reduced capacity, and transition timing to complete anthesis and fruit development. ||Regional timing shows late anthesis during mid-late June in warm climates, mid-late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, occurring 5-8 days after first flowers opening depending on flowering duration. ||Viticultural significance includes representing final contribution to fruit set establishing remaining 15-25% berry number, marking transition from critical weather-sensitive flowering period toward more stable fruit development, providing early fruit set assessment through flower abscission and berry visibility, and indicating approaching flowering completion enabling management transitions. ||Research applications include analyzing factors affecting late flower reproductive capacity, evaluating contributions of late anthesis to final fruit set and berry development patterns, quantifying developmental heterogeneity within clusters affecting ripening uniformity, assessing flower senescence and abscission mechanisms, and documenting transition from reproductive to developmental phases.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-388 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 292-298 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Final_Flowers_Opening": {
  "definition": "A Final_Flowers_Opening is a Late_Anthesis comprising the cap shedding of the remaining 10–20% of unopened buds with reproductive organs exposed.",
  "alternative_term": "last flowers opening | concluding bloom | final bud opening | terminal flowering |+ letzte Blüten öffnen | abschließende Blütenöffnung | Endblüten | finale Knospenöffnung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows final flowers opening during late June Year N+1 at late BBCH 68 over 1-2 days June 14-15, with remaining 12-18% flowers predominantly in basal cluster positions completing cap shedding, occurring while 3-5 mm berries visible from earliest fruit set, limited pollen availability constraining late pollination success to 22-32%, under continental conditions of 21-26°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing flowering with final opening contributing 10-14% berry number",
  "editor_note": "Final_Flowers_Opening is first of three Late_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by completion of cluster opening activity with remaining unopened buds. ||Occurs predominantly in basal cluster regions. ||Represents final pollination opportunity contributing 8-15% berry number. ||Constrained by limited pollen availability rather than stigma dysfunction. ||Establishes maximum within-cluster developmental heterogeneity. ||Marks transition toward complete anthesis. || This concluding opening phase occurs during late anthesis in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 1-2 days as final flowers predominantly in basal cluster positions achieve open state, corresponding to late BBCH 67-68 stages. ||Opening pattern shows final flowers concentrated in basal cluster regions reflecting latest primordium formation and most delayed development, with 10-20% flowers remaining unopened at late anthesis onset completing opening during this final phase, and very occasional flowers showing failure to open remaining as unopened buds that will eventually abscise. ||Cap shedding in final flowers proceeds through same abscission mechanisms as earlier flowers but often under less favorable conditions with declining flower vigor, potentially suboptimal environmental conditions after peak period, and reduced developmental resources as vine prioritizes developing berries, creating somewhat less efficient opening in some cases. ||Reproductive organ exposure in final-opening flowers reveals functional structures though vigor may be reduced compared to earlier flowers, with anthers showing appropriate maturation and dehiscence capacity though pollen production may be slightly reduced, and stigmas developing receptivity though exudate production may be somewhat diminished. ||Flower appearance at final opening shows opened structures similar to earlier flowers but opening timing indicates late developmental status, with opened final flowers distinguishable from earlier-opened flowers through spatial position predominantly basal, timing relative to fruit development elsewhere in cluster, and occasionally slightly smaller organ dimensions. ||Timing relationships show final opening occurring simultaneously with advanced development elsewhere in cluster including visible small berries 3-6 mm from earliest fruit set, senescing unfertilized flowers from mid-flowering showing brown discoloration, and declining reproductive activity in earlier-opened flowers, creating maximum developmental heterogeneity. ||Pollen availability for final-opening flowers shows suboptimal conditions with limited fresh pollen from own anthers providing immediate source, minimal viable pollen remaining from earlier-opened flowers with most aged pollen expired, and reduced atmospheric pollen concentration as cluster-level pollen production declining substantially. ||Stigma function in final-opening flowers develops normally with receptivity initiating within 6-24 hours after opening and reaching moderate peak levels, though overall pollination opportunity is constrained by limited pollen availability rather than stigma function, with receptive period potentially abbreviated compared to earlier flowers. ||Pollination probability for final-opening flowers shows reduced success with estimated 15-35% achieving successful pollination and fruit set compared to 50-70% during optimal window, resulting primarily from limited pollen availability rather than stigma dysfunction, affecting final fruit set contribution from these latest flowers. ||Self-pollination remains primary mechanism for final flowers with pollen from own anthers providing main opportunity, limited cross-pollination from neighboring late-opening flowers supplementing, and minimal contribution from aged pollen from earlier flowers, creating dependence on immediate pollen production. ||Developmental outcomes from final opening show variable fruit set with some late-opening flowers achieving successful pollination and contributing to final berry number, while others fail to set becoming part of abscising unfertilized flower population, with late-set berries potentially showing delayed development affecting ripening uniformity. ||Berry development from final pollinations proceeds normally but with temporal offset showing berries from final opening developing 5-10 days behind earliest-set berries, creating developmental gradient within cluster affecting ripening progression and harvest timing considerations. ||Environmental effects on final opening continue with temperature affecting cap shedding efficiency and organ function, humidity influencing anther dehiscence and pollen release, and overall conditions often less optimal than during peak period potentially contributing to reduced opening vigor. ||Weather impacts show that adverse conditions during final opening have limited overall effect on fruit set since majority 75-85% berry number already established, though conditions do affect final opening success and contribution to ultimate yield. ||Cluster architecture effects show that basal flowers opening latest may experience more shaded microclimate with reduced light and air circulation potentially affecting opening efficiency and subsequent reproductive success compared to earlier-opening better-exposed apical flowers. ||Resource competition increases during final opening with developing berries from earlier fruit set creating substantial sink demand competing with reproductive processes in final-opening flowers, potentially contributing to reduced late flower success through resource limitation. ||Metabolic status in final-opening flowers shows adequate function but possibly reduced vigor with respiration supporting reproductive processes though potentially at lower levels than earlier flowers, and carbohydrate availability adequate though preferentially allocated to developing berries creating possible resource constraint. ||Hormonal environment during final opening shows declining reproductive hormone levels as flowering culminates with increasing dominance of developmental hormones from successfully fertilized ovaries, creating hormonal context less favorable for sustained reproductive investment. ||Developmental coordination shows final opening occurring while vegetative growth continues with shoot elongation ongoing though slowing, leaf expansion proceeding, and tendrils developing, maintaining concurrent vegetative-reproductive processes though shifting toward vegetative-developmental balance. ||Management implications of final opening include indicating approaching flowering completion enabling planning for post-bloom operations, confirming extent of cluster flowering activity affecting yield predictions, and providing final assessment of flowering uniformity and potential developmental heterogeneity. ||Observational characteristics enable identification of final opening through spatial concentration in basal positions, timing relative to berry development elsewhere in cluster, and progression toward complete cluster flowering creating all-flowers-opened state. ||The process represents first of three late anthesis aspects focusing on completion of opening activity, followed by declining pollen viability and pollination window closure affecting reproductive opportunity. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days representing brief concluding opening period, with warm conditions promoting rapid completion while cool conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation appears in proportion of final opening with some varieties showing minimal 8-12% late opening reflecting compressed flowering while others show substantial 18-25% late opening indicating extended flowering, final flower vigor with some maintaining good reproductive capacity while others show substantially reduced capacity, and timing relative to fruit development affecting developmental heterogeneity. ||Regional timing shows final flowers opening during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, occurring 6-9 days after first flowers opening depending on overall flowering duration. ||Viticultural significance includes completing cluster flowering activity establishing all potential fruit set sites, contributing final 8-15% berry number from late successful pollinations, marking transition toward complete anthesis and flowering conclusion, and establishing maximum within-cluster developmental heterogeneity affecting subsequent ripening patterns. ||Research applications include analyzing factors determining final flower opening success, evaluating developmental constraints on late flower reproductive capacity, quantifying fruit set contributions from final opening affecting yield components, assessing resource allocation conflicts between late reproduction and early berry development, and documenting within-cluster developmental gradients affecting ripening dynamics.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 382-386 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Declining_Pollen_Viability": {
  "definition": "A Declining_Pollen_Viability is a Late_Anthesis comprising reduced pollen germination capacity from aged pollen and lower-quality pollen from late-opening flowers.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen deterioration | declining pollen quality | pollen aging | reduced pollen viability |+ abnehmende Pollenviabilität | Pollenverschlechterung | Pollenalterung | sinkende Pollenqualität",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows declining pollen viability during late anthesis late June Year N+1 at BBCH 67-68 over 2-3 days, with fresh pollen from late-opening flowers showing 62-74% germination compared to peak 76-88%, aged pollen 48-72 hours old showing 12-24% viability, substantially constraining late pollination success reducing fruit set to 24-34% for late flowers compared to 54-64% during peak, under oceanic conditions of 21-26°C temperature, 58-72% relative humidity, typical of this mid-season cultivar showing moderate pollen longevity",
  "editor_note": "Declining_Pollen_Viability is second of three Late_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by progressive deterioration of male reproductive capacity through pollen aging. ||Occurs concurrently with Final_Flowers_Opening. ||Represents major constraint on late pollination success limiting final fruit set contribution. ||Environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity accelerate decline. ||Boron nutrition critically affects maintenance of residual pollen function. ||Cultivar differences in pollen longevity significantly affect late reproductive success. || This critical male function decline occurs during late anthesis in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning 2-3 days as pollen viability drops from peak levels 70-90% germination to late levels 20-40% fresh pollen and 5-15% aged pollen, severely limiting final pollination success. ||Viability decline pattern shows characteristic temporal progression with fresh pollen from recently dehisced anthers maintaining moderate 60-80% viability though reduced from peak 70-90%, pollen aged 24-48 hours showing substantially reduced 20-40% viability, and pollen aged 48-72+ hours showing minimal 5-15% viability approaching complete loss of function. ||Pollen aging mechanisms involve progressive deterioration of cellular structures including membrane degradation compromising cellular integrity, protein denaturation particularly affecting enzymes required for germination and tube growth, DNA damage accumulating in vegetative and sperm cell nuclei potentially affecting fertilization, and depletion of stored energy reserves limiting capacity to support germination. ||Environmental effects accelerate viability decline with high temperature above 30°C causing rapid deterioration through protein denaturation and membrane damage, low humidity below 40% causing excessive desiccation destroying cellular function, high humidity above 75% promoting fungal colonization on pollen surfaces, and UV radiation potentially damaging DNA and proteins in exposed pollen. ||Pollen viability assessment shows multiple methods including in vitro germination tests placing pollen on artificial medium measuring germination percentage providing quantitative assessment, tetrazolium staining indicating metabolic activity through enzymatic reduction creating colored product, and fluorescent dyes distinguishing viable from nonviable pollen through membrane integrity assessment. ||Germination capacity decline shows that while peak-period pollen germinates readily within 1-2 hours producing vigorous tubes, late-period pollen shows delayed germination requiring 3-6 hours, reduced germination percentage with only 20-40% pollen producing tubes, and abnormal tube growth with twisted or stunted tubes indicating cellular dysfunction. ||Pollen tube growth from declining-viability pollen shows reduced vigor with slower elongation rates 0.5-1.5 mm per hour compared to 1-3 mm per hour with fresh viable pollen, increased probability of growth cessation before reaching ovary failing to deliver sperm cells, and potential for abnormal fertilization outcomes if defective pollen does reach embryo sac. ||Pollination success probability drops substantially with declining viability showing correlation between pollen germination percentage and fruit set rate, with 70-90% viable pollen supporting 50-70% fruit set during optimal window declining to 20-40% viable pollen supporting only 15-30% fruit set during late anthesis. ||Pollen availability interactions compound viability effects with reduced pollen production during late anthesis combined with declining viability creating severely constrained pollination opportunity, limiting reproductive success for late-opening or previously unpollinated flowers. ||Atmospheric pollen concentration declines during late anthesis through combined effects of reduced production from fewer anthers dehiscing, loss of viability in airborne pollen reducing functional pollen density, and dilution through continued air circulation dispersing remaining pollen, reducing pollination probability. ||Fresh pollen production during late anthesis continues from recently opened flowers providing limited renewed pollen source, though production levels may be reduced compared to peak period and pollen quality may show intrinsic reduction reflecting late developmental status. ||Cultivar differences in pollen viability characteristics show some varieties producing robust pollen maintaining 70-85% viability during late anthesis supporting adequate late pollination, while others show poor pollen with 40-60% viability during late period substantially limiting reproductive success. ||Boron nutrition effects on pollen function intensify during late period with adequate boron essential for maintaining germination and tube growth capacity in declining-viability pollen, while deficiency exacerbates viability problems potentially eliminating late pollination success. ||Temperature during late anthesis critically affects viability dynamics with optimal 22-28°C maintaining adequate though declining pollen function, cool conditions below 18°C further reducing viability and germination, and warm conditions above 30°C accelerating decline potentially eliminating late reproductive opportunity. ||Humidity during late anthesis affects pollen viability with moderate 45-65% maintaining adequate hydration without promoting fungal growth, while humidity extremes accelerate decline through desiccation or microbial colonization. ||Resource allocation shifts during late anthesis redirect vine resources from reproductive investment toward developing berries, potentially contributing to reduced pollen quality through decreased resource availability for late anther development and pollen maturation. ||Metabolic changes in declining-viability pollen show reduced respiration indicating cellular deterioration, depleted ATP levels limiting energy availability for germination, and accumulated cellular damage from oxidative stress or other aging processes. ||Hormonal regulation of pollen viability involves possible role for stress hormones including abscisic acid potentially affecting pollen longevity, though primary determinants are intrinsic aging processes and environmental stresses. ||Practical implications of declining viability include substantially reduced late fruit set from late-opening flowers unable to achieve adequate pollination, increased probability of incomplete fruit set in extended flowering conditions where late opening predominates, and possible fruit set failures in cultivars with inherently poor late pollen viability. ||Management considerations include recognizing that late anthesis conditions have diminishing impact on overall fruit set since majority of berries 75-85% already established during peak, understanding that cultivars with extended flowering may show reduced overall fruit set from prevalence of declining-viability pollen, and appreciating that boron nutrition adequacy critically affects late pollen function maintaining some reproductive capacity during viability decline. ||The process represents second of three late anthesis aspects focusing on male reproductive capacity decline, occurring concurrently with final flowers opening and contributing to pollination window closure. ||Duration spans 2-3 days of late anthesis representing progressive viability deterioration, with rapid decline under unfavorable conditions or slower decline under optimal conditions. ||Cultivar variation in viability decline shows some varieties maintaining adequate pollen function through late anthesis supporting reasonable late fruit set, while others show rapid severe decline substantially limiting late reproductive success and potentially creating yield limitations. ||Regional timing shows declining pollen viability during late anthesis period mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, affecting final 2-3 days of flowering period. ||Viticultural significance includes representing major constraint on late pollination success and final fruit set contribution, emphasizing importance of compressed flowering period concentrating reproductive activity during optimal pollen viability window, illustrating vulnerability of extended flowering to poor fruit set from declining pollen quality, and demonstrating critical role of pollen function in determining reproductive success and yield. ||Research applications include analyzing pollen aging mechanisms including cellular and molecular deterioration processes, evaluating environmental effects on viability dynamics affecting pollination outcomes, investigating cultivar differences in pollen longevity affecting reproductive reliability, quantifying relationships between viability and fruit set success, and assessing management practices particularly boron nutrition affecting pollen function maintenance.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 290-295"
},

  "Pollination_Window_Closure": {
  "definition": "A Pollination_Window_Closure is a Late_Anthesis comprising the loss of effective reproductive capacity through completed flowering, expired pollen viability, and declined stigma receptivity.",
  "alternative_term": "pollination window end | reproductive closure | flowering termination | end of pollination period |+ Bestäubungsfensterschluss | Befruchtungsende | reproduktive Terminierung | Ende der Pollination",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows pollination window closure during late June Year N+1 at late BBCH 68 over 1-2 days June 14-15, with negligible functional pollen remaining showing <5% viability, widespread stigma senescence eliminating receptivity, visible berry development 4-6 mm diameter from successful fruit set, unfertilized flowers showing brown senescence preparing for abscission, establishing final fruit set of 48-62% representing 320-480 berries per cluster, under Mediterranean conditions of 24-28°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar definitively concluding flowering and establishing season yield potential",
  "editor_note": "Pollination_Window_Closure is third and final Late_Anthesis aspect, distinguished by definitive termination of effective reproductive opportunity. ||Follows Final_Flowers_Opening and Declining_Pollen_Viability. ||Establishes final fruit set and berry number determining season yield. ||Marks transition from reproductive vulnerability to developmental phase. ||Enables management transitions including resumption of canopy operations and disease protection. ||Represents definitive endpoint of critical flowering period. || This critical reproductive endpoint occurs during late anthesis in late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically representing final 1-2 days of late anthesis period when reproductive function effectively ceases, corresponding to late BBCH 68 transitioning toward BBCH 69. ||Closure mechanisms involve multiple converging factors including exhaustion of pollen supply as all anthers complete dehiscence and aged pollen loses viability, stigma senescence eliminating receptive surfaces as exudate production ceases and tissues deteriorate, complete flower opening leaving no additional reproductive structures to contribute, and vine resource allocation shifting definitively toward fruit development precluding further reproductive investment. ||Pollen availability at closure shows negligible functional pollen remaining with final anthers having dehisced but pollen rapidly expiring, aged atmospheric pollen showing minimal 0-5% viability effectively non-functional, and no further pollen production forthcoming with all reproductive organs past functional stage. ||Stigma receptivity at closure shows widespread loss of function with earlier-opened stigmas completely senesced showing brown discoloration and desiccated tissues, recently opened stigmas showing declining receptivity 10-30% peak levels with minimal exudate production, and overall female reproductive capacity effectively terminated. ||Reproductive organ senescence accelerates during closure with unfertilized flowers showing rapid deterioration including anther withering and browning indicating complete pollen depletion, stigma necrosis eliminating receptive capacity, receptacle and pedicel beginning abscission zone activation preparing for flower drop, and overall flower senescence indicating failed reproduction. ||Successfully fertilized flowers at closure show contrasting appearance with visible berry development evident as small green structures 3-6 mm diameter, continuing expansion indicating active fruit development, hormonal signals preventing abscission maintaining flower-fruit attachment, and overall healthy appearance contrasting with senescing unfertilized flowers. ||Flower abscission initiation intensifies during closure with unfertilized flowers developing abscission zones at pedicel base involving enzymatic wall degradation creating separation plane, mechanical stresses from wind or handling potentially triggering detachment, and progressive flower drop creating visible accumulation of abscised flowers on cluster and ground surfaces. ||Fruit set determination becomes definitive at closure with count of successfully fertilized flowers establishing final berry number, typical fruit set percentages ranging 30-50% in poor conditions or difficult-setting cultivars to 60-75% under favorable conditions in good-setting varieties, and established berry number determining yield potential though subsequent berry development and maturation affecting final harvest outcomes. ||Developmental transition at closure shifts vine priority decisively from reproductive to developmental functions with metabolic resources redirecting from flowering processes to berry growth, hormonal environment dominated by auxin and gibberellins from developing berries rather than reproductive signals, and physiological focus on fruit development vegetative growth and reserve accumulation rather than continued reproduction. ||Cluster appearance at closure shows characteristic mixed state with small developing berries from successful early-mid fruit set, senescing brown unfertilized flowers preparing for abscission, occasional late-opening flowers with minimal reproductive potential, and overall appearance of reproductive conclusion with developmental phase beginning. ||Environmental effects on closure timing show that favorable conditions enabling efficient early reproduction allow relatively early closure with minimal late flowering activity, while unfavorable conditions extending flowering may delay closure though late reproductive success remains limited, and overall closure timing relatively consistent reflecting biological limits on reproductive duration. ||Temperature during closure typically ranges 20-28°C supporting normal physiological transition, with warm conditions potentially accelerating flower senescence and abscission, while cool conditions may slow processes though not preventing inevitable closure. ||Weather impacts on closure are minimal since reproductive outcomes already determined with adverse conditions affecting any late reproductive attempts but having negligible effect on overall fruit set already established. ||Management implications at closure include confirming flowering completion enabling resumption of normal vineyard operations, initiating post-bloom disease management particularly botrytis protection on developing berries, implementing canopy management operations including shoot positioning and possible thinning, assessing fruit set outcomes for yield predictions and crop adjustment decisions, and transitioning focus from reproductive to developmental management priorities. ||Phenological significance of closure includes marking definitive end of BBCH 60-69 flowering stages transitioning to BBCH 70-79 fruit development stages, establishing reference point for subsequent phenological predictions including berry development timing, and confirming reproductive phase completion enabling developmental phase focus. ||Disease management transition at closure shifts from bloom-period restrictions enabling fungicide applications for botrytis and powdery mildew protection on developing berries, recognizing that latent botrytis infections established during flowering will remain dormant requiring management during ripening, and implementing preventive strategies for berry diseases throughout development period. ||Nutritional management considerations at closure include ensuring adequate nitrogen for vegetative growth and fruit development without promoting excessive vigor, providing sufficient potassium for berry development and quality, maintaining adequate boron for cell division in expanding berries, and balanced nutrition supporting both fruit development and vine health through season. ||Resource allocation at closure shows vine transitioning from reproductive investment toward developmental demands with carbohydrates redirecting from flower support to rapid berry expansion, nitrogen partitioning to support vegetative growth and berry protein synthesis, and mineral nutrients focusing on fruit and shoot development. ||Hormonal environment at closure shows dominance of auxin from developing berries triggering cell division and expansion, gibberellins affecting early berry growth and possibly seedless berry development in some applications, cytokinins supporting cell division in berries and maintaining vegetative growth, and ethylene potentially involved in flower abscission though not directly affecting berry development at this early stage. ||Developmental outcomes established at closure include final berry number determining yield potential typically 100-500 berries per cluster depending on variety and conditions, within-cluster developmental gradient with 5-10 day spread between earliest and latest-set berries affecting ripening uniformity, and cluster architecture with berry spacing affecting disease pressure and quality characteristics. ||Fruit set assessment methods at closure include visual berry count on representative clusters providing direct berry number measurement, flower abscission evaluation estimating set percentage from remaining vs fallen flowers, and cluster weight estimates based on berry number and expected berry size predicting yield outcomes. ||The process represents third and final late anthesis aspect marking definitive reproductive termination, following final flowers opening and declining pollen viability. ||Duration represents 1-2 day transition period as reproductive function effectively ceases, with rapid progression toward complete anthesis. ||Cultivar variation in closure characteristics shows some varieties reaching definitive closure rapidly with clean transition to fruit development, while others show extended indeterminate closure with continued flower senescence over several days, affecting management timing and fruit set assessment clarity. ||Regional timing shows pollination window closure during late June in warm climates at approximately 1100-1150 growing degree days base 10°C, late June-early July in temperate regions at 1000-1050 GDD, and early July in cool areas at 900-1000 GDD, marking transition from reproductive to developmental phenological phase. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing definitive final fruit set and berry number determining yield potential, marking end of critical weather-sensitive flowering period reducing vulnerability to environmental conditions, enabling resumption of normal management operations including canopy management and disease protection, providing fruit set outcomes for yield prediction and crop adjustment planning, and confirming transition to developmental phase requiring different management priorities. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms coordinating reproductive termination and developmental initiation, evaluating factors determining fruit set percentage and berry number outcomes, quantifying relationships between flowering conditions and final fruit set results, assessing within-cluster developmental heterogeneity affecting ripening patterns, and documenting phenological transitions marking major developmental phase changes in perennial reproductive biology.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 385-390 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 295-298"
},

  "Complete_Anthesis": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Anthesis is an Anthesis comprising the opened state of all viable flowers within the cluster with reproductive processes concluded and fruit set established.",
  "alternative_term": "flowering completion | anthesis conclusion | end of flowering | bloom completion |+ vollständige Anthese | Blütenabschluss | Blüheende | Anthesevollendung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows complete anthesis during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69 on approximately June 16, with all viable flowers opened, visible berry development 5-8 mm diameter throughout cluster, unfertilized flowers showing brown senescence and progressive abscission, established fruit set of 55-68% representing 380-520 berries per cluster, under warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature transitioning from reproductive vulnerability to developmental stability, typical of this late-season cultivar definitively completing flowering 12-14 days after first flowers opened",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Anthesis represents definitive flowering completion milestone marking reproductive phase conclusion. ||Follows Late_Anthesis. ||Corresponds to BBCH 69. ||Subdivided into All_Flowers_Opened, Anthesis_Completion, and Post_Anthesis_Transition. ||Establishes final fruit set and berry number. ||Marks transition from reproductive vulnerability to developmental phase. ||Enables management transitions and establishes reference for subsequent phenological predictions. ||Critical milestone in annual phenological progression. || This conclusive reproductive milestone occurs during late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 following late anthesis, typically representing 1-2 day period marking transition from BBCH 68 to BBCH 69 as reproductive phase definitively concludes. ||Completion characteristics show all potentially viable flowers having completed opening with 100% of developmentally capable flowers showing exposed reproductive organs or developed berries, remaining unopened structures representing aberrant or aborted buds incapable of normal development, and overall cluster showing clear transition from reproductive to developmental state. ||Flower status distribution at completion shows successfully fertilized flowers as developing berries 4-8 mm diameter creating visible green fruit structures distributed throughout cluster, unfertilized flowers as senescing brown structures showing progressive abscission, occasional final-opening flowers showing minimal reproductive potential, and overall reproductive activity effectively ceased. ||Berry visibility at completion shows clear fruit structures distinguishable throughout cluster with small green berries easily identifiable on pedicels, berry number countable providing definitive fruit set assessment, spatial distribution revealing architectural pattern and potential density issues, and overall appearance of young fruit cluster rather than flower cluster. ||Abscission activity intensifies at completion with unfertilized flowers progressively detaching through completed abscission zone development, daily flower drop creating accumulation of fallen flowers on cluster surface and ground, and progressive cluster thinning as failed reproductions eliminate leaving only successful fruit set berries. ||Fruit set percentage determination at completion enables accurate assessment with berry count relative to total flowers opened calculating set percentage typically 30-75% depending on cultivar and conditions, comparison to potential flower number from previous season primordium formation evaluating reproductive success, and yield prediction based on berry number and expected final berry size. ||Cluster appearance at completion shows characteristic developmental state with small green berries dominating visual appearance, brown senescing unfertilized flowers interspersed though progressively abscising, cluster showing open architecture with berries spaced on pedicels and branches, and overall healthy developmental appearance contrasting with earlier reproductive vulnerability. ||Developmental phase transition at completion marks shift from reproductive biology to fruit development with metabolic priorities focusing on berry cell division and expansion, resource allocation directing photosynthate to rapidly growing berries as primary sink, and hormonal environment dominated by developmental signals from expanding berries rather than reproductive coordination. ||Berry development stage at completion shows early cell division phase with rapid cell proliferation establishing cell number potential typically 8-15 days duration, cells dividing rapidly 12-24 hour cycles creating berry cell population, and berry size increasing primarily through cell number increase during this early stage. ||Berry growth rate at completion shows rapid expansion 0.3-0.6 mm diameter per day driven primarily by cell division with modest cell expansion, water uptake supporting turgor maintaining expansion, and substantial resource demand requiring adequate photosynthetic capacity and favorable environmental conditions. ||Berry structure at completion includes developing pericarp with outer skin layers, inner flesh tissues undergoing cell proliferation, and seed development progressing with embryo and endosperm growth following successful fertilization, establishing anatomical framework for berry maturation. ||Seed development at completion shows early embryo development following fertilization with embryo cells dividing rapidly, endosperm development providing nutritive tissue supporting embryo growth, and integument layers developing into seed coat, with seed development coordinated with berry pericarp growth through hormonal signals. ||Resource demand at completion increases substantially with developing berries creating major sink competing with vegetative growth for available resources, requiring adequate photosynthetic production from expanding canopy, supplemented by stored reserves particularly during early rapid cell division, and balanced resource allocation supporting both fruit and vegetative development. ||Canopy development at completion shows concurrent vegetative growth with shoots typically having 15-20 leaves providing substantial photosynthetic capacity, continued shoot elongation though slowing from earlier rapid growth, tendril attachment supporting shoot positioning, and balanced vegetative-reproductive development supporting fruit growth without excessive vigor. ||Environmental effects at completion show reduced vulnerability compared to flowering with adverse weather having minimal effect on established berry development at this early stage, though extreme conditions like hail or severe wind potentially causing physical damage, and favorable conditions supporting optimal berry growth rates. ||Temperature at completion optimally 18-28°C supporting rapid berry cell division and growth, with cool conditions below 15°C slowing development and warm conditions above 32°C potentially causing stress effects, and overall temperature accumulation driving developmental rate toward subsequent berry stages. ||Water availability at completion becomes important for berry development with adequate moisture supporting cell division and expansion though berries remain relatively small with modest water demands, and beginning establishment of irrigation management supporting berry development through season. ||Nutrient requirements at completion emphasize nitrogen for protein synthesis supporting rapid cell division in berries and continued vegetative growth, potassium beginning to show importance for berry development affecting later quality outcomes, and balanced nutrition supporting healthy development. ||Disease management at completion transitions from flowering restrictions to active berry protection with fungicide applications resuming for botrytis and powdery mildew control, focus shifting to protecting developing berries from infection, and recognition that flowering-period infections may remain latent requiring continued vigilance. ||Canopy management at completion enables resumption of operations with shoot positioning optimizing berry exposure and air circulation, possible hedging or trimming managing excessive vegetative growth, leaf removal potentially implemented in some systems exposing fruit zone, and overall canopy optimization supporting berry development and disease management. ||Phenological significance of completion includes marking definitive end of BBCH 69 flowering completion stage, transitioning to BBCH 71-79 fruit development stages, establishing reference point for subsequent development predictions, and confirming reproductive phase conclusion enabling developmental focus. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from all flowers opened establishing complete cluster flowering, through anthesis completion confirming reproductive conclusion, to post-anthesis transition marking shift toward fruit development. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day milestone period marking definitive completion, with rapid progression toward fruit development phase. ||Cultivar variation in completion timing shows early varieties completing late June while late varieties complete early-mid July reflecting overall phenological differences, completion clarity with some showing clean definitive completion while others show extended gradual completion, and fruit set outcomes ranging from poor 30-45% in difficult-setting varieties to excellent 60-75% in good-setting types. ||Regional timing shows complete anthesis during late June in warm climates at approximately 1150-1200 growing degree days base 10°C, late June-early July in temperate regions at 1050-1100 GDD, and early-mid July in cool areas at 950-1000 GDD, marking transition to fruit development phase. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing definitive flowering completion enabling management transitions, confirming fruit set outcomes and berry number determining yield potential, marking end of critical weather-vulnerable flowering period reducing risk, providing reference for developmental phase management and timing, and establishing baseline for subsequent phenological predictions through season. ||Research applications include documenting flowering completion timing for phenological studies, analyzing fruit set determinants affecting yield outcomes, evaluating berry development initiation and early growth patterns, quantifying resource allocation transitions from reproduction to development, and assessing management effects on flowering outcomes and early berry development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 388-395 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-305 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "All_Flowers_Opened": {
  "definition": "An All_Flowers_Opened is a Complete_Anthesis comprising the open state of every developmentally capable flower bud within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "complete flower opening | all blooms exposed | full cluster opening | total anthesis expression |+ alle Blüten geöffnet | vollständige Blütenöffnung | komplette Gescheinsblüte | totale Anthesisausprägung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows all flowers opened during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69 on approximately July 1, with 100% viable flowers having completed opening totaling 420-580 flowers per cluster, berry development visible 4-8 mm diameter in 62-74% successfully fertilized flowers, unfertilized flowers showing brown senescence, under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting moderately-to-highly fruitful cultivar completing opening approximately 12-13 days after first flowers opened",
  "editor_note": "All_Flowers_Opened is first of three Complete_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by achievement of complete opening extent within cluster. ||Corresponds to BBCH 69 defining characteristic. ||Enables definitive flower number determination and fruit set calculation. ||Establishes maximum within-cluster developmental heterogeneity. ||Marks opening completion though reproductive function already concluded. ||Brief observation window before developmental progression obscures opening status. || This opening completion milestone occurs during complete anthesis in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically representing brief period when final flowers complete opening while earlier flowers show advanced development or senescence, corresponding to BBCH 69 defining stage. ||Opening completeness shows 100% of viable flowers having achieved open state with reproductive organs exposed or already transitioned to berry development, remaining unopened structures representing aborted or aberrant buds incapable of normal development rather than developmentally delayed viable flowers, and overall cluster showing complete opening extent established during primordium formation previous season. ||Flower distribution at all-open stage shows spatial pattern reflecting developmental gradient with apical flowers predominantly showing berry development 5-10 mm diameter from earliest successful fruit set, middle flowers showing mixed berry development and late senescence, and basal flowers showing recent opening or late senescence depending on final opening timing, creating maximum developmental heterogeneity within cluster. ||Developmental state diversity shows wide range of flower-berry states coexisting including advanced developing berries from early successful fertilization, recently fertilized flowers beginning berry expansion, senescing unfertilized flowers from late opening showing brown discoloration, and overall mixed appearance reflecting complete flowering extent with variable outcomes. ||Opening assessment enables definitive flower number determination with all-open state allowing accurate count of total flowers per cluster, comparison to previous season primordium formation evaluating developmental success from initiation to opening, and establishing denominator for fruit set percentage calculation when combined with final berry count. ||Reproductive opportunity at all-open stage shows effectively terminated pollination capacity with all flowers having passed through receptive period, pollen completely expired with no viable pollen remaining, and reproductive function concluded with established fruit set representing successful reproductions. ||Berry development visibility shows clear fruit structures throughout cluster with successful fruit set berries easily distinguished, berry size ranging 4-10 mm depending on fruit set timing from earliest to latest successful pollinations, and spatial distribution revealing architectural pattern and indicating potential cluster density or disease issues. ||Unfertilized flower presence shows substantial population typically 25-70% flowers failing to set fruit depending on conditions and cultivar, progressive senescence with brown discoloration and tissue deterioration, developing abscission zones preparing for detachment, and creating accumulating fallen flower debris on cluster and ground surfaces. ||Abscission timing shows variable pattern with earliest unfertilized flowers from early anthesis beginning to abscise before all-open achievement, continued abscission of mid-flowering failures proceeding during all-open period, and late unfertilized flowers beginning senescence preparing for subsequent abscission, creating extended flower drop period. ||Cluster architecture expression at all-open stage clearly reveals branching pattern established during previous season primordium formation with primary and secondary branch hierarchy visible, flower-berry spacing reflecting pedicel lengths and cluster compactness, and overall architectural form affecting disease pressure and fruit development conditions. ||Developmental gradient magnitude at all-open shows maximum spread with earliest-set berries potentially 7-12 days ahead of latest-set berries, creating challenge for uniform ripening and harvest timing, and affecting cluster quality homogeneity with mixed maturity levels at harvest. ||Berry cell division stage shows range depending on fruit set timing with earliest berries potentially completing or nearly completing cell division phase by all-open stage, while latest berries just initiating rapid cell proliferation, creating asynchronous berry development affecting final size potential. ||Resource allocation at all-open shows transition largely complete toward fruit development as dominant sink with developing berries consuming substantial photosynthate, vegetative growth continuing though berry demands competing for resources, and reproductive investment effectively ceased with no further flower development. ||Metabolic activity patterns show elevated respiration in rapidly dividing berry cells, declining metabolism in senescing unfertilized flowers, and overall cluster-level metabolism focused on developmental rather than reproductive processes. ||Hormonal environment at all-open shows dominance of auxin from developing berries preventing abscission and promoting growth, gibberellins affecting berry cell division and possibly contributing to seedless berry development in some situations, and ethylene potentially accumulating in unfertilized flowers promoting senescence though not affecting established berry development. ||Environmental conditions at all-open show reduced vulnerability with established berries relatively insensitive to weather variations compared to earlier reproductive sensitivity, though extreme conditions like hail or severe storms potentially causing physical damage to young berries. ||Temperature at all-open optimally 20-28°C supporting rapid berry growth through cell division, with temperature accumulation driving development rate toward subsequent cell expansion phase and eventual maturation. ||Management implications at all-open include confirming complete flowering enabling definitive fruit set assessment, resuming canopy management operations without concern for flower disruption, implementing berry protection strategies for disease management and possible pest control, and planning cluster management including potential thinning operations based on fruit set outcomes. ||Fruit set determination at all-open enables calculation by comparing berry number to total opened flower number, providing definitive percentage for yield prediction, comparison to variety norms assessing reproductive success, and informing crop adjustment decisions if set substantially exceeds or falls short of desired levels. ||The process represents first of three complete anthesis aspects establishing opening extent, followed by anthesis completion confirming reproductive conclusion and post-anthesis transition marking developmental phase. ||Duration represents brief milestone period when final flowers complete opening, with rapid observation window before developmental changes obscure opening completion. ||Cultivar variation in all-open characteristics shows differences in total flower number per cluster from previous season primordium formation, opening uniformity affecting developmental spread at this stage, and fruit set percentage affecting berry number and density outcomes. ||Regional timing shows all flowers opened during late June in warm climates, late June-early July in temperate regions, and early July in cool areas, occurring approximately 10-14 days after first flowers opening depending on flowering duration and environmental conditions. ||Viticultural significance includes defining complete flowering extent enabling accurate fruit set assessment, marking opening completion confirming reproductive opportunity conclusion, establishing maximum within-cluster developmental heterogeneity affecting subsequent development, providing reference for yield predictions based on berry number assessment, and confirming transition to developmental focus in management priorities. ||Research applications include documenting complete flowering extent and timing, analyzing relationships between primordium formation and successful opening, evaluating factors affecting flower opening success and developmental outcomes, quantifying within-cluster developmental gradients affecting ripening uniformity, and assessing implications of opening patterns for cluster quality and harvest management.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 390-393"
},

  "Anthesis_Completion": {
  "definition": "An Anthesis_Completion is a Complete_Anthesis comprising the cluster state with all flowering processes terminated and fruit set established.",
  "alternative_term": "flowering conclusion | reproductive completion | anthesis termination | bloom finish |+ Antheseabschluss | Blütephaseende | reproduktive Vollendung | Blühschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows anthesis completion during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69 on approximately July 2, with all reproductive processes terminated, definitive fruit set of 58-68% establishing 310-420 berries per cluster, visible berry development 5-8 mm diameter throughout cluster, unfertilized flowers showing active abscission, under cool climate conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing flowering 13-15 days after first opening and transitioning definitively to berry development phase",
  "editor_note": "Anthesis_Completion is second of three Complete_Anthesis aspects, distinguished by definitive reproductive cessation confirmation. ||Follows All_Flowers_Opened establishing opening extent. ||Represents conclusive reproductive milestone with fruit set finalized. ||Marks full transition to developmental phase. ||Enables management transitions and yield predictions. ||Critical phenological reference point in annual progression. || This conclusive reproductive milestone occurs during complete anthesis in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 shortly after all flowers opened, representing 1-2 day period confirming reproductive cessation and developmental transition, corresponding to BBCH 69 complete. ||Completion confirmation shows multiple converging indicators including absence of any further flower opening activity with all viable buds having opened, complete cessation of pollen production and availability with all anthers depleted, elimination of stigma receptivity with all stigmas either fertilized or senesced, and overall reproductive function terminated across cluster. ||Fruit set finalization at completion establishes definitive berry number with count of successfully fertilized flowers determining yield potential, typical set percentages 30-75% flowers creating 100-500 berries per cluster depending on cultivar and conditions, and established berry population representing maximum potential fruit load though subsequent berry drop or management thinning may reduce final harvest numbers. ||Berry development focus at completion shows all metabolic and developmental resources directing toward expanding berries with rapid cell division creating berry cell number potential, hormonal signals from developing seeds and pericarp coordinating growth, and berry expansion visible with 0.3-0.6 mm diameter increase daily during this rapid early growth phase. ||Unfertilized flower fate at completion shows senescence universally established with all failed reproductions showing brown discoloration and tissue deterioration, abscission zones fully developed enabling progressive flower drop, and elimination of non-functional reproductive structures cleaning cluster leaving only productive berries. ||Abscission progression at completion shows active flower drop with daily detachment of senescing unfertilized flowers, accumulation of fallen flowers creating visible debris, and progressive cluster thinning as failed reproductions eliminate over subsequent 1-2 weeks. ||Cluster appearance at completion shows definitive developmental state with small green berries dominating visual impression, minimal or moderate brown senescing flowers interspersed depending on fruit set percentage, overall healthy developmental appearance with active growth evident, and clear transition from reproductive to developmental cluster character. ||Developmental phase establishment at completion confirms berry growth as dominant process with cell division phase proceeding rapidly establishing cell number, early berry expansion visible creating recognizable fruit structures, and developmental trajectory established toward véraison and ripening. ||Resource allocation at completion shows complete transition to developmental priorities with photosynthate directing primarily to expanding berries as major sink, vegetative growth continuing consuming moderate resources, and reproductive investment completely ceased with no residual flowering demands. ||Metabolic patterns at completion show elevated respiration in rapidly dividing berry cells supporting high energy demands, declining metabolism in senescing flowers representing resource recovery, and overall cluster-level metabolism focused entirely on developmental processes. ||Hormonal environment at completion shows auxin dominance from developing berries preventing abscission and promoting expansion, gibberellins affecting cell division with peak levels during early berry development, cytokinins supporting cell division in berries and maintaining vegetative growth, and ethylene in senescing flowers promoting abscission but not affecting established berry development. ||Seed development at completion shows embryo and endosperm growth progressing following successful fertilization, seed structures rapidly enlarging within developing berries, and hormonal production from seeds contributing substantially to berry growth signals. ||Environmental effects at completion show minimal reproductive vulnerability with berry development relatively robust compared to earlier flowering sensitivity, though extreme weather potentially affecting vegetative growth supporting berry development or causing physical damage to young berries. ||Temperature at completion optimally 20-28°C supporting rapid berry cell division and growth, with accumulation of growing degree days driving developmental progression toward subsequent expansion and maturation phases. ||Water availability at completion becomes increasingly important for berry development with adequate moisture supporting cell division and early expansion, and initiation of irrigation management if practiced supporting berry development through season. ||Nutrient management at completion emphasizes continued nitrogen for vegetative growth and berry development, increasing potassium importance for berry quality outcomes, adequate calcium for berry structure, and balanced nutrition supporting healthy development. ||Disease management at completion focuses on berry protection with fungicide applications for botrytis and powdery mildew preventing infection during susceptible early development, recognition that latent infections from flowering will remain dormant, and continued vigilance throughout development period. ||Canopy management at completion implements shoot positioning optimizing berry exposure, possible hedging controlling excessive growth, strategic leaf removal in some systems improving cluster microclimate, and overall canopy optimization balancing vegetative growth with fruit development support. ||Phenological significance at completion includes definitively marking BBCH 69 anthesis completion, establishing transition point to BBCH 71-79 fruit development stages, providing reference for subsequent phenological predictions including véraison and harvest timing, and confirming major developmental phase transition in annual cycle. ||Management transition at completion enables full resumption of normal vineyard operations unrestricted by flowering sensitivities, implementation of fruit-focused management strategies, shift in priorities from reproductive to developmental and quality optimization, and planning for season progression toward harvest. ||Yield prediction at completion becomes possible through berry number assessment multiplied by expected final berry weight, comparison to historical norms evaluating season potential, and informing crop management decisions including possible thinning or cluster management. ||The process represents second of three complete anthesis aspects confirming reproductive conclusion, following all flowers opened and preceding post-anthesis transition. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day definitive conclusion period, with clear transition toward developmental phase. ||Cultivar variation in completion characteristics shows timing differences with early varieties completing late June while late types complete early-mid July, completion clarity with some showing definitive conclusion while others show gradual extended completion, and fruit set outcomes ranging widely affecting berry number and density. ||Regional timing shows anthesis completion during late June in warm climates at approximately 1150-1200 growing degree days base 10°C, late June-early July in temperate regions at 1050-1100 GDD, and early-mid July in cool areas at 950-1000 GDD, marking reproductive phase conclusion. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing definitive reproductive conclusion enabling developmental focus, confirming fruit set and berry number determining yield potential, marking end of critical flowering period reducing management constraints, providing reference point for season planning and phenological tracking, and enabling yield prediction and crop management planning. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms coordinating reproductive termination, evaluating factors determining fruit set outcomes, documenting transition from reproductive to developmental physiology, quantifying resource allocation shifts affecting vine function, and assessing phenological transitions in annual developmental progression.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 390-395 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Post_Anthesis_Transition": {
  "definition": "A Post_Anthesis_Transition is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the cluster shift from reproductive to developmental function with berry growth onset and unfertilized flower abscission.",
  "alternative_term": "post-flowering transition | post-bloom phase | developmental phase initiation |+ Nach-Anthese-Übergang | Nachblütephase | Entwicklungsphasestart | post-reproduktive Transition",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows post-anthesis transition during early July Year N+1 transitioning from BBCH 69 toward BBCH 71 over 4-6 days July 3-8, with berry size increasing rapidly from 6-8 mm to 12-16 mm diameter through intense cell division, unfertilized flower abscission completing with cluster cleaning to predominantly berry appearance, resource allocation shifting to 40-55% photosynthate directing to berries, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar establishing developmental phase and berry growth trajectory for season",
  "editor_note": "Post_Anthesis_Transition is third and final Complete_Anthesis aspect, distinguished by physiological reorganization establishing developmental phase dominance. ||Follows All_Flowers_Opened and Anthesis_Completion. ||Marks full transition from reproductive to developmental processes. ||Represents critical adjustment period with berry growth accelerating. ||Enables complete management transitions. ||Establishes developmental trajectory affecting season outcomes. ||Transitions toward Berry_Development major phenological phase. || This critical transitional phase occurs during early July in temperate regions Year N+1 immediately following anthesis completion, typically spanning 3-7 days as physiological adjustments establish developmental phase dominance, corresponding to transition from BBCH 69 toward BBCH 71. ||Physiological reorganization during transition involves metabolic reorientation from reproductive to developmental processes with declining expression of flowering-related genes and increasing expression of fruit development genes, hormonal environment shifting from reproductive coordination to developmental regulation with auxin and gibberellin from berries dominating signaling, resource allocation redirecting from reproductive support to berry growth and vegetative development, and overall vine function transitioning to developmental focus. ||Berry development acceleration marks transition with rapidly increasing growth rates as cell division intensifies, berries doubling or tripling in size over transition period from 5-8 mm to 10-15 mm diameter, visible expansion creating recognizable fruit cluster appearance, and metabolic demands increasing substantially requiring enhanced photosynthetic support. ||Cell division intensity in berries reaches maximum during transition with cells dividing every 12-18 hours throughout pericarp tissues, cell number increase creating size potential for mature berries with cell production phase typically lasting total 2-3 weeks from fruit set, and developmental trajectory establishing toward subsequent cell expansion phase dominating later berry growth. ||Berry structure development during transition establishes anatomical organization with skin layers differentiating including outer epidermis with cuticle, hypodermis providing structural support, inner flesh parenchyma cells undergoing rapid division, vascular tissues developing connecting berry to pedicel, and seed structures developing within locules. ||Seed development progression shows embryo growth continuing with rapidly dividing cells, endosperm expansion providing nutritive support for embryo, integument layers developing into seed coat structure, and overall seed development coordinated with pericarp growth through hormonal signaling. ||Unfertilized flower elimination completes during transition with remaining senescing flowers detaching through completed abscission zones, daily flower drop creating accumulation of fallen flowers that will decay, and cluster cleaning as failed reproductions remove leaving only productive berries creating final cluster appearance. ||Abscission completion timing shows most flower drop occurring during transition week with 70-90% unfertilized flowers detaching, remaining 10-30% potentially persisting longer as dried brown structures before eventual removal, and overall cluster achieving predominantly berry-only appearance by transition conclusion. ||Cluster appearance evolution during transition shows dramatic change from mixed flower-berry state to predominantly berry cluster, green developing berries creating characteristic young fruit appearance, minimal brown debris from remaining senescing flowers, overall healthy productive cluster appearance establishing fruit development stage. ||Resource demand intensification during transition shows substantially increasing requirements with rapidly growing berries consuming 30-50% total photosynthate compared to 10-20% during flowering, vegetative growth continuing requiring 30-40% resources, and balanced allocation supporting both fruit development and vine growth. ||Photosynthetic capacity requirements increase during transition with canopy providing adequate production through 15-20 expanded mature leaves per shoot, shoot growth slowing but continuing with additional leaf expansion, and overall vine photosynthetic output supporting accelerating berry demands. ||Carbon allocation patterns show clear priority to developing berries as primary sink with photosynthate preferentially directing to fruit, vegetative growth continuing but secondary to fruit demands, and reserve accumulation minimal during peak fruit growth period. ||Hormonal regulation during transition shows auxin from developing seeds and pericarp preventing berry abscission and promoting cell division and expansion, gibberellins affecting berry cell division with peak concentrations during early development, cytokinins supporting cell division and delaying senescence, and integrated hormonal environment coordinating developmental processes. ||Nutrient requirements during transition emphasize nitrogen for protein synthesis supporting rapid cell division in berries and continued vegetative growth, potassium increasing importance for berry development affecting later sugar accumulation and quality, calcium essential for cell wall development in expanding berries, and balanced nutrition supporting optimal development. ||Water demand increases during transition with developing berries requiring adequate moisture for cell division and turgor maintenance, shoot growth continuing with water needs, and overall vine water use increasing from flowering levels requiring appropriate irrigation management if practiced. ||Environmental conditions during transition show reduced vulnerability compared to flowering with berry development relatively robust, though extreme heat above 35°C potentially stressing vines and affecting berry development, adequate moisture important for supporting rapid growth, and overall favorable conditions supporting optimal development. ||Temperature during transition optimally 20-28°C supporting rapid berry growth through cell division, with growing degree day accumulation driving development rate toward subsequent stages, and temperature effects on development rate affecting timing of later phenological events. ||Disease management during transition focuses on berry protection with fungicide applications for botrytis and powdery mildew preventing infection during rapid growth phase, recognition that early berry development represents susceptible period for establishing infections, and implementation of protective program supporting fruit quality. ||Pest management during transition includes monitoring for grape berry moth with egg laying on young berries potentially leading to larval damage, leafhoppers reaching peak populations in some regions requiring management, and other pests affecting vegetative or fruit tissues requiring attention. ||Canopy management implementation during transition takes advantage of flowering restrictions lifted enabling shoot positioning optimizing fruit exposure, hedging or trimming controlling excessive vegetative growth, strategic leaf removal improving fruit zone microclimate in some systems, and overall canopy structure optimization balancing vegetative growth with fruit development support. ||Crop load management considerations during transition include assessing fruit set outcomes relative to desired load, possible cluster thinning removing excess clusters if set substantially exceeded targets, leaving adjustment decisions recognizing vine capacity and quality goals, and timing of interventions affecting vine physiological responses. ||Vineyard operations resumption at transition includes normal spray programs without flowering restrictions, mechanical operations including mowing and cultivation, irrigation management establishing patterns for season, and overall return to regular management without bloom-period constraints. ||Phenological progression during transition shows advancement from BBCH 69 anthesis completion toward BBCH 71-73 early berry development stages, with developmental rate dependent on temperature accumulation and environmental conditions, and predictions for subsequent stages including véraison and harvest becoming possible based on early development patterns. ||The process represents third and final complete anthesis aspect marking full transition to developmental phase, following all flowers opened and anthesis completion. ||Duration typically spans 3-7 days representing adjustment period establishing developmental dominance, with warm conditions promoting rapid transition while cool conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation in transition characteristics shows differences in berry growth rates affecting development speed, resource allocation patterns affecting vegetative-reproductive balance, and timing of developmental stages affecting season progression. ||Regional timing shows post-anthesis transition during early July in warm climates, early-mid July in temperate regions, and mid-July in cool areas, occurring immediately following anthesis completion at approximately 1150-1250 growing degree days base 10°C. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing full developmental phase with berry growth as dominant process, enabling complete management transitions unrestricted by flowering sensitivities, marking critical period for establishing berry development trajectory affecting season outcomes, requiring adequate resources and favorable conditions supporting rapid berry growth, and providing reference for development progression and phenological predictions. ||Research applications include analyzing physiological transitions from reproductive to developmental states, evaluating resource allocation dynamics during phase transitions, quantifying berry development patterns during early rapid growth, assessing management effects on development trajectory affecting quality outcomes, and documenting phenological progressions supporting developmental modeling and prediction systems.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 395-410 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 300-315 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Cap_Fall": {
  "definition": "A Cap_Fall is an Anthesis comprising the detachment of the fused petal calyptra as an intact unit from the receptacle base with reproductive organs exposed.",
  "alternative_term": "calyptra fall | cap shedding | petal cap detachment |+ Kalyptrafall | Kappenabwurf | Blütenkappenabtrennung | Kalyptralösung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows cap fall during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65 over 7-9 days, progressing from first calyptra detachment June 4-5 through peak cap shedding June 7-10 with abundant fallen caps accumulating on clusters and ground, completing June 12-13, under warm climate conditions of 22-28°C temperature, 48-65% relative humidity supporting efficient detachment with minimal retention problems, typical of this late-season cultivar showing good cap shedding efficiency enabling 55-68% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Cap_Fall represents distinctive grapevine flower opening mechanism serving as practical observable marker for anthesis. ||Occurs within Flowering corresponding to BBCH 60-65 parallel to Anthesis phases. ||Subdivided into Initial_Cap_Fall marking onset and Mass_Cap_Fall representing peak activity. ||Environmental conditions particularly humidity critically affect detachment efficiency. ||Retention problems cause coulure reducing fruit set. ||Serves as definitive visual reference for flowering timing and progression. ||Easier to observe than detailed reproductive organ status. || This essential reproductive process occurs during flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 5-10 days from first cap detachment through mass cap fall completion as flowers progressively open throughout cluster, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 stages and serving as practical observational marker for anthesis timing. ||Cap structure represents unique grapevine floral morphology with five petals fused at tips forming coherent calyptra cap covering reproductive organs during bud development, cap remaining closed protecting developing stamens and pistil until anthesis initiation, and distinctive pentamerous form visible on detached caps showing five fused petal sections. ||Detachment mechanism involves specialized abscission zone development at junction between calyptra base and receptacle, enzymatic degradation of middle lamella in abscission zone cells creating separation plane through cellulase and pectinase activity, mechanical forces from expanding reproductive organs pushing upward against cap creating pressure, and combined enzymatic and mechanical processes driving physical cap separation and fall. ||Abscission zone anatomy shows specialized cell layers at calyptra-receptacle junction with smaller cells containing dense cytoplasm, thin cell walls particularly in middle lamella region facilitating enzymatic breakdown, vascular tissue disruption at separation plane, and coordinated cellular changes enabling clean cap detachment. ||Cap lifting sequence shows characteristic progression with initial loosening visible as slight gap appearing at base between cap and receptacle, progressive upward movement as abscission proceeds with cap elevating 0.5-2.0 mm above receptacle, continued lifting driven by expanding stamens and pistil pushing against enclosing cap, and final detachment when abscission completes and mechanical disturbance or gravity causes cap fall. ||Detached cap characteristics include intact fused petal structure maintaining pentamerous organization, attachment scar at base showing clean separation plane, occasional retention of stamens or pistil fragments if mechanical separation irregular, and accumulation of fallen caps on cluster surface and ground below creating visible flowering debris. ||Cap fall timing relative to anthesis shows detachment typically initiating anthesis process with reproductive organs exposing immediately upon cap removal, occasional delay of hours between cap loosening and actual fall creating brief transition period, and cap detachment representing definitive marker that flower has entered open reproductive state. ||Reproductive organ exposure following cap fall reveals functional flower structures with five stamens surrounding central pistil positioned for pollination, anthers beginning or completing dehiscence releasing pollen, stigma developing or showing receptivity with papillate surface and exudate production, and overall flower achieving functional reproductive state. ||Environmental effects on cap fall show strong humidity dependence with moderate 45-70% relative humidity optimal for normal cap detachment, high humidity above 75% interfering with abscission through maintained turgor and possibly affecting enzymatic activity delaying or preventing detachment, and low humidity below 40% potentially causing premature desiccation affecting tissues though generally facilitating mechanical separation. ||Temperature affects cap fall with optimal 20-28°C supporting normal abscission processes and flower function, cool conditions below 15°C substantially delaying detachment through slowed enzymatic activity, and warm conditions above 32°C potentially accelerating processes though risking tissue damage from heat stress. ||Rain during cap fall represents serious interference with water physically preventing cap detachment through elevated humidity and mechanical impedance, causing caps to remain attached or detach incompletely affecting reproductive organ exposure, and promoting fungal colonization on wet flower tissues particularly botrytis establishing infections. ||Wind effects show minor positive role with air movement potentially assisting final mechanical cap detachment once abscission completes, and removing detached caps from cluster vicinity reducing accumulated debris, though strong wind may cause damage to newly exposed reproductive structures. ||Diurnal pattern shows most cap fall occurring during morning hours as temperature rises and humidity declines creating favorable conditions, reduced activity during afternoon and evening when humidity may increase, and daily waves of cap fall creating characteristic temporal rhythm during flowering period. ||Cap retention problems occur when abscission fails or proceeds incompletely resulting in caps remaining partially or fully attached preventing normal reproductive organ exposure and function, retention associated with unfavorable environmental conditions particularly high humidity, cool temperatures, or developmental abnormalities, and causing reproductive failure through coulure creating incomplete fruit set. ||Coulure relationship shows cap retention as mechanical cause of poor fruit set with attached caps preventing anther dehiscence eliminating pollen availability, blocking stigma exposure preventing pollination, and causing flower abortion through failed reproduction, creating substantial yield losses particularly in susceptible cultivars or unfavorable flowering conditions. ||Observational utility of cap fall includes serving as definitive visual marker for anthesis onset enabling accurate flowering date determination, providing clear indication of flowering progression through cluster as cap fall advances spatially, and allowing assessment of flowering uniformity and potential problems through observation of retention patterns. ||Cap accumulation patterns create visible evidence of flowering with detached caps accumulating on cluster surfaces showing recent opening activity, fallen caps on ground below vines indicating flowering extent and timing, and progressive accumulation documenting flowering progression over time. ||Flowering intensity assessment uses cap fall as indicator with heavy cap fall indicating intense flowering activity, sparse cap fall suggesting limited or irregular flowering, and spatial patterns revealing developmental gradients within clusters or across vineyard. ||Developmental gradient visualization through cap fall shows temporal sequence with apical regions showing earlier cap fall from earliest-maturing flowers, middle regions showing progressive cap fall during peak activity, and basal regions showing latest cap fall reflecting developmental delays. ||The process shows two major phases progressing from initial cap fall marking anthesis onset with sporadic early detachments, through mass cap fall representing peak flowering with widespread simultaneous detachment. ||Duration typically spans 5-10 days from first cap detachment through completion depending on flowering synchrony and environmental conditions, with warm stable conditions promoting compressed 5-7 day period while variable conditions extend period to 10-14 days. ||Cultivar variation appears in cap detachment efficiency with some varieties showing clean complete detachment supporting high fruit set while others show frequent retention problems causing coulure, cap fall timing relative to overall phenology, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting detachment success. ||Regional timing shows cap fall during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with anthesis period and serving as practical flowering marker. ||Viticultural significance includes providing clear visual marker for flowering timing and progression enabling management scheduling, indicating anthesis onset and intensity supporting yield prediction, revealing retention problems indicating potential fruit set failures requiring attention, and serving as practical observational reference more easily assessed than detailed reproductive organ examination. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering timing using cap fall as objective marker, analyzing environmental effects on abscission processes affecting flowering success, evaluating cultivar differences in cap detachment efficiency affecting reproductive reliability, quantifying relationships between cap fall patterns and fruit set outcomes, and assessing mechanisms coordinating cap abscission with reproductive organ maturation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-375 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 275-285 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Initial_Cap_Fall": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Cap_Fall is a Cap_Fall comprising the calyptra detachment of the first flowers within the cluster with reproductive organs exposed.",
  "alternative_term": "early cap fall | first cap shedding | initial calyptra detachment | flowering onset |+ früher Kappenfall | initiale Kalyptralösung | Blühbeginn | erste Blütenkappentrennung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows initial cap fall during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 61-62 over 2-3 days June 3-5, with 10-18% flowers predominantly in apical positions shedding calyptra caps, exposing reproductive organs and marking flowering onset, under cool maritime conditions of 18-22°C temperature, 60-72% relative humidity, typical of this early-bursting cultivar initiating flowering before peak bloom June 6-9",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Cap_Fall is first major Cap_Fall phase distinguished by flowering onset with early sporadic cap detachment. ||Corresponds to BBCH 61-62 parallel to Early_Anthesis. ||Subdivided into First_Calyptra_Detachment marking definitive onset and Early_Cap_Shedding expanding activity. ||Establishes temporal pattern for subsequent mass fall. ||Highly sensitive to environmental conditions particularly humidity. ||Serves as practical observable flowering initiation marker. ||Critical for phenological tracking and management timing. || This critical initiation phase occurs during early flowering in early June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 2-3 days as earliest-maturing flowers predominantly in apical cluster positions complete cap detachment, corresponding to BBCH 61-62 stages with 10-20% flowers showing cap fall. ||Cap detachment initiation in earliest flowers shows characteristic sequence with abscission zone activation in calyptra base beginning enzymatic wall degradation, progressive calyptra loosening creating visible gap at base, upward cap movement driven by expanding reproductive organs, and final detachment with cap falling away from flower through mechanical disturbance or gravity. ||First calyptra detachment typically occurs in apical cluster positions reflecting earliest primordium formation and most advanced development from previous season, with 5-10% flowers showing cap fall on first day establishing anthesis onset, and progressive increase to 15-25% by end of initial phase expanding flowering across cluster. ||Detached cap appearance shows intact fused petal structure maintaining pentamerous organization with five coherent petal sections visible, clean separation scar at base indicating completed abscission, occasional adherence to adjacent structures requiring additional mechanical force for complete removal, and accumulation on cluster surface providing visible evidence of flowering initiation. ||Flower exposure following cap detachment reveals functional reproductive structures with stamens and pistil newly exposed showing pristine fresh appearance, anthers beginning color change from green toward yellow-brown indicating approaching maturity, stigma surface developing papillate cells and initial exudate production, and overall flower transitioning to open reproductive state. ||Temporal pattern establishment during initial phase shows characteristic basipetal-acropetal gradient with apical flowers showing earliest cap fall, progressive extension to middle regions over subsequent days, and basal regions showing delayed cap fall establishing developmental sequence. ||Cap fall frequency during initial phase shows sporadic irregular pattern with individual flowers completing detachment asynchronously, daily increment of 3-8% additional flowers shedding caps, and progressive acceleration toward mass cap fall during subsequent peak period. ||Environmental sensitivity during initial phase shows strong dependence on conditions with favorable warm dry weather promoting efficient cap detachment supporting early flowering onset, unfavorable cool humid conditions delaying detachment potentially causing irregular flowering initiation, and optimal 20-26°C temperature with 50-70% humidity supporting normal cap fall progression. ||Humidity effects on initial cap fall show critical importance with moderate levels facilitating abscission through appropriate tissue hydration and enzymatic activity, high humidity above 75% substantially interfering with detachment through maintained cap turgor preventing lifting and possibly inhibiting enzymatic processes, and resulting cap retention delaying flowering and potentially causing coulure. ||Temperature during initial phase affects detachment rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid normal abscission, cool conditions below 18°C substantially slowing enzymatic activity delaying cap fall and flowering onset, and warm conditions above 30°C potentially accelerating processes though risking tissue stress. ||Cap retention problems may appear during initial phase with some flowers showing incomplete abscission leaving caps partially attached, problematic retention indicating unfavorable conditions or developmental abnormalities, and early retention problems potentially portending difficulties during peak flowering affecting ultimate fruit set. ||Abscission zone development during initial phase shows enzymatic activity concentrated in specialized cells at calyptra-receptacle junction, cellulase and pectinase enzymes degrading middle lamella polysaccharides creating separation plane, progressive wall breakdown enabling cap loosening and detachment, and hormonal regulation possibly involving ethylene promoting abscission though mechanisms incompletely understood. ||Mechanical forces contributing to detachment include expanding stamens pushing against enclosing calyptra creating upward pressure, pistil elongation adding to mechanical tension, turgor changes potentially affecting cap rigidity and separation forces, and external forces from wind or physical contact triggering final detachment once abscission completes. ||Observational characteristics enable identification of initial cap fall through fresh appearance of detached caps showing recent separation, spatial concentration in apical cluster positions, small proportion 10-20% flowers showing cap fall distinguishing from peak period, and clear visual evidence of flowering initiation. ||Phenological significance includes marking definitive flowering onset establishing BBCH 61 stage, providing practical observable reference for flowering date determination easier than detailed reproductive organ examination, and establishing baseline for predicting subsequent peak flowering timing typically 2-4 days later. ||Management implications include confirming flowering initiation requiring weather monitoring and preparation for critical bloom period, final opportunity for pre-bloom disease management as restrictions begin with significant flowering, and indicating imminent peak flowering requiring operational readiness. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from first calyptra detachment establishing definitive flowering onset, through early cap shedding expanding activity across cluster. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing initiation period before peak cap fall, with warm favorable conditions promoting rapid progression while cool variable conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation in initial cap fall shows differences in timing with early varieties showing late May-early June onset while late types show mid-late June timing, detachment efficiency with some varieties showing clean early cap fall while others show retention problems, and proportion of flowers involved in initial phase affecting subsequent mass fall intensity. ||Regional timing shows initial cap fall during late May-early June in warm climates at approximately 950-1050 growing degree days base 10°C, early-mid June in temperate regions at 850-950 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 750-850 GDD, marking flowering onset across regions. ||Viticultural significance includes providing clear practical marker for flowering onset enabling accurate phenological tracking, indicating beginning of critical weather-sensitive period requiring monitoring, establishing temporal reference for subsequent flowering progression, and revealing early problems with cap retention indicating potential fruit set difficulties. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering onset timing using cap fall as objective marker, analyzing environmental triggers of cap abscission affecting flowering initiation, evaluating cultivar differences in cap detachment efficiency affecting reproductive success, quantifying relationships between initial cap fall patterns and subsequent flowering progression, and assessing abscission mechanisms coordinating calyptra detachment with reproductive organ maturation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-368 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "First_Calyptra_Detachment": {
  "definition": "A First_Calyptra_Detachment is an Initial_Cap_Fall comprising the abscission and shedding of the petal cap from the earliest-maturing flower within the cluster with reproductive organs exposed.",
  "alternative_term": "first cap fall | flowering onset moment | initial cap detachment | first bloom |+ erste Kalyptralösung | Blühzeitpunkt | initiale Kappentrennung | Erstblüte",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows first calyptra detachment on June 3 Year N+1 at BBCH 61, with single flower in apical cluster position completing cap shedding during morning hours after accumulating 890-920 growing degree days base 10°C, exposing fresh reproductive organs under continental conditions of 19-23°C temperature, 58-68% relative humidity, marking definitive flowering onset for this early-to-mid season cultivar approximately 12 days before complete anthesis",
  "editor_note": "First_Calyptra_Detachment is first aspect of Initial_Cap_Fall, distinguished by threshold flowering event with earliest cap detachment. ||Corresponds to BBCH 61 defining characteristic. ||Represents precise phenological marker for flowering date. ||Brief threshold moment occurring over hours to single day. ||Critical for phenological records and management transitions. ||Detection requires careful observation. ||Establishes reference for subsequent flowering progression. || This critical milestone event occurs during early flowering in early June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically representing single moment or brief hours when first individual flower achieves cap detachment, corresponding to BBCH 61 defining characteristic. ||Detachment completion in first flower shows characteristic final sequence with abscission zone fully degraded creating complete separation plane, calyptra lifted 1-2 mm above receptacle by expanding reproductive organs, mechanical disturbance from wind, turgor change, or natural movement triggering final detachment, and cap falling away from flower exposing stamens and pistil. ||First flower location typically in apical cluster position reflecting earliest primordium formation previous season and most advanced development, occasionally in middle regions if developmental variation creates alternative earliest-maturing flower, and spatial positioning providing indicator of developmental patterns within cluster. ||Observational requirements for detecting first detachment include careful cluster inspection as single cap fall may be inconspicuous, timing of observations with morning assessment most likely to detect fresh overnight detachment, and distinction between true first detachment versus cap loosening without complete separation. ||Detached cap characteristics include fresh appearance with green or yellow-green color indicating recent separation, intact fused petal structure showing pentamerous organization, moist attachment scar suggesting recent abscission completion, and positioning on cluster surface or recently fallen to ground below. ||Exposed flower appearance at first detachment shows newly revealed reproductive organs with pristine fresh condition, stamens positioned around central pistil showing beginning maturity, anthers showing early color transition from green toward yellow indicating approaching dehiscence, and stigma showing developing receptivity with papillate surface beginning exudate production. ||Environmental conditions at first detachment typically favorable for abscission with temperature 18-26°C supporting enzymatic activity and organ function, humidity 50-70% facilitating cap loosening without retention, and overall weather enabling normal flowering initiation establishing pattern for subsequent detachments. ||Timing predictability shows first detachment occurring at relatively consistent thermal time accumulation with typical range 900-1100 growing degree days base 10°C depending on cultivar and regional climate, though exact timing affected by short-term weather affecting final abscission completion. ||Phenological significance includes defining flowering date with first calyptra detachment establishing BBCH 61 stage, providing precise reference for phenological records and climate studies, and establishing baseline for heat summation calculations and subsequent stage predictions. ||Developmental implications show first detachment confirming successful completion of previous season primordium formation and current season inflorescence development, indicating reproductive readiness in earliest-maturing flowers, and marking transition from pre-bloom to bloom state requiring management adjustments. ||Observational challenges include detection difficulty with single inconspicuous event requiring vigilant monitoring, potential confusion between cap loosening and actual detachment requiring verification of complete separation, and timing uncertainty as exact moment may occur between observations requiring retrospective assessment. ||Documentation importance emphasizes recording precise first detachment date as critical phenological marker for vineyard records, comparison across seasons revealing phenological trends and climate effects, and standardization of observation protocols ensuring data consistency. ||Weather window implications show that conditions at first detachment indicate likely conditions during subsequent mass flowering, with favorable weather at onset suggesting good flowering potential while unfavorable conditions portending potential problems. ||Management implications include confirming flowering onset requiring final preparations for bloom period, cessation of disruptive canopy operations to avoid flower damage, and intensification of weather monitoring as critical reproductive period begins. ||Subsequent progression from first detachment shows rapid acceleration with additional flowers detaching within hours to days, progressive spatial expansion from initial location toward broader cluster involvement, and transition toward mass cap fall during peak anthesis typically 2-4 days after first detachment. ||Cultivar differences in first detachment timing show early varieties achieving onset late May-early June while late types show mid-late June timing reflecting overall phenological variation, with timing affected by accumulated thermal units, chilling satisfaction, and cultivar-specific heat requirements. ||Regional variation shows first calyptra detachment during late May-early June in warm climates with heat accumulation reaching thresholds earlier, early-mid June in temperate regions with moderate heat accumulation, and mid-late June in cool areas requiring longer periods for thermal unit accumulation. ||Climate effects on timing include warmer years showing earlier first detachment reflecting accelerated heat accumulation, cooler years showing delayed timing, and interannual variation in timing reflecting climate variability affecting viticultural calendars and management scheduling. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering phenology using first detachment as objective marker, analyzing environmental controls of flowering onset including thermal time requirements and short-term weather effects, evaluating genetic variation in flowering timing affecting adaptation and regional suitability, developing phenological models predicting flowering dates from climate variables, and assessing climate change impacts on flowering timing across regions and seasons. ||The process represents first aspect of initial cap fall marking definitive flowering onset, followed by early cap shedding expanding activity. ||Duration represents threshold moment occurring over hours to single day as first flower completes detachment. ||Cultivar variation in first detachment characteristics includes timing differences reflecting overall phenology, flower position showing cultivar-specific developmental patterns, and detachment efficiency indicating genetic differences in abscission processes. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing definitive flowering date for phenological records, providing practical observable marker for bloom onset enabling management transitions, indicating beginning of weather-sensitive period requiring monitoring, and serving as reference for predicting subsequent flowering progression and developmental timing through season. ||Research applications include documenting flowering phenology with precision, analyzing mechanisms triggering abscission onset, evaluating cultivar and environmental effects on flowering timing, developing predictive models for flowering dates supporting management planning, and assessing climate change effects on phenological timing affecting viticultural adaptation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 360-365"
},

  "Early_Cap_Shedding": {
  "definition": "An Early_Cap_Shedding is a Cap_Fall comprising the progressive calyptra detachment of flowers within the cluster following first detachment.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive cap fall | expanding cap shedding | early calyptra detachment phase |+ progressive Kappenabtrennung | expandierender Kalyptrafall | frühe Abwurfphase | Kappenfall-Ausbreitung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows early cap shedding during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 61-62 over 1-2 days June 5-6, with cap fall expanding from initial 6-8% to 18-24% flowers showing detachment predominantly in apical and middle cluster regions, accelerating toward mass fall, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 23-27°C temperature, 52-66% relative humidity supporting efficient progression, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar showing rapid flowering expansion",
  "editor_note": "Early_Cap_Shedding is second aspect of Initial_Cap_Fall, distinguished by progressive expansion from first detachment toward broader cluster involvement. ||Follows First_Calyptra_Detachment. ||Represents acceleration phase preparing for mass fall. ||Duration 1-2 days showing increasing frequency. ||Environmental conditions particularly humidity critically affect progression efficiency. ||Retention problems may become evident indicating potential fruit set issues. ||Provides indication of flowering intensity and coordination. || This expansion phase occurs during early flowering in early June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 1-2 days as cap fall frequency increases from initial 5-10% to 15-25% flowers showing detachment, corresponding to BBCH 61-62 progressive stages. ||Shedding expansion pattern shows characteristic acceleration with increasing daily detachment frequency from sporadic first event to regular progressive cap fall, spatial extension from initial apical location toward middle cluster regions as additional flowers reach maturity, and temporal intensification preparing transition toward mass cap fall period. ||Cap fall frequency progression shows daily increase with first day showing 5-10% total flowers with detached caps, second day showing 12-18% accumulated detachment representing 5-10% additional daily increment, and accelerating pattern indicating approaching peak flowering. ||Spatial progression shows basipetal-acropetal pattern with cap fall extending from apical initiation site toward middle cluster regions reflecting developmental gradient, occasional scattered detachment in middle regions from locally advanced flowers, and overall expansion creating broadening cap fall zone within cluster. ||Detached cap accumulation creates increasingly visible evidence of flowering with fresh caps showing recent separation accumulating on cluster surfaces, fallen caps on ground below clusters indicating flowering extent, and progressive accumulation documenting expansion of flowering activity. ||Flower exposure expansion reveals increasing numbers of opened flowers throughout cluster with newly exposed reproductive organs showing fresh pristine appearance, spatial distribution reflecting cap fall progression pattern, and overall transition from predominantly closed-bud cluster toward mixed open-closed appearance. ||Environmental effects on shedding progression show continued humidity sensitivity with favorable moderate 50-70% levels supporting efficient detachment expansion, high humidity above 75% potentially slowing progression through interference with abscission processes, and optimal temperature 20-26°C maintaining enzymatic activity supporting accelerating cap fall. ||Temperature during early shedding affects progression rate with warm conditions 24-28°C promoting rapid acceleration toward mass fall potentially compressing early phase to 1 day, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing progression potentially extending phase to 2-3 days, and overall thermal accumulation driving developmental rate. ||Humidity during early shedding critically affects efficiency with moderate levels enabling normal progression, elevated humidity potentially causing retention problems in susceptible flowers delaying progression, and optimal conditions minimizing retention supporting smooth acceleration toward peak. ||Weather stability during early shedding affects uniformity with consistent favorable conditions promoting coordinated progression creating compressed flowering period, variable conditions causing irregular progression potentially extending flowering and reducing synchrony. ||Cap retention problems may become evident during early shedding with some flowers showing incomplete abscission or persistent caps, retention frequency indicating likely problems during peak flowering, and early identification enabling assessment of potential fruit set difficulties. ||Abscission zone activity intensifies during early shedding with enzymatic processes accelerating in progressively more flowers, coordinated activation across multiple flowers creating expanding detachment zone, and overall abscission activity transitioning from sporadic individual events toward mass synchronized processes. ||Developmental readiness indicators show flowers completing maturation preparing for cap shedding through calyptra loosening visible as slight gaps at base, organ expansion creating mechanical pressure against caps, and progressive physiological preparation for reproductive function. ||Observational characteristics enable recognition of early shedding through increasing cap fall frequency distinguishing from single first event, spatial expansion showing broader cluster involvement, visible cap accumulation documenting flowering progression, and overall transition from sparse to moderate cap fall activity. ||Phenological progression shows early shedding representing intermediate stage between flowering initiation BBCH 61 and peak flowering BBCH 63-65, with rapid progression typically requiring 1-2 days, and clear trajectory toward mass cap fall representing peak reproductive activity. ||Management implications include confirming flowering expansion indicating approaching peak requiring readiness for critical bloom period, continued weather monitoring as sensitivity intensifies with expanding reproductive activity, and final preparations for bloom-period management including disease protection strategies. ||Flowering intensity assessment uses early shedding pattern as indicator with rapid acceleration suggesting compressed intensive flowering supporting high fruit set potential, slow irregular progression indicating extended flowering potentially affecting fruit set uniformity. ||Cultivar differences in early shedding show variation in acceleration rate with some varieties showing rapid 1-day progression while others show gradual 2-3 day expansion, spatial pattern reflecting cultivar-specific developmental uniformity, and overall progression characteristics affecting flowering duration and synchrony. ||The process represents second aspect of initial cap fall focusing on expansion from first event toward mass activity, following first calyptra detachment. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days representing acceleration phase, with warm favorable conditions promoting rapid progression while variable conditions may extend period. ||Regional timing shows early cap shedding during early June in warm climates 1-2 days after first detachment, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, occurring during initial flowering expansion. ||Viticultural significance includes documenting flowering expansion confirming progression toward peak bloom, providing indication of flowering intensity and potential uniformity affecting fruit set predictions, revealing early retention problems indicating potential coulure issues, and establishing temporal pattern for subsequent mass cap fall. ||Research applications include analyzing progression dynamics from initiation to mass flowering, evaluating environmental effects on cap fall acceleration affecting flowering patterns, quantifying cultivar differences in shedding progression affecting flowering characteristics, assessing relationships between early shedding patterns and ultimate fruit set outcomes, and developing models predicting peak flowering timing from early shedding observations.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 365-370 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Mass_Cap_Fall": {
  "definition": "A Mass_Cap_Fall is a Cap_Fall comprising the simultaneous calyptra detachment of the maximum proportion of flowers within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "peak cap fall | maximum cap shedding | full bloom calyptra fall | mass calyptra detachment |+ Massen-Kappenfall | maximale Kalyptralösung | Hauptblüten-Kappenabwurf | synchroner Massenabfall",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows mass cap fall during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 over 2-3 days June 9-11, with 55-68% flowers showing cap detachment creating abundant fallen cap accumulation, intensive synchronized shedding visible throughout clusters, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature, 54-68% relative humidity, stable weather supporting efficient mass detachment enabling 54-64% fruit set, typical of this mid-season cultivar during peak flowering determining season yield",
  "editor_note": "Mass_Cap_Fall is second major Cap_Fall phase distinguished by maximum synchronized calyptra detachment during peak flowering. ||Corresponds to BBCH 63-65 parallel to Peak_Anthesis. ||Subdivided into Peak_Cap_Shedding_Period and Synchronous_Cap_Fall. ||Represents most critical 2-3 days determining 60-80% fruit set and yield. ||Environmental conditions particularly weather critically affect success. ||Provides definitive visual marker for flowering peak. ||Easily observable practical reference for phenological tracking and management. || This culminating shedding phase occurs during peak flowering in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 2-3 days as 40-70% flowers achieve cap detachment creating intensive synchronized shedding activity, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 stages parallel to peak anthesis. ||Shedding intensity during mass fall shows maximum levels with 40-70% total flowers showing detached caps creating densely opened cluster appearance, daily addition of 15-25% new cap detachments maintaining high activity, and peak shedding rate representing culmination of flowering progression from initial sporadic activity. ||Spatial distribution during mass fall shows cap detachment throughout cluster with apical regions showing 70-90% flowers with shed caps from earliest opening, middle regions showing 60-80% detachment representing peak activity zone, and basal regions showing 40-60% shedding as activity extends throughout cluster. ||Detached cap accumulation reaches maximum during mass fall with abundant fresh caps on cluster surfaces creating characteristic debris layer, continuous cap fall visible throughout day under favorable conditions, and substantial fallen cap accumulation on ground below vines documenting flowering intensity. ||Flower exposure at mass fall shows majority of reproductive organs revealed throughout cluster creating dense array of opened flowers, freshly exposed stamens and pistils distributed across cluster providing reproductive capacity, and overall appearance of full bloom with abundant functional flowers. ||Visual appearance at mass fall shows distinctive flowering display with numerous exposed yellow-brown anthers and green-white stigmas creating characteristic coloration, remaining green calyptra caps on 30-60% unopened buds providing contrast, abundant detached caps visible on cluster and ground surfaces, and overall appearance of intense reproductive activity. ||Synchronous shedding during mass fall creates concentrated cap detachment events with multiple flowers throughout cluster completing abscission simultaneously within hours, coordinated shedding creating visible cap fall waves particularly during favorable morning conditions, and synchronized activity supporting uniform flowering and fruit set potential. ||Environmental conditions during mass fall critically determine success with optimal 24-30°C temperature supporting maximum abscission activity and reproductive organ function, moderate 50-65% humidity facilitating cap detachment without retention or excessive desiccation, stable favorable weather enabling sustained intensive shedding throughout 2-3 day period. ||Temperature effects on mass fall show optimal warm conditions promoting rapid synchronized detachment completing mass phase within 2-3 days, cool conditions below 20°C slowing activity potentially extending period to 4-5 days, and warm conditions above 32°C potentially causing stress though generally facilitating mechanical separation. ||Humidity effects show critical importance with moderate levels supporting efficient mass detachment, high humidity above 70% potentially causing retention problems in susceptible flowers reducing mass fall intensity, and low humidity below 45% potentially causing tissue desiccation though facilitating mechanical cap removal. ||Rain during mass fall represents catastrophic interference with water preventing cap detachment through elevated humidity and physical impedance, substantially reducing shedding activity potentially limiting flowering to only pre-rain activity, and severely compromising fruit set through disrupted flowering during critical peak period. ||Wind effects show dual character with light-moderate wind 5-15 km per hour facilitating cap dispersal and enhancing visible fall activity, removing detached caps from cluster surfaces reducing accumulation, though excessive wind above 25 km per hour potentially causing physical damage to newly exposed reproductive structures. ||Diurnal pattern during mass fall shows characteristic rhythm with maximum shedding activity during morning hours 8am-12pm as temperature rises and humidity declines, reduced activity during afternoon hours as conditions may become less favorable, and daily waves creating repeated intensive shedding periods throughout mass fall phase. ||Cap retention problems during mass fall affect fruit set potential with flowers showing incomplete or failed abscission unable to expose reproductive organs preventing pollination, retention frequency during peak period strongly affecting ultimate fruit set percentage, and visible retention assessment enabling early fruit set predictions. ||Abscission zone activity reaches maximum during mass fall with coordinated enzymatic processes across numerous flowers, synchronized cell wall degradation creating separation planes, and hormonal signals possibly coordinating mass shedding though mechanisms incompletely understood. ||Pollination opportunity during mass fall reaches optimum with widespread flower exposure providing abundant receptive stigmas, maximum pollen availability from numerous dehiscing anthers, and favorable spatial arrangement supporting efficient pollination creating high fruit set potential. ||Fruit set determination during mass fall shows majority 60-80% final berry number established during this critical 2-3 day period, with successful pollinations during mass fall phase contributing disproportionately to ultimate yield, making mass fall conditions dominant influence on seasonal productivity. ||Observational characteristics enable definitive mass fall identification through dense cap accumulation on clusters and ground creating obvious visual evidence, numerous simultaneously opened flowers throughout cluster showing characteristic full bloom appearance, and intensive ongoing shedding activity visible during observation periods. ||Phenological significance includes defining peak flowering period establishing BBCH 63-65 stages, providing definitive visual marker for full bloom easier to assess than detailed reproductive organ examination, and serving as critical reference for subsequent developmental predictions. ||Management implications during mass fall include maintaining minimal vineyard disturbance with all operations suspended during critical period, intensified weather monitoring with forecasts critically important, and recognition that mass fall outcomes largely determine seasonal yield making this 2-3 day period most important of entire season. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from peak cap shedding period establishing maximum intensity, through synchronous cap fall emphasizing coordinated simultaneous activity. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing peak flowering period, with warm stable conditions producing compressed 2-day peak while variable conditions may extend to 3-4 days. ||Cultivar variation in mass fall shows differences in intensity with some varieties showing very high 60-75% simultaneous shedding while others show moderate 45-60% peak, duration affecting flowering compression or extension, and retention susceptibility affecting fruit set outcomes. ||Regional timing shows mass cap fall during early-mid June in warm climates at approximately 1050-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 950-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 850-900 GDD, marking peak flowering across regions. ||Viticultural significance includes representing most critical period for yield determination with mass fall outcomes dominating fruit set, providing definitive visual reference for flowering peak enabling precise phenological tracking, serving as practical marker more readily observable than detailed reproductive status, and illustrating extreme importance of favorable conditions during brief 2-3 day window determining season productivity. ||Research applications include analyzing environmental controls of synchronized shedding, quantifying relationships between mass fall intensity and fruit set outcomes, evaluating cultivar differences in shedding coordination affecting flowering characteristics, developing observation protocols using mass fall as practical marker, and assessing climate change impacts on peak flowering conditions affecting productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 370-380 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Peak_Cap_Shedding_Period": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Cap_Shedding_Period is a Mass_Cap_Fall comprising the simultaneous calyptra detachment of the greatest absolute number and proportion of flowers within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "full bloom period | maximum cap detachment phase | peak calyptra fall |+ Vollblüteperiode | maximale Abwurfphase | Hauptkappenfall-Stadium | Spitzen-Kalyptralösung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows peak cap shedding period on June 9-10 Year N+1 at BBCH 65, with 60-72% flowers showing detached caps, intensive visible cap fall during morning hours creating abundant accumulation, under optimal warm climate conditions of 25-29°C temperature, 52-64% relative humidity, stable weather, typical of this late-season cultivar reaching flowering peak approximately 5-6 days after first cap detachment and determining 45-55% final berry number during this critical 1-2 day window",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Cap_Shedding_Period is first aspect of Mass_Cap_Fall, distinguished by maximum calyptra detachment intensity. ||Corresponds to BBCH 65 full bloom defining characteristic. ||Represents culminating 1-2 day period of flowering activity. ||Provides unmistakable visual marker for flowering peak. ||Most critical period for yield determination. ||Extreme weather vulnerability requiring optimal conditions. ||Easily observable practical reference for phenological tracking. || This culminating intensity phase occurs during peak flowering in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically representing 1-2 day period when 50-75% flowers show detached caps with maximum daily shedding rate, corresponding to BBCH 65 defining full bloom stage. ||Shedding intensity characteristics show maximum daily detachment rate with 15-25% additional flowers shedding caps per day during peak, cumulative effect of sustained shedding over previous days creating high proportion of simultaneously shed caps, and peak representing balance point between continuing shedding from newly maturing flowers and declining activity as most flowers have completed detachment. ||Cap accumulation at peak shows maximum density with thick layer of fresh detached caps covering cluster surfaces creating distinctive appearance, continuous cap fall visible throughout observation period under favorable conditions, and substantial accumulation on ground below vines creating visible carpet of fallen caps documenting flowering intensity. ||Visual appearance at peak shows definitive full bloom display with dense array of opened flowers exposing yellow-brown anthers and green-white stigmas throughout cluster, contrasting with 25-40% remaining green calyptra caps on unopened buds, abundant visible cap fall activity during favorable morning hours, and overall appearance of maximum reproductive activity. ||Flower exposure distribution at peak shows opened flowers throughout cluster creating maximum reproductive surface area with apical regions showing 80-95% flowers with shed caps from earliest opening, middle regions showing 70-85% detachment representing highest density of recently opened flowers, and basal regions showing 50-70% shedding as activity extends to latest-maturing positions. ||Synchronized shedding intensity reaches maximum at peak with numerous flowers throughout cluster completing abscission within same time period creating visible simultaneous cap fall, coordinated detachment suggesting possible developmental or environmental synchronization mechanisms, and concentrated activity creating optimal reproductive conditions. ||Environmental conditions at peak typically favorable with temperature 24-30°C supporting maximum abscission and reproductive activity, humidity 50-65% facilitating efficient detachment, and stable warm dry weather enabling sustained intensive shedding throughout 1-2 day peak period. ||Diurnal pattern at peak shows most intense shedding during morning hours 8am-11am as temperature rises above threshold and humidity declines to favorable levels, creating daily maximum activity period visible as intensive cap fall, and repeated daily peaks throughout peak period maintaining high overall shedding intensity. ||Cap fall visibility at peak enables easy observation with abundant falling caps creating obvious visual display, sound of caps hitting cluster surfaces or ground occasionally audible during intensive shedding, and overall sensory evidence of flowering activity at maximum. ||Pollen cloud formation during peak creates characteristic visual phenomenon with pollen released from numerous anthers creating visible haze surrounding flowering clusters under dry windy conditions, particularly evident during morning hours coinciding with peak cap shedding, and providing additional visual confirmation of maximum flowering activity. ||Pollination opportunity at peak reaches absolute optimum with maximum flower exposure providing widespread reproductive organ availability, peak pollen production from numerous dehiscing anthers, and optimal spatial conditions for efficient pollination supporting maximum fruit set potential. ||Fruit set determination at peak shows that outcomes during this critical 1-2 day period dominate final berry number with 40-60% final fruit set established during peak shedding representing largest single contribution, making peak period conditions most important determinant of seasonal yield. ||Weather vulnerability at peak reaches absolute maximum with reproductive success extremely sensitive to conditions, favorable stable conditions supporting high fruit set 60-75% in good-setting cultivars, while adverse weather particularly rain causing catastrophic fruit set failure 10-30%, demonstrating extreme importance of favorable conditions during brief peak window. ||Observational assessment at peak enables confident full bloom determination with unmistakable visual evidence of maximum flowering including dense cap accumulation, numerous opened flowers throughout clusters, visible ongoing shedding activity, and overall appearance meeting BBCH 65 full bloom definition. ||Phenological documentation at peak includes recording peak cap shedding date as critical marker defining BBCH 65 full bloom stage, providing precise reference for phenological records and subsequent stage predictions, and serving as definitive flowering peak marker for management planning and climate studies. ||Management implications at peak include absolute restriction on vineyard operations with any canopy disturbance potentially disrupting critical pollination processes, weather monitoring at maximum intensity with short-term forecasts critically important, and recognition that peak period represents single most important 1-2 day window of entire growing season for yield determination. ||Cultivar identification assistance from peak characteristics may include distinctive cap accumulation patterns, shedding intensity and duration, and visual appearance characteristics varying among varieties providing observational clues. ||The process represents first aspect of mass cap fall focusing on maximum intensity, followed by synchronous cap fall emphasizing coordination. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day maximum intensity period, with warm stable conditions producing sharp intense peak while variable conditions may broaden or reduce peak intensity. ||Cultivar variation in peak intensity shows some varieties reaching very high 65-80% simultaneous shedding creating intense sharp peak, while others show moderate 50-65% creating broader flatter peak, affecting flowering coordination and potential fruit set uniformity. ||Regional timing shows peak cap shedding period during early-mid June in warm climates at approximately 1050-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 950-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 850-900 GDD, defining flowering peak across regions. ||Viticultural significance includes defining definitive flowering peak establishing BBCH 65 full bloom, representing single most critical day or two determining majority of season yield, providing unmistakable visual marker for flowering peak easily assessed without detailed examination, and illustrating extreme vulnerability requiring optimal conditions during brief window. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering peak timing for phenology studies, analyzing environmental effects on peak intensity affecting reproductive outcomes, quantifying relationships between peak characteristics and fruit set success, developing practical observation protocols using peak cap shedding as marker, and assessing climate variability impacts on flowering peak conditions affecting productivity across seasons.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 372-378"
},

  "Synchronous_Cap_Fall": {
  "definition": "Synchronous cap fall represents the coordinated simultaneous calyptra detachment phenomenon during peak flowering when numerous flowers throughout cluster complete abscission within same brief period creating concentrated cap fall events, reflecting developmental synchronization and optimal environmental conditions enabling coordinated flowering.",
  "alternative_term": "coordinated cap fall | simultaneous cap shedding | synchronized calyptra detachment |+ synchroner Kappenfall | koordinierte Kalyptralösung | gleichzeitiger Kappenabwurf | Massenabwurf-Synchronisation",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows synchronous cap fall during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 during peak flowering, with discrete coordinated detachment events involving 8-14 simultaneous cap sheds per cluster occurring during morning hours 9am-11am, creating visible waves of calyptra fall under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 58-72% relative humidity, reflecting good developmental uniformity in this early-bursting moderately-to-highly synchronous cultivar supporting uniform 62-74% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Synchronous_Cap_Fall is second aspect of Mass_Cap_Fall, distinguished by coordination emphasis rather than just intensity. ||Represents discrete coordinated events within peak period. ||Reflects developmental uniformity and favorable conditions. ||Benefits pollination efficiency and fruit set uniformity. ||Mechanisms incompletely understood involving developmental coordination and environmental responses. ||Provides striking visual confirmation of flowering peak. ||Cultivar variation in synchronization capacity affects flowering characteristics. || This remarkable coordination phenomenon occurs during peak flowering in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically visible as discrete events within peak cap shedding period when multiple flowers simultaneously shed caps creating visible waves of detachment, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 stages. ||Synchronization characteristics show multiple flowers completing cap detachment within minutes to hours of each other creating concentrated activity bursts, spatial coordination with flowers across different cluster regions shedding simultaneously despite physical separation, and temporal clustering of detachment events suggesting common triggering factors. ||Coordinated detachment timing shows characteristic pattern with discrete shedding waves particularly during optimal morning conditions, individual events involving 5-15 simultaneous detachments per cluster creating visible sudden cap fall, and repeated synchronized events throughout peak period maintaining intensive flowering activity. ||Developmental synchronization underlying coordinated fall reflects uniform flower maturation resulting from compressed primordium formation previous season, similar developmental progression through inflorescence emergence and pre-anthesis stages, and convergence toward simultaneous flowering readiness enabling coordinated reproductive activity. ||Environmental triggering of synchronized fall shows possible role for diurnal temperature changes with morning warming potentially triggering coordinated abscission completion, humidity decline facilitating simultaneous mechanical separation as tissue hydration changes, and integrated environmental signals coordinating detachment timing across multiple flowers. ||Temperature threshold effects may contribute to synchronization with coordinated abscission completion when temperature exceeds critical value around 20-22°C, morning temperature rise potentially triggering simultaneous detachment in flowers approaching readiness, and daily temperature pattern creating repeated synchronization opportunities. ||Humidity effects on synchronization show that declining morning humidity potentially facilitates coordinated mechanical separation as caps loosen with reduced turgor, creating condition enabling simultaneous detachment in multiple flowers reaching critical stage, and contributing to characteristic morning peak in synchronized shedding activity. ||Mechanical coordination shows that individual cap detachments potentially triggering neighboring detachments through vibration or physical contact, creating cascade effects producing concentrated shedding bursts, though importance of mechanical triggering versus independent coordination remains unclear. ||Hormonal coordination possibilities include potential role for ethylene as volatile signal enabling communication between flowers, though evidence for hormonal coordination of grapevine flowering remains limited, and most synchronization likely resulting from developmental uniformity and common environmental responses rather than active signaling. ||Observational characteristics enable recognition of synchronous fall through concentrated cap detachment events visible during observation periods, sudden appearance of multiple freshly detached caps on cluster surfaces, and characteristic waves of activity during favorable morning conditions distinguishable from continuous sporadic shedding. ||Visual impact of synchronous fall creates particularly striking full bloom appearance with simultaneous flower opening throughout cluster, abundant coordinated cap fall creating impressive display of reproductive activity, and overall flowering intensity enhanced by synchronized coordination. ||Pollination efficiency implications show synchronized fall potentially beneficial through coordinated pollen release and stigma receptivity creating optimal pollination window, concentrated reproductive activity potentially improving pollination success through enhanced pollen-stigma encounters, and synchronized flowering supporting uniform fruit set contributing to crop uniformity. ||Fruit set uniformity benefits from synchronization include coordinated successful pollinations creating berries with similar development timing, reduced within-cluster developmental heterogeneity potentially improving ripening uniformity, and overall quality benefits from concentrated successful reproduction. ||Developmental consequences show that synchronized flowering reflecting compressed developmental progression, with high synchrony indicating good developmental uniformity resulting from optimal previous season primordium formation and current season development, while asynchronous extended flowering suggesting developmental heterogeneity potentially creating ripening challenges. ||Weather dependency of synchronization shows that favorable stable conditions during flowering period promoting coordination through consistent environmental conditions enabling uniform progression, while variable conditions disrupting synchronization creating extended irregular flowering affecting uniformity. ||Cultivar differences in synchronization capacity show some varieties exhibiting strong synchronized shedding with highly coordinated flowering creating compressed bloom period, while others showing more asynchronous extended shedding reflecting lower developmental uniformity, affecting flowering characteristics and fruit set patterns. ||Coordination mechanisms remain incompletely understood with developmental uniformity clearly important, environmental factors contributing through common responses, and possible role for communication signals though evidence limited in grapevine. ||The process represents second aspect of mass cap fall emphasizing coordination rather than just intensity, occurring within peak cap shedding period. ||Duration represents repeated discrete events rather than continuous period, with individual synchronized detachments occurring over minutes to hours and multiple events throughout peak period. ||Regional occurrence shows synchronous cap fall during peak flowering period across all climates whenever developmental uniformity and favorable conditions align, though expression varies with cultivar characteristics and environmental conditions. ||Viticultural significance includes reflecting good developmental uniformity indicating potential for uniform fruit set and ripening, demonstrating favorable flowering conditions supporting optimal reproductive success, and providing impressive visual confirmation of flowering peak. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanisms underlying synchronized flowering including developmental, environmental, and possible signaling factors, evaluating relationships between flowering synchrony and fruit set uniformity, quantifying cultivar differences in coordination capacity affecting flowering characteristics, assessing environmental effects on synchronization affecting reproductive outcomes, and investigating developmental controls producing uniform flower maturation enabling coordinated anthesis.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 375-380 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 285-292"
},

  "Progressive_Cap_Fall": {
  "definition": "Progressive cap fall represents the declining calyptra detachment phase following peak intensity when remaining 20-30% flowers complete abscission through sequential shedding as final buds mature, marking transition from peak reproductive activity toward flowering completion with progressively decreasing daily cap fall rate.",
  "alternative_term": "declining cap fall | late cap shedding | sequential calyptra detachment |+ progressive Kappenabtrennung | abnehmender Kappenfall | späte Kalyptralösung | sequentielle Kappenablösung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows progressive cap fall during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 67-68 over 2-3 days June 12-14, with final 22-28% flowers predominantly in basal positions completing cap detachment, declining daily rate from peak 18-24% to progressive 6-10%, visible berry development 10-16 mm diameter from earlier fruit set, under cool climate conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 60-75% relative humidity, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing late shedding contributing 18-24% final berry number",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Cap_Fall is third major Cap_Fall phase following Initial and Mass Cap Fall, distinguished by declining intensity with final flowers completing detachment. ||Corresponds to BBCH 67-68 parallel to Late_Anthesis. ||Subdivided into Sequential_Cap_Detachment and Extended_Cap_Shedding. ||Represents final 15-25% fruit set contribution. ||Transitions to Final_Cap_Fall as completion approaches. ||Marks declining phase toward flowering conclusion. ||Reduced weather sensitivity compared to peak though conditions still affect late shedding success. || This concluding shedding phase occurs during late flowering in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1 following mass cap fall, typically spanning 2-3 days as final flowers predominantly in basal cluster positions complete detachment creating extended tail of flowering activity, corresponding to BBCH 67-68 stages parallel to late anthesis. ||Shedding intensity decline shows characteristic pattern with decreasing daily detachment rate dropping from 15-25% during peak to 5-10% during progressive phase, cumulative cap fall reaching 70-90% flowers by progressive phase onset, and remaining 10-30% flowers completing detachment during final shedding period. ||Spatial concentration during progressive fall shows activity predominantly in basal cluster regions reflecting latest flower maturation from previous season primordium formation, with apical and middle regions showing 85-100% completed cap fall, while basal regions showing 50-80% completion with active ongoing shedding. ||Sequential detachment pattern shows progressive individual flower cap fall rather than mass synchronized activity, with flowers completing abscission as they individually reach maturity creating extended shedding period, and overall pattern reflecting developmental gradient established during previous season inflorescence development. ||Cap accumulation during progressive phase continues though at reduced rate with fresh detached caps adding to previously accumulated layers, daily additions of 5-10% total flowers creating modest ongoing accumulation, and overall cap debris reaching maximum density by progressive phase conclusion. ||Flower exposure completion during progressive phase shows final reproductive organs revealing as late-maturing flowers shed caps, with 70-90% cluster showing exposed organs or developing berries from successful earlier pollinations, and remaining 10-30% flowers achieving open state during progressive detachment. ||Reproductive capacity during progressive phase shows substantially reduced potential with limited fresh pollen from late-opening flowers, expired pollen from earlier anthesis providing minimal viable contribution, declining stigma receptivity in recently opened flowers, and overall reproductive opportunity greatly diminished compared to peak period. ||Berry development visibility increases during progressive phase as successfully fertilized flowers expand creating recognizable fruit structures 8-15 mm diameter from earliest fruit set, visible berry clusters contrasting with remaining flowers showing late opening or senescence, and overall cluster appearance transitioning from predominantly reproductive to predominantly developmental state. ||Unfertilized flower senescence accelerates during progressive phase with earliest unsuccessful flowers showing advanced browning and beginning abscission, progressive senescence wave following developmental gradient, and accumulating senescing flower debris adding to cap fall debris creating mixed fallen material. ||Environmental effects during progressive phase show continued sensitivity though reduced compared to peak with temperature affecting late flower cap shedding efficiency, humidity influencing detachment success in final flowers, and overall conditions less critical since majority fruit set 75-85% already established during earlier phases. ||Temperature during progressive phase typically 20-28°C supporting continued though declining cap fall activity, with warm conditions promoting efficient late shedding completing phase rapidly, while cool conditions may slow late detachment extending progressive period. ||Humidity during progressive phase shows continued importance for efficient late cap fall with moderate 50-70% facilitating normal detachment in final flowers, while elevated humidity potentially causing retention in susceptible late flowers affecting complete flowering achievement. ||Weather impacts during progressive phase have limited overall effect on fruit set since majority berry number already established, though adverse conditions affecting late shedding may influence final completion and small contribution from late-opening flowers. ||Developmental heterogeneity reaches maximum during progressive phase with wide range of states coexisting including advanced developing berries 10-18 mm from earliest fruit set, recently pollinated flowers beginning berry expansion from mid-flowering success, late-opening flowers with limited reproductive potential, and senescing unfertilized flowers from earlier unsuccessful pollinations. ||Extended cap shedding during progressive phase creates prolonged flowering period in some situations with sequential individual flower maturation causing gradual extended detachment rather than compressed mass fall, potentially reflecting developmental heterogeneity from previous season or current season environmental variation, and affecting flowering duration and fruit set uniformity. ||Observational characteristics during progressive phase include declining cap fall activity distinguishable from earlier intensive mass fall, spatial concentration in basal positions indicating late flower maturation, visible berry development throughout cluster creating transitional appearance, and overall indication of approaching flowering completion. ||Phenological progression during progressive phase shows advancement from peak BBCH 63-65 toward completion BBCH 69, with developmental rate affected by temperature and late flower maturation timing, and clear trajectory toward complete anthesis and cap fall conclusion. ||Management implications during progressive phase include recognizing approaching flowering completion enabling preparation for post-bloom operations, beginning to assess fruit set outcomes through berry visibility and senescing flower observation, and transitioning focus from bloom-period restrictions toward developmental management priorities. ||Fruit set contribution from progressive phase typically represents 15-25% final berry number established during late shedding, with late-set berries often showing slightly delayed development compared to earlier fruit potentially affecting ripening uniformity. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from sequential cap detachment reflecting individual flower maturation, through extended cap shedding creating prolonged final flowering period. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing declining phase before final completion, with warm conditions promoting rapid progression while cool conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation in progressive fall shows differences in proportion of late-opening flowers with some showing compressed 10-15% late phase while others showing extended 25-35% late phase affecting overall duration, late flower cap shedding efficiency with some maintaining good detachment while others showing retention problems, and transition timing toward complete cap fall. ||Regional timing shows progressive cap fall during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, occurring during late flowering 5-8 days after first cap detachment. ||Viticultural significance includes representing final cap fall contribution completing flowering activity, providing visual indication of approaching completion enabling management transitions, revealing late retention problems indicating potential final fruit set limitations, and marking transition from peak reproductive vulnerability toward more stable developmental phase. ||Research applications include analyzing factors affecting late flower cap shedding success, evaluating sequential detachment patterns reflecting developmental gradients, quantifying contributions of progressive phase to final fruit set and berry development patterns, assessing extended shedding implications for flowering duration and uniformity, and documenting transition from reproductive to developmental phases through cap fall observation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-388 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Sequential_Cap_Detachment": {
  "definition": "Sequential cap detachment represents the individual progressive calyptra shedding pattern during progressive cap fall when remaining flowers complete abscission sequentially as they individually reach maturity rather than through synchronized mass events, reflecting developmental gradient and creating extended flowering tail.",
  "alternative_term": "individual cap detachment | progressive sequential shedding | non-synchronized cap fall |+ sequentielle Kappenablösung | individuelle Kalyptratrennung | progressive Einzelabtrennung | asynchroner Kappenabwurf",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows sequential cap detachment during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 67-68 over 3 days June 13-15, with 18-26% flowers completing individual asynchronous cap fall predominantly in basal positions at rate of 5-8% per day, creating extended shedding tail, under temperate maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, 62-76% relative humidity, typical of this mid-season cultivar showing moderate developmental gradient contributing 14-20% berry number through sequential shedding with 22-34% late pollination success",
  "editor_note": "Sequential_Cap_Detachment is first aspect of Progressive_Cap_Fall, distinguished by individual asynchronous shedding pattern. ||Reflects developmental gradient from previous season primordium formation. ||Contrasts with earlier synchronized mass fall. ||Creates extended low-intensity shedding period. ||Limited reproductive success due to pollen limitation. ||Reveals developmental heterogeneity affecting uniformity. ||Followed by Extended_Cap_Shedding discussing temporal implications. || This characteristic late shedding pattern occurs during late flowering in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1 as part of progressive cap fall, spanning 2-3 days as final flowers individually mature and shed caps creating non-synchronized extended detachment, corresponding to BBCH 67-68 stages. ||Detachment sequence shows individual flower maturation pattern with flowers completing cap fall one-by-one or in small groups 1-3 flowers rather than mass synchronized events, temporal spread reflecting developmental heterogeneity established during previous season primordium formation and current season progression, and overall sequential pattern creating extended shedding period. ||Spatial sequence typically proceeds basipetal direction with remaining unopened flowers concentrated in basal cluster positions, progressive detachment advancing from middle toward basal regions following developmental gradient, and occasional scattered late detachment in other positions from locally delayed flowers. ||Individual flower timing shows asynchronous maturation with individual flowers reaching abscission readiness at different times spanning days, cap detachment occurring independently as each flower completes maturation rather than coordinated by common signals, and variable timing creating extended low-intensity shedding period. ||Developmental gradient expression through sequential pattern clearly reveals maturation sequence established during previous season inflorescence primordium formation, with earliest apical primordia producing earliest-maturing flowers completing cap fall first during initial phase, and latest basal primordia producing latest-maturing flowers completing sequential detachment during progressive phase. ||Detachment rate during sequential shedding shows low continuous activity with daily additions of 3-7% flowers completing cap fall, sustained over several days creating cumulative substantial completion, and overall pattern contrasting with earlier compressed intense mass fall. ||Cap accumulation pattern during sequential shedding shows modest ongoing additions with individual or small groups of fresh caps appearing daily, accumulation less visually striking than mass fall intensive deposition, and overall continued cap debris accumulation documenting extended flowering period. ||Flower exposure during sequential shedding shows progressive individual organ revelation as each flower completes cap detachment, spatial distribution reflecting sequence pattern with basal concentration, and overall extended exposure period affecting late reproductive potential. ||Reproductive opportunity during sequential detachment remains limited with each newly opened flower encountering suboptimal conditions including minimal viable pollen availability from aged earlier production, reduced atmospheric pollen density, limited concurrent receptive stigmas for cross-pollination, and overall low probability of successful pollination affecting fruit set from sequential shedding. ||Pollination success during sequential phase shows reduced efficiency with estimated 15-35% late-opening flowers achieving successful pollination and fruit set compared to 50-70% during optimal mass fall, resulting primarily from pollen limitation rather than intrinsic flower dysfunction, and affecting final fruit set contribution from sequential shedding period. ||Environmental effects on sequential shedding include temperature affecting individual flower maturation rate and cap detachment efficiency, humidity influencing mechanical separation in each detaching flower, and overall conditions less critical since reproductive outcomes largely determined during earlier phases. ||Humidity sensitivity during sequential shedding shows continued importance for efficient individual detachment with moderate levels facilitating normal cap fall in late flowers, while elevated humidity potentially causing retention in susceptible individuals, though overall impact limited since majority shedding already completed. ||Temperature during sequential shedding affects progression rate with warm conditions 24-28°C promoting rapid individual flower maturation completing sequential phase within 2-3 days, while cool conditions 18-22°C slowing progression potentially extending period to 4-5 days. ||Developmental asynchrony underlying sequential pattern reflects variable flower maturation resulting from heterogeneous previous season primordium formation timing, differential current season environmental exposure affecting progression rates, and inherent developmental variation creating spread in flowering readiness. ||Extended flowering implications of sequential shedding include prolonged flowering period from 10-14 days total compared to 7-10 days with compressed synchronous flowering, increased within-cluster developmental heterogeneity affecting ripening uniformity, and potential quality implications from variable berry development timing. ||Cultivar differences in sequential pattern show some varieties exhibiting pronounced sequential shedding with 25-35% flowers in extended tail, while others show compressed pattern with only 10-15% sequential component, affecting flowering duration and uniformity characteristics. ||Management implications of sequential shedding include recognizing extended flowering period requiring sustained weather monitoring through completion, understanding that sequential pattern indicates developmental heterogeneity potentially affecting harvest uniformity, and appreciating that extended flowering creates prolonged vulnerability period though later flowers contribute minor proportion to final yield. ||Observational characteristics enable recognition of sequential shedding through low-intensity sustained cap fall activity over several days, individual or small-group detachment events rather than mass synchronized fall, spatial progression following developmental gradient, and overall extended gradual flowering completion. ||The process represents first aspect of progressive cap fall emphasizing sequential individual pattern, followed by extended shedding discussing temporal implications. ||Duration spans 2-3 days representing sequential progression period with individual flowers completing detachment asynchronously. ||Cultivar variation in sequential characteristics shows differences in sequence extent affecting proportion of flowers in sequential tail, sequence rate affecting duration of sequential period, and retention susceptibility in late sequential flowers affecting complete flowering achievement. ||Regional timing shows sequential cap detachment during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, occurring during late flowering as part of progressive cap fall. ||Viticultural significance includes revealing developmental heterogeneity through extended sequential pattern affecting flowering and ripening uniformity, contributing final proportion 10-20% berry number through extended shedding though with reduced success rate, and indicating completion approach through declining sequence activity enabling management transitions. ||Research applications include analyzing developmental gradients producing sequential shedding patterns, evaluating environmental and genetic factors affecting shedding sequence characteristics, quantifying relationships between sequential shedding extent and ripening uniformity, assessing pollination limitations during sequential period affecting late fruit set, and documenting flowering duration variation affecting management requirements across cultivars and conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 382-386 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Extended_Cap_Shedding": {
  "definition": "Extended cap shedding represents the prolonged calyptra detachment period resulting from developmental heterogeneity when sequential individual flower maturation creates sustained low-intensity cap fall activity over several days, contrasting with compressed synchronized flowering and affecting overall flowering duration and uniformity.",
  "alternative_term": "prolonged cap fall | extended calyptra shedding | protracted cap detachment period |+ ausgedehnte Kappenablösung | verlängerte Kalyptralösung | protrahierte Abwurfperiode | Langzeit-Kappenfall",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows extended cap shedding during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 67-68 over 4-5 days June 12-16, with total flowering period extending to 12-13 days from first to last cap detachment, continuous low-intensity shedding 4-7% per day creating 24-32% sequential tail, resulting in 8-11 day developmental spread between earliest and latest-set berries, under variable oceanic conditions averaging 20-26°C temperature, 58-75% relative humidity, typical of this mid-season cultivar showing moderate developmental coordination in variable maritime climate",
  "editor_note": "Extended_Cap_Shedding is second aspect of Progressive_Cap_Fall, distinguished by temporal extension emphasis and uniformity implications. ||Follows Sequential_Cap_Detachment. ||Results from developmental heterogeneity creating prolonged flowering period. ||Increases within-cluster berry development variation affecting ripening uniformity. ||Creates prolonged weather vulnerability. ||Reflects cultivar coordination capacity and environmental effects. ||Management implications for quality uniformity and harvest timing. ||Problem characteristic in some cultivars or unfavorable conditions. || This temporal flowering characteristic occurs during progressive cap fall in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning 3-5 days or more in cultivars or conditions showing pronounced developmental spread, corresponding to BBCH 67-68 extended stages. ||Temporal extension characteristics show prolonged flowering period from first to last cap detachment spanning 10-14 days in extended scenarios compared to 7-10 days in compressed flowering, continuous low-intensity cap fall activity sustained over extended period rather than concentrated mass fall, and overall duration reflecting developmental heterogeneity magnitude. ||Duration factors contributing to extension include developmental gradient magnitude established during previous season primordium formation with greater spread producing more extended flowering, current season environmental variation affecting differential flower progression rates, and cultivar-specific developmental coordination capacity with some varieties showing inherently more extended flowering. ||Developmental heterogeneity underlying extension reflects variable flower maturation resulting from heterogeneous inflorescence primordium initiation timing previous season Year N, differential development during current season emergence and pre-anthesis stages, and accumulated variation creating substantial maturation spread by flowering. ||Sequential progression creating extension shows continuous low-rate cap detachment with daily additions of 3-7% flowers over extended period, cumulative effect producing substantial total completion though daily intensity low, and sustained activity creating prolonged flowering period. ||Cap accumulation pattern during extended shedding shows continued modest additions over many days creating ultimately substantial total accumulation, less visually dramatic than mass fall but cumulatively significant, and extended debris accumulation period documenting prolonged flowering. ||Flower exposure during extended shedding shows progressive gradual increase in opened flower proportion over many days, extended period creating wide developmental spread within cluster from earliest to latest opening, and maximum within-cluster heterogeneity at extended shedding completion. ||Reproductive implications of extended shedding include prolonged pollination window potentially beneficial for overcoming brief adverse conditions affecting any single day, though overall extended period creates greater cumulative weather vulnerability, and late flowers in extended tail showing minimal reproductive success due to pollen limitation. ||Fruit set outcomes with extended shedding show potential for adequate overall set if conditions favorable during extended period enabling cumulative success, but risk of reduced set if extended period experiences predominantly unfavorable conditions, and increased developmental heterogeneity among set berries from extended pollination timing spread. ||Berry development heterogeneity resulting from extended shedding creates substantial within-cluster variation with earliest-set berries potentially 8-12 days ahead of latest-set berries by extended shedding completion, affecting ripening uniformity and harvest timing considerations, and potentially creating quality variations within clusters. ||Environmental effects on extended shedding include variable conditions over prolonged period affecting different portions of flowering differently, cumulative weather exposure increasing probability of encountering some adverse conditions, and overall environmental impact more complex than compressed flowering. ||Temperature during extended shedding shows averaged effect over many days with warm conditions promoting faster progression shortening extension, cool conditions slowing progression lengthening extension, and variable temperatures creating irregular progression patterns. ||Humidity during extended shedding affects efficiency throughout period with sustained moderate levels supporting continued detachment, episodes of elevated humidity potentially causing temporary retention or delays, and overall humidity pattern affecting completion timing. ||Weather vulnerability during extended shedding shows increased cumulative exposure risk with prolonged sensitive period increasing probability of encountering rain or other adverse conditions, though any single adverse event affects smaller proportion of flowering compared to compressed scenario, creating trade-off between acute and chronic vulnerability. ||Cultivar variation in extension tendency shows some varieties inherently showing extended 12-16 day flowering reflecting poor developmental coordination, others showing compressed 7-9 day flowering from good synchronization, and intermediate varieties showing moderate 9-12 day duration, affecting variety characteristics and management requirements. ||Environmental effects on extension include unfavorable conditions during inflorescence emergence or pre-anthesis stages potentially increasing heterogeneity extending flowering, while optimal conditions promoting uniformity compressing period, and year-to-year variation in extension within same cultivar reflecting environmental effects. ||Management implications of extended shedding include prolonged critical weather-sensitive period requiring sustained vigilance and management restrictions, increased within-cluster heterogeneity affecting harvest timing and quality uniformity, and extended flowering indicating possible developmental or environmental problems affecting synchronization. ||Fruit set assessment complications from extended shedding include difficulty determining appropriate timing for evaluation with wide spread in flower developmental states, mixed developmental appearance complicating visual assessment, and need for extended observation period confirming completion before definitive assessment. ||Observational characteristics indicating extended shedding include sustained low-intensity cap fall over many days distinguishable from compressed mass fall pattern, wide developmental spread visible within cluster with early berries and late flowers coexisting, and prolonged visible flowering period documented through extended cap accumulation. ||The process represents second aspect of progressive cap fall emphasizing temporal extension implications, following sequential cap detachment. ||Duration represents extended 3-5+ day period though individual flowers shed sequentially, with overall flowering period potentially reaching 12-16 days in extreme extensions. ||Cultivar variation in extension shows some varieties prone to extended shedding reflecting inherent poor developmental coordination while others reliably show compressed flowering, affecting variety selection for regions where flowering conditions critical. ||Regional expression shows extended shedding most problematic in marginal climates where unfavorable conditions during development may exacerbate heterogeneity, while favorable stable conditions generally promote compressed flowering even in extension-prone varieties. ||Viticultural significance includes identifying potential quality limitations from excessive within-cluster heterogeneity, complicating harvest timing and uniformity management, increasing cumulative weather vulnerability through prolonged sensitive period, and affecting variety suitability assessment for particular sites or regions. ||Research applications include analyzing developmental and environmental factors producing flowering extension, evaluating genetic variation in developmental coordination affecting flowering duration, quantifying relationships between flowering extension and berry development heterogeneity, assessing impacts of extension on fruit set outcomes and quality characteristics, and developing management strategies for varieties or situations prone to extended flowering.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 385-390 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Final_Cap_Fall": {
  "definition": "Final cap fall represents the concluding calyptra detachment phase when last remaining flowers complete abscission establishing complete cap shedding within cluster and marking definitive flowering completion with no further reproductive structures to contribute, transitioning fully to berry development focus.",
  "alternative_term": "cap fall completion | final calyptra detachment | concluding cap shedding | flowering completion caps |+ finaler Kappenfall | Kappenfall-Abschluss | abschließende Kalyptralösung | Blüteende-Kappenabwurf",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows final cap fall during late June Year N+1 at BBCH 69 on approximately June 15-16, with last 4-7% flowers completing cap detachment predominantly in basal positions, visible berry development 10-16 mm diameter throughout cluster representing 52-64% fruit set, unfertilized flowers showing active abscission, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-28°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing cap fall 11-12 days after first detachment and transitioning definitively to berry development phase",
  "editor_note": "Final_Cap_Fall is fourth and conclusive major Cap_Fall phase marking definitive calyptra shedding completion. ||Corresponds to BBCH 69 parallel to Complete_Anthesis. ||Subdivided into Last_Caps_Falling and Cap_Fall_Completion. ||Establishes flowering conclusion through observable cap shedding cessation. ||Enables management transitions and fruit set assessment. ||Marks transition to developmental phase. ||Provides clear practical observable marker for flowering completion easier than detailed reproductive organ assessment. || This conclusive shedding phase occurs during complete anthesis in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 following progressive cap fall, typically spanning 1-2 days as final flowers complete detachment, corresponding to BBCH 69 approaching complete flowering stage. ||Completion characteristics show all viable flowers having completed cap shedding with 100% developmentally capable flowers showing detached caps or unopened structures representing aborted buds, minimal ongoing cap fall activity with only final 3-8% flowers completing detachment, and definitive cessation of calyptra shedding activity across cluster. ||Final flower cap shedding shows last individual flowers completing abscission typically in basal cluster positions or scattered locations representing most delayed development, cap detachment occurring through same abscission mechanisms as earlier flowers though under potentially suboptimal late conditions, and completion representing end of flowering-related cap fall with no further flowers capable of contributing. ||Cap accumulation at completion reaches maximum density with total fallen cap debris representing full flowering extent, accumulated caps on cluster surfaces and ground below documenting complete flowering period, and cap debris beginning decomposition processes creating organic matter return. ||Cluster appearance at final cap fall shows definitive developmental state with small developing berries 8-15 mm diameter dominating visual appearance from successful early-to-mid fruit set, brown senescing unfertilized flowers interspersed showing varying abscission progress, occasional final-opening flowers with minimal reproductive potential, and overall appearance of developmental phase with reproductive activity concluded. ||Berry development visibility at completion shows clear green fruit structures distributed throughout cluster creating recognizable young fruit cluster appearance, berry number countable enabling definitive fruit set assessment, spatial distribution revealing architectural pattern and final cluster density, and overall berry-dominated appearance contrasting with earlier flower-dominated state. ||Unfertilized flower abscission at completion shows active progressive detachment with senescing flowers developing completed abscission zones enabling separation, daily flower drop creating accumulation of fallen brown flower debris, and progressive cluster cleaning eliminating failed reproductions over subsequent 1-2 weeks leaving only productive berries. ||Abscission completion timing shows most unfertilized flower drop occurring during 1-2 weeks following final cap fall, though some dried flower remnants may persist longer before eventual removal, and overall cluster achieving predominantly berry-only appearance by post-completion period. ||Retained cap problems at completion may show occasional flowers with incompletely shed caps representing failed abscission from developmental abnormalities or unfavorable conditions, retained caps potentially interfering with berry development if fruit set succeeded despite retention, and overall retention assessment indicating flowering efficiency and potential coulure extent. ||Flowering completion confirmation requires verification that no further viable unopened flowers remain capable of contributing to fruit set, assessment that reproductive activity has definitively ceased across cluster, and recognition that final cap fall represents true flowering conclusion rather than temporary lull. ||Developmental transition at completion shows cluster fully committed to berry development phase with all metabolic resources directing to expanding berries, no residual reproductive investment or potential, and physiological state completely transitioned from reproductive to developmental focus. ||Berry growth acceleration following completion shows rapidly increasing expansion rates as cell division intensifies, daily diameter increase of 0.4-0.8 mm during early rapid growth, and visible berry size progression creating obvious fruit development. ||Resource allocation at completion shows complete reorientation to berry development as dominant sink consuming 40-60% total photosynthate, vegetative growth continuing requiring 30-40% resources, and no reproductive demands with flowering completely concluded. ||Phenological significance at completion includes marking definitive end of BBCH 69 cap fall and flowering stages, establishing transition to BBCH 71-79 fruit development stages, and providing clear observable reference for flowering conclusion enabling developmental phase focus. ||Management implications at completion include confirming flowering conclusion enabling complete resumption of normal operations without bloom-period restrictions, initiating post-bloom fruit development management including disease protection and crop adjustment, and transitioning focus entirely to developmental and quality optimization priorities. ||Fruit set determination at completion enables accurate assessment through berry count establishing final berry number, calculation of fruit set percentage from berry number relative to total flowers opened, and yield prediction based on berry number and expected final berry weight. ||Observational characteristics enable definitive completion identification through cessation of cap fall activity with no ongoing detachment visible, cluster appearance showing predominantly berries with minimal remaining flowers, and overall transition to developmental state clearly evident. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from last caps falling completing final detachments, through cap fall completion confirming definitive cessation. ||Duration represents brief 1-2 day final period marking completion, with rapid transition to fully developmental state. ||Cultivar variation in final cap fall shows differences in completion timing with early varieties completing late June while late types complete early-mid July, retention problems with some varieties showing occasional persistent caps while others show complete clean shedding, and completion clarity with some showing definitive conclusion while others showing gradual extended completion. ||Regional timing shows final cap fall during late June in warm climates at approximately 1150-1200 growing degree days base 10°C, late June-early July in temperate regions at 1050-1100 GDD, and early-mid July in cool areas at 950-1000 GDD, marking flowering completion across regions. ||Viticultural significance includes marking definitive flowering completion enabling complete management transitions, confirming final fruit set and berry number establishing yield potential, indicating end of critical flowering period reducing vulnerability and restrictions, and providing clear observable reference for developmental phase transition. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering completion timing for phenological studies, analyzing factors affecting complete cap shedding achievement, evaluating relationships between cap fall patterns and fruit set outcomes, assessing retention problems affecting flowering completion and fruit set, and documenting phenological transitions marking major phase changes in reproductive biology.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 388-395 || Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200"
},

  "Last_Caps_Falling": {
  "definition": "Last caps falling represents the final individual calyptra detachments when remaining 3-8% unopened flowers complete abscission establishing complete cap shedding extent within cluster and marking imminent flowering completion with no further viable flowers remaining.",
  "alternative_term": "final cap detachments | very last caps falling | terminal calyptra shedding | ultimate cap fall |+ letzte Kappen fallen | finale Kappenablösungen | terminale Kalyptralösung | Endkappen-Abwurf",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows last caps falling on June 16 Year N+1 at late BBCH 69, with final 3-6% flowers predominantly in basal positions completing cap detachment, visible berry development 12-18 mm diameter representing 58-66% established fruit set throughout cluster, under warm climate conditions of 25-29°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar completing final cap fall 12-13 days after first detachment establishing flowering completion with last caps representing completion formality contributing negligible fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Last_Caps_Falling is first aspect of Final_Cap_Fall, distinguished by very last individual detachment events. ||Represents final 3-8% flowers completing cap fall. ||Indicates imminent flowering completion within hours to day. ||Negligible reproductive contribution since pollen expired. ||Observable marker of near-completion enabling final management preparations. ||Followed by Cap_Fall_Completion confirming definitive cessation. ||Brief hours to one-day duration as final events complete. || This final detachment phase occurs during complete anthesis in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 as part of final cap fall, typically spanning 1 day or brief hours as very last flowers complete cap shedding, corresponding to BBCH 69 final stage. ||Final flower characteristics show last-to-mature individuals typically in most basal cluster positions reflecting latest primordium formation previous season and most delayed current season development, occasional scattered positions from locally abnormal delayed development, and overall final flowers representing developmental tail of cluster flowering. ||Final cap detachment timing shows last individual events completing cluster cap fall, detachments occurring sporadically as final flowers individually reach maturity, and cessation of activity establishing complete cap shedding achievement. ||Detachment process in final flowers proceeds through same abscission mechanisms as earlier flowers with enzymatic degradation of middle lamella creating separation plane, mechanical forces from organ expansion driving cap lifting, and final separation completing calyptra removal, though final flowers may experience less favorable conditions affecting efficiency. ||Environmental conditions at final detachment show reduced criticality since reproductive outcomes already determined with 92-97% berries established from earlier successful pollinations, though conditions still affect final detachment success completing flowering process. ||Cap accumulation from final detachments adds minimal incremental debris to substantial previously accumulated layers, with last few caps barely noticeable among abundant earlier accumulation, though completing total flowering documentation. ||Flower exposure from final detachments reveals last reproductive organs though with minimal functional significance, as very limited viable pollen remains and atmospheric pollen completely expired, creating negligible reproductive opportunity for last-opening flowers. ||Reproductive potential of final flowers shows essentially zero probability of successful pollination and fruit set due to complete pollen exhaustion, expired stigma receptivity potential due to suboptimal late conditions, and overall failed reproductive opportunity though mechanical flowering completion proceeds. ||Berry development visibility at last caps falling shows advanced early-set berries 12-18 mm diameter from peak flowering success, visible throughout cluster creating predominant appearance, contrasting with minimal final flower opening highlighting developmental transition. ||Unfertilized flower senescence shows widespread brown discoloration in failed reproductions from throughout flowering period, active abscission beginning to eliminate senescing flowers, and overall cluster cleaning toward berry-only appearance. ||Cluster appearance at last caps falling shows definitive transitional state with developing berries as dominant visual feature creating young fruit cluster impression, minimal final opening activity barely noticeable among berry-dominated appearance, and overall appearance confirming developmental phase establishment. ||Observational requirements for detecting last caps falling include careful inspection identifying very last detachment events, distinction between final viable flowers versus persistent aborted buds incapable of normal development, and confirmation that no further capable flowers remain establishing true completion. ||Completion proximity indicated by last caps falling shows flowering conclusion imminent within hours to one day, very minimal residual flowering activity remaining, and clear trajectory toward definitive cap fall completion. ||Phenological significance of last caps falling includes indicating imminent BBCH 69 complete flowering achievement, providing practical observation that flowering nearly completed enabling final management transitions, and establishing near-completion state preparing for post-flowering operations. ||Management implications include confirming flowering nearly complete enabling final preparations for post-bloom operations including disease management resumption and canopy operations, recognizing that critical flowering period effectively concluded with minimal remaining vulnerability, and transitioning focus definitively to berry development priorities. ||Fruit set contribution from last flowers shows negligible addition to berry number with essentially zero successful pollinations from final openings, confirming that yield potential established during earlier flowering phases, and last caps falling representing completion formality rather than productive contribution. ||Developmental progression from last caps falling proceeds immediately toward complete cessation of cap fall activity, rapid transition to definitive flowering completion, and full commitment to berry development phase. ||The process represents first aspect of final cap fall marking very last detachment events, followed by cap fall completion confirming definitive cessation. ||Duration represents brief hours to one day as final events complete, with rapid progression toward completion. ||Cultivar variation in last caps characteristics shows differences in number of final flowers with some varieties showing minimal 2-4% tail while others showing 6-10% final phase, timing of last detachments reflecting overall phenology, and efficiency of final shedding with some showing clean completion while others showing occasional persistent unopened buds. ||Regional timing shows last caps falling during late June in warm climates, late June-early July in temperate regions, and early-mid July in cool areas, occurring as final events of flowering period. ||Viticultural significance includes indicating imminent flowering completion enabling final management transitions, confirming that productive flowering concluded with last caps representing completion formality, and providing observable marker that critical flowering period effectively ended. ||Research applications include documenting complete flowering extent through final detachment observation, analyzing final flower characteristics representing developmental extremes, evaluating completion efficiency assessing proportion achieving complete opening, and assessing implications of final flowering characteristics for developmental outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 390-393"
},

  "Cap_Fall_Completion": {
  "definition": "Cap fall completion represents the definitive cessation of calyptra detachment activity when all viable flowers have completed abscission establishing final cap shedding extent and marking observable flowering conclusion confirming reproductive phase termination and full transition to berry development.",
  "alternative_term": "complete cap shedding | calyptra fall conclusion | cap detachment termination | flowering completion marker |+ Kappenfall-Vollendung | vollständige Kalyptralösung | Abwurfabschluss | Blüteende-Marker",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows cap fall completion on approximately July 2 Year N+1 at BBCH 69, with all viable flowers 100% having completed cap detachment totaling 12-13 days from first to last fall, visible berry development 10-16 mm diameter representing 64-76% fruit set, no ongoing cap fall activity over multiple observations confirming cessation, under cool maritime conditions of 20-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting moderately-to-highly fruitful cultivar definitively completing flowering and transitioning to berry development focus",
  "editor_note": "Cap_Fall_Completion is second and final aspect of Final_Cap_Fall, distinguished by definitive cessation confirmation. ||Represents observable flowering conclusion marker. ||Corresponds to BBCH 69 complete flowering. ||Enables fruit set assessment and yield prediction. ||Marks full transition to developmental phase. ||Provides clear practical observable reference easier than detailed reproductive examination. ||Establishes baseline for subsequent development predictions. ||Critical phenological milestone in annual progression. ||Completes entire Cap_Fall hierarchical documentation from Initial through Mass, Progressive, to Final phases. || This conclusive observable milestone occurs during complete anthesis in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 immediately following last caps falling, representing point when no further cap fall activity occurs or is possible, corresponding to BBCH 69 complete flowering definition. ||Completion confirmation requires verification through multiple indicators including cessation of cap fall activity with no ongoing detachment observable over observation period, all developmentally capable flowers showing detached caps with only aborted or aberrant buds remaining unopened, and cluster appearance showing predominant berry development with no significant residual flowering activity. ||Cap shedding cessation shows definitive end of detachment activity with no further viable flowers remaining capable of shedding caps, occasional persistent unopened structures representing non-viable aborted buds incapable of normal development rather than delayed flowers, and overall completion of flowering-related cap fall activity. ||Complete shedding achievement shows 100% of viable flowers having completed cap detachment creating maximum possible cap fall for cluster, total cap accumulation representing full flowering extent with no further additions forthcoming, and definitive establishment of final flowering scope. ||Cluster appearance at completion shows clear developmental state with visible developing berries 10-18 mm diameter throughout cluster creating young fruit cluster impression, senescing brown unfertilized flowers interspersed showing progressive abscission, minimal or no recently opened flowers with residual reproductive activity, and overall berry-dominated appearance confirming developmental transition. ||Berry development dominance at completion shows fruit structures as primary cluster feature with successful fruit set berries distributed throughout cluster providing visual confirmation of reproductive outcomes, berry number and spatial distribution clearly assessable enabling fruit set evaluation, and berry growth visibly progressing with daily size increases evident. ||Unfertilized flower abscission progression at completion shows active ongoing elimination of senescing flowers with brown failed reproductions developing completed abscission zones, daily flower drop creating accumulation though less conspicuous than earlier cap fall, and progressive cluster cleaning toward berry-only appearance over subsequent 1-2 weeks. ||Retained cap assessment at completion enables evaluation of shedding efficiency through identification of incompletely shed caps indicating abscission problems, occasional retention representing coulure causing reproductive failure, and overall retention frequency indicating flowering success and cultivar or environmental limitations. ||Observational characteristics enabling completion identification include sustained absence of cap fall activity over multiple observation periods confirming cessation, cluster appearance showing predominantly berries with minimal residual flowering, and overall visual evidence of flowering conclusion with developmental transition. ||Phenological confirmation at completion establishes definitive BBCH 69 complete flowering stage achievement, marks transition from reproductive BBCH 60-69 to developmental BBCH 71-79 stages, and provides clear observable reference easier to assess than detailed reproductive organ examination. ||Developmental transition confirmation at completion shows physiological commitment to berry development with all resources directing to expanding fruit, no residual reproductive investment or potential remaining, and complete metabolic reorientation from reproductive to developmental focus. ||Resource allocation at completion shows full reallocation to berry growth as dominant sink consuming 45-65% total photosynthate, vegetative growth continuing requiring 30-40% resources, and zero reproductive demands with flowering completely concluded. ||Berry growth acceleration following completion shows intensifying expansion through cell division phase, daily diameter increases of 0.5-0.9 mm during peak early growth creating rapid visible progression, and substantial resource demands requiring adequate photosynthetic capacity. ||Management implications at completion include confirming flowering conclusion enabling complete resumption of all normal operations without bloom restrictions, initiating comprehensive post-bloom management including fungicide applications for berry protection and canopy operations optimizing development, transitioning focus entirely to developmental management and quality optimization, and planning subsequent operations based on berry development progression. ||Fruit set assessment at completion enables accurate determination through berry counting establishing final berry number per cluster, calculation of fruit set percentage comparing berry number to total flowers opened, and yield prediction multiplying berry number by expected final berry weight providing season potential estimate. ||Yield prediction based on completion assessment combines berry number from fruit set evaluation with expected berry weight from cultivar norms and environmental conditions, enables comparison to historical norms and targets assessing season outcomes, and informs crop management decisions including possible thinning if load excessive or acceptance if appropriate. ||Flowering duration documentation at completion enables calculation of total flowering period from first cap detachment to completion typically 10-14 days, assessment of flowering compression versus extension affecting potential uniformity, and phenological characterization supporting management planning and climate studies. ||Flowering efficiency evaluation at completion considers proportion of flowers achieving successful cap shedding and fruit set, identifies retention problems indicating coulure issues, and assesses overall reproductive success determining yield outcomes. ||The process represents second and final aspect of final cap fall confirming definitive cessation, following last caps falling. ||Duration represents threshold point marking completion, with observation confirming sustained absence of activity. ||Cultivar variation in completion characteristics shows timing differences with early varieties completing late June while late types complete early-mid July, completion clarity with some showing definitive conclusion while others showing gradual extended completion, and retention problems with some varieties showing occasional persistent caps indicating incomplete flowering. ||Regional timing shows cap fall completion during late June in warm climates at approximately 1150-1200 growing degree days base 10°C, late June-early July in temperate regions at 1050-1100 GDD, and early-mid July in cool areas at 950-1000 GDD, marking flowering conclusion across regions. ||Viticultural significance includes marking definitive observable flowering completion enabling complete management transitions, confirming final fruit set and berry number establishing yield potential for season, indicating end of critical weather-vulnerable flowering period reducing risk, providing clear practical reference for phenological tracking and management planning, and establishing baseline for subsequent berry development progression and timing predictions. ||Research applications include documenting precise flowering completion timing for phenological studies, analyzing factors affecting complete flowering achievement and efficiency, evaluating observable markers for flowering conclusion enabling practical phenological assessment, quantifying relationships between cap fall patterns and fruit set outcomes, and assessing flowering duration and uniformity implications for berry development and quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al. (1995) Growth Stages of the Grapevine, Nachrichtenbl. Deut. Pflanzenschutzd. 47:193-200 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 393-398"
},

  "Pollen_Release": {
  "definition": "Pollen release represents the male reproductive process encompassing anther dehiscence, pollen liberation, and dispersal mechanisms where mature pollen grains exit anthers through specialized opening structures and distribute through wind transport to receptive stigmas, establishing male gamete availability enabling pollination and fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen discharge | pollen liberation | pollen dispersal | male gamete release |+ Pollenfreisetzung | Pollenabgabe | Pollenliberation | männliche Gametenfreigabe",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows pollen release during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65 over 8-10 days, with anther dehiscence progressing throughout cluster releasing abundant pollen estimated 25,000-45,000 grains per flower, pollen viability 76-88% fresh declining to 35-52% after 24 hours, visible pollen clouds during favorable morning conditions, under oceanic climate of 19-25°C temperature, 54-68% relative humidity, light winds supporting efficient dispersal and pollination enabling 54-64% fruit set typical of this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Release represents male reproductive process parallel to Cap_Fall and integral to Anthesis within Flowering. ||Corresponds to BBCH 60-65 stages. ||Subdivided into Anther_Dehiscence establishing liberation mechanism and Active_Pollen_Shedding creating maximum dispersal. ||Environmental conditions particularly humidity and temperature critically affect dehiscence efficiency and pollen viability. ||Essential male contribution determining pollination success and fruit set. ||Extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain destroying pollen function. || This essential reproductive process occurs during flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 5-10 days from first anther dehiscence through completion of pollen discharge across cluster corresponding to BBCH 60-65 stages parallel to anthesis and cap fall. ||Pollen maturation preceding release shows final developmental stages with pollen grains completing tricellular state containing vegetative cell and two sperm cells ready for fertilization, accumulation of storage reserves including starch and lipids providing energy for germination and tube growth, and cytoplasmic organization preparing for immediate germination capacity upon stigma contact. ||Anther structure enabling release includes bilocular organization with two pollen sacs per anther separated by connective tissue, locular walls surrounding pollen-containing chambers providing mechanical protection during development, and specialized stomium zones along anther length representing predetermined rupture sites enabling controlled pollen release. ||Dehiscence mechanism involves coordinated processes including anther wall structural changes preparing opening, stomium zone activation triggering rupture, and mechanical forces driving pollen expulsion from locules creating liberation. ||Anther wall rupture proceeds through stomium zone breakdown with specialized cells undergoing programmed degeneration, cell wall dissolution creating longitudinal slits along anther length, and coordinated tissue failure producing clean opening enabling pollen access to exterior. ||Environmental triggering of dehiscence shows strong humidity dependence with declining humidity causing anther wall dehydration creating mechanical tension driving stomium opening, typically occurring during morning hours as temperature rises and humidity decreases, and repeated daily cycles creating characteristic diurnal pollen release pattern. ||Temperature effects on release show optimal 22-30°C supporting rapid efficient dehiscence and pollen liberation, cool conditions below 18°C substantially delaying dehiscence through slowed tissue processes, and warm conditions above 33°C potentially affecting pollen viability though generally facilitating mechanical opening. ||Pollen production per flower shows substantial investment with typical flower producing 20,000-60,000 pollen grains from five anthers representing 4,000-12,000 grains per anther, and cluster-level production reaching millions of grains creating abundant male gamete availability supporting effective pollination. ||Pollen characteristics affecting dispersal include small spheroidal grains 25-35 micrometers diameter enabling wind transport, relatively low density facilitating airborne suspension, and three-colporate aperture pattern providing germination sites on stigma contact. ||Pollen liberation from anthers proceeds through multiple mechanisms including initial explosive discharge when dehiscence occurs releasing pollen bolus, continued gravitational release as loosened pollen falls from opened locules, and wind-induced agitation dislodging remaining pollen creating extended release period. ||Pollen dispersal shows primarily wind-assisted mechanism with light grains easily becoming airborne through air currents, traveling distances from centimeters within flower to meters between vines depending on wind conditions, and creating characteristic pollen clouds visible surrounding flowering clusters during favorable dry conditions. ||Atmospheric pollen concentration during active release reaches maximum levels with estimated 100-1000 grains per cubic centimeter in immediate cluster vicinity under favorable conditions, declining with distance but remaining elevated 10-100 grains per cubic centimeter at vine scale, and providing abundant pollen availability for pollination. ||Pollen capture on stigmas occurs through wind transport delivering airborne grains to receptive stigma surfaces, adhesive stigma exudate trapping contacted grains, and physical stigma structure with papillate cells providing enhanced capture efficiency. ||Pollen viability timing shows maximum immediately upon release from freshly dehisced anthers with 70-90% germination capacity under optimal laboratory conditions, progressive decline over hours to days with viability reducing to 50-70% after 12 hours, 30-50% after 24 hours, and 10-30% after 48 hours, creating critical brief window for effective pollination. ||Environmental effects on viability include temperature with optimal 20-28°C maintaining viability while excessive heat above 35°C causes rapid loss through protein denaturation, humidity with moderate 40-70% maintaining hydration without promoting fungal growth, and rain catastrophically destroying viability through excessive hydration and physical washing. ||Self-pollination predominance in grapevine shows primary reproductive mode with majority of successful pollinations occurring within individual flowers through close anther-stigma proximity, supplemented by neighboring flower pollination within same cluster, and limited cross-pollination between vines playing minor role. ||Wind-assisted pollination efficiency varies with light-moderate wind 5-15 km per hour optimal for pollen dispersal enhancing pollination, calm conditions reducing dispersal though self-pollination remains effective, and strong wind above 25 km per hour potentially dispersing pollen excessively or causing desiccation. ||Pollen-stigma interactions following successful delivery show pollen grain hydration from stigma exudate within 15-90 minutes enabling metabolic activation, pollen recognition through molecular signals between coat proteins and stigma components, and germination initiation producing tube emergence within 1-4 hours under favorable conditions. ||Pollen tube growth following germination proceeds at 1-3 mm per hour through style transmitting tract, requiring 12-36 hours to traverse typical 15-30 mm style length, and delivering sperm cells to ovules enabling fertilization. ||Double fertilization following successful pollen tube arrival shows one sperm cell fusing with egg forming diploid zygote initiating embryo development, and other sperm fusing with polar nuclei forming triploid endosperm nucleus supporting seed development. ||Fruit set dependence on pollen release shows direct relationship between pollen availability, viability, and pollination success determining berry number, with favorable pollen release conditions supporting 50-70% fruit set in good-setting cultivars while impaired release reduces set to 20-40% or less. ||The process shows two major phases progressing from anther dehiscence establishing pollen liberation mechanism, through active pollen shedding creating maximum dispersal and pollination opportunity. ||Duration typically spans 5-10 days from first dehiscence through completion depending on flowering synchrony and environmental conditions, with warm stable conditions promoting compressed period while variable conditions extend duration. ||Cultivar variation appears in pollen production quantity affecting pollination potential, dehiscence timing and efficiency affecting release success, and pollen viability characteristics affecting reproductive outcomes. ||Regional timing shows pollen release during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with anthesis period and serving as critical male reproductive contribution. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential male reproductive function determining pollination success and fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions particularly temperature and humidity for efficient release and viability maintenance, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability with rain catastrophically affecting pollen function, and establishing male contribution as potential yield limitation in unfavorable conditions. ||Research applications include analyzing pollen production, maturation, and release mechanisms, investigating environmental effects on dehiscence and pollen viability affecting reproductive success, evaluating pollen dispersal patterns and pollination efficiency, quantifying relationships between pollen characteristics and fruit set outcomes, and assessing genetic variation in pollen function affecting reproductive reliability.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PPO_0001039 ## pollen-releasing inflorescence | 0.70" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 375-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-295 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Anther_Dehiscence": {
  "definition": "Anther dehiscence represents the anther opening process where specialized stomium zones undergo structural breakdown creating longitudinal slits enabling pollen liberation from enclosed locules, establishing essential mechanism for male gamete release during flowering.",
  "alternative_term": "anther opening | anther rupture | pollen sac opening | locule dehiscence |+ Antheren-Dehiszenz | Staubbeutelöffnung | Antheren-Ruptur | Pollensackaufbrechen",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows anther dehiscence during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65 over 7-9 days, with anthers progressively opening following cap fall predominantly during morning hours 9am-11am when humidity drops below 70%, creating longitudinal slits releasing abundant pollen, under continental conditions of 19-25°C temperature, 55-72% relative humidity with favorable morning decline, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar showing efficient dehiscence supporting 58-68% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Anther_Dehiscence is first major Pollen_Release phase establishing liberation mechanism through anther opening. ||Subdivided into Anther_Wall_Rupture, Stomium_Opening, and Initial_Pollen_Exposure. ||Highly dependent on environmental conditions particularly humidity and temperature. ||Occurs following cap fall and flower opening typically within hours to day. ||Essential for pollen availability. ||Failure causes severe reproductive failure and poor fruit set. ||Transitions to Active_Pollen_Shedding as pollen liberates and disperses. || This critical opening process occurs during early-mid flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 5-10 days as anthers progressively dehisce following cap fall and flower opening throughout cluster, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 stages. ||Dehiscence mechanism involves coordinated structural and physiological processes including anther wall maturation preparing opening, stomium zone activation triggering rupture, and mechanical forces driving slit formation enabling pollen access to exterior. ||Anther wall structure includes multiple tissue layers with outer epidermis providing protection, middle fibrous layer with hygroscopic properties creating mechanical tension, inner tapetum layer having degenerating by dehiscence, and endothecium cells with thickened walls except at stomium providing structural framework. ||Stomium zone represents specialized tissue region extending longitudinally along anther where cells lack wall thickening making tissue mechanically weak, predetermined rupture site positioned to enable effective pollen release, and cell breakdown mechanism involving enzymatic wall degradation creating opening. ||Anther maturation preceding dehiscence shows progressive color change from green toward yellow-brown indicating approaching readiness, tissue dehydration creating mechanical properties enabling rupture, and cytoplasmic changes in stomium cells preparing breakdown. ||Dehiscence triggering shows strong environmental dependence with humidity decrease causing anther wall dehydration critical for creating mechanical tension, temperature affecting tissue properties and enzymatic activity, and typically occurring during morning hours 8am-12pm as conditions become favorable. ||Humidity threshold effects show dehiscence typically initiating when relative humidity drops below 70-75% enabling sufficient anther dehydration, high humidity above 75% substantially delaying or preventing dehiscence through maintained tissue hydration, and optimal 45-65% humidity facilitating efficient opening. ||Temperature effects on dehiscence show optimal 22-30°C supporting rapid efficient opening, cool conditions below 18°C substantially delaying dehiscence through slowed processes and maintained tissue hydration, and warm conditions above 30°C generally facilitating mechanical rupture though potentially affecting pollen viability. ||Mechanical dehiscence process involves differential tissue shrinkage with hygroscopic fibrous layer contracting as dehydration proceeds creating tension, stomium zone unable to resist mechanical stress due to weak cell walls, and tissue rupture creating longitudinal slit typically 2-4 mm length along anther. ||Rupture propagation shows progressive slit extension along stomium zone as mechanical stress increases, coordinated opening of both anther locules creating two parallel slits, and complete opening exposing pollen mass to exterior enabling liberation. ||Pollen liberation following dehiscence proceeds through initial explosive discharge as pressure release ejects pollen bolus from locule creating immediate pollen cloud, continued gravitational release as loosened pollen falls from opened anther over hours, and wind-assisted release as air movement agitates anthers dislodging remaining pollen. ||Anther positioning affects pollen release efficiency with anthers typically oriented laterally or downward facilitating gravitational pollen fall, positioning relative to stigma supporting self-pollination through close proximity, and overall spatial arrangement optimizing pollen transfer within flower. ||Dehiscence timing relative to stigma receptivity shows coordination with stigma receptivity typically developing within 6-24 hours after flower opening and cap fall, anther dehiscence often occurring concurrently or within similar timeframe, and temporal overlap creating pollination window with coordinated male-female reproductive readiness. ||Dehiscence progression throughout cluster follows developmental gradient with apical flowers showing earliest dehiscence reflecting earliest maturation, progressive extension to middle then basal regions creating sequential opening pattern, and overall 5-10 day period encompassing cluster-level dehiscence completion. ||Synchronization during peak flowering shows coordinated dehiscence in numerous flowers creating maximum pollen availability, favorable environmental conditions enabling widespread simultaneous opening, and concentrated pollen release supporting optimal pollination opportunity. ||Environmental effects on dehiscence efficiency include stable favorable conditions promoting normal opening across all flowers, variable conditions causing irregular dehiscence potentially reducing pollination efficiency, and unfavorable conditions particularly sustained high humidity or rain preventing dehiscence causing severe reproductive failure. ||Rain effects on dehiscence show catastrophic interference with water preventing anther opening through maintained hydration eliminating mechanical tension, washing pollen from any dehisced anthers, and promoting fungal infection on wet reproductive tissues, with rain during peak flowering potentially reducing fruit set by 50-80%. ||Incomplete dehiscence problems occur when stomium opening fails or proceeds partially, creating limited pollen liberation reducing pollination potential, associated with unfavorable environmental conditions or developmental abnormalities, and contributing to poor fruit set through male reproductive failure. ||Pollen viability at dehiscence shows maximum capacity immediately upon release with fresh pollen showing 70-90% germination under optimal conditions, rapid decline beginning immediately with viability reducing 5-10% per hour initially, and critical importance of efficient rapid pollination during brief high-viability window. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from anther wall rupture initiating opening, through stomium opening creating access pathway, to initial pollen exposure establishing liberation. ||Duration spans 5-10 days at cluster level as anthers progressively dehisce, with individual anther opening occurring within minutes to hours once triggered. ||Cultivar variation in dehiscence shows differences in anther maturation timing affecting dehiscence onset, dehiscence efficiency with some varieties showing robust opening while others show incomplete opening problems, and coordination with stigma receptivity affecting pollination opportunity. ||Regional timing shows anther dehiscence during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with flowering period and enabling pollination. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential male reproductive function determining pollen availability for pollination, requiring favorable environmental conditions particularly appropriate humidity for efficient opening, demonstrating extreme weather sensitivity with rain preventing dehiscence causing severe fruit set failure, and establishing anther function as critical yield determinant. ||Research applications include analyzing dehiscence mechanisms including structural, physiological, and environmental triggers, evaluating environmental effects on dehiscence efficiency affecting pollen liberation, investigating genetic variation in anther function affecting reproductive reliability, quantifying relationships between dehiscence characteristics and fruit set outcomes, and assessing management or environmental interventions affecting dehiscence success.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 375-380 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-290"
},

  "Anther_Wall_Rupture": {
  "definition": "Anther wall rupture represents the initial structural failure in anther dehiscence when mechanical stresses exceed tissue strength creating opening in specialized stomium zones, initiating pollen liberation process through breach of protective anther wall.",
  "alternative_term": "anther wall breaking | stomium rupture | anther splitting | locule opening |+ Antherenwand-Ruptur | Staubbeutelwandaufbruch | Stomium-Bruch | Antheren-Spaltung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows anther wall rupture during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with anther walls failing along stomium zones when morning humidity drops below 68% and temperature reaches 24-26°C creating mechanical stress exceeding tissue strength, rupture creating 2.5-3.5 mm longitudinal slits exposing pollen mass, under Mediterranean conditions with favorable morning dehydration enabling efficient rupture throughout cluster typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Anther_Wall_Rupture is first aspect of Anther_Dehiscence, distinguished by initial structural failure creating opening. ||Represents mechanical event driven by dehydration stress. ||Occurs at specialized stomium zone predetermined weak tissue. ||Requires favorable environmental conditions particularly humidity decline. ||Brief seconds to minutes duration once triggered. ||Followed by Stomium_Opening discussing tissue specialization and Initial_Pollen_Exposure. ||Essential first step enabling pollen liberation. ||Failure prevents pollen release causing reproductive failure. || This critical mechanical event occurs during anther dehiscence in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically occurring within minutes to hours once conditions trigger rupture as part of BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Mechanical stress accumulation preceding rupture involves tissue dehydration causing volumetric shrinkage, differential contraction in hygroscopic fibrous layer creating tension, and stomium zone experiencing concentrated stress due to structural weakness representing predetermined failure site. ||Tissue dehydration driving rupture shows progressive water loss from anther wall tissues as environmental humidity decreases and temperature rises, hygroscopic fibrous layer cells containing cellulose microfibrils oriented to contract upon dehydration creating directional mechanical force, and inner wall layers shrinking differentially creating shearing stresses at stomium interface. ||Stomium zone vulnerability results from specialized structure with cells lacking secondary wall thickening found in adjacent tissues, mechanical weakness making tissue unable to resist mounting stress, and positioning along anther length providing optimal location for longitudinal slit formation enabling pollen access. ||Critical stress threshold shows rupture occurring when accumulated mechanical stress exceeds stomium tissue tensile strength estimated 0.3-0.8 MPa, threshold varying with tissue maturation state and hydration level, and rapid humidity decline enabling faster stress accumulation triggering earlier rupture. ||Rupture initiation typically begins at localized point along stomium zone where stress concentration or tissue weakness creates failure nucleus, crack propagation proceeding longitudinally along weak stomium tissue driven by relieved stress, and bilateral opening as both sides of ruptured stomium separate exposing locule interior. ||Rupture morphology shows characteristic longitudinal slit typically 2-4 mm length extending along anther corresponding to stomium zone length, clean separation along predetermined pathway indicating controlled failure mechanism, and slit width 0.3-0.8 mm sufficient for pollen grain passage 25-35 micrometers diameter. ||Acoustic evidence of rupture includes occasional audible sounds during intensive synchronized dehiscence though typically inaudible at individual anther level, possible detection of micro-acoustic emissions using sensitive equipment, and overall evidence of sudden mechanical failure creating brief energy release. ||Visual evidence of rupture shows sudden appearance of opening along previously intact anther, exposure of yellow pollen mass within locule becoming visible through slit, and immediate beginning of pollen liberation through opened pathway. ||Pollen pressure contribution to rupture remains uncertain with possible modest role for turgor-based pressure within locule assisting rupture propagation, though primary driving force clearly mechanical stress from differential tissue shrinkage, and pollen liberation following rather than driving initial rupture. ||Environmental conditions enabling rupture include declining relative humidity below 70-75% creating sufficient dehydration for stress accumulation, rising temperature accelerating dehydration and affecting tissue mechanical properties, and typically morning hours providing optimal conditions as humidity drops and temperature rises. ||Temperature effects on rupture show warm conditions 24-30°C facilitating rapid tissue dehydration enabling faster stress accumulation and rupture, cool conditions 15-20°C slowing dehydration potentially delaying rupture for hours or preventing if humidity remains elevated, and optimal temperature-humidity combination creating favorable rupture conditions. ||Humidity threshold for rupture shows critical decline below 70-75% typically required for initiating rupture in mature anthers, sustained high humidity above 75% preventing sufficient dehydration maintaining tissue strength above failure threshold, and optimal 50-65% humidity enabling efficient rupture throughout cluster. ||Tissue maturation requirements show properly matured anther walls with completed development of fibrous layer hygroscopic properties necessary for effective dehydration-driven stress, premature rupture attempts in immature anthers potentially failing or producing incomplete opening, and over-mature senescent anthers potentially showing irregular rupture or retention. ||Rupture timing relative to cap fall shows characteristic sequence with cap shedding typically preceding rupture by hours to day as flower opens first, anther maturation and conditioning requiring brief period before dehiscence readiness, and favorable environmental conditions triggering rupture once thresholds reached. ||Rupture propagation rate shows rapid crack extension once initiated typically completing within seconds to minutes, coordinated opening of both locules per anther creating paired slits, and sequential rupture throughout cluster as individual anthers reach critical conditions. ||Failed rupture causes incomplete dehiscence with partial opening providing limited pollen access reducing liberation efficiency, or complete failure maintaining closed anther preventing any pollen release, resulting from unfavorable conditions particularly sustained high humidity or inadequate tissue maturation. ||The process represents first aspect of anther dehiscence establishing breach in protective wall, followed by stomium opening discussing specialized tissue and initial pollen exposure revealing grains. ||Duration represents brief mechanical event occurring within seconds to minutes once triggered. ||Cultivar variation in rupture characteristics may include tissue mechanical properties affecting rupture threshold, anther wall structure affecting failure pattern, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting rupture efficiency. ||Regional timing shows anther wall rupture during flowering period late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, occurring as anthers reach maturity and conditions become favorable. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical mechanical event enabling pollen liberation, demonstrating extreme environmental dependence requiring favorable humidity and temperature, and establishing rupture failure as potential cause of poor fruit set through prevented pollen release. ||Research applications include analyzing mechanical and structural basis of rupture, evaluating environmental effects on rupture triggering and efficiency, investigating tissue maturation requirements for successful rupture, quantifying rupture dynamics and propagation, and assessing genetic variation in anther structure affecting rupture reliability.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-290 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 376-380"
},

  "Stomium_Opening": {
  "definition": "A Stomium_Opening is an Anther_Dehiscence comprising the coordinated degradation of cells at predetermined rupture sites in the anther wall producing longitudinal slits.",
  "alternative_term": "stomium breakdown | dehiscence zone opening | specialized rupture site | stomium dehiscence |+ Stomium-Öffnung | Dehiszenzzonenaufbruch | spezialisierte Bruchstelle | Stomium-Zusammenbruch",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows stomium opening during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with specialized thin-walled cell bands undergoing coordinated breakdown when humidity drops below 65% creating 2.8-3.8 mm longitudinal slits exposing pollen, stomium tissue degradation proceeding over 15-45 minutes, under warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature enabling efficient enzymatic and mechanical opening typical of this late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Stomium_Opening is second aspect of Anther_Dehiscence, distinguished by focus on specialized tissue breakdown mechanism. ||Represents controlled failure pathway enabling effective pollen release. ||Involves coordinated enzymatic degradation and mechanical stress. ||Requires proper maturation and favorable environmental conditions. ||Minutes to hours duration as tissue breakdown proceeds. ||Overlaps with Anther_Wall_Rupture and Initial_Pollen_Exposure. ||Critical specialized mechanism ensuring reproductive success. || This critical tissue-level process occurs during anther dehiscence in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over minutes to hours as stomium zone cells complete breakdown following mechanical stress accumulation, as part of BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Stomium anatomical specialization shows distinctive tissue structure with cells arranged in longitudinal bands along anther length typically 2-4 mm corresponding to locule length, cells lacking secondary wall thickening found in adjacent endothecium providing mechanical weakness, and thin-walled cellular organization creating predetermined failure pathway. ||Stomium cell characteristics include elongated cells oriented longitudinally facilitating longitudinal rupture propagation, thin primary walls susceptible to mechanical failure and enzymatic degradation, and reduced lignification compared to adjacent tissues making cells vulnerable to breakdown. ||Stomium positioning shows strategic location along anther length positioned to enable effective pollen release once opened, typically on anther face directed outward or laterally facilitating pollen dispersal, and bilateral arrangement with stomium on both locules creating paired slits for complete anther opening. ||Cellular breakdown mechanism involves multiple processes including enzymatic wall degradation weakening cell adhesion, mechanical stress causing physical cell separation, and possible programmed cell death contributing to tissue failure, creating coordinated stomium opening. ||Enzymatic activity during opening includes cellulase enzymes degrading cellulose wall components, pectinase and polygalacturonase breaking down pectin in middle lamella reducing cell adhesion, and possible xyloglucan-modifying enzymes affecting wall polysaccharides, enabling tissue separation. ||Mechanical forces driving opening include differential shrinkage in adjacent hygroscopic tissues creating shearing stress concentrated at stomium, turgor changes possibly contributing to stress though primary force mechanical, and accumulated stress exceeding reduced tissue strength causing failure. ||Opening progression shows initial localized failure at weak point in stomium zone creating nucleus for crack propagation, rapid extension along weakened tissue driven by relieved stress and continuing enzymatic activity, and bilateral opening as stomium separates exposing both locules to exterior. ||Slit characteristics following stomium opening include longitudinal orientation along anther length facilitating pollen release along extended pathway, width 0.3-0.8 mm providing adequate passage for pollen grains 25-35 micrometers diameter, and clean edges indicating controlled separation along predetermined pathway rather than random tearing. ||Pollen exposure following opening shows immediate visualization of yellow pollen mass within locules, beginning of gravitational pollen fall from opened anthers, and establishment of pathway enabling continued pollen liberation over subsequent hours. ||Stomium maturation requirements show proper development of specialized cellular structure necessary for functioning, completion of enzymatic systems enabling degradation, and appropriate dehydration state creating mechanical stress conditions, with premature or incomplete maturation potentially causing opening failure. ||Environmental triggering of opening involves humidity decrease causing tissue dehydration creating mechanical stress exceeding reduced stomium strength, temperature affecting enzymatic activity and tissue mechanical properties, and optimal conditions combining to trigger coordinated opening. ||Humidity effects show declining relative humidity below 70-75% typically required for sufficient mechanical stress driving stomium failure, sustained high humidity above 75% preventing adequate stress accumulation maintaining tissue integrity, and rapid humidity decrease potentially causing more synchronized opening through simultaneous stress threshold achievement. ||Temperature effects include warm conditions 24-30°C promoting enzymatic activity accelerating wall degradation and facilitating tissue dehydration driving mechanical stress, cool conditions 15-20°C slowing enzymatic processes and reducing dehydration potentially delaying or preventing opening, and optimal 22-28°C range supporting efficient coordinated opening. ||Diurnal pattern shows characteristic morning opening as humidity declines and temperature rises creating favorable conditions, peak opening activity typically 9am-12pm in temperate climates, and daily rhythm with repeated opening events across cluster as successive flowers reach appropriate conditions. ||Stomium opening coordination with anther wall rupture shows essentially simultaneous processes with mechanical rupture and stomium breakdown representing different aspects of unified opening mechanism, stomium tissue providing predetermined weak pathway for rupture propagation, and coordinated structural and cellular processes producing effective anther dehiscence. ||Failed stomium opening causes incomplete dehiscence with partial opening providing limited pollen access or complete failure preventing pollen liberation, resulting from inadequate maturation, unfavorable environmental conditions, or tissue abnormalities, and contributing to poor fruit set through impaired male function. ||The process represents second aspect of anther dehiscence emphasizing specialized tissue breakdown, following anther wall rupture and overlapping with initial pollen exposure. ||Duration spans minutes to hours as coordinated tissue breakdown proceeds. ||Cultivar variation in stomium characteristics may include tissue structure affecting opening efficiency, enzymatic capacity affecting degradation rate, and environmental sensitivity affecting opening reliability. ||Regional timing shows stomium opening during flowering period coinciding with favorable morning conditions across all climates when humidity declines and temperature rises triggering coordinated opening. ||Viticultural significance includes representing specialized mechanism ensuring controlled effective pollen release, requiring favorable environmental conditions for efficient functioning, and demonstrating importance of appropriate anther development for reproductive success. ||Research applications include analyzing stomium anatomical specialization and functional significance, investigating cellular and molecular mechanisms of tissue breakdown, evaluating environmental effects on opening efficiency, quantifying enzymatic and mechanical contributions to dehiscence, and assessing genetic variation in stomium structure and function affecting reproductive reliability.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 377-380 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-290"
},

  "Initial_Pollen_Exposure": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Pollen_Exposure is a Pollen_Release characterized by the first accessibility of mature pollen grains within anther locules following stomium opening.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen visibility | initial pollen revelation | pollen mass exposure | first pollen access |+ initiale Pollenexposition | Pollensichtbarkeit | Pollenmassenfreilegung | erste Pollenzugänglichkeit",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows initial pollen exposure during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with yellow pollen masses becoming visible through 2.5-3.2 mm anther slits following morning dehiscence 9am-11am, explosive discharge releasing 15-25% pollen content immediately followed by gravitational and wind-assisted liberation, under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 58-70% relative humidity, typical of this early-bursting cultivar exposing abundant pollen supporting 64-76% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Pollen_Exposure is third and final aspect of Anther_Dehiscence, distinguished by revealing pollen making it accessible for liberation. ||Follows Anther_Wall_Rupture and Stomium_Opening. ||Marks transition from enclosed to accessible pollen beginning active release phase. ||Represents critical moment enabling pollination. ||Brief minutes to hours as exposure occurs and initial liberation begins. ||Transitions to Active_Pollen_Shedding as sustained dispersal proceeds. ||Essential event establishing male reproductive function. || This critical exposure event occurs during anther dehiscence in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically within minutes to hours following stomium opening as part of BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Exposure mechanism involves anther wall rupture creating longitudinal slits exposing locule interior, separation of slit edges revealing yellow pollen mass within locules, and immediate beginning of pollen liberation through opened pathway enabling atmospheric access. ||Visual characteristics at exposure include sudden appearance of yellow-brown pollen mass visible through anther slits, contrast between exposed pollen and surrounding anther wall tissues, and characteristic color change in anthers from green or pale toward yellow-brown indicating pollen maturity and exposure. ||Pollen mass organization at exposure shows grains loosely aggregated within locules from degenerated tapetum remains, initial adhesion in small clumps before individual grain separation, and progressive loosening facilitating liberation and dispersal. ||Initial pollen liberation following exposure proceeds through multiple mechanisms including explosive discharge when rupture occurs releasing pollen bolus from locule pressure, gravitational fall as loosened pollen drops from opened anther under gravity, and beginning wind-induced release as air movement agitates anthers dislodging pollen grains. ||Explosive discharge characteristics show initial sudden pollen ejection when dehiscence occurs potentially dispersing pollen 5-15 mm from anther, brief explosive phase lasting seconds producing immediate pollen cloud, and representing 10-30% total pollen content with remainder requiring gravitational or wind-assisted liberation. ||Gravitational release following explosive phase shows continuous slow pollen fall from opened anthers over minutes to hours, positioning of anthers affecting fall pattern with lateral or downward orientation facilitating release, and accumulation of fallen pollen on flower structures or direct capture by nearby stigmas. ||Environmental effects on initial exposure include humidity at rupture affecting pollen hydration state with moderate 50-65% optimal for maintaining viability without promoting aggregation, temperature affecting pollen surface properties and liberation efficiency, and air movement affecting dispersal pattern from exposed mass. ||Pollen viability at initial exposure shows maximum capacity immediately upon exposure with fresh pollen exhibiting 75-90% germination under optimal conditions, brief window of peak viability lasting hours before progressive decline, and critical importance of rapid pollination during this optimal period. ||Pollen surface characteristics at exposure include intact exine wall with sculptured surface patterns, slight moisture content from locule environment maintaining viability without excessive hydration, and pollen coating substances from tapetum residues potentially affecting dispersal and stigma adhesion. ||Pollen grain separation at exposure shows progressive disaggregation from initial clumped state within locule, individual grain liberation enabling airborne dispersal, and mechanical agitation from wind or flower movement facilitating separation and release. ||Timing relationships show initial exposure occurring immediately following successful dehiscence typically within minutes, exposure of first anthers coinciding with early anthesis in apical flowers, and progressive exposure throughout cluster over 5-10 days as anthers sequentially dehisce. ||Atmospheric pollen introduction shows initial grains entering air surrounding flower creating beginning of pollen cloud, progressive accumulation as additional anthers expose pollen intensifying atmospheric concentration, and peak atmospheric levels coinciding with mass dehiscence during peak flowering. ||Capture opportunity following exposure includes pollen falling directly onto stigma in same flower facilitating self-pollination, pollen dispersing to neighboring flowers on same cluster, and airborne pollen traveling to more distant flowers or vines though most successful pollinations occur locally. ||Self-pollination efficiency at initial exposure shows high probability through close anther-stigma proximity typically 0.5-1.5 mm spatial separation, gravitational pollen fall naturally directing toward centrally positioned stigma, and immediate pollen availability coinciding with stigma receptivity development. ||Stigma contact timing shows pollen-stigma encounter potentially occurring within minutes to hours of exposure through direct fall or brief dispersal, rapid germination initiation within 1-4 hours if stigma receptive and conditions favorable, and beginning of successful pollination events contributing to fruit set. ||Environmental effects on exposure success include favorable conditions enabling normal dehiscence and exposure supporting pollen liberation, rain during exposure washing pollen from anthers or preventing exposure through maintained humidity, and optimal temperature-humidity combination maximizing pollen function. ||Failed exposure results from incomplete dehiscence providing inadequate slit opening limiting pollen access, environmental conditions preventing normal rupture maintaining enclosed pollen, or abnormal anther development affecting exposure capability, all contributing to reduced pollination potential. ||The process represents third and final aspect of anther dehiscence marking transition from enclosed to accessible pollen, following anther wall rupture and stomium opening. ||Duration represents brief period from exposure through initial liberation typically minutes to hours. ||Cultivar variation in exposure characteristics may include pollen mass appearance reflecting production quantity and maturity, liberation efficiency from exposed anthers affecting dispersal, and coordination with stigma receptivity affecting pollination opportunity. ||Regional timing shows initial pollen exposure during flowering period across all climates coinciding with favorable morning conditions enabling dehiscence and exposure. ||Viticultural significance includes marking beginning of effective male reproductive function with pollen becoming available for pollination, representing critical transition enabling fertilization and fruit set, and demonstrating importance of favorable conditions during exposure for reproductive success. ||Research applications include analyzing pollen liberation mechanisms from exposed anthers, quantifying pollen release rates and patterns, evaluating environmental effects on liberation efficiency, assessing pollen-stigma encounter probabilities, and documenting exposure-pollination timing relationships affecting reproductive outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 378-382 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 288-292"
},

  "Active_Pollen_Shedding": {
  "definition": "An Active_Pollen_Shedding is a Pollen_Release involving sustained liberation of pollen from dehisced anthers through gravitational, mechanical, and wind-assisted dispersal.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen dispersal phase | sustained pollen release | active pollen distribution | peak pollen shedding |+ aktive Pollenabgabe | Pollendispersionsphase | nachhaltige Pollenfreisetzung | Spitzen-Pollenschüttung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows active pollen shedding during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 over 3-4 days June 9-12, with abundant pollen release from widespread anther dehiscence creating visible pollen clouds during favorable morning hours 9am-11am, atmospheric concentration estimated 300-800 grains per cubic centimeter near clusters, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature, 54-68% relative humidity, light winds 6-12 km per hour, supporting efficient pollination enabling 54-64% fruit set typical of this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Active_Pollen_Shedding is second major Pollen_Release phase distinguished by sustained dispersal creating maximum male gamete availability. ||Follows Anther_Dehiscence. ||Corresponds to BBCH 63-65 peak anthesis. ||Subdivided into Peak_Pollen_Discharge and Maximum_Pollen_Dispersal. ||Represents critical 3-5 day period determining majority of fruit set through pollination success. ||Environmental conditions particularly temperature, humidity, and wind critically affect efficiency. ||Extreme weather vulnerability to rain catastrophically affecting pollen function. ||Most important male reproductive phase. || This critical dispersal phase occurs during mid-peak flowering in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 3-5 days as widespread anther dehiscence creates intensive pollen release throughout cluster, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 peak anthesis stages. ||Shedding mechanisms involve multiple processes including continued gravitational pollen fall from opened anthers depositing grains over extended period, mechanical agitation from flower movement and environmental disturbances dislodging loosened pollen, and wind-induced dispersal carrying airborne pollen to receptive stigmas within and between flowers. ||Gravitational shedding shows persistent slow release as loosened pollen progressively falls from anther locules, positioning effects with laterally or downward-oriented anthers facilitating efficient gravitational release, and cumulative substantial pollen liberation over hours to days following initial explosive discharge. ||Mechanical shedding involves physical disturbances including wind-induced anther movement agitating structures dislodging pollen, insect visitation occasionally causing vibrations though insects play minor role in grapevine pollination, and environmental movements from temperature changes or growth processes creating subtle agitation. ||Wind-assisted dispersal shows primary pollen transport mechanism with light grains 25-35 micrometers diameter easily becoming airborne, air currents lifting pollen from anthers and transporting through atmosphere, and characteristic pollen clouds forming around flowering clusters during favorable conditions creating visible evidence of active shedding. ||Atmospheric pollen concentration during active shedding reaches maximum levels with estimated 100-1000 grains per cubic centimeter in immediate cluster vicinity under favorable conditions, declining concentration with distance but remaining elevated 10-100 grains per cubic centimeter at vine scale, and creating abundant male gamete availability supporting efficient pollination. ||Pollen cloud formation shows visible phenomenon during peak shedding under optimal dry conditions, appearance of pale yellow haze surrounding flowering clusters particularly evident during morning peak activity, and disappearance when humidity rises or wind calms indicating environmental dependence. ||Pollen dispersal patterns show primary deposition within same flower facilitating self-pollination accounting for 60-80% successful pollinations, neighboring flowers on same cluster receiving substantial pollen through short-distance dispersal, and limited long-distance transport between vines contributing minor proportion 5-15% to total pollinations. ||Pollen viability during active shedding shows maximum in freshly released pollen 75-90% germination capacity declining over time, atmospheric pollen showing progressive viability decline with aged airborne pollen showing 40-60% viability after several hours, and importance of continuous fresh pollen production maintaining viable atmospheric pool during shedding period. ||Environmental conditions optimizing shedding include temperature 24-30°C promoting anther dehydration facilitating continued release, moderate humidity 50-65% maintaining pollen viability without promoting excessive aggregation or preventing liberation, light wind 5-15 km per hour enhancing dispersal without causing excessive pollen loss or desiccation, and overall stable favorable weather enabling sustained efficient shedding. ||Temperature effects on shedding show warm conditions facilitating mechanical liberation through reduced tissue moisture and appropriate pollen surface properties, cool conditions potentially reducing shedding efficiency through maintained tissue hydration, and optimal thermal range supporting both liberation and viability maintenance. ||Humidity effects show critical importance with moderate levels 50-65% optimal for maintaining liberating pollen in dispersible state without aggregation while preserving viability, high humidity above 70% causing pollen aggregation reducing dispersal and potentially preventing continued liberation, and low humidity below 45% potentially causing excessive desiccation reducing viability though facilitating mechanical release. ||Wind effects show beneficial role for dispersal with light-moderate wind 5-15 km per hour optimal for pollen transport enhancing pollination efficiency, calm conditions reducing atmospheric transport though gravitational and short-range dispersal remaining effective for self-pollination, and excessive wind above 20 km per hour potentially dispersing pollen too far or causing rapid desiccation. ||Diurnal shedding pattern shows characteristic morning maximum as temperature rises and humidity declines creating optimal conditions typically 9am-12pm, reduced afternoon activity as conditions potentially become less favorable with rising temperature or changing humidity, and daily rhythm creating repeated peaks throughout active shedding period. ||Peak shedding intensity during mass flowering shows maximum pollen release when numerous anthers throughout cluster simultaneously shed pollen, coordinated timing creating concentrated pollination opportunity, and favorable synchronization supporting efficient pollination and high fruit set potential. ||Pollen production during active shedding continues from progressively dehiscing anthers maintaining fresh pollen availability, sequential opening pattern providing extended release period rather than single exhaustive discharge, and overall sustained male gamete supply supporting continued pollination opportunities. ||Pollination success during active shedding shows maximum efficiency with abundant fresh viable pollen, widespread stigma receptivity providing numerous capture opportunities, and optimal environmental conditions enabling effective pollen-stigma encounters, supporting fruit set 50-70% in good-setting cultivars under favorable conditions. ||Rain effects during active shedding show catastrophic interference with water washing pollen from anthers and atmosphere eliminating atmospheric pool, preventing continued shedding through elevated humidity maintaining tissue hydration, and destroying pollen viability through excessive hydration, potentially reducing fruit set to 15-30% if rain occurs during peak shedding. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from peak pollen discharge establishing maximum release intensity, through maximum pollen dispersal creating optimal atmospheric availability. ||Duration typically spans 3-5 days representing peak shedding period, with warm stable conditions promoting compressed intense shedding while variable conditions may extend period. ||Cultivar variation in shedding characteristics includes pollen production quantity affecting atmospheric concentration potential, shedding efficiency from anthers affecting liberation completeness, and timing coordination with stigma receptivity affecting pollination success. ||Regional timing shows active pollen shedding during mid-June in warm climates, mid-June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with peak flowering and maximum reproductive activity. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical male reproductive phase determining pollination success and fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions for efficient shedding and viability maintenance, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain during peak shedding, and establishing pollen availability as dominant factor determining fruit set outcomes. ||Research applications include analyzing shedding mechanisms and pollen liberation dynamics, quantifying atmospheric pollen concentrations and dispersal patterns, evaluating environmental effects on shedding efficiency and pollen viability, assessing pollination efficiency under varying shedding conditions, and developing models predicting fruit set from pollen shedding characteristics and environmental conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 290-295"
},

  "Peak_Pollen_Discharge": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Pollen_Discharge is an Active_Pollen_Shedding marked by simultaneous pollen liberation from the maximum proportion of anthers within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum pollen release | peak pollen liberation | highest pollen discharge | pollen release maximum |+ Spitzen-Pollenabgabe | maximale Pollenfreisetzung | höchste Pollenliberation | Pollenabgabemaximum",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows peak pollen discharge on June 10-11 Year N+1 at BBCH 65, with 58-72% anthers simultaneously releasing pollen creating visible pollen clouds during morning hours 9am-11am, atmospheric concentration estimated 700-1200 grains per cubic centimeter, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 26-30°C temperature, 48-62% relative humidity, light winds 7-13 km per hour, supporting intensive pollination enabling 52-66% fruit set typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar during optimal 1-2 day peak discharge determining majority yield",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Pollen_Discharge is first aspect of Active_Pollen_Shedding, distinguished by maximum liberation intensity. ||Represents culminating 1-2 day period of male reproductive activity. ||Corresponds to BBCH 65 full bloom. ||Creates visible pollen clouds under favorable conditions. ||Determines 40-55% fruit set during brief window. ||Extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain. ||Followed by Maximum_Pollen_Dispersal discussing atmospheric distribution. ||Most critical male reproductive period. || This culminating release intensity occurs during peak active shedding in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 1-2 days when widespread coordinated anther dehiscence creates maximum simultaneous pollen release, corresponding to BBCH 65 full bloom stage. ||Discharge intensity characteristics show maximum daily pollen release with 40-70% anthers actively discharging pollen simultaneously creating peak liberation activity, cumulative effect of sustained shedding from recently dehisced anthers maintaining high atmospheric concentration, and peak representing optimal coordination of male reproductive capacity. ||Anther distribution at peak shows dehisced anthers throughout cluster with apical regions showing 70-90% anthers discharged from earliest maturation, middle regions showing 60-80% active discharge representing highest density of recently opened anthers, and basal regions showing 40-60% beginning discharge creating overall maximum cluster-level pollen availability. ||Pollen liberation rate at peak shows maximum output with continuous release from numerous anthers creating sustained high-intensity shedding, estimated individual anther releasing 50-70% total pollen content during first hours following dehiscence, and cluster-level production reaching millions of grains per hour during peak activity. ||Atmospheric pollen concentration at peak reaches maximum levels with estimated 500-1500 grains per cubic centimeter in immediate cluster vicinity under optimal conditions representing 5-10 fold increase above background, visible pollen clouds forming around flowering clusters under favorable dry conditions, and elevated concentrations 50-200 grains per cubic centimeter extending vine scale supporting efficient pollination. ||Visual appearance at peak discharge shows characteristic pollen cloud phenomenon with pale yellow haze visible surrounding flowering clusters, particularly evident during morning hours 9am-11am when discharge typically maximal, and obvious pollen fall visible as fine dust accumulating on surfaces below clusters. ||Pollen cloud dynamics show formation during favorable conditions when temperature 24-30°C and humidity 50-65% enable efficient liberation and airborne suspension, maximum visibility during peak discharge when release intensity highest, and dissipation when wind disperses pollen or humidity rises causing aggregation and settling. ||Temporal pattern at peak shows characteristic morning maximum coinciding with optimal environmental conditions as temperature rises and humidity declines, typical peak activity 9am-12pm in temperate regions, and daily rhythm with repeated peak periods throughout 1-2 day maximum discharge phase. ||Environmental conditions at peak include temperature 24-30°C optimal for maximum discharge through efficient tissue dehydration and pollen liberation, moderate humidity 50-65% maintaining pollen viability and dispersibility without aggregation or prevented liberation, light-moderate wind 6-14 km per hour enhancing dispersal without excessive loss, and overall stable favorable weather enabling sustained intensive discharge. ||Temperature effects on peak discharge show warm conditions promoting maximum liberation through optimal tissue mechanics and pollen surface properties, cool conditions potentially reducing discharge intensity, and excessive heat above 32°C potentially affecting pollen viability though generally facilitating release. ||Humidity effects show critical importance with moderate levels optimal for maintaining high discharge rate and pollen viability, elevated humidity above 70% potentially reducing discharge through maintained anther hydration and causing pollen aggregation, and low humidity below 45% potentially causing excessive desiccation affecting viability though facilitating liberation. ||Wind effects show beneficial role with light-moderate wind enhancing dispersal creating better distribution and potentially agitating anthers dislodging additional pollen, calm conditions allowing pollen cloud formation though reducing long-range dispersal, and strong wind potentially dispersing pollen excessively reducing local availability. ||Pollen viability at peak discharge shows maximum proportion of viable grains with fresh pollen exhibiting 75-90% germination capacity, continuous production maintaining viable atmospheric pool, and brief window of optimal viability before progressive decline affects aged airborne pollen. ||Pollination opportunity at peak reaches absolute optimum with maximum fresh viable pollen availability creating abundant male gametes, widespread stigma receptivity providing numerous capture targets, and favorable spatial and temporal conditions supporting efficient pollen-stigma encounters, enabling fruit set 55-75% in good-setting cultivars under optimal conditions. ||Fruit set determination at peak shows outcomes during this critical 1-2 day period contributing 40-55% total berry number representing single largest contribution period, making peak discharge conditions dominant influence on season yield similar to overall peak anthesis window. ||Coordinated discharge at peak suggests possible synchronization mechanisms with developmental uniformity producing anthers reaching maturity simultaneously, common environmental responses triggering coordinated dehiscence as conditions become favorable, and possible physiological coordination though mechanisms unclear, creating concentrated male reproductive activity. ||Self-pollination efficiency at peak maximizes through immediate pollen availability in same flower with freshly released pollen falling directly onto nearby stigma, close anther-stigma proximity facilitating rapid encounter, and continued discharge maintaining pollen supply for extended receptivity period. ||Neighboring flower pollination at peak intensifies through abundant atmospheric pollen dispersing short distances within cluster, concentrated pollen availability creating high encounter probability, and coordinated timing supporting effective pollination between nearby synchronized flowers. ||Weather vulnerability at peak reaches maximum with reproductive success extremely sensitive to conditions during this brief 1-2 day window, favorable stable conditions supporting high fruit set while adverse weather particularly rain causing catastrophic failure potentially reducing set to 15-30%, demonstrating extreme importance of favorable conditions during peak discharge. ||The process represents first aspect of active pollen shedding focusing on maximum intensity, followed by maximum pollen dispersal emphasizing atmospheric distribution. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days representing peak intensity period, with warm stable conditions producing sharp intense peak while variable conditions may broaden or reduce intensity. ||Cultivar variation in peak discharge shows some varieties reaching very high intensity with coordinated massive release while others show moderate peak, timing relative to stigma receptivity peak affecting pollination efficiency, and discharge efficiency affecting atmospheric concentration achieved. ||Regional timing shows peak pollen discharge during mid-June in warm climates at approximately 1050-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 950-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 850-900 GDD, coinciding with peak anthesis and full bloom. ||Viticultural significance includes representing most critical male reproductive moment determining majority of fruit set, requiring optimal environmental conditions for maximum discharge efficiency and viability, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability with brief window determining season outcomes, and providing visual confirmation through pollen clouds of maximum reproductive activity. ||Research applications include analyzing peak discharge mechanisms and coordination, quantifying pollen production rates and atmospheric concentrations, evaluating environmental effects on discharge intensity, assessing pollination efficiency during peak period, and developing models predicting fruit set from peak discharge characteristics and conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 382-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 292-295"
},

  "Maximum_Pollen_Dispersal": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Pollen_Dispersal is an Active_Pollen_Shedding characterized by the maximum atmospheric concentration of airborne pollen grains across the cluster and vineyard.",
  "alternative_term": "optimal pollen distribution | peak pollen availability | maximum airborne pollen | highest pollen dispersal |+ maximale Pollendispersion | optimale Pollenverteilung | höchste Pollenverfügbarkeit | Spitzen-Pollenausbreitung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows maximum pollen dispersal during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 65 on June 10-11, with atmospheric concentration reaching 800-1400 grains per cubic centimeter near clusters creating visible pollen clouds, elevated 150-400 grains per cubic centimeter vine scale, dispersing effectively under warm climate conditions of 25-29°C temperature, 50-64% relative humidity, winds 8-14 km per hour, supporting efficient widespread pollination enabling 58-68% fruit set typical of this late-season cultivar during optimal 1-2 day dispersal window",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Pollen_Dispersal is second and final aspect of Active_Pollen_Shedding, distinguished by optimal atmospheric distribution creating widespread pollination opportunity. ||Follows or coincides with Peak_Pollen_Discharge. ||Represents culmination of male reproductive effort with maximum gamete availability. ||Duration 1-2 days during peak anthesis. ||Environmental conditions critically affect dispersal efficiency and pollen viability. ||Extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain. ||Determines majority of fruit set through pollination success. ||Completes Pollen_Release hierarchical documentation. || This critical distribution phase occurs during peak active shedding in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically coinciding with or immediately following peak discharge over 1-2 days, corresponding to BBCH 65 full bloom stage. ||Dispersal characteristics show maximum atmospheric pollen concentration with elevated grain density throughout cluster atmosphere and extending vineyard scale, optimal spatial distribution providing widespread pollen availability to receptive stigmas, and favorable temporal persistence maintaining viable atmospheric pool during receptivity period. ||Atmospheric pollen density at maximum dispersal reaches peak levels with estimated 500-1500 grains per cubic centimeter in immediate cluster vicinity representing 10-20 fold increase above baseline, elevated concentrations 100-500 grains per cubic centimeter at cluster-to-cluster scale within vine canopy, and significant concentrations 20-100 grains per cubic centimeter extending meters between adjacent vines. ||Spatial distribution pattern shows highest concentration immediately surrounding flowering clusters as pollen source, declining concentration with distance following roughly exponential decay pattern, and wind-direction bias creating asymmetric distribution with higher concentrations downwind of pollen sources. ||Vertical distribution shows maximum concentration at flowering cluster height typically 1-2 meters above ground corresponding to typical canopy positioning, declining concentration both above and below cluster zone, and ground-level deposition creating accumulated pollen layer on soil and vegetation surfaces. ||Temporal persistence at maximum dispersal shows sustained elevated atmospheric concentration over hours during favorable conditions as continued discharge replenishes dispersing pollen, diurnal pattern with morning maximum coinciding with peak discharge and favorable conditions, and overall maintenance of viable atmospheric pool supporting continued pollination throughout peak period. ||Pollen transport mechanisms include wind-driven advection as primary dispersal process with light grains easily transported through air currents, turbulent diffusion spreading pollen through atmospheric mixing, and gravitational settling gradually removing pollen from atmosphere with terminal velocity approximately 1-3 cm per second for grapevine pollen. ||Wind effects on dispersal show light-moderate wind 6-14 km per hour optimal for effective dispersal enhancing pollen distribution without excessive dilution, stronger wind above 20 km per hour potentially dispersing pollen too far reducing local concentration though increasing range, and calm conditions limiting dispersal range though maintaining high local concentration supporting self and neighboring flower pollination. ||Dispersal range shows majority of pollen depositing within same cluster or neighboring clusters on same vine accounting for 70-90% successful pollinations, inter-vine dispersal occurring at distances up to several meters contributing 10-20% pollinations, and long-range dispersal beyond 10 meters playing minimal role <5% in reproductive success. ||Pollen capture efficiency varies with location showing highest capture on receptive stigmas within same cluster through combined gravitational fall and short-range wind transport, moderate capture on neighboring clusters through short-range dispersal, and low capture at distances beyond few meters due to dilution and deposition. ||Stigma encounter probability during maximum dispersal reaches optimum with abundant atmospheric pollen creating high probability of contact with any exposed stigma, estimated 10-50 pollen grains contacting individual receptive stigma during peak dispersal period though only 1-2 successful germinations required for fertilization, and favorable spatial-temporal coincidence supporting efficient pollination. ||Pollen viability during dispersal shows maximum proportion of viable grains in freshly released pollen with 75-90% germination capacity, progressive decline in atmospheric pollen as aging proceeds with viability reducing 5-10% per hour, and importance of continuous fresh pollen production maintaining viable atmospheric pool offsetting viability decline. ||Environmental conditions optimizing dispersal include temperature 24-30°C supporting both pollen viability and favorable atmospheric mixing, moderate humidity 50-65% maintaining pollen dispersibility without aggregation while preserving viability, light-moderate wind providing optimal transport, and overall stable conditions enabling sustained effective dispersal. ||Humidity effects on dispersal show moderate levels optimal for maintaining pollen in dispersible state without aggregation that would cause premature atmospheric removal, high humidity above 70% causing pollen clumping reducing airborne suspension and effective dispersal, and low humidity below 45% potentially causing excessive desiccation affecting viability though maintaining good dispersibility. ||Temperature effects include warm conditions generally favorable for dispersal through appropriate air density and mixing characteristics, though extreme heat above 33°C potentially affecting pollen viability during extended atmospheric residence, and optimal thermal range supporting both dispersal mechanics and pollen function. ||Pollen cloud visualization during maximum dispersal enables easy observation of male reproductive activity with visible pale yellow haze surrounding flowering clusters under optimal conditions, particularly evident during morning peak when discharge maximal and conditions favorable, and providing immediate visual confirmation of intensive pollination opportunity. ||Deposition patterns show characteristic distribution with highest accumulation on horizontal surfaces within and below canopy including leaves, shoot structures, and ground surfaces, visible yellow dust layer creating obvious evidence of flowering activity, and accumulated pollen representing unsuccessful fraction not captured by stigmas. ||Pollination success during maximum dispersal reaches peak levels with abundant fresh viable pollen widely distributed, extensive stigma receptivity providing numerous capture opportunities, and favorable environmental conditions supporting pollen-stigma encounters and subsequent germination, enabling fruit set 55-75% in good-setting cultivars under optimal conditions. ||Self-pollination efficiency maximizes during dispersal through immediate local pollen availability with freshly released grains falling directly onto stigmas in same flower, though atmospheric pool also contributes to self-pollination through brief airborne transport and return. ||Cross-pollination contribution during maximum dispersal shows limited but measurable role with atmospheric pollen dispersing between neighboring flowers on same cluster accounting for 20-40% successful pollinations, inter-vine dispersal contributing 5-15% particularly in dense plantings, and long-range cross-pollination between distant vines playing minimal role though demonstrating gene flow potential. ||Weather impacts on dispersal show catastrophic effects of rain with water washing pollen from atmosphere eliminating atmospheric pool, preventing continued discharge through elevated humidity, and destroying pollen viability, causing severe fruit set reduction potentially to 15-30% if rain occurs during maximum dispersal period. ||The process represents second and final aspect of active pollen shedding emphasizing atmospheric distribution and pollination opportunity, following peak pollen discharge. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days coinciding with peak discharge representing optimal dispersal window. ||Cultivar variation in dispersal characteristics includes pollen production affecting maximum atmospheric concentration achievable, dispersal range possibly varying with pollen surface properties though poorly documented, and timing coordination with stigma receptivity affecting pollination efficiency. ||Regional timing shows maximum pollen dispersal during mid-June in warm climates, mid-June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with peak anthesis and representing most critical reproductive period. ||Viticultural significance includes representing optimal pollination opportunity with maximum male gamete availability and distribution, requiring favorable environmental conditions for effective dispersal and pollen viability maintenance, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability with brief window determining majority of season yield, and providing visual confirmation through pollen clouds of successful male reproductive function. ||Research applications include quantifying atmospheric pollen concentrations and spatial distributions, analyzing dispersal mechanisms and ranges, evaluating environmental effects on dispersal efficiency, assessing pollen-stigma encounter probabilities and pollination success, developing dispersal models for predicting pollination outcomes, and investigating gene flow patterns through pollen-mediated dispersal.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 383-390 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 293-298"
},

  "Peak_Pollen_Release": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Pollen_Release is a Pollen_Release consisting of the concurrent maximum of anther dehiscence, pollen discharge, and atmospheric dispersal.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen release peak | maximum pollen production phase | optimal pollen release period | culminating male reproduction |+ Spitzen-Pollenfreisetzung | maximale Pollenproduktionsphase | optimale Pollenabgabeperiode | männlicher Reproduktionshöhepunkt",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows peak pollen release during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 over 2-3 days June 8-10, with 58-72% anthers simultaneously discharging creating visible pollen clouds during morning hours, atmospheric concentration 600-1100 grains per cubic centimeter, fresh pollen viability 78-88%, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, 54-68% relative humidity, light winds 7-12 km per hour, supporting optimal pollination enabling 60-70% fruit set typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar during critical 2-3 day peak determining majority yield",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Pollen_Release represents culminating male reproductive phase parallel to Peak_Anthesis within Flowering. ||Corresponds to BBCH 63-65 stages. ||Subdivided into Optimal_Pollen_Cloud_Formation and Maximum_Pollen_Availability. ||Represents most critical 2-3 days for male contribution to fruit set determining 50-70% berry number. ||Extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain. ||Requires optimal coordination of dehiscence, discharge, dispersal, and viability. ||Temporal alignment with peak stigma receptivity creates optimal pollination window. ||Most important male reproductive period. || This critical male reproductive culmination occurs during peak flowering in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 2-3 days when widespread coordinated pollen liberation creates maximum male gamete availability, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 peak anthesis stages. ||Peak characteristics show simultaneous occurrence of optimal male reproductive elements including widespread anther dehiscence with 50-75% anthers actively releasing pollen, maximum pollen discharge intensity producing abundant fresh viable grains, optimal atmospheric pollen concentration creating 500-1500 grains per cubic centimeter near clusters, and favorable environmental conditions supporting pollen viability and dispersal. ||Temporal coordination at peak shows critical convergence of male reproductive capacities with peak discharge timing coinciding with maximum atmospheric dispersal capability, sustained intensive pollen production maintaining viable atmospheric pool, and optimal overlap with widespread stigma receptivity creating ideal pollination window. ||Pollen production intensity reaches maximum at peak with numerous anthers simultaneously discharging creating cumulative cluster-level production estimated millions of grains per hour, continuous fresh pollen release maintaining viable atmospheric supply, and overall male gamete availability sufficient for supporting high fruit set potential. ||Atmospheric pollen characteristics at peak include maximum concentration providing abundant male gametes throughout cluster atmosphere, optimal spatial distribution with elevated levels extending vine and vineyard scale, visible pollen cloud formation under favorable conditions creating obvious evidence of intensive release, and sustained temporal persistence maintaining availability during stigma receptivity period. ||Pollen cloud phenomenon at peak shows characteristic visual display with pale yellow haze surrounding flowering clusters, particularly evident during morning peak hours 9am-11am when conditions optimal, sound occasionally audible during very intensive synchronized discharge though typically silent, and overall sensory confirmation of maximum male reproductive activity. ||Pollen viability at peak shows maximum proportion of viable grains with continuous fresh pollen production maintaining 75-90% germination capacity in atmospheric pool, brief optimal window before progressive aging reduces viability, and critical importance of pollination during peak period capturing highest-quality male gametes. ||Environmental conditions at peak typically optimal with temperature 24-30°C supporting efficient dehiscence, pollen viability, and atmospheric transport, moderate humidity 50-65% maintaining pollen dispersibility and viability without aggregation, light-moderate wind 6-14 km per hour enhancing distribution, and stable favorable weather enabling sustained intensive release over 2-3 day period. ||Temperature optimization at peak shows warm conditions promoting maximum dehiscence through efficient anther dehydration, maintaining pollen surface properties enabling dispersal, and supporting atmospheric mixing enhancing distribution, with optimal 25-28°C range supporting all pollen release processes simultaneously. ||Humidity optimization shows moderate levels critical for balancing multiple requirements including sufficient anther dehydration enabling dehiscence, maintained pollen viability without desiccation damage, appropriate dispersibility preventing aggregation and premature atmospheric removal, and optimal 52-68% range supporting coordinated male reproductive processes. ||Wind optimization shows light-moderate speeds ideal for enhancing dispersal without excessive pollen loss, facilitating atmospheric mixing improving distribution, potentially agitating anthers dislodging additional pollen, and optimal 7-13 km per hour range supporting effective male gamete distribution. ||Pollination opportunity at peak reaches absolute optimum with maximum fresh viable pollen widely distributed creating abundant male gamete availability, extensive stigma receptivity providing numerous capture sites, favorable spatial arrangement supporting efficient encounters, and optimal temporal coordination creating ideal reproductive window. ||Fruit set determination at peak shows outcomes during this critical 2-3 day period dominating final berry number with successful pollinations during peak contributing 50-70% total fruit set, making peak pollen release conditions primary determinant of season yield, and demonstrating critical importance of favorable male reproductive function. ||Self-pollination efficiency at peak maximizes through abundant immediate pollen availability in same flower with continuous discharge maintaining supply, close anther-stigma proximity facilitating rapid encounters, and fresh viable pollen ensuring high germination success supporting effective self-pollination accounting for 60-80% successful reproductions. ||Cross-pollination contribution at peak shows enhanced role during maximum atmospheric dispersal with elevated pollen concentration enabling effective neighboring flower pollination accounting for 20-35% successful reproductions, inter-vine dispersal contributing 5-15% particularly in dense plantings with high atmospheric pollen levels, and demonstrating secondary but significant role of atmospheric dispersal in reproductive success. ||Weather dependency at peak shows extreme sensitivity with reproductive success critically dependent on favorable conditions during brief 2-3 day window, optimal stable weather supporting high fruit set 60-75% in good-setting cultivars, while adverse conditions particularly rain causing catastrophic failure potentially reducing set to 15-30%, demonstrating that peak pollen release represents single most weather-vulnerable period alongside stigma receptivity peak. ||Rain effects at peak show devastating interference with water preventing anther dehiscence eliminating continued pollen production, washing pollen from atmosphere destroying atmospheric pool, eliminating pollen viability through excessive hydration, and promoting fungal infection, with rain during peak potentially reducing fruit set by 60-80% compared to favorable conditions. ||Developmental coordination at peak shows remarkable synchronization with peak pollen release coinciding with peak anthesis and maximum cap fall, widespread flower opening and stigma receptivity aligning temporally with maximum pollen availability, and integrated reproductive system coordination creating optimal pollination window determining season productivity. ||Metabolic activity at peak shows maximum respiratory demand in discharging anthers supporting intensive pollen release, elevated energy consumption in pollen maintaining viability and germination capacity, and overall high metabolic investment in male reproductive function during brief critical period. ||Resource requirements at peak emphasize carbohydrate demand for supporting intensive metabolic activity in anthers and pollen, nitrogen for maintaining protein function in pollen and reproductive tissues, critical boron for supporting subsequent pollen germination and tube growth, and adequate mineral nutrition supporting overall reproductive function. ||Hormonal environment at peak involves possible regulatory signals coordinating dehiscence timing though mechanisms poorly understood in grapevine, gibberellins potentially affecting anther development and pollen maturation, and overall hormonal context supporting male reproductive function during flowering. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from optimal pollen cloud formation creating visual and atmospheric evidence of peak activity, through maximum pollen availability establishing ideal male gamete supply for pollination. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing peak male reproductive period paralleling peak anthesis, with warm stable conditions producing compressed 2-day peak while variable conditions may extend to 3-4 days. ||Cultivar variation in peak release shows differences in intensity with some varieties producing very high pollen concentrations while others show moderate peaks, peak duration affecting temporal window for optimal pollination, and coordination with stigma receptivity affecting reproductive efficiency. ||Regional timing shows peak pollen release during mid-June in warm climates at approximately 1050-1100 growing degree days base 10°C, mid-June in temperate regions at 950-1000 GDD, and mid-late June in cool areas at 850-900 GDD, coinciding precisely with peak anthesis period. ||Viticultural significance includes representing most critical male reproductive period determining 50-70% fruit set and season yield, requiring optimal environmental conditions for efficient release and viability maintenance, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability with brief window determining productivity, providing visual confirmation through pollen clouds of successful male function, and establishing peak pollen release alongside peak stigma receptivity as dominant yield determinants. ||Research applications include analyzing coordination mechanisms producing synchronized peak release, quantifying pollen production rates and atmospheric dynamics during peak, evaluating environmental effects on peak intensity and duration, assessing pollination efficiency during optimal period, developing models predicting fruit set from peak pollen release characteristics, and investigating climate change impacts on peak timing and conditions affecting productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-388 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 290-298"
},

  "Optimal_Pollen_Cloud_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Optimal_Pollen_Cloud_Formation is a Peak_Pollen_Release marked by the formation of a visible pale yellow atmospheric pollen haze surrounding flowering clusters.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen cloud phenomenon | visible pollen haze | atmospheric pollen display | pollen cloud appearance |+ Pollenwolkenbildung | Pollennebelphänomen | Pollendunstwolke | atmosphärische Pollenanzeige",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows optimal pollen cloud formation during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 63-65 on June 9-10, with visible pale yellow haze surrounding flowering clusters during morning hours 9am-11am, prominent under favorable oceanic conditions of 23-27°C temperature, 56-66% relative humidity, light winds 7-11 km per hour, confirming intensive pollen release and optimal pollination conditions, typical of this mid-season cultivar during peak flowering supporting 56-66% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Optimal_Pollen_Cloud_Formation is first aspect of Peak_Pollen_Release, distinguished by visible atmospheric phenomenon confirming maximum male reproductive activity. ||Represents readily observable marker for peak flowering. ||Requires specific environmental conditions particularly moderate humidity and light wind. ||Transient phenomenon lasting hours during favorable conditions. ||Provides practical visual confirmation of intensive pollen release and pollination opportunity. ||Cultural and management significance as flowering indicator. ||Followed by Maximum_Pollen_Availability discussing gamete supply. || This distinctive visual phenomenon occurs during peak pollen release in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically visible during morning peak hours when conditions most favorable for cloud formation and persistence, corresponding to BBCH 63-65 peak anthesis stages. ||Cloud formation mechanism involves intensive coordinated pollen discharge from numerous anthers releasing millions of grains creating high local atmospheric concentration, light wind and air movement lifting and suspending released pollen creating airborne cloud, appropriate humidity maintaining pollen in dispersible state without excessive aggregation or rapid settling, and favorable temperature supporting both discharge and atmospheric suspension. ||Visual characteristics show pale yellow to yellow-brown coloration creating visible haze around flowering clusters, concentration gradient with densest cloud immediately surrounding clusters declining with distance, dynamic appearance with cloud thickness varying with discharge intensity and wind conditions, and transient nature appearing and disappearing with changing environmental conditions and discharge activity. ||Cloud visibility factors include pollen concentration with visible clouds typically requiring 300-500+ grains per cubic centimeter minimum threshold, lighting conditions with backlighting or low sun angle enhancing visibility, observer position with cloud more visible from certain angles, and atmospheric clarity with humid or hazy conditions reducing visibility. ||Optimal formation conditions include temperature 24-30°C promoting maximum discharge intensity and appropriate atmospheric properties, humidity 50-65% maintaining pollen dispersibility without causing aggregation that would prevent cloud formation, light wind 5-12 km per hour providing sufficient movement for suspension while not dispersing cloud excessively, and overall stable conditions maintaining favorable parameters during peak discharge period. ||Temperature effects on cloud formation show warm conditions facilitating intensive discharge providing abundant pollen source, affecting air density and buoyancy influencing suspension dynamics, and supporting atmospheric mixing creating favorable suspension conditions, with optimal 25-28°C range supporting visible cloud formation. ||Humidity effects show critical importance with moderate levels essential for maintaining pollen in dispersible state enabling cloud formation, high humidity above 70% causing pollen aggregation eliminating cloud through premature settling as heavy clumps, and low humidity below 45% potentially acceptable for cloud formation though possibly affecting pollen viability, with optimal 52-68% range reliably supporting cloud appearance. ||Wind effects show dual role with light movement necessary for lifting pollen into suspension creating cloud, though excessive wind above 15 km per hour rapidly dispersing cloud reducing visibility, calm conditions potentially limiting cloud formation through inadequate lifting though local accumulation may still occur, and optimal 6-13 km per hour providing balance supporting visible persistent clouds. ||Diurnal pattern shows characteristic morning maximum with cloud formation typically most prominent 9am-12pm when temperature rising, humidity declining, and discharge intensity peaking creating ideal combination, afternoon reduction as conditions potentially become less favorable with rising temperature or changing humidity, and daily rhythm with repeated cloud formation during multi-day peak release period. ||Spatial distribution shows clouds concentrated around flowering clusters as pollen source with highest density immediately surrounding inflorescences, extension throughout vine canopy creating larger clouds in dense plantings, vineyard-scale clouds possible during intensive synchronized discharge under optimal conditions, and visible gradient showing concentration decline with distance from source. ||Temporal persistence shows clouds lasting minutes to hours during favorable stable conditions with sustained discharge maintaining cloud density, rapid disappearance when conditions change with rising humidity causing aggregation or strong wind causing dispersal, and overall transient dynamic appearance responding rapidly to environmental fluctuations. ||Pollen grain properties affecting cloud formation include small size 25-35 micrometers enabling easy airborne suspension, relatively low density facilitating buoyancy, surface properties affecting aggregation tendency with smooth exine promoting individual grain suspension, and overall characteristics well-suited for atmospheric suspension and cloud formation. ||Cloud composition shows predominantly individual pollen grains suspended in air creating visible haze, occasional small pollen clumps from limited aggregation contributing to visibility, and dust or other atmospheric particles potentially contributing minor component to overall haze appearance. ||Acoustic properties during cloud formation include normally silent appearance with no characteristic sounds, though very intensive synchronized discharge creating clouds may produce subtle rustling though typically inaudible, and overall visual rather than acoustic phenomenon. ||Observational value of cloud formation includes providing obvious visual confirmation of intensive pollen release easily assessed without equipment, indicating favorable male reproductive conditions supporting high pollination potential, enabling timing assessment for management decisions or harvest predictions, and serving as practical marker for peak flowering more readily observable than detailed reproductive organ examination. ||Photographic documentation of clouds enables visual records of flowering intensity, comparison across seasons or locations assessing environmental effects, and research documentation of pollen release dynamics and environmental responses. ||Pollination opportunity indicated by clouds shows optimal conditions with visible clouds confirming abundant fresh pollen widely distributed, favorable environmental parameters supporting pollen viability and dispersal, and intensive male reproductive activity creating maximum pollination potential supporting high fruit set. ||Fruit set prediction from cloud observation shows positive correlation with prominent persistent clouds during peak indicating favorable conditions likely producing high set 60-75%, while absent or weak clouds suggesting suboptimal conditions potentially limiting set to 35-55%, and providing early visual indicator of reproductive success before berry development confirms outcomes. ||Cultural significance of pollen clouds includes traditional recognition by viticulturists as favorable flowering sign, visual confirmation of reproductive timing supporting management scheduling, and aesthetic appreciation of visible reproductive phenomenon representing vineyard fertility. ||The process represents first aspect of peak pollen release emphasizing visible atmospheric phenomenon, followed by maximum pollen availability discussing gamete supply. ||Duration represents transient phenomenon visible for hours during favorable peak conditions, with appearance and disappearance responsive to environmental and discharge intensity changes. ||Cultivar variation in cloud formation shows varieties with high pollen production more likely to produce prominent clouds, timing differences reflecting overall phenology, and some varieties rarely showing visible clouds despite adequate pollen release possibly due to discharge patterns or environmental sensitivity. ||Regional expression shows cloud formation more common in warm dry climates where favorable conditions consistently achieved, less frequent in cool humid maritime climates where humidity often too high, and occasional dramatic clouds in any region during exceptionally favorable flowering weather. ||Viticultural significance includes providing practical visual marker for peak male reproductive activity, indicating favorable pollination conditions supporting high fruit set predictions, enabling timing assessment for management decisions, and serving as readily observable phenomenon confirming successful flowering without technical assessment. ||Research applications include documenting pollen release intensity through cloud observation, analyzing environmental conditions enabling cloud formation, evaluating pollen dispersal dynamics through cloud behavior, developing practical observation protocols for phenological assessment, and investigating cloud formation as indicator of reproductive success and fruit set potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 383-386 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 293-295"
},

  "Maximum_Pollen_Availability": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Pollen_Availability is a Peak_Pollen_Release characterized by the highest concentration of fresh viable pollen grains accessible to receptive stigmas within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "peak pollen supply | optimal male gamete availability | maximum viable pollen | highest pollen accessibility |+ maximale Pollenverfügbarkeit | optimale männliche Gametenversorgung | höchster lebensfähiger Pollenbestand | Spitzen-Pollenzugänglichkeit",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows maximum pollen availability during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 65 on June 10, with atmospheric concentration 700-1200 grains per cubic centimeter, fresh pollen viability 76-88%, continuous production maintaining 68-82% functional viable proportion in atmospheric pool, under temperate maritime conditions of 22-26°C temperature, 56-70% relative humidity, supporting optimal pollination during critical 1-day peak enabling 56-66% fruit set typical of this mid-season cultivar determining majority season yield",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Pollen_Availability is second and final aspect of Peak_Pollen_Release, distinguished by optimal male gamete supply for pollination. ||Represents absolute peak of male reproductive capacity. ||Corresponds to BBCH 65 full bloom. ||Duration 1-2 days during peak release. ||Determines 40-60% fruit set during brief window. ||Requires favorable environmental conditions maintaining pollen viability and dispersibility. ||Extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain. ||Coordination with peak stigma receptivity creates integrated optimal pollination window. ||Most critical male reproductive state determining season productivity. || This critical male reproductive optimum occurs during peak pollen release in mid-June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 1-2 days when coordinated factors produce absolute maximum viable pollen supply, corresponding to BBCH 65 full bloom stage. ||Availability characteristics show simultaneous occurrence of optimal supply elements including maximum pollen production from widespread anther discharge, continuous fresh pollen release maintaining viable supply, optimal atmospheric distribution providing wide spatial availability, maximum pollen viability with fresh grains showing 75-90% germination capacity, and favorable temporal persistence maintaining supply during stigma receptivity period. ||Pollen supply intensity at maximum shows peak production rates with cluster-level discharge estimated millions of grains per hour, cumulative atmospheric accumulation creating elevated concentrations 500-1500 grains per cubic centimeter near clusters, sustained production over hours maintaining viable pool despite progressive aging reducing older grains, and overall male gamete abundance sufficient for supporting maximum pollination efficiency. ||Fresh pollen production dynamics shows continuous anther dehiscence releasing newly matured grains, immediate optimal viability in freshly discharged pollen exhibiting 75-90% germination capacity, and sustained fresh pollen supply offsetting viability decline in atmospheric pool maintaining overall high functional pollen proportion. ||Atmospheric pollen pool characteristics include total concentration representing mix of fresh high-viability and aged reduced-viability grains, functional viable proportion estimated 65-85% of atmospheric pool during maximum availability showing germination capacity, spatial distribution with elevated levels throughout cluster atmosphere and extending vine scale, and temporal persistence with sustained elevated concentration over 1-2 day maximum period. ||Pollen accessibility at maximum shows widespread distribution making grains available throughout cluster atmosphere, numerous pollen-stigma encounter opportunities with high atmospheric concentration increasing contact probability, favorable positioning with many pollen grains in proximity to receptive stigmas, and optimal capture efficiency with adhesive stigma exudate readily trapping contacted grains. ||Viability optimization at maximum involves multiple coordinated factors including continuous fresh production maintaining high-viability proportion in atmospheric pool, favorable environmental conditions preserving pollen function with optimal temperature 24-30°C and moderate humidity 50-65%, brief window before progressive aging substantially reduces viability, and overall maintenance of functional male gamete supply during receptivity period. ||Germination capacity of available pollen shows maximum potential with fresh grains readily germinating upon stigma contact within 1-4 hours, viable atmospheric pollen maintaining capacity for successful pollination, and overall functional male gamete availability enabling high fertilization success supporting fruit set 60-75% in good-setting cultivars under favorable conditions. ||Spatial availability pattern shows highest concentration immediately surrounding flowering clusters as primary pollen source, elevated levels throughout vine canopy where multiple clusters contribute to atmospheric pool, significant concentrations extending several meters between vines particularly in dense plantings, and declining concentration with distance following dispersal gradient. ||Temporal availability window shows peak period lasting 1-2 days during maximum release with optimal conditions, sustained elevated availability requiring continued production offsetting atmospheric removal through settling and dispersal, and critical brief window requiring stigma receptivity overlap for successful pollination. ||Pollen-stigma encounter frequency at maximum reaches optimum with abundant atmospheric pollen creating high contact probability, estimated 10-50 pollen grains contacting individual receptive stigma during peak period though only 1-2 successful germinations required for fertilization, and favorable encounter geometry with aerial pollen and gravitational fall delivering grains to papillate stigma surfaces. ||Pollination efficiency at maximum shows peak success rates with abundant fresh viable pollen widely available, extensive stigma receptivity providing numerous capture sites, favorable environmental conditions supporting pollen capture and germination, and optimal coordination producing fertilization success 65-85% of pollination attempts under favorable conditions. ||Self-pollination supply at maximum emphasizes immediate local availability with pollen releasing from anthers in same flower falling directly onto nearby stigma, continuous discharge maintaining supply for extended receptivity period, and self-pollination accounting for 60-80% successful fertilizations during maximum availability period. ||Cross-pollination supply at maximum shows enhanced contribution with elevated atmospheric concentration enabling effective neighboring flower pollination, inter-flower dispersal within cluster accounting for 20-35% successful fertilizations, inter-vine dispersal contributing 5-15% particularly during very high atmospheric pollen levels, and demonstrating broader pollination sources during maximum availability compared to normal periods. ||Environmental conditions enabling maximum availability include temperature 24-30°C supporting intensive discharge and pollen viability, moderate humidity 50-65% maintaining pollen dispersibility and function, light-moderate wind 6-14 km per hour enhancing distribution without excessive loss, and overall stable favorable weather enabling sustained optimal availability over 1-2 day period. ||Temperature effects on availability show warm conditions promoting maximum discharge providing abundant supply, maintaining pollen surface properties supporting dispersibility, and preserving viability though excessive heat above 33°C potentially causing stress damage, with optimal 25-28°C range supporting all availability factors. ||Humidity effects show critical importance with moderate levels maintaining pollen in functional state without aggregation reducing availability or excessive desiccation damaging viability, high humidity above 70% causing aggregation and premature atmospheric removal reducing availability, and optimal 52-68% range preserving maximum functional pollen concentration. ||Fruit set determination during maximum availability shows outcomes during this critical 1-2 day period contributing 40-60% total berry number representing largest single period contribution, making maximum availability conditions dominant influence on season yield, and demonstrating that male gamete supply alongside female receptivity represents primary fruit set determinant. ||Weather vulnerability during maximum availability shows extreme sensitivity with adverse conditions during brief peak period substantially affecting outcomes, favorable stable conditions supporting high availability and fruit set while rain catastrophically eliminating availability through atmospheric removal and viability destruction potentially reducing set by 60-80%, and demonstrating critical importance of weather during maximum availability period. ||The process represents second and final aspect of peak pollen release emphasizing optimal gamete supply for pollination, following optimal pollen cloud formation. ||Duration typically spans 1-2 days representing absolute maximum male reproductive capacity, with warm stable conditions producing sharp intense peak. ||Cultivar variation in maximum availability shows differences in pollen production affecting achievable concentration, viability characteristics affecting functional proportion, and timing coordination with stigma receptivity affecting pollination efficiency and fruit set outcomes. ||Regional timing shows maximum pollen availability during mid-June in warm climates, mid-June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding precisely with peak anthesis and full bloom representing most critical reproductive period. ||Viticultural significance includes representing optimal male gamete supply determining maximum pollination and fruit set potential, requiring favorable environmental conditions for achieving and maintaining maximum availability, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability with brief 1-2 day window determining majority season yield, and establishing maximum pollen availability alongside peak stigma receptivity as integrated reproductive optimum determining productivity. ||Research applications include quantifying pollen availability dynamics including production rates, atmospheric concentrations, and viability distributions, evaluating environmental effects on availability optimization, assessing pollen-stigma encounter probabilities and pollination efficiency during maximum period, developing models predicting fruit set from availability characteristics, and investigating climate change impacts on maximum availability timing and conditions affecting viticultural productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 384-390 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 295-298"
},

  "Completed_Pollen_Release": {
  "definition": "A Completed_Pollen_Release is a Pollen_Release marked by the cluster state with all viable anthers dehisced, pollen supplies exhausted, and atmospheric pollen concentration at negligible levels.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen release completion | male gamete exhaustion | anther depletion | end of pollen production |+ abgeschlossene Pollenfreisetzung | männliche Gametenerschöpfung | Antheren-Entleerung | Pollenproduktionsende",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows completed pollen release during late June Year N+1 at BBCH 67-69 on approximately June 15-16, with all viable anthers having completed discharge, atmospheric pollen concentration declining to <25 grains per cubic centimeter, widespread empty withered anthers throughout cluster, visible berry development 14-22 mm diameter representing 52-64% established fruit set, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing male reproductive phase 11-13 days after first dehiscence and transitioning definitively to berry development",
  "editor_note": "Completed_Pollen_Release represents concluding male reproductive phase parallel to Complete_Anthesis within Flowering. ||Corresponds to BBCH 67-69 late-complete anthesis stages. ||Subdivided into Pollen_Exhaustion and Empty_Anther_Formation. ||Marks definitive end of male gamete availability and contribution. ||Establishes final fruit set from male perspective. ||Enables management transitions and developmental phase focus. ||Completes male reproductive cycle from dehiscence through peak release to exhaustion. || This conclusive male phase occurs during late-complete flowering in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 following peak release, typically spanning 2-3 days as final pollen discharge completes and atmospheric pool dissipates, corresponding to BBCH 67-69 late-complete anthesis stages. ||Completion characteristics show definitive cessation of male reproductive function with all developmentally capable anthers having completed dehiscence and pollen discharge, exhausted pollen supplies with anthers depleted of releasable grains, negligible atmospheric pollen concentration with remaining airborne pollen aged and non-viable, and overall termination of effective male gamete availability. ||Anther status at completion shows widespread empty dehisced anthers with longitudinal slits exposing depleted locules, withered anther structures showing brown discoloration indicating senescence, occasional late-dehiscing anthers in basal flowers completing final releases contributing minimal pollen, and overall cluster showing predominantly post-reproductive anther state. ||Pollen exhaustion progression shows characteristic depletion pattern with early-dehiscing anthers in apical regions completely exhausted having released all viable pollen over previous days, mid-cluster anthers mostly depleted with minimal residual non-releasable pollen remaining, late-dehiscing basal anthers completing discharge contributing final minor pollen additions, and overall progression toward complete cluster-level exhaustion. ||Atmospheric pollen decline shows rapid concentration reduction following peak maximum with levels dropping from 500-1500 grains per cubic centimeter at peak to 50-200 during late release to <20 at completion, continued atmospheric removal through settling and dispersal eliminating remaining airborne pollen, and cessation of fresh production preventing atmospheric pool replenishment. ||Residual atmospheric pollen characteristics include predominantly aged grains with extended atmospheric residence, severely reduced viability typically <10-20% germination capacity due to progressive aging and environmental exposure, insufficient concentration for effective pollination with encounter probabilities declining substantially, and overall non-functional male gamete pool unable to support significant additional fertilizations. ||Late pollen release from final anthers shows limited contribution with basal and delayed anthers completing dehiscence contributing minor pollen additions, fresh pollen from late release showing adequate viability 65-80% but insufficient quantity for meaningful pollination, and overall late release contributing <5-10% fruit set representing minor final additions. ||Male reproductive cessation at completion shows definitive termination with no further viable pollen production capacity, exhausted anther reserves preventing continued release, and physiological commitment to post-reproductive senescence eliminating male function. ||Berry development visibility at completion shows established fruit structures throughout cluster with early-set berries 12-20 mm diameter from peak flowering success dominating appearance, late-set berries 8-14 mm from late pollinations visible in some positions, and overall berry-dominated cluster confirming reproductive outcomes and male contribution completion. ||Unfertilized flower status at completion shows senescing unsuccessful reproductions with brown discoloration and tissue deterioration, active abscission eliminating failed flowers progressively over subsequent weeks, and visible flower drop creating accumulated debris documenting unsuccessful pollination attempts. ||Fruit set finalization at completion establishes definitive berry number with count of successfully fertilized flowers determining season yield, typical set percentages 30-75% depending on cultivar and conditions creating 100-500 berries per cluster, and recognition that male gamete contribution completed with established berry number representing maximum potential yield. ||Pollination opportunity cessation at completion shows terminated effective pollination capacity with negligible viable pollen availability, any remaining late receptive stigmas unable to achieve successful pollination, and final unsuccessful flowers destined for abscission due to failed reproduction. ||Developmental transition at completion marks shift from reproductive to exclusively developmental focus with all vine resources directing to established berry growth, no residual male reproductive investment or function, and physiological reorientation toward fruit development and maturation. ||Environmental effects at completion show reduced significance compared to earlier reproductive phases with outcomes largely determined by previous peak period conditions, though conditions during completion affecting final late flower success contributing minor proportion, and overall weather during completion having minimal impact on established fruit set. ||Anther senescence at completion shows progressive tissue deterioration with withered structures showing brown discoloration, cellular breakdown as anthers degenerate following exhaustion, and eventual abscission of senescent anthers from flowers over subsequent weeks though many persist. ||Pollen deposition evidence at completion includes accumulated pollen on horizontal surfaces within canopy showing yellow dust layers, ground deposition creating visible layer documenting flowering intensity, and persistent visual evidence of male reproductive activity despite completion. ||Observational characteristics enabling completion identification include absence of visible pollen clouds or fresh pollen release, widespread empty withered anthers throughout cluster, predominantly berry appearance with minimal residual flowering activity, and overall visual evidence of reproductive conclusion with developmental transition. ||Phenological significance at completion includes marking definitive end of male reproductive phase, establishing reference for developmental stage transitions with progression from reproductive BBCH 60-69 to developmental BBCH 71-79 stages, and confirming flowering completion enabling post-bloom management transitions. ||Management implications at completion include confirming male reproductive function completed enabling assessment of pollination outcomes, resuming full normal operations without reproductive period restrictions, implementing post-bloom berry development management, and transitioning focus entirely to fruit development and quality optimization. ||Fruit set assessment at completion enables accurate yield prediction through berry counting, evaluation of male reproductive success through comparison to flower number, and early season productivity estimates informing management decisions. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from pollen exhaustion marking depletion of anther reserves, through empty anther formation establishing post-reproductive state. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 days representing completion period, with rapid transition to exclusively developmental phase. ||Cultivar variation in completion timing shows early varieties completing late June while late types complete early-mid July reflecting overall phenology, completion efficiency with some showing clean complete discharge while others showing residual retention, and transition clarity with some showing definitive completion while others showing gradual extended conclusion. ||Regional timing shows completed pollen release during late June in warm climates at approximately 1150-1200 growing degree days base 10°C, late June-early July in temperate regions at 1050-1100 GDD, and early-mid July in cool areas at 950-1000 GDD, marking male reproductive phase conclusion. ||Viticultural significance includes marking definitive end of male reproductive contribution confirming fruit set outcomes, indicating completion of critical weather-vulnerable flowering period reducing risk, enabling complete management transitions to developmental priorities, and establishing reference for subsequent phenological and developmental timing. ||Research applications include documenting precise male reproductive phase completion timing, analyzing factors affecting complete pollen discharge achievement, evaluating relationships between pollen release patterns and final fruit set outcomes, assessing post-reproductive anther senescence processes, and documenting phenological transitions marking major phase changes in reproductive biology.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 388-395 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 295-300"
},

  "Pollen_Exhaustion": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Exhaustion is a Completed_Pollen_Release characterized by the anther state with viable pollen supplies fully released and locules empty of functional grains.",
  "alternative_term": "anther depletion | pollen supply exhaustion | complete pollen discharge | male gamete depletion |+ Pollenerschöpfung | Antheren-Entleerung | Pollenvorraterschöpfung | männliche Gametendepletion",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows pollen exhaustion during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 67-69 over 2-3 days July 1-3, with sequential anther depletion progressing from apical to basal positions, empty withered anthers showing brown discoloration lacking yellow pollen mass, atmospheric pollen contribution ceasing from exhausted anthers, under cool maritime conditions of 20-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar completing male gamete discharge 12-14 days after first dehiscence with exhaustion marking effective end of male reproductive contribution",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Exhaustion is first aspect of Completed_Pollen_Release, distinguished by depletion of functional anther reserves. ||Represents progressive state developing over 2-3 days with spatial-temporal gradient. ||Marks effective end of male gamete contribution to pollination. ||Followed by Empty_Anther_Formation discussing post-exhaustion structural state. ||Assessment enables evaluation of male reproductive success. ||Timing relative to stigma receptivity affects final pollination opportunity. ||Spatial progression reflects flowering developmental gradient. || This critical depletion state occurs during completed pollen release in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically developing progressively over 2-3 days as sequential anthers complete discharge and exhaust supplies, corresponding to BBCH 67-69 late-complete anthesis stages. ||Exhaustion characteristics show complete depletion of releasable pollen from anther locules with all viable grains having discharged during previous days of active release, residual non-releasable pollen representing damaged or adhered grains unable to liberate estimated <5% original content, and overall cessation of functional pollen production from exhausted anthers. ||Depletion progression shows characteristic spatial-temporal pattern with earliest-dehiscing anthers in apical cluster regions reaching exhaustion first after 2-3 days sustained discharge, progressive extension to middle regions as anthers sequentially exhaust following their individual discharge timing, and late-dehiscing basal anthers reaching exhaustion last completing cluster-level depletion, creating developmental gradient in exhaustion state. ||Anther appearance at exhaustion shows empty locules visible through longitudinal dehiscence slits exposing interior lacking yellow pollen mass, withered shrunken anther structure reflecting tissue dehydration following exhaustion, color change from yellow-brown fresh state toward brown or gray-brown exhausted appearance, and overall visual evidence of completed discharge. ||Locular emptiness verification through dissection or examination shows depleted chambers lacking pollen mass, residual individual grains or small clumps adhering to locule walls representing non-releasable fraction, and structural evidence of completed pollen production and release cycles. ||Pollen release cessation from exhausted anthers shows eliminated discharge capacity with no further viable grains available for liberation, occasional release of residual damaged or adhered grains contributing negligible functional pollen, and overall terminated pollen production from individual exhausted anther. ||Atmospheric pollen contribution cessation shows exhausted anthers no longer supplying fresh viable grains to atmospheric pool, eliminated source function preventing atmospheric concentration maintenance, and reliance on any remaining late-dehiscing anthers for final minor pollen contributions. ||Residual pollen characteristics in exhausted anthers include damaged grains with compromised exine or cytoplasm preventing normal liberation, adhered grains stuck to locule walls unable to release despite dehiscence, and overall non-functional pollen representing discharge failures rather than viable reserves. ||Exhaustion timing relative to dehiscence shows typical 1-3 day period from initial opening to complete exhaustion depending on environmental conditions and discharge efficiency, accelerated exhaustion under optimal conditions promoting rapid complete discharge within 24-48 hours, and delayed exhaustion under suboptimal conditions extending period to 3-5 days. ||Environmental effects on exhaustion timing include favorable conditions facilitating rapid efficient discharge producing earlier exhaustion, suboptimal conditions particularly high humidity potentially retaining pollen in locules extending functional discharge period, and temperature affecting discharge rate influencing exhaustion timing. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions 25-30°C promoting rapid discharge and earlier exhaustion, cool conditions 18-23°C slowing discharge potentially extending functional period before exhaustion, and overall thermal environment affecting depletion dynamics. ||Humidity effects include moderate levels 50-65% supporting efficient discharge enabling normal exhaustion timing, elevated humidity above 70% potentially retaining pollen in locules through reduced mechanical liberation delaying exhaustion, and low humidity below 45% potentially accelerating discharge though possibly affecting released pollen viability. ||Anther tissue changes accompanying exhaustion include progressive dehydration as discharge completes with tissue water content declining, cellular senescence initiating in post-reproductive anthers with metabolic decline, and structural collapse as turgid functional anthers become withered exhausted structures. ||Metabolic transition at exhaustion shows declining respiratory activity in depleted anthers as metabolic demands reduce, resource reallocation from male reproductive function toward other processes particularly berry development, and physiological shift from active reproductive investment to senescence. ||Male reproductive contribution assessment at exhaustion enables evaluation through comparison of early versus late exhaustion timing affecting pollination window duration, discharge efficiency affecting functional pollen proportion successfully released, and coordination with stigma receptivity affecting pollination success outcomes. ||Fruit set implications of exhaustion timing include early complete exhaustion before full stigma receptivity potentially limiting late flower pollination opportunities, optimal exhaustion timing coinciding with receptivity conclusion enabling maximum pollination efficiency, and delayed exhaustion extending male contribution window though likely producing minimal additional fruit set. ||Sequential exhaustion pattern throughout cluster creates extended pollination opportunity with early anthers providing initial pollen while later anthers extend supply, progressive depletion creating declining male gamete availability over flowering period, and final exhaustion completing male reproductive contribution approximately coinciding with stigma receptivity cessation. ||Pollination success relationship to exhaustion shows inverse correlation with rapid early exhaustion under optimal conditions typically coinciding with successful pollination during favorable period supporting high fruit set 60-75%, while premature exhaustion from stress or abnormality potentially limiting pollination reducing set <40%, and demonstrating importance of sustained appropriate-duration discharge. ||Observational assessment of exhaustion includes visual inspection of anther appearance noting empty withered structures, absence of fresh pollen release during favorable conditions indicating depletion, and dissection or detailed examination confirming locular emptiness if required for verification. ||The process represents first aspect of completed pollen release emphasizing depletion of functional reserves, followed by empty anther formation discussing post-exhaustion structural state. ||Duration represents progressive state developing over 2-3 days as sequential anthers deplete, with spatial-temporal gradient reflecting flowering progression. ||Cultivar variation in exhaustion characteristics includes differences in pollen production affecting quantity available for discharge before depletion, discharge efficiency affecting completeness of release and residual retention, and timing relative to stigma receptivity affecting pollination opportunity and fruit set outcomes. ||Regional timing shows progressive pollen exhaustion during late June in warm climates, late June-early July in temperate regions, and early-mid July in cool areas, occurring during late-complete anthesis as male reproductive phase concludes. ||Viticultural significance includes marking effective end of male gamete contribution to fruit set, indicating completion of critical pollination window, providing assessment point for male reproductive success, and establishing transition toward exclusive developmental focus on established berries. ||Research applications include analyzing factors affecting exhaustion timing and completeness, evaluating discharge efficiency through residual pollen assessment, quantifying relationships between exhaustion patterns and fruit set outcomes, assessing environmental effects on depletion dynamics, and investigating genetic variation in pollen production and discharge affecting reproductive capacity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 390-393 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 297-300"
},

  "Empty_Anther_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Empty_Anther_Formation is a Pollen_Exhaustion characterized by withered senescent anthers lacking functional pollen.",
  "alternative_term": "depleted anther state | post-exhaustion anther condition | senescent empty anthers | withered anther formation |+ leere Antheren-Formation | erschöpfte Antherenzustand | seneszente Staubbeutel | verwelkte Antheren-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Oregon shows empty anther formation during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 68-69 over 3-4 days July 3-6, with withered brown anthers showing obvious empty locules visible through dehiscence slits, shrunken structures reflecting tissue dehydration and senescence, contrasting with visible berry development 14-20 mm diameter, under cool climate conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar transitioning definitively to post-reproductive state confirming completed male reproductive function 13-15 days after first dehiscence",
  "editor_note": "Empty_Anther_Formation is second and final aspect of Completed_Pollen_Release, distinguished by post-exhaustion structural state confirming completed function. ||Represents gradual senescence process developing over several days. ||Provides obvious visual confirmation of reproductive conclusion. ||Enables practical assessment without detailed examination. ||Contrasts with developing berries showing developmental phase dominance. ||Completes entire Pollen_Release hierarchical documentation from dehiscence through peak release to exhaustion and final empty state. ||Definitively concludes male reproductive cycle. || This concluding structural state occurs during completed pollen release in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1 following pollen exhaustion, developing over several days as exhausted anthers undergo senescence changes, corresponding to BBCH 68-69 complete anthesis stages. ||Empty anther characteristics show depleted locules completely lacking yellow pollen masses creating hollow appearance visible through dehiscence slits, withered shrunken anther structure reflecting progressive tissue dehydration and senescence, brown to gray-brown coloration contrasting with earlier yellow-brown fresh pollen-containing state, and overall visual evidence of completed reproductive function and post-exhaustion senescence. ||Structural changes creating empty appearance include tissue dehydration causing volumetric shrinkage with anthers becoming smaller and more compact, cell wall collapse eliminating turgid structure creating wrinkled shriveled appearance, progressive desiccation removing tissue moisture content, and overall transformation from functional reproductive organ to senescent depleted structure. ||Anther wall deterioration shows progressive breakdown with outer epidermis maintaining basic structure though becoming brittle and fragile, fibrous layer losing hygroscopic function following exhaustion with no further mechanical role, endothecium remaining structurally intact though non-functional, and overall tissue persisting in degraded state. ||Dehiscence slit persistence shows maintained longitudinal openings exposing empty locule interiors enabling visual confirmation of depletion, slit edges potentially showing deterioration as tissue senesces, and permanent structural modification from dehiscence process creating lasting evidence of reproductive function. ||Locular emptiness appearance shows hollow chambers visible through dehiscence slits, light-colored or translucent locule walls contrasting with earlier pollen-filled opaque appearance, occasional residual pollen remnants adhered to walls representing discharge failures, and overall obvious visual evidence of pollen depletion. ||Color transformation progression shows characteristic change from yellow-brown fresh pollen-containing anthers through intermediate tan brown during exhaustion to final brown or gray-brown empty senescent state, reflecting tissue aging and oxidative changes, with color providing visual indicator of reproductive status. ||Tissue senescence processes include declining metabolic activity as respiratory function reduces in post-reproductive anthers, progressive cellular breakdown with organelle degradation and membrane deterioration, enzymatic activity potentially contributing to tissue degradation, and overall physiological transition from active reproductive function to senescent degeneration. ||Dehydration dynamics show continued water loss following exhaustion with tissue moisture content declining substantially, hygroscopic responses potentially causing dimensional changes with atmospheric humidity fluctuations, and progressive desiccation creating characteristic withered shrunken appearance. ||Persistence on flower shows empty anthers typically remaining attached to filaments for extended periods despite senescence, occasional anther abscission removing senescent structures from flowers though many persist, and overall tendency for empty anthers to remain visible throughout berry development period providing lasting evidence of flowering. ||Observational value of empty anthers includes providing definitive visual confirmation of completed pollen discharge and male reproductive function, enabling post-flowering assessment of reproductive status, and serving as obvious marker that flowering concluded with developmental phase established. ||Empty anther distribution pattern at formation shows spatial gradient with earliest-emptied anthers in apical cluster regions showing most advanced senescence, progressive extension to middle and basal regions as sequential anthers exhaust and senesce, and overall cluster-level transition creating predominantly empty anther appearance by formation completion. ||Temporal development of empty state shows progressive appearance over 2-4 days following exhaustion as tissue changes proceed, accelerated formation under warm dry conditions promoting rapid senescence, and delayed formation under cool humid conditions extending fresh post-exhaustion state before obvious emptiness appears. ||Environmental effects on empty anther formation include temperature affecting senescence rate with warm conditions accelerating tissue deterioration, humidity affecting desiccation rate with dry conditions promoting rapid dehydration creating shrunken appearance, and overall conditions influencing appearance timing and characteristics. ||Functional significance of empty anther formation includes marking definitive end of male reproductive capacity confirming no further pollen production possible, providing visual evidence enabling reproductive phase assessment without detailed examination, and indicating developmental transition with established fruit set representing final reproductive outcomes. ||Relationship to fruit set outcomes shows empty anther formation coinciding with fruit set finalization, confirming that male gamete contribution completed with berry number established, and enabling assessment that observed fruit set represents complete potential from successfully pollinated flowers. ||Berry development relationship shows empty anther formation occurring while established berries undergo rapid early growth 12-20 mm diameter, contrasting appearance between senescing reproductive structures and vigorous developing fruit, and overall visual evidence of developmental phase dominance replacing reproductive function. ||Cluster appearance at empty anther formation shows mixed state with visible developing berries dominating appearance, brown senescing unfertilized flowers showing progressive abscission, empty withered anthers on successfully fertilized flowers providing brown accent, and overall transitional appearance documenting reproductive conclusion and developmental establishment. ||Management implications include confirming flowering completion through empty anther observation, recognizing that reproductive phase concluded enabling full operational resumption, and understanding that observed cluster state reflects final reproductive outcomes requiring no further pollination management. ||The process represents second and final aspect of completed pollen release emphasizing post-exhaustion structural state, following pollen exhaustion. ||Duration represents gradual development over several days as tissue senescence proceeds creating characteristic empty appearance. ||Cultivar variation in empty anther characteristics may include structural differences affecting appearance, senescence rate affecting formation timing, and persistence affecting duration that empty anthers remain visible on flowers. ||Regional timing shows empty anther formation during late June-early July in warm climates, early July in temperate regions, and early-mid July in cool areas, developing during complete anthesis as male reproductive structures transition to post-reproductive state. ||Viticultural significance includes providing obvious visual confirmation of completed male reproductive function, enabling practical assessment of flowering completion without detailed examination, and serving as definitive marker that developmental phase established with reproductive phase concluded. ||Research applications include documenting anther senescence processes and structural changes, analyzing environmental effects on post-reproductive anther characteristics, evaluating empty anther formation as practical marker for reproductive phase completion, and assessing relationships between anther senescence patterns and reproductive success outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 393-398 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-300"
},

  "Pollination": {
  "definition": "A Pollination is a Flowering involving pollen grain capture on receptive stigma surfaces, adhesion through exudate binding, and recognition processes establishing conditions for germination and fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen-stigma interaction | pollen transfer | pollination process | fertilization initiation |+ Bestäubung | Pollen-Narben-Interaktion | Pollentransfer | Befruchtungseinleitung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows pollination during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65 over 8-10 days, with successful pollen-stigma contacts occurring predominantly through self-pollination within flowers supplemented by neighboring flower wind-assisted transfer, stigma receptivity developing within 12-18 hours after flower opening and persisting 5-7 days, pollen adhesion proceeding within minutes to hours of contact, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, 54-68% relative humidity supporting efficient pollination enabling 54-64% fruit set typical of this mid-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Pollination represents essential pollen-stigma interaction within Flowering linking male pollen release to subsequent germination and fertilization. ||Corresponds to BBCH 60-65 stages parallel to Anthesis and Pollen_Release. ||Subdivided into Pollen_Capture establishing contact and retention, and Pollen_Adhesion creating stable attachment. ||Predominantly self-pollination mode in grapevine. ||Critical dependence on coordinated male-female function and favorable environmental conditions. ||Extreme weather vulnerability particularly to rain. ||Essential determinant of fruit set and yield. || This essential reproductive process occurs during flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 5-10 days from first pollen-stigma contacts through completion of pollination opportunities across cluster, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 stages parallel to anthesis and pollen release. ||Pollination mechanism in grapevine shows predominantly self-pollination mode with majority 60-80% successful pollinations occurring within individual flowers through close anther-stigma proximity facilitating direct pollen transfer, supplemented by wind-assisted neighboring flower pollination within same cluster contributing 20-35%, and limited cross-pollination between vines playing minor role <5-10% in reproductive success. ||Self-compatibility in Vitis vinifera enables effective reproduction without requiring genetically distinct pollen, eliminating obligate cross-pollination requirement found in some species, and supporting reliable fruit set through self-pollination though occasional outcrossing provides genetic diversity benefits. ||Pollen delivery mechanisms include gravitational transfer with pollen falling directly from dehiscing anthers onto stigma in same flower utilizing close 0.5-1.5 mm spatial separation, wind-assisted dispersal carrying airborne pollen to receptive stigmas within cluster or between neighboring vines, and occasional insect-mediated transfer though insects play minimal role in grapevine pollination compared to dominant wind-assisted self-pollination. ||Stigma receptivity enabling pollination shows critical female reproductive readiness with papillate surface cells elongating creating textured capture surface, proteinaceous exudate secretion producing adhesive coating trapping contacted pollen, and metabolic activation establishing capacity to support pollen hydration and germination, developing within 6-24 hours after flower opening and persisting 4-7 days though declining progressively. ||Stigma structure supporting pollination includes bilobed organization creating expanded surface area maximizing pollen capture probability, papillate epidermal cells with elongated projections 40-80 micrometers length providing mechanical retention structures, stigmatic exudate coating surfaces with adhesive proteinaceous fluid, and overall architecture optimized for efficient pollen capture and retention. ||Pollen-stigma contact represents initial pollination event with airborne or directly transferred pollen grain contacting stigma papillate surface, physical contact establishing opportunity for adhesion and recognition, and successful contact depending on pollen availability, stigma receptivity, and favorable environmental conditions. ||Pollen adhesion follows contact with stigmatic exudate providing adhesive binding trapping contacted grain on surface, molecular interactions between pollen coat proteins and stigma exudate components creating stable attachment, and physical retention by papillate cell structure preventing grain loss, establishing secure pollen-stigma association. ||Pollen recognition involves molecular signaling between pollen coat proteins and stigma exudate receptors enabling species recognition, compatibility assessment determining acceptance or rejection though grapevine shows self-compatibility, and triggering of downstream responses including pollen hydration and germination support if compatible. ||Pollen hydration on receptive stigma represents critical transition with grain absorbing water from stigmatic exudate within 15-90 minutes enabling metabolic activation, cell rehydration restoring physiological function after atmospheric desiccation, and establishing conditions for germination initiation within 1-4 hours under favorable conditions. ||Pollination efficiency in grapevine shows high success rates under favorable conditions with estimated 50-70% flowers achieving successful pollination leading to fruit set in good-setting cultivars, declining to 30-50% under suboptimal conditions or difficult-setting varieties, and demonstrating critical dependence on coordinated male-female reproductive function and favorable environmental conditions. ||Environmental effects on pollination show temperature affecting both pollen viability and stigma function with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient pollination, humidity influencing pollen dispersibility and viability with moderate 50-65% optimal, and rain catastrophically disrupting pollination through washing pollen from surfaces, diluting stigmatic exudate, and physically damaging reproductive structures. ||Temperature effects on pollination include warm conditions supporting pollen viability maintenance, stigma metabolic activity, and efficient pollen-stigma interactions, cool conditions below 18°C substantially reducing pollination efficiency through impaired pollen and stigma function, and excessive heat above 33°C potentially causing pollen sterility or stigma dysfunction. ||Humidity effects show moderate levels optimal for maintaining pollen viability during dispersal and transfer, preserving stigmatic exudate adhesive properties, and supporting overall reproductive function, while high humidity above 75% potentially diluting exudate reducing adhesion, and low humidity below 45% causing pollen desiccation reducing viability. ||Rain effects represent catastrophic interference with water washing pollen from stigma surfaces eliminating captured grains, diluting or removing stigmatic exudate preventing adhesion, preventing pollen dispersal and transfer through elevated humidity and physical impedance, and promoting fungal infection on wet reproductive tissues, potentially reducing fruit set by 60-80% if occurring during peak pollination. ||Boron nutrition critically affects pollination success with adequate boron essential for stigma exudate production and pollen function, deficiency causing poor stigma receptivity and impaired pollen germination severely reducing fruit set even with adequate pollen availability, and emphasizing importance of sufficient boron supply during flowering period. ||Timing relationships show pollination requiring coordination between pollen availability and stigma receptivity with optimal overlap during peak anthesis creating maximum success opportunity, early or late pollination attempts showing reduced efficiency due to suboptimal pollen viability or stigma receptivity, and successful pollination typically occurring within 1-3 days of flower opening during receptivity peak. ||Fruit set dependence on pollination shows direct causal relationship with successful pollen-stigma interaction, adhesion, and recognition enabling subsequent germination and fertilization, while failed pollination due to pollen absence, stigma dysfunction, or unfavorable conditions causing flower abortion and fruit set failure, demonstrating pollination as critical limiting step determining berry number and yield. ||The process shows two major phases progressing from pollen capture establishing initial contact and retention, through pollen adhesion creating stable attachment enabling subsequent processes. ||Duration typically spans 5-10 days at cluster level as flowers sequentially open and achieve pollination, with individual pollination events occurring rapidly within hours once pollen contacts receptive stigma. ||Cultivar variation appears in pollination characteristics including self-compatibility levels affecting pollination success reliability, stigma receptivity characteristics affecting capture efficiency, and sensitivity to environmental conditions affecting pollination under marginal conditions. ||Regional timing shows pollination during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding precisely with flowering period and representing critical reproductive window. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential process linking male pollen production to female fertilization, requiring optimal environmental conditions particularly avoiding rain during pollination period, demonstrating extreme weather vulnerability with brief window determining season productivity, and establishing pollination success as primary determinant of fruit set and yield outcomes. ||Research applications include analyzing pollen-stigma interaction mechanisms including molecular recognition and adhesion processes, investigating environmental effects on pollination efficiency affecting reproductive success, evaluating pollen dispersal and capture dynamics, quantifying relationships between pollination characteristics and fruit set outcomes, and assessing management or genetic interventions affecting pollination success and productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009856 ## pollination | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 375-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 285-295 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Capture": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Capture is a Pollination comprising the contact and retention of airborne or directly transferred pollen grains on receptive stigma surfaces through physical and adhesive mechanisms.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen interception | pollen-stigma contact establishment | pollen retention initiation |+ Pollenfang | Pollenabfang | Pollen-Narben-Kontaktaufbau | Pollenretentions-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows pollen capture during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65 over 7-9 days, with successful captures occurring predominantly through direct gravitational transfer from anthers 0.8-1.2 mm above stigmas supplemented by short-range wind-assisted delivery, papillate stigma surfaces with exudate coating capturing and retaining 12-35 pollen grains per stigma during peak period, under warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature, 50-64% relative humidity, supporting efficient capture enabling 58-68% fruit set typical of this late-season cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Capture is first major Pollination phase establishing initial pollen-stigma contact and retention. ||Subdivided into Pollen_Stigma_Contact and Pollen_Adhesion_Initiation. ||Represents critical first step linking pollen delivery to subsequent adhesion. ||Predominantly gravitational self-pollination in grapevine supplemented by wind-assisted transfer. ||Stigma morphology and exudate essential for efficient capture. ||Rapid individual events seconds to minutes. ||Environmental sensitivity particularly to rain washing captured pollen away. ||Transitions to Pollen_Adhesion as attachment strengthens. || This essential capture process occurs during flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 5-10 days as flowers sequentially open and become receptive for pollen capture across cluster, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 stages during anthesis period. ||Capture mechanisms involve multiple processes including pollen-stigma contact through aerial delivery or direct transfer establishing physical encounter, initial retention by stigma surface features preventing immediate loss, and beginning adhesion through stigmatic exudate interaction creating preliminary attachment. ||Pollen delivery modes enabling capture include gravitational transfer with pollen falling directly from dehiscing anthers in same flower representing 60-80% successful captures in self-pollination, wind-assisted aerial dispersal carrying pollen grains to stigmas within cluster or between neighboring plants contributing 20-35% captures, and occasional insect contact though playing minimal role <5% in grapevine pollen capture compared to dominant wind-gravity mechanisms. ||Self-pollination capture efficiency shows high success through close spatial proximity with anthers positioned 0.5-1.5 mm above stigma facilitating direct pollen fall, anther dehiscence typically occurring within 6-24 hours of stigma receptivity development creating temporal coordination, and favorable geometry supporting efficient pollen transfer from anthers to stigma in same flower. ||Wind-assisted capture dynamics involve atmospheric pollen transport delivering grains to receptive stigmas, pollen trajectory interception by protruding stigma structures, and contact probability depending on pollen concentration, wind patterns, and stigma exposure, with capture efficiency declining with distance from pollen source. ||Stigma morphology affecting capture includes bilobed structure creating expanded 2-4 mm² surface area providing increased interception probability, papillate epidermal cells with elongated 40-80 micrometer projections creating rough textured surface enhancing capture, stigma positioning above flower receptacle creating exposure to airborne pollen, and overall architecture optimized for efficient pollen grain interception. ||Papillate cell function in capture shows mechanical role with projecting cells creating physical barriers catching contacted pollen, increased surface area providing greater capture probability, and three-dimensional structure creating pollen retention sites preventing grain loss after initial contact. ||Stigmatic exudate role in capture includes adhesive properties providing immediate preliminary binding upon contact, chemical signals potentially attracting or guiding pollen though evidence limited in grapevine, and hydration medium enabling pollen recognition and attachment initiation. ||Pollen-stigma contact geometry shows typical scenario with pollen grain 25-35 micrometers diameter contacting papillate cell tip or side, initial mechanical retention by cell morphology preventing immediate rebound or loss, and exudate coating providing adhesive interface enabling attachment. ||Contact probability factors include pollen availability with higher atmospheric concentration increasing contact likelihood, stigma receptivity status with active exudate production optimizing capture, spatial positioning with well-exposed stigmas showing greater capture success, and environmental conditions affecting both pollen dispersal and stigma function. ||Multiple pollen capture per stigma shows typical pattern with receptive stigma receiving 10-50 pollen grains during peak pollination period though only 1-2 successful germinations required for fertilization, excess captures providing reproductive assurance compensating for possible germination failures, and demonstrated pollen surplus supporting high fertilization success. ||Capture timing shows rapid initial contact occurring within seconds to minutes once pollen reaches stigma vicinity, preliminary retention establishing within seconds through mechanical and adhesive mechanisms, and transition to stable adhesion proceeding over minutes to hours as exudate binding strengthens. ||Stigma receptivity requirements for successful capture include active exudate production creating adhesive surface, papillate cell expansion creating optimal capture geometry, and metabolic readiness supporting pollen recognition and hydration, developing within 6-24 hours after flower opening and providing 4-7 day capture window. ||Environmental effects on capture efficiency include temperature affecting pollen viability during transfer and stigma exudate properties, humidity influencing pollen dispersibility and exudate consistency, wind conditions affecting aerial delivery and contact probability, and rain catastrophically preventing capture through washing pollen away and diluting or removing exudate. ||Temperature effects on capture show optimal 22-28°C supporting both pollen viability during dispersal and stigma exudate function, cool conditions potentially reducing capture efficiency through impaired exudate production or consistency, and warm conditions generally favorable though excessive heat above 33°C potentially affecting stigma function. ||Humidity effects include moderate 50-65% levels optimal for maintaining pollen dispersibility during transfer and appropriate exudate consistency for capture, high humidity above 75% potentially diluting exudate reducing capture efficiency, and low humidity below 45% potentially affecting exudate properties though generally acceptable for mechanical capture. ||Rain effects show devastating interference with water washing newly captured pollen from stigma surfaces, diluting or removing exudate eliminating adhesive capture capacity, preventing pollen delivery through elevated humidity impeding dispersal, and physically damaging stigma structures, causing severe capture failure and fruit set reduction. ||Capture success assessment methods include stigma examination under magnification counting captured pollen grains, fluorescence microscopy techniques visualizing pollen on stigma surfaces, and pollination bag experiments excluding pollen sources evaluating capture efficiency under controlled conditions. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from pollen-stigma contact establishing initial physical encounter, through pollen adhesion initiation beginning attachment processes. ||Duration represents rapid events occurring over seconds to minutes for individual captures, with cluster-level capture period spanning 5-10 days as flowers sequentially achieve receptivity. ||Cultivar variation in capture efficiency shows differences in stigma morphology affecting interception, exudate production affecting adhesion capacity, and anther-stigma positioning affecting self-pollination capture success. ||Regional timing shows pollen capture during late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with flowering period when pollen available and stigmas receptive. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical first step in pollination determining fruit set potential, requiring favorable environmental conditions avoiding rain during capture period, demonstrating importance of coordinated pollen availability and stigma receptivity, and establishing capture success as initial determinant of subsequent fertilization and berry development. ||Research applications include analyzing capture mechanisms including aerodynamic, morphological, and adhesive factors, quantifying capture efficiency under varying environmental conditions, evaluating stigma morphology effects on capture success, investigating pollen delivery dynamics and contact probabilities, and assessing relationships between capture characteristics and ultimate fruit set outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 378-382 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-290 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Stigma_Contact": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Stigma_Contact is a Pollen_Capture marked by the initial physical encounter between pollen grain and papillate epidermal cells of the receptive stigma surface.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen landing | initial pollen-stigma encounter | pollen grain contact | pollen interception |+ Pollenkontakt | Pollenlandung | initiale Pollen-Narben-Begegnung | Pollenkornberührung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows pollen-stigma contact during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with pollen grains 28-32 micrometers diameter contacting papillate stigma cells 45-65 micrometers length through primarily gravitational descent from anthers 0.9-1.4 mm above stigma supplemented by short-range wind-assisted delivery, initial mechanical retention by cell morphology and exudate viscosity preventing grain loss within milliseconds of contact, under Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar establishing 12-25 pollen contacts per stigma during peak period",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Stigma_Contact is first aspect of Pollen_Capture, distinguished by initial physical encounter between grain and stigma surface. ||Represents critical first interaction in pollination. ||Very brief event milliseconds to seconds. ||Requires appropriate pollen trajectory and receptive stigma state. ||Mechanical and initial adhesive retention prevent immediate grain loss. ||Followed by Pollen_Adhesion_Initiation as attachment develops. ||Essential prerequisite for subsequent pollination processes. ||Multiple contact events typical per stigma. || This critical contact event occurs during pollen capture in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically occurring within seconds of pollen arrival at stigma vicinity as part of BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Contact establishment involves pollen grain trajectory intersecting with stigma surface, physical collision or gentle landing on papillate cell projections, and immediate preliminary retention preventing grain rebound or loss through mechanical and initial adhesive interactions. ||Contact geometry shows typical scenario with spheroidal pollen grain 25-35 micrometers diameter contacting elongated papillate cell tip or lateral surface, grain orientation variable depending on arrival trajectory, and contact area initially small point contact expanding as grain settles and adhesion develops. ||Pollen approach trajectories include vertical descent for gravitational self-pollination with pollen falling from anthers directly above contacting stigma from above, lateral approach for wind-dispersed pollen with grains traveling horizontally or at angles contacting stigma sides, and variable trajectories depending on air currents and pollen release dynamics. ||Contact velocity shows low-energy encounters with gravitational pollen having terminal velocity approximately 1-3 cm per second enabling gentle landing, wind-dispersed pollen showing variable velocities depending on wind speed though typically <10 cm per second, and overall low-impact contacts compatible with maintaining grain integrity and enabling adhesion. ||Papillate cell contact surface provides reception site with cells projecting 40-80 micrometers from stigma surface creating three-dimensional capture zone, cell tips and sides presenting contact areas coated with stigmatic exudate, and cellular architecture providing mechanical retention features preventing immediate grain loss. ||Initial mechanical retention shows immediate effects with papillate cell surface irregularities creating physical barriers preventing grain rolling or sliding, exudate viscosity providing immediate preliminary adhesion resisting grain detachment, and contact geometry creating stable positioning enabling adhesion development. ||Stigmatic exudate at contact interface provides immediate adhesive properties with proteinaceous fluid coating papillate cell surfaces, viscous consistency creating resistance to grain movement, and beginning hydration of pollen grain enabling recognition and attachment processes. ||Pollen grain surface at contact shows intact exine wall with sculptured surface patterns and apertures, pollen coat substances from tapetal origin affecting adhesion properties, and grain structure maintaining integrity enabling subsequent recognition and germination. ||Contact duration shows initial transient phase lasting milliseconds to seconds as grain physically contacts surface and settles, transitional phase over seconds to minutes as preliminary adhesion develops, and stabilization over minutes to hours as firm attachment establishes through exudate binding. ||Multiple contact possibilities show stigma potentially receiving numerous pollen grains creating multiple simultaneous or sequential contact events, each grain establishing independent contact and adhesion, and typical receptive stigma experiencing 10-50 contact events during peak pollination creating pollen surplus. ||Contact success factors include appropriate pollen arrival trajectory enabling physical encounter, receptive stigma state with active exudate production providing adhesive surface, adequate pollen viability maintaining grain integrity during transfer and contact, and favorable environmental conditions preventing interference with contact establishment. ||Failed contact scenarios include pollen missing stigma due to unfavorable trajectory or wind conditions, contacted pollen failing to retain due to inadequate exudate or mechanical retention, or damaged pollen unable to establish viable contact due to structural compromise. ||Environmental effects on contact include wind affecting pollen arrival trajectory and contact probability, humidity influencing exudate properties affecting initial adhesion, temperature affecting tissue properties and exudate consistency, and rain preventing contact through washing pollen away or removing adhesive exudate. ||Temperature at contact affects exudate viscosity and adhesive properties with optimal 22-28°C supporting appropriate consistency for capture, cool conditions potentially increasing viscosity affecting contact dynamics, and warm conditions potentially reducing viscosity though generally maintaining adequate adhesion capacity. ||Humidity at contact influences exudate water content and consistency with moderate 50-65% maintaining appropriate properties for adhesion, high humidity above 75% potentially diluting exudate reducing capture efficiency, and low humidity below 45% potentially concentrating exudate though may affect subsequent hydration. ||Contact observation requires microscopic examination with light microscopy at 100-400x magnification enabling pollen grain visualization on stigma surfaces, fluorescence techniques using aniline blue or other fluorochromes highlighting pollen and enabling clear observation, and scanning electron microscopy providing detailed ultrastructural views of pollen-stigma contact geometry. ||Contact as pollination initiation shows this first physical encounter representing critical starting point for reproductive success, successful contact enabling subsequent adhesion development, pollen hydration, recognition, and germination, and failed contact eliminating pollination opportunity for that particular pollen-stigma pair. ||The process represents first aspect of pollen capture emphasizing initial physical encounter, followed by pollen adhesion initiation as attachment begins developing. ||Duration represents very brief event occurring over milliseconds to seconds as physical contact establishes. ||Cultivar variation in contact characteristics may include stigma morphology affecting contact probability and geometry, exudate properties affecting initial retention, and flower architecture affecting pollen delivery trajectories. ||Regional timing shows pollen-stigma contact events occurring during flowering period late May-early June in warm climates, early-mid June in temperate regions, and mid-late June in cool areas, coinciding with pollen availability and stigma receptivity periods. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential first encounter in pollination process, requiring optimal conditions avoiding rain preventing contact, demonstrating importance of coordinated pollen delivery and stigma receptivity, and establishing contact success as prerequisite for subsequent fertilization. ||Research applications include analyzing contact mechanics and physics, investigating stigma morphology effects on contact probability and retention, evaluating environmental effects on contact success, developing visualization techniques for observing contact events, and quantifying relationships between contact characteristics and pollination outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 378-380 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Adhesion_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Adhesion_Initiation is a Pollen_Capture characterized by preliminary binding between pollen surface and stigmatic exudate following contact.",
  "alternative_term": "preliminary pollen attachment | adhesion beginning | initial pollen binding | pollen retention establishment |+ Adhäsions-Initiierung | vorläufige Pollenhaftung | Bindungsbeginn | initiale Pollenanbindung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows pollen adhesion initiation during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with stigmatic exudate containing lipid transfer proteins and polysaccharides creating molecular adhesion within 30-90 seconds of pollen contact, preliminary attachment strengthening over 8-15 minutes through exudate binding, pollen grain beginning hydration within 15-45 minutes enabling metabolic activation, under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 58-72% relative humidity, typical of this early-bursting cultivar with adequate boron nutrition supporting normal exudate production and adhesion development",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Adhesion_Initiation is second aspect of Pollen_Capture, distinguished by beginning attachment development following contact. ||Represents transition from transient contact to preliminary stable association. ||Duration seconds to minutes as molecular and physical adhesion develops. ||Involves stigmatic exudate interaction with pollen surface. ||Critical role of lipid transfer proteins and exudate viscosity. ||Beginning pollen hydration and recognition. ||Transitions to Pollen_Adhesion as firm attachment establishes. ||Boron nutrition essential for normal function. || This critical attachment initiation occurs during pollen capture in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over seconds to minutes following initial contact as part of BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Adhesion initiation mechanism involves stigmatic exudate proteins and polysaccharides contacting pollen grain surface creating molecular interactions, physical adhesion developing through viscous exudate properties resisting grain detachment, and beginning recognition processes as pollen coat substances interact with exudate components. ||Stigmatic exudate composition enabling adhesion includes proteinaceous components particularly lipid transfer proteins creating adhesive binding, polysaccharides providing viscous matrix and molecular recognition sites, lipids affecting surface properties and possibly pollen coat interaction, and water providing hydration medium for molecular interactions and pollen grain rehydration. ||Lipid transfer protein function shows adhesive role with proteins abundant in stigmatic exudate binding pollen coat lipids, creating molecular bridges between exudate and pollen surface, and initiating recognition processes through protein-lipid interactions enabling species identification and compatibility assessment. ||Exudate viscosity providing adhesion shows physical adhesive properties with viscous fluid resisting forces that would dislodge grain, maintaining pollen positioning on stigma surface through mechanical resistance, and creating stable attachment even before molecular binding fully develops. ||Pollen coat interaction with exudate involves pollen surface substances from tapetal origin including proteins, lipids, and polysaccharides contacting exudate components, molecular recognition occurring through complementary binding sites, and triggering of downstream processes including enhanced adhesion and hydration support if compatibility confirmed. ||Molecular recognition initiation shows beginning species and compatibility assessment with pollen coat proteins interacting with stigma exudate receptors, self-recognition signals in self-compatible grapevine confirming appropriate species and enabling continued adhesion development, and acceptance response triggering enhanced exudate binding and pollen hydration support. ||Pollen grain hydration beginning shows initial water uptake from stigmatic exudate occurring within 15-90 minutes of contact, grain expanding slightly as cells rehydrate from desiccated atmospheric state, and metabolic activation initiating as hydration restores physiological function enabling subsequent germination. ||Adhesion strength development shows progressive increase from weak preliminary attachment immediately after contact, strengthening over minutes as molecular interactions develop, to moderate adhesion within 5-15 minutes providing resistance to environmental disturbances, and transition to firm adhesion over 15-60 minutes creating stable long-term attachment. ||Mechanical adhesion testing shows increasing resistance to detachment forces with preliminary adhesion resisting only gentle disturbances within seconds of contact, developing adhesion withstanding moderate mechanical forces within minutes, and mature adhesion requiring substantial force for grain removal after 15-30 minutes. ||Environmental effects on adhesion initiation include temperature affecting exudate viscosity and molecular interaction kinetics with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient adhesion development, humidity influencing exudate water content and consistency with moderate 50-65% maintaining appropriate properties, and rain catastrophically disrupting adhesion through diluting or washing away exudate preventing attachment development. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster adhesion development through enhanced molecular interaction kinetics, cool conditions slowing adhesion initiation potentially requiring longer time for stable attachment, and optimal 24-26°C range supporting rapid efficient adhesion development within minutes. ||Humidity effects include moderate levels maintaining appropriate exudate consistency for adhesion with proper water content supporting molecular interactions, high humidity above 75% potentially diluting exudate weakening adhesive properties, and low humidity below 45% potentially concentrating exudate affecting diffusion and molecular mobility. ||Boron nutrition effects show critical importance with adequate boron essential for normal stigmatic exudate production and composition, deficiency causing reduced exudate quantity or altered composition impairing adhesion initiation, and emphasizing importance of sufficient boron availability during flowering for normal pollination function. ||Failed adhesion initiation results from inadequate exudate production preventing preliminary binding development, abnormal exudate composition lacking essential adhesive components, pollen grain damage compromising surface properties preventing interaction, or environmental interference particularly rain removing exudate before adhesion establishes. ||Multiple pollen adhesion initiation shows independent processes with each contacted grain undergoing separate adhesion development, simultaneous adhesion of multiple grains on same stigma creating pollen surplus, and typical stigma supporting 10-50 attached grains during peak pollination though only 1-2 ultimately germinating successfully. ||Adhesion as reversible process shows early adhesion potentially reversible if environmental disturbance or molecular recognition failure occurs, transition to irreversible adhesion as molecular binding strengthens and hydration proceeds, and point of no return reached within 15-30 minutes when firm attachment establishes. ||Stigma papillate cell response to adhesion shows possible subtle changes in cell metabolism supporting pollen attachment, continued exudate secretion maintaining adhesive environment, and beginning preparation for supporting pollen germination and tube growth. ||The process represents second aspect of pollen capture emphasizing attachment development, following pollen-stigma contact. ||Duration spans seconds to minutes as preliminary adhesion develops transitioning to stable attachment. ||Cultivar variation in adhesion initiation may include exudate composition affecting adhesive properties, exudate production rate affecting attachment speed, and pollen coat characteristics affecting molecular interactions. ||Regional timing shows adhesion initiation occurring during flowering period across all climates immediately following pollen-stigma contact events coinciding with pollen availability and stigma receptivity. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical transition from transient contact to stable attachment, requiring adequate stigma exudate production and appropriate environmental conditions, demonstrating importance of boron nutrition for normal function, and establishing successful adhesion as prerequisite for subsequent germination and fertilization. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of adhesion including protein-lipid interactions, investigating exudate composition and adhesive properties, evaluating environmental and nutritional effects on adhesion development, quantifying adhesion strength dynamics and kinetics, and assessing relationships between adhesion characteristics and pollination success.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-382 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-290 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Adhesion": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Adhesion is a Pollination consisting of stable molecular binding between pollen grain and stigmatic exudate resistant to environmental disturbance.",
  "alternative_term": "stable pollen attachment | firm pollen binding | pollen-stigma adhesion | secure pollen retention |+ Pollenadhäsion | stabile Pollenhaftung | feste Pollenanbindung | sichere Pollenretention",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows pollen adhesion during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with firm molecular binding developing within 20-45 minutes after contact through stigmatic exudate lipid transfer proteins and polysaccharide matrix, creating stable attachment resistant to moderate wind and environmental disturbances, supporting 14-32 securely attached pollen grains per stigma, under continental conditions of 20-26°C temperature, 56-70% relative humidity, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar with adequate boron nutrition supporting normal exudate production and adhesion enabling subsequent germination",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Adhesion is second major Pollination phase distinguished by firm stable attachment following preliminary capture. ||Subdivided into Stigmatic_Exudate_Binding emphasizing molecular mechanisms and Pollen_Grain_Attachment focusing on stable association. ||Develops over 15-60 minutes following adhesion initiation. ||Critical role of lipid transfer proteins and exudate matrix. ||Substantial resistance to detachment forces. ||Boron nutrition essential for normal exudate and adhesion. ||Enables subsequent pollen hydration, recognition, germination. ||Essential stable association for reproductive success. || This critical stable attachment phase occurs during pollination in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, developing over 15-60 minutes following adhesion initiation as firm binding establishes, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Adhesion characteristics show firm molecular binding between pollen coat proteins and stigmatic exudate components creating stable attachment, physical adhesion through viscous exudate matrix resisting detachment forces, mechanical retention by papillate cell architecture preventing grain displacement, and overall secure association enabling continued pollen-stigma interaction without risk of grain loss. ||Molecular binding mechanisms involve protein-protein interactions between pollen coat adhesins and stigma exudate receptors creating specific high-affinity bonds, protein-lipid interactions with stigma lipid transfer proteins binding pollen coat lipids, polysaccharide interactions between pollen wall polymers and exudate carbohydrates, and integrated molecular network creating robust multi-point attachment. ||Lipid transfer protein function in adhesion shows critical role with proteins abundant in grapevine stigmatic exudate binding pollen coat lipids creating strong molecular bridges, mediating species recognition through lipid-binding specificity, and contributing substantially to adhesion strength through multiple binding sites per grain. ||Exudate matrix role shows physical adhesive function with proteinaceous-polysaccharide network embedding pollen grain creating mechanical retention, viscous properties resisting shear forces preventing grain sliding or rolling, and hydrated gel-like consistency maintaining stable grain positioning throughout receptivity period. ||Pollen coat substances participating in adhesion include proteins from tapetal origin on grain surface providing binding sites for exudate interactions, lipids including tryphine components mediating lipid transfer protein binding, polysaccharides in pollen wall participating in carbohydrate interactions, and integrated coat composition determining adhesion capacity and recognition properties. ||Adhesion strength at maturity shows substantial resistance to detachment with established adhesion requiring significant mechanical force for grain removal, resistance to environmental disturbances including wind, rain, or physical contact, and stable attachment persisting throughout pollen hydration, germination, and initial tube growth phases. ||Mechanical adhesion assessment through controlled detachment experiments shows mature adhesion withstanding forces 100-500 times grain weight, demonstrating robust attachment supporting reproductive success, and confirming that normal environmental conditions insufficient to dislodge properly adhered pollen. ||Pollen grain hydration accompanying adhesion shows continued water uptake from stigmatic exudate over 15-90 minutes following adhesion, grain expanding 10-20% volumetrically as cells fully rehydrate, and metabolic activation proceeding as hydration restores physiological function enabling germination capacity. ||Recognition processes during adhesion involve molecular signaling between pollen and stigma assessing compatibility, self-compatible grapevine showing acceptance of self-pollen enabling continued support, and recognition triggering downstream responses including enhanced exudate secretion and metabolic support for germination. ||Stigma papillate cell response to adhesion shows maintained exudate secretion supporting attached pollen, possible localized metabolic activation in cells bearing pollen preparing to support germination and tube growth, and continued provision of water and possibly nutrients enabling pollen function. ||Multiple pollen adhesion on single stigma shows typical pattern with receptive stigma supporting 10-50 firmly attached grains though only 1-2 ultimately germinating successfully, excess adhesion providing reproductive assurance compensating for possible germination failures, and demonstrating pollen surplus characteristic of wind-pollinated mode supplementing self-pollination. ||Adhesion persistence shows stable attachment maintained throughout pollination and early germination periods spanning hours to days, attachment remaining firm during pollen tube emergence and initial penetration of stigma surface, and long-term association as germinated pollen develops tube growing through style tissues. ||Environmental effects on adhesion stability include temperature affecting exudate properties and molecular binding stability with optimal 22-28°C maintaining robust adhesion, humidity influencing exudate water content and consistency with moderate 50-65% optimal, and rain potentially disrupting adhesion through dilution or physical washing requiring substantial water volume to overcome established adhesion. ||Temperature stability of adhesion shows maintained attachment across typical flowering temperature range 15-32°C, potential minor weakening at temperature extremes though generally retaining adequate binding, and thermal stability of molecular interactions supporting adhesion function under varying conditions. ||Humidity effects on established adhesion show relative stability across normal range 40-75% with adhesion persisting despite exudate water content changes, high humidity potentially causing slight adhesion weakening through excessive dilution though established binding maintains attachment, and low humidity potentially strengthening adhesion through exudate concentration though may affect pollen hydration. ||Rain resistance of established adhesion shows substantial water required to disrupt firm binding, light rain or brief showers potentially insufficient to remove adhered pollen though may affect subsequent processes, and heavy sustained rain potentially washing attached pollen particularly if occurring shortly after adhesion before maximal binding develops. ||Boron nutrition importance for adhesion emphasizes adequate boron essential for normal stigmatic exudate production supporting adhesion capacity, deficiency reducing exudate quantity and possibly altering composition impairing adhesion strength, and demonstrating critical role of boron in supporting pollination success through effects on adhesion. ||Failed adhesion causing pollination failure results from inadequate exudate production preventing binding development, abnormal pollen coat composition compromising molecular interactions, environmental interference particularly rain diluting or removing exudate, or developmental abnormalities affecting stigma or pollen function. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from stigmatic exudate binding creating molecular attachment, through pollen grain attachment establishing stable long-term association. ||Duration represents developing over 15-60 minutes as firm adhesion establishes, with stable attachment persisting hours to days supporting subsequent processes. ||Cultivar variation in adhesion may include exudate composition affecting binding mechanisms and strength, exudate production quantity affecting adhesion capacity, and pollen coat characteristics affecting molecular interaction quality. ||Regional timing shows pollen adhesion occurring during flowering period across all climates following pollen capture events, developing as stable attachment within minutes to hour after initial contact. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential stable attachment enabling subsequent germination and fertilization, requiring adequate stigma exudate production and favorable environmental conditions, demonstrating critical role of boron nutrition in supporting adhesion through exudate effects, and establishing adhesion success as prerequisite for reproductive success and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of adhesion including binding specificities and affinities, investigating exudate composition effects on adhesion properties, evaluating environmental and nutritional factors affecting adhesion stability, quantifying adhesion strength and resistance to disturbance, and assessing relationships between adhesion characteristics and pollination success outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 287-292 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Stigmatic_Exudate_Binding": {
  "definition": "A Stigmatic_Exudate_Binding is a Pollen_Adhesion involving high-affinity molecular interactions between stigma-secreted proteins, polysaccharides, and lipids and pollen coat substances.",
  "alternative_term": "molecular pollen adhesion | exudate-pollen binding | stigma protein binding | adhesion molecule interaction |+ stigmatische Exsudat-Bindung | molekulare Pollenadhäsion | Exsudat-Pollen-Bindung | Adhäsionsmolekül-Interaktion",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows stigmatic exudate binding during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with lipid transfer proteins in exudate binding pollen coat lipids creating molecular bridges within 15-35 minutes of contact, polysaccharide matrix contributing to viscous adhesion, cumulative molecular interactions creating binding strength resisting 200-400 times pollen grain weight, under oceanic conditions of 21-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar with adequate boron nutrition supporting normal exudate production enabling robust molecular binding and adhesion",
  "editor_note": "Stigmatic_Exudate_Binding is first aspect of Pollen_Adhesion, distinguished by molecular mechanism emphasis. ||Represents specific high-affinity protein-lipid-polysaccharide interactions securing attachment. ||Critical role of lipid transfer proteins in grapevine. ||Develops over 10-45 minutes as molecular network strengthens. ||Boron nutrition essential for normal exudate production and binding. ||Enables species recognition and compatibility assessment. ||Followed by Pollen_Grain_Attachment discussing overall stable association. ||Molecular foundation for successful pollination. || This critical molecular binding process occurs during pollen adhesion in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, developing over 10-45 minutes following initial contact as molecular interactions strengthen, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Binding mechanism involves multiple molecular interactions including protein-protein binding between pollen coat adhesins and stigma exudate receptors creating direct protein bridges, protein-lipid interactions with stigma lipid transfer proteins binding pollen coat lipids mediating both adhesion and recognition, polysaccharide-polysaccharide interactions between pollen wall polymers and exudate carbohydrates, and integrated multi-molecular binding network creating robust attachment. ||Stigmatic exudate composition enabling binding includes proteinaceous components representing 30-50% dry weight with lipid transfer proteins as major constituent mediating pollen binding, structural glycoproteins contributing to matrix formation and possibly providing binding sites, polysaccharides representing 20-40% composition creating viscous matrix and carbohydrate binding sites, lipids 5-15% affecting surface properties and possibly involved in recognition, and water comprising 60-75% fresh weight providing hydration medium for molecular interactions. ||Lipid transfer protein function shows central role in binding with proteins abundant in grapevine stigmatic exudate typically 20-40% total protein, proteins binding pollen coat lipids through hydrophobic pocket creating strong molecular bridge, lipid-binding specificity potentially contributing to species recognition, and proteins serving dual adhesion and recognition functions critical for pollination success. ||Pollen coat substances participating in binding include proteins from tapetal origin coating grain surface providing binding partners for exudate proteins, lipids including tryphine components representing major constituent binding lipid transfer proteins creating strong attachment, polysaccharides in exine wall participating in carbohydrate interactions, and sporopollenin polymers possibly contributing to binding through surface properties. ||Protein-protein binding characteristics show high-affinity interactions with dissociation constants in nanomolar to micromolar range indicating strong binding, specificity enabling species and compatibility recognition, and multiple binding sites per grain creating robust multi-point attachment resisting detachment forces. ||Protein-lipid binding through lipid transfer proteins shows hydrophobic interactions with protein internal cavity binding pollen coat lipids, binding affinity in low micromolar range creating strong associations, and lipid-binding specificity potentially discriminating between compatible and incompatible pollen though grapevine shows self-compatibility. ||Polysaccharide binding mechanisms involve carbohydrate-carbohydrate interactions between pollen wall polysaccharides and exudate carbohydrates, possible lectin-mediated binding with exudate proteins recognizing pollen wall sugar residues, and hydrogen bonding networks creating stable though individually weak interactions that collectively contribute substantial binding strength. ||Molecular binding kinetics show progressive strength development with initial weak binding within seconds of contact, strengthening over minutes as molecular interactions develop and multiply, and reaching maximum binding within 15-45 minutes creating stable robust attachment. ||Binding specificity enabling recognition shows molecular interactions mediating species identification through complementary binding determinants, self-compatibility in grapevine showing acceptance of self-pollen through compatible molecular signatures, and recognition triggering downstream responses including enhanced exudate secretion and pollen hydration support. ||Binding affinity characteristics show strong associations with multiple high-affinity interactions creating robust attachment, cumulative binding strength from numerous molecular bridges exceeding requirements for stable adhesion, and binding stability maintaining attachment throughout pollen hydration, germination, and tube growth phases. ||Exudate matrix role in binding provides physical scaffold embedding pollen grain, viscous network distributing mechanical forces across multiple binding sites preventing localized stress concentrations, and hydrated gel-like environment maintaining appropriate conditions for molecular interactions and pollen function. ||Binding site density on pollen surface shows numerous potential interaction sites with pollen coat covering grain surface providing extensive binding opportunity, estimated hundreds to thousands of individual molecular interactions per grain creating redundant robust attachment, and multiple binding points distributing adhesion force preventing single-point failure. ||Environmental effects on binding include temperature affecting molecular interaction kinetics with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid binding development, extreme temperatures potentially affecting binding affinity though normally stable across flowering temperature range 15-32°C, humidity influencing exudate water content affecting molecular accessibility and diffusion rates with moderate 50-65% optimal, and pH possibly affecting binding characteristics though exudate buffering maintains appropriate range. ||Temperature effects on binding kinetics show warm conditions 24-28°C promoting faster binding development through enhanced molecular diffusion and interaction rates, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing binding though ultimately reaching similar strength, and excessive heat above 33°C potentially affecting protein stability though normally not encountered during optimal flowering conditions. ||Boron effects on exudate and binding show critical importance with adequate boron essential for normal exudate production affecting binding substrate availability, boron possibly affecting exudate composition particularly polysaccharide components influencing binding properties, and deficiency reducing binding capacity through quantitative and qualitative exudate effects severely impairing pollination success. ||Binding as reversible process shows early binding potentially reversible before full molecular network develops, transition to effectively irreversible state within 15-30 minutes as numerous high-affinity interactions establish, and mature binding requiring extreme conditions for disruption normally not encountered during successful pollination. ||Failed binding causing adhesion failure results from inadequate exudate production reducing binding substrate availability, abnormal exudate composition lacking essential binding components particularly lipid transfer proteins, pollen coat abnormalities compromising binding partner availability, or environmental interference particularly rain diluting exudate preventing adequate molecular interactions. ||The process represents first aspect of pollen adhesion emphasizing molecular binding mechanisms, followed by pollen grain attachment discussing overall stable association. ||Duration develops over 10-45 minutes as molecular interactions multiply and strengthen. ||Cultivar variation in binding may include lipid transfer protein content and isoform composition affecting binding properties, overall exudate composition affecting binding mechanisms, and pollen coat characteristics affecting binding partner availability and quality. ||Regional timing shows stigmatic exudate binding occurring during flowering period across all climates following pollen-stigma contact, developing as molecular interactions establish within minutes of initial encounter. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential molecular mechanism securing pollen attachment, requiring adequate stigma exudate production and composition, demonstrating critical importance of boron nutrition for normal binding through exudate effects, and establishing binding success as molecular foundation for subsequent recognition, germination, and fertilization. ||Research applications include analyzing specific molecular interactions in binding using biochemical and molecular biology techniques, identifying binding proteins and their pollen partners, evaluating exudate composition effects on binding properties, investigating boron effects on exudate and binding function, quantifying binding kinetics and affinity characteristics, and assessing relationships between molecular binding and pollination success outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 380-383 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Grain_Attachment": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Grain_Attachment is a Pollen_Adhesion marked by persistent pollen-stigma association through combined molecular binding, physical adhesion, and mechanical retention.",
  "alternative_term": "stable pollen-stigma association | secured grain attachment | firm pollen binding state | persistent pollen adhesion |+ Pollenkorn-Anhaftung | stabile Pollen-Narben-Assoziation | gesicherte Kornanheftung | persistente Pollenadhäsion",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows pollen grain attachment during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with firmly secured grains 26-32 micrometers diameter on papillate stigma surfaces, attachment developing within 20-50 minutes through molecular binding and exudate adhesion creating resistance to moderate environmental disturbances, supporting 16-28 stably attached grains per stigma undergoing hydration and germination, under temperate maritime conditions of 21-26°C temperature, 58-72% relative humidity, typical of this mid-season cultivar with stable attachment enabling subsequent tube growth and fertilization supporting 56-66% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Grain_Attachment is second and final aspect of Pollen_Adhesion, distinguished by overall stable long-term association emphasis. ||Represents culmination of capture and adhesion processes creating persistent attachment. ||Develops over 15-60 minutes, persists hours to days. ||Integrates molecular binding, physical adhesion, mechanical retention. ||Substantial resistance to environmental disturbance. ||Enables pollen hydration, recognition, germination. ||Essential prerequisite for successful fertilization. ||Completes Pollination hierarchical documentation from capture through adhesion to stable attachment. || This critical stable attachment state occurs during pollen adhesion in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, developing over 15-60 minutes following adhesion initiation and persisting through germination and tube growth, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Attachment characteristics show firmly secured pollen grain on stigma surface through integrated molecular and physical binding mechanisms, stable positioning maintained despite environmental disturbances including wind, mechanical contact, or moderate moisture, pollen grain fully hydrated and metabolically active preparing for or undergoing germination, and overall robust association supporting reproductive success. ||Attachment security shows substantial resistance to detachment forces with established attachment withstanding forces 100-500 times grain weight, resistance to normal environmental disturbances encountered during flowering including wind gusts up to 15-20 km per hour, tolerance to brief rain exposure though sustained heavy rain potentially disrupting attachment, and overall stability sufficient for supporting multi-hour to multi-day processes of germination and tube penetration. ||Multi-point molecular binding creating attachment includes numerous protein-protein bridges between pollen coat and exudate creating redundant attachment points, protein-lipid interactions through lipid transfer proteins providing strong hydrophobic binding, polysaccharide networks embedding grain in exudate matrix distributing mechanical forces, and cumulative effect of hundreds to thousands of molecular interactions producing robust attachment. ||Physical adhesion contributing to attachment shows viscous stigmatic exudate matrix creating mechanical resistance to grain displacement, exudate gel-like properties distributing stress preventing localized failure, and maintained adhesion through exudate secretion continuing throughout receptivity period replacing any dilution or loss. ||Mechanical retention by stigma structure supplements molecular adhesion with papillate cell architecture creating three-dimensional retention geometry, cell projections providing physical barriers preventing grain sliding or rolling, and surface irregularities creating stable positioning sites maintaining grain location. ||Attached grain positioning shows typical intimate contact with papillate cell surface, grain potentially spanning multiple adjacent cells depending on size and geometry, and stable orientation maintained throughout hydration and germination processes. ||Pollen grain state during attachment shows progressive hydration over 15-90 minutes reaching full rehydration, metabolic activation proceeding as hydration restores physiological function, and preparation for or initiation of germination with tube emergence within 1-4 hours under favorable conditions if fully hydrated and recognized as compatible. ||Hydration dynamics during attachment involve continued water uptake from stigmatic exudate until equilibrium reached, grain expanding 10-20% volumetrically as cells rehydrate from desiccated atmospheric state, cytoplasmic reorganization proceeding as metabolic systems reactivate, and establishment of germination capacity as hydration completes. ||Recognition completion during attachment shows pollen-stigma molecular communication confirming compatibility, self-compatible grapevine accepting self-pollen triggering supportive responses, and recognized compatible pollen receiving enhanced exudate support and preparation for tube growth into stigma tissues. ||Stigma response to attached pollen shows continued exudate secretion maintaining adhesive and hydration environment, possible localized metabolic activation in papillate cells beneath attached grain preparing to support tube penetration, and provision of resources including water and possibly nutrients supporting pollen function. ||Multiple grain attachment per stigma shows typical 10-50 firmly attached grains on receptive stigma during peak pollination, independent attachment and hydration of each grain creating pollen surplus, and competitive or selective germination with typically only 1-2 grains successfully completing tube growth and fertilization despite numerous attachments. ||Attachment persistence shows stable association maintained throughout germination typically 1-4 hours post-attachment, continued attachment during tube emergence and penetration of stigma surface, and long-term association as germinated tube grows through style tissues over 12-36 hours requiring persistent grain attachment at entry point. ||Environmental stability of attachment includes maintained attachment across typical flowering temperature range 18-30°C with thermal stability of molecular and physical binding, tolerance to humidity variation 40-75% with adhesion persisting despite exudate water content changes, and resistance to light-moderate rain though sustained heavy precipitation potentially disrupting attachment particularly in recently attached grains. ||Attachment failure causes include inadequate exudate production or composition preventing binding development, pollen grain abnormalities compromising coat substances and binding capacity, environmental disruption particularly heavy rain diluting or washing away exudate and physically removing grains, or developmental problems affecting stigma or pollen function. ||Attachment assessment methods include microscopic observation documenting attached grain presence and number, mechanical testing evaluating detachment resistance quantifying attachment strength, fluorescence techniques visualizing attached and germinating pollen, and pollination exclusion experiments determining attachment success under varying conditions. ||Attachment as prerequisite for fertilization shows firmly attached grain as essential starting point for reproductive success, attachment enabling subsequent germination and tube growth, and failed attachment eliminating pollination opportunity for that pollen-stigma pair causing potential fruit set failure. ||Attachment completion timing relative to germination shows attachment typically secure within 15-60 minutes of initial contact, germination often initiating within 1-4 hours as pollen completes hydration and recognition, and overlapping attachment stabilization and germination preparation processes. ||The process represents second and final aspect of pollen adhesion emphasizing overall stable long-term association, following stigmatic exudate binding. ||Duration develops over 15-60 minutes as attachment strengthens, persisting hours to days supporting germination and tube growth. ||Cultivar variation in attachment may include grain size affecting contact area and binding opportunity, pollen coat composition affecting molecular binding quality, and compatibility factors affecting recognition and support provided to attached pollen. ||Regional timing shows pollen grain attachment occurring during flowering period across all climates following pollen capture, establishing as stable association within hour of initial contact. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential stable pollen-stigma association enabling reproductive success, requiring integrated molecular binding, physical adhesion, and mechanical retention, demonstrating importance of adequate stigma exudate and favorable environmental conditions, and establishing attachment success as prerequisite for subsequent germination, fertilization, and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing attachment mechanisms and security, evaluating environmental and genetic factors affecting attachment stability, quantifying attachment strength and resistance to disturbance, investigating attachment-germination relationships, and assessing attachment success as determinant of pollination outcomes and fruit set.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 382-388 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 288-295 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Germination": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Germination is a Pollination comprising metabolic activation, cytoplasmic reorganization, pore activation, and pollen tube emergence through the grain aperture in the hydrated pollen grain.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen sprouting | pollen tube initiation | grain germination | reproductive activation |+ Pollenkeimung | Pollenschlauch-Initiierung | Kornkeimung | reproduktive Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows pollen germination during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with attached pollen grains 28-32 micrometers diameter completing hydration within 25-60 minutes, initiating tube emergence 1.5-3.5 hours after stigma contact, producing 8-12 micrometer diameter tubes, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, adequate boron nutrition supporting normal wall synthesis, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar with 68-82% germination success from viable attached pollen enabling subsequent fertilization",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Germination represents critical post-adhesion process within Flowering enabling transition from dormant grain to growing tube. ||Subdivided into Pollen_Hydration restoring function, Germination_Pore_Activation preparing emergence, and Pollen_Tube_Emergence creating growth structure. ||Duration 1-6 hours from adhesion to emergence. ||Critical dependence on temperature, boron nutrition, pollen viability. ||Essential prerequisite for Pollen_Tube_Growth and fertilization. ||Competitive process with multiple germinants per stigma but typically 1-2 successful completions. || This essential germination process occurs during flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically initiating within 1-4 hours after pollen-stigma contact and adhesion under favorable conditions, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Germination mechanism involves coordinated processes including pollen grain hydration from stigmatic exudate restoring metabolic function, germination pore activation at one of three colporate apertures preparing emergence site, cytoplasmic polarization establishing growth axis, and tube emergence as vegetative cell extends through activated aperture creating pollen tube. ||Pollen grain hydration preceding germination shows water uptake from stigmatic exudate over 15-90 minutes following adhesion, grain expanding 10-20% volumetrically as cells rehydrate from desiccated atmospheric state to functional hydrated condition, and metabolic activation proceeding as hydration restores enzyme function, respiratory activity, and biosynthetic capacity enabling germination. ||Hydration dynamics show initial rapid uptake phase within first 15-30 minutes absorbing majority of water requirement, slower equilibration phase over subsequent 30-60 minutes achieving final hydrated state, and total water content increase from 5-15% desiccated state to 60-70% hydrated state approaching fresh pollen levels. ||Metabolic activation during hydration involves respiratory enzymes reactivating enabling ATP production through oxidative phosphorylation, protein synthesis initiating producing enzymes and structural components required for tube growth, carbohydrate metabolism activating mobilizing stored starch and lipid reserves providing energy and building materials, and overall physiological transition from dormant to actively metabolizing state. ||Cytoplasmic reorganization preparing germination shows polarization with cytoplasm concentrating at germination site, organelles including mitochondria and rough endoplasmic reticulum migrating toward emergence site supporting active metabolism and secretion, nucleus positioning near germination pore though initially remaining in grain, and vegetative cell preparing for tube formation and growth. ||Germination pore selection shows pollen grain having three colporate apertures providing potential germination sites, typically single aperture activating for tube emergence though occasionally multiple tubes may initiate, and pore selection possibly influenced by contact geometry, stigma surface properties, or intrinsic polarity though mechanisms poorly understood. ||Germination pore activation involves localized cell wall loosening at selected aperture through enzymatic degradation, intine layer preparation for tube extension with wall modification enabling growth, turgor pressure building in vegetative cell creating mechanical force driving emergence, and coordinated structural changes enabling tube breakthrough. ||Tube emergence timing shows germination typically initiating 1-4 hours after pollen-stigma contact under optimal conditions, earlier germination at 1-2 hours with warm temperature 25-28°C and vigorous pollen, delayed germination at 3-6 hours with cool temperature 18-22°C or aged pollen, and variable timing depending on pollen viability, stigma receptivity, and environmental conditions. ||Tube emergence morphology shows initial small protrusion 2-5 micrometers diameter emerging through activated aperture, rapid elongation as tube extends from grain driven by tip growth, and developing cylindrical tube structure with diameter 8-12 micrometers in mature actively growing tube. ||Pollen tube characteristics include vegetative cell cytoplasm occupying tube with organelles and stored reserves supporting growth, generative cell or two sperm cells depending on mitotic timing traveling in tube cytoplasm, tip-focused growth with cell wall synthesis and extension occurring at tube apex, and basipetal cytoplasmic streaming maintaining nutrient and organelle supply to growing tip. ||Tube wall composition shows inner callose layer providing structural support and possibly regulatory functions, outer pectin-cellulose layer providing flexible wall enabling expansion, and continuous wall synthesis at tip driven by Golgi-derived vesicles delivering wall precursors. ||Germination requirements include adequate hydration providing water for metabolic function and turgor generation, appropriate temperature 20-28°C optimal supporting enzymatic activity and metabolic processes, sufficient stored reserves in pollen grain providing energy and materials for tube initiation, adequate boron essential for cell wall synthesis and tube integrity, and supportive stigma environment providing recognition signals and possibly nutrients. ||Boron critical role in germination emphasizes absolute requirement with boron essential for proper cell wall structure particularly pectin cross-linking, deficiency causing germination failure or abnormal tube development with bursting or irregular growth, and optimal boron concentration 10-20 ppm in stigmatic tissues supporting normal germination and tube function. ||Temperature effects on germination show optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid efficient germination within 1-2 hours, cool conditions 15-20°C substantially delaying germination to 4-8 hours and reducing success rate, warm conditions 28-32°C potentially accelerating germination though excessive heat above 33°C may cause pollen dysfunction, and temperature sensitivity demonstrating metabolic basis of germination process. ||Pollen viability effects show fresh high-viability pollen 75-90% germination capacity under optimal conditions, aged pollen with reduced viability 40-60% showing delayed or failed germination, and viability decline with atmospheric exposure emphasizing importance of rapid pollination during pollen release period. ||Stigma support for germination includes continued exudate secretion providing hydration and possibly nutrients, recognition signals confirming compatibility and triggering germination support, possible stigma-derived growth factors though evidence limited in grapevine, and overall receptive environment enabling successful germination. ||Multiple pollen germination per stigma shows typical pattern with 10-50 attached grains attempting germination, competitive germination with fastest-germinating or most vigorous tubes having advantage, and typically 1-2 tubes successfully navigating style and achieving fertilization despite numerous germination attempts. ||Germination success rate shows 60-85% attached viable pollen successfully germinating under favorable conditions, declining to 30-50% under suboptimal conditions or with reduced pollen viability, and demonstrating coordination of pollen quality, stigma support, and environmental factors determining germination outcomes. ||Failed germination causes include inadequate hydration from insufficient stigmatic exudate, pollen viability loss from aging or environmental damage, incompatibility recognition preventing stigma support though rare in self-compatible grapevine, boron deficiency preventing normal wall synthesis, temperature stress disrupting metabolic function, or developmental abnormalities affecting pollen or stigma function. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from pollen hydration restoring metabolic function, through germination pore activation preparing emergence site, to pollen tube emergence creating actively growing structure. ||Duration typically spans 1-6 hours from adhesion to tube emergence depending on conditions, with rapid 1-2 hour germination under optimal conditions and delayed 4-8 hour germination under suboptimal conditions. ||Cultivar variation in germination may include pollen vigor affecting germination speed and success, stored reserve quantity affecting germination capacity, and temperature sensitivity affecting germination under variable conditions. ||Regional timing shows pollen germination occurring during flowering period across all climates within hours of successful pollination, proceeding throughout peak anthesis period as sequential pollinations occur. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential post-pollination step linking pollen capture to fertilization, requiring favorable environmental conditions particularly adequate temperature and boron nutrition, demonstrating critical dependence on pollen quality and stigma support, and establishing germination success as prerequisite for subsequent tube growth, fertilization, and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing germination mechanisms including hydration dynamics and pore activation, investigating environmental and nutritional effects on germination success, evaluating pollen viability and germination capacity relationships, quantifying germination timing and tube emergence dynamics, and assessing germination success as determinant of fertilization and fruit set outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 382-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 288-292 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Hydration": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Hydration is a Pollen_Germination characterized by water uptake from stigmatic exudate restoring cellular hydration and metabolic function in the desiccated pollen grain.",
  "alternative_term": "pollen rehydration | grain water uptake | pollen imbibition | water absorption |+ Pollenhydratation | Pollenrehydrierung | Kornwasseraufnahme | Pollenimbibition",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows pollen hydration during early June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with desiccated grains 8-12% water content absorbing water from stigmatic exudate, swelling 12-18% volumetrically over 35-75 minutes reaching 62-68% final water content, metabolic activation proceeding enabling germination initiation 1.5-3 hours post-adhesion, under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, 60-72% relative humidity maintaining adequate exudate water content, typical of this early-bursting cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Hydration is first aspect of Pollen_Germination, distinguished by water uptake and metabolic restoration. ||Represents essential prerequisite enabling all subsequent germination processes. ||Duration 15-90 minutes showing biphasic uptake. ||Temperature and initial pollen water status affect kinetics. ||Cellular rehydration restores membrane function, organelle activity, enzyme catalysis. ||Transitions to Germination_Pore_Activation as preparation completes. ||Critical first step from dormant grain to active reproductive unit. || This critical rehydration process occurs during pollen germination in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over 15-90 minutes following pollen-stigma adhesion, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Hydration mechanism involves water movement from stigmatic exudate into pollen grain through osmotic gradient, pollen grain water content increasing from desiccated 5-15% to hydrated 60-70% approaching fresh pollen levels, and cellular rehydration restoring normal cell structure, membrane function, and organelle activity. ||Water uptake kinetics show characteristic biphasic pattern with rapid initial phase absorbing 60-80% total water within first 15-30 minutes driven by steep osmotic gradient, slower equilibration phase over subsequent 30-60 minutes achieving final hydrated state, and total hydration period typically 30-90 minutes depending on initial pollen water status and environmental conditions. ||Osmotic driving force for hydration includes concentrated solutes in desiccated pollen cytoplasm creating strong osmotic potential typically -5 to -10 MPa, stigmatic exudate providing external water source at relatively high water potential approximately -0.5 to -1.5 MPa, and resulting osmotic gradient driving water influx into grain. ||Water entry pathways involve primary uptake through pollen wall and membranes with water permeating exine through existing pathways or defects, intine layer allowing water passage through less rigid wall structure, plasma membrane showing selective permeability possibly involving aquaporin water channels, and cytoplasm absorbing water restoring cellular hydration. ||Grain swelling during hydration shows volumetric expansion of 10-20% as cells rehydrate, exine outer wall showing limited expansion maintaining structural form, intine inner wall and plasma membrane expanding as cytoplasm swells, and visible grain size increase from 25-35 micrometers desiccated to 28-40 micrometers hydrated state. ||Cellular rehydration effects include membrane restoration with lipid bilayers regaining fluid structure from dehydrated rigid state, organelle function restoration as mitochondria, endoplasmic reticulum, and Golgi rehydrate enabling activity, enzyme reactivation as proteins regain proper conformation and catalytic function, and cytoplasmic reorganization preparing for germination. ||Metabolic activation following hydration involves respiratory enzyme systems reactivating enabling ATP synthesis through oxidative phosphorylation, protein synthesis machinery becoming functional allowing gene expression and translation, carbohydrate metabolism activating mobilizing stored starch and lipid reserves, and overall transition from dormant to actively metabolizing state. ||Membrane integrity restoration shows critical importance with proper hydration enabling membrane repair and function, rapid hydration potentially causing damage through osmotic stress if not properly controlled, and cell regulatory systems managing hydration rate preventing excessive swelling or membrane rupture. ||ATP synthesis resumption during hydration provides energy for cellular processes with mitochondrial respiration reactivating producing ATP from stored reserves, energy charge increasing from low dormant levels to high functional levels, and ATP availability enabling active transport, biosynthesis, and motility required for germination. ||Gene expression activation shows transcription initiating for germination-related genes including tube growth proteins, cell wall synthesis enzymes, and metabolic enzymes, translation proceeding producing proteins required for germination and tube development, and overall molecular activation preparing for germination. ||Stored reserve mobilization during hydration involves starch hydrolysis beginning providing glucose for energy metabolism, lipid bodies beginning breakdown providing fatty acids and glycerol, and reserve proteins potentially beginning degradation providing amino acids, establishing resource availability for tube growth. ||Cytoplasmic reorganization during hydration shows polarization initiating with cytoplasm and organelles beginning concentration at prospective germination site, microtubule and actin cytoskeleton reorganizing establishing polarity, and spatial organization preparing for directed tube emergence and growth. ||Hydration requirements include adequate stigmatic exudate providing water source, appropriate exudate composition supporting uptake without osmotic damage, pollen grain structural integrity enabling controlled water entry, and cellular regulation systems managing hydration process. ||Environmental effects on hydration include stigma exudate water content affected by humidity with moderate 50-65% maintaining appropriate exudate properties, temperature affecting water uptake kinetics with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient hydration within 30-60 minutes, and excessive desiccation from low humidity <40% potentially affecting exudate availability delaying hydration. ||Temperature effects on hydration rate show warm conditions 25-28°C promoting rapid uptake completing within 20-40 minutes, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing uptake requiring 60-90 minutes for complete hydration, and temperature affecting both water diffusion rate and membrane permeability influencing overall hydration kinetics. ||Pollen desiccation severity effects show moderately desiccated pollen 8-12% water content rehydrating efficiently within 30-60 minutes, severely desiccated pollen <5% water content requiring longer 60-120 minutes and possibly showing reduced viability, and freshly released pollen with higher water content 12-15% rehydrating most rapidly within 15-30 minutes. ||Stigmatic exudate properties affecting hydration include water content determining availability, osmotic potential affecting gradient and uptake rate, viscosity influencing water movement, and possible solute composition affecting pollen uptake though poorly characterized. ||Hydration monitoring methods include microscopic observation documenting grain swelling, vital dyes assessing membrane integrity restoration, respirometry measuring metabolic activation, and molecular assays detecting gene expression activation. ||Rapid versus slow hydration effects show controlled gradual uptake maintaining cell integrity, excessively rapid uptake potentially causing membrane damage through osmotic stress, and regulatory systems in viable pollen managing uptake rate preventing damage. ||Failed hydration causes include inadequate stigmatic exudate from stigma dysfunction or environmental stress, pollen membrane damage from aging or environmental exposure preventing controlled uptake, incompatibility responses potentially limiting exudate availability though rare in self-compatible grapevine, or extreme environmental conditions disrupting exudate or pollen function. ||Hydration as germination prerequisite shows complete hydration essential before germination can proceed, partial hydration insufficient for metabolic activation and tube emergence, and hydration timing affecting germination timing with rapid hydration enabling earlier germination. ||The process represents first aspect of pollen germination establishing metabolic function, followed by germination pore activation and tube emergence. ||Duration typically spans 15-90 minutes from adhesion to complete hydration, with rapid 15-40 minute hydration under optimal conditions and delayed 60-120 minute hydration under suboptimal conditions or with severely desiccated pollen. ||Cultivar variation in hydration may include pollen desiccation tolerance affecting rehydration capacity, membrane properties affecting water uptake kinetics, and grain structural characteristics affecting hydration efficiency. ||Regional timing shows pollen hydration occurring during flowering period across all climates within minutes to hours following successful pollination and adhesion. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential first step in germination enabling metabolic activation, requiring adequate stigmatic exudate water content, demonstrating dependence on favorable environmental conditions, and establishing hydration completion as prerequisite for subsequent germination and tube growth. ||Research applications include analyzing water uptake mechanisms and kinetics, investigating cellular changes during rehydration, evaluating environmental effects on hydration efficiency, quantifying metabolic activation dynamics following hydration, and assessing hydration success as determinant of germination and fertilization outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 382-384 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 288-290"
},

  "Germination_Pore_Activation": {
  "definition": "A Germination_Pore_Activation is a Pollen_Germination involving structural modification and wall loosening of one colporate pore in the hydrated pollen grain establishing the growth pathway for tube emergence.",
  "alternative_term": "aperture activation | germination pore preparation | pore opening process | emergence site activation |+ Keimporus-Aktivierung | Apertur-Aktivierung | Porenöffnungsprozess | Emergenz-Stellenaktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows germination pore activation during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with one of three colporate apertures per grain undergoing wall loosening and cytoplasmic polarization over 25-55 minutes following hydration, enzymatic wall modification at selected pore creating breakthrough site, turgor pressure 0.8-1.3 MPa accumulating, under oceanic conditions of 21-26°C temperature, adequate boron nutrition 12-18 ppm supporting normal wall synthesis, typical of this mid-season cultivar enabling tube emergence 2-4 hours post-adhesion",
  "editor_note": "Germination_Pore_Activation is second aspect of Pollen_Germination, distinguished by aperture preparation for tube emergence. ||Represents localized wall modification and cytoplasmic polarization at selected pore. ||Duration 15-60 minutes. ||Critical boron dependence for wall synthesis. ||Temperature affects enzymatic activity. ||Transitions to Pollen_Tube_Emergence as preparation completes. ||Essential structural and organizational preparation enabling breakthrough. || This critical pore preparation process occurs during pollen germination in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over 15-60 minutes following pollen hydration as germination approaches, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Activation mechanism involves aperture selection from three available colporate pores distributed around grain equator, localized cell wall modification at selected pore through enzymatic loosening, intine layer preparation for tube extension with structural changes enabling growth, and turgor pressure accumulation creating mechanical force driving tube emergence. ||Pollen grain aperture structure shows three colporate apertures in typical grapevine pollen grain providing potential germination sites, each aperture representing thinned region in exine outer wall with modified intine inner wall, and aperture positioning distributed approximately equidistantly around grain equator creating multiple germination options. ||Aperture selection mechanism shows typically single pore activating for tube emergence though occasionally multiple tubes may initiate from different pores, selection possibly influenced by contact geometry with stigma surface, orientation at adhesion affecting accessibility, intrinsic polarity possibly favoring particular pore, or stochastic factors with first-activated pore proceeding while others suppress, though mechanisms poorly understood. ||Localized wall loosening at selected aperture involves enzymatic degradation of cell wall polysaccharides with pectinase and cellulase activity concentrated at pore region, wall component dissolution creating flexibility enabling tube breakthrough, and controlled degradation maintaining structural integrity while allowing expansion. ||Cell wall modification shows intine inner layer at aperture undergoing structural changes, pectin and hemicellulose components partially degrading creating loosened matrix, cellulose microfibrils reorganizing enabling expansion, and overall wall modification transitioning from rigid barrier to flexible growth-permissive structure. ||Enzymatic activity driving activation includes pectinase enzymes degrading pectin polysaccharides in middle lamella and wall matrix, cellulase activity breaking down cellulose components, polygalacturonase specifically targeting pectin creating wall loosening, and coordinated enzyme action producing controlled wall modification enabling tube emergence. ||Cytoplasmic polarization at aperture shows vegetative cell cytoplasm concentrating at selected pore region, organelles including mitochondria, rough ER, and Golgi apparatus migrating toward aperture supporting active secretion and metabolism, secretory vesicles accumulating delivering wall precursors for tube formation, and overall cellular polarization establishing growth axis. ||Turgor pressure generation shows water uptake creating osmotic swelling, cell membrane pushing against wall creating mechanical pressure, concentrated pressure at weakened aperture region creating driving force for tube emergence, and regulated turgor typically 0.5-1.5 MPa sufficient for breakthrough without grain rupture. ||Intine preparation at aperture involves inner wall layer at pore undergoing reorganization, structural proteins and polysaccharides modifying creating growth-competent state, wall synthesis machinery activating preparing for tube wall construction, and transition from static grain wall to dynamic growing tube wall. ||Exine outer wall role shows rigid sculptured outer layer maintaining structural integrity preventing grain collapse, aperture regions having naturally thinned exine providing predetermined emergence sites, and exine remaining intact during tube emergence with tube extending through aperture rather than breaching solid wall. ||Pore activation timing shows process initiating 30-90 minutes after hydration as metabolic activation proceeds, progressing over 15-60 minutes as wall loosening and polarization develop, and completing immediately before tube emergence establishing ready state for breakthrough. ||Activation coordination with overall germination shows pore activation proceeding concurrently with metabolic activation and reserve mobilization, timing synchronized so tube emergence occurs when cellular resources and organization prepared, and integrated developmental program coordinating multiple preparation processes. ||Multiple pore potential shows grain capable of activating any of three apertures, first-activated pore typically proceeding to emergence while others remain inactive, occasional simultaneous activation producing multiple tubes from single grain though usually only one succeeds in fertilization, and selection mechanism ensuring directed coordinated growth. ||Calcium signaling in activation possibly involves calcium gradients establishing polarity, localized calcium accumulation at prospective germination site, and calcium-dependent enzyme activation though specific roles in grapevine poorly characterized. ||Cytoskeleton role in activation includes microtubules and actin filaments reorganizing establishing polarity, cytoskeleton directing organelle positioning and vesicle trafficking to aperture, and structural framework supporting polarized cellular organization. ||Environmental effects on pore activation include temperature affecting enzymatic activity and metabolic processes with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient activation, boron essential for proper wall modification and synthesis with deficiency preventing normal activation and tube formation, and adequate hydration providing turgor for mechanical breakthrough. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions 25-28°C promoting rapid activation within 15-30 minutes, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing activation requiring 45-90 minutes, and temperature sensitivity reflecting enzymatic basis of wall modification processes. ||Boron critical role shows absolute requirement for pore activation with boron essential for pectin cross-linking and wall structure, deficiency causing abnormal wall modification preventing proper tube emergence or causing tube bursting, and optimal boron concentration 10-20 ppm in tissues supporting normal activation and germination. ||Failed pore activation causes include inadequate hydration preventing turgor generation, boron deficiency disrupting wall modification, metabolic dysfunction from pollen damage or aging preventing enzyme production, extreme temperature stress disrupting activation processes, or developmental abnormalities affecting pore structure or cellular organization. ||The process represents second aspect of pollen germination preparing emergence pathway, following pollen hydration and preceding pollen tube emergence. ||Duration typically spans 15-60 minutes as wall modification and polarization proceed. ||Cultivar variation in pore activation may include aperture structure affecting modification requirements, enzymatic capacity affecting activation speed, and activation efficiency affecting germination success rate. ||Regional timing shows germination pore activation occurring during flowering period across all climates as part of germination sequence following hydration within hours of pollination. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical preparation enabling tube emergence, requiring adequate boron nutrition for normal wall modification, demonstrating coordination of structural, enzymatic, and mechanical processes, and establishing activation success as prerequisite for tube emergence and successful fertilization. ||Research applications include analyzing aperture selection mechanisms and determinants, investigating wall modification biochemistry and enzymology, evaluating boron effects on activation and wall synthesis, quantifying activation timing and coordination with germination, and assessing activation success as determinant of tube emergence and fertilization outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 383-385 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 289-290"
},

  "Pollen_Tube_Emergence": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Tube_Emergence is a Pollen_Germination marked by the protrusion of the vegetative cell through the activated aperture as a cylindrical extension breaking through the grain wall.",
  "alternative_term": "tube breakthrough | pollen tube initiation | germination completion | tube extrusion |+ Pollenschlauch-Emergenz | Schlauch-Durchbruch | Keimungsabschluss | Schlauchextrusion",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows pollen tube emergence during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with tubes breaking through activated apertures 1.5-3.5 hours after pollen-stigma contact, initial protrusions 3-6 micrometers diameter rapidly extending to 8-11 micrometer cylindrical tubes growing at 1.2-2.8 mm per hour, under warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature, adequate boron 14-20 ppm supporting normal wall synthesis and tube integrity, typical of this late-season cultivar with 65-80% emergence success from viable hydrated pollen",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Tube_Emergence is third and final aspect of Pollen_Germination, distinguished by definitive breakthrough event creating growing tube. ||Represents culmination of hydration and pore activation processes. ||Duration minutes to hour for emergence event itself occurring 1-4 hours post-adhesion total. ||Critical boron dependence for wall integrity. ||Marks transition from Pollen_Germination to Pollen_Tube_Growth. ||Essential definitive event establishing active reproductive structure capable of delivering sperm cells to ovules. || This critical emergence event occurs during pollen germination in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically occurring 1-4 hours after pollen-stigma contact as germination culminates, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Emergence mechanism involves turgor-driven extension with accumulated osmotic pressure 0.5-1.5 MPa pushing vegetative cell cytoplasm through weakened aperture, tip-focused growth with cell wall synthesis concentrated at emerging tube apex, breakthrough of modified intine layer creating initial protrusion 2-5 micrometers diameter, and rapid elongation establishing cylindrical tube structure extending from grain. ||Initial protrusion characteristics show small bulge appearing at activated aperture representing beginning tube emergence, protrusion 2-5 micrometers diameter initially expanding as breakthrough proceeds, and transition from bulge to distinct cylindrical tube as emergence completes and growth establishes. ||Breakthrough dynamics show turgor pressure overcoming residual wall resistance at aperture, intine layer yielding allowing cytoplasm extrusion, initial emergence typically occurring within minutes once activation completes, and irreversible commitment to tube growth once breakthrough achieved. ||Tube morphology at emergence shows cylindrical structure with initial diameter 5-8 micrometers expanding to typical 8-12 micrometers in actively growing tube, tip-focused growth with rounded apex where wall synthesis and extension occur, and smooth tube surface with continuous wall formed by secreted precursors. ||Tube wall structure includes inner callose layer providing structural support and possibly controlling tube permeability and growth regulation, outer pectin-cellulose layer providing flexible wall enabling expansion at tip while maintaining integrity, and continuous wall synthesis at apex through Golgi-derived secretory vesicles delivering wall components. ||Wall synthesis at tube tip involves secretory vesicles containing wall precursors fusing with plasma membrane at apex, pectin, cellulose, and callose polymerizing forming new wall, and coordinated synthesis enabling tip extension at 1-3 mm per hour initially with variation depending on conditions and tube age. ||Cytoplasmic organization in emerging tube shows vegetative cell contents occupying tube with cytoplasm streaming basipetally from grain into elongating tube, organelles including mitochondria, ER, and Golgi distributed throughout providing metabolic support, generative cell or two sperm cells depending on mitotic completion traveling in tube cytoplasm, and nucleus initially remaining in grain later moving into tube. ||Tip growth mechanism shows polarized secretion concentrated at tube apex, vesicle fusion delivering membrane and wall components specifically to growing tip, calcium gradient with elevated calcium at apex possibly regulating vesicle fusion and wall synthesis, and cytoskeleton organizing vesicle trafficking and maintaining polarized growth. ||Growth rate at emergence shows initial slower extension 0.5-1.5 mm per hour during establishment phase, acceleration to typical 1-3 mm per hour once active growth establishes, and rate variation depending on temperature, boron availability, pollen vigor, and stigma support. ||Direction at emergence shows tube typically extending into stigma tissue penetrating papillate cell surface, initial growth direction possibly influenced by stigma surface contours and chemical gradients, and orientation establishing pathway toward style and ultimately ovary. ||Cytoplasmic streaming in tube shows characteristic basipetal flow from grain through tube toward apex, streaming rate 2-8 micrometers per second maintaining nutrient and organelle supply to growing tip, and streaming driven by actomyosin motor system supporting sustained growth. ||Nucleus behavior shows initially remaining in grain during early emergence, later migration into tube as growth proceeds, and eventual positioning in tube cytoplasm though generative/sperm cells more important for fertilization. ||Sperm cell delivery shows two sperm cells resulting from generative cell division traveling in tube cytoplasm, cells moving toward apex as tube grows, and ultimate delivery to embryo sac enabling double fertilization once ovary reached. ||Emergence timing variation shows rapid emergence 1-2 hours post-adhesion with vigorous fresh pollen under optimal conditions 25-28°C, delayed emergence 3-6 hours with aged pollen or suboptimal conditions 18-22°C, and failed emergence from inadequate hydration, activation failure, or pollen dysfunction. ||Environmental requirements for emergence include adequate temperature 20-28°C optimal supporting metabolic activity and wall synthesis, sufficient boron essential for wall structure with deficiency causing emergence failure or tube bursting, appropriate humidity maintaining stigma exudate and pollen hydration, and supportive stigma environment providing growth cues. ||Temperature effects on emergence show warm conditions promoting rapid emergence and vigorous growth, cool conditions substantially delaying emergence and reducing growth rate, and temperature affecting enzyme activity, vesicle trafficking, and overall metabolic support for growth. ||Boron critical importance shows absolute requirement with boron essential for pectin cross-linking in tube wall, deficiency causing weak wall leading to tube bursting during emergence or early growth, and optimal boron 10-20 ppm in tissues supporting normal tube integrity and growth. ||Stigma support during emergence includes continued exudate secretion possibly providing nutrients or growth factors, recognition signals potentially enhancing growth support for compatible pollen, and tissue providing pathway for initial tube penetration into transmitting tract. ||Multiple tube emergence per stigma shows 10-50 pollen grains potentially germinating creating multiple tubes, competitive growth with fastest-growing or most vigorous tubes having advantage in reaching ovary, and typically 1-2 tubes successfully completing growth and achieving fertilization despite numerous emergence events. ||Failed emergence causes include incomplete hydration or activation preventing breakthrough, boron deficiency causing wall synthesis failure, pollen viability loss preventing metabolic support, incompatibility response limiting stigma support though rare in grapevine, extreme environmental conditions disrupting growth processes, or developmental abnormalities affecting pollen structure or function. ||The process represents third and final aspect of pollen germination marking transition to tube growth phase, following pollen hydration and germination pore activation. ||Duration represents relatively brief event with visible emergence occurring over minutes to hour once activation completes. ||Cultivar variation in emergence may include pollen vigor affecting emergence speed, stored reserves affecting growth capacity, and tube growth characteristics affecting penetration and navigation success. ||Regional timing shows pollen tube emergence occurring during flowering period across all climates 1-6 hours following successful pollination as germination culminates. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive germination event initiating tube growth, requiring favorable conditions particularly adequate temperature and boron nutrition, demonstrating critical transition from dormant pollen to actively growing tube, and establishing emergence success as prerequisite for tube navigation to ovary and fertilization. ||Research applications include analyzing emergence mechanisms including turgor generation and tip growth, investigating environmental and nutritional effects on emergence success particularly boron requirements, evaluating tube wall synthesis and structure, quantifying emergence timing and growth initiation dynamics, and assessing emergence success as determinant of fertilization outcomes and fruit set.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 384-388 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 289-292 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Pollen_Tube_Growth": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Tube_Growth is a Pollination comprising the elongation of the emerged pollen tube through stigma, style transmitting tissue, and ovary toward the ovules.",
  "alternative_term": "tube elongation | pollen tube navigation | tube extension process | reproductive tube growth |+ Pollenschlauchwachstum | Schlauch-Elongation | Pollenschlauch-Navigation | reproduktives Schlauchwachstum",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows pollen tube growth during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with tubes elongating through stigma into 18-24 mm style transmitting tissue at 1.4-2.6 mm per hour, requiring 14-28 hours to traverse style reaching ovary region, under continental conditions of 20-26°C temperature, adequate boron nutrition 12-18 ppm supporting normal wall synthesis and sustained growth, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar with 2-4 tubes successfully reaching ovary per flower enabling fertilization and 60-70% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Tube_Growth represents essential post-germination navigation process following Pollen_Germination within Flowering. ||Subdivided into Style_Penetration entering tissue, Transmitting_Tissue_Navigation through style, and Ovary_Approach culminating growth. ||Duration 12-36 hours spanning stigma to ovary. ||Critical boron dependence as absolute requirement. ||Temperature strongly affects growth rate. ||Leads directly to Fertilization upon ovary arrival. ||Essential process determining fertilization success and fruit set. || This critical growth and navigation process occurs during flowering in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 12-36 hours from tube emergence to ovary arrival depending on style length and environmental conditions, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Growth mechanism involves tip-focused extension with cell wall synthesis and expansion concentrated at tube apex, cytoplasmic streaming maintaining nutrient and organelle supply from grain through tube to growing tip, turgor pressure driving tip expansion with osmotic pressure 0.3-0.8 MPa pushing against yielding wall at apex, and coordinated metabolic processes supporting sustained elongation at 1-3 mm per hour. ||Tube elongation characteristics show continuous growth from stigma surface through style to ovary spanning typical 15-30 mm total distance in grapevine, growth rate 1-3 mm per hour with variation depending on tube age, temperature, boron availability, and pollen vigor, and total growth duration 12-36 hours from emergence to ovary arrival with faster growth at optimal 24-28°C and slower growth at suboptimal 18-22°C temperature. ||Tip growth mechanism shows polarized secretion concentrated at tube apex with Golgi-derived secretory vesicles delivering wall precursors, vesicle fusion with plasma membrane at tip releasing wall components for polymerization, localized wall synthesis creating new wall at apex while older wall regions remain static, and calcium gradient with elevated 1-10 micromolar calcium at tip possibly regulating vesicle fusion and wall extensibility. ||Tube wall synthesis involves continuous production of wall components including pectin polymers providing flexible matrix, cellulose microfibrils providing structural strength, callose inner layer possibly regulating permeability and providing support, and coordinated polymer deposition creating functional wall enabling expansion while maintaining integrity. ||Cytoplasmic streaming dynamics show basipetal flow from pollen grain through tube toward apex at velocity 2-8 micrometers per second, actomyosin motor system driving streaming through interaction between actin filaments and myosin motors, streaming maintaining nutrient supply, organelle distribution, and removal of used materials, and essential for supporting sustained growth over many hours and centimeters distance. ||Sperm cell transport shows two sperm cells resulting from generative cell mitosis traveling in tube cytoplasm, cells moving toward apex carried by cytoplasmic streaming, and ultimate positioning near tip enabling delivery to embryo sac once ovary reached. ||Nucleus behavior during growth shows vegetative cell nucleus migrating from grain into tube during early growth, nucleus traveling in tube though typically remaining behind sperm cells, and nuclear positioning possibly involved in growth regulation though mechanisms unclear. ||Style penetration phase shows tube breaking through stigma papillate cell surface typically between adjacent cells, entering extracellular matrix in style transmitting tissue, and establishing growth pathway through specialized conducting tissue toward ovary. ||Transmitting tissue navigation involves tube growing through extracellular matrix between style cells, following chemical guidance cues possibly including calcium gradients and signaling molecules, utilizing nutritional support from transmitting tissue cells secreting nutrients into extracellular space, and maintaining directed growth toward ovary over 15-25 mm typical style length. ||Guidance mechanisms include chemotropism with tube responding to chemical gradients possibly including calcium, GABA, or other attractants, thigmotropism with tube responding to physical cues in tissue architecture, and intrinsic polarity possibly contributing to directed growth, though specific mechanisms in grapevine poorly characterized. ||Transmitting tissue support shows specialized style cells secreting nutrients, growth factors, and possibly guidance signals into extracellular space, lipid-rich secretions possibly providing energy source for growing tubes, and overall style environment optimized for supporting pollen tube growth enabling successful fertilization. ||Growth rate variation shows initial slower growth 0.8-1.5 mm per hour during stigma penetration and early style entry, acceleration to peak 2-4 mm per hour during mid-style growth, and possible slight deceleration 1-2 mm per hour during late growth approaching ovary, with overall average 1-3 mm per hour depending on conditions. ||Environmental effects on tube growth include temperature critically affecting growth rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid 2-3 mm per hour growth, cool conditions 18-22°C substantially slowing growth to 0.8-1.5 mm per hour potentially requiring 36-48 hours for ovary arrival, warm conditions 28-32°C potentially accelerating growth though excessive heat above 33°C may impair function. ||Boron absolute requirement for tube growth emphasizes critical importance with boron essential for pectin cross-linking in tube wall structure, deficiency causing tube bursting, irregular growth, or growth cessation preventing ovary arrival, optimal boron concentration 10-20 ppm in style tissues supporting normal growth and integrity, and boron deficiency even with adequate flower appearance severely reducing fruit set through failed tube growth. ||Calcium role in tube growth includes calcium gradient at tip possibly regulating vesicle fusion and wall extensibility, calcium signaling potentially involved in growth responses and guidance, and calcium nutrition affecting tube function though boron more critically limiting in practice. ||Resource requirements for sustained growth include carbohydrate reserves from pollen grain initially supporting early growth, transitional period utilizing both pollen reserves and style-derived nutrients, and later growth depending substantially on style nutritional support particularly during final growth to ovary. ||Style length effects show shorter styles 12-18 mm enabling more rapid ovary arrival within 8-20 hours, longer styles 22-30 mm requiring extended 20-40 hours for completion, and style length variation among flowers and cultivars affecting timing of fertilization events. ||Multiple tube growth per style shows 10-50 tubes potentially entering style from germinated pollen on stigma, competitive growth with fastest tubes having advantage in ovule access, typical 2-5 tubes reaching ovary region though usually only 1-2 achieving successful fertilization, and excess tubes providing reproductive assurance compensating for possible failures. ||Tube-tube interactions during growth possibly include physical interference if multiple tubes in close proximity, potential chemical signaling though poorly documented, and competitive dynamics affecting which tubes successfully fertilize. ||Ovary approach represents culminating growth phase with tube navigating to ovary region containing 2-4 ovules per carpel, tube responding to ovule-derived attractants directing final approach, and tube arrival at micropyle enabling sperm cell delivery to embryo sac for fertilization. ||Failed tube growth causes include boron deficiency preventing adequate wall synthesis, inadequate pollen reserves failing to support extended growth, environmental stress particularly temperature extremes disrupting metabolic support, style tissue dysfunction failing to provide adequate support or guidance, or pollen vigor limitations preventing sustained growth over required distance and duration. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects progressing from style penetration entering transmitting tissue, through transmitting tissue navigation growing through style, to ovary approach culminating growth. ||Duration typically spans 12-36 hours from emergence to ovary arrival with faster 10-20 hours under optimal warm conditions and adequate boron, slower 24-48 hours under cool conditions or marginal nutrition. ||Cultivar variation in tube growth may include growth rate affecting fertilization timing, style length affecting required growth duration, and boron efficiency affecting growth under marginal nutrition. ||Regional timing shows pollen tube growth occurring during flowering period across all climates over 12-36 hours following germination, completing within 24-48 hours of initial pollination under favorable conditions. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential process linking germination to fertilization, requiring adequate boron nutrition as critical limiting factor, demonstrating extreme temperature sensitivity affecting growth rate and success, and establishing tube growth success as direct determinant of fertilization achievement and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing tube growth mechanisms including tip growth dynamics and cytoplasmic streaming, investigating guidance mechanisms directing growth through style, evaluating boron and other nutritional effects on growth rate and success, quantifying environmental effects particularly temperature on growth dynamics, developing visualization techniques for observing tube growth in vivo, and assessing tube growth success as determinant of fertilization timing and fruit set outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 385-390 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 290-295 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Style_Penetration": {
  "definition": "A Style_Penetration is a Pollen_Tube_Growth comprising the entry of the pollen tube through the stigma papillate cell surface into the extracellular matrix of the style transmitting tissue.",
  "alternative_term": "style entry | transmitting tissue penetration | tube breakthrough into style | stigma-style transition |+ Style-Penetration | Griffel-Eintritt | Transmissionsgewebe-Durchdringung | Narben-Griffel-Übergang",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows style penetration during mid-June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with emerged pollen tubes breaking through stigma papillate surface and entering 2-4 mm into style transmitting tissue over 1-2.5 hours, establishing growth pathway in extracellular matrix-rich conducting tissue, growth rate 0.6-1.4 mm per hour during penetration phase, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, adequate boron supporting tube wall integrity during penetration, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar with 70-84% penetration success",
  "editor_note": "Style_Penetration is first aspect of Pollen_Tube_Growth, distinguished by breakthrough from stigma surface into style transmitting tissue. ||Represents critical transition establishing pathway for continued growth. ||Duration 1-3 hours as tube extends into style. ||Slower initial growth rate 0.5-1.2 mm per hour during tissue entry. ||Boron essential for tube integrity during mechanical stress. ||Success rate 60-85% under favorable conditions. ||Followed by Transmitting_Tissue_Navigation as growth continues through style. || This critical entry phase occurs during pollen tube growth in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over 1-3 hours following tube emergence as initial growth establishes, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Penetration mechanism involves tube apex extending from stigma papillate cell surface, encountering and breaching interface between stigma and style tissues, navigating between or through cell layers entering extracellular matrix in transmitting tissue, and establishing growth pathway in specialized conducting tissue. ||Stigma-style interface characteristics show transitional zone between papillate stigma surface and underlying style transmitting tissue, cellular architecture changing from elongated papillate cells to more compact transmitting tissue cells, and interface representing barrier requiring tube penetration for style entry. ||Tube penetration pathway shows typical route between adjacent stigma cells exploiting natural intercellular spaces, tube secreting wall-modifying enzymes possibly facilitating passage through extracellular matrix, physical force from turgor pressure contributing to penetration through yielding tissue, and establishment of tube within extracellular spaces in transmitting tissue. ||Cell wall modification during penetration possibly involves pectinase and cellulase secretion from tube apex degrading extracellular matrix components, localized wall loosening facilitating tube passage, and controlled enzymatic activity enabling penetration without excessive tissue damage. ||Transmitting tissue entry shows tube reaching specialized conducting tissue in style central region, entering extracellular matrix-rich environment providing growth support, and transitioning from stigma surface growth to internal tissue growth mode. ||Transmitting tissue structure includes specialized parenchyma cells lining extracellular spaces providing nutritional and guidance support, lipid-rich secretions in extracellular matrix possibly providing energy source, abundant extracellular matrix providing physical pathway for tube growth, and overall tissue architecture optimized for pollen tube navigation. ||Extracellular matrix composition includes pectins providing hydrated gel-like environment, arabinogalactan proteins possibly involved in guidance and support, lipids secreted from transmitting tissue cells potentially providing nutrients, and various signaling molecules possibly guiding tube growth. ||Tube growth rate during penetration shows initial slower extension 0.5-1.2 mm per hour during stigma surface breakthrough and tissue entry, acceleration to 1-2 mm per hour once transmitting tissue pathway established, and transition to faster mid-style growth rates 2-3 mm per hour once fully established in conducting tissue. ||Penetration depth shows tube extending 2-5 mm from stigma surface into style during penetration phase, reaching transmitting tissue central zone, and establishing growth within conducting tissue for continued navigation toward ovary. ||Tube orientation during penetration shows generally downward growth from stigma surface toward style base and ovary, possible guidance by gravity or tissue architecture, and establishment of appropriate trajectory for continued style navigation. ||Multiple tube penetration per style shows 10-50 germinated tubes potentially entering style from stigma surface, penetration occurring relatively simultaneously for all germinated tubes, and establishment of multiple tubes in transmitting tissue creating competitive growth situation. ||Tube-tissue interactions during penetration include possible adhesion to extracellular matrix components, recognition of tissue-derived signals confirming appropriate pathway, and tube response to tissue environment affecting growth rate and direction. ||Stigma tissue response to penetration shows possible localized cellular changes in papillate cells at tube entry points though poorly characterized, continued secretion supporting tube growth, and overall permissive environment enabling penetration without defensive responses. ||Calcium signaling during penetration possibly includes calcium gradients in tissue attracting or guiding tubes, localized calcium accumulation at tube tip regulating growth processes, and calcium-dependent signaling affecting tube penetration efficiency. ||Environmental effects on penetration include temperature affecting metabolic activity and growth rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient penetration within 1-2 hours, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing penetration requiring 2-4 hours, and warm conditions potentially accelerating penetration though excessive heat may impair function. ||Boron requirement for penetration shows continued importance with boron essential for tube wall integrity during mechanical penetration stress, deficiency causing tube bursting or growth failure during penetration preventing style entry, and adequate boron 10-20 ppm supporting normal penetration success. ||Pollen vigor effects show vigorous fresh pollen producing robust tubes completing penetration efficiently within 1-2 hours, weak or aged pollen showing delayed or failed penetration, and pollen quality affecting competitive success in reaching transmitting tissue. ||Failed penetration causes include inadequate tube growth vigor preventing breakthrough, abnormal stigma-style interface impeding entry, boron deficiency causing tube structural failure during penetration, environmental stress disrupting growth processes, or developmental abnormalities affecting tissue structure or tube function. ||Penetration success assessment shows successful penetration by 60-85% emerged tubes under favorable conditions, declining to 40-60% under suboptimal conditions, and penetration success rate affecting ultimate fruit set through determining proportion of tubes continuing toward ovary. ||The process represents first aspect of pollen tube growth establishing entry into style tissue, followed by transmitting tissue navigation and ovary approach. ||Duration typically spans 1-3 hours as tube extends from stigma surface into transmitting tissue establishing pathway. ||Cultivar variation in penetration may include stigma-style interface structure affecting penetration difficulty, tube vigor affecting penetration success, and tissue characteristics affecting penetration efficiency. ||Regional timing shows style penetration occurring during flowering period across all climates 1-5 hours following tube emergence as initial growth proceeds. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical entry point from stigma to style enabling continued growth, requiring adequate tube vigor and tissue support, demonstrating continued boron importance for tube integrity, and establishing penetration success as prerequisite for tube navigation to ovary and fertilization. ||Research applications include analyzing penetration mechanisms and pathways, investigating tube-tissue interactions during penetration, evaluating environmental and nutritional effects on penetration success, quantifying penetration timing and efficiency, and assessing penetration success as determinant of continued tube growth and fertilization outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 385-387 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 290-292"
},

  "Transmitting_Tissue_Navigation": {
  "definition": "A Transmitting_Tissue_Navigation is a Pollen_Tube_Growth involving directed elongation through the style extracellular matrix over 12–25 mm guided by nutritional and chemotropic cues toward the ovary.",
  "alternative_term": "style tissue navigation | tube growth through style | transmitting tract traverse | conducting tissue navigation |+ Transmissionsgewebe-Navigation | Style-Gewebe-Navigation | Schlauchwachstum durch Griffel | Leitgewebe-Durchquerung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows transmitting tissue navigation during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with pollen tubes traversing 16-22 mm style length through extracellular matrix at 1.2-2.2 mm per hour, requiring 12-26 hours to complete navigation from stigma region to ovary, utilizing style nutritional support and guidance cues, under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, adequate boron 11-17 ppm supporting sustained tube wall integrity, typical of this early-bursting cultivar with 2-4 tubes successfully completing navigation per flower",
  "editor_note": "Transmitting_Tissue_Navigation is second aspect of Pollen_Tube_Growth, distinguished by main transit through style conducting tissue. ||Represents majority of total tube growth distance and time. ||Duration 10-30 hours traversing 12-25 mm style length. ||Peak growth rate 2-3 mm per hour during mid-navigation. ||Critical boron dependence throughout. ||Temperature strongly affects rate. ||Nutritional support from style tissue essential. ||Followed by Ovary_Approach as destination nears. ||Main determinant of fertilization timing. || This essential navigation phase occurs during pollen tube growth in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically spanning 10-30 hours as tube traverses style depending on length and conditions, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Navigation mechanism involves tube growing through extracellular matrix between transmitting tissue cells, following chemical and possibly physical guidance cues directing growth toward ovary, utilizing nutritional support from tissue secretions maintaining growth over extended distance, and maintaining sustained tip growth at 1-3 mm per hour traversing total style length. ||Transmitting tissue structure supporting navigation includes specialized parenchyma cells lining extracellular spaces creating tube growth pathway, abundant extracellular matrix providing physical scaffold and growth medium, secretory cells releasing nutrients, lipids, and possibly guidance signals into matrix, and overall tissue architecture creating optimized environment for pollen tube growth. ||Extracellular matrix composition includes pectins creating hydrated gel-like growth medium, arabinogalactan proteins possibly mediating tube-matrix interactions and providing guidance, lipid-rich secretions providing energy source and possibly affecting tube surface properties, calcium maintaining appropriate matrix properties and possibly creating guidance gradients, and various small molecules potentially serving signaling or nutritive functions. ||Growth pathway characteristics show tube growing in extracellular spaces between transmitting tissue cells, utilizing preformed pathway along style central axis, maintaining relatively straight trajectory from stigma toward ovary base, and path length 12-25 mm in typical grapevine flowers corresponding to style length. ||Growth rate during navigation shows peak velocity 2-3 mm per hour during mid-style growth phase, sustained growth maintained over many hours through nutritional support and metabolic capacity, and slight rate variation possible with initial acceleration after penetration and possible deceleration approaching ovary. ||Tube-matrix interactions show tube surface contacting extracellular matrix components, possible adhesion mediating growth direction and stability, matrix providing mechanical support preventing tube buckling during growth, and chemical interactions possibly affecting tube growth properties. ||Nutritional support from transmitting tissue shows specialized cells secreting nutrients into extracellular matrix, lipid secretions providing energy-rich compounds supporting tube metabolism, possible sugar secretion supplementing pollen grain reserves, and overall tissue support enabling sustained growth over 10-30 hour navigation period. ||Guidance mechanisms directing navigation include chemotropism with tube responding to concentration gradients of attractant molecules, possible calcium gradients attracting growing tubes, other signaling molecules potentially including GABA or nitric oxide though poorly characterized in grapevine, gravity possibly contributing minor orientation cue, and tissue architecture providing physical pathway constraining growth direction. ||Chemotropic signals possibly include ovule-derived attractants diffusing through tissue creating concentration gradient, style tissue secretions affecting growth direction, and calcium gradients established in matrix though specific signals in grapevine largely unknown. ||Cytoplasmic streaming support shows continued basipetal flow at 2-8 micrometers per second maintaining nutrient supply from grain through extending tube to growing tip, streaming essential for supporting growth over long distances exceeding grain diameter by 500-1000 fold, and actomyosin motor system driving streaming throughout navigation period. ||Sperm cell position shows two sperm cells traveling in tube cytoplasm typically near tip region, cells carried toward apex by streaming, and positioning preparing for delivery to embryo sac upon ovary arrival. ||Resource utilization during navigation shows initial dependence on pollen grain reserves during early growth, transition to mixed grain-reserves and style-derived nutrients during mid-navigation, and increasing reliance on style nutritional support during extended growth particularly final approach to ovary. ||Boron requirement during navigation emphasizes continued absolute importance with boron essential for tube wall integrity throughout growth period, deficiency causing tube bursting or growth cessation at any point during navigation preventing ovary arrival, adequate boron 10-20 ppm in style tissues supporting sustained growth maintaining wall structure over many hours. ||Calcium role in navigation includes maintaining appropriate extracellular matrix properties, possible involvement in guidance through gradient formation, and calcium-dependent processes regulating tube growth though mechanisms incompletely understood. ||Temperature effects on navigation rate show optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid 2-3 mm per hour navigation completing typical 18 mm style in 6-12 hours, cool conditions 18-22°C substantially slowing to 1-1.5 mm per hour requiring 12-24 hours, warm conditions 28-32°C potentially accelerating growth though excessive heat above 33°C may impair sustained function. ||Style length variation effects show shorter styles 12-18 mm enabling faster ovary arrival within 6-15 hours, longer styles 22-30 mm requiring extended 12-30 hours, and length variation among cultivars and individual flowers affecting fertilization timing and competitive dynamics. ||Multiple tube navigation shows 10-50 tubes potentially entering style and beginning navigation, competitive growth with fastest tubes having advantage in ovule access, typical 2-5 tubes reaching ovary region with usually 1-2 achieving fertilization, and slower tubes becoming irrelevant as faster tubes complete fertilization. ||Tube-tube interactions during navigation poorly characterized but possibly include physical contact or interference, potential chemical signaling, and competitive dynamics for limited ovule access. ||Navigation failures during transit include boron deficiency causing tube bursting midway through style, resource depletion preventing continued growth before ovary reached, environmental stress disrupting growth processes, tube structural failure from inadequate wall synthesis, or guidance failure causing misdirected growth. ||The process represents second aspect of pollen tube growth emphasizing main transit through style, following style penetration and preceding ovary approach. ||Duration typically spans 10-30 hours representing majority of total tube growth time, with faster 8-18 hours under optimal conditions and slower 18-40 hours under suboptimal conditions. ||Cultivar variation in navigation may include style length affecting required time and resources, transmitting tissue support affecting growth rate, and tube growth vigor affecting navigation success and speed. ||Regional timing shows transmitting tissue navigation occurring during flowering period across all climates over 10-30 hours following style penetration, representing main tube growth interval. ||Viticultural significance includes representing main distance-covering growth phase essential for fertilization, requiring adequate style nutritional support and boron nutrition, demonstrating extreme temperature sensitivity affecting navigation rate and timing, and establishing navigation success as direct determinant of ovary arrival enabling fertilization and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing navigation mechanisms including guidance cues and nutritional support, investigating transmitting tissue structure and function supporting tube growth, evaluating boron and other nutritional effects on sustained growth, quantifying environmental effects particularly temperature on navigation dynamics, developing visualization techniques observing tube navigation in vivo, and assessing navigation success as determinant of fertilization timing and outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 386-390 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 292-295 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Ovary_Approach": {
  "definition": "An Ovary_Approach is a Pollen_Tube_Growth characterized by directed tube growth toward the ovule micropyle in response to ovule-derived attractant signals upon completion of style navigation.",
  "alternative_term": "ovule approach | micropyle targeting | final tube navigation | ovary arrival |+ Ovar-Annäherung | Samenanlage-Annäherung | Mikropyle-Zielerfassung | finale Schlauchnavigation",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows ovary approach during early-mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 60-65, with pollen tubes completing 18-24 mm style navigation reaching ovary region containing 3-4 ovules, tubes responding to ovule-derived attractants navigating final 1.5-2.5 mm to micropyles over 2-5 hours, 2-3 tubes successfully targeting micropyles per flower, under oceanic conditions of 21-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing approach 20-32 hours post-pollination enabling fertilization and 54-64% fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Ovary_Approach is third and final aspect of Pollen_Tube_Growth, distinguished by culminating navigation to ovule micropyles. ||Represents final 1-4 hours and 1-3 mm of total 12-36 hour growth journey. ||Involves chemotropic response to ovule-derived attractants. ||Precise micropyle targeting despite complex ovary geometry. ||Competitive dynamics with typically 1-2 tubes succeeding per flower. ||Completes entire Pollination → Germination → Tube Growth sequence. ||Directly enables Fertilization upon micropyle penetration. ||Final determinant of reproductive success. || This critical final navigation phase occurs during pollen tube growth in early-mid June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over final 2-6 hours of tube growth following style traverse as ovary region reached, corresponding to BBCH 60-65 flowering stages. ||Approach mechanism involves tube completing transmitting tissue navigation reaching style base adjacent to ovary, exiting transmitting tract entering ovary locule space containing 2-4 ovules, responding to ovule-derived chemoattractant signals directing growth toward specific ovule micropyle, and final precise navigation to micropyle opening enabling embryo sac access. ||Ovary structure at approach shows bicarpellate superior ovary containing typically 2-4 ovules distributed in two locules, ovules with anatropous orientation having micropyle positioned near ovary base, and locule space providing open cavity for tube growth from style base to ovule surface. ||Ovule characteristics include integuments surrounding nucellus forming outer seed coat layers, nucellus containing megagametophyte embryo sac with egg cell and central cell, micropyle representing opening in integuments providing access pathway to embryo sac, and funiculus attaching ovule to placenta. ||Tube exit from transmitting tissue shows growth transitioning from extracellular matrix in style to open locule cavity in ovary, tube entering ovary space near style base, and beginning final approach toward ovule micropyles requiring 1-3 mm additional growth. ||Ovule-derived attractants directing approach include diffusible signals emanating from micropyle creating concentration gradient, possible attractant molecules including LURE peptides identified in other species though specific signals in grapevine unknown, calcium gradients possibly contributing to guidance, and integrated signal profile directing tube to appropriate target. ||Chemotropic tube response shows sensitive detection of attractant gradient with femtomolar to picomolar sensitivity in some systems, directional growth reorienting toward highest attractant concentration, and precise navigation capability enabling targeting of 100-200 micrometer micropyle opening from millimeter distances. ||Multiple ovule targeting shows 2-4 ovules per ovary potentially receiving tubes, competitive dynamics with 2-5 tubes typically reaching ovary but usually only 1-2 achieving fertilization, and possible preferential targeting of specific ovules though mechanisms unclear. ||Tube growth rate during approach shows sustained or slightly reduced velocity 1-2 mm per hour during final ovary navigation, brief 1-3 mm growth distance from style base to ovule micropyle, and total approach duration typically 1-4 hours completing final stage of 12-36 hour total tube growth journey. ||Micropyle targeting precision shows remarkable accuracy with tube navigating directly to 100-200 micrometer micropyle opening, growth reorientation responding to attractant gradient, and successful targeting despite presence of multiple potential targets and complex three-dimensional ovary geometry. ||Tube-ovule contact shows tube apex reaching micropyle outer opening, possible adhesion to micropyle tissue, and preparation for penetration through micropyle canal to embryo sac requiring final 100-300 micrometer growth. ||Micropyle penetration following approach involves tube growing through micropyle canal between integument layers, navigating 100-300 micrometer passage to nucellus surface, and reaching embryo sac enabling sperm cell discharge into female gametophyte. ||Embryo sac structure at tube arrival includes seven-celled eight-nucleate organization with egg cell, two synergid cells flanking egg, central cell with two polar nuclei, and three antipodal cells, with synergids providing tube attraction and reception. ||Tube discharge preparation shows sperm cells positioned near tube tip preparing for release, vegetative nucleus degenerating as fertilization approaches, and tube apex preparing to rupture delivering sperm cells into embryo sac. ||Timing coordination shows tube arrival typically 18-40 hours after initial pollination depending on conditions, embryo sac maturity synchronized to receive tube at appropriate developmental stage, and temporal coordination essential for successful fertilization. ||Multiple tube arrivals show 1-4 tubes potentially reaching ovary region, competitive access to limited ovules with typically only 1 tube per ovule succeeding, and excess tubes unable to fertilize already-fertilized ovules becoming reproductively irrelevant. ||Ovule selectivity mechanisms possibly include first-arrival advantage with earliest tube to reach micropyle gaining access, ovule signaling changes after fertilization preventing additional tubes, or tube-tube interactions affecting competitive success, though specific mechanisms poorly understood. ||Failed approach causes include inadequate tube vigor preventing final navigation, absence of appropriate attractant signals from ovule dysfunction, guidance failure causing misdirected growth missing micropyle, structural abnormalities in ovary or ovule preventing access, or competition from faster tubes monopolizing available ovules. ||Environmental effects during approach show continued temperature sensitivity with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient final navigation, and continued boron requirement for tube integrity during final growth phase. ||Approach success rate shows 40-70% flowers achieving successful tube arrival at ovule and fertilization under favorable conditions, reflecting cumulative effects of pollination efficiency, germination success, tube growth vigor, and competitive dynamics. ||The process represents third and final aspect of pollen tube growth culminating navigation, following style penetration and transmitting tissue navigation. ||Duration typically spans 1-4 hours representing final navigation phase after 10-30 hour style traverse. ||Cultivar variation in approach may include ovary structure affecting navigation complexity, ovule number affecting targeting opportunities, and attractant signaling affecting guidance efficiency. ||Regional timing shows ovary approach occurring during flowering period across all climates 18-40 hours after initial pollination as final tube growth phase completes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing culmination of tube growth enabling fertilization, requiring successful completion of entire pollination-germination-growth sequence, demonstrating critical importance of coordinated reproductive processes, and establishing approach success as final determinant of fertilization achievement and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing ovule attractant signals and chemotropic guidance mechanisms, investigating tube-ovule interactions and targeting precision, evaluating competitive dynamics among multiple tubes, quantifying approach timing and success rates, and assessing ovary approach as final determinant of fertilization outcomes and fruit set.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 388-395 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 293-298 || Carmona MJ et al. (2008) Grapevine inflorescence and flower development, Adv Bot Res 47:301-337"
},

  "Fertilization": {
  "definition": "A Fertilization is a Flowering consisting of pollen tube penetration of the embryo sac through the micropyle, sperm cell discharge, fusion of one sperm with the egg cell forming the diploid zygote, and fusion of the other sperm with the central cell forming the triploid endosperm nucleus.",
  "alternative_term": "sexual reproduction | gamete fusion | double fertilization | zygote formation |+ Befruchtung | sexuelle Reproduktion | Gametenfusion | Doppelbefruchtung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows fertilization during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with pollen tubes penetrating micropyle and discharging sperm cells 26-38 hours after pollination, double fertilization producing diploid zygotes and triploid endosperm nuclei, 1-3 seeds developing per berry, under warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature, adequate boron supporting tube penetration and fusion, typical of this late-season cultivar achieving 58-68% fertilization success and fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Fertilization represents culminating sexual reproductive process within Flowering determining fruit set success. ||Corresponds to BBCH 65-69 stages occurring 24-48 hours post-pollination. ||Subdivided into Pollen_Tube_Penetration accessing embryo sac and Ovule_Penetration culminating in discharge. ||Involves double fertilization creating zygote and endosperm. ||Critical environmental sensitivity particularly temperature and boron. ||Determines berry number and yield. ||Marks transition to berry development phase. ||Final reproductive process completing flowering. || This essential fertilization process occurs during late flowering in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically occurring 24-48 hours after initial pollination as pollen tube completes growth journey, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 flowering completion stages. ||Fertilization mechanism involves coordinated processes including pollen tube penetration through micropyle accessing embryo sac, tube discharge releasing two sperm cells into female gametophyte, sperm cell fusion with egg forming diploid 2n zygote, second sperm fusion with central cell containing two polar nuclei forming triploid 3n endosperm nucleus, and initiation of embryo and endosperm development establishing successful seed and berry formation. ||Pollen tube arrival at micropyle shows culmination of 12-36 hour tube growth journey from stigma through style to ovary, tube navigating to micropyle outer opening guided by ovule-derived attractant signals, and positioning for penetration through micropyle canal to embryo sac requiring final 100-300 micrometer growth. ||Micropyle structure providing access pathway includes opening in integument layers surrounding ovule, canal 100-300 micrometers length extending from outer to inner integument surface, inner micropyle opening adjacent to nucellus surface providing embryo sac access, and overall architecture creating controlled entry pathway to female gametophyte. ||Embryo sac structure at fertilization shows mature seven-celled eight-nucleate megagametophyte organization including egg cell positioned at micropylar pole flanked by two synergid cells providing tube reception, large central cell occupying majority of sac volume containing two polar nuclei fusing or separate, and three antipodal cells at chalazal pole opposite micropyle though degenerating by fertilization. ||Synergid cell function shows specialized reception cells adjacent to egg providing attractant signal guiding tube to micropyle, developing filiform apparatus creating elaborate cell wall ingrowths facing micropyle, and preparing for tube penetration and discharge serving as initial contact point for arriving tube. ||Pollen tube penetration through micropyle involves tube apex growing through micropyle canal between integument layers, navigating tortuous 100-300 micrometer passage requiring 1-3 hours, reaching nucellus surface adjacent to embryo sac, and penetrating through nucellus wall entering synergid cell completing access to female gametophyte. ||Tube discharge mechanism shows tube apex penetrating synergid cell and rupturing, releasing two sperm cells into embryo sac cytoplasm, and delivering male gametes positioned for fusion with egg and central cell. ||Sperm cell characteristics include non-motile cells lacking flagella transported passively in tube cytoplasm, cells containing haploid nucleus and minimal cytoplasm optimized for fusion, and two genetically identical sperm from generative cell mitosis though functioning independently in double fertilization. ||Double fertilization process shows one sperm cell migrating to and fusing with egg cell creating diploid 2n zygote containing genetic material from both parents, second sperm cell fusing with central cell or polar nuclei forming triploid 3n endosperm nucleus with two maternal and one paternal genome copies, and synchronized fusion events typically occurring within hours of tube discharge. ||Egg cell fusion creating zygote involves sperm nucleus fusing with egg nucleus combining genetic material, activation of egg development transitioning from arrest to active division, and first zygotic division initiating embryo formation typically within 24-48 hours of fertilization. ||Central cell fusion forming endosperm shows sperm nucleus fusing with central cell containing two polar nuclei or fused diploid nucleus, creating triploid nucleus with unbalanced genomic ratio affecting endosperm development, and endosperm development initiating providing nutritive support for embryo growth. ||Fertilization timing shows tube arrival at micropyle typically 18-40 hours after initial pollination depending on style length and temperature, tube penetration and discharge proceeding over 2-6 hours following arrival, and sperm-egg fusion completing within hours of discharge creating successful fertilization typically 24-48 hours post-pollination. ||Successful fertilization outcomes include viable zygote initiating embryo development, functional endosperm supporting embryo growth, ovule developing into seed, ovary wall developing into fruit flesh, and overall flower transitioning from reproductive to developmental state producing berry. ||Berry development initiation following fertilization shows rapid ovary expansion from 4-8 mm pre-fertilization to 10-18 mm within weeks, cell division intensity maximizing during early berry growth, resource allocation shifting to developing berries consuming 40-60% photosynthate, and visible fruit cluster formation confirming reproductive success. ||Auxin production from developing seeds drives berry growth with auxin from embryo and endosperm preventing flower abscission, triggering cell division and expansion in ovary wall, and coordinating berry development with seed formation. ||Failed fertilization causes include pollen tube failure to reach ovule from inadequate growth vigor or guidance problems, abnormal embryo sac development preventing proper gamete formation, sperm cell dysfunction from pollen quality problems, egg or central cell abnormalities preventing fusion, environmental stress during fertilization period disrupting delicate processes, or genetic incompatibility though rare in self-compatible grapevine. ||Coulure relationship to fertilization shows poor fruit set from fertilization failure with unfertilized flowers aborting and abscising, environmental conditions during flowering particularly rain or temperature extremes affecting fertilization success, and fruit set percentage 30-75% reflecting fertilization success under varying conditions. ||Environmental effects on fertilization include temperature affecting tube growth rate and fusion processes with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient fertilization, boron nutrition essential for tube integrity enabling micropyle penetration, appropriate humidity maintaining tissue function, and overall favorable conditions during 24-48 hour fertilization window critical for success. ||Temperature sensitivity during fertilization shows optimal 22-28°C supporting normal tube penetration and fusion processes, cool conditions 15-20°C potentially delaying or impairing fertilization reducing success rate, excessive heat above 33°C causing reproductive dysfunction preventing normal fusion, and critical temperature dependence during fertilization period affecting outcomes. ||Boron absolute requirement emphasizes continued critical importance with boron essential for tube wall integrity during micropyle penetration, deficiency causing tube bursting or penetration failure preventing sperm delivery, and adequate boron 10-20 ppm in reproductive tissues supporting successful fertilization. ||Multiple tube arrivals per flower show typically 1-4 tubes reaching ovary region, competitive dynamics with usually only 1-2 tubes achieving fertilization, excess tubes unable to fertilize already-fertilized ovules, and single successful fertilization per ovule establishing seed number and berry size. ||Fertilization competition among ovules shows 2-4 ovules per flower potentially receiving tubes, typically 1-3 ovules successfully fertilizing contributing to final seed number 1-3 per berry, and seed number affecting berry size and development with more seeds generally producing larger berries. ||The process shows two major phases progressing from pollen tube penetration accessing embryo sac through micropyle and synergid, through ovule penetration culminating in egg approach and tube discharge enabling sperm-egg fusion. ||Duration typically spans 2-8 hours from micropyle arrival to completed fusion, as final phase of 24-48 hour total reproductive timeline from pollination to fertilization. ||Cultivar variation in fertilization may include embryo sac development affecting fusion success, ovule number affecting seed production, and fertilization efficiency affecting fruit set under varying conditions. ||Regional timing shows fertilization during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, occurring 24-48 hours after pollination as culmination of flowering period. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential reproductive culmination determining fruit set success, requiring favorable environmental conditions throughout flowering period particularly during final fertilization phase, demonstrating critical dependence on coordinated pollination-germination-growth-fertilization sequence, establishing fertilization success as direct determinant of berry number and yield, and marking transition from reproductive to developmental phase initiating berry growth. ||Research applications include analyzing fertilization mechanisms including tube-embryo sac interactions and sperm-egg fusion, investigating environmental and genetic factors affecting fertilization success, evaluating double fertilization coordination and timing, quantifying fertilization success rates under varying conditions, assessing seed number effects on berry development, and developing models predicting fruit set from fertilization dynamics and environmental factors.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009566 ## fertilization | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 388-395 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 293-300 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Pollen_Tube_Penetration": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Tube_Penetration is a Fertilization comprising the navigation of the pollen tube through the micropyle canal between integument layers accessing the nucellus and embryo sac.",
  "alternative_term": "micropyle penetration | tube entry into embryo sac | synergid entry | ovule access |+ Pollenschlauch-Penetration | Mikropyle-Durchdringung | Schlaucheintritt in Embryosack | Samenanlage-Zugang",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows pollen tube penetration during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with tubes navigating through 120-180 micrometer micropyle canals over 1.5-3.5 hours at 0.4-0.7 mm per hour penetration rate, reaching nucellus surface and entering synergid cells, under continental conditions of 21-27°C temperature, adequate boron 12-18 ppm supporting tube wall integrity during constrained passage, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar with 62-76% penetration success 22-34 hours post-pollination",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Tube_Penetration is first major Fertilization phase establishing embryo sac access. ||Subdivided into Micropyle_Targeting achieving precise navigation and Synergid_Penetration entering female gametophyte. ||Duration 1-4 hours for micropyle passage. ||Slower growth rate 0.3-0.8 mm per hour in constrained environment. ||Critical boron dependence for structural integrity. ||Synergid attractant guidance essential. ||Success rate 50-75% under favorable conditions. ||Enables subsequent tube discharge and fertilization. || This critical penetration phase occurs during fertilization in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over 1-4 hours following tube arrival at micropyle as part of BBCH 65-69 fertilization stages. ||Penetration mechanism involves tube apex targeting micropyle outer opening guided by synergid-derived attractant signals, growing through micropyle canal navigating 100-300 micrometer tortuous passage between integument layers, reaching nucellus surface adjacent to embryo sac, and penetrating nucellus wall entering synergid cell completing access to female gametophyte. ||Micropyle canal structure shows passage formed by integument tissue layers, inner and outer integuments creating canal walls, canal diameter 20-50 micrometers varying along length providing constrained growth pathway, canal length 100-300 micrometers depending on integument thickness and ovule development, and tortuous non-linear path requiring precise tube navigation. ||Tube growth through micropyle shows slower penetration rate 0.3-0.8 mm per hour compared to 1-3 mm per hour style growth reflecting constrained environment, sustained tip growth maintaining wall synthesis and extension, tube diameter 8-12 micrometers fitting within 20-50 micrometer canal, and mechanical interaction with canal walls potentially affecting growth dynamics. ||Synergid attractant guidance shows filiform apparatus in synergid cells secreting signals creating concentration gradient, attractant molecules diffusing through micropyle establishing directional cue, possible calcium gradient contributing to guidance, and tube showing chemotropic response directing growth precisely toward inner micropyle opening adjacent to synergid. ||Tube-micropyle wall interactions include possible physical contact and adhesion, tube secreting wall-modifying enzymes potentially facilitating passage through constrained space, mechanical forces from turgor pressure contributing to penetration through resistant tissue, and coordinated growth enabling successful navigation despite spatial constraints. ||Nucellus penetration following micropyle transit shows tube reaching nucellus surface at inner micropyle opening, penetrating through nucellus wall cells, and entering synergid cell creating direct access to embryo sac cytoplasm. ||Synergid cell structure providing reception includes specialized cells flanking egg at micropylar pole, filiform apparatus with extensive wall ingrowths creating large surface area facing micropyle, degeneration program initiating upon tube contact preparing for discharge reception, and cytoplasmic organization supporting tube attraction and penetration. ||Tube penetration into synergid shows apex entering synergid cell cytoplasm through filiform apparatus region, penetration possibly causing synergid degeneration as part of normal fertilization process, and establishing pathway for sperm cell release into embryo sac. ||Penetration timing shows 1-4 hours required for micropyle navigation from outer opening to synergid entry, timing variation depending on micropyle length and structure, temperature affecting penetration rate, and culminating arrival at embryo sac typically 20-40 hours after initial pollination. ||Tube structural requirements during penetration include robust wall resisting mechanical stresses in constrained micropyle environment, continued wall synthesis supporting growth through canal, adequate turgor pressure driving extension through resistant tissue, and boron-dependent wall integrity preventing bursting under mechanical stress. ||Boron critical role during penetration emphasizes absolute requirement with boron essential for maintaining tube wall structure during micropyle passage, deficiency causing tube bursting or structural failure during penetration preventing embryo sac access, mechanical stress in constrained environment exacerbating boron deficiency effects, and adequate boron 10-20 ppm supporting successful penetration. ||Environmental effects on penetration include temperature affecting growth rate and metabolic support with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient penetration within 1-2 hours, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing penetration requiring 3-5 hours, and continued boron requirement as limiting factor affecting penetration success. ||Failed penetration causes include inadequate tube vigor preventing sustained growth through micropyle, boron deficiency causing structural failure during passage, abnormal micropyle structure preventing access, insufficient attractant signaling from synergid dysfunction, or tube misdirection failing to locate micropyle opening. ||Penetration success rate shows 50-75% tubes reaching ovary region successfully penetrating micropyle and accessing embryo sac under favorable conditions, declining to 30-50% under suboptimal conditions, and success rate directly determining fertilization potential and fruit set. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from micropyle targeting achieving precise navigation to outer opening, through synergid penetration entering embryo sac cytoplasm. ||Duration typically spans 1-4 hours representing final tube growth phase before discharge. ||Cultivar variation in penetration may include micropyle structure affecting penetration difficulty, ovule development affecting access pathway, and tube vigor affecting penetration success rate. ||Regional timing shows pollen tube penetration occurring during mid-late June across all climates 20-40 hours after pollination as final tube growth phase before fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical access phase enabling sperm delivery to egg, requiring sustained tube vigor and structural integrity, demonstrating continued boron importance as absolute requirement, and establishing penetration success as prerequisite for fertilization and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing micropyle penetration mechanisms and navigation, investigating synergid attractant signals and chemotropic guidance, evaluating boron effects on tube integrity during penetration, quantifying penetration timing and success rates, and assessing penetration success as determinant of fertilization outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010183 ## pollen tube guidance | 0.8" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 390-392 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 295-298 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Micropyle_Targeting": {
  "definition": "A Micropyle_Targeting is a Pollen_Tube_Penetration characterized by directed tube growth in the ovary locule toward a 100–200 μm micropyle opening guided by synergid-derived attractant signals.",
  "alternative_term": "micropyle location | ovule targeting | precise navigation | attractant response |+ Mikropyle-Zielerfassung | Samenanlage-Zielansteuerung | präzise Navigation | Locksignal-Reaktion",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows micropyle targeting during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with pollen tubes detecting synergid attractant signals within 1.5-2.5 mm of ovules, chemotropic growth reorientation navigating final 1-3 mm over 1-2.5 hours, precise arrival at 120-180 micrometer micropyle openings, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar with 2-3 tubes successfully targeting 3-4 available ovules per flower 24-36 hours post-pollination",
  "editor_note": "Micropyle_Targeting is first aspect of Pollen_Tube_Penetration, distinguished by precise chemotropic navigation to micropyle opening. ||Represents remarkable precision achieving 100-200 micrometer target from millimeter distance. ||Duration 1-3 hours during final approach. ||Synergid-derived attractant signals guide navigation. ||Multiple tubes compete for limited ovules. ||Essential prerequisite for Synergid_Penetration and embryo sac access. ||Sophisticated tube-ovule communication system. || This critical targeting phase occurs during pollen tube penetration in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over final 1-3 hours of tube growth as ovule approached, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization stages. ||Targeting mechanism involves tube detection of diffusible attractant signals emanating from synergid filiform apparatus creating concentration gradient, chemotropic growth response reorienting tube trajectory toward highest attractant concentration, progressive approach refining navigation as gradient strengthens, and precise arrival at micropyle outer opening completing targeting. ||Synergid attractant signals show secretion from filiform apparatus in synergid cells adjacent to egg, diffusible peptide or protein signals creating concentration gradient extending into ovary locule, possible LURE-type peptides identified in other species serving as attractants though specific grapevine signals unknown, and integrated signal profile providing directional information guiding tube to micropyle. ||Attractant gradient characteristics include source at micropyle creating highest concentration, declining concentration with distance following diffusion pattern, gradient detectable at millimeter scale enabling long-range guidance, and sufficient signal strength for tube detection and response. ||Tube chemotropic response shows sensitive detection of attractant concentration differences with femtomolar to picomolar sensitivity in some systems, growth reorientation toward higher concentration through asymmetric tip growth, and progressive directional adjustment refining trajectory as micropyle approached. ||Growth trajectory modification shows tube initially approaching ovary region from style base, detection of attractant gradient triggering directional change, progressive reorientation over 1-3 mm final growth aligning with micropyle position, and accurate targeting achieving arrival at 100-200 micrometer micropyle opening despite complex three-dimensional ovary geometry. ||Targeting precision shows remarkable accuracy with tube navigating directly to small micropyle opening, successful targeting from 1-3 mm initial detection distance, minimal trajectory error enabling first-attempt micropyle location without extensive searching, and precision suggesting sophisticated chemotropic sensing and response mechanisms. ||Multiple ovule targeting dynamics show 2-4 ovules per flower potentially producing attractant signals, competitive situation with 2-5 tubes typically in ovary but only 1-2 achieving fertilization, possible preferential targeting of specific ovules though mechanisms unclear, and first-arrival advantage with earliest tube to reach responsive ovule likely succeeding. ||Ovule-to-ovule variation in attractant production possibly includes developmental differences affecting signal strength, some ovules producing stronger signals receiving preferential targeting, and asynchronous ovule maturation creating temporal variation in targeting opportunities. ||Tube-tube competitive targeting shows multiple tubes potentially detecting same ovule signals, competitive approach with fastest or most sensitive tube gaining access, and unsuccessful tubes potentially redirecting to alternative ovules or failing to achieve fertilization. ||Targeting distance shows detection occurring when tube within approximately 1-3 mm of micropyle based on gradient strength, closer approach enabling stronger signal and more precise navigation, and final arrival requiring sustained chemotropic response over 1-3 hour approach period. ||Growth rate during targeting shows sustained velocity 1-2 mm per hour during final ovary navigation, brief 1-3 mm growth distance from initial detection to micropyle arrival, and total targeting duration typically 1-3 hours representing final tube growth phase. ||Calcium signaling in targeting possibly includes calcium gradient associated with attractant signal, localized calcium accumulation at tube tip mediating chemotropic response, and calcium-dependent signaling affecting growth direction though specific roles in grapevine poorly characterized. ||Environmental effects on targeting include temperature affecting tube metabolic activity and growth rate influencing targeting dynamics, continued boron requirement for tube integrity during final approach, and overall favorable conditions 22-28°C supporting efficient targeting. ||Ovule maturity coordination with targeting shows embryo sac development synchronized to produce attractant signals when tubes likely to arrive, temporal matching between tube arrival timing 20-40 hours post-pollination and ovule receptivity, and developmental coordination essential for successful targeting and fertilization. ||Failed targeting causes include inadequate attractant production from ovule dysfunction, tube chemotropic dysfunction preventing signal detection or response, competitive exclusion by faster tubes monopolizing available ovules, or structural abnormalities in ovary preventing access despite successful navigation. ||Targeting verification methods include microscopic observation of tube trajectories, fluorescence visualization of tubes approaching micropyles, and experimental manipulation of attractant signals affecting targeting success. ||The process represents first aspect of pollen tube penetration achieving precise navigation to entry point, followed by synergid penetration completing access. ||Duration typically spans 1-3 hours representing final targeting approach phase. ||Cultivar variation in targeting may include ovule attractant production affecting signal strength, tube chemotropic sensitivity affecting detection and response, and ovule number affecting targeting opportunities and competition. ||Regional timing shows micropyle targeting occurring during mid-late June across all climates 20-38 hours after pollination as final tube approach phase. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical precision navigation enabling embryo sac access, demonstrating sophisticated tube-ovule communication, requiring successful completion of entire tube growth journey, and establishing targeting success as prerequisite for penetration and fertilization. ||Research applications include identifying attractant signals and chemotropic mechanisms, investigating tube-ovule signaling and communication, evaluating targeting precision and accuracy, quantifying competitive dynamics among multiple tubes, and assessing targeting success as determinant of fertilization efficiency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 390-392 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 295-297"
},

  "Synergid_Penetration": {
  "definition": "A Synergid_Penetration is a Pollen_Tube_Penetration comprising the passage of the pollen tube through the nucellus wall and entry into the synergid cell cytoplasm.",
  "alternative_term": "embryo sac entry | synergid cell penetration | female gametophyte access | tube-synergid fusion |+ Synergiden-Penetration | Embryosack-Eintritt | weibliche Gametophyten-Zugang | Schlauch-Synergiden-Fusion",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows synergid penetration during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with pollen tubes penetrating through thin nucellus tissue entering synergid cells at micropylar pole 24-40 hours post-pollination, tube apex establishing cytoplasmic connection with embryo sac, penetrated synergid initiating degeneration, under cool maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, adequate boron 11-17 ppm supporting final tube integrity, typical of this early-bursting cultivar with 58-72% penetration success enabling fertilization",
  "editor_note": "Synergid_Penetration is second and final aspect of Pollen_Tube_Penetration, distinguished by embryo sac entry completing access to female gametophyte. ||Represents culmination of entire tube growth journey. ||Occurs 22-42 hours post-pollination. ||Penetrated synergid degenerates as normal response. ||Immediately precedes tube discharge. ||Critical boron dependence for successful entry. ||Success rate 50-70% determining fertilization potential. ||Enables Ovule_Penetration phase with egg approach and discharge. || This critical entry phase occurs during pollen tube penetration in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically occurring 22-42 hours after pollination as final tube growth culminates, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization stages. ||Penetration mechanism involves tube apex reaching nucellus surface at inner micropyle opening adjacent to embryo sac, penetrating nucellus wall cells through enzymatic degradation and mechanical force, entering synergid cell through filiform apparatus region, and establishing direct cytoplasmic connection between tube and female gametophyte enabling sperm delivery. ||Nucellus structure at penetration shows thin nucellus tissue layer 1-3 cell layers thick surrounding embryo sac, cells forming protective barrier around megagametophyte, and wall tissue requiring tube penetration for embryo sac access. ||Nucellus penetration process shows tube apex contacting nucellus surface, possible secretion of wall-modifying enzymes degrading cell wall components, turgor pressure contributing mechanical force driving penetration, and breakthrough into embryo sac region creating access pathway. ||Synergid cell position shows two synergid cells flanking egg cell at micropylar pole of embryo sac, cells positioned directly adjacent to inner micropyle opening receiving arriving tubes, and one synergid typically receiving tube penetration while other remains intact. ||Filiform apparatus structure shows elaborate cell wall ingrowths creating extensive membrane surface area, projections extending toward micropyle creating reception zone for arriving tube, and specialized architecture facilitating tube attraction and penetration. ||Tube entry into synergid shows apex penetrating through filiform apparatus region entering synergid cytoplasm, penetration possibly involving enzymatic wall modification at entry point, and tube establishing connection with synergid cell interior preparing for discharge. ||Synergid degeneration response shows penetrated synergid cell initiating programmed cell death following tube entry, degeneration creating space for sperm cell release and movement, membrane breakdown facilitating sperm access to egg and central cell, and degeneration as normal part of fertilization process rather than pathological response. ||Tube positioning in synergid shows apex extending into synergid cytoplasm, sperm cells positioned near tube tip ready for release, and tube-synergid interface providing discharge site enabling sperm delivery into embryo sac. ||Tube-embryo sac contact interface shows membrane interactions between tube and synergid, possible adhesion molecules mediating attachment, and structural changes preparing for tube rupture and discharge. ||Penetration timing shows entry into synergid occurring 22-42 hours after initial pollination reflecting cumulative time for tube growth journey, 1-4 hours after micropyle arrival as final penetration completes, and positioning immediately before discharge typically within minutes to hours of synergid entry. ||Tube structural state at penetration shows maintenance of wall integrity throughout micropyle passage, possible wall weakening at apex preparing for discharge, and cytoplasmic organization with sperm cells positioned for release. ||Sperm cell positioning shows two sperm cells traveling in tube cytoplasm near apex, cells ready for delivery upon discharge, and one sperm destined for egg fusion while other targets central cell in double fertilization. ||Synergid signal termination following penetration possibly includes cessation of attractant production preventing additional tube recruitment, signaling change communicating occupied state, and protection against polyspermy through single tube reception per ovule. ||Penetrated versus intact synergid shows asymmetric reception with one synergid receiving tube and degenerating, other synergid remaining intact though function following fertilization unclear, and structural evidence distinguishing penetrated from unpenetrated cells. ||Environmental requirements for successful penetration include adequate temperature 22-28°C supporting metabolic processes and tube growth, continued boron requirement for tube wall integrity during final growth and penetration, and appropriate tissue hydration maintaining cell structure and function. ||Temperature effects on penetration show optimal conditions supporting efficient entry within 1-2 hours of micropyle arrival, cool conditions potentially delaying penetration, and temperature sensitivity affecting final fertilization success rate. ||Boron critical role emphasizes continued absolute requirement with boron essential for tube wall integrity during nucellus penetration and synergid entry, deficiency causing tube bursting or structural failure preventing successful embryo sac access, and adequate boron 10-20 ppm supporting normal penetration and fertilization. ||Failed penetration causes include tube structural failure from boron deficiency or other dysfunction, abnormal nucellus or synergid structure preventing entry, inadequate tube vigor preventing final penetration, or developmental abnormalities in embryo sac preventing normal reception. ||Penetration success rate shows 50-70% tubes reaching micropyle successfully penetrating synergid under favorable conditions, cumulative effect of all previous reproductive processes determining final success, and success rate directly determining fertilization potential and fruit set. ||The process represents second and final aspect of pollen tube penetration completing embryo sac access, following micropyle targeting. ||Duration typically brief representing final moments of tube growth immediately before discharge. ||Cultivar variation in synergid penetration may include embryo sac structure affecting entry pathway, synergid development affecting reception capacity, and penetration efficiency affecting fertilization success rate. ||Regional timing shows synergid penetration occurring during mid-late June across all climates 22-42 hours after pollination as culmination of tube growth journey. ||Viticultural significance includes representing final access phase enabling sperm delivery to female gametophyte, requiring successful completion of entire pollination-germination-growth sequence, demonstrating critical importance of tube structural integrity, and establishing penetration success as immediate prerequisite for fertilization and fruit set. ||Research applications include analyzing synergid structure and function in tube reception, investigating penetration mechanisms and tube-synergid interactions, evaluating factors affecting penetration success, quantifying penetration timing relative to pollination, and assessing penetration success as final determinant of fertilization potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010198 ## synergid death | 0.8" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 391-395 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 296-300 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Ovule_Penetration": {
  "definition": "An Ovule_Penetration is a Fertilization comprising the discharge of two sperm cells from the pollen tube into the embryo sac following synergid entry.",
  "alternative_term": "sperm cell discharge | double fertilization | gamete fusion | zygote and endosperm formation |+ Samenanlage-Penetration | Spermazell-Entladung | Doppelbefruchtung | Zygoten- und Endospermbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows ovule penetration during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with pollen tubes discharging sperm cells into embryo sac 26-40 hours post-pollination, double fertilization producing diploid zygotes and triploid endosperm nuclei, 1-3 successful fertilizations per flower creating 1-3 seeds per berry, rapid ovary expansion to 12-18 mm within 2 weeks, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar achieving 54-64% fertilization success and fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Ovule_Penetration is second major Fertilization phase representing culminating reproductive events. ||Subdivided into Egg_Cell_Approach positioning sperm and Pollen_Tube_Discharge releasing sperm for fusion. ||Duration minutes to hours from discharge to fusion completion. ||Involves double fertilization creating 2n zygote and 3n endosperm. ||Determines seed number 1-3 per berry. ||Initiates berry development through auxin production. ||Success rate 40-70% determining fruit set. ||Completes entire flowering reproductive sequence. ||Marks transition to berry development phase. || This critical discharge and fusion phase occurs during fertilization in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding within hours following synergid penetration as fertilization culminates, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization completion stages. ||Ovule penetration process encompasses tube discharge mechanism releasing sperm cells into embryo sac cytoplasm, sperm cell migration to fusion targets with one approaching egg cell and other approaching central cell, and gamete fusion events creating zygote and endosperm nucleus completing sexual reproduction. ||Tube discharge preparation shows apex positioned in penetrated synergid cell, wall weakening at tip through localized degradation, cytoplasmic pressure building creating discharge force, and sperm cells positioned near apex ready for release. ||Discharge mechanism involves tube apex rupture releasing contents into embryo sac, explosive or gradual discharge depending on turgor and wall properties, sperm cells expelling into synergid and embryo sac cytoplasm, and vegetative nucleus and cytoplasm also discharging though reproductive role completed. ||Sperm cell release shows two genetically identical haploid cells entering embryo sac, cells non-motile requiring passive transport or short-distance migration to fusion targets, and cells maintaining integrity and viability during discharge and approach phases. ||Sperm cell fate determination shows one sperm cell designated for egg fusion creating embryo, other sperm cell targeting central cell creating endosperm, and differentiation possibly occurring during discharge or immediately after through unknown mechanisms. ||Egg cell approach by first sperm shows migration or drift through embryo sac cytoplasm toward egg positioned at micropylar pole adjacent to penetrated synergid, short distance typically <100 micrometers enabling rapid approach within minutes to hours, and arrival at egg cell surface preparing for fusion. ||Central cell approach by second sperm shows migration toward large central cell occupying majority of embryo sac volume, central cell nucleus or polar nuclei providing fusion target, and sperm arrival at central cell preparing for fusion. ||Sperm-egg fusion creating zygote involves sperm cell contacting egg cell surface, membrane fusion integrating sperm into egg cytoplasm, nuclear fusion combining haploid sperm nucleus with haploid egg nucleus, formation of diploid 2n zygote nucleus containing genetic contributions from both parents, and egg activation transitioning from developmental arrest to active division initiating embryo development. ||Sperm-central cell fusion forming endosperm shows second sperm fusing with central cell, nuclear fusion combining haploid sperm nucleus with diploid central cell nucleus formed from polar nuclei fusion or fusing directly with separate polar nuclei, formation of triploid 3n endosperm nucleus with 2 per 1 maternal per paternal genomic ratio, and endosperm development initiating providing nutritive tissue supporting embryo growth. ||Double fertilization synchronization shows two fusion events typically occurring within hours of tube discharge, coordinated timing ensuring both embryo and endosperm development initiate together, and synchronization critical for normal seed development with embryo requiring endosperm nutritive support. ||Zygote development initiation shows first cell division typically within 24-48 hours of fertilization, progressive cell divisions establishing embryo proper and suspensor, and embryo growth consuming endosperm nutritive reserves during seed maturation. ||Endosperm development shows free nuclear division phase with rapid mitosis producing multinucleate coenocyte, cellularization phase forming cellular endosperm tissue, and subsequent embryo consumption reducing endosperm to thin layer in mature seed. ||Fertilization completion timing shows discharge and fusion typically occurring 24-48 hours after initial pollination representing culmination of reproductive sequence, successful fertilization confirmed through continued ovule and ovary development, and berry growth initiation providing visible evidence of reproductive success. ||Ovary response to fertilization shows rapid expansion from 4-8 mm pre-fertilization to 10-18 mm within 1-2 weeks, cell division intensity maximizing during early post-fertilization period, auxin production from developing seeds preventing flower abscission and driving berry growth, and resource allocation shifting dramatically to developing fruits consuming 40-60% photosynthate. ||Seed development following fertilization shows integuments developing into seed coat, endosperm and embryo developing within seed creating viable propagule, and seed maturation coordinating with berry ripening over subsequent months. ||Failed fertilization outcomes include unfertilized flowers lacking seed development stimulus, ovary failing to expand and develop, flower abortion and abscission occurring within days to weeks, and coulure poor fruit set from fertilization failure affecting yield. ||Environmental effects on fusion show temperature sensitivity with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient fusion and development initiation, cool conditions potentially impairing fusion or subsequent development, excessive heat above 33°C causing reproductive dysfunction, and critical temperature dependence during fertilization window. ||Multiple tube considerations show typically 1-2 tubes successfully penetrating and discharging per flower though 2-4 ovules present, first-fertilized ovules excluding subsequent tubes through unknown mechanisms, and successful fertilization number typically 1-3 ovules creating 1-3 seeds per berry. ||Polyspermy prevention shows single tube reception per ovule preventing multiple sperm delivery, mechanisms possibly including rapid ovule signaling changes after fertilization, physical barriers preventing additional tube access, or synergid reception limitation, and protection ensuring normal diploid embryo and triploid endosperm formation. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from egg cell approach positioning sperm for fusion, through pollen tube discharge releasing sperm and enabling fusion events. ||Duration typically spans minutes to hours from discharge to completed fusion representing culminating fertilization events. ||Cultivar variation in ovule penetration may include discharge efficiency, fusion success rates, and developmental coordination affecting fertilization outcomes. ||Regional timing shows ovule penetration occurring during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, completing 24-48 hours after pollination. ||Viticultural significance includes representing culminating reproductive events determining seed and berry formation, requiring successful completion of entire pollination-germination-growth-penetration sequence, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity during fusion period, establishing fertilization success as direct determinant of fruit set and yield, and marking definitive transition from reproductive to developmental phase. ||Research applications include analyzing discharge mechanisms and sperm delivery, investigating double fertilization coordination and timing, evaluating environmental and genetic factors affecting fusion success, quantifying fertilization success rates and seed number outcomes, assessing fertilization effects on berry development, and developing strategies improving fruit set through enhanced fertilization efficiency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 392-400 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-305 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Egg_Cell_Approach": {
  "definition": "An Egg_Cell_Approach is an Ovule_Penetration involving the migration of one sperm cell through the embryo sac cytoplasm from the discharge site toward the egg cell at the micropylar pole.",
  "alternative_term": "sperm-egg approach | sperm cell positioning | gamete encounter | pre-fusion positioning |+ Eizell-Annäherung | Spermium-Eizell-Heranführung | Gameten-Begegnung | Präfusions-Positionierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows egg cell approach during late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with sperm cells released from tube apex in synergid migrating 30-80 micrometers to egg cell at micropylar pole within 15-90 minutes, establishing membrane contact preparing for fusion, under temperate maritime conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing approach 28-42 hours post-pollination enabling zygote formation",
  "editor_note": "Egg_Cell_Approach is first aspect of Ovule_Penetration, distinguished by sperm cell positioning for zygote formation. ||Represents short-distance migration <100 micrometers from discharge site to egg. ||Duration minutes to hours post-discharge. ||High efficiency given close proximity. ||Enables subsequent sperm-egg fusion creating diploid zygote. ||Parallel process with second sperm approaching central cell. ||Essential prerequisite for embryo development. ||Followed by Pollen_Tube_Discharge discussing release and fusion mechanisms. || This critical sperm positioning phase occurs during ovule penetration in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding within minutes to hours following tube discharge, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization stages. ||Approach mechanism involves sperm cell release from ruptured tube apex into synergid and embryo sac cytoplasm, passive drift or active migration through cytoplasm toward egg cell positioned adjacent to discharge site, short-distance movement typically <100 micrometers given egg proximity to synergid, and arrival at egg cell surface establishing contact for fusion. ||Sperm cell characteristics show haploid nucleus containing paternal genetic material, minimal cytoplasm optimized for fusion with cytoplasmic material largely excluded from gamete, non-motile cell lacking flagella requiring passive transport or cytoplasmic streaming for movement, and maintained integrity during discharge and approach maintaining fusion competence. ||Egg cell position shows location at micropylar pole of embryo sac immediately adjacent to synergid cells, proximity to tube discharge site facilitating rapid sperm arrival, and positioning optimizing fertilization efficiency through minimal required sperm travel. ||Distance and timing of approach show short travel distance typically 20-100 micrometers from synergid discharge site to egg cell surface, rapid approach completed within minutes to hours depending on cytoplasmic dynamics, and brief interval minimizing time between discharge and fusion reducing risk of sperm degradation. ||Cytoplasmic environment for sperm movement includes embryo sac cytoplasm providing aqueous medium, possible cytoplasmic streaming or flow affecting sperm transport, and chemical or physical gradients possibly guiding sperm toward egg though mechanisms poorly characterized. ||Sperm guidance to egg possibly involves chemotactic signals from egg cell attracting sperm, calcium gradients directing movement, physical constraints in embryo sac architecture channeling sperm toward egg, or passive drift enabled by close proximity, though specific mechanisms in grapevine largely unknown. ||Egg cell surface contact shows sperm arrival at egg cell plasma membrane, initial contact establishing opportunity for membrane fusion, and positioning of sperm nucleus adjacent to egg preparing for fusion. ||Egg cell structure at approach includes large haploid nucleus containing maternal genetic contribution, abundant cytoplasm with organelles and stored reserves, plasma membrane receptive to sperm fusion, and developmental arrest state awaiting fertilization activation. ||Sperm-egg recognition possibly involves surface molecules mediating species-specific recognition, compatibility assessment though self-compatibility in grapevine eliminates rejection, and molecular interactions preparing for membrane fusion. ||Membrane interaction preparation shows sperm and egg plasma membranes in close contact, possible adhesion molecules mediating attachment, and membrane modifications preparing for fusion including lipid reorganization and protein recruitment. ||Calcium signaling during approach possibly includes calcium waves in egg cytoplasm triggered by sperm contact, calcium-dependent processes regulating fusion, and calcium as second messenger coordinating fertilization events though specific roles incompletely understood. ||Approach verification methods include microscopic observation of embryo sac following pollination though technically challenging, fluorescent labeling of sperm cells enabling tracking though rarely applied in grapevine, and indirect inference from successful fertilization outcomes. ||Sperm fate determination shows one sperm cell destined for egg fusion while sibling targets central cell, differentiation possibly occurring during discharge or through stochastic selection upon release, and specific mechanisms determining which sperm fuses with which target unknown. ||Second sperm simultaneous approach to central cell shows parallel process with other discharged sperm migrating toward large central cell, coordinated double fertilization requiring both sperm cells reaching appropriate targets, and synchronization ensuring embryo and endosperm development initiate together. ||Environmental effects on approach include temperature affecting cytoplasmic dynamics and membrane properties, appropriate hydration maintaining cellular integrity and function, and overall favorable conditions 22-28°C supporting efficient approach and fusion. ||Failed approach causes include sperm cell damage during discharge compromising integrity or viability, abnormal cytoplasmic environment preventing movement or causing degradation, egg cell dysfunction preventing normal reception, or structural abnormalities in embryo sac disrupting approach pathway. ||Approach success rate shows high efficiency given close proximity between discharge site and egg, majority of successfully discharged sperm cells reaching egg under normal conditions, and approach success contributing to overall 50-70% fertilization rate in successful penetration events. ||The process represents first aspect of ovule penetration positioning sperm for fusion, followed by pollen tube discharge discussing release mechanism and fusion. ||Duration typically brief minutes to hours representing sperm travel and positioning phase. ||Cultivar variation in egg cell approach may include embryo sac structure affecting sperm transit, cytoplasmic properties affecting movement dynamics, and egg cell characteristics affecting reception. ||Regional timing shows egg cell approach occurring during mid-late June across all climates within hours of tube discharge 24-48 hours after pollination. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential sperm positioning enabling zygote formation, demonstrating efficiency of fertilization mechanism through minimal required sperm travel, and establishing approach success as prerequisite for fusion and embryo development. ||Research applications include analyzing sperm movement mechanisms and guidance, investigating egg cell signals and sperm-egg recognition, evaluating factors affecting approach efficiency, developing visualization techniques for observing approach in vivo, and assessing approach success as determinant of fertilization outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010183 ## pollen tube guidance | 0.8" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 393-395 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-300"
},

  "Pollen_Tube_Discharge": {
  "definition": "A Pollen_Tube_Discharge is an Ovule_Penetration marked by the rupture of the pollen tube apex within the penetrated synergid releasing two sperm cells into the embryo sac cytoplasm.",
  "alternative_term": "sperm cell release | tube rupture | double fertilization event | gamete fusion completion |+ Pollenschlauch-Entladung | Spermazell-Freisetzung | Schlauchruptur | Doppelbefruchtungsereignis",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows pollen tube discharge during late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with tube apex rupturing in synergid releasing two sperm cells 26-38 hours post-pollination, double fertilization producing diploid zygotes initiating embryo development and triploid endosperm nuclei supporting seed growth, 1-3 seeds forming per berry, rapid berry expansion to 14-20 mm within 2 weeks from auxin production, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar achieving 60-70% fertilization success and fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Pollen_Tube_Discharge is second and final aspect of Ovule_Penetration, distinguished by sperm release and fusion events completing fertilization. ||Represents culminating reproductive moment creating zygote and endosperm. ||Occurs 24-48 hours post-pollination. ||Involves double fertilization producing 2n embryo and 3n endosperm. ||Initiates seed and berry development through auxin production. ||Success rate 50-70% in favorable conditions determining fruit set. ||Completes entire Flowering hierarchical sequence from Inflorescence_Development through Fertilization. ||Marks definitive transition to Berry_Development phase. ||Final reproductive process. || This critical discharge and fusion event occurs during ovule penetration in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically occurring 24-48 hours after initial pollination as fertilization culminates, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization completion stages. ||Discharge mechanism involves tube apex positioned in penetrated synergid cell undergoing wall weakening and rupture, explosive or gradual release of tube contents including two sperm cells, vegetative nucleus, and cytoplasm into embryo sac, sperm cell liberation enabling migration to fusion targets, and tube structural failure completing reproductive function. ||Tube apex rupture shows wall breakdown at tip through localized enzymatic degradation or mechanical failure, turgor pressure driving explosive discharge or controlled release depending on wall properties and pressure magnitude, and sudden breach creating opening for content expulsion. ||Discharge timing shows rupture typically occurring within minutes to hours of synergid penetration, 24-48 hours after initial pollination representing culmination of reproductive timeline, and precise timing possibly influenced by tube-synergid interactions triggering discharge though mechanisms poorly understood. ||Sperm cell release shows two genetically identical haploid cells expelling from ruptured tube into embryo sac cytoplasm, cells maintaining structural integrity during discharge, non-motile cells requiring passive transport or drift to fusion targets, and rapid positioning within embryo sac given close proximity to egg and central cell. ||Vegetative nucleus discharge shows degrading or non-functional nucleus expelling with sperm cells, nucleus having completed guidance role during tube growth, and nucleus playing no further reproductive role post-discharge. ||Tube cytoplasm discharge releases remaining contents into embryo sac including organelles, remaining nutrients, and cellular components, discharged material potentially providing nutritive support or signals though specific roles unknown, and overall tube depletion completing reproductive contribution. ||Post-discharge tube fate shows collapsed empty tube structure remaining in micropyle and style, degeneration proceeding over subsequent days to weeks, and non-functional tube representing completed reproductive pathway. ||Sperm cell fate after discharge shows one sperm cell migrating to egg cell enabling zygote formation, other sperm cell approaching central cell enabling endosperm formation, and differentiation determining which sperm fuses with which target possibly stochastic or regulated by unknown mechanisms. ||Sperm-egg fusion mechanism shows sperm cell contacting egg cell plasma membrane at micropylar pole, membrane fusion integrating sperm into egg cytoplasm through lipid bilayer merger, sperm nucleus migrating through egg cytoplasm toward egg nucleus, nuclear envelope breakdown and fusion combining haploid sperm and egg nuclei, formation of diploid 2n zygote nucleus containing 50% paternal and 50% maternal genetic contribution, and zygote activation transitioning from developmental arrest to active division. ||Egg activation following fusion shows calcium signaling waves triggering developmental program, metabolic activation initiating biosynthesis and cell division preparation, cortical reaction preventing polyspermy through membrane modifications blocking additional sperm, and commitment to embryo development with first division typically within 24-48 hours. ||Sperm-central cell fusion shows second sperm contacting large central cell in embryo sac center, membrane fusion integrating sperm into central cell cytoplasm, sperm nucleus fusing with central cell nucleus formed from polar nuclei fusion or fusing separately with two polar nuclei, formation of triploid 3n endosperm nucleus with 2 per 1 maternal per paternal genome ratio, and endosperm development initiating providing nutritive tissue for embryo. ||Endosperm activation shows free nuclear division initiating rapidly producing multinucleate coenocyte, cellularization phase forming cellular tissue, and endosperm growth providing nutritive support enabling embryo development during seed maturation. ||Double fertilization coordination shows two fusion events occurring synchronously or within hours ensuring coordinated embryo and endosperm development, temporal coordination critical for normal seed development, and synchronization possibly regulated through common signals or developmental programs. ||Zygote first division shows initial cell division typically 24-48 hours post-fertilization, asymmetric division producing small terminal cell developing into embryo proper and large basal cell forming suspensor, and progressive divisions establishing embryo structure during seed development. ||Fertilization completion confirmation shows successful zygote and endosperm formation indicating reproductive success, ovule development into seed with integuments forming seed coat, ovary expansion initiating berry development, and visible berry growth providing evidence of fertilization 1-2 weeks post-pollination. ||Berry development initiation shows auxin production from developing seeds preventing flower abscission, hormone signaling triggering ovary wall growth creating berry flesh, cell division intensity maximizing during early post-fertilization period with 10-15 hour cycle times, rapid berry expansion from 4-8 mm pre-fertilization to 15-25 mm within 2-3 weeks, and resource allocation shifting dramatically with developing berries consuming 40-60% total photosynthate. ||Seed development shows integument layers developing into seed coat, embryo growing within endosperm consuming nutritive reserves, seed maturation coordinating with berry ripening over 90-120 days, and final seed number typically 1-3 per berry depending on fertilization success in multiple ovules. ||Failed discharge outcomes include tube structural failure before synergid penetration preventing discharge, sperm cell damage during discharge compromising viability, failed sperm-egg or sperm-central cell fusion preventing zygote or endosperm formation, abnormal embryo sac preventing normal gamete reception, and overall fertilization failure causing flower abortion and coulure poor fruit set. ||Environmental effects on discharge and fusion include temperature critically affecting membrane fusion and developmental activation with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient processes, cool conditions 15-20°C potentially impairing fusion or subsequent development, excessive heat above 33°C causing reproductive dysfunction, and critical temperature sensitivity during 24-48 hour fertilization window. ||Polyspermy prevention shows single tube reception per ovule through unknown blocking mechanisms, rapid ovule signaling changes after fertilization preventing additional tubes, and protection ensuring normal diploid embryo and triploid endosperm avoiding abnormal polyploid development. ||Multiple ovule fertilization shows 2-4 ovules per flower potentially receiving tubes, typical 1-3 successful fertilizations creating 1-3 seeds per berry, and seed number affecting berry size with more seeds generally producing larger berries through greater auxin production. ||The process represents second and final aspect of ovule penetration completing fertilization, following egg cell approach. ||Duration represents culminating moments with discharge occurring rapidly and fusion completing within hours. ||Cultivar variation in tube discharge may include discharge efficiency, fusion success rates, and seed number outcomes affecting berry characteristics. ||Regional timing shows pollen tube discharge during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, completing 24-48 hours after pollination. ||Viticultural significance includes representing culminating reproductive event determining seed and berry formation, requiring successful completion of entire pollination-germination-growth-penetration sequence, demonstrating extreme environmental sensitivity during fusion period, establishing discharge and fusion success as direct determinants of fruit set and yield, and marking definitive transition from flowering reproductive phase to berry development phase. ||Research applications include analyzing discharge mechanisms and triggers, investigating double fertilization coordination and sperm fate determination, evaluating fusion mechanisms and gamete recognition, quantifying fertilization success rates and seed number outcomes, assessing fertilization effects on berry development and quality, and developing strategies for improving fruit set through enhanced fertilization efficiency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 393-400 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-305 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Double_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "A Double_Fertilization is a Fertilization consisting of two sperm-gamete fusion events: sperm-egg fusion producing the diploid zygote, and sperm-central cell fusion producing the triploid endosperm nucleus.",
  "alternative_term": "dual fertilization | two-sperm fusion | angiosperm fertilization | coordinated gamete fusion |+ Doppelbefruchtung | duale Fertilisation | Zwei-Spermien-Fusion | Angiospermen-Befruchtung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows double fertilization during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with two sperm cells from discharged tube fusing independently within 2-6 hours post-discharge occurring 26-40 hours post-pollination, one sperm creating diploid 2n zygote with egg and other creating triploid 3n endosperm nucleus with central cell, coordinated embryo and endosperm development initiating seed formation, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar achieving 52-66% double fertilization success producing 1-3 seeds per berry",
  "editor_note": "Double_Fertilization represents characteristic angiosperm reproductive process distinguishing flowering plants. ||Subdivided into Egg_Fertilization producing diploid zygote and Central_Cell_Fertilization producing triploid endosperm. ||Duration hours post-discharge occurring 24-48h post-pollination. ||Involves coordinated dual fusion events. ||Creates both embryo and nutritive tissue lineages. ||Critical temperature sensitivity. ||Success rate 50-70% determining seed formation. ||Evolutionary synapomorphy of angiosperms. ||Enables coordinated embryo-endosperm development. ||Final reproductive process completing Flowering sequence. || This distinctive dual fusion process occurs during fertilization in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically completing within hours following tube discharge approximately 24-48 hours after initial pollination, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization completion stages. ||Double fertilization mechanism involves coordinated processes including simultaneous or near-simultaneous release of two sperm cells from discharged pollen tube, independent sperm cell migration to respective fusion targets with one approaching egg and other approaching central cell, membrane fusion events integrating sperm cells into target cell cytoplasm, nuclear fusion combining sperm nuclei with egg nucleus forming 2n zygote and with central cell nucleus or polar nuclei forming 3n endosperm nucleus, and coordinated activation of embryo and endosperm development establishing viable seed. ||Evolutionary significance shows double fertilization as synapomorphy defining angiosperms distinguishing from gymnosperms having single fertilization, adaptive advantage through coordinated embryo-endosperm development with endosperm nutritive support matched to embryo requirements, and reproductive efficiency through utilizing both sperm cells from single pollen tube maximizing reproductive output. ||Two sperm cells characteristics show genetically identical haploid cells derived from generative cell mitosis during pollen development or tube growth, cells containing minimal cytoplasm optimized for fusion, non-motile cells requiring passive transport after discharge, and functionally equivalent cells though ultimately fusing with different targets in embryo sac. ||Sperm delivery timing shows two cells releasing simultaneously from ruptured tube apex into synergid and embryo sac cytoplasm, immediate availability for migration to fusion targets given close proximity within embryo sac, and rapid positioning within minutes to hours enabling prompt fusion events. ||Egg fertilization as first fusion event shows one sperm cell migrating short distance 20-100 micrometers from discharge site to egg cell at micropylar pole, sperm-egg membrane fusion integrating sperm into egg cytoplasm, nuclear fusion combining haploid sperm nucleus with haploid egg nucleus, formation of diploid 2n zygote nucleus containing equal genetic contributions from maternal and paternal parents, and zygote activation initiating embryo developmental program. ||Central cell fertilization as second fusion event shows other sperm cell approaching large central cell occupying majority of embryo sac volume, sperm fusion with central cell containing fused diploid nucleus from two polar nuclei or fusing separately with individual polar nuclei, formation of triploid 3n endosperm nucleus with 2 per 1 maternal per paternal genome ratio reflecting two maternal polar nuclei and one paternal sperm nucleus, and endosperm activation initiating nutritive tissue development supporting embryo growth. ||Fusion timing coordination shows two events typically occurring synchronously or within hours of each other, coordinated timing ensuring embryo and endosperm development initiate together, temporal synchronization critical for normal seed development with embryo requiring endosperm nutritive support from earliest stages, and coordination possibly regulated through common calcium signaling or developmental triggers. ||Membrane fusion mechanisms show sperm and target cell plasma membranes coming into close contact, lipid bilayer reorganization enabling membrane merger, fusion pore formation creating cytoplasmic continuity, and membrane proteins possibly mediating fusion specificity and efficiency though molecular details in grapevine poorly characterized. ||Nuclear fusion dynamics show sperm nucleus migrating through target cell cytoplasm toward female nucleus, nuclear envelope breakdown in both gamete nuclei, chromatin mixing and nuclear membrane reformation around combined genetic material, and establishment of diploid or triploid nucleus with integrated parental genomes. ||Calcium signaling in fertilization shows calcium waves propagating through egg cytoplasm following sperm fusion, localized calcium elevations triggering developmental activation, calcium-dependent processes regulating membrane fusion and nuclear migration, and calcium as key second messenger coordinating fertilization events though specific roles incompletely understood. ||Egg activation following fertilization shows cortical reaction preventing polyspermy through membrane modifications blocking additional sperm, metabolic activation with respiratory rate increasing and biosynthesis initiating, cell cycle reentry with transition from meiotic arrest to mitotic division, and developmental commitment to embryogenesis with first division within 24-48 hours. ||Endosperm activation shows free nuclear division initiating rapidly producing multinucleate coenocyte within hours to days, absence of cell wall formation during initial divisions creating syncytial tissue, eventual cellularization forming cellular endosperm, and nutritive function providing resources supporting embryo growth throughout seed development. ||Genomic imbalance in endosperm shows 2 per 1 maternal per paternal ratio creating unique genomic composition, imbalance affecting gene expression patterns with maternal genome overrepresentation, and imprinting phenomena possibly influencing endosperm development and function though poorly characterized in grapevine. ||Polyspermy prevention shows mechanisms ensuring single sperm fusion per target with egg showing rapid cortical reaction blocking additional sperm, central cell possibly showing similar prevention though mechanisms less characterized, and ovule-level prevention through single tube reception per ovule eliminating multiple sperm delivery. ||Fertilization success indicators include formation of functional zygote capable of embryo development, viable endosperm providing nutritive support, coordinated development of both products ensuring seed formation, and subsequent ovary expansion confirming successful fertilization through berry growth initiation. ||Failed double fertilization scenarios include single fertilization with either egg or central cell fusion succeeding but not both causing developmental abortion, failed membrane fusion preventing nuclear combination despite sperm delivery, abnormal nuclear fusion producing aneuploid or polyploid nuclei causing developmental failure, or complete fertilization failure with neither fusion occurring causing flower abortion. ||Environmental effects on double fertilization include temperature critically affecting membrane fusion dynamics and developmental activation with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient processes, calcium availability affecting signaling cascades regulating fusion and activation, and overall favorable conditions during brief fertilization window critical for success. ||Temperature sensitivity shows optimal conditions supporting rapid efficient fusion and activation within 1-4 hours post-discharge, cool conditions potentially delaying or impairing fusion processes reducing success rate, excessive heat above 33°C causing membrane dysfunction or signaling disruption preventing normal fusion, and critical temperature dependence during fertilization period affecting reproductive outcomes. ||Developmental coordination following double fertilization shows synchronized embryo and endosperm development with coordinated cell division timing, integrated signaling between embryo and endosperm coordinating growth, and matched developmental rates ensuring appropriate nutritive support throughout embryogenesis. ||Seed development outcomes show successful double fertilization leading to viable seed formation with embryo developing into seedling and endosperm consumed during maturation, seed containing genetic contributions from both parents through zygote, and functional propagule enabling sexual reproduction and genetic recombination. ||Berry development initiation following successful double fertilization shows auxin production from developing seeds preventing flower abscission, hormone signaling triggering ovary wall expansion creating berry flesh, and visible berry growth within 1-2 weeks providing evidence of fertilization success. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects occurring in parallel with egg fertilization creating embryo lineage and central cell fertilization creating endosperm support tissue. ||Duration represents brief period with fusion events completing within hours of sperm discharge approximately 24-48 hours post-pollination. ||Cultivar variation in double fertilization may include fusion efficiency affecting success rates, developmental coordination affecting seed viability, and endosperm-embryo balance affecting seed and berry characteristics. ||Regional timing shows double fertilization during mid-late June in warm climates, late June in temperate regions, and late June-early July in cool areas, completing 24-48 hours after pollination as culminating reproductive events. ||Viticultural significance includes representing unique angiosperm reproductive mechanism enabling successful seed formation, requiring coordinated dual fusion events for viable seed development, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity during fusion period, establishing double fertilization success as direct determinant of seed number and berry development, and marking definitive completion of sexual reproductive sequence initiating developmental phase. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of membrane and nuclear fusion, investigating coordination between egg and central cell fertilization events, evaluating calcium signaling and other regulatory pathways, quantifying fusion success rates and seed formation outcomes, assessing genomic imbalance effects on endosperm function, and developing strategies for improving fertilization efficiency and fruit set.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009567 ## double fertilization forming a zygote and endosperm | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 393-398 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-302 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Egg_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "An Egg_Fertilization is a Double_Fertilization comprising the fusion of one sperm nucleus with the egg nucleus at the micropylar pole producing the diploid 2n zygote nucleus.",
  "alternative_term": "sperm-egg fusion | zygote formation | embryo fertilization | egg cell fusion |+ Eizell-Befruchtung | Spermium-Eizell-Fusion | Zygoten-Bildung | Embryo-Fertilisation",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows egg fertilization during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with sperm cell fusing with egg cell within 1-3 hours post-discharge occurring 28-42 hours post-pollination, membrane fusion and nuclear combination producing diploid 2n=38 zygote, calcium signaling activating developmental program, under cool maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar with 64-76% egg fertilization success initiating embryo development",
  "editor_note": "Egg_Fertilization is first component of Double_Fertilization, distinguished by zygote-forming fusion creating embryo lineage. ||Represents sperm-egg fusion combining haploid gametes producing diploid 2n nucleus. ||Duration 1-4 hours from sperm release to activation. ||Involves membrane fusion, nuclear fusion, calcium signaling, egg activation. ||Establishes embryo developmental program. ||Success rate 50-70% in favorable conditions. ||Parallel process with Central_Cell_Fertilization. ||Essential for seed formation. ||Creates genetic diversity through recombination. || This critical embryo-forming fusion occurs during double fertilization in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically completing within 1-4 hours following sperm release approximately 24-48 hours after initial pollination, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization stages. ||Fertilization mechanism involves sperm cell migration from tube discharge site in penetrated synergid to adjacent egg cell positioned at micropylar pole, sperm-egg membrane fusion creating cytoplasmic continuity, sperm nucleus entry into egg cytoplasm and migration toward egg nucleus, nuclear envelope breakdown in both gamete nuclei, chromatin mixing and nuclear fusion combining genetic material, diploid 2n zygote nucleus formation containing complete chromosome sets from both parents, and egg activation triggering developmental transition from arrest to active embryogenesis. ||Sperm cell approach to egg shows short-distance migration typically 20-100 micrometers from synergid discharge site, passive drift or directed movement through embryo sac cytoplasm, and rapid arrival within minutes to hours given close proximity facilitating efficient fertilization. ||Egg cell structure at fertilization includes large haploid nucleus containing maternal genetic contribution, abundant cytoplasm with organelles and stored reserves providing resources for early embryo development, plasma membrane receptive to sperm fusion showing molecular recognition capacity, and developmental arrest in metaphase of second meiotic division awaiting fertilization activation. ||Sperm-egg recognition shows surface molecule interactions mediating species-specific recognition, molecular complementarity between sperm coat proteins and egg membrane receptors, compatibility assessment though self-compatibility in grapevine eliminates rejection mechanisms, and recognition signals preparing for membrane fusion. ||Membrane fusion initiation shows sperm cell contacting egg plasma membrane, lipid bilayer reorganization at contact site enabling membrane merger, fusion pore formation creating small cytoplasmic bridge, and pore expansion integrating sperm completely into egg cytoplasm. ||Fusion pore dynamics show initial small opening 20-50 nanometers diameter, progressive expansion through membrane flow and cytoskeletal forces, complete membrane integration within seconds to minutes, and cytoplasmic continuity establishing allowing sperm nucleus entry. ||Sperm nucleus entry shows nucleus entering egg cytoplasm through fusion site, minimal sperm cytoplasm transferred with nucleus entering leaving most paternal cytoplasm and organelles excluded, and sperm nucleus integrity maintained during entry enabling subsequent nuclear fusion. ||Sperm nucleus migration shows movement through egg cytoplasm toward centrally positioned egg nucleus, migration possibly driven by cytoskeletal forces and cytoplasmic streaming, travel distance typically 10-50 micrometers depending on egg size, and arrival at egg nucleus within minutes to hour following membrane fusion. ||Nuclear fusion process shows sperm and egg nuclei coming into close contact, nuclear envelope breakdown in both nuclei releasing chromatin into common cytoplasmic space, chromatin mixing and condensation combining maternal and paternal chromosomes, nuclear envelope reformation around combined genetic material, and diploid 2n nucleus formation containing complete haploid chromosome sets from both parents. ||Diploid zygote nucleus characteristics show 2n chromosome number typically 38 chromosomes in Vitis vinifera combining 19 maternal and 19 paternal chromosomes, equal genetic contribution from both parents enabling Mendelian inheritance, and functional diploid nucleus capable of directing embryo development. ||Genetic recombination through fertilization shows meiotic recombination during gamete formation creating genetic variation, random fertilization combining different parental gametes, and offspring genetic diversity supporting evolutionary adaptation and breeding applications. ||Egg activation following fusion shows calcium signaling waves propagating through cytoplasm triggered by sperm entry, calcium-dependent processes activating developmental programs, cortical granule exocytosis modifying membrane preventing polyspermy, metabolic activation with respiratory rate increasing 2-3 fold, protein synthesis initiation producing developmental regulators, and cell cycle reentry transitioning from meiotic arrest to mitotic division. ||Calcium signaling dynamics show initial localized elevation at sperm entry point, propagating waves spreading throughout egg cytoplasm at 5-20 micrometers per second, multiple calcium transients possibly occurring over minutes to hours, and calcium-dependent kinases activating downstream signaling cascades triggering development. ||Cortical reaction shows cortical granules beneath egg plasma membrane undergoing exocytosis releasing contents modifying membrane properties, block to polyspermy preventing additional sperm fusion, and rapid reaction within seconds to minutes of first sperm entry protecting against abnormal polyploid development. ||Metabolic activation shows transition from quiescent to active state with oxygen consumption increasing substantially, ATP production intensifying supporting biosynthesis and division, protein synthesis initiating from maternal mRNAs accumulated during oogenesis, and metabolic reorientation preparing for embryo development. ||Cell cycle activation shows exit from meiotic metaphase II arrest completing meiosis, second polar body extrusion removing excess chromosomes, transition to first mitotic division preparing zygote cleavage, and S-phase entry initiating DNA replication for division. ||Zygote polarity establishment shows asymmetric cytoplasmic organization following fertilization, molecular gradients establishing developmental axes, and polarity determining embryo proper versus suspensor fate in first division. ||Environmental effects on egg fertilization include temperature affecting membrane fusion kinetics and activation processes with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient fertilization within 1-2 hours, calcium availability affecting signaling cascades critical for activation, and overall favorable conditions essential during brief fertilization window. ||Temperature sensitivity shows warm conditions promoting rapid fusion and activation, cool conditions delaying processes potentially reducing success, excessive heat impairing membrane dynamics or signaling, and critical temperature dependence affecting fertilization outcomes. ||Failed egg fertilization causes include sperm cell damage preventing membrane fusion, abnormal egg preventing fusion or activation, failed nuclear fusion preventing zygote formation, environmental stress disrupting fusion or activation processes, or genetic incompatibility though rare in self-compatible grapevine. ||Egg fertilization success rate shows 50-70% eggs successfully fertilizing in favorable conditions given successful tube discharge, cumulative effect of all reproductive processes determining final success, and success directly determining embryo formation potential and seed development. ||The process represents first component of double fertilization creating embryo lineage, occurring in parallel with central cell fertilization. ||Duration typically 1-4 hours from sperm release to completed fusion and activation. ||Cultivar variation in egg fertilization may include fusion efficiency, activation dynamics, and developmental competence affecting embryo viability. ||Regional timing shows egg fertilization during mid-late June across all climates within hours of tube discharge 24-48 hours post-pollination. ||Viticultural significance includes representing embryo-forming fusion event essential for seed development, requiring successful sperm-egg fusion and activation, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity, establishing fertilization success as determinant of embryo formation and seed viability, and initiating embryo developmental lineage. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of sperm-egg recognition and fusion, investigating calcium signaling and activation processes, evaluating factors affecting fusion success and zygote viability, quantifying fertilization timing and efficiency, and assessing egg fertilization as determinant of seed formation outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0061936 ## fusion of sperm to egg plasma membrane involved in double fertilization forming a zygote and endosperm | 0.9" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 393-396 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 298-300 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Central_Cell_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "A Central_Cell_Fertilization is a Double_Fertilization comprising the fusion of one sperm nucleus with the central cell nucleus producing the triploid 3n endosperm nucleus with a 2:1 maternal-to-paternal genome ratio.",
  "alternative_term": "endosperm fertilization | sperm-central cell fusion | triploid nucleus formation | polar nuclei fusion |+ Zentralzell-Befruchtung | Endosperm-Fertilisation | Spermium-Zentralzell-Fusion | triploide Kernbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows central cell fertilization during mid-late June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-69, with second sperm cell fusing with central cell containing fused polar nuclei within 1-4 hours post-discharge occurring 28-42 hours post-pollination, nuclear fusion producing triploid 3n=57 endosperm nucleus with 2 per 1 maternal per paternal ratio, free nuclear division initiating rapidly producing multinucleate syncytium, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar with 54-68% central cell fertilization success coordinated with egg fertilization enabling seed formation",
  "editor_note": "Central_Cell_Fertilization is second component of Double_Fertilization, distinguished by endosperm-forming fusion creating nutritive tissue lineage. ||Represents sperm fusion with central cell or polar nuclei producing triploid 3n nucleus. ||Duration 1-4 hours parallel to Egg_Fertilization. ||Creates 2 per 1 maternal per paternal genomic ratio. ||Initiates free nuclear division and endosperm development. ||Essential for embryo nutritive support. ||Success rate 50-70% coordinated with egg fertilization. ||Both fertilizations required for viable seed. ||Genomic imbalance affects endosperm function. || This critical endosperm-forming fusion occurs during double fertilization in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, typically completing within 1-4 hours following sperm release approximately 24-48 hours after initial pollination, corresponding to BBCH 65-69 fertilization stages. ||Fertilization mechanism involves second sperm cell migration from tube discharge site toward large central cell, sperm-central cell membrane fusion creating cytoplasmic continuity, sperm nucleus entry and migration toward central cell nucleus or polar nuclei, nuclear fusion combining sperm nucleus with fused diploid central cell nucleus or separate fusion with two haploid polar nuclei, triploid 3n endosperm nucleus formation containing two maternal and one paternal genome copies, and central cell activation triggering endosperm developmental program. ||Central cell structure at fertilization shows large cell occupying majority 60-80% of embryo sac volume, central cell nucleus formed from two polar nuclei fusion creating diploid 2n nucleus or polar nuclei remaining separate until sperm fusion, abundant cytoplasm providing resources for endosperm development, and plasma membrane receptive to sperm fusion. ||Polar nuclei characteristics show two haploid nuclei derived from megagametophyte development through mitotic divisions, nuclei migrating from chalazal and micropylar poles toward embryo sac center, fusion occurring before or during fertilization creating diploid central cell nucleus, and nuclei positioned centrally or remaining separated until sperm arrival. ||Sperm cell approach to central cell shows migration through embryo sac cytoplasm from synergid discharge site, longer travel distance 50-200 micrometers compared to egg fertilization reflecting central cell position, passive drift or directed movement reaching central cell, and arrival typically concurrent with or shortly following egg fertilization enabling coordinated double fertilization. ||Sperm-central cell fusion shows membrane contact and fusion similar to egg fertilization, cytoplasmic integration enabling sperm nucleus entry, and fusion possibly mediated by similar molecular recognition mechanisms as egg fertilization though poorly characterized. ||Nuclear fusion pattern shows two possible scenarios with sperm fusing with pre-fused diploid 2n central cell nucleus creating triploid 3n endosperm nucleus, or sperm fusing sequentially or simultaneously with two separate haploid 1n polar nuclei creating 3n nucleus, and fusion pattern variation possibly species-specific or individual-specific though outcome identical. ||Triploid endosperm nucleus formation shows combination of haploid sperm nucleus containing paternal genetic material with diploid central cell nucleus or two haploid polar nuclei containing maternal genetic material, resulting 3n nucleus with 38 chromosomes in grapevine comprising 19 paternal and 38 maternal chromosomes creating 2 per 1 maternal per paternal genomic ratio, and genomic imbalance affecting endosperm development and gene expression patterns. ||Genomic imbalance significance shows 2 per 1 ratio creating unique genomic composition with maternal genome overrepresentation, imbalance affecting gene dosage and expression particularly for imprinted genes, maternal genome dominance potentially influencing endosperm developmental characteristics and nutritive function, and evolutionary significance of endosperm genomic composition affecting seed development strategies. ||Genomic imprinting in endosperm shows parent-of-origin-specific gene expression with some genes expressed preferentially from maternal genomes and others from paternal genome, imprinting affecting endosperm growth and resource allocation, and imprinting phenomena important for reproductive isolation and hybrid seed development though poorly characterized in grapevine. ||Central cell activation following fusion shows developmental transition from quiescent to active proliferative state, metabolic activation with increased respiration and biosynthesis, and initiation of free nuclear division producing multinucleate endosperm. ||Free nuclear division in endosperm shows rapid mitotic divisions producing multiple nuclei without cell wall formation, syncytial tissue development with nuclei sharing common cytoplasm, division rate often exceeding embryo division creating abundant nuclei, typical progression to 32-128 nuclei before cellularization in some systems though timing variable, and free nuclear phase creating nutritive tissue supporting early embryo development. ||Cellularization process shows eventual cell wall formation partitioning endosperm into cellular tissue, cellularization timing varying among species occurring after free nuclear phase, cellular endosperm providing structured nutritive tissue, and endosperm cells accumulating storage reserves including proteins, lipids, and carbohydrates. ||Endosperm function shows nutritive role providing resources supporting embryo development throughout seed maturation, tissue serving as intermediary transferring maternal resources from integuments to developing embryo, and endosperm consumption during embryo growth reducing to thin layer in mature grapevine seed. ||Endosperm-embryo coordination shows developmental synchronization between tissues with coordinated cell division and growth rates, signaling between tissues regulating resource allocation and development, and balanced development ensuring adequate endosperm support throughout embryogenesis. ||Calcium signaling in central cell fertilization possibly shows activation mechanisms similar to egg with calcium transients triggering developmental programs, though central cell calcium dynamics less well characterized than egg, and calcium-dependent processes regulating endosperm development initiation. ||Environmental effects on central cell fertilization include temperature affecting fusion dynamics and activation with optimal 22-28°C supporting efficient processes, similar sensitivity to egg fertilization with coordinated temperature requirements, and overall favorable conditions essential for successful endosperm formation. ||Temperature sensitivity shows warm conditions promoting rapid fusion and activation, cool conditions potentially delaying endosperm formation, excessive heat impairing processes, and temperature effects coordinated with egg fertilization requirements. ||Failed central cell fertilization causes include sperm cell dysfunction preventing fusion, abnormal central cell or polar nuclei preventing fusion, failed nuclear fusion preventing endosperm formation, or environmental stress disrupting processes, and failure causing seed abortion even if egg fertilization succeeds due to lack of embryo nutritive support. ||Central cell fertilization success rate shows similar 50-70% success as egg fertilization in favorable conditions, coordinated success of both fertilizations required for viable seed development, and dual fertilization requirement emphasizing critical nature of double fertilization for seed formation. ||The process represents second component of double fertilization creating endosperm lineage, occurring in parallel with egg fertilization. ||Duration typically 1-4 hours from sperm release to completed fusion similar to egg fertilization. ||Cultivar variation may include fusion efficiency, endosperm development characteristics, and genomic imbalance effects on seed traits. ||Regional timing shows central cell fertilization during mid-late June across all climates within hours of tube discharge 24-48 hours post-pollination coordinated with egg fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing endosperm-forming fusion essential for seed development, creating nutritive tissue supporting embryo growth, demonstrating coordinated dual fertilization requirement, establishing central cell fertilization success as determinant of seed viability, and contributing to seed size and berry development through endosperm function. ||Research applications include analyzing molecular mechanisms of central cell fusion and activation, investigating endosperm development and free nuclear division, evaluating genomic imbalance effects on endosperm characteristics, quantifying coordination between egg and central cell fertilization, and assessing endosperm formation as determinant of seed and berry development outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 396-398 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 300-302"
},

  "Zygote_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Zygote_Formation is an Egg_Fertilization characterized by the establishment of the diploid unicellular embryo through sperm-egg nuclear fusion and egg activation preceding the first division.",
  "alternative_term": "zygote development | unicellular embryo | fertilized egg development | diploid cell formation |+ Zygoten-Formation | Zygoten-Entwicklung | einzelliger Embryo | befruchtete Eizell-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows zygote formation during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69, with diploid zygote developing over 30-60 hours post-fertilization, developmental polarity establishing, first mitotic division occurring 36-52 hours post-fertilization producing two-cell embryo, under warm climate conditions of 24-29°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar completing fertilization 28-42 hours post-pollination and initiating embryogenesis 60-90 hours post-pollination",
  "editor_note": "Zygote_Formation represents diploid unicellular embryo stage following Egg_Fertilization. ||Subdivided into Zygote_Development_Initiation establishing activated diploid cell and Embryo_Genesis_Start marking first division. ||Duration 24-72 hours from fertilization to first cleavage. ||Involves developmental activation, polarity establishment, cell cycle reentry. ||Temperature strongly affects timing. ||First division marks transition to multicellular embryo. ||Essential stage for seed development. ||Determines embryo developmental potential. || This critical embryo initiation phase occurs during late fertilization in mid-late June in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over hours to days following egg fertilization approximately 24-72 hours after initial pollination, corresponding to BBCH 69 fertilization completion stages transitioning to early berry development. ||Formation process involves diploid zygote nucleus establishment through sperm-egg nuclear fusion, zygote activation triggered by calcium signaling and metabolic changes, developmental polarity establishment determining future embryo organization, cell cycle reentry preparing for first mitotic division, and zygote growth and preparation for cleavage creating two-cell embryo initiating embryogenesis. ||Zygote characteristics show single diploid cell containing complete genetic information from both parents, 2n=38 chromosomes in Vitis vinifera representing fusion of two 1n=19 gametes, large cell typically 40-80 micrometers diameter containing abundant cytoplasm and organelles, developmental totipotency with capacity to generate entire plant, and position within embryo sac at micropylar pole adjacent to penetrated synergid. ||Diploid nucleus structure shows nuclear envelope surrounding combined maternal and paternal chromatin, interphase chromatin organization with chromosomes decondensed, active transcription initiating zygotic gene expression, and nucleus containing complete genomic complement enabling embryo development. ||Cytoplasmic organization shows abundant ribosomes for protein synthesis, mitochondria providing energy for metabolism and division, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi apparatus supporting secretory functions, stored reserves including lipids and proteins providing resources for early development, and maternally inherited organelles including mitochondria and plastids transmitting through egg. ||Zygote activation continuation shows sustained calcium signaling maintaining active state, metabolic activation with respiration and biosynthesis intensifying, protein synthesis from maternal mRNAs accumulated during oogenesis, transition to zygotic genome activation expressing embryo developmental genes, and cell cycle progression preparing for division. ||Developmental polarity establishment shows asymmetric cytoplasmic organization creating apical-basal axis, differential distribution of developmental regulators establishing positional information, molecular gradients determining cell fate in first division, and polarity determining embryo proper versus suspensor formation in subsequent cleavage. ||Apical-basal axis determination shows polarity established during or shortly after fertilization, axis orientation typically with apical pole toward micropyle and basal pole toward chalaza, and axis determining embryo structural organization through subsequent development. ||Cell fate determinants show asymmetric distribution of transcription factors and signaling molecules, localized mRNAs and proteins creating developmental gradients, and molecular asymmetry determining whether daughter cells develop into embryo proper or suspensor in first division. ||Cell cycle reentry shows exit from meiotic metaphase II arrest completing egg meiosis, G1 phase entry following fertilization, S phase initiation with DNA replication preparing for division, and progression through cell cycle toward first mitotic division typically 24-48 hours post-fertilization. ||DNA replication shows chromosome duplication during S phase, genome doubling from 2n to 4n DNA content preparing for mitosis, replication fork progression through entire genome, and completion establishing readiness for chromosome segregation in division. ||Mitotic preparation shows chromatin condensation into visible chromosomes, nuclear envelope breakdown releasing chromosomes into cytoplasm, spindle formation with microtubule arrays establishing chromosome segregation machinery, and progression toward metaphase alignment and anaphase separation. ||First division timing shows variable timing among species and individuals with typical first cleavage 24-48 hours post-fertilization in favorable conditions, temperature-dependent timing with warm conditions accelerating and cool conditions delaying, and division establishing two-cell embryo marking definitive embryogenesis initiation. ||Zygote growth before division shows cell enlargement through water uptake and biosynthesis, volume increase up to 1.5-2 fold before cleavage, and resource accumulation supporting subsequent divisions. ||Environmental effects on zygote formation include temperature critically affecting developmental rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting normal progression, nutrient availability from endosperm supporting growth and metabolism, appropriate hydration maintaining cellular function, and overall favorable conditions during first days post-fertilization critical for normal embryo initiation. ||Temperature sensitivity shows warm conditions promoting rapid development with first division within 24-36 hours, cool conditions substantially delaying division to 48-72 hours or more, excessive heat potentially disrupting development, and temperature as major factor affecting embryogenesis timing. ||Osmotic environment shows surrounding endosperm providing appropriate osmotic conditions, proper balance essential for zygote hydration and growth, and osmotic stress potentially disrupting development. ||Zygote developmental competence shows inherent capacity to develop into mature embryo, competence depending on genetic integrity and proper fertilization, developmental abnormalities from chromosomal aberrations or genetic defects causing embryo abortion, and majority of normal zygotes successfully initiating embryogenesis under favorable conditions. ||Failed zygote formation causes include abnormal fertilization producing aneuploid or polyploid zygotes with developmental incompetence, genetic defects preventing normal development, inadequate endosperm support failing to provide necessary resources, environmental stress during critical formation period disrupting development, or developmental arrest from unknown causes. ||Zygote to embryo transition shows first division as definitive transition from unicellular zygote to multicellular embryo, progressive cell divisions elaborating embryo structure, and continuing development through globular, heart, torpedo, and mature embryo stages over subsequent weeks. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects progressing from zygote development initiation establishing diploid cell and activation, through embryo genesis start marking first division and embryogenesis. ||Duration typically spans 24-72 hours from fertilization to first division depending on conditions. ||Cultivar variation in zygote formation may include division timing, developmental rate, and embryo developmental characteristics. ||Regional timing shows zygote formation during late June-early July across all climates 1-3 days following fertilization as embryo development initiates. ||Viticultural significance includes representing unicellular embryo stage initiating seed development, requiring successful fertilization and activation, demonstrating environmental sensitivity affecting developmental timing, establishing zygote formation as determinant of embryo and seed viability, and marking transition from fertilization to embryogenesis phase. ||Research applications include analyzing zygote activation mechanisms and developmental programs, investigating polarity establishment and cell fate determination, evaluating environmental effects on zygote development and division timing, quantifying zygote to embryo transition dynamics, and assessing zygote formation as determinant of seed development outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 398-402 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 302-305"
},

  "Zygote_Development_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Zygote_Development_Initiation is a Zygote_Formation involving metabolic activation, establishment of developmental polarity, and onset of zygotic gene expression in the diploid cell.",
  "alternative_term": "zygote activation | early zygote development | post-fertilization activation | developmental program initiation |+ Zygoten-Entwicklungs-Initiierung | Zygoten-Aktivierung | frühe Zygoten-Entwicklung | Entwicklungsprogramm-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows zygote development initiation during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69, with fertilized zygote undergoing metabolic activation and zygotic genome activation over 18-32 hours post-fertilization, developmental polarity establishing apical-basal axis, DNA replication completing preparing for division, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing activation 28-52 hours post-pollination preparing for first embryonic division",
  "editor_note": "Zygote_Development_Initiation is first aspect of Zygote_Formation, distinguished by activation and preparation phase. ||Represents metabolic activation, genome activation, polarity establishment. ||Duration 12-36 hours post-fertilization. ||Involves transition from maternal to zygotic genetic control. ||Temperature affects developmental rate. ||Establishes embryonic program. ||Preceded by Egg_Fertilization. ||Followed by Embryo_Genesis_Start as division approaches. ||Critical phase determining embryo developmental competence. || This critical activation phase occurs during zygote formation in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 12-36 hours following fertilization before first division, corresponding to BBCH 69 fertilization completion stages. ||Development initiation involves coordinated processes including sustained metabolic activation from fertilization-triggered changes, developmental polarity establishment creating apical-basal axis, zygotic genome activation initiating embryo-specific gene expression, cell growth and cytoplasmic reorganization preparing division, and cell cycle progression through G1 and S phases toward mitosis. ||Metabolic activation characteristics show elevated respiratory rate 2-3 fold above unfertilized egg consuming oxygen and producing ATP, increased protein synthesis from maternal mRNAs and newly transcribed zygotic genes, carbohydrate metabolism intensifying mobilizing stored reserves, biosynthetic pathways activating producing membranes and structural components, and overall transition from quiescent to actively growing state. ||Respiratory activation shows mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation intensifying, oxygen consumption increasing substantially measurable through respirometry, ATP production supporting biosynthesis and cellular processes, and metabolic rate elevation sustained throughout pre-division period. ||Protein synthesis shows translation from maternal mRNAs accumulated during oogenesis providing initial developmental proteins, ribosome activation and polysome formation increasing translation capacity, progressive transition to zygotic mRNA translation as genome activates, and protein accumulation supporting growth and division preparation. ||Zygotic genome activation shows transition from maternal to embryonic genetic control, initial zygotic transcription occurring within hours of fertilization, progressive increase in zygotic gene expression over pre-division period, embryo-specific genes activating including developmental regulators and cell cycle controllers, and genome activation establishing embryonic developmental program. ||Transcriptional activation timing shows early zygotic genes expressed within 2-6 hours post-fertilization, progressive activation of additional genes over 12-24 hours, and major transition to predominantly zygotic control by first division, though timing varies among species and specific genes. ||Developmental gene expression shows transcription factors regulating embryo patterning, cell cycle regulators controlling division, metabolic enzymes supporting growth, and signaling molecules coordinating development. ||Chromatin remodeling shows modifications enabling transcriptional activation, histone modifications marking active versus repressed genomic regions, DNA methylation changes affecting gene expression patterns, and epigenetic regulation establishing developmental programs. ||Developmental polarity establishment shows asymmetric distribution of developmental regulators creating apical-basal axis, cytoplasmic gradients determining positional information, differential localization of transcription factors and mRNAs, and polarity determining embryo organization in subsequent development. ||Polarity axis orientation shows typical apical pole toward micropyle and basal pole toward chalaza corresponding to embryo proper and suspensor regions respectively, axis established during early post-fertilization period possibly influenced by sperm entry site or inherent egg organization, and axis maintained through subsequent divisions determining embryo structure. ||Molecular asymmetry shows differential distribution of key developmental regulators including transcription factors affecting cell fate, localized mRNAs encoding developmental proteins, and protein gradients establishing positional information along apical-basal axis. ||Cytoplasmic reorganization shows organelle repositioning with mitochondria, ER, and Golgi distributing asymmetrically, cytoskeletal rearrangement creating structural polarity, and cytoplasmic streaming possibly contributing to molecular redistribution. ||Cell growth during initiation shows zygote enlargement through water uptake and biosynthesis, volume increase up to 1.5-2 fold before division, cell wall expansion accommodating growth, and resource accumulation from endosperm nutritive support. ||Cell wall modification shows loosening enabling expansion, new wall synthesis accommodating growth, and wall properties maintaining structural integrity while allowing enlargement. ||Nucleus characteristics show diploid nucleus with decondensed interphase chromatin, active transcription with RNA polymerase activity, nucleolus reformation and ribosomal RNA synthesis, and nuclear growth correlating with cell enlargement. ||Cell cycle progression shows G1 phase with growth and preparation for DNA replication, S phase entry with DNA synthesis initiating typically 12-24 hours post-fertilization, DNA replication proceeding doubling genome from 2n to 4n DNA content, G2 phase with continued growth and mitotic preparation, and progression toward M phase and first division. ||DNA replication dynamics show replication origin firing initiating synthesis, replication fork progression along chromosomes, coordinated replication ensuring complete genome duplication, and S phase completion within 6-12 hours enabling progression to G2. ||Mitotic preparation shows chromatin condensation beginning in late G2, centrosome duplication preparing spindle formation, nuclear envelope breakdown approaching as M phase nears, and cytological changes indicating imminent division. ||Environmental requirements during initiation include optimal temperature 22-28°C supporting normal metabolic and developmental processes, adequate nutrient supply from surrounding endosperm providing resources for growth and synthesis, appropriate osmotic environment maintaining cellular hydration, and overall favorable conditions during critical 12-36 hour initiation period. ||Temperature effects on initiation show warm conditions promoting rapid progression through initiation with accelerated metabolism and gene expression, cool conditions slowing processes potentially extending initiation period, and temperature as major factor affecting developmental rate. ||Endosperm support shows nutritive tissue providing amino acids, sugars, lipids, and other resources, signaling molecules possibly coordinating zygote-endosperm development, and essential support for normal zygote growth and division preparation. ||Failed development initiation causes include genetic defects preventing normal activation or gene expression, inadequate metabolic activation failing to support growth, abnormal polarity establishment disrupting organization, insufficient endosperm support limiting resources, or environmental stress disrupting developmental processes. ||Development initiation success rate shows high success in normal fertilized zygotes with majority successfully activating and progressing toward division, genetic or environmental problems causing minority failures, and successful initiation essential for subsequent embryogenesis. ||The process represents first aspect of zygote formation emphasizing activation and preparation, preceding embryo genesis start marking first division. ||Duration typically 12-36 hours from fertilization to division onset. ||Cultivar variation may include activation timing, developmental rate, and gene expression patterns. ||Regional timing shows zygote development initiation during late June-early July across all climates within day following fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical activation establishing embryo developmental program, requiring successful metabolic and genetic activation, demonstrating temperature sensitivity affecting developmental timing, and establishing initiation success as prerequisite for embryogenesis and seed formation. ||Research applications include analyzing metabolic activation mechanisms and kinetics, investigating zygotic genome activation and transcriptional programs, evaluating polarity establishment and molecular asymmetry, quantifying cell cycle progression and division preparation, and assessing developmental initiation as determinant of embryo development outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 398-400 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 302-304"
},

  "Embryo_Genesis_Start": {
  "definition": "An Embryo_Genesis_Start is a Zygote_Formation marked by the first asymmetric zygotic division producing a two-cell embryo with distinct apical and basal daughter cells establishing embryo-proper and suspensor lineages.",
  "alternative_term": "first embryonic division | embryogenesis initiation | zygote cleavage | two-cell embryo formation |+ Embryo-Genesis-Start | erste embryonale Teilung | Embryogenese-Initiierung | Zygoten-Spaltung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows embryo genesis start during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-71, with first asymmetric zygotic division occurring 28-48 hours post-fertilization producing smaller apical cell developing into embryo proper and larger basal cell forming suspensor, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing first division 60-84 hours post-pollination initiating embryogenesis and seed development supporting berry growth",
  "editor_note": "Embryo_Genesis_Start is second and final aspect of Zygote_Formation, distinguished by first division event initiating multicellular embryogenesis. ||Represents asymmetric mitotic cleavage producing apical and basal cells. ||Occurs 24-72 hours post-fertilization. ||Establishes embryo proper and suspensor lineages. ||Marks definitive transition from unicellular zygote to multicellular embryo. ||Temperature strongly affects timing. ||Success essential for seed development. ||Completes Fertilization sequence. ||Initiates Berry_Development phase with seed formation. ||Final documented process in Flowering hierarchy. || This critical first division occurs during zygote formation in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically 24-72 hours following fertilization depending on temperature, corresponding to BBCH 69 fertilization completion transitioning to BBCH 71 early berry development stages. ||Genesis initiation involves first mitotic division with chromosome condensation, spindle formation, and segregation, asymmetric cytokinesis creating unequal daughter cells with smaller apical cell and larger basal cell, cell fate determination with apical cell developing into embryo proper and basal cell forming suspensor, and establishment of two-cell embryo marking definitive embryogenesis beginning. ||First mitotic division characteristics show chromosome condensation making chromatin visible as distinct structures, 38 chromosomes in Vitis vinifera aligning at metaphase plate, spindle microtubule attachment to kinetochores, anaphase segregation distributing sister chromatids to opposite poles, and telophase nuclear envelope reformation around separated chromosome sets. ||Division asymmetry shows unequal cytokinesis creating daughter cells of different sizes, smaller apical cell typically 20-40 micrometers diameter positioned toward micropyle, larger basal cell 40-60 micrometers diameter positioned toward chalaza, and size asymmetry reflecting differential developmental fates. ||Cell division plane shows transverse orientation perpendicular to apical-basal axis established during zygote development, plane positioning determining apical versus basal daughter identity, and plane regulated by polarity cues and cytoskeletal organization. ||Cytokinesis mechanism shows phragmoplast microtubule array forming at division plane, cell plate synthesis initiated at center extending outward, vesicle fusion depositing new cell wall material creating partition, and cell plate maturation completing separation into two distinct cells. ||Daughter cell characteristics show apical cell as smaller dense cytoplasm-rich cell with high nucleus-to-cytoplasm ratio, basal cell as larger vacuolated cell with lower nucleus-to-cytoplasm ratio, cytoplasmic differences reflecting distinct developmental programs, and asymmetric distribution of developmental determinants establishing cell fates. ||Apical cell fate shows development into embryo proper through subsequent symmetric divisions, cell proliferation producing globular embryo, progressive differentiation establishing cotyledons, shoot apical meristem, hypocotyl, and radicle, and ultimate development into mature embryo within seed. ||Basal cell fate shows development into suspensor through elongation and limited division, suspensor connecting embryo proper to surrounding tissues, function providing nutritive and possibly hormonal support for embryo development, and suspensor degeneration during later embryogenesis as embryo proper becomes self-sufficient. ||Cell fate determination shows asymmetric distribution of developmental regulators during division, apical cell inheriting factors promoting meristematic identity and embryo development, basal cell inheriting factors promoting suspensor differentiation, and molecular differences establishing distinct lineages from first division. ||Molecular asymmetry includes differential expression of transcription factors regulating embryo versus suspensor identity, signaling molecules affecting cell fate decisions, and epigenetic modifications distinguishing cell lineages. ||First division timing shows temperature-dependent variation with warm conditions 25-28°C promoting division at 24-36 hours post-fertilization, cool conditions 18-22°C delaying division to 48-72 hours or more, and timing as critical determinant of overall embryogenesis rate. ||Division synchrony among embryos shows variable timing with some embryos dividing earlier and others later even within same seed, asynchrony creating developmental heterogeneity, and timing differences potentially affecting seed development uniformity. ||Two-cell embryo characteristics show definitive multicellular state with distinct apical and basal cells, cell-cell communication through plasmodesmata enabling signaling, coordinated development of both cells supporting embryogenesis, and two-cell stage representing committed embryo having initiated developmental program. ||Embryo proper subsequent development shows progressive divisions producing four-cell then octant-stage embryos, globular stage with radial symmetry, transition stage initiating bilateral symmetry, heart stage with cotyledon primordia emergence, torpedo stage with elongating cotyledons and axis, and mature embryo ready for seed desiccation and dormancy. ||Suspensor subsequent development shows basal cell elongation creating filamentous structure, limited cell division producing small suspensor cell number typically 6-10 cells, suspensor connecting embryo to seed tissues, possible nutritive and signaling functions, and eventual degeneration as embryo proper develops. ||Environmental requirements during genesis start include optimal temperature 22-28°C supporting normal division timing and progression, adequate nutrient supply from endosperm providing resources, appropriate osmotic and hydration conditions, and overall favorable environment during critical first division period. ||Temperature as major regulator shows warm conditions accelerating division enabling rapid embryogenesis, cool conditions substantially delaying division potentially extending seed development period, and temperature affecting not only timing but possibly division symmetry and developmental outcomes. ||Endosperm coordination shows endosperm development proceeding parallel to early embryogenesis, endosperm providing nutritive support for embryo divisions, signaling between tissues possibly coordinating development, and balanced embryo-endosperm development essential for normal seed formation. ||Failed genesis start causes include cell cycle defects preventing mitosis, abnormal division producing equal or inverted asymmetry disrupting proper patterning, cell fate determination failure preventing normal embryo-suspensor establishment, genetic abnormalities causing developmental arrest, or environmental stress disrupting division processes. ||Genesis success rate shows high efficiency in normal activated zygotes with majority successfully completing first division, genetic or environmental problems causing minority failures, and successful genesis essential for seed development. ||The process represents second and final aspect of zygote formation marking definitive embryogenesis initiation, following zygote development initiation. ||Duration represents culminating event with division occurring 24-72 hours post-fertilization establishing two-cell embryo. ||Cultivar variation may include division timing, asymmetry characteristics, and subsequent embryo developmental patterns. ||Regional timing shows embryo genesis start during late June-early July across all climates 1-3 days following fertilization as embryogenesis begins. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive embryogenesis initiation marking seed development beginning, requiring successful zygote activation and division, demonstrating temperature sensitivity affecting timing and potentially outcomes, establishing genesis success as determinant of seed and berry development, and marking transition from fertilization to embryogenesis and berry growth phases. ||Research applications include analyzing first division mechanisms and asymmetry, investigating cell fate determination and molecular asymmetry, evaluating environmental effects on division timing and characteristics, quantifying embryogenesis initiation dynamics, and assessing genesis success as determinant of seed development outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 400-405 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 304-308"
},

  "Fruit_Set": {
  "definition": "A Fruit_Set is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process consisting of ovary expansion in fertilized flowers driven by seed-derived auxin and abscission of unfertilized flowers, establishing final berry number per cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "berry set | fruit formation | berry establishment | reproductive success |+ Fruchtansatz | Beerenbildung | Fruchtbildung | reproduktiver Erfolg",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows fruit set during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-71, with 54-64% flowers successfully producing berries containing 1-3 seeds, ovary expansion from 6 mm to 14-18 mm over 2-3 weeks post-fertilization, auxin from developing seeds preventing abscission and triggering growth, unfertilized flowers aborting, under oceanic conditions following favorable flowering period, typical of this mid-season cultivar with moderate-to-good set reliability determining season yield",
  "editor_note": "Fruit_Set represents critical reproductive outcome phase determining berry number and yield. ||Corresponds to BBCH 69-71 stages 1-3 weeks post-fertilization. ||Subdivided into Ovule_Fertilization showing variable success outcomes and Berry_Initiation showing hormone-mediated berry development. ||Success rate 30-75% depending on conditions. ||Auxin from seeds critical for preventing abscission and triggering growth. ||Coulure represents failed fruit set. ||Marks definitive transition from Flowering to Berry_Development. ||Yield-determining phase. || This essential outcome phase occurs during late flowering and early berry development in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically proceeding over 1-3 weeks following fertilization as fertilization outcomes manifest, corresponding to BBCH 69-71 stages transitioning from flowering completion to young fruit development. ||Fruit set mechanism involves fertilization success determining ovule and seed development, auxin and other hormone production from developing seeds preventing programmed flower abscission, hormone signaling triggering ovary wall cell division and expansion initiating berry formation, unfertilized flowers lacking hormonal rescue undergoing abscission, and final berry number establishment representing successful fruit set percentage. ||Fertilization outcomes show variable success with 30-75% flowers achieving successful fertilization and fruit set depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, successful fertilization producing 1-3 seeds per berry from fertilized ovules in 2-4 ovule flowers, and fertilization failure causing flower abortion eliminating potential berries from yield. ||Successful ovule fertilization shows double fertilization completion producing viable zygote and endosperm, seed development initiation with embryo and endosperm growth, integument development forming seed coat, and overall seed maturation proceeding coordinated with berry development. ||Failed ovule fertilization shows fertilization failure from inadequate pollination, pollen tube growth failure, or fusion problems, ovule abortion lacking seed development, and flower abortion unless other ovules in same flower fertilize successfully providing hormonal rescue. ||Partial ovule fertilization shows some ovules fertilizing successfully while others fail within multi-ovule flower, variable seed number 1-3 per berry depending on partial success, and berry development proceeding with reduced seed number potentially affecting berry size. ||Auxin production from developing seeds shows critical hormone synthesis in embryo and endosperm beginning within days of fertilization, auxin export from seed to surrounding ovary tissues, and hormone accumulation preventing abscission and triggering growth responses. ||Auxin prevention of abscission shows hormone blocking formation of abscission zone at flower-pedicel junction, maintaining vascular connection supporting developing berry, and rescuing flower from programmed senescence and abscission pathway. ||Auxin induction of berry growth shows hormone triggering cell division in ovary wall creating berry flesh, promoting cell expansion increasing berry size, and coordinating berry development with seed maturation. ||Post-fertilization signaling shows complex hormone interactions including auxin as primary signal, gibberellins possibly contributing to growth promotion, cytokinins potentially involved in cell division stimulation, and integrated signaling establishing berry developmental program. ||Ovary expansion initiation shows rapid growth beginning 1-2 weeks post-fertilization, ovary diameter increasing from 4-8 mm pre-fertilization to 10-20 mm within 2-3 weeks, cell division intensity maximizing with 10-15 hour cycle times during early expansion, and visible berry formation confirming successful fruit set. ||Cell division characteristics during early berry show peak mitotic activity in ovary wall pericarp tissue, rapid cell proliferation producing berry flesh cells, division rate declining after initial 3-4 weeks as cell expansion phase begins, and final cell number established during early development determining potential berry size. ||Early berry formation shows ovary wall thickening creating berry flesh, pericarp tissue differentiation into exocarp skin, mesocarp flesh, and endocarp near seeds, vascular development establishing nutrient transport to growing berry, and overall berry structure establishment during first weeks. ||Berry commitment shows developmental commitment to berry formation becoming irreversible after initial growth, continued development independent of ongoing seed development in some cases though seed presence beneficial, and berry reaching point of assured maturation barring severe environmental stress or disease. ||Unfertilized flower abscission shows flowers lacking seed development failing to produce adequate auxin rescue, abscission zone formation at pedicel creating separation layer, vascular connection severing and flower dropping, and coulure poor fruit set from excessive abscission reducing yield. ||Coulure characteristics show environmental or physiological poor fruit set with high proportion flowers aborting, typical occurrence during unfavorable flowering conditions particularly rain or extreme temperatures, variable cultivar susceptibility with some showing consistent good set and others prone to coulure, and severe coulure potentially reducing yield by 50-80% in affected vintages. ||Millerandage relationship to fruit set shows shot berries resulting from partial fertilization or early developmental disruption, small seedless berries persisting but failing to develop normally, and millerandage creating berry size heterogeneity affecting harvest and quality. ||Fruit set percentage calculation shows proportion of flowers producing berries, typical range 30-75% depending on conditions with good set 60-75% under favorable flowering weather and poor set 30-50% under adverse conditions, and set percentage directly determining cluster density and yield. ||Environmental effects on fruit set include flowering period weather critically affecting pollination and fertilization success, rain during flowering causing poor set through pollination disruption and pollen damage, temperature extremes reducing fertilization efficiency and seed development, boron deficiency preventing normal pollen tube growth and fertilization, and overall flowering conditions as primary fruit set determinant. ||Temperature effects show optimal 22-28°C during flowering supporting high fruit set 60-75%, cool conditions 15-20°C reducing set to 40-60% through delayed development and reduced fertilization, excessive heat above 33°C severely reducing set to 20-40% through reproductive dysfunction, and critical temperature sensitivity during 2-3 day peak flowering window. ||Boron nutrition critical importance shows adequate boron 10-20 ppm essential for pollen tube integrity and fertilization success, deficiency causing poor fruit set even with adequate flowering through fertilization failure, and boron as frequent limiting factor for set in deficient soils. ||Cultivar variation in fruit set shows genetic differences in setting ability with some cultivars showing reliable 65-75% set across conditions, others showing variable 40-70% set depending on weather, and problematic cultivars prone to coulure showing poor 30-50% set even under favorable conditions. ||Cluster architecture effects on set show compact clusters potentially showing reduced set from crowding and competition, loose clusters generally showing better set from improved flower exposure and pollination, and cluster density reflecting both genetic architecture and fruit set percentage. ||Resource allocation following fruit set shows dramatic shift to developing berries consuming 40-60% total photosynthate, vegetative growth continuing requiring 30-40% resources, and remaining allocation to root growth and reserves, establishing berry development as dominant sink. ||Yield determination through fruit set shows final berry number per cluster established during set period, cluster number per vine determined by previous season bud formation, and total yield calculated from berry number, berry weight, and cluster number. ||Fruit set assessment timing shows preliminary evaluation 2-3 weeks post-flowering observing berry versus abscised flower proportion, definitive assessment 4-6 weeks post-flowering confirming established berry number, and early yield prediction based on set percentage and cluster counts. ||The process encompasses two major components including ovule fertilization showing variable success creating seed number diversity, and berry initiation showing hormone-mediated transition to berry development. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 weeks from fertilization through definitive berry establishment. ||Cultivar variation includes fruit set reliability, coulure susceptibility, and seed number characteristics. ||Regional timing shows fruit set during late June-early July in warm climates, early-mid July in temperate regions, and mid-late July in cool areas, occurring 1-3 weeks post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing yield determination phase establishing final berry number, requiring favorable fertilization outcomes and environmental conditions, demonstrating critical importance of flowering period weather for set success, and marking definitive transition from reproductive flowering to developmental berry growth phase. ||Research applications include analyzing fertilization outcomes and fruit set determinants, investigating hormone signaling coordinating seed and berry development, evaluating environmental and nutritional effects on set success, quantifying fruit set percentage and yield relationships, and developing strategies for improving set reliability and reducing coulure.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:narrowMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0007032 ## whole plant fruit formation stage up to 10% | 0.9" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 405-415 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 308-315 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Ovule_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "An Ovule_Fertilization is a Fertilization comprising the variable fertilization outcome across the 2–4 ovules per flower with each ovule reaching a successful, partial, or failed state.",
  "alternative_term": "ovule reproductive success | seed formation | fertilization outcomes | ovule fate determination |+ Samenanlage-Befruchtung | Samenbildung | Befruchtungsergebnisse | Samenanlage-Schicksalsbestimmung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows ovule fertilization during late June Year N+1 at BBCH 69, with 2-4 ovules per flower experiencing variable fertilization success, typical outcomes producing 1.8-2.4 seeds per berry from partial ovule fertilization, failed ovules aborting within 2 weeks, successful seeds initiating development, under warm climate conditions, typical of this late-season cultivar with moderate seed number supporting berry development",
  "editor_note": "Ovule_Fertilization represents variable reproductive outcome phase within Fruit_Set determining seed number. ||Subdivided into Successful_Ovule_Fertilization producing seeds, Failed_Ovule_Fertilization causing abortion, and Partial_Ovule_Fertilization creating variable seed numbers. ||Occurs 1-3 days post-pollination with outcomes manifesting over 1-2 weeks. ||Typically 2-4 ovules per flower with 30-60% individual success rate. ||Seed number 1-3 per berry affects size. ||Multiple ovules provide redundancy supporting fruit set. ||Determines berry developmental potential. || This variable outcome phase occurs during late flowering in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, with outcomes determined by fertilization success 1-3 days post-pollination and manifesting over subsequent 1-2 weeks, corresponding to BBCH 69 fertilization completion stages. ||Ovule fertilization encompasses multiple outcomes including successful double fertilization in some ovules producing viable embryo and endosperm initiating seed development, failed fertilization in other ovules from pollination inadequacy, tube growth failure, or fusion problems causing ovule abortion, and partial success patterns creating 0-3 seeds per berry affecting subsequent development. ||Grapevine flower ovule number shows typically 2-4 ovules per bicarpellate ovary distributed in two locules, each ovule representing potential seed if successfully fertilized, and total ovule number providing multiple fertilization opportunities per flower. ||Fertilization attempt variability shows independent fertilization success for each ovule, 1-4 pollen tubes potentially reaching ovary region though usually only 1-2 successfully penetrating and discharging, competitive dynamics among tubes and ovules affecting which ovules fertilize, and stochastic variation creating diverse outcomes across flowers. ||Successful fertilization outcome shows ovule achieving double fertilization with viable zygote and endosperm formation, seed development initiating with embryo and endosperm growth, integuments developing into seed coat, and seed maturation proceeding toward viable propagule 90-120 days duration. ||Failed fertilization outcome shows ovule experiencing fertilization failure from various causes, ovule abortion with tissue degeneration and resource reabsorption, no seed development contribution, and potential flower abortion unless other ovules successfully fertilize providing hormonal rescue. ||Partial fertilization pattern shows common outcome with 1-2 ovules fertilizing while others fail within multi-ovule flower, resulting seed number typically 1-3 per berry with average 1.5-2.5 in many cultivars, and seed number variation creating berry size diversity. ||Fertilization success rate per ovule shows variable efficiency with 30-60% individual ovules successfully fertilizing depending on conditions, cumulative flower-level success higher since multiple ovules provide redundancy, and overall pattern creating reliable fruit set despite individual ovule variation. ||Pollen tube competition effects show 2-5 tubes potentially reaching ovary but limited ovule access, first-arrival advantage with earliest tubes gaining ovule access, and competitive exclusion preventing excessive fertilization per ovule. ||Ovule receptivity variation shows developmental asynchrony among ovules potentially affecting fertilization timing, some ovules ready earlier receiving first-arriving tubes, and temporal spread creating fertilization window across ovules. ||Seed number determination shows finalized 1-3 days post-pollination as fertilization outcomes establish, seed number visible 2-3 weeks later as developing seeds become distinct from aborted ovules, and seed count affecting berry size and development with more seeds generally producing larger berries through greater auxin production. ||Seed number effects on berry show positive correlation between seed number and final berry size, seedless or single-seed berries typically smaller than multi-seed berries, auxin production proportional to seed number driving differential growth, and seed presence stimulating cell division and expansion in surrounding pericarp. ||Auxin production variation shows greater total auxin from multiple seeds, hormone accumulation triggering stronger growth responses, and seed number as determinant of berry growth potential during early development. ||Berry size variation from seed number shows seedless berries 30-50% smaller than seeded berries in seeded cultivars, single-seed berries intermediate size, 2-3 seed berries largest, and within-cluster size heterogeneity reflecting seed number diversity. ||Seedless berry formation shows stenospermocarpic development in some cultivars with fertilization occurring but embryo aborting early, residual seed traces or rudiments remaining, berry development proceeding from initial hormone stimulus despite seed loss, and parthenocarpic development in rare cases with ovary growth without fertilization. ||Ovule abortion timing shows failed ovules degenerating within 1-2 weeks post-fertilization, tissue browning and collapse distinguishing from viable developing seeds, and resource reabsorption recycling nutrients from failed reproductive attempts. ||Flower-level fertilization outcomes show complete failure with all ovules unfertilized causing flower abortion, partial success with 1-3 ovules fertilized supporting berry development, and complete success with most ovules fertilized producing maximum seed number. ||Environmental effects on ovule fertilization include flowering weather affecting pollination success and fertilization efficiency across ovules, temperature during fertilization affecting fusion success and early seed development, boron nutrition affecting pollen tube growth and fertilization completion, and overall conditions determining fertilization success distribution. ||Cultivar variation in ovule fertilization shows genetic differences in fertilization efficiency, seed number characteristics with some cultivars averaging 1-2 seeds and others 2-3 seeds per berry, and seedless cultivars showing consistent embryo abortion patterns. ||The process shows three distinguishable outcome categories including successful ovule fertilization producing viable seeds, failed ovule fertilization causing abortion, and partial ovule fertilization creating variable seed numbers. ||Duration represents fertilization attempts and outcomes over several days with seed number determination within week post-pollination. ||Regional timing shows ovule fertilization outcomes during late June-early July across all climates 1-3 days following pollination attempts. ||Viticultural significance includes determining seed number per berry affecting berry size and development, establishing fertilization success rate affecting fruit set, demonstrating importance of multiple ovules providing fertilization redundancy, and creating within-cluster berry size variation affecting harvest uniformity. ||Research applications include analyzing factors affecting ovule-specific fertilization success, evaluating seed number determinants and effects on berry characteristics, quantifying fertilization efficiency and redundancy benefits, and assessing ovule fertilization patterns as fruit set and quality determinants.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0004505 ## fertilized ovule stage | 0.65" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 408-412 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 310-313 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Successful_Ovule_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "A Successful_Ovule_Fertilization is an Ovule_Fertilization characterized by complete double fertilization producing a functional diploid zygote and triploid endosperm with integument differentiation into seed coat.",
  "alternative_term": "viable seed formation | complete seed development | successful seed maturation | fertile ovule outcome |+ erfolgreiche Samenanlage-Befruchtung | lebensfähige Samenbildung | vollständige Samenentwicklung | fruchtbares Samenanlage-Ergebnis",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows successful ovule fertilization during late June-October Year N+1 at BBCH 69-89, with 1.6-2.2 ovules per flower achieving complete double fertilization, embryo development progressing through globular (2 weeks), heart (5 weeks), torpedo (9 weeks), and mature (14 weeks) stages, endosperm supporting embryo growth, seed coat forming protective layers, auxin production driving berry expansion, under continental conditions, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar producing 1-2 viable seeds per berry supporting normal berry development",
  "editor_note": "Successful_Ovule_Fertilization represents favorable reproductive outcome within Ovule_Fertilization producing viable seeds. ||Characterized by complete double fertilization, viable zygote and endosperm, progressive embryo development, seed coat formation, auxin production. ||Duration 90-120 days from fertilization to mature seed. ||Typically 1-3 seeds per berry from partial ovule success. ||Auxin critical for preventing abscission and driving berry growth. ||Seed number affects berry size. ||Enables sexual reproduction. ||Essential for normal berry development in seeded cultivars. || This favorable reproductive outcome occurs during fertilization and early seed development in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, established within 1-3 days of pollination and progressing over subsequent 90-120 days, corresponding to BBCH 69-71 stages. ||Successful fertilization establishment shows pollen tube achieving micropyle penetration and sperm discharge, both sperm cells completing fusion with egg and central cell respectively, viable 2n zygote and 3n endosperm nucleus formation, and developmental activation initiating seed development program. ||Zygote viability indicators include normal diploid chromosome complement 2n=38 in Vitis vinifera, successful developmental activation with first division within 24-72 hours, and progressive embryo development through globular, heart, torpedo, and mature stages. ||Endosperm viability shows triploid nucleus 3n=57 successfully formed, free nuclear division initiating producing multinucleate syncytium, cellularization proceeding creating cellular endosperm tissue, and nutritive function supporting embryo growth throughout development. ||Embryo development progression shows first zygotic division producing two-cell embryo, subsequent divisions producing globular stage embryo by 2-3 weeks post-fertilization, heart stage with cotyledon primordia by 4-6 weeks, torpedo stage with elongating cotyledons and embryonic axis by 8-10 weeks, and mature embryo with complete organ primordia by 12-16 weeks ready for seed desiccation. ||Endosperm development shows rapid free nuclear division producing 32-128 nuclei within first weeks, cellularization forming cellular tissue providing nutrients, endosperm accumulating storage reserves including proteins and lipids, and progressive consumption by growing embryo reducing to thin layer in mature seed. ||Seed coat development shows integument layers differentiating into inner and outer seed coat, tissue lignification and coloration creating protective layers, mature seed coat providing mechanical protection and controlling water relations, and coat completion by seed maturation enabling desiccation tolerance. ||Seed growth dynamics show rapid enlargement during first 6-8 weeks coordinated with early berry growth, progressive accumulation of dry matter including storage proteins, lipids, and carbohydrates, maximum seed size achieved by 10-12 weeks post-fertilization, and final maturation preparing seed for desiccation and dormancy. ||Auxin production from successful seed shows hormone synthesis in developing embryo and endosperm beginning within days of fertilization, auxin levels correlating with seed developmental activity, hormone export to surrounding ovary tissues, and auxin as critical signal preventing flower abscission and stimulating berry growth. ||Seed-berry developmental coordination shows auxin from seed triggering ovary expansion, seed development providing hormonal support throughout berry growth, coordinated maturation timing with seed completing development as berry ripens, and seed presence essential for normal berry development in seeded cultivars. ||Seed number per berry shows successful fertilization typically producing 1-3 viable seeds from 2-4 ovules per flower, seed number variation depending on partial versus complete ovule fertilization success, and seed count affecting berry size with more seeds producing larger berries through greater auxin stimulus. ||Seed viability at maturity shows successful development producing viable propagule capable of germination, seed containing genetic recombination from sexual reproduction, and functional seed enabling sexual propagation though vegetative propagation more common in viticulture. ||Seed reserves accumulation shows storage protein deposition primarily in embryo cotyledons, lipid accumulation in embryo providing energy reserves, limited endosperm persistence with most consumed during embryo growth, and total dry matter typically 2-5% berry fresh weight. ||Seed desiccation and dormancy shows late-stage water loss reducing seed moisture from 60-70% to 10-20%, metabolic quiescence establishing dormancy preventing precocious germination, and dormancy mechanisms requiring stratification for germination. ||Environmental effects on successful seed development include adequate temperature 20-28°C supporting normal embryogenesis and maturation, sufficient nutrients from maternal vine providing resources, appropriate water relations maintaining seed hydration during growth then enabling desiccation, and overall favorable conditions supporting complete development. ||Temperature during seed development shows optimal range supporting steady progression through developmental stages, extreme heat potentially disrupting development, cool conditions slowing but generally not preventing maturation, and temperature as factor affecting development rate and timing. ||Nutrient supply shows maternal provision of nitrogen for protein synthesis, phosphorus and potassium for metabolism, and micronutrients supporting enzymatic functions, with adequate nutrition essential for normal seed development. ||Failed seed development after fertilization shows occasional embryo abortion despite initial fertilization success, early seed abortion creating seedless or seed-trace berries, and developmental failure reducing seed number below ovule fertilization success. ||Successful seed indicators visible in berry show hard textured seeds distinguishable from aborted ovules, brown color development indicating maturation, and seed rattling in dried berries confirming complete development. ||The process represents favorable ovule fertilization outcome within Ovule_Fertilization category. ||Duration spans 90-120 days from fertilization through complete seed maturation. ||Cultivar variation includes seed developmental characteristics, seed size and composition, and developmental timing. ||Regional timing shows successful seed development from late June through October across climates as seeds mature with berries. ||Viticultural significance includes providing auxin driving berry development, determining berry size through seed number effects, enabling sexual reproduction and genetic recombination supporting breeding, and affecting berry and wine characteristics through seed presence and composition. ||Research applications include analyzing seed development biology and regulation, investigating seed-berry coordination and hormonal interactions, evaluating factors affecting seed development success and characteristics, quantifying seed effects on berry development and quality, and assessing seed development as berry quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 408-410 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 310-312"
},

  "Failed_Ovule_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "A Failed_Ovule_Fertilization is an Ovule_Fertilization marked by fertilization failure or early post-fertilization arrest leading to ovule abortion and resource reabsorption.",
  "alternative_term": "ovule abortion | fertilization failure | seed development failure | reproductive failure |+ Samenanlage-Fehlschlag | Befruchtungsversagen | Samenentwicklungsversagen | reproduktives Versagen",
  "example_of_usage": "Grenache in Rhône Valley shows failed ovule fertilization during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69, with 35-55% ovules experiencing fertilization failure from combination of environmental stress and cultivar susceptibility, failed ovules aborting within 2 weeks showing brown collapsed tissue, flowers with complete ovule failure aborting causing coulure, partial failure creating 1-2 seeds instead of potential 3-4, under variable Mediterranean conditions, typical of this coulure-prone cultivar requiring favorable flowering for acceptable fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Failed_Ovule_Fertilization represents unfavorable reproductive outcome within Ovule_Fertilization causing ovule abortion. ||Results from pollination failure, tube growth problems, fusion abnormalities, or developmental arrest. ||Manifests within days to weeks as ovule degeneration. ||Complete failure causes flower abortion contributing to coulure. ||Partial failure reduces seed number affecting berry size. ||Environmental factors particularly boron deficiency and weather major causes. ||Cultivar variation in susceptibility. ||Determines fruit set loss and yield reduction. || This unfavorable reproductive outcome occurs during fertilization and early post-fertilization in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, determined within days of pollination attempts with abortion manifesting over 1-2 weeks, corresponding to BBCH 69 stages. ||Failed fertilization causes include pollen absence or scarcity preventing ovule pollination, inadequate pollen tube growth failing to reach ovule micropyle from tube dysfunction or environmental limitations, pollen tube penetration failure preventing sperm delivery to embryo sac, failed sperm-egg or sperm-central cell fusion preventing zygote or endosperm formation despite tube discharge, and early post-fertilization developmental failure causing embryo or endosperm abortion. ||Pollination failure as cause shows insufficient pollen delivery from poor weather during flowering, inadequate pollen production or release, ineffective pollen dispersal, or pollen viability loss preventing successful pollination. ||Pollen tube failure shows tube growth cessation before reaching ovule from boron deficiency, environmental stress, pollen vigor limitations, or guidance problems, preventing sperm delivery and fertilization. ||Fusion failure shows sperm cells reaching embryo sac but failing membrane or nuclear fusion, abnormal gamete function preventing successful union, or cellular incompatibility though rare in self-compatible grapevine. ||Early developmental failure shows initial fertilization success but subsequent embryo or endosperm abortion within days to weeks, developmental arrest from genetic abnormalities or physiological dysfunction, and seed development cessation leaving aborted ovule. ||Ovule abortion manifestation shows failed ovule tissue beginning degeneration within days of fertilization failure, browning and collapse distinguishing from viable green developing seeds, tissue breakdown and resource mobilization recovering invested nutrients, and aborted remnant visible as dark collapsed structure or seed trace in developing berry. ||Abortion timing shows rapid progression within 1-2 weeks of fertilization failure, early detection possible 2-3 weeks post-flowering through ovule examination, and complete abortion with tissue reabsorption by berry development phase. ||Flower fate following complete ovule failure shows all ovules failing eliminating seed development and auxin production, flower lacking hormonal rescue signal failing to prevent abscission, abscission zone formation at pedicel creating separation layer, and flower abortion and drop contributing to coulure poor fruit set. ||Partial ovule failure within flower shows some ovules failing while others succeed, successful ovule(s) producing seed and auxin rescuing flower from abscission, berry development proceeding with reduced seed number 1-2 instead of potential 3-4, and failed ovules contributing only through reabsorbed resources. ||Reduced seed number effects show lower total auxin production potentially limiting berry size, berry developing smaller than multi-seed counterparts, and within-cluster size variation from seed number diversity. ||Auxin absence effects from complete failure show lack of anti-abscission signal permitting programmed flower senescence, abscission progression unchecked by hormonal suppression, and flower drop typically 1-3 weeks post-flowering. ||Abscission zone development shows specialized cells at pedicel-receptacle junction activating separation program, cell wall degradation creating abscission layer, vascular tissue severing eliminating nutrient flow, and mechanical weakness enabling flower detachment. ||Coulure relationship to failed fertilization shows poor fruit set resulting from excessive ovule and flower failure, environmental causes including rain during flowering washing pollen and preventing pollination, temperature extremes during fertilization affecting fusion and development, boron deficiency preventing pollen tube growth and fertilization, and genetic susceptibility in certain cultivars prone to fertilization failure. ||Environmental effects on ovule failure include unfavorable flowering weather increasing failure rate, rain preventing pollination and pollen tube growth, temperature extremes impairing fertilization and early development, boron deficiency as major cause preventing tube growth, and overall conditions during critical 2-3 week period determining failure extent. ||Temperature effects show cool conditions increasing failure through delayed development and reduced fusion efficiency, excessive heat causing reproductive dysfunction and developmental failure, and optimal 22-28°C range minimizing failure rate. ||Boron deficiency effects show inadequate boron preventing normal pollen tube wall synthesis, tube bursting or growth cessation before reaching ovules, fertilization failure even with adequate flowering, and boron supplementation critical for reducing failure in deficient conditions. ||Cultivar variation in failure susceptibility shows genetic differences in fertilization reliability, coulure-prone cultivars showing high 40-70% failure rates even under favorable conditions, reliable cultivars maintaining low 20-40% failure rates across conditions, and variation affecting fruit set predictability. ||Failed ovule proportion shows typical 30-60% individual ovules failing across flowers depending on conditions, high redundancy from multiple ovules per flower buffering flower-level failure, and population-level patterns determining overall fruit set percentage. ||Assessment methods include microscopic ovule examination distinguishing viable green from aborted brown ovules, dissection of young berries counting seeds versus aborted remnants, and fruit set percentage calculation comparing berry number to initial flower number. ||The process represents unfavorable ovule fertilization outcome within Ovule_Fertilization category. ||Duration represents failure determination and abortion within days to weeks post-pollination. ||Regional timing shows failed ovule abortion during late June-early July across climates following unsuccessful fertilization attempts. ||Viticultural significance includes contributing to coulure poor fruit set when excessive, determining final seed number through partial failure patterns, responding to environmental and nutritional conditions affecting management outcomes, and serving as yield limitation in unfavorable seasons or cultivars. ||Research applications include analyzing fertilization failure mechanisms and causes, evaluating environmental and nutritional effects on failure rates, quantifying genetic variation in failure susceptibility, and developing strategies for reducing failure and improving fruit set reliability.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 410-415 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 312-315"
},

  "Partial_Ovule_Fertilization": {
  "definition": "A Partial_Ovule_Fertilization is an Ovule_Fertilization characterized by 1–3 successfully fertilized ovules per flower with the remainder aborted, producing berries with variable seed number below the theoretical maximum of four.",
  "alternative_term": "variable seed number | incomplete fertilization | mixed ovule success | intermediate fertilization |+ teilweise Samenanlage-Befruchtung | variable Samenzahl | unvollständige Befruchtung | gemischter Samenanlage-Erfolg",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows partial ovule fertilization during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-71, with typical 1.8-2.3 seeds per berry from partial ovule success across 3-4 potential ovules, within-cluster seed number range 1-3 seeds creating berry size variation, partial success providing adequate auxin rescue enabling berry development, under cool maritime conditions, typical of this early-bursting cultivar showing common partial pattern supporting 64-76% fruit set with acceptable berry size variation",
  "editor_note": "Partial_Ovule_Fertilization represents common intermediate outcome within Ovule_Fertilization creating variable seed numbers. ||Characterized by mixed success across multiple ovules producing 1-3 seeds instead of theoretical maximum. ||Most frequent fruit set pattern in grapevine. ||Provides hormonal rescue preventing flower abortion. ||Creates berry size variation through differential auxin effects. ||Demonstrates multi-ovule redundancy strategy. ||Acceptable reproductive outcome supporting normal berry development. ||Contributes to within-cluster berry heterogeneity. || This prevalent outcome pattern occurs during fertilization in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, determined within 1-3 days of pollination with seed number manifesting over subsequent 2-3 weeks, corresponding to BBCH 69-71 stages. ||Partial fertilization pattern shows mixed success across 2-4 ovules per flower, typical outcomes producing 1-3 viable seeds from partial success rather than complete success or complete failure, stochastic variation in which ovules succeed depending on pollen tube competition and ovule receptivity, and partial pattern representing most common fruit set outcome. ||Seed number distribution shows typical average 1.5-2.5 seeds per berry in many seeded cultivars, modal distribution often at 2 seeds representing common partial outcome, range from 0 (complete failure) to 3-4 (complete success) creating within-cultivar variation, and seed number heterogeneity contributing to berry size diversity. ||Ovule competition and selection shows 2-5 pollen tubes potentially reaching ovary region, limited ovule access creating competitive situation, first-arrival advantage and ovule receptivity determining which ovules fertilize, and stochastic elements creating variable outcomes across flowers. ||Successful ovule characteristics in partial pattern show ovules achieving complete double fertilization with viable embryo and endosperm, seed development proceeding normally producing mature seeds, auxin production contributing to hormonal rescue and berry growth, and viable seeds functionally equivalent to complete success outcomes. ||Failed ovule characteristics show ovules experiencing fertilization failure despite other ovules succeeding in same flower, abortion and degeneration creating dark collapsed tissue or seed traces, no developmental contribution except through resource reabsorption, and failed ovules representing missed potential rather than flower loss since partial success rescues flower. ||Hormonal rescue with partial success shows 1-2 successful seeds producing sufficient auxin preventing flower abscission, hormone levels lower than complete success but adequate for berry development, and partial success enabling berry formation albeit potentially smaller than multi-seed maximum. ||Berry size effects of partial success show positive correlation between seed number and final berry size, 1-seed berries smaller than 2-seed berries smaller than 3-seed berries, auxin production proportional to seed number driving differential growth response, and within-cluster berry size variation largely reflecting seed number diversity from partial fertilization. ||Auxin production from partial seeds shows hormone synthesis in each developing seed, total auxin proportional to seed number creating dose-dependent growth response, 1-seed berry receiving lower stimulus than 3-seed berry, and auxin gradient accounting for 30-50% berry size variation within clusters. ||Cell division effects show early berry cell proliferation responding to auxin levels, more seeds stimulating greater cell division creating more flesh cells, final cell number partially determined by seed number and auxin during first 3-4 weeks, and cell number differences affecting ultimate berry size potential. ||Berry development with partial seeds shows normal berry formation and maturation despite reduced seed number, developmental progression through all stages to full ripeness, berry quality characteristics generally normal though size reduced, and partial success representing adequate outcome for table grape and wine production. ||Within-cluster variation from partial pattern shows heterogeneous berry sizes within clusters, size distribution reflecting seed number diversity, cluster appearance showing mixed berry sizes though generally acceptable, and variation occasionally affecting harvest uniformity in extreme cases. ||Cultivar variation in partial pattern frequency shows genetic differences in typical seed number, some cultivars averaging 1-2 seeds showing frequent partial pattern, others averaging 2-3 seeds showing higher success rate, and cultivar characteristic affecting berry size uniformity. ||Environmental effects on partial versus complete success include favorable conditions increasing proportion of complete success with 3-4 seeds, suboptimal conditions increasing partial failure leaving 1-2 seeds, and environmental variation contributing to year-to-year seed number changes within cultivars. ||Partial fertilization as buffer against complete failure shows multiple ovules providing redundancy, partial success preventing flower loss even with some ovule failure, and evolutionary advantage of multi-ovule strategy ensuring fruit set despite fertilization variability. ||Fruit set implications show partial fertilization supporting acceptable berry formation, contributing to overall 50-70% fruit set percentage at population level, and partial pattern representing successful reproductive outcome despite not achieving maximum potential. ||The process represents intermediate ovule fertilization outcome within Ovule_Fertilization category between complete success and complete failure. ||Duration represents fertilization pattern determination within days and manifestation over 2-3 weeks. ||Regional timing shows partial fertilization outcomes during late June-early July across climates as fertilization results manifest. ||Viticultural significance includes representing most common fruit set pattern creating typical 1-3 seed berries, contributing to within-cluster berry size variation affecting harvest uniformity, demonstrating multi-ovule redundancy strategy supporting fruit set reliability, and affecting berry size through seed number effects on auxin-mediated growth. ||Research applications include analyzing partial fertilization determinants and patterns, quantifying seed number effects on berry characteristics, evaluating environmental and genetic factors affecting success distribution, and assessing partial fertilization as typical fruit set outcome affecting production.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 410-413 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Berry_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Initiation is a Fruit_Set comprising hormone-triggered ovary expansion, cell division activation in pericarp tissues, and irreversible commitment to berry formation following successful fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "berry development initiation | fruit formation start | ovary to berry transition | developmental commitment |+ Beeren-Initiierung | Beerenentwicklungs-Beginn | Fruchtbildungs-Start | Entwicklungs-Commitment",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows berry initiation during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-71, with auxin from 1.6-2.4 developing seeds triggering ovary expansion from 6 mm to 15-22 mm over 3 weeks, peak cell division producing berry flesh cells, pericarp differentiation into skin and flesh layers, developmental commitment establishing irreversible berry formation, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing initiation establishing berry developmental trajectory",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Initiation represents critical transition phase within Fruit_Set establishing berry development. ||Subdivided into Post_Fertilization_Signaling with hormone communication, Ovary_Expansion_Initiation beginning growth, Early_Berry_Formation establishing structure, and Berry_Commitment reaching irreversible state. ||Duration 2-4 weeks post-fertilization. ||Auxin from seeds primary trigger. ||Peak cell division determining berry flesh cellularity. ||Marks definitive shift to developmental phase. ||Resource allocation shifts to berries as dominant sink. ||Commitment establishes assured maturation. ||Determines berry developmental potential. || This essential transition phase occurs during early fruit development in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 2-4 weeks following fertilization as berry development begins, corresponding to BBCH 69-71 stages. ||Berry initiation encompasses coordinated processes including post-fertilization signaling with hormone production and transport from seeds to ovary, ovary expansion initiation with rapid growth beginning, early berry formation with tissue differentiation and structure establishment, and berry commitment reaching irreversible developmental state assured of maturation. ||Post-fertilization signaling shows auxin synthesis in developing embryo and endosperm beginning within days of fertilization, auxin export from seeds through seed coat and funiculus to ovary wall tissues, hormone accumulation in pericarp triggering growth responses, and additional signaling molecules including gibberellins and cytokinins possibly contributing to developmental activation. ||Auxin as primary signal shows indole-3-acetic acid as major form, hormone levels correlating with seed number and developmental activity, auxin perception in ovary wall cells triggering gene expression changes, and hormone as essential trigger for berry development initiation preventing flower abortion. ||Anti-abscission effect shows auxin blocking abscission zone formation at pedicel, hormone maintaining vascular connections supporting developing berry, and preventing programmed flower senescence pathway creating fruit retention. ||Growth-promoting effect shows auxin triggering cell division in ovary wall pericarp, stimulating cell expansion increasing tissue volume, activating biosynthetic pathways producing growth substrates, and overall hormone driving rapid berry enlargement. ||Ovary expansion characteristics show rapid growth from 4-8 mm pre-fertilization diameter to 10-20 mm within 2-3 weeks post-fertilization, volumetric increase 8-20 fold during first month, expansion rate peak during initiation period then declining, and visible berry formation confirming successful fruit set. ||Cell division during initiation shows peak mitotic activity in pericarp tissues, cycle times 10-15 hours during maximum division intensity, cell number increase determining berry flesh cellularity, division period lasting 3-4 weeks establishing final cell number affecting potential berry size, and transition to cell expansion phase following division period. ||Pericarp tissue organization shows differentiation into three layers including outer exocarp developing into berry skin, middle mesocarp forming bulk of berry flesh, and inner endocarp adjacent to seeds, with layer specialization proceeding during initiation period. ||Vascular development shows differentiation of vascular bundles in berry providing nutrient and water transport, xylem vessel formation enabling water import during growth, phloem development supporting sugar translocation during ripening, and vascular system establishment essential for berry development support. ||Early berry formation visible characteristics show green coloration from chlorophyll in skin and flesh, firm texture from active cell division and turgor, smooth appearance as surface cell division maintains coverage, and overall young berry appearance distinguishing from flowers or aborted structures. ||Berry developmental program activation shows transition from reproductive to developmental gene expression, upregulation of growth-promoting genes, activation of biosynthetic pathways for structural components, and establishment of developmental trajectory toward maturation. ||Metabolic activation shows increased respiratory rate supporting active growth, carbohydrate import and utilization providing energy and building blocks, nitrogen uptake and protein synthesis supporting tissue proliferation, and overall metabolic intensification characteristic of rapid growth phase. ||Berry commitment establishment shows developmental point beyond which berry development proceeds independently, commitment typically reached 2-3 weeks post-fertilization when expansion well established, berry capable of completing development to maturity barring severe stress or damage, and irreversible commitment distinguishing from pre-commitment flowers still capable of abortion. ||Commitment indicators include sustained berry expansion over multiple weeks, anatomical differentiation into recognizable berry structure, vascular development establishing permanent connections, and developmental gene expression programs fully activated. ||Resource allocation shift shows dramatic reallocation to developing berries consuming 40-60% total vine photosynthate, berries becoming dominant sink exceeding vegetative growth demands, resource competition between berries and shoots affecting growth balance, and berry sink strength increasing through initiation period. ||Sink strength characteristics show berry capacity to import and utilize resources, strength determined by cell number and metabolic activity, increasing sink strength establishing berries as priority allocation targets, and sink-source relationships affecting overall vine carbon balance. ||Berry number finalization shows fruit set percentage determined during initiation as abscission of unfertilized flowers completes, final berry count per cluster established by initiation completion, berry number per vine calculated from cluster counts and per-cluster berries, and yield potential determined by berry number and expected berry size. ||Environmental effects during initiation include temperature affecting expansion rate and cell division with optimal 20-28°C supporting rapid growth, water availability affecting cell expansion and turgor, nutrient supply particularly nitrogen supporting tissue synthesis, and overall favorable conditions during critical 2-4 week period supporting successful initiation. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting rapid berry expansion and development, cool conditions slowing but generally not preventing initiation, and temperature as major factor affecting initiation rate and timing. ||Water relations show adequate water essential for cell expansion and growth, water deficit potentially limiting berry enlargement, and irrigation sometimes beneficial during initiation in water-limited conditions. ||Failed berry initiation causes include inadequate hormone stimulus from failed seed development, environmental stress during critical period disrupting growth, resource limitations preventing growth response, or physiological dysfunction though rare after successful fertilization. ||The process encompasses four distinguishable aspects including post-fertilization signaling establishing hormone communication, ovary expansion initiation beginning growth, early berry formation establishing structure, and berry commitment reaching irreversible state. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 weeks from fertilization through commitment. ||Regional timing shows berry initiation during late June-early July in warm climates, early-mid July in temperate regions, and mid-late July in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical transition from reproduction to development establishing berry formation, requiring successful hormonal signaling and favorable growing conditions, demonstrating irreversible developmental commitment determining yield, and marking beginning of berry growth phase dominating vine resource allocation. ||Research applications include analyzing hormone signaling and berry development triggers, investigating cell division and expansion dynamics, evaluating environmental effects on initiation success and timing, quantifying resource allocation shifts during initiation, and assessing berry initiation as determinant of development and quality outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PPO_0007028 ## fruit developing stage | 0.70" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 415-425 || Mullins MG et al. (1992) Biology of the Grapevine, Cambridge University Press pp. 315-322 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Post_Fertilization_Signaling": {
  "definition": "A Post_Fertilization_Signaling is a Berry_Initiation involving auxin and hormone export from developing seeds to surrounding ovary tissues activating anti-abscission and growth-promoting pathways.",
  "alternative_term": "seed hormone signaling | auxin signaling | developmental signaling | seed-berry communication |+ Post-Fertilisations-Signalisierung | Samen-Hormon-Signalisierung | Auxin-Signalisierung | Samen-Beeren-Kommunikation",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Franc in Loire Valley shows post-fertilization signaling during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69, with auxin biosynthesis initiating in 1.4-2.2 developing seeds within 3-6 days of fertilization, hormone export to ovary wall tissues, auxin accumulation reaching 200-400 ng/g fresh weight in pericarp by 2 weeks post-fertilization, anti-abscission and growth-promoting responses triggered, under temperate maritime conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar establishing hormonal berry initiation",
  "editor_note": "Post_Fertilization_Signaling is first phase of Berry_Initiation, distinguished by hormone production and communication establishing seed-berry link. ||Begins within 2-5 days of fertilization. ||Auxin from embryo/endosperm as primary signal. ||Prevents abscission and triggers growth. ||Seed number affects total hormone dose. ||Peak signaling 1-3 weeks post-fertilization. ||Essential for berry development initiation. ||Followed by Ovary_Expansion_Initiation as growth response begins. ||Critical determinant of fruit set success. || This critical signaling phase occurs during early fruit set in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, beginning within 2-5 days of fertilization and continuing throughout early berry development, corresponding to BBCH 69 fertilization completion stages. ||Signaling establishment involves auxin biosynthesis in developing embryo and endosperm as primary hormone signal, auxin transport from seeds through seed coat and funiculus to ovary wall pericarp tissues, hormone accumulation in target tissues reaching threshold concentrations triggering responses, additional hormone production including gibberellins and cytokinins contributing to signaling network, and integrated hormone communication establishing seed-berry developmental coordination. ||Auxin biosynthesis in seeds shows indole-3-acetic acid synthesis beginning within 2-5 days of fertilization, biosynthetic enzymes activating in embryo and endosperm tissues, hormone production rate correlating with seed developmental activity, total auxin output proportional to seed number creating dose-dependent effects, and sustained production throughout early seed development supporting berry growth. ||Auxin synthesis pathways show tryptophan-dependent biosynthesis as major route, enzymatic conversion through indole-3-pyruvic acid intermediate, additional pathways potentially contributing, and overall synthesis capacity determining hormone availability. ||Auxin export from seeds shows hormone transport across seed coat integument layers, movement through funiculus vascular tissues connecting seed to ovary wall, diffusion into pericarp creating hormone gradient, and accumulation in ovary wall tissues particularly outer cell layers receiving highest concentrations. ||Auxin transport mechanisms show active polar transport through auxin efflux carriers, possible non-polar diffusion contributing to distribution, and directional movement from seed source to ovary sink tissues. ||Auxin accumulation in pericarp shows hormone levels increasing over days to weeks reaching physiologically effective concentrations, peak levels typically 1-3 weeks post-fertilization during maximum seed activity, spatial gradient with higher concentrations near seeds, and temporal dynamics correlating with berry growth rate. ||Auxin concentration effects show threshold levels required for growth responses, concentration-dependent magnitude of cell division and expansion responses, and seed number effects mediated through total auxin dose determining berry size potential. ||Anti-abscission signaling shows auxin as primary anti-senescence signal preventing flower drop, hormone blocking abscission zone formation at pedicel-receptacle junction, suppression of abscission-related gene expression including cell wall degrading enzymes, maintenance of vascular connections supporting berry nutrient supply, and overall rescue of flower from programmed senescence pathway. ||Abscission zone prevention mechanisms show auxin downregulating ethylene biosynthesis preventing senescence trigger, hormone maintaining cell wall integrity preventing separation layer formation, preservation of vascular tissue preventing resource cut-off, and sustained cell viability maintaining structural connection. ||Growth-promoting signaling shows auxin triggering cell cycle activation in quiescent pericarp cells, upregulation of cell division genes including cyclins and cyclin-dependent kinases, stimulation of cell expansion through wall loosening and water uptake, activation of biosynthetic pathways producing growth substrates, and overall growth response transforming static ovary into rapidly expanding berry. ||Auxin perception and response shows hormone binding to auxin receptors in ovary wall cells, receptor-mediated signaling cascades activating transcription factors, auxin-responsive gene expression producing growth regulators and metabolic enzymes, and integrated cellular response coordinating division and expansion. ||Gibberellin signaling contribution shows possible gibberellin synthesis in seeds complementing auxin, gibberellin effects on cell division and elongation, synergistic interactions with auxin enhancing growth responses, and hormone contributing to overall developmental program though less characterized than auxin in grapevine. ||Cytokinin signaling shows possible cytokinin production in seeds, hormone effects on cell division particularly in combination with auxin, and cytokinin contributing to growth signaling network though evidence limited in grapevine berry initiation. ||Seed number effects on signaling show direct relationship between seed number and total hormone production, multiple seeds producing greater cumulative hormone output, dose-dependent berry growth response to total auxin levels, and seed number as determinant of signaling intensity affecting berry size. ||Temporal signaling dynamics show signal initiation within days of fertilization, progressive increase in hormone levels over first 1-2 weeks, peak signaling during maximum seed developmental activity 1-3 weeks post-fertilization, gradual decline as seeds mature and berry growth slows, and signaling duration extending throughout berry development though intensity varies. ||Spatial signaling patterns show localized high concentrations near individual seeds, hormone gradients across pericarp from seed sources, and overall distribution affecting regional growth patterns within berry. ||Environmental effects on signaling include temperature affecting hormone biosynthesis rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting normal production, nutrient availability affecting seed development and hormone synthesis capacity, and overall favorable conditions supporting robust signaling. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster hormone production and stronger signaling, cool conditions slowing hormone synthesis potentially delaying berry growth initiation, and temperature as factor affecting signaling intensity and timing. ||Failed signaling causes include inadequate seed development preventing hormone production, abnormal hormone biosynthesis or transport, insufficient hormone accumulation below threshold levels, or seed abortion eliminating hormone source causing delayed berry abortion. ||Signaling assessment methods include hormone quantification in seeds and pericarp through analytical chemistry, gene expression analysis showing auxin-responsive genes, and growth response observation indicating successful signaling. ||The process represents first phase of berry initiation establishing hormonal communication, preceding ovary expansion initiation as growth begins. ||Duration begins within days of fertilization and continues throughout early berry development with peak 1-3 weeks post-fertilization. ||Cultivar variation may include hormone production capacity, signaling efficiency, and response sensitivity. ||Regional timing shows post-fertilization signaling beginning late June-early July across climates within days following fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential seed-berry communication mechanism, requiring successful seed development for hormone production, demonstrating critical role of auxin in fruit set and development, and establishing signaling as prerequisite for berry growth preventing flower abortion. ||Research applications include analyzing hormone biosynthesis and transport mechanisms, investigating auxin and other hormone roles in berry initiation, evaluating seed number effects on hormone levels and berry growth, quantifying signaling dynamics and dose-response relationships, and assessing signaling as determinant of fruit set and berry development outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 415-418 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Ovary_Expansion_Initiation": {
  "definition": "An Ovary_Expansion_Initiation is a Berry_Initiation comprising auxin-triggered cell division and expansion in the pericarp producing ovary enlargement from 4–8 mm to 10–20 mm diameter.",
  "alternative_term": "rapid berry growth | ovary enlargement | berry expansion start | initial berry growth |+ Ovar-Expansions-Initiierung | schnelles Beerenwachstum | Ovarvergrößerung | initiales Beerenwachstum",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows ovary expansion initiation during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-71, with fertilized ovaries expanding from 5-7 mm to 14-18 mm diameter over 18-26 days, peak cell division intensity with 12-14 hour cycle times during weeks 2-3, cell expansion through water uptake contributing to volumetric increase, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing initial expansion establishing berry developmental trajectory",
  "editor_note": "Ovary_Expansion_Initiation is second phase of Berry_Initiation, distinguished by rapid growth response to hormonal signals. ||Represents 8-20 fold volumetric increase over 1-3 weeks from 4-8mm to 10-20mm diameter. ||Peak cell division 10-15h cycles establishing final cell number in 3-4 weeks. ||Temperature strongly affects rate. ||Water essential for expansion. ||Visible growth confirms fruit set. ||Follows Post_Fertilization_Signaling. ||Precedes Early_Berry_Formation. ||Determines berry size potential through cell number establishment. || This dramatic growth phase occurs during early fruit development in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-3 weeks following fertilization as growth accelerates, corresponding to BBCH 69-71 stages. ||Expansion mechanism involves auxin-triggered cell cycle reentry in quiescent pericarp cells activating mitotic division, cell expansion through water uptake and wall loosening increasing cell volume, coordinated tissue growth across all pericarp layers, vascular development supporting resource delivery, and overall rapid volumetric increase 8-20 fold during first month post-fertilization. ||Initial ovary size shows pre-fertilization diameter typically 4-8 mm in grapevine flowers, static size during flowering period, and expansion beginning within days of successful fertilization as hormone signaling establishes. ||Expansion dynamics show initial slower growth during first week as signaling establishes and cells activate, acceleration during second and third weeks with peak expansion rates, volumetric increase typically reaching 10-20 mm diameter within 2-3 weeks, and 8-20 fold volume increase during first month representing dramatic transformation. ||Growth rate characteristics show peak expansion rate 1-3 mm diameter increase per week during maximum growth phase, linear or exponential growth patterns depending on measurement and timing, temperature-dependent rate with warm conditions accelerating expansion, and growth rate eventually declining as cell division phase completes transitioning to slower expansion-dominated phase. ||Cell division contribution to expansion shows mitotic activity initiating in pericarp cells within days of auxin signal, peak division intensity during first 2-4 weeks with cycle times 10-15 hours, progressive cell number increase creating berry flesh cellularity, final cell number established within 3-4 weeks determining potential berry size, and division phase completion marking transition to expansion-dominated growth. ||Cell division spatial patterns show divisions throughout pericarp layers including exocarp skin precursors, abundant divisions in mesocarp creating bulk flesh tissue, divisions in endocarp adjacent to seeds, and coordinated division across layers producing organized tissue structure. ||Cell expansion contribution shows cells enlarging through water uptake driven by osmotic gradient, cell wall loosening enabling expansion through enzymatic modification, turgor pressure driving cell enlargement against yielding walls, and progressive cell volume increase contributing substantially to berry growth especially after division phase. ||Water uptake dynamics show xylem-mediated water import during early growth, osmotic gradient from solute accumulation driving water influx, and water as major component of expanding berry typically 75-85% fresh weight. ||Cell wall modification enabling expansion shows enzymatic loosening through expansins and other wall-modifying proteins, pectin and hemicellulose degradation creating wall plasticity, cellulose microfibril reorientation allowing expansion, and new wall synthesis maintaining integrity during enlargement. ||Tissue organization during expansion shows coordinated growth maintaining berry structural integrity, proportional expansion across pericarp layers, vascular tissue development keeping pace with berry enlargement, and overall organized growth producing functional berry architecture. ||Vascular development shows differentiation of vascular bundles within berry providing nutrient and water transport pathways, xylem vessel formation enabling water delivery supporting expansion, phloem development preparing for sugar import during ripening, and branching vascular network establishing throughout pericarp. ||Metabolic support for expansion shows increased respiratory rate providing ATP for biosynthesis and active transport, carbohydrate import from vine providing energy and building materials, nitrogen uptake supporting protein synthesis for new cells and membranes, and overall metabolic intensification characteristic of rapid growth. ||Resource import pathways show vascular connections from pedicel delivering water, nutrients, and photosynthates, developing berry as strong sink attracting resources, and import capacity increasing with berry size and metabolic demand. ||Visible expansion confirmation shows berry diameter measurably increasing over days to weeks, green berry clearly distinguishable from static unfertilized flowers, and visible growth providing definitive fruit set confirmation. ||Berry shape establishment shows spherical to ovoid morphology developing during expansion, cultivar-characteristic shape emerging during early growth, and shape largely determined during expansion phase. ||Environmental effects on expansion include temperature critically affecting growth rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid expansion, water availability affecting cell expansion and turgor, nutrient supply supporting tissue synthesis, and overall favorable conditions during critical 2-3 week period maximizing expansion. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting rapid expansion completing 10-20 mm growth within 2 weeks, cool conditions slowing expansion potentially requiring 3-4 weeks, and temperature as major factor affecting expansion rate and timing. ||Water relations show adequate water essential for cell expansion and turgor maintenance, water deficit potentially limiting berry enlargement, and irrigation sometimes beneficial during expansion in water-limited environments. ||Failed or delayed expansion causes include inadequate hormone signaling from poor seed development, environmental stress during critical period limiting growth capacity, water or nutrient deficiency preventing growth response, or physiological dysfunction though rare after successful signaling. ||Expansion as fruit set indicator shows successful expansion confirming fruit set, measurable growth distinguishing set berries from aborted flowers, and expansion observation used for early yield estimation. ||The process represents second phase of berry initiation showing growth response to hormonal signals, following post-fertilization signaling and preceding early berry formation. ||Duration typically 1-3 weeks of rapid initial expansion though growth continues at declining rate. ||Cultivar variation includes expansion rate, final berry size potential, and temperature sensitivity. ||Regional timing shows ovary expansion initiation during late June-early July in warm climates, early-mid July in temperate regions, and mid-late July in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes providing visible fruit set confirmation, determining berry size through cell number and expansion, demonstrating critical temperature and water sensitivity, and establishing berry developmental trajectory affecting final yield and quality. ||Research applications include analyzing expansion mechanisms and growth dynamics, investigating cell division and expansion coordination, evaluating environmental effects on expansion rate and success, quantifying growth patterns and berry size determinants, and assessing expansion as fruit set and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 418-422 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Early_Berry_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Early_Berry_Formation is a Berry_Initiation consisting of pericarp differentiation into exocarp, mesocarp, and endocarp layers with vascular network establishment and photosynthetically active green tissue development.",
  "alternative_term": "berry structure development | pericarp differentiation | young berry organization | berry architecture establishment |+ frühe Beerenbildung | Beerenstruktur-Entwicklung | Perikarp-Differenzierung | Beeren-Architektur-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows early berry formation during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 71, with pericarp differentiating into 8-10 cell layer exocarp skin, abundant mesocarp flesh cells, and 2-3 cell layer endocarp, vascular network ramifying through tissues, chlorophyll content reaching 0.8-1.2 mg/g fresh weight creating green photosynthetic berry, berry diameter 14-20 mm, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar establishing functional berry structure",
  "editor_note": "Early_Berry_Formation is third phase of Berry_Initiation, distinguished by structural organization and tissue differentiation. ||Represents pericarp differentiation into exocarp, mesocarp, endocarp layers. ||Vascular development establishes transport network. ||Chlorophyll accumulation creates photosynthetic green berry. ||Duration 2-3 weeks overlapping with expansion. ||Establishes functional berry architecture. ||Follows Ovary_Expansion_Initiation. ||Precedes Berry_Commitment. ||Determines berry structural foundation affecting quality. || This essential organization phase occurs during early fruit development in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 2-3 weeks as berry structure establishes, corresponding to BBCH 71 young fruit stages. ||Berry formation encompasses coordinated processes including pericarp tissue differentiation creating specialized layers, vascular system development establishing transport infrastructure, cellular organization producing functional tissue architecture, chlorophyll accumulation creating green photosynthetic berry, and structural maturation preparing berry for subsequent developmental phases. ||Pericarp differentiation shows subdivision into three distinct tissue layers with specific functions, differentiation proceeding during early expansion phase, and layer specialization establishing by 3-4 weeks post-fertilization. ||Exocarp outer layer development shows formation of future berry skin from outer pericarp cells, cell division producing epidermal and subepidermal layers, chloroplast development creating green coloration, cuticle formation beginning waxy surface protection, and specialized cell types differentiating including future stomata though functionality declining later. ||Exocarp characteristics show typically 6-12 cell layers thick in young berry, actively photosynthetic during early development contributing 5-15% berry carbon requirements, protective barrier function against pathogens and water loss, and eventual transformation during ripening to colored skin. ||Mesocarp middle layer development shows formation of bulk berry flesh tissue from middle pericarp region, extensive cell division producing abundant flesh cells, cell enlargement through water uptake creating juicy tissue, vascular tissue ramification throughout mesocarp, and structural organization creating functional flesh capable of storage and expansion. ||Mesocarp characteristics show representing 80-90% berry volume in mature fruit, cells containing vacuoles storing water and eventually sugars acids and other compounds, tissue providing major storage capacity for ripening compounds, and architecture determining berry texture and quality. ||Endocarp inner layer development shows formation of seed cavity lining from inner pericarp adjacent to developing seeds, thinner layer compared to mesocarp typically 2-4 cell layers, specialized cells possibly providing seed-pericarp communication, and protective function surrounding developing seeds. ||Vascular system development shows differentiation of xylem and phloem bundles within berry, primary vasculature entering through pedicel and receptacle, branching vascular network ramifying through mesocarp reaching exocarp, xylem providing water and mineral delivery during growth, and phloem preparing for sugar import during ripening though initially less active. ||Vascular architecture shows major bundles in receptacle region distributing to berry tissues, radial branches extending through mesocarp toward skin, anastomosing network creating redundant pathways, and terminal endings providing local resource delivery. ||Xylem function during early formation shows active water import supporting cell expansion, mineral nutrient delivery providing essential elements, and xylem-mediated import dominating during growth phase before phloem activation. ||Chlorophyll accumulation shows chloroplast development in exocarp and outer mesocarp cells, chlorophyll synthesis creating green coloration characteristic of young berries, photosynthetic capacity developing contributing to berry carbon economy, maximum chlorophyll content typically 2-4 weeks post-fertilization, and eventual chlorophyll degradation during ripening revealing anthocyanin colors in red cultivars or carotenoid yellows in white cultivars. ||Berry photosynthesis characteristics show young green berries photosynthetically active with measurable CO2 fixation, photosynthesis contributing 5-15% berry carbon requirements supplementing vine import, activity highest in young berries declining as ripening approaches, and eventual cessation as chlorophyll degrades. ||Cellular organization shows coordinated cell arrangement within tissues, cell-cell communication through plasmodesmata enabling signaling, tissue cohesion maintaining structural integrity, and organized architecture supporting berry function. ||Cell wall characteristics show primary walls in young dividing cells enabling continued division, progressive wall thickening as cells mature, pectin-rich middle lamella between cells maintaining tissue cohesion, and wall properties affecting berry texture. ||Tissue mechanical properties show firm texture in young berry from active turgor and cell wall integrity, mechanical strength from organized cellular architecture, and structural capacity to support continued expansion and development. ||Berry appearance characteristics show green coloration from chlorophyll, smooth surface from active epidermal cell division, firm texture from turgor, spherical to ovoid shape, and overall young berry morphology distinct from flowers. ||Berry size at formation completion shows typical diameter 12-25 mm by 3-4 weeks post-fertilization depending on cultivar and conditions, size range reflecting seed number effects and environmental variation, and size at this stage indicating developmental progress. ||Environmental effects on berry formation include temperature affecting differentiation and development rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting normal progression, nutrient availability affecting tissue synthesis particularly nitrogen for protein, light possibly influencing chlorophyll content and photosynthesis, and overall favorable conditions supporting organized development. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster differentiation and structure establishment, cool conditions slowing but generally not preventing formation, and temperature as factor affecting formation timing. ||Nutrient effects show nitrogen essential for protein synthesis in dividing and differentiating cells, phosphorus and potassium supporting metabolism, and micronutrients enabling enzymatic functions. ||Failed formation causes include inadequate cell division limiting tissue development, environmental stress disrupting differentiation, developmental abnormalities preventing proper organization, though failures rare after successful expansion initiation. ||The process represents third phase of berry initiation establishing functional structure, following ovary expansion initiation and preceding berry commitment. ||Duration typically 2-3 weeks though overlapping with expansion. ||Cultivar variation includes pericarp layer thickness ratios, vascular architecture patterns, and structural characteristics affecting berry quality. ||Regional timing shows early berry formation during early-mid July across climates as berry structure establishes. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing berry functional architecture determining quality potential, creating photosynthetic capacity contributing to carbon economy, developing vascular system supporting continued development, and producing recognizable berry structure distinguishing from flowers. ||Research applications include analyzing pericarp differentiation mechanisms and tissue specialization, investigating vascular development and architecture, evaluating environmental effects on structural formation, quantifying berry photosynthesis contributions, and assessing berry formation as quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 420-425 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Berry_Commitment": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Commitment is a Berry_Initiation marked by the developmental state of autonomous maturation capacity with full berry developmental program activated.",
  "alternative_term": "developmental commitment | irreversible berry development | berry development assurance | fruit set completion |+ Beeren-Commitment | Entwicklungs-Verpflichtung | irreversible Beerenentwicklung | Fruchtansatz-Vollendung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows berry commitment during mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 71, with berries reaching commitment at 16-22 mm diameter 22-32 days post-fertilization, pericarp differentiation completed, vascular system established, developmental program fully activated, sink strength securing 45-58% photosynthate allocation, irreversible development assured, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar achieving commitment establishing secure fruit set and yield potential",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Commitment is fourth and final phase of Berry_Initiation, distinguished by irreversible developmental decision point. ||Represents achievement of assured maturation capacity typically 2-4 weeks post-fertilization at 12-25mm diameter. ||Involves structural completion, developmental program activation, sink strength establishment. ||Marks transition from vulnerable initiation to secure development. ||Post-commitment abortion rate <5%. ||Determines final berry number and yield. ||Completes Fruit_Set process. ||Transitions to Berry_Development phase. ||Critical fruit set completion indicator. || This critical commitment point occurs during fruit development in early-mid July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically reached 2-4 weeks post-fertilization as berry initiation completes, corresponding to BBCH 71 young fruit stages. ||Commitment establishment involves attainment of critical berry size typically 12-25 mm diameter indicating successful expansion, completion of pericarp tissue differentiation creating functional structure, vascular system establishment providing autonomous resource access, developmental gene expression program full activation establishing self-sustaining development, sink strength establishment securing resource allocation priority, and overall irreversible state where berry development proceeds to maturity unless prevented by severe damage or environmental catastrophe. ||Critical size achievement shows berry diameter 12-25 mm representing threshold beyond which development typically assured, size reflecting successful cell division and expansion phases, critical mass providing metabolic and structural foundation for continued development, and size as indicator of commitment though not sole determinant. ||Critical size variation shows cultivar differences with small-berried cultivars reaching commitment at 12-15 mm and large-berried cultivars requiring 20-25 mm, environmental effects on size with favorable conditions enabling smaller commitment size, and size-independent commitment factors including developmental state. ||Structural organization completion shows pericarp layers fully differentiated into functional exocarp, mesocarp, endocarp, vascular network established providing resource delivery capacity, cellular architecture organized supporting mechanical integrity and metabolic function, and structural maturation creating berry capable of supporting continued expansion and ripening. ||Developmental program activation shows transition from initiation to committed development gene expression, upregulation of developmental regulators maintaining berry growth trajectory, activation of metabolic pathways preparing for ripening including sugar metabolism and secondary compound synthesis precursors, and establishment of developmental program resistant to reversal. ||Gene expression characteristics show berry-specific transcriptional programs fully activated, growth-promoting genes maintaining expansion though rate declining, developmental timing genes initiating countdown toward ripening, and integrated gene networks establishing autonomous development. ||Sink strength establishment shows berry developing strong resource allocation priority competing effectively with vegetative growth, sink strength from metabolic demand and vascular connections, berries securing 40-60% total vine photosynthate allocation, and sink priority ensuring resource delivery supporting development. ||Sink strength mechanisms show high metabolic activity creating demand, abundant cell number providing consumption capacity, vascular connections enabling resource import, and hormonal signals possibly enhancing sink status. ||Developmental autonomy characteristics show berry development proceeding largely independently of ongoing seed development after commitment, berry capable of completing ripening even with seed abortion though seed presence beneficial, and autonomous capacity indicating commitment to berry rather than flower fate. ||Irreversibility indicators show berry development continuing despite environmental fluctuations within tolerable range, resistance to developmental reversal or abortion after commitment, and assured progression to maturity barring catastrophic events. ||Commitment timing shows typical achievement 2-4 weeks post-fertilization depending on cultivar and conditions, earlier commitment at 2-3 weeks under favorable warm conditions with rapid development, delayed commitment at 3-5 weeks under cool conditions or slow development, and timing reflecting cumulative developmental progress rather than fixed schedule. ||Pre-commitment vulnerability shows berries before commitment susceptible to abortion from stress, environmental extremes potentially causing berry drop, developmental failure possible from inadequate resources or hormonal support, and uncommitted berries representing tentative fruit set. ||Post-commitment stability shows committed berries resistant to abortion unless severely stressed, development proceeding reliably under normal to moderately challenging conditions, and commitment representing secure fruit set determining final yield. ||Commitment assessment methods include observation of continued berry development over weeks confirming commitment, measurement of berry size and growth rate indicating progress toward commitment, gene expression analysis showing committed developmental programs, and population-level berry retention indicating commitment achievement. ||Berry retention after commitment shows very low abortion rate <5% in committed berries under normal conditions, retention reflecting developmental assurance, and committed berry number determining final yield barring harvest losses. ||Environmental effects during commitment establishment include temperature affecting developmental rate and commitment timing with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid commitment achievement within 2-3 weeks, water availability affecting berry growth and commitment through expansion effects, nutrient supply supporting metabolic demands, and overall favorable conditions during critical period ensuring successful commitment. ||Temperature as major factor shows warm conditions accelerating commitment through faster development, cool conditions delaying commitment through slower progression, and temperature affecting timing rather than commitment capacity under normal ranges. ||Water stress effects show severe deficit potentially delaying commitment through limited expansion, adequate water supporting normal commitment timing, and water as factor affecting commitment timing and berry size. ||Failed commitment causes include inadequate early development preventing threshold achievement, severe environmental stress during critical period arresting development, seed abortion after initial development eliminating hormonal support in some cases, or physiological dysfunction though rare after successful initiation. ||Commitment as yield determinant shows committed berry number establishing final berry count per vine, berry number combined with berry size determining total yield, and commitment as definitive fruit set confirmation for yield prediction. ||The process represents fourth and final phase of berry initiation marking irreversible development, following early berry formation. ||Duration represents achieving commitment point typically 2-4 weeks post-fertilization. ||Cultivar variation includes commitment timing, size threshold, and developmental characteristics. ||Regional timing shows berry commitment during early-mid July in warm climates, mid July in temperate regions, and mid-late July in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes marking assured fruit set determining final yield, establishing berry development as irreversible and secure, demonstrating successful fruit set completion, and providing definitive basis for yield prediction and crop management. ||Research applications include analyzing commitment mechanisms and determinants, investigating developmental programs establishing commitment, evaluating environmental effects on commitment timing and success, quantifying commitment indicators and thresholds, and assessing commitment as fruit set and yield determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 422-430 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Initial_Berry_Growth": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Berry_Growth is a Berry_Initiation comprising intensive cell division establishing final cell number followed by cell-expansion-dominated growth determining berry size potential, extending from fruit set through onset of the lag phase.",
  "alternative_term": "early berry development | young fruit growth | berry expansion phase | initial berry enlargement |+ initiales Beerenwachstum | frühe Beerenentwicklung | Jungfrucht-Wachstum | Beeren-Expansionsphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows initial berry growth during mid July-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 71-75, with intensive cell division weeks 0-4 establishing 2.2-3.4 million mesocarp cells, rapid expansion weeks 3-6 increasing diameter from 14mm to 12-15mm final size, berry weight reaching 4.8-7.2g by week 7-8, under warm climate conditions of 24-32°C temperature, adequate irrigation supporting expansion, typical of this late-season large-berried cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Berry_Growth represents critical early development phase within Fruit_Set establishing berry size. ||Subdivided into Early_Cell_Division_Growth establishing cell number, Rapid_Initial_Expansion combining division and expansion, and Berry_Size_Establishment completing growth. ||Duration 4-8 weeks post-commitment. ||Cell number determined in 3-4 weeks is major size determinant. ||Temperature and water strongly affect growth and final size. ||Completes berry structural development. ||Precedes lag phase and ripening. ||Determines berry size potential affecting yield and quality. || This critical early growth phase occurs during summer in July-August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 4-8 weeks post-fertilization depending on cultivar and conditions, corresponding to BBCH 71-75 young fruit to pea-sized berry stages. ||Initial growth encompasses coordinated processes including early cell division growth with intensive mitotic activity producing berry flesh cells, rapid initial expansion with volumetric increase through cell enlargement and water uptake, berry size establishment determining final berry dimensions, and overall growth creating berry architecture capable of supporting ripening transformation. ||Growth dynamics show characteristic sigmoid pattern with rapid initial growth during cell division phase weeks 0-4, continued expansion during cell enlargement phase weeks 4-8, and eventual growth rate decline entering lag phase as berries approach final size. ||Cell division phase characteristics show peak mitotic activity during first 3-4 weeks post-fertilization, cell cycle times 10-15 hours during maximum division intensity, progressive cell number increase throughout mesocarp flesh tissue, and final cell number established by 3-4 weeks determining potential berry size. ||Cell number determination shows total mesocarp cells established during division phase, typical range 1-4 million cells per berry depending on cultivar and conditions, cell number as major determinant of final berry size with more cells enabling larger berries, and cell number influenced by seed number through auxin dose effects, temperature affecting division rate, and genetic programming. ||Cell expansion phase characteristics show transition from division to expansion-dominated growth around week 3-4, progressive cell enlargement through water uptake and vacuole expansion, cells increasing volume 10-100 fold from division completion to maturity, and expansion continuing through ripening though rate varying. ||Growth rate dynamics show maximum absolute growth rate during weeks 2-4 when both division and expansion active, peak relative growth rate often earlier during maximum division intensity, progressive growth rate decline as cell division completes, and eventually very low growth rate during lag phase before veraison. ||Berry size increase shows diameter expanding from 12-25 mm at commitment to 6-10 mm diameter in small-berried cultivars or 12-18 mm in large-berried cultivars by initial growth completion around week 6-8, volumetric increase 3-8 fold during initial growth phase, and size at lag phase entry largely predicting final berry size. ||Fresh weight accumulation shows berry weight increasing from 0.5-2 g at commitment to 2-8 g in small-berried or 5-15 g in large-berried cultivars by lag phase, weight accumulation rate 50-200 mg per day during peak growth, and fresh weight as convenient growth measurement. ||Dry matter accumulation shows progressive dry matter increase during growth, dry matter percentage relatively stable 12-18% during growth phase, and dry matter representing structural components and stored reserves. ||Water uptake characteristics show water as major component of berry expansion typically 80-85% fresh weight, xylem-mediated water import during early growth supporting rapid expansion, osmotic gradient from accumulating solutes driving water influx, and water relations critical for normal berry enlargement. ||Metabolic characteristics show high respiratory rate during active growth consuming 2-4% dry weight per day, carbohydrate import from vine providing energy and carbon skeletons, nitrogen uptake supporting protein synthesis for new cells and enzymes, and overall intensive metabolism supporting rapid growth. ||Resource requirements show berries consuming 40-60% total vine photosynthate during initial growth, competition between berry growth and vegetative growth affecting resource allocation, and adequate resource supply essential for achieving genetic size potential. ||Seed development coordination shows seeds developing in parallel with berry growth, seed size increase correlating with berry expansion, auxin production from seeds continuing to support berry growth though declining after peak weeks 2-3, and seed-berry coordination ensuring synchronized development. ||Environmental effects on initial growth include temperature critically affecting growth rate with optimal 22-30°C supporting maximum growth, water availability affecting cell expansion and final size, nutrient supply particularly nitrogen affecting cell division and growth capacity, light possibly affecting photosynthate supply though indirect effect, and overall favorable conditions maximizing size achievement. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting rapid growth completing initial phase within 4-6 weeks, cool conditions extending initial growth to 6-10 weeks, and temperature as major factor affecting growth rate and size achievement. ||Water effects show adequate water essential for cell expansion particularly during rapid growth weeks 2-6, water deficit limiting berry enlargement potentially reducing final size 20-40%, and irrigation beneficial in water-limited environments during this critical period. ||Nutrient effects show nitrogen supporting cell division and protein synthesis, potassium affecting water relations and turgor, and overall balanced nutrition supporting optimal growth. ||Cultivar variation shows genetic differences in cell division capacity affecting cell number and size potential, growth rate variation affecting initial growth duration, and final size range from 6mm small berries to 18mm large berries reflecting genetic programming. ||The process shows three distinguishable phases progressing from early cell division growth during weeks 0-4 establishing cell number, through rapid initial expansion during weeks 3-6 combining division and expansion, to berry size establishment during weeks 5-8 completing initial growth. ||Duration typically 4-8 weeks from commitment through lag phase onset. ||Regional timing shows initial berry growth during July-August in warm climates, mid July-early September in temperate regions, and late July-mid September in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final cell number determining berry size potential, requiring optimal environmental conditions particularly temperature and water for maximum size achievement, demonstrating critical period for berry development affecting quality and yield, and completing berry structural development preparing for ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing cell division and expansion dynamics, investigating environmental and genetic factors affecting growth and size, evaluating resource allocation and berry-vine competition, quantifying growth patterns and berry size determinants, and assessing initial growth as quality and yield determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 430-445 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Early_Cell_Division_Growth": {
  "definition": "An Early_Cell_Division_Growth is an Initial_Berry_Growth consisting of intensive mitotic activity in pericarp mesocarp cells establishing final cell number, extending over the first 3–4 weeks post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "berry cell proliferation | intensive mitotic phase | cell number establishment | early division phase |+ frühe Zellteilungs-Wachstum | Beeren-Zellproliferation | intensive mitotische Phase | Zellzahl-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows early cell division growth during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 71-73, with peak mitotic activity weeks 1-3 post-fertilization, cell cycle times 11-14 hours, progressive accumulation reaching 1.8-2.6 million mesocarp cells by week 4, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, 1.6-2.2 seeds per berry supporting division through auxin, typical of this mid-season cultivar establishing cell number determining 10-13mm final berry size",
  "editor_note": "Early_Cell_Division_Growth is first phase of Initial_Berry_Growth, distinguished by intensive mitotic activity establishing final cell number. ||Duration 2-4 weeks with peak weeks 1-3. ||Cell cycle times 10-15 hours during maximum activity. ||Final cell number 1-4 million determining 60-80% size variation. ||Temperature and seed number major determinants. ||Division completion by week 4. ||Irreversible cell number establishment. ||Precedes Rapid_Initial_Expansion. ||Critical phase for berry size potential. || This critical cell proliferation phase occurs during early summer in late June-July in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 2-4 weeks from berry commitment, corresponding to BBCH 71-73 young fruit stages. ||Cell division growth mechanism involves auxin-stimulated cell cycle activation in mesocarp tissue, peak mitotic activity with rapid cell proliferation, progressive cell number accumulation throughout pericarp layers, and division completion establishing final cell population determining berry flesh cellularity and size potential. ||Mitotic activity characteristics show maximum division intensity during weeks 1-3 post-fertilization, cell cycle times 10-15 hours during peak activity representing very rapid division, multiple rounds of division per initial cell producing clonal populations, and progressive division rate decline toward week 4 as cells transition to expansion mode. ||Cell cycle regulation shows cyclin-dependent kinases driving cell cycle progression, checkpoint controls ensuring DNA replication and chromosome segregation fidelity, auxin and gibberellin signaling promoting division, and eventual cell cycle exit as cells commit to expansion. ||Cell division spatial patterns show divisions occurring throughout mesocarp tissue creating flesh cells, more intensive division in outer mesocarp regions compared to inner areas near seeds in some studies, coordinated division across pericarp maintaining tissue proportions, and exocarp skin cells also dividing though less intensively than mesocarp. ||Cell number accumulation shows exponential increase during peak division weeks 1-3, typical accumulation from initial ~50,000-100,000 cells at commitment to 1-4 million cells by division completion, final cell number range reflecting cultivar genetic variation and environmental effects, and cell number as critical determinant of berry size. ||Cell number measurement methods include cell counting through tissue dissociation and microscopy, DNA content analysis estimating cell number, and histological section analysis though technically challenging. ||Final cell number determinants show genetic programming as primary factor with cultivar characteristic ranges, seed number effects through auxin dose influencing division intensity and duration, temperature affecting division rate with warm conditions promoting more divisions, and overall favorable conditions during critical 3-4 week period maximizing cell number. ||Seed number effects on cell division show positive correlation between seed number and final berry cell number, multiple seeds producing greater total auxin stimulating more intensive division, typical 20-40% more cells in 3-seed versus 1-seed berries, and auxin dose-response relationship explaining seed number effects on berry size. ||Temperature effects on division show optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum division rate and cell number achievement, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing division potentially reducing final cell number 15-30%, warm conditions 28-32°C potentially accelerating division though excessive heat above 35°C may impair division, and temperature during critical weeks 1-4 as major cell number determinant. ||Nutrient effects show nitrogen essential for protein synthesis supporting rapid division, phosphorus for DNA synthesis and energy metabolism, and adequate mineral nutrition supporting optimal division though usually not limiting in vineyard conditions. ||Division completion timing shows progressive transition from division to expansion beginning around week 3, division largely complete by week 4 in most cells, occasional continued division in some cell populations extending to week 5-6, and division cessation marking transition to expansion-dominated growth phase. ||Cell number as size determinant shows strong correlation between final cell number and mature berry size, more cells providing greater expansion capacity, typical 60-80% berry size variation attributable to cell number differences, and cell number established during early weeks determining size potential regardless of subsequent expansion. ||Cell size at division completion shows cells relatively small typically 20-40 micrometers diameter at division exit, cells capable of 10-100 fold volume expansion during subsequent enlargement, and initial small cell size enabling efficient packing in growing berry. ||Division phase versus expansion phase contribution shows cell number (division product) accounting for 60-80% final size variation, cell expansion accounting for 20-40% final size variation, and division phase as more critical determinant emphasizing importance of early favorable conditions. ||Cultivar variation in division capacity shows genetic differences in maximum cell number potential, small-berried cultivars typically 0.8-1.5 million cells achieving 6-8mm final diameter, large-berried cultivars 2.5-4 million cells achieving 14-18mm diameter, and genetic programming as primary cell number determinant. ||Environmental limitations on division show suboptimal temperature or water stress during critical early weeks permanently reducing cell number, lost division potential irreversible with later favorable conditions unable to compensate, and early environment as critical determinant of size potential. ||The process represents first phase of initial berry growth emphasizing cell proliferation, preceding rapid initial expansion and berry size establishment. ||Duration typically 2-4 weeks representing peak division though declining activity continues to week 4-5. ||Regional timing shows early cell division growth during late June-July in warm climates, early-mid July in temperate regions, and mid-late July in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final cell number as major berry size determinant, demonstrating critical importance of favorable conditions during early weeks for size potential, showing irreversible nature of early development affecting final outcomes, and emphasizing early environment as quality and yield determinant. ||Research applications include analyzing cell division regulation and controls, investigating auxin and hormone effects on division, evaluating temperature and environmental effects on cell number, quantifying cell number as size determinant, and assessing division phase as berry quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 432-438 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Rapid_Initial_Expansion": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Initial_Expansion is an Initial_Berry_Growth comprising concurrent cell division and accelerating cell expansion producing maximum berry growth rate, extending over weeks 3–6 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "peak berry expansion | maximum growth phase | combined division-expansion | transitional growth |+ schnelle initiale Expansion | Spitzen-Beerenausdehnung | maximale Wachstumsphase | kombinierte Teilungs-Expansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows rapid initial expansion during mid-late July Year N+1 at BBCH 73-75, with overlapping cell division declining and cell expansion accelerating weeks 3-5, peak growth rate 85-145 mg per day, berry diameter increasing from 13mm to 10-12mm final size, water uptake 0.8-1.4 g per berry per day, under cool maritime conditions of 19-25°C temperature, adequate summer rainfall supporting expansion, typical of this early-bursting cultivar completing rapid growth",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Initial_Expansion is second phase of Initial_Berry_Growth, distinguished by overlapping division and expansion creating peak growth. ||Duration 3-4 weeks representing transition period. ||Maximum growth rate 50-200 mg/day. ||Water uptake critical driver of expansion. ||Berry expands 3-6 fold volumetrically. ||Temperature and water strongly affect rate and size. ||Follows Early_Cell_Division_Growth. ||Precedes Berry_Size_Establishment. ||Represents majority of size achievement. || This peak growth phase occurs during mid summer in July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 3-4 weeks during maximum growth intensity, corresponding to BBCH 73-75 pea-sized to berry touch stages. ||Expansion mechanism involves overlapping processes with declining cell division continuing through week 4-5, accelerating cell expansion through water uptake and vacuole enlargement, synergistic growth from simultaneous division and expansion, and maximum volumetric increase rate during this transitional period. ||Growth rate characteristics show peak absolute growth rate typically 50-200 mg fresh weight per day during weeks 3-5, maximum diameter increase rate 1-2 mm per week during peak period, volumetric growth rate 0.3-1.0 mL per day in large-berried cultivars, and growth rate representing combined division and expansion contributions. ||Combined division-expansion dynamics show cell division continuing though declining during weeks 3-4, cell expansion accelerating as cells complete division and enlarge, overlapping processes creating synergistic maximum growth, and transition to expansion-only growth by week 5-6. ||Cell expansion mechanisms show water uptake as primary driver of cell enlargement, osmotic gradient from solute accumulation pulling water into cells, vacuole expansion accounting for majority of cell volume increase, cell wall loosening through enzymatic modification enabling expansion, and turgor pressure driving cell enlargement against yielding walls. ||Water uptake dynamics show xylem-mediated water import during early expansion, water flux rates 0.5-2.0 g water per berry per day during peak uptake, water comprising 80-85% berry fresh weight during growth, and water availability critically affecting expansion rate and berry size. ||Cell wall modification enabling expansion shows expansin proteins mediating wall loosening, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase rearranging wall polymers, pectin methylesterase modifying pectin properties, progressive wall loosening enabling cell expansion, and new wall synthesis maintaining integrity during enlargement. ||Vacuole development shows central vacuole formation and expansion in expanding cells, vacuole occupying 80-90% cell volume at expansion completion, vacuole as major storage compartment for water and eventually sugars and acids, and vacuole development essential for cell expansion capacity. ||Solute accumulation driving water uptake shows organic acid synthesis particularly malate and tartrate, mineral ion import including potassium, sugar beginning to accumulate though low levels during growth, osmotic potential decline from -0.5 to -1.5 MPa driving water influx, and solute accumulation creating osmotic gradient essential for expansion. ||Diameter increase shows berry expanding from 12-18 mm at expansion phase entry to 8-12 mm in small-berried or 14-18 mm in large-berried cultivars by expansion completion, diameter increase 4-8 mm during rapid phase, and diameter as convenient expansion measurement. ||Volume increase shows exponential volumetric growth during rapid phase, volume expanding 3-6 fold during weeks 3-6, typical range from 0.8-2 mL at phase start to 3-8 mL at completion, and volumetric increase reflecting combined linear diameter increase. ||Fresh weight accumulation shows weight increase from 0.8-2 g at phase entry to 3-10 g at completion depending on cultivar, weight gain 50-200 mg per day during peak growth, cumulative weight gain 2-8 g during rapid phase, and fresh weight as practical growth measure correlating with volume. ||Berry appearance changes show berry expanding visibly over days to weeks, green color maintained during growth phase, smooth surface from coordinated growth, and transition from young berry to pea-sized or larger berry morphology. ||Skin growth coordination shows exocarp cells dividing and expanding maintaining surface coverage, coordinated skin growth preventing cracking during berry expansion, and skin expansion capacity limiting berry size in some cases. ||Berry cluster filling shows berries expanding to contact neighboring berries, cluster compactness increasing as berries fill available space, and cluster architecture affecting individual berry expansion through physical constraints. ||Environmental effects on expansion include temperature affecting expansion rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid expansion completing phase within 3-4 weeks, water availability critically affecting cell expansion and final size with adequate water essential, humidity possibly affecting surface expansion and cracking risk, and overall favorable conditions maximizing expansion and size achievement. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting rapid expansion, cool conditions slowing but generally not preventing expansion, and temperature as factor affecting expansion rate and duration. ||Water effects show adequate water essential for turgor-driven cell expansion, water deficit limiting expansion potentially reducing berry size 20-40%, irrigation beneficial during rapid expansion weeks 3-6 in water-limited environments, and water as most critical environmental factor during expansion. ||Nutrient effects show potassium affecting water relations and cell expansion, calcium influencing cell wall properties, and overall mineral nutrition supporting expansion though usually adequate in vineyards. ||Failed or limited expansion causes include water deficit preventing adequate cell enlargement, extreme temperature stress disrupting growth, skin growth limitation restricting berry expansion in rare cases, or physiological dysfunction though uncommon. ||The process represents second phase of initial berry growth emphasizing overlap of division and expansion, following early cell division growth and preceding berry size establishment. ||Duration typically 3-4 weeks representing peak growth transition period. ||Regional timing shows rapid initial expansion during mid July-early August across climates during maximum summer growth. ||Viticultural significance includes representing period of maximum berry growth rate determining substantial size increase, demonstrating critical water requirement during expansion for size achievement, showing transition from division to expansion as growth mechanism, and establishing majority of final berry size affecting yield and quality. ||Research applications include analyzing expansion mechanisms and cell enlargement, investigating water relations and turgor effects on expansion, evaluating environmental effects particularly water on expansion and size, quantifying growth dynamics during transition phase, and assessing expansion as berry size and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 438-445 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Berry_Size_Establishment": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Size_Establishment is an Initial_Berry_Growth characterized by completed cell division, decelerating cell expansion, and berry attainment of near-final dimensions, extending over weeks 5–8 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "final sizing phase | berry dimension establishment | size determination completion | pre-lag sizing |+ Beerengröße-Etablierung | finale Größenphase | Beerengröße-Bestimmung | Größen-Festlegung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows berry size establishment during early-mid August Year N+1 at BBCH 75-77, with cell division completed by week 5, cell expansion continuing but decelerating weeks 6-8, berry diameter reaching 9-11 mm representing 75-88% final mature size, fresh weight 3.2-5.8 g, growth rate declining to 8-18 mg per day approaching lag phase entry, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar establishing size determining yield potential",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Size_Establishment is third and final phase of Initial_Berry_Growth, distinguished by growth deceleration and final sizing. ||Duration 3-4 weeks as expansion slows. ||Cell division completed. ||Expansion continues but declining rate. ||Achieves 70-90% final size. ||Strong correlation with mature size enabling yield prediction. ||Approaches lag phase entry. ||Follows Rapid_Initial_Expansion. ||Completes initial berry growth phase. ||Determines berry size baseline for ripening. || This size-determining phase occurs during mid-late summer in late July-August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 3-4 weeks as growth slows, corresponding to BBCH 75-77 berry touch to beginning of bunch closure stages. ||Size establishment involves completion of cell division with no further cell proliferation after week 4-5, continued cell expansion though at declining rate, berry achieving 70-90% final fresh weight by establishment completion, growth rate progressive decline entering lag phase, and berry dimensions at establishment largely predicting mature size. ||Cell division cessation shows division completion by week 4-5 in most mesocarp cells, final cell number established determining cellular foundation, no further cell proliferation during subsequent development, and division completion marking transition to expansion-only growth. ||Cell expansion continuation shows cells continuing enlargement through water uptake and vacuole expansion, expansion rate declining from peak weeks 3-5 to slower rate weeks 6-8, progressive expansion deceleration as cells approach mature size, and expansion continuing into ripening though at very low rate. ||Berry size achievement shows diameter reaching 8-12 mm in small-berried cultivars or 14-18 mm in large-berried cultivars by establishment completion, size representing 70-90% final mature berry size, berry volume 2-8 mL depending on cultivar, and fresh weight 2-10 g establishing size baseline. ||Size predictability shows strong correlation between size at establishment and final mature size, typical r² 0.75-0.90 between week 8 size and harvest size indicating reliable prediction, early size largely determining final size barring major stress or shriveling, and establishment size enabling early yield estimation. ||Growth rate decline shows progressive deceleration from peak 50-200 mg per day during rapid expansion to 10-50 mg per day during size establishment, eventual very low growth <5 mg per day entering lag phase, and declining rate characteristic of transition from growth to lag phase. ||Lag phase approach shows berry growth rate declining to near-zero, berry entering quiescent period before veraison, lag phase duration typically 1-3 weeks depending on cultivar and conditions, and lag representing transition from growth to ripening preparation. ||Berry dimensions at establishment show cultivar-characteristic size ranges reflecting genetic programming and environmental effects, small-berried cultivars 6-10 mm diameter, medium-berried 10-14 mm, large-berried 14-18 mm, and size variation within cultivars 15-30% coefficient of variation reflecting seed number and environmental heterogeneity. ||Fresh weight at establishment shows typical ranges 2-4 g small-berried, 4-8 g medium-berried, 8-15 g large-berried cultivars, weight variation within clusters reflecting seed number effects and microenvironment, and weight as practical size measure. ||Berry composition at establishment shows water content 80-85% fresh weight, sugars low typically 2-5% fresh weight as hexoses, organic acids 1-2% dominated by malate and tartrate, pH relatively low 2.5-3.5, and overall hard acidic green berry characteristic. ||Skin characteristics show green chlorophyll-containing epidermis, firm texture from cell wall integrity and turgor, smooth surface from coordinated growth, and protective cuticle layer developing. ||Seeds at establishment show seeds approaching mature size developing in parallel with berry, typical 1-3 viable seeds per berry, seed weight 20-40 mg each at establishment, and seeds completing development shortly before or during ripening. ||Berry-vine relationship shows berries as strong sink consuming 40-60% photosynthate during growth, sink strength declining as growth slows, and resource allocation beginning shift toward other sinks as berry growth completes. ||Environmental effects during size establishment include temperature affecting expansion rate and lag phase timing, water availability affecting final expansion and size achievement, and overall conditions during weeks 6-8 determining final establishment size. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions accelerating establishment completing size determination earlier, cool conditions extending establishment period, and temperature affecting timing rather than final size potential within normal ranges. ||Water effects show adequate water enabling full expansion to genetic potential, water deficit during establishment potentially reducing final size 10-30% through limited expansion, deficit effects less severe than during earlier rapid expansion, and late season water management affecting final sizing. ||Nutrient effects show generally adequate nutrition during establishment with mineral deficiencies rare, potassium possibly affecting water relations and final sizing, and overall nutrition less critical than water. ||Cultivar variation shows genetic differences in final size potential, timing of size establishment relative to phenology, and lag phase characteristics. ||Size establishment as critical determinant shows early size determining berry and cluster weight, yield per vine calculated from berry size × berry number × cluster number, and establishment completing berry developmental foundation for ripening. ||The process represents third and final phase of initial berry growth establishing final size, following early cell division growth and rapid initial expansion. ||Duration typically 3-4 weeks as growth declines toward lag phase. ||Regional timing shows berry size establishment during late July-August in warm climates, August in temperate regions, and August-early September in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing berry size determining yield and cluster architecture, enabling early yield prediction from established berry dimensions, demonstrating that early size largely determines mature size emphasizing importance of favorable early conditions, and completing berry structural development preparing for ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing size determination mechanisms and predictability, investigating environmental effects on final size achievement, evaluating early size as mature size predictor, quantifying yield estimation from early berry measurements, and assessing size establishment as yield and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 443-450 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Fruit_Drop": {
  "definition": "A Fruit_Drop is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process consisting of berry abscission from the cluster through developmental failure, mechanical detachment, shot-berry arrest, or late physiological dysfunction.",
  "alternative_term": "berry abscission | fruit loss | berry drop | cluster berry loss |+ Fruchtfall | Beerenabszission | Fruchtverlust | Beerenfall",
  "example_of_usage": "Grenache in Rhône Valley shows fruit drop during July-August Year N+1 at BBCH 71-81, with early fruit drop 12-28% from fertilization failure weeks 1-3, occasional shatter 5-15% from summer storms, millerandage formation 8-18% creating shot berries, cumulative berry loss 25-45% in poor years, under variable Mediterranean conditions, typical of this coulure and drop-prone cultivar requiring favorable conditions for acceptable berry retention",
  "editor_note": "Fruit_Drop represents berry loss phenomena within Fruit_Set reducing berry number and yield. ||Subdivided into Early_Fruit_Drop from developmental failure, Shatter from weather damage, Millerandage_Formation creating shot berries, and Post_Set_Berry_Abscission from late failures. ||Timing and severity vary by mechanism. ||Cumulative losses 5-50% depending on cultivar and conditions. ||Major yield-limiting factor. ||Environmental and genetic susceptibility. ||Management strategies can reduce drop. ||Affects cluster architecture and quality. || This yield-reducing phenomenon occurs during summer development from early fruit set through ripening in late June-September in temperate regions Year N+1, with timing and severity varying by drop type, corresponding to BBCH 71-85 stages from young fruit through ripening. ||Fruit drop encompasses multiple distinct mechanisms including early fruit drop from failed berry development shortly after fertilization, shatter from weather-induced mechanical berry detachment during vulnerable periods, millerandage formation creating small arrested berries with variable persistence, post-set berry abscission from late developmental failure or stress responses, and overall berry loss reducing cluster berry number below initial fruit set. ||Drop incidence and timing show variable patterns with early drop typically 1-4 weeks post-flowering from developmental failure, shatter during flowering or early fruit set from rain or wind damage, millerandage formation during fruit set creating persistent shot berries, late drop occasionally during veraison or ripening from stress, and cumulative losses potentially reducing berry number 5-50% depending on severity. ||Early fruit drop characteristics show young berry abortion and abscission within first 2-4 weeks post-fertilization, failure from inadequate fertilization, seed abortion, or developmental dysfunction, abscission zone formation at pedicel enabling berry detachment, and early losses contributing to coulure poor fruit set if severe. ||Shatter characteristics show mechanical berry detachment from pedicel through weather damage, rain impact during flowering or early fruit set causing physical separation, wind damage breaking fragile pedicel connections, fallen berries lost from cluster reducing berry number, and shatter losses potentially severe 20-40% in extreme weather events. ||Millerandage characteristics show formation of small seedless or poorly developed shot berries during fruit set, arrested development creating persistently small 3-6 mm berries, variable persistence with some shot berries remaining through harvest and others abscising, and millerandage berries reducing cluster uniformity and potentially wine quality. ||Post-set abscission shows occasional late berry drop during veraison or ripening, abscission from developmental stress, water deficit, or disease, late losses typically limited <5% except under severe stress, and late drop distinguished from early developmental failures. ||Berry loss mechanisms show abscission requiring abscission zone formation and activation, abscission zone at pedicel-berry junction containing specialized separation cells, enzymatic cell wall degradation creating separation layer, vascular tissue severing enabling berry detachment, and mechanical weakness allowing berry fall. ||Abscission regulation shows hormone control with auxin from seeds preventing abscission, ethylene promoting abscission zone activation, auxin-ethylene balance determining abscission versus retention, and hormonal rescue failure enabling abscission in berries with inadequate seed development. ||Environmental effects on fruit drop include rain during flowering causing shatter and poor set increasing drop, temperature extremes affecting fertilization and development increasing early drop risk, water stress potentially triggering late drop, wind damage causing mechanical shatter, and overall adverse conditions increasing drop severity across mechanisms. ||Cultivar variation shows genetic differences in drop susceptibility, coulure-prone cultivars showing high early drop 30-50%, shatter-resistant cultivars maintaining berry retention despite weather, and cultivar characteristics affecting drop patterns. ||Drop assessment methods include berry number counts comparing flowering to harvest, cluster examination documenting berry scars from abscised berries, pedicel remnants indicating drop timing, and quantification of drop percentage relative to initial set. ||Drop impacts on yield show direct berry number reduction decreasing cluster and vine yield, severe drop 30-50% substantially affecting production economics, drop variability creating year-to-year yield fluctuations, and drop as major yield loss factor in susceptible cultivars or unfavorable years. ||Drop effects on cluster architecture show berry spacing increasing with drop, cluster looseness from missing berries, and architecture changes affecting subsequent disease risk and harvest characteristics. ||Drop prevention strategies include cultivar selection avoiding drop-prone varieties, weather protection during vulnerable periods reducing shatter risk, adequate boron nutrition supporting fertilization reducing early drop, water management preventing late drop from deficit stress, and overall cultural practices minimizing drop causes. ||The process encompasses four distinguishable drop mechanisms including early fruit drop from developmental failure, shatter from weather damage, millerandage formation creating arrested berries, and post-set berry abscission from late failures. ||Duration and timing vary by mechanism from early post-flowering through ripening. ||Regional timing shows fruit drop during late June-September across climates depending on drop type. ||Viticultural significance includes representing major yield loss factor potentially reducing production 5-50%, demonstrating cultivar and environmental susceptibility patterns, requiring management strategies to minimize drop, and affecting cluster characteristics and wine quality through berry loss. ||Research applications include analyzing drop mechanisms and abscission regulation, investigating environmental and genetic factors affecting drop susceptibility, evaluating prevention strategies and interventions, quantifying drop impacts on yield and quality, and assessing drop as production limitation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 410-415, 450-455 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Early_Fruit_Drop": {
  "definition": "An Early_Fruit_Drop is a Fruit_Drop comprising berry abscission of young developing berries from inadequate fertilization, seed abortion, or insufficient hormonal rescue during the first 2–4 weeks post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "post-flowering drop | developmental failure drop | coulure berry loss | early berry abortion |+ früher Fruchtfall | Post-Blüten-Fall | Entwicklungsversagen-Abfall | Coulure-Beerenverlust",
  "example_of_usage": "Malbec in Mendoza shows early fruit drop during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-73, with 18-32% berries aborting and abscising within 2-3 weeks post-flowering from fertilization failures and early seed abortion, peak drop week 2-3, abscission zones forming at pedicels, under variable spring conditions including occasional rain during flowering, typical of this moderately coulure-susceptible cultivar requiring favorable flowering for acceptable fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Early_Fruit_Drop is first type of Fruit_Drop, distinguished by developmental failure within 1-4 weeks post-flowering. ||Primary coulure mechanism. ||Results from fertilization failure or seed abortion eliminating hormonal rescue. ||Timing weeks 1-4 post-flowering. ||Incidence 10-50% depending on cultivar and conditions. ||Boron deficiency and weather major causes. ||Abscission zone activation at pedicel. ||Reduces berry number determining yield. ||Prevention through nutrition, cultivar selection, favorable conditions. || This developmental failure-induced drop occurs during early summer in late June-July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically within 1-4 weeks following flowering as fertilization outcomes manifest, corresponding to BBCH 69-73 fertilization completion to young fruit stages. ||Early drop mechanism involves fertilization failure or early seed abortion eliminating auxin source, inadequate hormone production failing to prevent abscission, abscission zone activation at berry pedicel, enzymatic cell wall degradation creating separation layer, and berry detachment and fall reducing cluster berry number. ||Fertilization failure causes show inadequate pollination preventing fertilization, pollen tube growth failure from boron deficiency or environmental stress, fusion abnormalities preventing zygote or endosperm formation, and complete fertilization failure in all ovules causing inevitable berry abortion. ||Seed abortion causes show early post-fertilization developmental failure, embryo or endosperm abortion within days to weeks of fertilization, genetic abnormalities preventing normal seed development, environmental stress during critical early period disrupting development, and seed failure eliminating hormonal rescue enabling abscission. ||Inadequate hormonal rescue shows insufficient auxin production from failed or aborting seeds, hormone levels below threshold required to suppress abscission, auxin-ethylene balance shifting toward abscission promotion, and hormonal failure permitting abscission zone activation. ||Abscission zone development shows specialized separation cells at pedicel-berry junction activating following hormone signal loss, cell wall degrading enzymes including cellulase and polygalacturonase synthesizing, middle lamella dissolution between cells creating separation plane, vascular tissue severing eliminating nutrient flow, and mechanical weakness enabling berry detachment. ||Abscission timing shows progressive abscission over 1-4 weeks post-flowering as fertilization failures manifest, peak drop typically 2-3 weeks post-flowering, early failures dropping within days and late failures within weeks, and timing reflecting developmental failure progression. ||Drop rate dynamics show initial lower drop rate during first week as berries still supported by residual hormones, acceleration during weeks 2-3 as failures accumulate, peak drop rate week 2-3 with daily berry loss visible, and eventual decline as remaining berries stabilize representing successful fruit set. ||Berry characteristics before drop show small size 4-8 mm diameter indicating limited growth, yellowing or browning suggesting physiological failure, failure to expand distinguishing from growing berries, and pedicel abscission zone visible as swelling or discoloration. ||Dropped berry examination shows small arrested berries on ground below clusters, internal examination revealing absent or aborted seeds, lack of normal berry development structures, and pathological features distinguishing from normal berries. ||Cluster appearance after early drop shows gaps from missing berries, pedicel scars indicating abscission sites, remaining berry spacing increased, and overall sparse cluster from high drop typical of poor set. ||Drop incidence variation shows cultivar differences with coulure-prone cultivars experiencing 30-50% early drop, reliable cultivars maintaining <10-20% drop, and genetic susceptibility as major determinant. ||Environmental effects include unfavorable flowering weather increasing fertilization failure and drop, rain preventing pollination and fertilization increasing early drop 20-40%, temperature extremes impairing fertilization and seed development, boron deficiency preventing pollen tube growth causing severe drop, and overall adverse conditions during flowering and early fruit set maximizing drop severity. ||Temperature effects show cool conditions during fertilization potentially increasing failure and drop, excessive heat impairing reproductive function, and optimal 22-28°C minimizing drop risk. ||Boron deficiency effects show critical importance with inadequate boron causing pollen tube failure, fertilization failure despite adequate flowering, severe early drop 40-60% in deficient conditions, and boron supplementation essential for reducing drop. ||Rain effects show rain during flowering preventing pollination and washing pollen, poor fertilization success leading to early drop, and rain as major early drop risk factor. ||Coulure relationship shows early fruit drop as primary coulure mechanism, excessive drop creating poor fruit set <30% set percentage, coulure-prone cultivars and seasons showing severe early drop, and coulure representing extreme early drop scenario. ||Drop prevention strategies include cultivar selection avoiding coulure-prone varieties, boron fertilization ensuring adequate levels 10-20 ppm during flowering, weather protection during flowering period where feasible, and overall management supporting successful fertilization reducing drop. ||Early drop versus later drop distinction shows early drop within first month from developmental failure, later drop from different mechanisms including shatter or stress, and timing distinguishing early developmental losses from other drop types. ||Drop assessment shows berry number counts comparing flowering to 4 weeks post-flowering, drop percentage calculation quantifying loss, cluster examination documenting remaining berry number, and early assessment enabling yield prediction adjustment. ||The process represents first type of fruit drop caused by developmental failure, distinguished from weather-induced shatter and other drop mechanisms. ||Duration typically 1-4 weeks post-flowering representing critical failure manifestation period. ||Regional timing shows early fruit drop during late June-July across climates following flowering. ||Viticultural significance includes representing primary coulure mechanism reducing fruit set, demonstrating critical importance of successful fertilization and early development, showing cultivar and environmental susceptibility requiring management, and determining final berry number affecting yield. ||Research applications include analyzing fertilization failure and seed abortion mechanisms, investigating hormonal regulation of early drop, evaluating environmental and nutritional effects on drop incidence, quantifying genetic variation in drop susceptibility, and developing strategies for reducing early drop and improving fruit set.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 410-415 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Shatter": {
  "definition": "A Shatter is a Fruit_Drop comprising mechanical detachment of flowers or young berries from clusters through rain impact, hail, or wind during flowering and early fruit set.",
  "alternative_term": "weather-induced drop | mechanical berry detachment | rain damage | hail shatter |+ Verrieselung | wetterbedingte Beerenfall | mechanische Beerenablösung | Regenschaden",
  "example_of_usage": "Riesling in Mosel shows shatter during mid June Year N+1 at BBCH 65-71, with heavy rainfall event during early fruit set causing 22-38% berry detachment through mechanical raindrop impact, flowers and young berries physically separated from fragile pedicels, immediate losses visible on vineyard floor, under cool humid climate with frequent June precipitation, typical shatter vulnerability requiring protective measures in severe weather years",
  "editor_note": "Shatter is second type of Fruit_Drop, distinguished by weather-induced mechanical detachment rather than developmental failure. ||Timing during flowering to 3 weeks post-flowering (BBCH 60-73). ||Caused by rain, hail, or wind impact. ||Immediate loss during weather event. ||Mechanical separation not abscission. ||Severity 5-50% depending on weather intensity. ||Compact clusters potentially more vulnerable. ||Uncontrollable yield risk. ||Limited prevention options. ||Differs from developmental Early_Fruit_Drop. || This weather-damage mechanism occurs during late spring to early summer in late May-July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically during flowering to 2-3 weeks post-flowering when attachment fragile, corresponding to BBCH 60-73 flowering to young fruit stages. ||Shatter mechanism involves mechanical impact from raindrops, hail stones, or wind forces exceeding attachment strength, physical separation of flowers or berries from pedicels through mechanical failure rather than abscission zone activation, immediate detachment and fall during or shortly after weather event, and berry loss visible as flowers or berries on ground below vines. ||Rain-induced shatter shows heavy rainfall during flowering or early fruit set physically dislodging flowers or young berries, raindrop impact forces exceeding weak attachment strength during vulnerable period, progressive berry loss during sustained rain events, and severe shatter possible 20-40% loss in torrential rain scenarios. ||Hail-induced shatter shows hailstone impact causing immediate flower or berry detachment, mechanical damage to clusters and shoots, severe losses possible 40-80% in direct hail events, and devastating effects during flowering creating near-total fruit loss in affected areas. ||Wind-induced shatter shows strong winds during flowering causing flower vibration and detachment, mechanical stress on fragile pedicel connections, progressive loss during sustained wind events, and wind effects exacerbating rain damage through combined mechanical forces. ||Attachment weakness during vulnerable period shows flowers and young berries having fragile pedicel connections before structural reinforcement, attachment strength progressively increasing as berries develop, critical vulnerability during flowering and first 2-3 weeks post-flowering, and vulnerability declining as pedicels strengthen and berries enlarge. ||Mechanical separation characteristics show physical breaking of pedicel tissue rather than organized abscission, irregular break surfaces distinguishing from clean abscission zone separation, no abscission zone involvement in immediate weather damage, and mechanical failure mechanism differing from developmental drop. ||Timing characteristics show shatter occurring during or immediately following weather event, instantaneous losses during severe weather, and timing corresponding to weather occurrence rather than developmental schedule. ||Shatter visibility shows flowers or berries immediately visible on ground or caught in vegetation, fresh green color indicating recent detachment, and obvious correlation with weather event timing. ||Cluster appearance after shatter shows gaps from missing berries, irregular pedicel breaks without abscission zone remnants, remaining flowers or berries potentially damaged, and overall disrupted cluster architecture. ||Berry development stage vulnerability shows flowers most vulnerable during anthesis to cap fall, young berries highly vulnerable first 1-2 weeks post-flowering, vulnerability declining weeks 3-4 as attachment strengthens, and mature berries relatively resistant though extreme hail can damage. ||Weather event severity effects show light rain causing minimal shatter <5%, heavy sustained rain causing moderate shatter 10-25%, torrential rain or hail causing severe shatter 30-50% or more, and event intensity as major shatter determinant. ||Cultivar variation in shatter susceptibility shows some cultivars having more fragile flower attachments increasing vulnerability, compact cluster architecture possibly increasing impact damage through berry crowding, and genetic differences affecting shatter resistance though less pronounced than environmental effects. ||Cluster architecture effects show compact clusters potentially experiencing greater shatter through impact transmission between berries, loose clusters showing more independent berry behavior, and architecture influencing shatter patterns. ||Geographic and temporal vulnerability shows regions with frequent flowering-period rain experiencing regular shatter risk, Mediterranean climates with dry flowering periods showing minimal shatter, and timing variability creating year-to-year shatter fluctuation. ||Prevention strategies show limited options due to weather unpredictability, protective structures like rain covers or hail nets providing physical protection where economically feasible, cultivar selection for favorable flowering timing avoiding typical storm periods, and overall reliance on favorable weather during vulnerable period. ||Shatter versus other drop distinction shows mechanical immediate loss distinguishing from progressive developmental drop, weather event correlation identifying shatter, fresh detachment evidence versus abscission zone formation, and timing during vulnerable period distinguishing from late drop. ||Shatter assessment shows immediate post-weather evaluation documenting berry loss, comparison of affected and protected areas quantifying impact, cluster counts determining loss percentage, and rapid assessment enabling damage quantification. ||Shatter impacts on yield show direct berry number reduction proportional to weather severity, severe events causing 30-50% losses affecting production economics substantially, year-to-year variability from weather creating yield unpredictability, and shatter as uncontrollable yield risk factor. ||Shatter recovery options show no recovery from lost berries with shatter losses permanent, remaining berries potentially compensating through larger size though limited compensation, and severe shatter potentially necessitating crop insurance claims. ||The process represents second type of fruit drop caused by weather damage, distinguished from developmental early drop and other mechanisms. ||Duration represents immediate loss during weather event rather than progressive drop. ||Regional timing shows shatter risk during late May-July across climates during flowering and early fruit set. ||Viticultural significance includes representing uncontrollable weather-induced yield loss, demonstrating critical vulnerability during flowering period, requiring protective infrastructure in high-risk areas, and contributing to production variability and risk. ||Research applications include quantifying weather impacts on fruit retention, evaluating cultivar and architectural effects on shatter susceptibility, developing protective strategies and technologies, and assessing shatter as production risk factor.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 450-455"
},

  "Millerandage_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Millerandage_Formation is a Fruit_Drop characterized by arrested seedless or poorly seeded berries of 3–6 mm diameter persisting on the cluster alongside normally developing berries.",
  "alternative_term": "shot berries | hen and chickens | berry size heterogeneity | arrested berry development |+ Verrieselung | Gescheine | Henne und Küken | Beerengrößen-Heterogenität",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows millerandage formation during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 69-75, with 12-28% berries developing as shot berries 3-5 mm diameter remaining seedless or poorly seeded, normal berries achieving 10-13 mm creating obvious size heterogeneity, shot berries persisting through harvest contributing high acidity, under oceanic conditions with variable spring weather, typical of this millerandage-susceptible cultivar requiring favorable fruit set conditions",
  "editor_note": "Millerandage_Formation is third type of Fruit_Drop phenomenon, though berries persist rather than drop. ||Represents arrested development during fruit set creating shot berries 3-6 mm. ||Timing weeks 1-4 post-flowering. ||Results from fertilization failure or early developmental arrest. ||Seedless or poorly seeded. ||Persists through harvest unlike Early_Fruit_Drop. ||Creates size heterogeneity affecting quality. ||Incidence 5-50% depending on severity. ||Cultivar susceptibility particularly Grenache, Malbec, Merlot. ||Reduces effective yield and quality. || This developmental heterogeneity phenomenon occurs during fruit set in late June-July in temperate regions Year N+1, with arrest typically during first 2-4 weeks post-flowering, corresponding to BBCH 69-75 fruit set to young fruit stages. ||Millerandage mechanism involves partial fertilization failure or early developmental arrest creating shot berries, seedless or single small seed development providing inadequate auxin for normal growth, arrested berry expansion remaining at 3-6 mm diameter versus 8-18 mm normal berries, persistent shot berries remaining attached through ripening creating size heterogeneity, and variable berry development within cluster from differential fertilization or development success. ||Shot berry characteristics show small size typically 3-6 mm diameter representing 20-40% normal berry size, seedless condition or single small poorly developed seed, hard firm texture from limited cell expansion, green color persisting longer than normal berries, high acidity and low sugar at harvest distinguishing from normal berries, and arrested development preventing normal berry maturation. ||Seedless shot berry development shows fertilization failure or very early seed abortion, berry initiation from residual hormone stimulus, limited growth without adequate seed auxin production, developmental arrest at small size, and persistence through harvest as hard green berries. ||Partially seeded shot berry development shows single small seed formation from partial fertilization success, limited auxin production insufficient for normal berry expansion, intermediate size between seedless and normal berries sometimes observed, and variable development reflecting seed development extent. ||Developmental arrest timing shows arrest during critical early growth weeks 1-4 post-fertilization, earlier arrest producing smaller more arrested berries, and timing determining final shot berry characteristics. ||Cluster heterogeneity from millerandage shows mixture of normal-sized berries 8-18 mm with shot berries 3-6 mm, size ratio normal shot typically 2 per 1 to 4 per 1 creating obvious heterogeneity, variable proportions with mild millerandage showing 5-15% shot berries and severe cases 30-50%, and within-cluster variation affecting appearance and quality. ||Millerandage causes include incomplete or variable fertilization success across flowers, environmental stress during flowering or early fruit set affecting fertilization or development, boron deficiency preventing normal pollen tube growth in subset of flowers, genetic susceptibility in certain cultivars prone to millerandage, cool flowering temperatures potentially affecting fertilization uniformity, and overall factors causing developmental heterogeneity. ||Fertilization variability as cause shows differential fertilization success across cluster flowers, some flowers achieving complete fertilization and normal development, others experiencing partial or complete failure creating shot berries, and fertilization heterogeneity translating to berry size heterogeneity. ||Environmental stress effects show stress during critical flowering or early fruit set periods affecting subset of flowers or berries, creating developmental heterogeneity within clusters, and stress severity determining millerandage extent. ||Cultivar susceptibility shows genetic differences with some cultivars prone to millerandage under marginal conditions, Grenache, Malbec, and Merlot showing notable susceptibility, resistant cultivars maintaining uniform berry development, and genetic factors affecting millerandage risk. ||Millerandage versus coulure distinction shows millerandage producing persistent shot berries versus coulure causing berry drop, both representing fruit set problems from similar causes, millerandage creating quality issues from heterogeneity while coulure reduces yield through loss, and overlapping occurrence possible with both phenomena in same season. ||Shot berry persistence shows shot berries remaining attached through ripening unlike early fruit drop, hard texture preventing normal ripening progression, harvest typically including shot berries mixed with normal berries, and persistence creating processing challenges. ||Harvest implications show shot berries harvested with normal berries creating heterogeneity, shot berries contributing high acidity and tannin from immature development, potential negative quality effects from inclusion though sometimes minor if proportion low, and sorting possibly used to remove shot berries in severe cases. ||Yield effects show reduced effective yield from shot berry limited size, shot berries contributing 20-40% normal berry weight, severe millerandage reducing yield 15-30% through size reduction, and yield impact less severe than coulure though quality concerns additional. ||Quality effects show shot berries contributing disproportionate acidity and herbaceous character if proportion high, potential positive effects from concentration if proportion low 5-10%, negative effects typically dominating when proportion >20%, and overall quality impact depending on millerandage severity. ||Millerandage assessment shows visual cluster examination documenting size heterogeneity, shot berry counting quantifying proportion, size measurements distinguishing shot from normal berries, and severity classification from percentage shot berries. ||Millerandage management shows boron fertilization preventing deficiency-induced millerandage, favorable flowering conditions reducing stress-induced heterogeneity, cluster thinning potentially removing heavily affected clusters, and berry sorting at harvest removing shot berries in severe cases. ||The process represents third type of fruit drop or more accurately arrested development creating persistent small berries. ||Duration represents developmental arrest during weeks 1-4 post-flowering. ||Regional timing shows millerandage formation during late June-July across climates during fruit set. ||Viticultural significance includes creating within-cluster heterogeneity affecting quality, reducing effective yield through limited shot berry size, demonstrating cultivar and environmental susceptibility, and requiring management to minimize occurrence and impacts. ||Research applications include analyzing millerandage formation mechanisms and causes, investigating fertilization and developmental heterogeneity, evaluating environmental and genetic factors affecting millerandage, quantifying quality impacts from shot berries, and developing prevention strategies.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 450-455 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Post_Set_Berry_Abscission": {
  "definition": "A Post_Set_Berry_Abscission is a Fruit_Drop comprising berry abscission during the lag phase, véraison, or early ripening following successful initial fruit set.",
  "alternative_term": "late berry drop | veraison drop | stress-induced abscission | post-commitment drop |+ Post-Set Beerenabszission | später Beerenfall | Veraison-Fall | stressinduzierte Abszission",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows post-set berry abscission during late July-August Year N+1 at BBCH 77-81, with 6-14% established berries aborting during lag phase and veraison from severe water deficit stress, heat waves above 38°C, and occasional Botrytis infection, late drop visible as berry scars on clusters, under warm dry Mediterranean conditions with variable summer precipitation, typical of this moderately stress-tolerant cultivar showing limited late drop under adequate irrigation",
  "editor_note": "Post_Set_Berry_Abscission is fourth type of Fruit_Drop, distinguished by late occurrence after successful initial fruit set. ||Timing weeks 4-12 post-flowering during BBCH 75-85. ||Caused by severe stress (water deficit, heat), disease, or dysfunction. ||Reactivates abscission zone after earlier rescue. ||Typically limited incidence <5-10% under normal conditions. ||Distinguished from Early_Fruit_Drop by timing and causes. ||Prevention through irrigation, disease management, stress mitigation. ||Represents late yield loss from established berries. || This late drop phenomenon occurs during mid-late summer in July-September in temperate regions Year N+1, typically weeks 4-12 post-flowering after initial fruit set completion, corresponding to BBCH 75-85 berry touch through ripening stages. ||Post-set abscission mechanism involves late developmental failure or stress response in previously successfully established berries, abscission zone activation at berry pedicel despite earlier successful hormonal rescue, ethylene production potentially triggering abscission program, enzymatic cell wall degradation creating separation layer, and berry detachment reducing cluster berry number from established maximum. ||Late developmental failure causes show severe water deficit stress triggering berry abortion and drop, excessive heat stress disrupting berry metabolism and triggering drop response, disease infection particularly fungal pathogens causing berry death and abscission, sunburn damage causing berry death and subsequent drop, and overall severe stress exceeding berry tolerance causing failure. ||Water deficit-induced drop shows severe sustained water stress during lag phase or veraison triggering abscission, stress disrupting berry metabolism and hormone balance, ethylene production possibly mediating stress-induced drop, typical drop 5-20% under severe deficit though usually <5% under moderate stress, and deficit timing and severity determining drop extent. ||Heat stress-induced drop shows extreme heat events above 38-42°C causing berry damage, heat disrupting cellular metabolism and membrane integrity, damaged berries subsequently aborting and abscising, and heat-induced drop typically localized to sun-exposed clusters. ||Disease-induced drop shows fungal infections including Botrytis bunch rot causing berry death, infected berries losing attachment and dropping, bacterial or viral diseases potentially causing drop in severe cases, and disease as occasional late drop cause particularly in humid conditions. ||Sunburn-induced drop shows excessive sun exposure causing berry surface damage, necrotic damage progressing to berry death, damaged berries eventually abscising, and sunburn drop typically affecting exposed west or southwest cluster sides. ||Physiological dysfunction causes show occasional late berry abortion from unknown internal developmental failures, possible resource competition effects in heavy crop loads, and dysfunction as rare late drop cause compared to environmental stresses. ||Abscission zone late activation shows reactivation of pedicel abscission zone after successful early prevention, hormone balance shift enabling activation despite earlier rescue, ethylene as possible abscission trigger, and abscission proceeding through typical enzymatic separation mechanisms. ||Drop timing characteristics show post-set drop occurring weeks 4-12 post-flowering after fruit set establishment, lag phase drop weeks 6-8 from stress during quiescent period, veraison drop weeks 8-10 from stress during critical transition, ripening drop weeks 10-14 from late stress or disease, and timing reflecting stress occurrence rather than developmental schedule. ||Drop incidence patterns show typically low incidence <5-10% under normal conditions, moderate drop 10-25% under severe stress events, rarely severe drop >25% except under catastrophic stress or disease, and post-set drop usually less severe than early fruit drop. ||Berry characteristics before late drop show berries initially developing normally through early phases, stress or disease causing visible symptoms before drop, shriveling, discoloration, or necrosis indicating problems, and symptomatic berries subsequently abscising. ||Dropped berry examination shows berries larger than early drop berries indicating later development before failure, disease symptoms visible in pathogen-induced drop, desiccation or damage in stress-induced drop, and pathology distinguishing late drop causes. ||Cluster appearance after late drop shows gaps from recently lost berries, pedicel scars indicating recent abscission, remaining berries potentially showing stress symptoms, and cluster architecture affected by late berry loss. ||Environmental effects include water deficit as major late drop cause particularly during lag phase or veraison, heat waves causing localized drop from damaged berries, disease pressure enabling infection-induced drop, and overall severe stress conditions triggering late abscission. ||Water deficit effects show progressive stress increasing drop risk, severe deficit >50% reduced vine water status triggering significant drop, timing during lag phase or veraison creating vulnerability, and adequate irrigation preventing deficit-induced drop. ||Heat effects show extreme events above 40°C causing damage and drop, heat stress exacerbating water deficit effects, and heat tolerance varying among cultivars affecting drop susceptibility. ||Disease effects show humid conditions promoting fungal infection, Botrytis bunch rot as major disease drop cause, and disease management reducing infection-induced drop. ||Cultivar variation shows genetic differences in stress tolerance affecting late drop susceptibility, some cultivars showing greater drought or heat tolerance, and disease resistance affecting infection-induced drop risk. ||Late drop versus early drop distinction shows late drop occurring weeks 4+ post-flowering after fruit set established, environmental stress or disease as causes versus developmental failure, typically lower incidence than early drop, and timing and causes distinguishing mechanisms. ||Drop prevention strategies show adequate irrigation during critical lag phase and veraison periods preventing deficit-induced drop, disease management reducing infection-induced drop, heat stress mitigation through cluster positioning or shading, and overall stress management minimizing late drop occurrence. ||The process represents fourth type of fruit drop caused by late developmental failure, distinguished from early developmental drop and other mechanisms. ||Duration represents stress or disease response after established fruit set. ||Regional timing shows post-set abscission during July-September across climates after initial fruit set completion. ||Viticultural significance includes representing late yield loss from environmental stress or disease, typically limited <5-10% under normal management though potentially severe under extreme conditions, demonstrating importance of water and disease management during later development, and affecting final yield from established berry number. ||Research applications include analyzing late abscission mechanisms and triggers, investigating stress and disease effects on established berries, evaluating management strategies preventing late drop, quantifying late drop impacts on yield, and assessing stress tolerance and disease resistance affecting drop susceptibility.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 450-458"
},

  "Berry_Development": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Development is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process consisting of the sequential phases of cell division, expansion, lag phase, véraison, and ripening from fruit set to harvest over 90–120 days.",
  "alternative_term": "berry maturation | fruit development | berry ripening progression | grape development |+ Beerenentwicklung | Beerenreifung | Fruchtentwicklung | Traubenentwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows berry development during mid July-late October Year N+1 at BBCH 71-89, with cell division phase weeks 0-4 establishing 2.4-3.2 million cells, expansion phase weeks 3-8 achieving 12-15 mm diameter, lag phase weeks 8-10, veraison week 10-12 initiating color change and sugar accumulation, ripening weeks 12-18 completing maturation reaching 24-26% sugar, 0.5-0.7% acid, full anthocyanin development, under warm climate conditions of 24-32°C, typical of this late-season cultivar achieving harvest maturity 110-130 days post-fruit set",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Development represents complete developmental sequence from fruit set through full ripeness. Encompasses Berry_Cell_Division_Phase, Berry_Expansion_Phase, Lag_Phase, Veraison, and Ripening_Phase. Duration 90-120 days varying by cultivar and climate. ||Sequential coordinated phases determining berry composition and quality. Temperature major driver of development rate. Comprehensive documentation of berry maturation establishing wine quality foundation. BBCH 71-89 stages. ||Primary viticultural focus for quality achievement. This complete developmental sequence occurs during summer to autumn in late June-October in temperate regions Year N+1, encompassing entire berry maturation from young fruit to ripe berry, corresponding to BBCH 71-89 stages from young fruit development through full ripeness. ||Berry development encompasses multiple sequential phases including berry cell division phase with intensive mitotic activity weeks 0-4 establishing final cell number, berry expansion phase with cell enlargement weeks 3-8 achieving primary size, lag phase weeks 6-10 representing metabolic reorganization and growth quiescence, veraison weeks 8-12 initiating ripening transformation with color change and sugar accumulation onset, and ripening phase weeks 10-16 completing maturation through sugar accumulation, acid decline, and flavor development. ||Cell division phase characteristics show peak mitotic activity during first 3-4 weeks post-fertilization establishing mesocarp flesh cellularity, cell cycle times 10-15 hours during maximum division intensity, final cell number 1-4 million cells per berry determining size potential, auxin-stimulated division from developing seeds, and division completion by week 4 marking transition to expansion-dominated growth. ||Expansion phase characteristics show cell enlargement through water uptake and vacuole expansion weeks 3-8, volumetric increase 3-8 fold during rapid expansion, berry achieving 70-90% final size by expansion completion, water comprising 80-85% fresh weight, and expansion rate progressively declining toward lag phase. ||Lag phase characteristics show growth rate declining to near-zero creating quiescent period weeks 6-10, berry maintaining green hard acidic state, metabolic reorganization preparing ripening transformation, seed maturation completing, and lag duration 1-3 weeks varying by cultivar and temperature before veraison onset. ||Veraison characteristics show dramatic transformation initiating weeks 8-12 with berry softening from cell wall modification, color change in red cultivars from anthocyanin synthesis or color revelation in white cultivars from chlorophyll degradation, sugar accumulation accelerating from phloem unloading activation, acid decline beginning particularly malate respiration, and overall transition from growth to ripening metabolism. ||Ripening phase characteristics show progressive sugar accumulation reaching 18-26% fresh weight as hexoses, continued acid decline to 0.4-0.8% particularly malic acid, secondary metabolite synthesis including anthocyanins, flavor compounds, and tannins, berry softening progression, and maturation completing over 4-6 weeks achieving harvest ripeness. ||Berry growth pattern shows characteristic double sigmoid curve with rapid growth phase I during cell division and expansion weeks 0-6, lag phase representing growth plateau weeks 6-10, and renewed growth phase II during ripening from sugar and water accumulation weeks 10-16. ||Fresh weight accumulation shows progressive increase from 0.5-2 g at commitment to 2-8 g at lag phase to 4-15 g at harvest depending on cultivar, weight increase rate varying through phases with maxima during expansion and ripening, and final weight determined by cell number, cell expansion, and ripening accumulation. ||Berry composition changes show dramatic transformation from hard green acidic berry at 2-5% sugar, 1-2% acid, pH 2.5-3.5 during growth phase, through intermediate composition during lag and veraison, to ripe berry at 18-26% sugar, 0.4-0.8% acid, pH 3.0-4.0 with accumulated flavor compounds and color. ||Sugar accumulation dynamics show low levels <5% during growth phase from metabolic consumption, accelerating accumulation from veraison through ripening, hexose sugars glucose and fructose dominating in approximately equal concentrations, and final concentration 18-26% representing 40-60% dry weight. ||Acid dynamics show initial accumulation to 1-2% during growth particularly malate and tartrate, peak acidity at veraison representing maximum organic acid content, progressive decline during ripening through malate respiration and dilution, tartrate relatively stable though declining slightly, and final acidity 0.4-0.8% at physiological maturity. ||pH changes show low pH 2.5-3.0 during growth phase from high acidity, progressive increase during ripening from acid decline, and final pH 3.0-4.0 at harvest with considerable cultivar and environmental variation. ||Color development shows green chlorophyll-containing berry during growth and lag phases, color change onset at veraison through anthocyanin synthesis in red cultivars or chlorophyll degradation revealing carotenoids in white cultivars, progressive color intensification during ripening, and final color determining wine hue. ||Anthocyanin accumulation in red cultivars shows synthesis initiating at veraison, progressive accumulation during ripening reaching 0.5-3.0 mg/g fresh weight, anthocyanin profile development with multiple cyanidin, peonidin, and malvidin glycosides, and accumulation determining wine color intensity and hue. ||Flavor compound development shows volatile and non-volatile compound synthesis during ripening, varietal aroma precursors accumulating including terpenes in aromatic varieties, methoxypyrazines declining from green to ripe states, esters and other volatiles developing, and flavor complexity increasing toward maturity. ||Texture changes show firm hard berry during growth phase from turgor and cell wall integrity, softening onset at veraison from pectin degradation and cell wall modification, progressive softening during ripening, and final texture ranging from firm to very soft depending on cultivar and maturity. ||Seed development coordination shows seeds developing in parallel with berry, seed maturation largely completing by lag phase or early veraison, seed color change from green to brown indicating maturation, and mature seeds with developed embryo, endosperm, and seed coat. ||Environmental effects on development include temperature as major factor affecting development rate with warm conditions accelerating and cool conditions slowing progression through phases, water availability affecting expansion and ripening accumulation, light possibly influencing anthocyanin synthesis and flavor development, and overall growing conditions determining development timing, berry composition, and quality. ||Temperature effects show heat accumulation driving phenological progression, growing degree days determining development timing, optimal ranges varying by phase with 24-28°C for growth, 22-28°C for ripening, and temperature affecting development rate and final composition. ||Water effects show adequate water essential during expansion for size achievement, deficit potentially beneficial during ripening enhancing concentration and quality in some cases, and water management strategies affecting berry development and wine quality. ||Cultivar variation shows genetic differences in development timing from early-ripening to late-ripening cultivars spanning 90-150 days fruit set to harvest, cell number and berry size characteristics, sugar and acid accumulation patterns, color and flavor development, and overall composition profiles determining varietal wine characteristics. ||Regional timing shows berry development during July-October in warm climates completing earlier, mid July-late October in temperate regions, and late July-November in cool climates with later harvest, demonstrating climatic effects on development duration. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical determinant of berry composition and wine quality, requiring optimal environmental conditions throughout development for quality achievement, demonstrating sequential coordinated developmental program, and establishing berry characteristics affecting all wine attributes including color, flavor, body, and balance. ||Research applications include analyzing developmental regulation and phase transitions, investigating environmental effects on development and composition, evaluating genetic variation in developmental characteristics, quantifying composition changes through development, and assessing development as quality determinant enabling harvest timing optimization and quality prediction.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010154 ## fruit development | 0.85", "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0001002 ## fruit development stage | 0.85" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 430-520 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Berry_Cell_Division_Phase": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Cell_Division_Phase is a Berry_Development comprising mitotic proliferation of pericarp mesocarp and exocarp cells establishing final cellular architecture, extending over the first 3–5 weeks post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "berry cell proliferation phase | mitotic growth phase | cell number establishment period | proliferative berry phase |+ Beeren-Zellteilungsphase | Zellproliferationsphase | mitotische Wachstumsphase | Zellzahl-Etablierungsperiode",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows berry cell division phase during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 71-73, with division activation days 3-6 post-fertilization, peak mitotic activity weeks 2-3 with 11-14 hour cell cycle times, progressive accumulation reaching 1.9-2.5 million mesocarp cells by week 4-5, division completion marking transition to expansion, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, 1.7-2.1 seeds per berry supporting division through auxin, typical of this mid-season cultivar establishing cellularity determining 10-13 mm final berry size",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Cell_Division_Phase is first major phase of Berry_Development, distinguished by intensive mitotic activity establishing final cell number. ||Subdivided into Active_Berry_Cell_Division with division activation and onset, and Peak_Division_Activity with maximum proliferation. ||Duration 3-5 weeks with peak weeks 1-3. ||Cell cycle times 10-15 hours. ||Final cell number 1-4 million determining 60-80% size variation. ||Temperature and seed number major determinants. ||Irreversible cell number establishment. ||Critical phase for berry size potential. ||Precedes expansion phase. || This critical cell proliferation phase occurs during early summer in late June-July in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 3-5 weeks from berry commitment with peak activity weeks 1-3, corresponding to BBCH 71-73 young fruit stages. ||Cell division phase mechanism involves auxin-stimulated cell cycle activation initiating mitotic activity, progressive cell number accumulation through repeated division rounds, peak division intensity during weeks 1-3 with maximum mitotic rates, gradual division rate decline weeks 3-5 as cells transition to expansion, and division completion establishing final cell population determining berry cellular foundation and size potential. ||Auxin stimulation of division shows hormone from developing seeds triggering cell cycle entry in quiescent pericarp cells, auxin signaling activating cyclin-dependent kinases and cell cycle regulators, hormone dose from seed number affecting division intensity and duration, and auxin as primary growth-promoting signal during early berry development. ||Cell cycle activation shows G1 phase entry from quiescent G0 state, progression through S phase with DNA replication, G2 phase preparation, and M phase mitosis producing daughter cells, with cycle times 10-15 hours during peak activity representing very rapid division characteristic of developmental growth. ||Division phase temporal progression shows initial division activation days 2-7 post-fertilization as auxin signaling establishes, mitotic activity onset week 1 with accelerating division rate, peak division activity weeks 2-3 with maximum cell proliferation, declining division weeks 3-4 as cells progressively exit cycle, and division completion week 4-5 with final cells entering expansion phase. ||Active berry cell division shows early intensive phase with division activation and onset establishing proliferative program, multiple cell generations produced through repeated division rounds, and coordinated division across pericarp tissues creating organized cellular architecture. ||Peak division activity represents maximum proliferative phase with highest mitotic rates, maximum cell number generation determining final cellularity, and tissue-specific division patterns in pericarp layers and seed compartment regions. ||Cell number accumulation dynamics show exponential increase during peak division weeks 1-3, typical progression from 50,000-100,000 cells at commitment to 1-4 million cells at division completion, accumulation rate varying with temperature and hormonal signaling, and final cell number as critical size determinant. ||Final cell number determination shows genetic programming establishing cultivar-characteristic cell number ranges, seed number effects through differential auxin dose creating 20-40% variation, temperature during division phase affecting proliferation rate and final number, and environmental conditions during critical weeks 1-4 determining achieved cellularity. ||Cell number variation shows small-berried cultivars achieving 0.8-1.5 million mesocarp cells producing 6-10 mm final diameter, medium-berried cultivars 1.5-2.5 million cells yielding 10-14 mm diameter, large-berried cultivars 2.5-4 million cells achieving 14-18 mm diameter, and cell number strongly correlating with mature berry size. ||Division spatial patterns show divisions throughout mesocarp flesh tissue creating bulk berry cells, exocarp epidermal and subepidermal divisions producing skin layers, endocarp inner layer divisions adjacent to seeds, and coordinated division maintaining tissue proportions and architecture. ||Periclinal versus anticlinal divisions show periclinal divisions parallel to berry surface increasing tissue thickness, anticlinal divisions perpendicular to surface increasing tissue area, and coordinated division planes creating three-dimensional tissue expansion. ||Division completion timing shows progressive cell cycle exit beginning week 3, majority of cells completing division by week 4, occasional continued division in some cell populations extending to week 5, and completion marking definitive transition to expansion phase. ||Cell size at division exit shows cells relatively small typically 20-40 micrometers diameter enabling efficient tissue packing, cells retaining expansion capacity for subsequent 10-100 fold volume increase, and initial small size characteristic of actively dividing populations. ||Division phase versus expansion phase contributions show cell number from division accounting for 60-80% mature berry size variation, cell expansion contributing 20-40% size variation, and division phase as more critical determinant emphasizing importance of early favorable conditions. ||Environmental effects on division phase include temperature critically affecting division rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum proliferation, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing division potentially reducing final cell number 15-30%, warm conditions 28-32°C accelerating division though excessive heat above 35°C impairing function, nitrogen supporting protein synthesis for division, and overall favorable conditions during weeks 1-4 maximizing cell number achievement. ||Temperature as major factor shows heat accumulation driving division progression, growing degree days during division phase correlating with cell number, and temperature affecting both rate and total divisions determining cellularity. ||Seed number effects show positive correlation between seeds per berry and final cell number, multiple seeds producing greater cumulative auxin stimulating more intensive division, and auxin dose-response relationship mediating seed effects on cellularity and size. ||Division irreversibility shows cell number established during weeks 1-4 permanent and unchangeable, lost division potential from suboptimal early conditions irreversible, later favorable conditions unable to compensate for early division limitation, and early environment as critical permanent determinant of berry size potential. ||The process shows two distinguishable phases including active berry cell division with division activation and onset establishing proliferative program, and peak division activity representing maximum proliferation determining final cellularity. ||Duration typically 3-5 weeks with peak activity weeks 1-3 and completion by week 4-5. ||Regional timing shows berry cell division phase during late June-July in warm climates, early-mid July in temperate regions, and mid-late July in cool areas. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final cell number as major berry size determinant accounting for 60-80% size variation, demonstrating critical importance of optimal conditions during early weeks for achieving size potential, showing irreversible nature of division phase with permanent effects on berry characteristics, and emphasizing early environment as determinant of quality and yield outcomes. ||Research applications include analyzing division regulation and cell cycle control, investigating auxin and hormonal effects on proliferation, evaluating temperature and environmental effects on division and cell number, quantifying cell number as size determinant, and assessing division phase as berry development and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 432-438 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Active_Berry_Cell_Division": {
  "definition": "An Active_Berry_Cell_Division is a Berry_Cell_Division_Phase comprising the activation and acceleration of mitotic activity in quiescent pericarp cells over the first 2–3 weeks post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "early mitotic phase | division activation period | initial proliferation phase | early cell division |+ aktive Beeren-Zellteilung | frühe mitotische Phase | Teilungs-Aktivierungsperiode | initiale Proliferationsphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows active berry cell division during late June-early July Year N+1 at BBCH 71-72, with division activation days 3-7 from auxin signaling, mitotic activity onset week 1, periclinal and anticlinal divisions proceeding with 12-15 hour cycle times, progressive cell number increase 6-12 fold over weeks 0-3, under cool maritime conditions of 19-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar initiating division establishing proliferative program",
  "editor_note": "Active_Berry_Cell_Division is first phase of Berry_Cell_Division_Phase, distinguished by division activation and establishment. ||Subdivided into Initial_Division_Activation with auxin-triggered cell cycle entry, Mitotic_Activity_Onset with first divisions occurring, and Periclinal_Cell_Division emphasizing radial tissue growth. ||Duration 2-3 weeks representing early division establishment. ||Cell cycle times 12-16 hours initially declining to 10-12 hours. ||Exponential cell number increase beginning. ||Precedes Peak_Division_Activity. ||Establishes proliferative program determining subsequent cellularity. || This initial proliferation phase occurs during early summer in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over weeks 0-3 post-fertilization as division establishes, corresponding to BBCH 71-72 young fruit early stages. ||Active division mechanism involves initial division activation with auxin signaling triggering cell cycle entry from quiescent state, mitotic activity onset as first divisions occur establishing proliferative program, periclinal cell divisions parallel to berry surface increasing tissue thickness, anticlinal divisions perpendicular to surface expanding tissue area, and coordinated division creating organized cellular architecture. ||Initial division activation shows auxin from developing seeds reaching threshold levels stimulating cell cycle entry, auxin receptor signaling cascades activating transcription factors, cell cycle gene expression initiating including cyclins and cyclin-dependent kinases, and G0 to G1 phase transition enabling DNA replication preparation. ||Division activation timing shows auxin signaling establishing days 2-5 post-fertilization, first cell cycle entries occurring days 3-7, and progressive activation as more cells enter cycle creating wave of proliferation. ||Mitotic activity onset shows first observable divisions occurring within first week post-fertilization, division rate accelerating as cell populations enter proliferative state, exponential cell number increase beginning as divisions compound, and establishment of active mitotic program characterizing berry as proliferative tissue. ||Early division characteristics show relatively asynchronous division across cell populations, progressive cell cycle entry creating temporal spread, division rate accelerating over first 2 weeks, and transition toward peak synchronous division by week 2-3. ||Cell cycle progression shows typical sequence of G1 growth phase, S phase DNA replication doubling chromosome number, G2 preparation phase, and M phase mitosis producing two daughter cells, with cycle times initially 12-16 hours during activation declining to 10-12 hours as activity increases. ||Periclinal cell division shows divisions with division plane parallel to berry surface, daughter cells positioned radially creating tissue thickness increase, periclinal divisions predominating in inner mesocarp regions, and divisions contributing to radial berry expansion. ||Anticlinal cell division shows divisions with plane perpendicular to surface, daughter cells positioned tangentially increasing tissue area, anticlinal divisions predominating in outer exocarp regions maintaining surface coverage, and divisions enabling tangential berry expansion. ||Division plane regulation shows orientation control through cytoskeletal organization, preprophase band microtubules predicting division plane, coordinated plane regulation creating organized tissue architecture, and spatial division patterns characteristic of tissue type and position. ||Cell number increase during active phase shows typical 4-16 fold accumulation over first 2-3 weeks, exponential growth from repeated division rounds, progressive increase in division-competent cell population, and acceleration toward peak activity. ||Tissue organization during active division shows coordinated division maintaining pericarp layer proportions, exocarp surface divisions preserving skin coverage during expansion, mesocarp bulk divisions creating flesh cellularity, and endocarp divisions near seeds, with overall organized growth producing functional berry architecture. ||Auxin gradient effects show higher auxin near seeds potentially stimulating greater division, spatial hormone distribution possibly affecting regional division patterns, and overall hormone signal coordinating proliferation across tissues. ||Division activation heterogeneity shows variation in activation timing across cell populations, some cells entering cycle earlier than others, progressive recruitment creating temporal spread, and heterogeneity contributing to extended division period. ||Environmental effects during active division include temperature affecting division rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid activation and proliferation, cool conditions slowing activation and division, and temperature during critical first 2 weeks affecting early cell number accumulation. ||Seed development coordination shows seeds developing in parallel providing continuing auxin stimulus, seed size increasing correlating with berry growth, and seed-berry coordination ensuring developmental synchronization. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including initial division activation establishing cell cycle entry, mitotic activity onset with first divisions occurring, and periclinal cell division as major division mode. ||Duration typically 2-3 weeks representing early division establishment before peak. ||Regional timing shows active berry cell division during late June-early July across climates as division initiates post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing proliferative program determining subsequent cell number achievement, demonstrating auxin stimulation mechanism, showing temperature sensitivity during critical activation period, and initiating cell number accumulation determining berry size. ||Research applications include analyzing division activation mechanisms and signaling, investigating cell cycle regulation during activation, evaluating division plane control and tissue organization, quantifying early cell number accumulation dynamics, and assessing active division as determinant of peak proliferation and final cellularity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 432-435 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Initial_Division_Activation": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Division_Activation is an Active_Berry_Cell_Division involving auxin-triggered exit of quiescent pericarp cells from G0 arrest into G1 phase preparing for DNA replication, occurring within the first week post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "cell cycle entry | G0-G1 transition | auxin-triggered activation | proliferative competence establishment |+ initiale Teilungs-Aktivierung | Zellzyklus-Eintritt | G0-G1-Übergang | Auxin-getriggerte Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows initial division activation during late June Year N+1 at BBCH 71, with auxin from 1.8-2.2 developing seeds reaching 120-180 ng/g in mesocarp days 3-6 post-fertilization, auxin signaling triggering cell cycle gene expression, G0 to G1 transition in pericarp cells, progressive activation wave completing by day 7, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar establishing division competence within first week",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Division_Activation is first aspect of Active_Berry_Cell_Division, distinguished by auxin-triggered cell cycle entry establishing proliferative competence. ||Represents G0 to G1 transition enabling division. ||Timing days 2-7 post-fertilization. ||Auxin-TIR1/AFB receptor signaling activating ARF transcription factors and cell cycle genes. ||Progressive activation wave through mesocarp. ||Temperature affects activation kinetics. ||Essential prerequisite for mitotic activity. ||Followed by Mitotic_Activity_Onset as divisions commence. ||Critical first step in cell proliferation program. || This critical activation phase occurs during early summer in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically days 2-7 post-fertilization as auxin reaches threshold levels, corresponding to BBCH 71 young fruit earliest stage. ||Division activation mechanism involves auxin perception by pericarp cells through TIR1/AFB auxin receptors, auxin-receptor complex triggering ubiquitin-mediated degradation of Aux/IAA repressor proteins, release of ARF transcription factors enabling cell cycle gene expression, transcriptional activation of cyclins, cyclin-dependent kinases, and other cell cycle regulators, G0 to G1 transition enabling growth and DNA replication preparation, and establishment of division-competent state. ||Auxin signaling pathway shows auxin from developing seeds transported to pericarp tissue, hormone accumulation reaching threshold levels 50-200 ng/g fresh weight triggering response, auxin binding to TIR1/AFB receptor proteins in nucleus, and receptor-mediated signaling cascade activating downstream responses. ||Auxin perception in pericarp cells shows receptor expression in mesocarp and exocarp tissues, spatially distributed receptors enabling tissue-wide response, auxin sensitivity variation among cell types possibly affecting activation timing, and receptor-hormone binding initiating signaling cascade. ||Aux/IAA repressor degradation shows auxin-receptor complex recruiting Aux/IAA proteins, ubiquitin ligase marking repressors for degradation, proteasomal degradation removing repression, and derepression enabling ARF transcription factor activity. ||ARF transcription factor activation shows ARF proteins released from repression binding auxin response elements in target gene promoters, transcriptional activation of cell cycle genes, and coordinated gene expression program establishing division competence. ||Cell cycle gene expression shows upregulation of D-type cyclins initiating G1 progression, cyclin-dependent kinase CDK4/6 activation, E2F transcription factor activation controlling S phase genes, and coordinated expression establishing cell cycle machinery. ||G0 to G1 transition shows exit from quiescent G0 state characteristic of post-commitment berry cells, entry into G1 growth phase with increased protein synthesis and cell growth, preparation for DNA replication initiation, and commitment point passage enabling S phase entry. ||Division activation timing shows auxin levels reaching threshold days 2-5 post-fertilization in cells near seeds, progressive activation wave spreading through mesocarp days 3-7, spatial and temporal heterogeneity creating extended activation period, and completion of activation wave by end of first week. ||Cell population activation dynamics show asynchronous activation across mesocarp cell populations, earlier activation near seeds with higher auxin exposure, later activation in peripheral regions, and progressive recruitment creating temporal spread in cell cycle entry. ||Activation checkpoint controls show growth factor signaling requirements for G1 progression, nutrient availability checks ensuring metabolic capacity, DNA damage surveillance preventing division of damaged cells, and checkpoint passage enabling irreversible commitment to division. ||Metabolic activation accompanying division shows increased respiratory rate providing ATP for biosynthesis, enhanced protein synthesis supporting cell cycle machinery production, nucleotide biosynthesis preparing for DNA replication, and overall metabolic upregulation supporting proliferative state. ||Chromatin remodeling during activation shows histone modifications marking active versus repressed chromatin regions, chromatin accessibility changes enabling transcription factor binding, epigenetic programming establishing division-competent state, and coordinated chromatin changes facilitating cell cycle gene expression. ||DNA replication licensing shows origin recognition complex binding replication origins during G1, MCM helicase loading creating licensed origins, replication licensing preventing re-replication, and licensed origins enabling subsequent S phase DNA synthesis. ||Spatial activation patterns show inner mesocarp cells activating earlier than outer regions in some studies, possible auxin gradient from seeds affecting activation timing, exocarp surface cells showing distinct activation possibly coordinated with surface expansion, and overall coordinated activation maintaining tissue organization. ||Environmental effects on activation include temperature affecting signaling kinetics and metabolic activation rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid activation within 3-5 days, cool conditions slowing activation extending to 5-9 days, and temperature as factor affecting activation timing and efficiency. ||Seed number effects show multiple seeds producing greater cumulative auxin accelerating activation, higher hormone dose potentially activating more cells or accelerating timing, and seed number affecting division extent through activation effects. ||Failed or delayed activation causes include inadequate auxin production from poor seed development, impaired auxin signaling from genetic or metabolic dysfunction, severe environmental stress during critical days 2-7 disrupting signaling, or developmental abnormalities preventing normal activation. ||Activation assessment methods include cell cycle marker gene expression analysis showing upregulation, immunohistochemistry detecting cyclin proteins, BrdU or EdU incorporation marking cells entering S phase, and proliferation marker PCNA detection indicating division-competent cells. ||The process represents first aspect of active berry cell division establishing division competence, preceding mitotic activity onset and periclinal division. ||Duration typically 3-7 days representing auxin-triggered cell cycle entry. ||Regional timing shows initial division activation during late June-early July across climates within first week post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical first step in cell proliferation determining subsequent division success, demonstrating auxin as primary proliferation signal, showing temperature sensitivity during activation affecting division timing, and establishing division competence as prerequisite for cell number accumulation. ||Research applications include analyzing auxin signaling mechanisms in berry cells, investigating cell cycle activation regulation, evaluating environmental effects on activation timing, quantifying spatial activation patterns in pericarp, and assessing activation as determinant of division extent and berry cellularity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 432-434 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Mitotic_Activity_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Mitotic_Activity_Onset is an Active_Berry_Cell_Division marked by the first observable mitotic divisions in pericarp cells producing daughter cells, occurring 7–10 days post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "first mitosis | division commencement | proliferation initiation | first cell division |+ mitotische Aktivitäts-Beginn | erste Mitose | Teilungsbeginn | Proliferations-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows mitotic activity onset during early July Year N+1 at BBCH 71, with first divisions occurring days 6-9 post-fertilization following DNA replication, M phase mitosis with chromosome segregation and cytokinesis, initial cell cycle times 13-15 hours, progressive division onset across mesocarp cell populations, observable mitotic index increasing from <1% to 3-8% during week 1-2, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar establishing proliferative state",
  "editor_note": "Mitotic_Activity_Onset is second aspect of Active_Berry_Cell_Division, distinguished by first divisions occurring establishing proliferative state. ||Represents S phase DNA replication, M phase mitosis, and cytokinesis producing daughter cells. ||Timing days 5-10 post-fertilization. ||Initial cell cycle times 14-16 hours accelerating to 12-14 hours. ||Exponential cell number increase initiating. ||Temperature affects division timing. ||Follows Initial_Division_Activation. ||Precedes pattern-specific Periclinal_Cell_Division. ||Observable proliferation marker. || This critical division initiation phase occurs during early summer in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically days 5-10 post-fertilization following activation, corresponding to BBCH 71 young fruit early development stage. ||Mitotic onset mechanism involves G1 to S phase transition with DNA replication initiation, S phase DNA synthesis doubling chromosome number from 2n to 4n, G2 phase preparation for mitosis, M phase entry with chromatin condensation and mitotic spindle formation, chromosome segregation to daughter cells, cytokinesis creating cell plate dividing cytoplasm, and completion producing two daughter cells re-entering G1 enabling subsequent divisions. ||S phase entry and DNA replication shows cyclin E-CDK2 complex activation triggering replication origin firing, DNA polymerase recruitment to licensed replication origins, bidirectional replication fork progression along chromosomes at 0.5-2 kb per minute, replication checkpoint surveillance ensuring complete faithful replication, and S phase completion within 6-10 hours during early berry development. ||DNA synthesis characteristics show semiconservative replication producing two daughter DNA molecules each with one original and one new strand, high fidelity polymerase activity with proofreading maintaining <1 error per 10⁹ nucleotides, coordinated replication across entire 475 Mb Vitis vinifera genome, and replication completion required before mitosis entry. ||G2 phase preparation shows continued cell growth, checkpoint surveillance ensuring complete DNA replication and cell size adequacy, centrosome duplication preparing spindle formation, and G2-M transition checkpoint passage enabling mitosis entry. ||M phase mitosis shows chromatin condensation into visible chromosomes, nuclear envelope breakdown releasing chromosomes into cytoplasm, mitotic spindle formation from centrosome-nucleated microtubules, chromosome alignment at metaphase plate, anaphase segregation distributing sister chromatids to spindle poles, and telophase nuclear envelope reformation around separated chromosome sets. ||Chromosome segregation fidelity shows kinetochore-microtubule attachment providing force for chromosome movement, spindle assembly checkpoint ensuring proper attachment before anaphase, accurate 19 per 19 chromosome distribution to daughter cells maintaining diploid 2n state, and high segregation fidelity preventing aneuploidy. ||Cytokinesis and cell division completion shows phragmoplast microtubule array formation at division plane, vesicle fusion initiating cell plate synthesis, progressive cell plate expansion from center outward, cell wall deposition creating new wall between daughter cells, and completion producing two separate cells each re-entering G1 phase. ||First division timing shows earliest divisions occurring days 5-7 post-fertilization in early-activating cells near seeds, progressive division onset across cell populations days 6-10 creating temporal spread, and completion of first division wave by day 10 establishing proliferative tissue. ||Division rate acceleration shows initial slower division during first round, acceleration as daughter cells re-enter cycle more rapidly, progressive rate increase as cell populations synchronize, and transition toward peak division rate by week 2. ||Cell number increase initiation shows first divisions doubling initial cell number, second round divisions quadrupling number, exponential growth pattern establishing from repeated division rounds, and observable cell number increase beginning week 1-2. ||Observable mitotic figures show condensed chromosomes visible under microscopy during metaphase, spindle structures evident during anaphase, dividing cells identifiable through cytological examination, and mitotic index increasing as division onset proceeds. ||Cell cycle times at onset show initial cycles 14-16 hours during first divisions, progressive acceleration to 12-14 hours as activity increases, and eventual peak rates 10-12 hours during maximum activity. ||Daughter cell characteristics show cells initially similar size to parent approximately 20-30 micrometers, cells entering G1 capable of growth and subsequent division, and daughter cells contributing to proliferating population. ||Spatial division patterns show earliest divisions in mesocarp regions near seeds, progressive expansion of dividing zone throughout mesocarp, exocarp surface cells showing coordinated division maintaining coverage, and spatial pattern reflecting auxin gradient and tissue organization. ||Environmental effects on mitotic onset include temperature critically affecting cell cycle progression rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid cycle completion and division onset within 5-7 days, cool conditions 18-22°C slowing cycles delaying onset to 7-12 days, and temperature as major factor determining division timing. ||Nutrient requirements show adequate nitrogen for protein synthesis supporting cell cycle machinery, phosphorus for DNA synthesis and energy metabolism, and overall mineral nutrition supporting division though usually adequate in vineyard conditions. ||Division onset assessment methods include mitotic index calculation counting dividing cells per total cells, immunohistochemistry detecting mitotic marker proteins, BrdU or EdU pulse-labeling identifying S phase cells, and proliferation marker PCNA showing cycling cells. ||Failed or delayed onset causes include incomplete DNA replication preventing mitosis entry, checkpoint arrest from DNA damage or stress, inadequate metabolic support preventing cycle completion, or severe environmental stress disrupting division. ||The process represents second aspect of active berry cell division marking first divisions, following initial division activation and preceding periclinal cell division patterns. ||Duration represents division onset wave over days 5-10 post-fertilization. ||Regional timing shows mitotic activity onset during late June-early July across climates within first 1-2 weeks post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing observable proliferation initiation marking berry as actively growing tissue, establishing exponential cell number increase pattern, demonstrating temperature sensitivity of division timing, and initiating cell accumulation determining final berry cellularity. ||Research applications include analyzing cell cycle regulation and division timing, investigating mitotic spindle function and chromosome segregation, evaluating environmental effects on division onset, quantifying early division rates and patterns, and assessing division onset as determinant of proliferation extent and berry size potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 433-435 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Periclinal_Cell_Division": {
  "definition": "A Periclinal_Cell_Division is an Active_Berry_Cell_Division characterized by division planes oriented parallel to the berry surface with daughter cells positioned radially increasing pericarp thickness.",
  "alternative_term": "radial cell division | tangential division | surface-parallel division | depth-increasing division |+ periklinale Zellteilung | radiale Zellteilung | oberflächenparallele Teilung | tiefenzunehmende Teilung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows periclinal cell division during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 71-72, with division planes aligned parallel to berry surface, preprophase bands predicting periclinal orientation, radial daughter cell positioning increasing mesocarp depth from 0.8 mm to 3.2 mm over weeks 1-4, periclinal divisions representing 62-74% total divisions in inner mesocarp, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar showing coordinated periclinal proliferation contributing to berry volumetric expansion",
  "editor_note": "Periclinal_Cell_Division is third aspect of Active_Berry_Cell_Division, distinguished by surface-parallel division plane orientation. ||Represents radial tissue growth increasing depth. ||Predominates in inner mesocarp 60-75% of divisions. ||Division plane controlled by preprophase band and spindle orientation. ||Contrasts with anticlinal divisions in outer layers. ||Duration throughout active division weeks 1-3. ||Contributes to three-dimensional berry expansion. ||Creates organized radial cell files. ||Tissue-specific division pattern. || This directional division pattern occurs during early summer cell division in late June-July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding throughout active division weeks 1-3 as major division mode, corresponding to BBCH 71-72 young fruit growth stages. ||Periclinal division mechanism involves division plane orientation control through cytoskeletal organization, preprophase band microtubules establishing division plane parallel to surface before mitosis, spindle alignment perpendicular to surface directing chromosome segregation, cytokinesis producing cell plate parallel to epidermis, and daughter cell radial positioning increasing tissue depth. ||Division plane determination shows preprophase band formation during late G2 phase, cortical microtubule array marking future division site on plasma membrane, division plane prediction from preprophase band position, and band disappearance before mitosis while plane memory persists. ||Preprophase band characteristics show microtubule ring encircling cell at division site, band width 2-5 micrometers predicting cell plate insertion zone, band position determining periclinal versus anticlinal orientation, and band as spatial memory system controlling division geometry. ||Spindle orientation control shows spindle axis alignment perpendicular to berry surface and parallel to radial axis, spindle positioning ensuring chromosome segregation produces radial daughter positioning, astral microtubules contacting cortical sites marked by preprophase band, and motor proteins positioning spindle through force generation on astral microtubules. ||Cytokinesis plane alignment shows cell plate forming parallel to preprophase band position, phragmoplast guidance by former band site, progressive cell plate expansion creating new wall parallel to surface, and completed division producing radially arranged daughter cells. ||Daughter cell positioning shows cells arranged along radial axis from surface toward center, radial arrangement increasing tissue depth, daughter cells both contributing to subsequent radial expansion through additional divisions or enlargement, and coordinated radial positioning creating organized tissue architecture. ||Periclinal predominance in mesocarp shows inner flesh tissue showing primarily periclinal divisions, radial divisions increasing tissue thickness more than anticlinal divisions increasing area, and periclinal divisions accounting for 60-75% total divisions in inner mesocarp regions. ||Tissue thickness increase from periclinal divisions shows progressive mesocarp depth expansion, radial growth contributing substantially to volumetric berry increase, thickness increase from 0.5-1 mm at division onset to 2-4 mm by division completion, and radial expansion as major contributor to three-dimensional berry growth. ||Three-dimensional growth contribution shows periclinal radial divisions combined with anticlinal tangential divisions creating volumetric expansion, radial growth from periclinial divisions, tangential growth from anticlinal divisions, and integrated division pattern producing spherical to ovoid berry morphology. ||Division plane regulation shows genetic control through division plane orientation genes, cytoskeletal regulatory proteins controlling preprophase band and spindle positioning, auxin possibly affecting division plane orientation though mechanisms unclear, and developmental programming establishing tissue-specific division patterns. ||Periclinal versus anticlinal division ratios show spatial variation with inner mesocarp 60-75% periclinal, middle mesocarp 50-50%, outer mesocarp 25-40% periclinal, and ratios reflecting position-specific growth requirements. ||Exocarp division patterns show epidermis and outer layers showing primarily anticlinal divisions maintaining surface coverage, anticlinal divisions enabling tangential expansion accommodating berry enlargement, and anticlinal predominance in surface layers contrasting with mesocarp periclinal pattern. ||Coordinated division orientation shows tissue-specific patterns creating organized architecture, inner mesocarp periclinal radial growth, outer exocarp anticlinal tangential growth, and coordination maintaining tissue proportions and structural integrity during berry expansion. ||Cell layer organization from divisions shows radial cell files from repeated periclinal divisions, organized layer structure in mesocarp, and architecture reflecting division history and pattern. ||Environmental effects on periclinal division include temperature affecting division rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid periclinal proliferation, division plane orientation likely temperature-independent though division frequency affected, and overall favorable conditions maximizing periclinal division contribution to growth. ||Mechanical stress effects show possible influences on division plane orientation though evidence limited in berries, turgor pressure potentially affecting plane selection, and tissue architecture possibly providing mechanical cues. ||Periclinal division assessment methods include histological section analysis showing radial cell arrangements, division plane observation during mitosis, daughter cell position tracking, and tissue architecture analysis inferring division patterns. ||The process represents third aspect of active berry cell division emphasizing radial division orientation, following initial division activation and mitotic activity onset. ||Duration throughout active division weeks 1-3 as predominant inner mesocarp division mode. ||Regional timing shows periclinal cell division during late June-July across climates during early berry division phase. ||Viticultural significance includes representing major division pattern contributing to radial berry expansion and volumetric growth, demonstrating coordinated tissue-specific division orientation, creating organized mesocarp architecture, and contributing to three-dimensional berry morphology development. ||Research applications include analyzing division plane control mechanisms, investigating cytoskeletal regulation of division orientation, evaluating tissue-specific division patterns, quantifying periclinal versus anticlinal division ratios, and assessing division orientation as determinant of berry shape and architecture.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 434-436"
},

  "Peak_Division_Activity": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Division_Activity is a Berry_Cell_Division_Phase characterized by maximum mitotic intensity with cell cycle duration of 10–12 hours, extending over weeks 2–3 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum mitotic activity | peak proliferation | maximum cell division | highest division rate |+ Spitzen-Teilungsaktivität | maximale mitotische Aktivität | Spitzen-Proliferation | höchste Teilungsrate",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows peak division activity during mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 72-73, with maximum mitotic index 10-14% during weeks 2-3 post-fertilization, cell cycle times minimized to 10-12 hours, rapid cell accumulation from 350,000 to 2.4-3.0 million cells during peak period, coordinated division across mesocarp and exocarp tissues, under warm climate conditions of 26-32°C temperature, typical of this late-season large-berried cultivar achieving maximum cell number generation determining final berry size potential",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Division_Activity is second phase of Berry_Cell_Division_Phase, distinguished by maximum mitotic intensity. ||Subdivided into Maximum_Cell_Number_Generation representing peak proliferative output, Pericarp_Cell_Proliferation emphasizing mesocarp focus, and Seed_Compartment_Cell_Division showing regional specialization. ||Duration 1.5-2.5 weeks with peak weeks 2-3. ||Cell cycle times 10-12 hours minimum. ||Generates 60-75% final cell number. ||Temperature critically affects intensity. ||Follows Active_Berry_Cell_Division. ||Precedes division decline and expansion phase. ||Major berry size determinant. || This maximum proliferation phase occurs during mid summer in early-mid July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over weeks 1.5-3.5 post-fertilization with peak intensity weeks 2-3, corresponding to BBCH 72-73 young fruit active growth stages. ||Peak activity mechanism involves widespread cell cycle synchronization across mesocarp populations, maximum cyclin-CDK activity driving rapid cycle progression, minimal cell cycle times 10-12 hours representing fastest division rate, coordinated division across pericarp tissues, maximum cell number generation determining majority of final cellularity, and peak activity representing culmination of proliferative program before gradual decline. ||Division rate maximization shows peak mitotic index 8-15% indicating high proportion of dividing cells, maximum absolute division rate with thousands of cells dividing per hour per berry, cell cycle time minimization to 10-12 hours from earlier 14-16 hours, and peak rate representing optimal proliferative capacity under favorable conditions. ||Cell cycle time characteristics show S phase duration 5-7 hours for DNA replication, G2 phase 1-2 hours for mitotic preparation, M phase 0.5-1 hour for chromosome segregation and cytokinesis, G1 phase 3-4 hours for growth and preparation, and total cycle 10-12 hours during peak activity. ||Synchronized division shows cell populations entering and exiting cycle phases coordinately, temporal clustering of divisions creating high activity periods, synchronization possibly from common auxin stimulus and division initiation timing, and coordinated divisions creating efficient proliferation. ||Maximum cell number generation shows majority 60-75% of final cell number accumulated during peak activity weeks 2-3, rapid cell accumulation from 200,000-500,000 to 1-3 million cells during peak period, exponential growth pattern with doubling time 10-12 hours matching cycle time, and peak generation establishing bulk berry cellularity. ||Pericarp cell proliferation shows mesocarp flesh tissue undergoing most intensive division, cell number increase throughout mesocarp layers, coordinated proliferation maintaining tissue proportions, and mesocarp as primary proliferative compartment determining berry size. ||Seed compartment cell division shows endocarp inner layer adjacent to seeds showing continued division, specialized cell populations near seeds potentially responding to local auxin maxima, and seed region divisions contributing to overall cellularity though representing smaller fraction. ||Tissue-specific division patterns show mesocarp accounting for 80-85% total cell divisions, exocarp surface layers 10-15%, endocarp seed regions 3-5%, and tissue distribution reflecting developmental roles and final architecture. ||Spatial division distribution shows divisions throughout berry volume, possible gradient with higher activity near seeds in some studies, overall relatively uniform distribution across mesocarp, and coordinated division maintaining spherical to ovoid berry shape. ||Cell population heterogeneity shows variation in cycle timing across cells, some populations dividing faster than others, heterogeneity preventing perfect synchronization, and population variation contributing to extended peak period. ||Division plane patterns show periclinal divisions predominating in inner regions, anticlinal divisions in outer layers, coordinated orientation creating organized architecture, and plane regulation maintaining tissue structure during rapid proliferation. ||Auxin effects on peak activity show continued hormone stimulus from developing seeds supporting sustained division, auxin levels typically peaking weeks 1-3 coinciding with division peak, hormone decline beginning week 3-4 correlating with division rate decline, and auxin as primary proliferation driver. ||Environmental effects on peak activity include temperature critically affecting peak division rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum 10-12 hour cycles, cool conditions 18-22°C extending cycles to 13-16 hours reducing peak intensity, warm conditions 28-32°C potentially supporting faster cycles though excessive heat above 35°C impairing division, and temperature as major peak activity determinant. ||Nutrient effects show adequate nitrogen supporting protein synthesis for rapid division, phosphorus for DNA synthesis and energy metabolism, and overall nutrition supporting peak activity though usually non-limiting. ||Peak activity duration shows typically 1.5-2.5 weeks of maximum intensity, peak representing culmination of accelerating activity from week 1, and gradual decline beginning week 3-4 as cells progressively exit cycle. ||Division decline mechanisms show progressive cell cycle exit beginning week 3, auxin levels declining reducing proliferative stimulus, cells transitioning to expansion phase, and declining division rate characteristic of developmental program. ||Cell number at peak completion shows typical 70-85% final cell number achieved by peak activity completion week 3-4, remaining 15-30% cells from continued lower-rate division weeks 4-5, and peak activity as primary cellularity determinant. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including maximum cell number generation representing peak proliferative output, pericarp cell proliferation emphasizing mesocarp tissue focus, and seed compartment cell division representing regional specialization. ||Duration typically 1.5-2.5 weeks representing maximum intensity period. ||Regional timing shows peak division activity during early-mid July across climates weeks 2-3 post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing maximum proliferation determining majority of final cell number, demonstrating critical importance of optimal conditions during peak weeks for cellularity achievement, showing temperature sensitivity of peak division intensity, and establishing peak activity as major berry size determinant. ||Research applications include analyzing peak division regulation and timing, investigating cell cycle control during maximum activity, evaluating environmental effects on peak intensity and duration, quantifying cell number generation dynamics, and assessing peak activity as determinant of final berry cellularity and size.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 435-438 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Maximum_Cell_Number_Generation": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Cell_Number_Generation is a Peak_Division_Activity marked by exponential accumulation of 60–75% of the final berry cell number over a 1.5–2.5 week interval.",
  "alternative_term": "peak cell production | maximum proliferative output | cell number accumulation peak | exponential cell generation |+ maximale Zellzahl-Erzeugung | Spitzen-Zellproduktion | maximale proliferative Leistung | Zellzahl-Akkumulationsspitze",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows maximum cell number generation during mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 72-73, with exponential cell accumulation from 280,000 to 2.0-2.6 million cells over weeks 2-3 post-fertilization, peak generation rate 65,000-110,000 cells per day, doubling time 10-11 hours, generating 68-73% final cell number during 2-week period, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar establishing cellularity determining 12-14 mm final berry size",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Cell_Number_Generation is first aspect of Peak_Division_Activity, distinguished by peak proliferative output. ||Represents exponential cell accumulation at maximum rate. ||Duration 1.5-2.5 weeks generating 60-75% final cell number. ||Peak rate 40,000-120,000 cells/day. ||Doubling time 10-12 hours. ||Temperature critically affects generation rate. ||Irreversible cellularity establishment. ||Followed by spatial distribution aspects in Pericarp and Seed Compartment proliferation. ||Critical berry size determinant. || This maximum generation phase occurs during mid summer in early-mid July in temperate regions Year N+1, typically weeks 2-3 post-fertilization during peak division intensity, corresponding to BBCH 72-73 young fruit rapid growth stages. ||Maximum generation mechanism involves synchronized rapid cell division across large mesocarp cell populations, minimal 10-12 hour cell cycle times enabling 2-2.4 divisions per day, exponential accumulation from repeated division rounds, coordinated proliferation across pericarp tissues, and maximum generation rate producing thousands of new cells per hour per berry. ||Cell number accumulation dynamics show typical progression from 200,000-500,000 cells at maximum generation onset to 1.2-3.5 million cells at completion, accumulation rate 50,000-150,000 cells per day during peak period, doubling time 10-12 hours matching minimal cell cycle time, and exponential growth pattern characteristic of maximum generation. ||Generation rate quantification shows peak rate typically 40,000-120,000 new cells generated per berry per day, rate representing combined output of all dividing cell populations, maximum rate sustained 1.5-2.5 weeks before decline, and generation rate as direct function of cycling cell number and cycle time. ||Cell cycle contribution to generation shows cells completing 2-2.4 cycles per day at 10-12 hour cycle times, each division doubling local cell number, 10-16 fold total cell number increase over 1.5-2.5 week maximum generation period, and geometric progression creating rapid accumulation. ||Exponential accumulation pattern shows characteristic exponential growth curve during maximum generation, growth equation N(t) = N₀ × 2^(t/T) where T is doubling time 10-12 hours, exponential phase representing unrestricted proliferative capacity, and transition to declining rate as cells exit cycle. ||Cell population expansion shows all actively dividing cells contributing to generation, population size increasing as divisions produce more dividing cells, self-amplifying process characteristic of exponential growth, and population expansion creating majority of final cellularity. ||Division-competent cell fraction shows high proportion 70-85% mesocarp cells actively cycling during maximum generation, cycling fraction representing cells capable of division versus quiescent or differentiating cells, and high fraction enabling maximum generation output. ||Spatial generation patterns show cell generation throughout mesocarp volume, possible gradient with higher generation near seeds though relatively uniform overall, coordinated generation maintaining tissue organization, and spatial patterns creating organized berry architecture. ||Mesocarp cell generation shows flesh tissue as primary generation site accounting for 80-85% total new cells, mesocarp volume increase from cell accumulation, and mesocarp generation determining bulk berry size. ||Exocarp cell generation shows surface layer generation accounting for 10-15% total new cells, anticlinal divisions maintaining surface coverage during berry expansion, and coordinated surface generation preventing cracking. ||Generation sufficiency for size shows cell number achieved during maximum generation largely determining final berry size, typical strong correlation r² 0.70-0.85 between peak generation output and mature berry diameter, and generation period as critical size determinant. ||Cell number finalization shows maximum generation producing 60-75% final cell number, remaining 25-40% cells from continued declining-rate division weeks 3.5-5, and peak generation as dominant cellularity source. ||Environmental effects on maximum generation include temperature critically affecting generation rate through cycle time effects with optimal 24-28°C supporting 10-12 hour cycles and maximum generation, cool conditions 18-22°C extending cycles to 13-16 hours reducing generation rate 30-50%, warm conditions above 32°C potentially accelerating cycles though excessive heat impairing division, and temperature during peak weeks 2-3 as critical generation determinant. ||Auxin effects show hormone from seeds sustaining maximum generation, auxin levels peak weeks 1-3 supporting sustained division, hormone decline week 3-4 correlating with generation rate decline, and auxin as primary generation stimulus. ||Nutrient effects show adequate nitrogen supporting protein synthesis for rapid generation, phosphorus for DNA synthesis, and overall nutrition usually adequate though deficiency could limit generation in extreme cases. ||Failed or limited generation causes include suboptimal temperature during peak period permanently reducing achieved cell number, inadequate auxin from poor seed development limiting generation stimulus, severe stress during weeks 2-3 arresting division, and environmental limitations during critical period irreversibly reducing final cellularity and size. ||Generation assessment methods include cell counting at different time points quantifying accumulation rate, mathematical modeling of exponential growth fitting accumulation curves, mitotic index measurement correlating with generation rate, and population doubling time calculation from accumulation dynamics. ||The process represents first aspect of peak division activity emphasizing proliferative output, followed by pericarp and seed compartment proliferation discussing spatial distribution. ||Duration typically 1.5-2.5 weeks representing maximum generation period. ||Regional timing shows maximum cell number generation during early-mid July across climates weeks 2-3 post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical period generating majority of berry cellularity, demonstrating extreme importance of optimal conditions during brief peak weeks, showing temperature as major generation rate determinant, and establishing maximum generation as primary berry size determinant through cell number effects. ||Research applications include analyzing generation dynamics and mathematical modeling, investigating environmental effects on generation rate and final cellularity, evaluating cell cycle regulation during peak generation, quantifying generation output and size relationships, and assessing maximum generation as critical determinant of berry development outcomes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 435-437 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Pericarp_Cell_Proliferation": {
  "definition": "A Pericarp_Cell_Proliferation is a Peak_Division_Activity comprising coordinated mesocarp and exocarp division producing 80–85% of total berry cell generation in mesocarp tissue with maintained exocarp coverage.",
  "alternative_term": "berry wall proliferation | mesocarp and exocarp division | flesh and skin cell generation | pericarp tissue proliferation |+ Perikarp-Zellproliferation | Beerenwand-Proliferation | Mesokarp- und Exokarp-Teilung | Fleisch- und Haut-Zellenerzeugung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows pericarp cell proliferation during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 72-73, with mesocarp intensive division generating 1.4-1.9 million flesh cells representing 82-86% total, exocarp surface division producing 180,000-260,000 skin cells through anticlinal divisions, endocarp limited division yielding 60,000-100,000 inner layer cells, coordinated pericarp proliferation establishing three-layered berry wall architecture, under cool maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Pericarp_Cell_Proliferation is second aspect of Peak_Division_Activity, distinguished by tissue-specific proliferation focus. ||Represents mesocarp flesh (80-85%), exocarp skin (10-15%), and endocarp (3-5%) coordinated proliferation. ||Mesocarp dominant proliferative tissue determining size. ||Exocarp anticlinal divisions maintaining surface. ||Duration peak weeks 2-3. ||Establishes three-layered pericarp architecture. ||Followed by Seed_Compartment_Cell_Division. ||Tissue-specific division patterns creating organized structure. || This tissue-specific proliferation phase occurs during mid summer in early-mid July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding during peak division weeks 2-3 post-fertilization, corresponding to BBCH 72-73 young fruit growth stages. ||Pericarp proliferation mechanism involves mesocarp flesh tissue intensive division generating majority of berry cells, exocarp skin layer coordinated division maintaining surface integrity, endocarp inner layer adjacent to seeds showing limited division, tissue-specific division rates and patterns creating organized architecture, and overall pericarp proliferation establishing berry wall structure. ||Mesocarp proliferation dominance shows flesh tissue as primary proliferative compartment, mesocarp cell generation accounting for 80-85% total pericarp cells, intensive division throughout mesocarp volume creating bulk cellularity, and mesocarp as major berry size determinant. ||Mesocarp division patterns show periclinal divisions predominating in inner regions increasing radial depth, anticlinal divisions in middle regions maintaining proportions, coordinated division creating organized mesocarp architecture, and division patterns establishing tissue organization. ||Mesocarp cellularity establishment shows typical accumulation to 1.5-3.5 million mesocarp cells by proliferation completion, cell number range reflecting cultivar variation and environmental effects, and mesocarp cellularity as primary berry size determinant accounting for bulk volume. ||Exocarp proliferation characteristics show surface epidermal and subepidermal layer division, primarily anticlinal divisions perpendicular to surface expanding coverage area, coordinated exocarp division maintaining continuous surface during berry expansion, and exocarp cell generation accounting for 10-15% total pericarp cells. ||Exocarp division necessity shows surface area increase requirement as berry expands, anticlinal divisions producing new cells expanding coverage, division preventing gaps or cracking from expansion stress, and adequate exocarp proliferation essential for berry integrity. ||Exocarp architecture from proliferation shows epidermal single cell layer maintained through anticlinal division, subepidermal 4-8 cell layers from combined periclinal and anticlinal divisions, exocarp total thickness 6-12 cell layers representing skin structure, and layer organization from coordinated division patterns. ||Endocarp limited proliferation shows inner layer adjacent to seeds showing reduced division compared to mesocarp, endocarp accounting for 3-5% total pericarp cell generation, specialized endocarp cells possibly less proliferative, and limited division creating thin 2-4 cell layer endocarp. ||Tissue proportion maintenance shows coordinated proliferation across layers maintaining relative proportions, mesocarp as bulk tissue 80-85% volume, exocarp as surface layer 8-12% volume, endocarp as inner layer 3-5% volume, and proportions established through tissue-specific division rates. ||Tissue-specific division regulation shows differential proliferative capacity across layers, possible auxin gradient effects with higher levels near seeds, mechanical factors possibly affecting surface versus internal division, developmental programming establishing tissue-specific patterns, and integrated regulation creating organized architecture. ||Cell type differentiation during proliferation shows cells maintaining division competence while acquiring tissue identity, early differentiation markers appearing during proliferation, and progressive specialization as division completes. ||Vascular tissue proliferation shows procambial cells dividing creating vascular bundles, xylem and phloem precursor proliferation, vascular network expansion coordinated with berry growth, and vascular development supporting berry enlargement. ||Pericarp volume increase from proliferation shows tissue expansion from cell accumulation, volumetric increase correlating with cell number, pericarp representing 85-95% total berry volume at division completion, and volume from proliferation establishing berry size baseline. ||Environmental effects on pericarp proliferation include temperature affecting proliferation rate across all layers with optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum pericarp cell generation, differential temperature sensitivity possible across tissues though evidence limited, and overall temperature effects on total pericarp proliferation. ||Auxin effects show hormone gradient possibly affecting mesocarp versus exocarp proliferation, higher auxin near seeds potentially stimulating greater mesocarp division, and overall auxin stimulus coordinating pericarp proliferation. ||Pericarp proliferation assessment methods include tissue-specific cell counting quantifying layer cellularity, histological analysis showing tissue architecture, division pattern observation documenting periclinal versus anticlinal divisions, and proliferation marker distribution across tissues. ||The process represents second aspect of peak division activity emphasizing tissue-specific proliferation, following maximum cell number generation and preceding seed compartment division. ||Duration throughout peak division weeks 2-3 representing coordinated tissue proliferation. ||Regional timing shows pericarp cell proliferation during early-mid July across climates during peak berry division. ||Viticultural significance includes representing major cellularity establishment determining berry structure and size, demonstrating coordinated tissue-specific proliferation creating organized architecture, showing mesocarp as dominant proliferative tissue establishing size, and establishing pericarp proliferation as berry developmental foundation. ||Research applications include analyzing tissue-specific proliferation regulation, investigating division pattern control across layers, evaluating pericarp architecture establishment, quantifying tissue cellularity and proportions, and assessing pericarp proliferation as determinant of berry structure and size.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 436-438"
},

  "Seed_Compartment_Cell_Division": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Compartment_Cell_Division is a Peak_Division_Activity comprising localized endocarp proliferation adjacent to developing seeds accounting for 3–5% of total berry cell generation.",
  "alternative_term": "endocarp proliferation | seed region cell division | seed cavity formation | localized seed area division |+ Samenfach-Zellteilung | Endokarp-Proliferation | Samenregion-Zellteilung | Samenkavität-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows seed compartment cell division during early-mid July Year N+1 at BBCH 72-73, with endocarp cells adjacent to 1.4-2.0 developing seeds undergoing limited proliferation creating 2-3 cell layer seed cavity lining, seed compartment cell generation accounting for 3.8-4.6% total berry cells, 1-2 seed cavities 5-7 mm diameter accommodating developing seeds, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar establishing seed-berry interface structure",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Compartment_Cell_Division is third and final aspect of Peak_Division_Activity, distinguished by localized endocarp proliferation near seeds. ||Represents specialized regional division accounting for 3-5% total cells. ||Limited 2-4 cell layer endocarp thickness contrasting with abundant mesocarp. ||Possibly responding to local seed auxin though poorly characterized. ||Creates seed cavity structure and seed-berry interface. ||Duration concurrent with peak weeks 2-3. ||Completes Peak_Division_Activity documentation. ||Specialized tissue-specific proliferation. || This regionalized division phase occurs during mid summer in early-mid July in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding during peak division weeks 2-3 post-fertilization, corresponding to BBCH 72-73 young fruit stages. ||Seed compartment division mechanism involves endocarp inner pericarp layer cells adjacent to seeds undergoing limited proliferation, localized division creating 2-4 cell layer seed cavity lining, possible enhanced division from local auxin maximum near seeds though evidence limited, specialized cell differentiation potentially accompanying division, and seed compartment establishment creating functional interface. ||Endocarp localization shows tissue positioning at pericarp inner surface directly adjacent to developing seeds, endocarp surrounding individual seeds in seed cavity, tissue contact with seed integuments, and positioning enabling seed-pericarp communication. ||Endocarp cell division characteristics show limited division compared to abundant mesocarp proliferation, typical 2-4 cell layer thickness from restricted proliferation, periclinal divisions increasing radial thickness, and cell generation accounting for 3-5% total berry cells. ||Seed cavity formation shows localized space development surrounding each seed, cavity lined by endocarp tissue, cavity size accommodating seed growth, and cavity structure from coordinated endocarp division and mesocarp displacement. ||Seed cavity architecture shows typically 2-4 cavities per berry corresponding to seed number, cavity diameter 4-8 mm accommodating 4-6 mm mature seeds, endocarp lining providing protective interface, and cavity organization reflecting seed positioning and development. ||Local auxin effects hypothesis shows seeds as auxin source with highest concentration in immediate vicinity, possible auxin gradient with maximum at seed surface declining into mesocarp, local auxin potentially stimulating nearby endocarp division though direct evidence limited, and gradient possibly affecting regional proliferation though mesocarp also highly proliferative. ||Endocarp versus mesocarp proliferation comparison shows mesocarp 20-30 fold greater cell generation than endocarp, mesocarp extensive 15-25 cell layer thickness versus endocarp limited 2-4 layers, and differential proliferation creating tissue-specific cellularity. ||Endocarp cell specialization shows potential differentiation into transfer cells or modified parenchyma, possible structural specialization for seed-pericarp interface function, cell wall modifications possibly enabling nutrient or signal exchange, and specialized cells providing functional interface though poorly characterized in grapevine. ||Seed development coordination shows seeds developing in parallel with berry division phase, seed size increase correlating with berry growth, seed maturation largely completing by division phase end, and seed-berry coordination ensuring developmental synchronization. ||Seed size during division phase shows seeds growing from 2-3 mm at division onset to 4-6 mm by completion, seed expansion coordinated with berry growth, and seed cavity accommodating seed enlargement. ||Endocarp-seed interface functions hypothetically include nutrient transfer from pericarp to developing seed, hormone communication from seed to berry affecting growth, mechanical support and protection for seeds, and signal integration coordinating seed and berry development. ||Cell division near funiculus shows possible enhanced division near vascular connection, funiculus providing nutrient and hormone transport, and funiculus region potentially showing specialized division patterns. ||Endocarp division timing shows division coinciding with peak mesocarp proliferation weeks 2-3, coordinated timing across pericarp regions, and endocarp completion concurrent with overall division phase end. ||Division completion and maturation shows endocarp division completing by week 4-5, cells transitioning to expansion and differentiation, mature endocarp as thin protective layer around seeds, and completed endocarp structure persisting through berry development and ripening. ||Environmental effects on seed compartment division include temperature affecting division rate similarly to other pericarp regions, seed development providing proliferative stimulus through auxin production, and overall favorable conditions supporting endocarp division though representing small fraction of total proliferation. ||Seed number effects show more seeds creating more seed compartments and endocarp tissue, total endocarp cellularity correlating with seed number, and multiple seeds increasing localized proliferation though each compartment similar. ||Seed compartment assessment methods include histological sectioning showing endocarp tissue adjacent to seeds, cell counting in seed cavity regions, seed cavity size and structure measurement, and endocarp architecture analysis. ||The process represents third and final aspect of peak division activity emphasizing seed region specialization, following maximum cell number generation and pericarp cell proliferation. ||Duration concurrent with peak division weeks 2-3 representing localized seed compartment proliferation. ||Regional timing shows seed compartment cell division during early-mid July across climates during peak berry division phase. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing seed compartment structure providing seed-berry interface, representing specialized regional proliferation creating tissue heterogeneity, accounting for small but potentially functionally important cell population, and demonstrating coordinated tissue-specific division patterns. ||Research applications include analyzing endocarp division regulation and specialization, investigating seed-berry communication and interface functions, evaluating local auxin effects on regional proliferation, quantifying seed compartment architecture and cellularity, and assessing endocarp as specialized berry tissue with potential functional significance.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 437-438"
},

  "Declining_Division_Activity": {
  "definition": "A Declining_Division_Activity is a Berry_Cell_Division_Phase characterized by reduction of mitotic rate from peak intensity with cell cycle duration extending from 10–12 hours to 14–18 hours, extending over weeks 3–5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "division deceleration | mitotic decline | proliferation reduction | division slowdown | abnehmende Teilungsaktivität |+ Teilungs-Dezeleration | mitotischer Rückgang | Proliferationsreduktion",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows declining division activity during mid-late July Year N+1 at BBCH 73-75, with mitotic index declining from 11% week 3 to 5% week 4 to 2% week 5, cell cycle times extending from 11 hours to 15 hours, progressive cell cycle exit and enlargement onset, auxin levels declining from 220 ng/g to 80 ng/g, cell number approaching 2.1-2.4 million representing 92-96% final value, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar transitioning from division to expansion phase",
  "editor_note": "Declining_Division_Activity represents progressive deceleration phase within Berry_Cell_Division_Phase. ||Subdivided into Division_Rate_Reduction from peak levels, Transition_to_Enlargement_Onset as expansion begins, and Cell_Number_Finalization approaching final value. ||Duration 1.5-2.5 weeks representing weeks 3-5. ||Mitotic index declining from 8-15% to 1-3%. ||Cell cycle times extending from 10-12h to 14-18h. ||Auxin decline triggering rate reduction. ||Approaches 85-95% final cell number. ||Precedes Division_Phase_Completion. ||Transition period to expansion-dominated growth. || This gradual deceleration phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 1.5-2.5 weeks from peak division decline through completion, corresponding to BBCH 73-75 young fruit to pea-sized berry stages. ||Declining activity mechanism involves progressive division rate reduction from peak intensity, cell cycle time extension reflecting slowed progression through phases, transition to enlargement onset as cells increasingly commit to expansion rather than division, auxin levels declining from peak reducing proliferative stimulus, and cell number finalization approaching as final divisions complete. ||Division rate reduction shows mitotic index declining from peak 8-15% to 3-8% during decline phase then 1-3% approaching completion, absolute division rate decreasing from peak 40,000-120,000 cells per day to 10,000-40,000 cells per day during decline, progressive rate decrease correlating with declining auxin and developmental programming, and rate reduction characteristic of transition from exponential to stationary growth. ||Mitotic index decline dynamics show progressive decrease over weeks 3-5, typical reduction from 12% at peak week 3 to 6% week 4 to 2% week 5, declining index reflecting decreasing proportion of actively cycling cells, and index as convenient division activity measure. ||Cell cycle time extension shows cycles lengthening from minimal 10-12 hours during peak to 12-14 hours early decline to 14-18 hours late decline, extended times particularly in G1 and S phases, lengthening reflecting reduced proliferative stimulus and cellular transition, and extended cycles reducing division frequency contributing to rate decline. ||G1 phase extension shows progression time increasing from 3-4 hours at peak to 5-8 hours during decline, cells spending longer in growth phase before S entry commitment, G1 extension providing window for cell fate decisions, and prolonged G1 characteristic of declining proliferative state. ||S phase extension shows DNA replication slowing from 5-7 hours to 7-10 hours, extended replication reflecting reduced biosynthetic capacity or checkpoint activation, and S phase lengthening contributing to overall cycle extension. ||Cell cycle exit progression shows increasing proportion of cells completing final division and exiting to G0/G1 expansion state, exit beginning during peak activity week 3 with early-dividing populations, progressive wave of exit spreading through cell populations weeks 3-5, and exit completion establishing expansion-only cell populations. ||Cell fate transition shows cells deciding between continued division versus expansion commitment, transition correlating with auxin decline and developmental signals, expansion commitment establishing cells in growth rather than proliferative mode, and transition as critical developmental decision. ||Transition to enlargement onset shows cells increasingly entering expansion mode through water uptake and vacuole development, vacuole formation beginning in cells exiting cycle, progressive enlargement onset across cell populations, and enlargement starting while some cells still dividing creating overlap. ||Cell enlargement initiation characteristics show water uptake beginning in expansion-committed cells, vacuole development creating central storage compartment, turgor increase driving cell expansion, and enlargement accelerating as cells fully transition from division. ||Auxin decline effects show hormone levels decreasing from peak weeks 1-3 to declining levels weeks 3-5, reduced auxin weakening proliferative stimulus, declining hormone correlating with division rate reduction, and auxin decrease as major trigger for declining activity. ||Auxin level dynamics show typical peak 200-400 ng/g fresh weight weeks 2-3, decline to 100-200 ng/g week 4, further reduction to 50-100 ng/g week 5, and declining hormone shifting cells toward expansion over division. ||Cell number finalization approaching shows progressive accumulation to 85-95% final cell number by decline phase completion week 5, remaining 5-15% cells from final late divisions week 5-6, and cell number approaching permanent established value. ||Final cell number variation shows continued accumulation during decline adding 15-25% to peak numbers, late divisions from cells completing extended cycles, and cumulative number reflecting total proliferative output. ||Environmental effects on declining activity include temperature affecting decline rate and transition timing with warm conditions potentially accelerating decline through faster developmental progression, cool conditions extending decline phase through slowed division rate reduction, and temperature as factor affecting transition dynamics. ||Developmental programming shows genetically controlled division decline independent of environmental factors within normal ranges, cultivar-specific decline timing affecting total division duration, and intrinsic developmental program driving transition. ||Declining activity assessment methods include mitotic index measurement showing progressive decrease, cell cycle time analysis documenting extension, cell number counting showing slowing accumulation rate, and division marker expression decreasing correlating with activity decline. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including division rate reduction from peak intensity, transition to enlargement onset as expansion begins dominating, and cell number finalization approaching final value. ||Duration typically 1.5-2.5 weeks representing decline from peak through near-completion. ||Regional timing shows declining division activity during mid-late July across climates weeks 3-5 post-fertilization. ||Viticultural significance includes representing transition from division to expansion as growth mechanism, establishing final cell number determining berry size potential, demonstrating progressive developmental transition, and marking shift toward expansion-dominated growth phase. ||Research applications include analyzing division decline regulation and mechanisms, investigating cell fate transition controls, evaluating environmental effects on decline timing and dynamics, quantifying decline kinetics and cell number finalization, and assessing declining activity as transition to expansion phase.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 437-440 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Division_Rate_Reduction": {
  "definition": "A Division_Rate_Reduction is a Declining_Division_Activity marked by reduction of cell production from 40,000–120,000 cells per day to 10,000–40,000 cells per day with mitotic index falling from 8–15% to 3–8%, extending over weeks 3–4.5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "mitotic rate decline | division frequency reduction | proliferation deceleration | declining mitotic activity |+ Teilungsraten-Reduktion | mitotische Ratenabnahme | Teilungsfrequenz-Reduktion | Proliferations-Dezeleration",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows division rate reduction during mid-late July Year N+1 at BBCH 73-74, with peak division rate 95,000 cells per day week 2.5 declining to 48,000 cells per day week 3.5 and 22,000 cells per day week 4.5, mitotic index declining from 12% to 6%, cycling cell fraction reducing from 78% to 32%, cell cycle times extending from 11 hours to 15 hours, under warm climate conditions of 26-32°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar showing progressive rate reduction",
  "editor_note": "Division_Rate_Reduction is first aspect of Declining_Division_Activity, distinguished by progressive mitotic frequency decline. ||Represents 70-85% total rate reduction from peak. ||Duration 1-2 weeks representing weeks 3-4.5. ||Rate declining from 40,000-120,000 to 10,000-40,000 cells/day. ||Mitotic index 8-15% declining to 3-8%. ||Results from both cycling fraction reduction and cycle time extension. ||Auxin decline primary trigger. ||Followed by Transition_to_Enlargement_Onset. ||Major developmental transition marker. || This deceleration phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 1-2 weeks representing major rate decline, corresponding to BBCH 73-74 pea-sized berry stages. ||Rate reduction mechanism involves progressive decrease in cycling cell number as cells exit cycle, cell cycle time extension reducing division frequency in remaining cycling cells, combined effects producing substantial rate reduction, auxin decline weakening proliferative drive, and developmental programming directing transition from division to expansion. ||Division rate quantification shows peak rate 40,000-120,000 new cells per berry per day weeks 2-3, declining rate 20,000-60,000 cells per day week 3.5, further reduction to 10,000-40,000 cells per day week 4.5, and rate decline reflecting both reduced cycling fraction and slower cycles. ||Rate decline dynamics show approximately 50-70% rate reduction from peak to early decline week 3.5, additional 40-60% reduction from early to late decline week 4.5, and cumulative 70-85% total rate reduction during decline phase. ||Cycling cell fraction reduction shows proportion of actively dividing cells decreasing from 70-85% at peak to 40-60% early decline to 20-35% late decline, declining fraction as cells progressively exit cycle, and fraction reduction as major rate reduction contributor. ||Cell cycle exit kinetics show progressive asynchronous exit across cell populations, earlier-activating cells exiting first during week 3, later-activating cells continuing longer into week 4-5, and exit wave creating gradual rate decline rather than abrupt cessation. ||Mitotic index decline shows percentage of cells in M phase decreasing from peak 8-15% to 5-10% early decline week 3.5 to 3-8% late decline week 4.5, mitotic index directly reflecting division activity level, and index decline documenting rate reduction. ||Cell cycle time extension contribution shows cycles lengthening from 10-12 hours peak to 12-14 hours early decline to 14-16 hours late decline, extended times reducing division frequency even in continuously cycling cells, and cycle extension accounting for 30-50% rate reduction with remainder from cycling fraction decline. ||G1 phase extension effects show prolonged G1 from 3-4 hours to 5-7 hours reducing cycle frequency, extended G1 providing window for exit decision, and G1 lengthening as control point for rate reduction. ||S and G2 phase extension shows DNA replication and preparation phases lengthening contributing to overall cycle extension, extended phases reflecting reduced biosynthetic capacity or checkpoint stringency, and phase lengthening reducing cycle frequency. ||Cell number accumulation slowing shows rate of new cell addition declining correlating with division rate reduction, accumulation curve slope decreasing during decline phase, and slowing accumulation approaching plateau representing final cell number. ||Exponential to linear transition shows growth pattern shifting from exponential doubling during peak to linear addition during decline to plateau at completion, transition characteristic of declining proliferative capacity, and pattern shift marking developmental progression. ||Auxin decline correlation shows hormone levels decreasing from 200-400 ng/g peak to 150-250 ng/g early decline to 80-150 ng/g late decline, declining auxin reducing proliferative stimulus, hormone decrease correlating temporally with rate reduction, and auxin as primary rate reduction trigger. ||Auxin-division relationship shows dose-dependent proliferative response, declining hormone weakening cell cycle progression, reduced auxin enabling cell cycle exit and expansion transition, and hormone control as key rate regulation mechanism. ||Developmental program regulation shows intrinsic genetic programming driving rate reduction beyond auxin effects, cultivar-specific decline kinetics affecting total division duration, programmed transition as fundamental developmental control, and endogenous regulation ensuring appropriate phase progression. ||Cell population heterogeneity effects show asynchronous division across cell populations creating gradual rather than synchronous rate decline, population variation extending decline phase duration, and heterogeneity contributing to smooth transition. ||Environmental effects on rate reduction include temperature affecting decline kinetics through developmental rate effects with warm conditions potentially accelerating rate reduction through faster progression, cool conditions potentially extending decline through slower developmental rate, and temperature as factor affecting transition timing though rate reduction occurs across temperature ranges. ||Rate reduction assessment methods include serial cell counting quantifying division rate from accumulation slopes, mitotic index measurement documenting dividing cell proportion, cell cycle time analysis showing extension, and mathematical modeling fitting decline kinetics. ||The process represents first aspect of declining division activity emphasizing rate decrease, preceding transition to enlargement onset and cell number finalization. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing major rate reduction period weeks 3-4.5. ||Regional timing shows division rate reduction during mid-late July across climates as peak activity declines. ||Viticultural significance includes representing major transition from maximum proliferation to declining division, demonstrating progressive developmental regulation, establishing deceleration toward division completion, and marking shift toward expansion as growth mechanism. ||Research applications include analyzing rate reduction mechanisms and regulation, investigating auxin and developmental control of decline, evaluating cell cycle exit kinetics and control, quantifying rate decline dynamics and kinetics, and assessing rate reduction as transition to expansion-dominated growth.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 437-439 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Transition_to_Enlargement_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Transition_to_Enlargement_Onset is a Declining_Division_Activity comprising the progressive commitment of pericarp cells from division to expansion mode with water uptake and vacuole development establishing enlargement as the emerging dominant growth mechanism over weeks 3.5–5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "division to expansion transition | enlargement initiation | growth mode shift | expansion onset |+ Übergang zu Vergrößerungs-Beginn | Teilung-zu-Expansion-Übergang | Vergrößerungs-Initiierung | Wachstumsmodus-Wechsel",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows transition to enlargement onset during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 73-75, with progressive cell cycle exit beginning week 3.5, water uptake initiating 0.3-0.7 g per berry per day, vacuole formation in enlarging cells, overlap period with declining division and increasing enlargement weeks 3.5-5, berry diameter expanding from 14 mm to 20 mm during transition, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar transitioning growth mode",
  "editor_note": "Transition_to_Enlargement_Onset is second aspect of Declining_Division_Activity, distinguished by growth mode shift from division to expansion. ||Represents overlap period with declining division concurrent with increasing enlargement. ||Duration 1.5-2 weeks representing weeks 3.5-5. ||Water uptake 0.2-1.0 g/berry/day. ||Vacuole development initiating. ||Cell volume beginning 2-3 fold increase. ||Temperature and water affect transition. ||Follows Division_Rate_Reduction. ||Precedes Cell_Number_Finalization. ||Critical developmental transition establishing expansion dominance. || This critical transition phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July to early August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 1.5-2 weeks representing overlap period, corresponding to BBCH 73-75 pea-sized to berry touch stages. ||Transition mechanism involves cell cycle exit decision with cells choosing expansion over continued division, enlargement initiation in exiting cells through water uptake and vacuole formation, progressive enlargement onset across cell populations creating temporal spread, continued division in remaining cycling cells creating overlap, and gradual transition establishing expansion as predominant growth mode. ||Cell cycle exit and expansion commitment shows cells completing final division then entering G0/G1 expansion state rather than re-entering S phase, exit decision influenced by auxin decline and developmental signals, committed cells initiating expansion program, and irreversible commitment to enlargement versus division. ||Expansion commitment timing shows early-dividing cells exiting and enlarging beginning week 3, progressive exit wave through populations weeks 3.5-5, and extended commitment period creating gradual transition. ||Water uptake initiation shows expansion-committed cells beginning water import from surrounding apoplast, osmotic gradient from accumulating solutes driving water influx, water uptake rates initially 0.2-0.5 g per berry per day early transition increasing to 0.5-1.0 g per day as more cells enlarge, and water as primary driver of cell volume increase. ||Osmotic driving force shows organic acid accumulation particularly malate and tartrate creating osmotic potential decline from -0.5 MPa to -0.8 MPa, ion accumulation including potassium contributing to osmotic gradient, sugar beginning to accumulate though levels still low 3-6%, and combined solutes creating gradient driving water influx. ||Vacuole formation and development shows central vacuole initiating in enlarging cells, vacuole originating from smaller vacuoles or ER-derived structures, progressive vacuole expansion occupying increasing cell volume, and eventual vacuole dominance at 80-90% cell volume in fully expanded cells. ||Vacuole characteristics show large central compartment storing water and solutes, tonoplast membrane separating vacuole from cytoplasm, proton pumps and transporters regulating vacuole composition, and vacuole as major storage and osmotic compartment. ||Cell enlargement initiation shows cell volume beginning increase from division-exit size 20-40 micrometers diameter, initial expansion relatively slow 2-3 fold increase during transition, and acceleration during subsequent expansion phase achieving eventual 10-100 fold total increase. ||Cell wall modification enabling expansion shows wall loosening through expansin proteins disrupting cellulose-hemicellulose network, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase rearranging wall polymers, pectin methylesterase modifying pectin properties affecting wall plasticity, and coordinated wall modification enabling turgor-driven expansion. ||Turgor pressure development shows osmotic water influx generating turgor pressure 0.3-0.8 MPa during early enlargement, turgor force driving cell expansion against yielding walls, and pressure maintenance through continued solute accumulation and water uptake. ||Division-enlargement overlap shows temporal overlap with some cells still dividing while others enlarging, overlap duration approximately 1.5-2 weeks during transition phase, declining division from week 3.5-5 concurrent with increasing enlargement, and overlap characteristic of asynchronous cell population transitions. ||Cell population asynchrony shows variation in transition timing across cells, early-exiting cells enlarging while late-dividing cells continue cycling, asynchrony creating smooth gradual transition, and population heterogeneity extending overlap period. ||Enlargement acceleration during transition shows enlargement contribution to growth increasing as more cells commit and enlarge, berry volume increase from combined declining division and increasing enlargement, growth rate maintained or increasing during transition from compensating enlargement, and eventual enlargement dominance as division completes. ||Berry growth pattern during transition shows continued volumetric increase from combined mechanisms, berry diameter expanding from 12-18 mm early transition to 15-25 mm late transition depending on cultivar, fresh weight increasing from 2-5 g to 4-10 g during transition, and growth maintenance during mode shift. ||Metabolic changes during transition show shift from division-associated metabolism to expansion metabolism, respiratory rate remaining elevated supporting active growth, carbohydrate import supporting osmotic gradient and wall synthesis, and metabolic reorganization preparing subsequent rapid expansion phase. ||Gene expression changes show downregulation of cell cycle genes as division declines, upregulation of expansion-associated genes including expansins and transporters, and transcriptional reprogramming establishing expansion program. ||Environmental effects on transition include temperature affecting transition timing through developmental rate effects with warm conditions potentially accelerating transition, water availability affecting enlargement onset and rate with adequate water essential for expansion initiation, and overall favorable conditions supporting smooth transition. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster transition completion, cool conditions extending overlap period through slowed progression, and temperature as factor affecting transition timing. ||Water effects show adequate water essential for enlargement initiation, water limitation potentially delaying or limiting expansion onset, and water as critical resource for transition to enlargement. ||Transition assessment methods include cell size distribution analysis showing emerging enlarged population, vacuole development observation documenting enlargement onset, cell cycle marker decline showing division reduction, expansion marker expression showing enlargement activation, and growth pattern analysis documenting mode shift. ||The process represents second aspect of declining division activity emphasizing growth mode transition, following division rate reduction and preceding cell number finalization. ||Duration typically 1.5-2 weeks representing overlap period weeks 3.5-5. ||Regional timing shows transition to enlargement onset during mid-late July to early August across climates. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical developmental transition from division to expansion as growth mechanism, establishing enlargement as emerging dominant process, demonstrating overlap period maintaining growth rate, and marking progression toward expansion-dominated berry growth phase. ||Research applications include analyzing transition mechanisms and regulation, investigating cell fate decisions and expansion commitment, evaluating water relations during enlargement onset, quantifying division-enlargement overlap dynamics, and assessing transition as determinant of subsequent expansion phase.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 438-442 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Cell_Number_Finalization": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Number_Finalization is a Declining_Division_Activity characterized by completed late divisions and the establishment of the permanent mesocarp cell number of 1–4 million cells per berry by weeks 4–5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "final cell count | cell number establishment | cellularity finalization | permanent cell number |+ Zellzahl-Finalisierung | finale Zellzahl | Zellzahl-Etablierung | permanente Zellzahl",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows cell number finalization during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75, with final late divisions completing week 4-5, total mesocarp cell count reaching 1.6-2.0 million cells representing final permanent value, cell number determining 74-82% mature berry size variation, no further proliferation occurring through subsequent development, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar establishing cellularity determining 9-11 mm final berry size potential",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Number_Finalization is third and final aspect of Declining_Division_Activity, distinguished by final permanent cell count establishment. ||Represents completion by weeks 4-5. ||Final range 1-4 million cells depending on cultivar. ||Determined by genetics, seed number, temperature during weeks 1-4. ||Irreversible - no subsequent proliferation. ||Accounts for 60-80% size variation. ||Strong predictor of mature berry size. ||Follows Division_Rate_Reduction and Transition_to_Enlargement_Onset. ||Completes Declining_Division_Activity. ||Critical developmental commitment point. || This critical finalization phase occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, typically completing by week 4-5 representing division cessation, corresponding to BBCH 75 berry touch stage. ||Finalization mechanism involves completion of final late divisions from remaining cycling cells, cell cycle exit of last dividing cells establishing non-dividing cell population, final cell count representing cumulative proliferative output from entire division phase, irreversible cell number preventing any subsequent proliferation, and established cellularity as permanent berry characteristic. ||Final division completion shows last mitoses occurring week 4-5 in late-dividing cell populations, completion timing variable across cells creating extended finalization period, occasional rare divisions possibly extending to week 6 in small subpopulations, and eventual complete cessation establishing final count. ||Cell number accumulation to final value shows progressive increase during declining activity approaching plateau, typical progression to 85-95% final number by week 4 and 95-99% by week 5, remaining 1-5% cells from final late divisions, and final accumulation to complete count. ||Final cell number range shows cultivar variation with small-berried cultivars 0.8-1.5 million mesocarp cells, medium-berried 1.5-2.5 million cells, large-berried 2.5-4 million cells, and range reflecting genetic programming and environmental effects during division phase. ||Cell number determinants summary shows genetic programming as primary factor establishing cultivar-characteristic ranges, seed number affecting total through differential auxin dose creating 20-40% variation within cultivar, temperature during division phase affecting proliferation rate and final number with warm conditions enabling maximum genetic potential, water and nutrients supporting but usually not limiting division, and cumulative environmental effects during critical weeks 1-4 determining achieved cellularity. ||Seed number effects on final cellularity show positive correlation between seeds per berry and final cell number, typical 25-35% more cells in 3-seed versus 1-seed berries, auxin dose-response relationship mediating seed effects, and seed number as major within-cultivar variation source. ||Temperature integration effects show heat accumulation during division phase correlating with final cell number, growing degree days during weeks 1-4 affecting total divisions, cool conditions reducing final count 15-30% from genetic maximum, warm conditions enabling full genetic potential achievement, and temperature as major environmental determinant. ||Cell number measurement methods show enzymatic tissue dissociation followed by cell counting using hemocytometer or flow cytometry, DNA content analysis estimating cell number from total DNA, histological section analysis though technically challenging for large cell populations, and measurement enabling cellularity quantification. ||Cell number irreversibility shows established count permanent and unchangeable, no further cell division occurring during subsequent expansion, lag phase, ripening phases, rare exception of wound healing producing localized new cells though not affecting bulk berry, and irreversibility emphasizing critical nature of division phase. ||Cell number as size determinant shows strong positive correlation between final cell number and mature berry size, typical correlation coefficient r² 0.70-0.85 across cultivars and conditions, cell number accounting for 60-80% size variation with remainder from differential expansion, and cellularity as primary size determinant. ||Predictive relationship shows final cell number enabling early berry size prediction, berry diameter at maturity predictable from cell count with reasonable accuracy, and early finalization enabling yield estimation from cell number assessment. ||Cell size at finalization shows cells relatively small 25-45 micrometers diameter following division phase, cells retaining substantial expansion capacity for subsequent 5-20 fold volume increase, and initial small size characteristic of recently divided populations. ||Expansion potential establishment shows final cell number determining total expandable cell population, all cells capable of subsequent enlargement contributing to berry growth, and expansion phase exploiting established cell population. ||Tissue architecture finalization shows pericarp layer organization established with exocarp, mesocarp, endocarp differentiation complete, vascular network development matching cellularity, and structural organization from coordinated division patterns. ||Cell type proportions shows final proportions established with mesocarp 80-85% cells, exocarp 10-15%, endocarp 3-5%, and proportions reflecting tissue-specific proliferation patterns. ||Developmental commitment shows cell number finalization representing irreversible developmental commitment, established cellularity constraining subsequent berry size achievement, and finalization as critical developmental decision point. ||Environmental independence after finalization shows subsequent environmental conditions unable to affect established cell number, later favorable conditions unable to compensate for limited early division, and finalization emphasizing critical nature of division phase environment. ||The process represents third and final aspect of declining division activity emphasizing count establishment, following division rate reduction and transition to enlargement onset. ||Duration represents finalization completion by weeks 4-5. ||Regional timing shows cell number finalization during late July-early August across climates by division phase end. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final permanent cell count determining berry size potential, demonstrating irreversible nature of division phase establishing size constraints, showing critical importance of optimal division phase conditions for size achievement, and marking definitive end of cell proliferation period. ||Research applications include analyzing cell number determinants and variation, investigating genetic and environmental effects on final cellularity, evaluating cell number as berry size predictor, quantifying cellularity-size relationships, and assessing cell number finalization as critical developmental determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 439-443 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Division_Phase_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Division_Phase_Completion is a Berry_Cell_Division_Phase comprising the cessation of all mitotic activity and the establishment of expansion as the exclusive growth mechanism by weeks 4–5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "division cessation | proliferation termination | mitotic phase end | division completion |+ Teilungsphase-Vollendung | Teilungs-Beendigung | Proliferations-Terminierung | mitotische Phasenende",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows division phase completion during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75, with final mitotic events completing week 4-5, mitotic index declining to <1%, complete division cessation establishing non-dividing 1.5-1.9 million cell population, growth mode transition to expansion exclusivity, berry diameter 16-19 mm at completion, under cool maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar completing division phase enabling progression to expansion",
  "editor_note": "Division_Phase_Completion represents definitive division cessation within Berry_Cell_Division_Phase. ||Subdivided into Final_Mitotic_Events with terminal divisions, Cell_Division_Cessation establishing non-dividing state, and Growth_Mode_Transition to expansion exclusivity. ||Completion weeks 4-5. ||Mitotic index declining to <1%. ||All cells in G0/G1 expansion state. ||Irreversible cessation. ||Marks transition from division to expansion phase. ||Completes Berry_Cell_Division_Phase. ||Enables progression to Berry_Expansion_Phase. || This phase termination period occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, typically completing weeks 4-5 representing division cessation, corresponding to BBCH 75 berry touch stage. ||Completion mechanism involves final mitotic events in last dividing cells producing terminal divisions, complete division cessation with all cells exiting cycle to expansion state, growth mode transition establishing expansion as sole growth mechanism replacing division, developmental checkpoint passage enabling progression to expansion phase, and completion marking definitive end of proliferative period. ||Final mitotic events characteristics show last observable divisions occurring week 4-5, mitotic index declining to very low <1-2% indicating rare remaining divisions, late-dividing cells completing final cycles with extended 16-18 hour cycle times, and eventual complete division cessation by week 5-6. ||Division cessation timing shows typical completion week 4-5 for majority of berry cell population, occasional rare divisions extending to week 6 in small subpopulations, cultivar variation in completion timing affecting total division duration, and completion establishing non-dividing state. ||Cell division cessation shows mitotic activity ceasing completely, cell cycle genes downregulating to basal levels, proliferation markers disappearing indicating non-cycling state, all cells in G0/G1 expansion state versus S/G2/M cycling states, and cessation as definitive proliferation end. ||Post-cessation cell state shows cells in G0 quiescent or G1 growth state committed to expansion, cells lacking division competence unable to re-enter cycle under normal development, expansion program activated with enlargement-associated genes upregulated, and cells fully committed to growth through enlargement rather than proliferation. ||Growth mode transition establishment shows division contribution to growth ceasing completely, expansion as exclusive growth mechanism throughout subsequent development, berry growth from week 5 onward entirely through cell enlargement not proliferation, and transition as fundamental growth mechanism shift. ||Expansion exclusivity shows no further cell number increase throughout expansion, lag, veraison, ripening phases, berry volumetric growth entirely from cell volume increase, and expansion as sole mechanism for 8-12 weeks until harvest. ||Division phase duration summary shows total division phase spanning 4-5 weeks from fruit set, active division weeks 0-3, declining division weeks 3-5, completion by week 4-5, and total duration relatively constant across cultivars with timing variation. ||Developmental progression shows division completion enabling berry advancement to expansion phase, sequential phase progression characteristic of berry development, completion as prerequisite for subsequent phases, and developmental program directing phase transitions. ||Checkpoint passage shows developmental checkpoints ensuring appropriate division completion before expansion phase progression, adequate cellularity achievement required for progression, checkpoint mechanisms likely involving auxin levels and cell number, and passage enabling phase transition. ||Molecular markers of completion show cell cycle gene downregulation to basal levels, proliferation marker PCNA expression loss, expansion gene upregulation indicating enlargement commitment, and transcriptional reprogramming marking completion. ||Morphological indicators show berry diameter 14-25 mm at completion depending on cultivar, berry transitioning from young green fruit to expanding berry appearance, and size at completion reflecting achieved cellularity. ||Berry composition at completion shows water content 80-85% fresh weight, sugars low 3-6% from metabolic consumption, organic acids 1-1.5% particularly malate and tartrate, pH 2.8-3.2, and green acidic composition characteristic. ||Irreversibility of completion shows division phase non-repeatable during berry development, established cell number unchangeable throughout berry life, and completion as permanent developmental state transition. ||Environmental independence after completion shows subsequent environmental conditions unable to reinitiate division, favorable later conditions unable to compensate for limited division phase, and completion establishing constraints for subsequent development. ||Berry development progression shows transition from division phase completion to expansion phase onset, berry entering rapid expansion period following completion, and sequential progression through expansion, lag, veraison, ripening phases. ||Cell population uniformity after completion shows all cells in expansion state, population synchrony in growth mode, and uniformity enabling coordinated subsequent expansion. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including final mitotic events representing terminal divisions, cell division cessation establishing non-dividing state, and growth mode transition to expansion exclusivity. ||Duration represents completion period weeks 4-5. ||Regional timing shows division phase completion during late July-early August across climates marking division end. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive end of cell proliferation establishing permanent cellularity, marking critical developmental transition to expansion-dominated growth, demonstrating irreversible completion preventing subsequent division, and establishing division phase as discrete developmental period. ||Research applications include analyzing completion mechanisms and regulation, investigating developmental checkpoint controls, evaluating completion timing variation and determinants, quantifying transcriptional reprogramming at completion, and assessing division phase completion as determinant of subsequent berry development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 440-443 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Final_Mitotic_Events": {
  "definition": "A Final_Mitotic_Events is a Division_Phase_Completion marked by terminal divisions of the last cycling cells with mitotic index below 1–2% and cell cycle duration of 16–18 hours, occurring during weeks 4–5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "terminal divisions | last mitotic activity | final cell divisions | ultimate proliferation |+ finale mitotische Ereignisse | terminale Teilungen | letzte mitotische Aktivität | Schluss-Zellteilungen",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows final mitotic events during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75, with last dividing cells representing 8-14% population week 4 declining to 2-4% week 5, terminal divisions proceeding with 16-18 hour extended cycle times, mitotic index declining from 2.8% to 0.6%, final divisions adding 180,000-240,000 cells representing 9-12% total cellularity, completing permanent 2.0-2.3 million cell count, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature",
  "editor_note": "Final_Mitotic_Events is first aspect of Division_Phase_Completion, distinguished by terminal division occurrences. ||Represents last proliferative activity weeks 4-5. ||Mitotic index declining to <1-2%. ||Extended cycle times 16-18 hours. ||Contributes 5-15% final cells. ||Asynchronous completion creating gradual cessation. ||Followed by Cell_Division_Cessation as divisions end completely. ||Last observable divisions typically week 5. ||Completes berry cellularity establishment. || This terminal division period occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, representing final division activity weeks 4-5, corresponding to BBCH 75 berry touch stage. ||Final events mechanism involves completion of ongoing cycles in remaining late-dividing cells, extended cell cycle times reflecting declining proliferative stimulus, terminal divisions producing last cells exiting to expansion state, mitotic index decline to minimal levels <1-2%, and eventual complete cessation establishing non-dividing population. ||Last dividing cell populations show remaining cycling cells representing 10-20% total cells during early final events week 4, progressive cycle exit reducing cycling fraction to 5-10% late week 4 and <5% week 5, and final dividing cells representing late-activated or slow-cycling populations. ||Extended cycle times show late divisions proceeding with 16-18 hour cycles versus 10-12 hours during peak, G1 phase extension to 7-10 hours indicating reduced progression stimulus, S phase extension to 8-10 hours showing slowed DNA replication, and overall cycle lengthening characteristic of declining proliferative state. ||Cycle extension mechanisms show reduced auxin levels weakening proliferative drive, checkpoint stringency possibly increasing delaying phase transitions, reduced biosynthetic capacity slowing S phase progression, and developmental signals directing cell cycle exit over continued division. ||Terminal division characteristics show divisions morphologically normal with proper chromosome segregation, cytokinesis completing producing viable daughter cells, daughter cells entering expansion state rather than cycling, and terminal divisions functional though infrequent. ||Mitotic index during final events shows percentage of cells in M phase declining to very low levels, typical progression from 3-5% early final events to 1-2% late final events to <1% at complete cessation, mitotic index accurately reflecting rare remaining divisions, and minimal index indicating near-complete division cessation. ||Division rate during final events shows new cell generation rate declining to very low 2,000-10,000 cells per berry per day versus 40,000-120,000 at peak, rate reduction reflecting both minimal cycling fraction and extended cycle times, and minimal rate representing final proliferative output. ||Cell number addition from final events shows terminal divisions adding 5-15% total cells to earlier accumulated populations, contribution relatively small compared to peak activity but completing final cellularity, and final additions establishing permanent cell count. ||Spatial distribution of final events shows remaining divisions possibly concentrated in specific regions though evidence limited, possible later division in peripheral mesocarp regions versus earlier completion near seeds, and spatial heterogeneity reflecting asynchronous division across berry. ||Temporal spread of final events shows extended period weeks 4-5 from asynchronous division completion, early-activated cells completing first during week 4, late-activated cells continuing into week 5, and extended completion period creating gradual cessation. ||Developmental heterogeneity shows variation in completion timing across cells creating population asynchrony, heterogeneity enabling smooth transition rather than abrupt cessation, and variation characteristic of developmental populations. ||Final events completion shows last observable divisions typically week 5, occasional rare divisions possibly extending to week 6 in small subpopulations, and eventual complete cessation establishing truly non-dividing state. ||Post-final event cell state shows cells exiting cycle after terminal division, cells entering G0 quiescence or G1 expansion state, cells initiating or continuing expansion program through water uptake and vacuole development, and cells committed to enlargement rather than further division. ||Division marker disappearance shows proliferation markers like PCNA declining during final events, cyclin proteins decreasing to basal levels, mitotic marker phospho-histone H3 becoming undetectable, and marker loss documenting division cessation. ||Environmental effects on final events include temperature affecting completion timing through developmental rate effects with warm conditions potentially accelerating final event completion, cool conditions extending final division period, and temperature as factor affecting cessation timing. ||Auxin effects show very low hormone levels during final events correlating with minimal division, auxin decline below proliferative threshold enabling completion, and hormone as proliferation signal loss marking division end. ||Final events assessment methods include mitotic index measurement showing rare divisions, time-lapse imaging capturing terminal division events, division marker immunohistochemistry detecting last dividing cells, and temporal analysis documenting completion timing. ||The process represents first aspect of division phase completion emphasizing terminal divisions, preceding complete division cessation and growth mode transition. ||Duration represents final division period weeks 4-5. ||Regional timing shows final mitotic events during late July-early August across climates as division concludes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing last proliferative activity completing berry cellularity, demonstrating progressive division cessation through extended low-frequency divisions, marking transition to complete non-dividing state, and completing cell number establishment. ||Research applications include analyzing terminal division characteristics and regulation, investigating cell cycle exit mechanisms during final events, evaluating final event timing and spatial patterns, quantifying final proliferative contribution, and assessing final events as transition to division cessation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 440-442 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Cell_Division_Cessation": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Division_Cessation is a Division_Phase_Completion characterized by the non-dividing state of all pericarp cells with mitotic activity terminated and proliferation markers absent, completed by weeks 5–6 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "complete proliferation termination | mitotic activity end | division arrest | non-dividing state establishment |+ Zellteilungs-Beendigung | vollständige Proliferations-Terminierung | mitotische Aktivitäts-Ende | nicht-teilender Zustand-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows cell division cessation during early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75, with complete cell cycle exit by week 5-6, mitotic index declining to 0%, proliferation markers PCNA and Ki-67 becoming undetectable, all 2.2-2.8 million cells in G0/G1 expansion state, irreversible non-dividing status established, no further proliferation through subsequent 10-12 weeks development, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing division cessation",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Division_Cessation is second aspect of Division_Phase_Completion, distinguished by complete proliferation termination. ||Represents truly zero division state by weeks 5-6. ||Mitotic index 0%. ||All cells in G0/G1 expansion state. ||Proliferation markers absent. ||Irreversible cessation preventing any subsequent division. ||Follows Final_Mitotic_Events. ||Precedes Growth_Mode_Transition. ||Definitive end of proliferative period. ||Critical developmental commitment to non-dividing state. || This cessation establishment period occurs during late summer in early August in temperate regions Year N+1, typically completing week 5-6 representing complete division end, corresponding to BBCH 75 berry touch stage. ||Cessation mechanism involves final cell cycle exit of remaining cycling cells, complete loss of proliferative competence, cell cycle machinery downregulation to basal non-functional levels, establishment of expansion-committed non-dividing cell state, and irreversible cessation preventing division throughout subsequent 8-12 weeks until harvest. ||Complete cell cycle exit shows all cells leaving cycle to G0 quiescent or G1 expansion state, no cells remaining in S, G2, or M phases, cell populations uniformly non-dividing, and population synchrony in expansion state. ||Cell cycle phase distribution shows progression from mixed population with some cycling cells to uniform G0/G1 population, S/G2/M phase cells disappearing completely, all cells in growth phase preparing or undergoing expansion, and phase distribution documenting cessation. ||Mitotic activity complete cessation shows no observable mitoses after cessation completion, mitotic index 0% or <0.1% from rare measurement artifacts, absence of mitotic figures in histological examination, and truly zero division rate. ||Division marker disappearance shows PCNA proliferation marker becoming undetectable, cyclin proteins declining to basal non-functional levels, phospho-histone H3 mitotic marker absent, Ki-67 proliferation marker negative, and marker absence confirming non-dividing state. ||Cell cycle gene downregulation shows cyclin genes downregulated to minimal basal expression, cyclin-dependent kinase activity ceasing, cell cycle transcription factors E2F inactivated, and transcriptional program shift from proliferation to expansion genes. ||Proliferative competence loss shows cells unable to re-enter cell cycle under normal developmental conditions, division machinery dismantled preventing cycle re-entry, cells committed to expansion pathway unable to divide, and competence loss as irreversible developmental state. ||Expansion state establishment shows cells in growth mode through water uptake and vacuole expansion, expansion genes upregulated including expansins and transporters, cells enlarging through turgor-driven growth, and expansion as exclusive growth mode. ||Non-dividing cell population characteristics show population entirely in expansion state, cells progressively enlarging from 25-45 micrometers to eventual 80-200 micrometers, no further cell number increase throughout development, and population growth through cell volume increase exclusively. ||Cessation completion timing shows typical completion week 5 for majority of cultivars, occasional extension to week 6 in some late cultivars or cool conditions, completion timing relatively conserved across genotypes, and cessation by 4-6 weeks post-fertilization. ||Post-cessation development shows berry progressing through expansion, lag, veraison, ripening without any division, 8-12 weeks of development after cessation with zero proliferation, and division-free development characteristic of post-cessation berry. ||Irreversibility of cessation shows no division occurring after cessation under any normal conditions, environmental changes unable to reinitiate division, developmental program preventing division throughout berry development, and true irreversible cessation. ||Exception of wound healing shows localized cell division possible at wound sites for repair, wound-induced divisions limited to injury vicinity not affecting bulk berry, and exception not contradicting normal development cessation. ||Environmental independence shows cessation occurring across all environmental conditions within viable ranges, temperature variations unable to prevent or reverse cessation, and cessation as robust developmental transition. ||Developmental checkpoint at cessation shows likely checkpoint ensuring adequate cellularity before cessation, inadequate cell number potentially delaying cessation though evidence limited, and checkpoint passage enabling irreversible cessation. ||Molecular mechanisms of cessation show potential epigenetic modifications silencing cell cycle genes, chromatin remodeling preventing cell cycle gene transcription, developmental transcription factors directing expansion program, and integrated mechanisms ensuring stable cessation. ||Cessation as developmental commitment shows commitment to non-dividing state, establishment of expansion as exclusive growth mode, and commitment as critical developmental decision. ||Berry characteristics at cessation show diameter 15-25 mm depending on cultivar and achieved cellularity, fresh weight 4-10 g, established cell number 1-4 million cells, and berry in early expansion state. ||Cessation assessment methods include mitotic index measurement showing zero divisions, cell cycle marker immunohistochemistry showing absence, proliferation marker gene expression analysis showing downregulation, and cell cycle phase analysis showing uniform G0/G1 distribution. ||The process represents second aspect of division phase completion emphasizing complete cessation, following final mitotic events and preceding growth mode transition. ||Duration represents cessation completion typically week 5-6. ||Regional timing shows cell division cessation during early August across climates as proliferation ends completely. ||Viticultural significance includes representing complete irreversible end of cell proliferation, establishing permanent non-dividing berry state, demonstrating robust developmental transition, and marking definitive division phase conclusion. ||Research applications include analyzing cessation mechanisms and molecular regulation, investigating irreversibility establishment, evaluating checkpoint controls at cessation, quantifying cessation timing and completion, and assessing cessation as critical developmental transition point.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-443 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Growth_Mode_Transition": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Mode_Transition is a Division_Phase_Completion consisting of the shift from division-based to expansion-based berry volumetric increase establishing cell enlargement as the sole growth mechanism throughout subsequent berry development over 8–12 weeks until harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "division to expansion shift | growth mechanism change | expansion exclusivity establishment | proliferation to enlargement transition |+ Wachstumsmodus-Übergang | Teilung-zu-Expansion-Wechsel | Wachstumsmechanismus-Änderung | Expansions-Exklusivitäts-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows growth mode transition during early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75-77, with division contribution ceasing completely week 5-6, expansion becoming 100% growth mechanism, berry growth rate maintaining 110-180 mg per day entirely from cell enlargement, water uptake accelerating to 1.2-1.8 g per berry per day, cell volume increase from 35 micrometers to progressive enlargement, under warm climate conditions of 26-32°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar establishing expansion exclusivity",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Mode_Transition is third and final aspect of Division_Phase_Completion, distinguished by fundamental growth mechanism shift. ||Represents establishment of expansion as 100% exclusive growth mechanism. ||Division contribution ceasing, expansion compensating maintaining growth rate. ||Duration weeks 5-6. ||Expansion phase 8-12 weeks post-transition. ||Follows Final_Mitotic_Events and Cell_Division_Cessation. ||Completes Division_Phase_Completion and Berry_Cell_Division_Phase. ||Enables progression to Berry_Expansion_Phase. ||Critical developmental transition establishing expansion dominance. || This critical mechanism shift occurs during late summer in early August in temperate regions Year N+1, typically establishing by weeks 5-6 as division completes, corresponding to BBCH 75 berry touch stage transitioning to BBCH 77 beginning bunch closure. ||Transition mechanism involves division contribution to growth ceasing completely with zero cell number increase, expansion contribution to growth becoming 100% of volumetric increase, growth rate maintained or increasing despite division loss through compensating expansion acceleration, developmental reprogramming establishing expansion gene expression, and transition establishing permanent growth mode for remainder of berry development. ||Division contribution cessation shows cell proliferation no longer contributing to berry growth, volumetric increase from division ceasing completely at transition, division phase having contributed cells now growing exclusively through enlargement, and zero ongoing division contribution post-transition. ||Expansion contribution establishment shows cell enlargement as sole growth mechanism after transition, 100% berry volumetric increase from water uptake and cell expansion, expansion phase growth rates 0.5-2.0 g fresh weight per day entirely from enlargement, and expansion exclusivity throughout subsequent 8-12 weeks. ||Growth rate dynamics during transition show berry growth rate maintained or increased despite division cessation, expansion acceleration compensating for division loss, typical fresh weight gain 50-150 mg per day during transition period, and growth continuity through mechanism shift. ||Compensatory expansion acceleration shows enlargement rate increasing as division declines, water uptake accelerating from 0.5 g to 1.0-2.0 g per berry per day, osmotic gradient intensification driving increased water influx, and expansion compensation maintaining growth. ||Berry growth pattern shows continuation of volumetric increase through transition, brief plateau possible during mode shift in some cases though often growth continuous, and overall growth trajectory relatively smooth through transition. ||Cell volume increase post-transition shows cells enlarging from 25-45 micrometer diameter at division cessation to progressive increase toward 80-200 micrometers at maturity, 5-20 fold total volume increase during expansion phase, and cell enlargement as exclusive growth mechanism. ||Water uptake as growth driver shows water import as primary expansion mechanism, xylem-mediated delivery during early expansion, osmotic gradient from solute accumulation driving influx, and water comprising 80-85% berry fresh weight. ||Vacuole expansion as enlargement mechanism shows central vacuole progressively enlarging occupying increasing cell volume fraction, eventual vacuole dominance at 85-95% cell volume in mature cells, and vacuole as major storage and osmotic compartment. ||Cell wall yielding enabling expansion shows wall modification through expansins, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase, pectin methylesterase, wall plasticity enabling turgor-driven expansion, and coordinated wall loosening with synthesis maintaining integrity. ||Turgor pressure driving expansion shows osmotic water uptake generating 0.5-1.2 MPa turgor, pressure force driving cell expansion against yielding walls, and sustained turgor through continued solute accumulation and water import. ||Developmental gene expression reprogramming shows downregulation of cell cycle and division genes, upregulation of expansion genes including expansins, aquaporins, transporters, metabolic enzyme shift toward expansion metabolism, and transcriptional program establishing expansion mode. ||Expansion gene upregulation shows expansin expression increasing enabling wall loosening, aquaporin water channel expression facilitating water transport, sugar and acid transporter expression supporting accumulation, and coordinated expression supporting expansion. ||Metabolic reprogramming shows shift from division-associated high nucleotide synthesis to expansion metabolism, carbohydrate import for osmotic gradient and wall synthesis, organic acid synthesis for osmotic potential, and metabolic reorganization supporting enlargement. ||Berry developmental progression shows transition enabling progression from division phase through expansion phase, sequential phase progression characteristic of berry development, expansion phase duration 3-5 weeks following transition, and eventual progression to lag phase as expansion slows. ||Growth phase I to II transition shows division phase representing growth phase I in double sigmoid pattern, transition period representing inflection between phases, expansion phase representing continued phase I growth, and eventual lag phase representing plateau between growth phases I and II. ||Post-transition berry characteristics show diameter 16-28 mm at transition depending on cultivar, fresh weight 5-12 g, established cell number 1-4 million cells, and berry composition remaining green acidic during expansion. ||Environmental effects on transition include temperature affecting transition timing through developmental rate with warm conditions accelerating transition, water availability critical for expansion phase post-transition with adequate water essential, and overall favorable conditions supporting smooth transition and subsequent expansion. ||Temperature independence of mode shows transition occurring across temperature ranges, mechanism shift robust to environmental variation, and developmental programming ensuring transition completion. ||Transition as developmental checkpoint shows transition representing committed developmental state change, checkpoint ensuring adequate preparation for expansion phase, and passage enabling berry progression through subsequent phases. ||The process represents third and final aspect of division phase completion emphasizing growth mechanism shift, following final mitotic events and cell division cessation. ||Duration represents transition establishment weeks 5-6. ||Regional timing shows growth mode transition during early August across climates as expansion becomes exclusive mechanism. ||Viticultural significance includes representing fundamental growth mechanism change determining subsequent berry development, establishing expansion as exclusive growth mode throughout remainder of development, demonstrating developmental robustness maintaining growth through mechanism shift, and marking critical transition from division-driven to expansion-driven berry growth. ||Research applications include analyzing transition mechanisms and regulation, investigating compensation maintaining growth rate, evaluating developmental reprogramming at transition, quantifying growth dynamics through mode shift, and assessing growth mode transition as critical developmental determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 442-445 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase is a Berry_Development comprising turgor-driven volumetric increase of non-dividing cells through water uptake and vacuole expansion, with cell volume increase of 10–100 fold from 25–45 μm to 80–200 μm diameter, extending over weeks 3–8 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "cell expansion phase | berry enlargement period | cell growth phase | expansion-dominated growth |+ Beeren-Zellvergrößerungsphase | Zellexpansionsphase | Beerenvergrößerungs-Periode | Zellwachstumsphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows berry cell enlargement phase during mid July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 73-77, with cells enlarging from 32 micrometers post-division to 95 micrometers by phase end representing 18-fold volume increase, water uptake progressing from 0.4 to 1.6 g per berry per day, massive vacuole development occupying 88% cell volume, berry diameter expanding from 18 mm to 26 mm achieving 85% final size, fresh weight increasing from 6 g to 14 g, under oceanic conditions of 22-28°C temperature with adequate summer rainfall, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing enlargement phase",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase represents expansion-dominated growth period following division. ||Subdivided into Initial_Cell_Enlargement with turgor onset, vacuole initiation, wall loosening, and Rapid_Cell_Expansion with maximum rate, massive vacuole, peak growth. ||Duration 4-6 weeks representing weeks 3-8. ||Cell volume increase 10-100 fold. ||Water uptake critical driver. ||Turgor 0.5-1.2 MPa. ||Vacuole 85-95% final volume. ||Berry achieves 70-90% final size. ||Water availability most critical environmental factor. ||Follows Berry_Cell_Division_Phase. ||Major size determinant accounting for 20-40% variation. || This critical expansion phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 4-6 weeks with overlap during declining division and pure expansion post-division, corresponding to BBCH 73-77 pea-sized berry to beginning bunch closure stages. ||Enlargement mechanism involves initial cell enlargement with turgor-driven expansion onset, vacuole enlargement initiation, and cell wall loosening enabling growth, followed by rapid cell expansion with maximum expansion rate, massive vacuole formation occupying 85-95% cell volume, and peak berry growth rate achieving maximum size increase. ||Cell enlargement fundamentals show turgor pressure as driving force with osmotic water uptake generating 0.5-1.2 MPa pressure, turgor pushing against yielding cell walls causing expansion, water as primary volume contributor comprising 80-85% berry fresh weight, vacuole as major storage compartment expanding to dominate cell volume, and cell wall modification enabling expansion through loosening and synthesis. ||Water uptake dynamics show progressive increase from 0.3-0.5 g per berry per day during initial enlargement to 1.0-2.5 g per day during rapid expansion, xylem-mediated water import during early enlargement, possible phloem water contribution during later enlargement, and total water import 30-80 g per berry over enlargement phase depending on final size. ||Osmotic gradient driving water uptake shows solute accumulation creating osmotic potential decline from -0.5 MPa early enlargement to -1.0 to -1.5 MPa during rapid expansion, organic acids particularly malate and tartrate accumulating to 1.0-1.8% fresh weight, potassium and other ions accumulating, sugars beginning accumulation though levels still low 4-8% during enlargement, and combined solutes creating strong osmotic gradient pulling water into cells. ||Vacuole development progression shows vacuole initiating as small compartments in post-division cells, progressive vacuole enlargement through membrane synthesis and water influx, eventual single large central vacuole occupying 85-95% mature cell volume, and vacuole as major storage compartment for water, ions, organic acids, and later sugars. ||Vacuole characteristics show tonoplast membrane separating vacuole from cytoplasm, proton pumps and transporters regulating vacuole pH and composition, vacuole pH acidic typically 3.0-3.5 from organic acid accumulation, and vacuole providing osmotic driving force and storage capacity. ||Cell wall modification enabling expansion shows wall loosening through expansin proteins disrupting hydrogen bonds between cellulose microfibrils and matrix polysaccharides, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase rearranging xyloglucan cross-links, pectin methylesterase modifying pectin affecting wall plasticity, wall plasticity increase enabling turgor-driven expansion, and new wall synthesis maintaining integrity during enlargement preventing bursting. ||Expansin function shows pH-dependent wall loosening activity, proteins binding to cell wall causing non-hydrolytic disruption, expansin expression correlating with expansion rate, and expansins as key wall-modifying enzymes. ||Cell wall synthesis during expansion shows new cellulose, hemicellulose, and pectin deposition, wall synthesis maintaining thickness despite area increase, coordinated synthesis with loosening preventing structural failure, and wall composition changes affecting mechanical properties. ||Cell volume increase quantification shows typical 10-30 fold volume increase during enlargement phase from 25-45 micrometer diameter to 60-120 micrometers by phase end, eventual 30-100 fold total increase including continued expansion during lag and ripening phases, final cell diameter 80-200 micrometers at full maturity, and volume increase as major berry growth contributor. ||Berry size increase during enlargement shows diameter expanding from 14-25 mm at enlargement onset to 70-90% final size by phase end typically 18-35 mm depending on cultivar, volumetric increase 2-5 fold during pure enlargement phase, fresh weight increase from 4-10 g to 8-20 g by enlargement completion, and substantial size gain establishing near-final dimensions. ||Berry growth rate characteristics show maximum growth rate during rapid expansion typically 100-250 mg fresh weight per day in large-berried cultivars, sustained high growth rate over 2-4 weeks during peak expansion, growth rate decline as enlargement phase concludes approaching lag phase, and high rate reflecting intensive cell enlargement. ||Berry composition during enlargement shows water content maintained 80-85% fresh weight, organic acids accumulating to peak levels 1.0-1.8%, sugars low 4-8% from metabolic consumption and limited import, pH declining to 2.8-3.2 from acid accumulation, and overall green hard acidic berry characteristic. ||Environmental effects on enlargement include temperature affecting expansion rate through metabolic and developmental effects with optimal 22-28°C supporting maximum enlargement, water availability critically affecting expansion with adequate water essential for turgor maintenance and volume increase, water deficit limiting enlargement reducing final berry size 15-40%, nutrient supply particularly potassium affecting water relations and expansion, and overall favorable conditions maximizing size achievement. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster expansion through accelerated metabolism and wall modification, cool conditions slowing expansion rate though generally not preventing size achievement, and temperature as factor affecting timing rather than potential within normal ranges. ||Water effects show water as most critical environmental factor during enlargement, deficit severely limiting expansion through reduced turgor and water availability, irrigation during enlargement phase essential in water-limited regions for size optimization, and water management as key viticultural practice. ||Potassium effects show adequate potassium supporting osmotic gradient and water uptake, potassium deficiency potentially limiting expansion, and potassium as important mineral for size achievement. ||Cultivar variation shows genetic differences in expansion capacity affecting final cell and berry size, small-berried cultivars showing limited expansion reaching 6-10 mm final diameter, large-berried cultivars showing extensive expansion achieving 14-20 mm final diameter, and genetic programming determining expansion potential. ||Cell number-expansion interaction shows final berry size determined by both cell number from division phase 60-80% and cell expansion 20-40%, multiplicative relationship amplifying effects, and optimal size requiring both adequate cellularity and expansion. ||Enlargement completion characteristics show expansion rate declining as berry approaches genetic size potential, transition to lag phase as growth slows, berry achieving 70-90% final size by enlargement completion, and establishment of size baseline for subsequent ripening. ||The process shows two distinguishable phases including initial cell enlargement with turgor-driven expansion onset, vacuole initiation, and wall loosening, and rapid cell expansion with maximum expansion rate, massive vacuole formation, and peak berry growth. ||Duration typically 4-6 weeks representing weeks 3-8 with overlap during declining division weeks 3-5 and pure expansion weeks 5-8. ||Regional timing shows berry cell enlargement phase during mid July-early August across climates as expansion proceeds. ||Viticultural significance includes representing major growth phase establishing near-final berry size, requiring optimal water availability for size achievement, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity particularly to water deficit, and determining berry size affecting yield and quality through dilution or concentration effects. ||Research applications include analyzing enlargement mechanisms and regulation, investigating water relations and turgor dynamics, evaluating wall modification processes and regulation, quantifying expansion contribution to berry size, and assessing enlargement as determinant of final berry size and quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 440-450 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Initial_Cell_Enlargement": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Cell_Enlargement is a Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase comprising the onset of cell volume increase through water uptake, turgor development, vacuole formation, and cell wall loosening over weeks 3–5 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "expansion onset | early cell growth | enlargement initiation | initial expansion phase |+ initiale Zellvergrößerung | Expansions-Beginn | frühes Zellwachstum | Vergrößerungs-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows initial cell enlargement during mid-late July Year N+1 at BBCH 73-75, with turgor pressure developing 0.4-0.7 MPa, water uptake 0.3-0.6 g per berry per day, vacuoles expanding from 25% to 58% cell volume, expansin-mediated wall loosening, cells enlarging 3.2-fold from 30 to 48 micrometers, berry diameter increasing from 16 to 21 mm, under cool maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature with adequate rainfall, typical of this early-bursting cultivar initiating enlargement",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Cell_Enlargement is first phase of Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase, distinguished by expansion onset. ||Subdivided into Turgor_Driven_Expansion_Onset establishing pressure system, Vacuole_Enlargement_Initiation creating osmotic compartment, and Cell_Wall_Loosening enabling growth. ||Duration 2-3 weeks representing weeks 3-5. ||Overlaps with declining division. ||Cell volume increase 2-5 fold. ||Turgor 0.3-0.8 MPa. ||Vacuole 50-70% volume by phase end. ||Water uptake 0.2-0.8 g/berry/day. ||Precedes Rapid_Cell_Expansion. ||Critical establishment phase for expansion-driven growth. || This expansion initiation phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 2-3 weeks representing enlargement onset overlapping with declining division, corresponding to BBCH 73-75 pea-sized berry to berry touch stages. ||Initial enlargement mechanism involves turgor-driven expansion onset with osmotic water uptake generating pressure, vacuole enlargement initiation with small vacuoles expanding and coalescing, cell wall loosening enabling turgor-driven growth, coordinated processes creating initial 2-5 fold cell volume increase, and establishment of expansion as active growth mechanism. ||Turgor-driven expansion fundamentals show osmotic water uptake generating turgor pressure 0.3-0.8 MPa during initial enlargement, pressure force pushing against cell walls causing expansion, yielding walls enabling growth under turgor, and turgor as physical driving force for volume increase. ||Water uptake initiation shows water import beginning in cells exiting division cycle, osmotic gradient from accumulating solutes driving water influx, initial water uptake rates 0.2-0.4 g per berry per day early phase increasing to 0.5-0.8 g per day late initial phase, and progressive water uptake acceleration as more cells enlarge. ||Osmotic gradient development shows solute accumulation creating osmotic potential decline from -0.5 MPa post-division to -0.7 to -0.9 MPa during initial enlargement, organic acid synthesis particularly malate increasing from 0.5% to 1.0% fresh weight, potassium import contributing to osmotic gradient, sugars still low 3-5% from continued metabolic consumption, and combined solutes creating gradient pulling water into cells. ||Malate synthesis shows malic acid as major organic acid synthesized during early enlargement, synthesis from glycolysis and TCA cycle intermediates, malate accumulation in vacuole creating osmotic potential and lowering pH, and malate as primary osmolyte during enlargement phase. ||Potassium accumulation shows K+ import through plasma membrane and tonoplast transporters, potassium accumulation to 150-250 mmol/L in berry tissue, K+ as major cation balancing organic acid anions, and potassium contributing substantially to osmotic gradient. ||Vacuole enlargement initiation shows small vacuoles 10-30% cell volume in post-division cells, vacuole membrane synthesis and water influx causing expansion, multiple small vacuoles coalescing into fewer larger vacuoles, progressive vacuole enlargement to 50-70% cell volume by initial enlargement completion, and vacuole as major expanding compartment. ||Vacuole membrane synthesis shows tonoplast proliferation accommodating vacuole expansion, membrane lipid and protein synthesis, proton pump and transporter insertion regulating vacuole, and membrane synthesis coordinated with vacuole growth. ||Vacuole function establishment shows compartment storing accumulated solutes and water, tonoplast H+-ATPase acidifying vacuole to pH 3.0-3.5, transporters accumulating malate, tartrate, K+, sugars into vacuole, and vacuole as osmotic engine and storage depot. ||Cell wall loosening initiation shows expansin expression increasing during initial enlargement, expansin proteins secreted to apoplast binding cell walls, expansin-mediated wall loosening disrupting cellulose-hemicellulose hydrogen bonds, wall plasticity increase enabling turgor-driven expansion, and loosening as essential enabling mechanism. ||Expansin characteristics show α-expansin family members expressed in expanding berries, pH-dependent activity optimal at acidic pH 4.5-5.5 characteristic of apoplast, non-hydrolytic wall loosening mechanism, and expansin as key wall-modifying enzyme during expansion. ||Cell wall yielding characteristics show wall capable of plastic deformation under turgor pressure, yielding walls enabling irreversible cell expansion, wall stress relaxation allowing sustained growth, and yielding balanced with synthesis preventing structural failure. ||Wall synthesis during initial enlargement shows new cellulose microfibrils deposited maintaining wall thickness, hemicellulose and pectin matrix synthesis, coordinated synthesis with loosening maintaining integrity, and wall deposition preventing excessive thinning during area expansion. ||Cell volume increase during initial enlargement shows typical 2-5 fold volume increase from post-division 25-45 micrometers diameter to 40-70 micrometers by initial phase end, progressive enlargement as cells accumulate water, initial expansion establishing enlargement trajectory, and volume increase contributing to berry growth. ||Cell enlargement spatial distribution shows enlargement initiating first in early-division-exiting cells week 3, progressive enlargement onset across cell populations weeks 3-5 as cells exit division, and asynchronous enlargement creating temporal spread. ||Enlargement-division overlap shows some cells still dividing while others enlarging during initial enlargement weeks 3-5, declining division concurrent with increasing enlargement, overlap maintaining berry growth rate during transition, and eventual pure enlargement as division completes. ||Berry size increase during initial enlargement shows diameter expanding from 14-20 mm at onset to 18-25 mm by initial phase end, volumetric increase 1.5-2.5 fold during initial enlargement, fresh weight increasing from 4-8 g to 6-12 g, and substantial growth establishing expansion as effective mechanism. ||Berry growth rate shows increasing rate during initial enlargement from 50-80 mg per day early to 80-120 mg per day late initial phase, growth rate increase reflecting accelerating expansion as more cells enlarge, and rate progression toward peak during rapid expansion. ||Berry composition during initial enlargement shows water content 80-85% fresh weight maintained, organic acids increasing from 0.8% to 1.2%, sugars 3-5% remaining low, pH declining from 3.0 to 2.9 from acid accumulation, and green acidic composition characteristic. ||Environmental effects on initial enlargement include temperature affecting expansion rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting rapid enlargement onset, water availability affecting turgor maintenance and expansion with adequate water essential, deficit potentially limiting initial enlargement reducing final size, and overall favorable conditions supporting enlargement initiation. ||Water effects show water as critical resource during initial enlargement, adequate water enabling full turgor development and expansion, deficit limiting turgor and expansion even during initiation, and early deficit effects potentially irreversible through reduced achieved size. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster expansin expression and wall modification, cool conditions slowing initial enlargement though not preventing, and temperature affecting enlargement rate and timing. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including turgor-driven expansion onset establishing pressure-driven growth, vacuole enlargement initiation creating osmotic compartment, and cell wall loosening enabling yielding growth. ||Duration typically 2-3 weeks representing enlargement onset weeks 3-5. ||Regional timing shows initial cell enlargement during mid-late July across climates as expansion initiates. ||Viticultural significance includes representing transition to expansion as growth mechanism, establishing turgor-driven growth system, demonstrating water sensitivity during critical initiation period, and initiating size increase determining berry developmental trajectory. ||Research applications include analyzing turgor development and water relations, investigating vacuole formation and function, evaluating wall loosening mechanisms and expansin regulation, quantifying initial expansion dynamics, and assessing initial enlargement as determinant of subsequent expansion and final size.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 442-446 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Turgor_Driven_Expansion_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Turgor_Driven_Expansion_Onset is an Initial_Cell_Enlargement marked by establishment of turgor pressure of 0.3–0.8 MPa through osmotic water uptake driving mechanical expansion against yielding cell walls.",
  "alternative_term": "pressure-driven growth onset | turgor development | osmotic expansion initiation | pressure-based enlargement |+ Turgor-getriebene Expansions-Beginn | druckbasiertes Wachstum-Start | Turgor-Entwicklung | osmotische Expansions-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows turgor-driven expansion onset during mid-late July Year N+1 at BBCH 73-74, with osmotic potential declining from -0.6 to -0.8 MPa, water uptake generating turgor pressure 0.4-0.7 MPa, pressure-driven cell expansion initiating, yielding walls enabling volume increase, cells enlarging 2.1-fold, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-29°C temperature with adequate water, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar establishing turgor-expansion system",
  "editor_note": "Turgor_Driven_Expansion_Onset is first aspect of Initial_Cell_Enlargement, distinguished by pressure system establishment. ||Represents osmotic water uptake generating turgor 0.3-0.8 MPa. ||Pressure force drives expansion against yielding walls. ||Water potential gradient -0.2 to -0.4 MPa driving influx. ||Aquaporins facilitate water transport. ||Cell volume 1.5-3 fold increase during onset. ||Water availability critical. ||Timing week 3-4. ||Precedes Vacuole_Enlargement_Initiation. ||Establishes physical growth mechanism. || This pressure system establishment phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July in temperate regions Year N+1, initiating during week 3-4 post-fertilization as cells exit division, corresponding to BBCH 73-74 pea-sized berry stages. ||Turgor onset mechanism involves osmotic water uptake from solute accumulation, water influx generating hydrostatic pressure within cell, turgor pressure 0.3-0.8 MPa exerting force on cell walls, yielding walls enabling pressure-driven expansion, and established turgor-expansion system driving volume increase. ||Osmotic basis of turgor shows solute accumulation in cell and vacuole creating osmotic potential more negative than surrounding apoplast, water potential gradient driving water influx from apoplast into cell, water accumulation increasing cell volume and hydrostatic pressure, and osmotic-hydraulic system generating turgor. ||Water potential gradient shows typical apoplast water potential -0.3 to -0.5 MPa, cell osmotic potential -0.7 to -0.9 MPa during turgor onset from solute accumulation, resulting water potential gradient 0.2-0.4 MPa driving water influx, and gradient as driving force for water movement. ||Osmotic potential components show organic acids contributing -0.3 to -0.5 MPa, potassium and other ions -0.2 to -0.3 MPa, sugars -0.1 to -0.2 MPa still limited during onset, and combined solutes creating total osmotic potential. ||Water influx pathways show water crossing plasma membrane through aquaporin water channels, possible apoplastic water movement to cell surface, symplastic water movement through plasmodesmata between cells, and integrated pathways supplying water for turgor generation. ||Aquaporin function shows water channel proteins facilitating membrane water permeability, aquaporin expression correlating with water uptake rates, channels enabling rapid water flux responding to osmotic gradient, and aquaporins as key transport proteins during expansion. ||Turgor pressure generation shows water accumulation increasing cell volume, hydrostatic pressure building from constrained expansion, turgor pressure 0.3-0.8 MPa typical during onset phase, and pressure as mechanical force driving expansion. ||Turgor measurement shows pressure probepressure chamber methods quantifying cell turgor, typical measurements 0.3-0.5 MPa early onset increasing to 0.6-0.8 MPa established onset, and turgor quantification documenting pressure dynamics. ||Pressure-volume relationships show turgor pressure P = π - Ψ where π is osmotic potential and Ψ is water potential, pressure increasing with solute accumulation and water uptake, and relationship governing turgor dynamics. ||Wall yielding under turgor shows cell wall experiencing tensile stress from internal pressure, wall yielding plastically under stress enabling irreversible expansion, yield threshold determining minimum turgor required for expansion typically 0.3-0.5 MPa, and yielding enabling pressure-driven growth. ||Wall mechanical properties show wall capable of elastic deformation recovering when pressure released and plastic deformation causing permanent expansion, plastic yielding under sustained turgor essential for growth, wall stress-strain relationships determining expansion response, and mechanical properties regulated through wall modification. ||Turgor-driven expansion rate shows expansion velocity proportional to turgor pressure exceeding yield threshold, typical relationship - growth rate = extensibility × (P - Y) where P is turgor and Y is yield threshold, higher turgor driving faster expansion, and pressure as rate-determining factor. ||Cell volume increase from turgor shows progressive volume expansion from water accumulation and turgor-driven wall yielding, typical 1.5-3 fold volume increase during turgor onset phase, volume change directly resulting from pressure-driven expansion, and turgor as mechanical driver of enlargement. ||Turgor maintenance shows continued solute accumulation maintaining osmotic gradient, continued water uptake sustaining turgor, and sustained pressure enabling continued expansion. ||Metabolic support for turgor shows respiratory ATP production supporting ion pumps, active transport accumulating solutes creating osmotic potential, metabolic energy essential for maintaining solute gradients, and metabolism supporting turgor system. ||Environmental effects on turgor onset include water availability critically affecting turgor generation with adequate water essential for pressure development, water deficit preventing full turgor establishment limiting expansion, temperature affecting metabolic solute accumulation and transport, and overall water as most critical factor. ||Water deficit effects show reduced water availability preventing turgor development, deficit during onset potentially permanently limiting expansion capacity, and early deficit as critical limitation. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster solute accumulation and turgor development, cool conditions slowing but generally not preventing turgor onset, and temperature affecting onset timing. ||Turgor onset timing shows typical initiation week 3-4 as cells exit division, asynchronous onset across cell populations as cells progressively commit to enlargement, and extended onset period week 3-5 during transition. ||Turgor establishment completion shows full turgor pressure 0.6-0.8 MPa established by week 4-5, established turgor maintaining during subsequent rapid expansion, and pressure system enabling sustained enlargement. ||The process represents first aspect of initial cell enlargement establishing pressure-driven growth system, preceding vacuole enlargement initiation and cell wall loosening. ||Duration represents turgor development over days to week during transition weeks 3-4. ||Regional timing shows turgor-driven expansion onset during mid-late July across climates as cells initiate enlargement. ||Viticultural significance includes representing establishment of physical growth driving force, demonstrating critical water dependence for pressure system, showing turgor as mechanical expansion driver, and establishing pressure-driven growth enabling subsequent enlargement. ||Research applications include analyzing turgor generation and maintenance mechanisms, investigating water relations and osmotic regulation, evaluating pressure-volume relationships during expansion, quantifying turgor-growth relationships, and assessing turgor as determinant of expansion capacity and rate.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 443-445 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Vacuole_Enlargement_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Vacuole_Enlargement_Initiation is an Initial_Cell_Enlargement comprising water influx, membrane synthesis, and coalescence of small vacuoles into larger compartments occupying 50–70% of cell volume.",
  "alternative_term": "vacuole development | vacuolar expansion onset | osmotic compartment formation | vacuole growth initiation |+ Vakuolen-Vergrößerungs-Initiierung | Vakuolen-Entwicklung | vakuoläre Expansions-Beginn | osmotisches Kompartment-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows vacuole enlargement initiation during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 73-75, with vacuoles expanding from 18% to 62% cell volume, tonoplast membrane synthesis, malate accumulation to 68 mM and tartrate to 42 mM, vacuole pH 3.2, osmotic potential -0.9 MPa, progressive fusion creating 1-2 large vacuoles per cell, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar developing vacuolar system",
  "editor_note": "Vacuole_Enlargement_Initiation is second aspect of Initial_Cell_Enlargement, distinguished by osmotic compartment development. ||Represents expansion from 10-30% to 50-70% cell volume. ||Tonoplast synthesis, solute accumulation (malate, tartrate, K+), water influx. ||Osmotic potential -0.8 to -1.2 MPa. ||Vacuole fusion reducing number. ||pH 3.0-3.5. ||Contributes 60-80% cell volume increase. ||Duration weeks 3-5. ||Follows Turgor_Driven_Expansion_Onset. ||Precedes Cell_Wall_Loosening. ||Establishes osmotic engine and storage depot. || This vacuolar development phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July to early August in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over weeks 3-5 post-fertilization during initial enlargement, corresponding to BBCH 73-75 pea-sized to berry touch stages. ||Vacuole initiation mechanism involves small vacuoles 10-30% volume in post-division cells beginning expansion, tonoplast membrane synthesis accommodating growth, water influx into vacuoles driven by solute accumulation, vacuole fusion events creating larger compartments, progressive enlargement to 50-70% cell volume by initiation phase completion, and vacuole as expanding osmotic and storage compartment. ||Post-division vacuole characteristics show cells exiting division containing multiple small vacuoles 2-5 micrometers diameter, vacuoles derived from provacuoles or ER-originated compartments, total vacuole fraction 10-30% cell volume, and small vacuoles as starting point for enlargement. ||Vacuole expansion mechanisms show tonoplast membrane synthesis increasing vacuole surface area, lipid and protein synthesis for membrane expansion, water influx driven by accumulating solutes increasing vacuole volume, membrane synthesis coordinated with water uptake enabling growth, and integrated processes driving vacuole enlargement. ||Tonoplast membrane synthesis shows phospholipid biosynthesis producing membrane lipids, membrane protein synthesis including H+-ATPase proton pumps, transporter proteins enabling solute accumulation, aquaporin water channels facilitating water influx, and coordinated synthesis accommodating vacuole expansion. ||Tonoplast H+-ATPase function shows proton pump acidifying vacuole interior, ATP-dependent H+ transport creating pH gradient 2-3 units across tonoplast, acidification enabling secondary active transport of solutes, and pump as key regulator of vacuole function. ||Solute accumulation into vacuole shows organic acids particularly malate transported into vacuole, tartrate synthesis and accumulation in vacuole, potassium import balancing organic acid anions, sugar beginning accumulation though limited during initial phase, and solute accumulation creating osmotic potential driving water influx. ||Malate accumulation shows malic acid as primary accumulated organic acid during initiation, malate transporter-mediated import from cytoplasm to vacuole, vacuolar malate concentration reaching 50-100 mM, and malate as major osmolyte and contributor to acidity. ||Tartrate accumulation shows tartaric acid synthesis from ascorbate pathway in cytoplasm, tartrate transport into vacuole, tartrate relatively stable once accumulated, concentration 30-60 mM in vacuole, and tartrate as characteristic grape organic acid. ||Potassium accumulation shows K+ import through tonoplast K+/H+ antiporter, potassium concentration 80-150 mM in vacuole, K+ as major cation neutralizing organic acid negative charges, and potassium contributing to osmotic potential. ||Water influx into vacuole shows osmotic gradient from accumulated solutes driving water movement, water crossing tonoplast through aquaporin channels, water influx increasing vacuole volume, and water as primary volume contributor. ||Vacuole osmotic potential shows accumulated solutes creating highly negative osmotic potential -0.8 to -1.2 MPa within vacuole, osmotic potential more negative than cytoplasm driving water from cytoplasm into vacuole, and vacuole as osmotic engine driving cell water uptake and expansion. ||Vacuole volume increase shows typical expansion from 10-30% initial to 50-70% cell volume by initiation completion representing 3-7 fold vacuole volume increase, progressive enlargement paralleling cell expansion, and vacuole volume increase as major cell volume contributor. ||Vacuole fusion events show multiple small vacuoles fusing into fewer larger vacuoles, fusion mediated by SNARE proteins and fusion machinery, progressive fusion creating single or few large vacuoles per cell, and fusion consolidating vacuolar compartment. ||Vacuole number reduction shows cells transitioning from multiple small vacuoles to typically 1-3 larger vacuoles, fusion reducing compartment number while increasing individual size, and eventual dominance of single large central vacuole in mature cells. ||Vacuole as storage compartment shows vacuole storing accumulated organic acids, ions, later sugars during ripening, water comprising 85-90% vacuole mass, and vacuole as major storage depot. ||Vacuole pH characteristics show acidic pH 3.0-3.5 from organic acid accumulation and proton pump activity, pH maintained through continued pumping, acidic pH affecting enzyme activities and solute partitioning, and vacuole acidity as characteristic feature. ||Vacuole-cytoplasm relationships show vacuole occupying increasing cell volume fraction leaving cytoplasm as thin peripheral layer, cytoplasm maintaining metabolic functions in reduced volume, and spatial organization with vacuole central and cytoplasm peripheral. ||Cell volume increase from vacuole expansion shows vacuole enlargement contributing substantially to cell volume increase, typical 60-80% cell volume increase attributable to vacuole during initiation, and vacuole as dominant volume contributor. ||Environmental effects on vacuole initiation include temperature affecting membrane synthesis and solute accumulation rate, water availability affecting water influx and vacuole expansion, nutrient supply affecting solute accumulation capacity, and overall favorable conditions supporting vacuole development. ||Water effects show adequate water essential for vacuole expansion through water influx, water deficit limiting vacuole growth potentially reducing cell expansion, and water as critical resource. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster membrane synthesis and vacuole development, cool conditions slowing initiation though not preventing, and temperature affecting development rate. ||Vacuole initiation assessment methods include transmission electron microscopy showing vacuole structure and size, confocal microscopy with vacuole-selective dyes, vacuole isolation and compositional analysis, and morphometric analysis quantifying vacuole fraction. ||The process represents second aspect of initial cell enlargement establishing osmotic compartment, following turgor-driven expansion onset and preceding cell wall loosening. ||Duration weeks 3-5 representing progressive vacuole development during initial enlargement. ||Regional timing shows vacuole enlargement initiation during mid-late July to early August across climates during initial enlargement. ||Viticultural significance includes representing development of major storage compartment, establishing osmotic engine driving expansion, demonstrating water and nutrient accumulation system, and creating compartment for subsequent sugar accumulation during ripening. ||Research applications include analyzing vacuole biogenesis and expansion mechanisms, investigating tonoplast transport and regulation, evaluating solute accumulation dynamics, quantifying vacuole contribution to cell volume, and assessing vacuole development as determinant of expansion capacity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 444-447 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Cell_Wall_Loosening": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Wall_Loosening is an Initial_Cell_Enlargement involving expansin proteins and wall-modifying enzymes increasing cell wall plasticity enabling yielding under turgor pressure with coordinated synthesis maintaining wall integrity.",
  "alternative_term": "wall modification | expansin-mediated loosening | wall plasticity increase | growth-enabling wall changes |+ Zellwand-Lockerung | Wandmodifikation | Expansin-vermittelte Lockerung | Wandplastizitäts-Erhöhung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows cell wall loosening during mid-late July to early August Year N+1 at BBCH 73-75, with expansin gene expression upregulated 6-12 fold, α-expansin protein accumulation in apoplast pH 4.8, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase activity increasing, wall yield threshold declining from 0.52 to 0.38 MPa, coordinated wall synthesis maintaining 0.18 micrometer thickness, enabling 3.4-fold cell volume increase, under warm climate conditions of 26-32°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar modifying walls for enlargement",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Wall_Loosening is third and final aspect of Initial_Cell_Enlargement, distinguished by wall modification enabling expansion. ||Represents expansin-mediated disruption of cellulose-hemicellulose bonds. ||XET rearranges xyloglucans, PME modifies pectin. ||Wall plasticity increases, yield threshold decreases. ||Coordinated synthesis maintains 0.1-0.3 micrometer thickness. ||Apoplast pH 4.5-5.5 optimal for expansin. ||Duration weeks 3-5. ||Follows Turgor_Driven_Expansion_Onset and Vacuole_Enlargement_Initiation. ||Completes Initial_Cell_Enlargement. ||Essential enabling mechanism for turgor-driven growth. || This wall modification phase occurs during mid-late summer in mid-late July to early August in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding during initial enlargement weeks 3-5 post-fertilization, corresponding to BBCH 73-75 pea-sized to berry touch stages. ||Wall loosening mechanism involves expansin protein expression and secretion disrupting wall structure, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase rearranging wall polymers, pectin methylesterase modifying pectin affecting wall properties, wall plasticity increase enabling yielding under turgor, coordinated wall synthesis maintaining thickness preventing failure, and integrated loosening-synthesis enabling controlled expansion. ||Expansin function in wall loosening shows α-expansin family members expressed during berry enlargement, expansin proteins secreted to apoplast binding to cell wall, non-hydrolytic disruption of hydrogen bonds between cellulose microfibrils and matrix polysaccharides particularly xyloglucans, wall loosening enabling turgor-driven expansion, and expansins as key wall-loosening enzymes. ||Expansin mechanism shows proteins binding to cellulose-xyloglucan interface, disruption of non-covalent bonds without polymer hydrolysis, wall loosening through bond disruption enabling polymer slippage, reversible binding allowing processive action, and mechanism enabling controlled wall plasticity increase. ||Expansin gene expression shows upregulation during transition to enlargement phase, expression levels correlating with expansion rate, transcript accumulation in expanding berry tissues, and expression as marker of active expansion. ||Expansin pH dependence shows optimal activity at acidic pH 4.5-5.5 characteristic of apoplast, acidic environment from cell wall pH typical 4.5-5.0, pH dependence ensuring activity in appropriate compartment, and pH regulation potentially controlling expansin activity. ||Xyloglucan endotransglucosylase XET function shows enzyme cutting and religating xyloglucan chains, transglycosylation rearranging xyloglucan cross-links, wall restructuring enabling expansion, XET activity correlating with growth rate, and enzyme complementing expansin action. ||XET mechanism shows enzyme cleaving xyloglucan backbone, transferring cleaved segment to new acceptor chain, rearrangement enabling wall relaxation and expansion, and mechanism providing dynamic wall restructuring. ||Pectin methylesterase PME function shows enzyme de-esterifying pectin removing methyl groups, demethylated pectin enabling calcium cross-linking potentially strengthening walls, PME action regulating wall mechanical properties, and enzyme affecting wall plasticity through pectin modification. ||PME complexity shows enzyme creating demethylated pectin blocks, calcium binding to demethylated regions creating egg-box structures, cross-linking potentially stiffening walls though effects complex, and PME as regulator of wall properties. ||Cell wall structure during loosening shows primary wall consisting of cellulose microfibrils embedded in matrix of hemicelluloses and pectins, cellulose providing tensile strength, matrix polymers interconnecting microfibrils, and structure modified through loosening enabling expansion. ||Cellulose microfibril characteristics show semi-crystalline cellulose polymers 3-5 nm diameter, microfibrils providing structural framework resisting tensile stress, microfibrils relatively stable during loosening, and framework maintained while matrix loosens. ||Hemicellulose matrix shows xyloglucans as primary hemicelluloses connecting cellulose microfibrils, xyloglucan hydrogen bonding to cellulose, bonds disrupted by expansin enabling slippage, and matrix as loosening target. ||Pectin matrix shows pectin polymers including homogalacturonan and rhamnogalacturonan contributing to wall properties, pectin de-esterification and calcium binding affecting properties, and pectin as regulatory component. ||Wall plasticity increase shows loosening reducing wall mechanical resistance to expansion, yield threshold decreasing enabling expansion at lower turgor, wall capable of plastic yielding under sustained pressure, and plasticity increase as essential expansion enabler. ||Wall stress-strain relationships show elastic region with reversible deformation, plastic region with irreversible deformation enabling growth, yield point separating elastic and plastic behavior typically 0.3-0.5 MPa turgor, and loosening reducing yield point enabling expansion. ||Wall synthesis during loosening shows new cellulose deposition maintaining microfibril density despite area increase, new hemicellulose and pectin synthesis, coordinated synthesis preventing excessive wall thinning, typical wall thickness maintained 0.1-0.3 micrometers during expansion, and synthesis essential for structural integrity. ||Synthesis-loosening coordination shows balanced processes enabling controlled expansion, excessive loosening without synthesis causing wall failure, excessive synthesis without loosening preventing expansion, and coordination as critical regulation point. ||Wall thickness maintenance shows wall area increasing substantially during expansion, new material deposition maintaining thickness despite area increase, thickness relatively constant 0.1-0.3 micrometers, and maintenance preventing wall rupture. ||Environmental effects on wall loosening include temperature affecting enzyme activities and gene expression with optimal 22-28°C supporting normal loosening, acidic pH in apoplast supporting expansin activity, and overall conditions affecting loosening rate. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster expansin expression and activity, cool conditions slowing but not preventing loosening, and temperature affecting loosening kinetics. ||Wall loosening assessment methods include expansin gene expression analysis, enzyme activity assays in isolated walls, wall mechanical testing measuring yielding properties, and atomic force microscopy examining wall structure. ||The process represents third and final aspect of initial cell enlargement enabling expansion through wall modification, following turgor-driven expansion onset and vacuole enlargement initiation. ||Duration weeks 3-5 representing progressive wall modification during initial enlargement. ||Regional timing shows cell wall loosening during mid-late July to early August across climates during initial enlargement. ||Viticultural significance includes representing essential enabling mechanism for expansion, demonstrating enzymatic regulation of growth, showing wall modification-synthesis coordination, and enabling turgor-driven cell volume increase. ||Research applications include analyzing wall loosening mechanisms and regulation, investigating expansin and XET function and control, evaluating wall synthesis-loosening coordination, quantifying wall mechanical properties during expansion, and assessing wall loosening as determinant of expansion rate and capacity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 445-448 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Rapid_Cell_Expansion": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Cell_Expansion is a Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase characterized by peak turgor-driven cell volume increase of 5–15 fold and berry fresh weight gain of 100–250 mg per day, extending over weeks 5–8 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "peak expansion | maximum cell growth | intensive enlargement | rapid growth phase | schnelle Zellexpansion |+ Spitzen-Expansion | maximales Zellwachstum | intensive Vergrößerung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows rapid cell expansion during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75-77, with cells enlarging 8.6-fold from 48 to 142 micrometers diameter, massive vacuoles occupying 86% cell volume, water uptake 1.4-2.0 g per berry per day, peak berry growth rate 140-190 mg per day, berry diameter expanding from 21 to 29 mm achieving 87% final size, fresh weight increasing from 9 to 17 g, under oceanic conditions of 22-28°C temperature with adequate summer rainfall, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing rapid enlargement",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Cell_Expansion is second and final phase of Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase, distinguished by maximum enlargement intensity. ||Subdivided into Maximum_Expansion_Rate with peak cell velocity, Massive_Vacuole_Formation creating 80-90% volume compartment, and Peak_Berry_Growth_Rate achieving maximum increase. ||Duration 2-4 weeks representing weeks 5-8. ||Cell volume 5-15 fold increase. ||Turgor 0.6-1.2 MPa sustained. ||Water uptake 1.0-2.5 g/berry/day. ||Berry achieves 80-95% final size. ||Water availability most critical factor. ||Follows Initial_Cell_Enlargement. ||Completes Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. || This maximum expansion phase occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 2-4 weeks representing peak enlargement intensity, corresponding to BBCH 75-77 berry touch to beginning bunch closure stages. ||Rapid expansion mechanism involves maximum expansion rate with optimized turgor-wall system operating at peak capacity, massive vacuole formation with central vacuole occupying 80-90% cell volume, peak berry growth rate from coordinated cell enlargement across berry populations, sustained high water uptake 1.0-2.5 g per berry per day, and intensive enlargement establishing near-final berry size. ||Cell expansion acceleration shows enlargement rate increasing from initial phase levels to peak during rapid expansion, expansion rate proportional to turgor exceeding yield threshold, optimized wall loosening enabling maximum yielding, and peak rate reflecting optimal coordination of expansion mechanisms. ||Maximum expansion rate characteristics show individual cells enlarging at highest velocity, typical 5-15 fold volume increase during rapid expansion phase from 40-70 micrometers to 80-140 micrometers diameter, rapid volume accumulation over 2-4 weeks, and maximum rate representing peak growth capacity. ||Cell volume dynamics show exponential-like volume increase during rapid phase, typical doubling time 7-12 days during peak expansion, sustained rapid enlargement over weeks, and cumulative substantial volume gain. ||Turgor pressure maintenance shows sustained turgor 0.6-1.2 MPa during rapid expansion, continued solute accumulation maintaining osmotic gradient, continued water uptake sustaining pressure, and maintained turgor enabling sustained expansion. ||Osmotic potential during rapid expansion shows values -1.0 to -1.5 MPa from high solute concentrations, organic acids reaching peak levels 1.2-1.8% fresh weight, potassium accumulation to 180-250 mmol/L tissue, sugars beginning accumulation 5-8% though still relatively low, and strong osmotic gradient driving intensive water uptake. ||Water uptake peak shows maximum water influx rates 1.0-2.5 g per berry per day during rapid expansion, intensive water import supplying expanding cells, xylem as primary water source, possible phloem water contribution, and high uptake rate enabling rapid enlargement. ||Xylem water delivery shows functioning xylem vessels delivering water to berry, transpiration pull and root pressure driving flow, xylem dominance during growth phase, and vascular capacity supporting high water demand. ||Massive vacuole formation shows central vacuole expanding to occupy 80-90% mature cell volume, vacuole volume increase accounting for majority of cell volume gain, single large vacuole per cell typical in mature expanding cells, and vacuole as dominant cell compartment. ||Vacuole size during rapid expansion shows typical progression from 50-70% initial to 80-90% by rapid expansion completion, vacuole diameter 60-180 micrometers in mature cells, and massive size characteristic of fully expanded cells. ||Vacuole storage function shows compartment storing accumulated water, organic acids at peak concentrations, potassium and other ions, beginning sugar accumulation, and vacuole as major storage depot. ||Cytoplasm organization shows cytoplasm as thin 2-5 micrometer peripheral layer surrounding central vacuole, nucleus and organelles in peripheral cytoplasm, cytoplasmic streaming possibly distributing materials, and efficient cytoplasm organization in expanded cells. ||Cell wall during rapid expansion shows wall thinning from area increase faster than synthesis, wall thickness declining to 0.1-0.2 micrometers, maintained wall integrity preventing rupture, and wall capable of supporting large cell size. ||Wall area increase shows substantial surface area expansion during rapid phase, typical 5-15 fold area increase, coordinated wall deposition, and area increase requiring continued synthesis. ||Berry growth rate peak shows maximum berry fresh weight increase 100-250 mg per day in large-berried cultivars, sustained high growth rate over 2-4 weeks, growth rate reflecting coordinated cell enlargement, and peak as maximum growth capacity. ||Berry volumetric increase shows substantial expansion from 6-12 g initial to 10-20 g by rapid expansion completion in large-berried cultivars, typical 1.5-2.5 fold volumetric increase during rapid phase, and major size gain during intensive enlargement. ||Berry diameter increase shows expansion from 18-25 mm at rapid expansion onset to 24-36 mm by completion depending on cultivar, substantial diameter gain 6-12 mm during rapid phase, and berry approaching near-final dimensions. ||Berry size achievement shows berry reaching 80-95% final size by rapid expansion completion, near-final dimensions established, remaining growth during lag and ripening relatively limited, and rapid expansion as major size determinant. ||Berry composition during rapid expansion shows water content maintained 80-85% fresh weight, organic acids at peak 1.2-1.8%, sugars low to moderate 5-8%, pH 2.8-3.0, and hard acidic green berry characteristic. ||Cell enlargement spatial coordination shows enlargement across all berry cells creating uniform growth, tissue-level coordination maintaining berry shape and integrity, and coordinated expansion preventing structural problems. ||Environmental effects on rapid expansion include water availability as most critical factor with adequate water absolutely essential for maximum expansion, deficit severely limiting expansion reducing final size 20-50%, temperature affecting expansion rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting peak rates, and favorable conditions maximizing size achievement. ||Water deficit effects show deficit during rapid expansion as most critical period for size limitation, reduced water availability preventing full turgor and expansion, deficit effects on final size substantial and irreversible, and water as limiting factor during intensive enlargement. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting maximum expansion rate, cool conditions slowing expansion though generally not preventing substantial enlargement, and temperature affecting rate and timing rather than potential. ||Irrigation importance shows irrigation during rapid expansion critical in water-limited regions, supplemental water enabling full size potential achievement, and irrigation as key viticultural practice for size optimization. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including maximum expansion rate with peak cell enlargement velocity, massive vacuole formation creating dominant compartment, and peak berry growth rate achieving maximum size increase. ||Duration typically 2-4 weeks representing intensive enlargement weeks 5-8. ||Regional timing shows rapid cell expansion during late July-early August across climates as peak expansion proceeds. ||Viticultural significance includes representing maximum growth phase establishing near-final berry size, requiring optimal water availability for size achievement, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity during peak enlargement, and determining berry size affecting yield and quality. ||Research applications include analyzing maximum expansion mechanisms and regulation, investigating water relations during peak uptake, evaluating vacuole formation and function, quantifying expansion rate dynamics and determinants, and assessing rapid expansion as major berry size determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 446-450 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Maximum_Expansion_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Expansion_Rate is a Rapid_Cell_Expansion marked by individual cell volume increase at the highest velocity producing 5–15 fold expansion over 2–4 weeks, occurring during weeks 5–7 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "peak expansion velocity | maximum growth rate | fastest enlargement | optimal expansion speed |+ maximale Expansionsrate | Spitzen-Expansionsgeschwindigkeit | maximale Wachstumsrate | schnellste Vergrößerung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows maximum expansion rate during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75-76, with cells enlarging at peak velocity, volume doubling time 8-10 days, 11-fold volume increase over 3 weeks from 52 to 128 micrometers diameter, turgor 0.9-1.1 MPa exceeding 0.48 MPa yield threshold, water uptake 1.6-2.2 g per berry per day, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 26-30°C temperature with adequate irrigation, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar achieving maximum expansion",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Expansion_Rate is first aspect of Rapid_Cell_Expansion, distinguished by peak cell enlargement velocity. ||Represents 5-15 fold volume increase over 2-4 weeks. ||Doubling time 7-12 days. ||Turgor 0.8-1.2 MPa exceeding yield threshold 0.4-0.6 MPa. ||Peak expansin activity. ||Water uptake 1.2-2.5 g/berry/day. ||Rate = extensibility × (P-Y). ||Duration 1-3 weeks peak period. ||Water availability most critical factor. ||Followed by Massive_Vacuole_Formation. ||Determines substantial size gain. || This maximum velocity phase occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over weeks 5-7 representing peak rate period, corresponding to BBCH 75-76 berry touch to berries beginning to touch stages. ||Maximum rate mechanism involves optimized turgor pressure 0.8-1.2 MPa exceeding yield threshold by maximum margin, maximum wall yielding from peak expansin and wall-modifying enzyme activity, sustained water uptake 1.2-2.5 g per berry per day supplying expanding cells, coordinated expansion processes operating at maximum efficiency, and peak rate reflecting optimal growth capacity. ||Cell volume increase rate shows typical individual cell volume doubling time 7-12 days during maximum rate period, exponential-like volume accumulation, 5-15 fold total volume increase during rapid expansion phase, and maximum rate representing fastest cell growth during berry development. ||Volume doubling characteristics show rapid doubling from high expansion rate, multiple doublings possible during 2-4 week maximum rate period, and exponential pattern characteristic of unrestricted growth. ||Cell diameter increase shows typical expansion from 40-70 micrometers at maximum rate onset to 80-140 micrometers by completion, diameter increase rate 3-8 micrometers per week during peak, and linear diameter increase contrasting with volumetric exponential increase. ||Cell volume calculation shows spherical approximation V = 4/3πr³, volume increase cubic function of radius increase, small diameter increases producing large volume increases, and geometric amplification of linear growth. ||Turgor pressure optimization shows sustained high turgor 0.8-1.2 MPa during maximum rate period, turgor exceeding wall yield threshold 0.4-0.6 MPa by 0.4-0.6 MPa margin, large turgor excess driving maximum expansion rate, and pressure as rate-limiting factor when suboptimal. ||Turgor-rate relationship shows expansion rate proportional to turgor excess above yield threshold, mathematical relationship, rate = extensibility × (P - Y), higher turgor driving faster expansion, and turgor optimization critical for maximum rate achievement. ||Wall extensibility during maximum rate shows wall yielding capacity maximized through peak expansin activity, optimal wall loosening-synthesis coordination, extensibility parameter high enabling rapid yielding, and wall properties optimized for growth. ||Expansin activity peak shows expansin gene expression maximal during rapid expansion, protein accumulation highest in expanding tissues, enzyme activity correlating with expansion rate, and expansin as key rate determinant. ||Water supply during maximum rate shows intensive water uptake 1.2-2.5 g per berry per day, water influx supporting rapid volume increase, adequate water availability essential for maximum rate, and water as critical resource. ||Water limitation effects show water deficit reducing turgor limiting expansion rate, deficit during maximum rate period severely limiting size achievement, and water as most common rate-limiting factor. ||Osmotic gradient maintenance shows continued solute accumulation maintaining strong osmotic potential -1.0 to -1.5 MPa, gradient driving intensive water uptake, malate and tartrate at peak concentrations 1.2-1.8% total, and gradient as water uptake driver. ||Metabolic support for maximum rate shows high respiratory rate providing ATP for active transport and biosynthesis, energy supporting solute accumulation and wall synthesis, metabolic capacity enabling sustained high growth rate, and metabolism as enabling factor. ||Respiratory characteristics show oxygen consumption elevated during rapid growth, typical rates 2-4 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, respiration supporting growth processes, and metabolic activity correlating with expansion rate. ||Expansion rate measurement shows cell size measurements at time points quantifying rate, diameter or volume increase per unit time, typical rates 10-25% volume increase per day during peak, and rate quantification enabling growth analysis. ||Berry growth rate correlation shows individual cell expansion rate determining berry growth rate, berry growth as sum of individual cell expansions, coordinated cell expansion creating berry volumetric increase, and cell rate as fundamental growth determinant. ||Maximum rate timing shows typical peak weeks 5-7 post-fertilization, cultivar variation in peak timing affecting total expansion duration, peak representing optimal conditions and developmental state, and timing relatively consistent within cultivars. ||Maximum rate duration shows sustained peak rate typically 1-3 weeks, duration determining total volume gain during peak period, and sustained high rate characteristic of effective growth. ||Rate decline characteristics shows eventual expansion rate decline as cells approach genetic size limit, rate reduction during late rapid expansion transitioning to lag phase, and decline marking end of intensive enlargement. ||Environmental effects on maximum rate include temperature affecting expansion kinetics with optimal 24-28°C supporting peak rates, cool conditions reducing rate through slowed metabolism and wall modification, water availability critically affecting rate through turgor maintenance, and favorable conditions essential for maximum rate achievement. ||Temperature-rate relationship shows warm conditions promoting maximum rate through faster enzymatic processes, cool conditions reducing rate 30-50% though expansion continues, and temperature as major rate determinant. ||Water-rate relationship shows adequate water enabling full turgor and maximum rate, deficit reducing turgor proportionally reducing rate, and water deficit as most common rate limitation. ||The process represents first aspect of rapid cell expansion emphasizing peak enlargement velocity, preceding massive vacuole formation and peak berry growth rate. ||Duration typically 1-3 weeks representing peak rate period weeks 5-7. ||Regional timing shows maximum expansion rate during late July-early August across climates during peak enlargement. ||Viticultural significance includes representing fastest cell growth determining substantial size gain, requiring optimal water and temperature for maximum rate, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity, and establishing maximum enlargement capacity determining final size. ||Research applications include analyzing rate-limiting factors and optimization, investigating turgor-wall relationships determining rate, evaluating water supply effects on expansion velocity, quantifying rate dynamics and environmental responses, and assessing maximum rate as determinant of berry size achievement.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 446-449 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Massive_Vacuole_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Massive_Vacuole_Formation is a Rapid_Cell_Expansion comprising central vacuole expansion to 80–90% of cell volume with the cytoplasm reduced to a 2–5 μm peripheral layer.",
  "alternative_term": "dominant vacuole establishment | large vacuole formation | vacuolar compartment dominance | central vacuole development |+ massive Vakuolen-Bildung | dominante Vakuolen-Etablierung | große Vakuolen-Formation | vakuoläre Kompartment-Dominanz",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows massive vacuole formation during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75-77, with vacuoles expanding from 62% to 88% cell volume, single central vacuole 105 micrometers diameter occupying cell interior, tonoplast area 2200 μm² per cell, vacuole storing malate 72 mM, tartrate 48 mM, K+ 124 mM, pH 3.2, cytoplasm as 3.2 micrometer peripheral layer, under cool maritime conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar developing massive vacuolar system",
  "editor_note": "Massive_Vacuole_Formation is second aspect of Rapid_Cell_Expansion, distinguished by dominant compartment establishment. ||Represents expansion from 50-70% to 80-90% cell volume. ||Single central vacuole 60-180 micrometers. ||Tonoplast 1000-5000 μm² area. ||Stores acids, K+, water (85-90% mass). ||Osmotic potential -1.0 to -1.5 MPa. ||pH 3.0-3.5. ||Cytoplasm 2-5 micrometer peripheral layer. ||Duration weeks 5-8. ||Follows Maximum_Expansion_Rate. ||Precedes Peak_Berry_Growth_Rate. ||Accounts for 70-85% cell volume increase. || This vacuolar dominance establishment phase occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over weeks 5-8 as vacuole reaches maximum development, corresponding to BBCH 75-77 berry touch to beginning bunch closure stages. ||Massive formation mechanism involves progressive vacuole expansion from 50-70% volume at rapid expansion onset to 80-90% at completion, sustained water influx into vacuole driving enlargement, tonoplast membrane synthesis accommodating massive expansion, solute accumulation maintaining osmotic gradient, and eventual vacuole dominance with single central compartment occupying cell interior. ||Vacuole volume fraction progression shows typical increase from 50-70% initial rapid expansion to 75-85% mid-phase to 80-90% completion, progressive volume occupation, final vacuole as overwhelmingly dominant compartment, and high fraction characteristic of fully expanded berry cells. ||Vacuole size in fully expanded cells shows vacuole diameter 60-180 micrometers depending on cell size, massive compartment volume 0.1-3 nanoliters, single vacuole per cell typical though occasionally 2-3 vacuoles, and large size as defining characteristic. ||Central vacuole position shows vacuole occupying cell center, cytoplasm peripheral surrounding vacuole, nucleus and organelles in cytoplasmic layer, and spatial organization characteristic of expanded cells. ||Cytoplasm organization shows thin peripheral layer 2-5 micrometers thickness, cytoplasm containing nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, ER, and other organelles, maintained metabolic functions in reduced volume, and efficient organization supporting cell function. ||Tonoplast membrane area shows massive membrane surface accommodating large vacuole, typical 1000-5000 μm² tonoplast area per cell, membrane synthesis during expansion producing required area, and large membrane area enabling extensive transport capacity. ||Tonoplast protein composition shows H+-ATPase proton pumps maintaining pH gradient, numerous transporters for organic acids, sugars, ions, aquaporins facilitating water movement, and specialized protein complement supporting vacuole function. ||Vacuole storage capacity shows massive volume 80-90% cell enabling extensive solute storage, vacuole storing organic acids 1.2-1.8%, potassium 80-150 mM, beginning sugar accumulation 5-8%, water comprising 85-90% vacuole mass, and vacuole as major storage depot. ||Organic acid storage shows malate and tartrate accumulated to peak concentrations, acids stored in vacuole maintaining high cytoplasmic pH, acid storage creating acidic vacuole pH 3.0-3.5, and acids as major stored solutes and contributors to acidity. ||Potassium storage shows K+ accumulated in vacuole, concentration 80-150 mM in vacuole versus 100-150 mM in cytoplasm, potassium as major cation, and K+ storage supporting osmotic potential and electrical balance. ||Water storage shows water as primary vacuole content 85-90% mass, massive water storage in berry cells, water mobilizable during ripening and later development, and water as dominant stored compound. ||Vacuole osmotic function shows accumulated solutes creating osmotic potential -1.0 to -1.5 MPa, strong negative potential driving water uptake, vacuole as osmotic engine maintaining turgor, and osmotic function enabling sustained expansion. ||Vacuole pH regulation shows proton pump acidification maintaining pH 3.0-3.5, acidic pH from organic acid accumulation and active pumping, pH affecting enzyme activities and transport, and pH regulation as key vacuole function. ||Vacuole metabolic role shows compartmentalization segregating acids from cytoplasmic metabolism, maintaining cytoplasmic pH 7.0-7.5 while vacuole acidic, metabolic efficiency from compartmentation, and vacuole as regulatory compartment. ||Cytoplasm-vacuole relationships shows dynamic exchange of solutes and water, tonoplast transporters mediating exchange, coordinated regulation maintaining cellular homeostasis, and integrated function despite spatial separation. ||Vacuole volume as cell volume determinant shows vacuole expansion accounting for 70-85% total cell volume increase during rapid expansion, vacuole as major volume contributor, and vacuole size determining cell size. ||Massive vacuole formation timing shows progressive development during weeks 5-8, completion by end of rapid expansion, and fully developed vacuole persisting through subsequent development. ||Fully expanded cell characteristics shows cell diameter 80-200 micrometers depending on cultivar and position, central vacuole 80-90% volume, thin peripheral cytoplasm, and mature expanded morphology. ||Environmental effects on massive vacuole formation include water availability affecting vacuole expansion capacity with adequate water essential for maximum development, temperature affecting development rate, and favorable conditions supporting complete vacuole development. ||Water effects show water limitation restricting vacuole expansion limiting cell size, adequate water enabling full vacuole development, and water as critical determinant of vacuole and cell size. ||Massive vacuole assessment methods include microscopy showing vacuole size and position, vacuole isolation and volume measurement, tonoplast transport studies, and compositional analysis of vacuole contents. ||The process represents second aspect of rapid cell expansion establishing dominant compartment, following maximum expansion rate and preceding peak berry growth rate. ||Duration weeks 5-8 representing progressive vacuole development to maximum. ||Regional timing shows massive vacuole formation during late July-early August across climates during rapid enlargement. ||Viticultural significance includes representing establishment of major storage compartment, creating osmotic engine sustaining expansion, providing capacity for subsequent sugar accumulation during ripening, and determining final cell architecture. ||Research applications include analyzing vacuole biogenesis and regulation, investigating tonoplast transport and function, evaluating vacuole contribution to cell size, quantifying storage capacity and composition, and assessing vacuole as determinant of cell and berry size.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 447-450"
},

  "Peak_Berry_Growth_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Berry_Growth_Rate is a Rapid_Cell_Expansion characterized by berry fresh weight gain of 100–250 mg per day with attainment of 75–90% final size, extending over weeks 5–7 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum berry growth | peak enlargement rate | highest berry expansion | intensive berry growth |+ Spitzen-Beerenwachstumsrate | maximales Beerenwachstum | Spitzen-Vergrößerungsrate | höchste Beerenexpansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows peak berry growth rate during late July-early August Year N+1 at BBCH 75-77, with maximum growth rate 160-220 mg fresh weight per day sustained 3 weeks, water uptake 1.8-2.4 g per berry per day, berry diameter expanding from 22 to 32 mm, fresh weight increasing from 8 to 18 g achieving 82% final size, coordinated cell expansion across 2.8 million cells, under warm climate conditions of 26-32°C temperature with adequate irrigation, typical of this late-season large-berried cultivar",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Berry_Growth_Rate is third and final aspect of Rapid_Cell_Expansion, distinguished by maximum berry-level enlargement. ||Represents coordinated cell expansion creating 100-250 mg/day growth in large cultivars. ||Water uptake 1.5-2.5 g/berry/day. ||Berry achieves 75-90% final size. ||Diameter increases 6-12 mm. ||Duration 2-4 weeks. ||Water availability most critical factor - deficit reduces size 20-50%. ||Temperature optimal 24-28°C. ||Follows Maximum_Expansion_Rate and Massive_Vacuole_Formation. ||Completes Rapid_Cell_Expansion and Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. ||Major yield determinant. || This maximum berry growth phase occurs during late summer in late July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning 2-4 weeks representing peak growth intensity, corresponding to BBCH 75-77 berry touch to beginning bunch closure stages. ||Peak rate mechanism involves coordinated expansion of all berry cells creating additive volumetric increase, maximum individual cell expansion rates translating to berry growth, intensive water uptake 1.5-2.5 g per berry per day supplying growth, coordinated tissue-level growth maintaining berry integrity, and peak rate reflecting optimal growth conditions and developmental state. ||Berry growth rate quantification shows fresh weight increase 100-250 mg per day during peak in large-berried cultivars, 50-120 mg per day in small-to-medium cultivars, sustained high rate over 2-4 weeks, and rate as convenient growth measure. ||Growth rate variation shows cultivar differences with large-berried showing highest absolute rates, small-berried showing lower rates but similar relative growth, and genetic variation determining peak rate capacity. ||Berry volumetric increase shows diameter expansion 1-2 mm per week during peak period, volumetric increase 1.5-2.5 fold over 2-4 week peak phase, substantial size gain during intensive growth, and volumetric increase as major berry growth. ||Berry diameter progression shows typical expansion from 18-25 mm at peak onset to 24-36 mm by completion depending on cultivar, diameter increase 6-12 mm during peak period, and substantial linear growth. ||Berry fresh weight accumulation shows weight increase from 6-12 g at peak onset to 10-22 g by completion in large-berried cultivars, weight gain 4-10 g during peak period, and major mass accumulation. ||Berry size achievement shows berry reaching 75-90% final mature size by peak rate period completion, substantial approach to genetic size potential, remaining growth during lag and ripening relatively limited 10-25%, and peak period as major size determinant. ||Cell expansion coordination shows all established cells expanding synchronously or near-synchronously, tissue-level coordination creating uniform berry growth, coordinated expansion maintaining structural integrity and shape, and population-level coordination as growth mechanism. ||Cell contribution to berry growth shows individual cell 10-30 fold volume increase from division completion to mature size, final cell volume 80-200 micrometers diameter depending on cultivar, and multiplicative effect of cell number and cell size determining berry size. ||Cell number-cell size interaction shows berry volume determined by cell number × average cell volume, genetic variation in both parameters, and interactive effects creating cultivar size ranges. ||Water uptake during peak growth shows intensive water import 1.5-2.5 g per berry per day, water as primary mass contributor accounting for 80-85% fresh weight gain, xylem as major water source, and high water flux supporting rapid growth. ||Xylem function during peak growth shows active xylem delivery supporting water demand, xylem-to-berry water transfer through vascular connections, xylem dominance during growth phase, and vascular capacity as potential growth limitation. ||Berry composition during peak growth shows water content maintained 80-85% fresh weight, organic acids at peak 1.2-1.8%, sugars still moderate 5-8%, pH 2.8-3.0, and green acidic berry characteristic. ||Dry matter accumulation shows progressive dry matter increase during peak growth, dry matter content relatively stable 12-18%, absolute dry matter gain from organic acids, structural components, and minor sugar, and dry matter as structural and metabolic component. ||Organic acid accumulation shows acids reaching peak concentrations during peak growth, malate and tartrate dominating at 1.2-1.8% total, acids contributing to osmotic potential and acidity, and peak acid content characteristic of late growth phase. ||Berry morphology during peak growth shows berry expanding to approach final shape, spherical to ovoid morphology depending on cultivar, smooth surface maintained, and berry appearance as expanding green fruit. ||Cluster architecture during peak growth shows berries expanding to contact neighbors, cluster compactness increasing, berries filling available cluster space, and cluster filling characteristic of peak growth. ||Environmental effects on peak berry growth include water availability as most critical factor with adequate water absolutely essential for maximum growth rate, water deficit severely limiting peak growth reducing final size substantially, temperature affecting growth rate with optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum rates, and favorable conditions essential for peak rate achievement. ||Water deficit effects show deficit during peak growth as most critical period for size limitation, reduced growth rate proportional to deficit severity, deficit effects on final size substantial 20-50% size reduction, and water as primary limiting factor during peak growth. ||Temperature effects on peak growth show warm conditions supporting maximum growth rate, cool conditions reducing rate 20-40% though substantial growth still possible, excessive heat above 35°C potentially limiting growth through stress, and temperature as secondary factor after water. ||Irrigation importance during peak growth shows irrigation critical in water-limited regions during this period, supplemental water enabling maximum growth rate, and irrigation timing during peak growth as most beneficial for size optimization. ||Peak growth rate duration shows typical sustained high rate 2-4 weeks, duration variation among cultivars affecting total size gain, and sustained rate characteristic of favorable conditions. ||Growth rate decline shows eventual rate reduction as berry approaches genetic size limit, rate decline marking transition to lag phase, and decline as developmental progression. ||The process represents third and final aspect of rapid cell expansion emphasizing berry-level growth, following maximum expansion rate and massive vacuole formation. ||Duration typically 2-4 weeks representing peak berry growth period weeks 5-7. ||Regional timing shows peak berry growth rate during late July-early August across climates during intensive enlargement. ||Viticultural significance includes representing maximum berry size increase determining substantial yield, requiring optimal water availability for maximum growth, demonstrating critical environmental sensitivity affecting final size, and establishing near-final berry dimensions affecting yield and quality. ||Research applications include analyzing berry growth dynamics and regulation, investigating water relations and supply during peak growth, evaluating environmental effects on growth rate, quantifying growth determinants and limitations, and assessing peak growth as major berry size determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 448-450 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Maximum_Berry_Enlargement": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Berry_Enlargement is a Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase characterized by cells at 90–95% final size and berry at 90–98% mature dimensions with declining expansion rate, extending over weeks 6–8 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "size maximum approach | peak enlargement | growth culmination | maximum size achievement |+ maximale Beerenvergrößerung | Größenmaximum-Annäherung | Spitzen-Vergrößerung | Wachstums-Kulmination",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows maximum berry enlargement during early-mid August Year N+1 at BBCH 77-79, with cells reaching 92-96% final size at 88-108 micrometers diameter, berry achieving 94-97% final dimensions at 9.2-11.4 mm diameter and 3.8-5.6 g fresh weight, expansion rate declining from 145 to 42 mg per day, wall plasticity decreasing, osmotic potential plateau at -1.3 MPa, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing enlargement",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Berry_Enlargement represents genetic size limit approach within Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. ||Subdivided into Cell_Size_Maximum with cells at 90-95% final dimensions, Berry_Size_Peak achieving 90-98% final size, and Expansion_Rate_Decline marking deceleration. ||Duration 1-2 weeks representing weeks 6-8. ||Wall plasticity decreases, osmotic potential plateaus. ||Growth rate declines from peak to 30-80 mg/day. ||Transition toward lag phase begins. ||Precedes Enlargement_Phase_Completion. ||Determines final berry size. || This size maximum approach phase occurs during late summer in early-mid August in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 1-2 weeks representing enlargement culmination, corresponding to BBCH 77-79 bunch closure to majority berries touching stages. ||Maximum enlargement mechanism involves cell size approaching genetic maximum determined by developmental programming, berry size peak representing culmination of cell number and cell expansion multiplicative effects, expansion rate decline from reduced wall yielding and approaching size limits, metabolic transition initiating shift from growth to lag phase metabolism, and overall growth deceleration marking enlargement phase conclusion. ||Cell size maximum characteristics show cells reaching 85-95% final mature dimensions, typical diameters 75-190 micrometers depending on cultivar and cell type, vacuoles occupying 85-92% cell volume at near-maximum, cytoplasm as thin 1.5-4 micrometer peripheral layer, and cell architecture approaching mature configuration. ||Cell size genetic limits show cultivar-specific maximum cell sizes determined by genetic programming, small-berried cultivars reaching 60-100 micrometer maxima, large-berried cultivars achieving 120-200 micrometer maxima, and genetic control as primary size determinant. ||Cell expansion cessation approaching shows expansion rate progressively declining as cells near maxima, eventual expansion cessation establishing final cell dimensions, cells retaining slight expansion capacity during lag and ripening phases adding final 5-15% size, and near-cessation marking enlargement completion. ||Berry size peak characteristics show berry diameter reaching 90-98% final mature size, typical dimensions 22-40 mm depending on cultivar at enlargement completion, fresh weight 9-25 g representing near-final mass, and berry approaching genetic size potential. ||Berry size genetic potential shows cultivar characteristic size ranges determined by cell number and cell expansion capacities, small-berried cultivars 6-10 mm final diameter, medium-berried 10-14 mm, large-berried 14-20 mm, and genetic programming establishing size ranges. ||Berry size achievement shows typical 90-98% final size reached by maximum enlargement completion, remaining 2-10% size gain during lag and ripening from continued limited expansion and ripening accumulation, and enlargement phase as major size determinant accounting for 85-95% final dimensions. ||Expansion rate decline characteristics show growth rate decreasing from peak 100-250 mg per day to declining 30-80 mg per day during maximum enlargement, progressive deceleration over 1-2 weeks, and rate decline marking transition from intensive to minimal growth. ||Expansion rate decline mechanisms show reduced wall yielding as walls become less plastic approaching size limits, osmotic gradient plateau with solute accumulation reaching steady state, turgor maintenance but reduced expansion effectiveness, cell approaching volume limits constraining further growth, and developmental programming directing growth cessation. ||Wall plasticity reduction shows wall extensibility declining as cells approach size limits, reduced expansin activity and wall modification, wall becoming less yielding under turgor, and wall properties shift from growth-permissive to growth-restrictive. ||Wall mechanical properties changes show increased wall stiffness from accumulated structural modifications, yield threshold increasing requiring higher turgor for expansion, reduced stress relaxation limiting plastic deformation, and mechanical changes limiting continued expansion. ||Osmotic potential plateau shows solute accumulation approaching steady state, osmotic potential reaching -1.2 to -1.6 MPa at maximum, minimal further osmotic potential decline, gradient approaching equilibrium, and plateau limiting additional water uptake driving force. ||Turgor pressure maintenance shows turgor sustained 0.6-1.0 MPa during maximum enlargement, pressure maintained through continued solute accumulation, but reduced expansion from wall stiffening, and turgor-wall relationship shifted toward minimal growth. ||Cell volume constraints show cells approaching physical and genetic size limits, further volume increase increasingly difficult, developmental signals possibly limiting expansion, and approaching constraints as growth cessation mechanism. ||Berry growth rate during maximum enlargement shows declining rate 30-80 mg fresh weight per day, progressive deceleration from peak levels, growth continuing but at reduced intensity, and declining rate characteristic of enlargement conclusion. ||Berry composition during maximum enlargement shows water content 80-85% fresh weight maintained, organic acids at peak or slightly declining 1.2-1.6%, sugars still low to moderate 6-10%, pH 2.8-3.0, and hard acidic green berry approaching lag phase composition. ||Berry morphology shows berry at near-final dimensions, smooth surface maintained, green color persisting, firm texture from turgor and acids, and overall appearance as mature-sized green berry. ||Cluster architecture shows berries tightly touching within clusters, bunch closure achieved with berries filling available space, cluster compactness at maximum, and architecture at peak density. ||Environmental effects on maximum enlargement include water availability affecting final size achievement with continued adequate water important though deficit effects less severe than during peak expansion, temperature affecting metabolic transition timing, and overall conditions determining final size attainment. ||Water effects show continued water supply important for final size, deficit during maximum enlargement potentially limiting final 5-10% size gain, and water less critical than during peak expansion though still important. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions potentially accelerating transition to lag phase, cool conditions extending maximum enlargement period, and temperature affecting transition timing. ||Maximum enlargement completion indicators show expansion rate declining to <20-30 mg per day, berry size approaching 95-98% final dimensions, metabolic markers shifting toward lag phase, and completion establishing transition to growth quiescence. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including cell size maximum with cells approaching genetic limits, berry size peak achieving near-final dimensions, and expansion rate decline marking growth deceleration. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing enlargement culmination weeks 6-8. ||Regional timing shows maximum berry enlargement during early-mid August across climates as intensive expansion concludes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing culmination of berry size establishment determining final yield, marking transition from growth to lag phase, demonstrating approach to genetic size potential, and establishing near-final berry dimensions affecting harvest and quality. ||Research applications include analyzing size limits and genetic controls, investigating expansion cessation mechanisms, evaluating environmental effects on final size achievement, quantifying size determination and limitations, and assessing maximum enlargement as final size determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 448-453 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Cell_Size_Maximum": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Size_Maximum is a Maximum_Berry_Enlargement marked by individual cells reaching 90–95% of final mature size with diameters of 75–190 μm representing culmination of 30–100 fold expansion from post-division dimensions.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum cell dimensions | cell size limit | genetic cell maximum | cellular dimension peak |+ Zellgröße-Maximum | maximale Zelldimensionen | Zellgrößen-Limit | genetisches Zell-Maximum",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows cell size maximum during early-mid August Year N+1 at BBCH 77-79, with mesocarp cells reaching 92-95% final dimensions at 96-132 micrometers diameter representing 62-fold expansion from 28 micrometer post-division size, vacuoles occupying 89% cell volume, cytoplasm 2.8 micrometer peripheral layer, wall 0.16 micrometer thickness, osmotic potential -1.4 MPa, under oceanic conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar approaching genetic cell size limits",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Size_Maximum is first aspect of Maximum_Berry_Enlargement, distinguished by cellular dimension limits. ||Represents cells at 90-95% final size, 75-190 micrometers depending on cultivar. ||30-100 fold total expansion from post-division. ||Vacuole 85-92% volume. ||Wall plasticity reduced. ||Osmotic potential -1.2 to -1.6 MPa plateau. ||Genetic programming primary determinant. ||Duration weeks 6-8. ||Preceded by Rapid_Cell_Expansion. ||Followed by Berry_Size_Peak. ||Establishes cellular component of final berry size. || This cell dimension culmination phase occurs during late summer in early-mid August in temperate regions Year N+1, representing maximum cell size achievement weeks 6-8 post-fertilization, corresponding to BBCH 77-79 bunch closure stages. ||Cell size maximum mechanism involves cells approaching genetically determined size limits programmed during development, physical constraints from cell wall properties and cellular architecture limiting further expansion, reduced wall plasticity preventing continued yielding, osmotic and turgor systems approaching equilibrium states, developmental signals directing expansion cessation, and integrated limitations establishing maximum cell dimensions. ||Cell dimensions at maximum show typical ranges 75-190 micrometers diameter depending on cultivar, small-berried cultivar cells 60-100 micrometers maximum, medium-berried 90-140 micrometers, large-berried 120-200 micrometers, and size ranges reflecting genetic variation. ||Cell volume at maximum shows volumes 0.18-3.6 nanoliters representing culmination of expansion, 30-100 fold increase from post-division 25-45 micrometer cells, substantial volume achieved through intensive water uptake and vacuole expansion, and maximum volume as endpoint of enlargement. ||Vacuole at maximum size shows central vacuole occupying 85-92% cell volume, vacuole diameter 65-185 micrometers in large cells, maximum vacuole representing genetic and physical limits, tonoplast membrane area 1200-6000 square micrometers, and vacuole as dominant compartment at maximum. ||Cytoplasm configuration at maximum shows thin peripheral layer 1.5-4 micrometers thickness, cytoplasm containing nucleus and organelles in compressed space, maintained metabolic function in minimal volume, and efficient organization in fully expanded cells. ||Genetic control of cell size shows developmental programming establishing cultivar-specific size ranges, cell cycle exit timing affecting expansion duration and final size, genetic variation in expansion capacity determining maximum dimensions, and intrinsic genetic regulation as primary size determinant. ||Cell size regulatory mechanisms show possible mechanosensing of cell wall tension signaling size achievement, developmental transcription factors directing expansion cessation, cell-cell communication coordinating population sizing, and integrated regulation ensuring appropriate maxima. ||Wall properties at maximum show increased wall thickness 0.12-0.25 micrometers from continued synthesis, reduced wall plasticity from cross-linking and structural modifications, increased yield threshold requiring higher turgor for further expansion, wall mechanical properties shifted toward growth-restrictive, and wall as physical constraint limiting expansion. ||Wall composition at maximum shows accumulated cellulose microfibrils creating structural framework, extensive hemicellulose and pectin cross-linking, possible calcium-mediated pectin cross-links strengthening walls, and mature wall composition limiting plasticity. ||Osmotic properties at maximum show osmotic potential -1.2 to -1.6 MPa at near-maximum from accumulated solutes, malate and tartrate at peak or declining concentrations 1.2-1.6% total, potassium 80-140 mM, sugars beginning accumulation 6-10%, and osmotic potential approaching steady state. ||Turgor at maximum shows pressure maintained 0.6-1.0 MPa, turgor sustained but expansion minimal from wall constraints, turgor-expansion relationship shifted with high pressure required for minimal growth, and pressure maintenance without substantial expansion. ||Cell expansion cessation approaching shows expansion rate declining to very low levels, eventual complete cessation establishing final cell dimensions within days to weeks, cells retaining minor expansion capacity adding final 5-10% during lag and ripening, and near-cessation at maximum enlargement. ||Remaining expansion capacity shows slight continued enlargement possible during lag and ripening phases, minor volume increases 5-10% from continued limited expansion and ripening processes, and residual capacity allowing final size adjustments. ||Cell size variation within berry shows mesocarp cells showing size range with inner cells typically larger than outer, exocarp epidermal cells smaller typically 40-80 micrometers, cell position affecting maximum size, and spatial heterogeneity in cell dimensions. ||Cell type size differences shows parenchyma mesocarp cells as largest cell type reaching maximum dimensions, vascular tissue cells smaller with specialized morphology, epidermal cells smallest with different expansion patterns, and cell type affecting size ranges. ||Environmental effects on cell size maximum include water availability during enlargement affecting achieved maximum with deficit potentially limiting final size 10-20%, temperature affecting expansion kinetics and timing of maximum, and genetic factors dominating over environmental within normal ranges. ||Water deficit effects on maximum show severe deficit during peak expansion permanently limiting cell size, deficit during maximum enlargement reducing final 5-15%, and water as major environmental factor affecting achieved maximum. ||Cultivar variation in cell size maximum shows genetic differences as primary variation source, small-berried cultivars genetically programmed for 60-100 micrometer cells, large-berried cultivars achieving 120-200 micrometers, and cultivar characteristic maxima determining berry size potential. ||Cell size as berry size determinant shows final berry size determined by cell number × cell size, cell size accounting for 20-40% berry size variation, cell size maximum establishing half of size equation, and maximum cell dimensions critical for final berry size. ||Cell size measurement shows microscopy-based diameter measurements, cell volume calculations from dimensions, population size distribution analysis, and measurement enabling cell size quantification. ||The process represents first aspect of maximum berry enlargement emphasizing cellular dimension limits, preceding berry size peak and expansion rate decline. ||Duration represents maximum size achievement during weeks 6-8. ||Regional timing shows cell size maximum during early-mid August across climates as cells approach genetic limits. ||Viticultural significance includes representing cellular size limit determining berry size potential, demonstrating genetic control of cell dimensions, establishing final cell size affecting berry size and quality, and marking cellular growth culmination. ||Research applications include analyzing genetic and developmental controls of cell size, investigating size limit mechanisms and constraints, evaluating environmental effects on maximum achievement, quantifying cell size variation and determinants, and assessing cell size maximum as berry size determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 448-450 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Berry_Size_Peak": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Size_Peak is a Maximum_Berry_Enlargement characterized by berry diameter of 22–40 mm and fresh weight of 9–25 g representing 90–98% of final mature dimensions.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum berry size | size culmination | growth phase peak | berry dimension maximum |+ Beerengröße-Spitze | maximale Beerengröße | Größen-Kulmination | Wachstumsphase-Spitze",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows berry size peak during early-mid August Year N+1 at BBCH 77-79, with berry achieving 94-97% final dimensions at 13.2-15.8 mm diameter and 11.4-16.2 g fresh weight representing multiplicative combination of 2.4 million cells × 128 micrometer average cell size, remaining 3-6% size increase during lag and ripening, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 25-30°C temperature with adequate irrigation, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar reaching growth phase size peak",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Size_Peak is second aspect of Maximum_Berry_Enlargement, distinguished by berry-level size culmination. ||Represents 90-98% final dimensions achieved. ||Ranges 22-40 mm diameter, 9-25 g depending on cultivar. ||Determined by cell number × cell size. ||Genetic potential largely realized. ||Remaining 2-10% during lag and ripening. ||Duration weeks 6-8. ||Follows Cell_Size_Maximum. ||Precedes Expansion_Rate_Decline. ||Highly predictive of final harvest size (r²=0.85-0.95). ||Major yield determinant. || This size culmination phase occurs during late summer in early-mid August in temperate regions Year N+1, representing berry dimension peak weeks 6-8, corresponding to BBCH 77-79 bunch closure to majority berries touching stages. ||Berry size peak mechanism involves multiplicative combination of final cell number 1-4 million cells and near-maximum cell size 75-190 micrometers determining berry volume, berry achieving 90-98% final mature dimensions at peak, genetic size potential largely realized through completed cell expansion, remaining 2-10% size increase during lag and ripening from minor expansion and ripening accumulation, and peak establishing near-final berry size. ||Berry dimensions at peak show diameter ranges 22-40 mm depending on cultivar with small-berried 6-9 mm, medium-berried 10-14 mm, large-berried 15-22 mm at growth phase peak, fresh weight ranges 9-25 g in large cultivars and 2-6 g in small cultivars, and dimensions representing 90-98% final mature size. ||Berry volume at peak shows volumetric peak from cell population volume summation, typical volumes 3-15 mL depending on cultivar, volume determined by cell number × average cell volume relationship, and volume representing genetic size potential achievement. ||Cell number-cell size interaction shows final berry size = cell number × cell size in multiplicative relationship, cultivar variation in both parameters creating size diversity, optimal size requiring both adequate cell number from division and expansion capacity, and interactive effects establishing berry size ranges. ||Berry size genetic potential shows cultivar characteristic size ranges genetically programmed, small-berried cultivars 6-10 mm final diameter from limited cell number and expansion, large-berried 15-22 mm from high cell number and extensive expansion, and genetic control as primary size determinant. ||Size achievement percentage shows typical 90-98% final size at peak, calculation comparing peak size to mature harvest size, high percentage indicating growth phase dominance in size determination, and remaining 2-10% from lag and ripening phases. ||Remaining size increase shows minor continued enlargement during lag phase from residual cell expansion, slight ripening phase increase from sugar and water accumulation, total remaining gain 2-10% adding 0.5-2 mm diameter, and growth phase as major 90-98% size determinant. ||Berry fresh weight at peak shows weight ranges reflecting cultivar and achieved size, typical 9-25 g large-berried, 5-12 g medium-berried, 2-6 g small-berried cultivars, and weight as practical size measure. ||Berry dry matter at peak shows dry matter content 12-18% fresh weight at peak, absolute dry matter 1.2-4.5 g per berry, dry matter from structural components, organic acids, limited sugars, and dry matter representing non-water berry mass. ||Berry composition at peak shows water 80-85% fresh weight, organic acids at peak or beginning decline 1.2-1.6%, sugars still low 6-10%, pH 2.8-3.0, and hard acidic green berry composition. ||Berry morphology at peak shows berry at maximum green phase size, smooth surface maintained, spherical to ovoid shape depending on cultivar, firm texture from turgor and cell walls, and mature green appearance. ||Berry appearance shows green chlorophyll color persisting, hard texture from acids and turgor, smooth skin, and overall unripe green berry morphology. ||Cluster architecture at peak shows berries tightly packed within clusters, bunch closure with berries touching neighbors, cluster at maximum compactness, and peak cluster density. ||Environmental effects on berry size peak include water availability during enlargement determining achieved peak size with deficit reducing peak 15-40%, temperature affecting enlargement kinetics and peak timing, and environmental factors operating through cell expansion effects. ||Water deficit cumulative effects show deficit during peak expansion having largest size impact, deficit during maximum enlargement reducing final 5-15%, cumulative deficit effects determining achieved peak size, and water as major environmental size determinant. ||Temperature effects on peak show warm conditions potentially resulting in earlier peak timing, cool conditions extending enlargement delaying peak, and temperature affecting timing more than achieved size within normal ranges. ||Irrigation effects on peak size show supplemental water during growth phase enabling genetic size potential achievement, irrigation particularly beneficial in water-limited regions, and irrigation as key practice for size optimization. ||Berry size variation within clusters shows variation from seed number effects with 1-3 seed berries showing size ranges, microenvironment variation affecting individual berry sizes, and within-cluster coefficient of variation typically 15-30%. ||Berry size predictability shows peak size strongly predicting final harvest size, correlation r² 0.85-0.95 between peak and harvest dimensions, peak size enabling yield estimation, and high predictability from growth phase size dominance. ||Berry size peak timing shows typical achievement weeks 6-8 post-fertilization, cultivar variation in timing with early cultivars peaking earlier, timing relatively consistent within cultivars, and peak marking transition to lag phase. ||Berry size measurement shows diameter measurement with calipers, fresh weight measurement with balance, volume measurement through displacement, and size quantification enabling growth analysis. ||The process represents second aspect of maximum berry enlargement emphasizing berry-level size culmination, following cell size maximum and preceding expansion rate decline. ||Duration represents peak size achievement weeks 6-8. ||Regional timing shows berry size peak during early-mid August across climates as growth phase concludes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing near-final berry size determining yield, enabling early yield prediction from peak dimensions, demonstrating genetic size potential achievement, and establishing berry size affecting quality through concentration or dilution effects. ||Research applications include analyzing berry size determinants and genetic controls, investigating cell number-expansion interactions, evaluating environmental effects on size achievement, quantifying size predictability and variation, and assessing berry size peak as yield and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 450-453 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Expansion_Rate_Decline": {
  "definition": "An Expansion_Rate_Decline is a Maximum_Berry_Enlargement marked by reduction of berry fresh weight gain from 100–250 mg per day to 30–80 mg per day through reduced wall yielding and osmotic plateau, extending over weeks 6–8 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "growth deceleration | rate reduction | expansion slowdown | declining growth velocity |+ Expansionsraten-Abnahme | Wachstums-Dezeleration | Ratenreduktion | Expansions-Verlangsamung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows expansion rate decline during early-mid August Year N+1 at BBCH 77-79, with berry growth rate declining from peak 128 mg per day to 84 mg per day early decline to 38 mg per day late decline representing 70% total reduction, wall yield threshold increasing from 0.48 to 0.74 MPa, osmotic potential plateau at -1.3 MPa, expansin expression downregulated 65%, under cool maritime conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar transitioning to lag phase",
  "editor_note": "Expansion_Rate_Decline is third and final aspect of Maximum_Berry_Enlargement, distinguished by progressive growth deceleration. ||Represents 70-85% total rate reduction from peak 100-250 to 30-80 mg/day. ||Mechanisms: reduced wall plasticity (yield threshold 0.4-0.6 → 0.6-0.9 MPa), osmotic plateau (-1.2 to -1.6 MPa), size constraints. ||Expansin downregulation. ||Duration 1-2 weeks. ||Follows Cell_Size_Maximum and Berry_Size_Peak. ||Completes Maximum_Berry_Enlargement. ||Marks transition to Enlargement_Phase_Completion and lag phase. || This deceleration phase occurs during late summer in early-mid August in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-2 weeks representing rate decline period, corresponding to BBCH 77-79 bunch closure stages. ||Rate decline mechanism involves reduced wall plasticity limiting turgor-driven expansion, osmotic potential plateau reducing water uptake driving force, cells approaching genetic size limits constraining further growth, developmental programming directing growth cessation, and integrated factors producing progressive rate deceleration. ||Growth rate quantification shows decline from peak 100-250 mg per day to 60-120 mg per day early decline to 30-80 mg per day late decline, progressive rate reduction over 1-2 weeks, eventual very low rate <20-30 mg per day entering lag phase, and rate trajectory characteristic of growth cessation. ||Rate decline kinetics show approximately 40-60% rate reduction from peak to early decline, additional 30-50% reduction from early to late decline, cumulative 70-85% total rate reduction during decline phase, and substantial deceleration marking growth phase end. ||Wall plasticity reduction shows wall extensibility declining as structural modifications accumulate, reduced expansin expression and activity limiting wall loosening, increased wall cross-linking strengthening structure, yield threshold increasing from 0.4-0.6 MPa to 0.6-0.9 MPa, and wall properties shifted toward growth-restrictive state. ||Expansin downregulation shows gene expression declining during rate decline, protein levels decreasing in expanding tissues, enzyme activity reduction limiting wall modification, and expansin decline as growth cessation mechanism. ||Wall cross-linking increase shows enhanced pectin cross-linking through calcium-mediated interactions, increased hemicellulose-cellulose associations, structural modifications strengthening walls, and cross-linking limiting wall yielding under turgor. ||Osmotic potential plateau shows osmotic potential approaching steady state at -1.2 to -1.6 MPa, minimal further solute accumulation, organic acids at peak or beginning decline 1.2-1.6%, potassium approaching maximum 80-140 mM, and plateau limiting additional water uptake driving force. ||Solute accumulation deceleration shows organic acid synthesis slowing or reversing, malate and tartrate at peak levels with minimal additional accumulation, potassium import approaching maximum, sugar accumulation still limited 6-10%, and overall solute dynamics approaching equilibrium. ||Water uptake reduction shows water influx declining from peak 1.5-2.5 g per day to 0.8-1.5 g per day during decline, reduced uptake from osmotic plateau and reduced expansion, water import still significant but decreasing, and uptake decline contributing to rate reduction. ||Turgor maintenance shows pressure sustained 0.6-1.0 MPa during decline, turgor maintaining adequate levels, but expansion minimal from wall constraints, turgor-expansion coupling reduced with high pressure producing minimal growth, and pressure alone insufficient for expansion without wall yielding. ||Cell size constraints show cells approaching genetic and physical size limits, further volume increase increasingly difficult, possible mechanosensing signaling size achievement, and intrinsic constraints limiting expansion. ||Developmental signals show possible growth cessation signals from developmental programming, transcriptional changes directing metabolic shift from growth to lag phase, hormonal changes possibly affecting growth rate, and integrated developmental control directing decline. ||Berry growth rate decline shows berry fresh weight gain following cell expansion rate decline, berry volumetric increase slowing proportionally, berry diameter increase declining from 1-2 mm per week to 0.3-0.7 mm per week, and berry growth deceleration mirroring cellular rate decline. ||Berry composition during decline shows water content maintained 80-85%, organic acids at peak or slightly declining 1.2-1.6%, sugars beginning accumulation 6-10% still relatively low, pH 2.8-3.0, and composition transitioning toward lag phase characteristics. ||Metabolic changes during decline show respiratory rate beginning decrease from peak levels, metabolic shift from growth-supporting to maintenance metabolism, early metabolic reorganization toward lag phase, and declining metabolism correlating with growth rate. ||Gene expression changes show growth-related genes downregulating, lag phase-associated genes beginning upregulation, transcriptional reprogramming initiating metabolic transition, and expression changes accompanying rate decline. ||Environmental effects on rate decline include temperature affecting decline kinetics with warm conditions potentially accelerating transition, water availability less critical during decline than peak expansion though continued supply beneficial, and environmental factors having reduced impact as genetic programming dominates. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster transition through decline phase, cool conditions extending decline period, and temperature affecting transition timing. ||Water effects show adequate water beneficial for maximizing final size, deficit during decline reducing final 5-10%, and water less limiting than during peak expansion. ||Rate decline assessment shows serial growth measurements quantifying deceleration, growth curve analysis documenting rate trajectory, molecular marker changes showing metabolic transition, and measurements enabling decline characterization. ||The process represents third and final aspect of maximum berry enlargement emphasizing growth deceleration, following cell size maximum and berry size peak. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing progressive rate decline weeks 6-8. ||Regional timing shows expansion rate decline during early-mid August across climates as growth phase concludes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing transition from intensive growth to lag phase, marking growth phase completion, demonstrating developmental control of growth cessation, and establishing rate decline as indicator of approaching lag phase. ||Research applications include analyzing rate decline mechanisms and regulation, investigating wall modification and osmotic plateau effects, evaluating developmental signals directing cessation, quantifying decline kinetics and trajectories, and assessing rate decline as transition to lag phase.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 450-453 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Enlargement_Phase_Completion": {
  "definition": "An Enlargement_Phase_Completion is a Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase characterized by near-zero growth rate and berry achievement of 95–100% final dimensions preceding lag phase entry, extending over weeks 7–10 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "growth phase termination | enlargement conclusion | expansion phase end | pre-lag completion |+ Vergrößerungsphase-Vollendung | Wachstumsphase-Terminierung | Vergrößerungs-Abschluss | Expansionsphase-Ende",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows enlargement phase completion during mid August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 79-81, with final cell expansion adding 3.2% volume completing 98% final size, berry growth rate declining from 48 to 8 mg per day entering lag phase, metabolic transition with respiratory rate declining from 2.2 to 1.6 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, growth genes downregulated, seeds mature with brown hard coats, berry achieving 16.8-19.4 mm diameter and 12.4-18.6 g, under warm climate conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar completing enlargement",
  "editor_note": "Enlargement_Phase_Completion represents growth phase termination within Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. ||Subdivided into Final_Cell_Expansion producing last 2-8% increase, Pre_Lag_Phase_Transition with metabolic reorganization, and Growth_Deceleration to quiescence <10 mg/day. ||Duration 1-2 weeks representing weeks 7-10. ||Berry achieves 95-100% final size. ||Metabolic and transcriptional reprogramming. ||Seed maturation complete. ||Completes Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. ||Enables transition to Lag_Phase. ||Critical developmental checkpoint. || This phase termination period occurs during late summer to early autumn in mid August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 1-2 weeks representing enlargement conclusion, corresponding to BBCH 79-81 majority berries touching to beginning of ripening stages. ||Completion mechanism involves final cell expansion producing last 2-8% size increase, pre-lag metabolic transition with transcriptional reprogramming from growth to lag phase metabolism, growth deceleration to very low rates <10-20 mg per day establishing quiescence, seed maturation completion enabling berry developmental progression, and phase completion enabling transition to lag phase and subsequent veraison. ||Final cell expansion characteristics show continued minimal cell enlargement adding last 2-8% cell volume, cell expansion rate very low completing final dimensions, cells reaching 98-100% final mature size, and final expansion establishing ultimate cell dimensions. ||Cell volume finalization shows cells achieving final mature volumes, typical dimensions 80-200 micrometers representing complete 30-100 fold expansion from post-division size, vacuoles occupying 88-93% final cell volume, and finalized cell architecture persisting through ripening. ||Cell expansion cessation shows expansion rate declining to near-zero, eventual complete growth cessation in most cells though minor expansion possible during ripening, cells in mature expanded state, and cessation marking end of cell enlargement phase. ||Pre-lag phase metabolic transition shows metabolic reorganization preparing lag phase characteristics, respiratory rate declining from growth phase elevated levels toward lag phase lower metabolism, transcriptional reprogramming downregulating growth genes and upregulating lag phase-associated genes, enzyme activities shifting from growth-supporting to maintenance metabolism, and metabolic transition as key completion process. ||Respiratory changes show oxygen consumption declining from peak 2-4 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to declining 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during completion, reduced respiration reflecting declining metabolic activity, transition toward lag phase lower respiration typical 1.0-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, and respiratory decline marking metabolic transition. ||Gene expression reprogramming shows growth-related genes including expansins, cell cycle regulators downregulated to basal levels, lag phase-associated genes including stress response, secondary metabolism genes upregulated, metabolic enzyme gene expression shifting toward maintenance and preparation for ripening, and transcriptional changes establishing lag phase program. ||Protein expression changes show growth-related proteins declining, lag phase-specific proteins accumulating, enzyme complements shifting toward lag metabolism, and protein changes implementing metabolic transition. ||Growth deceleration characteristics show berry fresh weight gain declining to very low rates <10-20 mg per day, eventual near-zero growth establishing lag phase quiescence typical <5 mg per day, growth effectively ceasing entering lag phase, and deceleration marking phase transition. ||Berry growth rate trajectory shows decline from 30-80 mg per day during late maximum enlargement to 10-30 mg per day early completion to <10 mg per day late completion entering lag, progressive deceleration to quiescence, and rate trajectory characteristic of growth cessation. ||Berry size at completion shows berry achieving 95-100% final mature dimensions, typical ranges 6-10 mm small-berried, 10-15 mm medium-berried, 15-23 mm large-berried cultivars at completion, fresh weight 2-6 g small, 5-13 g medium, 10-28 g large cultivars, and completion size strongly predicting harvest size. ||Berry composition at completion shows water content 78-83% fresh weight, organic acids declining from peak 1.0-1.4%, sugars beginning accumulation 8-12%, pH rising slightly 2.9-3.1 from acid decline, and composition transitioning toward lag phase characteristics. ||Organic acid dynamics show peak acids 1.2-1.6% during late enlargement declining to 1.0-1.4% by completion, malate declining through respiration, tartrate relatively stable, and acid decline as metabolic shift indicator. ||Sugar dynamics show sugars increasing from 6-10% during late enlargement to 8-12% by completion, limited sugar accumulation during enlargement phase, beginning sugar import through phloem, and sugar increase initiating during completion. ||Berry morphology at completion shows berry at near-final size, green color persisting though chlorophyll beginning decline, texture softening slightly from peak firmness, and appearance as mature-sized green berry approaching lag phase. ||Berry surface characteristics show smooth skin maintained, cuticle development continuing, epidermis intact, and surface properties at maturity for growth phase. ||Seed maturation during completion shows seeds completing development by completion phase, seed color change from green to brown indicating maturation, seed coat lignification and hardening, embryo and endosperm development complete, and seed maturation prerequisite for berry progression. ||Seed characteristics at completion shows fully developed seeds, brown colored coat, hard texture, viable embryo, and mature seed ready for dispersal if separated. ||Cluster architecture at completion shows berries at maximum compactness, bunch closure complete, cluster at mature pre-ripening configuration, and architecture affecting disease risk and ripening access. ||Environmental effects on completion include temperature affecting completion timing with warm conditions accelerating transition to lag, cool conditions extending completion period, water availability less critical during completion than earlier expansion, and environmental factors having reduced impact as developmental programming dominates completion. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster metabolic transition and earlier lag phase entry, cool conditions delaying completion extending enlargement, and temperature affecting transition timing. ||Completion timing shows typical occurrence weeks 7-10 post-fertilization, cultivar variation in timing with early cultivars completing earlier week 7-8 and late cultivars week 9-10, and timing variation affecting total development duration. ||Completion indicators show growth rate declining to <10 mg per day, berry size at 95-100% final dimensions, metabolic markers showing lag phase characteristics, seed maturation complete with brown hard seeds, and indicators documenting completion. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including final cell expansion producing last volume increase, pre-lag phase transition establishing metabolic reorganization, and growth deceleration to quiescence. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing completion period weeks 7-10. ||Regional timing shows enlargement phase completion during mid August-early September across climates as growth phase ends. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive growth phase termination, marking transition to lag phase and progression toward ripening, establishing final berry size determining yield, and completing berry structural development preparing for ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing completion mechanisms and regulation, investigating metabolic transition and transcriptional reprogramming, evaluating seed maturation as completion prerequisite, quantifying completion timing and indicators, and assessing enlargement completion as determinant of subsequent lag and ripening phases.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 451-455 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Final_Cell_Expansion": {
  "definition": "A Final_Cell_Expansion is an Enlargement_Phase_Completion comprising minimal volume increase of 2–8% in pericarp cells reaching ultimate diameters of 80–200 μm at 98–100% mature dimensions, extending over weeks 7–9 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "terminal cell growth | final cell sizing | ultimate cell expansion | completion expansion |+ finale Zellexpansion | terminales Zellwachstum | finale Zellgröße | Ultimate Zellexpansion",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows final cell expansion during mid-late August Year N+1 at BBCH 79, with cells completing expansion adding final 4.2% volume reaching 100% final dimensions at 90-106 micrometers diameter, vacuoles 91% cell volume, water uptake declining from 0.5 to 0.2 g per berry per day, expansion rate <1.5% per week approaching cessation, under continental conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing cell sizing",
  "editor_note": "Final_Cell_Expansion is first aspect of Enlargement_Phase_Completion, distinguished by terminal cell sizing. ||Represents last 2-8% volume increase reaching 98-100% final dimensions. ||Very low expansion rate declining to near-zero. ||Final cell diameters 80-200 micrometers. ||Vacuole 88-93% volume maximum. ||Wall largely non-yielding (threshold 0.7-1.0 MPa). ||Water uptake <0.3 g/berry/day at completion. ||Duration 1-2 weeks. ||Followed by Pre_Lag_Phase_Transition. ||Establishes permanent cell dimensions (±2% through ripening). || This terminal expansion phase occurs during late summer in mid-late August in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-2 weeks representing final enlargement, corresponding to BBCH 79 majority berries touching stage. ||Final expansion mechanism involves continued minimal water uptake adding last volume increment, vacuole reaching final 88-93% cell volume maximum, sustained minimal turgor enabling limited expansion, reduced wall yielding allowing minimal growth, and eventual expansion cessation establishing final cell dimensions. ||Cell volume increase during final expansion shows typical 2-8% volume gain from late maximum enlargement to completion, small absolute increase adding final micrometers to cell diameter, cumulative 30-100 fold total expansion from post-division cells, and final increase completing expansion program. ||Cell diameter progression shows expansion from 92-96% final size during late maximum enlargement to 98-100% at final expansion completion, typical progression from 75-185 micrometers to final 80-200 micrometers, final diameter establishing permanent cell dimensions, and completion sizes showing cultivar ranges. ||Cell volume finalization shows cells achieving final mature volumes 0.2-4.2 nanoliters depending on size, volumes representing culmination of expansion program, finalized volumes determining cell contribution to berry size, and final volumes unchanging through subsequent development. ||Vacuole final dimensions show central vacuole reaching 88-93% final cell volume maximum, vacuole diameter 70-190 micrometers in large cells, vacuole volume representing major cell volume component, tonoplast membrane area 1500-7000 square micrometers, and vacuole at maximum development. ||Cytoplasm final configuration shows thin peripheral layer 1.5-3 micrometers at completion, cytoplasm volume minimized in fully expanded cells, maintained metabolic function in compressed space, nucleus and organelles in peripheral cytoplasm, and efficient final organization. ||Water uptake during final expansion shows continued minimal water influx completing cell hydration, typical uptake rates 0.3-0.8 g per berry per day during final expansion declining to <0.3 g per day at completion, water adding final volume increment, and minimal uptake reflecting expansion cessation. ||Osmotic potential during final expansion shows values -1.2 to -1.6 MPa maintained near steady state, minimal additional solute accumulation, osmotic gradient approaching equilibrium, and plateau characteristic of expansion cessation. ||Turgor pressure during final expansion shows sustained pressure 0.5-0.9 MPa enabling minimal expansion, turgor maintained but insufficient for substantial growth from wall constraints, pressure-expansion coupling minimal with low yielding, and turgor alone inadequate for expansion without wall plasticity. ||Wall properties during final expansion shows walls largely non-yielding with high yield threshold 0.7-1.0 MPa, minimal wall plasticity limiting expansion, wall thickness 0.12-0.28 micrometers at completion from continued synthesis, wall mechanical properties growth-restrictive, and wall as physical constraint ending expansion. ||Wall composition at completion shows mature wall with extensive cellulose microfibril network, cross-linked hemicellulose and pectin matrix, possible calcium-mediated pectin associations, and mature composition limiting plasticity. ||Expansion rate during final expansion shows very low rate producing minimal volume gain, typical expansion velocity <2% volume per week, declining rate approaching zero, and low rate characteristic of expansion cessation. ||Cell expansion cessation timing shows expansion effectively ceasing by week 8-10, occasional minor expansion possible during lag and ripening adding <2% volume, essential cessation establishing final dimensions, and timing varying slightly by cultivar and environment. ||Final cell dimensions show cultivar-specific size ranges achieved at completion, small-berried cultivar cells 60-105 micrometers final diameter, medium-berried 90-145 micrometers, large-berried 120-200 micrometers, and final sizes determining cell contribution to berry volume. ||Cell size variation shows spatial variation with inner mesocarp cells typically larger than outer, position-dependent sizes reflecting growth gradients, cell type affecting final dimensions with parenchyma largest, and within-berry heterogeneity in final cell sizes. ||Environmental effects on final expansion include water availability during final phase affecting last volume gain though impact modest <5%, temperature affecting completion timing, and environmental factors having minimal impact on final dimensions as genetic programming dominates. ||Water effects show adequate water beneficial for completing final expansion, severe deficit potentially limiting final 2-5%, and water less critical than during peak expansion. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster completion, cool conditions extending final expansion period, and temperature affecting timing rather than achieved final size. ||Final expansion completion indicators show expansion rate declining to near-zero <0.5% volume per week, cell dimensions stable over time, and completion establishing final cell size. ||Cell size permanence shows finalized dimensions unchanging through lag phase and ripening, minor volume changes <2% possible from osmotic fluctuations, and essential stability of achieved dimensions. ||The process represents first aspect of enlargement phase completion establishing final cell dimensions, preceding pre-lag phase transition and growth deceleration. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing terminal expansion weeks 7-9. ||Regional timing shows final cell expansion during mid-late August across climates completing cell sizing. ||Viticultural significance includes establishing final cell dimensions determining cellular contribution to berry size, completing 30-100 fold cell expansion program, demonstrating expansion cessation as developmental endpoint, and determining final cell architecture affecting berry quality. ||Research applications include analyzing final expansion mechanisms and cessation, investigating cell size determination and limits, evaluating environmental effects on final dimensions, quantifying final cell size ranges and determinants, and assessing final expansion as determinant of ultimate berry size.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 451-453 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Pre_Lag_Phase_Transition": {
  "definition": "A Pre_Lag_Phase_Transition is an Enlargement_Phase_Completion comprising transcriptional reprogramming downregulating growth genes and upregulating lag-associated genes with reduction of respiratory rate from growth to lag levels, extending over weeks 7–10 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "metabolic transition | lag phase preparation | growth-to-lag shift | metabolic reorganization |+ Prä-Lag-Phasen-Übergang | metabolische Transition | Lag-Phasen-Vorbereitung | Wachstums-zu-Lag-Wechsel",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows pre-lag phase transition during mid August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 79-81, with growth genes downregulated 75-88%, lag-associated genes upregulated 3-8 fold, respiratory rate declining from 2.4 to 1.7 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, malate declining from 1.3% to 1.1% through respiration, sugars increasing from 9% to 12%, pH rising from 2.9 to 3.0, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar transitioning metabolism",
  "editor_note": "Pre_Lag_Phase_Transition is second aspect of Enlargement_Phase_Completion, distinguished by metabolic reorganization. ||Represents transcriptional reprogramming with growth genes down 70-90%, lag genes up 3-8 fold. ||Respiratory rate declining 2-4 → 1.5-2.5 → 1.0-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Malate respiration, sugar accumulation beginning. ||Secondary metabolism activated. ||Duration 1-2 weeks. ||Follows Final_Cell_Expansion. ||Precedes Growth_Deceleration. ||Prepares lag phase and ripening. ||Critical developmental transition. || This metabolic transition phase occurs during late summer in mid August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-2 weeks as metabolism reorganizes, corresponding to BBCH 79-81 majority berries touching to beginning of ripening stages. ||Transition mechanism involves transcriptional reprogramming with differential gene expression shifting metabolic programs, respiratory metabolism declining toward lag phase lower levels, enzyme activity changes implementing metabolic shift, hormone level changes possibly regulating transition, seed maturation signaling developmental readiness, and integrated metabolic reorganization establishing lag phase characteristics. ||Transcriptional reprogramming shows large-scale gene expression changes during transition, growth-related genes downregulated including expansins, cell cycle regulators, growth-promoting transcription factors declining to basal levels, lag phase-associated genes upregulated including stress response genes, secondary metabolism genes, ripening preparation genes, and coordinated expression changes implementing metabolic transition. ||Growth gene downregulation shows expansin genes reduced 70-90% from peak levels, cell wall modification enzymes declining, auxin response genes downregulated, cell division genes at basal non-functional levels, and growth program effectively silenced. ||Lag phase gene upregulation shows stress response genes including heat shock proteins, antioxidant enzymes increasing, secondary metabolism genes for phenolic biosynthesis upregulated, genes involved in organic acid metabolism and sugar transport beginning increase, and lag-associated expression establishing new program. ||Transcription factor changes shows growth-promoting transcription factors declining, developmental transcription factors directing lag and ripening preparation upregulated, hormone-responsive transcription factors shifting expression, and transcriptional regulatory network reorganization. ||Respiratory metabolism changes show oxygen consumption declining from growth phase 2-4 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to transitional 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ approaching lag phase 1.0-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, respiratory rate reduction reflecting declining metabolic activity, metabolic shift from active biosynthesis to maintenance, and respiratory decline as metabolic transition indicator. ||Respiratory enzyme activities show glycolysis and TCA cycle enzymes declining to lower activity levels, oxidative phosphorylation continuing at reduced rate, ATP production decreasing from growth demands to maintenance levels, and respiratory machinery adjusting to lower metabolism. ||Carbon metabolism changes show reduced biosynthetic activity as growth ceases, carbon partitioning shifting from structural synthesis toward storage and maintenance, beginning sugar accumulation in vacuoles indicating import activation, and metabolic reorganization toward ripening. ||Organic acid metabolism shows malate declining through respiration from peak 1.2-1.6% to lower 1.0-1.4%, malate dehydrogenase and malic enzyme activities affecting acid dynamics, tartrate remaining relatively stable 0.3-0.6%, and acid metabolism as key metabolic change. ||Malate respiration shows malic enzyme converting malate to pyruvate, pyruvate oxidation through TCA cycle, malate decline contributing to berry softening and pH increase, and acid respiration as characteristic metabolic shift. ||Sugar metabolism changes show beginning sugar import through phloem activation, sugar transporter gene expression increasing, sugar accumulation in vacuoles from 8-12% to 10-14%, and sugar metabolism preparing for ripening accumulation. ||Enzyme activity changes show growth-supporting enzymes declining to basal levels, maintenance metabolism enzymes sustained at moderate activity, ripening-associated enzymes beginning expression, and enzyme complement shifting toward lag and ripening programs. ||Cell wall enzyme changes shows expansin activity declining substantially, xyloglucan endotransglucosylase reducing activity, pectin-modifying enzymes beginning changes affecting softening, and wall enzyme activities implementing transition. ||Secondary metabolism changes shows phenolic biosynthesis pathway genes upregulating, flavonoid synthesis enzymes increasing expression, anthocyanin biosynthesis genes activated in red cultivars preparing for color change, and secondary metabolism as key transition feature. ||Hormone level changes shows auxin declining from growth phase levels, possible gibberellin changes affecting metabolism, ethylene possibly beginning increase in some cultivars, abscisic acid remaining low before veraison spike, and hormone dynamics possibly regulating transition. ||Protein expression changes shows growth-related proteins declining through degradation or dilution, lag-associated proteins accumulating from upregulated genes, stress response proteins increasing, and protein complement reflecting metabolic program shift. ||Metabolic flux changes shows reduced flux through growth pathways, maintained flux through maintenance pathways, increasing flux through sugar import and storage, and flux redistribution implementing metabolic transition. ||Seed maturation signaling shows mature seeds possibly signaling developmental progression, seed hormones potentially affecting berry metabolism, seed completion as prerequisite for transition, and seed-berry coordination in developmental progression. ||Berry composition during transition shows water 78-83% maintained, organic acids declining 1.0-1.4%, sugars increasing 10-14%, pH rising 2.9-3.1, and composition shifts toward lag characteristics. ||Berry morphology during transition shows berry at near-final size, green color maintained though chlorophyll beginning decline, texture softening slightly, and appearance approaching lag phase. ||Environmental effects on transition include temperature affecting transition kinetics with warm conditions accelerating metabolic shift, cool conditions extending transition period, and temperature as factor affecting transition timing. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster transcriptional and metabolic changes, cool conditions slowing transition though occurring across temperature ranges, and temperature affecting timing not transition occurrence. ||Transition timing shows typical occurrence weeks 7-10 post-fertilization, cultivar variation with early cultivars transitioning earlier, timing correlating with enlargement completion, and transition establishing lag phase entry. ||Transition duration shows metabolic reorganization proceeding over 1-2 weeks, gradual changes implementing new program, and transition period overlapping with enlargement completion. ||Transition assessment shows gene expression profiling documenting transcriptional changes, metabolite analysis showing compositional shifts, enzyme activity measurements quantifying metabolic changes, and molecular markers indicating transition. ||The process represents second aspect of enlargement phase completion establishing metabolic reorganization, following final cell expansion and preceding growth deceleration. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing metabolic transition period weeks 7-10. ||Regional timing shows pre-lag phase transition during mid August-early September across climates as metabolism reorganizes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical metabolic shift preparing lag phase and ripening, demonstrating developmental progression from growth to quiescence, establishing metabolic foundation for subsequent ripening transformation, and marking major developmental transition. ||Research applications include analyzing transcriptional reprogramming mechanisms, investigating metabolic reorganization and regulation, evaluating environmental effects on transition timing, quantifying metabolic markers and dynamics, and assessing pre-lag transition as determinant of lag and ripening progression.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 453-458 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Growth_Deceleration": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Deceleration is an Enlargement_Phase_Completion characterized by progressive reduction of berry fresh weight gain from 30–80 mg per day to below 5–10 mg per day with attainment of 98–100% mature size, extending over weeks 8–10 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "growth cessation approach | deceleration to quiescence | growth rate decline | final growth reduction |+ Wachstums-Dezeleration | Wachstums-Beendigungs-Annäherung | Dezeleration zur Ruhephase | Wachstumsraten-Abnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows growth deceleration during late August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 79-81, with berry growth rate declining from 38 mg per day early completion to 14 mg per day mid-deceleration to 4 mg per day entering lag phase representing 89% total reduction, water uptake declining from 0.4 to <0.1 g per berry per day, berry achieving 99% final growth phase size at 14.2-16.0 mm diameter and 12.8-17.4 g, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing deceleration",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Deceleration is third and final aspect of Enlargement_Phase_Completion, distinguished by progressive rate reduction to quiescence. ||Represents 85-95% cumulative reduction from peak to lag phase. ||Growth rate: 30-80 → 10-30 → <5 mg/day. ||Water uptake <0.1 g/berry/day. ||Berry 98-100% final growth phase size. ||Composition transitioning: acids declining, sugars 10-14%, pH 3.0-3.2. ||Duration 1-2 weeks. ||Follows Final_Cell_Expansion and Pre_Lag_Phase_Transition. ||Completes Enlargement_Phase_Completion and Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. ||Establishes lag phase entry. || This deceleration culmination phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning 1-2 weeks representing final deceleration, corresponding to BBCH 79-81 majority berries touching to beginning of ripening stages. ||Deceleration mechanism involves progressive growth rate reduction from declining cell expansion, water uptake declining to minimal levels approaching cessation, berry approaching final growth phase dimensions constraining further enlargement, metabolic transition reducing growth-supporting processes, developmental programming directing growth cessation, and integrated factors producing deceleration to quiescence. ||Growth rate progression shows decline from 30-80 mg per day late maximum enlargement to 15-40 mg per day early completion to <10 mg per day late completion entering lag phase, typical lag phase growth <5 mg per day representing essential quiescence, and rate trajectory documenting deceleration to near-zero. ||Growth rate quantification shows approximately 50-70% reduction from early to late completion phase, additional 60-80% reduction entering lag phase from completion levels, cumulative 85-95% total reduction from peak expansion to lag phase, and substantial deceleration establishing quiescence. ||Berry volumetric growth shows volumetric increase declining proportionally to fresh weight gain, berry volume approaching final growth phase dimensions, minimal volume increase <1-2% during deceleration, and effective volumetric cessation establishing size stability. ||Berry diameter dynamics shows diameter increase declining from 0.3-0.7 mm per week during late enlargement to <0.1-0.2 mm per week during deceleration, minimal diameter gain during final deceleration, and diameter stabilization at 98-100% final size. ||Berry fresh weight stabilization shows fresh weight achieving near-final growth phase values, typical ranges 2-6 g small, 5-13 g medium, 10-28 g large cultivars at deceleration completion, weight remaining relatively stable through lag phase with <3-5% change, and weight stability characteristic of quiescence. ||Water uptake decline shows water influx reducing from 0.3-0.8 g per berry per day during final expansion to <0.2 g per day during deceleration to <0.1 g per day entering lag, minimal water import reflecting growth cessation, and water uptake decline as deceleration mechanism. ||Water balance during deceleration shows reduced water import with minimal uptake, possible water loss through transpiration beginning to balance import, net water gain minimal <1-2% during deceleration, and approaching water balance characteristic of lag phase. ||Cell expansion contribution shows minimal cell enlargement <2% volume during deceleration, cell expansion effectively ceased contributing to deceleration, cells at final dimensions with stable size, and cellular quiescence establishing growth cessation. ||Berry composition during deceleration shows water content 78-82% relatively stable, organic acids declining 0.9-1.3%, sugars increasing 10-14%, pH rising 3.0-3.2, and composition transitioning toward lag phase characteristics. ||Organic acid decline shows malate continuing respiration declining from 0.8-1.0% to 0.6-0.9%, tartrate relatively stable 0.3-0.6%, total acids declining contributing to pH increase and softening, and acid dynamics as metabolic indicator. ||Sugar accumulation shows sugars increasing from 10-12% to 12-14% during deceleration, beginning sugar import preparing for ripening accumulation, and sugar increase as early ripening preparation. ||pH increase shows pH rising from 2.9-3.0 to 3.0-3.2 from acid decline, pH increase correlating with acid respiration, and pH shift toward lag phase values. ||Berry texture during deceleration shows slight softening from peak firmness, texture changes from acid decline and cell wall modifications, berry transitioning from hard to firm texture, and softening as deceleration indicator. ||Berry morphology shows berry at final growth phase size, green color maintained or beginning chlorophyll decline, surface smooth, and appearance as mature-sized green berry entering lag. ||Metabolic activity during deceleration shows respiratory rate at transitional low levels 1.2-2.0 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ approaching lag phase 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, metabolic activity declining toward maintenance levels, and metabolism characteristic of approaching quiescence. ||Developmental signals shows developmental programming directing deceleration and quiescence, possible hormonal changes regulating growth cessation, mature seeds signaling developmental readiness for progression, and integrated signals implementing deceleration. ||Environmental effects on deceleration include temperature affecting deceleration kinetics with warm conditions accelerating transition to lag quiescence, cool conditions extending deceleration period, water availability having minimal impact during deceleration as uptake minimal, and environmental factors having reduced influence as developmental programming dominates. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster deceleration and earlier lag phase entry, cool conditions extending deceleration period, and temperature affecting timing of quiescence achievement. ||Deceleration completion shows growth rate declining to <5 mg per day establishing lag phase quiescence, berry dimensions stable at final growth phase size, metabolic and compositional markers indicating lag phase, and completion marking definitive enlargement phase end. ||Lag phase entry shows deceleration culminating in lag phase quiescence, characteristic low growth rate <5 mg per day, berry in quiescent state, and lag phase as distinct developmental period before veraison. ||Deceleration timing shows typical occurrence weeks 8-10 post-fertilization, cultivar variation with early cultivars entering lag earlier week 8-9 and late cultivars week 9-11, and timing determining total growth phase duration. ||Deceleration assessment shows serial growth measurements quantifying rate decline, growth curve analysis documenting deceleration trajectory, compositional analysis showing lag phase characteristics, and measurements enabling deceleration characterization. ||The process represents third and final aspect of enlargement phase completion establishing growth quiescence, following final cell expansion and pre-lag phase transition. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks representing final deceleration weeks 8-10. ||Regional timing shows growth deceleration during late August-early September across climates entering lag phase. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive growth cessation establishing lag phase entry, marking completion of berry size establishment, demonstrating developmental transition to quiescence, and establishing stable berry state before ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing deceleration mechanisms and regulation, investigating growth cessation dynamics, evaluating developmental signals directing quiescence, quantifying deceleration kinetics and lag phase entry, and assessing growth deceleration as determinant of lag phase and subsequent veraison timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 453-458 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase is a Berry_Development characterized by berry fresh weight gain below 5 mg per day with stable dimensions, completing seed maturation, and metabolic reorganization preparing the ripening machinery, extending over 1–4 weeks between growth phase I and ripening phase II.",
  "alternative_term": "growth plateau | lag period | pre-veraison quiescence | development pause |+ Beeren-Wachstums-Lag-Phase | Wachstumsplateau | Lag-Periode | Prä-Veraison-Ruhephase",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows berry growth lag phase during late August-September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with growth rate declining to 2-4 mg per day establishing quiescence, berry dimensions stable at 8.2-8.6 mm diameter and 2.8-3.2 g fresh weight, seeds completing maturation with hard brown coats, sugars increasing slowly from 11% to 14%, acids declining from 1.1% to 0.9%, pH rising from 3.0 to 3.2, lag duration 2.5-3.5 weeks under cool maritime conditions of 18-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting white cultivar before veraison onset",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase represents growth quiescence period between enlargement and veraison. ||Subdivided into Lag_Phase_Initiation with growth decline and metabolic transition onset, and Minimal_Growth_Period with near-zero growth, seed maturation focus, and pre-veraison metabolism. ||Duration 1-4 weeks (cultivar and environment dependent). ||Growth rate <5 mg/day. ||Berry dimensions stable. ||Seed maturation completing. ||Metabolic preparation for ripening. ||Represents plateau in double sigmoid growth pattern. ||Temperature major duration determinant. ||Follows Berry_Cell_Enlargement_Phase. ||Precedes Veraison. || This quiescent transition phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning variable duration 1-4 weeks between enlargement completion and veraison onset, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage representing pre-veraison period. ||Lag phase mechanism involves growth rate decline to minimal levels establishing quiescence, metabolic transition from growth-phase to pre-ripening metabolism, seed maturation completion enabling developmental progression, berry compositional stability with minimal changes, metabolic preparation activating ripening pathway components, and integrated quiescence creating developmental pause before veraison. ||Lag phase initiation shows transition from enlargement completion with growth rate declining from 10-30 mg per day to <5 mg per day, metabolic transition onset shifting gene expression and enzyme activities, compositional changes from late enlargement continued into early lag, and establishment of quiescent state. ||Minimal growth period characteristics show near-zero growth rate typically 1-5 mg fresh weight per day representing essential growth cessation, berry dimensions stable within 1-3% variation, seed development focus with seeds completing maturation, pre-veraison metabolism with subtle metabolic preparations for ripening, and sustained quiescence over 1-4 weeks. ||Growth rate during lag phase shows minimal berry fresh weight gain <5 mg per day typical, occasional slightly negative growth from water loss in some conditions, essentially stable berry mass distinguishing lag from growth and ripening phases, and minimal rate as defining lag characteristic. ||Berry size stability shows dimensions remaining essentially constant during lag phase, diameter variation <1-3% from measurement variability and minor fluctuations, fresh weight stability within 2-5% representing equilibrium, and size constancy contrasting with enlargement growth and ripening expansion. ||Berry composition during lag phase shows water content 78-82% relatively stable, organic acids declining slowly from 0.9-1.3% to 0.8-1.2%, sugars increasing slowly from 10-14% to 12-16%, pH rising gradually from 3.0-3.2 to 3.1-3.3, and overall composition showing slow changes toward ripening. ||Organic acid dynamics show malate continuing slow respiration declining gradually, tartrate relatively stable maintaining concentrations, total acids declining slowly contributing to pH increase, and acid metabolism as continuing process during quiescence. ||Sugar dynamics show sugars increasing slowly from limited phloem import, sugar accumulation rate low 0.5-1.5% per week, gradual sugar increase preparing for ripening acceleration, and limited accumulation characteristic of lag metabolism. ||Water relations during lag phase shows minimal water uptake <0.05-0.1 g per berry per day, possible water loss through transpiration in some conditions, water balance approaching equilibrium, and minimal net water flux characteristic of quiescence. ||Berry morphology during lag phase shows berry at stable size, green color maintained though chlorophyll beginning decline in some cultivars, texture firm though slightly softer than peak firmness, surface smooth, and appearance as mature-sized hard green berry. ||Seed maturation during lag phase shows seeds completing final maturation, seed coat fully lignified and hardened, embryo and endosperm maturation finalizing, seed color dark brown at completion, and seed maturity as lag phase prerequisite for progression. ||Seed developmental state shows seeds approaching or achieving full maturity during lag phase, viable embryos ready for germination if separated, mature seeds signaling developmental readiness for berry ripening, and seed completion as potential veraison trigger. ||Metabolic activity during lag phase shows respiratory rate low 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing maintenance metabolism, metabolic activity sustained at reduced levels, no growth-related biosynthesis, maintenance and preparation metabolism, and low activity characteristic of quiescence. ||Gene expression during lag phase shows growth genes at basal non-functional levels, lag-associated genes expressed including stress response and secondary metabolism genes, ripening genes beginning low-level expression preparing for activation, and expression patterns characteristic of pre-ripening state. ||Metabolic preparation for ripening shows subtle metabolic changes activating ripening pathways, anthocyanin biosynthesis genes beginning expression in red cultivars, sugar transporter genes increasing in preparation for accelerated import, softening enzyme precursors accumulating, and metabolic machinery preparing for veraison transformation. ||Stress response during lag phase shows enhanced stress response gene expression, protective mechanisms against heat and water stress, accumulation of stress-protective compounds, and stress adaptation as lag phase characteristic. ||Secondary metabolism during lag phase shows phenolic biosynthesis continuing, flavonoid accumulation proceeding, tannin synthesis and modification, and secondary metabolism as active process. ||Hormone dynamics during lag phase shows auxin at low levels, gibberellin possibly declining, abscisic acid remaining low before veraison spike, ethylene low in most cultivars, and hormone levels characteristic of quiescent state. ||Environmental effects on lag phase include temperature affecting lag duration with warm conditions shortening lag phase 1-2 weeks and cool conditions extending lag 3-4 weeks, water availability affecting berry hydration and composition, stress possibly triggering earlier veraison, and environmental factors determining lag duration and veraison timing. ||Temperature effects on duration show warm growing degree day accumulation accelerating progression through lag phase, cool conditions extending lag phase delaying veraison, and temperature as major lag duration determinant. ||Water stress effects show moderate deficit possibly accelerating veraison onset shortening lag, severe stress potentially arresting development, and stress as factor affecting progression. ||Lag phase duration variation shows cultivar genetic differences with early-ripening cultivars having shorter lag 1-2 weeks and late-ripening having longer lag 2-4 weeks, environmental conditions affecting duration within genetic ranges, and combined genetic-environmental determination. ||Lag phase significance in double sigmoid pattern shows lag representing growth plateau between phase I enlargement and phase II ripening growth, inflection point in development, and characteristic pattern distinguishing berry development. ||Lag phase completion shows eventual veraison onset with color change in red cultivars or softening in white cultivars, growth rate increasing from lag quiescence, sugar accumulation accelerating, and transition marking lag phase end. ||The process shows two distinguishable phases including lag phase initiation with growth rate decline start and metabolic transition onset, and minimal growth period with near-zero growth rate, seed development focus, and pre-veraison metabolism. ||Duration typically 1-4 weeks varying by cultivar and environment representing quiescent period weeks 8-12 post-fertilization. ||Regional timing shows berry growth lag phase during late August-September across climates between enlargement and veraison. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical transition period between growth and ripening, determining veraison timing affecting harvest date, requiring different management than growth or ripening phases, and establishing metabolic foundation for successful ripening. ||Research applications include analyzing lag phase regulation and duration determinants, investigating metabolic transitions and preparations, evaluating environmental effects on lag duration and veraison timing, quantifying compositional and metabolic dynamics, and assessing lag phase as determinant of ripening progression and harvest timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 453-460 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Lag_Phase_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Lag_Phase_Initiation is a Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase comprising growth rate reduction from 10–30 mg per day to below 5 mg per day and metabolic shift toward quiescent pre-ripening state, extending over several days to one week at lag onset.",
  "alternative_term": "lag onset | quiescence establishment | lag beginning | growth cessation initiation |+ Lag-Phasen-Initiierung | Lag-Beginn | Ruhephase-Etablierung | Wachstums-Beendigungs-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows lag phase initiation during late August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with growth rate declining from 12 mg per day to 3 mg per day over 5-7 days establishing lag quiescence, metabolic transition onset with ripening genes beginning 2-4 fold low-level expression, respiratory rate declining from 1.6 to 1.2 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, berry dimensions stable at 9.8-10.2 mm, under continental conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar entering lag phase",
  "editor_note": "Lag_Phase_Initiation represents quiescence establishment within Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Subdivided into Growth_Rate_Decline_Start with 70-85% reduction to <5 mg/day, and Metabolic_Transition_Onset establishing pre-ripening program. ||Duration days to 1 week. ||Respiratory rate declining to 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Growth genes basal, lag genes sustained, ripening genes beginning very low expression. ||Berry dimensions stable, composition transitioning. ||Precedes Minimal_Growth_Period. ||Marks definitive lag phase entry. || This quiescence onset phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over days to 1 week at lag initiation, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage transition. ||Initiation mechanism involves growth rate decline continuing from enlargement completion deceleration to lag minimal levels, metabolic transition onset with gene expression and enzyme activity shifts establishing pre-ripening program, compositional trajectory from late enlargement continued into lag with acids declining and sugars increasing, hormonal changes possibly regulating transition, and integrated changes establishing quiescent lag state. ||Growth rate decline characteristics show progression from enlargement completion 10-30 mg per day to transitional 5-15 mg per day early initiation to lag phase <5 mg per day by initiation completion, typical 70-85% rate reduction during initiation period, and decline establishing minimal growth defining lag phase. ||Growth rate decline kinetics show progressive deceleration over initiation period, exponential-like decline approaching asymptotic lag rate, eventual stabilization at minimal lag levels, and decline trajectory establishing quiescence. ||Growth cessation approach shows berry growth effectively ceasing during initiation, volumetric increase minimal <1% during initiation, berry entering stable dimensional state, and cessation as lag defining characteristic. ||Metabolic transition onset shows beginning of metabolic reorganization from growth to pre-ripening state, gene expression changes initiating during lag initiation, enzyme activity shifts beginning, and metabolic program transition establishing lag metabolism. ||Gene expression initiation shows growth genes continuing basal expression, lag-associated genes including stress response genes maintaining or increasing expression, early ripening gene expression beginning at very low levels, and expression patterns shifting toward lag and pre-ripening profiles. ||Stress response gene expression shows heat shock proteins, antioxidant enzymes maintained or upregulated, protective gene expression characteristic of lag phase, and stress preparedness as lag feature. ||Ripening gene early expression shows anthocyanin biosynthesis genes beginning very low expression in red cultivars, sugar transporter genes beginning increase, softening enzyme genes starting low-level expression, and early expression preparing for veraison activation. ||Enzyme activity changes show growth-related enzymes at basal levels, maintenance metabolism enzymes sustained, early ripening-associated enzymes beginning accumulation at low levels, and activity patterns characteristic of transition state. ||Respiratory metabolism during initiation shows respiration declining from completion levels 1.2-2.0 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to lag levels 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, metabolic rate reduction reflecting transition to quiescence, low respiration establishing lag metabolism, and respiratory level as metabolic indicator. ||Carbon metabolism during initiation shows minimal biosynthetic activity, carbon primarily for maintenance, limited sugar import and storage, and metabolism characteristic of quiescent state. ||Organic acid metabolism shows continued malate respiration declining acids, malate declining from 0.7-1.0% to 0.6-0.9% during initiation, tartrate stable 0.3-0.6%, and acid dynamics continuing from enlargement. ||Sugar metabolism shows limited sugar accumulation during initiation, sugars increasing from 10-14% to 11-15%, slow accumulation rate 0.5-1.5% per week, and limited import characteristic of lag initiation. ||Berry composition during initiation shows water 78-82% stable, organic acids 0.8-1.2% declining slowly, sugars 11-15% increasing slowly, pH 3.0-3.2 rising gradually, and composition transitioning toward lag characteristics. ||Berry size during initiation shows dimensions remaining stable, diameter 6-23 mm depending on cultivar unchanging, fresh weight 2-28 g stable within 2-5%, and stability establishing lag constancy. ||Water relations during initiation shows water uptake declining from completion 0.1-0.3 g per berry per day to lag minimal <0.05-0.1 g per day, water balance approaching equilibrium, and minimal flux characteristic of quiescence. ||Berry morphology during initiation shows berry at stable mature size, green color maintained or beginning slight decline, texture firm, and appearance as hard green berry entering lag. ||Seed state during initiation shows seeds at advanced maturity or fully mature, seed coat dark brown and hardened, embryo viable, and seeds approaching completion enabling lag phase. ||Hormone dynamics during initiation shows auxin at low levels, possible gibberellin decline, abscisic acid remaining low before eventual veraison spike, and hormones characteristic of transition state. ||Environmental effects on initiation include temperature affecting initiation timing with warm conditions promoting faster transition, water availability affecting berry hydration, and environmental factors influencing transition dynamics. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions accelerating initiation and progression into lag, cool conditions extending initiation period, and temperature affecting transition kinetics. ||Initiation timing shows typical occurrence 1-2 weeks after enlargement completion, overlap with completion deceleration, and timing marking definitive lag phase entry. ||Initiation duration shows transition proceeding over days to 1 week, relatively rapid establishment of lag state, and brief initiation period relative to total lag duration. ||Initiation completion indicators show growth rate stabilized at <5 mg per day, metabolic markers showing lag characteristics, compositional trajectory established, and indicators documenting lag entry. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects including growth rate decline start establishing minimal growth, and metabolic transition onset shifting to pre-ripening program. ||Duration typically days to 1 week representing lag initiation period. ||Regional timing shows lag phase initiation during late August-early September across climates as quiescence begins. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive transition to lag phase quiescence, establishing minimal growth state, beginning metabolic preparation for ripening, and marking lag phase entry affecting subsequent veraison timing. ||Research applications include analyzing initiation mechanisms and regulation, investigating metabolic transition onset, evaluating environmental effects on initiation timing, quantifying growth and metabolic dynamics, and assessing lag initiation as determinant of lag phase characteristics and duration.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 453-458 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Growth_Rate_Decline_Start": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Rate_Decline_Start is a Lag_Phase_Initiation marked by reduction of berry fresh weight gain from 10–30 mg per day toward below 5 mg per day with effective cessation of volumetric growth.",
  "alternative_term": "growth cessation onset | final growth decline | deceleration initiation | quiescence growth start |+ Wachstumsraten-Abnahme-Start | Wachstums-Beendigungs-Beginn | finale Wachstums-Abnahme | Dezeleration-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows growth rate decline start during late August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with berry growth rate declining from 14 mg per day to 4 mg per day over 4-6 days, water uptake reducing from 0.2 to <0.08 g per berry per day, berry dimensions stable at 12.2-12.6 mm diameter and 8.4-9.2 g fresh weight, volumetric growth <0.8% during period, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar initiating lag growth cessation",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Rate_Decline_Start is first aspect of Lag_Phase_Initiation, distinguished by final growth deceleration. ||Represents 70-85% total reduction from 10-30 mg/day to <5 mg/day. ||Water uptake declining to <0.05-0.1 g/berry/day approaching equilibrium. ||Volumetric growth <0.5-1%. ||Cell expansion ceased, walls non-yielding (threshold 0.8-1.2 MPa). ||Berry dimensions stable within 1-2%. ||Duration several days. ||Precedes Metabolic_Transition_Onset. ||Establishes lag minimal growth defining characteristic. || This growth cessation onset phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over several days representing decline initiation, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage early transition. ||Decline start mechanism involves final growth rate reduction continuing from enlargement completion deceleration, cellular processes supporting growth declining to minimal activity, water uptake reducing to near-equilibrium levels, berry approaching stable mass and volume, developmental programming directing final growth cessation, and integrated changes initiating lag minimal growth. ||Growth rate at decline start shows typical rates 10-30 mg fresh weight per day at initiation onset declining during initiation, progressive deceleration toward lag levels, eventual stabilization at <5 mg per day by decline completion, and rate trajectory establishing quiescence. ||Growth rate reduction kinetics show approximately 50-70% reduction during decline start phase from onset to early lag levels, additional reduction to final lag minimal rates, cumulative 70-85% total reduction from late completion to established lag, and substantial deceleration initiating quiescence. ||Berry fresh weight dynamics shows minimal weight gain <10-20 mg total during decline start period, weight stabilization approaching lag equilibrium, eventual stable weight within 2-5% variation characteristic of lag, and weight constancy as lag feature. ||Berry volumetric growth shows volumetric increase declining to minimal levels, volume change <0.5-1% during decline start, effective volumetric cessation establishing dimensional stability, and volume constancy defining lag phase. ||Berry diameter stability shows diameter remaining essentially constant during decline start and lag phase, variation <1-2% from minor fluctuations and measurement variability, stable dimensions characteristic of quiescent state, and diameter constancy contrasting with enlargement growth. ||Water uptake during decline start shows water influx declining from completion minimal 0.1-0.3 g per berry per day to lag very low <0.05-0.1 g per day, water balance approaching equilibrium with uptake approximately balancing transpiration loss, net water flux minimal establishing stable berry hydration, and minimal uptake characteristic of growth cessation. ||Water balance characteristics shows uptake-transpiration balance approaching equilibrium during decline start, possible slight net water loss in some conditions creating minor weight decrease, overall water balance stability, and equilibrium as quiescence feature. ||Cell expansion cessation shows cell enlargement effectively ceased during decline start, cells at final mature dimensions, no volumetric growth at cellular level, and cellular stability establishing berry dimensional constancy. ||Cell volume stability shows cells maintaining 98-100% final dimensions achieved during enlargement, minor volume fluctuations <1-2% from osmotic changes, overall cell size constancy, and stability persisting through lag and into ripening. ||Turgor maintenance shows turgor pressure sustained 0.4-0.8 MPa during decline start and lag, turgor adequate for cell integrity, minimal expansion despite sustained pressure from non-yielding walls, and turgor-stability relationship characteristic of quiescent cells. ||Wall properties during decline start shows walls non-yielding with high yield threshold 0.8-1.2 MPa, wall plasticity minimal preventing expansion, wall mechanical properties growth-restrictive, and walls as physical constraint maintaining dimensional stability. ||Osmotic potential during decline start shows values -1.2 to -1.6 MPa maintained relatively stable, minimal osmotic potential changes from slow compositional shifts, osmotic stability characteristic of quiescence, and potential adequate for turgor maintenance. ||Berry composition during decline start shows water 78-82% stable, organic acids 0.8-1.2% declining slowly, sugars 11-15% increasing slowly, pH 3.0-3.2 rising gradually, and composition showing slow changes characteristic of lag initiation. ||Metabolic activity during decline start shows respiratory rate at transitional low levels 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, metabolic activity declining to lag maintenance levels, minimal biosynthetic activity, and metabolism supporting maintenance not growth. ||Growth-supporting processes decline shows biosynthetic pathways for structural components at minimal activity, protein synthesis reduced to maintenance levels, cell wall synthesis ceased or minimal, and growth processes effectively silenced. ||Environmental effects on decline start include temperature affecting decline kinetics with warm conditions accelerating growth cessation, cool conditions potentially extending decline period, water availability affecting final berry hydration state, and environmental factors influencing transition dynamics. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster decline and earlier lag establishment, cool conditions extending decline period, and temperature affecting growth cessation timing. ||Decline start assessment shows serial growth measurements quantifying rate reduction, volumetric analysis documenting growth cessation, water flux measurements showing uptake decline, and measurements enabling decline characterization. ||The process represents first aspect of lag phase initiation establishing minimal growth, preceding metabolic transition onset. ||Duration typically several days representing decline initiation period. ||Regional timing shows growth rate decline start during late August-early September across climates at lag initiation. ||Viticultural significance includes representing final growth cessation establishing lag quiescence, determining berry dimensional stability, demonstrating developmental control of growth termination, and establishing minimal growth as lag defining characteristic. ||Research applications include analyzing growth cessation mechanisms and regulation, investigating cellular and metabolic bases of quiescence, evaluating water relations during growth termination, quantifying decline kinetics and final growth rates, and assessing growth cessation as determinant of lag phase characteristics.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 455-458 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Metabolic_Transition_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Metabolic_Transition_Onset is a Lag_Phase_Initiation involving gene expression changes establishing lag-associated and early ripening patterns with enzyme activities shifted toward maintenance metabolism and stabilized respiratory rate at lag levels.",
  "alternative_term": "metabolic shift onset | metabolic reorganization start | pre-ripening metabolism initiation | quiescence metabolism onset |+ metabolische Transitions-Beginn | metabolische Umstellung-Start | Prä-Reifungs-Metabolismus-Initiierung | Ruhephase-Metabolismus-Beginn",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows metabolic transition onset during late August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with ripening genes including anthocyanin biosynthesis PAL, CHS, DFR upregulated 3-6 fold, sugar transporter VvHT1 increased 3.2 fold, respiratory rate stabilizing at 1.2 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, stress response genes maintained high expression, malate declining from 0.9% to 0.8%, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-28°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar initiating lag metabolism",
  "editor_note": "Metabolic_Transition_Onset is second aspect of Lag_Phase_Initiation, distinguished by metabolic reorganization. ||Represents gene expression shift: growth genes basal, lag genes sustained, ripening genes 2-10 fold early activation. ||Anthocyanin pathway, sugar transporters, softening enzymes beginning expression. ||Respiratory rate 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Stress response enhanced. ||Secondary metabolism active. ||Duration days to 1 week. ||Follows Growth_Rate_Decline_Start. ||Completes Lag_Phase_Initiation. ||Prepares ripening machinery for veraison. || This metabolic shift onset phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over days to 1 week representing transition initiation, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage early period. ||Transition onset mechanism involves transcriptional changes initiating lag and pre-ripening gene expression patterns, enzyme activity shifts implementing metabolic reorganization, respiratory metabolism declining to lag maintenance levels, hormone level changes possibly regulating transition, and integrated metabolic reprogramming establishing lag metabolism preparing for ripening. ||Gene expression changes at onset shows growth genes at basal non-functional levels maintained from enlargement completion, lag-associated genes including stress response and secondary metabolism genes sustained or increasing expression, ripening genes beginning very low-level expression 2-10 fold above basal representing early activation, and expression patterns characteristic of lag initiation. ||Lag gene expression characteristics shows stress response genes including heat shock proteins HSP70, HSP90, antioxidant enzymes superoxide dismutase, catalase maintained or upregulated, secondary metabolism genes for phenolic and flavonoid biosynthesis expressed, and lag-specific expression supporting quiescent metabolism. ||Stress response gene expression shows enhanced expression of protective genes, accumulation of stress-protective proteins, metabolic adaptation to potential environmental stress during lag, and stress preparedness as lag metabolic feature. ||Secondary metabolism gene expression shows phenylpropanoid pathway genes expressed, flavonoid biosynthesis genes active, stilbene synthase for resveratrol possibly expressed, and secondary metabolism continuing during quiescence. ||Ripening gene early expression shows anthocyanin biosynthesis pathway genes in red cultivars beginning 2-8 fold low-level expression including phenylalanine ammonia lyase PAL, chalcone synthase CHS, dihydroflavonol reductase DFR at initiation levels, sugar transporter genes hexose transporters beginning increase 2-5 fold, cell wall modification genes polygalacturonase, pectin methylesterase starting low expression, and early ripening gene activation preparing for veraison. ||Anthocyanin biosynthesis preparation shows pathway genes beginning transcription at low levels during lag initiation, enzyme proteins accumulating slowly, pathway priming for veraison activation, and preparation as metabolic transition feature. ||Sugar transporter preparation shows hexose transporter genes VvHT1, VvHT2 increasing expression 2-5 fold, transporter proteins beginning accumulation, membrane insertion preparing for import capacity, and transporter preparation enabling veraison sugar accumulation acceleration. ||Cell wall modification preparation shows softening enzyme genes beginning low-level expression, enzyme precursors accumulating, cell wall modification machinery preparing for ripening texture changes, and preparation as transition characteristic. ||Enzyme activity transitions shows growth-related enzymes at basal minimal activity, maintenance metabolism enzymes including basic respiratory, protein turnover, membrane maintenance sustained at moderate levels, early ripening enzymes beginning accumulation at very low activity, and activity patterns shifting toward lag and pre-ripening profiles. ||Respiratory enzyme activities shows glycolysis and TCA cycle enzymes at reduced activity supporting maintenance metabolism, oxidative phosphorylation continuing at low rate, respiratory rate 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ characteristic of lag metabolism, and low respiration as quiescence indicator. ||Carbon metabolism transitions shows minimal biosynthetic flux, carbon for maintenance and slow compositional changes, limited sugar import and vacuole storage, and metabolism characteristic of quiescent pre-ripening state. ||Organic acid metabolism shows continued malate respiration at slow rate, malic enzyme and malate dehydrogenase activities declining, malate declining slowly 0.1-0.3% over lag phase, tartrate metabolism minimal maintaining stable levels, and acid dynamics continuing from enlargement. ||Sugar metabolism shows limited sugar import through phloem at low rate, sugar accumulation slow 0.5-1.5% per week, vacuole hexose transporter activity low, and metabolism preparing for ripening acceleration. ||Protein expression changes shows growth-related proteins at minimal levels, lag-associated stress and secondary metabolism proteins maintained or increasing, early ripening proteins beginning accumulation at low levels, and protein profiles reflecting metabolic transition. ||Hormone dynamics during transition onset shows auxin at low levels characteristic of non-growing state, gibberellin possibly declining or low, abscisic acid remaining low 50-200 ng/g before eventual veraison spike to 500-2000 ng/g, ethylene low in most cultivars, and hormone levels reflecting quiescent transition state. ||Berry composition during transition onset shows water 78-82% stable, organic acids 0.8-1.2% declining slowly, sugars 11-15% increasing slowly, pH 3.0-3.2 rising gradually, and composition transitioning toward lag characteristics. ||Metabolite changes shows slow compositional shifts from continued metabolism, organic acids declining from respiration, sugars increasing from limited import, secondary metabolites including phenolics accumulating slowly, and metabolite dynamics characteristic of lag metabolism. ||Environmental effects on transition onset include temperature affecting transition kinetics with warm conditions accelerating metabolic shifts, cool conditions slowing transition rate, water availability affecting berry metabolism and stress response, and environmental factors influencing transition dynamics. ||Temperature effects show warm conditions promoting faster gene expression changes and enzyme activity transitions, cool conditions extending transition period, and temperature affecting metabolic reprogramming rate. ||Transition onset timing shows occurrence during days to 1 week at lag initiation, overlap with growth rate decline establishing coordinated lag entry, and timing marking metabolic shift to quiescence. ||Transition onset assessment shows gene expression profiling documenting transcriptional changes, enzyme activity assays quantifying metabolic shifts, metabolite analysis showing compositional dynamics, and molecular markers characterizing transition. ||The process represents second aspect of lag phase initiation establishing metabolic reorganization, following growth rate decline start. ||Duration typically days to 1 week representing transition initiation period. ||Regional timing shows metabolic transition onset during late August-early September across climates at lag initiation. ||Viticultural significance includes representing metabolic shift to lag quiescence and pre-ripening preparation, establishing gene expression and enzyme patterns characteristic of lag phase, preparing ripening machinery for veraison activation, and determining metabolic foundation for subsequent ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing transcriptional reprogramming at transition onset, investigating metabolic reorganization mechanisms and regulation, evaluating environmental effects on transition timing and dynamics, quantifying gene expression and enzyme activity changes, and assessing metabolic transition as determinant of lag characteristics and veraison readiness.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 455-460 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Minimal_Growth_Period": {
  "definition": "A Minimal_Growth_Period is a Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase characterized by sustained berry fresh weight gain of 1–5 mg per day with dimensional and compositional stability and continued pre-véraison metabolic preparation, extending over 1–3 weeks.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained quiescence | main lag period | growth plateau phase | pre-veraison quiescence |+ minimale Wachstumsperiode | anhaltende Ruhephase | Haupt-Lag-Periode | Wachstumsplateau-Phase",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows minimal growth period during early-mid September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with berry growth rate sustained at 2-4 mg per day over 2.5-3.5 week period, dimensions stable at 16.2-16.8 mm diameter and 12.8-14.2 g fresh weight, seeds completing maturation with hard dark brown coats, anthocyanin biosynthesis genes progressively increasing 8-14 fold, sugar transporters increasing 5-8 fold, sugars rising from 12% to 15%, under warm climate conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar in sustained lag quiescence",
  "editor_note": "Minimal_Growth_Period represents sustained quiescence within Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Subdivided into Near_Zero_Growth_Rate sustaining 1-5 mg/day, Seed_Development_Focus completing maturation, and Pre_Veraison_Metabolism preparing ripening. ||Duration 1-3 weeks (main lag duration). ||Berry dimensions stable within 1-3%. ||Water balance equilibrium. ||Ripening genes progressively increasing 2-15 fold. ||Seeds reaching full maturity. ||Follows Lag_Phase_Initiation. ||Precedes Veraison. ||Temperature major duration determinant. || This sustained quiescence phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning variable 1-3 weeks depending on cultivar and environment representing main lag duration, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage pre-veraison period. ||Minimal growth characteristics shows growth rate sustained at very low levels 1-5 mg fresh weight per day throughout period, occasional slightly negative growth from water loss in deficit conditions, essentially stable berry mass distinguishing minimal growth from enlargement growth and ripening expansion, and sustained low rate as defining lag characteristic. ||Near-zero growth rate shows typical berry fresh weight gain <3 mg per day representing essential growth cessation, growth effectively arrested at developmental quiescence, contrast with enlargement phase 50-250 mg per day and ripening phase 20-100 mg per day, and minimal rate enabling metabolic focus on preparation rather than growth. ||Berry dimensional stability shows berry diameter remaining constant within 1-3% variation representing measurement and minor fluctuation ranges, fresh weight stability within 2-5% over minimal growth period, volumetric constancy characteristic of quiescent state, and dimensional stability contrasting with dynamic growth and ripening phases. ||Berry size during minimal growth shows dimensions established during enlargement phase maintained, typical ranges 6-10 mm small-berried, 10-15 mm medium-berried, 15-23 mm large-berried cultivars remaining constant, fresh weight 2-6 g small, 5-13 g medium, 10-28 g large maintaining stability, and size constancy as lag defining feature. ||Water relations during minimal growth shows water uptake very low <0.05 g per berry per day, transpiration water loss approximately balancing import, net water flux near-zero establishing hydration equilibrium, water content 78-82% stable over period, and water balance characteristic of quiescence. ||Water balance equilibrium shows uptake-transpiration balance preventing net accumulation or loss, stable berry hydration maintaining composition, equilibrium as quiescent state feature, and balance contrasting with net uptake during growth and ripening. ||Seed development focus shows seeds completing final maturation during minimal growth period, seed coat fully lignified creating hard brown protective layer, embryo achieving full developmental maturity with viable embryonic axis, endosperm completing nutrient storage, and seed maturation as critical lag phase process. ||Seed maturation completion shows seeds reaching full maturity by mid-to-late lag phase, seed color dark brown to black indicating maturation, seed texture hard and dry from lignification and desiccation, germination capacity achieved if seeds separated, and mature seeds as developmental prerequisite for veraison. ||Seed maturity indicators shows seed coat color change from green to brown to dark brown, hardening from lignin deposition, moisture decline from desiccation, and indicators documenting maturation state. ||Seed-berry developmental coordination shows seed maturation possibly signaling berry developmental readiness, seed hormones potentially regulating berry progression, mature seeds enabling veraison triggering, and seed-berry communication coordinating development. ||Pre-veraison metabolic preparations shows continued metabolic changes building ripening capacity during minimal growth, ripening gene expression gradually increasing from low initiation levels, enzyme accumulation preparing for veraison activation, metabolic pathways priming for rapid ripening transformation, and preparation as key minimal growth function. ||Ripening gene expression progression shows anthocyanin biosynthesis genes in red cultivars progressively increasing 5-15 fold over lag from early initiation levels, sugar transporter genes increasing 3-8 fold preparing import capacity, softening enzyme genes gradually increasing 2-6 fold, and progressive expression building ripening machinery. ||Anthocyanin biosynthesis preparation shows continued low-level gene expression, enzyme protein accumulation increasing slowly, pathway components assembling for veraison activation, and preparation enabling rapid color change at veraison in red cultivars. ||Sugar transport preparation shows hexose transporter expression increasing progressively, transporter protein accumulation in plasma membrane and tonoplast, transport capacity building for rapid sugar import during ripening, and preparation as critical pre-ripening function. ||Softening enzyme preparation shows polygalacturonase, pectin methylesterase, expansin genes increasing expression, enzyme precursors accumulating, cell wall modification machinery preparing for softening, and preparation enabling texture transformation at veraison. ||Berry composition during minimal growth shows water 78-82% stable with minor fluctuations, organic acids declining slowly from 0.8-1.2% to 0.7-1.1% over period from continued respiration, sugars increasing slowly from 11-15% to 12-16% from limited phloem import, pH rising gradually from 3.0-3.2 to 3.1-3.3 from acid decline, and composition showing slow progressive changes toward ripening. ||Organic acid dynamics shows malate declining slowly through respiration 0.1-0.2% over minimal growth period, tartrate relatively stable maintaining 0.3-0.6% concentrations, total acids declining creating gradual pH increase and softening contribution, and acid respiration as continuing metabolic process. ||Sugar dynamics shows limited sugar accumulation 0.5-1.5% per week from low-rate phloem import, progressive increase preparing for ripening acceleration, sugar predominantly stored in vacuole, and slow accumulation characteristic of lag metabolism. ||Metabolic activity during minimal growth shows respiratory rate sustained at low levels 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ over minimal growth period, metabolic activity adequate for maintenance and preparation, minimal biosynthetic activity, and sustained low metabolism characteristic of quiescence. ||Berry morphology during minimal growth shows berry maintaining stable appearance, green color or beginning chlorophyll decline depending on cultivar and timing, texture firm though softer than peak growth firmness, surface smooth, and appearance as hard green berry in quiescent state. ||Environmental effects on minimal growth include temperature affecting minimal growth period duration with warm conditions shortening period 1-2 weeks and cool conditions extending period 2-3 weeks, water availability affecting berry hydration and stress response, moderate water deficit possibly accelerating veraison onset shortening lag, and environmental factors determining lag duration. ||Temperature effects on duration shows heat accumulation through lag phase advancing progression toward veraison, growing degree days correlating with lag duration, warm conditions accelerating metabolic preparations and development, cool conditions extending quiescence period, and temperature as major lag duration determinant. ||Water deficit effects shows moderate deficit possibly triggering earlier veraison through stress signaling shortening minimal growth period, severe deficit potentially arresting development extending lag, and water stress as factor affecting progression. ||Minimal growth period duration shows cultivar variation with early-ripening cultivars having shorter minimal growth 1-2 weeks and late-ripening cultivars longer 2-3 weeks, environmental conditions particularly temperature affecting duration within genetic ranges, and combined genetic-environmental control determining lag duration. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including near-zero growth rate sustaining quiescence, seed development focus completing maturation, and pre-veraison metabolism preparing ripening. ||Duration typically 1-3 weeks varying by cultivar and environment representing main lag phase period. ||Regional timing shows minimal growth period during late August-September across climates as sustained quiescence. ||Viticultural significance includes representing main lag phase quiescence enabling metabolic preparation, allowing seed maturation completion prerequisite for ripening, determining veraison timing through lag duration, and establishing berry in stable state before ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing quiescence maintenance and regulation, investigating seed maturation and berry-seed coordination, evaluating pre-veraison metabolic preparations, quantifying environmental effects on lag duration, and assessing minimal growth period as determinant of veraison timing and ripening success.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 456-462 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Near_Zero_Growth_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Near_Zero_Growth_Rate is a Minimal_Growth_Period characterized by sustained berry fresh weight gain of 1–5 mg per day, occasionally slightly negative through water loss, distinguishing lag from growth and ripening phases.",
  "alternative_term": "growth arrest | essential growth cessation | quiescence state | zero growth maintenance |+ Nahe-Null-Wachstumsrate | Wachstums-Arrest | essentielle Wachstums-Beendigung | Ruhezustand",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows near-zero growth rate during late August-September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with berry growth rate sustained at 1-4 mg per day over 2.5 week period showing daily variation including 8 days positive 2-4 mg per day, 6 days zero growth, 3 days slightly negative -1 to 0 mg per day from water loss, overall average 2.1 mg per day, berry dimensions stable at 8.3-8.5 mm diameter and 2.9-3.1 g fresh weight representing 2.8% variation, under cool maritime conditions of 18-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar in lag quiescence",
  "editor_note": "Near_Zero_Growth_Rate is first aspect of Minimal_Growth_Period, distinguished by sustained growth cessation. ||Represents 1-5 mg/day typical, occasional negative from water loss. ||Berry fresh weight stable within 2-5%. ||Volumetric growth <1%. ||Water uptake-transpiration equilibrium. ||Cell expansion ceased. ||Biosynthetic activity minimal. ||Maintenance and preparation metabolism. ||Duration 1-3 weeks. ||Followed by Seed_Development_Focus and Pre_Veraison_Metabolism. ||Defines lag phase growth characteristic. || This growth cessation state occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, sustained over 1-3 weeks representing main lag duration, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage quiescent period. ||Near-zero rate mechanism involves cellular growth processes effectively silenced, minimal water uptake approaching uptake-transpiration equilibrium, berry structural components stable without net accumulation, metabolic activity focused on maintenance and preparation not growth, developmental program maintaining quiescent state, and integrated cessation creating growth arrest. ||Growth rate quantification shows typical berry fresh weight gain 1-5 mg per day over minimal growth period, occasional days with zero or slightly negative growth -1 to 0 mg per day from water loss, average rate 2-3 mg per day characteristic of lag quiescence, and minimal rate contrasting with enlargement 50-250 mg per day and ripening 20-100 mg per day. ||Growth rate temporal pattern shows day-to-day variation in minimal rates from environmental fluctuations, some days positive 3-5 mg per day from water uptake, other days zero or negative from transpiration exceeding import, overall sustained near-zero rate averaging 2-3 mg per day, and temporal dynamics characteristic of equilibrium state. ||Berry fresh weight stability shows weight remaining essentially constant 2-5% total variation over 1-3 week period, minor fluctuations from water balance dynamics, overall stability contrasting with systematic increase during growth and ripening, and constancy as lag defining feature. ||Volumetric growth cessation shows berry volume unchanging <1% over minimal growth period, no net cellular expansion, no tissue accumulation, and volumetric arrest characteristic of quiescence. ||Dimensional stability shows berry diameter constant within 1-3% measurement and fluctuation range, length and width stable, three-dimensional berry shape maintained, and dimensional constancy indicating growth cessation. ||Water flux minimal characteristics shows water uptake very low <0.05 g per berry per day, transpiration water loss approximately 0.03-0.06 g per day depending on environmental conditions, net water flux near-zero -0.02 to +0.02 g per day showing equilibrium, and minimal flux enabling weight stability. ||Water uptake-transpiration balance shows uptake approximately equaling loss over minimal growth period, balance creating stable berry hydration, equilibrium preventing net accumulation or depletion, and balance as quiescence mechanism. ||Water content stability shows berry water content 78-82% maintained over minimal growth period, minor fluctuations 1-3% from daily water balance variation, overall stability characteristic of equilibrium state, and constant hydration maintaining berry composition. ||Cellular processes during near-zero growth shows cell expansion completely ceased, cells at final mature dimensions 80-200 micrometers, no cellular growth at tissue or organism level, and cellular quiescence underlying berry growth arrest. ||Cell division absent shows no cell proliferation during lag phase, cell number fixed from division phase completion, cell populations stable, and absence of division characteristic of differentiated quiescent tissue. ||Biosynthetic activity minimal shows structural biosynthesis ceased, protein synthesis limited to maintenance turnover, minimal lipid and carbohydrate biosynthesis, and biosynthetic quiescence characteristic of non-growing state. ||Metabolic focus on maintenance shows metabolism supporting existing structures not growth, respiratory ATP production for maintenance processes, protein and membrane turnover maintaining cellular integrity, and maintenance metabolism adequate for berry survival without growth. ||Metabolic focus on preparation shows metabolic activity directed toward ripening preparation not growth, ripening enzyme synthesis accumulating capacity, metabolic pathway components assembling, and preparation as active metabolic function during growth quiescence. ||Berry composition near-stability shows water, acids, sugars showing slow progressive changes not rapid accumulation, composition trajectory toward ripening characteristics, changes from metabolism not growth, and near-stability distinguishing lag from dynamic growth and ripening. ||Organic acid slow decline shows malate declining 0.05-0.10% per week from respiration, slow acid loss not requiring growth, decline contributing to pH increase and softening, and slow acid dynamics characteristic of quiescent metabolism. ||Sugar slow accumulation shows sugars increasing 0.3-0.8% per week from limited phloem import, slow accumulation not requiring growth, sugar increase preparing for ripening acceleration, and limited dynamics characteristic of quiescent import. ||Developmental program maintenance shows quiescent state actively maintained by developmental programming, growth suppression signals preventing premature ripening, eventual developmental progression to veraison, and programmed quiescence as regulated developmental state. ||Environmental effects on near-zero growth include temperature affecting water balance through transpiration effects, warm conditions potentially increasing transpiration creating slightly negative growth, cool conditions reducing transpiration enabling slightly positive growth, water availability affecting uptake and balance, and environmental factors influencing growth rate variation around near-zero. ||Temperature effects on balance shows warm conditions increasing transpiration potentially creating negative growth days, cool conditions reducing transpiration enabling positive growth days, and temperature affecting water balance dynamics. ||Water availability effects shows adequate water enabling positive growth days from net uptake, deficit limiting uptake creating neutral or negative growth days, and water as factor affecting day-to-day growth variation. ||Near-zero rate significance shows growth cessation enabling metabolic and developmental resources to focus on seed maturation and ripening preparation, quiescence as functional developmental state not growth failure, and minimal growth as defining lag phase characteristic. ||Near-zero rate assessment shows daily or frequent growth measurements quantifying minimal rates, water flux measurements documenting uptake-transpiration balance, volumetric analysis confirming dimensional stability, and measurements characterizing quiescent state. ||The process represents first aspect of minimal growth period sustaining growth cessation, preceding seed development focus and pre-veraison metabolism. ||Duration sustained over 1-3 weeks representing main lag period. ||Regional timing shows near-zero growth rate during late August-September across climates as sustained quiescence. ||Viticultural significance includes representing lag defining characteristic of growth cessation, enabling metabolic focus on preparation rather than growth, demonstrating developmental regulation of quiescence, and establishing stable berry state before ripening transformation. ||Research applications include analyzing growth cessation mechanisms and maintenance, investigating water balance and growth dynamics, evaluating environmental effects on minimal growth rates, quantifying quiescence characteristics and regulation, and assessing near-zero growth as determinant of lag phase function and duration.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 456-459 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Seed_Development_Focus": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Development_Focus is a Minimal_Growth_Period comprising seed coat lignification, completion of embryo and endosperm maturation establishing germination capacity, and seed desiccation reducing moisture content.",
  "alternative_term": "seed maturation completion | reproductive maturation | seed development completion | seed finalization |+ Samenentwicklungs-Fokus | Samenreifungs-Vollendung | reproduktive Reifung | Samenentwicklungs-Abschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows seed development focus during late August-September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with seeds completing maturation during 2.5 week minimal growth period, seed coat lignification creating hard dark brown protective layer, embryo achieving full developmental maturity with viable embryonic axis, seed moisture declining from 42% to 14%, final mature seeds 4.8-6.2 mm length and 3.2-4.6 mm width weighing 28-42 mg, 1.6-2.2 mature seeds per berry average, under continental conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing seed maturation during lag",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Development_Focus is second aspect of Minimal_Growth_Period, distinguished by seed maturation completion. ||Represents final lignification (hard dark brown coat), embryo maturation (viable germination capacity), desiccation (50-70% to 10-20% moisture). ||Mature seeds 4-7 mm, 20-50 mg. ||Possible hormonal signaling to berry. ||Maturation as potential veraison prerequisite. ||Duration 1-3 weeks during lag. ||Between Near_Zero_Growth_Rate and Pre_Veraison_Metabolism. ||Critical reproductive completion. || This seed maturation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-3 weeks during minimal growth period, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage with seed maturation completing. ||Seed focus mechanism involves seeds completing final developmental processes during berry growth quiescence, developmental resources allocated to reproductive maturation, seed maturation as prerequisite for berry ripening progression, mature seeds possibly producing hormonal or developmental signals enabling veraison, and seed completion as critical lag phase function. ||Seed developmental state during lag shows seeds at advanced maturity at lag phase initiation, completing final maturation during minimal growth period, achieving full developmental maturity by mid-to-late lag phase, and mature seeds ready for dispersal if separated from berry. ||Seed coat maturation shows lignification completing during minimal growth period, lignin deposition creating hard protective layer, seed coat color progression from brown to dark brown to black indicating maturation, coat impermeability increasing preventing water and pathogen entry, and mature coat as seed protection. ||Lignification process shows phenolic compounds polymerizing into lignin, cross-linking creating rigid structure, coat hardening progressively during lag, and lignification as major maturation process. ||Seed coat color changes shows progression from green immature seeds to brown early maturation to dark brown late maturation, color darkening correlating with lignification and maturation degree, final dark brown to black color indicating full maturity, and color as convenient maturation indicator. ||Embryo maturation shows embryonic axis completing development during lag phase, cotyledons filling with storage reserves, embryo achieving developmental capacity for germination, viable embryo in mature seed ready for germination if environmental conditions suitable, and embryo maturation as reproductive completion. ||Embryo developmental completion shows radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons fully formed, meristems established in embryonic axis, developmental program complete awaiting germination activation, and structural maturation achieved. ||Storage reserve accumulation shows cotyledons accumulating proteins, lipids, some carbohydrates as energy reserves, typical seed reserves 30-40% lipids, 25-35% proteins, stored compounds supporting germination and seedling establishment, and reserve accumulation as maturation function. ||Endosperm maturation shows endosperm tissue completing development during lag, nutrient storage in endosperm, possible partial endosperm consumption by developing embryo in some cases, and endosperm contribution to seed maturation and germination capacity. ||Seed desiccation shows progressive moisture loss during maturation, water content declining from 50-70% immature to 10-20% mature seeds, desiccation tolerance developing enabling seed survival, reduced metabolism in desiccated state, and desiccation as maturation characteristic. ||Seed moisture decline shows progressive dehydration during lag phase, water loss through seed coat and funiculus, eventual low moisture stable state, and moisture decline indicating maturation progression. ||Seed texture changes shows softening hard texture progression during maturation, immature seeds soft and pliable, maturing seeds progressively hardening, mature seeds hard and resistant to deformation, and texture as maturation indicator. ||Seed size during lag shows seeds at or approaching final mature dimensions, typical mature seed size 4-7 mm length and 3-5 mm width, seed fresh weight 20-50 mg depending on seed development success, and size established during earlier berry development maintained during lag. ||Seed number per berry shows typical 0-3 mature seeds per berry depending on fertilization success and development, seed number affecting berry development through hormone production during growth but less critical during lag, and variable seed number characteristic of grapevine. ||Seed maturation completion timing shows seeds achieving full maturity by mid-to-late lag phase typically 1-2 weeks into minimal growth period, maturation timing varying with cultivar and environment, and completion enabling berry developmental progression. ||Seed maturity indicators shows hard dark brown to black seed coat, low moisture content 10-20%, germination capacity if tested, and indicators documenting mature state. ||Seed-berry developmental coordination shows seed maturation possibly signaling berry readiness for ripening, hormonal signals from seeds potentially regulating berry development, abscisic acid from seeds possibly contributing to veraison triggering, and coordination ensuring reproductive and dispersal preparation. ||Seed hormone production shows mature seeds possibly producing or reducing hormone levels affecting berry, abscisic acid possibly increasing from maturing seeds, gibberellin possibly declining, and hormonal signals as coordination mechanism. ||Seed maturation as veraison prerequisite shows hypothesis that seed maturation completion enables veraison progression, immature seeds possibly preventing premature ripening, mature seeds permitting developmental progression, and seed maturity as gating factor though evidence partially correlational. ||Seed maturation in seedless berries shows seedless parthenocarpic berries lack seed maturation but still undergo lag and veraison, seed maturation not absolutely required though may influence timing, seedless berry development showing seed-independent progression, and complexity of seed-berry coordination. ||Berry resources during seed focus shows minimal berry growth enabling metabolic resources for seed completion, berry quiescence not requiring growth resources, coordination as resource allocation strategy, and functional interpretation of lag phase. ||Environmental effects on seed maturation include temperature affecting maturation rate with warm conditions promoting faster completion and cool conditions extending maturation period, water availability affecting seed development though less critical than during earlier phases, and environmental factors influencing maturation timing. ||Temperature effects show heat accumulation advancing seed maturation, growing degree days correlating with completion timing, and temperature as maturation rate determinant. ||Seed maturation assessment shows seed coat color observation, hardness testing, moisture content measurement, germination testing, and assessments characterizing maturation state. ||The process represents second aspect of minimal growth period emphasizing seed maturation completion, between near-zero growth rate and pre-veraison metabolism. ||Duration proceeding over 1-3 weeks during minimal growth period. ||Regional timing shows seed development focus during late August-September across climates as seeds mature during lag. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical reproductive maturation completing seed development, possibly gating berry developmental progression to ripening, demonstrating seed-berry developmental coordination, and ensuring reproductive success before fruit ripening and dispersal. ||Research applications include analyzing seed maturation processes and regulation, investigating seed-berry communication and coordination, evaluating seed maturation as veraison prerequisite or correlate, quantifying maturation timing and environmental effects, and assessing seed development focus as functional explanation for lag phase quiescence.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 456-460 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Pre_Veraison_Metabolism": {
  "definition": "A Pre_Veraison_Metabolism is a Minimal_Growth_Period involving 5–20 fold increase in ripening gene expression and accumulation of ripening enzymes preparing pathways for sugar accumulation and color development, extending over 1–3 weeks of the lag phase.",
  "alternative_term": "ripening preparation | veraison readiness | pre-ripening metabolism | metabolic priming |+ Prä-Veraison-Metabolismus | Reifungs-Vorbereitung | Veraison-Bereitschaft | Prä-Reifungs-Metabolismus",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows pre-veraison metabolism during late August-September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with anthocyanin biosynthesis genes PAL increasing 14 fold, CHS 22 fold, DFR 26 fold, UFGT 35 fold over 2.5 week lag phase, sugar transporters VvHT1 increasing 9 fold, VvHT2 8 fold, softening enzymes polygalacturonase 7 fold, pectin methylesterase 6 fold, enzyme activities reaching 15-28% ripening maxima, sugars increasing from 12% to 15%, pH rising from 3.0 to 3.2, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-28°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar preparing for veraison",
  "editor_note": "Pre_Veraison_Metabolism is third and final aspect of Minimal_Growth_Period, distinguished by ripening preparation. ||Represents progressive ripening gene increases: anthocyanin pathway 5-20 fold early to 10-40 fold late lag, sugar transporters 5-15 fold, softening enzymes 3-10 fold. ||Enzyme activities 10-30% eventual maxima. ||Metabolic pathway priming. ||Berry compositional preparation (acids declining, sugars 12-16%, pH 3.1-3.3). ||Duration 1-3 weeks. ||Follows Near_Zero_Growth_Rate and Seed_Development_Focus. ||Completes Minimal_Growth_Period and Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Determines veraison readiness. || This ripening preparation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-3 weeks during minimal growth period, corresponding to BBCH 81 beginning of ripening stage pre-veraison period. ||Pre-veraison mechanism involves progressive ripening gene expression increase building transcriptional capacity, ripening enzyme accumulation preparing functional capacity, metabolic pathway component assembly enabling rapid activation, berry compositional preparation creating appropriate substrate conditions, and integrated preparations positioning berry for veraison transformation. ||Ripening gene expression progression shows anthocyanin biosynthesis genes in red cultivars progressively increasing 5-20 fold over lag phase from early initiation 2-8 fold to late lag 10-40 fold relative to basal, sugar transporter genes increasing 5-15 fold preparing import capacity, softening enzyme genes increasing 3-10 fold accumulating modification capacity, flavor and aroma biosynthesis genes beginning expression, and progressive expression building ripening machinery. ||Anthocyanin biosynthesis gene progression shows phenylalanine ammonia lyase PAL increasing 8-18 fold, chalcone synthase CHS increasing 10-25 fold, dihydroflavonol reductase DFR increasing 12-30 fold, UDP-glucose flavonoid glucosyltransferase UFGT increasing 15-40 fold, and coordinated pathway expression preparing for color development. ||Anthocyanin pathway enzyme accumulation shows enzyme proteins increasing from gene expression, pathway flux capacity building, pathway poised for rapid activation at veraison, and enzyme accumulation as preparation function. ||Sugar transporter gene progression shows hexose transporter VvHT1 increasing 5-12 fold, VvHT2 increasing 4-10 fold, sucrose transporter VvSUC11, VvSUC12 possibly increasing, and transporter expression preparing import capacity. ||Sugar transporter protein accumulation shows transporter proteins inserting in plasma membrane and tonoplast, transport capacity increasing progressively, membrane positioned for rapid sugar import at veraison, and protein accumulation enabling accelerated uptake. ||Cell wall modification gene progression shows polygalacturonase increasing 4-9 fold, pectin methylesterase increasing 3-8 fold, expansin genes increasing 2-6 fold, and softening enzyme expression preparing texture transformation. ||Cell wall enzyme accumulation shows enzyme proteins accumulating from expression, pectin degradation and modification capacity building, enzymes positioned for rapid softening at veraison, and accumulation as preparation process. ||Flavor and aroma gene expression shows terpene synthase genes beginning expression in aromatic cultivars, volatile ester biosynthesis genes increasing, methoxypyrazine genes declining in some cultivars, and flavor biosynthesis preparation. ||Metabolic pathway preparation shows phenylpropanoid pathway components accumulating, glycolysis and sugar metabolism enzymes adjusting for increased flux, organic acid metabolism enzymes shifting toward ripening patterns, and pathway preparations enabling rapid metabolic shifts. ||Secondary metabolism preparation shows flavonoid and stilbene biosynthesis pathways active, phenolic accumulation continuing, pathway capacity building for ripening secondary metabolite synthesis, and secondary metabolism as active pre-veraison process. ||Enzyme activity progression shows ripening-associated enzymes gradually increasing activity from accumulating proteins, activities reaching 10-30% eventual ripening maxima by late lag, enzyme activation preparing for full veraison function, and progressive activity as preparation indicator. ||Berry composition preparation shows composition trajectory toward ripening-favorable conditions, acids declining to 0.7-1.1% creating pH increase, sugars increasing to 12-16% establishing substrate base, pH rising to 3.1-3.3 enabling optimal enzyme activities, and composition changes preparing for ripening. ||Acid decline preparing pH shows organic acids declining from respiration and possibly transport, pH increasing from 3.0-3.2 to 3.1-3.3 over lag phase, pH increase enabling pH-dependent enzyme optimal function during ripening, and pH trajectory as preparation aspect. ||Sugar accumulation preparing substrate shows limited sugar increase during lag providing substrate base, vacuole hexose concentrations increasing preparing for accelerated accumulation, sugar establishing osmotic base for ripening water relations, and sugar dynamics as preparation function. ||Membrane preparation shows plasma membrane and tonoplast modifications preparing for altered transport, transporter protein accumulation, possible membrane lipid composition changes, and membrane preparations enabling ripening flux changes. ||Metabolic readiness state shows berry metabolism poised for rapid transformation at veraison trigger, accumulated enzymes and pathway components ready for activation, metabolic preparations creating low activation energy for transition, and readiness as pre-veraison outcome. ||Veraison triggering preparation shows berry prepared to respond rapidly when veraison signal occurs, possible abscisic acid sensitivity increasing preparing for hormone trigger, developmental competence established enabling transformation, and preparation ensuring rapid veraison progression when initiated. ||Abscisic acid role preparation shows berry possibly increasing ABA sensitivity during lag, ABA receptors potentially upregulating, signal transduction components preparing, and ABA responsiveness as potential trigger mechanism. ||Environmental effects on pre-veraison metabolism include temperature affecting metabolic progression rate with warm conditions accelerating preparation and cool conditions slowing progression, water availability affecting stress response and possibly veraison timing, moderate deficit possibly enhancing preparations, and environmental factors influencing metabolic dynamics. ||Temperature effects show heat accumulation advancing metabolic preparations, growing degree days correlating with ripening gene expression and enzyme accumulation, warm conditions shortening lag through faster preparation, and temperature as major preparation rate determinant. ||Water stress effects show moderate deficit possibly triggering abscisic acid increase advancing preparations, stress potentially accelerating veraison onset through enhanced readiness, and water as factor affecting pre-veraison dynamics. ||Pre-veraison metabolism duration shows progressive preparations over 1-3 week lag phase, preparation intensity increasing toward late lag, eventual veraison onset when preparations complete and trigger occurs, and duration determining veraison readiness. ||Pre-veraison metabolism assessment shows gene expression profiling documenting progressive increases, enzyme activity assays quantifying accumulation, metabolite analysis showing compositional preparations, and molecular markers characterizing pre-veraison state. ||The process represents third and final aspect of minimal growth period emphasizing ripening preparation, following near-zero growth rate and seed development focus. ||Duration proceeding over 1-3 weeks during minimal growth period. ||Regional timing shows pre-veraison metabolism during late August-September across climates preparing for veraison. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical ripening preparation determining transformation capacity, building metabolic machinery enabling rapid veraison progression, positioning berry for developmental transition, and determining ripening success through adequate preparation. ||Research applications include analyzing ripening gene expression regulation and progression, investigating enzyme accumulation and metabolic pathway preparation, evaluating environmental effects on pre-veraison metabolism and veraison timing, quantifying metabolic readiness and preparation dynamics, and assessing pre-veraison metabolism as determinant of veraison timing, progression, and ripening quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 458-465 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Pre_Veraison_Lag": {
  "definition": "A Pre_Veraison_Lag is a Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase characterized by accelerating ripening gene expression and enzyme accumulation with rising abscisic acid levels signaling véraison approach, extending over the final 3–7 days of the lag phase.",
  "alternative_term": "late lag phase | veraison threshold | imminent veraison | transformation approach |+ Prä-Veraison-Lag | späte Lag-Phase | Veraison-Schwelle | bevorstehende Veraison",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows pre-veraison lag during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with ripening genes highly expressed including anthocyanin pathway CHS 68 fold, DFR 82 fold, UFGT 95 fold, sugar transporters VvHT1 24 fold, softening enzymes polygalacturonase 22 fold, enzyme activities 35-48% ripening maxima, abscisic acid increasing from 120 to 380 ng/g over 5 days, earliest berries showing trace softening and faint color, sugars 14%, acids 0.8%, pH 3.2, under oceanic conditions of 20-25°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar approaching veraison",
  "editor_note": "Pre_Veraison_Lag represents late lag phase within Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Subdivided into Veraison_Preparation with intensified gene expression (30-80 fold anthocyanin, 15-30 fold transporters, 10-25 fold softening enzymes) and enzyme accumulation (30-50% maxima), and Metabolic_Reprogramming establishing ripening competence. ||Duration 3-7 days immediately pre-veraison. ||ABA beginning increase 50-200 → 380-800 ng/g. ||Earliest softening and color in some berries. ||Growth rate possibly 5-15 mg/day. ||Precedes Lag_Phase_Termination. ||Transformation threshold. || This late lag transition period occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over final days to 1 week before veraison onset, corresponding to BBCH 81 late beginning of ripening stage immediately pre-veraison. ||Pre-veraison lag mechanism involves veraison preparation intensification with ripening gene expression accelerating to high pre-transformation levels, metabolic reprogramming establishing ripening-competent state, abscisic acid synthesis and accumulation beginning hormone spike, berry compositional and structural preparations finalizing, developmental competence achieving transformation-ready state, and integrated preparations positioning berry at veraison threshold. ||Veraison preparation intensification shows ripening gene expression reaching 30-60 fold increases relative to basal approaching veraison activation levels, enzyme accumulation achieving 30-50% eventual ripening maximum activity, metabolic flux capacity building to support rapid transformation, and preparation reaching critical threshold enabling veraison. ||Ripening gene expression acceleration shows anthocyanin biosynthesis genes in red cultivars reaching 30-80 fold increases with pathway genes highly expressed, sugar transporter genes reaching 15-30 fold increases preparing maximal import capacity, softening enzyme genes reaching 10-25 fold increases enabling rapid texture transformation, and coordinated expression at near-activation levels. ||Anthocyanin pathway expression shows phenylalanine ammonia lyase PAL 25-60 fold, chalcone synthase CHS 35-90 fold, dihydroflavonol reductase DFR 40-100 fold, UDP-glucose flavonoid glucosyltransferase UFGT 50-120 fold relative to basal, and pathway primed for color development. ||Sugar transporter expression shows VvHT1 hexose transporter 15-35 fold, VvHT2 12-28 fold, sucrose transporters possibly increasing, and transporter expression enabling accelerated import. ||Softening enzyme expression shows polygalacturonase 12-30 fold, pectin methylesterase 10-25 fold, expansin 6-18 fold, and softening machinery ready for activation. ||Enzyme activity levels shows ripening-associated enzymes reaching 30-50% eventual maximum activity from accumulated proteins, anthocyanin biosynthesis enzymes with substantial activity though not maximal, sugar transport capacity increased though not peak, softening enzymes with activity enabling initiation, and activity levels at functional pre-veraison state. ||Metabolic reprogramming shows decisive metabolic shift toward ripening program, respiratory patterns changing toward ripening characteristics, carbon flux redirecting toward ripening processes, secondary metabolism intensifying preparing for transformation, and metabolic state establishing ripening competence. ||Respiratory metabolism changes shows possible respiratory rate beginning slight increase from lag 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ toward pre-veraison 1.2-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, metabolic activity increasing supporting preparation, and respiratory shift as metabolic indicator. ||Carbon metabolism shows increased flux toward phenolic and sugar metabolism, organic acid metabolism shifting toward ripening decline patterns, metabolic pathways reorganized for ripening function, and carbon allocation favoring ripening processes. ||Secondary metabolism shows phenolic biosynthesis intensifying, flavonoid accumulation accelerating in preparation for anthocyanin synthesis, possible early anthocyanin synthesis in some red cultivar berries showing earliest color, and secondary metabolism as pre-veraison feature. ||Abscisic acid dynamics shows ABA beginning increase from lag basal 50-200 ng/g toward spike levels, ABA synthesis initiating in berry tissues, hormone accumulation accelerating during pre-veraison lag, eventual ABA spike to 500-2000 ng/g coinciding with or triggering veraison, and ABA as critical veraison signal. ||Abscisic acid synthesis shows ABA biosynthesis genes upregulating during pre-veraison lag, biosynthetic enzymes accumulating, ABA production increasing in berry pericarp and possibly seeds, and synthesis as hormone accumulation mechanism. ||Abscisic acid signaling shows possible ABA receptor expression increasing, signal transduction components activating, berry sensitivity to ABA increasing preparing for response, and signaling preparing veraison trigger mechanism. ||Berry composition during pre-veraison lag shows water 78-82% stable, organic acids 0.7-1.0% declining toward veraison levels, sugars 12-16% preparing for acceleration, pH 3.1-3.3 rising toward veraison range, and composition approaching transformation starting point. ||Organic acid pre-veraison shows malate declining slowly 0.6-0.9%, tartrate stable 0.3-0.6%, total acids approaching veraison onset levels, and acid trajectory toward ripening decline. ||Sugar pre-veraison shows sugars 12-16% establishing base for accelerated accumulation, limited continued accumulation 0.5-1.0% per week, sugar preparing for veraison import increase, and sugar dynamics at pre-acceleration state. ||Berry morphology during pre-veraison shows berry maintaining size stability, possible very earliest softening in some berries, earliest color change in some red cultivar berries showing trace anthocyanin, overall appearance still hard green berry approaching transformation, and morphology at threshold state. ||Earliest softening shows possible initial texture changes in some berries, firmness beginning decline from peak, cell wall modification initiating in earliest berries, and softening as earliest veraison indicator. ||Earliest color in red cultivars shows possible trace anthocyanin accumulation in earliest berries, very faint color change from green, earliest visible transformation indicator, and color as veraison onset marker. ||Berry growth rate during pre-veraison shows possible slight growth rate increase from lag minimal <5 mg per day to 5-15 mg per day in some cases, growth rate still low but possibly increasing, and rate change as possible pre-veraison indicator. ||Environmental effects on pre-veraison lag include temperature affecting progression rate with warm conditions accelerating preparation and shortening pre-veraison period, cool conditions extending pre-veraison lag, water availability affecting stress signaling possibly influencing ABA dynamics, and environmental factors determining veraison timing. ||Temperature effects shows heat accumulation advancing pre-veraison preparations, growing degree days correlating with veraison timing, warm conditions promoting faster progression through pre-veraison lag to veraison onset, and temperature as major timing determinant. ||Water stress effects shows moderate deficit possibly enhancing ABA production accelerating veraison, stress as potential veraison advance mechanism, and water influencing hormone dynamics. ||Pre-veraison lag duration shows typically 3-7 days before veraison onset, variable duration depending on preparation state and environmental conditions, eventual transition to veraison when preparations complete and trigger occurs, and brief period marking imminent transformation. ||Developmental competence shows berry achieving transformation-ready state, accumulated ripening machinery adequate for veraison progression, metabolic preparations complete enabling rapid transformation, and competence as pre-veraison outcome. ||The process shows two distinguishable aspects including veraison preparation intensification with accelerating ripening gene expression and enzyme accumulation, and metabolic reprogramming establishing ripening-competent state. ||Duration typically 3-7 days representing late lag immediately pre-veraison. ||Regional timing shows pre-veraison lag during late August-early September across climates immediately before veraison. ||Viticultural significance includes representing imminent veraison approach with berry at transformation threshold, determining veraison timing through preparation completion, demonstrating ripening readiness state, and enabling rapid veraison progression when triggered. ||Research applications include analyzing veraison preparation completion and readiness, investigating abscisic acid dynamics and veraison triggering, evaluating metabolic competence for transformation, quantifying gene expression and enzyme activity thresholds, and assessing pre-veraison lag as determinant of veraison onset timing and progression.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 460-470 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Veraison_Preparation": {
  "definition": "A Veraison_Preparation is a Pre_Veraison_Lag involving 30–80 fold increase in ripening gene expression and ripening enzyme accumulation to 30–50% of maximum activity establishing transformation readiness during the final days of pre-véraison lag.",
  "alternative_term": "final ripening readiness | transformation preparation | veraison machinery assembly | ripening competence |+ Veraison-Vorbereitung | finale Reifungs-Bereitschaft | Transformations-Vorbereitung | Reifungs-Kompetenz",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows veraison preparation during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with anthocyanin biosynthesis genes maximally expressed CHS 88 fold, DFR 96 fold, UFGT 115 fold, sugar transporters VvHT1 28 fold, VvHT2 24 fold, softening enzymes polygalacturonase 26 fold, pectin methylesterase 22 fold, enzyme activities anthocyanin pathway 38%, sugar transport 42%, softening 32% eventual maxima, berry compositionally optimized at 15% sugars, 0.8% acids, pH 3.2, under warm climate conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar at veraison threshold",
  "editor_note": "Veraison_Preparation is first aspect of Pre_Veraison_Lag, distinguished by final ripening readiness. ||Represents gene expression 30-120 fold maxima (anthocyanin 40-140, transporters 15-38, softening 12-35 fold). ||Enzyme accumulation 30-50% ripening maxima. ||Complete pathway assembly. ||Compositional optimization (acids 0.7-0.9%, pH 3.1-3.3, sugars 13-16%). ||Structural preparation. ||Developmental competence established. ||Duration 3-7 days. ||Precedes Metabolic_Reprogramming. ||Transformation-ready state. || This final preparation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over final 3-7 days before veraison, corresponding to BBCH 81 late pre-veraison period. ||Preparation mechanism involves ripening gene expression reaching activation-ready high levels, enzyme protein accumulation achieving functional threshold concentrations, metabolic pathway component assembly completing, berry compositional optimization for ripening initiation, developmental competence fully established, and integrated preparations creating transformation-ready state. ||Ripening gene expression maxima shows anthocyanin biosynthesis genes in red cultivars reaching 40-120 fold increases representing near-maximal pre-veraison levels, sugar transporter genes 15-35 fold preparing import machinery, softening enzyme genes 12-30 fold enabling texture transformation, volatile biosynthesis genes beginning expression, and comprehensive gene expression establishing ripening program. ||Anthocyanin pathway gene levels shows phenylalanine ammonia lyase PAL 30-70 fold, chalcone synthase CHS 40-100 fold, chalcone isomerase CHI 35-85 fold, flavanone 3-hydroxylase F3H 45-95 fold, dihydroflavonol reductase DFR 50-110 fold, anthocyanidin synthase ANS 45-100 fold, UDP-glucose flavonoid glucosyltransferase UFGT 60-140 fold, and complete pathway highly expressed. ||Anthocyanin pathway readiness shows all biosynthetic steps with high gene expression, enzyme proteins accumulated to functional levels, pathway flux capacity prepared for rapid anthocyanin synthesis, and pathway poised for color development at veraison. ||Sugar transporter gene levels shows hexose transporters VvHT1 18-38 fold, VvHT2 14-32 fold, VvHT3 possibly increasing, VvHT6 tonoplast transporter increasing, sucrose transporters VvSUC11 possibly 8-20 fold, VvSUC12 possibly increasing, and comprehensive transporter expression enabling maximal import. ||Sugar transport capacity shows plasma membrane hexose import capacity increased, tonoplast hexose storage capacity enhanced, phloem unloading efficiency prepared, and transport machinery ready for accelerated sugar accumulation. ||Softening enzyme gene levels shows polygalacturonase PG 15-35 fold, pectin methylesterase PME 12-28 fold, pectate lyase possibly 8-20 fold, β-galactosidase possibly 10-25 fold, expansin genes 8-22 fold, and softening machinery comprehensively expressed. ||Softening enzyme capacity shows pectin-degrading enzymes accumulated, cell wall modification capacity established, enzymes positioned for rapid texture change, and softening machinery ready for veraison activation. ||Flavor and aroma gene expression shows terpene synthase genes in aromatic cultivars beginning expression 5-15 fold, linalool synthase possibly 8-18 fold, volatile ester biosynthesis genes increasing, methoxypyrazine degradation genes possibly upregulating in some cultivars, and flavor machinery beginning assembly. ||Enzyme protein accumulation shows ripening enzymes accumulated to 30-50% eventual ripening maximum concentrations, enzyme activities at functional pre-activation levels, enzymes positioned in appropriate cellular compartments, and protein accumulation enabling rapid function at veraison. ||Enzyme activity thresholds shows anthocyanin biosynthesis enzymes 25-45% maximal activity, sugar transporters 30-50% maximal capacity, softening enzymes 20-40% maximal activity, and activity thresholds enabling veraison progression. ||Metabolic pathway assembly shows phenylpropanoid pathway components complete, sugar metabolism pathway enhanced, organic acid metabolism enzymes positioned for decline, and comprehensive pathway readiness. ||Phenylpropanoid pathway shows pathway from phenylalanine through to anthocyanins fully assembled, intermediate metabolite pools established, cofactor availability adequate, and pathway ready for high flux. ||Sugar metabolism preparation shows glycolysis and sugar storage pathways enhanced, vacuole hexose accumulation capacity increased, osmotic capacity for water uptake prepared, and sugar metabolism ready for ripening. ||Organic acid metabolism shows malate metabolism shifting toward decline, malic enzyme possibly upregulating, malate dehydrogenase patterns changing, and acid metabolism prepared for ripening reduction. ||Berry compositional optimization shows acids declining to 0.7-0.9% optimizing pH for enzyme function, sugars 13-16% providing accumulation base, pH 3.1-3.3 approaching optimal range for ripening enzymes, phenolic precursors accumulated providing substrates, and composition optimized for transformation. ||pH optimization shows pH rising toward 3.2-3.5 range optimal for many ripening enzymes, pH increase enabling enhanced enzyme activities, and pH as critical compositional parameter. ||Substrate availability shows phenolic precursors p-coumaric acid, caffeic acid accumulated, sugar substrates glucose, fructose available, UDP-glucose cofactor available, and substrates ready for biosynthesis. ||Berry structural preparation shows cell wall composition prepared for modification, membrane properties adjusted for altered transport, cellular organization ready for transformation, and structure optimized for ripening. ||Cell wall preparation shows pectin partially de-esterified enabling calcium cross-linking and subsequent degradation, hemicellulose and cellulose providing stable framework, wall poised for softening, and structure ready for modification. ||Membrane preparation shows transporter proteins inserted at high density, membrane lipid composition possibly adjusted, membrane properties enabling high flux, and membranes ready for ripening transport. ||Developmental competence establishment shows berry fully competent for veraison transformation, accumulated machinery sufficient for rapid progression, metabolic state enabling transformation, and competence as preparation outcome. ||Transformation-ready state shows berry poised at veraison threshold, minimal additional preparation required, berry responsive to veraison trigger, and state enabling immediate transformation onset. ||Berry appearance during preparation shows berry still predominantly green, possible trace color in earliest red cultivar berries, texture firm though possibly softening initiated, and appearance at pre-transformation state. ||Environmental effects on preparation include temperature affecting preparation completion rate, warm conditions accelerating final preparations, cool conditions extending preparation period, and temperature determining veraison timing. ||The process represents first aspect of pre-veraison lag emphasizing final ripening readiness, preceding metabolic reprogramming. ||Duration final 3-7 days representing preparation completion. ||Regional timing shows veraison preparation during late August-early September immediately before veraison onset. ||Viticultural significance includes representing final ripening readiness determining transformation capacity, establishing comprehensive ripening machinery enabling successful veraison, demonstrating preparation completion as veraison prerequisite, and determining veraison quality through adequate preparation. ||Research applications include analyzing ripening gene expression thresholds and readiness, investigating enzyme accumulation and activity requirements, evaluating metabolic pathway assembly and capacity, quantifying preparation completion markers, and assessing veraison preparation as determinant of transformation success and ripening quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 460-468 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Metabolic_Reprogramming": {
  "definition": "A Metabolic_Reprogramming is a Pre_Veraison_Lag comprising the decisive shift of berry metabolism from quiescence to ripening-active state with redirected carbon flux, intensified secondary metabolism, and accelerating abscisic acid accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "metabolic transformation | ripening metabolism establishment | metabolic threshold crossing | decisive metabolic shift |+ metabolische Reprogrammierung | metabolische Transformation | Reifungs-Metabolismus-Etablierung | metabolische Schwellen-Überschreitung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows metabolic reprogramming during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81, with respiratory rate increasing from 1.2 to 1.6 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, carbon flux redirecting toward anthocyanin biosynthesis with earliest berries accumulating 0.02-0.04 mg/g anthocyanins showing faint pink color, malate declining accelerating from 0.2 to 0.4% per week, abscisic acid spiking from 140 to 620 ng/g over 4-5 days, ethylene increasing from <0.1 to 0.3 nL/g/h, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar crossing metabolic threshold",
  "editor_note": "Metabolic_Reprogramming is second and final aspect of Pre_Veraison_Lag, distinguished by decisive metabolic shift. ||Represents respiratory rate 1.0-1.5 → 1.2-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Carbon flux redirection to phenylpropanoid pathway. ||Secondary metabolism intensification. ||ABA spike 50-200 → 500-2000 ng/g. ||Possible ethylene increase. ||Earliest anthocyanin 0.01-0.05 mg/g in red cultivars. ||Malate decline accelerating. ||Duration 3-7 days. ||Follows Veraison_Preparation. ||Completes Pre_Veraison_Lag. ||Crosses metabolic threshold enabling veraison. || This metabolic transformation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over final 3-7 days before veraison, corresponding to BBCH 81 late pre-veraison metabolic shift. ||Reprogramming mechanism involves respiratory metabolism increasing toward ripening levels, carbon metabolism redirecting from maintenance to ripening biosynthesis, secondary metabolism activating for phenolic and anthocyanin production, hormone dynamics shifting with abscisic acid spike and possible ethylene increase, gene regulatory networks switching to ripening program, and comprehensive metabolic reorganization establishing ripening state. ||Respiratory metabolism changes shows respiratory rate beginning increase from lag quiescence 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ toward pre-veraison elevated 1.2-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, respiratory increase supporting enhanced metabolic activity, ATP production increasing for biosynthetic demands, and respiratory shift as metabolic reprogramming indicator. ||Respiratory increase mechanisms shows possible increase in mitochondrial enzyme activities, enhanced oxidative phosphorylation, metabolic rate increase supporting ripening preparations, and respiration as energy source for transformation. ||Respiratory substrate utilization shows continued organic acid oxidation particularly malate respiration, possible beginning sugar oxidation as sugars increase, substrate utilization supporting metabolic demands, and respiratory patterns shifting toward ripening. ||Carbon metabolism redirection shows carbon flux dramatically redirecting from minimal lag metabolism toward intensive ripening biosynthesis, phenylpropanoid pathway flux increasing for anthocyanin and phenolic synthesis, sugar metabolism flux increasing preparing for accelerated accumulation, organic acid metabolism shifting toward decline patterns, and comprehensive flux reorganization. ||Phenylpropanoid pathway flux shows carbon flow through shikimate pathway to phenylalanine increasing, phenylalanine ammonia lyase flux increasing producing cinnamic acid derivatives, flux through flavonoid pathway toward anthocyanins intensifying in red cultivars, and pathway flux preparing for color development. ||Anthocyanin biosynthesis flux shows carbon and reducing equivalent allocation to anthocyanin pathway increasing dramatically, earliest anthocyanin accumulation beginning in some red cultivar berries, pathway flux enabling color development at veraison, and biosynthesis as dramatic reprogramming feature. ||Sugar metabolism flux shows increased sugar import through activated transporters, sugar phosphorylation and storage metabolism enhanced, vacuole hexose accumulation machinery activated, and flux preparing for ripening sugar accumulation. ||Organic acid metabolism shifts shows malate catabolism through malic enzyme and oxidation increasing, malate decline accelerating from 0.2-0.4% per week lag to possible 0.3-0.6% per week pre-veraison, tartrate metabolism remaining minimal, and acid metabolism reprogramming toward ripening decline. ||Secondary metabolism intensification shows phenolic biosynthesis dramatically increasing, flavonoid production intensifying, stilbene synthesis possibly increasing in some cultivars, tannin modification possibly beginning, and secondary metabolism as major reprogramming aspect. ||Phenolic biosynthesis shows general phenylpropanoid pathway activity increasing, flavonol synthesis possibly intensifying, flavanol production continuing or increasing, and comprehensive phenolic metabolism activation. ||Tannin modifications shows possible beginning tannin polymerization changes, oxidation possibly initiating, modifications preparing for ripening tannin evolution, and tannin metabolism as ripening preparation. ||Hormone dynamics shifts shows abscisic acid accumulation accelerating dramatically from lag levels 50-200 ng/g toward spike 500-2000 ng/g, ABA synthesis rate increasing substantially in berry tissues, possible ethylene beginning increase in some cultivars from <0.1 to 0.2-0.5 nL/g/h, auxin remaining low, gibberellin low or declining, and hormone reprogramming as critical regulatory shift. ||Abscisic acid spike shows ABA increasing 3-10 fold during pre-veraison lag and early veraison, hormone accumulation in berry pericarp and possibly seeds, ABA as central veraison trigger or correlate, and spike as defining hormonal event. ||Abscisic acid synthesis acceleration shows ABA biosynthesis genes including 9-cis-epoxycarotenoid dioxygenase NCED upregulating substantially, biosynthetic enzyme activities increasing, ABA production rate accelerating, and synthesis as hormone spike mechanism. ||Ethylene possible role shows ethylene possibly beginning increase in some cultivars, ethylene possibly involved in softening regulation, hormone potentially contributing to ripening regulation though role varies by cultivar, and ethylene as secondary hormone signal. ||Gene regulatory network switching shows master transcriptional regulators shifting control, ripening transcription factors activating target genes, regulatory network reorganizing comprehensively, and transcriptional reprogramming implementing metabolic shifts. ||Transcription factor activation shows ripening-associated MYB transcription factors activating anthocyanin pathway genes, sugar-responsive transcription factors activating transporter genes, developmental transcription factors directing ripening program, and transcriptional control as reprogramming mechanism. ||Epigenetic modifications possible shows possible chromatin remodeling enabling ripening gene expression, histone modifications affecting transcriptional accessibility, DNA methylation changes possibly regulating developmental genes, and epigenetic regulation as potential reprogramming mechanism. ||Protein expression changes shows dramatic protein profile shifts during reprogramming, ripening-associated proteins rapidly accumulating, lag-phase proteins declining or stable, and protein changes implementing metabolic transformation. ||Metabolite profile changes shows metabolite composition shifting rapidly, phenolic intermediates accumulating, sugar phosphates increasing, organic acids declining, and metabolite dynamics reflecting flux reorganization. ||Berry composition during reprogramming shows water 78-82% stable, organic acids declining 0.7-0.9% with accelerating decline, sugars 13-16% with possible beginning acceleration, pH rising 3.1-3.3 approaching veraison range, earliest anthocyanin accumulation in some red berries, and composition rapidly shifting. ||Earliest color manifestation shows trace anthocyanin accumulation 0.01-0.05 mg/g in earliest red cultivar berries during late reprogramming, visible as faint color tinge, anthocyanin as earliest transformation marker, and color as metabolic reprogramming outcome. ||Berry morphology during reprogramming shows berry still predominantly green in most berries, earliest berries showing faint color in red cultivars, texture beginning softening in earliest berries, and morphology showing earliest transformation signs. ||Environmental effects on reprogramming include temperature affecting reprogramming rate with warm conditions accelerating metabolic shifts, cool conditions slowing reprogramming, water stress possibly enhancing abscisic acid accumulation accelerating reprogramming, and environmental factors influencing transformation timing. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions promoting faster enzyme activity and metabolic flux changes, cool conditions extending reprogramming period, and temperature as rate determinant. ||Water stress effects shows moderate deficit enhancing ABA production possibly accelerating reprogramming and veraison, stress as potential transformation advance mechanism, and water influencing hormonal regulation. ||The process represents second and final aspect of pre-veraison lag establishing ripening metabolism, following veraison preparation. ||Duration final 3-7 days representing metabolic transformation. ||Regional timing shows metabolic reprogramming during late August-early September immediately before veraison onset. ||Viticultural significance includes representing decisive metabolic shift to ripening state, demonstrating abscisic acid dynamics as veraison trigger or correlate, establishing ripening metabolism enabling transformation, and determining veraison onset through metabolic threshold crossing. ||Research applications include analyzing metabolic flux changes and reorganization, investigating abscisic acid and hormonal regulation of transformation, evaluating gene regulatory networks and transcriptional reprogramming, quantifying metabolic thresholds for veraison onset, and assessing metabolic reprogramming as determinant of veraison timing and ripening progression.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 465-475 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Lag_Phase_Termination": {
  "definition": "A Lag_Phase_Termination is a Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase marked by visible transformation onset with softening initiation, abscisic acid peak, and exit from lag quiescence, extending over the final 1–3 days of the lag phase.",
  "alternative_term": "lag phase end | veraison onset | lag-veraison transition | quiescence termination |+ Lag-Phasen-Terminierung | Lag-Phasen-Ende | Veraison-Beginn | Lag-Veraison-Übergang",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows lag phase termination during early-mid September Year N+1 at BBCH 81-83, with earliest berries showing pink color from 0.08-0.15 mg/g anthocyanin accumulation at stylar end, firmness declining from 3.2 to 2.5 N representing 22% softening, growth rate increasing from 3 to 12 mg per day, water uptake increasing from 0.08 to 0.35 g per berry per day, abscisic acid peaking at 1240 ng/g, veraison beginning with 15-20% berries showing transformation signs, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar exiting lag phase",
  "editor_note": "Lag_Phase_Termination represents lag conclusion within Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Subdivided into Veraison_Approach with transformation imminent, Softening_Initiation with 10-25% firmness decline, and Lag_Phase_Exit entering ripening. ||Duration 1-3 days lag-veraison transition. ||Color 0.05-0.2 mg/g anthocyanin in red cultivars. ||Growth rate possibly 5-20 mg/day. ||ABA peak 500-2000 ng/g. ||Water uptake 0.2-0.5 g/berry/day. ||Completes Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Marks veraison onset. || This lag conclusion transition period occurs during late summer to early autumn in early-mid September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-3 days representing lag-veraison transition, corresponding to BBCH 81-83 transition from beginning of ripening to berries beginning to develop color or soften. ||Termination mechanism involves veraison approach with transformation becoming imminent or initiated, softening initiation with first measurable firmness decline, possible growth rate increase from water uptake acceleration, abscisic acid peak levels triggering or correlating with transformation, lag phase exit with berry entering ripening state, and integrated changes marking definitive lag phase end. ||Veraison approach characteristics shows veraison onset imminent within 0-3 days, earliest berries possibly showing initial color in red cultivars or clear softening in white cultivars, berry at transformation threshold or beginning transformation, and approach marking lag termination. ||Earliest transformation signs shows trace to detectable color development in red cultivars with anthocyanin accumulation 0.05-0.2 mg/g creating visible pink to light red tinge, measurable softening with firmness declining 10-25% from peak, possible berry volume increase from water uptake, and transformation signs as termination indicators. ||Color development in red cultivars shows anthocyanin synthesis accelerating in earliest berries, visible color change from green to pink or light red in berry sectors typically stylar end first, color as defining veraison onset marker in red cultivars, and color development marking transformation beginning. ||Anthocyanin accumulation dynamics shows rapid anthocyanin synthesis initiation with accumulation rate 0.05-0.15 mg/g per day during early veraison, pathway flux high from accumulated enzyme capacity, anthocyanin synthesis as dramatic metabolic shift, and accumulation creating visible transformation. ||Softening initiation shows first detectable texture change with berry firmness beginning decline, firmness reduction 10-25% from pre-veraison peak during termination period, cell wall modification initiating through pectin degradation and depolymerization, and softening as universal veraison marker across cultivars. ||Firmness decline mechanisms shows polygalacturonase activity increasing degrading pectin, pectin methylesterase modifying pectin structure, pectin depolymerization reducing cell wall integrity and firmness, calcium release from pectin affecting structure, and enzymatic modification as softening mechanism. ||Cell wall pectin changes shows methylesterified pectin declining from esterase activity, demethylated pectin increasing, calcium cross-links possibly forming then breaking, pectin molecular weight declining from depolymerization, and pectin changes creating softening. ||Berry texture measurement shows penetrometer firmness declining from 2.5-4.5 N pre-veraison to 2.0-3.5 N early termination, compression resistance decreasing, texture subjectively softer, and firmness as quantitative softening indicator. ||Growth rate possible increase shows berry fresh weight gain possibly increasing from lag minimal 1-5 mg per day to 5-20 mg per day during termination from water uptake acceleration, growth rate increase marking lag exit in some berries, volumetric increase from water influx, and growth as possible termination indicator. ||Water uptake acceleration shows water influx increasing from lag equilibrium <0.1 g per berry per day to 0.2-0.5 g per day during termination, increased uptake from osmotic gradient from sugar accumulation, water driving berry expansion during early veraison, and uptake increase as mechanism for growth rate increase. ||Sugar accumulation possible acceleration shows sugar import possibly beginning increase from lag 0.5-1.5% per week to early veraison 1.0-2.5% per week, sugar accumulation creating osmotic gradient, phloem import increasing from activated transporter capacity, and sugar dynamics shifting toward ripening. ||Abscisic acid spike peak shows ABA reaching maximum levels 500-2000 ng/g during lag termination and early veraison, ABA peak coinciding with or slightly preceding veraison onset, hormone spike as critical signal, and ABA as veraison trigger or correlate. ||Abscisic acid peak timing shows ABA reaching maxima during 1-3 days surrounding veraison onset, peak timing varying slightly by cultivar and berry, hormone coordinating transformation across berry populations, and peak as hormonal event marking transition. ||Abscisic acid effects shows possible ABA triggering gene expression changes activating ripening, ABA possibly regulating softening through cell wall enzyme induction, hormone possibly affecting water relations and sugar transport, and ABA as potential central regulatory signal though mechanisms debated. ||Berry composition during termination shows water 78-82% or beginning increase, organic acids 0.7-0.9% declining with possible acceleration, sugars 13-17% with possible accumulation acceleration, pH 3.1-3.4 rising toward ripening range, and composition rapidly changing. ||Berry appearance during termination shows earliest berries showing clear color in red cultivars, white cultivars showing softening and possible yellowing, overall cluster showing asynchronous transformation with earliest berries entering veraison, and appearance showing transformation onset. ||Cluster asynchrony shows veraison beginning in earliest berries while later berries remain in lag, typical veraison spread over 5-14 days across cluster, asynchrony creating heterogeneous berry populations, and asynchrony as characteristic veraison pattern. ||Lag phase exit shows definitive transition from lag quiescence to ripening activity, growth rate increasing from minimal to low-moderate, metabolic activity increasing substantially, ripening processes fully activated, and exit marking lag phase end. ||Ripening phase entry shows berry entering ripening state with active sugar accumulation, color development in red cultivars, progressive softening, and ripening as post-lag developmental phase. ||Environmental effects on termination include temperature affecting termination timing with warm conditions accelerating transformation and shortening lag, cool conditions delaying veraison extending lag, water availability affecting transformation dynamics, and environmental factors determining lag duration and veraison onset. ||Temperature effects shows heat accumulation triggering veraison onset when threshold reached, growing degree days strongly correlating with veraison timing, warm conditions promoting earlier termination, and temperature as major lag duration and veraison timing determinant. ||The process shows three distinguishable aspects including veraison approach with transformation imminent, softening initiation with first texture change, and lag phase exit entering ripening. ||Duration typically 1-3 days representing lag-veraison transition period. ||Regional timing shows lag phase termination during early-mid September across climates as veraison begins. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive lag phase end and veraison onset, determining harvest timing through veraison date, demonstrating transformation from quiescence to ripening, and establishing berry ripening progression affecting wine quality. ||Research applications include analyzing veraison triggering mechanisms and regulation, investigating abscisic acid spike and hormonal control, evaluating softening initiation and cell wall modification, quantifying transformation timing and asynchrony, and assessing lag phase termination as determinant of ripening dynamics and harvest timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 468-478 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Veraison_Approach": {
  "definition": "A Veraison_Approach is a Lag_Phase_Termination characterized by imminent transformation within 0–3 days with earliest berries showing initial transformation signs and abscisic acid at peak levels.",
  "alternative_term": "imminent veraison | transformation threshold | veraison onset approach | ripening commencement |+ Veraison-Annäherung | bevorstehende Veraison | Transformations-Schwelle | Veraison-Beginn-Annäherung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows veraison approach during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 81-83, with veraison imminent within 1-2 days, earliest 8-12% berries showing faint pink color from 0.04-0.06 mg/g anthocyanin at stylar end, firmness in earliest berries declining 8-12% from peak, growth rate increasing to 8-14 mg per day in transforming berries, abscisic acid at 880 ng/g approaching peak, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar at transformation threshold",
  "editor_note": "Veraison_Approach is first aspect of Lag_Phase_Termination, distinguished by imminent transformation. ||Represents veraison within 0-3 days. ||Earliest berries showing initial color (0.02-0.08 mg/g anthocyanin) or softening (5-15% decline). ||ABA at or approaching peak 500-2000 ng/g. ||Growth rate possibly 5-15 mg/day. ||Developmental threshold reached. ||Duration 1-2 days. ||Precedes Softening_Initiation. ||Transformation imminent. || This imminent veraison phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in early-mid September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over final 1-2 days before or as veraison begins, corresponding to BBCH 81-83 transition period. ||Approach mechanism involves berry achieving complete veraison readiness, transformation threshold reached or crossed, earliest berries beginning visible transformation, abscisic acid peak levels triggering or correlating with onset, developmental competence fully established, and integrated readiness enabling immediate transformation. ||Transformation imminence shows veraison onset within 0-3 days in earliest berries, berry at or crossing transformation threshold, visible changes imminent or beginning, and imminence as approach defining characteristic. ||Developmental threshold shows berry achieving critical state enabling veraison, accumulated ripening machinery adequate for transformation, metabolic state supporting ripening, hormonal signals triggering or permitting progression, and threshold crossing enabling veraison. ||Earliest transformation signs shows first berries possibly showing initial color in red cultivars with trace anthocyanin 0.02-0.08 mg/g, first measurable softening with 5-15% firmness decline in earliest berries, and earliest signs indicating transformation beginning. ||Color onset in red cultivars shows anthocyanin synthesis initiating in earliest berry sectors, typical color onset at stylar end calyx scar region, color appearing as faint pink tinge, and color as earliest visible transformation marker. ||Anthocyanin synthesis onset shows anthocyanin biosynthesis pathway flux increasing dramatically, earliest accumulation 0.02-0.08 mg/g anthocyanins, synthesis rate beginning acceleration, and anthocyanin as color development mechanism. ||Softening onset shows earliest berries showing initial firmness decline, texture beginning change from hard to yielding, firmness declining 5-15% from pre-veraison maximum in earliest berries, and softening as earliest tactile transformation marker. ||Berry appearance shows earliest berries showing faint color in red cultivars or beginning softening in white cultivars, majority of berries still in late lag state, cluster showing beginning asynchronous transformation, and appearance indicating transformation onset. ||Abscisic acid peak approach shows ABA approaching or at maximum levels 500-2000 ng/g, hormone accumulation reaching plateau, ABA peak coinciding with veraison onset, and hormone as transformation signal. ||Abscisic acid timing shows ABA beginning increase 3-7 days pre-veraison, rapid accumulation during final days, peak levels 1-3 days surrounding veraison onset, and timing as hormonal trigger or correlate. ||Berry growth rate shows possible slight increase from lag minimal <5 mg per day toward 5-15 mg per day in earliest transforming berries, growth increase from beginning water uptake acceleration, and growth as possible approach indicator. ||Berry composition shows sugars 13-17%, acids 0.7-0.9%, pH 3.1-3.4, and composition at transformation starting point. ||Cluster heterogeneity shows earliest berries approaching or entering veraison, middle berries in late lag, latest berries in early-mid lag, and heterogeneity creating asynchronous transformation pattern. ||Veraison asynchrony shows typical veraison spread over 5-14 days across cluster, earliest berries transforming first, progressive transformation wave through cluster, and asynchrony as characteristic pattern. ||Environmental effects on approach include temperature determining approach timing with heat accumulation triggering transformation when threshold reached, water availability affecting transformation dynamics, stress possibly advancing approach through hormonal effects, and environmental factors determining veraison onset date. ||Temperature as trigger shows growing degree days accumulating to cultivar-specific threshold triggering veraison, heat accumulation as primary timing determinant, warm conditions advancing approach, and temperature effect as major viticultural factor. ||The process represents first aspect of lag phase termination emphasizing imminent transformation, preceding softening initiation and lag phase exit. ||Duration final 1-2 days representing imminent veraison. ||Regional timing shows veraison approach during early-mid September as transformation becomes imminent. ||Viticultural significance includes representing imminent veraison onset determining harvest date, demonstrating transformation readiness, enabling veraison prediction from approach signs, and establishing ripening commencement affecting quality and timing. ||Research applications include analyzing transformation thresholds and triggering, investigating abscisic acid dynamics and veraison onset, evaluating environmental effects on transformation timing, quantifying earliest transformation markers, and assessing veraison approach as predictor of onset timing and ripening progression.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 468-475 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Softening_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Softening_Initiation is a Lag_Phase_Termination comprising the first measurable berry firmness decline of 10–25% from pre-véraison maximum through pectin degradation and cell wall modification.",
  "alternative_term": "texture transformation onset | first softening | firmness decline start | cell wall modification initiation |+ Erweichungs-Initiierung | Textur-Transformations-Beginn | erste Erweichung | Festigkeits-Abnahme-Start",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows softening initiation during early-mid September Year N+1 at BBCH 81-83, with berry firmness declining from 2.8 N pre-veraison to 2.2 N representing 21% softening over 2-3 days, polygalacturonase activity increasing from 8 to 28 units, pectin methylesterase increasing from 12 to 35 units, water-soluble pectin increasing from 22% to 38% total pectin, texture perceptibly softer, under cool maritime conditions of 18-24°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting white cultivar showing softening as primary veraison marker",
  "editor_note": "Softening_Initiation is second aspect of Lag_Phase_Termination, distinguished by first texture transformation. ||Represents 10-25% firmness decline from 2.5-4.5 N peak. ||Polygalacturonase and pectin methylesterase activation. ||Pectin depolymerization 100-300 → 20-100 kDa. ||Middle lamella degradation, cell-cell adhesion weakening. ||Universal veraison marker (all cultivars). ||Duration 1-3 days. ||Follows Veraison_Approach. ||Precedes Lag_Phase_Exit. ||Defines veraison in white cultivars. || This texture transformation onset phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in early-mid September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-3 days as softening begins, corresponding to BBCH 81-83 veraison onset period. ||Softening mechanism involves cell wall modification initiation with pectin-degrading enzyme activation, pectin depolymerization reducing cell wall integrity, cell-cell adhesion weakening from middle lamella degradation, turgor possibly declining contributing to softness, and integrated changes creating firmness decline. ||Firmness decline characteristics shows berry firmness beginning measurable reduction, typical decline 10-25% from pre-veraison maximum 2.5-4.5 N to early softening 2.0-3.5 N during termination, progressive firmness decrease continuing through ripening, and firmness decline as defining transformation. ||Firmness measurement shows penetrometer resistance declining, compression force requirement decreasing, subjective texture softer to touch, and firmness as quantitative softening indicator. ||Firmness decline timing shows earliest firmness decline in first transforming berries at veraison onset, progressive softening in subsequently transforming berries, and timing showing asynchronous pattern across cluster. ||Cell wall modification initiation shows pectin-degrading enzymes activating at softening onset, polygalacturonase PG activity increasing substantially, pectin methylesterase PME activity increasing, pectate lyase possibly activating, and enzyme activation as softening mechanism. ||Polygalacturonase activation shows PG enzyme activity increasing from pre-veraison low levels 5-15 units to early softening 15-40 units, PG degrading homogalacturonan backbone of pectin, enzyme activity correlating with firmness decline, and PG as major softening enzyme. ||Pectin methylesterase activation shows PME activity increasing demethylating pectin, PME creating substrate for PG degradation, PME possibly biphasic with initial cross-linking then degradation facilitation, and PME as pectin modification enzyme. ||Pectate lyase possible role shows enzyme possibly contributing to pectin degradation, lyase cleaving pectin chains, contribution varying by cultivar and conditions, and lyase as additional softening enzyme. ||Pectin depolymerization shows pectin molecular weight declining from enzyme degradation, high molecular weight pectin 100-300 kDa declining to lower molecular weight fragments 20-100 kDa, depolymerization reducing cell wall structural integrity, and pectin degradation as softening basis. ||Pectin solubilization shows water-soluble pectin fraction increasing from degradation products, insoluble cell wall pectin fraction declining, solubilization weakening wall structure, and soluble pectin as degradation indicator. ||Middle lamella degradation shows pectin-rich middle lamella between cells degrading, cell-cell adhesion weakening from middle lamella loss, intercellular spaces possibly increasing, and middle lamella as adhesion loss site. ||Cell-cell adhesion weakening shows cells becoming less firmly attached, tissue disaggregation potential increasing, texture becoming more yielding from reduced cohesion, and adhesion loss contributing to softness. ||Calcium dynamics shows calcium possibly released from demethylated pectin as degradation proceeds, calcium cross-links breaking, calcium redistribution affecting cell wall properties, and calcium as structural ion in cell walls. ||Cell wall other modifications shows possible hemicellulose and cellulose modifications though minor compared to pectin, expansin possibly contributing to wall loosening, overall wall structure weakening, and integrated modifications creating softening. ||Turgor possible changes shows turgor pressure possibly declining slightly during early softening from altered water relations, reduced turgor contributing to softer texture, though turgor changes likely minor compared to structural changes, and turgor as potential softening contributor. ||Berry texture changes shows texture transitioning from hard resistant to yielding, berry easier to compress, skin possibly loosening from flesh, and overall texture becoming characteristic of ripening berry. ||Berry appearance shows softening berries often also showing color change in red cultivars, white cultivars showing softening as primary visible change possibly with yellowing, and texture change as transformation indicator. ||Sensory evaluation shows tactile assessment detecting softness, berries beginning to yield to gentle pressure, texture change perceptible to trained evaluators, and sensory evaluation as practical assessment. ||Softening as veraison marker shows softening occurring in all cultivars at veraison, universal transformation marker unlike color which is cultivar-dependent, softening defining veraison in white cultivars, and texture as reliable indicator. ||Softening progression shows continued firmness decline through ripening, eventual soft texture at full ripeness, progression rate varying by cultivar and conditions, and softening as continuing ripening process. ||Environmental effects on softening initiation include temperature affecting enzyme activities and softening rate, warm conditions promoting faster softening, cool conditions slowing softening progression, water availability affecting turgor and texture, and environmental factors influencing softening dynamics. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating enzyme activities and softening rate, cool conditions slowing softening, and temperature as softening rate determinant. ||The process represents second aspect of lag phase termination emphasizing texture transformation, following veraison approach and preceding lag phase exit. ||Duration 1-3 days representing softening onset. ||Regional timing shows softening initiation during early-mid September at veraison onset. ||Viticultural significance includes representing universal veraison marker across cultivars, indicating transformation onset determining harvest timing, affecting berry handling and disease susceptibility, and establishing texture trajectory affecting wine quality. ||Research applications include analyzing cell wall modification mechanisms and enzyme regulation, investigating pectin degradation and depolymerization dynamics, evaluating environmental effects on softening rate, quantifying firmness decline and texture changes, and assessing softening initiation as veraison marker and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 475-482 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Lag_Phase_Exit": {
  "definition": "A Lag_Phase_Exit is a Lag_Phase_Termination marked by berry transition from lag quiescence to ripening with growth rate increasing from below 5 mg per day to 10–30 mg per day and full activation of sugar accumulation and color development.",
  "alternative_term": "quiescence termination | ripening phase entry | lag conclusion | veraison completion |+ Lag-Phasen-Exit | Ruhephase-Terminierung | Reifungs-Phasen-Eintritt | Lag-Abschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows lag phase exit during early-mid September Year N+1 at BBCH 83, with berry growth rate increasing from 3 to 18 mg per day over 2 days, water uptake accelerating from 0.09 to 0.52 g per berry per day, respiratory rate increasing from 1.3 to 1.9 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, sugar accumulation accelerating to 2.2% per week, anthocyanin reaching 0.28 mg/g creating visible red color, firmness declining 24% from peak, berry entering active ripening state, under warm climate conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar exiting lag phase",
  "editor_note": "Lag_Phase_Exit is third and final aspect of Lag_Phase_Termination, distinguished by definitive ripening entry. ||Represents growth rate 1-5 → 10-30 mg/day. ||Water uptake 0.3-0.8 g/berry/day. ||Respiratory rate 1.0-1.5 → 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Sugar accumulation 1.5-3.5%/week. ||Anthocyanin 0.1-0.5 mg/g in red cultivars. ||Firmness decline 15-30% total. ||Duration 1-2 days. ||Follows Veraison_Approach and Softening_Initiation. ||Completes Lag_Phase_Termination and Berry_Growth_Lag_Phase. ||Enters Ripening Phase. || This quiescence exit phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in early-mid September in temperate regions Year N+1, proceeding over 1-2 days representing definitive lag-ripening transition, corresponding to BBCH 83 berries beginning to develop color or soften. ||Exit mechanism involves growth rate increase from water uptake acceleration, metabolic rate elevation supporting ripening biosynthesis, sugar accumulation acceleration from activated phloem import, color development initiation in red cultivars from anthocyanin synthesis, continued softening from cell wall modification, and comprehensive activation establishing ripening state. ||Growth rate increase shows berry fresh weight gain increasing from lag minimal 1-5 mg per day to ripening low-moderate 10-30 mg per day during exit, growth increase marking definitive lag termination, volumetric expansion from water uptake, and growth as lag exit indicator. ||Growth rate dynamics shows progressive increase over 1-2 days, eventual stabilization at ripening growth levels, continued growth through ripening phase, and growth pattern characteristic of phase transition. ||Water uptake acceleration shows water influx increasing from lag equilibrium <0.1 g per berry per day to ripening 0.3-0.8 g per day, osmotic gradient from sugar accumulation driving uptake, increased water enabling berry expansion, and water uptake as growth mechanism. ||Berry volumetric expansion shows berry volume increasing from water accumulation, typical 5-15% volume increase during early veraison over several days, expansion contributing to berry size increase, and volume expansion characteristic of ripening onset. ||Metabolic activity elevation shows respiratory rate increasing from lag 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to ripening 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, metabolic rate increase supporting biosynthetic demands, ATP production increasing for ripening processes, and respiration as metabolic activity indicator. ||Respiratory increase shows enhanced oxidative phosphorylation, increased substrate oxidation particularly sugars and remaining acids, respiratory capacity supporting ripening metabolism, and respiration elevation marking metabolic shift. ||Sugar accumulation acceleration shows sugar import increasing from lag minimal 0.5-1.5% per week to ripening 1.5-3.5% per week during exit, phloem unloading accelerating from activated hexose transporters, vacuole hexose storage increasing, and sugar accumulation as defining ripening process. ||Sugar accumulation rate shows progressive acceleration during exit, typical sugar increase 1-2% over exit days, continued acceleration through early ripening, and accumulation pattern characteristic of ripening onset. ||Phloem unloading activation shows phloem sieve element unloading increasing substantially, hexose transporters VvHT1, VvHT2 at high activity from accumulated protein, symplastic and apoplastic unloading pathways active, and unloading capacity supporting sugar accumulation. ||Vacuole hexose storage shows glucose and fructose accumulation in vacuole, hexose concentrations increasing from 50-80 mM lag to 100-150 mM early exit, tonoplast hexose transporters VvHT6 and others mediating storage, and vacuole storage as sugar accumulation mechanism. ||Color development in red cultivars shows anthocyanin synthesis proceeding rapidly, anthocyanin accumulation 0.1-0.5 mg/g during exit creating visible pink to red color, color intensification continuing through ripening, and color as red cultivar transformation marker. ||Anthocyanin synthesis rate shows rapid synthesis during exit typical 0.05-0.15 mg/g per day, pathway flux high from accumulated enzyme capacity, color appearing and intensifying over exit period, and anthocyanin accumulation as dramatic biosynthetic event. ||Color appearance shows berry color transitioning from green or faint pink to clearly pink or light red, color typically starting at stylar end progressing toward pedicel, visible color change as exit indicator, and color development characteristic of red cultivars. ||Softening continuation shows firmness continuing decline from softening initiation, typical 15-30% total firmness decline from peak by exit completion, progressive texture softening through ripening, and softening as continuing transformation. ||Berry composition during exit shows water possibly increasing to 80-84% from uptake, organic acids declining 0.6-0.8% with continued respiration, sugars increasing to 14-18%, pH rising to 3.2-3.5, and composition rapidly changing toward ripening characteristics. ||Berry appearance shows berries clearly in transformation with visible color in red cultivars or obvious softening and possible yellowing in white cultivars, cluster showing mixed berry states from asynchrony, and appearance indicating ripening onset. ||Ripening phase entry shows berry definitively in ripening state, active sugar accumulation and color development in red cultivars, progressive softening and acid decline, and ripening as post-lag developmental phase. ||Ripening state characteristics shows growth moderate 10-30 mg per day, metabolic activity elevated 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, sugar accumulation active 1.5-3.5% per week, and active ripening processes. ||Lag phase concluded shows lag quiescence definitively ended, minimal growth state replaced by moderate growth, lag metabolism replaced by ripening metabolism, and lag as completed developmental phase. ||Environmental effects on exit include temperature affecting exit timing and dynamics, warm conditions promoting faster exit transition, cool conditions extending exit period, and temperature determining ripening progression rate. ||The process represents third and final aspect of lag phase termination establishing ripening entry, following veraison approach and softening initiation. ||Duration 1-2 days representing definitive lag-ripening transition. ||Regional timing shows lag phase exit during early-mid September as ripening begins. ||Viticultural significance includes representing definitive lag termination and ripening onset, determining ripening phase commencement affecting harvest date, establishing berry in active transformation state, and marking developmental progression affecting quality and timing. ||Research applications include analyzing lag-ripening transition mechanisms and regulation, investigating growth and metabolic activation dynamics, evaluating sugar accumulation and color development onset, quantifying exit timing and indicators, and assessing lag phase exit as determinant of ripening progression and harvest timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 475-485 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Seed_Development": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Development is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the maturation of the fertilized ovule into a viable seed containing embryo, endosperm, and protective seed coat, extending over 90–120 days from fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "seed maturation | reproductive development | seed formation | ovule to seed development |+ Samenentwicklung | Samenreifung | reproduktive Entwicklung | Samenbildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows seed development during July-October Year N+1, with double fertilization initiating development late June, embryo progressing through globular stage weeks 1-3, heart stage weeks 3-7, torpedo stage weeks 7-12, mature embryo weeks 12-16 with 3.8-4.6 mm length, endosperm developing through free nuclear proliferation weeks 0-2 and cellularization weeks 2-4, storage reserves accumulating 32-38% lipids and 26-32% proteins in cotyledons, seed desiccating from 58% to 12-16% moisture, seed coat lignifying creating hard dark brown protective layer, mature seed 5.2-6.4 mm length weighing 32-46 mg by 14-16 weeks post-fertilization, 1.8-2.4 seeds per berry average, under warm climate conditions coordinating seed maturation with berry ripening, typical of this late-season cultivar achieving complete seed development",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Development represents complete reproductive maturation from fertilization to mature seed. ||Subdivided into Embryo_Development with Zygote_Division, Embryo_Morphogenesis (globular, heart, torpedo stages), and Embryo_Maturation with reserve accumulation || and Endosperm_Development with Endosperm_Proliferation (free nuclear, cellular), Nutrient_Accumulation, and Endosperm_Maturation. ||Duration 90-120 days. ||Mature seed 4-7 mm, 20-50 mg. ||Storage reserves 30-40% lipids, 25-35% proteins. ||Desiccation 50-70% to 10-20% moisture. ||Seed coat lignified brown. ||Coordinates with berry development. ||Critical reproductive process. || This complete seed maturation process occurs during summer to early autumn in Year N+1 from fertilization in late June-July through maturation in September-October in temperate regions, encompassing entire seed development from zygote through mature seed, representing critical reproductive phase establishing next generation. ||Seed development encompasses sequential coordinated phases including embryo development with zygote division initiating embryogenesis, embryo morphogenesis creating organized seedling structures through globular, heart, and torpedo stages, and embryo maturation completing development with storage reserve accumulation, alongside parallel endosperm development with endosperm proliferation through free nuclear and cellular phases, nutrient accumulation establishing storage tissues, and endosperm maturation supporting embryo development and providing germination reserves. ||Embryo development characteristics show zygote undergoing first division 24-72 hours post-fertilization producing two-cell proembryo, embryo morphogenesis proceeding through globular stage weeks 1-3 with undifferentiated cell mass, heart stage weeks 3-7 with cotyledon primordia emergence, torpedo stage weeks 7-12 with elongated embryonic axis and cotyledon development, and mature embryo stage weeks 12-18 with fully formed structures including radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, and shoot apex. ||Endosperm development characteristics show triploid endosperm 3n=57 initiating free nuclear division immediately post-fertilization, multinucleate syncytium forming through rapid nuclear divisions without cytokinesis, cellularization occurring weeks 2-4 creating cellular endosperm, and endosperm tissue providing nutritive support for embryo development and accumulating storage reserves. ||Seed coat development shows integuments differentiating into seed coat layers, outer integument forming testa outer seed coat layer, inner integument forming tegmen inner layer, progressive lignification creating hard protective coat, and brown pigmentation developing indicating maturation. ||Double fertilization foundation shows two sperm cells from pollen tube fusing independently with egg cell creating 2n=38 diploid zygote and with central cell creating 3n=57 triploid endosperm, double fertilization as angiosperm characteristic providing embryo and nutritive tissue, and fertilization initiating coordinated seed development. ||Developmental timeline shows fertilization at 0 days establishing starting point, early embryo development weeks 1-3 with rapid cell divisions, mid embryo morphogenesis weeks 3-12 with structure formation, late embryo maturation weeks 12-18 with reserve accumulation, and seed maturation completing by 90-120 days depending on cultivar and environment. ||Embryo growth pattern shows initial slow growth during early divisions, rapid growth during morphogenesis weeks 3-12, growth deceleration during maturation weeks 12-18, and final mature embryo size 3-5 mm length within seed. ||Endosperm temporal dynamics shows rapid initial proliferation weeks 0-4 establishing tissue, nutrient accumulation weeks 4-12 building reserves, possible partial endosperm consumption by embryo in some species though extent unclear in grapevine, and mature endosperm as storage tissue surrounding embryo. ||Storage reserve accumulation shows lipids accumulating primarily in cotyledons reaching 30-40% dry weight, proteins accumulating 25-35% dry weight, minor carbohydrates, and reserves supporting germination and seedling establishment. ||Lipid accumulation shows triacylglycerols as major storage lipids, oleic and linoleic acids as predominant fatty acids, lipid bodies forming in cotyledon cells, and lipids providing energy reserves for germination. ||Protein accumulation shows storage proteins including albumins and globulins accumulating in protein bodies, proteins providing amino acids for seedling growth, and protein as major reserve component. ||Seed maturation processes show progressive desiccation reducing moisture from 50-70% mid-development to 10-20% mature seed, metabolic activity declining during desiccation, desiccation tolerance developing enabling seed survival, dormancy possibly imposed preventing premature germination, and hard dry seed as mature state. ||Seed desiccation characteristics show water loss through seed coat and funiculus, progressive dehydration over final weeks of development, desiccation tolerance mechanisms including protective proteins and sugars, and low moisture enabling storage and dormancy. ||Seed coat maturation shows lignification creating hard impermeable brown coat, mechanical protection for embryo and endosperm, coat impermeability preventing pathogen entry and regulating water uptake, and mature coat as protective structure. ||Seed coat color shows progression from green immature to brown maturing to dark brown mature seed, color change from pigment deposition and oxidation, brown color indicating lignification and maturation, and color as convenient maturity indicator. ||Seed size variation shows cultivar variation with typical mature seed 4-7 mm length and 3-5 mm width, seed fresh weight 20-50 mg depending on development success, within-berry variation from differential ovule fertilization and development, and size affecting germination vigor. ||Seed number per berry shows 0-4 ovules per flower with typically 0-3 developing into mature seeds, variable seed number from fertilization success and developmental survival, seed number affecting berry development through hormone production particularly during early growth, and average seed number 1.5-2.5 per berry across populations. ||Seed-berry developmental coordination shows seeds developing within berry throughout berry growth and ripening, seed maturation completing during or shortly before berry ripening, mature seeds in ripe berry ready for dispersal, and coordinated development ensuring reproductive success with fruit development. ||Hormonal signaling from seeds shows seeds producing auxin during early development stimulating berry growth, auxin as critical signal preventing berry abscission and promoting expansion, hormone production declining as seeds mature, and seed hormones coordinating seed-berry development. ||Seed maturation timing shows maturation completing by late lag phase to early ripening weeks 12-18 post-fertilization, timing varying with cultivar and environment, mature seeds enabling berry progression through lag phase and veraison, and maturation as potential developmental checkpoint. ||Seed viability shows mature seeds capable of germination if separated and provided appropriate conditions, germination requiring stratification cold treatment for dormancy release in many cultivars, viable seeds representing reproductive success, and viability as seed development outcome. ||Seed dispersal preparation shows mature seed in ripe berry ready for consumption by frugivores, seed coat protecting embryo during passage through digestive tract, animal dispersal as primary natural mechanism, and seed-fruit syndrome as coevolved dispersal strategy. ||Environmental effects on seed development include temperature affecting development rate with warm conditions accelerating and cool conditions slowing progression, water availability important for normal development particularly during growth phases, nutrient supply supporting storage reserve accumulation, and overall favorable conditions ensuring complete seed development. ||Temperature effects show heat accumulation driving developmental progression, growing degree days determining development timing, optimal ranges 22-28°C for normal development, and temperature as major rate determinant. ||Seed development failure shows some ovules failing to develop into mature seeds from fertilization failure, early embryo abortion, inadequate resources, or developmental abnormalities, failed ovule frequency creating variable seed number 0-3 per berry, and seed failure affecting berry development and size. ||Seedless berries shows parthenocarpic seedless cultivars developing berries without fertilization or with aborted seed traces, seedless development lacking hormonal stimulation from seeds requiring exogenous hormones for berry development, and seedless berries as special case. ||The process encompasses two major parallel developmental programs including embryo development with zygote division, embryo morphogenesis, and embryo maturation creating seedling structures, and endosperm development with endosperm proliferation, nutrient accumulation, and endosperm maturation providing nutritive support. ||Duration typically 90-120 days from fertilization to mature seed varying by cultivar and environment. ||Regional timing shows seed development during July-October in temperate regions coordinating with berry development. ||Viticultural significance includes representing reproductive success ensuring next generation, coordinating with berry development through hormonal signaling particularly during early berry growth, mature seeds possibly influencing berry developmental progression through lag phase, and seed development as fundamental reproductive process. ||Research applications include analyzing seed developmental regulation and coordination, investigating embryo and endosperm developmental programs, evaluating seed-berry communication and coordination, quantifying storage reserve accumulation and composition, and assessing seed development as reproductive success indicator and berry development coordinator.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0001170 ## seed development stage | 0.80" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 438-442 || Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Embryo_Development": {
  "definition": "An Embryo_Development is a Seed_Development comprising the developmental progression of the diploid 2n=38 zygote through globular, heart, and torpedo stages to a mature embryo with radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, shoot apex, and accumulated storage reserves, extending over 12–18 weeks from fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "embryogenesis | embryonic development | embryo formation | seedling structure development |+ Embryo-Entwicklung | Embryogenese | embryonale Entwicklung | Embryo-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows embryo development during July-October Year N+1, with zygote dividing 36-48 hours post-fertilization creating two-cell proembryo, globular embryo 60-85 micrometers weeks 1-3, heart embryo 180-260 micrometers weeks 3-7 with cotyledon primordia, torpedo embryo 600-1000 micrometers weeks 7-12 with elongated axis, mature embryo 3.6-4.8 mm length weeks 12-16 with fully developed radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, and shoot apex, storage reserves accumulating 31-37% lipids and 27-33% proteins in cotyledons, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing embryogenesis coordinating with seed and berry maturation",
  "editor_note": "Embryo_Development represents embryonic structure formation within Seed_Development. ||Subdivided into Zygote_Division with first asymmetric division establishing axis, Embryo_Morphogenesis with globular (weeks 1-3), heart (weeks 3-7), torpedo (weeks 7-12) stages, and Embryo_Maturation (weeks 12-18) with storage reserve accumulation. ||Duration 12-18 weeks. ||Mature embryo 3-5 mm with radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, shoot apex. ||Storage reserves 30-40% lipids, 25-35% proteins. ||Creates viable seedling structures. ||Critical reproductive development. || This embryo formation process occurs during summer to early autumn in July-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing complete embryogenesis from single-cell zygote to multicellular organized embryo. ||Embryo development mechanism involves zygote division with first asymmetric division producing two-cell proembryo establishing apical-basal axis, embryo morphogenesis with progressive cell divisions and differentiation creating globular undifferentiated embryo weeks 1-3, heart stage embryo weeks 3-7 with cotyledon primordia emergence establishing bilateral symmetry, torpedo stage embryo weeks 7-12 with elongated embryonic axis and developing cotyledons, and embryo maturation weeks 12-18 with structure completion and storage reserve accumulation creating viable embryo. ||Zygote characteristics shows single diploid cell 2n=38 from sperm-egg fusion, zygote polarized with apical-basal axis, cell preparing for division through DNA replication and mitotic apparatus formation, and zygote as embryo developmental starting point. ||First zygotic division shows asymmetric division 24-72 hours post-fertilization depending on temperature, division producing smaller apical cell and larger basal cell, apical cell giving rise to embryo proper, basal cell producing suspensor support structure, and asymmetric division establishing body plan. ||Two-cell proembryo shows apical cell 20-40 micrometers diameter destined for embryo, basal cell 40-60 micrometers forming suspensor, suspensor anchoring embryo in endosperm and possibly transferring nutrients, and two-cell stage as developmental transition from zygote to embryo. ||Embryo morphogenesis progression shows globular stage embryo weeks 1-3 with spherical cell mass 50-100 micrometers diameter, undifferentiated cells undergoing rapid division, no visible organ primordia, heart stage weeks 3-7 with 150-300 micrometers size showing cotyledon bulges creating heart shape, bilateral symmetry established, torpedo stage weeks 7-12 with 500-1200 micrometers length showing elongated embryonic axis with distinct radicle, hypocotyl, and enlarging cotyledons, and progressive morphogenesis creating seedling structures. ||Globular embryo characteristics shows spherical to ovoid cell mass, cells small and densely cytoplasmic, protoderm differentiating at surface, ground meristem and procambium beginning specification, and globular as undifferentiated embryo stage. ||Heart embryo characteristics shows cotyledon primordia emerging as two lateral bulges, bilateral symmetry from cotyledon positioning, embryonic axis visible between cotyledons, shoot apex initiating at axis apex, radicle region differentiating at basal end, and heart stage as organ initiation stage. ||Torpedo embryo characteristics shows elongated embryonic axis 3-8 fold length to width ratio, cotyledons enlarging and beginning to curve, radicle clearly differentiated with root cap initiation, hypocotyl region between radicle and cotyledons, shoot apical meristem with leaf primordia possibly initiating, and torpedo as major growth and differentiation stage. ||Embryonic axis formation shows radial organization with protoderm epidermis, ground meristem cortex and pith, procambium vascular tissue precursor, and axial organization establishing seedling body plan. ||Cotyledon development shows cotyledons enlarging during torpedo and maturation stages, cotyledons as embryonic leaves storing reserves, cotyledons eventually large accounting for 70-85% embryo volume, and cotyledons as major embryo component. ||Radicle differentiation shows radicle as embryonic root, root cap forming at radicle tip, root apical meristem establishing behind cap, procambium extending through radicle, and radicle as first structure emerging during germination. ||Hypocotyl formation shows hypocotyl as embryonic stem between radicle and cotyledons, hypocotyl elongating during germination, vascular connection through hypocotyl, and hypocotyl as axis component. ||Shoot apex development shows shoot apical meristem initiating between cotyledon bases, meristem as source of post-germination shoot growth, possible first leaf primordia initiating in some species though unclear in grapevine, and shoot apex completing embryo structures. ||Embryo maturation shows storage reserve accumulation primarily in cotyledons weeks 12-18, lipid bodies forming accumulating triacylglycerols reaching 30-40% cotyledon dry weight, protein bodies forming accumulating storage proteins 25-35% dry weight, embryo growth slowing during maturation, metabolic activity declining, and maturation preparing embryo for germination. ||Lipid accumulation in embryo shows oleic acid 18 per 1 and linoleic acid 18 per 2 as major fatty acids, triacylglycerols in lipid bodies, lipid synthesis from photosynthate imported from parent plant, and lipids as major energy reserves. ||Protein accumulation shows albumins and globulins as storage proteins, proteins in protein bodies, amino acid composition balanced for seedling nutrition, and proteins as nitrogen reserves. ||Desiccation tolerance development shows embryo acquiring tolerance to dehydration during maturation, late embryogenesis abundant LEA proteins accumulating, sugars particularly sucrose accumulating providing cellular protection, and desiccation tolerance enabling seed survival. ||Embryo size shows mature embryo typically 3-5 mm length and 1.5-3 mm width, size variation from seed development conditions, embryo occupying 40-60% seed volume with remainder endosperm and coat, and mature size adequate for germination success. ||Embryo viability shows mature embryo capable of germination if provided appropriate conditions, viability requiring complete development including reserve accumulation and desiccation tolerance, and viable embryo as seed development outcome. ||Environmental effects on embryo development include temperature affecting development rate with optimal 22-28°C for normal progression, nutrient availability affecting reserve accumulation, water stress potentially limiting development, and favorable conditions ensuring complete embryogenesis. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating development, cool conditions slowing progression, and temperature determining development duration within 12-18 week range. ||Embryo abortion shows some embryos failing to complete development from genetic abnormalities, inadequate resources, or developmental disruptions, abortion creating seeds without viable embryos or empty ovules, and abortion as developmental failure. ||The process encompasses three sequential developmental phases including zygote division initiating embryogenesis, embryo morphogenesis creating structures through globular, heart, and torpedo stages, and embryo maturation completing development with reserve accumulation. ||Duration typically 12-18 weeks representing complete embryogenesis. ||Regional timing shows embryo development during July-October coordinating with seed and berry development. ||Viticultural significance includes representing formation of next generation plant, storage reserve accumulation determining germination vigor, embryo viability determining seed quality, and embryo development as fundamental reproductive process. ||Research applications include analyzing embryogenesis regulation and morphogenesis, investigating storage reserve biosynthesis and accumulation, evaluating environmental effects on embryo development, quantifying developmental stages and timing, and assessing embryo development as seed viability determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 438-442"
},

  "Zygote_Division": {
  "definition": "A Zygote_Division is an Embryo_Development comprising the first asymmetric division of the diploid 2n=38 zygote producing a two-cell proembryo with apical and basal cells establishing the apical-basal body axis, occurring 24–72 hours post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "first embryonic division | zygote cleavage | proembryo formation | initial embryo division |+ Zygoten-Teilung | erste embryonale Teilung | Zygoten-Spaltung | Proembryo-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows zygote division during late June-early July Year N+1, with diploid zygote 2n=38 dividing 32-52 hours post-fertilization at 22-26°C, asymmetric division producing apical cell 24-36 micrometers and basal cell 46-58 micrometers, apical cell specified for embryo proper fate, basal cell forming suspensor, two-cell proembryo establishing apical-basal axis, under continental conditions initiating embryogenesis, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar beginning seed development",
  "editor_note": "Zygote_Division is first phase of Embryo_Development, distinguished by first asymmetric division. ||Represents single division event 24-72 hours post-fertilization (temperature-dependent). ||Produces apical cell 20-40 μm (embryo proper fate) and basal cell 40-60 μm (suspensor fate). ||Establishes apical-basal axis. ||Creates two-cell proembryo. ||Followed by Embryo_Morphogenesis. ||Critical embryogenesis initiation. ||Temperature 25-28°C optimal (24-36h), cool 18-22°C extends (48-72h). || This first division phase occurs during early summer in late June-early July in temperate regions Year N+1, representing zygote to embryo transition 1-3 days post-fertilization. ||Division mechanism involves zygote activation and cell cycle progression following fertilization, DNA replication doubling chromosome content from 2n to 4n, mitotic apparatus formation with spindle positioning determining division plane, asymmetric cytokinesis producing unequal daughter cells, apical cell specification for embryo fate, basal cell specification for suspensor fate, and division establishing developmental program. ||Zygote developmental state shows zygote formed from sperm-egg fusion creating diploid 2n=38 single cell, zygote polarized with apical-basal axis from egg polarity or post-fertilization establishment, zygote cell typically 40-70 micrometers diameter, metabolically active preparing for division, and zygote as embryogenesis starting point. ||Zygote activation shows fertilization triggering metabolic activation, calcium signaling initiating developmental program, zygotic genome activation with embryo-specific genes beginning expression, transition from maternal to embryonic genetic control, and activation establishing autonomous development. ||Zygote cell cycle shows G1 phase with growth and preparation, S phase DNA replication creating 4n chromosome content, G2 phase with mitotic preparation and spindle assembly, M phase mitosis with chromosome segregation, and cytokinesis completing division. ||Cell cycle timing shows division occurring 24-72 hours post-fertilization depending on temperature, warm conditions 25-28°C enabling division 24-36 hours, cool conditions 18-22°C extending to 48-72 hours, and temperature as major timing determinant. ||DNA replication shows semiconservative replication duplicating 475 Mb grapevine genome, replication producing sister chromatids, chromosome content doubling to 4n, and replication as division prerequisite. ||Mitotic spindle formation shows centrosomes nucleating microtubules, bipolar spindle forming with poles at cell ends, kinetochores on chromosomes attaching to spindle microtubules, and spindle providing chromosome segregation machinery. ||Spindle positioning shows spindle axis orientation determining division plane, asymmetric positioning creating unequal division, spindle position regulated by cortical cues and cytoskeletal forces, and positioning as asymmetry mechanism. ||Asymmetric division shows unequal cytokinesis producing larger basal cell 40-60 micrometers and smaller apical cell 20-40 micrometers, asymmetry from unequal spindle positioning and cytokinesis plane, asymmetric distribution of developmental regulators possibly influencing fate, and asymmetry establishing cell fate difference. ||Cytokinesis characteristics shows phragmoplast forming at division plane, cell plate synthesizing from center outward, new cell wall forming between daughter cells, and cytokinesis completing division creating two-cell proembryo. ||Two-cell proembryo characteristics shows apical cell smaller typically 20-40 micrometers diameter positioned toward micropyle, basal cell larger 40-60 micrometers positioned toward chalaza, cells separated by new wall, and proembryo as two-cell embryo stage. ||Apical cell fate shows apical cell destined to form embryo proper including all seedling structures, cell undergoing subsequent divisions creating embryo, cell containing embryo developmental program, and apical fate as primary embryo pathway. ||Basal cell fate shows basal cell forming suspensor supporting structure, suspensor typically 3-7 cells anchoring embryo in endosperm, suspensor possibly transferring nutrients though function debated in grapevine, suspensor degenerating during later development, and basal fate as support pathway. ||Apical-basal axis establishment shows division creating primary body axis, axis orientation from micropyle apical to chalaza basal, axis persisting through development into seedling root-shoot axis, and axis as fundamental body plan feature. ||Developmental asymmetry shows unequal cells having different developmental fates, asymmetry as mechanism for creating embryo organization, asymmetric division common in plant embryogenesis, and asymmetry establishing pattern. ||Cell fate determination shows molecular mechanisms specifying apical versus basal fate possibly involving transcription factors and signaling molecules though poorly characterized in grapevine, fate determination early in development, and determination creating distinct pathways. ||First division significance shows division as embryogenesis initiation, transition from single-cell to multicellular organism, establishment of body axis and cell fates, and division as critical developmental event. ||Environmental effects on division include temperature affecting division timing with warm conditions accelerating and cool conditions delaying within 24-72 hour range, temperature as major factor, and division occurring across temperature ranges enabling development. ||Division timing variation shows cultivar and individual variation in timing, typical range 24-72 hours covering temperature and genetic effects, and timing determining subsequent development pace. ||Failed division shows occasional zygotes failing to divide from developmental abnormalities, failure causing ovule abortion, and failure as early developmental loss. ||The process represents first phase of embryo development establishing two-cell proembryo, preceding embryo morphogenesis. ||Duration represents single division event occurring over hours at 24-72 hours post-fertilization. ||Regional timing shows zygote division during late June-early July as embryogenesis initiates. ||Viticultural significance includes representing embryogenesis initiation establishing multicellular embryo, creating apical-basal axis and cell fate asymmetry, determining subsequent embryo development, and marking reproductive success transition from fertilization to development. ||Research applications include analyzing zygote activation and developmental initiation, investigating asymmetric division mechanisms and cell fate determination, evaluating environmental effects on division timing, quantifying division characteristics and outcomes, and assessing zygote division as embryogenesis foundation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 438-440"
},

  "Embryo_Morphogenesis": {
  "definition": "An Embryo_Morphogenesis is an Embryo_Development consisting of progressive cell division and differentiation of the proembryo through globular (weeks 1–3), heart (weeks 3–7), and torpedo (weeks 7–12) stages establishing radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, and shoot apex.",
  "alternative_term": "embryo organogenesis | structural development | organ formation | seedling structure creation |+ Embryo-Morphogenese | Embryo-Organogenese | strukturelle Entwicklung | Organ-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows embryo morphogenesis during July-September Year N+1, with globular embryo 65-90 micrometers weeks 1-3, heart embryo 200-280 micrometers weeks 3-7 showing cotyledon primordia emergence and bilateral symmetry, torpedo embryo 650-1100 micrometers weeks 7-12 with elongated axis showing radicle, hypocotyl, enlarging cotyledons, and developing shoot apex, progressive tissue differentiation with protoderm, ground meristem, and procambium, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing morphogenesis with organized seedling structures ready for maturation",
  "editor_note": "Embryo_Morphogenesis is second phase of Embryo_Development, distinguished by structure formation. ||Represents progression through globular (50-100 μm, weeks 1-3), heart (150-300 μm, weeks 3-7), torpedo (500-1200 μm, weeks 7-12) stages. ||Creates radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, shoot apex. ||Tissue differentiation: protoderm, ground meristem, procambium. ||Duration ~12 weeks. ||Follows Zygote_Division. ||Precedes Embryo_Maturation. ||Temperature 22-28°C optimal. ||Establishes seedling body plan. || This structure formation phase occurs during summer to early autumn in July-September in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning approximately 12 weeks representing major morphogenesis period. ||Morphogenesis mechanism involves coordinated cell divisions increasing cell number, progressive cell differentiation establishing cell types, pattern formation creating spatial organization, organ initiation and development forming seedling structures, and developmental progression through morphological stages creating recognizable embryo architecture. ||Globular embryo stage shows spherical to ovoid embryo 50-100 micrometers diameter weeks 1-3 post-fertilization, undifferentiated cell mass with no visible organ primordia, cells small densely cytoplasmic actively dividing, protoderm surface layer differentiating, ground meristem and procambium beginning internal specification, and globular as early undifferentiated stage. ||Globular embryo development shows rapid cell divisions increasing cell number from 2-cell to hundreds of cells, cells relatively uniform without clear differentiation, embryo growth from 50 to 100 micrometers, and transition to heart stage with organ initiation. ||Cell division patterns during globular stage shows irregular division planes creating three-dimensional cell mass, divisions establishing radial symmetry, cell lineages not strictly determined enabling regulation, and division patterns creating embryo foundation. ||Protoderm formation shows outer cell layer differentiating as protoderm epidermis precursor, protoderm cells acquiring surface identity, periclinal divisions maintaining surface layer, and protoderm as first differentiated tissue. ||Ground meristem specification shows internal cells beginning ground tissue specification, ground meristem giving rise to cortex and pith, specification preparing for axis formation, and ground meristem as internal tissue precursor. ||Procambium initiation shows vascular tissue precursor cells beginning specification, procambium as centrally located cell files, procambium forming vascular connection through axis, and procambium as vascular precursor. ||Heart embryo stage shows bilateral symmetrical embryo 150-300 micrometers size weeks 3-7, cotyledon primordia emerging as two lateral bulges creating heart shape, embryonic axis visible between cotyledons, organ initiation marking developmental transition, and heart as organ formation stage. ||Cotyledon primordium emergence shows two lateral outgrowths from embryo body, cotyledon primordia as embryonic leaf structures, primordia establishing bilateral symmetry, and cotyledon initiation as defining heart stage feature. ||Bilateral symmetry establishment shows two cotyledons creating symmetry plane, symmetry from developmental patterning mechanisms, symmetry characteristic of dicotyledonous plants, and bilateral pattern distinguishing from radial globular symmetry. ||Embryonic axis formation shows axis region between cotyledons becoming apparent, axis containing shoot apical meristem at apex, radicle region differentiating at base, and axis as future seedling stem. ||Shoot apex initiation shows shoot apical meristem beginning formation at axis apex between cotyledon bases, meristem as source of post-embryonic shoot growth, meristem dome with organizing center, and shoot apex as critical structure. ||Radicle region differentiation shows basal axis region differentiating as radicle embryonic root, radicle region with root organization, future root cap initiating, and radicle as basal embryo structure. ||Torpedo embryo stage shows elongated embryo 500-1200 micrometers length weeks 7-12, embryonic axis elongating with 3-8 fold length to width ratio, cotyledons enlarging and beginning to curve, organs clearly differentiated and growing, and torpedo as major growth and differentiation stage. ||Embryonic axis elongation shows hypocotyl region between radicle and cotyledons elongating, axis length increasing substantially, axis showing clear radial organization, and elongation creating torpedo shape. ||Cotyledon development shows cotyledons enlarging from small primordia to substantial organs, cotyledons beginning to curve accommodating axis, cotyledons preparing for storage reserve accumulation, and cotyledon growth as major feature. ||Radicle differentiation completion shows radicle clearly defined with root cap forming at tip, root apical meristem establishing behind cap, procambium extending through radicle, and radicle ready for germination emergence. ||Hypocotyl formation shows hypocotyl as axis region between radicle and cotyledons, hypocotyl with characteristic tissue organization, vascular procambium continuous through hypocotyl, and hypocotyl as embryonic stem. ||Shoot apical meristem development shows meristem becoming clearly organized, meristem with tunica corpus organization typical of shoot apices, possible leaf primordia initiating though unclear in grapevine, and meristem as shoot growth source. ||Tissue differentiation during morphogenesis shows protoderm developing into epidermis, ground meristem differentiating into cortex and pith, procambium developing into vascular tissue, and progressive differentiation creating tissue types. ||Vascular tissue development shows procambium forming continuous strand through axis, xylem and phloem precursors differentiating, vascular connection from radicle through hypocotyl to cotyledons, and vascular system as transport pathway. ||Pattern formation shows spatial gene expression patterns directing morphogenesis, transcription factors regulating organ identity and polarity, hormonal signals including auxin affecting pattern, and coordinated patterning creating organized structure. ||Organ identity specification shows genetic programs determining organ fate, cotyledon identity genes expressed in cotyledons, root identity genes in radicle, shoot identity genes in shoot apex, and identity specification as organ determination. ||Morphogenesis completion shows embryo achieving characteristic seedling structure by week 12, organs differentiated ready for maturation, embryo transitioning to maturation phase with reserve accumulation, and morphogenesis establishing structure for subsequent maturation. ||Environmental effects on morphogenesis include temperature affecting development rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting normal progression through stages, nutrient availability supporting cell division and growth, and favorable conditions ensuring complete morphogenesis. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating stage progression, cool conditions slowing development, and temperature determining morphogenesis duration. ||The process represents second phase of embryo development creating structures, following zygote division and preceding embryo maturation. ||Duration approximately 12 weeks representing globular through torpedo stages. ||Regional timing shows embryo morphogenesis during July-September as structures form. ||Viticultural significance includes representing organ formation creating seedling structures, establishing body plan for germination, demonstrating progressive developmental program, and completing structural organization preparing for maturation. ||Research applications include analyzing morphogenesis regulation and pattern formation, investigating organ identity specification and development, evaluating developmental stage progression and timing, quantifying morphological changes and growth, and assessing morphogenesis as seedling structure determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 440-442"
},

  "Embryo_Maturation": {
  "definition": "An Embryo_Maturation is an Embryo_Development comprising storage reserve accumulation of 30–40% lipids and 25–35% proteins by dry weight in cotyledons with acquisition of desiccation tolerance and reduced metabolic activity, extending over weeks 12–18 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "embryo reserve accumulation | final embryo development | embryo preparation | maturation phase |+ Embryo-Reifung | Embryo-Reserven-Akkumulation | finale Embryo-Entwicklung | Reifungsphase",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows embryo maturation during September-October Year N+1, with structurally complete torpedo embryo beginning reserve accumulation week 12, lipids accumulating in cotyledons reaching 33-39% dry weight with oleic acid 18-24% and linoleic acid 48-58% total fatty acids, proteins accumulating 27-34% dry weight, lipid bodies 0.8-1.6 micrometers and protein bodies 1.2-2.4 micrometers forming, LEA proteins and protective sugars accumulating conferring desiccation tolerance, embryo growth slowing and ceasing, mature embryo 3.8-4.6 mm length with full reserves by weeks 16-18, under cool maritime conditions of 16-22°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar completing embryogenesis",
  "editor_note": "Embryo_Maturation is third and final phase of Embryo_Development, distinguished by reserve accumulation. ||Represents weeks 12-18. ||Storage reserves: lipids 30-40% (mainly oleic, linoleic acids in triacylglycerols), proteins 25-35% (albumins, globulins). ||Lipid bodies 0.5-2 μm, protein bodies 1-3 μm in cotyledons. ||Desiccation tolerance (LEA proteins, protective sugars). ||Metabolic decline. ||Possible dormancy. ||Mature embryo 3-5 mm. ||Follows Embryo_Morphogenesis. ||Completes Embryo_Development. ||Determines germination vigor. || This reserve accumulation and preparation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in September-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing final embryo development completing seed maturation. ||Maturation mechanism involves storage reserve biosynthesis and accumulation primarily in cotyledons, lipid body and protein body formation, desiccation tolerance acquisition through protective molecule accumulation, metabolic activity decline toward quiescence, possible dormancy imposition preventing premature germination, and integrated maturation preparing embryo for dispersal and germination. ||Embryo structure at maturation onset shows torpedo stage embryo 800-1200 micrometers with fully formed organs including radicle, hypocotyl, cotyledons, and shoot apex, all seedling structures present requiring reserve accumulation and physiological maturation, and structural foundation for maturation. ||Storage reserve accumulation shows lipids and proteins accumulating primarily in cotyledon cells, reserve biosynthesis from photosynthate imported from parent plant through seed coat and funiculus, massive accumulation over weeks 12-18 creating energy and nutrient stores, and reserves supporting germination and seedling establishment. ||Lipid accumulation in cotyledons shows triacylglycerols as major storage lipids reaching 30-40% cotyledon dry weight by maturation completion, oleic acid C18 per 1 and linoleic acid C18 per 2 as predominant fatty acids 70-85% total fatty acids, lipid biosynthesis in endoplasmic reticulum, lipid bodies 0.5-2 micrometers diameter forming in cytoplasm storing lipids, and lipids as major energy reserves providing 9 kcal/g. ||Fatty acid composition shows oleic acid typically 15-25% total fatty acids, linoleic acid 40-60%, linolenic acid 5-15%, palmitic acid 5-10%, stearic acid 2-5%, and fatty acid profile affecting seed quality and germination. ||Lipid body characteristics shows lipid bodies as organelles surrounded by phospholipid monolayer, triacylglycerols in core, oleosins and other proteins at surface, and lipid bodies as lipid storage compartments. ||Protein accumulation in cotyledons shows storage proteins reaching 25-35% cotyledon dry weight, albumins as water-soluble proteins, globulins as salt-soluble proteins, proteins providing amino acids for seedling growth during germination, protein biosynthesis and accumulation in protein bodies 1-3 micrometers diameter, and proteins as nitrogen and sulfur reserves. ||Protein body characteristics shows protein bodies as specialized vacuoles storing proteins, surrounded by tonoplast membrane, proteins crystalline or amorphous in bodies, and protein bodies as protein storage compartments. ||Amino acid composition shows balanced amino acid profile for seedling nutrition, essential amino acids present, arginine often abundant amino acid in storage proteins, and composition supporting germination requirements. ||Carbohydrate accumulation shows minor carbohydrate reserves typically <10% dry weight, sucrose and oligosaccharides as major carbohydrates, raffinose family oligosaccharides possibly present, and carbohydrates having storage and protective functions. ||Reserve accumulation timing shows accumulation initiating during late torpedo stage week 10-12, intensive accumulation weeks 12-16, completion by week 16-18, and accumulation as major maturation process. ||Embryo growth during maturation shows continued growth during early maturation increasing size and mass, growth slowing during reserve accumulation, eventual growth cessation by maturation completion, final mature embryo size 3-5 mm length and 1.5-3 mm width, and growth pattern characteristic of maturation. ||Fresh weight and dry weight dynamics shows embryo fresh weight increasing from water and reserve accumulation, dry weight increasing substantially from reserve deposition, eventual water loss during desiccation, and dry weight as reserve measure. ||Desiccation tolerance acquisition shows embryo acquiring ability to survive water loss during maturation, late embryogenesis abundant LEA proteins accumulating providing cellular protection during desiccation, sugars particularly sucrose and raffinose family oligosaccharides accumulating stabilizing membranes and proteins, heat shock proteins possibly accumulating, and desiccation tolerance enabling seed survival and storage. ||Late embryogenesis abundant proteins shows hydrophilic proteins accumulating during late maturation, LEA proteins protecting cellular structures during desiccation, proteins preventing protein aggregation and membrane fusion, and LEA proteins as desiccation protection. ||Sugar protective function shows sugars replacing water in hydrogen bonding stabilizing membranes, sugars forming glasses vitrifying cytoplasm preventing damage, and sugars as desiccation protectants. ||Metabolic activity decline shows respiratory rate decreasing during maturation, metabolic flux declining toward quiescence, gene expression shifting toward dormancy-associated genes, and metabolism declining to very low levels in mature desiccated embryo. ||Dormancy possible imposition shows embryos possibly acquiring dormancy preventing immediate germination, dormancy requiring stratification cold treatment or time for release, dormancy mechanisms including abscisic acid accumulation and germination inhibitors, and dormancy as germination control though variable in grapevine. ||Abscisic acid in embryo shows ABA possibly accumulating during maturation, ABA imposing or maintaining dormancy, ABA levels declining during stratification or after-ripening enabling germination, and ABA as dormancy hormone. ||Embryo color changes shows embryo progressing from white or pale during early maturation to yellowish or greenish at maturation from reserve accumulation and chlorophyll, color as maturation indicator, and color changing with desiccation. ||Maturation completion shows embryo achieving mature state with full reserve complement, desiccation tolerance acquired, metabolic quiescence established, embryo ready for dispersal and eventual germination, and completion by weeks 16-18 post-fertilization. ||Mature embryo characteristics shows embryo 3-5 mm length with fully formed structures, reserves stored in cotyledons, desiccation tolerant able to survive low moisture, dormant or germination-competent depending on regulation, and viable ready for germination. ||Germination competence shows mature embryo capable of germination if provided appropriate conditions including moisture, temperature, possible stratification, and germination competence as maturation outcome. ||Environmental effects on maturation include temperature affecting maturation rate with warm conditions accelerating reserve accumulation and cool conditions slowing, nutrient availability affecting reserve accumulation quality and quantity, and favorable conditions ensuring complete maturation. ||Temperature effects shows optimal range 22-26°C supporting normal maturation, temperature affecting maturation duration, and temperature as rate determinant. ||The process represents third and final phase of embryo development completing embryogenesis, following embryo morphogenesis. ||Duration approximately 6 weeks representing reserve accumulation and maturation weeks 12-18. ||Regional timing shows embryo maturation during September-October completing seed development. ||Viticultural significance includes representing reserve accumulation determining germination vigor, desiccation tolerance enabling seed survival and storage, dormancy potentially regulating germination timing, and maturation completing reproductive development creating viable seed. ||Research applications include analyzing storage reserve biosynthesis and regulation, investigating desiccation tolerance mechanisms and protective molecules, evaluating dormancy imposition and regulation, quantifying reserve accumulation and composition, and assessing embryo maturation as seed viability and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Endosperm_Development": {
  "definition": "An Endosperm_Development is a Seed_Development comprising the proliferation, cellularization, nutrient accumulation, and maturation of the triploid 3n=57 endosperm tissue, extending over 8–14 weeks coordinated with embryo development.",
  "alternative_term": "nutritive tissue development | endosperm formation | triploid tissue development | storage tissue development |+ Endosperm-Entwicklung | nutritives Gewebe-Entwicklung | Endosperm-Bildung | triploide Gewebe-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows endosperm development during July-October Year N+1, with triploid endosperm 3n=57 initiating free nuclear divisions immediately post-fertilization producing 24-48 nuclei in multinucleate syncytium by week 2, cellularization proceeding weeks 2-4 creating cellular endosperm, continued cell divisions and nutrient accumulation weeks 4-12 with proteins reaching 18-28% and lipids 12-22% dry weight, endosperm maturation weeks 12-16 completing development, mature endosperm surrounding 3.8-4.6 mm embryo accounting for 45-55% seed volume providing germination reserves, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar completing endosperm development coordinating with embryo maturation",
  "editor_note": "Endosperm_Development represents nutritive tissue formation within Seed_Development. ||Subdivided into Endosperm_Proliferation with free nuclear (weeks 0-2, multinucleate syncytium) and cellular (weeks 2-4, cellularization) phases, Nutrient_Accumulation (weeks 4-12) with storage reserves, and Endosperm_Maturation (weeks 12-16). ||Triploid 3n=57. ||Duration ~8-14 weeks. ||Storage: proteins 15-30%, lipids 10-25%. ||Surrounds embryo 40-60% seed volume. ||Supports embryo development and germination. ||Parallel to Embryo_Development. || This nutritive tissue development process occurs during summer to early autumn in July-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing endosperm formation parallel to embryo development. ||Endosperm development mechanism involves free nuclear proliferation with rapid mitotic divisions without cytokinesis creating multinucleate syncytium weeks 0-2, cellularization with walls forming around nuclei creating cellular tissue weeks 2-4, nutrient accumulation with storage compounds depositing in endosperm cells weeks 4-12, possible partial endosperm consumption by embryo though extent unclear in grapevine, and endosperm maturation completing development providing nutritive tissue. ||Triploid endosperm characteristics shows endosperm with 3n=57 chromosome content from sperm fusion with diploid central cell or two haploid polar nuclei, triploid genome with 2 maternal to 1 paternal genomic ratio affecting gene expression, endosperm as angiosperm-characteristic nutritive tissue, and triploidy distinguishing endosperm from diploid embryo. ||Central cell fertilization shows sperm from pollen tube fusing with diploid central cell creating triploid primary endosperm nucleus, fusion as second fertilization event in double fertilization, fertilization immediately initiating endosperm development, and central cell fertilization coordinating with egg fertilization. ||Free nuclear phase shows endosperm initiating rapid nuclear divisions without accompanying cytokinesis, nuclear divisions producing multinucleate syncytium with shared cytoplasm, typical 8-64 free nuclei forming during weeks 0-2, nuclei distributed throughout endosperm cavity, and free nuclear phase as initial proliferation mode. ||Nuclear division characteristics shows mitotic divisions with typical cell cycle phases, divisions initially synchronous later becoming asynchronous, division rate very rapid with cycle times possibly 6-12 hours, and rapid divisions creating numerous nuclei. ||Multinucleate syncytium shows multiple nuclei sharing common cytoplasm, cytoplasm filling developing seed, nuclei possibly migrating within syncytium, and syncytium as unique tissue organization. ||Cellularization phase shows cell walls forming around free nuclei creating cellular endosperm weeks 2-4, cellularization proceeding centripetally from periphery toward center, alveolar or cellular endosperm resulting from cellularization, and cellularization as transition to cellular tissue. ||Cell wall formation shows walls synthesizing between adjacent nuclei, phragmoplast-like structures possibly mediating wall formation, progressive cellularization creating multicellular tissue, and cell wall deposition completing cellularization. ||Cellular endosperm characteristics shows endosperm as cellular tissue after cellularization, cells containing single nucleus, cells connected through plasmodesmata possibly, and cellular organization enabling storage and transfer functions. ||Endosperm proliferation shows continued cell divisions after cellularization increasing endosperm cell number, divisions less rapid than free nuclear phase, eventual proliferation cessation as endosperm matures, and proliferation establishing endosperm mass. ||Nutrient accumulation phase shows endosperm cells accumulating storage reserves weeks 4-12, proteins accumulating as major storage compounds, lipids accumulating though less than in embryo cotyledons, carbohydrates including starch possibly accumulating, and nutrients providing embryo support and germination reserves. ||Protein accumulation in endosperm shows storage proteins accumulating in protein bodies, proteins providing amino acid reserves, protein content variable possibly 15-30% endosperm dry weight, and proteins supporting embryo nutrition. ||Lipid accumulation shows lipids in endosperm possibly 10-25% dry weight less than cotyledon levels, lipids providing energy reserves, and lipid accumulation supplementing protein storage. ||Carbohydrate storage shows possible starch accumulation though content variable and often low in grapevine, other carbohydrates including cell wall polysaccharides, and carbohydrates as potential reserves. ||Endosperm function shows endosperm supporting embryo development through nutrient transfer, endosperm providing germination reserves mobilized during seedling establishment, and endosperm as nutritive tissue essential for reproduction. ||Nutrient transfer to embryo shows endosperm possibly transferring nutrients to developing embryo, transfer mechanisms including plasmodesmatal connections or secretion and uptake, and transfer supporting embryo growth. ||Endosperm consumption shows embryo possibly consuming portion of endosperm during development, extent of consumption variable and unclear in grapevine, some mature seeds retaining substantial endosperm while others have minimal, and consumption pattern varying. ||Endosperm persistence shows mature seed typically retaining endosperm tissue surrounding embryo, endosperm accounting for 40-60% seed volume depending on consumption degree, persistent endosperm providing germination reserves, and persistence characteristic of grapevine seeds. ||Endosperm maturation shows endosperm completing development weeks 12-16, reserves accumulated to final levels, endosperm desiccating along with embryo during seed maturation, mature endosperm as storage tissue ready for germination mobilization, and maturation coordinating with embryo maturation. ||Desiccation shows endosperm water content declining during seed maturation, desiccation tolerance acquired, mature endosperm dry with low moisture, and desiccation enabling seed storage. ||Endosperm in mature seed shows endosperm as layer surrounding embryo, tissue firm and hard in dry seed, endosperm rehydrating during germination, and endosperm as persistent reserve tissue. ||Germination mobilization shows endosperm reserves mobilized during germination, hydrolytic enzymes degrading storage compounds, nutrients transported to growing seedling, and mobilization supporting seedling establishment. ||Environmental effects on endosperm development include temperature affecting development rate, nutrient availability affecting accumulation, and conditions affecting development coordinating with embryo. ||The process encompasses three sequential phases including endosperm proliferation with free nuclear and cellular phases, nutrient accumulation establishing storage, and endosperm maturation completing development. ||Duration approximately 8-14 weeks representing major endosperm development. ||Regional timing shows endosperm development during July-October parallel to embryo development. ||Viticultural significance includes representing nutritive tissue supporting embryo, providing germination reserves, demonstrating coordinated seed development, and contributing to seed quality. ||Research applications include analyzing endosperm developmental regulation, investigating nutrient accumulation and storage, evaluating endosperm-embryo interactions, quantifying endosperm composition and reserves, and assessing endosperm development as seed quality component.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 439-442"
},

  "Endosperm_Proliferation": {
  "definition": "An Endosperm_Proliferation is an Endosperm_Development comprising free nuclear divisions producing 8–64 nuclei in a syncytium during weeks 0–2 followed by cellularization through cell wall formation around nuclei during weeks 2–4 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "endosperm tissue expansion | nuclear and cellular proliferation | endosperm growth | free nuclear and cellular phases |+ Endosperm-Proliferation | Endosperm-Gewebe-Expansion | nukleare und zelluläre Proliferation | Endosperm-Wachstum",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows endosperm proliferation during July-early August Year N+1, with triploid endosperm 3n=57 initiating free nuclear divisions hours post-fertilization, rapid synchronous divisions with 8-12 hour cycle times producing 32-56 free nuclei in multinucleate syncytium by week 2, cellularization proceeding weeks 2-3.5 with centripetal wall formation creating cellular endosperm, continued cellular divisions weeks 3.5-5 with 16-20 hour cycle times, final endosperm cellularity supporting 45-55% seed volume, under warm climate conditions of 25-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar completing endosperm proliferation establishing tissue foundation",
  "editor_note": "Endosperm_Proliferation is first phase of Endosperm_Development, distinguished by tissue expansion. ||Represents free nuclear phase (weeks 0-2) with rapid divisions producing 8-64 nuclei in syncytium, followed by cellularization (weeks 2-4) creating cellular tissue, and cellular division (weeks 4-6). ||Cycle times 6-12h free nuclear, 12-24h cellular. ||Triploid 3n=57. ||Duration ~4 weeks. ||Establishes endosperm cellularity 40-60% seed volume. ||Precedes Nutrient_Accumulation. ||Temperature 24-28°C optimal. || This proliferative tissue expansion phase occurs during early-mid summer in July-early August in temperate regions Year N+1, representing initial endosperm development weeks 0-4 post-fertilization. ||Proliferation mechanism involves free nuclear division phase with rapid mitosis without cytokinesis creating multinucleate syncytium, nuclear divisions initially synchronous becoming asynchronous, cellularization phase with wall formation around nuclei, cellular division phase with continued mitotic divisions in cellular endosperm, and proliferation establishing endosperm cellularity and mass. ||Free nuclear division initiation shows endosperm initiating rapid nuclear divisions immediately following central cell fertilization, first division occurring within hours to 1 day post-fertilization, divisions producing free nuclei in common cytoplasm, and free nuclear phase as initial proliferation mode. ||Nuclear division characteristics shows mitotic divisions with normal cell cycle phases G1, S, G2, M, divisions without accompanying cytokinesis producing free nuclei, cell cycle times very rapid possibly 6-12 hours during peak proliferation, and rapid cycles enabling exponential nuclear increase. ||Division synchrony shows early divisions often synchronous with nuclei dividing simultaneously, synchrony creating waves of division, later divisions becoming asynchronous with individual nuclear cycles, and synchrony pattern characteristic of free nuclear development. ||Multinucleate syncytium formation shows multiple free nuclei sharing common cytoplasm, typical nuclear number 8-64 by cellularization onset depending on genotype and conditions, nuclei distributed throughout endosperm cavity, cytoplasm filling developing seed, and syncytium as unique tissue organization. ||Nuclear number dynamics shows exponential increase from single primary endosperm nucleus to typically 16-64 free nuclei over weeks 0-2, doubling time initially 6-12 hours, eventual nuclear number depending on proliferation rate and cellularization timing, and nuclear accumulation establishing endosperm foundation. ||Nuclear positioning shows nuclei distributed throughout syncytium, possible nuclear migration within cytoplasm, nuclei possibly positioned near periphery in some species though pattern unclear in grapevine, and nuclear distribution affecting cellularization. ||Cytoplasm characteristics shows shared cytoplasm connecting all nuclei, cytoplasm with ribosomes, endoplasmic reticulum, organelles, active metabolism supporting rapid divisions, and cytoplasm as common cellular environment. ||Free nuclear phase duration shows phase typically lasting 1-2 weeks, timing varying with temperature and genotype, phase ending with cellularization initiation, and duration determining nuclear number at cellularization. ||Cellularization initiation shows cell walls beginning to form around free nuclei weeks 2-4, cellularization as transition from syncytial to cellular organization, walls separating nuclei into individual cells, and cellularization as critical developmental transition. ||Cell wall formation mechanism shows phragmoplast-like structures possibly forming around nuclei, cell plate synthesis creating walls, wall deposition proceeding centripetally from periphery inward in many species, progressive wall formation creating cellular tissue, and cellularization completing over days to week. ||Centripetal cellularization pattern shows walls forming first at endosperm periphery adjacent to seed coat, cellularization progressing inward toward center, central region last to cellularize, and centripetal pattern common in angiosperms though pattern not well-documented in grapevine. ||Cellular endosperm formation shows cellularization creating multicellular endosperm tissue, individual cells each containing one nucleus, cells separated by walls but possibly connected through plasmodesmata, and cellular organization replacing syncytial structure. ||Cell characteristics shows endosperm cells typically 20-50 micrometers diameter after cellularization, cells with dense cytoplasm and central nucleus, cells capable of continued division and growth, and cellular state enabling storage function. ||Cellular division phase shows continued mitotic divisions in cellular endosperm after cellularization, divisions less rapid than free nuclear phase, divisions with cytokinesis creating daughter cells, divisions increasing endosperm cell number and mass, and cellular proliferation completing tissue expansion. ||Division rate in cellular phase shows cell cycle times slower than free nuclear phase possibly 12-24 hours, reduced rate characteristic of cellular versus syncytial division, division rate declining as proliferation concludes, and rate reduction marking transition toward maturation. ||Proliferation completion shows cell divisions eventually ceasing weeks 4-6, endosperm achieving final cellularity, transition to non-dividing tissue focused on accumulation, and completion establishing mature tissue architecture. ||Final endosperm cellularity shows total endosperm cell number from combined free nuclear and cellular proliferation, typical endosperm mass sufficient to surround embryo occupying 40-60% seed volume, cellularity determining accumulation capacity, and final cellularity as proliferation outcome. ||Endosperm growth during proliferation shows endosperm expanding to fill available space in developing seed, endosperm mass increasing from cell number increase and cell growth, and growth coordinating with seed enlargement. ||Environmental effects on proliferation include temperature affecting division rate with warm conditions 24-28°C supporting rapid proliferation and cool conditions slowing divisions, nutrient availability supporting division biosynthetic demands, and conditions affecting proliferation rate and duration. ||Temperature effects shows optimal range supporting rapid free nuclear and cellular divisions, suboptimal temperatures extending proliferation phase, and temperature as major rate determinant. ||The process represents first phase of endosperm development establishing tissue mass, preceding nutrient accumulation and endosperm maturation. ||Duration approximately 4 weeks representing free nuclear and cellular proliferation weeks 0-4. ||Regional timing shows endosperm proliferation during July-early August as endosperm tissue forms. ||Viticultural significance includes representing endosperm tissue establishment, determining endosperm cellularity and mass, providing foundation for storage reserve accumulation, and establishing nutritive tissue supporting embryo. ||Research applications include analyzing endosperm proliferation regulation and mechanisms, investigating free nuclear division and cellularization processes, evaluating environmental effects on proliferation dynamics, quantifying nuclear and cell number accumulation, and assessing endosperm proliferation as determinant of endosperm mass and storage capacity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Nutrient_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Nutrient_Accumulation is an Endosperm_Development comprising deposition of 15–30% proteins, 10–25% lipids, and carbohydrate reserves by dry weight in protein bodies and lipid bodies of cellular endosperm, extending over weeks 4–12 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "storage reserve accumulation | endosperm reserve deposition | nutrient storage | compound accumulation |+ Nährstoff-Akkumulation | Speicherreserven-Akkumulation | Endosperm-Reserven-Deposition | Nährstoffspeicherung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows nutrient accumulation during August-September Year N+1, with endosperm cells accumulating storage proteins 18-26% dry weight in protein bodies 1.8-3.4 micrometers diameter, lipids 14-22% in lipid bodies 0.7-1.4 micrometers, minor starch 6-12% in amyloplasts, progressive accumulation weeks 6-12 with peak rate 8-14% dry weight per week, final endosperm reserves supporting 3.8-4.6 mm embryo development and providing germination nutrition, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing endosperm storage accumulation",
  "editor_note": "Nutrient_Accumulation is second phase of Endosperm_Development, distinguished by storage reserve deposition. ||Represents weeks 4-12. ||Major reserves: proteins 15-30% (protein bodies 1-5 μm), lipids 10-25% (lipid bodies 0.5-2 μm), minor carbohydrates 5-15%. ||Accumulation rate 5-15% DW/week peak. ||Supports embryo development. ||Provides germination reserves. ||Duration ~8 weeks. ||Follows Endosperm_Proliferation. ||Precedes Endosperm_Maturation. ||Temperature 22-26°C optimal. || This reserve deposition phase occurs during mid-late summer to early autumn in August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, representing major endosperm accumulation period coordinating with embryo development. ||Accumulation mechanism involves storage compound biosynthesis from imported photosynthate, protein synthesis and deposition in protein bodies, lipid synthesis and storage in lipid bodies, possible carbohydrate accumulation including starch, organelle biogenesis creating storage compartments, and progressive accumulation establishing reserve levels supporting embryo and germination. ||Photosynthate import shows carbohydrates imported from parent plant through seed coat and funiculus, sucrose as major transported carbohydrate, import providing carbon and energy for biosynthesis, and import as substrate source for storage compound synthesis. ||Import pathway shows phloem delivery to seed, unloading in seed coat, transfer through integuments to endosperm, and endosperm cells taking up substrates for metabolism. ||Protein accumulation characteristics shows storage proteins as major endosperm reserves, typical protein content 15-30% endosperm dry weight varying with genotype and conditions, proteins synthesized on endoplasmic reticulum ribosomes, proteins packaged in protein storage vacuoles forming protein bodies, and proteins providing amino acid reserves. ||Storage protein types shows albumins as water-soluble proteins, globulins as salt-soluble proteins, protein composition balanced for nutritional value, and protein types characteristic of seed storage proteins. ||Protein biosynthesis shows amino acids incorporated into polypeptide chains, post-translational modifications including glycosylation possible, protein folding and oligomerization, and synthesized proteins targeted to protein bodies. ||Protein body formation shows protein storage vacuoles forming as specialized organelles, protein bodies 1-5 micrometers diameter in endosperm cells, proteins crystalline or amorphous within bodies, tonoplast membrane surrounding protein bodies, and protein bodies as protein storage compartments. ||Protein body characteristics shows bodies containing concentrated storage proteins, proteins densely packed, bodies stable during desiccation, proteins mobilized during germination through proteolysis, and protein bodies as efficient storage structures. ||Lipid accumulation characteristics shows lipids accumulating in endosperm though typically less than embryo cotyledon levels, lipid content 10-25% endosperm dry weight, triacylglycerols as major storage lipids, fatty acids similar to embryo including oleic and linoleic acids, lipids synthesized in endoplasmic reticulum, and lipids stored in lipid bodies. ||Lipid body formation shows lipid bodies budding from endoplasmic reticulum, lipid bodies 0.5-2 micrometers diameter, triacylglycerols in core, phospholipid monolayer and proteins at surface, and lipid bodies as lipid storage organelles. ||Lipid body characteristics shows bodies distributed in cytoplasm, stable lipid storage form, lipids mobilized during germination through lipolysis, and lipid bodies providing concentrated energy reserves. ||Carbohydrate accumulation shows possible starch accumulation though extent variable in grapevine endosperm, starch content often low possibly 5-15% when present, amyloplasts as starch storage organelles if present, other carbohydrates including cell wall polysaccharides, and carbohydrates as potential though minor reserves compared to proteins and lipids. ||Starch characteristics shows α-amylose and amylopectin as starch components if present, starch grains in amyloplasts, starch mobilized through amylase activity during germination, and starch as glucose polymer storage form. ||Cell wall polysaccharides shows cellulose, hemicelluloses, pectins in endosperm cell walls, cell walls structural not primarily storage, some mobilization possible during germination, and cell walls as structural carbohydrates. ||Minor components shows minerals, vitamins, phytic acid as phosphorus storage, phenolic compounds, and diverse metabolites contributing to endosperm composition. ||Accumulation timing shows accumulation initiating weeks 4-6 after proliferation, intensive accumulation weeks 6-12, accumulation slowing and completing weeks 12-14, and timing coordinating with embryo reserve accumulation. ||Accumulation rate shows progressive increase in storage compound content, typical accumulation 5-15% dry weight per week during peak accumulation, and rate determining final reserve levels. ||Subcellular organization shows endosperm cells packed with protein bodies, lipid bodies, possible amyloplasts, and storage organelles occupying most cell volume. ||Cell metabolism during accumulation shows active biosynthetic metabolism, high respiratory rate supporting synthesis, substantial ATP requirement for polymerization, and metabolism focused on reserve production. ||Nutrient support for embryo shows endosperm possibly transferring nutrients to developing embryo, transfer supporting embryo growth and reserve accumulation, transfer mechanisms including cellular connections or secretion-uptake, and support function as key endosperm role. ||Endosperm size during accumulation shows endosperm maintaining volume around developing embryo, endosperm tissue layer 100-500 micrometers thick surrounding embryo, and endosperm mass increasing from reserve accumulation. ||Endosperm composition shows protein, lipid, carbohydrate balance determining nutritional quality, balance varying with genotype and conditions, composition affecting germination vigor, and composition as seed quality determinant. ||Reserve quality shows factors including protein amino acid balance, fatty acid composition, mineral content affecting nutritional value and germination success, and quality determined by accumulation conditions. ||Environmental effects on accumulation include temperature affecting biosynthetic rate and final reserve levels, nutrient availability affecting accumulation quantity and quality, water availability supporting normal development, and favorable conditions maximizing reserve accumulation. ||Temperature effects shows optimal range 22-26°C supporting normal accumulation, suboptimal temperatures potentially reducing reserves, and temperature as accumulation rate factor. ||Nutrient availability shows adequate nitrogen supporting protein accumulation, adequate minerals supporting complete nutrition, and nutrition affecting reserve quality. ||The process represents second phase of endosperm development establishing storage reserves, following endosperm proliferation and preceding endosperm maturation. ||Duration approximately 8 weeks representing major accumulation weeks 4-12. ||Regional timing shows nutrient accumulation during August-September coordinating with embryo maturation. ||Viticultural significance includes representing endosperm storage reserve establishment, supporting embryo development through nutrient transfer, providing germination reserves, and determining seed nutritional quality. ||Research applications include analyzing storage compound biosynthesis and regulation, investigating accumulation patterns and organelle formation, evaluating environmental effects on reserve accumulation, quantifying endosperm composition and nutritional value, and assessing nutrient accumulation as seed quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Endosperm_Maturation": {
  "definition": "An Endosperm_Maturation is an Endosperm_Development characterized by completion of storage reserve accumulation, acquisition of desiccation tolerance, and metabolic quiescence in the endosperm by weeks 12–16 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "endosperm completion | final endosperm development | endosperm desiccation | maturation phase |+ Endosperm-Reifung | Endosperm-Vollendung | finale Endosperm-Entwicklung | Endosperm-Dehydratation",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows endosperm maturation during September-October Year N+1, with storage reserves completing accumulation reaching 22-27% proteins and 15-21% lipids dry weight, desiccation tolerance acquired through LEA proteins and protective sugars, metabolic activity declining toward quiescence, water content declining from 58% to 14% during weeks 12-16, mature endosperm firm and pale surrounding 3.6-4.4 mm embryo accounting for 48-56% seed volume, endosperm ready for germination mobilization providing nutrient support, under continental conditions of 18-24°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing endosperm maturation coordinating with seed maturation",
  "editor_note": "Endosperm_Maturation is third and final phase of Endosperm_Development, distinguished by maturation completion. ||Represents weeks 12-16. ||Reserve completion: proteins 18-28%, lipids 12-22%. ||Desiccation tolerance (LEA proteins, protective sugars). ||Water content 50-70% → 10-20%. ||Metabolic quiescence. ||Mature endosperm 40-60% seed volume surrounding embryo. ||Ready for germination mobilization. ||Duration ~4 weeks. ||Follows Nutrient_Accumulation. ||Completes Endosperm_Development. ||Coordinates with Embryo_Maturation and seed maturation. || This final endosperm development phase occurs during early-mid autumn in September-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing endosperm maturation completion within seed maturation. ||Maturation mechanism involves storage reserve accumulation completion, desiccation tolerance acquisition through protective molecule synthesis, metabolic activity decline toward dormant state, water loss during seed desiccation, structural changes preparing for desiccation and storage, and mature endosperm as stable tissue providing germination reserves. ||Reserve accumulation completion shows storage compounds reaching final levels weeks 12-16, protein content typically 18-28% dry weight at maturity, lipid content 12-22%, carbohydrates including structural and storage components, and completed reserves representing maximum accumulation. ||Final reserve composition shows balanced protein, lipid, carbohydrate composition determining nutritional value, composition varying with genotype and development conditions, reserves in stable storage forms in protein bodies and lipid bodies, and composition as seed quality characteristic. ||Reserve stability shows storage compounds stable during desiccation and storage, proteins and lipids in organelles protected, reserves mobilizable during germination, and stability essential for seed viability. ||Desiccation tolerance acquisition shows endosperm acquiring ability to survive water loss during seed maturation, late embryogenesis abundant LEA proteins possibly accumulating providing cellular protection, sugars including sucrose and raffinose oligosaccharides accumulating stabilizing cellular structures, and desiccation tolerance mechanisms enabling seed survival. ||Protective proteins shows LEA proteins and heat shock proteins possibly accumulating, proteins preventing cellular damage during dehydration, proteins stabilizing membranes and other proteins, and protective proteins as desiccation tolerance mechanisms. ||Protective sugars shows sugars replacing water in hydrogen bonding with membranes and proteins, sugars forming glasses vitrifying cytoplasm preventing crystallization damage, and sugars as important protectants during desiccation. ||Metabolic activity decline shows respiratory rate declining during maturation, biosynthetic activity decreasing as accumulation completes, gene expression shifting toward dormancy-associated patterns, and metabolism approaching quiescent dormant state. ||Respiratory decline shows oxygen consumption decreasing substantially, metabolic rate minimal in mature desiccated endosperm, quiescent metabolism enabling long-term storage, and respiration as metabolic activity indicator. ||Gene expression changes shows storage protein and lipid biosynthesis genes downregulating as accumulation completes, maturation and desiccation-associated genes upregulating, dormancy-related genes possibly expressed, and expression patterns reflecting maturation. ||Water content decline shows endosperm progressively desiccating during seed maturation weeks 12-18, water content declining from 50-70% during accumulation to 10-20% in mature dry seed, desiccation proceeding along with embryo water loss, and low moisture enabling seed storage and dormancy. ||Desiccation process shows water loss through seed coat and funiculus to parent plant and atmosphere, progressive dehydration over final maturation weeks, osmotic and metabolic changes accommodating water loss, and desiccation as controlled developmental process. ||Desiccation tolerance mechanisms shows cellular adaptations enabling survival at low moisture, membrane stabilization preventing fusion, protein protection preventing denaturation, and tolerance mechanisms essential for seed viability. ||Structural changes during maturation shows endosperm cells becoming compressed and dense as water lost, cell contents concentrated, protein and lipid bodies maintaining integrity, and structural changes characteristic of mature dry endosperm. ||Cell wall modifications shows possible cell wall changes during maturation, walls maintaining integrity during desiccation, walls affecting water relations, and wall properties important for mature tissue. ||Endosperm texture shows mature endosperm firm and hard in dry seed, tissue surrounding embryo as protective layer, texture affecting seed handling, and hardness from desiccation. ||Endosperm color shows endosperm pale to yellowish in mature seed, color from accumulated reserves and pigments, color as maturity indicator, and appearance characteristic of mature tissue. ||Endosperm in mature seed shows endosperm as persistent tissue surrounding embryo, endosperm accounting for 40-60% seed volume depending on embryo size and endosperm consumption, mature endosperm ready for mobilization during germination, and endosperm as stable reserve tissue. ||Maturation completion timing shows endosperm maturation largely completing by weeks 14-16 coordinating with embryo maturation and seed desiccation, timing varying with cultivar and environment, and completion as maturation endpoint. ||Mature endosperm characteristics shows tissue with completed reserves, desiccation tolerant able to survive low moisture, metabolically quiescent in dormant state, structurally stable for storage, and viable ready to support germination. ||Germination preparation shows mature endosperm reserves positioned for mobilization, hydrolytic enzymes synthesized or activated during germination degrading storage compounds, nutrients transported to growing seedling, and endosperm depletion during seedling establishment. ||Reserve mobilization shows proteins hydrolyzed to amino acids by proteases, lipids hydrolyzed to fatty acids and glycerol by lipases, fatty acids converted to sugars through β-oxidation and gluconeogenesis, carbohydrates hydrolyzed to sugars by carbohydrases, and mobilized nutrients supporting seedling growth. ||Endosperm function during germination shows endosperm as nutrient source for seedling until photosynthesis established, mobilization coordinated with seedling development, eventual endosperm depletion as reserves consumed, and endosperm role as temporary nutritive tissue. ||Environmental effects on maturation include temperature affecting maturation rate and completion timing, water availability affecting desiccation timing though process is developmentally controlled, and conditions affecting maturation coordinating with overall seed maturation. ||Temperature effects shows optimal range 20-26°C supporting normal maturation, temperature affecting maturation duration, and temperature as rate determinant. ||Maturation as seed completion shows endosperm maturation as component of overall seed maturation, coordinated completion with embryo maturation and seed coat maturation, and integrated maturation creating viable mature seed ready for dispersal. ||The process represents third and final phase of endosperm development completing nutritive tissue maturation, following nutrient accumulation. ||Duration approximately 4 weeks representing maturation completion weeks 12-16. ||Regional timing shows endosperm maturation during September-October completing seed development. ||Viticultural significance includes representing endosperm maturation completion, establishing viable nutritive tissue for germination, coordinating with embryo and seed maturation, and determining seed storage stability and germination capacity. ||Research applications include analyzing endosperm maturation regulation and mechanisms, investigating desiccation tolerance and protective mechanisms, evaluating metabolic decline and quiescence establishment, quantifying reserve stability and mobilization capacity, and assessing endosperm maturation as seed viability and germination vigor determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Seed_Coat_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Coat_Formation is a Seed_Development comprising the differentiation of ovule integuments into outer testa and inner tegmen layers with progressive lignification producing a hard impermeable protective structure, extending over 12–16 weeks post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "protective layer formation | seed covering development | integument differentiation | coat development |+ Samenschale-Bildung | Schutzschicht-Formation | Samenbedeckungs-Entwicklung | Integument-Differenzierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows seed coat formation during July-October Year N+1, with ovule integuments differentiating into seed coat following fertilization, outer integument cells developing into testa with radial elongation and secondary wall deposition 2.8-4.2 micrometers thickness, progressive lignification weeks 8-16 creating rigid structure, brown pigmentation developing from tan to dark brown, inner integument forming tegmen 25-45 micrometers thickness, mature seed coat 85-135 micrometers total thickness providing mechanical protection and impermeability with controlled permeability at hilum, hard smooth surface by week 16, under warm climate conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar completing seed coat maturation",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Coat_Formation represents protective layer development within Seed_Development. ||Subdivided into Integument_Development with ovule integuments differentiating (outer → testa, inner → tegmen), Testa_Lignification with outer layer lignifying and pigmenting brown, and Seed_Coat_Hardening completing structure. ||Duration 12-16 weeks. ||Mature coat 50-150 μm (testa 60-80%, tegmen 20-40%). ||Lignified, impermeable (except hilum/micropyle), hard brown. ||Mechanical and pathogen protection. ||Coordinates with embryo/endosperm development. ||Temperature 22-26°C optimal. || This protective structure formation process occurs during summer to early autumn in July-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing seed coat development from fertilization through mature seed. ||Seed coat formation mechanism involves integument development with ovule integuments differentiating into seed coat layers, testa lignification with outer integument lignifying creating hard outer layer, seed coat hardening with progressive structural maturation, pigmentation developing creating brown color, and mature coat providing protection and regulating seed physiology. ||Integument foundation shows ovule containing two integuments surrounding nucellus and embryo sac, outer integument 3-5 cell layers thick, inner integument 2-4 cell layers thick, integuments as precursors for seed coat development, and integument differentiation initiating following fertilization. ||Outer integument characteristics shows outer integument giving rise to testa outer seed coat, integument positioned at ovule exterior, cells undergoing differentiation and lignification, and outer layer as primary protective structure. ||Inner integument characteristics shows inner integument developing into tegmen inner seed coat layer, integument between testa and endosperm, cells differentiating though less lignified than testa, and inner layer as secondary coat component. ||Seed coat layer structure shows mature seed coat with distinct testa and tegmen layers, testa as outer brown lignified layer providing mechanical protection, tegmen as inner layer with less lignification, and two-layer structure characteristic of grapevine seeds. ||Testa development shows outer integument cells elongating radially, cells depositing secondary cell walls, lignin accumulating in walls creating rigidity, cells eventually dying leaving lignified walls as protective layer, and testa as major protective component. ||Testa cell wall thickening shows substantial secondary wall deposition, walls 2-5 micrometers thickness in mature testa, cellulose microfibrils embedded in lignin matrix, and thick walls providing mechanical strength. ||Lignification process shows phenolic precursors including monolignols synthesized, monolignols polymerized into lignin, lignin deposited in cell walls creating rigid structure, progressive lignification increasing wall rigidity, and lignification as key protective mechanism. ||Lignin characteristics shows complex phenolic polymer, lignin types including guaiacyl and syringyl lignin, lignin cross-linking with cell wall polysaccharides, and lignin providing impermeability and strength. ||Lignification timing shows lignification initiating during mid-seed development weeks 8-12, intensive lignification weeks 12-16, completion by seed maturation, and timing coordinating with embryo maturation. ||Testa pigmentation shows brown pigments including oxidized phenolics accumulating during lignification, pigments creating characteristic brown seed coat color, color darkening with maturation from tan to dark brown, and color as maturation indicator. ||Pigment development shows phenolic compounds oxidizing during maturation, enzymatic and non-enzymatic oxidation producing brown pigments, pigmentation correlating with lignification and hardening, and color indicating coat maturity. ||Tegmen development shows inner integument differentiating less extensively than outer, tegmen cells with primary and thinner secondary walls, tegmen less lignified and pigmented than testa, tegmen as inner protective and regulatory layer, and tegmen completing development during maturation. ||Tegmen function shows possible role in regulating water and solute movement to embryo and endosperm, tegmen as barrier though less impermeable than testa, and inner layer contributing to coat structure. ||Seed coat thickness shows mature seed coat typically 50-150 micrometers total thickness, testa accounting for 60-80% thickness as major layer, tegmen thinner 20-40% thickness, and coat thickness providing protection while enabling eventual germination. ||Coat impermeability shows lignified testa creating largely impermeable barrier to water and gases, impermeability preventing pathogen entry and regulating imbibition, controlled permeability at hilum and micropyle regions enabling eventual water uptake, and impermeability as protective function. ||Hilum characteristics shows hilum as seed attachment scar where funiculus detached, hilum region with less lignification enabling preferential water entry, hilum as water entry point during germination imbibition, and hilum as structural feature. ||Micropyle characteristics shows micropyle as small opening where pollen tube entered, micropyle region enabling gas exchange, possible water entry point though less than hilum, and micropyle as seed structural feature. ||Mechanical protection shows hard lignified coat protecting embryo and endosperm from mechanical damage, coat resisting compression and impact, protection essential for seed dispersal and storage, and mechanical strength as major coat function. ||Pathogen protection shows impermeable coat preventing fungal and bacterial entry, lignified structure resistant to degradation, coat protecting internal tissues during storage and until germination, and pathogen resistance as protection function. ||Desiccation protection shows coat reducing water loss rate from internal tissues, coat enabling controlled desiccation during seed maturation, coat maintaining low seed moisture during storage, and desiccation control as physiological function. ||Seed coat maturation shows progressive structural changes during final seed development weeks 12-18, lignification completing, coat hardening increasing rigidity, color darkening to mature brown, and maturation coordinating with embryo and endosperm maturation. ||Hardening process shows coat becoming increasingly rigid and hard, hardness from lignification and structural changes, mature coat requiring substantial force to fracture, and hardness as maturation outcome. ||Coat texture shows mature seed coat hard and smooth, coat surface with characteristic pattern from cell organization, texture affecting seed handling, and surface as seed characteristic. ||Environmental effects on seed coat formation include temperature affecting development rate with optimal 22-26°C supporting normal coat development, nutrient availability particularly phenolic precursors affecting lignification, water availability affecting normal development, and conditions affecting coat quality. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions promoting lignification and maturation, cool conditions potentially extending development, and temperature as rate factor. ||The process encompasses three sequential phases including integument development with ovule integuments differentiating into coat layers, testa lignification with outer layer lignifying and pigmenting, and seed coat hardening completing protective structure. ||Duration approximately 12-16 weeks representing coat development coordinating with seed maturation. ||Regional timing shows seed coat formation during July-October as protective layer develops. ||Viticultural significance includes representing protective structure formation essential for seed viability, enabling seed storage and dispersal, regulating seed hydration and germination, and determining seed physical characteristics. ||Research applications include analyzing seed coat development and regulation, investigating lignification mechanisms and regulation, evaluating coat permeability and protection functions, quantifying coat structure and composition, and assessing seed coat formation as seed protection and germination regulator.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 439-442"
},

  "Integument_Development": {
  "definition": "An Integument_Development is a Seed_Coat_Formation comprising the cellular differentiation of outer integument toward testa and inner integument toward tegmen establishing the layered coat architecture, extending over weeks 0–8 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "layer differentiation | integument to coat transition | coat layer formation | early coat development |+ Integument-Entwicklung | Schicht-Differenzierung | Integument-zu-Schale-Übergang | Schalen-Schicht-Formation",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows integument development during July-August Year N+1, with ovule integuments differentiating following fertilization, outer integument cells elongating radially 2.5-4 fold increasing from 15-25 to 45-75 micrometers length, cell expansion and possible divisions increasing tissue thickness, primary cell wall synthesis establishing structure, inner integument cells differentiating with limited expansion maintaining 12-22 micrometers dimensions, organized cellular layers establishing coat architecture, lignin biosynthesis genes beginning 2-5 fold upregulation by week 6-8 preparing for lignification, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar initiating seed coat development",
  "editor_note": "Integument_Development is first phase of Seed_Coat_Formation, distinguished by layer differentiation. ||Represents weeks 0-8. ||Ovule integuments (outer 3-5 layers, inner 2-4 layers) differentiate post-fertilization. ||Outer → testa (cell elongation 2-5 fold radially, expansion), Inner → tegmen (limited differentiation). ||Primary cell wall synthesis. ||Gene expression: coat-specific, lignin pathway genes beginning. ||Precedes Testa_Lignification. ||Establishes coat foundation. ||Temperature 22-28°C optimal. || This layer differentiation phase occurs during summer in July-August in temperate regions Year N+1, representing initial seed coat development. ||Development mechanism involves fertilization triggering integument differentiation from ovule protective layers to seed coat structures, outer integument cell elongation and expansion, inner integument cell differentiation though less extensive, cell wall synthesis establishing primary walls, and developmental programming directing coat formation. ||Ovule integument characteristics shows ovule containing two integuments surrounding nucellus and embryo sac prior to fertilization, outer integument typically 3-5 cell layers thick, inner integument 2-4 cell layers, integuments as protective envelopes around female gametophyte, and integuments as seed coat precursors. ||Outer integument pre-fertilization shows outer integument as outermost ovule layer, integument with parenchymatous cells, integument forming part of micropyle opening, and integument poised for differentiation. ||Inner integument pre-fertilization shows inner integument between outer integument and nucellus, thinner than outer integument, cells small and compact, and inner layer as secondary envelope. ||Fertilization trigger shows double fertilization initiating seed development, fertilization signaling integument differentiation, developmental shift from ovule protection to seed coat formation, and fertilization as developmental switch. ||Outer integument differentiation shows outer integument cells beginning expansion and elongation, cells elongating radially outward increasing integument thickness, cell division possibly occurring increasing cell number, and outer development establishing testa foundation. ||Cell elongation patterns shows cells elongating predominantly in radial direction, elongation increasing tissue thickness, elongated cells creating organized layer structure, and elongation as morphogenetic process. ||Cell expansion shows cell volume increase from water uptake and vacuole enlargement, cells expanding 2-5 fold from initial size, expansion without necessarily division, and expansion contributing to tissue growth. ||Cell division shows possible mitotic divisions in some integument regions, divisions increasing cell number, division patterns maintaining layer organization, and divisions contributing to tissue development. ||Outer integument cell fate shows cells programmed for testa differentiation, eventual cell wall thickening and lignification, cells eventually dying leaving lignified walls, and fate as outer protective layer. ||Inner integument differentiation shows inner integument cells undergoing differentiation though less extensive than outer, cells maintaining smaller size compared to outer integument, primary wall synthesis establishing cell structure, and inner layer developing toward tegmen. ||Inner integument fate shows cells forming tegmen inner coat layer, less extensive lignification than testa, cells maintaining viability longer than testa cells, and fate as inner layer. ||Cell wall synthesis shows primary cell wall deposition establishing cell structure, cellulose microfibrils and matrix polysaccharides synthesized, walls providing cellular integrity, and primary walls as foundation for subsequent secondary wall deposition. ||Cellulose synthesis shows cellulose synthase complexes in plasma membrane synthesizing cellulose microfibrils, microfibrils deposited in wall providing structural framework, and cellulose as major wall component. ||Matrix polysaccharides shows hemicelluloses and pectins synthesized and secreted, matrix filling spaces between microfibrils, matrix affecting wall properties, and polysaccharides as wall components. ||Tissue organization shows integuments developing organized cellular layers, cell files maintaining radial organization, tissue architecture establishing coat structure, and organization as developmental feature. ||Vascular development shows possible vascular traces extending into integuments supplying developing coat, vascular supply enabling nutrient and water delivery, and vasculature supporting development. ||Integument growth shows integuments enlarging to accommodate growing embryo and endosperm, integument growth coordinated with internal tissue development, eventual integument size determining seed coat dimensions, and growth establishing coat size. ||Differentiation timing shows differentiation initiating immediately post-fertilization, progressive differentiation over weeks 0-8, differentiation preparing for lignification phase, and timing as developmental progression. ||Differentiation molecular mechanisms shows gene expression changes directing integument to seed coat fate, transcription factors regulating coat development, hormonal signals possibly regulating differentiation, and molecular programs directing development. ||Gene expression shows coat-specific genes upregulating, genes encoding cell wall biosynthesis enzymes, lignin biosynthesis pathway genes beginning expression, and expression establishing coat program. ||Hormonal regulation shows auxin possibly involved in integument development, other hormones potentially regulating coat formation, and hormonal coordination of development. ||Environmental effects on integument development include temperature affecting development rate with optimal 22-28°C supporting normal differentiation, nutrient availability supporting cell growth and wall synthesis, and conditions affecting early coat development. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions promoting faster differentiation, cool conditions slowing development, and temperature as rate factor. ||The process represents first phase of seed coat formation establishing layer foundation, preceding testa lignification and seed coat hardening. ||Duration approximately 8 weeks representing early differentiation weeks 0-8. ||Regional timing shows integument development during July-August as coat begins formation. ||Viticultural significance includes representing seed coat initiation establishing protective structure foundation, determining coat architecture and cell organization, preparing for subsequent lignification creating protection, and establishing developmental basis for mature seed coat. ||Research applications include analyzing integument differentiation regulation and mechanisms, investigating cell fate determination and development, evaluating gene expression and molecular control, quantifying structural development and growth, and assessing integument development as seed coat formation foundation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Testa_Lignification": {
  "definition": "A Testa_Lignification is a Seed_Coat_Formation comprising deposition of lignin in secondary cell walls of testa cells with phenolic polymerization producing brown pigmentation and impermeable rigidity, extending over weeks 8–16 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "outer coat lignification | testa hardening | protective layer lignification | phenolic polymer deposition |+ Testa-Lignifizierung | äußere Schalen-Lignifizierung | Testa-Verhärtung | Schutzschicht-Lignifizierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows testa lignification during August-October Year N+1, with outer integument testa cells depositing secondary walls 2.6-4.4 micrometers thickness weeks 8-16, phenylpropanoid pathway producing monolignol precursors with PAL, C4H, 4CL, CAD enzyme activities increasing 5-15 fold, lignin polymerization through peroxidase-catalyzed radical coupling creating guaiacyl-syringyl lignin polymer, lignin content accumulating to 24-36% testa dry weight, brown pigmentation developing from tan to dark brown, testa cells dying leaving lignified walls, mature testa providing hard impermeable protective layer except at hilum, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar completing testa lignification",
  "editor_note": "Testa_Lignification is second phase of Seed_Coat_Formation, distinguished by lignin deposition. ||Represents weeks 8-16. ||Secondary walls 2-5 μm in testa cells. ||Phenylpropanoid pathway (PAL, C4H, 4CL, CAD) produces monolignols. ||Lignin polymerization creating 20-40% DW. ||Brown pigmentation from phenolic oxidation. ||Testa cell death. ||Creates impermeability (except hilum/micropyle), mechanical protection, rigidity. ||Follows Integument_Development. ||Precedes Seed_Coat_Hardening. ||Major protective structure formation. ||Temperature 22-26°C optimal. || This lignification and hardening phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in August-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing major seed coat protective structure development. ||Lignification mechanism involves secondary cell wall deposition in testa cells, monolignol precursor synthesis through phenylpropanoid pathway, monolignol transport to cell wall, lignin polymerization creating complex phenolic polymer, lignin cross-linking with wall polysaccharides, testa cell death leaving lignified walls as protective structure, and pigmentation from phenolic oxidation creating brown color. ||Testa cell characteristics shows outer integument cells differentiated into testa layer, cells elongated radially 40-80 micrometers length, cells depositing thick secondary walls, and testa as outer protective layer. ||Secondary cell wall deposition shows substantial wall material deposited inside primary wall, secondary walls 2-5 micrometers thickness in mature testa, wall deposition increasing cell wall mass 5-10 fold, walls composed of cellulose microfibrils embedded in lignin matrix, and secondary walls providing mechanical strength. ||Wall deposition timing shows secondary wall synthesis initiating weeks 6-8, intensive deposition weeks 8-14, completion by week 14-16, and timing coordinating with lignification. ||Cellulose in secondary walls shows cellulose microfibrils as structural framework, microfibrils oriented in organized patterns, cellulose providing tensile strength, and cellulose as major wall component. ||Lignin biosynthesis shows phenylpropanoid pathway producing monolignol precursors, pathway enzymes including phenylalanine ammonia lyase PAL, cinnamate 4-hydroxylase C4H, 4-coumarate CoA ligase 4CL, cinnamyl alcohol dehydrogenase CAD producing monolignols, and biosynthetic pathway as lignin precursor source. ||Monolignol types shows p-coumaryl alcohol, coniferyl alcohol, sinapyl alcohol as three major monolignols, monolignols differing in methoxylation degree, and monolignol composition affecting lignin properties. ||Monolignol transport shows monolignols synthesized in cytoplasm, monolignols transported across plasma membrane to apoplast, transport to cell wall for polymerization, and transport as biosynthesis step. ||Lignin polymerization shows monolignols polymerizing through radical coupling reactions in cell wall, peroxidases and laccases catalyzing oxidation and coupling, polymerization creating complex three-dimensional lignin polymer, progressive polymerization building lignin matrix, and polymerization as lignification mechanism. ||Lignin structure shows irregular heteropolymer with various linkage types, guaiacyl and syringyl lignin units in grapevine testa, lignin molecular weight very high molecular weight polymer, and structure providing rigidity. ||Lignin deposition pattern shows lignin deposited throughout secondary wall, lignin embedding cellulose microfibrils, lignin filling wall spaces creating dense matrix, and lignin distribution creating rigid structure. ||Lignin-polysaccharide cross-linking shows lignin covalently bonded to hemicelluloses and possibly pectins, cross-links increasing structural integrity, cross-linking creating integrated wall structure, and bonding enhancing rigidity. ||Lignification progression shows progressive lignin accumulation weeks 8-16, lignin content increasing from near-zero to 20-40% testa dry weight, increasing lignification correlating with hardening, and progressive accumulation creating protection. ||Lignification spatial pattern shows lignification initiating in outer testa cells, lignification progressing inward through testa layers, eventual lignification throughout testa, and centripetal pattern characteristic. ||Testa cell death shows testa cells eventually dying during or after lignification, cell death part of normal maturation, dead cells leaving lignified walls as protective structure, and programmed cell death as developmental process. ||Cell death timing shows cell death during late lignification weeks 14-16, eventual complete cell death by maturation, dead cells in mature seed coat, and death completing testa maturation. ||Pigmentation development shows brown pigments accumulating during lignification, pigments from phenolic compound oxidation, enzymatic oxidation through peroxidases and polyphenol oxidases, non-enzymatic oxidation possible, and pigmentation creating characteristic brown seed coat. ||Pigment characteristics shows brown to dark brown color, pigments including oxidized flavonoids, tannins, other phenolics, pigmentation intensity increasing with maturation, and color as maturation indicator. ||Color progression shows testa color changing from pale tan early to brown mid-maturation to dark brown mature, color darkening correlating with lignification degree, final color varying from medium to very dark brown depending on cultivar, and color as visual maturity marker. ||Testa impermeability shows lignified testa creating largely impermeable barrier, impermeability to water preventing uncontrolled imbibition, impermeability to gases regulating respiration, impermeability to pathogens preventing entry, and impermeability as protective function. ||Permeability control shows impermeability except at hilum and micropyle regions, hilum as preferential water entry site during germination, micropyle possibly enabling gas exchange, and controlled permeability enabling eventual germination. ||Mechanical protection shows lignified testa providing hard rigid structure, testa resisting mechanical damage from compression, impact, abrasion, protection essential for seed survival during dispersal and storage, and mechanical strength as primary protective function. ||Testa rigidity shows lignin-cellulose composite creating rigid structure, rigidity increasing with lignification degree, mature testa requiring substantial force to fracture or penetrate, and rigidity as protection mechanism. ||Chemical protection shows lignin resistant to microbial degradation, phenolic compounds possibly having antimicrobial properties, chemical protection preventing pathogen attack, and chemical resistance as protection. ||Environmental effects on testa lignification include temperature affecting lignification rate with optimal 22-26°C supporting normal progression, nutrient availability particularly phenolic precursors affecting lignin biosynthesis, light possibly affecting phenolic metabolism, and conditions affecting lignification quality and completion. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions promoting faster lignification and pigmentation, cool conditions potentially slowing lignification, and temperature as rate factor. ||Nutrient effects shows adequate nitrogen and minerals supporting phenolic biosynthesis, nutrient status affecting lignin quantity and quality, and nutrition as lignification factor. ||The process represents second phase of seed coat formation creating protective structure, following integument development and preceding seed coat hardening. ||Duration approximately 8 weeks representing major lignification weeks 8-16. ||Regional timing shows testa lignification during August-October as protective layer hardens. ||Viticultural significance includes representing primary protective structure formation, creating mechanical and pathogen protection enabling seed survival, regulating seed permeability affecting germination, and establishing seed coat physical characteristics determining seed quality. ||Research applications include analyzing lignification regulation and biosynthesis, investigating lignin structure and composition in seed coats, evaluating protective functions and permeability properties, quantifying lignification dynamics and completion, and assessing testa lignification as seed protection and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109"
},

  "Seed_Coat_Hardening": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Coat_Hardening is a Seed_Coat_Formation characterized by maximum coat rigidity, finalized impermeability, mature dark brown pigmentation, and completed tegmen development by weeks 14–18 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "coat maturation completion | final hardening | protective structure completion | coat finalization |+ Samenschale-Verhärtung | Schalen-Reifungs-Vollendung | finale Verhärtung | Schutzstruktur-Vollendung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows seed coat hardening during September-October Year N+1, with testa completing lignification reaching 28-34% dry weight lignin, coat rigidity increasing substantially achieving 68-92 N penetration resistance mature hardness, impermeability maximized with controlled permeability at hilum, brown pigmentation reaching mature dark brown color, tegmen completing development 22-38 micrometers thickness with 8-14% lignin, coat desiccating to 12-16% moisture compacting tissues, mature integrated coat 68-118 micrometers total thickness providing maximum mechanical and pathogen protection, under cool maritime conditions of 16-22°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar completing seed coat maturation by week 16-18",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Coat_Hardening is third and final phase of Seed_Coat_Formation, distinguished by final maturation. ||Represents weeks 14-18. ||Lignification completion 25-40% DW testa. ||Rigidity maximum (>50-100 N penetration resistance). ||Impermeability finalized (except hilum/micropyle). ||Dark brown pigmentation. ||Tegmen completion 15-40 μm (5-15% lignin). ||Coat desiccation 10-20% moisture, compaction. ||Mature coat 50-150 μm (testa 60-80%, tegmen 20-40%). ||Follows Testa_Lignification. ||Completes Seed_Coat_Formation. ||Maximum protection established. || This final hardening and maturation phase occurs during early-mid autumn in September-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing seed coat maturation completion coordinating with overall seed maturation. ||Hardening mechanism involves continued lignin cross-linking increasing structural integrity, possible additional lignin deposition completing accumulation, cell wall maturation and stabilization, coat desiccation removing moisture increasing density and hardness, structural compaction from water loss, and mature coat as maximally protective structure. ||Lignification completion shows lignin accumulation reaching final levels 25-40% testa dry weight, lignin polymerization completing creating fully cross-linked matrix, lignin distribution throughout testa uniform, and completed lignification as hardening foundation. ||Lignin cross-linking shows continued cross-link formation between lignin and wall polysaccharides, cross-linking increasing wall rigidity and integration, mature wall as highly cross-linked structure, and cross-linking as hardening mechanism. ||Cell wall maturation shows walls achieving final structural state, wall components stabilized in mature configuration, walls maximally rigid from lignification and cross-linking, and mature walls as protective structures. ||Coat rigidity increase shows progressive hardening as maturation proceeds, rigidity increasing substantially during final maturation weeks 14-18, mature coat requiring high force to fracture typically >50-100 N penetration resistance, and maximum rigidity as maturation outcome. ||Hardness measurement shows penetrometer or compression testing quantifying hardness, hardness increasing 3-5 fold from early to mature hardening, mature seed coat hard and resistant to deformation, and hardness as quantitative maturation indicator. ||Coat impermeability finalization shows impermeability maximized in mature coat, water permeability very low except at hilum, gas permeability minimal, impermeability preventing uncontrolled water uptake and pathogen entry, and impermeability as protection function. ||Impermeability testing shows water uptake measurements showing very low permeability, coat preventing rapid imbibition except through hilum, controlled permeability enabling eventual germination, and impermeability as coat characteristic. ||Hilum characteristics shows hilum region as controlled permeability site, hilum as seed attachment scar, hilum with less lignified cells enabling preferential water entry during germination, and hilum as functional feature. ||Micropyle characteristics shows micropyle as small pore region, possible gas exchange through micropyle, micropyle contributing to controlled permeability, and micropyle as structural feature. ||Brown pigmentation completion shows pigmentation reaching maximum intensity, mature seed coat medium to dark brown depending on cultivar, color from accumulated oxidized phenolics, color stable in mature dry seed, and dark brown as mature characteristic. ||Color stability shows mature pigmentation stable during seed storage, color indicating maturation state, color variation among cultivars from medium brown to nearly black, and color as seed identification feature. ||Tegmen maturation shows inner integument-derived tegmen completing development, tegmen as inner coat layer 15-40 micrometers thickness, tegmen less lignified than testa 5-15% lignin, tegmen cells possibly remaining alive in mature seed or dying, and tegmen as secondary protective layer. ||Tegmen structure shows tegmen cells smaller than testa cells, tegmen walls thinner with less secondary wall deposition, tegmen positioned between testa and endosperm, and tegmen as inner boundary. ||Coat layer integration shows testa and tegmen forming integrated two-layer structure, layers adhering through middle lamella, integrated coat functioning as unified protective structure, and layer integration as structural feature. ||Total coat thickness shows mature seed coat 50-150 micrometers total thickness varying with cultivar and position, testa accounting for 30-100 micrometers 60-80% total, tegmen 20-50 micrometers 20-40%, and thickness providing protection while enabling germination. ||Coat desiccation shows coat water content declining during final maturation, water loss increasing coat density, desiccated coat harder and more compact, coat moisture 10-20% in mature dry seed, and desiccation as hardening factor. ||Structural compaction shows coat tissues compacting as water removed, cell wall spaces reduced, coat density increasing, compaction contributing to hardness, and compaction as maturation change. ||Coat texture shows mature coat surface hard and smooth, surface with fine texture from cell organization, surface possibly glossy from lipids or cuticle, and texture as seed characteristic. ||Surface features shows possible surface sculpture or patterns from cell shapes, surface relatively smooth in grapevine, surface affecting seed handling and identification, and surface as morphological feature. ||Mechanical properties shows mature coat with high tensile strength, compression resistance, impact resistance, mechanical properties enabling seed survival during handling and storage, and mechanical protection as primary function. ||Protective function completion shows mature coat providing maximum protection from mechanical damage, desiccation, pathogens, and environmental stresses, protection enabling long-term seed storage and survival until germination, and protection as coat primary function. ||Coat maturation timing shows maturation completing by weeks 14-18 coordinating with embryo and endosperm maturation, timing varying slightly with cultivar and environment, mature coat in mature ready-to-disperse seed, and timing as developmental endpoint. ||Maturation completion indicators shows coat dark brown color, maximum hardness, complete impermeability, and indicators documenting maturation. ||Mature seed coat characteristics shows coat as hard rigid brown structure, coat 50-150 micrometers thickness, coat impermeable except at hilum, coat protecting embryo and endosperm, and coat enabling seed viability and storage. ||Environmental effects on hardening include temperature affecting maturation rate with optimal 20-26°C supporting normal hardening, humidity affecting desiccation with low humidity promoting faster drying and hardening, and environmental conditions affecting final coat properties. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating final maturation, cool conditions potentially extending hardening period, and temperature as rate factor. ||Humidity effects shows low humidity promoting coat desiccation and hardening, high humidity slowing desiccation, and humidity affecting hardening dynamics. ||The process represents third and final phase of seed coat formation completing protective structure, following integument development and testa lignification. ||Duration approximately 4 weeks representing final hardening weeks 14-18. ||Regional timing shows seed coat hardening during September-October as seed matures. ||Viticultural significance includes representing seed coat maturation completion, establishing maximum protective structure for seed storage and dispersal, enabling long-term seed viability, and determining final seed physical characteristics affecting handling and germination. ||Research applications include analyzing hardening mechanisms and regulation, investigating coat mechanical properties and protective functions, evaluating maturation dynamics and completion, quantifying coat structure and composition, and assessing seed coat hardening as seed protection and viability determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Seed_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Maturation is a Seed_Development comprising completion of reserve accumulation, acquisition of desiccation tolerance, dormancy establishment, and reduction of seed water content from 50–70% to 10–20%, extending over weeks 12–18 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "final seed development | seed maturation phase | seed completion | mature seed formation |+ Samenreifung | finale Samenentwicklung | Samenreifungsphase | Samen-Vollendung",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows seed maturation during September-October Year N+1, with embryo completing reserve accumulation 33-39% lipids and 28-34% proteins in cotyledons, endosperm completing 22-27% proteins and 14-20% lipids, LEA proteins accumulating providing desiccation tolerance, protective sugars sucrose 8-13% and raffinose 2-4% dry weight, progressive desiccation reducing water content from 58% to 12-16%, respiratory rate declining from 1.8 to <0.2 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, embryo dormancy established requiring 75-100 days stratification, abscisic acid 340-620 ng/g, seed coat hardening completing, mature seed 4.2-5.8 mm length weighing 24-38 mg, viable and ready for dispersal, under continental conditions of 18-24°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar completing seed maturation coordinating with berry ripening",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Maturation represents final seed development within Seed_Development. ||Subdivided into Embryo_Desiccation_Tolerance with LEA proteins and protective sugars, Seed_Dormancy_Acquisition with embryo dormancy and ABA (200-800 ng/g), and Seed_Ripening_Completion. ||Duration weeks 12-18. ||Reserves completed: embryo 30-40% lipids/25-35% proteins, endosperm 18-28% proteins/12-22% lipids. ||Desiccation 50-70% → 10-20% moisture. ||Respiration 1.5-2.5 → <0.1-0.3 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Dormancy requires stratification 60-120 days 1-5°C. ||Mature seed 4-7 mm, 20-50 mg, viable. ||Temperature 20-26°C optimal. || This final maturation phase occurs during early-mid autumn in September-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing seed development completion producing mature seed. ||Maturation mechanism involves storage reserve accumulation completion in embryo and endosperm, desiccation tolerance acquisition through protective molecule synthesis, metabolic activity decline toward dormant state, progressive desiccation reducing water content, possible dormancy imposition through abscisic acid and other mechanisms, seed coat hardening completing protection, and integrated maturation producing viable seed ready for dispersal. ||Reserve accumulation completion shows embryo cotyledons completing lipid and protein accumulation reaching 30-40% and 25-35% dry weight respectively, endosperm completing reserve accumulation 18-28% proteins and 12-22% lipids, total seed reserves adequate for germination and seedling establishment, and completed reserves as maturation outcome. ||Embryo reserve characteristics shows lipids as triacylglycerols in lipid bodies, proteins as albumins and globulins in protein bodies, reserves stored primarily in cotyledons, and reserves providing germination energy and nutrients. ||Endosperm reserve characteristics shows proteins and lipids in specialized organelles, endosperm surrounding embryo, endosperm reserves supporting embryo and seedling, and endosperm as nutritive tissue. ||Desiccation tolerance acquisition represents critical maturation process enabling seed survival at low moisture, late embryogenesis abundant LEA proteins accumulating in embryo and possibly endosperm, heat shock proteins possibly accumulating, protective sugars including sucrose and raffinose family oligosaccharides accumulating, desiccation tolerance mechanisms protecting cellular structures, and tolerance enabling seed storage. ||Late embryogenesis abundant proteins shows hydrophilic proteins accumulating during late maturation, LEA proteins protecting membranes and proteins during desiccation, proteins preventing aggregation and maintaining structure, multiple LEA protein families expressed, and LEA proteins as major desiccation protectants. ||Heat shock proteins shows HSPs possibly accumulating during maturation, chaperone proteins protecting other proteins, HSPs contributing to stress tolerance, and HSPs as cellular protectants. ||Protective sugar accumulation shows sucrose accumulating to high levels 5-15% dry weight, raffinose family oligosaccharides including raffinose, stachyose possibly accumulating, sugars replacing water in hydrogen bonding with membranes and proteins, sugars forming glasses vitrifying cytoplasm preventing crystallization, and sugars as essential desiccation protectants. ||Sugar protective mechanisms shows sugars stabilizing membranes during water loss, sugars preventing protein denaturation, glass formation at low moisture preventing cellular damage, and sugars enabling desiccation survival. ||Metabolic activity decline shows respiratory rate decreasing substantially during maturation, biosynthetic activity declining as reserve accumulation completes, gene expression shifting toward dormancy-associated patterns, and metabolism approaching quiescent state characteristic of mature dry seed. ||Respiratory decline shows oxygen consumption decreasing from maturation levels 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to very low mature seed <0.1-0.3 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, respiratory rate reduction enabling metabolic quiescence, quiescent metabolism enabling long-term storage, and respiration as metabolic activity indicator. ||Gene expression changes shows storage compound biosynthesis genes downregulating, maturation-associated genes including LEA and dormancy-related genes upregulating, developmental transcriptional program shifting toward quiescence, and expression changes implementing maturation. ||Progressive desiccation shows water content declining from 50-70% during mid-development to 30-40% late maturation to final 10-20% in mature dry seed, water loss through seed coat to parent plant initially then to atmosphere after abscission, controlled developmental desiccation distinguished from stress-induced dehydration, and low moisture as mature seed characteristic. ||Desiccation kinetics shows progressive water loss over maturation weeks 12-18, typical water loss rate 3-8% moisture per week, accelerated desiccation during final maturation, and desiccation timing coordinating with maturation completion. ||Water loss pathways shows water moving from seed through funiculus to berry while attached, water evaporating through coat after seed separation or berry drying, and water movement regulated by coat permeability and environmental conditions. ||Seed moisture measurement shows gravimetric water content determination through drying, mature seed moisture 10-20% fresh weight basis, moisture critical for storage stability, and moisture as maturation indicator. ||Seed dormancy acquisition shows many grapevine cultivars exhibiting seed dormancy requiring stratification for germination, dormancy mechanisms including embryo dormancy possibly from abscisic acid, coat-imposed dormancy from impermeability possible though less important than embryo dormancy, and dormancy preventing premature germination. ||Embryo dormancy shows embryo unable to germinate immediately after maturation, dormancy requiring cold stratification typically 60-120 days at 1-5°C for release, dormancy broken through stratification enabling germination, and embryo dormancy as primary dormancy type in grapevine. ||Abscisic acid role shows ABA possibly accumulating during late seed maturation, ABA levels possibly 200-800 ng/g dry weight in mature seed, ABA imposing or maintaining dormancy, ABA declining during stratification enabling germination, and ABA as dormancy hormone. ||Coat-imposed dormancy shows hard seed coat possibly contributing to dormancy through impermeability or mechanical resistance, coat effects generally secondary to embryo dormancy in grapevine, scarification not typically required though coat removal may accelerate germination, and coat as potential dormancy factor. ||Dormancy variation shows dormancy depth varying among cultivars, some cultivars showing weak dormancy germinating readily, others showing deep dormancy requiring extended stratification, and genetic variation affecting dormancy. ||Metabolic quiescence establishment shows metabolism declining to basal maintenance levels, quiescent seed capable of long-term storage, quiescence reversible through imbibition and germination conditions, and quiescence as dormant seed state. ||Seed coat hardening completion shows coat lignification and hardening completing during maturation, hard brown coat protecting mature seed, coat as covered in Seed_Coat_Formation, and coat completion coordinating with overall maturation. ||Seed appearance shows mature seed hard with brown to dark brown coat, seed typically 4-7 mm length and 3-5 mm width, seed fresh weight when mature 20-50 mg depending on development, seed shape ovoid to ellipsoid, and appearance as mature seed characteristic. ||Seed viability shows mature seed viable capable of germination when appropriate conditions provided, viability requiring complete development including reserve accumulation and desiccation tolerance, dormancy requiring release before germination, and viability as maturation outcome. ||Seed longevity shows mature seeds storable for extended periods, storage longevity depending on moisture and temperature, dry cool storage optimal typically 1-5°C and <10% moisture, proper storage enabling viability retention for years, and longevity as seed quality attribute. ||Storage conditions shows cool dry conditions optimal for maintaining viability, warm moist conditions accelerating deterioration, sealed storage preventing moisture gain, and storage management as post-maturation factor. ||Maturation timing shows maturation largely completing by weeks 16-18 post-fertilization, timing varying somewhat with cultivar and environment, maturation coordinating with berry ripening, and timing as developmental endpoint. ||Maturation completion indicators shows seed hard and brown, low moisture 10-20%, dormant if tested, and indicators documenting mature state. ||Mature seed characteristics shows seed with completed reserves, desiccation tolerant, dormant or germination-competent, hard brown coat, viable ready for dispersal, and mature seed as developmental outcome. ||Environmental effects on seed maturation include temperature affecting maturation rate with optimal 20-26°C supporting normal progression, humidity affecting desiccation with low humidity promoting drying, and conditions affecting maturation quality and timing. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating maturation, cool conditions extending maturation period, and temperature as rate determinant. ||Humidity effects shows low humidity promoting desiccation, high humidity slowing water loss potentially delaying maturation, and humidity affecting desiccation dynamics. ||The process encompasses three final sequential maturation phases including embryo desiccation tolerance acquisition, seed dormancy acquisition establishing germination control, and seed ripening completion finalizing maturation. ||Duration approximately 6 weeks representing final maturation weeks 12-18. ||Regional timing shows seed maturation during September-October completing seed development. ||Viticultural significance includes representing seed development completion producing viable seed, enabling seed storage and long-term viability, coordinating seed maturation with berry ripening and dispersal, and determining seed germination characteristics affecting propagation. ||Research applications include analyzing seed maturation regulation and mechanisms, investigating desiccation tolerance and protective molecules, evaluating dormancy mechanisms and regulation, quantifying maturation dynamics and completion, and assessing seed maturation as seed viability and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Embryo_Desiccation_Tolerance": {
  "definition": "An Embryo_Desiccation_Tolerance is a Seed_Maturation involving accumulation of LEA proteins, sucrose, and raffinose oligosaccharides stabilizing membranes and proteins enabling embryo survival at 10–20% moisture content, extending over weeks 12–16 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "dehydration tolerance | desiccation survival capacity | water loss tolerance | drought tolerance acquisition |+ Embryo-Austrocknungstoleranz | Dehydratations-Toleranz | Austrocknungs-Überlebenskapazität | Wasserverlust-Toleranz",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows embryo desiccation tolerance development during September-early October Year N+1, with LEA proteins accumulating to 8-16% total embryo protein including LEA 1, 2, 3 families, protective sugars accumulating with sucrose 7-12% and raffinose 2.8-4.6% dry weight, possible HSP70 and HSP90 heat shock proteins accumulating, embryo water content declining from 54% to 28% during tolerance acquisition weeks 12-15, full tolerance enabling survival at 12-16% final moisture, tolerance tested by artificial desiccation showing >85% germination after rehydration, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar developing desiccation tolerance enabling seed viability and storage",
  "editor_note": "Embryo_Desiccation_Tolerance is first aspect of Seed_Maturation, distinguished by survival capacity acquisition. ||Represents weeks 12-16. ||LEA proteins 5-20% total protein (multiple families) protecting membranes and proteins. ||Protective sugars: sucrose 5-15%, raffinose family 2-6% DW. ||Water replacement and glass formation mechanisms. ||Possible HSP accumulation. ||Embryo moisture 50-70% → 10-20%. ||Enables survival at low moisture, seed storage. ||Precedes Seed_Dormancy_Acquisition. ||Critical seed survival adaptation. ||Temperature 20-26°C optimal. || This dehydration tolerance acquisition phase occurs during early autumn in September-early October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing embryo protective capacity development. ||Tolerance acquisition mechanism involves late embryogenesis abundant protein synthesis and accumulation, protective sugar biosynthesis and accumulation, possible heat shock protein accumulation, membrane compositional changes possibly enhancing stability, cellular structural adaptations enabling low-moisture survival, and integrated protective systems enabling desiccation tolerance. ||Desiccation tolerance definition shows ability to survive water content reduction to very low levels 10-20% moisture, tolerance enabling seed survival during maturation desiccation and storage, tolerance reversible through imbibition during germination, and tolerance as seed-specific adaptation. ||Moisture reduction shows embryo water content declining from 50-70% during mid-development to 30-40% during early desiccation to final 10-20% in mature dry seed, substantial water loss requiring protective adaptations, desiccation occurring progressively during maturation, and low moisture as mature characteristic. ||Desiccation tolerance timing shows tolerance developing during late maturation weeks 12-16, tolerance acquisition preceding or accompanying desiccation, fully developed tolerance by maturation completion, and timing as developmental requirement. ||Late embryogenesis abundant protein accumulation shows LEA proteins as major desiccation protectants, multiple LEA protein families expressed including LEA 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, LEA proteins accumulating substantially during late embryogenesis, typical LEA protein content 5-20% total embryo protein in mature seed, and LEA proteins as characteristic seed proteins. ||LEA protein families shows diverse LEA protein types with different structures and functions, all LEA proteins hydrophilic with high proportion of charged and polar amino acids, LEA proteins lack ordered structure in solution but may fold during desiccation, and diversity providing comprehensive protection. ||LEA protein functions shows proteins protecting membranes during dehydration, proteins preventing protein aggregation, proteins acting as molecular chaperones, proteins stabilizing cellular structures, proteins binding water molecules, and multiple protective functions supporting desiccation survival. ||LEA protein gene expression shows LEA genes strongly upregulated during late maturation, abscisic acid inducing LEA gene expression, transcription factors regulating LEA expression, and expression as LEA accumulation mechanism. ||LEA protein localization shows LEA proteins distributed in cytoplasm, nucleus, possibly associated with membranes, and cellular distribution enabling protection. ||Protective sugar accumulation shows sucrose accumulating to high levels 5-15% embryo dry weight, raffinose family oligosaccharides including raffinose, stachyose possibly accumulating 2-6% dry weight, total soluble sugars 10-25% providing substantial protection, and sugars as essential desiccation protectants. ||Sucrose characteristics shows sucrose as non-reducing disaccharide, sucrose highly soluble and stable, sucrose as major transported and storage sugar, and sucrose as primary protective sugar. ||Raffinose family oligosaccharides shows raffinose as trisaccharide, stachyose as tetrasaccharide, RFOs synthesized from sucrose, RFOs particularly effective desiccation protectants, and RFOs as specialized protective sugars. ||Sugar protective mechanisms shows sugars replacing water in hydrogen bonding with membranes, sugars maintaining membrane spacing and fluidity, sugars preventing membrane fusion during dehydration, sugars stabilizing proteins preventing denaturation, sugars forming glasses at low moisture vitrifying cytoplasm, glass transition preventing crystallization and molecular mobility, and multiple mechanisms providing comprehensive protection. ||Water replacement hypothesis shows sugars substituting for water in hydrogen bonds with phospholipid headgroups, substitution maintaining membrane integrity, and replacement as membrane protection mechanism. ||Glass formation shows concentrated sugars forming highly viscous glassy state at low moisture, glass limiting molecular motion preventing damage, glass stabilizing cellular structures, and glass formation as critical protection mechanism. ||Heat shock protein possible accumulation shows HSPs possibly accumulating during late maturation, HSP70 and HSP90 families as molecular chaperones, HSPs protecting proteins from denaturation, HSPs assisting protein refolding, and HSPs as additional protective proteins. ||Membrane compositional changes shows possible phospholipid composition changes increasing membrane stability, possible increases in saturated fatty acids reducing fluidity, membrane adaptations enhancing desiccation tolerance, and membrane changes as structural protection. ||Cellular structural adaptations shows cells becoming highly concentrated during desiccation, organelles remaining intact through protective mechanisms, cytoplasm vitrifying in glassy state, cellular architecture preserved enabling rehydration, and structural maintenance essential for survival. ||Desiccation damage prevention shows protective mechanisms preventing protein denaturation, membrane fusion, DNA damage, oxidative damage, and structural disruption, prevention enabling embryo survival and germination capacity retention. ||Oxidative stress management shows antioxidant systems possibly upregulated, reactive oxygen species scavenging preventing damage, oxidative protection as component of desiccation tolerance, and antioxidants as protective molecules. ||Desiccation tolerance testing shows tolerance assayed by artificial desiccation and rehydration testing viability, tolerant embryos surviving desiccation to 10-20% moisture and recovering upon imbibition, tolerance quantified by germination or growth after desiccation, and testing enabling tolerance characterization. ||Tolerance development dynamics shows progressive tolerance acquisition during maturation, tolerance increasing as protective molecules accumulate, full tolerance achieved by maturation completion, and dynamics as developmental progression. ||Tolerance as seed characteristic shows desiccation tolerance distinguishing orthodox seeds like grapevine from recalcitrant seeds lacking tolerance, tolerance enabling dry seed storage, tolerance as adaptation for seed dispersal and survival, and tolerance as fundamental seed trait. ||Tolerance reversibility shows desiccation tolerance maintained in dry seed, imbibition reversing desiccation, rehydration enabling resumption of metabolism and germination, and reversibility enabling seed function. ||Storage stability shows desiccation-tolerant seeds storable long-term under appropriate conditions, dry cool storage maintaining viability, tolerance enabling seed banks and propagation, and stability as tolerance benefit. ||Environmental effects on tolerance acquisition include temperature affecting development rate with optimal 20-26°C supporting tolerance development, environmental stresses possibly enhancing tolerance, and conditions affecting protective molecule accumulation. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions supporting normal tolerance development, temperature affecting accumulation kinetics, and temperature as rate factor. ||The process represents first aspect of seed maturation establishing desiccation survival capacity, preceding seed dormancy acquisition and ripening completion. ||Duration tolerance acquisition during weeks 12-16 representing protective capacity development. ||Regional timing shows embryo desiccation tolerance development during September-early October as protection establishes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical seed survival mechanism enabling maturation and storage, determining seed storability and longevity, demonstrating seed adaptation to dispersal and dormancy, and establishing seed viability maintenance capacity. ||Research applications include analyzing desiccation tolerance mechanisms and regulation, investigating protective molecule functions and interactions, evaluating tolerance development dynamics, quantifying protective compound accumulation, and assessing desiccation tolerance as seed viability and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Seed_Dormancy_Acquisition": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Dormancy_Acquisition is a Seed_Maturation marked by establishment of metabolic blocks preventing germination with cold stratification requirement of 60–120 days at 1–5°C for release, extending over weeks 14–18 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy establishment | germination block | dormancy development | germination control |+ Samen-Dormanz-Erwerb | Dormanz-Etablierung | Keimungs-Blockierung | Dormanz-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows seed dormancy acquisition during late September-October Year N+1, with embryo developing deep dormancy preventing immediate germination, abscisic acid accumulating to 420-680 ng/g dry weight in mature embryo during weeks 14-18, germination inhibitor accumulation and metabolic blocks establishing, mature seed requiring 85-110 days cold stratification at 2-4°C for complete dormancy release, unstratified seeds showing <5% germination while stratified seeds germinating 78-92%, dormancy as adaptation preventing autumn germination ensuring winter passage before spring germination, under warm climate conditions of 22-28°C maturation temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar establishing dormancy for germination timing control",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Dormancy_Acquisition is second aspect of Seed_Maturation, distinguished by germination control establishment. ||Represents weeks 14-18. ||Embryo physiological dormancy (primary type). ||ABA accumulation possibly 200-800 ng/g. ||Metabolic blocks preventing germination. ||Requires stratification 60-120 days at 1-5°C for release. ||Dormancy depth varies by cultivar (weak to deep). ||Coat-imposed dormancy secondary. ||Adaptive significance: prevents premature germination, ensures spring germination. ||Follows Embryo_Desiccation_Tolerance. ||Precedes Seed_Ripening_Completion. ||Critical germination timing control. || This germination control establishment phase occurs during early-mid autumn in late September-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing embryo dormancy development. ||Dormancy acquisition mechanism involves embryo physiological state changes preventing germination, possible abscisic acid accumulation imposing dormancy, germination inhibitor accumulation or germination promoter deficiency, metabolic blocks preventing embryo growth, developmental arrest maintaining dormancy, and integrated dormancy mechanisms preventing premature germination. ||Seed dormancy definition shows inability to germinate under normally favorable conditions despite being viable, dormancy as block preventing germination even when water, oxygen, temperature adequate, dormancy requiring specific treatments for release, and dormancy as regulated developmental state. ||Dormancy types shows embryo dormancy as primary type in grapevine with embryo unable to germinate, coat-imposed dormancy possible but generally secondary from hard impermeable coat, physiological dormancy as classification with embryo physiological block, and dormancy type affecting release requirements. ||Embryo dormancy characteristics shows embryo in dormant non-germinative state in mature seed, embryo morphologically complete and viable but unable to grow, dormancy residing in embryo tissue not primarily coat, and embryo dormancy as grapevine characteristic. ||Dormancy depth shows dormancy intensity varying among cultivars, deep dormancy requiring extended stratification 90-120 days, intermediate dormancy requiring moderate stratification 60-90 days, weak dormancy with limited requirements 30-60 days or germinating readily, and dormancy depth as genetic variation. ||Cultivar variation shows different grapevine cultivars exhibiting varying dormancy depths, Vitis vinifera typically showing intermediate to deep dormancy, wild Vitis species possibly showing different patterns, and genetic control of dormancy intensity. ||Abscisic acid role shows ABA as hormone regulating dormancy in many species, ABA possibly accumulating during seed maturation in grapevine, ABA levels in mature seed possibly 200-800 ng/g dry weight, ABA imposing or maintaining dormancy through metabolic effects, ABA inhibiting germination-related processes, and ABA as major dormancy regulator though evidence in grapevine incomplete. ||ABA accumulation timing shows ABA synthesis possibly increasing during late maturation, ABA content rising weeks 14-18, peak ABA in mature dormant seed, and timing coordinating with dormancy establishment. ||ABA biosynthesis shows ABA synthesized through carotenoid pathway, zeaxanthin epoxidase and 9-cis-epoxycarotenoid dioxygenase NCED as key enzymes, biosynthesis in embryo and possibly other seed tissues, and synthesis as ABA accumulation mechanism. ||ABA effects on embryo shows ABA inhibiting embryo axis growth, ABA suppressing germination-related gene expression, ABA maintaining metabolic quiescence, and ABA as germination inhibitor. ||Germination inhibitor accumulation shows possible accumulation of other inhibitory compounds in embryo or seed, inhibitors preventing germination until removed or inactivated, and inhibitors as potential dormancy factors though less studied than ABA. ||Germination promoter deficiency shows germination potentially requiring gibberellins, cytokinins, other promoters, dormant embryo deficient in promoters, promoter deficiency contributing to germination block, and promoter balance as dormancy mechanism. ||Metabolic blocks shows metabolic pathways required for germination blocked in dormant embryo, blocks including respiratory limitations, biosynthetic capacity limitations, cell cycle progression blocks, and metabolic blocks preventing embryo growth. ||Respiratory capacity shows dormant embryo with limited respiratory capacity, respiration increasing during stratification and germination, respiratory limitation as potential dormancy mechanism, and respiration as metabolic indicator. ||Cell division block shows dormant embryo unable to resume cell division and growth, cell cycle arrest maintaining dormancy, release enabling cell cycle progression, and division block as dormancy mechanism. ||Developmental arrest shows embryo development paused in mature state, arrest preventing germination, arrest reversible through dormancy release, and arrest as dormancy state. ||Dormancy acquisition timing shows dormancy developing during late maturation weeks 14-18, dormancy established by seed maturation completion, dormant state in mature seed at dispersal, and timing as developmental endpoint. ||Stratification requirement shows cold stratification as primary dormancy release treatment, stratification typically 60-120 days at 1-5°C for complete dormancy release, cold treatment enabling subsequent germination at warm temperature, and stratification as release mechanism. ||Stratification effects shows stratification causing ABA decline and gibberellin increase, metabolic capacity increasing, embryo transitioning from dormant to germinative state, and stratification enabling subsequent germination. ||After-ripening possible role shows dry storage after-ripening possibly contributing to dormancy release in some seeds, after-ripening less important than stratification in grapevine, and after-ripening as additional factor. ||Coat-imposed dormancy possible shows hard seed coat possibly contributing to dormancy through mechanical resistance or impermeability, coat effects generally secondary to embryo dormancy in grapevine, scarification or coat removal not typically required though may accelerate germination, and coat as minor dormancy factor. ||Dormancy adaptive significance shows dormancy preventing germination immediately after seed maturation and dispersal in autumn, dormancy ensuring germination delayed until favorable spring conditions after winter cold, cold requirement ensuring winter passage before germination, and dormancy as adaptation to temperate climate seasonality. ||Ecological role shows dormancy synchronizing germination with spring after winter, dormancy preventing germination in autumn before harsh winter, and dormancy as survival mechanism. ||Dormancy assessment shows germination testing determining dormancy state, dormant seeds failing to germinate under favorable conditions, stratified seeds germinating readily, and germination as dormancy indicator. ||Germination after stratification shows stratified seeds germinating 70-95% under favorable conditions 20-25°C with moisture, germination demonstrating dormancy release, and germination as functional test. ||Environmental effects on dormancy acquisition include temperature during seed maturation possibly affecting dormancy depth, maturation conditions influencing ABA accumulation, and environmental factors affecting dormancy establishment. ||Temperature effects shows warm maturation possibly promoting dormancy development, temperature affecting dormancy depth, and temperature as maturation factor. ||The process represents second aspect of seed maturation establishing germination control, following embryo desiccation tolerance and preceding seed ripening completion. ||Duration dormancy acquisition during weeks 14-18 representing germination control establishment. ||Regional timing shows seed dormancy acquisition during late September-October as maturation completes. ||Viticultural significance includes representing germination timing control preventing premature germination, demonstrating adaptation to temperate seasonality, requiring stratification for seed propagation, and affecting germination success in viticulture and breeding. ||Research applications include analyzing dormancy mechanisms and regulation, investigating hormonal control particularly abscisic acid and gibberellins, evaluating stratification effects and release mechanisms, quantifying dormancy depth variation, and assessing dormancy acquisition as germination control determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Seed_Ripening_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Ripening_Completion is a Seed_Maturation characterized by minimum 10–20% moisture, maximum coat hardness, established dormancy, and metabolic quiescence with respiration below 0.1–0.3 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ by weeks 16–18 post-fertilization.",
  "alternative_term": "seed maturation completion | final seed development | mature seed formation | developmental completion |+ Samenreifungs-Vollendung | Samenreifungs-Abschluss | finale Samenentwicklung | Entwicklungs-Vollendung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows seed ripening completion during October Year N+1, with storage reserves finalized at 35-39% lipids and 29-34% proteins in embryo cotyledons, 21-26% proteins and 15-20% lipids in endosperm, complete desiccation reducing moisture to 11-15%, seed coat achieving maximum hardness 74-96 N penetration resistance with dark brown color, dormancy fully established requiring 90-115 days stratification, metabolic quiescence with respiration <0.15 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, mature seed 5.4-6.6 mm length weighing 36-48 mg, viability 88-94% after stratification, seed completing development by week 16-17 coordinating with berry full ripeness BBCH 89, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 22-28°C autumn temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar producing mature viable seed ready for dispersal",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Ripening_Completion is third and final aspect of Seed_Maturation, distinguished by developmental completion. ||Represents weeks 16-18. ||All processes concluded: reserves finalized (embryo 30-40% lipids/25-35% proteins, endosperm 18-28% proteins/12-22% lipids), desiccation complete 10-20% moisture, coat maximally hard dark brown, dormancy fully established, metabolic quiescence <0.1-0.3 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Mature seed 4-7 mm, 20-50 mg, viable >80-95%. ||Dispersal ready. ||Coordinates with berry ripeness. ||Follows Embryo_Desiccation_Tolerance and Seed_Dormancy_Acquisition. ||Completes Seed_Maturation and Seed_Development. ||Developmental endpoint. || This final completion phase occurs during mid autumn in October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing seed development endpoint producing mature dispersal-ready seed. ||Completion mechanism involves final storage reserve deposition reaching maximum levels, complete desiccation to final low moisture, seed coat maturation completing hardening and pigmentation, full dormancy establishment, metabolic activity declining to minimal quiescence, seed achieving mature state ready for dispersal, and integrated completion producing viable seed. ||Storage reserve finalization shows embryo reserves at maximum 30-40% lipids and 25-35% proteins in cotyledons, endosperm reserves at final 18-28% proteins and 12-22% lipids, total seed reserves adequate for germination and seedling establishment, reserves stable in dry seed, and reserve completion as maturation outcome. ||Reserve stability shows storage compounds stable during desiccation and dormancy, lipids and proteins in stable organized form in lipid bodies and protein bodies, reserves protected from degradation, stability enabling long-term viability, and stability as mature characteristic. ||Complete desiccation shows seed water content reaching final 10-20% fresh weight in mature seed, moisture at equilibrium with ambient humidity typically 10-15% at 50-60% relative humidity, very low moisture enabling metabolic quiescence and storage, moisture reduction from 50-70% to 10-20% representing 70-85% water loss, and low moisture as completion indicator. ||Final moisture characteristics shows moisture distributed throughout seed tissues, embryo and endosperm at similar low moisture, moisture enabling vitrification and metabolic arrest, moisture critical for storage stability, and moisture as key seed property. ||Seed coat maturation completion shows coat achieving maximum hardness typically >60-100 N penetration resistance, coat fully lignified with 25-40% lignin in testa, coat dark brown from complete pigmentation, coat providing maximum protection, and coat maturation as structural completion. ||Coat color finalization shows mature coat medium to dark brown depending on cultivar, color from accumulated oxidized phenolics, color stable in mature seed, color intensity as maturity indicator, and color as identification feature. ||Coat protective function shows mature coat providing mechanical protection from damage, impermeability preventing pathogen entry and controlling imbibition, coat enabling seed survival during dispersal and storage, and protection as coat function. ||Dormancy complete establishment shows dormancy fully established in mature seed, dormancy at maximum depth requiring full stratification for release, dormant state stable during storage, dormancy controlling germination timing, and dormancy completion as maturation feature. ||Dormancy in mature seed shows embryo in deeply dormant state, dormancy preventing germination until stratification, dormancy stable for months to years in storage, and dormancy as mature seed characteristic. ||Metabolic quiescence achievement shows respiratory rate declining to very low minimal levels <0.1-0.3 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in mature dry seed, biosynthetic activity essentially ceased, gene expression at basal levels with minimal transcription, metabolic activity adequate for maintenance only, and quiescence enabling storage. ||Respiratory characteristics shows mature seed respiration 50-100 fold lower than during active development, oxygen consumption minimal, respiration sufficient for viability maintenance, and low respiration as quiescence indicator. ||Metabolic maintenance shows minimal metabolism maintaining cellular integrity, repair processes possibly operating slowly, metabolism reversible through imbibition, and maintenance enabling viability retention. ||Seed physical characteristics shows mature seed 4-7 mm length and 3-5 mm width, seed fresh weight 20-50 mg, seed shape ovoid to ellipsoid, seed color dark brown, seed texture hard and smooth, and characteristics as mature seed features. ||Seed viability shows mature seed fully viable capable of germination after stratification, viability >80-95% in properly matured and stored seeds, viability as functional maturation outcome, and viability as seed quality measure. ||Viability testing shows germination tests after stratification determining viability, tetrazolium tests showing embryo viability, viability declining gradually during long-term storage, and testing enabling quality assessment. ||Seed longevity shows properly stored seeds maintaining viability for years, storage conditions critical with cool dry optimal, storage at 1-5°C and 5-10% moisture enabling extended longevity, suboptimal conditions reducing longevity, and longevity as storage characteristic. ||Seed dispersal readiness shows mature seed ready for dispersal by frugivory, seed coat protecting embryo during passage through digestive tract, seed survival enabling dispersal, and dispersal as ecological function. ||Berry ripening coordination shows seed maturation completing during or shortly before berry full ripeness, timing ensuring seeds mature when fruit attractive to frugivores, coordination as reproductive strategy, and timing as seed-fruit synchronization. ||Seed abscission shows seed possibly separating from funiculus during or after berry ripening, separated seed free within berry, abscission enabling dispersal, and separation as completion event. ||Completion timing shows ripening completion by weeks 16-18 post-fertilization, timing varying slightly with cultivar and environment, completion coordinating with berry maturation typically BBCH 87-89 berries ripe for harvest, and timing as developmental endpoint. ||Maturation completion indicators shows seed hard and dark brown, very low moisture 10-20%, dormant if tested, metabolic quiescence achieved, and indicators documenting completion. ||Mature seed properties shows seed with completed reserves, desiccation tolerant, dormant, hard brown coat, viable, and properties as developmental outcomes. ||Seed after maturation shows mature seed ready for dispersal and storage, seed maintaining viability during storage if conditions appropriate, seed capable of germination after stratification, and mature seed as completed developmental product. ||Environmental effects on completion include temperature affecting final maturation rate, humidity affecting final desiccation, and environmental conditions affecting completion timing and quality. ||Temperature effects shows warm autumn conditions promoting faster completion, cool conditions possibly extending final maturation, and temperature as rate factor. ||Humidity effects shows low humidity promoting final desiccation, high humidity slowing water loss, and humidity affecting final moisture. ||The process represents third and final aspect of seed maturation completing all development, following embryo desiccation tolerance and seed dormancy acquisition. ||Duration final completion during weeks 16-18 representing developmental endpoint. ||Regional timing shows seed ripening completion during October as mature seed produced. ||Viticultural significance includes representing seed development completion producing viable dispersal-ready seed, coordinating seed and berry maturation timing, enabling seed viability for propagation and breeding, and determining seed quality for storage and germination. ||Research applications include analyzing seed maturation completion and developmental regulation, investigating maturation coordination with berry ripening, evaluating seed quality and viability determinants, quantifying maturation timing and indicators, and assessing seed ripening completion as reproductive success determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1971) Reproductive anatomy in cultivated grapes, Am J Enol Vitic 22:92-109 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 441-442"
},

  "Veraison": {
  "definition": "A Veraison is a Berry_Development comprising berry softening, anthocyanin synthesis in red cultivars, accelerated phloem sugar import, organic acid decline, and resumed berry expansion, extending over 5–14 days within the cluster typically at weeks 8–12 post-fertilization corresponding to BBCH 83–85.",
  "alternative_term": "color change | ripening onset | berry transformation | veraison period |+ Véraison | Farbumschlag | Reifungsbeginn | Beeren-Transformation",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows veraison during late August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 83-85, with berry softening initiating with 12-22% firmness decline from 3.2 to 2.6 N, anthocyanin accumulation beginning 0.06-0.14 mg/g creating visible pink color at stylar end, sugar acceleration to 2.2% per week, malate declining from 0.85% to 0.72%, berry growth 14 mg per day, water uptake 0.48 g per berry per day, ABA spiking to 920 ng/g, veraison spreading over 8-12 days within cluster, occurring 9.5-10.5 weeks post-flowering at 1250-1350 GDD, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar beginning ripening transformation",
  "editor_note": "Veraison represents lag-to-ripening transition within Berry_Development. ||Characterized by berry softening (universal, 10-25% initial firmness decline), color development in red cultivars (anthocyanin 0.05-0.2 mg/g onset), sugar acceleration (1.5-3.5%/week), acid decline, berry expansion (10-30 mg/day), ABA spike (500-2000 ng/g). ||Duration 5-14 days cluster-level asynchrony. ||BBCH 83-85. ||Timing: GDD-triggered, weeks 8-12 post-fertilization. ||Subdivided into Berry_Softening (and other aspects). ||Critical developmental milestone determining harvest timing. ||Temperature dominant environmental factor. || This transformation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-September in temperate regions Year N+1, representing lag-to-ripening transition marking onset of berry ripening. ||Veraison mechanism involves berry softening through cell wall modification particularly pectin degradation creating first measurable firmness decline 10-25%, color development in red cultivars through anthocyanin biosynthesis creating visible pink to red color, sugar accumulation acceleration from hexose transporter activation increasing import 2-5 fold, organic acid decline from enhanced malate respiration, berry expansion from increased water uptake driven by osmotic gradient from sugars, abscisic acid spike coordinating or triggering transformation, and integrated changes establishing ripening metabolism and growth. ||Berry softening characteristics shows firmness declining from pre-veraison maximum 2.5-4.5 N to initial softening 2.0-3.5 N representing 10-25% decline, progressive softening continuing through ripening, softening as universal veraison marker occurring in all cultivars, softening from cell wall modification particularly pectin degradation in middle lamella and cell walls, and softening as defining transformation. ||Color development in red cultivars shows anthocyanin biosynthesis pathway activating, anthocyanin accumulation beginning with 0.05-0.2 mg/g at veraison onset increasing rapidly, visible color change from green to pink or light red, color typically initiating at stylar end progressing toward pedicel, color development as red cultivar veraison marker, and color from phenolic pigment synthesis. ||White cultivar veraison shows white cultivars lacking anthocyanin synthesis, veraison marked by softening and possible yellowing from chlorophyll decline, softening as primary visible marker, and white cultivar transformation without color development. ||Sugar accumulation acceleration shows sugar import increasing from lag minimal 0.5-1.5% per week to veraison-ripening 1.5-3.5% per week, hexose transporters activated from accumulated protein, phloem unloading enhanced, sugars increasing from 12-17% at veraison to progressive accumulation, and sugar increase as ripening characteristic. ||Organic acid decline shows malate respiration increasing, malate declining from 0.7-1.0% at veraison onset, tartrate relatively stable, pH rising from 3.1-3.4 toward ripening values, and acid dynamics characteristic of ripening onset. ||Berry expansion resumption shows berry growth rate increasing from lag minimal <5 mg per day to veraison-ripening 10-30 mg per day, water uptake accelerating from <0.1 to 0.3-0.8 g per berry per day, osmotic gradient from sugars driving water influx, berry volume increasing 5-15% during veraison period, and expansion marking lag phase exit. ||Abscisic acid dynamics shows ABA spiking from lag levels 50-200 ng/g to veraison peak 500-2000 ng/g, ABA as veraison trigger or correlate, hormone coordinating transformation, ABA possibly regulating gene expression and metabolism, and ABA spike as hormonal signature. ||Metabolic transformation shows respiratory rate increasing from lag 1.0-1.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to ripening 1.5-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, carbon flux redirected to ripening processes including anthocyanin and sugar metabolism, secondary metabolism intensified, and metabolic shift establishing ripening state. ||Gene expression changes shows ripening genes highly upregulated including anthocyanin pathway, sugar transporters, softening enzymes, ripening transcription factors activating target genes, and expression establishing ripening program. ||Veraison timing shows onset typically weeks 8-12 post-fertilization varying with cultivar and environment, early cultivars showing veraison 7-9 weeks, mid-season 9-11 weeks, late cultivars 11-14 weeks, and timing determining harvest date. ||Heat accumulation triggering shows growing degree days from flowering to veraison as major timing determinant, cultivar-specific GDD thresholds triggering veraison, warm conditions advancing veraison, cool conditions delaying, and temperature as primary timing factor. ||Veraison asynchrony shows veraison beginning in earliest berries while others remain in lag, typical within-cluster veraison spread 5-14 days, asynchrony creating heterogeneous berry populations, earliest berries at stylar cluster positions often, and asynchrony as characteristic pattern. ||Cluster veraison progression shows progressive transformation wave through cluster, earliest 10-20% berries showing veraison at onset, 50% veraison midpoint used as cluster veraison date, eventual 80-95% berries transformed, and progression over days to weeks. ||Berry appearance at veraison shows berries softening to touch, red cultivars showing pink to red color development, white cultivars possibly showing yellowing, berry size increasing, and appearance indicating transformation. ||Veraison assessment shows visual observation of color and softening, firmness measurement quantifying softening, sugar and acid analysis showing compositional changes, and measurements characterizing veraison. ||BBCH staging shows BBCH 81 late lag pre-veraison, BBCH 83 berries beginning to develop color in red or berries beginning to soften in white as veraison onset, BBCH 85 softening of berries as advanced veraison, and staging documenting progression. ||Environmental effects on veraison include temperature as dominant factor with GDD threshold triggering onset, water stress possibly advancing veraison through ABA, light possibly affecting anthocyanin synthesis, and environmental factors determining timing and quality. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions advancing veraison 7-14 days, cool conditions delaying comparable period, and temperature affecting cluster uniformity. ||Water stress effects shows moderate deficit possibly advancing veraison 3-7 days through enhanced ABA, severe stress potentially disrupting development, and stress as timing factor. ||Veraison significance shows transition marking lag phase end and ripening onset, determining harvest timing from veraison date, establishing berry composition trajectory toward maturity, critical quality determinant, and major developmental milestone. ||Viticultural management shows veraison timing determining harvest planning, cluster thinning often at veraison, deficit irrigation possibly managing veraison timing, and management affecting veraison and quality. ||The process encompasses berry softening with initial and progressive phases, alongside color development in red cultivars covered separately, sugar and acid dynamics, and berry expansion. ||Duration veraison transformation over 5-14 days at cluster level with individual berry transformation over 2-5 days. ||Regional timing shows veraison during late August-September in temperate climates varying with cultivar and season. ||Viticultural significance includes representing critical developmental transition determining ripening onset and harvest date, establishing berry quality trajectory, demonstrating environmental sensitivity particularly temperature, and serving as major vineyard monitoring milestone. ||Research applications include analyzing veraison triggering mechanisms and regulation, investigating hormonal control particularly abscisic acid, evaluating environmental effects on timing and uniformity, quantifying transformation dynamics and asynchrony, and assessing veraison as determinant of ripening progression and harvest quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## viticulture-specific transition phase, no equivalent in generic plant ontologies" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 468-485 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 || Coombe BG (1995) Adoption of a system for identifying grapevine growth stages, Aust J Grape Wine Res 1:104-110"
},

  "Berry_Softening": {
  "definition": "A Berry_Softening is a Veraison consisting of cell wall structural modification producing 40–70% total firmness decline by full ripeness, occurring in all cultivars as a universal véraison marker.",
  "alternative_term": "texture transformation | firmness decline | berry texture change | softening process |+ Beeren-Erweichung | Textur-Transformation | Festigkeits-Abnahme | Beeren-Textur-Änderung",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows berry softening during late August-September Year N+1 at BBCH 83-85, with initial softening showing 14-20% firmness decline from 2.8 to 2.3 N over 4-6 days at veraison onset, polygalacturonase activity increasing from 8 to 32 units, pectin methylesterase from 12 to 42 units, water-soluble pectin increasing from 22% to 45% total pectin, progressive softening continuing through ripening with eventual 52-64% total firmness decline to 1.2-1.6 N, pectin molecular weight declining from 180 kDa to 45 kDa, middle lamella degradation weakening cell adhesion, under cool maritime conditions of 16-22°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting white cultivar showing softening as primary veraison marker",
  "editor_note": "Berry_Softening represents texture transformation within Veraison. ||Universal veraison marker (all cultivars). ||Subdivided into Initial_Berry_Softening (first 10-25% decline, cell wall modification onset, turgor changes) and Progressive_Softening (continued degradation, 40-70% total decline). ||Mechanism: pectin degradation (PG, PME primary), middle lamella degradation, cell-cell adhesion weakening. ||Turgor changes minor. ||Firmness 2.5-4.5 → 2.0-3.5 N initial → 1.0-2.5 N ripe. ||Duration veraison through ripening. ||Temperature affects rate. ||Critical quality and handling determinant. || This texture transformation process occurs during late summer through autumn in late August-October in temperate regions Year N+1, spanning veraison onset through ripening representing major textural change. ||Softening mechanism involves cell wall modification particularly pectin degradation through polygalacturonase and pectin methylesterase activities, middle lamella degradation weakening cell-cell adhesion, cell wall structural changes reducing firmness, possible minor turgor pressure changes though less important than structural modifications, progressive texture change from hard firm to soft yielding, and integrated changes creating characteristic ripe berry texture. ||Firmness decline trajectory shows firmness decreasing from pre-veraison maximum 2.5-4.5 N penetrometer resistance to initial softening 2.0-3.5 N representing 10-25% decline at veraison onset, progressive decline during ripening to 1.0-2.5 N representing 40-70% total reduction, eventual soft texture at full ripeness, and firmness decline as quantitative softening measure. ||Penetrometer measurement shows force required to penetrate berry skin and flesh declining with softening, measurement quantifying texture objectively, typical measurement using 2-5 mm diameter probe, and penetrometer as standard firmness assessment. ||Compression testing shows force required to compress berry declining, compression resistance decreasing 30-60% from pre-veraison to ripe, and compression as alternative firmness measure. ||Subjective texture shows berry tactilely harder pre-veraison, becoming noticeably softer at veraison, progressively more yielding through ripening, eventual soft pliable texture at maturity, and subjective assessment as practical evaluation. ||Cell wall modification shows pectin-degrading enzyme activation at veraison onset, enzymes including polygalacturonase PG, pectin methylesterase PME, pectate lyase PL, expansins possibly contributing, enzyme activities increasing substantially during veraison and ripening, and enzymatic modification as primary softening mechanism. ||Polygalacturonase activity shows PG cleaving homogalacturonan pectin backbone, PG activity increasing 5-20 fold from pre-veraison to veraison-ripening, PG activity correlating strongly with firmness decline, and PG as major softening enzyme. ||Pectin methylesterase activity shows PME demethylating pectin creating substrate for PG, PME activity increasing 3-10 fold, PME role complex with initial cross-linking possible then degradation facilitation, and PME as pectin modification enzyme. ||Pectate lyase possible role shows PL cleaving pectin through β-elimination, PL possibly contributing to degradation, activity variable by cultivar, and PL as additional enzyme. ||Expansin possible role shows expansins possibly contributing to wall loosening, expansin expression increasing during ripening in some studies, role less clear than pectinases, and expansins as potential contributors. ||Pectin structural changes shows pectin molecular weight declining from enzyme degradation, high molecular weight pectin 100-300 kDa at pre-veraison declining to lower 20-100 kDa fragments during ripening, depolymerization reducing structural integrity, and pectin degradation as softening basis. ||Pectin solubilization shows water-soluble pectin fraction increasing from degradation, insoluble cell wall pectin declining, soluble pectin as degradation product marker, and solubilization weakening structure. ||Middle lamella degradation shows pectin-rich middle lamella between cells degrading, degradation weakening cell-cell adhesion, cells becoming less firmly attached, possible cell separation in some cases, and middle lamella as critical adhesion site. ||Cell-cell adhesion weakening shows reduced intercellular bonding from middle lamella loss, tissue disaggregation potential increasing, texture becoming less coherent, and adhesion loss contributing to softness. ||Cell wall other changes shows possible hemicellulose modifications though minor compared to pectin, cellulose framework remaining largely intact, overall wall structure weakening, and integrated wall changes creating softening. ||Turgor pressure possible changes shows turgor possibly declining slightly during ripening from altered water relations, turgor changes generally minor 10-20% compared to cell wall structural changes 50-80% contribution to softening, turgor role secondary to structural modifications, and turgor as minor softening factor. ||Water relations shows berry water content relatively stable or slightly increasing during ripening, water influx from sugar osmotic gradient, water distribution possibly changing, and water affecting turgor and texture. ||Softening as universal marker shows softening occurring in all grapevine cultivars at veraison, universal marker unlike color which is red cultivar-specific, softening defining veraison in white cultivars, and universality making softening critical veraison indicator. ||Softening timing shows initiation at veraison onset coinciding with or following first visible color in red cultivars, rapid initial softening over first days of veraison, continued progressive softening through ripening weeks, and timing coordinating with overall transformation. ||Softening rate shows rapid initial firmness decline 10-25% over first 3-7 days veraison, slower continued decline during ripening 1-3% per day, eventual plateau at soft ripe texture, and rate pattern characteristic of transformation. ||Cultivar variation shows firmness levels and decline rates varying among cultivars, some cultivars maintaining firmer texture longer, others softening more rapidly, final ripe firmness varying 1.0-2.5 N, and genetic variation affecting softening. ||Berry handling implications shows softer berries more susceptible to mechanical damage, softening affecting harvest timing and handling, disease susceptibility potentially increasing with softening from easier pathogen penetration, and softening as practical concern. ||Sensory implications shows texture as important quality attribute, consumer preference varying with application, table grapes requiring firmness while wine grapes soften fully, and texture affecting acceptability. ||Wine quality implications shows softening affecting crushing and pressing, soft berries releasing juice more readily, texture influencing extraction during fermentation, and softening affecting processing. ||Environmental effects on softening include temperature affecting softening rate with warm conditions promoting faster softening and cool conditions slowing, water availability affecting berry turgor and softening dynamics, and environmental factors influencing softening progression. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating enzymatic activities and firmness decline, cool conditions slowing softening rate, and temperature as rate factor. ||The process encompasses two sequential softening phases including initial berry softening with first firmness decline from cell wall modification onset, and progressive softening with continued degradation and increasing pliability. ||Duration softening initiating at veraison over 3-7 days initial decline then continuing through ripening 4-8 weeks total. ||Regional timing shows berry softening during late August-October from veraison through harvest. ||Viticultural significance includes representing universal veraison marker defining transformation across cultivars, determining berry texture affecting quality and handling, demonstrating cell wall modification as primary ripening process, and influencing harvest timing and berry management. ||Research applications include analyzing cell wall modification enzymes and regulation, investigating pectin degradation mechanisms and dynamics, evaluating softening genetics and cultivar variation, quantifying firmness decline and texture changes, and assessing berry softening as quality determinant and veraison marker.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 475-485 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Initial_Berry_Softening": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Berry_Softening is a Berry_Softening marked by firmness decline from pre-véraison 2.5–4.5 N to 2.0–3.5 N (10–25% reduction) through cell wall modification onset and pectin solubilization, extending over 3–7 days at véraison onset.",
  "alternative_term": "first softening | veraison softening onset | initial firmness decline | early softening |+ anfängliche Beeren-Erweichung | erste Erweichung | Veraison-Erweichungs-Beginn | initiale Festigkeits-Abnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows initial berry softening during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 83, with firmness declining 16-22% from 3.4 to 2.7 N over 4-6 days at veraison onset, polygalacturonase activity increasing from 11 to 28 units, pectin methylesterase from 18 to 38 units, water-soluble pectin increasing from 24% to 42% total pectin, pectin molecular weight declining from 210 to 140 kDa, middle lamella beginning degradation weakening cell adhesion, possible minor turgor decline 10-12%, rapid initial softening 3.2% firmness per day, under oceanic conditions of 20-26°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar initiating veraison texture transformation",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Berry_Softening is first phase of Berry_Softening, distinguished by first firmness decline. ||Represents 3-7 days at veraison onset. ||Firmness decline 10-25% (2.5-4.5 → 2.0-3.5 N). ||Subdivided into Cell_Wall_Modification_Onset (PG, PME activation), Pectin_Solubilization_Start (20-30% → 35-50% soluble), Turgor_Reduction_Initiation (minor, 10-15% decline). ||Rapid rate 2-4%/day. ||Universal veraison marker. ||Preceded by lag phase. ||Followed by Progressive_Softening. ||Temperature affects enzyme activation. || This first softening phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, representing veraison onset texture change. ||Initial softening mechanism involves cell wall modification onset with polygalacturonase and pectin methylesterase activation beginning pectin degradation, pectin solubilization start with insoluble pectin converting to soluble forms, middle lamella beginning degradation weakening cell adhesion, possible minor turgor pressure reduction though contribution less than structural changes, and rapid initial firmness decline creating detectable softness. ||Firmness decline characteristics shows firmness declining from pre-veraison maximum typically 2.5-4.5 N penetrometer resistance to initial softening 2.0-3.5 N representing 10-25% decline, typical decline 15-20% average, rapid decline over first 3-7 days veraison, and initial decline as first measurable softening. ||Pre-veraison firmness shows berry at maximum firmness during late lag phase, firmness from turgid cells with rigid cell walls, hard texture resistant to deformation, and peak firmness as pre-softening state. ||Firmness measurement shows penetrometer force recording objective firmness, measurements documenting initial decline, typical penetrometer probe 2-5 mm diameter, force in Newtons N, and measurement as quantitative assessment. ||Initial softening detection shows firmness decline detectable by instrumentation and trained sensory assessment, berries becoming noticeably softer to tactile evaluation, softening coinciding with or slightly following first visible color in red cultivars, and detection as softening indicator. ||Softening rate during initial phase shows rapid decline 2-4% firmness per day over initial 3-7 days, faster than subsequent ripening softening rate, rapid initial change characteristic of veraison transformation, and rate as initial phase feature. ||Cell wall modification onset shows pectin-degrading enzyme activation at veraison onset, enzymes including polygalacturonase PG and pectin methylesterase PME beginning activity increase, enzyme activation as softening mechanism, and enzymatic modification initiating structural change. ||Polygalacturonase activation shows PG activity increasing from low pre-veraison levels 5-15 units to initial softening 15-40 units, PG cleaving homogalacturonan pectin backbone, PG as major softening enzyme, and PG activation as critical event. ||PG expression and activity shows PG genes upregulated during late lag and veraison, PG protein accumulating, enzyme activity increasing substantially, and gene-protein-activity cascade as mechanism. ||Pectin methylesterase activation shows PME activity increasing from pre-veraison 10-25 units to initial 25-50 units, PME demethylating pectin creating PG substrate, PME as pectin modification enzyme, and PME activation enabling PG action. ||PME function shows PME removing methyl groups from pectin, demethylated pectin accessible to PG cleavage, PME possibly creating calcium cross-links initially before degradation, and PME as regulatory enzyme. ||Pectate lyase possible activation shows PL possibly beginning activity increase, PL contributing to pectin cleavage through different mechanism than PG, PL role variable, and PL as additional enzyme. ||Expansin possible role shows expansins possibly contributing to wall loosening, expansin expression possibly increasing, contribution less certain than pectinases, and expansins as potential wall modifiers. ||Pectin structural changes shows pectin molecular weight beginning decline from enzyme cleavage, initial depolymerization fragmenting pectin chains, molecular weight declining from pre-veraison 150-300 kDa to initial 100-200 kDa, and depolymerization initiating structural weakening. ||Pectin solubilization start shows water-soluble pectin fraction beginning increase, insoluble cell wall pectin declining, soluble pectin increasing from 20-30% to 35-50% total pectin during initial softening, and solubilization as degradation indicator. ||Soluble vs insoluble pectin shows soluble pectin as degradation products released from walls, insoluble pectin as structural wall-bound pectin, ratio shift indicating degradation degree, and solubilization weakening structure. ||Middle lamella beginning degradation shows pectin-rich middle lamella between cells beginning enzymatic attack, middle lamella degradation weakening cell-cell adhesion, adhesion loss contributing to softening, and middle lamella as critical target. ||Cell-cell adhesion beginning weakening shows intercellular bonding reduced from middle lamella pectin loss, cells becoming less firmly attached, tissue coherence declining, and adhesion weakening as softening mechanism. ||Turgor reduction possible initiation shows turgor pressure possibly declining slightly during initial softening, turgor changes minor compared to structural changes, turgor possibly 0.5-0.8 MPa pre-veraison declining to 0.4-0.7 MPa initial softening representing 10-15% reduction, and turgor as minor factor. ||Turgor role assessment shows structural wall changes primary softening cause contributing 70-85% firmness decline, turgor changes secondary contributing 15-30%, and structural dominance as softening basis. ||Water relations shows berry water content stable or slightly increasing, water uptake from sugar osmotic gradient, water affecting turgor but not primary softening driver, and water as background factor. ||Berry appearance shows berries becoming noticeably softer to touch, texture yielding more readily to pressure, visual appearance possibly showing slight gloss from surface changes, and appearance indicating softening. ||Tactile assessment shows trained evaluators detecting softness increase, berries less resistant to gentle compression, texture change perceptible, and tactile as practical evaluation. ||Softening timing shows initiation at veraison onset typically coinciding with or within 1-2 days of first color in red cultivars or concurrent with metabolic changes in white cultivars, timing marking veraison onset, and timing as transformation indicator. ||Softening coordination shows softening coordinated with other veraison changes including color development in red cultivars, sugar acceleration, acid decline, berry expansion, and coordinated transformation as integrated process. ||Environmental effects on initial softening include temperature affecting enzyme activation and activity with warm conditions promoting faster softening, water availability affecting turgor and berry hydration, and environmental factors influencing softening dynamics. ||Temperature effects shows warm conditions accelerating enzyme activities and firmness decline, cool conditions slowing initial softening, and temperature as rate factor. ||The process encompasses three concurrent initial softening aspects including cell wall modification onset with enzyme activation, pectin solubilization start with structural changes, and turgor reduction initiation though minor. ||Duration initial softening over 3-7 days representing first firmness decline at veraison. ||Regional timing shows initial berry softening during late August-early September at veraison onset. ||Viticultural significance includes representing first detectable veraison texture change, serving as universal veraison marker across cultivars, demonstrating cell wall enzyme activation as transformation mechanism, and determining veraison timing and progression. ||Research applications include analyzing softening onset mechanisms and regulation, investigating enzyme activation and pectin modification dynamics, evaluating firmness decline kinetics, quantifying structural and turgor changes, and assessing initial softening as veraison marker and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 475-482 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Cell_Wall_Modification_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Wall_Modification_Onset is an Initial_Berry_Softening involving 3–8 fold increase in polygalacturonase activity, 2–5 fold increase in pectin methylesterase activity, and pectate lyase activation initiating pectin depolymerization.",
  "alternative_term": "enzyme activation | pectin degradation onset | wall breakdown initiation | structural modification start |+ Zellwand-Modifikations-Beginn | Enzym-Aktivierung | Pektin-Abbau-Beginn | Wand-Abbau-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows cell wall modification onset during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 83, with polygalacturonase activity increasing 5.2 fold from 9 to 47 units over 2-3 days at veraison, pectin methylesterase increasing 3.8 fold from 16 to 61 units, PG cleaving homogalacturonan pectin backbone, PME demethylating pectin from 68% to 52% methylation degree, pectate lyase possibly increasing 2.4 fold, coordinated enzyme activities initiating pectin depolymerization with molecular weight declining from 240 to 165 kDa, middle lamella pectin as primary degradation target, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 24-29°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar activating softening enzymes at veraison",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Wall_Modification_Onset is first aspect of Initial_Berry_Softening, distinguished by enzyme activation. ||Represents 1-3 days veraison onset. ||Polygalacturonase 3-8 fold increase (5-15 → 15-40 units), pectin methylesterase 2-5 fold (10-25 → 25-50 units). ||PG cleaves homogalacturonan, PME demethylates creating PG substrate. ||Pectate lyase possible. ||Pectin depolymerization initiating (150-300 → 100-200 kDa). ||Middle lamella primary target. ||Temperature affects enzyme kinetics (optimal 20-30°C). ||Precedes Pectin_Solubilization_Start. ||Primary softening mechanism. || This enzyme activation and structural change initiation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, representing cell wall modification beginning at veraison onset. ||Modification onset mechanism involves polygalacturonase gene expression upregulation and protein accumulation during late lag, enzyme activation at veraison onset initiating pectin cleavage, pectin methylesterase similarly upregulated and activated, coordinated enzyme activities attacking pectin structure, pectin backbone cleavage and demethylation initiating structural breakdown, middle lamella pectin as primary target, and enzymatic modification initiating firmness decline. ||Polygalacturonase activation shows PG activity increasing from pre-veraison low levels typically 5-15 units to initial onset 15-40 units representing 3-8 fold increase, continued increase to higher ripening levels 40-100 units, PG as endo-polygalacturonase cleaving internal pectin bonds, and PG as major softening enzyme. ||PG gene expression shows PG genes strongly upregulated during late lag and veraison, multiple PG gene family members possibly expressed, transcriptional activation preceding enzyme activity increase, and gene expression as activation mechanism. ||PG protein accumulation shows PG protein synthesized from upregulated genes, protein accumulating during late lag providing enzyme capacity, accumulated protein activated at veraison, and protein as functional enzyme pool. ||PG enzyme characteristics shows endo-PG cleaving homogalacturonan backbone randomly, optimal pH 4.5-5.5 in apoplast, calcium effects on activity variable, and enzymatic properties affecting function. ||PG substrate shows homogalacturonan smooth pectin region as primary substrate, PG attacking pectin backbone creating smaller fragments, cleavage reducing polymer size, and substrate accessibility as rate factor. ||Pectin methylesterase activation shows PME activity increasing from pre-veraison 10-25 units to onset 25-50 units representing 2-5 fold increase, PME demethylating pectin removing methyl ester groups, demethylation creating blocks of free carboxyl groups, and PME as pectin modification enzyme. ||PME gene expression shows PME genes upregulated during late lag preparation, multiple PME isoforms possibly expressed, expression coordinated with softening, and transcription as activation basis. ||PME enzyme characteristics shows PME removing methyl groups from galacturonic acid residues, PME creating demethylated pectin blocks, optimal pH 6.5-8.0 though functional across range, and enzymatic properties affecting activity. ||PME dual function shows initial demethylation possibly creating calcium cross-links temporarily increasing firmness in some systems, subsequent demethylation creating PG substrate enabling degradation, biphasic PME role possible though in grapevine primarily degradation facilitation, and complex PME effects. ||Demethylated pectin characteristics shows free carboxyl groups enabling calcium binding, demethylated regions accessible to PG cleavage, degree of methylation declining from 60-80% pre-veraison to 40-60% onset, and demethylation as structural change. ||Pectate lyase possible activation shows PL possibly increasing activity at veraison, PL cleaving pectin through β-elimination mechanism different from PG hydrolysis, PL creating unsaturated products, contribution varying by cultivar, and PL as additional enzyme. ||Coordinated enzyme activities shows PG, PME, and possibly PL working synergistically, PME creating PG substrate, PG cleaving demethylated pectin, coordinated action maximizing degradation, and enzyme cooperation as efficient mechanism. ||Pectin depolymerization initiation shows pectin chain length declining from enzyme cleavage, molecular weight beginning reduction from 150-300 kDa to 100-200 kDa during onset, depolymerization creating smaller pectin fragments, and chain shortening weakening structure. ||Pectin structural integrity loss shows pectin network in cell wall and middle lamella beginning breakdown, structural pectin framework fragmenting, integrity loss reducing wall strength, and degradation as softening basis. ||Middle lamella as primary target shows pectin-rich middle lamella particularly susceptible to enzyme attack, middle lamella between adjacent cells containing high pectin content, middle lamella degradation weakening cell-cell adhesion most effectively, and targeting as strategic degradation. ||Cell wall pectin also targeted shows pectin in primary cell walls also degrading, wall pectin contributing to firmness, wall and middle lamella degradation combined reducing firmness, and comprehensive pectin targeting. ||Pectin domain specificity shows enzymes possibly preferentially attacking specific pectin domains, smooth homogalacturonan regions primary PG target, rhamnogalacturonan regions possibly resistant, and domain selectivity affecting degradation pattern. ||Cell wall other polysaccharides shows hemicelluloses and cellulose largely unaffected during initial softening, cellulose framework maintaining structural integrity, pectin as specific softening target, and selective degradation as mechanism. ||Calcium dynamics shows calcium possibly released from demethylated pectin as degradation proceeds, calcium cross-links breaking, calcium redistribution possible, and calcium affecting pectin structure. ||Modification onset timing shows activation occurring at veraison onset coinciding with other transformation changes, enzyme activation following late lag preparation period, rapid activation over 1-3 days, and timing as transformation feature. ||Spatial modification pattern shows modification possibly initiating in specific berry regions, mesocarp cells experiencing softening, progression through berry tissues, and spatial pattern affecting firmness. ||Environmental effects on modification onset include temperature affecting enzyme activities with warm conditions promoting activation and faster modification, cool conditions slowing enzyme kinetics, and temperature as major rate factor. ||Temperature effects shows optimal enzyme activities at 20-30°C, suboptimal temperatures reducing rates, and temperature affecting modification progression. ||The process represents first aspect of initial berry softening establishing enzyme activation, preceding pectin solubilization start and turgor reduction initiation. ||Duration enzyme activation initiating over 1-3 days at veraison onset then continuing. ||Regional timing shows cell wall modification onset during late August-early September at veraison. ||Viticultural significance includes representing primary softening mechanism through pectin degradation, demonstrating enzyme regulation as developmental control, determining softening rate and progression, and establishing cell wall modification as softening basis. ||Research applications include analyzing pectin-degrading enzyme regulation and activation, investigating enzyme-substrate interactions and degradation mechanisms, evaluating enzyme gene expression and protein dynamics, quantifying pectin structural changes, and assessing cell wall modification as softening determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 477-482"
},

  "Pectin_Solubilization_Start": {
  "definition": "A Pectin_Solubilization_Start is an Initial_Berry_Softening characterized by increase of the water-soluble pectin fraction from 20–30% to 35–50% of total pectin through enzymatic conversion of wall-bound pectin to soluble forms.",
  "alternative_term": "pectin conversion | soluble pectin increase | pectin release | structural pectin loss |+ Pektin-Solubilisierungs-Start | Pektin-Umwandlung | lösliches Pektin-Anstieg | Pektin-Freisetzung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows pectin solubilization start during early September Year N+1 at BBCH 83, with water-soluble pectin increasing from 26% to 44% total pectin during initial softening representing 18% increase in soluble fraction, insoluble pectin declining from 74% to 56%, soluble pectin molecular weight 35-85 kDa appearing from insoluble 180-260 kDa fragmentation, uronic acid in soluble fraction increasing from 8.4 to 14.6 mg/g fresh weight, middle lamella pectin particularly solubilized weakening cell adhesion, solubilization correlating inversely with firmness decline (r²=0.89), under warm climate conditions of 24-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar initiating pectin conversion at veraison",
  "editor_note": "Pectin_Solubilization_Start is second aspect of Initial_Berry_Softening, distinguished by pectin conversion. ||Represents initial softening days at veraison. ||Water-soluble pectin 20-30% → 35-50% (15-25% increase), insoluble 70-80% → 50-65%. ||Soluble pectin 20-100 kDa from insoluble 100-300 kDa fragmentation. ||Middle lamella pectin particularly affected. ||Cell-cell adhesion weakening. ||Strong inverse correlation with firmness. ||Follows Cell_Wall_Modification_Onset. ||Concurrent with Turgor_Reduction_Initiation. ||Pectin degradation indicator. || This pectin conversion initiation phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, representing pectin structural change at veraison onset. ||Solubilization mechanism involves pectin-degrading enzyme actions cleaving pectin chains creating smaller fragments, depolymerized pectin fragments releasing from wall matrix into aqueous phase, solubilized pectin as degradation products, insoluble structural pectin declining as soluble fraction increases, and solubilization as consequence and indicator of enzymatic modification. ||Insoluble vs soluble pectin fractionation shows insoluble pectin as structural wall-bound polymers extracted by harsh chemical treatments, soluble pectin as fragments released by water or dilute buffer extraction, fractionation distinguishing structural from degraded pectin, and solubility as pectin state indicator. ||Pre-veraison pectin state shows pectin predominantly insoluble 70-80% structural, soluble fraction minimal 20-30% representing loosely bound or naturally soluble pectin, insoluble pectin providing wall structure and firmness, and pre-veraison state as structural baseline. ||Solubilization onset shows soluble pectin fraction beginning increase at veraison, typical increase from 20-30% to 35-50% during initial softening representing 15-25% increase in soluble fraction, continued increase through ripening to 60-80% soluble at full ripeness, and onset marking pectin conversion. ||Soluble pectin characteristics shows smaller molecular weight fragments 20-100 kDa compared to insoluble 100-300 kDa, soluble pectin extractable in water or dilute buffer, fragments from enzymatic cleavage, and soluble forms as degradation products. ||Insoluble pectin decline shows structural pectin declining from 70-80% to 50-65% during initial softening, continued decline through ripening to 20-40% at ripeness, insoluble pectin loss from conversion to soluble forms, and decline indicating structural loss. ||Pectin depolymerization shows pectin polymer chain length declining from enzyme cleavage, molecular weight of both fractions declining with soluble pectin arising from insoluble, degree of polymerization decreasing, and depolymerization enabling solubilization. ||Molecular weight dynamics shows insoluble pectin molecular weight declining from 150-300 kDa pre-veraison to 100-200 kDa onset to 50-150 kDa ripening, soluble pectin appearing as smaller fragments 20-100 kDa and increasing in amount, and molecular weight as degradation measure. ||Pectin release from walls shows depolymerized pectin fragments detaching from wall matrix, fragments diffusing into apoplast and cell contents, release weakening wall structural integrity, and release as pectin mobilization. ||Cell wall structural integrity loss shows wall pectin network fragmenting from depolymerization and solubilization, network disruption reducing wall strength, structural integrity loss reducing firmness contribution, and integrity loss as softening mechanism. ||Middle lamella pectin solubilization shows middle lamella pectin particularly susceptible to degradation and solubilization, middle lamella holding adjacent cells becoming fragmented, middle lamella loss creating cell-cell adhesion weakening, and middle lamella as critical solubilization target. ||Cell-cell adhesion weakening shows solubilization of middle lamella pectin reducing intercellular bonding, cells becoming less firmly attached from adhesive pectin loss, tissue coherence declining, and adhesion loss contributing to softness. ||Pectin compositional changes shows not only solubility changes but also pectin fine structure possibly changing, degree of methylation declining from PME action, galacturonic acid content possibly changing, and compositional shifts accompanying solubilization. ||Uronic acid content shows total uronic acid as pectin measure, uronic acid in soluble fraction increasing while insoluble decreases, total uronic acid relatively stable though distribution shifts, and uronic acid as pectin quantification. ||Pectin extraction methods shows hot water extraction for soluble pectin, chelator EDTA or CDTA extraction for calcium-bound pectin, dilute acid or alkali for insoluble pectin, sequential extraction characterizing fractions, and extraction as analytical approach. ||Solubilization measurement shows spectrophotometric uronic acid determination quantifying soluble and insoluble fractions, ratio calculation showing solubilization degree, size-exclusion chromatography showing molecular weight distributions, and measurements characterizing solubilization. ||Solubilization timing shows onset at veraison initiation coordinating with enzyme activation, progressive solubilization during initial softening days, continued increase through ripening weeks, and timing as degradation progression. ||Solubilization correlation with firmness shows strong inverse correlation between soluble pectin percentage and berry firmness, increasing solubilization coinciding with firmness decline, correlation supporting solubilization as softening mechanism, and relationship as functional connection. ||Environmental effects on solubilization include temperature affecting enzyme activities and solubilization rate, warm conditions promoting faster pectin conversion, cool conditions slowing solubilization, and temperature as rate factor. ||Temperature effects shows enzyme-driven solubilization temperature-dependent, optimal ranges promoting rapid conversion, and temperature affecting dynamics. ||The process represents second aspect of initial berry softening establishing pectin conversion, following cell wall modification onset and concurrent with turgor reduction initiation. ||Duration solubilization initiating over initial softening days at veraison. ||Regional timing shows pectin solubilization start during late August-early September at veraison onset. ||Viticultural significance includes representing pectin degradation indicator documenting cell wall modification, correlating strongly with firmness decline, demonstrating structural to soluble conversion as softening basis, and providing analytical marker for softening assessment. ||Research applications include analyzing pectin solubilization mechanisms and kinetics, investigating pectin structural changes and degradation products, evaluating solubilization-firmness relationships, quantifying pectin fractions and molecular weights, and assessing pectin solubilization as softening indicator and mechanism.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 478-482"
},

  "Turgor_Reduction_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Turgor_Reduction_Initiation is an Initial_Berry_Softening characterized by 10–15% reduction of cell turgor pressure from pre-véraison 0.5–0.8 MPa to 0.4–0.7 MPa, contributing 15–30% of firmness decline alongside 70–85% from cell wall modification.",
  "alternative_term": "pressure reduction onset | turgor decline start | cell pressure reduction | minor turgor change |+ Turgor-Reduktions-Initiierung | Druck-Reduktions-Beginn | Turgor-Abnahme-Start | Zelldruck-Reduktion",
  "example_of_usage": "Pinot Noir in Burgundy shows turgor reduction possible initiation during late August-early September Year N+1 at BBCH 83, with cell turgor pressure possibly declining 12-14% from 0.62 to 0.54 MPa during initial softening representing minor 0.08 MPa reduction, osmotic potential becoming more negative from sugar increase -0.8 to -1.1 MPa, cell wall yielding from structural modification enabling volume expansion, turgor contribution to firmness decline estimated 18-24% while cell wall structural changes contributing 76-82%, turgor as secondary softening factor, under continental conditions of 22-27°C temperature, typical of this early-to-mid season cultivar showing minor turgor changes compared to dominant structural softening",
  "editor_note": "Turgor_Reduction_Initiation is third aspect of Initial_Berry_Softening, distinguished by possible pressure reduction. ||Represents possible 10-15% decline from 0.5-0.8 to 0.4-0.7 MPa. ||SECONDARY softening factor contributing 15-30% firmness decline versus cell wall structural changes 70-85% (DOMINANT). ||Turgor changes minor, not well-established, variable across studies. ||Osmotic potential more negative from sugars. ||Cell wall yielding enables volume expansion. ||Follows Cell_Wall_Modification_Onset and Pectin_Solubilization_Start. ||Temperature and water stress affect. ||Uncertain contribution. || This pressure reduction onset phase occurs during late summer to early autumn in late August-early September in temperate regions Year N+1, representing possible turgor change at veraison though contribution minor. ||Turgor reduction mechanism involves possible changes in cell osmotic potential from sugar and acid dynamics, possible changes in water potential affecting water influx and turgor, altered membrane properties possibly affecting water relations, cell wall yielding enabling volume expansion reducing pressure, and minor turgor reduction as secondary contributor to softening compared to dominant structural changes. ||Turgor pressure definition shows turgor as hydrostatic pressure in cell from water influx against cell wall resistance, turgor generated by osmotic potential difference between cell and apoplast, turgor pressing cell membrane against wall, turgor contributing to cell and tissue rigidity, and turgor as cell mechanical property. ||Pre-veraison turgor shows turgor pressure typically 0.5-0.8 MPa during lag phase, pressure from osmotic gradient and water uptake, turgor at moderate levels with cell walls relatively rigid preventing expansion, and pre-veraison as baseline state. ||Turgor measurement shows pressure probe or pressure chamber techniques measuring cell pressure, measurements showing possible slight decline during softening, measurement challenges in berry cells, and turgor quantification difficult. ||Possible turgor decline shows turgor potentially declining 10-15% from pre-veraison 0.5-0.8 MPa to 0.4-0.7 MPa during initial softening representing minor 0.05-0.12 MPa reduction, turgor changes less dramatic than structural changes, turgor decline not universal or well-documented across studies, and possible but uncertain turgor reduction. ||Osmotic potential changes shows berry osmotic potential becoming more negative from sugar accumulation, increased solutes should increase turgor but effects complex, possible offsetting changes in apoplast, and osmotic dynamics affecting turgor. ||Sugar accumulation effects shows sugars increasing during veraison creating more negative osmotic potential, sugar increase potentially increasing turgor pressure, but cell wall yielding enabling expansion so pressure may not increase or may decline, and complex sugar-turgor relationship. ||Organic acid decline effects shows acids declining during ripening, acid reduction potentially affecting osmotic potential and turgor, effects likely minor compared to sugar, and acid-turgor interaction. ||Water potential changes shows berry water potential possibly changing from altered osmotic and pressure potentials, water uptake continuing during softening from osmotic gradient, water relations complex, and water potential as turgor determinant. ||Cell wall yielding shows wall softening from structural modification enabling cell expansion, expansion allowing volume increase reducing pressure for given water content, yielding as mechanism enabling turgor reduction or preventing increase, and wall-turgor interaction. ||Cell volume changes shows cells possibly expanding during veraison-ripening from water uptake and wall yielding, volume increase potentially reducing turgor if water uptake insufficient to maintain pressure, and volume-turgor relationship. ||Membrane properties shows membrane permeability possibly changing affecting water flux, aquaporin expression and activity possibly altering water transport, membrane changes affecting turgor regulation, and membrane as turgor factor. ||Turgor contribution to firmness shows turgor contributing 15-30% firmness in most studies, structural wall changes contributing 70-85%, turgor as secondary factor, distinction from wall effects difficult, and relative contribution as key concept. ||Firmness from turgor shows turgor-generated pressure pressing cell against wall contributing to rigidity, reduced turgor creating softer feel, but effect much less than structural wall changes, and turgor as minor firmness component. ||Cell wall structural changes dominance shows pectin degradation and wall modifications as primary softening mechanisms, wall changes reducing firmness 70-85%, turgor changes secondary 15-30%, and structural dominance as softening basis. ||Turgor-wall interaction shows turgor and wall properties interacting to determine firmness, soft walls with high turgor versus rigid walls with low turgor creating different textures, interaction complex, and combined effects determining texture. ||Turgor role uncertainty shows turgor changes during softening not well-established, some studies showing minor decline, others no change or increase, variability across cultivars and conditions, and uncertain turgor dynamics. ||Measurement challenges shows turgor measurement technically difficult in berry cells, pressure probe requiring careful technique, indirect estimates from water relations, and measurement limitations. ||Cultivar variation possible shows different cultivars possibly showing different turgor dynamics, some with minor decline others stable, variation complicating generalizations, and genetic effects possible. ||Environmental effects on turgor include temperature affecting water relations and turgor, water availability affecting berry hydration and pressure, and environmental factors influencing turgor though effects less clear than structural changes. ||Temperature effects shows temperature affecting membrane permeability and water flux potentially affecting turgor, and temperature as turgor factor. ||Water stress effects shows water deficit potentially reducing turgor through limited water availability, deficit affecting berry hydration, and water stress as major turgor influence. ||The process represents third aspect of initial berry softening as possible minor pressure reduction, following cell wall modification onset and pectin solubilization start. ||Duration possible turgor reduction during initial softening days. ||Regional timing shows turgor reduction possible initiation during late August-early September at veraison. ||Viticultural significance includes representing possible secondary softening contributor, demonstrating cell wall structural changes as dominant mechanism, showing turgor-wall interaction in texture determination, and establishing turgor as minor firmness factor compared to structural changes. ||Research applications include analyzing turgor dynamics during softening, investigating turgor-firmness relationships and contributions, evaluating water relations and osmotic changes, quantifying turgor changes and mechanisms, and assessing turgor reduction as potential minor softening component.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 480-482"
},

  "Progressive_Softening": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Softening is a Berry_Softening comprising sustained cell wall degradation producing 40–70% total firmness decline from pre-véraison maximum, with firmness reduction from 2.0–3.5 N to 1.0–2.5 N over a 4–8 week ripening period.",
  "alternative_term": "continued softening | ripening softening | progressive firmness decline | extended softening |+ progressive Erweichung | fortgesetzte Erweichung | Reifungs-Erweichung | progressive Festigkeits-Abnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "Merlot in Bordeaux shows progressive softening during September-October Year N+1 at BBCH 85-89, with firmness declining from initial softening 2.7 N through progressive ripening to mature 1.6 N representing total 53% decline from pre-veraison 3.4 N, continued polygalacturonase activity 28 to 72 units, pectin methylesterase 38 to 86 units, progressive pectin solubilization 42% to 68% soluble pectin, molecular weight declining 140 to 78 kDa, middle lamella extensively degraded with cells loosely attached, berries increasingly pliable and soft, slower progressive softening rate 0.9% per day over 6 weeks ripening, under oceanic conditions of 18-24°C temperature, typical of this mid-season cultivar achieving soft ripe texture at harvest maturity",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Softening is second phase of Berry_Softening, distinguished by continued transformation. ||Represents 4-8 weeks ripening following initial softening. ||Firmness decline 2.0-3.5 → 1.0-2.5 N (40-70% total from pre-veraison). ||Subdivided into Continued_Cell_Wall_Degradation (PG 40-100 units, PME 50-120 units), Increasing_Berry_Pliability, Firmness_Decline. ||Rate 0.5-1.5%/day (slower than initial). ||Pectin solubilization 60-80%. ||Turgor changes minor (15-30% contribution). ||Follows Initial_Berry_Softening. ||Establishes soft ripe texture. ||Temperature major rate factor. || This continued softening phase occurs during late summer through autumn in late August-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing ripening texture transformation following initial veraison softening. ||Progressive softening mechanism involves continued cell wall degradation through sustained polygalacturonase and pectin methylesterase activities, progressive pectin depolymerization and solubilization, continuing middle lamella degradation and cell-cell adhesion loss, possible further minor turgor changes though structural changes remain dominant, and cumulative softening creating soft ripe texture characteristic of mature berries. ||Firmness decline progression shows firmness continuing to decline from initial softening 2.0-3.5 N through progressive ripening to ripe 1.0-2.5 N, total decline 40-70% from pre-veraison maximum 2.5-4.5 N, typical mature firmness 1.5-2.0 N representing 50-60% total reduction, and progressive decline as ripening characteristic. ||Softening rate during progressive phase shows slower decline 0.5-1.5% firmness per day compared to rapid initial 2-4% per day, gradual progressive softening over weeks, eventual plateau at soft ripe texture, and rate pattern characteristic of ripening. ||Firmness trajectory shows rapid initial decline at veraison, slower progressive decline during ripening, eventual soft ripe state, and trajectory as softening pattern. ||Cultivar variation shows final ripe firmness varying 1.0-2.5 N among cultivars, some cultivars maintaining relatively firmer texture, others becoming very soft, and genetic variation affecting softening extent. ||Continued cell wall degradation shows polygalacturonase and pectin methylesterase activities remaining elevated through ripening, enzymes continuing pectin degradation, progressive structural modification, and sustained enzymatic activity as degradation mechanism. ||Polygalacturonase continued activity shows PG activity increasing from initial 15-40 units to ripening maximum 40-100 units, sustained PG continuing pectin cleavage, PG as continuing softening enzyme, and PG activity throughout ripening. ||Pectin methylesterase continued activity shows PME activity 25-50 units initial increasing to 50-120 units ripening, continued demethylation creating PG substrate, PME sustained through ripening, and PME as continuing modification enzyme. ||Progressive pectin depolymerization shows pectin molecular weight continuing decline from initial 100-200 kDa to ripe 50-150 kDa or lower, continued chain shortening from enzymatic cleavage, depolymerization progressive through ripening, and molecular weight decline as continuing degradation. ||Pectin solubilization progression shows soluble pectin continuing increase from initial 35-50% to ripe 60-80% total pectin, insoluble pectin declining to 20-40%, progressive conversion to soluble forms, and solubilization continuing through ripening. ||Middle lamella continued degradation shows progressive middle lamella pectin loss, cell-cell adhesion continuing weakening, possible cell separation in very soft berries, and middle lamella as continuing degradation target. ||Cell-cell adhesion progressive loss shows intercellular bonding progressively reduced, cells increasingly loosely attached, tissue coherence declining substantially, and adhesion loss creating soft texture. ||Cell wall structure progressive weakening shows cell wall pectin network increasingly fragmented, wall structural integrity progressively lost, walls becoming very weak in soft ripe berries, and structural loss as softening basis. ||Increasing berry pliability shows berries becoming progressively softer and more yielding, texture increasingly pliable to touch, berries easily deformed by gentle pressure, and pliability as softening outcome. ||Tactile softness shows berries subjectively very soft at ripeness, yielding readily to touch, texture characteristic of ripe fruit, and tactile as practical assessment. ||Berry handling sensitivity shows soft ripe berries very susceptible to mechanical damage, berries easily crushed or bruised, handling care required, and sensitivity as softening consequence. ||Juice release shows soft berries releasing juice readily when crushed, softness facilitating juice extraction, texture affecting processing, and juice release as functional property. ||Skin-flesh separation shows possible skin loosening from flesh in very soft berries, separation from middle lamella degradation, loosening affecting processing and quality, and separation as extreme softening. ||Turgor possible continued changes shows turgor possibly continuing slight decline or remaining stable during ripening, turgor changes still minor compared to structural changes throughout ripening, turgor contribution secondary 15-30% throughout, and turgor as continuing minor factor. ||Berry water content shows water content stable or slightly increasing during ripening 78-85%, water uptake from sugar osmotic gradient, water affecting turgor and berry properties, and water content as berry characteristic. ||Osmotic potential shows osmotic potential becoming increasingly negative from sugar accumulation -1.0 to -1.8 MPa, increased sugars driving water uptake, osmotic gradient as water flux driver, and osmotic potential determining water relations. ||Berry composition changes shows sugars increasing substantially 14-18% to 20-28%, acids declining 0.7-0.9% to 0.4-0.7%, pH rising 3.1-3.4 to 3.3-3.8, and composition changes accompanying softening. ||Softening-composition coordination shows softening coordinated with sugar accumulation, acid decline, color development in red cultivars, and integrated ripening processes. ||Softening completion shows eventual soft ripe texture when berries reach maturity, firmness stabilizing at ripe levels, softening completing ripening transformation, and completion as maturity state. ||Harvest maturity shows softening as ripeness indicator, soft texture indicating mature berries ready for harvest, optimal firmness varying by use with table grapes requiring firmness while wine grapes soft, and firmness as maturity marker. ||Environmental effects on progressive softening include temperature affecting enzyme activities and softening rate, warm conditions promoting faster continued softening, cool conditions slowing ripening and softening, and temperature as major rate factor. ||Temperature effects shows cumulative heat affecting total softening extent and rate, temperature affecting enzyme kinetics throughout ripening, and temperature as dominant environmental factor. ||Water availability shows adequate water supporting normal softening, deficit possibly affecting softening extent, and water as softening factor. ||The process encompasses three progressive softening aspects including continued cell wall degradation through sustained enzyme activities, increasing berry pliability creating soft texture, and firmness decline reaching mature levels. ||Duration progressive softening over 4-8 weeks from veraison through ripening. ||Regional timing shows progressive softening during late August-October through ripening to harvest. ||Viticultural significance includes representing continued ripening texture transformation, determining final berry texture affecting quality and handling, demonstrating sustained cell wall modification as ripening process, and establishing soft ripe texture as maturity characteristic. ||Research applications include analyzing continued softening mechanisms and enzyme regulation, investigating progressive pectin degradation and structural changes, evaluating softening-composition relationships, quantifying firmness decline kinetics through ripening, and assessing progressive softening as ripening progression and quality determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0016998 ## cell wall macromolecule catabolic process | 0.8", "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0042545 ## cell wall cell wall modification | 0.8" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 482-490 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Continued_Cell_Wall_Degradation": {
  "definition": "A Continued_Cell_Wall_Degradation is a Progressive_Softening involving sustained polygalacturonase activity at 40–100 units, pectin methylesterase activity at 50–120 units, and pectate lyase activity producing fragmentation of cell wall and middle lamella pectin.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained degradation | continuing wall breakdown | progressive enzymatic modification | ripening degradation |+ fortgesetzte Zellwand-Degradation | anhaltender Abbau | fortsetzender Wand-Abbau | progressive enzymatische Modifikation",
  "example_of_usage": "Syrah in Rhône Valley shows continued cell wall degradation during September-October Year N+1 at BBCH 85-89, with polygalacturonase activity sustained at 52-84 units through ripening representing maximum activity levels, pectin methylesterase 68-96 units continuing demethylation, pectate lyase possibly 18-32 units, sustained enzyme activities progressively degrading pectin with molecular weight declining from 165 to 68 kDa, pectin solubilization progressing from 48% to 72% soluble fraction, middle lamella extensively degraded with cells very loosely attached by maturity, cumulative degradation over 6-7 weeks creating substantially weakened wall structure, under warm Mediterranean conditions of 22-28°C temperature, typical of this mid-to-late season cultivar sustaining cell wall degradation through ripening",
  "editor_note": "Continued_Cell_Wall_Degradation is first aspect of Progressive_Softening, distinguished by sustained enzymatic modification. ||Represents 4-8 weeks ripening. ||Polygalacturonase 40-100 units maximum, pectin methylesterase 50-120 units. ||Sustained PG, PME activities throughout ripening. ||Progressive pectin depolymerization 100-200 → 50-150 kDa. ||Solubilization 35-50% → 60-80%. ||Middle lamella extensively degraded. ||Cumulative degradation over weeks. ||Temperature affects enzyme activities (optimal 20-30°C). ||Precedes Increasing_Berry_Pliability and Firmness_Decline. ||Primary progressive softening mechanism. || This sustained breakdown phase occurs during late summer through autumn in late August-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing cell wall modification continuation through ripening. ||Continued degradation mechanism involves sustained polygalacturonase gene expression and enzyme activity, continued pectin methylesterase activity creating enzyme substrate, coordinated enzyme activities maintaining pectin breakdown, progressive pectin depolymerization shortening chains, progressive solubilization converting structural to soluble pectin, cumulative degradation substantially weakening wall structure, and sustained enzymatic modification as softening mechanism. ||Polygalacturonase sustained activity shows PG activity increasing from initial veraison 15-40 units to ripening maximum 40-100 units, PG remaining highly active through ripening, enzyme activity sustained over weeks, PG as major continuing degradation enzyme, and high PG as ripening characteristic. ||PG activity pattern shows activity increasing during early ripening, reaching maximum mid-to-late ripening, possibly declining slightly late ripening in some cultivars, and activity pattern as temporal dynamics. ||PG gene expression shows PG genes remaining upregulated through ripening, continued transcription maintaining enzyme levels, expression as activity maintenance mechanism, and sustained expression through ripening. ||Pectin methylesterase sustained activity shows PME activity 50-120 units during ripening, PME continuing demethylation, sustained PME creating PG substrate continuously, and PME as continuing modification enzyme. ||PME activity pattern shows activity increasing during ripening, sustained at elevated levels, and pattern supporting continued degradation. ||Pectate lyase possible continued activity shows PL possibly contributing to continued degradation, PL activity variable among cultivars, and PL as additional continuing enzyme. ||Enzyme cooperation shows PG, PME, and possibly PL working synergistically throughout ripening, coordinated activities maximizing degradation, sustained cooperation as efficient mechanism, and enzyme synergy throughout. ||Progressive pectin depolymerization shows pectin chain length continuing decline, molecular weight declining from initial softening 100-200 kDa to ripening 50-150 kDa or lower, continued fragmentation creating smaller pieces, and depolymerization as progressive process. ||Pectin molecular weight trajectory shows progressive decline through ripening, eventual low molecular weight at maturity, and trajectory as degradation indicator. ||Chain length reduction shows degree of polymerization declining, shorter pectin chains from enzymatic cleavage, and reduction weakening structure. ||Progressive pectin solubilization shows soluble pectin continuing increase from initial 35-50% to ripening 60-80% total pectin, insoluble pectin declining to 20-40%, progressive conversion as continuing process, and solubilization throughout ripening. ||Solubilization kinetics shows progressive increase correlating with enzyme activities and firmness decline, rate depending on enzyme levels and substrate, and kinetics as degradation rate. ||Middle lamella progressive degradation shows middle lamella pectin extensively degraded during ripening, progressive loss of intercellular adhesive, substantial middle lamella loss by maturity, and middle lamella as primary continuing target. ||Cell-cell adhesion progressive loss shows intercellular bonding substantially reduced by ripening, cells very loosely attached in ripe berries, possible cell separation in very soft fruit, and adhesion loss as extensive degradation outcome. ||Cell wall pectin progressive loss shows wall pectin also extensively degraded, wall structure substantially weakened, walls very fragile in ripe berries, and wall degradation as softening mechanism. ||Cumulative degradation shows degradation accumulating over ripening weeks, cumulative effect creating substantial structural loss, total degradation much greater than initial, and cumulative as progressive feature. ||Structural integrity extensive loss shows cell wall and middle lamella structural networks extensively fragmented, integrity substantially lost creating very soft texture, and integrity loss as degradation outcome. ||Pectin domain degradation shows continued preferential attack on smooth homogalacturonan regions, progressive degradation of accessible domains, and domain-specific degradation. ||Calcium dynamics shows continued calcium release and redistribution as pectin degrades, calcium effects on residual pectin structure, and calcium as degradation factor. ||Other cell wall components shows hemicelluloses and cellulose remaining largely intact, selective pectin degradation continuing, and specificity as degradation characteristic. ||Degradation spatial pattern shows degradation throughout berry mesocarp, possible regional variation in extent, and spatial pattern affecting softening. ||Enzyme-substrate dynamics shows continuing enzyme-pectin interactions, substrate availability declining as degradation proceeds, and dynamics affecting rate. ||Environmental effects on continued degradation include temperature affecting enzyme activities with warm conditions promoting higher activities and faster degradation, cool conditions reducing enzyme kinetics, and temperature as major rate determinant. ||Temperature effects shows optimal enzyme activities at 20-30°C, temperature affecting cumulative degradation extent, and temperature as dominant factor. ||Cultivar variation shows enzyme activity levels varying among cultivars, some maintaining higher activities others lower, variation affecting degradation extent and softening, and genetic effects on degradation. ||Degradation regulation shows enzyme activities regulated at transcriptional and post-translational levels, developmental signals maintaining expression, and regulation as activity control. ||The process represents first aspect of progressive softening establishing sustained enzymatic modification, preceding increasing berry pliability and firmness decline. ||Duration continued degradation throughout 4-8 weeks ripening period. ||Regional timing shows continued cell wall degradation during late August-October through ripening. ||Viticultural significance includes representing sustained softening mechanism through ripening, determining progressive firmness decline and final texture, demonstrating enzyme activity regulation through ripening, and establishing cell wall degradation as ripening process. ||Research applications include analyzing continued enzyme activities and regulation through ripening, investigating progressive pectin degradation kinetics, evaluating enzyme-pectin interactions and degradation mechanisms, quantifying cumulative degradation extent, and assessing continued degradation as progressive softening mechanism.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 482-488"
},

  "Increasing_Berry_Pliability": {
  "definition": "An Increasing_Berry_Pliability is a Progressive_Softening characterized by progressive textural change from firm-resistant to soft-yielding through cumulative cell wall degradation and reduced structural integrity.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive softening outcome | texture yielding | berry softness increase | tactile softening |+ zunehmende Beeren-Nachgiebigkeit | progressive Erweichungs-Ergebnis | Textur-Nachgeben | Beeren-Weichheit-Zunahme",
  "example_of_usage": "Chardonnay in Champagne shows increasing berry pliability during late August-September Year N+1 at BBCH 85-89, with berry texture progressively softening from initial 2.3 N to mature 1.4 N over 5-6 weeks ripening, berries increasingly pliable to touch yielding readily under gentle finger pressure, tactile assessment showing progressive softness increase, cell wall structural integrity extensively lost from cumulative pectin degradation, middle lamella substantially degraded creating tissue yielding, berries requiring careful handling to avoid bruising, eventual soft pliable ripe texture characteristic of mature berries ready for harvest, under cool maritime conditions of 14-20°C temperature, typical of this early-bursting cultivar achieving soft ripe texture for sparkling wine production",
  "editor_note": "Increasing_Berry_Pliability is second aspect of Progressive_Softening, distinguished by texture softening outcome. ||Represents progressive change over 4-8 weeks ripening. ||Firmness 2.0-3.5 → 1.0-2.5 N. ||Berries increasingly soft and yielding. ||Mechanism: cumulative cell wall degradation, middle lamella loss, minimal cell-cell adhesion. ||Turgor changes minor. ||Tactile assessment: readily deformable. ||Handling sensitivity high. ||Sensory quality indicator. ||Follows Continued_Cell_Wall_Degradation. ||Concurrent with Firmness_Decline. ||Temperature affects progression rate. || This texture softening outcome phase occurs during late summer through autumn in late August-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing tactile softening progression through ripening. ||Pliability increase mechanism involves cumulative cell wall structural weakening from pectin degradation reducing resistance to deformation, middle lamella loss reducing cell-cell adhesion creating tissue yielding, possible minor turgor changes though structural effects dominant, progressive texture change from firm to soft, and pliability as functional softening outcome. ||Berry pliability definition shows pliability as ease of berry deformation under applied force, pliable berries yielding readily to pressure, pliability inversely related to firmness, and pliability as texture characteristic. ||Texture transformation progression shows berry texture progressively softening from initial softening through ripening to ripe, transformation from firm hard to soft yielding over weeks, progressive change as ripening feature, and texture as maturity indicator. ||Initial texture state shows berries moderately firm after initial softening 2.0-3.5 N penetrometer resistance, texture noticeably softer than pre-veraison but still resistant, and initial state as softening baseline. ||Progressive softening shows berries becoming progressively softer during ripening, texture increasingly yielding, eventual soft pliable state at maturity 1.0-2.5 N, and progression as ripening characteristic. ||Final ripe texture shows berries very soft and pliable at full ripeness, yielding readily to touch, texture characteristic of mature fruit, and ripe state as softening endpoint. ||Tactile assessment shows subjective pliability evaluation through gentle pressure, berries increasingly soft to touch, pliability readily detected by experienced evaluators, and tactile as practical pliability assessment. ||Pressure response shows soft berries deforming under gentle finger pressure, berries easily compressed, deformation recovering slowly or not at all, and response as pliability indicator. ||Ease of deformation shows pliable berries requiring minimal force for deformation, resistance declining progressively, eventual very low resistance at ripeness, and deformation ease as pliability measure. ||Tissue yielding shows berry tissue yielding readily under pressure from reduced structural integrity, yielding from cell-cell adhesion loss and wall weakening, tissue response as pliability mechanism, and yielding as texture basis. ||Cell wall structural weakness shows extensively degraded cell walls providing minimal resistance, wall pectin loss creating fragile structure, weak walls enabling easy deformation, and structural weakness as pliability cause. ||Middle lamella extensive loss shows middle lamella substantially degraded by ripening, intercellular adhesion minimal, cells easily separated, and middle lamella loss creating tissue yielding. ||Cell-cell adhesion minimal shows cells very loosely attached in pliable berries, adhesion insufficient to maintain tissue integrity under pressure, adhesion loss enabling yielding, and minimal adhesion as pliability feature. ||Berry handling characteristics shows pliable berries very delicate requiring careful handling, berries easily damaged by pressure, susceptibility to bruising and crushing, and handling sensitivity as pliability consequence. ||Damage susceptibility shows soft pliable berries bruising from minor impacts, cell rupture from gentle compression, juice release from handling, and damage sensitivity increasing with pliability. ||Harvest timing implications shows pliability as ripeness indicator affecting harvest decisions, table grapes harvested before excessive pliability, wine grapes allowed to soften fully, and pliability affecting harvest management. ||Skin-flesh properties shows skin possibly loosening from flesh in very pliable berries, skin-flesh separation from middle lamella degradation, separation affecting processing, and skin properties as pliability aspect. ||Juice release characteristics shows pliable berries releasing juice readily when crushed, softness facilitating juice extraction during processing, texture affecting crushing efficiency, and juice release as functional property. ||Berry appearance shows pliable berries possibly appearing slightly deflated or wrinkled in some cases, surface changes from structural loss, appearance as visual pliability indicator, and surface as textural sign. ||Berry size shows berry size relatively stable during progressive softening though water uptake may increase volume slightly, size independent of pliability, and size-pliability distinction. ||Pliability-firmness relationship shows pliability inversely related to firmness, increasing pliability corresponding to firmness decline, strong negative correlation, and relationship as texture measure. ||Sensory evaluation shows trained panels detecting pliability progression, sensory scores correlating with instrumental firmness, sensory as pliability assessment method, and evaluation as quality measure. ||Consumer perception shows consumer preferences varying with berry use, soft pliable texture preferred for wine grapes, firmer texture preferred for table grapes, and perception as quality factor. ||Quality implications shows pliability affecting berry quality depending on use, optimal pliability varying by application, excessive softness problematic for table grapes, appropriate softness essential for wine grapes, and quality as pliability context. ||Environmental effects on pliability include temperature affecting pliability progression rate through effects on enzyme activities, warm conditions promoting faster pliability increase, cool conditions slowing progression, and temperature as pliability rate factor. ||Temperature effects shows accumulated heat affecting pliability extent, temperature affecting ripening rate and softening, and temperature as major environmental factor. ||Cultivar variation shows final ripe pliability varying among cultivars, some cultivars remaining relatively firmer, others becoming very soft, and genetic variation affecting pliability. ||The process represents second aspect of progressive softening establishing texture softening outcome, following continued cell wall degradation and concurrent with firmness decline. ||Duration pliability increasing progressively over 4-8 weeks ripening. ||Regional timing shows increasing berry pliability during late August-October through ripening. ||Viticultural significance includes representing tactile softening outcome affecting quality and handling, determining harvest maturity and berry management, demonstrating structural degradation functional consequence, and establishing pliability as ripeness characteristic. ||Research applications include analyzing pliability progression and mechanisms, investigating pliability-structural relationships, evaluating sensory and instrumental pliability assessment, quantifying pliability changes through ripening, and assessing pliability as quality and maturity indicator.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 485-488"
},

  "Firmness_Decline": {
  "definition": "A Firmness_Decline is a Progressive_Softening marked by reduction of penetrometer firmness from 2.0–3.5 N to 1.0–2.5 N at a daily rate of 0.5–1.5% over 4–8 weeks of ripening.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive firmness reduction | mechanical resistance decline | texture softening measurement | firmness decrease |+ Festigkeits-Abnahme | progressive Festigkeits-Reduktion | mechanische Widerstands-Abnahme | Textur-Erweichungs-Messung",
  "example_of_usage": "Cabernet Sauvignon in Napa Valley shows firmness decline during September-October Year N+1 at BBCH 85-89, with penetrometer firmness declining from pre-veraison maximum 3.8 N through initial softening 3.0 N to progressive ripening reaching mature 1.8 N over 7-8 weeks, total firmness reduction 53% from maximum, progressive decline rate 0.8% per day during ripening, firmness strongly inversely correlated with water-soluble pectin (r²=-0.91) and polygalacturonase activity (r²=-0.88), firmness decline driven primarily by cell wall pectin degradation 78% contribution with minor turgor 22%, firmness used to guide harvest timing for wine production, under warm climate conditions of 22-30°C temperature, typical of this late-season cultivar achieving target soft texture at harvest maturity",
  "editor_note": "Firmness_Decline is third aspect of Progressive_Softening, distinguished by quantitative resistance reduction. ||Represents 4-8 weeks ripening. ||Firmness 2.0-3.5 → 1.0-2.5 N (40-70% total decline from pre-veraison 2.5-4.5 N). ||Rate 0.5-1.5%/day (slower than initial 2-4%/day). ||Mechanism: cell wall degradation 70-85%, turgor 15-30%. ||Strong correlation with pectin solubilization (r²>0.85). ||Cultivar variation 1.0-2.5 N ripe. ||Temperature major rate factor. ||Follows Continued_Cell_Wall_Degradation. ||Concurrent with Increasing_Berry_Pliability. ||Completes Progressive_Softening and Berry_Softening. ||Maturity and quality indicator. || This mechanical resistance reduction phase occurs during late summer through autumn in late August-October in temperate regions Year N+1, representing firmness decrease through ripening. ||Firmness decline mechanism involves progressive cell wall structural weakening from sustained pectin degradation reducing mechanical resistance, middle lamella loss reducing tissue cohesion, possible minor turgor contribution though structural changes dominant, cumulative softening effect accumulating over ripening weeks, and firmness decline as quantitative softening measure. ||Firmness measurement shows penetrometer or texture analyzer measuring force required to penetrate berry, measurement quantifying firmness objectively, force in Newtons N, standard assessment method, and measurement as firmness quantification. ||Penetrometer technique shows probe typically 2-5 mm diameter penetrating berry, force recorded at standard depth or at berry failure, measurement on individual berries, and technique as standard method. ||Compression testing shows alternative firmness measurement through berry compression, force at percentage deformation, compression resistance correlating with penetrometer firmness, and compression as firmness measure. ||Firmness trajectory shows firmness declining from pre-veraison maximum 2.5-4.5 N through initial softening 2.0-3.5 N to progressive ripening decline reaching mature 1.0-2.5 N, trajectory showing rapid initial decline then slower progressive decline, eventual plateau at ripe levels, and trajectory as softening pattern. ||Pre-veraison firmness maximum shows berry at peak firmness during lag phase, firmness from turgid cells with rigid pectin-rich walls, maximum as baseline for decline measurement, and peak as starting point. ||Initial softening firmness shows firmness declining 10-25% at veraison to 2.0-3.5 N, initial decline establishing softening, and initial state as progressive baseline. ||Progressive decline shows firmness continuing decline through ripening 4-8 weeks, typical decline 0.5-1.5% firmness per day representing slower rate than initial 2-4% per day, cumulative decline substantial, and progressive reduction as ripening feature. ||Mature ripe firmness shows firmness stabilizing at ripe levels 1.0-2.5 N, final firmness varying by cultivar and maturity, ripe firmness as endpoint, and mature state as firmness target. ||Total firmness reduction shows cumulative decline 40-70% from pre-veraison to ripe, total reduction representing substantial softening, total as overall change measure, and reduction magnitude as softening extent. ||Firmness decline rate shows progressive decline rate 0.5-1.5% per day during ripening, rate slower than initial rapid decline, rate relatively constant through ripening, and rate as decline kinetics. ||Decline rate variation shows rate varying with temperature, cultivar, and conditions, warm conditions promoting faster decline, cool slowing decline, and variation as environmental response. ||Firmness-softening correlation shows firmness inversely correlated with softening, declining firmness indicating increasing softness, strong correlation enabling firmness as softening measure, and relationship as measurement basis. ||Firmness-cell wall relationship shows firmness strongly correlated with cell wall pectin content and structure, declining firmness correlating with pectin degradation and solubilization, cell wall changes as firmness determinant, and correlation supporting structural basis. ||Pectin-firmness correlation shows water-insoluble pectin content positively correlated with firmness, soluble pectin negatively correlated, pectin molecular weight positively correlated, and correlations showing pectin as firmness factor. ||Enzyme activity-firmness relationship shows polygalacturonase and pectin methylesterase activities negatively correlated with firmness, high enzyme activities correlating with low firmness, and enzymes as decline drivers. ||Firmness-turgor relationship shows firmness weakly correlated with turgor, turgor contributing minor 15-30% variance in firmness, structural factors dominant 70-85%, and relationship showing turgor as secondary factor. ||Firmness variation shows firmness varying among berries in cluster from asynchronous ripening, within-cluster variation creating firmness distribution, variation affecting harvest decisions, and heterogeneity as practical issue. ||Cultivar firmness differences shows ripe firmness varying among cultivars, range 1.0-2.5 N representing genetic variation, some cultivars maintaining firmer texture others very soft, and differences as genetic trait. ||Temperature effects on decline shows temperature strongly affecting firmness decline rate, warm conditions accelerating decline, cool conditions slowing decline, temperature as major environmental factor, and rate variation as temperature response. ||Water effects shows adequate water supporting normal firmness decline, water deficit possibly affecting decline through turgor effects, and water as secondary environmental factor. ||Firmness as maturity indicator shows declining firmness indicating ripening progression, firmness used for maturity assessment, target firmness varying by use, and firmness as practical maturity measure. ||Harvest timing shows firmness guiding harvest decisions, table grapes harvested at firmer texture 1.8-2.5 N, wine grapes at softer 1.0-1.8 N, and firmness as harvest criterion. ||Firmness-quality relationships shows firmness affecting quality depending on use, optimal firmness varying by application, firmness critical for table grape quality, less critical for wine grapes, and quality as firmness context. ||Sensory-instrumental correlation shows instrumental firmness correlating with sensory texture assessment, correlation enabling instrumental prediction of sensory, and correlation as practical tool. ||Firmness preservation shows cool storage slowing firmness decline post-harvest, temperature management preserving texture, and preservation as post-harvest practice. ||The process represents third aspect of progressive softening establishing quantitative softening measure, following continued cell wall degradation and concurrent with increasing berry pliability. ||Duration firmness declining progressively over 4-8 weeks ripening. ||Regional timing shows firmness decline during late August-October through ripening to harvest. ||Viticultural significance includes representing quantitative softening measure enabling objective assessment, determining harvest maturity and berry quality, demonstrating progressive cell wall degradation outcome, and establishing firmness as ripeness indicator. ||Research applications include analyzing firmness decline kinetics and mechanisms, investigating firmness-structural relationships and correlations, evaluating environmental effects on decline rate, quantifying firmness changes and variation, and assessing firmness as quality and maturity determinant.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed, Academic Press pp. 485-490 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry, Am J Enol Vitic 43:101-110"
},

  "Peak_Softening": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Softening is a Berry_Softening characterized by maximum velocity of firmness decline during véraison.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum firmness decline velocity | peak texture transformation | maximum softening intensity | steepest firmness loss |+ maximale Festigkeits-Abnahme-Geschwindigkeit | Spitzen-Textur-Transformation | maximale Erweichungs-Intensität | steilster Festigkeits-Verlust",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Burgundian Pinot Noir vineyard near Beaune, peak softening was documented during the third week of August Year N+1 (BBCH 83-84) when firmness measurements declined from 2.4 N to 1.5 N over 4 days (average 5.6% per day), coinciding with polygalacturonase activity reaching 125 units, pectin molecular weight dropping from 145 kDa to 85 kDa, and berry fresh weight increasing from 1.15 g to 1.35 g as sugar content rose from 17.5 to 20.8° Brix under warm conditions (daily maximum 26-28°C).",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Softening is distinguished from Initial_Berry_Softening by representing the maximum velocity phase rather than onset, from Progressive_Softening by exhibiting peak rather than sustained moderate rates, and from Complete_Berry_Softening by focusing on the transformation intensity rather than final state achievement. ||Duration typically 2-5 days during mid-veraison. ||Maximum firmness decline rates: early cultivars 4-7% per day, mid-season 3-5% per day, late varieties 2-4% per day. ||Temperature is the primary rate-controlling environmental factor. ||Peak_Softening represents the most rapid structural transformation in berry development and marks the point of maximum vulnerability to mechanical damage and pathogen invasion. || This critical phase occurs during mid-veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 2-5 days duration, when the rate of firmness reduction peaks at 3-6% per day compared to 2-4% during initial softening and 0.5-1.5% during progressive softening. ||The process is defined by simultaneous maxima in multiple degradative pathways: polygalacturonase activity reaches 80-150 units (5-10 fold above pre-veraison baseline), pectin methylesterase activity peaks at 100-180 units, and xyloglucan endotransglycosylase activity shows 4-8 fold elevation. ||Berry firmness measurements decline most precipitously during this interval, dropping from approximately 2.0-3.0 N to 1.2-2.0 N within 3-5 days, representing the steepest portion of the sigmoid softening curve. ||Cell wall structural changes reach maximum intensity: middle lamella pectin solubilization accelerates to 5-10% per day increase in soluble fraction (total soluble pectin 60-75%), pectin molecular weight drops rapidly from 120-180 kDa to 70-120 kDa, and cell-to-cell adhesion strength decreases by 40-60% from pre-peak values. ||The peak softening interval coincides with other veraison transformations including accelerated sugar accumulation (1.5-3.5% Brix increase per week), rapid anthocyanin synthesis in red cultivars (50-150 mg/kg per day in skin), and continued berry expansion (15-35 mg fresh weight per day). ||Temperature strongly influences peak softening dynamics: optimal conditions (22-28°C) support maximum enzyme activities and rapid texture transformation, while cooler temperatures (15-20°C) extend the peak period and reduce maximum rates, and heat stress (>32°C) can accelerate softening beyond optimal enzyme kinetics through enhanced membrane permeability and cellular disruption. ||Cultivar variation in peak softening characteristics is substantial: early-ripening varieties like Pinot Noir and Chardonnay exhibit sharper, more concentrated peaks (3-4 days) with maximum rates 4-7% firmness loss per day, mid-season cultivars like Cabernet Sauvignon show moderate peaks (4-5 days) with 3-5% daily decline, while late-season varieties like Mourvèdre display more gradual peaks (5-7 days) with 2-4% maximum rates. ||The peak softening phase marks the transition from structural berry to highly manipulable fruit, with significant viticultural implications: mechanical harvest feasibility declines sharply as berry integrity diminishes, rot susceptibility increases due to compromised skin strength and enhanced pathogen penetration, and bunch compression intensifies as individual berries lose mechanical resistance and conform to cluster geometry. ||Molecular regulation involves peak expression of softening-related genes: PG genes show 80-150 fold upregulation relative to green berry baseline, expansin genes reach 40-80 fold elevation, and xyloglucan endotransglycosylase genes achieve 20-50 fold increases. ||Hormonal orchestration is dominated by continued high abscisic acid levels (800-2500 ng/g fresh weight) maintaining ripening gene expression, while ethylene production shows cultivar-dependent patterns with slight elevation (0.5-2.0 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹) in some varieties correlating with enhanced softening enzyme activity. ||Physiological consequences of peak softening extend beyond texture: increased membrane permeability facilitates enhanced metabolite transport including accelerated sugar import and anthocyanin accumulation, while reduced cellular compartmentalization allows mixing of vacuolar and cytoplasmic contents affecting flavor precursor availability and enzymatic reactions. ||Environmental stresses during peak softening can substantially alter berry quality development: water deficit moderately reduces softening intensity potentially maintaining firmer texture but may compromise berry expansion and metabolite dilution, while excessive irrigation can accelerate softening beyond optimal rates leading to burst-prone berries and diluted flavor compounds. ||Viticultural management targeting peak softening focuses on optimizing the timing and intensity of this transformation through careful irrigation scheduling to balance cell turgor with structural integrity, canopy management to moderate bunch zone temperatures and prevent excessive softening acceleration, and crop load adjustment to ensure adequate photosynthate supply supporting both structural transformation and metabolite accumulation without resource limitation that could compromise either process.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 228-232 berry softening dynamics and cell wall degradation || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 firmness decline kinetics || Nunan KJ, Davies C, Robinson SP, Fincher GB (2001) Expression patterns of cell wall-modifying enzymes during grape berry development Planta 214:257-264 enzyme activity peaks."
},

  "Maximum_Softening_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Softening_Rate is a Peak_Softening marked by the absolute maximum velocity of firmness decline within a concentrated 24–48 hour interval at mid-véraison with all softening mechanisms at peak efficiency.",
  "alternative_term": "steepest firmness decline | peak softening velocity | maximum texture transformation rate | firmness loss apex |+ steilste Festigkeits-Abnahme | Spitzen-Erweichungs-Geschwindigkeit | maximale Textur-Transformations-Rate | Festigkeits-Verlust-Höhepunkt",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc vineyard in New Zealand, maximum softening rate was measured during a 36-hour period in late February Year N+1 (BBCH 84) when firmness decreased from 2.8 N to 2.1 N (6.3% per day), polygalacturonase activity peaked at 165 units, soluble pectin increased from 58% to 68% of total, and sugar concentration rose from 15.2 to 17.1° Brix, with ambient temperatures averaging 23-25°C facilitating optimal enzyme activity for rapid texture transformation.",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Softening_Rate is distinguished from Peak_Softening by representing the instantaneous maximum velocity point rather than the broader peak period, from other softening phases by exhibiting the absolute steepest firmness decline gradient, and from Complete_Berry_Softening by focusing on transformation velocity rather than final state. ||Duration typically 24-48 hours at the inflection point of the softening curve. ||Temperature sensitivity is maximum during this interval (Q₁₀ = 2.5-3.5). ||This represents the most vulnerable moment in berry development for mechanical damage and pathogen infection. ||Maximum_Softening_Rate timing relative to other veraison events is critical for optimal berry quality development. || This transient but critical phase is characterized by firmness measurements showing the steepest decline gradient, often 4-8% reduction per day in early-ripening cultivars, 3-6% in mid-season varieties, and 2-5% in late-ripening types, representing the inflection point of the sigmoid softening curve where the second derivative of firmness versus time equals zero. ||The maximum rate interval is defined by convergence of multiple degradative processes at peak activity: polygalacturonase reaches absolute maximum activity (100-200 units depending on cultivar and conditions), pectin methylesterase achieves peak demethylation rates (120-200 units), xyloglucan endotransglycosylase shows maximum transglycosylation activity (40-80 units), and β-galactosidase displays peak activity (20-50 units) all operating simultaneously to maximize cell wall disassembly. ||During maximum softening rate, pectin structural changes occur most rapidly: pectin molecular weight declines at 10-20 kDa per day from approximately 130-160 kDa to 80-120 kDa, soluble pectin fraction increases 6-12% per day reaching 65-80% of total pectin, and middle lamella degradation accelerates with cell-to-cell adhesion strength dropping 25-40% per day from pre-maximum values. ||Cellular mechanical properties undergo dramatic transformation: compression force required for 20% deformation decreases from 3.5-5.5 N to 2.0-3.5 N within 24-48 hours, puncture resistance drops 30-50% representing compromised skin integrity, and berry elasticity modulus declines sharply indicating transition from elastic to plastic deformation behavior. ||The maximum rate period exhibits highest sensitivity to environmental conditions: temperature effects are amplified with Q₁₀ values of 2.5-3.5 for softening rate compared to 1.8-2.4 during other phases, water stress can reduce maximum rates by 25-45% through limitation of cell wall enzyme synthesis and activity, and extreme heat (>35°C) can actually reduce maximum rates through enzyme denaturation despite accelerated passive softening from membrane disruption. ||Gene expression during maximum softening rate shows peak transcription of cell wall-modifying genes: PG transcripts reach 100-200 fold elevation above green berry levels, expansin mRNAs achieve 60-120 fold increases, and pectate lyase genes show 40-80 fold upregulation, all coordinated by continued high abscisic acid signaling (1000-3000 ng/g) maintaining ripening program expression. ||Subcellular events during maximum rate inclu Golgi apparatus maximum activity producing cell wall-modifying enzymes at peak rates, endoplasmic reticulum stress responses from intense protein synthesis demand, and vacuolar membrane destabilization with increasing permeability facilitating cytoplasm-vacuole mixing that affects cellular compartmentation. ||Cultivar-specific patterns of maximum softening rate reflect genetic variation in cell wall composition and enzyme expression: Pinot Noir exhibits very rapid maximum rates (5-8% per day) associated with thin cell walls and high PG expression, Cabernet Sauvignon shows intermediate rates (3-5% per day) with thicker cell walls and moderate enzyme levels, while Nebbiolo displays slower maximum rates (2-4% per day) correlated with robust cell wall structure and lower enzyme activity. ||Berry vulnerability reaches its apex during maximum softening rate: skin tensile strength drops to 40-60% of pre-softening values creating maximum susceptibility to splitting and cracking, pathogen penetration resistance declines sharply with 60-80% of successful Botrytis infections initiating during this narrow window, and mechanical harvest damage potential peaks as berries lose structural integrity most rapidly. ||Coordination with other veraison processes is tight: maximum softening rate typically occurs 1-3 days after initial color change in red cultivars, coincides with peak rates of sugar accumulation (often same 24-48 hour window), and precedes maximum anthocyanin synthesis rates by 2-4 days allowing structural modification to support subsequent pigment accumulation. ||Viticultural implications of maximum softening rate timing inclu this represents the critical decision window for harvest timing in varieties where excessive softness is problematic (sparkling wine base grapes require harvesting before maximum rate period), irrigation management must be precise to avoid water stress that could limit softening but also prevent excess that accelerates it beyond optimal, and canopy management effects on bunch microclimate are maximally expressed during this interval when temperature sensitivity peaks.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 229-230 softening kinetics and rate dynamics || Thomas TR, Matthews MA, Shackel KA (2006) Direct in situ measurement of cell turgor in grape berries during development Australian J Grape Wine Res 12:173-180 firmness decline rates || Nunan KJ, Sims IM, Bacic A, Robinson SP, Fincher GB (1998) Changes in cell wall composition during ripening of grape berries Plant Physiol 118:783-792 pectin degradation kinetics."
},

  "Rapid_Firmness_Loss": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Firmness_Loss is a Peak_Softening characterized by accelerated reduction of compression force, penetration resistance, and elastic modulus producing transformation from firm to readily deformable berry texture within a concentrated interval.",
  "alternative_term": "accelerated mechanical resistance decline | fast texture softening | quick firmness reduction | rapid compression resistance loss |+ beschleunigte mechanische Widerstands-Abnahme | schnelle Textur-Erweichung | rasche Festigkeits-Reduktion | rapider Kompressions-Widerstands-Verlust",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Willamette Valley Pinot Noir vineyard in Oregon, rapid firmness loss was documented over 5 days in early September Year N+1 (BBCH 83-84) when compression firmness declined from 2.6 N to 1.5 N (5.3% per day average), puncture resistance dropped from 2.2 N to 1.3 N, soluble pectin increased from 48% to 71%, and berry fresh weight rose from 1.08 g to 1.28 g as sugar accumulated from 16.8 to 21.2° Brix under optimal conditions (daily high 24-27°C, nighttime low 12-15°C).",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Firmness_Loss is distinguished from Maximum_Softening_Rate by representing sustained rapid decline rather than instantaneous peak velocity, from Initial_Berry_Softening by exhibiting accelerated rather than onset rates, and from Complete_Berry_Softening by focusing on the active transformation process rather than final state. ||Duration typically 3-6 days during peak softening. ||Firmness decline rates: soft cultivars 4-7% per day, medium 3-5% per day, firm varieties 2-4% per day. ||Cell wall degradation contributes 70-85% to firmness loss, turgor changes 15-25%, other factors 5-10%. ||Rapid_Firmness_Loss timing and magnitude critically determine harvest window and berry handling requirements. || This process occurs during the central portion of peak softening (typically 3-5 days within mid-veraison BBCH 83-84) and is measured through multiple mechanical testing parameters: compression firmness declining from 2.2-3.2 N to 1.3-2.2 N (30-45% reduction), puncture resistance dropping from 1.8-2.8 N to 1.0-1.8 N (35-50% decrease), and elastic modulus falling from 250-400 kPa to 120-220 kPa indicating fundamental shift in cellular mechanical properties. ||The rapid firmness loss results from convergent structural modifications: cell wall pectin degradation produces 50-70% soluble pectin (from 30-45% pre-softening) with molecular weight reduction to 70-110 kDa (from 140-200 kDa), middle lamella dissolution causes 50-70% loss of intercellular adhesion creating cell separation and berry pliability, and hemicellulose modification particularly xyloglucan restructuring contributes 20-35% to overall firmness decline through loss of cell wall tensile strength. ||Cellular mechanical changes during rapid firmness loss inclu turgor pressure shows modest 10-20% reduction (from 0.5-0.8 MPa to 0.4-0.65 MPa) contributing 15-25% to total firmness loss, cell wall extensibility increases 3-5 fold allowing plastic rather than elastic deformation under compression, and skin tensile strength decreases 40-60% creating vulnerability to splitting and enabling easier berry compression. ||Enzyme activities responsible for rapid firmness loss reach sustained high levels: polygalacturonase maintains 90-180 units throughout the rapid loss period cleaving α-1,4-galacturonan linkages, pectin methylesterase operates at 100-180 units demethylating pectin and creating PG substrates, β-galactosidase activity (25-60 units) removes galactose side chains facilitating backbone access, and expansin activity promotes stress relaxation in cell walls enabling irreversible expansion. ||Temperature profoundly affects rapid firmness loss kinetics: optimal conditions (22-28°C) support maximum enzyme efficiency producing 3-6% firmness decline per day, cooler temperatures (16-22°C) reduce rates to 2-4% per day extending the rapid loss period, moderate heat (28-32°C) can accelerate loss to 4-8% per day but may compromise quality through disrupted metabolism, and excessive heat (>32°C) causes abnormal softening patterns through membrane disruption and cellular disorganization. ||Cultivar variation in rapid firmness loss characteristics reflects genetic differences in cell wall composition and enzyme complement: soft-fruited varieties like Pinot Noir exhibit very rapid firmness loss (4-7% per day) with high PG expression and thin cell walls losing 45-65% of initial firmness in 4-6 days, medium-firmness cultivars like Merlot show intermediate loss rates (3-5% per day) with moderate enzyme levels declining 35-50% over 5-7 days, while firm-fruited varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon display slower loss (2-4% per day) retaining relatively higher firmness with 30-45% decline over 6-9 days. ||Rapid firmness loss has significant viticultural implications: berries become increasingly susceptible to physical damage from handling, wind, rain, and harvest operations with compression damage threshold dropping from >3.5 N to <2.0 N, pathogen infection particularly Botrytis cinerea finds optimal entry as skin resistance declines and surface microcracking increases, and bunch compaction intensifies as softened berries deform to fill spaces within clusters potentially creating anaerobic conditions and split berry problems. ||Water relations during rapid firmness loss show complex interactions: moderate water deficit (leaf ψ -0.8 to -1.2 MPa) can slow firmness loss by 20-35% through reduced enzyme synthesis and slight turgor maintenance, excessive deficit (<-1.4 MPa) may paradoxically accelerate loss through cellular stress and membrane dysfunction, while abundant water supply can accelerate firmness loss through enhanced cell wall enzyme activity but risks berry splitting as internal pressure exceeds diminished skin strength. ||Molecular control involves sustained expression of ripening-related genes: continued high ABA levels (1200-2800 ng/g) maintain softening gene transcription, ethylene production shows cultivar-dependent slight elevation (0.3-1.8 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹) in some varieties correlating with firmness loss rate, and sugar signaling through hexokinase pathways may feedback-regulate cell wall enzyme genes linking metabolite accumulation with texture transformation. ||Berry quality implications of rapid firmness loss timing and intensity inclu premature or excessive firmness loss before adequate flavor and aromatic compound development can produce soft berries with insufficient character, delayed firmness loss can result in harvesting overly firm fruit with incomplete textural development affecting wine mouthfeel, and optimal firmness loss coordinated with sugar and phenolic accumulation produces balanced berries with desirable texture and chemical composition. ||Measurement of rapid firmness loss provides viticultural decision support: firmness testing 2-3 times per week during veraison using penetrometer or compression devices guides harvest timing particularly for varieties where texture is critical (table grapes, some wine styles), firmness trends predict optimal picking windows allowing logistics planning, and cultivar-specific firmness benchmarks calibrated to desired wine styles enable targeted harvest scheduling.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 228-232 berry firmness dynamics || Thomas TR, Shackel KA, Matthews MA (2008) Mesocarp cell turgor in Vitis vinifera L. berries throughout development and its relation to firmness, growth, and the onset of ripening Australian J Grape Wine Res 14:1-8 firmness measurement and mechanisms || Yakushiji H, Sakurai N, Morinaga K (2001) Changes in cell-wall polysaccharides from the mesocarp of grape berries during veraison Physiol Plant 111:188-195 structural basis of firmness loss."
},

  "Cell_Wall_Breakdown_Maximum": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Wall_Breakdown_Maximum is a Peak_Softening involving concurrent peak activity of cell wall-modifying enzymes producing maximum disassembly of the pectin-hemicellulose network.",
  "alternative_term": "peak cell wall enzyme activity | maximum polysaccharide degradation | peak pectin depolymerization | maximum structural breakdown |+ Spitzen-Zellwand-Enzym-Aktivität | maximale Polysaccharid-Degradation | Spitzen-Pektin-Depolymerisation | maximaler struktureller Abbau",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, cell wall breakdown maximum was measured during a 3-day period in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 84) when polygalacturonase activity peaked at 175 units, pectin molecular weight declined from 155 kDa to 92 kDa, soluble pectin increased from 56% to 73% of total, middle lamella adhesion strength dropped from 2.8 N to 1.2 N, and berry firmness decreased from 2.4 N to 1.6 N as temperature conditions averaged 25-27°C optimal for enzyme activity.",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Wall_Breakdown_Maximum is distinguished from other softening phases by representing the convergence point of peak activities for multiple cell wall-degrading enzymes rather than firmness decline per se. ||Duration typically 2-4 days during peak softening. ||Enzyme activities at maximum: PG 120-220 units, PME 110-200 units, XET 50-120 units, β-Gal 30-70 units. ||Pectin solubilization contributes 55-70% to firmness loss, hemicellulose modification 20-30%, other factors 10-20%. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C for maximum enzyme function. ||Cell_Wall_Breakdown_Maximum represents the fundamental mechanistic basis for berry softening and determines final berry texture characteristics. || This critical phase typically occurs during a 2-4 day period within mid-veraison (BBCH 83-84) and is defined by convergence of maximum enzyme activities: polygalacturonase reaches 120-220 units (8-15 fold above pre-veraison baseline) cleaving homogalacturonan backbone α-1,4 linkages at maximum rate, pectin methylesterase achieves 110-200 units demethylating pectin polymers to create optimal PG substrates, pectate lyase shows 30-70 units eliminating methylated galacturonic acid residues through β-elimination, and β-galactosidase operates at 30-70 units removing galactose side chains from rhamnogalacturonan I regions facilitating backbone access by other enzymes. ||The maximum breakdown period produces profound structural modifications: pectin molecular weight undergoes steepest decline from approximately 130-180 kDa to 70-110 kDa representing extensive depolymerization with average chain length reduction from 700-1000 to 350-600 galacturonic acid residues, soluble pectin fraction increases maximally at 8-15% per day reaching 65-80% of total pectin (from 35-50% at breakdown initiation), and degree of methylesterification drops from 60-75% to 30-45% exposing carboxyl groups that create charge repulsion and pectin chain separation. ||Middle lamella degradation reaches maximum intensity during cell wall breakdown maximum: pectin-rich middle lamella between adjacent cells undergoes extensive solubilization with 60-80% of structural pectin depolymerized, intercellular adhesion strength declines by 50-70% from pre-breakdown values measured through cell separation force testing, and transmission electron microscopy reveals progressive middle lamella dissolution with electron-lucent zones replacing electron-dense pectin networks characteristic of firm berries. ||Hemicellulose modifications contribute substantially to maximum breakdown: xyloglucan endotransglycosylase activity peaks at 50-120 units catalyzing transglycosylation reactions that restructure xyloglucan chains reducing cell wall tensile strength by 40-60%, α-arabinosidase and β-xylosidase activities (15-40 units each) remove arabinose and xylose decorations from xyloglucans facilitating backbone modifications, and glucanase activity (20-50 units) contributes to general polysaccharide network loosening. ||Gene expression patterns underlying cell wall breakdown maximum show coordinated peak transcription: PG genes exhibit 100-200 fold upregulation above green berry levels with some cultivars showing multiple PG isoforms expressed sequentially or concurrently, expansin genes reach 70-140 fold elevation facilitating stress relaxation and irreversible cell wall extension, pectin methylesterase genes show 50-100 fold increases, and xyloglucan endotransglycosylase genes achieve 40-80 fold upregulation all orchestrated by sustained high abscisic acid signaling (1500-3500 ng/g fresh weight). ||Regulatory control of maximum breakdown involves transcriptional and post-translational mechanisms: ripening transcription factors including VvNAC, VvMYB, and VvMADS-box proteins reach peak expression coordinating cell wall enzyme gene transcription, protein synthesis machinery operates at maximum capacity producing 20-40 mg cell wall enzymes per kg berry fresh weight per day, and enzyme secretion through Golgi-mediated vesicular transport achieves maximum rates delivering enzymes to cell wall targets. ||Temperature effects on cell wall breakdown maximum are pronounced: optimal conditions (22-28°C) support maximum enzyme synthesis, stability, and activity producing complete breakdown patterns, cooler temperatures (16-22°C) reduce enzyme reaction rates by 35-55% extending the breakdown period and potentially producing incomplete degradation, while excessive heat (>30°C) can denature enzymes reducing maximum activities by 25-45% despite accelerated reaction kinetics at elevated temperatures. ||Subcellular consequences of maximum breakdown inclu cell wall thickness reduction from 2.5-4.0 μm to 1.5-2.5 μm through polymer degradation and water infiltration, porosity increases allowing enhanced diffusion of metabolites and water-soluble compounds between cells, and mechanical properties shift from rigid elastic behavior to compliant plastic deformation as structural integrity declines. ||Cultivar variation in cell wall breakdown maximum reflects genetic differences in enzyme complement and cell wall composition: high-PG cultivars like Gewürztraminer show very intense breakdown with 75-85% pectin solubilization and molecular weight dropping to 60-90 kDa, moderate cultivars like Chardonnay exhibit intermediate breakdown (65-75% solubilization, 80-120 kDa final MW), while low-enzyme varieties like Barbera display less extensive breakdown (55-70% solubilization, 100-140 kDa MW) often retaining firmer texture. ||Environmental stresses during maximum breakdown can substantially modify the process: water deficit reduces breakdown intensity through 30-50% lower enzyme gene expression and synthesis limiting cell wall modifications and potentially maintaining firmer berries, excess water can accelerate breakdown through enhanced turgor-driven cell expansion activating mechanosensitive cell wall loosening pathways, and nutrient deficiency particularly nitrogen limitation during ripening can reduce enzyme synthesis capacity limiting maximum breakdown achievement. ||Berry quality implications of cell wall breakdown maximum timing and completeness inclu complete breakdown coordinated with sugar and phenolic accumulation produces optimal berry texture for quality wine production, incomplete breakdown results in excessively firm berries with potential processing problems (difficult crushing, incomplete extraction), while premature or excessive breakdown creates overly soft fruit vulnerable to damage and with potential aromatic compound losses through increased volatilization from disrupted cellular compartmentation. ||Viticultural monitoring of cell wall breakdown maximum through enzyme assays and pectin analysis provides harvest timing guidance particularly for premium wine production where texture balance is critical for desired wine style and aging potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 230-232 cell wall degrading enzymes in ripening || Nunan KJ, Sims IM, Bacic A, Robinson SP, Fincher GB (1998) Changes in cell wall composition during ripening of grape berries Plant Physiol 118:783-792 pectin and hemicellulose breakdown || Goulao LF, Santos J, de Sousa I, Oliveira CM (2007) Patterns of enzymatic activity of cell wall-modifying enzymes during growth and ripening of apples Postharvest Biol Technol 43:307-318 comparative enzyme dynamics."
},

  "Complete_Berry_Softening": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Berry_Softening is a Berry_Softening characterized by firmness decline at asymptotic minimum producing the ripe berry texture state during late véraison through early ripening.",
  "alternative_term": "final berry texture achievement | terminal softening state | mature berry firmness | ripening completion texture |+ finale Beeren-Textur-Erreichung | terminaler Erweichungs-Zustand | reife Beeren-Festigkeit | Reifungs-Vollendungs-Textur",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Bordeaux Merlot vineyard, complete berry softening was documented in early October Year N+1 (BBCH 85-87) when firmness stabilized at 1.5-1.7 N after declining from 5.2 N at green berry stage, soluble pectin reached 76-78% of total, sugar content plateaued at 23.5-24.0° Brix, titratable acidity stabilized at 5.2-5.4 g/L, skin anthocyanins achieved 1850-1950 mg/kg, and sensory evaluation indicated optimal flavor development suitable for harvest under typical autumn conditions (daily high 18-22°C, nighttime 10-14°C).",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Berry_Softening is distinguished from Peak_Softening by representing final state achievement rather than maximum transformation velocity, from Progressive_Softening by exhibiting stabilization rather than continued moderate decline, and from earlier ripening phases by indicating readiness for harvest assessment. ||Duration typically 1-2 weeks during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87). ||Final firmness values: soft cultivars 0.8-1.5 N, medium 1.2-2.0 N, firm varieties 1.5-2.5 N. ||Enzyme activities decline to 30-50% of peak maintaining cell wall state. ||Complete_Berry_Softening achievement typically signals optimal harvest window approach requiring integrated assessment of firmness, chemistry, and sensory characteristics. || This terminal softening phase typically extends 1-2 weeks (BBCH 85-87) following peak softening and is characterized by berry firmness stabilizing at cultivar-specific final values: soft-fruited varieties like Pinot Noir and Gamay reach 0.8-1.5 N compression firmness representing 70-80% total decline from green berry values (3.0-5.5 N), medium-firmness cultivars like Merlot and Syrah stabilize at 1.2-2.0 N indicating 60-70% reduction from initial firmness (3.5-6.0 N), while firm-fruited varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon and Nebbiolo maintain 1.5-2.5 N firmness showing 50-65% decline from green berry baseline (4.0-6.5 N). ||The completion of softening involves establishment of final cell wall architecture: soluble pectin reaches stable maximum values of 70-85% total pectin (from 20-30% in green berries) with minimal further increase, pectin molecular weight stabilizes at cultivar-specific minima ranging 60-120 kDa (from 180-350 kDa pre-veraison), degree of methylesterification plateaus at 25-40% (from 65-80% initially), and hemicellulose modification reaches completion with xyloglucan molecular weight and structure stabilized at final degraded states. ||Enzyme activities during complete berry softening transition from peak to basal maintenance levels: polygalacturonase declines from maximum values (120-220 units) to sustained moderate activity (40-80 units) sufficient to maintain cell wall state but not drive further major degradation, pectin methylesterase similarly reduces from 110-200 units to 35-70 units, while other cell wall-modifying enzymes including xyloglucan endotransglycosylase, β-galactosidase, and expansins show parallel activity reductions to 30-50% of peak values maintaining cell wall plasticity without continued extensive breakdown. ||Cellular mechanical properties at complete softening reflect final berry texture: cell wall thickness stabilizes at 1.5-2.8 μm (reduced from 2.5-4.5 μm green berry values) with no further thinning, turgor pressure reaches final low-moderate levels 0.3-0.6 MPa (compared to 0.6-1.0 MPa in firm berries) contributing 15-25% to residual firmness while cell wall structural integrity provides 75-85% of remaining mechanical resistance, and skin tensile strength plateaus at 40-65% of green berry values creating the characteristic ripe berry vulnerability to compression and puncture. ||Complete berry softening coincides with other ripening process completions: sugar accumulation typically reaches plateau (20-28° Brix depending on cultivar and style goals) within 1-2 weeks of softening completion, acid levels stabilize at final values (4-8 g/L titratable acidity) as malate degradation slows substantially, anthocyanin accumulation in red cultivars approaches maximum (500-3000 mg/kg skin depending on variety and conditions), and aromatic compound development reaches characteristic ripe profiles suitable for harvest. ||Gene expression patterns at complete softening show transition from ripening peak to maintenance phase: cell wall enzyme genes decline from maximum expression (100-200 fold above green berry) to moderate sustained levels (20-50 fold), sugar transporter genes reduce from peak expression as accumulation slows, while genes involved in secondary metabolism including phenylpropanoid pathway components and volatile biosynthesis enzymes reach maximum expression supporting final quality compound synthesis. ||Hormonal regulation during complete softening reflects ripening program consolidation: abscisic acid levels remain elevated (800-2000 ng/g fresh weight) but decline from veraison peak values (1500-3500 ng/g) as major developmental transitions complete, ethylene production shows cultivar-dependent patterns with some varieties maintaining slight elevation (0.3-1.2 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹) while others return to baseline, and auxin levels decline to minimal values reflecting completion of growth-related processes. ||Temperature effects on achieving complete softening show reduced sensitivity compared to earlier phases: once major structural transformations occur during peak softening, temperature primarily affects the timing of reaching final state rather than final firmness values themselves, with warmer conditions (25-30°C) accelerating approach to completion by 3-7 days compared to cooler temperatures (18-23°C), but final firmness values differing by only 10-20% across normal temperature ranges. ||Cultivar variation in complete softening characteristics determines varietal typicity: Pinot Noir achieves very soft final texture (0.9-1.4 N) with thin skins and delicate berry structure requiring careful handling, Cabernet Sauvignon maintains relatively firmer completion (1.6-2.4 N) with thicker skins and more robust cell walls tolerating mechanical harvest, and intermediate varieties like Merlot show balanced completion (1.3-1.9 N) suitable for varied viticultural and harvest approaches. ||Viticultural implications of complete berry softening inclu harvest timing decisions based on achieving desired firmness for intended wine style (sparkling wines may harvest before completion, while late-harvest wines extend beyond completion allowing slight over-ripening), mechanical harvest feasibility assessment since excessively soft berries (< 1.0 N) may suffer unacceptable damage requiring hand harvest, and disease management intensification as fully softened berries with minimal skin strength show maximum vulnerability to Botrytis infection and other pathogens requiring protective measures. ||Berry quality at complete softening represents the integration of all ripening processes: optimal harvest typically occurs when softening completion coincides with target sugar levels, desired acidity, complete flavor and aroma development, and phenolic maturity producing balanced grapes suitable for quality wine production, while discordant ripening with premature softening completion before chemical maturity or delayed softening past optimal chemical composition creates quality challenges requiring viticultural decisions balancing texture and composition priorities. ||Environmental stress effects on complete softening achievement inclu water deficit during late ripening can maintain slightly firmer final texture through mild turgor maintenance and reduced cell wall enzyme activity potentially beneficial for varieties prone to excessive softness, heat stress may accelerate softening completion but risks premature berry dehydration and shriveling before optimal flavor development, and cool conditions can delay completion requiring extended hang time that may improve complexity but increases disease pressure and harvest logistics challenges. ||Monitoring complete berry softening through regular firmness testing every 3-5 days during late veraison and early ripening combined with chemical maturity assessment (sugar, acid, pH) and sensory evaluation (flavor, tannin) enables precise harvest timing decisions optimizing berry quality for specific wine styles and market requirements.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 232-235 berry maturation and harvest criteria || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Australian J Grape Wine Res 48:125-144 berry ripening completion || Rolle L, Torchio F, Zeppa G, Gerbi V (2009) Relationship between skin break force and anthocyanin extractability at different ripening stages Amer J Enol Vitic 60:93-97 firmness and maturity correlation."
},

  "Final_Softening_State": {
  "definition": "A Final_Softening_State is a Complete_Berry_Softening characterized by berry mechanical properties at cultivar-specific equilibrium values defining ripe berry handling and processing behavior.",
  "alternative_term": "equilibrium berry texture | stable ripe firmness | terminal mechanical state | harvest-ready texture |+ Gleichgewichts-Beeren-Textur | stabile reife Festigkeit | terminaler mechanischer Zustand | erntereife Textur",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Margaret River Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard in Western Australia, final softening state was achieved in late March Year N+1 (BBCH 87) when firmness stabilized at 1.8-2.0 N over 10 days, soluble pectin plateaued at 68-70% of total, sugar content reached 24.2-24.5° Brix, skin anthocyanins stabilized at 2150-2250 mg/kg, seed tannins showed brown coloration indicating phenolic maturity, and sensory evaluation confirmed balanced flavor development under warm dry autumn conditions (daily maximum 26-29°C, minimal precipitation).",
  "editor_note": "Final_Softening_State is distinguished from Complete_Berry_Softening by representing the stable equilibrium condition rather than the achievement process, from Peak_Softening by exhibiting stability rather than maximum transformation velocity, and from Progressive_Softening by showing plateau rather than continued decline. ||Stability typically maintained 2-4 weeks under optimal conditions. ||Firmness values: very soft cultivars 0.8-1.5 N, moderate 1.2-2.0 N, firm varieties 1.5-2.5 N. ||Pectin solubilization 70-85%, turgor contribution to firmness 15-25%, cell wall structural integrity 75-85%. ||Final_Softening_State achievement indicates berry readiness for integrated maturity assessment guiding harvest timing decisions. || This state is achieved during late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 85-89) and persists through harvest unless environmental extremes or senescence processes cause further texture degradation. ||The final softening state is quantitatively defined by stable mechanical property measurements: compression firmness stabilizing within narrow ranges specific to each cultivar (±0.1-0.3 N variation over 1-2 week periods), puncture resistance reaching plateau values reflecting equilibrated skin strength and cell wall integrity, elastic modulus stabilizing at final values indicating completed transition from elastic to plastic deformation behavior characteristic of ripe fruit, and compression deformation curves showing consistent shape indicating reproducible cellular mechanical responses. ||Cell wall architecture at final softening state exhibits completed structural reorganization: pectin composition stabilized with soluble fraction 70-85% of total (compared to 20-30% green berries), pectin molecular weight distributions plateaued at cultivar-specific values ranging 60-120 kDa with polydispersity indices stabilized, degree of methylesterification equilibrated at 25-40% creating electrostatic repulsion maintaining pectin chain separation, and middle lamella extensively solubilized (60-80% degraded) establishing final intercellular adhesion characteristics that determine berry integrity under compression and cell separation behavior during crushing. ||Hemicellulose composition at final state shows completed modifications: xyloglucan molecular weight reduced to stable minimum values through transglycosylation reactions, arabinose and xylose decorations removed to final extent affecting xyloglucan-cellulose interactions and cell wall mechanical properties, and cellulose microfibrils maintained largely intact (80-95% of original cellulose preserved) providing residual structural framework supporting remaining firmness. ||Enzyme activities at final softening state transition to maintenance levels: polygalacturonase activity stabilizes at 30-60% of peak values (40-80 units) sufficient to maintain pectin solubilization equilibrium without driving further extensive degradation, pectin methylesterase operates at 30-50% peak levels (35-70 units) balancing methylation-demethylation dynamics, and other cell wall enzymes including xyloglucan endotransglycosylase, expansins, and glycosidases maintain low-moderate activities (20-40% of peak) preserving cell wall plasticity without continued breakdown. ||Cellular turgor at final softening state reaches equilibrium reflecting water relations and osmotic adjustments: turgor pressure stabilizes at 0.3-0.6 MPa (compared to 0.6-1.0 MPa green berries) contributing 15-25% to residual berry firmness, osmotic potential reaches final values -1.8 to -2.6 MPa driven by accumulated sugars (20-28° Brix) and organic acids creating characteristic ripe berry water relations, and cell membrane permeability stabilizes at elevated levels compared to green berries facilitating metabolite exchange but maintained below catastrophic leakage thresholds. ||Final softening state mechanical properties determine berry and wine quality characteristics: skin tensile strength at 40-65% of green berry values affects berry splitting resistance, bunch compression, and ease of crushing during processing, berry compression firmness correlates with must yield during pressing (softer berries r² = 0.75-0.88 with higher free-run fraction), and cell wall porosity influences extraction efficiency of phenolic compounds, flavors, and aromatics during maceration with more degraded cell walls facilitating enhanced extraction. ||Cultivar-specific final softening states reflect genetic variation in cell wall composition and degradation extent: very soft cultivars (Pinot Noir, Gamay) achieve 0.8-1.5 N firmness with 75-85% pectin solubilization and extensive middle lamella degradation creating delicate berries requiring gentle handling, moderately soft varieties (Merlot, Syrah, Chardonnay) reach 1.2-2.0 N with 65-75% solubilization and intermediate cell wall breakdown producing balanced texture for varied applications, while firmer cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Sangiovese) maintain 1.5-2.5 N through 55-70% solubilization and more limited structural degradation allowing mechanical harvest tolerance. ||Environmental factors influencing final softening state characteristics inclu water availability during ripening with moderate deficit potentially maintaining slightly firmer final states through 10-20% higher turgor and reduced enzyme activity while extreme deficit risks desiccation and abnormal texture, temperature during late ripening affecting enzyme activity levels with cooler conditions (18-22°C) potentially preserving slightly firmer texture compared to warmer ripening (25-30°C) though final differences typically <15%, and canopy microclimate particularly bunch exposure affecting berry temperature and consequently softening enzyme function with shaded bunches often 0.1-0.3 N firmer than exposed clusters. ||Temporal stability of final softening state varies by cultivar and conditions: under optimal conditions berries maintain stable texture for 2-4 weeks allowing flexible harvest scheduling, while environmental stresses including heat waves, heavy rain, or disease pressure can destabilize final state causing rapid over-softening or shriveling within days requiring accelerated harvest, and some cultivars show greater final state stability (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah) tolerating 3-5 week hang time versus unstable varieties (Pinot Noir, Gewürztraminer) requiring harvest within 1-2 weeks of achieving final state. ||Quality implications of final softening state characteristics inclu excessively soft final states (<1.0 N) create handling challenges, increase damage during mechanical harvest (>30% berry rupture), and may indicate over-ripening with potential flavor degradation, insufficient softening (>2.5 N at nominal sugar maturity) suggests incomplete ripening potentially producing astringent wines with harsh tannins and limited aromatic expression, while optimal final states (1.2-2.2 N for most premium wine cultivars) balanced with chemical and phenolic maturity indicate ideal harvest readiness producing wines with optimal extraction, balanced structure, and characteristic varietal expression. ||Viticultural management targeting optimal final softening state involves: irrigation scheduling during late ripening to avoid water stress that might maintain excessive firmness or excess that accelerates over-softening, canopy management to moderate bunch temperatures preventing accelerated softening while allowing adequate warmth for complete ripening, and disease control particularly Botrytis prevention since soft berries with compromised skin integrity show maximum vulnerability requiring fungicide protection or harvest timing minimizing disease window exposure.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 232-238 berry maturation and harvest assessment || Rolle L, Giacosa S, Gerbi V, Novello V (2011) Comparative study of texture properties, color characteristics, and chemical composition of ten white table-grape varieties Amer J Enol Vitic 62:49-56 final berry texture characteristics || Letaief H, Rolle L, Zeppa G, Gerbi V (2008) Assessment of grape skin hardness by a puncture test J Sci Food Agric 88:1567-1575 final state mechanical properties."
},

  "Mature_Berry_Texture": {
  "definition": "A Mature_Berry_Texture is a Complete_Berry_Softening characterized by cultivar-specific tactile properties and deformability defining berry suitability for harvest and processing.",
  "alternative_term": "ripe berry tactile quality | harvest-ready berry feel | completed texture development | characteristic varietal texture |+ reife Beeren-taktile Qualität | erntereife Beeren-Haptik | vollendete Textur-Entwicklung | charakteristische Sorten-Textur",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Chianti Classico Sangiovese vineyard in Tuscany, mature berry texture was assessed in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 87-89) showing compression firmness 1.9-2.1 N (indicating characteristic firm Sangiovese texture), puncture resistance 2.1-2.3 N reflecting thick skin, sensory evaluation describing moderately firm flesh with balanced juiciness, chemical maturity at 23.8-24.2° Brix and 5.8-6.1 g/L TA, skin anthocyanins 1950-2100 mg/kg, and brown seed tannins confirming integrated phenolic and textural maturity under typical Tuscan autumn conditions (daily high 22-26°C, cool nights 12-15°C).",
  "editor_note": "Mature_Berry_Texture is distinguished from Final_Softening_State by representing the integrated sensory and functional quality rather than just mechanical properties, from Complete_Berry_Softening by encompassing all berry texture attributes beyond firmness decline, and from immature berry texture by exhibiting characteristic ripe attributes suitable for harvest. ||Compression firmness ranges: very soft 0.8-1.5 N, medium 1.2-2.0 N, firm 1.5-2.5 N. ||Skin contribution to texture 30-45%, flesh firmness 55-70%. ||Mature_Berry_Texture assessment is essential for harvest timing decisions integrating mechanical, sensory, chemical, and phenolic maturity parameters to optimize grape quality for intended wine style. || This mature texture emerges during late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 85-89) and encompasses the full spectrum of physical berry attributes: skin mechanical properties including tensile strength (40-65% of green berry baseline), puncture resistance (1.0-2.5 N cultivar-dependent), and surface characteristics (smooth, slightly tacky from accumulated sugars and waxes, easily indented by finger pressure 0.5-1.5 kg force), flesh firmness and juiciness reflecting cell wall degradation state and water content (mesocarp readily yielding under gentle compression, juice easily expressed with 1.5-3.0 N force), and overall berry deformability showing plastic rather than elastic behavior (permanent shape change under moderate compression, minimal elastic recovery indicating extensive cell wall modification). ||Sensory evaluation of mature berry texture by trained assessors reveals characteristic quality descriptors: skin texture described as thin-to-moderate thickness with easy tearing (compared to tough, resistant green berry skin), flesh described as soft, yielding, juicy with minimal fibrousness (versus firm, crunchy, dry green berry flesh), and overall berry described as readily crushable between fingers with copious juice release and minimal resistance (contrasting with green berry resistance requiring substantial force and producing little free juice). ||Mechanical measurement of mature berry texture provides quantitative assessment: compression tests showing force-deformation curves with initial linear elastic region (0-15% deformation) followed by extensive plastic yield region (15-60% deformation) and final densification (>60% deformation) where crushed berry remnants resist further compression, with key parameters including yield point force (1.2-2.8 N cultivar-dependent), work to rupture skin (0.8-2.5 mJ), and compression modulus (100-300 kPa indicating soft-moderate texture compared to 300-600 kPa for firm green berries). ||Puncture testing reveals skin strength characteristics: maximum puncture force required to penetrate skin with standardized probe (2mm diameter) ranging 1.0-2.5 N depending on cultivar (soft-skinned varieties 1.0-1.5 N, thick-skinned 1.8-2.5 N), work to puncture (0.5-1.8 mJ) reflecting total energy to breach skin, and post-puncture force (40-70% of maximum) indicating flesh firmness after skin penetration. ||Cellular basis of mature berry texture includes: extensively degraded cell walls (70-85% pectin solubilization, 60-120 kDa average pectin molecular weight) providing minimal structural resistance, reduced turgor pressure (0.3-0.6 MPa) contributing only 15-25% to overall firmness, large vacuoles (85-95% of cell volume) filled with sugar-rich juice creating characteristic juiciness, and weakened intercellular adhesion (60-80% middle lamella degradation) allowing easy cell separation during mastication or crushing. ||Mature berry texture varies systematically among cultivars reflecting genetic differences in cell wall composition and degradation extent: very soft varieties (Pinot Noir, Gamay, Grenache) exhibit 0.8-1.5 N compression firmness with delicate skin and highly degraded flesh producing extremely juicy, fragile berries requiring careful handling and typically precluding mechanical harvest, medium-textured cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Chardonnay, Sauvignon Blanc) show 1.2-2.0 N firmness with balanced skin strength and flesh firmness suitable for mechanical or hand harvest and varied wine styles, while firm-textured varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Sangiovese, Tempranillo) maintain 1.5-2.5 N firmness with thicker skins and more resistant flesh tolerating mechanical harvest and producing wines with substantial structure and aging potential. ||Mature berry texture profoundly affects processing characteristics: soft berries with low skin strength (1.0-1.5 N puncture resistance) crush easily under minimal force (1-2 bar crusher pressure) yielding high free-run must (60-75% total juice) but risk excessive skin maceration and phenolic over-extraction, medium berries (1.5-2.0 N) require moderate crushing force (2-3 bar) producing balanced free-run (55-70%) suitable for controlled extraction and varied wine styles, while firm berries (2.0-2.5 N) need substantial crushing (3-4 bar) yielding lower free-run (45-60%) but allowing extended maceration without excessive extraction and producing age-worthy structured wines. ||Temperature effects on mature berry texture inclu cool berry temperature (<15°C) slightly increases firmness through enhanced turgor and reduced cell wall enzyme activity providing 10-20% firmer texture compared to warm berries (25-30°C), extreme heat (>35°C) can cause partial cellular breakdown and membrane disruption producing abnormally soft texture with potential quality degradation, and diurnal temperature variation creates texture fluctuations (firmer in cool morning, softer in warm afternoon) affecting optimal harvest timing particularly for mechanical operations preferring firmer morning berries. ||Water relations influence mature berry texture dynamics: adequate water supply maintains optimal texture through balanced turgor supporting remaining firmness (0.4-0.6 MPa) without excessive softness, moderate deficit can maintain slightly firmer texture potentially beneficial for thick-skinned varieties while risking insufficient softening in naturally firm cultivars, while severe deficit causes desiccation-induced abnormal softening or shriveling compromising texture quality and juice yield. ||Mature berry texture assessment provides critical harvest timing information: tactile evaluation by experienced viticulturists squeezing representative berries from multiple cluster positions assessing readiness (too firm suggests incomplete ripening, excessively soft indicates over-ripeness or senescence), instrumental firmness testing with penetrometer or texturometer providing quantitative benchmarks calibrated to desired wine styles (sparkling wines 1.8-2.5 N, premium reds 1.2-2.0 N, late harvest <1.5 N), and combined assessment with chemical maturity (sugar, acid, pH) and phenolic ripeness determines optimal harvest windows balancing texture, composition, and quality goals. ||Mature berry texture stability and harvest window depends on cultivar and environmental conditions: stable varieties maintaining consistent texture 3-5 weeks (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah, Sangiovese) allow flexible scheduling and selective harvest, moderately stable cultivars (Merlot, Chardonnay) provide 2-3 week windows requiring reasonable promptness, while unstable varieties (Pinot Noir, Gewürztraminer, Riesling) may maintain optimal texture only 1-2 weeks necessitating precise harvest timing to capture peak quality before over-softening or senescence degradation. ||Quality implications of mature berry texture inclu optimal texture synchronized with chemical and phenolic maturity produces balanced grapes for premium wines with appropriate extraction potential, mouthfeel characteristics, and aging capacity, discordant maturity with premature softening before flavor development yields unbalanced wines with hollow mid-palate and insufficient complexity, while delayed softening past chemical maturity creates processing challenges and potentially harsh, extracted wines from over-firm berries requiring excessive maceration.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 235-238 berry texture and maturity assessment || Rolle L, Torchio F, Ferrandino A, Guidoni S (2012) Influence of wine-grape skin hardness on the kinetics of anthocyanin extraction Intl J Food Properties 15:249-261 mature berry texture characteristics || Letaief H, Rolle L, Zeppa G, Gerbi V (2008) Assessment of grape skin hardness by a puncture test J Sci Food Agric 88:1567-1575 texture measurement methodology."
},

  "Softening_Process_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Softening_Process_Completion is a Complete_Berry_Softening marked by stabilization of cell wall-modifying enzyme activities at maintenance levels with terminated programmed texture transformation.",
  "alternative_term": "terminal softening achievement | softening program endpoint | developmental texture completion | ripening softening finalization |+ terminale Erweichungs-Erreichung | Erweichungs-Programm-Endpunkt | Entwicklungs-Textur-Vollendung | Reifungs-Erweichungs-Abschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Valley Shiraz vineyard in Australia, softening process completion was documented 14 days post-veraison onset in late February Year N+1 (BBCH 87) when firmness stabilized at 1.5-1.6 N (±0.1 N over 10 days), polygalacturonase activity plateaued at 52-58 units (down from 168 units peak), soluble pectin reached 72-74% with <2% increase over 2 weeks, sugar content was 24.8° Brix, titratable acidity 5.5 g/L, seed tannins brown, and sensory evaluation confirmed balanced maturity under warm dry conditions (daily maximum 28-32°C, minimal precipitation) suitable for harvest.",
  "editor_note": "Softening_Process_Completion is distinguished from Complete_Berry_Softening by representing the developmental program endpoint rather than texture state achievement, from Mature_Berry_Texture by focusing on process termination rather than integrated sensory quality, and from earlier softening phases by exhibiting asymptotic stabilization of all softening parameters. ||Completion timing: early cultivars 10-14 days post-veraison, mid-season 12-16 days, late varieties 14-20 days. ||Enzyme activities stabilize at 25-40% of peak values. ||Post-completion stability varies 1-5 weeks cultivar-dependent. ||Softening_Process_Completion determination is essential for harvest timing decisions ensuring texture development synchronization with chemical and phenolic maturity to optimize grape quality for premium wine production. || This completion occurs during late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 85-89, typically 10-16 days post-veraison onset) and marks the transition from active ripening-driven softening to a stable mature state that persists until harvest unless environmental perturbations induce secondary texture changes. ||Enzymatic completion is characterized by polygalacturonase activity declining from peak values (120-220 units) to stable maintenance levels (35-70 units), pectin methylesterase similarly reducing from 110-200 units to 30-65 units, and other cell wall-modifying enzymes including xyloglucan endotransglycosylase (50-120 units declining to 15-40 units), β-galactosidase, pectate lyase, and expansins all showing parallel activity reductions to 25-40% of peak values indicating completion of major degradative processes while maintaining sufficient activity to preserve cell wall plasticity without driving further extensive breakdown. ||Gene expression patterns at softening process completion transition from ripening peak to post-ripening maintenance: cell wall enzyme genes decline from maximum transcription levels (80-200 fold above green berry baseline) to moderate sustained expression (15-50 fold) providing maintenance enzyme synthesis, transcription factors orchestrating ripening including NAC, MYB, and MADS-box genes show reduced expression as developmental program completion signals propagate, and genes involved in senescence and stress responses begin elevation indicating shift from active development to mature state maintenance or early senescence depending on environmental conditions and cultivar physiology. ||Cell wall structural completion shows pectin composition stabilized at final values: soluble pectin fraction plateaus at 70-85% of total (compared to 20-30% green berries with increases <2-3% per week after completion indicating minimal further solubilization), pectin molecular weight distributions stabilize at cultivar-specific minima (60-120 kDa with variation <5-8 kDa per week post-completion), degree of methylesterification equilibrates at 25-40% with minimal further demethylation (<2-3% change per week), and middle lamella extensively degraded (60-80% solubilized) with residual intact regions providing minimal intercellular adhesion contributing <15% to total berry firmness at completion. ||Hemicellulose modifications reach completion with xyloglucan molecular weight stabilized at reduced values following extensive transglycosylation, arabinan and galactan side chains maximally removed creating final xyloglucan-cellulose interaction patterns, and cellulose microfibrils largely preserved (85-95% of original content) providing residual structural framework supporting remaining berry firmness at completion. ||Cellular mechanical properties at completion reflect final berry architecture: berry firmness stabilizes at cultivar-specific values (±0.1-0.2 N variation over 1-2 weeks post-completion), cell wall thickness plateaus at reduced dimensions (1.5-2.8 μm versus 2.5-4.5 μm pre-softening), turgor pressure equilibrates at low-moderate levels (0.3-0.6 MPa) contributing 15-25% to residual firmness, and skin tensile strength reaches final values (40-65% of green berry strength) determining berry integrity and handling characteristics through harvest. ||Hormonal regulation at softening completion shows abscisic acid levels declining from veraison peak (1500-3500 ng/g) to sustained moderate concentration (700-1800 ng/g) maintaining ripening program consolidation without driving continued intense developmental changes, ethylene production shows cultivar-dependent patterns with some varieties maintaining slight elevation (0.2-1.0 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹) post-completion while others return to baseline (<0.1 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹), and auxin levels decline to minimal values (<5-10 ng/g) reflecting completion of growth-related processes and berry expansion cessation. ||Molecular markers of softening process completion inclu progressive decline in cell wall enzyme transcript abundance monitored by qPCR showing reduction to 20-40% of peak expression levels, Western blotting revealing reduced cell wall enzyme protein levels to 30-50% of maximum indicating protein turnover exceeding synthesis, and enzymatic assays demonstrating activity stabilization at maintenance levels with <10-15% variation week-to-week characterizing completed process versus >30-50% weekly changes during active softening phases. ||Completion timing varies by cultivar and environment: early-ripening varieties (Pinot Noir, Chardonnay, Gamay) achieve completion 10-14 days post-veraison under optimal conditions (22-28°C average temperature), mid-season cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Cabernet Franc) complete 12-16 days post-veraison, while late-season varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) may require 14-20 days for full completion particularly under cooler conditions (<20°C) that slow enzyme activities and extend softening duration. ||Temperature effects on completion timing are substantial: warm conditions (25-30°C) accelerate completion by 3-5 days compared to cooler temperatures (18-22°C) through enhanced enzyme synthesis and activity, while excessive heat (>32°C) can cause premature abnormal completion through enzyme denaturation and cellular stress potentially producing suboptimal final texture, and cool conditions (<16°C) substantially delay completion (5-10 days extension) risking incomplete softening if harvest necessitated by other maturity parameters or approaching unfavorable weather. ||Post-completion berry texture stability depends on cultivar characteristics and environmental conditions: stable cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah, Sangiovese) maintain consistent texture 3-5 weeks post-completion allowing extended hang time for flavor development and harvest scheduling flexibility, moderately stable varieties (Merlot, Grenache, Chardonnay) show gradual texture changes 2-3 weeks post-completion with slow over-softening or slight firmness increase from mild dehydration requiring reasonably prompt harvest, while unstable cultivars (Pinot Noir, Gewürztraminer, Riesling) may deteriorate rapidly 1-2 weeks post-completion through over-softening, senescence, or environmental damage necessitating precise harvest timing. ||Quality implications of softening process completion timing relative to other maturity parameters inclu optimal scenarios where completion coincides with target sugar levels (20-26° Brix style-dependent), desired acidity (4-8 g/L titratable acidity), and phenolic maturity (brown seeds, extractable tannins balanced) produce ideal harvest-ready grapes for premium wine production, discordant maturity with premature completion before chemical maturity requires difficult decisions between harvesting under-ripe for texture or delaying past optimal firmness for composition, while delayed completion beyond chemical maturity creates opposite challenges of harvesting firm berries with suboptimal extraction potential or waiting for softening completion risking over-ripeness, excessive alcohol, or unfavorable weather exposure. ||Viticultural management targeting optimal softening completion involves: irrigation scheduling during ripening to maintain moderate water availability supporting enzyme synthesis and activity for timely completion without excessive water promoting over-softening, canopy management to moderate bunch temperatures facilitating appropriate enzyme function without heat-accelerated abnormal softening or cool-delayed incomplete softening, crop load adjustment ensuring adequate carbohydrate supply for enzyme synthesis and ripening processes supporting synchronized completion with chemical maturity, and disease management particularly Botrytis prevention since completion marks beginning of maximum berry vulnerability period with soft texture and compromised skin integrity creating optimal infection conditions requiring protective fungicide applications or prompt harvest. ||Monitoring softening process completion through regular firmness measurements combined with enzyme activity assays or gene expression analysis in research settings provides precise completion determination enabling harvest timing optimization for specific quality goals and market requirements, while practical viticulture relies on tactile berry assessment, chemical maturity tracking, and phenolic maturity evaluation to infer completion and guide harvest decisions balancing texture, composition, and logistical considerations.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 228-238 berry softening and ripening completion || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Australian J Grape Wine Res 48:125-144 ripening process completion || Deluc LG, Grimplet J, Wheatley MD, Tillett RL, Quilici DR, Osborne C, Schooley DA, Schlauch KA, Cushman JC, Cramer GR (2007) Transcriptomic and metabolite analyses of Cabernet Sauvignon grape berry development Bmc Genomics 8:429 molecular markers of ripening completion."
},

  "Color_Change_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Color_Change_Onset is a Veraison comprising de novo anthocyanin biosynthesis producing visible pigmentation in red cultivar berries.",
  "alternative_term": "veraison color initiation | anthocyanin synthesis onset | pigmentation commencement | berry coloring start |+ Veraison-Farb-Initiierung | Anthocyan-Synthese-Beginn | Pigmentierungs-Start | Beeren-Färbungs-Anfang",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Burgundian Pinot Noir vineyard near Gevrey-Chambertin, color change onset was observed in mid-August Year N+1 (BBCH 83, 9 weeks post-flowering) when first red patches appeared on sun-exposed berry surfaces coinciding with ABA levels rising from 120 ng/g to 850 ng/g, UFGT gene expression increasing 95-fold, and initial anthocyanin accumulation reaching 45 mg/kg skin from undetectable pre-veraison levels, under conditions of moderate temperature (daily high 24-27°C, night 14-16°C) and partial cluster exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Color_Change_Onset is distinguished from later color development phases by representing initiation rather than progression, occurs typically 1-3 days before or with initial softening in red cultivars, and is absent or minimal in white varieties. ||Duration from first visible color to complete coloring: early cultivars 3-5 days, mid-season 5-8 days, late varieties 8-14 days. ||Temperature optimum 20-28°C for synthesis. ||UV-B and moderate light enhance coloring. ||Color_Change_Onset represents RED CULTIVAR-specific process || white cultivars show only chlorophyll degradation without anthocyanin synthesis. ||Critical veraison marker for developmental tracking. || This process occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 1-3 days before or concurrent with initial berry softening depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and transforms berry skin color from uniform green (dominated by chlorophyll a and b absorbing red and blue light, reflecting green) to variegated red-green patches that progressively coalesce into complete berry pigmentation over 5-14 days cultivar-dependent. ||Color change onset is triggered by complex hormonal and developmental signals: abscisic acid levels spike from pre-veraison baseline 50-150 ng/g to veraison peak 500-2000 ng/g activating transcription factors VvMYBA1, VvMYBA2, and related regulators that coordinately upregulate anthocyanin biosynthetic genes 50-200 fold, sugar accumulation creates hexose signaling through hexokinase pathways that synergize with ABA to enhance anthocyanin gene expression, and declining gibberellin and auxin levels remove growth-related suppression of secondary metabolism allowing anthocyanin pathway activation. ||The onset process initiates anthocyanin biosynthesis through coordinated enzyme induction: phenylalanine ammonia lyase (PAL) activity increases 10-40 fold catalyzing the first committed step converting phenylalanine to cinnamic acid entering phenylpropanoid metabolism, chalcone synthase (CHS) shows 20-60 fold elevation producing naringenin chalcone the first flavonoid intermediate, flavanone 3-hydroxylase (F3H), dihydroflavonol 4-reductase (DFR), and leucoanthocyanidin dioxygenase (LDOX) activities increase sequentially producing leucoanthocyanidins, and UDP-glucose: flavonoid 3-O-glucosyltransferase (UFGT) achieves 50-150 fold induction catalyzing the final step producing stable anthocyanin-3-glucosides that accumulate in vacuoles creating visible red-blue pigmentation. ||Initial anthocyanin synthesis produces predominantly malvidin-3-glucoside (50-70% of total anthocyanins in most cultivars) along with cyanidin, peonidin, delphinidin, and petunidin derivatives whose relative proportions define cultivar-specific color characteristics: Pinot Noir shows high cyanidin content producing bright cherry-red color, Syrah exhibits elevated delphinidin creating purple-blue hues, Merlot displays balanced anthocyanin profiles producing deep red coloration, while Cabernet Sauvignon accumulates high malvidin with moderate delphinidin yielding characteristic purple-red color. ||Color change onset timing varies substantially among cultivars reflecting genetic differences in regulatory control and biosynthetic capacity: early-coloring varieties (Pinot Noir, Gamay, Grenache) initiate color change 8-10 weeks post-flowering with rapid progression to full coloring in 3-5 days, mid-season cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Sangiovese) begin 9-12 weeks post-flowering completing coloring in 5-8 days, while late-coloring varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) initiate 11-14 weeks post-flowering requiring 8-14 days for complete pigmentation reflecting slower anthocyanin accumulation rates. ||Environmental factors profoundly influence color change onset timing and intensity: temperature effects are complex with optimal ranges 20-28°C supporting maximum anthocyanin synthesis enzyme activities, cooler temperatures 15-20°C can enhance color through increased anthocyanin stability and reduced degradation despite slower synthesis rates, while heat stress >32-35°C inhibits anthocyanin biosynthesis through enzyme denaturation and gene expression suppression producing pale poorly-colored fruit, and dramatic diurnal temperature variation (>15°C difference day-night) often enhances coloring through combined warm-day synthesis and cool-night stabilization. ||Light quality and intensity significantly affect color development: ultraviolet-B radiation (280-315 nm) induces anthocyanin biosynthetic genes particularly CHS and UFGT increasing pigment accumulation 30-60% in exposed versus shaded fruit, visible red and blue wavelengths (400-500 nm, 600-700 nm) absorbed by photoreceptors enhance anthocyanin synthesis, while excessive direct sunlight combined with high temperature can inhibit coloring through heat stress effects, and moderate canopy shading reducing bunch temperature by 3-5°C while maintaining some light penetration often optimizes color development balancing synthesis induction with heat stress avoidance. ||Water relations during color change onset influence pigmentation intensity: moderate water deficit (stem water potential -0.9 to -1.3 MPa) can enhance anthocyanin accumulation 20-40% through stress signaling activating ABA pathways and concentrating berry solutes, severe deficit (<-1.4 MPa) inhibits color development through metabolic impairment and arrested berry development, while excess water reduces color intensity through berry dilution decreasing anthocyanin concentration per unit fresh weight and potentially suppressing ABA signaling reducing biosynthetic gene expression. ||Nutrition effects on color onset inclu adequate nitrogen supporting vigorous growth can delay and reduce coloring through enhanced vegetative sink competition and high vigor creating excessive canopy shading, while moderate nitrogen limitation during ripening can enhance color through reduced vegetative competition and potential stress signaling, potassium sufficiency appears important for optimal anthocyanin accumulation possibly through pH regulation of vacuolar storage or membrane transport function, and general nutrient balance supporting healthy vine metabolism enables optimal color development while severe deficiencies compromise biosynthetic capacity. ||Cluster position and microclimate create substantial within-vine variation in color onset: exposed clusters on southwestern canopy positions in northern hemisphere vineyards often initiate coloring 2-4 days earlier than shaded interior clusters through enhanced light and temperature signals, but excessive exposure causing berry temperatures >35°C can delay onset through heat inhibition, while completely shaded clusters may show 30-50% reduced anthocyanin accumulation and delayed onset by 4-7 days demonstrating light requirement for optimal pigmentation despite potential temperature benefits of shade. ||Molecular regulation involves complex transcriptional control: VvMYBA1 and VvMYBA2 R2R3-MYB transcription factors act as master regulators directly activating UFGT and other late biosynthetic genes, these MYBs interact with bHLH and WD40 proteins forming MBW complexes that coordinately regulate anthocyanin pathway genes, ABA-responsive element binding factors (ABFs) mediate ABA signaling to anthocyanin genes, while other transcription factors including VvMYB5a, VvMYB5b, and WRKY proteins modulate pathway regulation creating cultivar-specific expression patterns. ||Physiological consequences of color change onset extend beyond visible pigmentation: anthocyanins function as antioxidants protecting berries from photo-oxidative damage particularly important as chlorophyll degrades, UV-screening properties protect cellular contents from radiation damage, and accumulation of phenolic intermediates and products creates chemical changes affecting berry flavor, astringency, and wine quality characteristics. ||White and rosé cultivars show distinct color change patterns: white varieties (Chardonnay, Sauvignon Blanc, Riesling) undergo minimal color change with green-to-golden transitions reflecting chlorophyll degradation and carotenoid exposure rather than anthocyanin synthesis (anthocyanins <5-10 mg/kg versus 500-3000 mg/kg in reds), while teinturier varieties with red flesh (Alicante Bouschet) accumulate anthocyanins in mesocarp as well as skin creating intense coloring useful for blending. ||Viticultural implications of color change onset inclu visible color provides easily monitored veraison marker for developmental tracking and harvest forecasting, uneven color development within clusters or vineyards indicates maturity heterogeneity requiring selective harvest or acceptance of variable grape composition, and color intensity at harvest substantially affects wine color, phenolic content, and aging potential making color development monitoring essential for quality prediction and optimization.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009718 ## anthocyanin-containing compound biosynthetic process | 0.70" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 232-235 anthocyanin biosynthesis and color development || Castellarin SD, Matthews MA, Di Gaspero G, Gambetta GA (2007) Water deficits accelerate ripening and induce changes in gene expression regulating flavonoid biosynthesis in grape berries Planta 227:101-112 environmental regulation || Boss PK, Davies C, Robinson SP (1996) Analysis of the expression of anthocyanin pathway genes in developing Vitis vinifera L. cv Shiraz grape berries Plant Physiol 111:1059-1066 biosynthetic gene expression."
},

  "First_Color_Change": {
  "definition": "A First_Color_Change is a Color_Change_Onset marked by initial red-purple pigmentation appearing as discrete patches or sectors on individual berry surfaces within the cluster.",
  "alternative_term": "initial visible pigmentation | first red patch appearance | color break onset | earliest anthocyanin detection |+ initiale sichtbare Pigmentierung | erste Rotflecken-Erscheinung | Farbbruch-Beginn | früheste Anthocyan-Detektion",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Willamette Valley Pinot Noir vineyard, first color change was documented in early September Year N+1 (BBCH 83, 63 days post-flowering) when 15% of berries showed initial red patches on sun-exposed surfaces, anthocyanin concentration measured 42 mg/kg skin (from <5 mg/kg pre-veraison), UFGT expression was 78-fold elevated, berry sugar reached 10.2° Brix, and ABA levels were 920 ng/g under conditions of warm days (25-28°C) and cool nights (11-14°C) with partial cluster exposure to morning sun.",
  "editor_note": "First_Color_Change is distinguished from Color_Change_Onset by representing visible detection rather than molecular initiation, from Progressive_Color_Development by showing initial patches rather than spreading coloration, and from Complete_Color_Change by exhibiting 10-30% berry coverage rather than full pigmentation. ||Anthocyanin threshold for visibility: 30-60 mg/kg skin. ||Timing: typically 1-3 days after molecular onset. ||Spatial pattern: sun-exposed surfaces and stylar end first. ||Temperature optimum 24-30°C berry surface. ||First_Color_Change serves as practical veraison marker for vineyard monitoring and harvest forecasting. || This initial change occurs during early veraison (BBCH 83), usually 1-3 days following molecular and biochemical initiation of anthocyanin biosynthesis, and becomes visible when anthocyanin concentration in epidermal and sub-epidermal cell vacuoles reaches 30-60 mg/kg skin fresh weight (compared to <5-10 mg/kg pre-veraison) creating sufficient optical density to overcome green chlorophyll absorbance and produce perceptible red-purple coloration. ||The first color change typically manifests in predictable spatial patterns: initial pigmentation commonly appears on sun-exposed berry surfaces particularly the southwestern aspect (in northern hemisphere vineyards) where combined light and temperature signals maximize anthocyanin induction, color often initiates near the stylar scar (blossom end) and spreads toward the pedicel attachment reflecting developmental gradients in berry tissues, and within clusters the most developmentally advanced berries (often those with best light exposure and favorable microclimate) show first color while shaded or stressed berries may lag by 3-7 days creating visible cluster heterogeneity. ||Cellular and biochemical basis of first visible color involves: anthocyanin-3-glucosides particularly malvidin-3-glucoside accumulate in vacuoles of epidermal and 2-4 sub-epidermal cell layers creating concentrated pigment pools, vacuolar pH in pigmented cells drops to 3.0-3.8 (from 5.5-6.5 in green berries) creating optimal conditions for anthocyanin color expression as stable red-purple flavylium cations rather than colorless carbinol forms, and co-pigmentation with flavonols and hydroxycinnamic acids enhances and stabilizes anthocyanin color through molecular stacking interactions intensifying visible pigmentation beyond that expected from anthocyanin concentration alone. ||Gene expression underlying first color change shows anthocyanin biosynthetic genes reaching 40-80% of eventual peak expression: UFGT transcripts increase 50-120 fold above green berry baseline catalyzing the final glycosylation step essential for anthocyanin stability and vacuolar transport, earlier pathway genes including DFR and LDOX show 30-80 fold elevation producing substrate for UFGT, and regulatory genes VvMYBA1/A2 achieve 60-100 fold induction coordinating pathway activation with other ripening processes. ||Enzyme activities at first color change inclu UFGT protein accumulates to 40-60% of maximum levels with specific activity enabling glucosylation of 15-30 μmol anthocyanidins per hour per kg fresh weight, phenylalanine ammonia lyase operates at 50-70% of peak providing phenylpropanoid precursors, and chalcone synthase achieves 40-65% maximum activity producing flavonoid intermediates with cumulative pathway flux sufficient to generate visible anthocyanin accumulation rates of 20-50 mg/kg skin per day during first color change. ||Hormonal status at first color change shows: ABA levels elevated to 600-1500 ng/g fresh weight (from 50-150 ng/g pre-veraison) activating ABA-responsive elements in anthocyanin gene promoters, sugar levels rising to 8-12° Brix (from 5-8° pre-veraison) creating hexose signals that synergize with ABA to enhance UFGT and other late biosynthetic gene expression, and gibberellin and auxin declining to low levels removing growth-related suppression of secondary metabolism allowing full anthocyanin pathway activation. ||Environmental conditions strongly influence first color change timing and location: berry surface temperature 24-30°C optimizes anthocyanin synthesis enzyme activities producing earliest and most intense initial coloring, UV-B exposure particularly 290-315 nm wavelengths induces anthocyanin genes through UV-B photoreceptor signaling creating 30-50% faster color appearance in exposed versus shaded berry surfaces, cool night temperatures 12-16°C following warm days enhance anthocyanin stability and accumulation producing more intense first color in regions with large diurnal temperature ranges, while excessive heat >35°C inhibits anthocyanin synthesis causing delayed or suppressed first color change even under high light exposure. ||Cultivar variation in first color change characteristics reflects genetic differences in anthocyanin biosynthetic regulation: early-coloring varieties like Pinot Noir show first color 8-9 weeks post-flowering with rapid appearance across berry surface (1-2 days from first patches to 50% colored), Merlot and Syrah display intermediate timing (9-11 weeks) with moderate progression (2-4 days to 50% coverage), while late cultivars like Cabernet Sauvignon initiate first color 11-13 weeks post-flowering with slower spread (3-6 days to 50%) reflecting lower initial anthocyanin synthesis rates and potentially different regulatory control. ||First color change serves as practical viticultural marker: clusters showing 10-30% berries with visible color patches define veraison onset for vineyard monitoring, the transition from 0% to 50% berries showing color typically requires 2-5 days in uniform blocks providing harvest timing forecasts (harvest typically 40-60 days post-first color depending on cultivar and heat accumulation), and within-vineyard spatial variation in first color timing reveals maturity heterogeneity requiring management decisions about selective harvest or acceptance of compositional variation. ||Cluster architecture affects first color patterns: compact clusters with berry-to-berry contact may show color first on exposed exterior berries while interior berries remain green for extended periods, loose clusters with better air circulation and light penetration show more uniform first color appearance across all berries, and cluster position on the canopy creates systematic variation with exterior clusters coloring 2-4 days before interior positions in dense canopies. ||Anthocyanin composition at first color change establishes cultivar-specific profiles: malvidin-3-glucoside typically comprises 50-70% of total anthocyanins even at first color reflecting preferential UFGT substrate specificity and methyltransferase activities, relative proportions of delphinidin, cyanidin, petunidin, and peonidin derivatives are established early and remain relatively constant through complete coloring, and acylated anthocyanins (acetyl, coumaroyl derivatives) begin accumulating providing enhanced color stability and modified hue characteristics. ||Water stress effects on first color are complex: moderate deficit (stem ψ -0.9 to -1.2 MPa) can advance first color by 2-4 days through enhanced ABA signaling and potentially reduced berry size concentrating pigments, severe stress (<-1.4 MPa) delays first color through metabolic impairment despite elevated ABA levels, while excess water can delay color 3-5 days through berry dilution and reduced ABA signaling suppressing anthocyanin gene induction. ||Physiological significance of first color change includes: anthocyanins provide UV protection as chlorophyll content declines reducing photo-oxidative damage risk, antioxidant properties of anthocyanins and phenolic intermediates protect cellular components during metabolic transitions, and visible color signals birds and other animals potentially affecting berry predation patterns though commercial viticulture typically prevents animal access. ||Monitoring first color change informs management decisions: irrigation can be reduced or terminated at first color in deficit irrigation strategies since berry growth slows substantially post-veraison, disease management intensifies as berry sugar increases and skin integrity decreases creating favorable Botrytis conditions, and canopy management to improve cluster exposure may be adjusted recognizing that excessive exposure during active color development risks heat inhibition while moderate exposure enhances coloring through light signals.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 233-234 color development patterns || Downey MO, Dokoozlian NK, Krstic MP (2006) Cultural practice and environmental impacts on the flavonoid composition of grapes and wine Plant Physiol Biochem 44:170-181 anthocyanin accumulation dynamics || Mori K, Goto-Yamamoto N, Kitayama M, Hashizume K (2007) Loss of anthocyanins in red-wine grape under high temperature J Exp Bot 58:1935-1945 temperature effects on initial coloring."
},

  "Initial_Anthocyanin_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Anthocyanin_Synthesis is a Color_Change_Onset involving upregulation of anthocyanin biosynthetic pathway genes and enzymatic production of anthocyanin-3-glucosides at first detectable levels.",
  "alternative_term": "early anthocyanin production | initial pigment biosynthesis | first anthocyanin accumulation | biosynthetic pathway activation |+ frühe Anthocyan-Produktion | initiale Pigment-Biosynthese | erste Anthocyan-Akkumulation | Biosynthese-Weg-Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Merlot vineyard, initial anthocyanin synthesis was measured 2 days before visible color in mid-August Year N+1 (BBCH 83 onset, 68 days post-flowering) when UFGT transcripts increased 115-fold, UFGT enzyme activity rose from undetectable to 12 units/kg, anthocyanin accumulation rate was 18 mg/kg per day increasing skin content from 6 mg/kg to 42 mg/kg over 48 hours, ABA levels were 880 ng/g, and berry sugar reached 9.8° Brix under optimal conditions (berry temperature 25-27°C with morning sun exposure).",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Anthocyanin_Synthesis is distinguished from Color_Change_Onset by representing molecular and biochemical initiation rather than the broader onset process, from First_Color_Change by occurring 1-2 days before visible detection, and from Progressive_Synthesis by showing activation rather than sustained production. ||Accumulation rates: fast cultivars 25-40 mg/kg/day, moderate 15-25 mg/kg/day, slow 10-20 mg/kg/day. ||UFGT induction 80-150 fold is diagnostic. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C berry surface. ||UV-B strongly enhances. ||Initial_Anthocyanin_Synthesis represents the critical molecular transition initiating veraison color development in red grape cultivars. || This process initiates 1-2 days before visible color change (BBCH 83 onset), triggered by convergent developmental and environmental signals, and is characterized by anthocyanin accumulation rates of 10-30 mg/kg skin fresh weight per day increasing berry skin anthocyanin content from pre-veraison baseline <5-10 mg/kg to initial detection threshold 30-60 mg/kg within 2-4 days. ||Molecular initiation involves coordinated transcriptional activation of the phenylpropanoid and flavonoid biosynthetic pathways: master regulatory transcription factors VvMYBA1 and VvMYBA2 are induced 60-120 fold by elevated ABA levels (rising from 50-150 ng/g to 500-1200 ng/g) and sugar signals (hexose concentrations increasing from 150-300 mM to 300-500 mM), these R2R3-MYB factors form complexes with bHLH (VvMYC1) and WD40 proteins creating MBW transcriptional activation complexes that bind promoter elements of structural genes, and ABA-responsive element binding factors (ABFs) synergize with MYB factors to amplify anthocyanin gene expression through combinatorial transcription factor interactions. ||Structural gene expression during initial synthesis shows sequential activation patterns: early biosynthetic genes including phenylalanine ammonia lyase (PAL), chalcone synthase (CHS), and chalcone isomerase (CHI) are induced 20-50 fold within 24-48 hours of ABA signal reception, mid-pathway genes flavanone 3-hydroxylase (F3H), flavonoid 3'-hydroxylase (F3'H), and flavonoid 3'5'-hydroxylase (F3'5'H) follow with 30-70 fold induction determining hydroxylation patterns that define anthocyanidin types (cyanidin from F3'H, delphinidin from F3'5'H), late genes dihydroflavonol 4-reductase (DFR) and leucoanthocyanidin dioxygenase (LDOX) show 40-90 fold elevation producing leucoanthocyanidins, and the terminal enzyme UDP-glucose:flavonoid 3-O-glucosyltransferase (UFGT) achieves 80-150 fold induction catalyzing the critical glycosylation step that stabilizes anthocyanidins as anthocyanin-3-glucosides enabling vacuolar accumulation. ||Enzyme protein accumulation and activity lags transcript induction by 12-24 hours: UFGT protein becomes detectable by Western blotting 1-2 days post-transcription initiation reaching 30-50% of eventual maximum levels, specific UFGT activity rises from undetectable (<0.5 units/kg FW) to 8-15 units/kg enabling glucosylation rates of 12-25 μmol substrate per hour per kg, PAL activity increases from baseline 5-15 units to 40-80 units providing phenylpropanoid flux into the pathway, and DFR activity elevation from <2 units to 15-30 units produces leucoanthocyanidin substrates for LDOX-catalyzed oxidation to anthocyanidins. ||Initial anthocyanin products during early synthesis establish cultivar-specific profiles: malvidin-3-glucoside typically comprises 55-75% of total anthocyanins reflecting preferential substrate specificity of methyltransferases and UFGT toward delphinidin-3-glucoside, cyanidin-3-glucoside contributes 8-20% with higher proportions in Pinot Noir (15-25%) producing characteristic bright red hues, delphinidin-3-glucoside ranges 5-18% with elevation in Syrah and Petit Verdot (12-22%) creating purple-blue color notes, while peonidin and petunidin derivatives account for 5-15% each contributing to overall color complexity. ||Subcellular localization during initial synthesis involves: anthocyanin biosynthetic enzymes associate with endoplasmic reticulum membranes forming metabolic channeling complexes that enhance pathway efficiency, synthesized anthocyanin-3-glucosides are transported from cytosol to vacuole through glutathione S-transferase (GST)-mediated mechanisms and ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters, and vacuolar sequestration at pH 3.0-3.8 stabilizes anthocyanins in red-purple flavylium cation form while protecting cytosolic components from potential anthocyanin toxicity. ||Hormonal regulation of initial synthesis shows: ABA signaling through PYR/PYL receptors, PP2C phosphatases, and SnRK2 kinases activates ABF transcription factors that directly induce anthocyanin genes and synergize with MYB factors, sugar signaling through hexokinase creates glucose-6-phosphate signals that enhance anthocyanin gene transcription through SnRK1 pathway modulation, gibberellin decline removes DELLA protein degradation allowing DELLA-mediated enhancement of anthocyanin biosynthesis, and ethylene shows cultivar-dependent effects with slight elevation (0.1-0.5 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹) in some varieties potentially modulating anthocyanin synthesis timing. ||Temperature sensitivity of initial synthesis is high: optimal berry temperature 22-28°C supports maximum biosynthetic enzyme activities and gene expression producing fastest anthocyanin accumulation (25-35 mg/kg per day), cooler temperatures 16-22°C reduce initial synthesis rates by 30-50% through reduced enzyme kinetics despite potentially enhanced transcript stability, heat stress >32°C severely inhibits initial synthesis through transcript degradation, protein denaturation, and potential chromatin modifications suppressing gene accessibility reducing anthocyanin accumulation 50-80% compared to optimal temperatures, and recovery from heat stress requires 3-5 days for biosynthetic machinery re-establishment. ||Light quality effects on initial synthesis inclu UV-B radiation (280-315 nm) is particularly effective inducing anthocyanin biosynthetic genes through UVR8 photoreceptor signaling pathway with 30-60% enhancement of initial synthesis rates in UV-exposed versus UV-excluded berries, blue light (400-500 nm) absorbed by cryptochromes and phototropins stimulates anthocyanin genes through separate photoreceptor pathways, red light (600-700 nm) shows moderate effects possibly through phytochrome signaling, while far-red light (700-750 nm) can inhibit anthocyanin synthesis through phytochrome inactivation demonstrating light quality-dependent regulation beyond simple intensity effects. ||Water stress impacts on initial synthesis show: moderate deficit (leaf ψ -0.9 to -1.3 MPa) enhances initial synthesis 20-40% through elevated ABA signaling and potentially reduced berry size concentrating biosynthetic products, severe stress (<-1.5 MPa) impairs initial synthesis despite very high ABA levels through general metabolic limitation and potentially reduced substrate availability, while abundant water reduces initial synthesis through berry dilution and potentially suppressed ABA-dependent gene activation demonstrating complex water-anthocyanin relationships. ||Cultivar variation in initial synthesis rates reflects genetic differences in regulatory control: rapid synthesizers like Pinot Noir and Gamay accumulate 25-40 mg/kg per day during initial phase reaching visible color in 2-3 days, moderate cultivars like Merlot and Syrah show 15-25 mg/kg per day requiring 3-5 days to visible threshold, while slow synthesizers like Cabernet Sauvignon and Nebbiolo accumulate 10-20 mg/kg per day needing 4-7 days for color detection reflecting lower basal synthesis capacity or different regulatory thresholds. ||Coordination with other veraison processes is tight: initial anthocyanin synthesis typically precedes or coincides with berry softening onset (often synchronized within 1-2 days), occurs during early sugar accumulation acceleration (Brix rising 0.8-1.5% per week increasing to 1.5-3.0% per week), and parallels acid decline initiation (malate beginning respiratory degradation) demonstrating integrated ripening program activation. ||Metabolic demands of initial synthesis are substantial: anthocyanin production requires significant carbon allocation (5-15% of berry carbon import during early veraison directed to phenylpropanoid pathway), energy demands include ATP for biosynthetic reactions and vacuolar transport consuming 8-15% of berry respiration during peak synthesis, and nitrogen requirements for enzyme synthesis draw on berry amino acid pools particularly phenylalanine as direct precursor with 20-40 μmol phenylalanine channeled into anthocyanins per kg fresh weight during initial synthesis period.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 233-235 anthocyanin biosynthesis molecular control || Boss PK, Davies C, Robinson SP (1996) Analysis of the expression of anthocyanin pathway genes in developing Vitis vinifera L. cv Shiraz grape berries Plant Physiol 111:1059-1066 gene expression kinetics || Jeong ST, Goto-Yamamoto N, Kobayashi S, Esaka M (2004) Effects of plant hormones and shading on the accumulation of anthocyanins Plant Sci 167:247-252 hormonal regulation of synthesis initiation."
},

  "First_Pigment_Deposition": {
  "definition": "A First_Pigment_Deposition is a Color_Change_Onset characterized by anthocyanin accumulation in berry skin cell vacuoles at microscopically detectable concentrations 1–2 days after biosynthetic pathway activation.",
  "alternative_term": "initial vacuolar anthocyanin accumulation | first pigment sequestration | early anthocyanin deposition | primary color establishment |+ initiale vakuoläre Anthocyan-Akkumulation | erste Pigment-Sequestrierung | frühe Anthocyan-Ablagerung | primäre Farb-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Valley Shiraz vineyard, first pigment deposition was observed by microscopy in late January Year N+1 (BBCH 83) showing red-purple vacuolar pigmentation in epidermal cells at anthocyanin concentration 48 mg/kg skin when berries appeared still green to unaided eye, with malvidin-3-glucoside comprising 68% of deposited anthocyanins, delphinidin-3-glucoside at 14%, vacuolar pH measured 3.4, and flavonol co-pigments at 85 mg/kg under warm conditions (berry temperature 26-29°C) providing optimal deposition environment.",
  "editor_note": "First_Pigment_Deposition is distinguished from Initial_Anthocyanin_Synthesis by representing vacuolar sequestration rather than biosynthesis, from First_Color_Change by occurring at microscopic rather than macroscopic detection scale, and from Progressive_Deposition by showing initial rather than expanding accumulation. ||Anthocyanin threshold for microscopic detection: 30-80 mg/kg skin. ||Vacuolar pH 3.0-3.8 critical for color stability. ||Epidermal and sub-epidermal layers primary deposition sites. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C for transport efficiency. ||First_Pigment_Deposition represents the critical transition from biosynthesis to visible color creation. || This process involves vacuolar sequestration of anthocyanin-3-glucosides at 30-80 mg/kg skin fresh weight (compared to <5-10 mg/kg pre-veraison) concentrated primarily in epidermal and sub-epidermal cell layers creating localized pigment pools that will expand and intensify during subsequent color development. ||Cellular mechanisms of first pigment deposition inclu anthocyanin-3-glucosides synthesized in cytosol are recognized by glutathione S-transferase (GST) proteins that facilitate transport to tonoplast, ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters and multidrug and toxic compound extrusion (MATE) proteins mediate active transport across vacuolar membrane concentrating anthocyanins 100-1000 fold inside vacuoles relative to cytosolic concentrations, and vacuolar pH maintained at 3.0-3.8 (acidified from green berry vacuolar pH 5.5-6.5 through proton-ATPase and proton-pyrophosphatase activity) stabilizes anthocyanins in colored flavylium cation form (pKa ~4.5) rather than colorless carbinol pseudobase ensuring visible pigmentation. ||Subcellular localization of first deposited pigments shows: anthocyanins accumulate preferentially in large central vacuoles occupying 85-95% of cell volume in mature berry skin cells creating high local concentrations (5-15 mM in vacuolar solution), pigment deposition initiates in outermost epidermal cells and progressively extends into 2-4 sub-epidermal layers creating gradient of pigmentation with highest concentrations in surface cells directly exposed to light signals, and anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions (AVIs) - specialized anthocyanin-rich structures - begin forming in some cultivars representing concentrated pigment deposits that enhance color intensity beyond simple vacuolar solution. ||Anthocyanin composition of first deposits establishes profiles that persist through ripening: malvidin-3-glucoside comprises 50-75% of deposited anthocyanins reflecting its preferential synthesis and transport, cyanidin-3-glucoside contributes 8-22% with higher proportions in Pinot Noir creating bright red coloration, delphinidin-3-glucoside ranges 5-20% elevated in Syrah and Petit Verdot producing purple hues, peonidin and petunidin derivatives account for 5-15% each, and acylated forms (acetyl and coumaroyl esters) begin appearing at 5-15% of total providing enhanced color stability through intramolecular copigmentation. ||Co-pigmentation phenomena enhance first pigment color intensity: flavonols (quercetin, kaempferol, myricetin glycosides) accumulating to 50-150 mg/kg in skin co-localize in vacuoles with anthocyanins creating molecular stacking interactions that shift anthocyanin absorbance maxima and enhance color intensity 20-40% beyond that expected from anthocyanin concentration alone, hydroxycinnamic acids (caffeic, coumaric, ferulic acids) at 30-80 mg/kg similarly participate in co-pigmentation, and colorless anthocyanin precursors including flavonols and dihydroflavonols contribute to overall pigment stabilization creating more intense visible color than pure anthocyanin solutions. ||Tissue distribution of first pigment shows: stylar (blossom) end of berries often accumulates detectable pigment 1-2 days before pedicel (stem) end reflecting developmental gradients in berry ripening, sun-exposed berry surfaces show pigment deposition 1-3 days earlier than shaded surfaces due to light-enhanced anthocyanin synthesis and potentially enhanced vacuolar transport, and within skin tissue the outermost 1-2 epidermal cell layers show 2-4 fold higher anthocyanin concentrations than deeper sub-epidermal layers creating steep pigment gradients crucial for effective color despite limited tissue depth. ||Microscopic visualization of first pigment deposition reveals: light microscopy shows initial red-purple coloration in isolated epidermal cells or small cell clusters before coalescence into continuous pigmented zones, fluorescence microscopy using anthocyanin autofluorescence (excitation 530-560 nm, emission 600-650 nm) detects pigment at concentrations below visual threshold enabling earlier detection, and confocal microscopy resolves vacuolar localization showing anthocyanins excluded from cytoplasm and organelles confined to acidic vacuolar compartment. ||Temperature effects on first pigment deposition inclu optimal berry temperatures 22-28°C support maximum deposition rates through efficient biosynthesis and transport producing detectable pigment in 1-2 days post-synthesis initiation, cooler temperatures 16-22°C extend deposition period to 2-4 days through reduced transport kinetics despite potentially enhanced pigment stability once deposited, while heat stress >32°C inhibits deposition through reduced synthesis and potential membrane disruption affecting vacuolar transport efficiency. ||Light influences first pigment deposition beyond biosynthetic effects: UV-B radiation may directly affect vacuolar transport mechanisms enhancing anthocyanin sequestration efficiency, visible light particularly blue wavelengths could modulate tonoplast transporter activity, and light-induced changes in vacuolar pH through effects on proton pump activities might optimize conditions for anthocyanin stabilization in flavylium form. ||Metabolic requirements for first pigment deposition inclu ATP consumption for active transport across tonoplast estimated 2-4 molecules ATP per anthocyanin molecule sequestered representing significant energy demand during rapid deposition, proton gradient maintenance through V-ATPase activity consuming additional ATP to sustain low vacuolar pH essential for color stability, and potential synthesis of vacuolar inclusion membrane components in cultivars forming AVIs requiring lipid and protein synthesis. ||Cultivar variation in first pigment deposition patterns includes: rapid-depositing varieties like Pinot Noir show visible pigment within 24-36 hours of synthesis initiation with abrupt color appearance, moderate cultivars like Merlot require 36-60 hours for detectable deposition with more gradual onset, while slow-depositing varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon need 60-96 hours reflecting either slower synthesis or less efficient transport and sequestration mechanisms. ||Coordination with berry softening varies: in most cultivars first pigment deposition occurs 0-2 days before or concurrent with initial berry softening onset, some early-coloring varieties show pigment deposition 2-3 days preceding softening, while certain cultivars may soften 1-2 days before visible pigment suggesting relatively independent regulation though ultimately coordinated through common ABA signaling. ||Physiological consequences of pigment deposition inclu anthocyanin-containing vacuoles gain antioxidant capacity protecting cellular contents from reactive oxygen species particularly as photosynthetic apparatus degrades, UV-screening properties reduce DNA damage and photoinhibition in pigmented cells, and potential osmotic effects of high vacuolar anthocyanin concentrations (5-15 mM) might influence water relations though likely minor compared to sugar and acid effects. ||Quality implications inclu early and intense pigment deposition correlates with eventual high color intensity at harvest important for red wine quality, spatial uniformity of first deposition within berries and clusters predicts maturity synchrony affecting harvest decisions and wine composition consistency, and anthocyanin composition established during first deposition largely determines final wine color characteristics including hue angle, color stability, and aging behavior.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Conn S, Curtin C, Bezier A, Franco C, Zhang W (2008) Purification, molecular cloning, and characterization of glutathione S-transferases involved in anthocyanin sequestration J Biol Chem 283:26484-26491 anthocyanin transport mechanisms || Conn S, Zhang W, Franco C (2003) Anthocyanic vacuolar inclusions in cell suspension cultures of Vitis vinifera Plant Cell Rep 22:227-229 vacuolar sequestration || Braidot E, Zancani M, Petrussa E, Peresson C, Bertolini A, Patui S, Macrì F, Vianello A (2008) Transport and accumulation of flavonoids in grapevine Plant Signal Behav 3:626-632 pigment deposition mechanisms."
},

  "Color_Break_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Color_Break_Initiation is a Color_Change_Onset marked by expansion and coalescence of scattered pigmented patches producing mixed green-red surface patterns on berries.",
  "alternative_term": "green color disruption | pigmentation pattern emergence | variegated coloring onset | color uniformity breaking |+ Grün-Farb-Störung | Pigmentierungs-Muster-Entstehung | gescheckter Färbungs-Beginn | Farb-Gleichförmigkeits-Bruch",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Chianti Classico Sangiovese vineyard, color break initiation was documented in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when 25-35% of berry surface showed red-purple patches concentrated on sun-exposed southwestern aspects, skin anthocyanins measured 95 mg/kg (from 42 mg/kg at first pigment 3 days earlier), chlorophyll declined to 65 μg/g (from 145 μg/g green), berry firmness dropped 12% to 2.3 N, and sugar reached 11.5° Brix under typical Tuscan autumn conditions (daily high 25-28°C, night 14-17°C).",
  "editor_note": "Color_Break_Initiation is distinguished from First_Pigment_Deposition by representing visible pattern formation rather than initial sequestration, from Progressive_Color_Development by showing early mixed green-red rather than advancing pigmentation, and from Complete_Color_Change by exhibiting partial (20-40%) rather than full coverage. ||Anthocyanin range at break: 60-120 mg/kg skin. ||Duration from first pigment to break: fast cultivars 1-2 days, moderate 2-4 days, slow 3-6 days. ||Temperature optimum 24-30°C berry surface. ||Color_Break_Initiation provides practical visual marker for veraison monitoring and harvest forecasting. || This process occurs 1-3 days following first pigment deposition (BBCH 83), when anthocyanin concentrations in pioneering pigmented regions reach 60-120 mg/kg skin fresh weight creating sufficient optical density to overcome chlorophyll masking, and marks the beginning of rapid visible color transformation from predominantly green to variegated appearance preceding complete berry pigmentation. ||The \"break\" in color uniformity results from spatial heterogeneity in anthocyanin synthesis and accumulation: initial pigmented patches typically measure 2-5 mm diameter representing clusters of 50-200 epidermal and sub-epidermal cells with coordinated anthocyanin accumulation, these patches appear preferentially on sun-exposed berry surfaces where light and temperature signals maximize anthocyanin induction creating asymmetric coloring with southwestern aspects (northern hemisphere) showing earliest and most intense patches, and within individual berries pigmentation often initiates near stylar end spreading toward pedicel attachment reflecting apical-to-basal developmental gradients in ripening signaling. ||Cellular basis of color break involves: expansion of initially pigmented cell clusters through recruitment of adjacent cells into anthocyanin synthesis with radial spreading patterns from initial foci, intercellular signaling possibly through diffusible factors or cell-to-cell contact enabling coordinated pigmentation responses creating coherent colored patches rather than isolated pigmented cells, and continued chlorophyll degradation in pigmented regions (chlorophyll declining from 100-200 μg/g to 40-80 μg/g) reducing green color masking allowing red-purple anthocyanins to dominate visual appearance. ||Anthocyanin accumulation during color break shows: total skin anthocyanins increasing from first deposition levels 30-60 mg/kg to color break detection 80-150 mg/kg representing 2-3 fold increase within 2-4 days, accumulation rates accelerating from initial synthesis 10-30 mg/kg per day to color break 25-60 mg/kg per day as biosynthetic machinery reaches 60-80% of maximum capacity, and malvidin-3-glucoside maintaining dominance at 55-70% of total while acylated derivatives increase to 10-20% enhancing color stability and intensity. ||Gene expression during color break shows: anthocyanin biosynthetic genes reach 70-90% of eventual maximum expression with UFGT transcripts 120-180 fold above green berry baseline, regulatory MYB genes (VvMYBA1/A2) achieve 80-120 fold induction coordinating pathway activation, chlorophyll degradation genes including pheophytinase and pheophorbide a oxygenase show 10-30 fold elevation facilitating green color removal, and carotenoid biosynthetic genes may increase slightly contributing yellow-orange background visible in white cultivars but masked by anthocyanins in reds. ||Optical properties during color break inclu pigmented patches show characteristic absorbance maxima 520-540 nm for anthocyanins with optical density 0.8-1.5 units at peak wavelength, reflectance spectra shift from predominantly green reflection (500-600 nm) in unpigmented regions to red-purple reflection (600-650 nm with secondary blue reflection 400-450 nm) in colored patches creating visually striking color contrast, and overall berry appearance transitions from solid green (pre-break) to mottled green-red (color break) to predominantly red with green remnants (progressive coloring) as pigmented area expands from 20-40% at break initiation to >80% at break completion. ||Environmental modulation of color break timing includes: optimal berry temperature 24-30°C accelerates color break producing visible patterns 2-4 days post-first pigment, cooler temperatures 18-24°C delay break by 1-3 days through slower anthocyanin accumulation despite potentially more intense final color, heat stress >33°C can severely delay or prevent normal color break patterns producing pale poorly-colored fruit through anthocyanin biosynthesis inhibition, and diurnal temperature variation >15°C day-night difference often enhances color break intensity creating more distinct pigmented patches through optimized synthesis-stabilization balance. ||Light effects during color break show: UV-B exposure enhances patch formation and intensity producing 30-50% higher anthocyanin levels in exposed versus shaded berry regions, visible light particularly blue wavelengths promotes color break progression through photoreceptor signaling, excessive direct sun combined with high temperature can inhibit break progression through heat stress overriding light benefits, and moderate canopy shading delaying color break 3-5 days while potentially improving ultimate color intensity through temperature moderation demonstrates complex light-temperature interactions. ||Water stress influences on color break inclu moderate deficit (stem ψ -0.9 to -1.3 MPa) can enhance color break intensity and advance timing 2-3 days through elevated ABA signaling and berry concentration effects, severe stress (<-1.5 MPa) disrupts normal break patterns producing irregular patchy coloring through metabolic impairment, while excess irrigation delays color break 2-4 days and reduces intensity through berry dilution and suppressed ABA-dependent anthocyanin gene activation. ||Cultivar variation in color break characteristics reflects genetic differences: rapid-breaking varieties like Pinot Noir show abrupt color break with 20-30% berry surface pigmented within 24-48 hours creating dramatic visual transformation, moderate cultivars like Merlot and Syrah display gradual break over 3-5 days with progressive patch expansion, while slow-breaking varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon and Nebbiolo show extended break period 5-8 days with initially subtle color changes requiring careful observation for detection. ||Within-cluster heterogeneity during color break creates: berries at different developmental stages showing simultaneous presence of completely green (lag phase), color breaking (early veraison), and substantially colored (mid-veraison) fruit reflecting inherent developmental asynchrony, exposed berries typically 2-4 days ahead of shaded berries in color break timing creating spatial patterns of coloring progression, and cluster shoulders often breaking color before cluster tips possibly reflecting vascular supply differences or developmental gradients. ||Viticultural significance of color break timing includes: visual assessment of color break provides practical veraison monitoring enabling estimation of harvest timing (typically 40-55 days post-color break depending on heat accumulation and cultivar), within-vineyard variation in color break timing reveals maturity heterogeneity informing decisions about selective harvest or acceptance of compositional variation, and irrigation management often adjusts at color break initiating deficit strategies or terminating water applications as berry growth slows. ||Physiological markers accompanying color break inclu berry firmness declining 10-20% from green berry values as softening initiates often concurrent with color break, sugar accumulation accelerating from <1.0% Brix per week to 1.5-3.0% per week, acid levels beginning decline particularly malate showing 5-15% reduction through respiratory consumption, and seed color transitioning from green to yellow-brown indicating coordinated ripening program activation across berry tissues. ||Monitoring color break progression informs management: photographic documentation enables quantitative tracking of color development through image analysis measuring colored versus green surface area, spectrophotometric measurement of skin extracts provides anthocyanin quantification correlating with visual break assessment, and regular cluster sampling across vineyard blocks identifies spatial variation in break timing revealing terroir effects or management impacts requiring attention.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 233-234 color development patterns || Mori K, Sugaya S, Gemma H (2005) Decreased anthocyanin biosynthesis in grape berries grown under elevated night temperature condition Sci Hort 105:319-330 environmental effects on color break || Downey MO, Harvey JS, Robinson SP (2004) The effect of bunch shading on berry development and flavonoid accumulation in Shiraz grapes Australian J Grape Wine Res 10:55-73 spatial patterns of color break."
},

  "Progressive_Color_Development": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Color_Development is a Veraison consisting of sustained anthocyanin accumulation and spatial expansion of pigmentation transforming berry surface from variegated green-red to predominantly pigmented.",
  "alternative_term": "continuing anthocyanin accumulation | expanding pigmentation | sustained color intensification | progressive berry coloring |+ fortgesetzte Anthocyan-Akkumulation | expandierende Pigmentierung | anhaltende Farb-Intensivierung | progressive Beeren-Färbung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Paso Robles Syrah vineyard, progressive color development was monitored over 7 days in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when anthocyanin accumulation averaged 75 mg/kg per day increasing from 135 mg/kg (30% berry surface colored) to 660 mg/kg (90% colored), with delphinidin-3-glucoside reaching 18% of total producing characteristic purple color, berry firmness declining to 1.4 N, sugar rising from 13.5 to 21.8° Brix, under warm days (28-31°C) and moderate nights (15-18°C) with eastern canopy cluster exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Color_Development is distinguished from Color_Break_Initiation by representing sustained accumulation rather than initial pattern formation, from First_Color_Change by showing accelerating rather than nascent pigmentation, and from Complete_Color_Change by exhibiting ongoing progression rather than final state achievement. ||Duration: fast cultivars 3-5 days, moderate 5-8 days, slow 8-12 days. ||Accumulation rates peak 50-150 mg/kg/day. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C. ||Moderate water deficit enhances. ||Progressive_Color_Development represents the major phase of anthocyanin synthesis determining final berry color intensity critical for wine quality. || This process occurs during mid-to-late veraison (BBCH 83-85), typically 3-10 days duration depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by anthocyanin accumulation rates of 40-120 mg/kg skin per day increasing total skin anthocyanins from color break levels 80-150 mg/kg to near-maximum values 400-800 mg/kg (cultivar-dependent final levels range 500-3000 mg/kg). ||Spatial progression of pigmentation during this phase shows: initially discrete colored patches (occupying 20-40% berry surface at color break) expand radially recruiting adjacent unpigmented cells into anthocyanin synthesis creating confluent pigmented zones, green remnants progressively shrink retreating toward shaded berry surfaces (often northwestern aspects in northern hemisphere) and pedicel attachment zones that receive minimal light signals, and within-berry pigmentation gradients develop with sun-exposed surfaces showing 2-4 fold higher anthocyanin concentrations than shaded areas creating spatial heterogeneity even on individual berries. ||Anthocyanin accumulation kinetics during progressive development follow: biosynthetic rates peak at 50-150 mg/kg per day during mid-phase (days 3-6 of progressive development) when enzyme activities reach maximum levels, total skin anthocyanins increase sigmoidally with inflection point typically at 40-60% of final concentration, and absolute anthocyanin content per berry rises 8-15 fold from color break (4-8 mg total per berry) to late progressive phase (50-100 mg per berry) reflecting both increased concentration and slight berry expansion. ||Biosynthetic machinery during progressive development operates at peak capacity: UFGT enzyme activity reaches maximum levels 25-45 units/kg fresh weight catalyzing glucosylation of 40-80 μmol anthocyanidins per hour per kg, PAL activity peaks at 80-150 units providing phenylpropanoid flux sustaining pathway operation, DFR and LDOX achieve 70-120 units producing leucoanthocyanidin and anthocyanidin substrates, and coordinated expression of all pathway enzymes creates metabolic channeling efficiency maximizing anthocyanin output while minimizing intermediate accumulation. ||Gene expression during progressive development maintains: anthocyanin biosynthetic genes sustained at 80-100% of peak levels with UFGT transcripts 150-200 fold above green berry baseline, regulatory MYB factors (VvMYBA1/A2) continue high expression 100-150 fold coordinating pathway genes, while genes for competing pathways including proanthocyanidin synthesis (LAR, ANR) decline creating favorable metabolic channeling toward anthocyanins, and sugar transporters show parallel elevation supporting hexose accumulation that provides both substrate and signaling for anthocyanin synthesis. ||Anthocyanin composition during progressive development shows: malvidin-3-glucoside maintains dominance at 50-70% while absolute levels increase from 40-80 mg/kg at color break to 250-500 mg/kg late progressive phase, acylated anthocyanins (acetyl and coumaroyl derivatives) increase from 10-15% to 15-25% of total enhancing color stability, diglucosides common in non-vinifera species remain absent or trace in Vitis vinifera, and hydroxylation patterns establishing delphinidin, cyanidin, petunidin, and peonidin ratios remain relatively constant reflecting stable expression of F3'H and F3'5'H hydroxylases. ||Vacuolar sequestration during progressive development involves: anthocyanin concentrations in epidermal cell vacuoles reach 8-20 mM (from 3-8 mM at color break) approaching solubility limits, vacuolar pH maintained at 3.0-3.5 through enhanced V-ATPase activity ensuring flavylium cation stability, anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions (AVIs) expand in cultivars forming these structures creating highly concentrated pigment deposits (>50 mM local concentrations), and co-pigmentation with flavonols and hydroxycinnamic acids continues amplifying color intensity 30-50% beyond that expected from anthocyanin concentration alone. ||Chlorophyll degradation accelerates during progressive development: chlorophyll a and b decline from color break levels 40-80 μg/g to late progressive phase 10-30 μg/g through pheophytinase and pheophorbide a oxygenase activities, green color masking progressively eliminated allowing anthocyanin pigmentation to dominate visual appearance, carotenoid content remains relatively stable (20-40 μg/g) contributing yellow-orange background visible in white cultivars but overwhelmed by anthocyanins in reds, and complete disappearance of photosynthetic pigments creates characteristic ripe berry translucency in some cultivars. ||Environmental modulation of progressive development shows: optimal temperature 22-28°C supports maximum progression rates completing color development in 4-6 days for early cultivars, cooler temperatures 16-22°C extend progression to 6-10 days but may enhance final color intensity through improved anthocyanin stability, heat stress >32°C severely impairs progression with anthocyanin accumulation reduced 40-70% and extended development periods 10-14 days often producing inadequately colored fruit, and diurnal temperature variation >12-15°C day-night difference optimizes progression through balanced synthesis and stabilization. ||Light effects on progressive development inclu UV-B exposure continues enhancing anthocyanin synthesis throughout progression maintaining 30-50% higher accumulation in exposed versus shaded regions, visible light particularly blue wavelengths sustains photoreceptor signaling supporting biosynthetic gene expression, canopy architecture affecting cluster light exposure creates within-vine variation with exterior clusters showing 25-45% higher final anthocyanin levels than interior positions, and leaf removal during progressive development can enhance coloring 20-35% if temperature stress avoided though excessive exposure risks heat inhibition. ||Water relations influence on progressive development: moderate deficit (-0.9 to -1.3 MPa stem ψ) maintains or enhances progression through sustained ABA signaling and berry concentration producing 15-30% higher final anthocyanin concentrations, severe stress (<-1.5 MPa) arrests progression reducing final color 30-60% through metabolic limitation despite elevated ABA, while excess water dilutes berries and suppresses ABA-dependent gene expression reducing final anthocyanin 20-40% compared to moderate deficit, and timing of deficit imposition affects outcome with pre-veraison stress more beneficial than deficit imposed during progressive development. ||Cultivar variation in progressive development reflects: rapid developers like Pinot Noir complete progression in 3-5 days reaching 1200-2000 mg/kg final anthocyanins, moderate cultivars like Merlot and Syrah require 5-8 days achieving 800-1500 mg/kg, while slow developers like Cabernet Sauvignon and Nebbiolo need 8-12 days reaching 600-1200 mg/kg demonstrating genetic differences in maximum synthesis rates and biosynthetic duration. ||Coordination with other ripening processes during progressive development: berry softening accelerates concurrently with firmness declining 40-60% from green berry values, sugar accumulation peaks at 1.5-3.5% Brix per week during progressive color development, acid decline intensifies particularly malate respiratory consumption reducing titratable acidity 15-30%, and seed maturation progresses with testa lignification and browning paralleling skin color development. ||Metabolic costs of progressive development are substantial: anthocyanin biosynthesis consumes 10-20% of berry carbon import during peak color development, nitrogen demands for enzyme synthesis and anthocyanin precursors draw on berry reserves requiring 30-60 μmol phenylalanine per kg fresh weight, energy requirements including ATP for biosynthesis and vacuolar transport represent 12-20% of berry respiration during maximum accumulation rates, and competition for carbon between anthocyanin synthesis, sugar accumulation, and other metabolic processes may create trade-offs affecting final berry composition.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 233-236 anthocyanin accumulation kinetics || Castellarin SD, Matthews MA, Di Gaspero G, Gambetta GA (2007) Water deficits accelerate ripening and induce changes in gene expression regulating flavonoid biosynthesis in grape berries Planta 227:101-112 environmental effects on color progression || Matus JT, Loyola R, Vega A, Peña-Neira A, Bordeu E, Arce-Johnson P, Alcalde JA (2009) Post-veraison sunlight exposure induces MYB-mediated transcriptional regulation of anthocyanin and flavonol synthesis in berry skins Plant Physiol 149:1647-1661 light regulation of progressive development."
},

  "Increasing_Anthocyanin_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "An Increasing_Anthocyanin_Accumulation is a Progressive_Color_Development characterized by exponential rise of berry skin anthocyanin concentration toward cultivar-specific maxima driven by peak biosynthetic activity.",
  "alternative_term": "escalating pigment synthesis | rising anthocyanin content | amplifying color compound accumulation | intensifying anthocyanin production |+ eskalierende Pigment-Synthese | steigende Anthocyan-Konzentration | verstärkende Farbstoff-Akkumulation | intensivierende Anthocyan-Produktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Bordeaux Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, increasing anthocyanin accumulation was quantified during 6 days in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 84) when skin anthocyanins rose from 185 mg/kg to 695 mg/kg (average 85 mg/kg per day), with malvidin-3-glucoside increasing from 105 to 390 mg/kg, berry Brix advancing 14.5 to 19.8°, firmness declining to 1.8 N, and ABA sustained at 1650-1850 ng/g under favorable conditions (daily high 26-28°C, night 14-17°C, moderate water deficit stem ψ -1.1 MPa) in eastern canopy exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Increasing_Anthocyanin_Accumulation is distinguished from Initial_Anthocyanin_Synthesis by representing peak rates rather than onset, from Progressive_Color_Development by focusing on quantitative accumulation rather than spatial progression, and from final accumulation by exhibiting exponential increase rather than plateau. ||Peak rates: high accumulators 100-150 mg/kg/day, moderate 60-100 mg/kg/day, lower 40-70 mg/kg/day. ||Temperature optimum 23-28°C. ||Moderate deficit enhances 20-35%. ||Increasing_Anthocyanin_Accumulation phase critically determines final berry color intensity and wine quality potential. || This process occurs during mid-veraison (BBCH 84), typically 3-8 days post-color break, and is characterized by anthocyanin accumulation rates of 50-150 mg/kg skin fresh weight per day (compared to initial synthesis 10-30 mg/kg per day) increasing total skin anthocyanins from 100-200 mg/kg at early progressive development to 400-1000 mg/kg at late progressive phase representing 4-10 fold amplification. ||Kinetics of increasing accumulation follow sigmoidal patterns: initial lag phase (days 0-2 post-color break) shows relatively slower rates 20-40 mg/kg per day as biosynthetic machinery approaches maximum capacity, exponential phase (days 3-6) exhibits peak rates 60-150 mg/kg per day when all pathway enzymes operate at maximum with optimal substrate availability and favorable conditions, plateau approach (days 7-10) displays declining rates 30-60 mg/kg per day as concentrations near cultivar-specific maxima and potential feedback inhibition or substrate limitation begins, and final plateau (days 10-14) shows minimal further increase <10 mg/kg per day indicating completion of major anthocyanin accumulation. ||Biosynthetic basis of increasing accumulation involves: UFGT enzyme reaching maximum activity 30-50 units/kg fresh weight catalyzing glucosylation at peak rates 50-100 μmol substrate per hour per kg, PAL activity sustained at 100-180 units maintaining phenylpropanoid flux adequate for downstream pathway demands, coordinated elevation of all biosynthetic enzymes (CHS, F3H, F3'H, F3'5'H, DFR, LDOX) creates metabolic channeling efficiency with minimal intermediate accumulation, and transcriptional maintenance at 90-100% of maximum expression sustained through continued high ABA levels (1200-2500 ng/g) and sugar signaling (berry Brix 12-20°) provides enzyme synthesis matching protein turnover. ||Anthocyanin composition during increasing accumulation maintains: malvidin-3-glucoside dominance at 50-70% of total with absolute levels rising from 60-120 mg/kg early progressive to 280-600 mg/kg late progressive phase, cyanidin-3-glucoside contributes 8-20% reaching 30-150 mg/kg, delphinidin-3-glucoside ranges 5-18% achieving 20-140 mg/kg with higher proportions in Syrah and Petit Verdot, peonidin and petunidin derivatives account for 5-15% each, and acylated anthocyanins increase from 10-15% to 18-28% of total enhancing color stability through intramolecular copigmentation. ||Cellular mechanisms supporting increasing accumulation inclu vacuolar sequestration capacity expanding through vacuole enlargement and membrane transporter upregulation enabling anthocyanin concentrations reaching 12-25 mM in epidermal cell vacuoles, GST and ABC transporter protein levels sustained at high expression maintaining efficient cytosol-to-vacuole transport preventing cytoplasmic anthocyanin accumulation that could be toxic, vacuolar pH maintenance at 3.0-3.5 through V-ATPase activity ensuring anthocyanin stability in colored flavylium form, and formation or expansion of anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions in some cultivars creating highly concentrated pigment deposits exceeding 60 mM local concentration. ||Subcellular energy demands of increasing accumulation are substantial: ATP consumption for biosynthetic reactions estimated 4-8 moles ATP per mole anthocyanin synthesized representing significant metabolic cost, additional ATP for vacuolar transport (2-3 moles per anthocyanin molecule) and proton pumping maintaining pH gradient, total energy cost during peak accumulation (60-120 mg/kg per day, ~150-300 μmol per kg) requiring 900-2400 μmol ATP per day representing 15-25% of total berry respiration during this phase. ||Carbon allocation during increasing accumulation shows: phenylpropanoid pathway flux consuming 15-25% of berry carbon import during peak color development with approximately 80-150 μmol phenylalanine channeled into anthocyanins per kg fresh weight per day, this creates potential competition with sugar accumulation though both processes typically progress simultaneously suggesting adequate carbon supply under normal conditions, nitrogen requirements for enzyme synthesis and phenylalanine precursor draw on berry amino acid pools with 40-80 μmol total amino acids consumed per kg per day during maximum accumulation. ||Temperature sensitivity of increasing accumulation is pronounced: optimal berry temperature 23-28°C supports maximum accumulation rates 80-150 mg/kg per day enabling rapid progression, moderate cooling to 18-23°C reduces rates 30-50% extending accumulation period but may enhance final levels through improved anthocyanin stability once synthesized, heat stress 32-35°C severely inhibits accumulation reducing rates 60-80% and potentially lowering final anthocyanin concentrations 40-70% through enzyme denaturation and transcript degradation, and extreme heat >35°C can completely arrest accumulation producing pale inadequately colored fruit even if conditions later improve. ||Light quantity and quality effects inclu UV-B radiation (280-315 nm) enhances accumulation rates 35-60% through UVR8-mediated gene induction, blue light (430-470 nm) increases rates 20-40% via cryptochrome signaling, red light shows moderate 10-20% enhancement, while excessive visible radiation combined with heat can reduce accumulation through photoinhibition and thermal stress demonstrating complex light-temperature interactions requiring optimization. ||Water deficit impacts on increasing accumulation show: moderate deficit (stem ψ -0.9 to -1.3 MPa) enhances accumulation 20-35% through elevated ABA maintaining high biosynthetic gene expression and berry concentration effects, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) impairs accumulation despite very high ABA through general metabolic limitation reducing final anthocyanin 35-60%, while abundant water dilutes berries and may suppress ABA-responsive genes reducing accumulation 25-45% compared to moderate deficit demonstrating complex dose-dependent relationships. ||Cultivar differences in increasing accumulation rates reflect: high-accumulator varieties like Petit Verdot and Tannat achieve peak rates 100-150 mg/kg per day reaching final levels 2000-3000 mg/kg, moderate accumulators like Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot show 60-100 mg/kg per day peaks with 800-1500 mg/kg final, while lower-accumulator cultivars like Pinot Noir (despite rapid color break) display 40-70 mg/kg per day maximum achieving 600-1200 mg/kg final demonstrating genetic variation in both rate and duration of accumulation. ||Coordination with berry development processes: increasing anthocyanin accumulation coincides with peak sugar accumulation rates (1.5-3.5% Brix per week) suggesting integrated carbon metabolism regulation, parallels maximum berry softening velocity (firmness declining 3-6% per day), occurs during intense acid decline particularly malate consumption, and synchronizes with phenolic compound synthesis including tannins and flavonols creating complex flavor and structural wine components. ||Quality implications inclu final anthocyanin levels strongly correlate with wine color intensity (r² = 0.85-0.95) making increasing accumulation monitoring critical for quality prediction, rate and duration of increasing accumulation affect anthocyanin composition particularly acylated derivative proportions influencing color stability and aging potential, and environmental optimization during this phase through irrigation, canopy management, and crop load adjustment can substantially enhance final color 30-60% compared to suboptimal conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 234-236 anthocyanin accumulation dynamics || Tarara JM, Lee J, Spayd SE, Scagel CF (2008) Berry temperature and solar radiation alter acylation, proportion, and concentration of anthocyanin in Merlot grapes Amer J Enol Vitic 59:235-247 environmental effects on accumulation kinetics || Cohen SD, Tarara JM, Kennedy JA (2008) Assessing the impact of temperature on grape phenolic metabolism Anal Chim Acta 621:57-67 temperature sensitivity of accumulation."
},

  "Color_Intensity_Increase": {
  "definition": "A Color_Intensity_Increase is a Progressive_Color_Development marked by deepening saturation of berry surface pigmentation from pale pink-red to intense red-purple through cumulative anthocyanin accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "deepening color saturation | amplifying pigmentation intensity | increasing chromatic strength | intensifying visual color |+ zunehmende Farb-Sättigung | verstärkende Pigmentierungs-Intensität | steigende chromatische Stärke | intensivierende visuelle Farbe",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Mendoza Malbec vineyard in Argentina, color intensity increase was documented over 8 days in late February Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when CIE L* declined from 48 to 28 (darkening), chroma increased from 32 to 51 (greater saturation), skin anthocyanins rose from 225 mg/kg to 980 mg/kg, absorbance at 520 nm increased from 0.8 to 2.4 OD, berry Brix advanced 15.2 to 22.5°, under optimal high-altitude conditions (daily high 27-30°C, night 12-15°C, intense UV, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.15 MPa).",
  "editor_note": "Color_Intensity_Increase is distinguished from Increasing_Anthocyanin_Accumulation by representing visual/spectral manifestation rather than biochemical quantity, from Progressive_Color_Development by focusing on intensity rather than spatial progression, and from Complete_Color_Change by exhibiting ongoing increase rather than final state. ||CIE L* range: color break 50-65, peak intensity 25-40. ||Copigmentation contributes 30-50% intensity enhancement. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C. ||Moderate deficit enhances 25-40%. ||Color_Intensity_Increase provides practical visual assessment of ripening progress and wine quality prediction. || This process parallels increasing anthocyanin accumulation occurring during mid-to-late veraison (BBCH 84-85), typically 4-10 days post-color break, and is characterized by progressive shifts in color metrics: CIE L* (lightness) declining from 50-65 at color break to 25-40 at peak intensity indicating darkening, chroma (C*) increasing from 20-35 to 35-55 reflecting greater color saturation, and hue angle shifting from 20-35° (orange-red) toward 0-15° (pure red) or 340-355° (red-purple) as anthocyanins overwhelm residual chlorophyll and carotenoid contributions. ||Optical basis of intensity increase involves: anthocyanin concentration rising from 100-200 mg/kg to 500-1200 mg/kg creates proportional increase in light absorption at 520-540 nm wavelengths where anthocyanins show maximum absorbance, extinction coefficient effects where concentrated anthocyanin solutions show non-linear color intensity increases through molecular interactions and aggregation, copigmentation phenomena between anthocyanins and colorless flavonols or hydroxycinnamic acids producing 30-50% color intensification beyond that expected from anthocyanin concentration alone through bathochromic shifts and hyperchromic effects, and anthocyanin vacuolar inclusion formation in some cultivars creating localized pigment concentrations >60 mM generating extremely intense color visible even in small tissue volumes. ||Spectral characteristics during intensity increase show: absorbance spectra developing characteristic anthocyanin profile with maximum 520-540 nm and secondary peak 270-280 nm, visible absorbance at 520 nm increasing from optical density 0.3-0.6 at color break to 1.5-3.0 at peak intensity representing 5-10 fold amplification, reflectance spectra showing declining green reflection (500-600 nm) from 30-45% at color break to <10-15% at peak intensity while red reflection (620-650 nm) increases from 15-25% to 30-50%, and emergence of characteristic purple-blue secondary reflection (400-450 nm) in delphinidin-rich cultivars contributing to varietal color signatures. ||Cellular and tissue-level changes underlying intensity increase inclu anthocyanin concentration in epidermal and sub-epidermal cell vacuoles rising from 5-10 mM to 15-30 mM approaching solubility limits, pigmentation depth extending from 1-2 to 3-5 cell layers into berry skin creating optical density sufficient for intense color, chlorophyll degradation from 40-80 μg/g to <10-20 μg/g eliminating green color masking, and cell wall-bound phenolics accumulating providing additional light absorption and color background supporting anthocyanin-based primary coloration. ||Anthocyanin compositional changes during intensity increase show: total anthocyanins rising 4-8 fold from 120-180 mg/kg to 500-1200 mg/kg depending on cultivar, malvidin-3-glucoside absolute levels increasing proportionally from 70-110 mg/kg to 300-750 mg/kg maintaining 50-70% dominance, acylated anthocyanins (acetyl, coumaroyl derivatives) increasing from 12-20% to 20-30% of total providing enhanced color stability and modified spectral properties, and anthocyanin-flavonol ratios shifting from 2:1-4:1 at color break to 5:1-10:1 at peak intensity as anthocyanin synthesis outpaces flavonol accumulation though high absolute flavonol levels (80-200 mg/kg) maintain copigmentation effects. ||Environmental modulation of intensity increase includes: optimal temperature 22-28°C supporting maximum anthocyanin synthesis produces most rapid and complete intensity increase achieving deep color in 5-7 days, moderate cooling 18-23°C may enhance final intensity through improved anthocyanin stability despite slower accumulation requiring 8-12 days to peak, heat stress >32°C severely impairs intensity increase with final color 40-70% below optimal temperature treatment producing pale inadequately colored fruit, and diurnal temperature variation >12-15°C combining warm days facilitating synthesis with cool nights enhancing stability often optimizes final intensity. ||Light effects on intensity increase demonstrate: UV-B radiation enhances intensity 30-50% through increased anthocyanin synthesis and potential effects on copigment accumulation, moderate visible light exposure optimizes intensity while excessive radiation combined with heat can reduce intensity through anthocyanin degradation and synthesis inhibition, canopy position effects create 35-60% intensity variation between sun-exposed and shaded clusters, and cluster-level light distribution affects within-cluster intensity uniformity with exposed berries showing 2-4 fold higher intensity than completely shaded berries. ||Water stress influences show: moderate deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.3 MPa) enhances intensity 25-40% through elevated anthocyanin concentration and potential berry size reduction concentrating pigments per unit surface area, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) reduces intensity despite high anthocyanin concentration through metabolic impairment limiting synthesis, while excess water dilutes berries and reduces intensity 30-50% through lower anthocyanin per unit fresh weight and potentially reduced synthesis through suppressed ABA signaling. ||Cultivar variation in intensity characteristics reflects: high-intensity varieties like Petit Verdot, Tannat, and Syrah achieve very deep color (L* 20-30, anthocyanins 1500-3000 mg/kg) with strong purple notes from high delphinidin, moderate-intensity cultivars like Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot display deep red color (L* 25-35, 800-1500 mg/kg anthocyanins), while lower-intensity varieties like Pinot Noir and Grenache show bright-to-medium red (L* 30-40, 600-1200 mg/kg) with characteristic hue differences reflecting anthocyanin composition. ||Temporal progression of intensity increase follows: rapid initial increase during days 3-6 of progressive development when anthocyanin synthesis peaks, slower continued increase days 7-10 as accumulation rates decline approaching maximum, and plateau or slight decrease post-day 10 as synthesis stops and potential degradation begins in some conditions demonstrating importance of harvest timing for optimal color capture. ||Monitoring intensity increase provides quality assessment: visual comparison with color standards or photographic references enables semi-quantitative tracking, portable colorimeters measuring CIE L*a*b* values provide objective intensity quantification correlating with wine color potential (r² = 0.80-0.92), and spectrophotometric analysis of skin extracts measuring anthocyanin absorbance at 520 nm gives precise color intensity prediction for harvest timing optimization. ||Wine quality implications of intensity increase inclu final berry color intensity strongly predicts wine color density (r² = 0.85-0.95) with deeper berry color producing higher wine absorbance at 520 nm, intensity progression rate affects anthocyanin stability characteristics with rapid intense coloring sometimes associated with less stable anthocyanins versus moderate progression producing more stable pigments, and spatial uniformity of intensity within clusters or vineyards indicates ripening synchrony affecting harvest decisions and wine composition consistency. ||Physiological correlates of intensity increase inclu color deepening typically parallels berry softening with peak intensity coinciding with 50-70% total firmness reduction, synchronizes with maximum sugar accumulation rates (berry Brix rising 1.5-3.5% per week during peak intensity increase), and occurs during intense malate degradation creating flavor and acid balance changes accompanying color development demonstrating integrated ripening program controlling multiple quality parameters simultaneously.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 234-236 color development and quality || Rolle L, Torchio F, Giacosa S, Gerbi V (2009) Modifications of mechanical characteristics and phenolic composition in berry skins and seeds of Mondeuse winegrapes throughout the on-vine drying process Amer J Enol Vitic 60:418-425 color intensity dynamics || Guidoni S, Ferrandino A, Novello V (2008) Effects of seasonal and agronomical practices on skin anthocyanin profile of Nebbiolo grapes Amer J Enol Vitic 59:22-29 environmental effects on color intensity."
},

  "Uniform_Pigmentation_Progress": {
  "definition": "A Uniform_Pigmentation_Progress is a Progressive_Color_Development comprising the spatial coalescence of scattered patches into continuous coloring covering the entire berry surface with consistent intensity and hue.",
  "alternative_term": "homogeneous color coverage | consistent pigmentation distribution | even berry coloring | spatial color uniformity |+ homogene Farb-Abdeckung | konsistente Pigmentierungs-Verteilung | gleichmäßige Beeren-Färbung | räumliche Farb-Uniformität",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Rheingau Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir) vineyard, uniform pigmentation progress was evaluated over 6 days in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when berry surface color coverage increased from 65% to 96% uniformly pigmented, spatial anthocyanin variation (CV) declined from 42% to 18%, CIE L* variation decreased from 32% to 11%, skin anthocyanins reached 1150 mg/kg average with <200 mg/kg standard deviation across berry positions, berry sugar was 21.8° Brix, under cool autumn conditions (daily high 19-22°C, night 9-12°C) with good cluster exposure from summer leaf removal.",
  "editor_note": "Uniform_Pigmentation_Progress is distinguished from Progressive_Color_Development by representing spatial homogenization rather than temporal progression, from Color_Intensity_Increase by focusing on uniformity rather than saturation, and from Complete_Color_Change by showing advancing uniformity rather than final state. ||Uniformity threshold: >90-95% berry surface consistently pigmented. ||Timing: fast cultivars 5-7 days post-break, moderate 7-10 days, slow 10-14 days. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C. ||Uniform light exposure critical. ||Uniform_Pigmentation_Progress indicates ripening synchrony essential for optimal harvest timing and wine quality consistency. || This process occurs during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 84-85), typically 6-12 days post-color break depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and transforms berry appearance from variegated patches of intense and pale color to uniform coverage where >90-95% of berry surface shows consistent pigmentation suitable for harvest assessment and quality evaluation. ||Spatial patterns of uniformity achievement show: initially pigmented sun-exposed surfaces (occupying 50-70% berry area at mid-progressive development) expand into shaded regions through continued anthocyanin synthesis in previously unpigmented cells, green remnants concentrated on northwestern aspects (northern hemisphere) and near pedicel attachment progressively shrink and disappear as chlorophyll degradation completes and anthocyanin accumulation reaches these developmental lag zones, and within-berry color gradients diminish from 3-5 fold variation between most and least pigmented regions at color break to <1.5-2 fold variation at uniform pigmentation representing substantial spatial homogenization. ||Cellular basis of uniformity achievement involves: recruitment of previously unpigmented epidermal and sub-epidermal cells into anthocyanin synthesis through diffusion of developmental signals possibly including sugars, ABA, or other mobile factors, cell-to-cell communication potentially through plasmodesmata enabling coordinated ripening responses across berry surface, and completion of chlorophyll degradation throughout entire berry skin (chlorophyll declining to <5-10 μg/g uniformly) eliminating green color masking allowing full anthocyanin color expression even in lower-pigment regions. ||Anthocyanin distribution during uniformity progress shows: total skin anthocyanin reaching 70-90% of final maximum levels (500-2000 mg/kg cultivar-dependent) with continued accumulation in previously lagging regions, spatial variation in anthocyanin concentration decreasing from coefficient of variation 45-65% at color break to 15-30% at uniform pigmentation measured across multiple berry surface positions, and accumulation rates in initially unpigmented regions (30-50 mg/kg per day) exceeding rates in early-pigmented areas (15-30 mg/kg per day) enabling catch-up and uniformity achievement. ||Biosynthetic machinery distribution during uniformity progress includes: UFGT and other anthocyanin biosynthetic enzyme expression spreading from initial synthesis zones to encompass entire berry epidermis creating uniform biosynthetic capacity, regulatory transcription factors (VvMYBA1/A2, VvMYC1) showing more uniform expression across berry surface compared to initial patchy expression at color break, and hormonal signals particularly ABA (1500-2500 ng/g throughout berry) providing uniform developmental cues enabling synchronized ripening responses across all berry regions. ||Optical consequences of uniform pigmentation inclu berry surface reflectance spectra becoming consistent across multiple measurement positions with standard deviation of 520 nm absorbance declining from 0.4-0.8 OD units at color break to 0.1-0.3 OD at uniform pigmentation, color coordinates (CIE L*a*b*) showing reduced spatial variation with L* coefficient of variation decreasing from 25-40% to 8-15% indicating consistent lightness/darkness across berry, and hue angle variation declining from 15-30° range to <8-12° demonstrating uniform color quality approaching monochromatic berry appearance. ||Environmental influences on uniformity achievement show: optimal temperature 22-28°C promotes rapid uniformity in 6-8 days through efficient anthocyanin synthesis in all berry regions, cooler temperatures 18-23°C may enhance final uniformity through extended development period (9-12 days) allowing complete pigmentation even in challenging shaded areas, heat stress >32°C impairs uniformity producing patchy coloring with persistent green or pale zones reflecting spatial variation in heat exposure and metabolic capacity under stress, and large diurnal temperature variation >15°C may enhance uniformity through cool nights enabling pigmentation in regions that experience excessive daytime heat. ||Light distribution effects on uniformity are pronounced: canopy architecture creating uniform cluster light exposure produces uniform berry pigmentation in 7-10 days, while dense canopies with strong light gradients generate 20-40% variation in final pigmentation requiring 12-16 days for partial uniformity achievement or never achieving complete uniformity, leaf removal or cluster thinning during progressive development can accelerate uniformity 2-4 days through improved light penetration to previously shaded berry surfaces, and cluster positioning with rotating or revolving clusters would theoretically optimize uniformity though impractical in commercial viticulture. ||Water relations effects inclu moderate deficit uniformly applied promotes consistent uniformity across all berries through systemic ABA elevation and uniform metabolic stress responses, spatially variable water availability from non-uniform irrigation or heterogeneous soil creates variable berry development and pigmentation uniformity challenges, and sudden water availability changes during progressive development can disrupt uniformity creating zones of different color intensity reflecting timing of developmental signal reception. ||Cultivar variation in uniformity progression shows: rapid-uniforming varieties like Pinot Noir achieve >90% uniform coverage in 5-7 days post-color break, moderate cultivars like Merlot and Cabernet Sauvignon require 7-10 days for uniformity, while slow-uniforming varieties like Nebbiolo may need 10-14 days or show persistent spatial variation even at harvest reflecting genetic differences in developmental synchrony and anthocyanin synthesis distribution. ||Within-cluster uniformity achievement shows: berries at different developmental stages creating cluster heterogeneity with leading berries achieving uniformity 3-5 days before lagging berries, cluster shoulders often reaching uniformity before tips possibly reflecting vascular supply differences, and compact clusters with berry-berry contact potentially showing delayed uniformity in contact zones through restricted light and gas exchange affecting local metabolism. ||Quality implications of uniform pigmentation inclu uniform berry color indicates ripening synchrony enabling optimal harvest timing when all fruit achieves target maturity, lack of uniformity reveals developmental heterogeneity potentially requiring selective harvest or acceptance of variable wine composition, color uniformity often correlates with other maturity parameters suggesting berries achieving uniform pigmentation also show consistent sugar, acid, and phenolic development, and visual assessment of cluster uniformity provides practical harvest readiness evaluation tool for viticulturists. ||Monitoring uniformity progress involves: photographic documentation enabling image analysis measuring percentage of berry surface showing target color intensity, visual scoring using standardized color charts rating clusters on 1-5 or 1-10 scales for uniformity, and sampling berries from different cluster positions for anthocyanin analysis revealing spatial variation quantitatively guiding harvest timing and quality predictions. ||Temporal coordination with other ripening processes: uniform pigmentation typically achieved when berry sugar reaches 18-24° Brix depending on cultivar and style, coincides with 60-80% of total berry softening completed, occurs during late malate decline producing desired acid balance, and parallels seed maturation (brown color, lignified testa) indicating integrated berry development approaching harvest readiness. ||Viticultural management targeting uniformity includes: canopy management to improve cluster light exposure accelerates and enhances uniformity, irrigation scheduling to maintain moderate consistent deficit promotes uniform developmental signaling across all berries, crop load adjustment to optimize source-sink balance enables adequate resource supply for all berries achieving synchronized maturation, and disease control particularly Botrytis prevention since immature green berry remnants show enhanced disease susceptibility potentially serving as infection foci compromising cluster quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 234-236 color development uniformity || Downey MO, Harvey JS, Robinson SP (2003) Analysis of tannins in seeds and skins of Shiraz grapes throughout berry development Australian J Grape Wine Res 9:15-27 spatial patterns of berry development || Cortell JM, Kennedy JA (2006) Effect of shading on accumulation of flavonoid compounds in Pinot Noir fruit and extraction in wine Amer J Enol Vitic 57:33-43 light effects on color uniformity."
},

  "Uniform_Color_Development": {
  "definition": "A Uniform_Color_Development is a Veraison characterized by spatial consistency of berry surface pigmentation with minimal variation across the entire berry surface.",
  "alternative_term": "homogeneous berry pigmentation | consistent color expression | spatially uniform coloring | synchronized color maturation |+ homogene Beeren-Pigmentierung | konsistente Farb-Expression | räumlich uniforme Färbung | synchronisierte Farb-Reifung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Coast Pinot Noir vineyard, uniform color development was achieved 10 days post-color break in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when >96% berry surface showed consistent color, anthocyanin spatial variation (CV) was 14%, CIE L* variation 9%, skin anthocyanins averaged 1285 mg/kg (SD ±165 mg/kg), berry sugar 22.4° Brix, titratable acidity 6.2 g/L, firmness 1.3 N, under optimal cool coastal conditions (daily high 21-24°C, night 10-13°C, morning fog moderating cluster temperature) with good canopy light distribution from summer leaf removal.",
  "editor_note": "Uniform_Color_Development is distinguished from Progressive_Color_Development by representing spatial homogenization achievement rather than temporal progression, from Uniform_Pigmentation_Progress by showing completed rather than advancing uniformity, and from Complete_Color_Change by focusing on spatial consistency rather than maximum intensity. ||Uniformity criteria: >95% berry surface, anthocyanin CV <15-20%, CIE L* CV <10-15%, hue variation <8-12°. ||Timing: fast cultivars 7-9 days post-break, moderate 9-12 days, slow 12-16 days. ||Optimal temperature 22-28°C. ||Uniform light exposure critical. ||Uniform_Color_Development indicates ripening synchrony essential for harvest timing and wine quality consistency. || This process occurs during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87), typically 8-14 days post-color break depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by >95% berry surface showing consistent color with spatial variation coefficients declining to <15-20% for anthocyanin concentration, <10-15% for CIE L* lightness values, and <8-12° for hue angle representing substantial homogenization from color break variation of 45-65% anthocyanin CV, 25-40% L* CV, and 15-30° hue range. ||Achievement of uniform color development requires completion of anthocyanin synthesis across entire berry epidermis: previously unpigmented or weakly pigmented zones particularly shaded surfaces and pedicel attachment regions accumulate anthocyanins to 70-90% of peak-pigmented surface concentrations (compared to 20-40% during progressive development), total skin anthocyanins reach 80-95% of cultivar-specific maxima ranging 500-2800 mg/kg with spatial distribution showing standard deviation <150-250 mg/kg across berry positions, and chlorophyll degradation completes uniformly throughout berry skin with residual chlorophyll <5-10 μg/g eliminating all green color masking enabling full anthocyanin color expression. ||Cellular basis of uniform development involves: recruitment of all epidermal and sub-epidermal cells into anthocyanin biosynthesis with UFGT and other pathway enzyme expression becoming uniform across berry surface (expression variation <20-30% compared to >60-80% variation during color break), regulatory transcription factors VvMYBA1/A2 showing consistent activity throughout berry epidermis driven by uniform ABA distribution (1800-2800 ng/g with <15% spatial variation), vacuolar sequestration capacity uniform across all skin cells enabling consistent anthocyanin accumulation to 12-25 mM vacuolar concentrations, and cell-to-cell developmental coordination through diffusible signals or contact-mediated communication ensuring synchronized ripening responses across entire berry surface. ||Anthocyanin composition at uniform development shows: malvidin-3-glucoside maintaining 50-70% dominance with absolute levels 300-1800 mg/kg depending on cultivar, acylated anthocyanins reaching 20-30% of total providing enhanced color stability (acetyl and coumaroyl derivatives 150-600 mg/kg combined), and anthocyanin profiles (relative proportions of malvidin, delphinidin, cyanidin, petunidin, peonidin) becoming consistent across berry surface with <10-15% variation in individual anthocyanin percentages compared to >25-35% variation during progressive development. ||Optical characteristics of uniform development inclu reflectance spectra measured at multiple berry positions showing consistent profiles with characteristic anthocyanin absorbance maximum 520-540 nm and standard deviation <0.15-0.25 OD units across positions (compared to 0.4-0.8 OD variation during color break), CIE colorimetric coordinates achieving uniformity with L* (lightness) 25-40 showing <3-5 unit variation, a* (red-green axis) 20-45 with <4-6 unit variation, b* (yellow-blue axis) -5 to +15 with <3-5 unit variation, and hue angle stabilizing at cultivar-specific values (0-15° for pure reds like Cabernet Sauvignon, 340-355° for purple-reds like Syrah) with <5-8° variation indicating consistent color quality. ||Environmental factors affecting uniform development achievement inclu optimal temperature 22-28°C promotes rapid uniformity in 8-10 days through efficient anthocyanin synthesis across all berry regions including previously lagging zones, cooler conditions 18-23°C may enhance final uniformity through extended development period (11-15 days) allowing complete pigmentation maturation, heat stress >32°C impairs uniformity creating persistent color variation through spatial differences in heat tolerance and metabolic capacity, and stable environmental conditions without dramatic fluctuations favor uniformity while variable conditions (temperature swings, water stress cycling) can disrupt synchronized development maintaining heterogeneity. ||Light distribution critically affects uniformity: uniform cluster light exposure through optimal canopy architecture produces uniform berry pigmentation with <15% anthocyanin variation across berry surface, heterogeneous light environments from dense canopies or cluster shading create 30-60% pigmentation variation potentially preventing full uniformity achievement, leaf removal or cluster exposure adjustment during veraison can improve uniformity by 25-40% through enhanced light penetration to previously shaded regions, and cluster positioning relative to canopy (exterior versus interior, orientation) creates systematic effects on uniformity timing with exposed clusters achieving uniform development 3-5 days earlier than shaded positions. ||Water relations influence on uniformity shows: moderate consistent deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.3 MPa maintained throughout veraison) promotes uniform development through systemic ABA-mediated ripening signals affecting all berry regions equivalently, spatially variable water availability from heterogeneous irrigation or soil characteristics creates non-uniform berry development with 25-45% variation in color parameters, deficit timing affects uniformity with pre-veraison imposition producing better uniformity than deficit applied during color development, and sudden water availability changes (heavy rain, irrigation resumption) can disrupt uniformity by triggering asynchronous metabolic responses across berry surface. ||Cultivar variation in uniform development characteristics reflects: rapid-uniforming varieties like Pinot Noir achieve >95% uniform coverage in 7-9 days post-color break with very consistent appearance, moderate cultivars like Merlot and Cabernet Sauvignon require 9-12 days for uniformity showing good but not perfect consistency, while slow or variable-uniforming varieties like Nebbiolo and Sangiovese may need 12-16 days and still exhibit 20-30% residual variation reflecting genetic differences in developmental synchrony and anthocyanin synthesis coordination. ||Within-vineyard spatial variation in uniform development reveals: terroir effects from soil, microclimate, or vine age differences creating 4-8 day variation in uniformity achievement across vineyard blocks, vine vigor effects with high-vigor vines showing delayed and less complete uniformity through extended vegetative-reproductive competition and excessive canopy density, and rootstock influences with vigorous rootstocks potentially delaying uniformity 2-4 days compared to low-vigor stocks through altered carbon allocation and water relations. ||Quality implications of uniform color development inclu uniformity indicates ripening synchrony suggesting berries achieving consistent color also show coordinated sugar, acid, and phenolic maturation enabling optimal harvest timing, lack of uniformity reveals developmental heterogeneity potentially requiring selective harvest of uniform clusters or acceptance of compositional variation in wine, uniform color strongly correlates with wine quality consistency (r² = 0.75-0.88) since spatial variation in color reflects broader maturity differences affecting multiple quality parameters, and visual assessment of uniformity provides practical harvest readiness evaluation more accessible than chemical analysis enabling field-based decisions. ||Monitoring uniform development involves: photographic documentation with image analysis measuring color uniformity coefficients across berry surfaces and clusters, portable colorimeters measuring CIE L*a*b* at multiple berry positions (typically 4-6 points around equator) revealing spatial variation quantitatively, visual scoring using standardized charts rating clusters 1-5 for uniformity (1 = highly variable, 5 = completely uniform) providing rapid semi-quantitative assessment, and selective sampling of berries from different cluster positions and vineyard zones for anthocyanin analysis revealing spatial variation guiding harvest timing and quality prediction. ||Temporal coordination with other maturity parameters shows: uniform color development typically achieved when berry sugar reaches 20-26° Brix (cultivar and style dependent), coincides with 70-85% of total berry softening completed producing characteristic ripe firmness 1.2-2.2 N, occurs during late acid decline with titratable acidity 4-7 g/L and pH 3.2-3.6 approaching harvest targets, and parallels phenolic maturity with seed browning and extractable tannin optimization indicating integrated berry development approaching optimal harvest window. ||Physiological significance includes: uniform pigmentation across berry surface maximizes UV protection and antioxidant capacity distributed throughout skin tissue, consistent anthocyanin levels enable predictable extraction during winemaking producing consistent wine color and phenolic profiles, and uniformity reflects overall metabolic coordination suggesting synchronized synthesis of other quality compounds including flavors, aromas, and structural phenolics contributing to wine complexity. ||Viticultural management targeting uniform development includes: canopy management creating optimal light distribution through shoot positioning, leaf removal, and cluster exposure balancing synthesis induction with heat stress avoidance, irrigation scheduling maintaining consistent moderate deficit throughout veraison avoiding water stress fluctuations that disrupt synchronized development, crop load adjustment optimizing source-sink balance ensuring adequate carbohydrate supply for all berries achieving coordinated maturation, disease control preventing localized infections that create developmental heterogeneity through pathogen-induced metabolic disruption, and soil management addressing spatial variability in water and nutrient availability that creates non-uniform vine responses affecting berry development consistency. ||Harvest timing optimization based on uniform development: achieving >95% uniform color indicates ripening completion suitable for harvest quality assessment, persistent non-uniformity (>20-25% variation) may necessitate selective harvest removing uniform clusters while leaving variable fruit for later picking, or acceptance of compositional variation recognizing wine quality implications, and integration of color uniformity with chemical maturity (sugar, acid, pH) and sensory evaluation (flavor, tannin) enables comprehensive harvest readiness determination balancing multiple quality parameters for optimal wine production.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 234-238 color development uniformity and maturity || Tarara JM, Lee J, Spayd SE, Scagel CF (2008) Berry temperature and solar radiation alter acylation, proportion, and concentration of anthocyanin in Merlot grapes Amer J Enol Vitic 59:235-247 environmental effects on color uniformity || Cortell JM, Kennedy JA (2006) Effect of shading on accumulation of flavonoid compounds in Pinot Noir fruit and extraction in wine Amer J Enol Vitic 57:33-43 canopy management effects on uniformity."
},

  "Even_Berry_Coloration": {
  "definition": "An Even_Berry_Coloration is a Uniform_Color_Development marked by minimal spatial variation in color intensity, hue, and saturation across the berry surface without patches, gradients, or discontinuities.",
  "alternative_term": "spatially consistent berry color | uniform surface pigmentation | homogeneous berry appearance | consistent color distribution |+ räumlich konsistente Beeren-Farbe | uniforme Oberflächen-Pigmentierung | homogenes Beeren-Aussehen | konsistente Farb-Verteilung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Rioja Tempranillo vineyard in Spain, even berry coloration was documented in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 86) when colorimetric measurements at 8 berry positions showed CIE L* 32.4 (SD ±2.8), a* 35.2 (SD ±3.6), hue angle 8.4° (SD ±4.2°), anthocyanin spatial variation CV 16%, skin anthocyanins averaging 945 mg/kg across positions (range 835-1055 mg/kg), berry sugar 23.1° Brix, firmness 1.6 N, under typical continental conditions (daily high 24-27°C, night 11-14°C) with balanced canopy providing moderate cluster exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Even_Berry_Coloration is distinguished from Uniform_Color_Development by representing the achieved state rather than the developmental process, from Color_Distribution_Uniformity by focusing on individual berry evenness rather than cluster/vineyard uniformity, and from Maximum_Color_Intensity by emphasizing spatial consistency rather than peak pigmentation. ||Evenness criteria: anthocyanin CV <12-18%, CIE L* CV <8-12%, hue variation <6-10°. ||Typical timing: 8-12 days post-color break. ||Temperature uniformity and light distribution critical. ||Even_Berry_Coloration indicates maturity suitable for harvest quality assessment and efficient winemaking extraction. || This condition emerges during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87), achieved 8-12 days post-color break in most cultivars, and is quantified by colorimetric measurements showing spatial coefficients of variation <12-18% for anthocyanin concentration measured at multiple berry positions (typically 4-8 sampling points around berry equator and poles), <8-12% for CIE L* lightness values, <10-15% for chroma saturation, and <6-10° for hue angle representing substantial reduction from progressive development variation of 35-55% anthocyanin CV, 20-35% L* CV, and 12-20° hue range. ||Achievement of even coloration requires uniform anthocyanin distribution: all epidermal and sub-epidermal cell layers (typically 3-5 cells deep) contain anthocyanins at concentrations within 80-95% of maximum values for that berry with previously shaded regions (northwestern aspects in northern hemisphere, pedicel zones) showing 75-90% of peak-exposed surface levels compared to 30-50% during progressive development, vacuolar anthocyanin concentrations in individual cells range 10-28 mM with spatial standard deviation <3-5 mM indicating minimal cell-to-cell variation, and anthocyanin composition (malvidin, delphinidin, cyanidin, petunidin, peonidin ratios) remains consistent across berry surface with <8-12% variation in individual anthocyanin percentages. ||Cellular basis of even coloration involves: completion of anthocyanin biosynthesis throughout entire berry epidermis with UFGT and pathway enzyme activities uniform across all regions (activity variation <18-25% compared to >50-70% during color break), regulatory factors (VvMYBA1/A2, VvMYC1, ABFs) showing consistent expression and activity across berry surface driven by uniform developmental signals including ABA (1800-3000 ng/g with <12% spatial variation) and sugars (berry Brix 18-26° with <8% within-berry variation), and chlorophyll degradation complete in all skin regions with residual chlorophyll <3-8 μg/g enabling unmasked anthocyanin color throughout. ||Optical properties of even coloration show: reflectance spectra measured at 6-10 berry positions display consistent profiles with anthocyanin absorbance maximum 520-540 nm showing standard deviation <0.12-0.20 OD units, red light reflection (620-650 nm) 30-50% with <5-8% variation across positions, purple-blue secondary reflection (400-450 nm) in delphinidin-rich cultivars showing <8-12% variation, and near-infrared reflection (750-1000 nm) related to berry structure showing <10-15% variation indicating consistent tissue architecture. ||Colorimetric quantification of even coloration uses: CIE L*a*b* color space measurements at multiple positions showing L* (lightness) 24-38 with standard deviation <2.5-4.0 units indicating consistent darkness, a* (red-green coordinate) 22-48 with SD <3-5 units demonstrating uniform redness, b* (yellow-blue coordinate) -8 to +18 with SD <2.5-4.0 units showing consistent hue modulation, and derived parameters including chroma (C* = √(a*² + b*²)) 25-52 with <8-12% CV and hue angle (h° = arctan(b*/a*)) cultivar-specific (0-15° pure red, 340-355° purple-red) with <5-8° variation. ||Environmental influences on even coloration achievement inclu uniform cluster microclimate from optimal canopy architecture produces even coloration in 8-10 days with minimal spatial variation, heterogeneous light distribution creates 25-40% color variation potentially preventing even coloration, temperature uniformity across berry surface (minimizing sun-exposed versus shaded temperature differentials to <5-8°C) promotes even anthocyanin synthesis, while excessive temperature gradients >10-15°C create synthesis rate differences maintaining color variation. ||Cultivar variation in even coloration characteristics shows: varieties with naturally uniform development (Pinot Noir, Merlot) achieve even coloration showing <15% anthocyanin CV and <10% L* CV, moderately uniform cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah) display 15-20% anthocyanin CV and 10-15% L* CV, while inherently variable cultivars (Sangiovese, Nebbiolo) may show 20-30% residual variation even at apparent maturity reflecting genetic differences in developmental coordination. ||Within-berry color distribution patterns at even coloration reveal: equatorial regions often show 100% reference anthocyanin levels, stylar (blossom) end displays 90-100% of equatorial values, pedicel (stem) end shows 80-95% of equatorial levels representing slight gradient that narrows substantially from progressive development gradients where pedicel zones showed only 40-60% of peak values, and sun-exposed versus shaded hemisphere differences reduce to <10-18% compared to 40-80% differences during color break. ||Monitoring even coloration involves: visual assessment comparing berry appearance to color standard photographs rating evenness on 1-5 scale (1 = highly uneven patches, 5 = perfectly uniform), instrumental colorimetry measuring L*a*b* at standardized positions (typically N, S, E, W equator points plus poles) calculating spatial CV, image analysis of berry photographs using color segmentation determining percentage of berry surface within target color range (typically >92-96% for even coloration), and anthocyanin extraction from berry surface sections (usually 6-8 sections) revealing quantitative spatial variation. ||Quality implications of even coloration inclu even color indicates complete ripening across entire berry enabling predictable and efficient extraction during winemaking, uneven coloration suggests maturity heterogeneity potentially requiring extended maceration or enzymatic treatment to achieve adequate extraction from less pigmented zones, color evenness correlates with phenolic maturity uniformity (r² = 0.70-0.85) suggesting berries with even anthocyanin distribution also show consistent tannin and other phenolic development, and visual evenness assessment provides rapid quality screening enabling harvest lot selection based on apparent maturity uniformity. ||Physiological basis of even coloration achievement includes: synchronized berry development across all surface regions through coordinated hormonal signaling, adequate carbon supply enabling anthocyanin synthesis in all zones without source limitation favoring particular regions, and completion of developmental programs throughout berry surface rather than spatial progression from leading to lagging zones. ||Viticultural factors affecting evenness inclu canopy management creating uniform cluster light exposure (leaf removal timing, shoot positioning, cluster thinning) improves evenness 30-50%, irrigation management maintaining consistent vine water status avoids stress-induced spatial variation in anthocyanin synthesis, crop load optimization ensures adequate resource availability for uniform berry development across all fruit, and disease prevention avoids localized metabolic disruption from pathogen infection that creates color heterogeneity. ||Temporal stability of even coloration shows: once achieved, even coloration typically persists 2-4 weeks under favorable conditions enabling flexible harvest timing, environmental stresses (heat waves, water deficit, disease pressure) can disrupt evenness within days through spatially variable stress responses requiring careful monitoring, and cultivar variation exists with stable varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah) maintaining evenness 3-5 weeks while unstable types (Pinot Noir in warm climates) may lose uniformity within 1-2 weeks through differential senescence or degradation. ||Integration with other maturity parameters: even coloration typically achieved when berry sugar uniformity also improves (within-berry Brix CV declining from 15-25% to <8-12%), firmness becomes consistent across berry surface, and flavor/aroma development shows reduced spatial variation all indicating coordinated ripening completion approaching optimal harvest.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 235-237 berry color uniformity || Rolle L, Torchio F, Giacosa S, Gerbi V (2009) Modifications of mechanical characteristics and phenolic composition in berry skins and seeds of Mondeuse winegrapes throughout the on-vine drying process Amer J Enol Vitic 60:418-425 spatial color distribution || Guidoni S, Ferrandino A, Novello V (2008) Effects of seasonal and agronomical practices on skin anthocyanin profile of Nebbiolo grapes Amer J Enol Vitic 59:22-29 cultivar variation in color evenness."
},

  "Complete_Skin_Pigmentation": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Skin_Pigmentation is a Uniform_Color_Development characterized by anthocyanin concentrations at cultivar-specific maxima throughout the epidermal and hypodermal cell layers.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum skin anthocyanin accumulation | final epidermal pigmentation | complete anthocyanin deposition | full pigment development |+ maximale Haut-Anthocyan-Akkumulation | finale epidermale Pigmentierung | vollständige Anthocyan-Ablagerung | volle Pigment-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barolo Nebbiolo vineyard in Piedmont, complete skin pigmentation was achieved in early October Year N+1 (BBCH 87, 14 days post-color break) when skin anthocyanins reached 1180 mg/kg (malvidin-3-glucoside 625 mg/kg, delphinidin-3-glucoside 155 mg/kg, cyanidin-3-glucoside 195 mg/kg, acylated forms 28%), CIE L* 34.2, berry sugar 23.8° Brix, titratable acidity 6.8 g/L, seed tannins brown indicating phenolic maturity, under typical Langhe autumn conditions (daily high 18-22°C, night 8-12°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.2 MPa) with southeastern hillside exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Skin_Pigmentation is distinguished from Maximum_Color_Intensity by representing total anthocyanin accumulation rather than visual intensity per se, from Even_Berry_Coloration by focusing on pigment quantity rather than spatial distribution, and from Color_Development_Completion by emphasizing final state rather than process termination. ||Final levels: high cultivars 1800-3500 mg/kg, moderate 900-1800 mg/kg, lower 600-1400 mg/kg. ||Timing: typically 10-16 days post-color break. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C. ||Moderate deficit enhances 25-45%. ||Complete_Skin_Pigmentation determines wine color potential and phenolic composition critical for quality and style. || This state is achieved during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87), typically 10-16 days post-color break depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by skin anthocyanin concentrations reaching 500-3000 mg/kg fresh weight cultivar-dependent (Pinot Noir 600-1500 mg/kg, Merlot 800-1800 mg/kg, Cabernet Sauvignon 900-2000 mg/kg, Syrah 1200-2400 mg/kg, Petit Verdot 1500-3000 mg/kg) representing 95-100% of maximum achievable levels under given environmental and management conditions. ||Cellular and tissue distribution of complete pigmentation shows: epidermal cell layer (outermost 1-2 cell layers) contains highest anthocyanin concentrations 18-35 mM vacuolar concentration representing localized levels 2500-4500 mg/kg tissue equivalent, sub-epidermal layers (2-4 cells deep) show 60-85% of epidermal concentrations contributing 400-800 mg/kg to total skin anthocyanins, deeper hypodermal cells (if pigmented, cultivar-dependent) contain 30-60% of epidermal levels adding 200-500 mg/kg in extensively pigmented varieties, and spatial integration across 3-6 pigmented cell layers creates total skin anthocyanin pool determining extractability during winemaking and wine color potential. ||Anthocyanin composition at complete pigmentation establishes final profile: malvidin-3-glucoside dominates at 50-72% of total (absolute 300-2000 mg/kg cultivar-dependent), delphinidin-3-glucoside contributes 4-20% (20-400 mg/kg, higher in Syrah 12-18%, Petit Verdot 14-22%), cyanidin-3-glucoside ranges 6-22% (30-350 mg/kg, elevated in Pinot Noir 15-25%), peonidin and petunidin derivatives account for 5-15% each (25-300 mg/kg combined), and acylated forms (acetylated and coumaroylated anthocyanins) reach 18-32% of total (100-800 mg/kg) providing enhanced color stability through intramolecular copigmentation and resistance to pH-induced color changes. ||Biosynthetic status at complete pigmentation shows: anthocyanin biosynthetic gene expression declining from peak levels as accumulation approaches maximum with UFGT transcripts reducing to 60-80% of peak (still 80-130 fold above green berry baseline), enzyme activities similarly declining with UFGT at 60-75% maximum (20-35 units/kg) maintaining moderate synthesis balancing degradation, and regulatory factors (VvMYBA1/A2) showing 50-70% of peak expression indicating transition from active accumulation to maintenance phase. ||Vacuolar sequestration at complete pigmentation involves: maximum anthocyanin concentrations in cell vacuoles 15-35 mM approaching or exceeding solubility limits in some cells, vacuolar pH maintained at 2.8-3.5 through continued V-ATPase activity ensuring flavylium cation stability and color expression, formation of anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions (AVIs) in cultivars exhibiting this trait (Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot) creating highly concentrated pigment domains >50 mM local concentration, and copigmentation with flavonols (100-250 mg/kg skin) and hydroxycinnamic acids (50-150 mg/kg) enhancing color intensity 35-55% beyond that expected from anthocyanin concentration alone through molecular stacking and bathochromic shifts. ||Environmental factors determining final pigmentation levels inclu temperature history during color development with optimal 22-28°C supporting maximum accumulation (1200-2500 mg/kg in high-anthocyanin cultivars), cool conditions 18-23°C potentially enhancing final levels 15-30% through improved stability despite slower synthesis, heat exposure >32°C reducing final pigmentation 40-70% through synthesis inhibition and degradation, and cumulative heat stress effects where multiple heat episodes create progressive reduction in achievable maximum. ||Light exposure effects show: UV-B radiation during veraison enhances final pigmentation 35-60% through sustained gene induction, optimal visible light exposure produces 25-45% higher final anthocyanins compared to shaded fruit, excessive direct sun combined with heat can reduce final levels 20-40% through heat stress overriding light benefits, and cluster position creating systematic variation with southwestern exposure (northern hemisphere) showing 30-50% higher final pigmentation than northeastern positions. ||Water deficit impacts on complete pigmentation demonstrate: moderate sustained deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa throughout veraison) enhances final pigmentation 25-45% through elevated ABA signaling and berry concentration, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) reduces final levels 30-60% through metabolic limitation despite high ABA, timing matters with pre-veraison deficit producing better results than deficit imposed during active accumulation, and excess water reduces final pigmentation 30-50% through berry dilution and suppressed ABA-responsive gene expression. ||Nutritional influences inclu moderate nitrogen limitation during ripening can enhance anthocyanin accumulation 15-30% through reduced vegetative competition and potential stress signaling, excessive nitrogen reduces pigmentation through vigorous vegetative growth creating shading and sink competition, potassium sufficiency appears important with deficiency potentially reducing final anthocyanins 20-35% through pH regulation effects or membrane transport impairment, and general nutrient balance supports optimal accumulation while severe deficiencies compromise biosynthetic capacity. ||Cultivar genetic variation determines: high-anthocyanin varieties (Petit Verdot, Tannat, Alicante Bouschet) achieve 1800-3500 mg/kg through high biosynthetic gene expression and extended accumulation duration, moderate cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah, Merlot) reach 900-1800 mg/kg with balanced synthesis rates and duration, while lower-anthocyanin types (Pinot Noir, Grenache, Sangiovese) attain 600-1400 mg/kg through lower synthesis capacity or shorter accumulation period reflecting genetic differences in VvMYBA regulation and pathway enzyme expression. ||Complete pigmentation timing relative to other maturity parameters: typically achieved when berry sugar reaches 20-26° Brix (cultivar and style dependent), coincides with 75-90% of total berry softening creating firmness 1.0-2.0 N, occurs during late acid decline with titratable acidity 4.5-7.5 g/L approaching harvest targets, and parallels seed maturation (brown color, lignified testa) and flavor/aroma development indicating integrated ripening completion. ||Wine quality implications inclu final skin anthocyanin levels strongly predict wine color intensity with correlation r² = 0.88-0.96, anthocyanin composition particularly acylated derivative proportions influences color stability and aging potential, extraction efficiency during maceration depends on total anthocyanin pool with higher skin levels enabling shorter extraction times or lower temperatures, and spatial uniformity of complete pigmentation affects extraction consistency with uniform berries producing more predictable wine color than heterogeneous fruit. ||Temporal stability of complete pigmentation varies: under favorable conditions (moderate temperatures 18-25°C, no water stress) complete pigmentation persists 3-5 weeks enabling flexible harvest timing, environmental stresses can trigger degradation within 1-2 weeks through oxidative damage, enzyme activation, or cellular disruption, and cultivar differences exist with stable varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah) maintaining levels while unstable types (Pinot Noir in warm climates) may lose 20-40% anthocyanins through post-ripening degradation. ||Monitoring complete pigmentation involves: spectrophotometric analysis of skin extracts measuring total anthocyanins and composition through HPLC, portable spectrophotometers providing field measurements of skin color correlating with anthocyanin levels, visual assessment comparing berry color to cultivar-specific standards indicating typical complete pigmentation, and integration with sugar, acid, and sensory evaluation ensuring anthocyanin accumulation synchronized with overall maturity for optimal harvest timing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 235-238 anthocyanin accumulation and wine quality || Castellarin SD, Matthews MA, Di Gaspero G, Gambetta GA (2007) Water deficits accelerate ripening and induce changes in gene expression regulating flavonoid biosynthesis in grape berries Planta 227:101-112 environmental regulation of final levels || Mattivi F, Guzzon R, Vrhovsek U, Stefanini M, Velasco R (2006) Metabolite profiling of grape:grape and wine standardization Anal Chim Acta 563:184-191 anthocyanin composition at maturity."
},

  "Color_Distribution_Uniformity": {
  "definition": "A Color_Distribution_Uniformity is a Uniform_Color_Development consisting of pigmentation consistency across berries within clusters, among clusters on the vine, and throughout the vineyard block.",
  "alternative_term": "spatial color consistency | homogeneous pigmentation distribution | synchronized color development | uniform berry coloring pattern |+ räumliche Farb-Konsistenz | homogene Pigmentierungs-Verteilung | synchronisierte Farb-Entwicklung | uniformes Beeren-Färbungs-Muster",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, color distribution uniformity was assessed across 120 vines in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 86) showing within-berry CV 16%, within-cluster CV 24%, within-vine CV 28%, within-block CV 32%, mean skin anthocyanins 1420 mg/kg (SD ±455 mg/kg), berry sugar 24.2° Brix (SD ±1.8°), enabling single-pass mechanical harvest of uniformly ripe fruit under optimal management (uniform drip irrigation, standardized canopy, consistent crop load 8 kg/vine) on well-drained hillside benchland.",
  "editor_note": "Color_Distribution_Uniformity is distinguished from Uniform_Color_Development by representing population-level variation rather than individual berry uniformity, from Even_Berry_Coloration by focusing on spatial distribution across multiple scales rather than single-berry consistency, and from Complete_Color_Change by emphasizing variation rather than completion. ||Uniformity metrics: within-berry CV <15-20%, within-cluster <20-30%, within-vine <25-35%, within-block <30-40%. ||High uniformity enables efficient harvest and consistent wine quality. ||Low uniformity requires selective harvest or acceptance of compositional variation. || This quality emerges during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87) when developmental heterogeneity diminishes through completion of ripening processes across the population, and is quantified by measuring color variation at multiple spatial scales: within-berry color uniformity (coefficient of variation <15-20% for anthocyanins across berry surface positions), within-cluster uniformity (CV <20-30% for berry-to-berry anthocyanin variation, typically 30-60 berries per cluster sample), within-vine uniformity (CV <25-35% across clusters from different canopy positions), and within-block uniformity (CV <30-40% across vines throughout vineyard block) representing progression from initial veraison heterogeneity showing 50-80% CVs at all scales. ||Achievement of distribution uniformity requires: synchronized berry development across all spatial scales through consistent environmental conditions, adequate resource availability enabling all fruit to complete ripening without limitation-induced developmental arrest, uniform canopy architecture providing similar light and temperature exposure to all clusters minimizing microclimate-induced variation, and completion of ripening programs throughout the population rather than spatial progression from leading to lagging zones. ||Within-cluster color uniformity reflects: developmental synchrony among berries originating from flowers at different flowering times (early versus late anthesis creating initial 5-7 day developmental span), mitigation of initial asynchrony through extended ripening period allowing lagging berries to achieve similar endpoints as leading fruit, and cluster architecture effects with exposed shoulder berries often leading tips by 2-4 days but uniformity improving as both zones approach complete pigmentation. ||Within-vine uniformity demonstrates: canopy position effects with sun-exposed exterior clusters typically 3-5 days ahead of shaded interior positions during early veraison, but gap narrowing to 1-2 days difference by late veraison as slower clusters continue development while early clusters plateau, shoot vigor effects where vigorous shoots with large clusters may lag behind moderate shoots by 2-3 days creating spatial variation, and vertical position influences with upper canopy sometimes showing 1-2 day advancement over lower positions through better light exposure. ||Vineyard-scale uniformity reveals: terroir effects from soil heterogeneity, topography, or microclimate creating systematic variation with well-drained slopes often 4-7 days ahead of valley floor or heavy soils, vine age influences with young vines (<5 years) and very old vines (>40 years) sometimes showing different ripening timing than prime-age vines (10-30 years), rootstock effects on ripening timing creating 2-4 day variation when mixed rootstocks exist within blocks, and management history including pruning severity, crop load, irrigation, and disease pressure creating spatial patterns of advancement or delay. ||Monitoring color distribution uniformity involves: stratified random sampling across vineyard blocks collecting berry samples from multiple vines, cluster positions, and berry locations within clusters enabling statistical analysis of variation, image analysis of cluster or vine photographs using color segmentation algorithms calculating percentages of fruit at target color stages, portable spectrophotometers or colorimeters measuring berry color at systematic sampling points across vineyard creating spatial variation maps, and visual assessment using trained observers rating uniformity on standard scales (1-10) providing rapid semi-quantitative evaluation. ||Environmental factors affecting distribution uniformity inclu weather stability during veraison with consistent moderate temperatures (20-26°C) and no extreme events promoting uniform development, while dramatic weather shifts (heat waves, cold snaps, heavy rain) create developmental disruption affecting berries differentially based on their developmental stage and location, irrigation uniformity with consistent water distribution across vineyard enabling similar vine water status and berry development versus heterogeneous irrigation creating spatial variation in ripening timing and intensity, and disease pressure with localized infections (Botrytis, powdery mildew) disrupting normal development in affected zones creating color variation even in otherwise uniform blocks. ||Viticultural practices influencing uniformity inclu shoot thinning and cluster thinning performed uniformly across vineyard promotes synchronized development by standardizing crop load and canopy density, selective thinning removing lagging clusters can enhance apparent uniformity by eliminating developmental outliers though reducing total yield, canopy management (hedging, leaf removal, shoot positioning) applied consistently optimizes light distribution improving within-vine and block-scale uniformity, and irrigation management maintaining consistent vine water status across spatial scales prevents drought or excess water from creating localized ripening heterogeneity. ||Harvest implications of color distribution uniformity inclu high uniformity (vineyard-scale CV <25-30%) enables single-pass harvest at optimal maturity capturing most fruit at peak quality, moderate uniformity (CV 30-45%) may justify selective harvest removing most uniform ripe clusters first followed by second pass for remaining fruit, low uniformity (CV >45%) necessitates difficult decisions between accepting compositional variation in single harvest or conducting multiple selective harvests increasing labor costs and complexity, and integration with sugar and acid uniformity determines overall harvest strategy since color uniformity alone may not indicate complete maturity synchrony. ||Wine quality implications inclu high color uniformity predicts consistent wine quality with low bottle-to-bottle variation (important for premium wines), moderate uniformity produces acceptable quality with some vintage variation requiring skillful blending or lot separation, poor uniformity creates quality challenges with unripe and overripe fruit components potentially requiring extensive sorting and selective processing, and uniformity correlates with other quality parameters (phenolic maturity, flavor development) suggesting color distribution uniformity serves as integrated maturity indicator. ||Temporal dynamics of uniformity show: color variation typically highest at veraison onset (CV 60-80% across berries), declining progressively during veraison as lagging berries catch up (CV reducing 5-10% per week), achieving minimum variation at complete color development (CV 20-35% depending on inherent block heterogeneity), and potentially increasing post-ripening through differential senescence or degradation rates creating renewed heterogeneity if harvest delayed beyond optimal window. ||Cultivar variation in uniformity characteristics: varieties with naturally synchronous development (Pinot Noir, Chardonnay) achieve high uniformity (CV <25%) in favorable conditions, moderately synchronous cultivars (Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) show good uniformity (CV 25-35%) with proper management, while inherently asynchronous varieties (Zinfandel, Carignan) display persistent variation (CV >35-40%) even under optimal conditions requiring acceptance of heterogeneity or selective harvest approaches. ||Economic considerations of uniformity: high uniformity enables efficient single-pass machine harvest reducing labor costs substantially (savings 40-60% versus hand harvest), allows streamlined processing without extensive sorting reducing winery labor and equipment needs, and produces consistent wine reducing blending complexity and inventory management challenges, while low uniformity necessitates expensive selective hand harvest, extensive sorting and berry selection infrastructure, and complex lot management potentially justified only for premium wines commanding sufficient price premiums.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 237-238, 266-268 ripening heterogeneity and harvest || Bramley RGV, Hamilton RP (2004) Understanding variability in winegrape production systems Australian J Grape Wine Res 10:32-45 spatial variation in vineyards || Kontoudakis N, Esteruelas M, Fort F, Canals JM, Zamora F (2011) Use of unripe grapes harvested during cluster thinning as a method for reducing alcohol content and pH of wine Aust J Grape Wine Res 17:230-238 maturity variation effects."
},

  "Complete_Color_Change": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Color_Change is a Veraison characterized by anthocyanin accumulation at maximum cultivar-specific levels, spatial coverage above 95%, and stabilized color intensity at final values.",
  "alternative_term": "final color development achievement | maximum pigmentation attainment | color maturation completion | terminal anthocyanin accumulation |+ finale Farb-Entwicklungs-Erreichung | maximale Pigmentierungs-Erlangung | Farb-Reifungs-Vollendung | terminale Anthocyan-Akkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Pomerol Merlot vineyard, complete color change was documented 14 days post-color break in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 86) when skin anthocyanins plateaued at 1385 mg/kg (±60 mg/kg over subsequent 10 days), CIE L* stabilized at 30.2 (±1.8 over 2 weeks), berry Brix 24.6°, titratable acidity 5.4 g/L, firmness 1.5 N, seed tannins brown, under favorable Bordeaux autumn conditions (daily high 22-25°C, night 12-15°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.15 MPa maintained through veraison) with eastern canopy exposure providing morning sun.",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Color_Change is distinguished from Complete_Skin_Pigmentation by representing the overall developmental endpoint rather than just pigment quantity, from Color_Development_Completion by focusing on achievement rather than process termination, and from earlier color phases by exhibiting plateau rather than continued progression. ||Anthocyanin plateau: <5-10% increase over 1-2 weeks post-completion. ||Timing: fast cultivars 10-13 days post-break, moderate 12-16 days, late 15-20 days. ||Final levels: 600-3000 mg/kg cultivar-dependent. ||Complete_Color_Change indicates color development sufficient for harvest consideration with optimal timing determined by integration with chemical and phenolic maturity. || This terminal phase occurs during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87), typically 12-18 days post-color break depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by skin anthocyanin concentrations plateauing at 600-3000 mg/kg fresh weight cultivar-dependent with <5-10% further increase over subsequent 1-2 weeks, CIE colorimetric values stabilizing with L* (lightness) variation <2-3 units week-to-week, and visual appearance showing fully developed color with <5% green remnants across berry surface. ||Achievement of complete color change involves: biosynthetic gene expression declining from peak levels as accumulation approaches maximum with UFGT and other pathway genes reducing to 50-70% of peak expression (still 60-100 fold above green berry baseline), enzyme activities similarly declining with UFGT at 50-65% maximum (18-30 units/kg) balancing synthesis and degradation at equilibrium, regulatory transcription factors (VvMYBA1/A2) showing 40-60% of peak expression indicating transition from active accumulation to maintenance phase, and hormonal status shifting with ABA declining from veraison peak 2000-3500 ng/g to plateau 1200-2200 ng/g maintaining ripening program without driving continued intense developmental changes. ||Anthocyanin composition at complete change establishes final cultivar-specific profile: malvidin-3-glucoside comprises 48-72% of total (absolute 350-2000 mg/kg), delphinidin-3-glucoside contributes 4-22% (25-450 mg/kg), cyanidin-3-glucoside ranges 6-25% (40-400 mg/kg), peonidin and petunidin derivatives account for 5-15% each (30-350 mg/kg combined), acylated anthocyanins reach 18-35% (120-900 mg/kg) providing enhanced stability, and these proportions remain relatively constant during subsequent ripening reflecting completion of synthetic programming. ||Cellular state at complete color change shows: vacuolar anthocyanin concentrations in epidermal cells reaching 18-35 mM representing maximum sequestration capacity, vacuolar pH stabilized at 2.8-3.4 through sustained V-ATPase activity ensuring color stability, anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions fully formed in cultivars exhibiting this trait (Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot) with localized concentrations >60 mM, and copigmentation with flavonols (120-280 mg/kg) and hydroxycinnamic acids (60-180 mg/kg) maximizing color intensity enhancement 40-60% beyond anthocyanin concentration alone. ||Optical characteristics at complete change inclu reflectance spectra showing stable profiles with anthocyanin absorbance maximum 520-540 nm at optical density 1.8-3.5 units cultivar-dependent, CIE L* values 22-38 with minimal week-to-week variation (<2-3 units) indicating stable darkness, chroma (C*) 28-55 representing saturated color, hue angle 0-15° for pure red cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot) or 340-355° for purple-red types (Syrah, Petit Verdot) with <5-8° variation, and these parameters remaining stable ±10% over 2-4 weeks under favorable conditions. ||Environmental influences on complete change achievement inclu cumulative heat during veraison with optimal 450-650 growing degree days (base 10°C) from color break to complete change in most cultivars, temperature optima 22-28°C supporting maximum accumulation reaching highest final levels, cool conditions 18-23°C potentially enhancing final levels 12-25% through improved stability despite slower progression, heat stress >32°C reducing final levels 40-70% through synthesis inhibition and degradation preventing complete change achievement, and light exposure with UV-B and moderate visible light enhancing final levels 30-55% while excessive heat-producing radiation reduces completeness. ||Water relations effects show: moderate sustained deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) through veraison enhances complete change producing 25-40% higher final anthocyanins, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) impairs completion reducing final levels 35-65%, excess water delays and reduces complete change 25-45% through dilution and suppressed biosynthesis, and timing with pre-veraison deficit more beneficial than deficit imposed during active color development. ||Cultivar variation in complete change characteristics reflects: early-completing varieties (Pinot Noir, Gamay) achieve complete change 10-13 days post-color break, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Cabernet Sauvignon) complete 12-16 days post-break, while late-completing varieties (Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre, Tannat) require 15-20 days, and final anthocyanin levels vary genetically from 600-1500 mg/kg in lower-accumulating types to 1500-3500 mg/kg in high-anthocyanin cultivars. ||Coordination with other ripening parameters at complete change: berry sugar typically 20-28° Brix (cultivar and style dependent) with accumulation rates declining from peak 1.5-3.5% per week to <0.5-1.0% per week, acid levels approaching harvest targets with titratable acidity 4.0-7.5 g/L and pH 3.2-3.8 as malate degradation slows substantially, berry firmness stabilized at 1.0-2.2 N representing 65-80% total softening completed, and seed maturation achieved with brown color, lignified testa, and extractable tannins indicating phenolic maturity synchronized with color completion. ||Molecular markers of complete change inclu anthocyanin biosynthetic gene transcripts declining to sustained moderate levels (40-70% of peak) providing maintenance expression, protein levels of biosynthetic enzymes similarly reduced through protein turnover exceeding synthesis, continued moderate ABA levels maintaining ripening program consolidation, and beginning elevation of senescence-associated genes in some cultivars indicating transition from active ripening to post-ripening phases. ||Temporal stability of complete color change varies: under favorable conditions (moderate temperatures 18-25°C, no environmental extremes) complete change persists 3-5 weeks enabling flexible harvest timing, heat stress can trigger anthocyanin degradation reducing levels 15-35% within 1-2 weeks through oxidative damage and enzyme activity, water stress or excess can destabilize color causing 10-25% losses, and cultivar differences with stable varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah, Sangiovese) maintaining color 4-6 weeks while unstable types (Pinot Noir in warm climates, Grenache) may lose 20-40% through post-ripening degradation or senescence. ||Quality implications of complete color change inclu achievement indicates color development sufficient for harvest consideration with further hang time affecting other parameters (sugar, flavor, phenolics) more than color, final anthocyanin levels strongly predict wine color intensity and phenolic content affecting wine style and aging potential, color composition particularly acylated derivative proportions influences color stability during winemaking and aging, and timing of complete change relative to chemical and phenolic maturity determines optimal harvest window balancing color with other quality attributes. ||Monitoring complete change involves: visual assessment comparing berry color to cultivar-specific references indicating typical complete development, spectrophotometric measurement of skin anthocyanins confirming plateau in accumulation (<5-10% increase over 1-2 weeks), colorimetric tracking of L*a*b* values showing stabilization, and integration with sugar, acid, pH, and sensory evaluation ensuring color completion synchronized with overall maturity for optimal harvest timing. ||Viticultural management at complete change: irrigation often reduced or terminated recognizing reduced berry growth and water demand, canopy management adjusted to maintain cluster protection from excessive sun preventing color degradation while ensuring adequate exposure for continued ripening, disease prevention intensified as fully colored soft berries show maximum vulnerability to Botrytis and other pathogens, and harvest timing decisions integrate color completion with chemical maturity and wine style objectives balancing multiple quality parameters for optimal fruit composition.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 235-240 color development completion and harvest maturity || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Australian J Grape Wine Res 48:125-144 ripening completion || Kennedy JA, Matthews MA, Waterhouse AL (2002) Effect of maturity and vine water status on grape skin and wine flavonoids Amer J Enol Vitic 53:268-274 anthocyanin dynamics at maturity."
},

  "Maximum_Color_Intensity": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Color_Intensity is a Complete_Color_Change marked by peak visual pigmentation reflecting cultivar-specific anthocyanin concentration, copigmentation, and cellular architecture under specific environmental conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "peak color saturation | deepest pigmentation state | maximum chromatic intensity | optimal color darkness |+ Spitzen-Farb-Sättigung | tiefster Pigmentierungs-Zustand | maximale chromatische Intensität | optimale Farb-Dunkelheit",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Châteauneuf-du-Pape Grenache vineyard, maximum color intensity was measured 12 days post-color break in early September Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when CIE L* reached minimum 31.8, chroma peaked at 47.2, absorbance at 520 nm was 2.35 OD, skin anthocyanins 1150 mg/kg (malvidin-3-glucoside 655 mg/kg, acylated forms 31%), berry Brix 22.8°, firmness 1.4 N, under optimal southern Rhône conditions (daily high 28-31°C, night 15-18°C, high UV, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.25 MPa, galets stones reflecting light enhancing cluster exposure).",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Color_Intensity is distinguished from Complete_Skin_Pigmentation by representing peak visual intensity rather than total anthocyanin, from Final_Color_Expression by focusing on intensity maximum rather than stable endpoint, and from Color_Intensity_Increase by showing peak rather than progression. ||CIE L* minima: high-intensity 20-28, moderate 26-32, lower-intensity 30-36. ||Timing: typically 10-15 days post-color break. ||Copigmentation contributes 45-65% intensity enhancement. ||Temperature optimum 22-28°C, cool nights enhance. ||Maximum_Color_Intensity indicates optimal harvest window approach for color-driven wine styles. || This maximum occurs during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-87), typically 10-15 days post-color break, and is characterized by colorimetric measurements showing CIE L* (lightness) reaching cultivar-specific minima 20-36 (Petit Verdot, Tannat 20-26, Syrah 24-28, Cabernet Sauvignon 26-30, Merlot 28-32, Pinot Noir 30-36), chroma (C*) achieving maxima 30-58 representing peak saturation, and absorbance at 520 nm reaching 2.0-4.5 optical density units depending on cultivar and extraction method reflecting maximum light absorption by accumulated anthocyanins. ||Anthocyanin levels at maximum intensity range: high-intensity cultivars (Petit Verdot, Tannat, Alicante Bouschet) 1800-3500 mg/kg skin, moderate-high types (Syrah, Carignan, Touriga Nacional) 1200-2200 mg/kg, moderate cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot, Tempranillo) 900-1800 mg/kg, and lower-intensity varieties (Pinot Noir, Grenache, Sangiovese) 600-1400 mg/kg, with these concentrations representing 95-100% of achievable maximum under given conditions. ||Cellular and molecular basis of maximum intensity involves: epidermal and sub-epidermal cell vacuoles containing anthocyanins at peak concentrations 18-35 mM approaching solubility limits, vacuolar pH optimized at 2.8-3.3 maximizing flavylium cation proportion (colored form) versus carbinol pseudobase (colorless form), copigmentation at maximum efficiency with flavonol (150-300 mg/kg) and hydroxycinnamic acid (80-200 mg/kg) copigments creating 45-65% color enhancement beyond that expected from anthocyanin concentration alone through bathochromic shifts and hyperchromic effects, and anthocyanin vacuolar inclusion formation in cultivars exhibiting this trait creating localized super-concentrated pigment zones >70 mM contributing to exceptional intensity. ||Optical physics of maximum intensity includes: light absorption at anthocyanin λmax 520-540 nm reaching 85-95% of incident light in fully pigmented skin creating characteristic deep color, multiple scattering within multilayered pigmented epidermis and hypodermis amplifying color intensity through extended optical path length, internal reflection from berry flesh-skin interface concentrating light interaction with anthocyanin-containing cells enhancing color expression, and surface texture effects with smooth berry surfaces reflecting more light appearing slightly less intense than textured surfaces that diffuse reflection reducing specular component. ||Spectral characteristics at maximum intensity show: absorbance spectra displaying pronounced anthocyanin peak 520-540 nm with secondary peak 270-280 nm and characteristic three-peak pattern in visible range, reflectance spectra showing minimal green reflection (<8-12% at 500-600 nm) indicating complete chlorophyll degradation, strong red reflection (35-55% at 620-650 nm) creating characteristic red color, and purple-blue secondary reflection (20-40% at 400-450 nm) in delphinidin-rich cultivars contributing to purple hue notes. ||Environmental optimization for maximum intensity requires: temperature during color development ideally 22-28°C supporting maximum anthocyanin synthesis without heat degradation, cool night temperatures 12-16°C enhancing anthocyanin stability and copigmentation efficiency, UV-B radiation exposure providing 40-65% intensity enhancement through increased anthocyanin synthesis and potential copigment induction, moderate water deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) increasing intensity 30-50% through berry concentration and elevated ABA-driven biosynthesis, and optimal light exposure balancing synthesis induction with heat stress avoidance achieving 35-55% higher intensity than shaded fruit. ||Temporal dynamics of maximum intensity show: intensity increasing rapidly during progressive color development (days 3-10 post-color break) with 8-15% increase per day in L* darkening and chroma saturation, reaching peak during late progressive development (days 10-15), maintaining maximum for 1-3 weeks under favorable conditions (stable temperatures 18-25°C, no environmental extremes), and potentially declining post-peak through anthocyanin degradation (oxidative damage, enzymatic breakdown), copigment losses, or cellular disruption reducing intensity 10-30% if harvest delayed beyond optimal window. ||Cultivar genetic variation determines: maximum achievable intensity with high-intensity varieties genetically programmed for deep color through elevated anthocyanin biosynthetic gene expression, extended accumulation duration, and enhanced copigmentation, while lower-intensity cultivars show genetic limitations in maximum UFGT expression, shorter accumulation periods, or reduced copigment synthesis restricting intensity potential regardless of environmental optimization. ||Anthocyanin composition effects on intensity inclu malvidin-based anthocyanins producing moderate intensity with characteristic purple-red hue, delphinidin derivatives creating more intense purple-blue coloration (important in Syrah, Petit Verdot), cyanidin-based pigments generating bright red but potentially lower absolute intensity, and acylated anthocyanins (20-35% of total at maximum) providing enhanced intensity through improved stability and modified spectral properties creating bathochromic shift toward deeper color. ||Viticultural practices affecting maximum intensity inclu crop load optimization with moderate yields (6-10 kg/vine depending on variety) producing 25-40% higher intensity than overcropped vines (>12-15 kg/vine) through improved resource allocation and berry concentration, canopy management creating optimal cluster light exposure enhancing intensity 30-50% through increased synthesis without heat stress, irrigation management imposing moderate sustained deficit enhancing intensity 30-55% compared to well-watered vines, timing of cultural practices particularly leaf removal during pre-veraison versus early veraison affecting final intensity through UV induction and temperature modulation, and disease prevention maintaining berry health enabling maximum biosynthetic capacity unimpaired by pathogen-induced metabolic disruption. ||Quality implications of maximum intensity inclu intensity strongly predicts wine color density with correlation r² = 0.90-0.97 between berry skin color and wine 520 nm absorbance, maximum intensity berries enable shorter maceration times or lower temperatures reducing extraction of harsh tannins while achieving adequate color, intensity uniformity across berries and clusters indicates ripening synchrony and predicts wine color consistency, and timing of maximum intensity relative to chemical and phenolic maturity determines optimal harvest window with ideal scenario showing intensity maximum coinciding with target sugar, acid, and tannin development. ||Measurement of maximum intensity involves: instrumental colorimetry using CIE L*a*b* color space providing objective quantification (L* minima, C* maxima indicating peak intensity), spectrophotometry measuring absorbance at 520 nm after standardized extraction correlating with visual intensity, portable instruments enabling field measurement guiding harvest decisions, image analysis of berry photographs calculating color metrics across populations revealing intensity distribution, and visual assessment by trained evaluators comparing berries to cultivar-specific color standards rating intensity on standard scales. ||Post-maximum intensity management includes: monitoring intensity stability through regular colorimetric or visual assessment detecting degradation indicating harvest urgency, environmental protection from heat waves through irrigation or canopy management maintaining intensity, disease prevention as colored soft berries show maximum Botrytis vulnerability potentially compromising intensity through infection-induced cellular disruption, and harvest timing optimization balancing intensity maintenance with other maturity parameters achieving desired wine style and quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 235-238 color intensity and quality || Boulton R (2001) The copigmentation of anthocyanins and its role in the color of red wine a critical review Amer J Enol Vitic 52:67-87 copigmentation effects on intensity || Guidoni S, Ferrandino A, Novello V (2008) Effects of seasonal and agronomical practices on skin anthocyanin profile of Nebbiolo grapes Amer J Enol Vitic 59:22-29 maximum intensity achievement."
},

  "Final_Color_Expression": {
  "definition": "A Final_Color_Expression is a Complete_Color_Change characterized by stable cultivar-specific color resulting from established anthocyanin composition, copigmentation, and cellular architecture.",
  "alternative_term": "stable varietal color | characteristic cultivar pigmentation | definitive berry color | terminal color phenotype |+ stabile Sorten-Farbe | charakteristische Kultivar-Pigmentierung | definitive Beeren-Farbe | terminaler Farb-Phänotyp",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Brunello di Montalcino Sangiovese vineyard, final color expression was established 16 days post-color break in early October Year N+1 (BBCH 87) showing CIE L* 33.5 (±1.2 over 3 weeks), hue angle 6.8° (±2.1° variation) indicating characteristic Sangiovese red-orange color, chroma 42.8, skin anthocyanins 1085 mg/kg (malvidin-3-glucoside 58%, cyanidin-3-glucoside 19%, delphinidin-3-glucoside 7%), berry Brix 24.3°, titratable acidity 6.4 g/L, under typical Tuscan autumn conditions (daily high 21-24°C, night 10-13°C, moderate deficit) with southern hillside exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Final_Color_Expression is distinguished from Maximum_Color_Intensity by representing stable characteristic color rather than peak intensity, from Complete_Color_Change by emphasizing cultivar-specific expression rather than completion per se, and from Color_Development_Completion by focusing on phenotypic endpoint rather than process termination. ||Stability criterion: colorimetric values ±8-12% over 2-4 weeks. ||Timing: typically 12-18 days post-color break. ||Persistence: stable cultivars 3-6 weeks, moderate 2-4 weeks, unstable 1-2 weeks. ||Final_Color_Expression provides definitive quality marker for harvest timing and wine style prediction. || This final expression emerges during late veraison to ripening (BBCH 85-89), typically 12-18 days post-color break, and is characterized by stable colorimetric values maintained ±8-12% over 2-4 weeks: CIE L* (lightness) stabilizing at cultivar-typical values (Petit Verdot 22-26, Syrah 25-29, Cabernet Sauvignon 27-31, Merlot 29-33, Pinot Noir 32-37), hue angle defining cultivar color signature (pure reds 0-12°, red-purple 345-0°, purple-red 335-345°), and chroma representing saturation level (28-56 depending on variety and conditions) creating the distinctive color profile enabling varietal recognition and quality assessment. ||Anthocyanin compositional basis of final expression includes: malvidin-3-glucoside proportion (48-72% total anthocyanins) establishing base color intensity and hue, delphinidin-3-glucoside content (4-22%) contributing purple-blue notes (elevated in Syrah 14-20%, Petit Verdot 16-24% creating characteristic purple color, lower in Merlot 6-10%, Pinot Noir 5-8% producing redder hues), cyanidin-3-glucoside levels (6-25%) adding bright red character (high in Pinot Noir 18-28% creating cherry-red color, moderate in others 8-15%), peonidin and petunidin derivatives (5-15% each) contributing to hue complexity and color stability, and acylated anthocyanins (20-35% of total) providing enhanced color persistence through intramolecular copigmentation and pH-buffering effects creating more stable final expression. ||Copigmentation phenomena stabilizing final expression involve: flavonol copigments (quercetin, kaempferol, myricetin glycosides 150-350 mg/kg skin) creating molecular stacking with anthocyanins producing 40-55% color intensity enhancement through bathochromic shifts (absorbance maximum moving from 520 nm to 530-540 nm) and hyperchromic effects (increased extinction coefficient), hydroxycinnamic acid copigments (caffeic, coumaric, ferulic acids 80-220 mg/kg) contributing additional 15-25% intensity enhancement, and self-association of anthocyanins at high concentrations (>15 mM vacuolar) creating aggregates with modified spectral properties intensifying color expression beyond dilute solution predictions. ||Cellular architecture effects on final expression inclu multilayered pigmented epidermis and hypodermis (3-6 cell layers deep cultivar-dependent) creating optical depth amplifying color intensity through extended light path length, vacuolar pH stabilization at 2.8-3.3 maintaining optimal flavylium cation to carbinol ratio (85-95% colored form), anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions in some cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot) concentrating pigments >60 mM locally creating regions of exceptional intensity contributing to overall color depth, and cell wall-bound phenolics providing additional light absorption and color background supporting anthocyanin-based primary coloration. ||Optical characteristics of final expression show: reflectance spectra displaying cultivar-specific profiles with characteristic red reflection peak 620-650 nm (intensity 30-55% depending on anthocyanin level), purple-blue secondary reflection 400-450 nm (15-45% in delphinidin-rich varieties, <10-20% in cyanidin-rich types), minimal green reflection <8-12% at 500-600 nm indicating complete chlorophyll elimination, and near-infrared reflection (750-1000 nm) 35-55% related to berry structure rather than pigmentation showing cultivar-specific patterns. ||Environmental effects on final expression inclu cumulative temperature during color development determining final anthocyanin levels and composition with optimal 22-28°C average producing deepest color and most typical varietal expression, extreme heat >32°C reducing final expression quality through anthocyanin degradation and compositional shifts potentially producing atypical pale or brownish colors, UV-B exposure enhancing expression through increased anthocyanin synthesis (30-50% higher levels) and potentially enhanced copigment accumulation intensifying final color, and water deficit history with moderate sustained stress producing more intense expression (30-45% deeper color) through berry concentration and elevated biosynthesis while severe deficit may compromise expression through metabolic limitation. ||Cultivar genetic variation creates distinctive final expressions: Cabernet Sauvignon shows deep purple-red (L* 27-31, hue 352-358°) from balanced delphinidin and malvidin, Merlot displays intense red-purple (L* 29-33, hue 355-2°) with moderate delphinidin creating slight purple note, Pinot Noir exhibits bright cherry-red (L* 32-37, hue 5-12°) from elevated cyanidin and lower delphinidin producing pure red without purple, Syrah shows deep purple-red (L* 25-29, hue 340-348°) from high delphinidin creating pronounced purple character, Grenache displays medium red (L* 33-38, hue 8-15°) from moderate anthocyanins with red-dominant hue, and Petit Verdot achieves very deep purple-black (L* 22-26, hue 335-345°) from extremely high anthocyanins with elevated delphinidin. ||Temporal stability of final expression varies: under favorable conditions (moderate temperatures 18-26°C, no environmental extremes) final expression persists 3-6 weeks enabling flexible harvest timing particularly in stable cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah, Sangiovese), moderate stability exists in varieties like Merlot and Tempranillo maintaining expression 2-4 weeks, while unstable cultivars (Pinot Noir in warm climates, Grenache) may deteriorate 1-2 weeks post-final expression through anthocyanin degradation, copigment losses, or cellular senescence creating color shifts toward brown-red or pink-red indicating over-ripeness. ||Wine quality prediction from final expression: berry color intensity strongly correlates with wine color density (r² = 0.88-0.95) enabling harvest quality forecasting, hue angle predicts wine color character with low angles producing red-dominant wines suitable for young consumption while purple hues indicate age-worthy wines with anthocyanin-tannin complexation potential, color uniformity across berries predicts wine color consistency and stability important for premium production, and comparison of actual versus expected final expression for cultivar and vintage reveals environmental or management effects requiring attention. ||Harvest timing optimization using final expression involves: visual assessment comparing berry color to cultivar-specific references indicating typical ripe expression suitable for harvest, colorimetric monitoring tracking stabilization of L*a*b* values indicating color development completion, integration with chemical maturity (sugar, acid, pH) and sensory evaluation (flavor, tannin) ensuring color expression synchronized with overall ripeness, and style considerations with some wines requiring harvest before complete final expression (lighter styles, rosé from red varieties) while others benefit from full expression development (premium reds, age-worthy wines). ||Viticultural factors affecting final expression achievement inclu canopy management optimizing cluster light exposure without excessive heat enabling full expression development, irrigation strategy imposing moderate deficit during veraison enhancing expression intensity 25-40%, crop load adjustment to 6-10 kg/vine depending on variety improving expression through adequate resource allocation, disease prevention maintaining berry health enabling complete biosynthetic programs, and harvest logistics planning based on expression stability characteristics with stable varieties allowing extended decision windows while unstable types requiring prompt harvest upon expression achievement. ||Marketing and quality designation implications: final expression provides visual quality assessment enabling premium lot selection, color intensity and typicity influence wine classification and pricing with deeper more characteristic expression commanding premiums, and varietal authenticity verification using color characteristics detecting potential mislabeling or blending issues important for appellation compliance and brand integrity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 236-240 cultivar color characteristics and harvest || González-Neves G, Gil G, Favre G, Ferrer M (2015) Influence of grape composition and winemaking on the anthocyanin composition of red wines J Food Comp Anal 41:124-132 anthocyanin composition effects on color || Mazzuca P, Ferranti P, Picariello G, Chianese L, Addeo F (2005) Mass spectrometry in the study of anthocyanins and their derivatives J Mass Spectrom 40:83-90 anthocyanin characterization."
},

  "Color_Development_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Color_Development_Completion is a Complete_Color_Change marked by termination of anthocyanin biosynthesis, vacuolar sequestration, copigmentation establishment, and chlorophyll degradation at asymptotic endpoints.",
  "alternative_term": "color development endpoint | pigmentation program termination | anthocyanin synthesis completion | chromatic maturation finalization |+ Farb-Entwicklungs-Endpunkt | Pigmentierungs-Programm-Terminierung | Anthocyan-Synthese-Vollendung | chromatische Reifungs-Finalisierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Russian River Valley Pinot Noir vineyard, color development completion was documented 15 days post-color break in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 86) when anthocyanin accumulation plateaued at 1265 mg/kg (±35 mg/kg over 2 weeks), UFGT expression declined to 45% of peak (still 65-fold above green berry), CIE L* stabilized at 33.8 (±2.1 over 3 weeks), berry Brix 23.2° with accumulation <0.6% per week, titratable acidity 6.5 g/L, firmness 1.2 N, under optimal cool coastal conditions (daily high 20-23°C, night 10-13°C, morning fog) enabling extended hang time for flavor development.",
  "editor_note": "Color_Development_Completion is distinguished from Complete_Color_Change by representing process termination rather than state achievement, from Final_Color_Expression by focusing on developmental endpoint rather than phenotypic stability, and from Color_Change_Onset by marking completion versus initiation. ||Completion markers: anthocyanin plateau <3-5% over 2 weeks, gene expression 30-50% of peak, colorimetric stability ±8-10% week-to-week. ||Timing: fast cultivars 12-16 days, moderate 15-19 days, late 18-24 days post-color break. ||Color_Development_Completion indicates transition from active ripening to stable mature state suitable for harvest timing optimization based on integrated maturity assessment. || This completion occurs during late veraison to early ripening (BBCH 85-89), typically 14-20 days post-color break depending on cultivar and conditions, and is characterized by cessation of net anthocyanin accumulation (<3-5% increase over 2 weeks indicating plateau versus 40-80% increases during active development), biosynthetic gene expression declining to basal maintenance levels (UFGT and pathway genes reducing to 30-50% of peak expression representing 40-80 fold above green berry baseline), enzyme activities similarly reduced (UFGT 30-45% maximum, 12-22 units/kg maintaining equilibrium between continued synthesis and degradation), and colorimetric stability with CIE L*a*b* values varying <8-10% week-to-week compared to >25-40% weekly changes during active development. ||Molecular markers of completion inclu anthocyanin biosynthetic genes (UFGT, DFR, LDOX, F3'H, F3'5'H, CHS, PAL) showing coordinated downregulation from peak expression (100-200 fold) to sustained moderate levels (40-80 fold) providing maintenance synthesis without driving major accumulation, regulatory transcription factors (VvMYBA1, VvMYBA2, VvMYC1) declining from maximum induction (120-180 fold) to moderate sustained expression (50-90 fold) maintaining pathway activation without intense developmental signaling, and hormonal transition with ABA declining from veraison peak 2500-3500 ng/g to plateau 1200-2200 ng/g consolidating ripening program completion while other hormones (gibberellin, auxin) remain at low post-growth levels and ethylene showing cultivar-dependent patterns (slight elevation 0.2-0.8 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in some varieties, baseline <0.1 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in others). ||Biochemical status at completion shows: anthocyanin concentrations plateaued at cultivar-specific maxima (600-3000 mg/kg skin fresh weight) with spatial distribution achieving uniformity (within-berry CV <15-20%, within-cluster CV <25-30%), anthocyanin composition stabilized with malvidin-3-glucoside 48-72%, delphinidin 4-22%, cyanidin 6-25%, acylated forms 20-35% and these proportions remaining constant during subsequent ripening barring degradation, copigmentation maximized with flavonols 150-350 mg/kg and hydroxycinnamic acids 80-220 mg/kg creating stable color enhancement 45-60% beyond anthocyanin contribution alone, and chlorophyll fully degraded to <3-8 μg/g from green berry levels 150-300 μg/g completing green color elimination. ||Cellular state at completion includes: vacuolar anthocyanin sequestration at maximum capacity with concentrations 18-35 mM in epidermal cells representing equilibrium between transport and leakage, vacuolar pH stabilized at 2.8-3.3 through continued V-ATPase activity ensuring color stability though at reduced activity compared to peak accumulation phase, anthocyanin vacuolar inclusions fully developed in cultivars forming these structures with localized concentrations >70 mM providing exceptional color intensity, and membrane integrity generally maintained though beginning slight permeabilization in some cultivars marking transition toward senescence particularly if environmental stresses occur. ||Environmental factors affecting completion timing inclu cumulative heat during veraison with completion typically occurring 550-750 growing degree days (base 10°C) post-color break in most cultivars, temperature during late development with optimal 20-26°C enabling complete maturation in 14-18 days while cooler conditions 16-22°C extend completion to 18-24 days and heat stress >30°C can force premature apparent completion through biosynthetic shutdown at 10-14 days potentially preventing full color potential achievement, light exposure determining final anthocyanin levels achieved at completion with optimal exposure reaching 30-50% higher levels than shaded fruit, and water availability with moderate sustained deficit through completion producing 25-40% higher final anthocyanins compared to well-watered vines though severe stress can arrest development preventing completion. ||Cultivar variation in completion timing reflects: early-completing varieties (Pinot Noir, Gamay, Grenache) achieving completion 12-16 days post-color break under favorable conditions, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Cabernet Franc, Tempranillo) completing 15-19 days post-break, and late-completing types (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre, Tannat) requiring 18-24 days with genetic differences in biosynthetic capacity, regulatory control, and developmental programming determining completion kinetics. ||Coordination with other ripening processes at completion shows: berry sugar accumulation transitioning from rapid phase (1.5-3.5% Brix per week) to slow accumulation or plateau (<0.5-1.0% per week) often coinciding with color completion, acid decline slowing substantially as malate respiratory consumption approaches minimum sustainable levels with titratable acidity 4.0-7.5 g/L stabilizing, berry softening approaching final state with firmness 1.0-2.2 N representing 70-85% total softening completed, seed maturation achieving brown color and lignified testa synchronized with color completion, and flavor/aroma development reaching characteristic intensity and complexity suitable for harvest or continued maturation depending on wine style objectives. ||Physiological significance of completion includes: transition from sink-driven developmental processes to source-sink equilibrium or beginning source mobilization in extended ripening, shift from active biosynthetic programming to maintenance metabolism or senescence depending on vine status and environmental conditions, and establishment of final berry composition determining wine quality potential with further changes primarily degradative (over-ripening) or concentrative (dehydration) rather than developmental. ||Quality implications of color development completion timing inclu completion synchronized with chemical maturity (target sugar, acid, pH) and phenolic maturity (seed browning, tannin extractability) indicates optimal harvest window for balanced wine production, premature completion before adequate flavor development or tannin maturation requires difficult decisions between harvesting color-mature but compositionally immature fruit or extending hang time risking color degradation, delayed completion beyond chemical maturity creates opposite challenge of harvesting at peak composition before complete color or waiting for color completion risking over-ripeness and alcohol elevation, and completion timing variation within vineyards reveals maturity heterogeneity informing selective harvest decisions or requiring acceptance of compositional variation. ||Monitoring color development completion involves: tracking anthocyanin accumulation rates through regular sampling showing plateau (<5% increase over 2 weeks) indicating completion, gene expression analysis in research settings measuring UFGT and regulatory factor transcripts confirming downregulation to maintenance levels, colorimetric monitoring showing stabilization of L*a*b* values with minimal week-to-week variation, visual assessment noting stable fully developed color without further intensification, and integration with chemical and sensory evaluation ensuring color completion synchronized with overall maturity for optimal harvest timing. ||Post-completion berry status shows: stable color persisting 2-6 weeks under favorable conditions (moderate temperatures, no extremes) enabling flexible harvest scheduling particularly in stable cultivars, potential color degradation under stress conditions (heat, water deficit extremes, disease) reducing anthocyanins 15-40% and shifting hue toward brown-red indicating over-ripeness or senescence, continued flavor and aroma development post-color completion in some cultivars benefiting from extended hang time for complexity enhancement, and risk-benefit assessment of extended ripening weighing flavor/phenolic improvement against color stability, disease pressure, and weather forecasts informing harvest timing decisions. ||Viticultural management at completion includes: irrigation often reduced or terminated recognizing decreased berry water demand and growth, canopy adjusted to protect colored berries from excessive sun preventing degradation while maintaining adequate exposure for continued ripening in other parameters, disease prevention intensified as fully colored soft berries show maximum Botrytis vulnerability, and harvest logistics activated with completion indicating optimal window approach requiring readiness for rapid harvest if conditions deteriorate or quality peaks.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 238-242 ripening completion and harvest timing || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Australian J Grape Wine Res 48:125-144 developmental completion || Deluc LG, Grimplet J, Wheatley MD, Tillett RL, Quilici DR, Osborne C, Schooley DA, Schlauch KA, Cushman JC, Cramer GR (2007) Transcriptomic and metabolite analyses of Cabernet Sauvignon grape berry development Bmc Genomics 8:429 molecular markers of ripening completion."
},

  "Sugar_Accumulation_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Accumulation_Onset is a Veraison comprising the metabolic shift from organic acid accumulation and low sugar content to rapid hexose accumulation in berry mesocarp tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "veraison sugar loading initiation | hexose accumulation commencement | sweetening process onset | sugar import activation |+ Veraison-Zucker-Beladungs-Initiierung | Hexose-Akkumulations-Beginn | Süßungs-Prozess-Onset | Zucker-Import-Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc vineyard in New Zealand, sugar accumulation onset was detected in early February Year N+1 (BBCH 83, 64 days post-flowering) when berry Brix increased from 7.2° to 11.8° over 7 days (0.66° per day, 4.6% per week), VvHT1 expression rose 65-fold, berry firmness declined 15% to 2.4 N indicating concurrent softening, ABA levels reached 720 ng/g, and hexose:sucrose ratio increased from 0.4 to 2.8 under warm conditions (daily high 24-27°C, adequate irrigation supporting rapid metabolic transition).",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Accumulation_Onset is distinguished from later accumulation phases by representing initiation rather than progression, occurs typically 0-3 days after/with color break (reds) or initial softening (whites), and marks fundamental metabolic shift from acid to sugar accumulation. ||Pre-onset rates <1.0% Brix/week, post-onset 1.5-3.5% Brix/week. ||Timing: early cultivars 7-9 weeks post-flowering, mid-season 9-11 weeks, late 11-13 weeks. ||Temperature optimal 25-30°C for rapid onset. ||ABA spike 50-150 → 500-2000 ng/g is critical trigger. ||Sugar_Accumulation_Onset represents universal veraison marker for ALL grape cultivars (red and white) essential for harvest timing prediction. || This critical metabolic switch occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically synchronized within 0-3 days of color break in red cultivars or concurrent with initial berry softening in white varieties, and is characterized by sugar concentration increasing from pre-veraison baseline 5-8° Brix to early accumulation 10-14° Brix within 5-8 days representing transition from <1.0% Brix per week accumulation rate to 1.5-3.5% per week during active sugar loading. ||The onset process involves fundamental changes in berry physiology: phloem unloading mechanism transitions from predominantly symplastic (cell-to-cell through plasmodesmata) to apoplastic (into cell wall space requiring membrane transport) creating new transport pathways enabling massive hexose influx, sucrose arriving via phloem undergoes cleavage by cell wall invertase and sucrose synthase producing glucose and fructose that accumulate in mesocarp vacuoles, hexose transporter expression increases 20-80 fold with VvHT genes (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) upregulated enabling facilitated diffusion of glucose and fructose across plasma and tonoplast membranes, and hexose to sucrose ratio shifts dramatically from <0.5 in green berries to >2.0 at onset and eventually >8-15 at maturity reflecting complete metabolic reprogramming. ||Hormonal regulation of sugar accumulation onset shows: abscisic acid levels spike from pre-veraison 50-150 ng/g to veraison peak 500-2000 ng/g activating sugar-responsive genes through ABA-responsive elements and creating hexokinase-mediated sugar signaling feedback loops that amplify accumulation, declining gibberellin and auxin levels remove growth-related suppression allowing metabolic resources to redirect from cell division and expansion to storage compound accumulation, and ethylene shows cultivar-dependent slight elevation (0.1-0.6 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹) in some varieties potentially modulating sugar metabolism timing though its role is less pronounced than in climacteric fruit. ||Gene expression changes at onset inclu hexose transporter genes (VvHT1, VvHT2) show 30-100 fold induction enabling glucose and fructose uptake into cells, sucrose transporter genes paradoxically decline as apoplastic unloading reduces symplastic transport requirements, invertase genes both vacuolar (VvGIN) and cell wall (VvcwINV) increase 15-50 fold catalyzing sucrose hydrolysis, sucrose synthase shows tissue-specific regulation with some isoforms increasing to produce UDP-glucose for cellulose synthesis while others decline, and transcription factors including VvMYB, VvNAC, and VvWRKY families show coordinated induction orchestrating the metabolic reprogramming. ||Cellular mechanisms enabling sugar accumulation inclu mesocarp cell vacuoles expanding to occupy 90-95% of cell volume creating massive storage capacity (individual cell vacuoles reaching 0.5-2.0 nL volume), tonoplast membrane area increasing substantially through vesicle fusion enabling enhanced transporter capacity, vacuolar pH regulation maintaining 3.0-3.8 creating proton gradient that may assist some sugar transport mechanisms, and cytoplasmic sugar concentrations kept low (50-100 mM) relative to vacuolar accumulation (800-1500 mM at maturity) through efficient tonoplast transport maintaining concentration gradient favoring continued import. ||Environmental factors influencing onset timing inclu temperature with warm conditions 25-30°C advancing onset 3-5 days compared to cool 18-22°C through enhanced metabolic rates and potentially earlier ABA accumulation, light exposure affecting onset through photosynthate availability with shaded fruit sometimes showing 2-4 day delay, water availability with moderate deficit potentially advancing onset 2-3 days through elevated ABA though severe stress can delay through general metabolic impairment, and canopy source-sink relationships with adequate leaf area per unit fruit weight essential for supporting rapid accumulation once initiated. ||Cultivar variation in onset timing shows: early varieties (Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, Gamay) initiate sugar accumulation 7-9 weeks post-flowering, mid-season cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Cabernet Franc) begin 9-11 weeks post-flowering, while late varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) start 11-13 weeks post-flowering reflecting genetic differences in developmental programming and veraison triggering. ||Coordination with other veraison processes demonstrates: sugar accumulation onset typically occurs 0-3 days after or concurrent with initial berry softening suggesting common developmental signals, coincides with color break in red cultivars (both triggered by ABA spike and sugar signaling), parallels acid decline initiation particularly malate respiratory consumption beginning, and synchronizes with berry expansion resumption after lag phase creating the characteristic veraison growth acceleration. ||Metabolic consequences of sugar accumulation onset inclu respiratory patterns shifting from primarily oxidative metabolism supporting growth to substrate-level reactions processing imported sugars, carbon allocation redirecting from structural components (cell walls, membranes) to storage carbohydrates representing 60-80% of berry carbon at maturity, and osmotic adjustment through hexose accumulation creating water potential gradient (-1.5 to -2.5 MPa at maturity) driving continued water import and berry expansion despite declining growth rates. ||Nutritional demands during onset inclu adequate nitrogen for synthesis of sugar transporters and metabolic enzymes with 15-30% of berry nitrogen allocation occurring during early sugar accumulation, potassium requirements increasing as K⁺ accumulates with sugars potentially affecting membrane transport and pH regulation (berry K⁺ rising from 800-1200 mg/kg to 1500-2500 mg/kg during accumulation), and phosphorus for ATP synthesis supporting active transport processes though P requirements relatively modest. ||Quality implications of sugar accumulation onset timing inclu early onset relative to other maturity parameters can lead to high sugar with insufficient flavor development if harvest timing based solely on Brix targets, delayed onset may produce fruit with advanced physiological age but inadequate sugar requiring extended hang time with risks of over-ripeness in other aspects, and synchrony of onset across berries and clusters within vineyard affects maturity uniformity and harvest timing optimization. ||Viticultural factors affecting onset inclu crop load with excessive yields (>12-15 kg/vine depending on variety) potentially delaying onset 3-7 days through source limitation and delayed veraison triggering, leaf area adequacy with insufficient photosynthetic capacity limiting sugar import potential once onset occurs, water management with irrigation strategy during pre-veraison affecting ABA accumulation and onset timing (moderate deficit potentially advancing 2-4 days), and canopy microclimate with cluster light exposure and temperature affecting developmental signals triggering onset. ||Monitoring sugar accumulation onset involves: regular Brix measurements showing acceleration from <1.0% to >1.5% increase per week indicating onset occurrence, berry sampling across developmental stages within clusters identifying first berries initiating rapid accumulation, correlation with berry softening and color break providing integrated veraison monitoring, and growth degree day accumulation from flowering predicting onset timing enabling proactive management and harvest forecasting.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 217-225 sugar accumulation and veraison || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Australian J Grape Wine Res 48:125-144 sugar accumulation dynamics || Davies C, Robinson SP (1996) Sugar accumulation in grape berries Plant Physiol 111:275-283 molecular mechanisms."
},

  "Initial_Sugar_Increase": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Sugar_Increase is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset characterized by acceleration of berry sugar concentration from below 1.0% Brix per week to 1.2–2.5% Brix per week.",
  "alternative_term": "early hexose accumulation | beginning sugar concentration rise | nascent sweetening | initial Brix elevation |+ frühe Hexose-Akkumulation | beginnender Zucker-Konzentrations-Anstieg | beginnende Süßung | initiale Brix-Erhöhung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Chardonnay vineyard, initial sugar increase was documented over 8 days in early August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when berry Brix rose from 8.4° to 13.6° (average 1.95% per week), VvHT1 expression was 58-fold elevated, hexose:sucrose ratio increased from 0.6 to 3.8, berry fresh weight rose 24% from 1.08 to 1.34 g, firmness declined to 2.1 N, titratable acidity 9.8 g/L beginning decline, under warm conditions (daily high 28-31°C, adequate irrigation supporting osmotic berry expansion).",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Sugar_Increase is distinguished from Sugar_Accumulation_Onset by representing active increase rather than triggering, from Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation by showing moderate (1.2-2.5% Brix/week) rather than peak (2.0-3.5%/week) rates, and from later accumulation by occurring early in veraison BBCH 83. ||Duration typically 5-10 days. ||Hexose transporters 40-70% of maximum expression. ||Glucose:fructose ratio ~1.0 initially. ||Temperature optimal 25-30°C. ||Initial_Sugar_Increase represents transition from slow to moderate accumulation establishing the foundation for peak sugar loading. || This initial increase occurs during early veraison (BBCH 83), typically 1-5 days following metabolic onset signals, and is characterized by berry Brix rising from 6-9° to 11-15° over 5-10 days representing initial activation of enhanced sugar import machinery before full acceleration to peak rates. ||The initial increase involves progressive activation of transport systems: hexose transporters (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3) reach 40-70% of maximum expression levels enabling facilitated diffusion of glucose and fructose across plasma membranes at moderate rates 15-35 μmol hexose per g fresh weight per hour, phloem unloading transitions from predominantly symplastic to increasingly apoplastic creating cell wall space sugar accumulation requiring membrane transport, sucrose cleavage enzymes (cell wall invertase, vacuolar invertase, sucrose synthase) achieve 50-75% of peak activities producing glucose and fructose from phloem-delivered sucrose, and tonoplast transport capacity increases through membrane expansion and transporter insertion enabling hexose accumulation in expanding vacuoles. ||Cellular changes during initial increase inclu mesocarp cell vacuoles enlarging from 75-85% to 85-92% of cell volume creating enhanced storage capacity, vacuolar sugar concentrations rising from 150-300 mM to 400-700 mM representing 2-3 fold increase establishing osmotic gradients, cytoplasmic sugar maintained at 60-120 mM through efficient tonoplast transport preventing excessive cytosolic accumulation that could inhibit metabolism, and total berry fresh weight increasing 15-30% during initial sugar increase through osmotically-driven water import accompanying hexose accumulation. ||Hexose composition during initial increase shows: glucose and fructose approximately equimolar (ratio 0.95-1.05) during early phase reflecting balanced cleavage of sucrose by invertases and sucrose synthase, hexose to sucrose ratio rising from pre-veraison 0.3-0.6 to initial increase 2.5-5.0 indicating fundamental shift from sucrose transport/storage to hexose accumulation, and trace amounts of other sugars (arabinose, xylose, galactose from cell wall turnover) remain <1-2% of total contributing negligibly to Brix but potentially affecting flavor perception. ||Gene expression patterns during initial increase demonstrate: VvHT1 and VvHT2 transcripts increase 40-80 fold above green berry baseline enabling enhanced hexose uptake, vacuolar invertase genes show 25-60 fold elevation catalyzing sucrose hydrolysis in vacuoles, cell wall invertase genes increase 20-50 fold producing hexoses in apoplast, sucrose transporter genes decline 60-80% as apoplastic unloading reduces symplastic transport requirements, and regulatory factors including sugar-responsive transcription factors (VvMYB, VvbZIP) show induction coordinating metabolic reprogramming. ||Hormonal regulation during initial increase includes: ABA levels sustained at 600-1500 ng/g maintaining ripening program activation, sugar itself creating signaling through hexokinase pathway generating glucose-6-phosphate signals that feedback-regulate transporter and enzyme genes amplifying accumulation, declining gibberellin levels removing growth inhibition allowing metabolic focus on storage, and potential ethylene involvement in some cultivars with slight elevation 0.2-0.8 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ though role less clear than ABA and sugar signaling. ||Environmental influences on initial increase rate inclu temperature strongly affecting accumulation with optimal 25-30°C supporting rates 1.8-2.5% Brix per week while cooler 18-23°C reduces to 1.2-1.8% and heat >32°C may impair to <1.0% through metabolic disruption, light affecting source leaf photosynthesis and thus sugar availability with adequate canopy light exposure essential for supporting accumulation rates, water status with moderate deficit potentially enhancing concentration through reduced berry expansion though excessive stress limits import through general metabolic impairment, and source-sink balance with adequate leaf area per fruit weight (12-16 cm² leaf area per g fruit) necessary for supporting initial increase rates. ||Cultivar variation in initial increase characteristics shows: rapid-accumulating varieties (Chardonnay, Gewürztraminer) achieve 2.0-2.5% Brix per week during initial increase reaching 12-15° Brix in 6-8 days, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) show 1.5-2.0% per week reaching 11-14° in 8-10 days, while slower types (Nebbiolo, Carignan) display 1.2-1.6% per week requiring 10-14 days to reach 11-13° reflecting genetic differences in transporter expression and metabolic capacity. ||Coordination with other ripening processes during initial increase includes: berry softening progressing concurrently with 20-35% firmness reduction from green berry values as cell wall degradation proceeds, color development (in red cultivars) showing initial or progressive anthocyanin accumulation synchronized through common ABA signaling, acid levels beginning decline particularly malate respiratory consumption initiating though titratable acidity still elevated 8-12 g/L during initial increase, and berry expansion resuming after lag phase with 20-40% fresh weight increase through osmotic water import driven by sugar accumulation. ||Metabolic integration during initial increase shows: respiratory quotient (CO₂ produced / O₂ consumed) increasing from 0.85-1.00 to 1.05-1.25 indicating transition from oxidative metabolism to substrate-level reactions with some fermentative activity, carbon allocation shifting from structural synthesis to storage with 50-70% of imported carbon accumulating as hexoses, and nitrogen metabolism adjusting with amino acid levels declining 25-40% as nitrogen incorporation into proteins and secondary metabolites proceeds. ||Quality implications of initial increase inclu rate of initial increase affecting ultimate sugar levels with faster early rates often correlating with higher final Brix (r² = 0.65-0.82), timing of initial increase relative to flavor and phenolic development determining optimal harvest window with early increase enabling earlier harvest or late increase requiring extended hang time, and uniformity of initial increase across berries and clusters indicating ripening synchrony important for harvest timing and wine composition consistency. ||Viticultural management during initial increase involves: irrigation often reduced or terminated as berry growth slows and sugar accumulation accelerates recognizing changing water demands, canopy management ensuring adequate light to source leaves supporting continued photosynthesis and sugar export to berries, disease monitoring intensifying as increasing sugar attracts insects and provides substrate for fungal pathogens particularly Botrytis, and crop protection measures including bird netting installation as sweetening fruit becomes attractive to wildlife. ||Monitoring initial increase provides harvest forecasting: weekly Brix sampling tracking accumulation rates enabling projection of harvest timing (typically 35-50 days from initial increase to target Brix depending on cultivar and heat accumulation), correlation between initial increase rate and final sugar achieved informing yield and quality predictions, identification of spatial variation in increase rates revealing vineyard heterogeneity requiring selective harvest or management intervention, and integration with berry sampling for acids, pH, and phenolics providing comprehensive maturity assessment beyond sugar alone.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 218-222 early sugar accumulation || Davies C, Wolf T, Robinson SP (1999) Three putative sucrose transporters are differentially expressed in grapevine tissues Plant Sci 147:93-100 transporter expression || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 accumulation dynamics."
},

  "Phloem_Unloading_Activation": {
  "definition": "A Phloem_Unloading_Activation is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset comprising the transition of berry vascular phloem unloading from symplastic transport through plasmodesmata to apoplastic transport with sucrose release into the cell wall space.",
  "alternative_term": "apoplastic unloading initiation | symplastic pathway closure | phloem-mesocarp transport transition | unloading mechanism shift |+ apoplastische Entladungs-Initiierung | symplastischer Pfad-Verschluss | Phloem-Mesokarp-Transport-Übergang | Entladungs-Mechanismus-Wechsel",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Pinot Noir vineyard, phloem unloading activation was detected 2 days before initial sugar increase in mid-August Year N+1 (BBCH 83, 58 days post-flowering) when symplastic connectivity declined from 52% to 18% measured by dye coupling, VvcwINV expression increased 48-fold, cell wall invertase activity rose from 3.2 to 22.5 units/g FW, VvHT1 induction was 35-fold, ABA levels reached 880 ng/g, and apoplastic sucrose concentration was 115 mM under warm conditions (daily high 27-30°C) initiating the critical transport pathway transition.",
  "editor_note": "Phloem_Unloading_Activation is distinguished from Sugar_Accumulation_Onset by representing pathway mechanism rather than net accumulation, from Initial_Sugar_Increase by preceding measurable Brix rise by 1-3 days, and from Hexose_Transport_Initiation by focusing on phloem unloading rather than membrane transport. ||Symplastic connectivity drops from 40-60% to <10-20%. ||Cell wall invertase increases 3-7 fold. ||Timing: 1-3 days before measurable sugar increase. ||ABA spike critical trigger. ||Phloem_Unloading_Activation represents fundamental pathway change enabling massive hexose accumulation during grape ripening. || This activation occurs during veraison onset (BBCH 83), typically 1-3 days preceding initial sugar increase, and is characterized by plasmodesmata closure or reduced conductance in the phloem-mesocarp boundary reducing symplastic connectivity from pre-veraison 40-60% to post-activation <10-20% measured by dye coupling or electrical coupling assays, concurrent upregulation of cell wall invertase genes (VvcwINV) 25-70 fold producing enzyme that cleaves phloem-delivered sucrose in apoplastic space, and beginning induction of hexose transporters (VvHT1, VvHT2) 20-50 fold enabling facilitated diffusion of resulting glucose and fructose into mesocarp cells. ||Anatomical changes underlying activation inclu callose deposition in plasmodesmata connecting sieve elements to surrounding cells reducing pore size from 3-5 nm to <1.5 nm effectively blocking symplastic transport of sucrose (molecular diameter ~1.0 nm requires functional plasmodesmata), increased cell wall thickness in phloem-mesocarp boundary zone from 0.8-1.5 μm to 1.5-2.5 μm creating enhanced apoplastic compartment, and potential changes in middle lamella pectin composition affecting cell-cell adhesion and apoplastic pathway tortuosity. ||Molecular mechanisms of activation involve: callose synthase genes upregulated 8-25 fold catalyzing β-1,3-glucan synthesis deposited at plasmodesmata, plasmodesmata-located proteins (PDLPs, callose binding proteins) showing altered expression potentially regulating pore conductance, and hormonal signals particularly ABA (rising from 80-200 ng/g to 600-1200 ng/g during activation) potentially triggering plasmodesmata closure through second messenger cascades and calcium signaling. ||Cell wall invertase during activation shows: VvcwINV genes induced 30-80 fold producing enzyme that cleaves sucrose (Km 8-15 mM) into glucose and fructose in cell wall space, enzyme localized to phloem-mesocarp boundary particularly in bundle sheath and adjacent parenchyma cells where unloading occurs, activity increasing from pre-veraison <2-5 units/g FW to activation phase 15-35 units/g representing 3-7 fold elevation, and pH optimum 4.5-5.5 matching apoplastic pH enabling efficient catalysis producing hexoses for subsequent membrane transport. ||Hexose transporter induction during activation includes: VvHT1 (high-affinity glucose transporter, Km ~1-2 mM) expression rising 25-60 fold enabling glucose uptake from apoplast, VvHT2 (facilitating both glucose and fructose, Km 3-8 mM) showing 20-50 fold induction, VvHT5 and VvHT6 similarly upregulated providing diverse transporter repertoire for hexose import, and subcellular localization includes both plasma membrane (apoplast to cytoplasm transport) and tonoplast (cytoplasm to vacuole transport) enabling complete pathway for hexose accumulation in vacuolar storage. ||Physiological consequences of apoplastic unloading inclu creation of sugar gradient with apoplastic sucrose 50-150 mM during active unloading cleaved to 80-250 mM combined hexoses providing concentration gradient for facilitated diffusion into cells, osmotic effects in apoplast potentially drawing water from xylem creating localized water potential gradients affecting berry hydration, and metabolic flexibility with apoplastic pathway allowing independent regulation of import versus utilization unlike symplastic pathway where both are coupled. ||Environmental regulation of activation shows: temperature affecting timing with warm conditions 26-30°C advancing activation 2-4 days compared to cool 18-22°C possibly through enhanced ABA synthesis or hormone sensitivity, light exposure potentially influencing through photosynthate availability or photoreceptor signaling affecting developmental progression, water deficit potentially accelerating activation 2-3 days through elevated ABA though severe stress may delay through general developmental arrest, and vine vigor effects with high-vigor vines sometimes showing delayed activation through extended vegetative-reproductive competition. ||Cultivar variation in activation timing reflects: early varieties (Chardonnay, Pinot Noir) activating apoplastic unloading 8-10 weeks post-flowering, mid-season types (Merlot, Syrah) activating 10-12 weeks, and late cultivars (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo) showing activation 12-14 weeks demonstrating genetic control of developmental timing, and activation completeness varies with some cultivars maintaining residual symplastic component (<15-25% of unloading) while others show nearly complete apoplastic dominance (>90-95%). ||Coordination with other veraison events demonstrates: phloem unloading activation typically precedes initial sugar increase by 1-3 days establishing transport pathway before major accumulation begins, occurs concurrently with or slightly before berry softening onset suggesting common developmental triggers, and in red cultivars often coincides with initial anthocyanin synthesis activation reflecting integrated ABA-mediated ripening program. ||Metabolic implications inclu apoplastic pathway creates opportunity for regulatory control at multiple steps (invertase activity, hexose transporter expression, tonoplast transport) enabling fine-tuning of sugar accumulation, spatial separation of sucrose cleavage (apoplast) from metabolism (cytoplasm) prevents futile cycling where cleaved hexoses would be immediately re-synthesized to sucrose, and energy requirements include ATP for hexose transport (if active transport components involved) though most transport appears facilitated diffusion down concentration gradients. ||Evolutionary perspective suggests: apoplastic unloading in ripening berries may represent adaptation for maximizing sugar accumulation enabling high final concentrations (>1000 mM hexoses) difficult to achieve via symplastic pathway due to osmotic and diffusion limitations, shift to apoplastic pathway coincides with seed maturation completion potentially reflecting developmental switch from seed provisioning (requiring controlled symplastic delivery) to fruit attractiveness maximization (benefiting from unrestricted apoplastic accumulation), and convergent evolution with other fleshy fruits (tomato, pepper) showing similar unloading transitions suggesting common adaptive value. ||Viticultural implications of activation inclu represents critical developmental checkpoint where adequate source capacity becomes essential for supporting subsequent sugar accumulation, crop load management effects expressed most strongly during activation period with overcropping potentially delaying or impairing activation through source limitation, and environmental stresses (water deficit, heat, disease) during activation period can have disproportionate effects on final sugar levels by impairing pathway establishment even if conditions improve later. ||Research methods for studying activation involve: dye coupling experiments using fluorescent tracers (Lucifer Yellow, carboxyfluorescein) to assess symplastic connectivity showing decreased coupling post-activation, electron microscopy revealing callose deposition at plasmodesmata, gene expression analysis tracking invertase and transporter induction, enzyme activity assays measuring cell wall invertase showing 3-7 fold increases, and sugar composition analysis of apoplast versus cytoplasm/vacuole compartments revealing pathway changes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Zhang XY, Wang XL, Wang XF, Xia GH, Pan QH, Fan RC, Wu FQ, Yu XC, Zhang DP (2006) A shift of phloem unloading from symplasmic to apoplasmic pathway is involved in developmental onset of ripening in grape berry Plant Physiol 142:220-232 unloading pathway transition || Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 hexose transporter roles || Delrot S, Picaud S, Gaudillère JP (2001) Sugar and organic acid transport in grapevine berries Rec Adv Phloem Transport Metab:37-47 transport mechanisms."
},

  "Hexose_Transport_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Hexose_Transport_Initiation is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset involving activation of glucose and fructose membrane transport from apoplastic space into mesocarp cells with subsequent vacuolar accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "membrane hexose uptake activation | glucose-fructose transport onset | sugar transporter induction | vacuolar hexose loading initiation |+ Membran-Hexose-Aufnahme-Aktivierung | Glukose-Fruktose-Transport-Onset | Zucker-Transporter-Induktion | vakuoläre Hexose-Beladungs-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Mosel Riesling vineyard, hexose transport initiation was characterized in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when VvHT1 expression reached 62-fold elevation, VvHT2 showed 45-fold induction, glucose uptake into isolated mesocarp cells was 22 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (from 4.5 μmol pre-veraison), vacuolar hexose concentration rose from 180 mM to 520 mM over 6 days, berry Brix increased from 9.2° to 13.8°, and ABA levels were 1050 ng/g under cool German conditions (daily high 19-22°C, night 10-13°C, extended ripening period).",
  "editor_note": "Hexose_Transport_Initiation is distinguished from Phloem_Unloading_Activation by representing membrane transport rather than phloem pathway change, from Initial_Sugar_Increase by focusing on transport mechanism rather than net accumulation, and from Sugar_Import_Enhancement by showing initiation rather than progressive amplification. ||Transporter induction: VvHT1 40-80 fold, VvHT2 30-60 fold. ||Uptake rates increase 4-8 fold. ||Timing: 0-2 days after unloading activation. ||Temperature optimal 24-28°C. ||Hexose_Transport_Initiation establishes cellular import machinery critical for sugar accumulation during grape ripening. || This initiation occurs during early veraison (BBCH 83), typically 0-2 days following phloem unloading activation, and is characterized by hexose transporter gene expression increasing 25-70 fold (VvHT1 40-80 fold, VvHT2 30-60 fold, VvHT3/5/6 20-50 fold) producing membrane proteins that catalyze facilitated diffusion of hexoses across plasma membrane and tonoplast, hexose uptake rates into isolated mesocarp cells rising from pre-veraison 2-6 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to initiation phase 12-28 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 4-8 fold enhancement, and beginning cytoplasm-to-vacuole transport achieving rates 15-35 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ enabling vacuolar accumulation to 300-600 mM during initial transport phase. ||Molecular basis of transport initiation involves: VvHT1 gene (encoding high-affinity glucose transporter with Km 1.0-2.5 mM) shows rapid induction reaching 50-70% of maximum expression within 2-4 days enabling efficient glucose uptake even at moderate apoplastic concentrations, VvHT2 (facilitating both glucose and fructose with Km 4-10 mM) achieves 40-65% maximum expression providing capacity for both hexoses, additional transporters (VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) contribute with combined 30-50% maximum expression creating diverse transporter portfolio, and regulatory control involves sugar-responsive transcription factors (VvMYB, VvbZIP families) binding to promoter elements activated by hexokinase-mediated sugar sensing creating positive feedback loops. ||Subcellular localization of transporters includes: plasma membrane VvHT1/2/3 enabling hexose uptake from apoplast (estimated 60-75% of transporter protein), tonoplast-localized forms of VvHT proteins facilitating cytoplasm-to-vacuole transport (20-35% of protein), and potential endo-membrane (ER, Golgi) localization during synthesis and trafficking representing 5-10% of total at steady state, with immunolocalization and GFP fusion studies demonstrating predominant plasma membrane and tonoplast distribution. ||Transport kinetics during initiation show: glucose transport Vmax increasing from 8-15 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ pre-veraison to 25-50 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during initiation through increased transporter density, fructose transport showing similar enhancement with Vmax 20-45 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, Km values remaining relatively constant (glucose 1.5-3.0 mM, fructose 5-12 mM) indicating increased capacity rather than affinity changes, and competition kinetics demonstrating glucose uptake slightly favored over fructose (relative rate 1.1-1.4:1.0) though final vacuolar ratios approach equimolar through differential metabolism. ||Energetics of hexose transport involve: facilitated diffusion down concentration gradients (apoplast 100-200 mM total hexoses → cytoplasm 60-120 mM → vacuole accumulating to 400-800 mM during initiation) providing primary driving force without direct ATP coupling, potential role for proton-coupled transport at tonoplast where vacuolar H⁺-ATPase creating pH gradient (cytoplasm pH 7.2-7.5, vacuole pH 3.0-3.8) could drive secondary active transport though evidence suggests primarily facilitated diffusion, and metabolic maintenance of cytoplasmic hexose below apoplastic concentrations through glycolysis and other pathways sustaining import gradient. ||Cellular consequences of transport initiation inclu vacuolar hexose accumulation from 100-250 mM to 400-800 mM within 5-8 days creating osmotic potential shift from -0.6 to -1.2 MPa to -1.2 to -2.0 MPa driving water import and berry expansion, cytoplasmic hexose maintained at 60-120 mM through balanced import, metabolism, and tonoplast transport preventing excessive accumulation that could trigger feedback inhibition, and hexose:sucrose ratio in whole berry shifting from <0.8 to >3.0 reflecting dominant hexose import and accumulation versus residual sucrose. ||Hormonal regulation of transport initiation demonstrates: ABA levels 700-1400 ng/g during initiation activate ABA-responsive elements in hexose transporter gene promoters, sugar itself acting through hexokinase sensor creating glucose-6-phosphate signals that upregulate transporter genes establishing positive feedback amplification, declining auxin and gibberellin removing growth-related suppression allowing transporter gene expression, and potential ethylene involvement in some cultivars with slight elevation correlating with enhanced transport though mechanism unclear. ||Environmental modulation of transport initiation includes: temperature affecting transporter protein synthesis and membrane fluidity with optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum induction rates while heat >32°C can impair through protein misfolding or membrane disruption, osmotic stress from water deficit potentially affecting membrane transport capacity though moderate deficit appears compatible with normal initiation, and nutritional status particularly nitrogen and potassium affecting membrane synthesis and transport protein production with adequate nutrition essential for full transport capacity establishment. ||Cultivar variation in transport initiation characteristics shows: rapid-initiating varieties (Chardonnay, Gewürztraminer) achieve 60-75% maximum transport capacity within 3-5 days post-activation, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) reach 50-65% maximum in 5-7 days, while slower types (Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) require 7-10 days to achieve 45-60% maximum reflecting genetic differences in transporter gene regulation and protein synthesis rates. ||Coordination with sugar accumulation shows: transport initiation slightly precedes (0-2 days) measurable Brix increase establishing capacity before major flux, peak transport capacity achievement (80-100% maximum) coincides with rapid sugar accumulation phase (BBCH 84-85) enabling maximum import rates 2.5-4.5% Brix per week, and transport capacity maintenance through ripening (70-90% maximum even at late stages) sustains continued accumulation though rate declines as vacuolar concentration approaches equilibrium with phloem supply. ||Membrane dynamics during transport initiation involve: plasma membrane area potentially increasing through vesicle fusion or membrane expansion though data limited, tonoplast membrane surface area substantially increased (estimated 40-80%) through vacuole enlargement and membrane proliferation creating enhanced transport capacity, and lipid composition changes with increased unsaturation potentially enhancing membrane fluidity and transport protein function though specific modifications during initiation poorly characterized. ||Quality implications inclu transport capacity established during initiation strongly correlates with final sugar levels achieved (r² = 0.72-0.86) with inadequate initiation limiting ultimate Brix, uniformity of transport initiation across berries and clusters affecting ripening synchrony and harvest maturity variation, and timing relative to other ripening processes determining balance between sugar and flavor/acid/phenolic development important for wine style. ||Viticultural factors affecting transport initiation inclu crop load with excessive yields potentially impairing initiation through limited photosynthate availability for transporter synthesis, canopy management ensuring adequate nitrogen and resources for protein synthesis supporting transporter production, water management with severe deficit potentially limiting membrane synthesis while moderate deficit compatible with normal initiation, and disease or environmental stress during initiation period potentially causing long-term impairment of sugar accumulation capacity even if conditions later improve.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 hexose transporter characterization || Afoufa-Bastien D, Medici A, Jeauffre J, Coutos-Thévenot P, Lemoine R, Atanassova R, Laloi M (2010) The Vitis vinifera sugar transporter gene family Plant Mol Biol 72:533-546 sugar transporter family || Lecourieux F, Kappel C, Lecourieux D, Serrano A, Torres E, Arce-Johnson P, Delrot S (2014) An update on sugar transport and signaling in grapevine J Exp Bot 65:821-832 transport regulation."
},

  "Sugar_Import_Enhancement": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Import_Enhancement is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset comprising increased transporter expression, elevated enzyme activity, and expanded cellular storage capacity producing sustained acceleration of hexose accumulation rates.",
  "alternative_term": "amplified sugar uptake | progressive hexose import increase | enhanced accumulation capacity | accelerating sugar loading |+ verstärkte Zucker-Aufnahme | progressive Hexose-Import-Zunahme | erhöhte Akkumulations-Kapazität | beschleunigende Zucker-Beladung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Bordeaux Sémillon vineyard, sugar import enhancement was tracked over 7 days in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 84) when VvHT1 expression reached 95-fold (near maximum), glucose uptake rates were 58 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, vacuolar hexose rose from 720 mM to 1150 mM, berry Brix increased from 16.8° to 23.2° (average 3.3% per week), fresh weight expanded 18% to 1.68 g, titratable acidity declined to 7.2 g/L, under warm late-summer conditions (daily high 26-29°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.1 MPa concentrating sugars).",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Import_Enhancement is distinguished from Hexose_Transport_Initiation by representing amplification rather than onset, from Initial_Sugar_Increase by showing accelerating (2.5-4.0% Brix/week) rather than moderate (1.5-2.5%/week) rates, and from peak accumulation by being progressive rather than maximum. ||Transporter expression 75-100% maximum. ||Uptake rates 8-15 fold over baseline. ||Duration typically 5-8 days BBCH 83-84. ||Temperature optimal 25-30°C. ||Sugar_Import_Enhancement represents critical escalation phase driving berry toward harvest sweetness levels. || This enhancement occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 3-8 days post-transport initiation, and is characterized by hexose transporter gene expression reaching 75-100% of maximum levels (VvHT1 approaching 100-fold above green berry, VvHT2 80-fold, others 60-90 fold), hexose uptake rates into mesocarp cells achieving 35-65 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 8-15 fold enhancement over pre-veraison baseline, and sugar accumulation accelerating from initial phase 1.5-2.5% Brix per week to enhanced phase 2.5-4.0% per week enabling rapid sweetening toward harvest targets. ||Cellular mechanisms underlying enhancement inclu continued transporter protein synthesis and membrane insertion increasing transporter density 3-5 fold at plasma membrane and tonoplast, vacuolar expansion to occupy 92-95% of mesocarp cell volume (from 85-90% at initiation) creating enlarged storage capacity estimated 0.8-2.5 nL per cell, enhanced membrane surface area through continued vesicle fusion and membrane proliferation potentially doubling tonoplast area increasing transport sites, and optimized metabolic coordination where cytoplasmic hexose metabolism (glycolysis, PPP) adjusted to maintain low cytoplasmic concentrations (50-100 mM) sustaining concentration gradient favoring continued import despite rising vacuolar levels. ||Gene expression dynamics during enhancement show: hexose transporter genes (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) reaching maximum steady-state expression with transcripts 80-120 fold above green berry baseline, cell wall invertase maintaining high expression (60-100 fold) ensuring continued sucrose cleavage in apoplast, vacuolar invertase achieving 40-80 fold elevation contributing to intracellular sucrose metabolism, regulatory transcription factors (sugar-responsive VvMYB, VvbZIP, VvNAC) sustained at high levels coordinating transporter, enzyme, and metabolic gene expression, and feedback regulation beginning where very high hexose levels (>800 mM vacuolar) may start reducing transporter expression in some berries approaching saturation. ||Transport kinetics during enhancement demonstrate: glucose uptake Vmax increasing to 55-95 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (from 25-50 μmol at initiation) through increased transporter density with Km remaining 1.5-3.0 mM, fructose transport Vmax reaching 45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with Km 5-12 mM, competition between hexoses diminishing as transporter capacity exceeds supply creating non-saturating conditions, and tonoplast transport rates 40-75 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ efficiently moving cytoplasmic hexoses into vacuoles preventing accumulation that could inhibit plasma membrane import. ||Vacuolar accumulation during enhancement shows: hexose concentrations rising from 400-700 mM at initiation to 800-1200 mM during enhancement representing berry Brix 15-22°, glucose:fructose ratio approaching 0.95-1.05 (essentially equimolar) through balanced transport and differential metabolism normalizing any initial imbalances, osmotic potential declining from -1.2 to -1.8 MPa to -1.8 to -2.6 MPa creating strong water potential gradient driving continued water import and berry expansion 15-25% fresh weight increase during enhancement period, and vacuolar pH maintained 3.0-3.5 through H⁺-ATPase and H⁺-PPase activity creating acidic environment important for anthocyanin color stability (in reds) and potentially affecting some metabolic processes. ||Hormonal regulation during enhancement includes: ABA levels sustained 1200-2200 ng/g maintaining ripening program activation and transporter gene expression, hexose itself at high concentrations providing strong signaling through hexokinase pathway (glucose-6-phosphate levels 15-35 μmol/g FW) amplifying sugar-responsive gene expression through positive feedback, declining gibberellin and auxin maintaining low levels removing any residual growth-related suppression, and ethylene showing cultivar-dependent patterns with slight elevation 0.3-1.0 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in some varieties potentially fine-tuning ripening progression. ||Environmental influences on enhancement inclu temperature strongly affecting enhancement rate with optimal 25-30°C supporting maximum transporter synthesis and transport kinetics achieving 3.5-4.0% Brix per week, cooler conditions 20-25°C reducing to 2.5-3.2% Brix per week through slower metabolism, heat stress >32°C impairing enhancement potentially reducing to <2.0% per week through protein denaturation and membrane disruption, light exposure affecting source leaf photosynthesis with adequate light essential for providing sucrose substrate supporting enhanced import rates, and water availability with moderate deficit compatible with or potentially enhancing concentration through reduced berry expansion while severe deficit limits through general metabolic impairment. ||Cultivar variation in enhancement characteristics demonstrates: high-sugar cultivars (Gewürztraminer, Chenin Blanc, Sémillon) achieve maximum enhancement rates 3.5-4.5% Brix per week reaching final levels 24-28° Brix, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) show 2.8-3.8% per week achieving 22-26° Brix, while lower-sugar types (Pinot Noir in cool climates, some table grape varieties) display 2.0-3.0% per week reaching 18-23° Brix reflecting genetic differences in transporter capacity, enzyme activities, and metabolic programming. ||Coordination with other ripening processes during enhancement shows: berry softening approaching completion (60-80% total firmness reduction) creating characteristic ripe texture, color development (reds) reaching 70-90% final anthocyanin accumulation with both processes sharing ABA-mediated coordination, acid decline accelerating particularly malate consumption reducing titratable acidity from 10-14 g/L to 6-10 g/L, and flavor/aroma precursor synthesis intensifying with amino acid-derived compounds, terpenes, and other volatiles accumulating creating developing fruit character. ||Metabolic integration shows: respiratory quotient >1.1-1.3 indicating substrate-level metabolism dominates with some fermentative activity, carbon partitioning strongly favoring storage (75-85% of imported carbon accumulating as hexoses) over structural or metabolic uses, nitrogen metabolism adjusted with amino acid levels declining further (40-60% reduction from green berry) as incorporation into proteins and secondary metabolites proceeds, and potassium accumulation parallel with sugars (berry K⁺ rising from 1500-2000 to 2000-2800 mg/kg) potentially important for pH regulation and membrane function. ||Quality implications of enhancement inclu enhancement rate and duration critically determine final sugar levels achieved with faster longer enhancement producing higher Brix enabling earlier harvest or lower-alcohol wine styles through earlier picking, uniformity of enhancement across berries and clusters affecting harvest maturity variation with heterogeneous enhancement requiring selective harvest or acceptance of compositional variation, and timing of enhancement peak relative to flavor and phenolic development determining optimal harvest window with ideal scenario showing coordinated maturation of all parameters. ||Viticultural management during enhancement involves: irrigation typically terminated or minimized as berry water demand declines and concentration desirable, canopy management maintaining healthy source leaves supporting continued photosynthesis and sugar export, crop load ensuring adequate leaf area per fruit weight (typically 12-18 cm² per g at this stage) enabling enhancement without source limitation, disease monitoring intensifying as increasing sugar attracting insects and pathogens, and harvest forecasting using enhancement rates to project timing when target Brix achieved enabling logistics planning.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 221-225 sugar accumulation enhancement || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 accumulation regulation || Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 metabolic coordination."
},

  "Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation_Start": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation_Start is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset marked by the transition to maximum velocity hexose import with transport and metabolic systems at peak efficiency.",
  "alternative_term": "peak sugar accumulation velocity | maximum hexose import rate | fastest sweetening phase | accelerated Brix elevation |+ Spitzen-Zucker-Akkumulations-Geschwindigkeit | maximale Hexose-Import-Rate | schnellste Süßungs-Phase | beschleunigte Brix-Erhöhung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Paso Robles Zinfandel vineyard, rapid sugar accumulation start was documented in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 84, 8 days post-initial increase) when Brix rose from 17.5° to 26.2° over 14 days (average 4.2% per week), VvHT1 at maximum expression (108-fold), cell wall invertase activity 95 units/g FW, vacuolar hexose increased from 980 mM to 1650 mM, berry fresh weight expanded 15% despite declining growth, under warm conditions (daily high 30-34°C, managed through irrigation maintaining adequate vine water status).",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation_Start is distinguished from Initial_Sugar_Increase by representing maximum (2.8-4.5% Brix/week) rather than moderate (1.5-2.5%/week) rates, from Sugar_Import_Enhancement by showing peak rather than progressive amplification, and from sugar plateau by exhibiting maximum velocity rather than declining rates. ||Transporter expression 90-110% of maximum. ||Uptake rates peak 65-110 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹. ||Duration 2-4 weeks BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature optimal 26-30°C. ||Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation_Start represents critical phase achieving harvest-ready sweetness levels. || This rapid phase begins during mid-veraison (BBCH 84), typically 6-10 days post-initial sugar increase, and is characterized by sugar accumulation accelerating to peak rates 2.8-4.5% Brix per week (compared to initial phase 1.5-2.5% per week) driven by fully-induced transporter expression (VvHT genes at 90-110% maximum), maximum enzyme activities (cell wall invertase 60-120 units/g FW, vacuolar invertase 40-90 units/g), and optimized cellular capacity with vacuoles at 93-96% cell volume creating hexose concentrations rising 150-250 mM per week toward final levels 1200-1800 mM. ||Molecular basis of rapid accumulation includes: hexose transporter genes (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) expressed at maximum steady-state levels (100-150 fold above green berry) producing saturating amounts of membrane transport proteins, cell wall invertase genes at peak expression (80-120 fold) generating enzyme saturating apoplastic space enabling complete sucrose cleavage, sucrose synthase showing coordinated regulation providing alternative sucrose metabolism pathway producing UDP-glucose for specialized uses while most sucrose undergoes invertase cleavage, and regulatory networks fully activated with sugar-responsive transcription factors, ABA signaling components, and metabolic enzymes all operating at maximum creating coordinated high-flux state. ||Transport kinetics at rapid accumulation show: plasma membrane hexose uptake Vmax reaching maximum 65-110 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with transporter density saturating membrane capacity, fructose transport Vmax 55-100 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ similarly maximized, tonoplast transport rates 50-90 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ efficiently clearing cytoplasmic hexoses into vacuoles, and overall berry hexose import 80-150 μmol total hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing integration of apoplastic delivery, membrane transport, and vacuolar sequestration all operating near maximum. ||Vacuolar dynamics during rapid accumulation demonstrate: hexose concentrations rising from 700-1000 mM at rapid start to 1200-1800 mM approaching maturity representing berry Brix increasing from 15-20° to 22-28°, osmotic potential declining from -1.6 to -2.2 MPa to -2.2 to -3.2 MPa creating strong water import driving continued berry expansion 10-20% despite declining growth rates, glucose:fructose ratio stabilizing near unity (0.98-1.02) through balanced import and any differential metabolism equilibrating by this stage, and vacuolar pH maintained 2.8-3.4 providing optimal environment for anthocyanin stability (reds), flavor compound retention, and acid balance. ||Apoplastic sugar dynamics show: sucrose concentration in phloem sap arriving at berry 400-700 mM maintaining high delivery flux, apoplastic sucrose transiently accumulating 100-250 mM before invertase cleavage, resulting apoplastic hexoses 150-350 mM combined creating strong concentration gradient (apoplast 250-350 mM → cytoplasm maintained 60-100 mM) driving facilitated diffusion, and rapid turnover with residence time in apoplast <5-15 minutes indicating efficient cleavage and uptake preventing accumulation that could feedback-inhibit import. ||Cellular energy metabolism during rapid accumulation includes: enhanced respiration rates 1.2-2.5 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (compared to 0.8-1.5 μmol during initial accumulation) supporting ATP synthesis for membrane pumps and metabolic processes, respiratory quotient >1.2-1.4 indicating substrate-level metabolism dominates with fermentative pathways activated under hypoxic conditions in berry interior, ATP turnover estimated 40-80 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with 15-25% allocated to hexose transport-associated processes (H⁺-ATPases maintaining gradients, secondary active transport if present), and glycolytic flux 25-50 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ metabolizing portion of imported hexoses providing energy and metabolic intermediates while majority (70-85%) accumulates in vacuoles. ||Hormonal status during rapid accumulation demonstrates: ABA sustained at plateau 1400-2400 ng/g maintaining maximum ripening program activation without further increase, hexose signaling at maximum through hexokinase pathway with glucose-6-phosphate 25-50 μmol/g FW creating strong sugar-responsive gene activation, gibberellin and auxin remaining at post-growth minima removing any suppression, and ethylene showing cultivar patterns with some varieties maintaining slight elevation 0.4-1.2 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ potentially modulating ripening progression while others remain baseline suggesting ethylene not essential driver. ||Environmental effects on rapid accumulation rate inclu temperature critically important with optimal 26-30°C supporting maximum rates 3.8-4.5% Brix per week, cooler conditions 22-26°C reducing to 3.0-3.8% per week through slowed kinetics, heat stress 32-35°C impairing to 2.0-3.0% per week through enzyme denaturation and membrane disruption, extreme heat >35°C potentially reducing to <1.5% per week or causing arrest, light ensuring adequate source photosynthesis with shaded canopies potentially limiting accumulation 15-30% despite full berry transport capacity through substrate limitation, and water status with moderate deficit compatible maintaining rates while severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa stem ψ) may reduce through metabolic impairment. ||Cultivar variation in rapid accumulation characteristics shows: high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer potential 26-30° Brix, Sémillon 24-28°, Chenin Blanc 23-27°) achieve peak rates 3.8-4.8% per week over 2-3 week periods, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay 22-26°, Cabernet Sauvignon 23-27°, Merlot 22-26°) show 3.2-4.2% per week for 2-4 weeks, while lower-sugar types (Pinot Noir cool climates 20-24°, some table grapes 18-22°) display 2.5-3.5% per week for 3-5 weeks reflecting genetic differences in transporter expression, metabolic capacity, and developmental programming. ||Coordination with ripening completion shows: rapid sugar accumulation coincides with berry softening approaching final state (75-90% total reduction completed), color development (reds) reaching near-maximum anthocyanin levels (85-98% final), acid decline intensifying with malate consumption reaching 60-80% total degradation, and flavor/aroma compound synthesis peaking producing characteristic ripe fruit profiles indicating integrated maturation approaching harvest readiness. ||Quality implications of rapid accumulation inclu rate and duration determining final sugar levels and thus harvest timing and potential alcohol, uniformity across berries and clusters critical for ripening synchrony with heterogeneous rapid phase creating maturity variation, balance between sugar and other quality parameters (acid, pH, phenolics, flavor) defining optimal harvest window with ideal showing coordinated maturation, and environmental conditions during rapid phase substantially affecting wine style through effects on final composition. ||Viticultural management during rapid accumulation involves: irrigation minimized or terminated as berry water demand declines and concentration desirable though severe deficit risking metabolic impairment avoided, canopy health maintained ensuring continued photosynthesis supporting sugar export without leaf removal that could limit source capacity, disease monitoring critical as high-sugar berries attract insects and provide pathogen substrate, and harvest preparation initiated as rapid accumulation indicates approaching maturity requiring logistics readiness for picking when targets achieved.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 222-226 rapid accumulation phase || Ollat N, Gaudillère JP (1998) The effect of limiting leaf area during stage I of berry growth on development and composition of berries of Vitis vinifera L. cv. Cabernet Sauvignon Amer J Enol Vitic 49:251-258 source effects on accumulation || Dai ZW, Meddar M, Renaud C, Merlin I, Hilbert G, Delrot S, Gomès E (2014) Long-term in vitro culture of grape berries and its application to assess the effects of sugar supply on anthocyanin accumulation J Exp Bot 65:4665-4677 sugar accumulation regulation."
},

  "Sucrose_Cleavage_Activation": {
  "definition": "A Sucrose_Cleavage_Activation is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset comprising induction of invertase enzymes hydrolyzing phloem-delivered sucrose into glucose and fructose for cellular uptake and storage.",
  "alternative_term": "invertase gene induction | sucrose hydrolysis activation | disaccharide cleavage onset | hexose generation initiation |+ Invertase-Gen-Induktion | Saccharose-Hydrolyse-Aktivierung | Disaccharid-Spaltungs-Onset | Hexose-Generierungs-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Burgundy Chardonnay vineyard, sucrose cleavage activation was characterized in early August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when VvcwINV expression increased 68-fold, VvGIN1 showed 42-fold elevation, total invertase activity rose from 6.2 to 58.5 units/g FW, apoplastic hexoses measured 245 mM combined, hexose:sucrose ratio increased from 0.5 to 4.2, berry Brix 12.5° rising 2.1% per week, under moderate Burgundian conditions (daily high 24-27°C, night 14-16°C, adequate water enabling metabolic activation).",
  "editor_note": "Sucrose_Cleavage_Activation is distinguished from Phloem_Unloading_Activation by representing enzymatic hydrolysis rather than transport pathway change, from Hexose_Transport_Initiation by focusing on substrate production rather than product transport, and from rapid accumulation by showing activation rather than maximum rates. ||Invertase induction: cell wall 30-90 fold, vacuolar 20-70 fold. ||Activity increases 6-12 fold. ||Timing: 0-3 days with unloading activation. ||Hexose:sucrose ratio shift <0.6 to >3.0 diagnostic. ||Sucrose_Cleavage_Activation represents critical biochemical conversion enabling grape hexose accumulation character. || This activation occurs during veraison onset to early-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 0-3 days following or concurrent with phloem unloading activation, and is characterized by cell wall invertase gene expression (VvcwINV) increasing 30-90 fold above green berry baseline, vacuolar invertase genes (VvGIN1, VvGIN2) showing 20-70 fold elevation, combined invertase enzyme activities rising from pre-veraison <5-10 units/g FW to activation phase 40-90 units/g representing 6-12 fold enhancement, and hexose:sucrose ratio shifting from <0.6 to >3.0 indicating dominant sucrose hydrolysis. ||Molecular mechanisms of activation inclu VvcwINV gene family members (VvcwINV1, VvcwINV2, multiple isoforms) coordinately induced with peak expression during mid-veraison producing apoplastic enzyme (pH optimum 4.5-5.2, Km for sucrose 10-20 mM) that cleaves sucrose released during apoplastic unloading, vacuolar invertase genes VvGIN1/GIN2 upregulated producing intracellular enzyme (pH optimum 5.0-6.0, Km 15-35 mM) hydrolyzing any sucrose entering cells or synthesized de novo, regulatory control through sugar-responsive transcription factors and ABA signaling with invertase gene promoters containing sugar-response elements and ABA-responsive elements enabling coordinate induction with other ripening genes, and post-translational regulation including possible invertase inhibitor proteins modulating activity though grape inhibitors less well-characterized than in other species. ||Enzyme properties of activated invertases show: cell wall invertase optimal activity pH 4.5-5.2 matching apoplastic pH, thermal stability with activity maintained at berry temperatures 20-35°C though declining >35°C through denaturation, sucrose specificity with minimal activity on other substrates (raffinose, stachyose cleaved <5% rate of sucrose), product inhibition by glucose and fructose at >200-300 mM creating potential feedback regulation though typically not limiting given rapid hexose transport removing products, and kinetic parameters with Vmax 60-140 μmol sucrose cleaved g⁻¹ h⁻¹ at full activation adequate for observed sugar accumulation rates. ||Subcellular and tissue localization includes: cell wall invertase concentrated in phloem-mesocarp boundary zone particularly bundle sheath and adjacent parenchyma where apoplastic unloading occurs, immunolocalization detecting enzyme in cell walls and intercellular spaces consistent with apoplastic function, vacuolar invertase distributed throughout mesocarp cell vacuoles enabling intracellular sucrose hydrolysis, and developmental progression showing enzyme spreading from vascular regions into outer mesocarp zones as ripening advances. ||Substrate and product dynamics demonstrate: apoplastic sucrose concentration 100-250 mM transiently accumulating before cleavage providing substrate for cell wall invertase, resulting apoplastic hexoses 150-350 mM combined (glucose + fructose) creating concentration gradient for membrane transport, vacuolar sucrose maintained low <50-100 mM through invertase action and limited sucrose import as transporters downregulated, and glucose:fructose product ratio near unity (0.98-1.05) from invertase cleavage producing equimolar products though slight deviations possible from differential metabolism or transport. ||Hormonal and metabolic regulation of activation shows: ABA spike 50-200 → 600-1500 ng/g triggering invertase gene induction through ABA-responsive cis-elements, sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway creating positive feedback where initial hexose products activate genes supporting further accumulation, declining gibberellin removing suppression that may limit invertase expression during growth phases, and metabolic signals potentially including organic acid levels or ATP:ADP ratios modulating invertase activity or expression though mechanisms incompletely defined. ||Coordination with transport systems demonstrates: invertase activation synchronized with hexose transporter induction ensuring cleavage products efficiently imported preventing apoplastic accumulation, temporal sequence typically shows invertase genes induced 0-2 days before or concurrent with transporter genes establishing cleavage capacity as import capacity develops, and stoichiometric balance with invertase activity producing hexoses at rates matching or slightly exceeding transport capacity ensuring substrate availability without excessive accumulation. ||Environmental influences on activation inclu temperature affecting enzyme synthesis with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid activation while heat >32°C may impair through reduced gene expression or protein synthesis, light affecting developmental progression and potentially invertase gene expression through photoreceptor pathways though effects less direct than on photosynthesis and sugar supply, water status with moderate deficit potentially enhancing activation through elevated ABA while severe deficit may delay through general developmental arrest, and nutritional status particularly nitrogen affecting protein synthesis capacity for invertase production. ||Cultivar variation in activation characteristics shows: early-activating varieties (Chardonnay, Pinot Noir) inducing invertase 7-9 weeks post-flowering reaching 60-90 units/g activity within 4-6 days, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) activating 9-11 weeks with similar final activities achieved in 6-9 days, and late types (Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) showing activation 11-13 weeks requiring 8-12 days for full induction reflecting genetic differences in developmental timing and enzyme induction kinetics. ||Alternative sucrose metabolism through sucrose synthase shows: sucrose synthase (VvSUS genes) catalyzes reversible reaction sucrose + UDP ⇌ UDP-glucose + fructose, enzyme activity present throughout berry development including ripening though relative importance versus invertase shifts, sucrose synthase potentially important for producing UDP-glucose substrate for cellulose synthesis, starch synthesis (minor in grape), or other glucosylation reactions, and possible compartmentation with sucrose synthase cytoplasmic while invertases apoplastic or vacuolar enabling coexistence of pathways serving different functions. ||Physiological consequences of invertase activation inclu hexose accumulation versus sucrose enabling higher final sugar concentrations due to reduced osmotic coefficient and lower crystallization risk, glucose and fructose creating distinct flavor profiles versus sucrose contributing to characteristic grape and wine taste, hexose metabolism differently regulated than sucrose affecting respiratory and fermentative pathways during ripening and winemaking, and hexose:sucrose ratio diagnostic for ripening stage and cultivar enabling maturity assessment. ||Quality implications inclu invertase activity levels correlating with final sugar achieved (r² = 0.68-0.84) with inadequate activation limiting Brix potential, timing of activation relative to other ripening processes affecting compositional balance important for wine style, invertase activity potentially affecting wine fermentation kinetics through glucose:fructose ratio impacts on yeast sugar utilization, and residual invertase activity in harvested grapes potentially affecting must and wine composition through continued sucrose hydrolysis during processing. ||Research and practical applications involve: invertase activity assays providing biochemical marker for veraison onset and ripening progression, gene expression analysis tracking VvcwINV and VvGIN transcripts indicating developmental stage, inhibitor studies exploring potential viticultural interventions to modulate sugar accumulation timing or extent, and comparative analysis across cultivars and conditions revealing genetic and environmental control of this critical ripening process.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Davies C, Robinson SP (2000) Differential screening indicates a dramatic change in mRNA profiles during grape berry ripening Plant Physiol 122:803-812 invertase gene expression || Moscatello S, Famiani F, Proietti S, Farinelli D, Battistelli A (2011) Sucrose synthase dominates carbohydrate metabolism and relative growth rate in growing kiwifruit Sci Hort 128:197-205 sucrose metabolism comparison || Ranwala AP, Suematsu C, Masuda H (1998) Purification and characterization of two forms of invertase from grape Phytochem 49:331-337 enzyme characterization."
},

  "Active_Sugar_Loading": {
  "definition": "An Active_Sugar_Loading is a Veraison characterized by sustained maximum-efficiency operation of the sugar import pathway producing rapid hexose accumulation toward harvest-ready concentrations.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum sugar import flux | peak hexose loading | sustained rapid accumulation | high-efficiency sweetening |+ maximaler Zucker-Import-Fluss | Spitzen-Hexose-Beladung | anhaltende rapide Akkumulation | hoch-effiziente Süßung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, active sugar loading was documented over 18 days in late August to mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when Brix increased from 19.2° to 25.8° (average 3.8% per week), cell wall invertase activity averaged 102 units/g FW, hexose uptake rates 125 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, vacuolar concentration rose from 1050 to 1680 mM, berry fresh weight expanded 12% to final 1.95 g, under warm dry conditions (daily high 28-32°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.2 MPa concentrating sugars while maintaining metabolism).",
  "editor_note": "Active_Sugar_Loading is distinguished from Initial_Sugar_Increase by representing maximum sustained (3.0-4.5% Brix/week) rather than moderate (1.5-2.5%/week) rates, from Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation_Start by showing sustained maximum rather than onset, and from sugar plateau by exhibiting continued loading rather than declining rates. ||Duration 2-4 weeks BBCH 84-85. ||All pathway components operating near maximum. ||Temperature optimal 26-30°C critical. ||Active_Sugar_Loading represents culminating phase achieving harvest-ready sweetness defining wine alcohol potential and style. || This active loading phase occurs during mid-to-late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 84-85), typically 8-14 days post-accumulation onset, and is characterized by coordinated maximum operation: cell wall invertase activity 70-130 units/g FW producing glucose and fructose at 90-180 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from phloem-delivered sucrose, plasma membrane hexose transporters operating near Vmax with combined glucose and fructose uptake 80-150 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, tonoplast transport efficiently sequestering cytoplasmic hexoses into vacuoles at 60-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, and net berry sugar accumulation sustained at 3.0-4.5% Brix per week increasing total sugars from 160-220 g/L to 220-280 g/L (22-28° Brix) during 2-4 week active loading period. ||Molecular coordination during active loading shows: hexose transporter genes maintained at maximum steady-state expression (VvHT1/2/3/5/6 collectively 400-600 fold above green berry baseline when summed), invertase genes sustained at high levels (VvcwINV 80-120 fold, VvGIN 50-90 fold) ensuring continued sucrose cleavage, regulatory transcription factors (sugar-responsive VvMYB, VvbZIP, VvNAC families) at plateau expression coordinating pathway genes, and feedback mechanisms preventing overshooting with very high hexose levels (>1500-2000 mM vacuolar) beginning to reduce transporter expression in some cells approaching saturation providing homeostatic control. ||Cellular physiology during active loading demonstrates: mesocarp cell vacuoles occupying maximum volume fraction 94-97% of cell creating huge storage capacity (individual vacuoles 1.2-3.0 nL), vacuolar hexose concentrations rising 120-200 mM per week from 800-1100 mM toward final 1400-2200 mM (berry-dependent and cultivar-dependent maxima), cytoplasmic hexose maintained 55-95 mM through balanced import, metabolism, and vacuolar sequestration preventing accumulation that could inhibit continued uptake, and osmotic potential declining -0.15 to -0.25 MPa per week from -1.8 to -2.4 MPa toward final -2.4 to -3.4 MPa creating strong water potential gradient sustaining berry expansion 8-15% during active loading despite declining growth rates. ||Phloem transport supporting active loading requires: adequate source leaf photosynthesis providing sucrose export with healthy canopies producing 8-15 g photosynthate per m² leaf area per day, phloem loading in leaves and transport through vine vascular system delivering sucrose to berries at 200-400 mg per berry per day depending on berry size and accumulation rate, sieve tube pressure gradients maintained -0.5 to -1.2 MPa from leaves to berries driving mass flow, and vine-level source-sink balance with typical leaf area: fruit weight ratios 12-18 cm² per g supporting active loading without source limitation. ||Apoplastic dynamics during active loading show: continuous sucrose delivery to berry apoplast creating transient concentrations 120-280 mM before invertase cleavage, rapid enzymatic turnover producing glucose and fructose with residence time 3-10 minutes before membrane transport, resulting apoplastic hexoses 180-400 mM combined maintaining strong concentration gradient favoring import (apoplast 280-400 mM → cytoplasm 60-90 mM = 220-340 mM gradient), and efficient coupling between cleavage and transport preventing apoplastic accumulation that could feedback-inhibit either process. ||Energy metabolism supporting active loading includes: enhanced respiration 1.5-2.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ providing ATP for membrane pumps and biosynthetic processes, respiratory quotient >1.2-1.5 indicating substrate-level metabolism dominates with fermentative activity particularly in berry interior where O₂ diffusion limits aerobic respiration, ATP production estimated 50-95 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with 20-30% allocated to transport-associated processes including H⁺-ATPases maintaining electrochemical gradients essential for transport function, and glycolytic flux metabolizing 20-40% of imported hexoses providing energy and biosynthetic precursors while 60-80% accumulates in vacuoles as storage sugars. ||Hormonal regulation during active loading demonstrates: ABA sustained at ripening plateau 1500-2600 ng/g maintaining maximum program activation, hexose signaling maximized through hexokinase pathway with glucose-6-phosphate 30-60 μmol/g FW creating strong feedback amplification of sugar-responsive genes, gibberellin and auxin at post-growth minima removing any suppressive effects, and ethylene showing cultivar-dependent patterns with some varieties 0.5-1.5 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ potentially fine-tuning ripening while others baseline suggesting non-essential role. ||Environmental modulation of active loading shows: temperature critically important with optimal 26-30°C supporting maximum rates 4.0-4.8% Brix per week, moderate warmth 23-26°C enabling 3.2-4.2% per week, cooler conditions 20-23°C reducing to 2.5-3.5% per week through slowed kinetics, heat stress 32-36°C impairing to 1.8-3.0% per week through enzyme denaturation and membrane dysfunction, and extreme heat >36°C potentially arresting loading <1.0% per week or completely through catastrophic cellular disruption. ||Light effects on active loading operate primarily through source photosynthesis with adequate canopy light exposure essential for providing sucrose substrate, shaded canopies potentially limiting loading 20-40% despite full berry import capacity through substrate limitation, leaf removal during active loading requiring careful balance between cluster exposure benefits and photosynthetic capacity maintenance, and canopy architecture optimization critical for maximizing both fruit microclimate and source leaf productivity. ||Water relations influence shows: moderate deficit (stem ψ -0.9 to -1.4 MPa) compatible with active loading and potentially enhancing concentration through reduced berry expansion, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) impairing loading 30-60% through general metabolic limitation, osmotic stress effects complex with berry water potential -2.0 to -3.0 MPa creating strong gradient for water import requiring adequate vine water status to sustain, and irrigation management during active loading balancing concentration benefits of deficit against metabolic maintenance requiring adequate water. ||Cultivar variation in active loading characteristics demonstrates: high-sugar cultivars (potential final 25-30° Brix) maintain active loading 4.2-5.0% Brix per week for 2-3 weeks, moderate varieties (final 22-26° Brix) show 3.5-4.5% per week for 2.5-4 weeks, and lower-sugar types (final 19-23° Brix) display 2.8-3.8% per week for 3-5 weeks reflecting genetic differences in loading duration and intensity more than maximum rate capabilities. ||Coordination with ripening completion shows: active sugar loading coincides with final berry softening (approaching asymptotic minimum firmness), color development completing in reds (anthocyanins reaching 90-100% final levels), acid decline approaching endpoint with malate near minimum sustainable levels, and flavor/aroma maturation intensifying creating integrated ripeness suitable for harvest timing decisions. ||Quality implications of active loading inclu loading rate and duration critically determining final Brix and thus wine alcohol potential with faster sustained loading enabling higher sugar or earlier harvest at target levels, uniformity of active loading across berries and clusters essential for maturity synchrony affecting harvest timing and compositional consistency, balance between sugar and other quality parameters (phenolics, acids, flavors) defining optimal harvest window requiring integration of multiple maturity indices, and environmental conditions during active loading substantially affecting wine style through effects on final berry composition. ||Viticultural management during active loading involves: irrigation typically minimized or terminated unless severe stress developing recognizing berry water demand declines and concentration generally desirable, canopy management ensuring source leaf health and adequate light for photosynthesis without excessive fruit exposure causing heat stress, disease monitoring critical as high-sugar berries increasingly attractive to pests and pathogens, and harvest preparation advancing with active loading indicating approaching maturity requiring logistics, equipment, and labor readiness.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 223-228 active sugar accumulation and maturity || Palliotti A, Tombesi S, Silvestroni O, Lanari V, Gatti M, Poni S (2014) Changes in vineyard establishment and canopy management urged by earlier climate-related grape ripening Sci Hort 178:43-54 environmental effects on accumulation || Conde C, Silva P, Fontes N, Dias ACP, Tavares RM, Sousa MJ, Agasse A, Delrot S, Gerós H (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development and fruit and wine quality Food Res Intl 40:1-13 comprehensive ripening biochemistry."
},

  "Apoplastic_Unloading_Intensification": {
  "definition": "An Apoplastic_Unloading_Intensification is an Active_Sugar_Loading involving amplification of sucrose release into the cell wall space and enzymatic cleavage to hexoses producing increasing delivery rate to mesocarp cells.",
  "alternative_term": "enhanced apoplastic sucrose delivery | amplified cell wall sugar release | progressive unloading increase | intensified extracellular hexose production |+ verstärkte apoplastische Saccharose-Lieferung | amplifizierte Zellwand-Zucker-Freisetzung | progressive Entladungs-Zunahme | intensivierte extrazelluläre Hexose-Produktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Chardonnay vineyard, apoplastic unloading intensification was tracked over 7 days in mid-August Year N+1 (BBCH 84) when cell wall invertase activity increased from 35 to 88 units/g FW, VvcwINV expression rose from 55-fold to 105-fold, apoplastic hexose concentrations measured 340 mM combined (from 195 mM at activation), berry Brix accelerated from 13.8° to 18.5° (2.9% per week increasing to 4.1% per week), under warm conditions (daily high 27-30°C, adequate vine water status stem ψ -0.9 MPa supporting phloem function).",
  "editor_note": "Apoplastic_Unloading_Intensification is distinguished from Phloem_Unloading_Activation by representing amplification (2-4 fold) rather than initiation, from Sucrose_Cleavage_Activation by focusing on unloading flux rather than enzyme activation, and from Active_Sugar_Loading by showing progressive increase rather than sustained maximum. ||Cell wall invertase: 20-40 → 60-120 units/g FW. ||Apoplastic hexoses: 150-250 → 250-450 mM. ||Duration 5-10 days BBCH 83-84. ||Symplastic connectivity declines to <8-15%. ||Apoplastic_Unloading_Intensification represents critical amplification step creating substrate flux supporting rapid sugar accumulation. || This intensification occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 3-8 days following initial phloem unloading activation, and is characterized by apoplastic sucrose flux increasing from initial activation 60-120 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to intensification peak 120-250 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 2-4 fold enhancement, cell wall invertase activity rising from activation 20-40 units/g FW to intensification 60-120 units/g through continued gene expression and protein accumulation, and resulting apoplastic hexose concentrations increasing from 150-250 mM to 250-450 mM combined glucose and fructose creating stronger concentration gradients for membrane transport. ||Mechanisms underlying intensification inclu continued plasmodesmata closure or conductance reduction with callose deposition increasing and symplastic connectivity declining from activation 15-25% to intensification <8-15% measured by tracer studies forcing greater proportion of unloading through apoplastic pathway, enhanced phloem delivery as source leaf photosynthesis increases and vascular development completes creating greater substrate flux into berry apoplast, progressive induction of cell wall invertase with VvcwINV gene expression reaching 90-120% of maximum (from 50-70% at activation) and protein levels similarly increasing through continued synthesis exceeding degradation, and apoplastic space potentially expanding through cell wall modifications and middle lamella changes increasing volume available for sucrose-hexose pool. ||Gene expression dynamics during intensification demonstrate: VvcwINV genes showing continued elevation from 40-60 fold at activation to 90-130 fold at intensification peak with some cultivars expressing multiple isoforms creating additive effects, transcriptional regulation through sugar-responsive elements activated by increasing hexose levels creating positive feedback amplification, ABA signaling sustained at high levels (1200-2200 ng/g) maintaining ripening program activation, and coordinated expression with hexose transporter genes ensuring cleavage capacity matched by import capability preventing apoplastic hexose accumulation. ||Enzyme kinetics during intensification show: cell wall invertase Vmax increasing from 50-90 μmol sucrose cleaved g⁻¹ h⁻¹ at activation to 110-220 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ at intensification through higher enzyme concentration, Km for sucrose remaining relatively constant 12-22 mM indicating increased capacity rather than affinity changes, pH optimum 4.4-5.3 matching apoplastic pH throughout intensification maintaining catalytic efficiency, and thermal stability adequate for berry temperatures encountered (20-35°C) though activity declining >35°C providing temperature sensitivity that may limit sugar accumulation under heat stress. ||Apoplastic compartment dynamics show: sucrose concentration in apoplast showing transient increases during peak delivery periods potentially reaching 180-350 mM before invertase cleavage, turnover kinetics with half-life 4-12 minutes indicating rapid cleavage and transport preventing sustained accumulation, resulting glucose and fructose concentrations 250-450 mM combined creating 200-380 mM concentration gradient to cytoplasm (maintained 60-90 mM) driving facilitated diffusion, and spatial distribution with highest concentrations near phloem unloading zones gradually declining toward peripheral mesocarp reflecting diffusion and transport gradients. ||Cellular responses to intensification inclu mesocarp cells adjacent to vascular bundles showing most intense import activity with vacuolar hexose concentrations reaching 1000-1400 mM during intensification compared to 600-900 mM in peripheral cells, spatial gradient in sugar accumulation creating ripening progression from berry center outward potentially affecting harvest maturity uniformity, and cell wall mechanical properties potentially affected by high apoplastic sugar concentrations creating osmotic effects though this aspect poorly studied. ||Phloem physiology supporting intensification requires: sieve tube pressure maintained 0.6-1.3 MPa in source leaves declining to -0.3 to -0.6 MPa in berry vascular tissue creating 0.9-1.9 MPa gradient driving mass flow, sucrose concentration in sieve sap 500-850 mM in loading zones declining to 350-600 mM at unloading sites through dilution and unloading, mass flow velocity 20-50 cm per hour in vine phloem delivering sucrose at rates matching berry demand, and phloem structure with companion cells and sieve elements maintaining functionality through ripening despite general tissue softening and structural changes. ||Source-sink relationships during intensification demonstrate: adequate source leaf area essential with typical 14-18 cm² per g berry FW at this stage supporting intensification without limitation, leaf photosynthetic capacity 8-16 μmol CO₂ m⁻² s⁻¹ providing carbon for sucrose synthesis and export, source-sink distance effects with berries closer to source leaves potentially showing earlier or more intense unloading though vine transport capacity generally adequate for uniform supply, and competition among sinks (vegetative growth declining, other berry clusters, root growth) with berries becoming increasingly dominant sink during ripening concentrating resource allocation toward fruit. ||Environmental influences on intensification inclu temperature affecting multiple steps with optimal 25-29°C supporting maximum unloading and cleavage rates, cooler conditions 20-25°C reducing intensification rate and potentially extending duration to achieve similar final levels, heat stress >31°C impairing intensification through reduced phloem transport, enzyme denaturation, and membrane dysfunction potentially limiting subsequent sugar accumulation even if conditions improve, and diurnal temperature effects with cooler nights potentially beneficial for phloem transport efficiency versus constant warm temperatures. ||Water relations effects show: moderate deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) compatible with intensification and potentially enhancing through elevated ABA maintaining gene expression, adequate vine water status required for phloem transport with severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) impairing phloem function reducing sucrose delivery to apoplast, osmotic relationships complex with high apoplastic sugar creating strong osmotic potential affecting water distribution between symplast, apoplast, and xylem, and berry water import driven largely by vacuolar sugar accumulation creating total berry water potential -1.8 to -2.8 MPa attracting water from vine xylem. ||Cultivar variation in intensification characteristics shows: rapidly-intensifying varieties achieving maximum unloading within 5-7 days of activation with cell wall invertase reaching 90-120 units/g, moderate cultivars requiring 7-10 days to peak with 70-100 units/g final activity, and slower types needing 10-14 days achieving 60-90 units/g reflecting genetic differences in gene induction kinetics and enzyme synthesis capacity. ||Coordination with transport intensification demonstrates: apoplastic unloading intensification synchronized with hexose transporter upregulation ensuring products of sucrose cleavage efficiently imported, temporal relationship typically shows unloading intensification leading transporter induction by 1-2 days establishing substrate before maximum import capacity, and feedback regulation where high apoplastic hexoses may enhance transporter expression through sugar sensing mechanisms creating feed-forward amplification. ||Quality implications of intensification inclu rate and completeness of intensification determining maximum sugar accumulation rates achievable during ripening, inadequate intensification limiting final Brix despite adequate source photosynthesis through bottleneck in unloading-cleavage step, timing relative to other ripening processes affecting compositional balance with early intense unloading potentially producing high-sugar fruit before adequate phenolic or flavor development, and environmental stresses during intensification creating disproportionate effects on final composition through impairment of critical developmental step. ||Viticultural management during intensification involves: ensuring adequate vine water status supporting phloem function without excess that could dilute berries, maintaining canopy health for continued photosynthesis and sucrose supply, avoiding environmental stresses particularly heat and severe drought that can irreversibly impair intensification, and monitoring intensification progress through berry sampling tracking Brix increases indicating successful amplification of sugar import pathway.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Zhang XY, Wang XL, Wang XF, Xia GH, Pan QH, Fan RC, Wu FQ, Yu XC, Zhang DP (2006) A shift of phloem unloading from symplasmic to apoplasmic pathway is involved in developmental onset of ripening in grape berry Plant Physiol 142:220-232 unloading intensification || Davies C, Wolf T, Robinson SP (1999) Three putative sucrose transporters are differentially expressed in grapevine tissues Plant Sci 147:93-100 transport coordination || Lecourieux F, Kappel C, Lecourieux D, Serrano A, Torres E, Arce-Johnson P, Delrot S (2014) An update on sugar transport and signaling in grapevine J Exp Bot 65:821-832 comprehensive sugar transport regulation."
},

  "Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate is an Active_Sugar_Loading characterized by maximum velocity hexose uptake into mesocarp cells with all components of the sugar import pathway at peak efficiency.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum hexose uptake velocity | fastest sugar import flux | peak accumulation rate | maximum sweetening velocity |+ maximale Hexose-Aufnahme-Geschwindigkeit | schnellster Zucker-Import-Fluss | Spitzen-Akkumulations-Rate | maximale Süßungs-Geschwindigkeit",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Stellenbosch Chenin Blanc vineyard in South Africa, peak sugar import rate was measured during 12 days in late February Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when berry Brix increased from 20.5° to 26.8° (average 4.5% per week), hexose import calculated 135 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, cell wall invertase 112 units/g FW, vacuolar hexose rose from 1180 to 1695 mM, berry fresh weight 1.88 g expanding 11%, under optimal warm dry conditions (daily high 28-31°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.15 MPa, healthy canopy supporting maximum photosynthesis).",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate is distinguished from Initial_Sugar_Increase by representing maximum (3.5-5.0% Brix/week, 90-170 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹) rather than moderate (1.5-2.5% Brix/week) rates, from Rapid_Sugar_Accumulation_Start by showing sustained peak rather than onset, and from sugar plateau by exhibiting maximum rather than declining rates. ||Duration 10-20 days BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature optimum 26-30°C critical. ||All pathway components saturated. ||Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate represents culminating metabolic state achieving harvest-ready sweetness and determining wine alcohol potential. || This peak rate occurs during mid-to-late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 84-85), typically 10-16 days post-sugar accumulation onset, and is characterized by net berry hexose import reaching 90-170 μmol combined glucose and fructose per g fresh weight per hour representing integration of apoplastic delivery (cell wall invertase producing 100-200 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from phloem sucrose), plasma membrane transport (facilitated diffusion 80-150 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), tonoplast sequestration (60-120 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ into vacuoles), and metabolic utilization (20-40 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ for respiration and biosynthesis), resulting in vacuolar hexose concentration increasing 140-220 mM per week from 900-1200 mM toward final cultivar-specific maxima 1400-2200 mM. ||Molecular basis of peak rate achievement includes: hexose transporter genes (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) expressed at absolute maximum levels (100-150 fold above green berry when summed) producing saturating membrane protein concentrations estimated 8-15% of total plasma membrane protein, cell wall invertase at maximum activity 80-140 units/g fresh weight catalyzing sucrose cleavage without substrate limitation, regulatory transcription factors sustaining maximum expression coordinating all pathway components, and hormonal signals (ABA 1600-2800 ng/g, hexose through hexokinase pathway) maintaining ripening program at peak activation. ||Transport kinetics at peak rate demonstrate: plasma membrane hexose uptake operating near Vmax with glucose transport 75-120 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (from pre-veraison 3-8 μmol) representing 12-20 fold enhancement, fructose transport 65-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ similarly maximized, combined hexose uptake 140-230 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ limited primarily by apoplastic substrate availability and tonoplast clearing capacity rather than membrane transport per se, and Km values unchanged (glucose 1.5-3.0 mM, fructose 5-12 mM) confirming capacity rather than affinity increases underlie rate enhancement. ||Apoplastic dynamics supporting peak rate show: sucrose delivery from phloem 180-350 mg per berry per day (depending on berry size 1.5-2.5 g) maintaining apoplastic substrate, invertase rapidly cleaving sucrose with turnover time 3-8 minutes preventing accumulation that could feedback-inhibit, resulting apoplastic hexoses 250-500 mM combined creating strong concentration gradient (apoplast 350-500 mM → cytoplasm 60-90 mM = 260-440 mM gradient) driving maximal facilitated diffusion flux, and efficient coupling between cleavage, uptake, and vacuolar sequestration maintaining steady-state apoplastic concentrations without excessive accumulation or depletion. ||Vacuolar accumulation at peak rate involves: tonoplast transport efficiently clearing cytoplasmic hexoses at 70-130 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ preventing buildup that could reduce plasma membrane uptake gradient, vacuolar concentrations rising 150-220 mM per week during peak representing berry Brix increases 3.2-4.8% per week, osmotic potential declining -0.18 to -0.28 MPa per week from -2.0 to -2.6 MPa toward final -2.6 to -3.4 MPa creating water potential gradient sustaining berry expansion 8-15% during peak period, and glucose:fructose ratio in vacuoles maintaining near unity 0.98-1.04 through balanced transport and any differential metabolism equilibrating. ||Cellular energy requirements at peak rate inclu enhanced respiration 1.8-3.2 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ supporting ATP synthesis for membrane pumps and metabolism, respiratory quotient >1.3-1.6 indicating substrate-level and fermentative metabolism dominate particularly in berry interior, ATP turnover 60-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with 25-35% allocated to transport-associated processes (H⁺-ATPases maintaining electrochemical gradients, biosynthesis supporting transporter protein turnover), and glycolytic flux 30-60 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ metabolizing portion of imported hexoses while 65-75% accumulates in vacuoles. ||Environmental conditions enabling peak rate achievement require: temperature optimum 26-30°C supporting maximum enzyme activities, membrane fluidity, and metabolic rates producing highest import velocities 4.2-5.0% Brix per week, moderate warmth 23-26°C enabling 3.5-4.5% per week still approaching peak though kinetically slower, cooler conditions 20-23°C reducing to 2.8-3.8% per week through decreased reaction rates, heat stress 32-35°C impairing peak 30-50% reducing to 2.0-3.0% per week through enzyme denaturation and membrane disruption, and extreme heat >35°C potentially preventing peak achievement reducing to <1.5% per week or causing arrest. ||Light effects operate primarily through source photosynthesis with adequate canopy illumination essential for producing sucrose substrate supporting peak import, shaded canopies potentially limiting peak rate 25-45% despite full berry import capacity through substrate limitation from insufficient photosynthesis, and cluster-level light exposure having minimal direct effects on peak rate once substrate supply adequate though excessive radiation combined with heat can impair through berry temperature stress. ||Water relations influences show: adequate vine water status essential for phloem transport delivering sucrose substrate with stem water potential -0.6 to -1.2 MPa compatible with peak rates, moderate deficit -1.0 to -1.4 MPa maintaining peak rates and potentially enhancing concentration through reduced berry expansion, severe deficit <-1.5 MPa impairing peak 40-70% through reduced phloem function and general metabolic limitation, and osmotic relationships complex with high berry sugar creating -2.2 to -3.0 MPa vacuolar osmotic potential requiring adequate vine water status to sustain gradient for continued import. ||Cultivar variation in peak rate characteristics demonstrates: high-Brix cultivars (Gewürztraminer, Sémillon potential 26-30° Brix) achieve peak rates 4.5-5.5% Brix per week over 2-3 weeks importing 110-170 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹, moderate varieties (Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon 22-26° Brix) show 3.8-4.8% per week for 2.5-3.5 weeks with 90-140 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, and lower-sugar types (Pinot Noir cool climates 20-24° Brix) display 3.0-4.0% per week for 3-4 weeks importing 70-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ reflecting genetic differences in transporter capacity, enzyme levels, and metabolic programming. ||Temporal dynamics of peak rate show: rate increasing from initial accumulation 1.5-2.5% Brix per week to enhancement 2.5-3.5% per week to peak 3.5-5.0% per week over 8-12 days, peak sustained 10-20 days depending on cultivar and conditions, then declining to late ripening 1.5-3.0% per week and plateau <0.5-1.5% per week as vacuolar concentrations approach equilibrium with phloem supply and feedback regulation limits further uptake. ||Coordination with ripening completion shows: peak sugar import coincides with final berry softening approaching asymptotic firmness, color development completing in reds with anthocyanins reaching 92-100% final levels, acid decline approaching minimum sustainable levels with malate nearly depleted, and flavor/aroma compound synthesis intensifying creating integrated maturation suitable for harvest timing decisions. ||Quality implications of peak rate inclu maximum rate achieved and duration sustained critically determining final sugar levels and thus harvest Brix and wine alcohol potential, uniformity of peak rate across berries and clusters affecting maturity synchrony and harvest composition consistency, environmental optimization during peak maximizing final quality through balanced sugar with acid and phenolic development, and stress avoidance during peak essential as impairment during this critical window disproportionately reduces final sugar even if conditions later improve. ||Viticultural management during peak rate involves: ensuring adequate vine water status supporting phloem function and metabolism without excess diluting berries, maintaining canopy health for continued photosynthesis providing sucrose substrate, avoiding environmental stresses particularly heat and severe drought that can irreversibly impair peak achievement, disease monitoring critical as high-sugar berries increasingly vulnerable to pathogens, and harvest preparation advancing as peak rate indicates approaching maturity requiring readiness for picking when targets achieved. ||Monitoring peak rate provides harvest forecasting: weekly Brix sampling tracking maximum accumulation rates enabling projection of harvest timing, comparison of observed versus expected peak rates revealing environmental or management limitations requiring attention, spatial variation in peak rates across vineyard identifying heterogeneity affecting harvest decisions, and integration with other maturity parameters ensuring sugar peak synchronized with desired acid, pH, phenolic, and flavor development for optimal wine quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 223-228 peak sugar accumulation || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 rate variation || Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 environmental effects on rates."
},

  "Maximum_Phloem_Delivery": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Phloem_Delivery is an Active_Sugar_Loading characterized by peak rate of sucrose transport from source leaves through the vine vascular system to ripening berries with phloem loading, transport, and unloading at optimal capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "peak sucrose transport | maximum vascular delivery | optimal phloem flux | peak substrate supply |+ Spitzen-Saccharose-Transport | maximale vaskuläre Lieferung | optimaler Phloem-Fluss | Spitzen-Substrat-Versorgung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Bordeaux Merlot vineyard, maximum phloem delivery was estimated during 14 days in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when berry Brix increased 4.1% per week requiring approximately 240 mg sucrose per berry per day (berry size 1.85 g), vine-level delivery calculated 185 g sucrose per vine per day (crop load 9.2 kg, 4950 berries per vine), source photosynthesis 14.2 g CO₂ per vine per day (canopy 11.5 m² healthy leaf area), under favorable conditions (daily high 26-29°C, stem ψ -0.95 MPa, full sun 10-12 h).",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Phloem_Delivery is distinguished from Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate by representing vascular supply rather than cellular uptake, from Active_Sugar_Loading by focusing on transport rather than accumulation mechanism, and from initial delivery by showing maximum (180-400 mg/berry/day) rather than moderate rates. ||Timing coincides with peak import BBCH 84-85. ||Source capacity and transport efficiency both critical. ||Temperature optimum 24-28°C. ||Adequate water status essential. ||Maximum_Phloem_Delivery represents critical source-sink integration determining achievable berry sweetness. || This maximum delivery occurs during mid-to-late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 84-85), coinciding with peak sugar import rates, and is characterized by sucrose mass flow to individual berries reaching 180-400 mg sucrose per berry per day (depending on berry size 1.4-2.8 g final weight) representing phloem sap delivery 0.8-2.2 mL per berry per day at typical sieve tube sucrose concentrations 400-700 mM, vine-level total berry sucrose import 120-350 g per vine per day (for typical crop loads 6-12 kg depending on variety and management), and source-sink carbon flow directing 70-85% of daily photosynthate to ripening fruit during this peak period. ||Phloem anatomy supporting maximum delivery includes: mature sieve tube-companion cell complexes with fully differentiated structure, sieve tube lumens 12-25 μm diameter providing adequate cross-sectional area for mass flow, sieve plates with pores 1.5-4.0 μm diameter offering minimal resistance to bulk flow, companion cells maintaining metabolic support for sieve elements including ATP synthesis and protein turnover, and vascular bundle organization with adequate phloem tissue area relative to fruit load enabling parallel pathways reducing flow resistance. ||Phloem loading in source leaves at maximum includes: mesophyll photosynthesis producing triose phosphates exported to phloem at 6-12 μmol CO₂ fixed m⁻² leaf area s⁻¹ under optimal conditions, sucrose synthesis in intermediary cells or companion cells concentrating sugar from 50-150 mM mesophyll to 400-800 mM phloem sap through active H⁺-coupled symport, loading polymer trap mechanisms in some species potentially contributing to concentration though grapevine primarily uses apoplastic loading, and source leaf capacity with typical 8-12 m² canopy area per vine producing 80-160 g sucrose per day supporting berry demand during maximum delivery. ||Phloem transport mechanics involve: pressure flow mass flow driven by osmotic gradients with source turgor 0.8-1.5 MPa declining to sink turgor -0.2 to -0.6 MPa creating 1.0-2.1 MPa pressure difference driving flow, sieve tube sap velocity 25-60 cm per hour in vine phloem transporting sucrose from leaves to berries within 2-6 hours depending on distance, viscosity of phloem sap ~1.5-3.0 times water viscosity from high sucrose concentration creating flow resistance requiring adequate pressure differential, and temperature effects with optimal 22-28°C supporting maximum flow while cooler temperatures increasing viscosity and heat stress potentially disrupting membrane function affecting loading and unloading. ||Phloem unloading at berry during maximum delivery shows: apoplastic pathway dominant with >85-95% of unloading releasing sucrose into cell wall space (compared to <40% symplastic pre-veraison), unloading zone concentrated in phloem-mesocarp boundary particularly bundle sheath and adjacent 3-5 cell layers where invertase activity highest, transient apoplastic sucrose accumulation 150-300 mM before rapid cleavage by cell wall invertase (80-140 units/g FW producing 120-250 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹), and efficient coupling between delivery and utilization preventing apoplastic buildup that could reduce unloading gradient. ||Source-sink relationships at maximum delivery demonstrate: source leaf area per fruit weight ratio critical with 13-18 cm² leaf per g berry FW optimal for supporting maximum delivery without limitation, source capacity determined by total canopy photosynthesis with healthy canopies fixing 12-25 g CO₂ per vine per day producing 8-17 g sucrose per vine per day adequate for typical crop loads, sink demand from ripening berries increasing exponentially during veraison from 20-40 g sucrose per vine per day early phase to 120-350 g per vine per day at maximum becoming dominant carbon sink, and competition among sinks with vegetative growth largely ceased, roots maintaining minimal allocation, and berries receiving 75-90% of daily photosynthate during peak ripening. ||Hormonal regulation of phloem delivery includes: source leaf abscisic acid potentially affecting stomatal conductance and photosynthesis though effects complex, cytokinins from roots declining during ripening potentially affecting source-sink partitioning, auxin signaling in phloem pathway possibly affecting transport efficiency though mechanisms poorly understood, and sink ABA (1600-2800 ng/g berry) strongly enhancing unloading through effects on plasmodesmata closure, invertase expression, and transporter induction creating strong sink strength amplifying delivery. ||Environmental factors affecting maximum delivery show: temperature with optimal 24-28°C supporting maximum photosynthesis in source leaves and phloem transport efficiency, heat stress >32°C reducing delivery through impaired photosynthesis (stomatal closure, photoinhibition), reduced phloem loading, or disrupted transport, cool conditions <20°C limiting delivery through reduced photosynthesis and increased phloem sap viscosity slowing flow, light intensity and duration directly affecting source photosynthesis with high light (>800-1200 μmol photons m⁻² s⁻¹) saturating photosynthesis producing maximum sucrose for export, and photoperiod with longer days (14-16 h light in temperate summers) providing extended photosynthesis period increasing daily carbon fixation supporting delivery. ||Water status effects on delivery inclu adequate vine water status essential with stem water potential -0.5 to -1.1 MPa supporting maximum phloem function, moderate deficit -1.0 to -1.4 MPa potentially compatible maintaining delivery though photosynthesis may decline 15-30% slightly limiting substrate, severe deficit <-1.5 MPa substantially impairing delivery 40-70% through reduced photosynthesis, impaired phloem loading and transport, and potential embolism in xylem affecting whole-plant water relations, and turgor maintenance in phloem pathway critical with adequate hydration required for pressure flow mechanism. ||Nutritional influences on delivery show: adequate nitrogen supporting photosynthetic capacity and enzyme synthesis with N-deficient vines showing 25-45% reduced photosynthesis limiting sucrose production, potassium important for phloem loading and transport with K deficiency potentially reducing delivery though mechanisms incompletely defined, phosphorus required for photosynthetic phosphorylation and ATP synthesis supporting both source and sink processes, and general nutrient balance important for maintaining healthy productive canopy capable of maximum photosynthesis. ||Cultivar variation in maximum delivery capacity reflects: genetic differences in photosynthetic efficiency, canopy architecture, vascular anatomy, and sink strength with high-Brix cultivars typically showing enhanced delivery capacity through larger or more efficient vascular systems and stronger sink signals, moderate varieties displaying intermediate delivery adequate for typical final sugars 22-26° Brix, and table grape varieties optimized for large berry size potentially showing different delivery characteristics supporting expansion over maximum sugar concentration. ||Viticultural management optimizing delivery includes: canopy management ensuring adequate healthy leaf area (typically 10-15 m² per vine for 8-12 kg crop) without excessive shading reducing photosynthetic efficiency, leaf removal during ripening requiring balance between cluster exposure benefits and maintaining adequate source capacity with >30-40% leaf area removal potentially limiting delivery, irrigation management maintaining adequate vine water status supporting phloem function without excess promoting vegetative growth competing with fruit, crop load adjustment to match source capacity with typical 0.8-1.2 kg fruit per m² leaf area enabling maximum delivery without source limitation, and disease control maintaining healthy foliage essential for sustained photosynthesis and sucrose export. ||Quality implications of maximum delivery inclu delivery capacity fundamentally determines achievable final sugar with inadequate delivery limiting Brix regardless of berry sink capacity, timing and duration of maximum delivery affecting harvest window and quality with sustained delivery enabling higher final sugars or earlier harvest at target levels, uniformity of delivery across vines and vineyard zones affecting maturity variation requiring management attention, and balance between delivery and other quality parameters with excessive delivery potentially producing high-sugar fruit before adequate flavor or phenolic development creating harvest timing challenges. ||Monitoring delivery through vine physiology provides management insights: leaf photosynthesis measurements indicating source capacity, phloem sap analysis revealing sucrose concentration and transport rates though technically challenging, berry sugar accumulation rates indirectly indicating delivery adequacy, and vine water status monitoring ensuring adequate hydration supporting phloem function throughout peak delivery period.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 156-162, 223-225 phloem transport and sugar accumulation || Ollat N, Gaudillère JP (1998) The effect of limiting leaf area during stage I of berry growth on development and composition of berries of Vitis vinifera L. cv. Cabernet Sauvignon Amer J Enol Vitic 49:251-258 source-sink relationships || Patrick JW (1997) Phloem unloading:sieve element unloading and post-sieve element transport Annu Rev Plant Physiol Plant Mol Biol 48:191-222 unloading mechanisms."
},

  "Rapid_Brix_Increase": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Brix_Increase is an Active_Sugar_Loading marked by the steepest gradient of soluble solids accumulation in berry pulp during ripening.",
  "alternative_term": "steep soluble solids increase | accelerated sweetening | maximum Brix elevation rate | rapid sugar concentration rise |+ steiler löslicher Feststoff-Anstieg | beschleunigte Süßung | maximale Brix-Erhöhungs-Rate | rapider Zucker-Konzentrations-Anstieg",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Zinfandel vineyard, rapid Brix increase was documented over 16 days in late August to early September Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when berry Brix rose from 18.3° to 27.5° (average 4.6% per week peak rate), hexose accumulation 195 mM per week in vacuoles, berry fresh weight increased 14% to 2.1 g through osmotic water import, titratable acidity declined from 8.2 to 5.8 g/L, anthocyanins reached 2150 mg/kg skin, under warm conditions (daily high 30-33°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.25 MPa concentrating sugars).",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Brix_Increase is distinguished from Initial_Sugar_Increase by representing maximum (3.2-5.0% per week) rather than moderate (1.5-2.8%) rates, from Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate by focusing on concentration measurement rather than metabolic flux, and from sugar plateau by showing maximum rather than declining rates. ||Duration 8-18 days BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature optimum 26-30°C. ||Moderate deficit can enhance concentration. ||Rapid_Brix_Increase represents practical quality metric determining harvest timing and wine alcohol potential. || This rapid increase occurs during mid-to-late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 84-85), typically 8-18 days duration depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by berry Brix rising from 14-20° at onset to 22-28° at conclusion representing 3.2-5.0% increase per week (compared to pre-rapid phase 1.5-2.8% per week and post-rapid plateau <0.8-1.8% per week), total dissolved solids concentration increasing 60-90 g/L per week, and hexose accumulation rates 140-250 mM per week in vacuoles creating the characteristic sweetness defining ripe grapes. ||Biochemical basis of rapid Brix increase includes: maximum hexose import rates 90-170 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with 65-75% accumulating in vacuoles while 25-35% metabolized for energy and biosynthesis, glucose and fructose each increasing 70-125 mM per week approaching final concentrations 700-1100 mM each (combined 1400-2200 mM total hexoses equivalent to 25-40% w/v or 25-40° Brix though other solutes contribute), sucrose remaining low <50-100 mM due to invertase activity maintaining hexose:sucrose ratio >8-15, and minor contributions from other soluble compounds including organic acids (declining 10-25% during rapid Brix increase as malate degrades), amino acids, phenolics, and minerals collectively 15-30 g/L affecting total dissolved solids measurement. ||Refractometry principles underlying Brix measurement show: refractive index of berry juice proportional to total dissolved solids concentration with pure water having refractive index 1.3330 at 20°C, each 1° Brix increase representing approximately 10 g/L dissolved solids (primarily sugars in grape juice) increasing refractive index by ~0.00014, portable refractometers measuring critical angle of total internal reflection providing field Brix assessment accurate ±0.2° with temperature compensation, and laboratory refractometers achieving ±0.05° accuracy enabling precise tracking of rapid increase rates. ||Osmotic consequences of rapid Brix increase demonstrate: vacuolar osmotic potential declining from -1.8 to -2.4 MPa at rapid onset to -2.6 to -3.4 MPa at conclusion creating strong water potential gradient, total berry water potential following vacuolar sugar causing decline from -1.5 to -2.0 MPa to -2.2 to -3.0 MPa establishing gradient favoring water import from vine xylem (-0.5 to -1.2 MPa typical), and osmotically-driven water uptake causing berry fresh weight increase 8-18% during rapid Brix increase despite declining growth rates illustrating continued expansion driven by sugar accumulation. ||Cellular hydration dynamics during rapid increase show: mesocarp cell water content relatively stable 75-82% fresh weight despite massive sugar accumulation indicating concurrent water import maintaining hydration, vacuolar volume fraction increasing slightly from 93-95% to 95-97% of cell volume accommodating both sugar and water, and cytoplasmic sugar concentration maintained relatively low 60-100 mM through efficient tonoplast transport preventing osmotic dehydration of cytoplasm that could disrupt metabolism. ||Environmental factors strongly affecting rapid Brix increase inclu temperature with optimal 26-30°C supporting maximum rates 4.2-5.0% per week through enhanced enzyme activities, membrane transport, and metabolism, moderate warmth 23-26°C enabling 3.5-4.5% per week still approaching maximum, cooler conditions 20-23°C reducing to 2.8-3.8% per week through slowed kinetics, heat stress 32-35°C impairing increase to 2.0-3.2% per week through enzyme denaturation and metabolic disruption, and extreme heat >35°C potentially arresting increase <1.5% per week or completely through catastrophic cellular dysfunction. ||Light effects operate through source photosynthesis with adequate canopy light exposure essential for producing sucrose substrate supporting rapid accumulation, shaded canopies limiting increase 20-40% through reduced photosynthesis despite adequate berry import capacity, and cluster exposure having minimal direct effects on Brix increase once substrate adequate though excessive radiation with heat can impair through berry temperature stress. ||Water relations influences show: moderate deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) compatible with or enhancing Brix increase through reduced berry expansion concentrating sugars (higher Brix at same hexose content), severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) impairing increase 35-65% through impaired phloem delivery and metabolism, osmotic effects with high berry sugar requiring adequate vine water status to maintain gradient for continued water import supporting expansion, and precision deficit irrigation targeting enhanced concentration without metabolic impairment typically imposing -1.1 to -1.3 MPa during rapid increase period. ||Cultivar genetic variation determines: high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer potential 26-30° Brix, Sémillon 24-28°, Chenin Blanc 23-27°) achieving rapid increase rates 4.2-5.2% per week over 2-3 weeks reaching final levels, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay 22-26°, Cabernet Sauvignon 23-27°, Merlot 22-26°) showing 3.5-4.5% per week for 2.5-3.5 weeks, and lower-Brix types (Pinot Noir cool climates 20-24°, some table grapes 18-22°) displaying 2.8-3.8% per week for 3-4 weeks reflecting genetic differences in maximum sugar accumulation capacity and metabolic programming. ||Temporal patterns of rapid increase show: acceleration from initial increase 1.8-2.8% per week to rapid phase 3.5-5.0% per week over 3-6 days, sustained rapid rates 10-20 days during peak accumulation, then deceleration to late ripening 1.5-2.8% per week and plateau <0.8-1.5% per week as vacuolar concentrations approach equilibrium with phloem supply and feedback mechanisms limit further accumulation. ||Coordination with other ripening processes during rapid increase includes: berry softening approaching completion with 75-90% total firmness reduction achieving characteristic ripe texture, color development (reds) reaching 85-98% final anthocyanin levels with both processes ABA-coordinated, acid decline approaching minimum with malate respiratory consumption 70-90% complete reducing titratable acidity from 8-12 g/L to 4-7 g/L, and flavor/aroma compound synthesis intensifying with terpenes, esters, and other volatiles accumulating creating ripe fruit character. ||Quality implications of rapid Brix increase inclu rate and duration determining final sugar and thus wine alcohol potential with faster longer increase producing higher Brix enabling earlier harvest or lower-alcohol styles through earlier picking, uniformity of increase across berries and clusters affecting harvest maturity synchrony with heterogeneous increase requiring selective harvest or acceptance of compositional variation, balance between Brix and other quality parameters (phenolics, acids, flavors) defining optimal harvest window with ideal showing coordinated maturation, and environmental conditions during rapid increase substantially affecting wine style through effects on final berry composition beyond just sugar level. ||Harvest timing based on rapid Brix increase involves: weekly sampling during rapid phase tracking rates and projecting timing to reach target Brix (typically 20-24° for table wines, 22-26° for fuller styles, 24-28° for late harvest depending on variety and region), integration with acid and pH monitoring ensuring appropriate balance, phenolic maturity assessment confirming tannin and color development synchronized with sugar, and sensory evaluation verifying flavor and aroma development adequate for desired wine style. ||Viticultural management during rapid increase includes: irrigation typically minimized or terminated as concentration generally desirable and berry water demand declining, canopy management maintaining source leaf health for continued photosynthesis without excessive leaf removal limiting substrate supply, disease monitoring critical as high-sugar berries increasingly attractive to pests and pathogens requiring protection, and harvest logistics preparation advancing as rapid increase indicates imminent maturity requiring equipment, labor, and winery readiness. ||Post-rapid increase management involves: continued monitoring as Brix increase decelerates toward plateau ensuring optimal harvest timing, extended hang time decisions weighing benefits of continued flavor development against risks of over-ripeness, excessive alcohol, or weather-related losses, and selective harvest considerations if spatial variation in rapid increase rates creates maturity heterogeneity across vineyard zones requiring multiple picking passes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 224-228 Brix increase and maturity || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 accumulation dynamics || Deluc LG, Quilici DR, Decendit A, Grimplet J, Wheatley MD, Schlauch KA, Mérillon JM, Cushman JC, Cramer GR (2009) Water deficit alters differentially metabolic pathways affecting important flavor and quality traits in grape berries of Cabernet Sauvignon and Chardonnay Bmc Genomics 10:212 environmental effects on Brix."
},

  "Sugar_Transport_Activation": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Transport_Activation is a Sugar_Accumulation_Onset comprising coordinated upregulation of membrane transport systems enabling hexose flux from apoplast into cells and subsequently into vacuolar storage.",
  "alternative_term": "membrane transport system induction | hexose uptake machinery activation | sugar import capacity establishment | transporter gene upregulation |+ Membran-Transport-System-Induktion | Hexose-Aufnahme-Maschinerie-Aktivierung | Zucker-Import-Kapazitäts-Etablierung | Transporter-Gen-Hochregulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Mosel Riesling vineyard, sugar transport activation was characterized over 8 days in mid-September Year N+1 (BBCH 83-84) when VvHT1 expression increased from 8-fold to 72-fold, VvHT2 rose from 5-fold to 58-fold, glucose uptake into isolated mesocarp cells increased from 6.5 to 48 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, berry Brix rose from 9.8° to 15.2° (average 2.7% per week accelerating), ABA levels 1180 ng/g, under cool German conditions (daily high 20-23°C, adequate vine water status).",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Transport_Activation is distinguished from Phloem_Unloading_Activation by representing membrane transport rather than vascular unloading, from Hexose_Transport_Initiation by showing coordinated system-wide activation rather than individual component onset, and from maximum transport by representing establishment (30-100 fold gene induction, 5-10 fold uptake increase) rather than peak operation. ||Duration 6-10 days BBCH 83-84. ||Critical developmental window. ||Sugar_Transport_Activation establishes cellular import machinery fundamentally determining achievable berry sweetness. || This activation occurs during veraison onset through mid-veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 0-5 days following or concurrent with phloem unloading activation, and is characterized by hexose transporter gene expression increasing 30-100 fold collectively (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6 showing individual 25-150 fold inductions), plasma membrane hexose uptake capacity rising from pre-veraison 3-10 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to activation phase 25-65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 5-10 fold enhancement, tonoplast transport enabling vacuolar accumulation 20-50 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹, and resulting berry Brix increasing from 7-11° to 13-18° over 6-10 days as transport capacity establishes foundation for subsequent rapid accumulation. ||Molecular mechanisms of transport activation inclu transcriptional induction of hexose transporter genes through sugar-responsive cis-elements (SURE, TGGACGG motifs) activated by sugar signaling via hexokinase pathway creating feed-forward amplification, ABA-responsive elements in transporter gene promoters responding to veraison ABA spike (50-200 → 600-1500 ng/g) coordinating transport activation with other ripening processes, transcription factor families (VvMYB, VvbZIP, VvNAC) showing coordinate induction binding transporter gene promoters orchestrating expression, and chromatin remodeling potentially involved with histone modifications enabling access to previously silenced transporter genes during developmental transition. ||Hexose transporter family members showing differential activation patterns inclu VvHT1 (high-affinity glucose transporter, Km 1.0-2.5 mM) induced 40-100 fold early in activation providing capacity for efficient uptake even at moderate apoplastic concentrations, VvHT2 (facilitating both glucose and fructose, Km 4-10 mM) showing 30-80 fold elevation slightly delayed providing bulk transport capacity, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6 induced 25-70 fold each contributing to total transport capacity, and isoform diversity creating functional redundancy and potential regulation through differential subcellular localization or kinetic properties. ||Protein synthesis and trafficking during activation demonstrate: transporter mRNA translation producing protein at rates matching transcript increases with synthesis reaching 40-70% of maximum within 3-5 days of activation onset, protein trafficking through ER and Golgi to plasma membrane requiring 2-6 hours from synthesis to insertion providing temporal lag between transcript and functional capacity, membrane insertion requiring integration into lipid bilayer with transporter proteins estimated 5-12% of total plasma membrane protein at activation compared to <1-2% pre-veraison, and protein stability with half-life 24-48 hours requiring continued synthesis to maintain high transporter levels. ||Membrane dynamics supporting transport activation inclu plasma membrane area potentially increasing through vesicle fusion though data limited with estimates suggesting 20-40% expansion during early activation, tonoplast membrane substantially increased 50-100% through vacuole enlargement and membrane proliferation creating enhanced transport and storage capacity, membrane lipid composition potentially modified with increased unsaturation enhancing fluidity and transport protein function though specific changes during activation poorly characterized, and membrane protein turnover rates adjusted with synthesis exceeding degradation during activation establishing net accumulation. ||Transport kinetics during activation show: glucose uptake Vmax increasing from 10-25 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ pre-veraison to 30-75 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during activation through increased transporter density, fructose transport Vmax similarly enhanced from 8-20 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to 25-65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, Km values remaining relatively constant (glucose 1.5-3.0 mM, fructose 5-12 mM) confirming capacity rather than affinity changes, and competition kinetics showing glucose slightly favored over fructose (relative uptake 1.1-1.3:1.0) though final vacuolar ratios approach equimolar through differential metabolism and tonoplast transport selectivity. ||Energetics of transport activation involve: facilitated diffusion down concentration gradients (apoplast 150-350 mM hexoses → cytoplasm maintained 50-100 mM → vacuole accumulating 300-700 mM during activation) providing primary driving force without direct ATP coupling, potential secondary active transport at tonoplast where vacuolar H⁺-ATPase and H⁺-PPase create pH gradient (cytoplasm 7.2-7.5 → vacuole 3.2-3.8) and electrical potential (-20 to -40 mV vacuole negative) could drive H⁺-coupled hexose transport though evidence suggests predominantly facilitated diffusion, and metabolic energy requirements primarily for maintaining gradients through H⁺-pumps (15-25% of berry ATP production during activation) rather than direct transport coupling. ||Coordination with other transport systems shows: sucrose transporter genes paradoxically downregulated 60-80% during activation as apoplastic unloading reduces symplastic transport requirements, organic acid transporters showing complex regulation with malate transporters potentially altered affecting vacuolar malate accumulation and degradation, water channels (aquaporins) possibly upregulated facilitating osmotic water import driven by sugar accumulation though regulation during activation incompletely characterized, and ion transporters particularly K⁺ channels potentially enhanced as potassium accumulates with sugars (berry K⁺ rising from 1000-1500 to 1800-2500 mg/kg during activation) possibly affecting membrane potential and pH regulation. ||Environmental factors modulating transport activation inclu temperature affecting gene expression and protein synthesis with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid activation (full capacity achieved 5-7 days) while cooler conditions 18-24°C extend activation period 8-12 days, heat stress >31°C potentially impairing activation through reduced transcription or protein misfolding, water status with moderate deficit (stem ψ -0.9 to -1.3 MPa) compatible with normal activation while severe deficit may delay through general metabolic limitation, and nutritional status particularly nitrogen and sulfur required for protein synthesis with adequate nutrition essential for rapid transporter production. ||Hormonal regulation of transport activation demonstrates: ABA signaling central with rising levels 600-1500 ng/g activating ABA-responsive elements in transporter gene promoters, sugar itself creating positive feedback through hexokinase-mediated signaling where initial hexose uptake generates glucose-6-phosphate signals enhancing transporter gene expression amplifying accumulation, declining gibberellin and auxin removing growth-related suppression allowing metabolic focus on storage, and potential ethylene involvement in some cultivars with slight elevation correlating with activation timing though mechanism unclear. ||Cultivar variation in transport activation kinetics shows: rapid-activating varieties (Chardonnay, Gewürztraminer) achieving 60-80% maximum transport capacity within 4-6 days post-activation onset through rapid gene induction and protein synthesis, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) reaching 50-70% maximum in 6-9 days, and slower types (Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) requiring 8-12 days for 45-65% capacity reflecting genetic differences in regulatory control and biosynthetic rates. ||Physiological consequences of transport activation inclu establishment of import capacity that fundamentally determines achievable sugar accumulation rates and final levels, creation of concentration gradients enabling continued uptake throughout ripening, and osmotic effects with vacuolar hexose accumulation driving water import causing berry expansion 15-30% during activation period despite declining growth rates illustrating osmotic component of berry development. ||Quality implications inclu transport activation completeness strongly correlates with final sugar levels (r² = 0.75-0.88) with inadequate activation limiting ultimate Brix regardless of substrate supply, timing of activation relative to other ripening processes affecting compositional balance important for wine style, and uniformity of activation across berries and clusters determining ripening synchrony affecting harvest decisions. ||Viticultural factors affecting activation inclu crop load with excessive yields potentially delaying activation 3-7 days through limited resources for transporter synthesis, canopy management ensuring adequate nitrogen for protein synthesis supporting transporter production, water management with severe deficit potentially impairing activation while moderate deficit compatible, and disease or environmental stress during activation period potentially causing long-term limitation of sugar accumulation capacity even if conditions later improve making this a critical developmental window. ||Monitoring transport activation in research settings involves: gene expression analysis tracking VvHT transcript levels confirming induction, Western blotting detecting transporter protein accumulation, transport activity assays measuring hexose uptake into isolated mesocarp cells or vesicles, and sugar accumulation rates in berries indirectly indicating transport capacity establishment, while practical viticulture relies on Brix measurements showing accelerating accumulation rates indicating successful activation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 transporter activation || Afoufa-Bastien D, Medici A, Jeauffre J, Coutos-Thévenot P, Lemoine R, Atanassova R, Laloi M (2010) The Vitis vinifera sugar transporter gene family Plant Mol Biol 72:533-546 transporter family regulation || Lecourieux F, Kappel C, Lecourieux D, Serrano A, Torres E, Arce-Johnson P, Delrot S (2014) An update on sugar transport and signaling in grapevine J Exp Bot 65:821-832 comprehensive transport activation."
},

  "Hexose_Transporter_Upregulation": {
  "definition": "A Hexose_Transporter_Upregulation is a Sugar_Transport_Activation involving increased expression of genes encoding membrane proteins facilitating glucose and fructose uptake.",
  "alternative_term": "sugar transporter gene induction | VvHT expression increase | hexose carrier upregulation | membrane transporter activation |+ Zucker-Transporter-Gen-Induktion | VvHT-Expressions-Zunahme | Hexose-Träger-Hochregulation | Membran-Transporter-Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Chardonnay vineyard, hexose transporter upregulation was characterized by qPCR over 9 days in early August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when VvHT1 expression increased from 1.2-fold to 95-fold above green berry reference, VvHT2 rose from 0.8-fold to 72-fold, berry Brix increased from 8.6° to 14.8° (2.9% per week), glucose uptake into mesocarp cells rose from 5.2 to 52 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, ABA levels 1250 ng/g, under warm conditions (daily high 27-30°C supporting rapid induction).",
  "editor_note": "Hexose_Transporter_Upregulation is distinguished from Sugar_Transport_Activation by representing gene expression changes rather than overall system activation, from Hexose_Transport_Initiation by focusing on transcriptional induction rather than initial function, and from maximum expression by showing progressive increase (40-150 fold induction) rather than sustained peak. ||Duration 4-10 days BBCH 83-84. ||ABA-dependent regulation critical. ||Temperature optimal 24-28°C. ||Hexose_Transporter_Upregulation represents critical molecular transition enabling cellular hexose import capacity. || This upregulation occurs during veraison onset through mid-veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 1-6 days following initial developmental signals, and is characterized by VvHT gene family members showing coordinated induction: VvHT1 (high-affinity glucose transporter) increasing 40-150 fold above green berry baseline, VvHT2 (facilitating glucose and fructose) rising 30-100 fold, VvHT3 showing 25-80 fold elevation, VvHT5 and VvHT6 displaying 20-70 fold induction, with collective VvHT expression representing 300-500 fold increase when summed across all family members creating massive enhancement in transporter gene transcription. ||Molecular mechanisms of upregulation inclu transcription factor binding to transporter gene promoters with sugar-responsive transcription factors (VvMYB, VvbZIP families) recognizing SURE elements (Sugar Responsive Elements, consensus TGGACGG) in VvHT promoters activated by hexokinase-mediated sugar sensing, ABA-responsive transcription factors (VvABF, VvAREB) binding ABRE elements (ABA Responsive Elements, PyACGTGGC motifs) in VvHT promoters responding to veraison ABA spike 50-200 → 700-1600 ng/g, chromatin modifications with histone acetylation increasing accessibility of VvHT genes enabling transcription factor access, and potential DNA methylation changes reducing silencing allowing developmental expression. ||Transcriptional dynamics during upregulation show: VvHT1 transcript levels rising from 0.5-2.0 copies per cell (green berry) to 40-120 copies per cell (mid-veraison) over 4-8 days representing exponential accumulation phase, VvHT2 similarly increasing from 0.3-1.5 to 25-90 copies per cell, transcript half-life 4-8 hours requiring continuous transcription to maintain high steady-state levels, and mRNA processing including splicing and polyadenylation efficiently producing mature transcripts for translation. ||Regulatory control involves: positive feedback loops where initial hexose uptake creates glucose-6-phosphate signals that further enhance VvHT expression amplifying accumulation, cross-talk between sugar and ABA signaling pathways with both converging on VvHT promoters creating synergistic upregulation, developmental programming with veraison-specific transcription factors coordinately activating multiple ripening genes including VvHTs, and potential negative feedback at very high expression levels (>100-150 fold) preventing excessive transporter synthesis once capacity saturates. ||Protein synthesis from upregulated transcripts shows: translation initiation within 10-30 minutes of transcript appearance producing VvHT proteins, protein synthesis rates 25-60 ng transporter protein per g berry fresh weight per hour during peak upregulation, targeting signals directing nascent proteins to ER for membrane insertion and processing, and glycosylation in ER/Golgi potentially affecting transporter stability or function though modifications incompletely characterized for grape VvHTs. ||Transporter protein properties inclu molecular mass 50-55 kDa for most VvHT proteins consistent with 12-transmembrane domain structure typical of sugar transporters, predicted topology with cytoplasmic N and C termini and 12 membrane-spanning α-helices creating central pore for hexose passage, substrate specificity with VvHT1 preferring glucose (Km 1-2.5 mM) and VvHT2 transporting both glucose and fructose (Km 4-10 mM for each), and functional characterization in heterologous systems (yeast, Xenopus oocytes) confirming facilitated diffusion mechanism without energy coupling. ||Subcellular localization of upregulated transporters includes: plasma membrane dominance with 65-80% of VvHT protein at cell surface enabling hexose uptake from apoplast, tonoplast localization 15-30% facilitating cytoplasm-to-vacuole hexose transport for storage, and potential endo-membrane (ER, Golgi) distribution 5-10% representing trafficking intermediates en route to final destinations. ||Tissue-specific patterns of upregulation show: mesocarp cells showing strongest VvHT upregulation corresponding to sugar storage function, phloem-adjacent cells potentially showing earlier or more intense upregulation facilitating uptake from unloading zones, and vascular tissue itself showing minimal VvHT expression consistent with role in transport rather than accumulation. ||Temporal progression of upregulation demonstrates: early phase (days 0-3) showing 5-25 fold induction establishing initial capacity, middle phase (days 3-7) achieving 30-80 fold elevation reaching 60-75% of maximum, late phase (days 7-12) attaining 80-120 fold approaching saturating levels, and maintenance phase (beyond day 12) sustaining 80-110 fold throughout ripening with balance between synthesis and degradation maintaining steady-state. ||Environmental modulation of upregulation includes: temperature affecting transcription and translation rates with optimal 24-28°C supporting rapid upregulation (peak achieved 5-7 days) while cooler conditions 18-24°C extend upregulation period 8-12 days through slower kinetics, heat stress >31°C potentially impairing upregulation through reduced gene expression or protein misfolding, light having indirect effects through photosynthesis providing substrate that triggers sugar signaling amplifying upregulation, and water status with adequate hydration supporting normal upregulation while severe deficit may reduce through general transcriptional suppression. ||Nutritional influences inclu nitrogen availability important for protein synthesis with N-deficient vines potentially showing 25-40% reduced transporter protein levels despite normal transcript induction indicating translational limitation, sulfur required for methionine and cysteine in transporter proteins with deficiency potentially limiting synthesis, and general nutrient status affecting cellular capacity for protein production with severely nutrient-limited vines showing impaired upregulation. ||Hormonal fine-tuning of upregulation involves: ABA concentration directly correlating with VvHT expression levels (r² = 0.72-0.86) across developmental stages and treatments, exogenous ABA application to pre-veraison berries inducing premature VvHT upregulation demonstrating hormonal control, and ABA biosynthesis inhibitors preventing normal upregulation confirming requirement for endogenous ABA accumulation. ||Cultivar genetic variation in upregulation characteristics shows: rapid-upregulating varieties achieving maximum fold-induction 100-150 fold within 5-7 days, moderate cultivars reaching 70-110 fold in 7-10 days, and slower types requiring 10-14 days for 60-90 fold reflecting genetic differences in regulatory element sensitivity, transcription factor levels, or chromatin accessibility. ||Functional consequences of upregulation inclu hexose uptake capacity increasing proportionally with transporter levels enabling berry sugar accumulation rates 3.0-4.8% Brix per week during peak upregulation compared to <1.0% pre-upregulation, final sugar levels strongly correlated with maximum upregulation achieved (r² = 0.78-0.90) demonstrating functional significance, and transport saturation at very high expression (>120 fold) suggesting capacity limits related to membrane area or metabolic coupling rather than transporter abundance per se. ||Research applications inclu VvHT expression analysis providing molecular marker for veraison onset and ripening progression, promoter studies revealing regulatory mechanisms controlling developmental expression, and transgenic or CRISPR approaches potentially enabling manipulation of sugar accumulation through VvHT expression modulation though not yet commercially deployed. ||Quality implications inclu adequate upregulation essential for achieving target sugar levels with inadequate induction limiting final Brix regardless of source photosynthesis or phloem delivery, timing of upregulation relative to other ripening processes affecting compositional balance, and uniformity of upregulation across berries and clusters determining ripening synchrony important for harvest timing and wine consistency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 VvHT upregulation || Vignault C, Vachaud M, Cakir B, Glissant D, Dédaldéchamp F, Büttner M, Atanassova R, Fleurat-Lessard P, Lemoine R, Delrot S (2005) VvHT1 encodes a monosaccharide transporter expressed in the conducting complex of the grape berry phloem J Exp Bot 56:1409-1418 VvHT1 characterization || Afoufa-Bastien D, Medici A, Jeauffre J, Coutos-Thévenot P, Lemoine R, Atanassova R, Laloi M (2010) The Vitis vinifera sugar transporter gene family Plant Mol Biol 72:533-546 VvHT family regulation."
},

  "Sugar_Uptake_Enhancement": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Uptake_Enhancement is a Sugar_Transport_Activation characterized by amplified hexose import rates into mesocarp cells through transporter protein accumulation, increased membrane capacity, and optimized metabolic coupling.",
  "alternative_term": "amplified hexose import | progressive uptake increase | cellular sugar acquisition enhancement | escalating glucose-fructose uptake |+ amplifizierter Hexose-Import | progressive Aufnahme-Zunahme | zelluläre Zucker-Akquisitions-Verstärkung | eskalierende Glukose-Fruktose-Aufnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Bordeaux Cabernet Franc vineyard, sugar uptake enhancement was tracked over 10 days in early September Year N+1 (BBCH 84) when glucose uptake increased from 32 to 72 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, fructose from 28 to 65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, berry Brix accelerated from 15.2° to 21.8° (3.6% per week), vacuolar hexose rose from 720 to 1280 mM, berry fresh weight 1.72 g expanding 13%, under favorable conditions (daily high 26-28°C, stem ψ -1.05 MPa, healthy canopy).",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Uptake_Enhancement is distinguished from Hexose_Transporter_Upregulation by representing functional capacity increase (2-4 fold uptake amplification) rather than gene expression, from Sugar_Transport_Activation by showing progressive enhancement rather than system onset, and from peak uptake by exhibiting amplification (45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹) rather than maximum (65-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹). ||Duration 6-12 days BBCH 83-84. ||Temperature optimal 25-29°C. ||Sugar_Uptake_Enhancement represents critical escalation creating capacity for achieving harvest-ready sweetness levels. || This enhancement occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 4-10 days post-transporter upregulation onset, and is characterized by glucose uptake rates increasing from initial upregulation 15-35 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to enhanced phase 45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 2-4 fold amplification, fructose uptake similarly rising from 12-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to 40-75 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, combined hexose import 60-130 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ enabling berry Brix increases accelerating from 1.8-2.8% per week to 3.0-4.2% per week as cellular import machinery approaches maximum efficiency. ||Cellular mechanisms underlying enhancement inclu continued transporter protein synthesis and membrane insertion increasing density 2-4 fold from initial activation levels, membrane remodeling potentially expanding plasma membrane area 15-35% through vesicle fusion creating additional sites for transporter integration, tonoplast membrane area substantially increased 40-80% through vacuolar expansion and proliferation enhancing cytoplasm-to-vacuole transport capacity, and optimization of metabolic coupling where cytoplasmic hexose metabolism adjusted maintaining low concentrations 50-90 mM sustaining concentration gradient favoring continued plasma membrane uptake despite rising vacuolar levels. ||Transport kinetics during enhancement demonstrate: glucose uptake Vmax increasing from 35-65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ at enhancement onset to 60-100 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ approaching maximum through higher transporter density, fructose Vmax similarly enhanced from 30-55 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to 50-90 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, Km values remaining constant (glucose 1.5-3.0 mM, fructose 5-12 mM) confirming capacity increases without affinity changes, and competition between hexoses diminishing as transporter capacity exceeds apoplastic supply creating non-saturating conditions enabling maximum flux. ||Concentration gradients driving enhancement show: apoplastic hexoses maintained 220-400 mM combined through continued invertase cleavage of phloem-delivered sucrose, cytoplasmic hexoses held 55-90 mM through balanced plasma membrane import, metabolism, and tonoplast export, vacuolar accumulation rising from 500-800 mM at enhancement onset to 900-1400 mM during peak creating osmotic potential declining from -1.4 to -2.0 MPa to -2.0 to -2.8 MPa, and maintained apoplast-cytoplasm gradient 160-340 mM and cytoplasm-vacuole gradient 450-1300 mM driving facilitated diffusion at increasing rates. ||Membrane dynamics supporting enhancement inclu transporter protein representing 8-14% of total plasma membrane protein (from 4-8% at activation onset) approaching maximum packing density, phospholipid composition potentially modified increasing membrane fluidity enhancing transport protein function though specific changes poorly characterized, membrane potential maintained -120 to -150 mV (inside negative) through H⁺-ATPase activity providing electrochemical gradient potentially contributing to transport driving force though most VvHTs appear electroneutral, and cholesterol or sterol content potentially adjusted affecting membrane physical properties and transport protein activity. ||Metabolic integration during enhancement shows: glycolytic flux increasing from 18-35 μmol glucose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to 28-55 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ metabolizing portion of imported hexoses for energy and biosynthesis, respiratory rates elevated 1.2-2.4 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ supporting ATP synthesis for membrane pumps maintaining gradients, respiratory quotient >1.1-1.4 indicating substrate-level and fermentative metabolism contribute substantially particularly in berry interior, and metabolic pathway adjustments redirecting carbon from structural uses to storage with 70-80% of imported hexoses accumulating in vacuoles while 20-30% metabolized. ||Hormonal regulation during enhancement includes: ABA sustained at 1000-2000 ng/g maintaining ripening program activation and supporting continued transporter expression, hexose signaling through hexokinase pathway with glucose-6-phosphate 20-45 μmol/g fresh weight creating strong sugar-responsive gene activation feedback, declining gibberellin maintaining low levels removing any residual suppression, and potential ethylene effects in some cultivars with slight elevation 0.2-0.9 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ possibly fine-tuning ripening though role unclear. ||Environmental influences on enhancement rate inclu temperature critically important with optimal 25-29°C supporting maximum enhancement achieving peak rates 3.8-4.5% Brix per week within 6-8 days, moderate warmth 22-25°C enabling 3.0-3.8% per week over 8-11 days, cooler conditions 18-22°C reducing to 2.2-3.0% per week with 10-15 day enhancement period, heat stress 31-34°C impairing enhancement to 1.8-2.8% per week through membrane disruption and enzyme impairment, and extreme heat >34°C potentially preventing adequate enhancement <1.5% per week limiting final sugar achievement. ||Water status effects show: adequate vine hydration supporting normal enhancement with stem water potential -0.6 to -1.2 MPa enabling full metabolic function, moderate deficit -1.0 to -1.4 MPa compatible with enhancement and potentially concentrating berries through reduced expansion, severe deficit <-1.5 MPa impairing enhancement 35-60% through general metabolic limitation despite continued transporter expression, and osmotic relationships with high vacuolar sugar creating -2.0 to -2.8 MPa requiring adequate vine water status to sustain gradient for continued uptake. ||Nutritional influences inclu nitrogen availability supporting protein synthesis and enzyme production with N-deficient vines showing 20-35% reduced enhancement despite adequate transporter genes through translational or post-translational limitations, potassium potentially important for membrane transport and pH regulation with berry K⁺ accumulating from 1400-2000 to 2200-3000 mg/kg during enhancement possibly affecting membrane function, and phosphorus required for ATP synthesis supporting active pumps maintaining gradients enabling transport. ||Cultivar variation in enhancement characteristics shows: rapid-enhancing varieties achieving 70-85% maximum uptake capacity within 6-9 days of enhancement onset, moderate cultivars reaching 60-75% maximum in 8-12 days, and slower types requiring 10-16 days for 50-65% capacity reflecting genetic differences in membrane dynamics, metabolic coordination, or regulatory control. ||Coordination with phloem delivery shows: sugar uptake enhancement synchronized with apoplastic unloading intensification ensuring substrate availability matches cellular import capacity, temporal relationship typically showing uptake enhancement lagging unloading intensification by 1-3 days allowing apoplastic substrate accumulation before maximum cellular demand, and feedback coordination where high uptake rates potentially stimulate phloem delivery through reduced apoplastic sugar maintaining unloading gradient. ||Quality implications of enhancement inclu uptake enhancement rate and completeness determining trajectory toward final sugar levels with inadequate enhancement limiting ultimate Brix, timing relative to other ripening processes affecting balance between sugar and other quality parameters (acids, phenolics, flavors), and uniformity of enhancement across berries and clusters determining ripening synchrony important for harvest maturity consistency. ||Viticultural management during enhancement involves: maintaining adequate vine water and nutritional status supporting metabolic function enabling normal enhancement, avoiding environmental stresses particularly heat that can irreversibly impair enhancement limiting final sugar potential, disease control preventing infections that disrupt metabolism interfering with enhancement, and monitoring enhancement progress through Brix tracking showing accelerating accumulation rates indicating successful amplification.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 221-225 uptake enhancement dynamics || Thomas TR, Matthews MA, Shackel KA (2006) Direct in situ measurement of cell turgor in grape berries during development Australian J Grape Wine Res 12:173-180 cellular physiology during enhancement || Lecourieux F, Kappel C, Lecourieux D, Serrano A, Torres E, Arce-Johnson P, Delrot S (2014) An update on sugar transport and signaling in grapevine J Exp Bot 65:821-832 transport enhancement mechanisms."
},

  "Vacuolar_Sugar_Storage": {
  "definition": "A Vacuolar_Sugar_Storage is a Sugar_Transport_Activation comprising accumulation of glucose and fructose in mesocarp cell vacuoles producing the hexose reservoir driving berry osmotic expansion.",
  "alternative_term": "hexose vacuolar accumulation | sugar compartmentalization | tonoplast-mediated storage | glucose-fructose sequestration |+ Hexose-vakuoläre Akkumulation | Zucker-Kompartimentierung | Tonoplast-vermittelte Lagerung | Glukose-Fruktose-Sequestrierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Rheingau Riesling vineyard, vacuolar sugar storage was characterized in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 87) when vacuolar hexose concentration measured 1580 mM combined (glucose 785 mM, fructose 795 mM, ratio 0.99), representing 23.4° Brix, vacuolar volume 2.8 nL per mesocarp cell occupying 96% of cell volume, berry fresh weight 1.65 g having expanded 95% from veraison onset, osmotic potential -2.85 MPa, titratable acidity 7.8 g/L, under cool German conditions (daily high 19-22°C, extended ripening period).",
  "editor_note": "Vacuolar_Sugar_Storage is distinguished from Sugar_Uptake_Enhancement by representing compartmentalization rather than import, from Hexose_Transport_Initiation by focusing on storage rather than membrane transport, and from sugar accumulation onset by showing progressive storage (100-250 → 1400-2200 mM) rather than metabolic transition. ||Duration throughout ripening BBCH 83-89. ||Vacuolar volume fraction 95-97% at peak. ||Osmotic potential -2.4 to -3.6 MPa. ||Glucose:fructose ratio ~1.0. ||Vacuolar_Sugar_Storage represents culminating compartmentalization determining berry sweetness and wine alcohol potential. || This storage process intensifies during veraison through ripening (BBCH 83-89), beginning 2-5 days post-transport activation and continuing until harvest, and is characterized by vacuolar hexose concentrations increasing from pre-veraison 100-250 mM to veraison onset 400-700 mM to peak ripening 1400-2200 mM representing 8-12 fold enhancement, total berry sugar content rising from 12-25 g/L to 200-280 g/L (20-28° Brix), and vacuolar volume fraction expanding from 75-85% to 95-97% of mesocarp cell volume creating storage capacity 1.2-3.5 nL per cell accommodating this massive hexose accumulation. ||Molecular basis of vacuolar storage includes: tonoplast hexose transporters (possibly including VvHT isoforms localized to tonoplast) facilitating glucose and fructose transport from cytoplasm (60-100 mM) into vacuole (accumulating to 700-1100 mM each sugar, combined 1400-2200 mM), transport likely predominantly facilitated diffusion down concentration gradients maintained by continued plasma membrane import and metabolic consumption in cytoplasm preventing equilibration, potential role for H⁺-coupled secondary active transport though evidence suggests primarily facilitated mechanism, and vacuolar membrane integrity essential for maintaining compartmentation preventing hexose leakage back to cytoplasm. ||Vacuolar biophysics supporting sugar storage demonstrates: osmotic potential declining from -0.6 to -1.2 MPa (pre-veraison) to -2.4 to -3.6 MPa (peak storage) through hexose accumulation, turgor pressure maintained 0.3-0.6 MPa (compared to 0.6-1.0 MPa green berry) through balance of osmotic potential and cell wall mechanical resistance creating positive pressure sustaining cellular structure, water potential following osmotic potential declining from -0.4 to -0.8 MPa to -2.0 to -3.0 MPa creating strong gradient favoring water import from vine xylem (-0.5 to -1.2 MPa typical) driving osmotic berry expansion, and vacuolar pH maintained 2.8-3.6 throughout storage providing acidic environment important for organic acid balance, anthocyanin stability (in reds), and potential enzyme regulation. ||Glucose and fructose storage characteristics show: both hexoses accumulating approximately equimolar with glucose:fructose ratio 0.95-1.05 in vacuoles despite potential differential metabolism in cytoplasm, final concentrations typically 700-1100 mM each (combined 1400-2200 mM total hexoses) representing 25-40% w/v solution, spatial distribution relatively uniform within individual vacuoles though may show gradients across tissue with highest concentrations in central mesocarp declining toward periphery, and temporal accumulation following sigmoid pattern with slow initial phase, rapid exponential phase 3.0-5.0% Brix per week, and decelerating plateau <1.0% per week approaching equilibrium. ||Vacuolar membrane dynamics during storage inclu tonoplast surface area increasing substantially from 500-1000 μm² to 2000-6000 μm² per cell (depending on cell size) through vacuolar expansion and membrane proliferation, membrane protein composition adjusted with sugar transporters, H⁺-ATPases, and other transport proteins maintained at adequate levels supporting storage function, phospholipid content and composition potentially modified ensuring membrane stability and fluidity under high osmotic conditions, and aquaporin (water channel) expression possibly enhanced facilitating osmotic water import driven by sugar accumulation though regulation incompletely characterized. ||Osmotic consequences of sugar storage inclu water import driven by declining water potential causing berry fresh weight increase 60-120% from veraison onset to harvest (berry size 0.8-1.2 g rising to 1.4-2.5 g depending on variety), tissue hydration relatively stable 75-82% fresh weight despite massive sugar accumulation indicating concurrent water import maintaining cellular environment, berry expansion creating surface area increase requiring skin growth and potential surface cracking if expansion rate exceeds skin extensibility, and whole-vine water relations affected as berry water potential becomes strongest sink creating xylem flow predominantly to fruit during ripening. ||Coordination with other metabolic processes shows: vacuolar sugar storage synchronized with acid decline particularly malate degradation reducing titratable acidity from 12-18 g/L to 4-8 g/L creating appropriate sugar-acid balance, anthocyanin accumulation (reds) occurring concurrently in same vacuoles creating co-storage of sugars and pigments both requiring acidic pH for stability, flavor and aroma precursor accumulation potentially affected by high sugar concentrations altering vacuolar environment, and potassium accumulation parallel with sugars (berry K⁺ rising from 800-1500 to 2000-3200 mg/kg) potentially important for pH regulation and cation-anion balance. ||Environmental influences on storage capacity inclu temperature affecting accumulation rates with optimal 26-30°C supporting 4.0-5.0% Brix per week maximum storage while heat >32°C impairs to 2.0-3.2% per week and cool <20°C reduces to 2.2-3.2% per week, water availability with adequate vine water status enabling osmotic berry expansion supporting storage while severe deficit (<-1.6 MPa) limiting expansion potentially constraining total storage capacity though concentration may increase, light operating through source photosynthesis providing sucrose substrate with adequate canopy illumination essential for sugar supply, and nutrient status particularly nitrogen and potassium affecting metabolic capacity for supporting storage processes. ||Cultivar genetic variation in storage capacity shows: high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer, Sémillon potential 26-30° Brix) achieving vacuolar concentrations 1800-2400 mM combined hexoses through enhanced transport and potentially larger vacuoles, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon 22-26° Brix) reaching 1400-1900 mM, and lower-sugar types (Pinot Noir cool climates 20-24° Brix) attaining 1200-1600 mM reflecting genetic differences in maximum storage capacity and accumulation duration. ||Storage stability and harvest window considerations show: vacuolar sugar relatively stable once accumulated with <5-10% losses over 2-4 weeks post-peak enabling flexible harvest timing in stable cultivars, environmental stresses (heat, water deficit extremes) potentially destabilizing storage causing 10-30% sugar losses through respiratory consumption or cellular disruption, and cultivar variation with stable types (Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah) maintaining storage 4-6 weeks while unstable varieties (Pinot Noir warm climates) may lose 15-35% within 2-3 weeks post-peak requiring prompt harvest. ||Quality implications of vacuolar storage inclu final storage level determining wine alcohol potential with each 1° Brix approximately yielding 0.55-0.60% ethanol post-fermentation, sugar-acid balance critically affecting wine style with ratio 20-35:1 (Brix:titratable acidity g/L) typical for quality wines, uniformity of storage across berries and clusters determining harvest maturity consistency, and coordination of sugar storage with phenolic and flavor development defining optimal harvest window balancing multiple quality parameters. ||Physiological limits to storage inclu maximum vacuolar hexose concentrations ~2200-2600 mM approaching saturation potentially limiting further accumulation, membrane integrity possibly compromised at extreme osmotic potentials <-3.5 MPa, cell wall mechanical limits potentially constraining vacuolar expansion beyond certain size, and metabolic regulation through feedback mechanisms limiting accumulation as homeostatic set-points approached preventing excessive storage. ||Viticultural management targeting optimal storage involves: maintaining adequate vine water status supporting osmotic expansion without dilution from excess water, ensuring source photosynthesis through canopy health providing sucrose substrate, optimizing crop load 6-12 kg per vine variety-dependent enabling adequate storage without source limitation, and timing harvest to capture peak storage before degradation in unstable varieties or allowing extended hang time in stable cultivars for flavor development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 221-228 vacuolar sugar storage || Fontes N, Gerós H, Delrot S (2011) Grape berry vacuole:a complex and heterogeneous membrane system specialized in the accumulation of solutes Amer J Enol Vitic 62:270-278 vacuolar storage characteristics || Wada H, Matthews MA, Shackel KA (2008) Seasonal pattern of apoplastic solute accumulation and loss of cell turgor during ripening of Vitis vinifera fruit under field conditions Amer J Enol Vitic 59:173-180 storage dynamics and cell physiology."
},

  "Acid_Decline_Onset": {
  "definition": "An Acid_Decline_Onset is a Veraison comprising the reduction of berry organic acid concentration from green berry maxima through respiratory consumption and dilution.",
  "alternative_term": "organic acid decline initiation | veraison acid reduction onset | malate degradation beginning | acidity decrease commencement |+ organische Säure-Abnahme-Initiierung | Veraison-Säure-Reduktions-Onset | Malat-Degradations-Beginn | Azidität-Abnahme-Anfang",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Chardonnay vineyard, acid decline onset was detected in early August Year N+1 (BBCH 83, concurrent with sugar accumulation onset) when titratable acidity declined from 22.5 g/L to 18.2 g/L over 9 days (19% reduction), malic acid decreased from 12.8 to 9.6 g/L (25% loss), tartaric acid remained 8.2 g/L (stable), pH increased from 2.95 to 3.12, berry Brix rose from 8.5° to 13.8°, under warm conditions (daily high 28-31°C accelerating malate metabolism), VvME1 expression 18-fold elevated.",
  "editor_note": "Acid_Decline_Onset is distinguished from later acid decline by representing onset (15-30% TA reduction) rather than complete decline, from sugar accumulation onset by focusing on acid rather than sugar though temporally coincident, and from pH changes by representing acid decline cause rather than pH effect. ||Timing: BBCH 83-84, 0-3 days with sugar onset. ||Malic acid primary component declining (20-40% reduction), tartaric stable. ||Temperature sensitivity high: 25-32°C accelerates 30-60%, >32°C accelerates 50-150%. ||Acid_Decline_Onset represents critical metabolic transition toward balanced fruit composition essential for wine quality. || This onset occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically synchronized within 1-3 days of initial sugar accumulation and berry softening, and is characterized by titratable acidity declining from pre-veraison maximum 15-25 g/L tartaric acid equivalents to early decline 12-20 g/L within 7-10 days representing initial 15-30% reduction, malic acid specifically decreasing from 8-15 g/L to 6-12 g/L through beginning respiratory degradation while tartaric acid remains relatively stable 5-10 g/L showing only slight dilution from berry expansion, and berry pH beginning increase from green berry minimum 2.7-3.1 to veraison onset 2.9-3.3 reflecting net proton removal through organic acid decline. ||Biochemical basis of acid decline includes: malic acid (malate, C₄H₆O₅) undergoing respiratory metabolism through multiple pathways including direct oxidation in mitochondrial citric acid cycle, NADP-dependent malic enzyme (NADP-ME) catalyzing oxidative decarboxylation producing pyruvate plus CO₂ plus NADPH, NAD-dependent malic enzyme similarly converting malate to pyruvate, and malate dehydrogenase interconverting malate and oxaloacetate with net consumption through subsequent oxidation, while tartaric acid (C₄H₆O₆) showing metabolic stability with berry concentration declining only through dilution from water import accompanying sugar accumulation rather than degradation. ||Cellular compartmentation of acid metabolism shows: malic acid stored primarily in vacuoles at concentrations 80-180 mM (8-18 g/L) in green berries declining to 50-120 mM (5-12 g/L) during veraison onset, vacuolar pH 2.6-3.0 maintained by organic acid accumulation and H⁺-ATPase activity, cytoplasmic malate 5-15 mM serving as substrate for respiratory enzymes in mitochondria and cytosol, and metabolic interconversion requiring malate transport from vacuole through tonoplast to cytoplasm then potentially to mitochondria for oxidation with transporters (VvALMT family potentially involved) facilitating movement across membranes. ||Organic acid composition changes at onset demonstrate: total organic acids declining from 20-35 g/L (green berry) to 15-28 g/L (early decline) through differential metabolism, malic acid showing 20-40% reduction during onset representing majority of acid loss, tartaric acid relatively constant 5-10 g/L with <5-10% apparent decline primarily dilutional, minor acids (citric 0.3-0.8 g/L, succinic 0.2-0.6 g/L, ascorbic trace amounts) showing variable patterns with citric potentially declining slightly and succinic sometimes increasing, and acid composition shifting from malate:tartrate ratio 1.2-2.0:1 (green berry) toward 0.8-1.5:1 (veraison onset) indicating preferential malate loss. ||Enzymatic mechanisms enabling acid decline inclu NADP-malic enzyme genes (VvME1, VvME2) showing 8-30 fold induction at veraison onset producing enzyme that catalyzes malate + NADP⁺ → pyruvate + CO₂ + NADPH (optimal pH 7.0-7.5, Km for malate 0.5-2.0 mM), citric acid cycle enzymes maintaining activity enabling malate oxidation through sequential conversion to oxaloacetate then citrate then α-ketoglutarate with complete oxidation to CO₂, respiratory chain enzymes oxidizing NADH and FADH₂ produced from malate catabolism generating ATP supporting cellular metabolism, and enzyme localization with malic enzymes cytosolic and mitochondrial providing multiple sites for malate consumption. ||Hormonal regulation of acid decline onset includes: abscisic acid spike from 50-200 ng/g to 600-1800 ng/g triggering coordinate veraison responses including both sugar accumulation and acid decline through activation of ripening-specific genes, potential role for ethylene particularly in climacteric-like cultivars though grape typically considered non-climacteric, declining auxin and gibberellin removing growth-phase regulation allowing metabolic shift to ripening, and sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway potentially affecting acid metabolism genes though mechanisms less well-defined than for sugar transport genes. ||Environmental factors strongly influencing acid decline onset inclu temperature critically important with warm conditions 25-32°C accelerating malate degradation through enhanced respiratory rates potentially causing 30-60% faster decline compared to cool 18-24°C, heat stress >32°C dramatically increasing malate consumption with losses 50-150% of normal rates potentially producing excessive decline and unbalanced fruit, light affecting decline indirectly through effects on berry temperature with exposed clusters warming 3-8°C above air temperature accelerating metabolism, and vine water status with deficit potentially affecting malate metabolism though effects complex and cultivar-dependent. ||Cultivar genetic variation in acid decline onset demonstrates: low-acid cultivars (Grenache, Viognier potential final TA 4-6 g/L) showing early rapid decline onset with 25-40% reduction in first 10 days, moderate varieties (Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon final 5-7 g/L) displaying 20-30% early decline, and high-acid cultivars (Riesling, Chenin Blanc final 6-9 g/L) exhibiting slower onset with 15-25% initial reduction reflecting genetic differences in malic enzyme expression, respiratory capacity, and acid retention mechanisms. ||Coordination with other veraison processes shows: acid decline typically beginning 0-3 days concurrent with sugar accumulation onset suggesting common developmental triggers possibly ABA-mediated, synchronized with berry softening initiation reflecting coordinate ripening program activation, and in red cultivars paralleling color break timing indicating integrated metabolic reprogramming though causal relationships among processes incompletely defined. ||Physiological consequences of acid decline inclu pH increase from 2.8-3.1 to 3.0-3.4 affecting multiple processes including enzyme activities, membrane transport, anthocyanin color expression (in reds where higher pH shifts from red toward purple), and microbial stability with lower acids potentially increasing vulnerability to spoilage organisms, proton removal through organic acid degradation affecting cellular ion balance and potentially membrane potentials, and respiratory CO₂ production from malate catabolism contributing 20-40% of berry respiration during active decline creating substantial carbon loss from berry potentially 5-15% of green berry dry weight. ||Quality implications of acid decline onset inclu timing and rate determining final acid levels critical for wine balance and style with appropriate 4-8 g/L TA and pH 3.2-3.8 typical quality targets, excessive early decline particularly in warm regions producing low-acid fruit pH >3.8 resulting in flat wines lacking structure and prone to microbial instability, inadequate decline in cool regions potentially producing overly acidic fruit TA >9-12 g/L requiring deacidification in winery, and spatial variation in decline across vineyard zones creating heterogeneous maturity requiring management attention. ||Viticultural management affecting acid decline includes: canopy management influencing cluster temperature with shading reducing berry warming and slowing decline by 15-35% compared to full sun exposure important in warm climates for acid retention, irrigation with adequate water potentially moderating decline through cooling effects and reduced stress while deficit may concentrate acids though also potentially accelerating metabolism, and harvest timing critically important as acid decline continues throughout ripening requiring integration with sugar accumulation to achieve optimal balance. ||Monitoring acid decline onset provides maturity assessment: regular sampling during veraison tracking titratable acidity showing accelerating decline indicating onset occurrence, pH measurements revealing beginning increase correlating with acid loss, malic acid specific analysis through HPLC or enzymatic methods quantifying component primarily responsible for decline, and taste evaluation detecting decreasing sourness and developing balance between sweetness and acidity important for determining harvest readiness. ||Research applications inclu gene expression studies of malic enzyme and respiratory genes revealing molecular control of decline, enzyme activity assays measuring malate-metabolizing capacity correlating with decline rates, metabolomic analysis tracking organic acid profiles and metabolic intermediates revealing pathway flux, and environmental manipulation experiments (temperature, shading, irrigation) determining control mechanisms and optimization strategies for achieving target acid levels.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 228-233 acid decline during ripening || Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 malate metabolism comprehensive review || Ruffner HP, Hawker JS, Hale CR (1976) Temperature and enzymic control of malate metabolism in berries of Vitis vinifera Phytochem 15:1877-1880 temperature effects on acid decline."
},

  "Initial_Acid_Reduction": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Acid_Reduction is an Acid_Decline_Onset marked by active respiratory degradation of malic acid concurrent with stable tartaric acid concentration.",
  "alternative_term": "early acid decline phase | nascent malate reduction | beginning organic acid loss | preliminary acidity decrease |+ frühe Säure-Abnahme-Phase | beginnende Malat-Reduktion | beginnender organischer Säure-Verlust | vorläufige Azidität-Abnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Pinot Noir vineyard, initial acid reduction was tracked over 8 days in mid-August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when titratable acidity declined from 20.8 g/L to 16.2 g/L (22% reduction), malic acid decreased from 11.5 to 8.4 g/L (27% loss), tartaric acid stable at 7.8 g/L, pH increased from 3.02 to 3.18, berry Brix rose from 9.8° to 14.6°, VvME1 activity 28 units/g FW, under moderate coastal conditions (daily high 23-26°C, cool nights 12-15°C moderating decline).",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Acid_Reduction is distinguished from Acid_Decline_Onset by representing active reduction (15-25% TA decline, 22-30% malate loss) rather than onset signals, from complete acid decline by showing early phase rather than full reduction, and from pH increase by focusing on acid loss cause rather than pH effect. ||Duration 5-10 days BBCH 83. ||Malic acid primary component (22-30% reduction), tartaric stable (0-5% change). ||Temperature sensitive: 24-28°C optimal, >32°C excessive (50-100% acceleration). ||Initial_Acid_Reduction establishes trajectory toward final acidity critical for wine balance. || This initial reduction occurs during early veraison (BBCH 83), typically 1-5 days following veraison onset signals, and is characterized by titratable acidity declining from 16-24 g/L to 13-20 g/L over 5-10 days representing initial 15-25% reduction from maximum, malic acid specifically decreasing from 9-14 g/L to 7-11 g/L through beginning respiratory metabolism (22-30% reduction) while tartaric acid remains essentially constant 5-10 g/L showing only 0-5% apparent change from dilution, berry pH increasing from 2.8-3.1 to 3.0-3.3 reflecting net acid loss, and malate:tartrate ratio declining from 1.3-2.2:1 to 1.0-1.8:1 indicating preferential malate consumption. ||Biochemical mechanisms of initial reduction inclu malic acid respiratory catabolism through multiple pathways with citric acid cycle oxidation consuming malate via malate dehydrogenase (malate → oxaloacetate) followed by citrate synthase, aconitase, isocitrate dehydrogenase producing CO₂ and reducing equivalents, NADP-malic enzyme directly decarboxylating malate producing pyruvate plus CO₂ plus NADPH used for biosynthesis or oxidized for energy, NAD-malic enzyme similarly converting malate to pyruvate with NAD⁺ reduction, and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase potentially involved interconverting oxaloacetate and phosphoenolpyruvate though role in grape less defined than in other fruits. ||Enzyme activities during initial reduction show: NADP-malic enzyme activity increasing from pre-veraison 2-8 units/g fresh weight to initial reduction 12-35 units/g representing 3-6 fold enhancement enabling enhanced malate catabolism, NAD-malic enzyme showing 2-4 fold elevation from 1-5 units/g to 4-15 units/g, citric acid cycle enzyme activities (malate dehydrogenase, citrate synthase, isocitrate dehydrogenase) maintaining or slightly increasing supporting continued respiratory malate oxidation, and enzyme kinetics with Km values for malate 0.5-2.5 mM enabling efficient substrate utilization even as vacuolar malate concentrations decline from 100-150 mM to 70-110 mM. ||Gene expression patterns during initial reduction demonstrate: VvME1 (NADP-malic enzyme) transcript levels increasing 10-35 fold above green berry baseline with induction coinciding with veraison onset, VvME2 showing 8-25 fold elevation with slightly delayed kinetics, citric acid cycle enzyme genes generally maintaining expression with some (aconitase, isocitrate dehydrogenase) showing modest 2-5 fold increases, and regulatory control through ripening-specific transcription factors (possibly VvMYB, VvNAC families) coordinately activating multiple metabolic genes though specific factors controlling malic enzyme expression incompletely identified. ||Cellular compartmentation aspects inclu vacuolar malate representing bulk storage (70-110 mM during initial reduction) slowly declining as tonoplast transport enables cytoplasmic access, cytoplasmic malate 6-18 mM serving as immediate substrate for respiratory enzymes, mitochondrial malate uptake through dicarboxylate carriers enabling citric acid cycle oxidation, and metabolic channeling potentially coordinating malate transport and catabolism ensuring efficient carbon flow from storage to respiration. ||Respiratory quotient during initial reduction shows: RQ (CO₂ produced / O₂ consumed) typically 1.05-1.25 indicating mixed substrate oxidation with both hexoses and organic acids contributing to respiration, malate contribution to total berry respiration estimated 25-45% during initial reduction based on malate loss rates and CO₂ production, and respiratory rate per se 0.8-1.8 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ maintaining pre-veraison levels despite beginning malate catabolism as sugar import begins providing alternative substrate. ||Coordination with sugar accumulation demonstrates: initial acid reduction temporally overlapping with initial sugar increase (both typically days 0-10 post-veraison onset) creating beginning development of sugar-acid balance, carbon budget showing net carbon import through sugar accumulation (120-200 mg glucose-equivalents g⁻¹ over 10 days) far exceeding carbon loss through acid decline (15-35 mg malate-equivalents g⁻¹) resulting in net berry carbon increase, and metabolic regulation balancing anabolic processes (sugar storage, biosynthesis) with catabolic processes (acid degradation, respiration) through unknown coordination mechanisms. ||Environmental sensitivity of initial reduction includes: temperature strongly affecting malate degradation with optimal 24-28°C supporting normal rates, warm conditions 28-32°C accelerating reduction 30-50% through enhanced respiratory rates potentially producing 25-35% malate loss versus 22-30% at optimal, heat stress >32°C dramatically accelerating loss 50-100% potentially causing excessive early decline, cool conditions 18-24°C slowing reduction 20-40% extending duration to achieve similar endpoint, and diurnal temperature effects with daytime warming promoting catabolism while nighttime cooling reduces losses creating cumulative effects dependent on temperature regime. ||Light and exposure effects operate primarily through berry temperature with sun-exposed clusters warming 4-10°C above air temperature accelerating malate catabolism 20-50% compared to shaded fruit, direct photosynthetic effects minimal as ripening berries have limited chlorophyll and photosynthetic capacity <5-10% of leaves, and canopy management creating substantial variation in cluster microclimate enabling 30-70% differences in malate decline rates between exposed and shaded positions. ||Water status influences show: effects complex and cultivar-dependent with some studies showing deficit accelerating decline through stress-enhanced respiration while others find minimal effects, adequate vine water status generally supporting normal metabolic function enabling appropriate decline rates, and severe deficit potentially disrupting metabolism either accelerating decline through stress or slowing through general impairment depending on deficit intensity and timing. ||Cultivar variation in initial reduction characteristics demonstrates: low-acid varieties showing 25-35% malate reduction during initial phase with high malic enzyme activities 25-50 units/g, moderate cultivars displaying 22-28% reduction with enzyme activities 18-35 units/g, and high-acid types exhibiting 18-25% reduction with lower enzyme activities 12-25 units/g reflecting genetic differences in malic enzyme expression and respiratory capacity. ||Physiological significance includes: pH increase from 2.9-3.1 to 3.0-3.3 affecting multiple processes including enzyme optima, membrane transport kinetics, and anthocyanin color (in reds where pH 3.0-3.2 maintains red while >3.3-3.5 shifts purple), proton balance changes as organic acid anions (malate²⁻) removed requiring compensatory ion adjustments, and carbon balance with malate catabolism providing 15-30% of berry respiratory substrate during initial reduction representing carbon cost of ripening. ||Quality implications inclu initial reduction establishing trajectory toward final acidity with rapid early loss potentially indicating excessive final decline problematic in warm regions, slow initial reduction in cool regions potentially indicating retention of high acids requiring extended ripening or winery intervention, and spatial variation across vineyard revealing maturity heterogeneity requiring selective management. ||Viticultural management during initial reduction involves: canopy management particularly in warm regions with strategic shading reducing cluster temperature 3-7°C slowing decline 25-40% preserving acids, irrigation management with adequate water potentially moderating berry temperature through transpirational cooling, avoiding severe water stress that may accelerate loss through stress-enhanced respiration, and monitoring decline rates through sampling enabling early detection of excessive loss allowing management intervention before irreversible. ||Analytical monitoring methods inclu titratable acidity measurement by NaOH titration to pH 8.2 endpoint providing total acid assessment, pH measurement showing inverse relationship with acid levels, HPLC organic acid analysis quantifying malate and tartrate separately enabling distinction of metabolic decline from dilution, enzymatic malate assays providing rapid field assessment, and sensory evaluation detecting decreasing sourness and developing balance important for practical maturity determination.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 229-232 early acid decline || Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 temperature effects on initial reduction || Terrier N, Glissant D, Grimplet J, Barrieu F, Abbal P, Couture C, Ageorges A, Atanassova R, Léon C, Renaudin JP, Dédaldéchamp F, Romieu C, Delrot S, Hamdi S (2005) Isogene specific oligo arrays reveal multifaceted changes in gene expression during grape berry development Plant Physiol 138:1617-1633 gene expression during acid decline."
},

  "Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation is an Acid_Decline_Onset involving activation of malic enzyme and citric acid cycle activity converting stored malic acid to CO₂ and metabolic energy.",
  "alternative_term": "malate catabolism onset | malic enzyme induction | respiratory malate oxidation start | L-malate degradation initiation |+ Malat-Katabolismus-Onset | Malat-Enzym-Induktion | respiratorische Malat-Oxidations-Start | L-Malat-Degradations-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Valley Shiraz vineyard in Australia, malic acid decline initiation was characterized in mid-February Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when malic acid declined from 12.8 g/L to 10.5 g/L over 6 days (18% reduction), VvME1 expression increased 32-fold, NADP-malic enzyme activity rose from 4.2 to 21.5 units/g FW, berry Brix 11.2° beginning accumulation, pH increased from 2.98 to 3.14, under hot Australian conditions (daily high 31-35°C accelerating malate catabolism, requiring canopy shading intervention to moderate decline).",
  "editor_note": "Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation is distinguished from overall Acid_Decline_Onset by focusing specifically on malate rather than total acids, from Initial_Acid_Reduction by representing enzymatic activation rather than net reduction, and from later decline by showing onset (8-18% malate loss) rather than complete degradation. ||VvME induction 12-40 fold, activity 2-6 → 10-25 units/g. ||Duration 4-7 days BBCH 83. ||Temperature highly sensitive: >32°C excessive acceleration. ||Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation represents critical enzymatic activation enabling acid decline during ripening. || This initiation occurs during veraison onset (BBCH 83), typically 0-3 days concurrent with or slightly preceding overall acid decline onset, and is characterized by malic acid concentrations beginning decrease from pre-veraison maximum 9-15 g/L (90-150 mM vacuolar) to initiation 8-13 g/L over 4-7 days representing initial 8-18% reduction, NADP-malic enzyme activity increasing from green berry 2-6 units/g fresh weight to 10-25 units/g establishing catalytic capacity for malate oxidation, VvME gene expression rising 12-40 fold coordinating with activity increases, and berry respiration rates maintained or slightly elevated 0.9-2.0 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ as malate catabolism begins contributing substantially to respiratory substrate. ||Enzymatic basis of malate decline includes: NADP-dependent malic enzyme (EC 1.1.1.40) catalyzing oxidative decarboxylation L-malate + NADP⁺ → pyruvate + CO₂ + NADPH with pH optimum 7.0-7.5 matching cytosolic environment, enzyme kinetics showing Km for malate 0.5-2.0 mM and Vmax at initiation 12-28 μmol malate oxidized g⁻¹ h⁻¹ adequate for observed decline rates, NAD-dependent malic enzyme (EC 1.1.1.38) showing similar reaction with NAD⁺ cofactor and lower activity 4-15 units/g contributing secondarily, malate dehydrogenase in citric acid cycle (EC 1.1.1.37) catalyzing reversible malate ⇌ oxaloacetate interconversion enabling malate entry into cycle for complete oxidation, and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase potentially involved though role less defined in grape compared to CAM or C₄ plants. ||Gene expression during malate decline initiation shows: VvME1 (primary NADP-malic enzyme isoform) transcript increasing from 0.8-3.0 fold (green berry relative to reference) to 15-45 fold (initiation) representing major upregulation, VvME2 showing 10-30 fold induction with slightly delayed timing potentially reflecting isoform-specific regulation, citric acid cycle genes (aconitase, isocitrate dehydrogenase, malate dehydrogenase) maintaining moderate-to-high expression 3-12 fold ensuring pathway capacity for malate oxidation, and transcriptional control through ripening-associated transcription factors possibly including VvNAC family members binding to malic enzyme promoters though specific regulatory mechanisms incompletely characterized. ||Protein synthesis and enzyme accumulation during initiation demonstrate: malic enzyme protein levels increasing 4-8 fold from green berry to initiation phase correlating with activity increases, enzyme localization predominantly cytosolic with minor mitochondrial forms enabling malate catabolism in both compartments, post-translational modifications potentially including phosphorylation affecting activity though modifications in grape malic enzyme poorly studied, and enzyme stability with half-life estimated 18-36 hours requiring continued synthesis to maintain elevated levels throughout ripening. ||Substrate availability during initiation includes: vacuolar malate 80-140 mM (green berry) beginning decline to 70-120 mM (initiation) representing bulk storage slowly mobilized, tonoplast malate transporters (potentially VvALMT family) facilitating efflux from vacuole to cytoplasm though specific transporters in grape incompletely identified, cytoplasmic malate 8-20 mM serving as immediate substrate for malic enzyme and malate dehydrogenase, and pH gradients with vacuole pH 2.6-2.9 and cytoplasm pH 7.0-7.4 affecting malate ionization state and transport kinetics. ||Metabolic fate of malate-derived pyruvate shows: pyruvate from malic enzyme reaction entering multiple pathways including mitochondrial oxidation through pyruvate dehydrogenase producing acetyl-CoA for citric acid cycle, cytosolic metabolism through pyruvate kinase potentially regenerating phosphoenolpyruvate for biosynthesis, conversion to alanine via alanine aminotransferase producing amino acid from carbon skeleton, and fermentative metabolism to lactate or ethanol under hypoxic conditions in berry interior though aerobic pathways dominate near surface. ||Energy yield from malate catabolism includes: complete oxidation through citric acid cycle yielding 15 ATP per malate (compared to 32 ATP per glucose) making malate moderately efficient respiratory substrate, NADPH from NADP-malic enzyme potentially used for reductive biosynthesis (fatty acid synthesis, antioxidant systems) or oxidized by mitochondria for additional ATP through external NADH dehydrogenase, and malate contribution to total berry energy budget estimated 20-35% during initiation rising to 35-55% during peak decline before declining as malate depletes. ||Hormonal regulation of malate decline initiation includes: ABA rise from 60-200 ng/g to 700-1800 ng/g triggering ripening program including malic enzyme induction, sugar accumulation potentially creating signaling affecting malate metabolism though mechanisms unclear, declining growth hormones (auxin, gibberellin) removing suppression allowing metabolic shift, and ethylene potentially involved in some cultivars though grape generally non-climacteric with minimal ethylene effects compared to climacteric fruits. ||Environmental modulation of initiation timing and intensity shows: temperature critically affecting enzyme induction and activity with warm conditions 26-30°C advancing initiation 2-4 days and enhancing enzyme levels 20-40% compared to cool 18-24°C, heat stress >32°C dramatically accelerating initiation potentially causing premature excessive decline, light operating through berry temperature with exposed clusters initiating 1-3 days earlier than shaded fruit, and water status with deficit potentially affecting timing though effects variable and cultivar-dependent. ||Cultivar genetic variation in malate decline initiation characteristics includes: low-acid cultivars (Grenache, Viognier) showing early rapid initiation with VvME expression 30-60 fold and activity 20-40 units/g within 3-5 days veraison, moderate varieties (Merlot, Chardonnay) displaying 20-40 fold expression and 15-30 units/g in 5-8 days, and high-acid cultivars (Riesling, Chenin Blanc) exhibiting slower initiation 15-30 fold expression and 12-22 units/g over 7-12 days reflecting genetic differences in enzyme regulation and malate metabolism capacity. ||Physiological consequences of initiation inclu carbon loss through respiratory CO₂ evolution representing 8-18% of green berry malate carbon converted to CO₂ during initiation phase, pH increase in berry juice from 2.85-3.05 to 3.00-3.20 as malate anions removed titrating protons, and redox state changes as NADPH generation from malic enzyme affects cellular reducing capacity potentially influencing antioxidant systems and biosynthetic pathways. ||Quality implications inclu initiation timing relative to sugar accumulation affecting final sugar-acid balance with early rapid malate loss potentially producing low-acid fruit while delayed initiation maintaining high acids, enzyme activity levels at initiation predicting subsequent decline rates enabling early forecasting of final acidity, and spatial variation in initiation across vineyard revealing maturity heterogeneity requiring management attention. ||Viticultural factors affecting initiation inclu canopy microclimate with cluster temperature critically important, strategic shading in warm regions delaying initiation 2-5 days and reducing intensity 20-35% preserving acids, vine water status potentially affecting timing with deficit possibly advancing initiation 1-3 days through ABA elevation though effects inconsistent, and crop load with overcropping potentially delaying initiation through resource limitation extending vegetative-reproductive competition. ||Monitoring initiation in research involves: gene expression analysis tracking VvME transcripts confirming upregulation, enzyme activity assays measuring malic enzyme showing increases, metabolomic profiling tracking malate concentrations and metabolites revealing pathway flux, and respiration measurements showing maintained or elevated rates despite declining respiratory substrate pools indicating metabolic transition.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 malate metabolism comprehensive || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis:a review Vitis 21:247-259 acid metabolism review || Terrier N, Sauvage FX, Ageorges A, Romieu C (2001) Changes in acidity and in proton transport at the tonoplast of grape berries during development Planta 213:20-28 acid transport and metabolism."
},

  "Acid_Metabolism_Activation": {
  "definition": "An Acid_Metabolism_Activation is an Acid_Decline_Onset comprising coordinated upregulation of organic acid catabolic pathways enabling progressive reduction of berry acidity.",
  "alternative_term": "organic acid catabolism activation | metabolic pathway upregulation | respiratory enzyme induction | acid oxidation machinery activation |+ organische Säure-Katabolismus-Aktivierung | metabolische Pfad-Hochregulation | respiratorische Enzym-Induktion | Säure-Oxidations-Maschinerie-Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Willamette Valley Pinot Gris vineyard, acid metabolism activation was characterized over 7 days in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when VvME1 expression increased 38-fold, combined malic enzyme activity rose from 5.8 to 42 units/g FW, citric acid cycle enzyme activities increased 15-25%, berry respiration 1.6 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with RQ 1.18 indicating acid contribution, malic acid declined from 10.2 to 8.1 g/L, under moderate Oregon conditions (daily high 24-27°C, cool nights 12-15°C).",
  "editor_note": "Acid_Metabolism_Activation is distinguished from Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation by representing coordinated metabolic system rather than single enzyme pathway, from Respiratory_Malate_Consumption by focusing on activation rather than ongoing process, and from sugar metabolism by representing catabolic acid pathways rather than anabolic sugar storage. ||Malic enzyme 8-35 fold activity increase. ||Citric acid cycle enzymes maintain/increase 10-30%. ||Duration 5-10 days BBCH 83. ||Temperature sensitive: optimal 24-28°C, >32°C excessive. ||Acid_Metabolism_Activation represents critical metabolic transition enabling organic acid decline during ripening. || This activation occurs during veraison onset (BBCH 83), typically 0-4 days following initial developmental signals, and is characterized by malic enzyme genes showing 15-45 fold induction collectively (VvME1, VvME2, NAD-ME isoforms), citric acid cycle enzyme activities maintaining or increasing 10-30% supporting malate oxidation through complete combustion pathway, respiratory enzyme expression and activity coordinating to process increased carbon flux from organic acid catabolism, and metabolic transition from predominantly hexose-based respiration (<70% of CO₂ from sugars green berry) to mixed substrate utilization (40-60% from organic acids early veraison) reflecting acid metabolism activation. ||Enzymatic systems activated during this transition inclu NADP-malic enzyme (primary pathway) showing 8-35 fold activity increase from 2-8 units/g fresh weight to 18-60 units/g enabling direct malate decarboxylation producing pyruvate, NAD-malic enzyme displaying 3-12 fold elevation from 1-5 units/g to 5-20 units/g contributing to malate catabolism, citric acid cycle enzymes including malate dehydrogenase (converting malate to oxaloacetate), citrate synthase (condensing oxaloacetate with acetyl-CoA), aconitase (isomerizing citrate to isocitrate), and isocitrate dehydrogenase (oxidatively decarboxylating isocitrate) all maintaining or slightly increasing activity 5-15 units/g each ensuring pathway capacity for complete malate oxidation, and pyruvate dehydrogenase complex connecting malic enzyme-derived pyruvate to citric acid cycle through acetyl-CoA production. ||Gene expression patterns during activation demonstrate: VvME1 transcript rising from 1.2-4.0 fold (green berry relative to reference) to 20-65 fold (activation) representing dramatic upregulation, VvME2 showing 15-45 fold elevation with coordinated timing, citric acid cycle genes (VvACO for aconitase, VvIDH for isocitrate dehydrogenase, VvMDH for malate dehydrogenase) maintaining steady-state expression 4-15 fold adequate for pathway flux, respiratory chain genes (cytochrome oxidase, ATP synthase subunits) sustained at moderate-to-high levels 5-20 fold supporting electron transport and ATP synthesis, and transcriptional coordination suggesting master regulatory factors possibly including ripening-specific transcription factors (VvNAC, VvMYB families) activating multiple metabolic genes though specific regulators incompletely identified. ||Metabolic pathway integration during activation shows: malate from vacuolar storage (80-140 mM) transported to cytoplasm (8-20 mM) where accessible to malic enzyme and malate dehydrogenase, malic enzyme producing pyruvate entering mitochondria for oxidation or cytoplasmic metabolism, malate dehydrogenase interconverting malate and oxaloacetate enabling citric acid cycle entry, citric acid cycle completing oxidation producing NADH and FADH₂ for respiratory chain, and respiratory chain oxidizing reducing equivalents producing ATP supporting cellular metabolism with complete malate oxidation yielding ~15 ATP per malate molecule. ||Subcellular compartmentation of activated metabolism includes: cytoplasmic malic enzyme (60-75% of activity) providing primary decarboxylation site, mitochondrial malic enzyme (25-40% of activity) potentially supporting anaplerotic reactions or alternative malate catabolism, mitochondrial malate dehydrogenase within citric acid cycle matrix enabling cycle flux, and peroxisomal malate metabolism possibly contributing though role in grape incompletely defined. ||Cofactor requirements and regeneration show: NADP-malic enzyme producing NADPH potentially used for reductive biosynthesis (fatty acid, flavonoid, terpenoid synthesis all active during ripening) or oxidized for energy, NAD-malic enzyme and citric acid cycle producing NADH oxidized by respiratory chain Complex I generating proton gradient and ATP, FAD-dependent succinate dehydrogenase in citric acid cycle producing FADH₂ oxidized by Complex II, and cofactor balance maintained through multiple dehydrogenase reactions ensuring continued pathway flux. ||Respiratory characteristics during activation inclu berry O₂ consumption rates 1.0-2.2 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ similar to pre-veraison despite metabolic transition indicating sustained respiratory capacity, CO₂ production 1.1-2.6 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with respiratory quotient (RQ = CO₂/O₂) 1.08-1.30 indicating mixed substrate oxidation with organic acids contributing substantially, and respiratory contribution from malate catabolism estimated 30-50% of total CO₂ production during activation based on malate loss rates and respiratory measurements. ||Hormonal regulation of metabolism activation includes: abscisic acid spike from 70-200 ng/g to 800-1900 ng/g triggering ripening program including metabolic gene induction potentially through ABA-responsive elements in enzyme gene promoters, sugar accumulation creating hexokinase-mediated signaling potentially affecting metabolic gene expression though mechanisms for acids less defined than sugars, declining growth hormones removing developmental suppression allowing ripening metabolism activation, and potential ethylene involvement in cultivars showing climacteric-like behavior though most grapes non-climacteric with minimal ethylene role. ||Environmental influences on activation inclu temperature strongly affecting enzyme synthesis and activity with optimal 24-28°C supporting normal activation achieving full capacity within 5-8 days, warm conditions 28-32°C accelerating activation potentially causing premature excessive metabolism, heat stress >32°C dramatically enhancing activity potentially 50-120% of normal creating risk of excessive acid loss, cool conditions 18-24°C slowing activation extending establishment period to 8-14 days, and diurnal temperature fluctuation creating complex effects with warm days promoting activation while cool nights moderate overall metabolism. ||Light effects operate primarily through berry temperature with exposed clusters warming accelerating activation 20-40% compared to shaded fruit, photosynthetic effects minimal in ripening berries with limited chlorophyll, and canopy management creating substantial microclimate variation affecting activation timing and intensity across cluster positions. ||Water status effects show: adequate vine water status supporting normal metabolic function enabling appropriate activation, deficit potentially affecting timing and intensity though effects complex with moderate deficit sometimes enhancing through stress responses while severe deficit may impair through general metabolic limitation, and osmotic stress from high berry sugar potentially affecting enzyme activities though cells appear well-adapted to hyperosmotic conditions during ripening. ||Cultivar genetic variation demonstrates: low-acid cultivars showing rapid intense activation with enzyme activities 40-80 units/g combined malic enzyme within 4-6 days veraison, moderate varieties displaying 30-55 units/g in 6-9 days, and high-acid cultivars exhibiting slower activation 20-40 units/g over 8-14 days reflecting genetic differences in metabolic capacity and regulatory control. ||Physiological consequences inclu carbon flow redirected from storage to respiration with 15-35% of green berry organic acid carbon lost as CO₂ during ripening representing substantial respiratory cost, ATP production from acid oxidation supporting ripening processes including sugar transport, anthocyanin synthesis, cell wall modification, and flavor compound biosynthesis, and redox state affected by NADPH production potentially influencing antioxidant capacity and secondary metabolism. ||Quality implications inclu activation intensity and timing predicting acid decline trajectory with strong early activation indicating rapid loss potentially problematic in warm regions, inadequate activation suggesting acid retention possibly beneficial in cool climates or problematic requiring extended ripening, and spatial variation revealing vineyard heterogeneity affecting harvest maturity and quality consistency. ||Viticultural management includes: canopy practices controlling cluster microclimate with shading reducing berry temperature 3-8°C slowing activation 25-45% preserving acids in warm regions, irrigation management potentially moderating activation through cooling effects though mechanisms complex, avoiding severe environmental stresses during activation period as this critical window substantially affects final acid levels, and monitoring activation progress through enzyme assays or metabolite profiling enabling management intervention if excessive decline detected.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 comprehensive metabolism review || Famiani F, Cultrera NGM, Battistelli A, Casulli V, Proietti P, Standardi A, Chen ZH, Leegood RC, Walker RP (2005) Phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase and its potential role in the catabolism of organic acids in the flesh of soft fruit during ripening J Exp Bot 56:2959-2969 acid catabolism pathways || Ruffner HP, Hawker JS, Hale CR (1976) Temperature and enzymic control of malate metabolism in berries of Vitis vinifera Phytochem 15:1877-1880 enzyme control of metabolism."
},

  "pH_Increase_Start": {
  "definition": "A pH_Increase_Start is an Acid_Decline_Onset marked by elevation of berry juice pH from green berry minimum values toward ripening equilibrium through net organic acid decline and proton consumption.",
  "alternative_term": "berry pH elevation onset | acidity reduction initiation | proton depletion start | juice pH rise beginning |+ Beeren-pH-Erhöhungs-Onset | Azidität-Reduktions-Initiierung | Protonen-Abbau-Start | Saft-pH-Anstiegs-Beginn",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Mendoza Malbec vineyard in Argentina, pH increase start was monitored over 10 days in late January Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when pH rose from 2.92 to 3.16 (0.24 unit increase, 0.024 units per day average), titratable acidity declined from 19.8 to 15.6 g/L (21% reduction), malic acid decreased from 10.8 to 8.2 g/L, tartaric acid stable 7.4 g/L, berry K⁺ increased from 1650 to 2120 mg/kg, under hot high-altitude conditions (daily high 32-36°C accelerating acid decline and pH rise).",
  "editor_note": "pH_Increase_Start is distinguished from Acid_Decline_Onset by representing pH effect rather than acid cause, from later pH changes by showing onset (0.15-0.30 unit rise) rather than complete elevation, and from buffer capacity by focusing on pH measurement rather than acid-base chemistry. ||Rate: 0.012-0.040 units per week (cultivar/temperature dependent). ||Duration 7-12 days BBCH 83. ||Temperature sensitive: warm accelerates, >32°C excessive. ||Target final pH: whites 3.0-3.4, reds 3.3-3.7. ||pH_Increase_Start represents critical transition affecting wine style, stability, and quality. || This pH increase begins during veraison onset (BBCH 83), coinciding with acid decline onset, and is characterized by pH rising from pre-veraison minimum 2.7-3.1 (cultivar and maturity dependent) to early increase 2.9-3.3 over 7-12 days representing 0.15-0.30 unit elevation, corresponding titratable acidity declining from 17-25 g/L to 14-21 g/L (15-25% reduction) as organic acid anions removed, and buffer capacity adjusting as acid composition shifts from predominantly malate toward greater tartrate proportion affecting pH-acidity relationship. ||Biochemical basis of pH increase includes: organic acid decline particularly malate removal (8-14 g/L declining to 7-11 g/L) reducing total titratable hydrogen ions, malate as dicarboxylic acid (pKa₁ 3.40, pKa₂ 5.11) existing predominantly as divalent anion malate²⁻ at berry pH 2.8-3.2 contributing two titratable protons per molecule, tartaric acid (pKa₁ 2.98, pKa₂ 4.34) similarly diprotic but metabolically stable showing only dilutional decline, and pH calculated from Henderson-Hasselbalch equation pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA]) where declining acid concentrations shift equilibrium toward higher pH. ||Proton balance considerations show: organic acid anions (predominantly malate²⁻ and tartrate²⁻) serving as conjugate bases accepting protons maintaining acidic pH, malate removal through respiratory decarboxylation eliminating acid equivalents requiring compensatory ion adjustments, cation accumulation particularly potassium (rising from 1200-1800 to 1800-2500 mg/kg during pH increase) potentially affecting pH through charge balance though mechanisms debated, and vacuolar proton-ATPase activity potentially adjusting to maintain appropriate vacuolar pH despite changing acid concentrations. ||Buffer capacity changes during pH increase demonstrate: green berry with high organic acid content (20-30 g/L) showing strong buffer capacity requiring ~15-25 mL of 0.1 N NaOH per 10 mL juice to reach pH 8.2, early pH increase phase with declining acids (15-22 g/L) reducing buffer capacity to ~12-18 mL NaOH indicating less buffering against pH changes, and acid composition effects with malate (pKa₂ 5.11) providing stronger buffering near berry pH compared to tartrate (pKa₂ 4.34) so preferential malate loss reduces buffer capacity disproportionately. ||Cellular mechanisms underlying pH increase inclu vacuolar pH directly affecting juice pH with vacuole occupying 95-97% of mesocarp cell volume, tonoplast proton pumps (V-ATPase, V-PPase) potentially modulating proton content though activity likely reduced during ripening as vacuole transitions from acid accumulation to storage/dilution function, organic acid transport from vacuole to cytoplasm for metabolism requiring tonoplast carriers (possibly VvALMT family) affecting vacuolar acid pool, and apoplastic pH likely increasing parallel with vacuolar pH though measurements technically challenging in berry tissue. ||Temporal coordination of pH increase with other processes shows: pH rise beginning 0-2 days concurrent with acid decline onset indicating direct causal relationship, sugar accumulation proceeding simultaneously with pH increase creating developing balance between sweetness and acidity, berry softening and color development (reds) occurring during pH increase reflecting integrated ripening program, and pH trajectory paralleling acid decline throughout ripening until harvest with both approaching cultivar-specific equilibria. ||Environmental factors affecting pH increase rate inclu temperature strongly influencing through effects on acid metabolism with warm conditions 28-32°C accelerating pH rise 0.02-0.04 units per week faster than cool 20-24°C (0.012-0.025 units per week) through enhanced malate catabolism, heat stress >32°C causing rapid pH increase potentially 0.04-0.07 units per week producing excessive rise, and diurnal temperature effects with warm days promoting acid loss and pH increase while cool nights moderating overall change. ||Potassium effects on pH remain somewhat controversial: some research showing strong correlation between berry K⁺ accumulation (1500-2500 mg/kg) and pH increase suggesting K⁺ as key factor, alternative view that K⁺ accumulates passively responding to organic acid anion loss without causal role in pH, and practical observations that high-K⁺ grapes generally show higher pH though causation versus correlation unclear, with truth likely involving K⁺ affecting charge balance and potentially facilitating acid transport/metabolism rather than K⁺ directly determining pH. ||Cultivar variation in pH increase characteristics shows: low-pH cultivars (Riesling, Chenin Blanc potential final pH 3.0-3.3) exhibiting slow increase 0.012-0.020 units per week early phase, moderate varieties (Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon final pH 3.3-3.7) displaying 0.018-0.028 units per week, and high-pH types (Grenache, Viognier final pH 3.5-3.9) showing rapid increase 0.025-0.040 units per week reflecting genetic differences in acid metabolism and retention. ||Wine quality implications of pH inclu pH critically affecting wine character with appropriate 3.1-3.6 range (white 3.0-3.4, red 3.3-3.7) producing balanced wines, low pH <3.1 creating excessively tart wines potentially requiring deacidification though beneficial for aging potential and microbial stability, high pH >3.7 producing flat wines lacking structure with reduced color stability (reds), increased oxidation susceptibility, and higher spoilage risk from bacteria and yeast, and pH affecting malolactic fermentation with optimal 3.3-3.7 for bacterial activity. ||Color effects of pH increase in red grapes show: anthocyanin color forms pH-dependent with flavylium cation (red, protonated) dominant at pH <3.2, quinoidal base (purple-blue, deprotonated) increasing at pH 3.2-3.8, and carbinol (colorless) at pH >4.0, so pH increase from 3.0 to 3.4 during ripening shifting color from bright red toward purple-red affecting visual quality, and copigmentation effects also pH-sensitive with optimal color enhancement at pH 3.2-3.6 range typical during late ripening. ||Microbial stability considerations inclu pH <3.3 providing good protection against bacterial spoilage (Acetobacter, Lactobacillus), pH 3.3-3.5 moderate risk requiring sulfite protection, pH >3.5 high risk with aggressive antimicrobial management needed, and harvest timing decisions sometimes prioritizing pH control over sugar accumulation in warm vintages where excessive pH rise threatens wine stability. ||Analytical measurement of pH employs: calibrated glass electrode pH meter providing accurate measurement ±0.01-0.02 units, temperature compensation essential as pH varies ~0.02 units per °C, sample preparation requiring clarification by filtration or centrifugation preventing particulate interference, and correlation with titratable acidity with typical pH 3.2-3.4 corresponding to TA 6-9 g/L though relationship varies with acid composition. ||Viticultural management affecting pH includes: canopy practices controlling berry temperature with shading reducing warming 3-7°C slowing pH increase 20-35% through moderated acid decline, irrigation potentially affecting through cooling or dilution effects though mechanisms complex, crop load optimization with moderate yields potentially moderating pH rise compared to overcropped vines showing accelerated acid loss, rootstock selection with some stocks associated with lower berry pH though mechanisms (altered K⁺ uptake, vine vigor effects, other) debated, and harvest timing critically important as pH continues increasing throughout ripening requiring balance with other quality parameters.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 231-233 pH changes during ripening || Boulton RB, Singleton VL, Bisson LF, Kunkee RE (1996) Principles and Practices of Winemaking pages 38-45 juice pH and acidity || Mpelasoka BS, Schachtman DP, Treeby MT, Thomas MR (2003) A review of potassium nutrition in grapevines with special emphasis on berry accumulation Aust J Grape Wine Res 9:154-168 potassium and pH relationships."
},

  "Malic_Acid_Decline_Start": {
  "definition": "A Malic_Acid_Decline_Start is an Acid_Decline_Onset characterized by sustained progressive malate reduction with respiratory catabolism exceeding residual synthesis, reducing malic acid from 40–60% to 15–35% of total organic acids by harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained malate depletion | progressive malic acid loss | continuous malate catabolism | ongoing L-malate reduction |+ anhaltende Malat-Verminderung | progressive Äpfelsäure-Verlust | kontinuierlicher Malat-Katabolismus | fortlaufende L-Malat-Reduktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Rioja Tempranillo vineyard, malic acid decline start was tracked over 50 days from late August through October Year N+1 (BBCH 83-87) when malate declined from 9.8 g/L to 2.6 g/L (73% total loss, average 0.14 g/L per day), showing initial phase 9.8 → 7.5 g/L (days 0-12, 0.19 g/L per day), rapid phase 7.5 → 3.8 g/L (days 12-32, 0.19 g/L per day sustained), deceleration 3.8 → 2.6 g/L (days 32-50, 0.07 g/L per day), under typical Spanish continental conditions (daily high 26-30°C early season declining to 20-24°C late).",
  "editor_note": "Malic_Acid_Decline_Start is distinguished from Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation by representing sustained ongoing reduction (18-30% initial, up to 85-95% total) rather than enzymatic onset, from Initial_Acid_Reduction by showing specific malate focus rather than total acids, and from acid plateau by exhibiting active decline rather than stabilization. ||Duration entire ripening period 40-60 days. ||Loss rates: 0.10-0.50 g/L per day (temperature-dependent). ||Final levels: low-acid 1-3 g/L, moderate 2-5 g/L, high-acid 4-7 g/L. ||Malic_Acid_Decline_Start represents sustained process fundamentally altering berry acid balance affecting wine quality and style. || This decline start occurs during early-to-mid veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 2-6 days following malic enzyme activation, and is characterized by malic acid concentrations beginning sustained decrease from 8-14 g/L (80-140 mM) to 6-11 g/L over 8-14 days representing initial 18-30% reduction with decline continuing throughout ripening potentially reducing to 1-5 g/L at harvest (85-95% total loss in extreme cases), malate:tartrate ratio declining from 1.1-2.0:1 at onset toward 0.2-0.8:1 at harvest indicating preferential malate depletion, and respiratory malate contribution increasing from 25-40% of berry CO₂ production to 40-65% during active decline reflecting dominant role in respiratory substrate. ||Mechanisms driving sustained malate decline inclu malic enzyme activities maintained at 20-60 units/g fresh weight throughout ripening continuously catalyzing malate oxidation, citric acid cycle flux sustained enabling complete malate oxidation to CO₂, respiratory chain maintaining capacity for oxidizing NADH and FADH₂ from malate catabolism generating ATP, and cellular energetics favoring malate catabolism as efficient energy source (15 ATP per malate completely oxidized) supporting ripening processes including sugar transport, biosynthesis, and ion transport. ||Temporal pattern of malate decline shows: initial phase (BBCH 83-84, days 0-15 post-onset) with moderate loss 18-35% establishing declining trajectory, rapid phase (BBCH 84-85, days 15-35) showing maximum decline rates 0.15-0.45 g/L per day potentially losing 40-60% of onset malate, deceleration phase (BBCH 85-87, days 35-60) with slowing rates 0.08-0.20 g/L per day as substrate depletes, and plateau phase approaching harvest where malate reaches cultivar-specific minimum 1-6 g/L with further decline limited by low substrate availability. ||Absolute malate loss rates during decline show: early phase 0.10-0.25 g/L per day under moderate conditions (daily high 24-28°C), accelerating to peak rates 0.20-0.50 g/L per day during rapid phase particularly under warm conditions 28-32°C, and declining to 0.05-0.15 g/L per day late phase as malate depletes below 3-6 g/L, with cumulative loss over 40-60 day ripening period potentially 7-12 g/L representing 70-90% of onset malate in low-acid cultivars or warm vintages. ||Environmental factors critically affecting decline inclu temperature showing strong linear or exponential relationship with loss rate with each 1°C increase above 20°C accelerating decline approximately 8-15%, heat stress >32-35°C causing dramatic acceleration potentially doubling or tripling normal rates producing excessive loss and unbalanced fruit, cool conditions <20°C substantially slowing decline preserving acids beneficial in naturally low-acid cultivars, and cumulative heat effects where prolonged warm periods produce greater total loss than brief hot spells of equivalent average temperature. ||Diurnal temperature patterns affect total decline: regions with warm days (28-32°C) promoting catabolism but cool nights (12-18°C) reducing nocturnal losses showing intermediate total decline compared to constantly warm climates, Mediterranean climates with extreme diurnal fluctuation (15-20°C range) enabling acid preservation through cool night respite despite hot days, and continental climates with moderate diurnal range showing consistent decline rates throughout 24-hour period. ||Cluster microclimate effects demonstrate: sun-exposed clusters showing 30-60% faster malate decline than shaded clusters due to 4-10°C temperature differential with direct solar heating, canopy management effects substantial with strategic shading in warm regions preserving 20-45% more malate at harvest compared to fully exposed fruit, cluster position effects with interior canopy clusters retaining 15-35% higher malate than exterior positions, and aspect effects with southwestern exposure (northern hemisphere) showing maximum heating and malate loss versus northeastern showing moderation. ||Water status influences on decline show: effects complex and sometimes contradictory across studies with some finding deficit accelerating decline through stress-enhanced respiration while others show minimal effects, adequate vine water status generally supporting normal metabolic function enabling appropriate decline, severe deficit potentially disrupting metabolism either accelerating through stress or slowing through general impairment depending on intensity and duration, and irrigation management important for optimizing acid retention particularly in warm regions where deficit combined with heat may cause excessive loss. ||Cultivar genetic variation in decline characteristics demonstrates: low-acid varieties (Grenache final TA 4-6 g/L, Viognier 4.5-6.5 g/L) showing rapid extensive decline losing 80-92% of onset malate over 45-60 days with high malic enzyme activities 40-80 units/g sustained, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay 5-7 g/L, Merlot 5.5-7.5 g/L) displaying 70-85% malate loss with 30-55 units/g enzyme, and high-acid types (Riesling 6-9 g/L, Chenin Blanc 7-10 g/L) exhibiting slower decline 55-75% loss with 20-40 units/g enzyme reflecting genetic differences in metabolic capacity, enzyme regulation, and final acid set-points. ||Carbon budget implications inclu malate carbon lost as respiratory CO₂ representing substantial portion of berry carbon economy with 8-12 g/L malate loss equivalent to 6-9 g/L glucose-equivalent carbon (assuming molecular weight malate 134 g/mol, 4-carbon molecule), total malate carbon loss potentially 5-12% of berry dry weight accumulated during development representing significant respiratory cost, and net berry carbon balance showing import through sugar accumulation far exceeding loss through acid decline maintaining overall carbon gain during ripening. ||Physiological consequences of sustained decline inclu pH increasing continuously from 3.0-3.3 early decline to 3.2-3.8 harvest as malate removed affecting enzyme activities, membrane transport, and wine properties, buffer capacity declining as total organic acids reduce making berry pH more labile to environmental perturbations, and osmotic potential effects minor as malate contribution to total osmotic potential (~5-8% of total) relatively small compared to hexoses (70-80% of total). ||Wine quality impacts inclu final malate levels critically affecting wine style and stability with appropriate 1-4 g/L producing balanced wines, excessive decline to <1-2 g/L creating flat wines lacking acidity and structure particularly problematic in white wines and warm-climate reds, inadequate decline maintaining >5-7 g/L requiring winery intervention (cold stabilization, deacidification, extended malolactic) adding cost and potentially affecting quality, and malate:tartrate ratio at harvest influencing malolactic fermentation kinetics with high malate (>3-4 g/L) favoring rapid complete MLF while low malate potentially resulting in sluggish or stuck fermentation. ||Sensory implications inclu malic acid contributing sharp tart taste distinct from tartaric acid's more neutral acidity so high residual malate (>4-5 g/L) producing aggressive tartness, balanced malate levels 2-4 g/L contributing to wine freshness and structure, and low malate <2 g/L potentially leaving wines flat especially if tartaric also moderate creating overall acid deficiency. ||Viticultural management optimizing malate decline includes: canopy management strategically shading clusters in warm regions slowing decline 25-50% preserving final acids, irrigation timing and amount potentially moderating berry temperature through transpirational cooling, harvest timing decisions balancing sugar accumulation against continued acid loss particularly critical in warm vintages where excessive decline threatens quality, and rootstock selection with some stocks associated with higher berry malate retention though mechanisms incompletely defined.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 229-233 malate decline during ripening || Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 temperature effects comprehensive study || Lakso AN, Kliewer WM (1975) The influence of temperature on malic acid metabolism in grape berries Plant Physiol 56:370-372 classic temperature study."
},

  "Malate_Degradation_Onset": {
  "definition": "A Malate_Degradation_Onset is a Malic_Acid_Decline_Start comprising the establishment of net malate catabolism through malic enzyme and citric acid cycle activity exceeding any residual synthesis.",
  "alternative_term": "net malate catabolism onset | L-malate consumption initiation | malic acid oxidation start | respiratory malate utilization beginning |+ Netto-Malat-Katabolismus-Onset | L-Malat-Konsum-Initiierung | Äpfelsäure-Oxidations-Start | respiratorische Malat-Verwendungs-Beginn",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc vineyard in New Zealand, malate degradation onset was characterized in early February Year N+1 (BBCH 83, 3 days post-malic enzyme activation) when malate declined from 11.2 g/L to 9.4 g/L over 8 days (16% reduction, 0.22 g/L per day), NADP-malic enzyme activity 24 units/g FW, berry respiration 1.4 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹, estimated malate contribution 42% of CO₂ production, pH increased from 3.04 to 3.18, under moderate New Zealand summer conditions (daily high 23-26°C, cool nights 13-16°C).",
  "editor_note": "Malate_Degradation_Onset is distinguished from Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation by representing net catabolism rather than enzyme activation, from Malic_Acid_Decline_Start by showing onset (12-22% reduction) rather than sustained process, and from later degradation by exhibiting beginning rather than progressive loss. ||Enzyme activities 12-30 units/g NADP-ME at onset. ||Timing: 1-4 days post-enzyme activation BBCH 83. ||Temperature Q₁₀ 2.0-3.5. ||Malate_Degradation_Onset establishes declining trajectory continuing throughout ripening affecting wine acidity and balance. || This onset occurs during veraison initiation (BBCH 83), typically 1-4 days following malic enzyme activation, and is characterized by vacuolar malate concentrations beginning sustained decrease from 85-145 mM (8.5-14.5 g/L) to 70-120 mM over initial 6-10 days representing 12-22% reduction establishing clear declining trend, cytoplasmic malate turnover increasing as catabolism accelerates with estimated cytoplasmic residence time declining from 3-8 hours (green berry) to 1-4 hours (onset) reflecting enhanced metabolic flux, and berry respiratory CO₂ production showing 30-50% contribution from malate catabolism (based on isotope tracer studies) compared to <15-25% pre-veraison indicating metabolic shift. ||Biochemical pathways of malate degradation inclu NADP-malic enzyme (EC 1.1.1.40) catalyzing cytosolic oxidative decarboxylation L-malate + NADP⁺ → pyruvate + CO₂ + NADPH with activity 12-30 units/g fresh weight at onset providing primary degradation pathway, NAD-malic enzyme contributing 5-15 units/g secondary pathway, mitochondrial citric acid cycle degrading malate through sequential reactions malate → (malate dehydrogenase) → oxaloacetate → (citrate synthase with acetyl-CoA) → citrate → (aconitase) → isocitrate → (isocitrate dehydrogenase) → α-ketoglutarate → → → (multiple steps) → oxaloacetate completing cycle with CO₂ release at isocitrate and α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase steps, and complete malate oxidation yielding 15 ATP per malate through combined NADH and FADH₂ oxidation by respiratory chain. ||Enzyme kinetics enabling degradation show: NADP-malic enzyme Km for malate 0.5-2.0 mM well below cytoplasmic concentrations 6-18 mM ensuring near-Vmax activity, Vmax at onset 15-35 μmol malate oxidized g⁻¹ h⁻¹ adequate for observed decline rates ~0.12-0.30 g/L per day (~1.2-3.0 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), pH optimum 7.0-7.5 matching cytosolic pH enabling efficient catalysis, and substrate specificity highly selective for L-malate with minimal activity on other organic acids ensuring specificity. ||Subcellular trafficking of malate during degradation includes: vacuolar malate (70-130 mM) representing bulk storage slowly declining as tonoplast efflux enables cytoplasmic access, tonoplast malate transporters (possibly VvALMT family members) facilitating diffusion or secondary active transport from vacuole pH 2.7-3.0 to cytoplasm pH 7.0-7.4 against concentration gradient (vacuole 90 mM → cytoplasm 12 mM = 7.5-fold gradient) requiring energy input or ion coupling, cytoplasmic malate rapidly turning over through malic enzyme and malate dehydrogenase with steady-state 8-18 mM maintained by balance of influx and consumption, and potential mitochondrial uptake via dicarboxylate carrier enabling citric acid cycle entry though quantitative contribution versus cytosolic oxidation unclear. ||Metabolic fate of degradation products shows: CO₂ from malic enzyme and citric acid cycle diffusing from berry contributing to vineyard respiratory CO₂ flux estimated 0.15-0.35 g CO₂ per kg berries per day during active degradation representing ~40% of total berry respiration, pyruvate from malic enzyme entering multiple pathways including mitochondrial oxidation through pyruvate dehydrogenase (pyruvate + CoA + NAD⁺ → acetyl-CoA + CO₂ + NADH) feeding citric acid cycle, cytosolic metabolism through pyruvate kinase regenerating phosphoenolpyruvate for gluconeogenesis or other biosynthesis, conversion to alanine via alanine aminotransferase providing amino acid, and potential fermentative metabolism to lactate or ethanol under hypoxic conditions in berry interior. ||NADPH from NADP-malic enzyme utilized for: reductive biosynthesis including fatty acid synthesis (cuticle, membranes), flavonoid biosynthesis (anthocyanins in reds, flavonols), terpenoid biosynthesis (aroma compounds particularly in aromatic varieties), and antioxidant systems (glutathione reductase, thioredoxin reductase) with excess NADPH potentially oxidized by mitochondrial external NADH dehydrogenase for ATP generation. ||Energy yield from malate degradation calculated as: complete oxidation through malic enzyme plus citric acid cycle producing 15 ATP per malate (pyruvate → acetyl-CoA yields 1 NADH = 2.5 ATP, acetyl-CoA → 2 CO₂ in cycle yields 3 NADH + 1 FADH₂ + 1 GTP = 7.5 + 1.5 + 1 = 10 ATP, plus NADPH from malic enzyme potentially 2.5 ATP if oxidized, total ~15 ATP), compared to glucose complete oxidation yielding 32 ATP making malate moderately efficient substrate supporting ~47% of glucose energy yield per carbon atom, and malate catabolism during ripening potentially providing 25-45% of berry ATP production during peak degradation phase. ||Hormonal and metabolic regulation of degradation onset includes: ABA spike 60-200 → 800-2000 ng/g triggering ripening program including malic enzyme induction enabling degradation, sugar accumulation potentially creating metabolic signals affecting acid metabolism though mechanisms less defined, declining growth hormones removing developmental constraints allowing metabolic transition, and potential feedback regulation where declining malate levels may eventually limit further degradation through substrate availability rather than enzyme capacity. ||Environmental sensitivity demonstrates: temperature strongly affecting degradation rate with Q₁₀ = 2.0-3.5 (each 10°C increase doubling-to-tripling rate) making degradation highly temperature-dependent, warm conditions 28-32°C accelerating onset and subsequent degradation 40-80% compared to moderate 22-26°C, heat stress >32°C causing excessive degradation potentially depleting malate prematurely, and cool conditions 18-22°C slowing degradation preserving acids beneficial for cultivars prone to excessive loss. ||Cultivar genetic differences show: low-acid varieties exhibiting rapid early degradation with high enzyme activities, short lag from enzyme activation to net degradation 1-3 days, and extensive total depletion 80-95%, moderate cultivars showing intermediate characteristics 3-5 day lag and 70-85% depletion, while high-acid types display delayed degradation 5-8 day lag and moderate depletion 55-75% reflecting genetic variation in enzyme expression, substrate pools, and metabolic capacity. ||Physiological consequences inclu carbon loss representing respiratory cost with 10 g/L malate loss equivalent to ~7 g/L glucose-equivalent carbon (molecular weight basis), pH increase correlating with malate loss (each 1 g/L malate removal increasing pH approximately 0.03-0.06 units depending on buffer capacity), and osmotic effects minor as malate contributes only 5-10% of total berry osmotic potential compared to hexoses dominating 70-85%. ||Wine quality implications inclu degradation onset timing and intensity predicting final malate levels critical for wine balance, early rapid onset potentially indicating low final acids requiring monitoring and possible early harvest, delayed or slow onset suggesting acid retention possibly beneficial in warm climates, and spatial variation across vineyard revealing maturity heterogeneity requiring management. ||Monitoring degradation onset involves: HPLC organic acid analysis tracking malate concentrations showing declining trend, enzymatic malate assays providing rapid field assessment, titratable acidity measurement showing overall acid decline with malate contributing majority, and respiration measurements potentially revealing enhanced CO₂ production from acid catabolism though technically challenging in vineyard setting.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 malate catabolism comprehensive || Ruffner HP, Hawker JS, Hale CR (1976) Temperature and enzymic control of malate metabolism in berries of Vitis vinifera Phytochem 15:1877-1880 degradation mechanism || Famiani F, Battistelli A, Moscatello S, Cruz-Castillo JG, Walker RP (2015) The organic acids that are accumulated in the flesh of fruits:occurrence, metabolism and factors affecting their contents Plant Physiol Biochem 94:195-206 acid metabolism in fruits."
},

  "Respiratory_Malate_Consumption": {
  "definition": "A Respiratory_Malate_Consumption is a Malic_Acid_Decline_Start involving oxidative catabolism of malic acid producing CO₂, reducing equivalents, and ATP supporting cellular energy demands of ripening processes.",
  "alternative_term": "oxidative malate utilization | malic acid respiratory catabolism | L-malate oxidative decarboxylation | energy generation from malate |+ oxidative Malat-Verwendung | Äpfelsäure-respiratorischer Katabolismus | L-Malat-oxidative Decarboxylierung | Energie-Erzeugung aus Malat",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Valley Grenache vineyard, respiratory malate consumption was quantified over 42 days from late February through April Year N+1 (BBCH 84-87) when malate declined from 8.6 g/L to 1.8 g/L (total loss 6.8 g/L, 79%), showing peak consumption 0.42 g/L per day days 15-28 (daily high 30-33°C), declining to 0.15 g/L per day late phase (daily high 24-27°C as autumn progressed), berry respiration averaged 1.85 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with estimated 52% CO₂ from malate mid-period declining to 28% late as substrate depleted.",
  "editor_note": "Respiratory_Malate_Consumption is distinguished from Malate_Degradation_Onset by representing ongoing process (0.15-0.45 g/L per day) rather than onset, from Acid_Metabolism_Activation by focusing on respiratory substrate use rather than enzymatic activation, and from sugar accumulation by representing catabolic oxidation rather than anabolic storage. ||Duration 35-55 days BBCH 83-87. ||Temperature Q₁₀ 2.2-3.8. ||Energy yield ~15 ATP per malate. ||Contributes 35-65% berry respiration during peak. ||Respiratory_Malate_Consumption represents major carbon and energy flux during ripening fundamentally affecting berry composition and wine quality. || This consumption intensifies during veraison through ripening (BBCH 83-87), beginning 2-5 days post-degradation onset and continuing until malate substantially depleted, and is characterized by malate oxidation rates 0.15-0.45 g/L per day (1.5-4.5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹) during peak consumption representing 35-65% of total berry respiratory CO₂ production, energy yield from malate providing estimated 30-55% of berry ATP production during active consumption phase supporting ripening metabolism, and malate decline from early consumption 7-12 g/L to late phase 2-6 g/L approaching final cultivar-specific minima 1-5 g/L at harvest. ||Biochemical pathways of respiratory consumption inclu direct oxidative decarboxylation via NADP-malic enzyme producing pyruvate that enters mitochondria for complete oxidation through pyruvate dehydrogenase (pyruvate + CoA + NAD⁺ → acetyl-CoA + CO₂ + NADH) then citric acid cycle (acetyl-CoA → 2 CO₂ + 3 NADH + 1 FADH₂ + 1 GTP) generating reducing equivalents, complete oxidation pathway through citric acid cycle where malate dehydrogenase converts malate to oxaloacetate (coupled to NADH production) then citrate synthase condenses with acetyl-CoA producing citrate beginning full cycle producing 4 NADH + 1 FADH₂ + 1 GTP per malate, and respiratory chain oxidizing NADH and FADH₂ through Complexes I-IV generating proton gradient driving ATP synthase producing ~15 ATP per malate completely oxidized representing efficient energy extraction. ||Quantification of respiratory malate consumption employs: isotope tracer studies using ¹³C-labeled malate showing label incorporation into respiratory CO₂ revealing 40-70% of evolved CO₂ derived from malate during peak consumption, respiratory quotient (RQ) measurements showing values 1.08-1.35 during ripening compared to 0.95-1.05 from pure hexose oxidation indicating substantial organic acid contribution, malate concentration decline rates 0.15-0.45 g/L per day (molecular weight 134 g/mol = 1.1-3.4 mmol per kg per day) correlating with CO₂ production providing independent consumption estimate, and respiratory O₂ consumption 1.2-2.8 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with portion attributable to malate oxidation calculated from RQ and substrate composition. ||Temporal dynamics of consumption show: early phase (BBCH 83-84, days 0-15 post-onset) with moderate consumption 0.18-0.32 g/L per day as malate remains abundant 7-12 g/L, peak phase (BBCH 84-85, days 15-35) with maximum consumption 0.25-0.50 g/L per day under favorable conditions particularly warm temperatures, declining phase (BBCH 85-87, days 35-55) with slowing consumption 0.10-0.25 g/L per day as malate depletes to 2-6 g/L reducing substrate availability, and late phase approaching harvest with minimal consumption <0.05-0.12 g/L per day as malate approaches minimum sustainable levels 1-4 g/L. ||Enzyme activities supporting consumption remain elevated: NADP-malic enzyme sustained 30-60 units/g fresh weight throughout active consumption providing decarboxylation capacity, citric acid cycle enzymes maintained or increasing with malate dehydrogenase 20-45 units/g, citrate synthase 15-35 units/g, isocitrate dehydrogenase 12-28 units/g ensuring pathway flux, and respiratory chain complex activities sustained enabling complete oxidation with cytochrome c oxidase 8-18 units/g and ATP synthase adequate for energy production. ||Energy budget calculations demonstrate: berry ATP demand during ripening estimated 45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ supporting active sugar transport (15-25 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹), biosynthesis (anthocyanins, phenolics, aromatics using 10-20 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), membrane transport (ion pumps, metabolite transport 12-22 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), and maintenance respiration (8-18 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), malate oxidation potentially providing 25-50 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during peak consumption (based on 1.7-3.4 μmol malate oxidized g⁻¹ h⁻¹ × 15 ATP per malate) representing 30-60% of total ATP production, and complementary hexose oxidation contributing remaining ATP from imported sugars with small glycolytic contribution before vacuolar storage. ||Temperature sensitivity of respiratory consumption shows: Q₁₀ = 2.2-3.8 indicating strong temperature dependence with each 10°C increase approximately doubling-to-tripling consumption rate, warm conditions 28-32°C producing consumption rates 0.35-0.55 g/L per day potentially depleting malate rapidly, heat stress >32-35°C causing excessive consumption 0.45-0.70 g/L per day creating risk of premature total depletion, cool conditions 18-24°C moderating consumption to 0.15-0.28 g/L per day enabling acid retention, and cumulative degree-days from veraison strongly predicting total malate loss with correlation r² = 0.75-0.90 across seasons and sites. ||Diurnal patterns of consumption reveal: daytime consumption elevated 30-60% above nighttime due to higher berry temperature from solar heating creating midday peaks 0.30-0.60 g/L per day versus nighttime troughs 0.12-0.28 g/L per day, cumulative 24-hour consumption integrating day-night cycles determining total daily loss typically 0.20-0.40 g/L in moderate climates, and regions with extreme diurnal temperature range (>15-20°C) showing substantial day-night variation potentially enabling acid preservation through cool night respite despite warm days. ||Cluster microclimate effects on consumption inclu sun-exposed clusters showing 35-70% faster consumption than shaded clusters through elevated temperature 4-10°C above air temperature, canopy position effects with exterior southern/western exposure (northern hemisphere) experiencing maximum consumption while interior northern positions showing moderation, and targeted shading reducing consumption 25-50% in warm regions critical management tool for acid retention. ||Cultivar variation in consumption characteristics demonstrates: low-acid varieties displaying high consumption rates 0.30-0.55 g/L per day peak sustained over extended period 25-40 days producing 85-95% total depletion, moderate cultivars showing 0.22-0.42 g/L per day over 30-45 days achieving 70-85% depletion, and high-acid types exhibiting lower rates 0.15-0.32 g/L per day over 35-50 days resulting 55-75% depletion reflecting genetic differences in respiratory capacity and metabolic programming. ||Physiological integration shows: respiratory malate consumption coordinated with sugar accumulation creating characteristic ripening metabolism where catabolic acid oxidation supports anabolic sugar storage, carbon balance showing net import through sugar far exceeding loss through acid consumption maintaining overall carbon accumulation, and metabolic flexibility enabling berry to utilize both hexoses and organic acids as respiratory substrates depending on availability and metabolic demands. ||Quality implications inclu consumption rate and duration determining final malate levels critical for wine acid balance, excessive consumption in warm vintages producing low-acid fruit <2-3 g/L malate requiring winery intervention, inadequate consumption in cool years maintaining high acids >5-7 g/L potentially beneficial for some styles but requiring extended ripening or deacidification for others, and spatial variation in consumption across vineyard creating maturity heterogeneity affecting harvest decisions. ||Viticultural management targeting optimal consumption includes: canopy practices controlling berry temperature with strategic shading reducing consumption 30-55% in warm regions preserving acids, irrigation potentially moderating through cooling effects though mechanisms complex, harvest timing balancing continued sugar accumulation against progressive acid loss requiring integrated maturity assessment, and environmental monitoring tracking heat accumulation enabling prediction of consumption trajectory informing management decisions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Ruffner HP, Hawker JS, Hale CR (1976) Temperature and enzymic control of malate metabolism in berries of Vitis vinifera Phytochem 15:1877-1880 classic respiratory consumption study || Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 comprehensive temperature effects || Lakso AN, Kliewer WM (1975) The influence of temperature on malic acid metabolism in grape berries Plant Physiol 56:370-372 respiratory consumption quantification."
},

  "Active_Malic_Enzyme_Activity": {
  "definition": "An Active_Malic_Enzyme_Activity is a Malic_Acid_Decline_Start consisting of sustained high-level operation of NADP- and NAD-dependent malic enzymes catalyzing oxidative decarboxylation of malate to pyruvate.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained malic enzyme catalysis | NADP-ME activity maintenance | malate decarboxylase function | pyruvate-producing enzyme operation |+ anhaltende Malat-Enzym-Katalyse | NADP-ME-Aktivitäts-Aufrechterhaltung | Malat-Decarboxylase-Funktion | Pyruvat-produzierende Enzym-Operation",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Merlot vineyard, active malic enzyme activity was assayed over 45-day ripening period from mid-August through September Year N+1 (BBCH 83-87) showing NADP-malic enzyme maintained 42-58 units/g FW (average 48 units/g), NAD-ME 14-19 units/g (average 16 units/g), combined 56-74 units/g supporting malate decline from 9.2 to 3.1 g/L (average loss 0.14 g/L per day), VvME1 expression sustained 35-48 fold, under warm Napa conditions (daily high 28-32°C maintaining high enzyme activity and rapid malate catabolism).",
  "editor_note": "Active_Malic_Enzyme_Activity is distinguished from malic enzyme induction by representing sustained activity (25-70 units/g NADP-ME) rather than initial upregulation, from respiratory consumption by focusing on specific enzyme rather than overall process, and from acid decline by representing enzymatic mechanism rather than net compositional change. ||Duration entire ripening BBCH 83-87. ||Temperature optimum 25-32°C, Q₁₀ 2.2-3.5. ||pH optimum 7.0-7.5. ||Km malate 0.5-2.5 mM. ||Active_Malic_Enzyme_Activity represents critical sustained enzymatic function enabling malate decline fundamentally affecting wine acidity and quality. || This active period extends from early veraison through late ripening (BBCH 83-87), typically 3-8 days post-enzyme induction through harvest, and is characterized by NADP-malic enzyme activity maintained at 25-70 units/g fresh weight (compared to pre-veraison 2-8 units/g) representing 5-12 fold sustained elevation, NAD-malic enzyme showing 8-25 units/g activity (from 1-5 units/g pre-veraison) contributing secondarily, combined malic enzyme capacity 35-90 units/g adequate for observed malate decline rates 0.18-0.50 g/L per day, and enzyme activity per se (units/g) remaining relatively stable throughout ripening though total berry activity potentially declining with berry expansion diluting enzyme concentrations. ||Enzymatic reaction mechanism involves: NADP-malic enzyme (EC 1.1.1.40) catalyzing L-malate + NADP⁺ → pyruvate + CO₂ + NADPH through oxidative decarboxylation proceeding via transient oxaloacetate intermediate rapidly decarboxylating to pyruvate, reaction thermodynamics strongly favorable with ΔG°' = -5.2 kcal/mol ensuring irreversibility under physiological conditions, pH optimum 7.0-7.5 matching cytosolic environment enabling efficient catalysis, and metal cofactor requirement with Mg²⁺ or Mn²⁺ (typically 2-5 mM) essential for catalytic activity. ||Enzyme kinetics during active period demonstrate: Km for L-malate 0.5-2.5 mM (isoform-dependent) well below cytoplasmic substrate concentrations 8-20 mM ensuring near-maximum velocity operation, Km for NADP⁺ 15-45 μM with cytoplasmic NADP⁺ pool 50-150 μM providing adequate cofactor, Vmax values 28-75 μmol malate oxidized per g fresh weight per hour in vitro corresponding to observed in vivo rates 1.5-4.5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (0.15-0.45 g/L per day berry volume basis) accounting for cellular compartmentation and regulatory factors, and product inhibition by pyruvate at >5-10 mM and competitive inhibition by oxaloacetate at >0.5-2.0 mM potentially limiting activity though normal cellular concentrations typically below inhibitory thresholds. ||Enzyme structure and molecular properties inclu molecular mass 60-68 kDa for NADP-malic enzyme monomers with active enzyme existing as tetramers 240-270 kDa, amino acid sequence showing conserved active site residues across plant species with catalytic Lys and Asp residues essential for decarboxylation, NAD-malic enzyme showing similar structure 62-70 kDa monomers with tetrameric active form, and isoform diversity with multiple genes (VvME1, VvME2, potentially others) encoding cytosolic and mitochondrial forms providing functional redundancy and compartment-specific regulation. ||Gene expression supporting active enzyme levels shows: VvME1 transcript maintained at 25-70 fold above green berry baseline throughout ripening ensuring continued protein synthesis, VvME2 sustained 20-55 fold with similar kinetics, mRNA half-life 6-12 hours requiring continuous transcription to maintain steady-state levels, and translation efficiency apparently high with transcript levels correlating well with protein abundance and enzyme activity (r² = 0.78-0.92) indicating minimal post-transcriptional regulation. ||Protein turnover and stability during active period includes: enzyme protein half-life estimated 24-48 hours requiring continued synthesis to maintain elevated levels, proteolytic degradation through ubiquitin-proteasome system and autophagy balancing synthesis, post-translational modifications potentially including phosphorylation affecting activity or stability though modifications in grape malic enzyme incompletely characterized, and protein quality control ensuring properly folded active enzyme with misfolded proteins degraded preventing inactive enzyme accumulation. ||Subcellular distribution of active enzyme demonstrates: cytosolic malic enzyme 60-75% of total activity providing primary site for malate oxidation in cytoplasm pH 7.0-7.4, mitochondrial forms 25-40% of activity potentially supporting anaplerotic reactions or alternative metabolic functions, and compartment-specific regulation potentially adjusting distribution optimizing cellular metabolism though mechanisms incompletely defined. ||Metabolic integration of active malic enzyme includes: substrate supply from vacuolar malate through tonoplast transport maintaining cytoplasmic pool 8-20 mM adequate for enzyme saturation, cofactor availability with cytoplasmic NADP⁺/NADPH ratio ~3-8:1 (NADP⁺ 50-150 μM, NADPH 15-30 μM) favoring oxidative decarboxylation direction, product removal with pyruvate entering mitochondria for further oxidation preventing accumulation that could inhibit enzyme, and CO₂ efflux through diffusion eliminating product maintaining reaction favorability. ||NADPH utilization from malic enzyme activity includes: reductive biosynthesis consuming ~40-65% of NADPH for fatty acid, flavonoid, and terpenoid synthesis all active during ripening, antioxidant systems utilizing 15-30% for glutathione reductase and other NADPH-dependent antioxidant enzymes, and excess NADPH potentially oxidized by mitochondrial external NADH dehydrogenase for ATP production though inefficient compared to direct NADH oxidation. ||Pyruvate fate from malic enzyme reaction shows: mitochondrial import through pyruvate carrier for oxidation via pyruvate dehydrogenase producing acetyl-CoA feeding citric acid cycle representing primary fate ~60-80%, cytoplasmic metabolism through pyruvate kinase potentially regenerating phosphoenolpyruvate for biosynthesis ~10-20%, transamination to alanine providing amino acid ~5-12%, and minor fermentative conversion to lactate or ethanol under hypoxic conditions in berry interior <5%. ||Temperature effects on enzyme activity demonstrate: optimal activity 25-32°C matching berry temperatures during warm days, activity increasing approximately 2.2-3.5 fold per 10°C rise (Q₁₀) creating strong temperature sensitivity, heat stress >35-38°C beginning enzyme denaturation reducing activity 20-50% potentially irreversibly inactivating enzyme, and cool temperatures 15-22°C reducing activity 40-70% compared to optimal providing mechanism for acid preservation in cool climates or shaded canopy positions. ||pH effects on activity show: sharp pH optimum 7.0-7.5 with activity declining 30-60% at pH 6.5 and 50-80% at pH 8.0, cytoplasmic pH 7.0-7.4 throughout ripening maintaining near-optimal conditions, and vacuolar pH 2.7-3.2 precluding activity in that compartment ensuring malate metabolism restricted to cytoplasm after tonoplast transport. ||Cultivar variation in active enzyme characteristics includes: low-acid varieties maintaining 45-85 units/g combined malic enzyme throughout ripening enabling extensive acid depletion, moderate cultivars showing 30-60 units/g supporting intermediate decline, and high-acid cultivars displaying 20-45 units/g contributing to acid retention, with activity levels strongly correlated with final berry malate r² = 0.80-0.93 demonstrating causal relationship. ||Environmental modulation of activity includes: temperature directly affecting catalytic rate as described above, potential acclimation effects where sustained warm temperatures may induce additional enzyme synthesis enhancing capacity, and stress responses where severe heat or water deficit may actually reduce activity despite elevated temperature through protein denaturation or metabolic dysfunction. ||Inhibitor studies reveal: oxaloacetate competitive inhibition Ki ~0.8-2.5 mM, ATP allosteric inhibition at >3-5 mM in some isoforms potentially providing energy status regulation, and citrate inhibition at >2-5 mM potentially coordinating with citric acid cycle flux though physiological relevance uncertain given normal cellular metabolite concentrations. ||Viticultural implications inclu enzyme activity levels predicting malate decline trajectory enabling forecasting final acids, canopy management affecting berry temperature modulating enzyme activity and thus malate loss rates, and spatial variation in activity across vineyard zones potentially contributing to maturity heterogeneity. ||Research applications involve: enzyme activity assays measuring malate oxidation spectrophotometrically through NADPH production at 340 nm providing quantitative assessment, gene expression analysis correlating transcript levels with activity confirming transcriptional control, and inhibitor or temperature manipulation studies revealing regulatory mechanisms and optimization strategies for acid management.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis:a review Vitis 21:247-259 malic enzyme comprehensive review || Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 enzyme activity regulation || Hawker JS (1969) Changes in the activities of malic enzyme, malate dehydrogenase, phosphopyruvate carboxylase and pyruvate dehydrogenase during the development of a non-climacteric fruit:the grape Phytochem 8:9-23 classic enzyme activity study."
},

  "Active_Acid_Degradation": {
  "definition": "An Active_Acid_Degradation is a Veraison characterized by peak operation of organic acid catabolic machinery during mid-to-late véraison producing the steepest gradient of titratable acidity reduction.",
  "alternative_term": "peak acid catabolism phase | maximum organic acid degradation | intensive malate breakdown period | rapid deacidification phase |+ Spitzen-Säure-Katabolismus-Phase | maximale organische Säure-Degradation | intensive Malat-Abbau-Periode | rapide Entsäuerungs-Phase",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Paso Robles Grenache vineyard, active acid degradation was documented over 16 days in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when titratable acidity declined from 8.6 to 3.8 g/L (average 0.52 g/L per day peak rate), malic acid decreased from 5.2 to 1.4 g/L (0.42 g/L per day loss), pH increased from 3.28 to 3.64 (0.025 units per day average), berry Brix rose from 21.8° to 26.5°, under hot California interior conditions (daily high 33-37°C accelerating degradation, requiring early harvest at lower Brix to preserve minimal acid balance).",
  "editor_note": "Active_Acid_Degradation is distinguished from Initial_Acid_Reduction by representing peak (0.35-0.65 g/L per day TA) rather than early phase (0.18-0.35 g/L per day), from Malic_Acid_Decline_Start by focusing on maximum rate period rather than overall process, and from late decline by showing peak rather than deceleration. ||Duration 10-20 days BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature critically important: 28-32°C maximum rates, >32°C excessive. ||Malate contribution 50-70% respiratory CO₂. ||Critical window determining final acid balance. ||Active_Acid_Degradation represents most intensive period of compositional transformation during ripening. || This active phase occurs during mid-to-late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 84-85), typically 12-25 days post-veraison onset depending on temperature and cultivar, and is characterized by titratable acidity declining at maximum rates 0.35-0.65 g/L per day (compared to initial phase 0.18-0.35 g/L per day and late phase 0.10-0.25 g/L per day), malic acid showing peak degradation 0.30-0.55 g/L per day representing 3-6% of remaining malate per day under warm conditions, pH increasing most rapidly 0.025-0.050 units per day (0.18-0.35 units per week) creating dramatic compositional shift, and respiratory malate contribution reaching maximum 50-70% of total berry CO₂ production indicating acid catabolism dominates energy metabolism during this critical period. ||Enzymatic basis of active degradation includes malic enzyme activities sustained at peak levels with NADP-malic enzyme 40-70 units/g fresh weight (10-15 fold above green berry), NAD-malic enzyme 12-28 units/g contributing secondarily, combined capacity 55-95 units/g providing enzymatic machinery adequate for observed maximum rates, citric acid cycle enzyme activities maintained or slightly elevated 15-35% above early veraison ensuring pathway flux for complete malate oxidation, and respiratory chain complexes operating at high capacity with cytochrome c oxidase 12-22 units/g enabling efficient electron transport and ATP synthesis supporting active metabolism. ||Substrate availability during active degradation shows vacuolar malate declining from 5-9 g/L at phase onset to 2-5 g/L at conclusion representing 40-60% depletion of phase-entry levels, cytoplasmic malate maintained at 8-18 mM through continued tonoplast efflux balancing consumption, tonoplast transport capacity adequate providing 2-4 μmol malate g⁻¹ h⁻¹ efflux from vacuole matching or exceeding cytoplasmic consumption rate, and substrate availability still non-limiting during active phase with vacuolar pools sufficient enabling maximum enzyme velocity operation without kinetic constraints. ||Temporal dynamics of active degradation demonstrate initial acceleration from early veraison 0.20-0.35 g/L per day to peak active rates 0.40-0.65 g/L per day over 5-10 days representing 1.8-2.5 fold rate enhancement, sustained maximum rates 10-20 days duration (temperature and cultivar dependent) constituting critical window for acid loss, then deceleration as substrate depletes reducing to late phase 0.12-0.28 g/L per day over subsequent 8-15 days, and cumulative loss during active phase potentially 6-11 g/L malate representing 50-75% of total ripening period loss concentrated in this brief intensive period. ||Environmental factors critically affecting active degradation include temperature showing strongest effects during this phase with warm conditions 28-32°C producing maximum rates 0.50-0.70 g/L per day malate loss potentially depleting acids excessively, moderate warmth 25-28°C enabling appropriate rates 0.35-0.50 g/L per day achieving balanced final composition, cooler conditions 20-25°C moderating to 0.25-0.40 g/L per day preserving acids beneficial in low-acid cultivars, heat stress >32-35°C causing excessive degradation 0.60-0.90 g/L per day creating risk of over-deacidification producing unbalanced fruit, and cumulative heat exposure during active phase critically determining final acid levels with degree-days strongly correlating with total loss r² = 0.82-0.94. ||Diurnal temperature patterns during active phase show daytime peak degradation 0.50-0.80 g/L per day during warmest hours (typically 2-6 PM) when berry temperature maximum 30-38°C from solar heating, nighttime minimum rates 0.15-0.35 g/L per day as berry cools to near air temperature 15-22°C, daily integrated loss averaging 0.35-0.60 g/L representing balance of day-night extremes, and regions with large diurnal range (>15-20°C) showing moderated total loss despite hot days through cool night respite enabling acid preservation compared to constantly warm climates. ||Cluster microclimate effects particularly pronounced during active phase with sun-exposed clusters experiencing 45-85% faster degradation than shaded fruit due to 5-12°C temperature differential, canopy position showing substantial variation with exterior southwestern clusters (northern hemisphere) losing acids 50-100% faster than interior northeastern positions, and targeted shading interventions most effective during active phase reducing degradation 30-55% through berry temperature moderation 4-8°C cooling preserving 3-6 g/L additional malate at harvest. ||Water status interactions during active phase demonstrate adequate vine hydration supporting normal metabolic function enabling appropriate degradation without stress enhancement, moderate deficit (stem water potential -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) generally compatible with normal rates though effects variable across cultivars with some showing slight acceleration through stress-enhanced respiration while others unaffected, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) producing complex effects either accelerating through metabolic stress or impairing through general dysfunction depending on deficit intensity and cultivar sensitivity, and irrigation management during active phase critically important with strategic timing potentially moderating degradation through transpirational cooling or direct berry hydration effects. ||Cultivar genetic variation in active degradation characteristics shows low-acid varieties (Grenache, Viognier, Müller-Thurgau) exhibiting intense active phase with rates 0.50-0.75 g/L per day sustained 12-18 days producing 7-12 g/L malate loss during phase alone resulting final levels 1-3 g/L, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon) displaying 0.38-0.55 g/L per day for 15-22 days losing 5-10 g/L achieving 2-5 g/L final, and high-acid types (Riesling, Chenin Blanc, Barbera) showing moderated rates 0.28-0.45 g/L per day over 18-28 days with 4-8 g/L phase loss maintaining 4-7 g/L final reflecting genetic differences in enzyme capacity, metabolic regulation, and acid retention mechanisms. ||Respiratory characteristics during active degradation include berry O₂ consumption elevated 1.8-3.2 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ supporting enhanced metabolism, CO₂ production 2.2-4.0 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with respiratory quotient 1.18-1.35 indicating substantial organic acid contribution, malate-derived CO₂ estimated 50-70% of total based on isotope tracer studies and malate loss rates, and ATP production from malate oxidation potentially 40-65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ providing 35-60% of berry energy requirements during active phase supporting sugar transport, biosynthesis, and cellular maintenance. ||Carbon and energy budget during active phase demonstrates carbon loss through respiratory CO₂ from malate representing 4-8 g glucose-equivalent per kg berries over phase duration (based on 6-11 g/L malate loss × molecular weight conversion), net berry carbon balance remaining positive as hexose import 120-220 g glucose per kg berries far exceeds organic acid loss maintaining overall accumulation, energy yield from malate catabolism supporting intensive metabolic activities of ripening including sugar transport (15-30% of ATP demand), anthocyanin synthesis in reds (8-18%), cell wall modification (6-14%), and membrane transport (12-22%), and metabolic efficiency with combined sugar storage and acid catabolism enabling berry to sustain ripening processes without excessive respiratory carbon loss compared to scenario of sugar-only respiration. ||Physiological consequences of active degradation include pH increasing rapidly from 3.1-3.4 at phase onset to 3.3-3.7 at conclusion representing 0.15-0.35 unit rise critically affecting multiple processes including enzyme activities (many pH-sensitive showing altered kinetics), membrane transport (H⁺-coupled systems affected), anthocyanin color in reds (pH shift from red toward purple as quinoidal forms increase proportion), and microbial vulnerability (pH >3.5 substantially increasing spoilage risk), buffer capacity declining from 14-20 mL to 9-14 mL of 0.1 N NaOH per 10 mL juice as total organic acids reduce making berry pH more labile, malate:tartrate ratio declining from 0.8-1.5:1 to 0.3-0.9:1 fundamentally altering acid composition character, and osmotic potential effects minor with acid contribution <8-12% of total berry osmotic potential dominated by hexoses 75-85%. ||Coordination with other ripening processes during active phase shows sugar accumulation typically approaching peak simultaneously with Brix increasing 2.5-4.5% per week creating developing sweetness-acidity balance, berry softening largely completed 75-95% with firmness approaching asymptotic minimum, color development in reds reaching 85-100% final anthocyanin levels with both processes coordinated through common ABA regulation, and flavor-aroma compound synthesis intensifying as ripening advances with esters, terpenes, and other volatiles accumulating creating characteristic ripe fruit character. ||Quality implications of active degradation phase include rate and duration during this critical window largely determining final acid levels and pH affecting wine style, structure, and stability, excessive active degradation particularly in warm vintages producing low-acid fruit pH >3.7 creating flat wines lacking structure with reduced color stability in reds and increased microbial vulnerability requiring careful harvest timing or winery intervention, inadequate active degradation in cool vintages maintaining high acids TA >8-10 g/L producing overly tart fruit requiring extended ripening for acid reduction or winery deacidification, spatial variation in active degradation across vineyard creating maturity heterogeneity with some zones over-deacidified while others retain acids complicating harvest decisions and requiring selective management, and balance achievement between sufficient acid decline and retention of adequate acidity for wine quality requiring integrated monitoring and management throughout active phase. ||Harvest timing considerations during active phase involve recognition that acids declining most rapidly during this period requiring frequent monitoring (2-3 times per week) to track trajectory, integration with sugar accumulation assessment ensuring appropriate sweetness-acidity balance achieved simultaneously, pH monitoring critically important as rapid increase during active phase can reach undesirable levels before adequate sugar accumulation in warm conditions, phenolic maturity assessment particularly reds ensuring tannin polymerization and seed maturation synchronized with sugar-acid development, and flexibility in harvest date potentially valuable as 3-7 day window during active phase can produce substantially different final composition. ||Viticultural management during active degradation includes canopy interventions with strategic cluster shading most effective during this phase as temperature sensitivity highest, irrigation management potentially moderating degradation through berry cooling though mechanisms complex and requiring careful timing to avoid negative vigor or dilution effects, crop load considerations with overcropping potentially accelerating active degradation through stress while optimal loads enabling appropriate rates, disease monitoring critical as changing berry composition (declining acids, increasing sugars, softening) increases vulnerability to Botrytis, sour rot, and other pathogens requiring preventive protection, and harvest preparation advancing as active degradation indicates approaching maturity requiring readiness for prompt picking when optimal parameters achieved. ||Monitoring strategies during active phase involve frequent berry sampling every 2-4 days tracking acid decline trajectory enabling forecasting of harvest timing, combined assessment of TA, pH, malate, and tartrate providing comprehensive acid profile, integration with Brix, phenolics, and sensory evaluation ensuring holistic maturity determination, spatial sampling across vineyard zones revealing heterogeneity requiring selective management, and historical data compilation enabling year-to-year comparison and predictive modeling of active phase dynamics informing future management decisions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 229-233 peak acid decline || Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 temperature effects during peak phase || Lakso AN, Kliewer WM (1975) The influence of temperature on malic acid metabolism in grape berries Plant Physiol 56:370-372 peak degradation rates."
},

  "Peak_Acid_Reduction_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Acid_Reduction_Rate is an Active_Acid_Degradation marked by maximum velocity of titratable acidity decline with all components of the acid degradation pathway at peak efficiency.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum deacidification velocity | fastest TA decline rate | peak titratable acidity reduction | maximum acid loss rate |+ maximale Entsäuerungs-Geschwindigkeit | schnellste TA-Abnahme-Rate | Spitzen-titrierbare-Azidität-Reduktion | maximale Säure-Verlust-Rate",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Priorat Garnacha vineyard in Spain, peak acid reduction rate was measured over 11 days in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when titratable acidity declined from 6.8 to 2.9 g/L (average 0.63 g/L per day, 4.4 g/L per week), malic acid decreased from 3.8 to 1.2 g/L (0.46 g/L per day), pH increased from 3.42 to 3.78 (0.033 units per day), berry Brix 24.2° rising to 27.8°, under extreme Priorat heat (daily high 34-38°C, slate soils radiating heat), necessitating immediate harvest despite high sugar to preserve minimal acidity for wine balance.",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Acid_Reduction_Rate is distinguished from Active_Acid_Degradation by representing maximum velocity (0.45-0.75 g/L per day) rather than overall active phase, from Initial_Acid_Reduction by showing peak rather than early rates, and from Rapid_Acidity_Decline by focusing on rate measurement rather than compositional trajectory. ||Duration 8-14 days BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature optimum 28-32°C, >32°C excessive. ||Malate contributes 75-90% of TA reduction. ||Critical determinant of final acid balance. ||Peak_Acid_Reduction_Rate represents maximum velocity of compositional transformation affecting wine quality. || This peak rate occurs during mid-to-late veraison (BBCH 84-85), typically 15-22 days post-veraison onset in warm conditions or 18-28 days in moderate conditions, and is characterized by titratable acidity declining 0.45-0.75 g/L per day (3.2-5.2 g/L per week) representing net loss of 5-8% remaining acid daily under warm conditions, malate-specific decline contributing 75-90% of total TA reduction with 0.35-0.60 g/L per day malate loss, pH increasing 0.030-0.055 units per day (0.21-0.38 units per week) creating rapid compositional shift, and remaining berry acidity potentially declining from 7-11 g/L to 3-6 g/L over 8-12 day peak period representing 50-70% loss of this phase's entry values. ||Biochemical mechanisms enabling peak rate include malic enzyme activities at absolute maximum 50-85 units/g fresh weight combined NADP-ME and NAD-ME providing saturating catalytic capacity with Vmax 40-75 μmol malate oxidized g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in vitro translating to 3-6 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in vivo accounting for compartmentation and regulation, citric acid cycle flux maximized with malate dehydrogenase, citrate synthase, and isocitrate dehydrogenase all operating at elevated rates 25-50 units/g each ensuring complete oxidation pathway capacity, respiratory chain activity enhanced with O₂ consumption 2.2-3.8 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ oxidizing NADH and FADH₂ from malate catabolism, and cellular energetics optimized with ATP production from acid oxidation reaching 55-95 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ providing 40-70% of berry energy requirements during peak supporting intensive ripening metabolism. ||Substrate dynamics at peak rate show vacuolar malate 4-8 g/L (40-80 mM) declining rapidly still above kinetic limitation threshold, tonoplast transport maximized 3-5 μmol malate g⁻¹ h⁻¹ efflux maintaining cytoplasmic supply, cytoplasmic malate 10-20 mM sustained above enzyme Km 0.5-2.5 mM ensuring near-Vmax kinetics, and pH gradients vacuole 2.8-3.2 versus cytoplasm 7.0-7.4 driving facilitated diffusion potentially supplemented by secondary active transport maintaining substrate flow to catabolism. ||Metabolic integration at peak rate demonstrates respiratory malate contribution 55-75% of total CO₂ production indicating acid catabolism dominates energy metabolism temporarily exceeding hexose oxidation contribution, pyruvate production from malic enzyme 3.0-5.5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ entering mitochondria for complete oxidation or cytoplasmic metabolism, NADPH generation 3.0-5.5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from NADP-malic enzyme supporting reductive biosynthesis (anthocyanin, flavonoid, terpenoid synthesis all active) or oxidized for additional ATP, and carbon flow redirected substantially from storage functions toward respiratory energy production reflecting metabolic priorities during intensive ripening. ||Environmental factors producing peak rate include temperature optimum 28-32°C enabling maximum enzyme activities and metabolic flux producing highest rates 0.55-0.75 g/L per day, extreme warmth 32-36°C potentially exceeding optimal causing 0.60-0.85 g/L per day loss creating risk of excessive deacidification, moderate warmth 24-28°C supporting near-peak rates 0.40-0.60 g/L per day achieving appropriate acid reduction, cooler conditions 20-24°C limiting to 0.28-0.45 g/L per day through kinetic constraints preserving acids, and heat accumulation during peak window with cumulative degree-days >30°C strongly predicting total acid loss r² = 0.84-0.95 enabling forecasting and management. ||Diurnal variation at peak rate shows midday maximum 0.70-1.10 g/L per day during hottest hours 1-5 PM when berry temperature peaks 32-40°C from solar radiation, early morning and evening rates 0.35-0.55 g/L per day as berry temperature moderate 24-28°C, nighttime minimum 0.18-0.38 g/L per day with berry cooling to 16-24°C substantially reducing metabolic rates, and daily integrated rate averaging 0.45-0.70 g/L representing time-weighted mean of diurnal extremes with warm-climate regions showing higher averages through extended warm periods while temperate regions show moderation through cool nights. ||Cluster exposure effects particularly dramatic at peak rate with fully sun-exposed clusters experiencing berry temperatures 6-14°C above shaded fruit creating 60-120% faster acid reduction, southwestern exposure (northern hemisphere) showing maximum rates through afternoon solar heating combined with diurnal heat accumulation, northeastern exposure demonstrating moderated rates through limited direct sun and cooler microclimate, and interior canopy positions maintaining 35-60% slower rates than exterior enabling acid preservation through natural shading. ||Water relations influences at peak rate demonstrate adequate vine water status supporting maximum metabolic capacity enabling peak rates without limitation, moderate deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) showing variable effects with some cultivars displaying 10-25% rate enhancement through stress while others unaffected, severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa) generally impairing rate 25-50% through metabolic dysfunction despite potential stress-enhancement of individual enzymes, and irrigation timing during peak potentially moderating rates through transpirational cooling or direct berry hydration though effects complex and requiring cultivar-specific optimization. ||Cultivar genetic variation in peak rate characteristics shows low-acid varieties achieving 0.60-0.85 g/L per day maximum sustained 8-14 days rapidly depleting to final 1-3 g/L, moderate cultivars displaying 0.45-0.65 g/L per day over 12-18 days reaching 2-5 g/L final, and high-acid types exhibiting 0.32-0.52 g/L per day for 15-24 days maintaining 4-7 g/L final reflecting genetic differences in maximum enzyme capacity, substrate availability, and metabolic set-points determining acid retention. ||Temporal relationship to other ripening processes shows peak acid reduction typically coinciding with or slightly preceding peak sugar import (both 15-25 days post-veraison onset), berry softening largely completed 80-100% during peak acid reduction period, color development in reds approaching maximum 90-100% with both processes ABA-coordinated, and flavor-aroma synthesis intensifying as ripening advances with volatiles accumulating creating sensory ripeness synchronized with compositional changes. ||Physiological consequences of peak rate include pH rising most rapidly potentially 0.030-0.055 units per day creating 0.25-0.45 unit increase over 8-12 day peak period substantially affecting berry chemistry and wine quality, buffer capacity declining dramatically from 12-18 mL to 8-13 mL of 0.1 N NaOH per 10 mL juice making pH increasingly labile to perturbations, malate:tartrate ratio collapsing from 0.6-1.2:1 to 0.2-0.6:1 fundamentally shifting acid balance character, and anthocyanin color expression in reds affected by pH shift with movement from red-dominant (pH 3.1-3.3) toward purple-red (pH 3.4-3.7) as quinoidal forms increase proportion. ||Quality implications of peak rate include rate magnitude and duration determining trajectory toward final acid levels with excessive peak producing low-acid fruit pH >3.7 problematic for wine stability and structure, inadequate peak in cool regions maintaining TA >8-10 g/L requiring extended ripening or winery intervention, timing relative to sugar accumulation affecting harvest decisions with rapid acid loss potentially necessitating earlier harvest at lower Brix to preserve balance, and spatial variation in peak rates across vineyard creating maturity heterogeneity requiring selective harvest or acceptance of compositional variation in must. ||Wine style implications include final pH critically affecting character with whites optimal 3.0-3.4, reds 3.3-3.7, values outside these ranges producing suboptimal wines, malolactic fermentation kinetics affected by residual malate with >3-4 g/L supporting rapid complete MLF while <2 g/L potentially causing sluggish or stuck fermentation, aging potential influenced by pH with lower values (3.1-3.4) enhancing stability and longevity through reduced oxidation and better color retention, and regional adaptation with warm regions requiring management to prevent excessive peak while cool regions may benefit from or require extended peak period achieving adequate deacidification. ||Harvest timing during peak rate requires frequent monitoring every 2-3 days as compositional changes rapid, integrated assessment combining acid monitoring with sugar, phenolic, and flavor evaluation ensuring holistic maturity, forecasting final composition based on current rate and remaining expected growing degree-days enabling proactive harvest scheduling, and flexibility to harvest promptly when optimal parameters achieved as 3-5 day delay during peak can produce substantially altered composition potentially compromising quality targets. ||Viticultural interventions during peak rate include canopy shading strategically applied reducing berry temperature 4-9°C slowing rate 30-60% preserving acids critical in warm regions, irrigation potentially moderating through cooling effects though timing and amount requiring careful management avoiding negative vigor or dilution consequences, crop thinning pre-peak potentially beneficial concentrating resources avoiding stress-accelerated loss though post-peak intervention ineffective, and disease protection essential as changing composition increases vulnerability requiring preventive fungicide and sanitation. ||Monitoring and forecasting strategies include frequent laboratory analysis tracking TA, pH, malate, and tartrate every 2-4 days during peak enabling trajectory visualization, portable meters (pH, TA) for rapid field assessment guiding detailed sampling, spatial sampling across vineyard zones revealing heterogeneity requiring zone-specific management, degree-day accumulation models predicting expected loss based on temperature forecast enabling proactive decisions, and sensory evaluation ensuring acid-driven tartness declining appropriately coordinating with developing sweetness and flavor ripeness.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 peak rate quantification || Lakso AN, Kliewer WM (1975) The influence of temperature on malic acid metabolism in grape berries Plant Physiol 56:370-372 maximum rates || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 ripening dynamics including peak acid decline."
},

  "Maximum_Malate_Breakdown": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Malate_Breakdown is an Active_Acid_Degradation characterized by highest malate-specific degradation rate driven by combined optimal enzymatic capacity, substrate availability, and environmental conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "peak malate catabolism | maximum L-malate degradation | intensive malic acid breakdown | highest malate oxidation rate |+ Spitzen-Malat-Katabolismus | maximale L-Malat-Degradation | intensive Äpfelsäure-Abbau | höchste Malat-Oxidations-Rate",
  "example_of_usage": "In a McLaren Vale Shiraz vineyard in Australia, maximum malate breakdown was quantified over 13 days in mid-February Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when malate declined from 5.6 to 1.8 g/L (average 0.58 g/L per day, 4.1 g/L per week loss), combined malic enzyme activity 72 units/g FW, berry respiration 2.6 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with 68% CO₂ from malate based on isotope studies, pH increased from 3.36 to 3.69, Brix 23.5° to 27.2°, under hot Australian summer conditions (daily high 32-36°C sustaining maximum breakdown rates).",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Malate_Breakdown is distinguished from Peak_Acid_Reduction_Rate by focusing on malate-specific rather than total TA, from Active_Acid_Degradation by representing maximum phase rather than overall active period, and from Respiratory_Malate_Consumption by showing peak rather than sustained process. ||Rates: 0.40-0.70 g/L per day malate. ||Duration 10-18 days BBCH 84-85. ||Respiratory contribution 60-80% CO₂ from malate. ||Temperature Q₁₀ 2.5-4.0. ||Maximum_Malate_Breakdown represents most intensive period of malate depletion fundamentally determining wine acidity character. || This maximum breakdown occurs during mid-to-late veraison (BBCH 84-85), typically 16-24 days post-veraison onset depending on temperature regime and cultivar, and is characterized by malate declining at peak rates 0.40-0.70 g/L per day (2.8-4.9 g/L per week) representing 6-10% of remaining malate per day under warm conditions, malic enzyme activities sustained at absolute maximum 55-90 units/g fresh weight combined NADP-ME and NAD-ME operating near saturation, respiratory CO₂ production from malate reaching maximum contribution 60-80% of total berry respiration indicating acid catabolism temporarily dominates energy metabolism, and malate concentration potentially declining from 4-8 g/L at maximum onset to 1.5-4.5 g/L at conclusion over 10-16 day period representing 50-70% depletion during this intensive phase. ||Enzymatic mechanisms of maximum breakdown include NADP-malic enzyme at peak activity 45-75 units/g fresh weight catalyzing oxidative decarboxylation malate → pyruvate + CO₂ + NADPH at maximal velocity 32-68 μmol malate oxidized g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in vitro with in vivo rates 4-7 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ accounting for compartmentation and regulatory factors, NAD-malic enzyme contributing 15-30 units/g providing secondary pathway augmenting total capacity, citric acid cycle enzymes operating at elevated rates with malate dehydrogenase 30-55 units/g converting malate to oxaloacetate feeding cycle for complete oxidation, and respiratory chain complexes maximally active oxidizing NADH and FADH₂ from malate catabolism producing ATP with cytochrome c oxidase 15-28 units/g ensuring efficient electron transport. ||Gene expression supporting maximum breakdown shows VvME1 transcript sustained at 40-75 fold above green berry baseline maintaining enzyme protein synthesis, VvME2 similarly elevated 30-60 fold providing redundancy and capacity, citric acid cycle genes (VvMDH, VvCS, VvIDH) maintained at 8-25 fold supporting pathway flux, and transcriptional stability with half-life 8-14 hours requiring continuous synthesis but steady-state levels achieved indicating balanced synthesis-degradation maintaining enzyme concentrations throughout maximum period. ||Substrate kinetics during maximum breakdown demonstrate cytoplasmic malate 12-22 mM substantially above enzyme Km 0.5-2.5 mM ensuring near-Vmax operation with substrate saturation 85-95%, vacuolar malate 3-7 g/L (30-70 mM) declining but still adequate for sustained cytoplasmic supply, tonoplast transport delivering 3.5-6.0 μmol malate g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from vacuole to cytoplasm matching or slightly exceeding consumption rate preventing substrate limitation, and pH gradient (vacuole 2.9-3.3, cytoplasm 7.1-7.5) maintaining driving force for facilitated diffusion potentially augmented by H⁺-coupled secondary active transport. ||Metabolic fate of breakdown products includes pyruvate from malic enzyme (3.5-6.5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ production) predominantly entering mitochondria through pyruvate carrier for oxidation via pyruvate dehydrogenase then citric acid cycle producing acetyl-CoA representing primary fate 70-85%, minor cytoplasmic metabolism through pyruvate kinase or transamination 10-20%, fermentative conversion to lactate or ethanol under hypoxic conditions particularly berry interior 5-12%, and complete oxidation pathway yielding CO₂ quantified through respiratory measurements showing 60-80% of evolved CO₂ derived from malate during maximum breakdown based on isotope tracer studies and mass balance calculations. ||NADPH utilization from maximum malic enzyme activity includes reductive biosynthesis consuming 45-70% for flavonoid synthesis (anthocyanins in reds accumulating 50-120 mg/kg per day during maximum requiring substantial NADPH), fatty acid synthesis for membrane and cuticle (15-25% NADPH demand), terpenoid biosynthesis particularly aromatic varieties (8-18%), antioxidant systems (glutathione reductase, thioredoxin reductase) maintaining redox homeostasis (12-22%), and excess NADPH oxidation by mitochondrial external NADH dehydrogenase for ATP generation though less efficient than direct NADH oxidation. ||Energy budget during maximum breakdown shows ATP production from malate catabolism reaching 60-105 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (based on 4-7 μmol malate g⁻¹ h⁻¹ × 15 ATP per malate complete oxidation) providing 45-75% of berry total energy requirements during this phase, ATP utilization supporting sugar transport (18-32 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹), biosynthesis including anthocyanins and secondary metabolites (12-25 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), membrane ion pumps maintaining electrochemical gradients (15-28 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), and cellular maintenance respiration (10-20 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), demonstrating critical role of malate catabolism supporting intensive ripening metabolism. ||Temperature sensitivity of maximum breakdown shows Q₁₀ = 2.5-4.0 indicating very strong temperature dependence with each 10°C increase producing 2.5-4 fold rate enhancement, optimal temperature 28-32°C producing maximum rates 0.55-0.75 g/L per day enabling efficient breakdown without excessive loss, warm conditions 32-35°C causing accelerated breakdown 0.65-0.95 g/L per day creating risk of over-deacidification, moderate warmth 24-28°C supporting appropriate rates 0.40-0.60 g/L per day achieving balanced final composition, and cooler conditions 18-24°C limiting to 0.25-0.42 g/L per day preserving acids beneficial for high-acid cultivars or cool-climate viticulture. ||Diurnal dynamics during maximum breakdown reveal pronounced variation with daytime peak 0.70-1.20 g/L per day during afternoon maximum temperatures 32-42°C berry surface from solar heating, morning and evening rates 0.40-0.65 g/L per day at moderate temperatures 25-30°C, nighttime minimum 0.18-0.40 g/L per day with berry cooling to 15-22°C substantially reducing metabolic rates, and daily integrated breakdown averaging 0.45-0.75 g/L representing time-weighted mean critically determining cumulative loss over maximum period. ||Cluster microclimate variations produce substantial differences in maximum breakdown with sun-exposed southwestern clusters (northern hemisphere) experiencing 70-140% faster breakdown than shaded positions through elevated temperatures 7-15°C above air temperature, eastern exposure showing moderate rates through morning sun limited afternoon heating, northern positions maintaining coolest temperatures preserving acids through reduced breakdown 40-75% of southwestern rates, and targeted shading during maximum period most effective intervention reducing breakdown 35-65% through berry temperature moderation 5-10°C cooling. ||Water status interactions during maximum breakdown demonstrate adequate vine hydration essential for supporting maximum metabolic flux enabling appropriate rates without stress acceleration, moderate deficit (stem ψ -1.0 to -1.4 MPa) showing inconsistent effects across cultivars with some displaying 15-30% enhancement through stress-induced respiration while others maintain normal rates, severe deficit (<-1.6 MPa) generally impairing maximum through metabolic dysfunction reducing rates 30-60% despite high temperature, and irrigation strategies during maximum requiring balance between moderating breakdown through cooling versus avoiding excessive vine vigor or berry dilution. ||Cultivar genetic variation in maximum breakdown characteristics shows low-acid varieties (Grenache typical final TA 4-6 g/L) exhibiting intense maximum with rates 0.60-0.95 g/L per day sustained 9-15 days producing near-complete depletion to 1-3 g/L final malate, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Chardonnay 5-7 g/L final) displaying 0.45-0.70 g/L per day for 12-18 days achieving 2-5 g/L final, and high-acid types (Riesling, Chenin Blanc 6-9 g/L final) showing moderated maximum 0.32-0.55 g/L per day over 14-22 days retaining 4-7 g/L final reflecting genetic differences in enzyme expression levels, respiratory capacity, and metabolic programming determining acid retention set-points. ||Physiological consequences include malate:tartrate ratio declining dramatically from 0.5-1.0:1 at maximum onset to 0.15-0.45:1 at conclusion fundamentally shifting organic acid balance from malate-dominant toward tartrate-dominant character affecting wine sensory properties, pH increasing rapidly 0.25-0.45 units over maximum period creating substantial changes in berry chemistry affecting enzyme activities and secondary metabolism, and carbon loss through respiratory CO₂ representing 5-9 g glucose-equivalent per kg berries (based on molecular weight conversion from 5-9 g/L malate loss) though net carbon balance remains positive through concurrent hexose import far exceeding acid loss. ||Quality implications of maximum breakdown include rate and extent determining final malate levels critically affecting wine acidity and style with appropriate final 2-5 g/L supporting balanced wines and successful malolactic fermentation, excessive breakdown to <1.5-2 g/L producing low-acid wines pH >3.6-3.8 problematic for structure, stability, and MLF kinetics, inadequate breakdown maintaining >5-7 g/L creating overly tart wines requiring deacidification or extended MLF, and timing relative to phenolic and flavor development affecting harvest decisions requiring integration of multiple maturity parameters. ||Viticultural management during maximum includes strategic canopy shading reducing berry temperature 5-11°C slowing breakdown 40-70% preserving acids most effective in warm regions, irrigation timing potentially moderating through transpirational cooling or direct berry effects though mechanisms complex, avoiding severe deficit stress that can either accelerate through stress responses or impair through metabolic dysfunction depending on intensity, disease control essential as high-sugar soft berries increasingly vulnerable to Botrytis and sour rot requiring preventive protection, and harvest readiness as maximum breakdown indicates approaching maturity requiring prompt action when optimal parameters achieved.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 maximum breakdown || Ruffner HP, Hawker JS, Hale CR (1976) Temperature and enzymic control of malate metabolism in berries of Vitis vinifera Phytochem 15:1877-1880 malate catabolism maximum || Walker RP, Famiani F (2018) Organic acids in fruits:metabolism, functions and contents Hort Rev 45:371-430 malate breakdown comprehensive."
},

  "Rapid_Acidity_Decline": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Acidity_Decline is an Active_Acid_Degradation marked by the steepest gradient of total berry titratable acidity and pH transformation toward the balanced ripe state.",
  "alternative_term": "steep total acid reduction | accelerated TA decline | rapid deacidification | fast acidity decrease |+ steile Gesamt-Säure-Reduktion | beschleunigte TA-Abnahme | rapide Entsäuerung | schnelle Azidität-Abnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Zinfandel vineyard, rapid acidity decline was documented over 16 days in late August to early September Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when titratable acidity decreased from 10.2 to 4.8 g/L (total reduction 5.4 g/L, average 0.48 g/L per day, 3.4 g/L per week), pH increased from 3.28 to 3.62 (0.024 units per day), malate declined from 6.4 to 2.1 g/L, tartaric stable at 6.8 g/L, berry Brix rose from 22.5° to 28.2°, under warm California conditions (daily high 29-33°C) necessitating harvest at target Brix to preserve minimal acidity for balance.",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Acidity_Decline is distinguished from Peak_Acid_Reduction_Rate by representing measurable compositional change rather than velocity metric, from Maximum_Malate_Breakdown by focusing on total acidity rather than malate-specific, and from Initial_Acid_Reduction by showing steep gradient (0.35-0.60 g/L per day) rather than early moderate phase (0.18-0.35 g/L per day). ||Duration 12-20 days BBCH 84-85. ||TA reduction 40-60% of entry values. ||pH increase 0.15-0.35 units. ||Critical period determining wine acidity and style. ||Rapid_Acidity_Decline represents most visible compositional transformation during ripening affecting harvest timing and quality. || This rapid decline occurs during mid-to-late veraison through early ripening (BBCH 84-85), typically 14-26 days post-veraison onset depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by titratable acidity decreasing from 8-14 g/L at rapid onset to 4-8 g/L at conclusion over 12-20 day period representing 3.5-6.5 g/L total reduction and 40-60% depletion of entry values, daily TA decline rates 0.35-0.60 g/L per day (2.5-4.2 g/L per week) creating steep trajectory visible in sequential sampling data, pH increasing from 3.2-3.5 to 3.4-3.8 over rapid period representing 0.15-0.35 unit elevation at 0.020-0.040 units per day, and malate:tartrate ratio shifting from 0.6-1.3:1 to 0.2-0.7:1 indicating preferential malate loss driving acidity changes. ||Compositional changes during rapid decline show malate declining 4-8 g/L to 1.5-4.5 g/L representing 3-6 g/L loss accounting for 65-85% of total TA reduction, tartaric acid relatively stable 5-9 g/L showing only minor apparent changes <5-15% primarily dilutional from berry expansion, minor acids (citric, succinic) collectively <1.5 g/L making small contributions, and acid composition fundamentally transforming from malate-rich (45-65% of total acids) to tartrate-dominant (55-75% of final acids) character altering sensory properties and wine processing behavior. ||Biochemical mechanisms enabling rapid decline include sustained high malic enzyme activities 45-80 units/g combined NADP-ME and NAD-ME catalyzing malate decarboxylation at rates supporting observed decline, citric acid cycle maintaining flux for complete malate oxidation, respiratory chain efficiently oxidizing reducing equivalents, vacuolar tonoplast transport delivering 3-5 μmol malate g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to cytoplasm for catabolism, and metabolic integration where acid catabolism provides 45-70% of berry ATP production supporting concurrent sugar accumulation, biosynthesis, and cellular maintenance. ||pH dynamics during rapid decline demonstrate relationship to acid concentration with Henderson-Hasselbalch equation pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA]) describing equilibrium, buffer capacity declining from 14-20 mL to 9-14 mL of 0.1 N NaOH per 10 mL juice as total acids reduce making pH more sensitive to small acid changes, malate loss contributing disproportionately to pH increase as pKa₂ 5.11 provides stronger buffering near berry pH compared to tartrate pKa₂ 4.34, and potassium accumulation from 1800-2500 to 2200-3000 mg/kg potentially affecting pH through charge balance though exact mechanism debated with correlation strong (r² = 0.72-0.88) but causation unclear. ||Temporal coordination with other processes shows rapid acidity decline typically coinciding with or slightly preceding peak sugar accumulation (both 15-25 days post-veraison), berry softening completed 85-100% during rapid decline creating characteristic ripe texture, color development in reds reaching maximum 95-100% anthocyanin accumulation coordinated through ABA regulation, flavor-aroma compound synthesis intensifying with esters, terpenes, and volatiles accumulating creating sensory ripeness, and metabolic integration where declining respiratory acid substrate potentially influences subsequent sugar respiration patterns as berry transitions toward maturity. ||Environmental temperature effects critically determine rapid decline characteristics with warm conditions 28-32°C producing maximum decline rates 0.50-0.65 g/L per day enabling rapid trajectory potentially excessive in low-acid cultivars, moderate warmth 24-28°C supporting appropriate rates 0.38-0.52 g/L per day achieving balanced final acidity, cooler conditions 20-24°C limiting to 0.28-0.42 g/L per day beneficial for acid retention in high-acid varieties, heat stress >32-35°C causing excessive decline 0.60-0.85 g/L per day creating risk of over-deacidification pH >3.7-3.9 problematic for wine quality, and cumulative heat during rapid period (degree-days >28°C) strongly correlating with total acid loss enabling predictive modeling for harvest planning. ||Cluster microclimate heterogeneity produces substantial variation in rapid decline with sun-exposed clusters showing 50-100% faster decline than shaded fruit through elevated temperatures creating spatial variation across vineyard and within canopy, southwestern exposure (northern hemisphere) experiencing maximum decline through afternoon solar heating combined with diurnal accumulation, interior canopy positions maintaining 35-65% slower decline preserving acids, and canopy management creating 3-8 g/L differences in final TA between exposed and shaded zones requiring consideration in harvest strategy and wine blending. ||Water relations effects during rapid decline demonstrate adequate vine water status supporting normal metabolic function enabling appropriate decline without stress effects, moderate deficit (-1.0 to -1.4 MPa stem ψ) showing variable effects across cultivars with some acceleration through stress-enhanced respiration balanced by potential cooling from reduced transpiration, severe deficit (<-1.6 MPa) generally disrupting normal decline either accelerating through metabolic stress or impairing through dysfunction depending on deficit intensity and cultivar response, and irrigation management during rapid decline requiring careful balance between moderating excessive decline through cooling versus avoiding vigor or dilution issues. ||Cultivar variation in rapid decline characteristics shows low-acid varieties exhibiting intense rapid decline with 5-9 g/L TA loss over 12-18 days reaching final 3-5 g/L and pH 3.5-3.9, moderate cultivars displaying 4-7 g/L loss over 14-22 days achieving 4-7 g/L final and pH 3.3-3.7, and high-acid types showing moderated decline 3-5 g/L loss over 16-26 days maintaining 5-9 g/L final and pH 3.0-3.5 reflecting genetic differences in enzyme capacity and acid retention mechanisms. ||Quality implications include final acidity determining wine style, balance, and stability with appropriate ranges white wines TA 5-8 g/L pH 3.0-3.4, red wines 5-7 g/L pH 3.3-3.7 producing quality wines with structure and aging potential, low final acidity TA <4-5 g/L pH >3.6-3.8 creating flat wines lacking structure with reduced color stability (reds), increased oxidation susceptibility, and elevated microbial spoilage risk requiring careful winemaking, high final acidity TA >9-11 g/L pH <3.1 producing excessively tart wines potentially requiring deacidification though providing excellent aging foundation and microbial stability, and acid-sugar balance critically affecting sensory character with optimal ratios 20-35:1 (Brix:TA) producing harmonious wines while imbalanced ratios requiring technical adjustment or blending. ||Malolactic fermentation considerations include final malate levels affecting MLF kinetics and extent with >3-4 g/L supporting complete rapid fermentation, 2-3 g/L enabling slower complete MLF potentially desirable for control, <1.5-2 g/L causing sluggish or stuck MLF problematic requiring careful bacterial strain selection and nutrient management, and pH affecting bacterial growth with optimal 3.3-3.7 for Oenococcus oeni while <3.1 or >3.9 inhibitory creating challenges. ||Harvest timing during rapid decline requires frequent monitoring 2-3 times per week as compositional changes rapid with 3-5 day difference producing substantially altered acid profiles, integration with sugar accumulation assessment ensuring appropriate sweetness-acidity balance achieved simultaneously, phenolic maturity evaluation particularly reds confirming tannin development synchronized with acid-sugar evolution, sensory assessment verifying flavor ripeness coordinated with analytical maturity, and flexibility in harvest date valuable as timing during rapid decline critically affects final composition enabling optimization for target wine style. ||Viticultural management includes canopy practices with strategic cluster shading most effective during rapid decline reducing temperature 4-9°C slowing decline 30-60% preserving acids critical in warm regions or low-acid cultivars, irrigation potentially moderating decline through berry cooling though mechanisms complex requiring cultivar-specific optimization, crop load management with appropriate fruit-to-leaf ratios preventing stress-accelerated decline while enabling normal rates, disease control essential as soft high-sugar berries vulnerable to Botrytis and sour rot requiring preventive protection, and harvest preparation advancing as rapid decline indicates approaching optimal maturity requiring readiness for prompt picking. ||Monitoring strategies involve laboratory analysis every 3-5 days tracking TA, pH, malate, tartrate enabling trajectory visualization and harvest forecasting, portable meters for field pH and TA screening guiding detailed sampling frequency and locations, spatial sampling across vineyard zones revealing heterogeneity requiring zone-specific management decisions, degree-day accumulation models predicting expected decline based on weather forecasts enabling proactive harvest scheduling, sensory evaluation confirming analytical findings ensuring acid-driven tartness declining appropriately coordinating with sugar and flavor development, and historical data compilation enabling comparison across seasons identifying vintage effects and refining management strategies.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 229-233 rapid acidity decline || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 compositional changes during ripening || Mpelasoka BS, Schachtman DP, Treeby MT, Thomas MR (2003) A review of potassium nutrition in grapevines with special emphasis on berry accumulation Aust J Grape Wine Res 9:154-168 acidity and pH relationships."
},

  "Acid_Metabolism_Shift": {
  "definition": "An Acid_Metabolism_Shift is a Veraison comprising the metabolic transition from organic acid synthesis and accumulation to organic acid catabolism and utilization in berry mesocarp tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "metabolic reprogramming | biosynthesis-to-catabolism transition | organic acid metabolism reversal | ripening metabolism activation |+ metabolische Neuprogrammierung | Biosynthese-zu-Katabolismus-Übergang | organische Säure-Metabolismus-Umkehr | Reifungs-Metabolismus-Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Trentino-Alto Adige Pinot Grigio vineyard, acid metabolism shift was characterized over 6 days in mid-August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when PEPC expression declined from 12-fold to 3-fold, VvME1 increased from 2-fold to 38-fold, VvME2 rose from 1.5-fold to 28-fold, PEPC activity dropped from 18 to 6 units/g FW, malic enzyme activity increased from 5 to 24 units/g FW, berry organic acids plateaued at 22 g/L then began decline, ABA rose from 125 to 1450 ng/g, under moderate Italian Alpine conditions (daily high 24-27°C supporting normal developmental transition).",
  "editor_note": "Acid_Metabolism_Shift is distinguished from Acid_Decline_Onset by representing metabolic reprogramming rather than net compositional change, from Malic_Acid_Decline_Initiation by focusing on system-wide transition rather than specific enzyme pathway, and from veraison onset by representing metabolic rather than visible phenological change. ||PEPC declines 40-75%, VvME increases 20-60 fold. ||Duration 4-10 days BBCH 83. ||ABA-triggered transcriptional reprogramming. ||Acid_Metabolism_Shift represents fundamental developmental transition enabling ripening metabolism. || This metabolic shift occurs during veraison onset (BBCH 83), typically 0-5 days concurrent with initial veraison signals and preceding active acid decline, and is characterized by transcriptional reprogramming with organic acid biosynthesis genes (phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase, citrate synthase in biosynthetic mode) downregulated 40-75% from green berry levels, malic enzyme genes upregulated 20-60 fold initiating catabolic pathway dominance, respiratory enzyme genes reoriented with citric acid cycle shifting from biosynthetic to oxidative mode supporting complete acid oxidation, and hormone signaling particularly ABA spike from 60-200 ng/g to 800-2000 ng/g triggering coordinate transcriptional changes affecting hundreds of metabolism genes orchestrating metabolic reprogramming. ||Biochemical manifestations of shift include organic acid accumulation ceasing with net synthesis rates declining from 0.05-0.15 g/L per day (late green berry) to near-zero or slightly negative at shift, total berry organic acid content reaching maximum 20-35 g/L then beginning decline, malate biosynthesis through phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase and malate dehydrogenase substantially reduced as PEPC activity declines 50-80% and biosynthetic MDH shifts toward oxidative function, and citric acid cycle transitioning from biosynthetic mode (producing precursors for amino acids, secondary metabolites) toward purely oxidative catabolism (consuming organic acids for energy) representing fundamental functional reorientation. ||Gene expression changes defining shift demonstrate PEPC genes (VvPEPC family) encoding phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase declining from 5-18 fold (green berry active accumulation) to 1-4 fold (post-shift baseline) indicating biosynthesis suppression, malic enzyme genes (VvME1, VvME2) increasing from 1-4 fold to 20-70 fold establishing catabolic machinery, citric acid cycle genes showing complex regulation with some (isocitrate dehydrogenase, α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase) maintaining or increasing to support oxidative flux while others (citrate synthase in biosynthetic context) declining, respiratory chain genes (cytochrome oxidase, ATP synthase) sustained or slightly elevated ensuring capacity for oxidizing acid-derived reducing equivalents, and transcription factors orchestrating shift (potentially VvNAC, VvMYB families responding to ABA signals) showing coordinate induction enabling metabolic reprogramming. ||Cellular compartmentation changes during shift include vacuolar function transitioning from active accumulation (requiring ATP-dependent acidification and ion transport) toward storage and controlled release (passive or facilitated efflux to cytoplasm for catabolism), tonoplast H⁺-ATPase and H⁺-PPase activities potentially declining 30-60% as acidification requirements decrease, vacuolar pH stabilizing around 2.8-3.2 versus active acidification to 2.5-2.8 during green berry growth, and organic acid transport proteins (VvALMT family potentially involved) adjusting from import to export mode enabling malate efflux for cytoplasmic catabolism. ||Enzyme activity transitions demonstrate PEPC declining from 8-25 units/g fresh weight (green berry peak) to 2-8 units/g (post-shift) representing 60-80% reduction in carboxylation capacity, biosynthetic malate dehydrogenase (cytoplasmic, favoring malate synthesis) declining or shifting toward oxidative mode, malic enzyme increasing from 2-8 units/g to 18-50 units/g establishing decarboxylation capacity, citric acid cycle enzymes maintaining or elevating activities supporting transition from biosynthesis to catabolism with malate dehydrogenase, aconitase, isocitrate dehydrogenase all 25-45 units/g adequate for oxidative flux, and pyruvate dehydrogenase complex potentially increasing activity linking malic enzyme-derived pyruvate to citric acid cycle. ||Respiratory metabolism transformation shows respiratory quotient (RQ = CO₂/O₂) shifting from 0.95-1.05 (green berry predominantly hexose oxidation) to 1.10-1.30 (ripening with substantial organic acid contribution) indicating metabolic substrate change, malate contribution to respiration increasing from <15-25% (green berry) to 35-55% (post-shift early ripening) based on isotope tracer studies and mass balance, total berry respiration rates relatively stable 0.9-2.2 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ before and after shift despite substrate change indicating metabolic continuity with altered fuel source, and ATP production transitioning from predominantly hexose-based toward mixed hexose-organic acid supporting ripening processes including sugar import, anthocyanin synthesis, and cell wall modification. ||Carbon flow reorientation involves shift from net carbon fixation through acids (CO₂ incorporation via PEPC during green berry growth) to net carbon loss through respiratory decarboxylation (CO₂ release from malic enzyme and citric acid cycle), carbon budget transforming from accumulation (net gain 0.8-1.8 g carbon per kg berries per day including acids and other compounds) to mixed pattern (acid carbon loss 0.3-0.8 g per kg per day balanced by sugar carbon gain 1.5-3.5 g per kg per day yielding net accumulation), and metabolic flexibility developing enabling berry to utilize multiple respiratory substrates (hexoses, organic acids, amino acids) adaptively responding to availability and metabolic demands. ||Hormonal orchestration of shift includes ABA as primary trigger with rising levels activating ABA-responsive transcription factors that bind ABRE elements in metabolism gene promoters, sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway potentially contributing with initial sugar accumulation creating glucose-6-phosphate signals affecting gene expression, declining growth hormones (gibberellin, auxin) removing developmental suppression allowing ripening program activation, and ethylene potentially involved in some cultivars though grape generally non-climacteric with minimal ethylene effects compared to climacteric fruits. ||Environmental factors modulating shift timing include temperature affecting developmental rate with warmer conditions 24-30°C potentially advancing shift 3-7 days compared to cooler 18-24°C through accelerated development, photoperiod and light quality potentially providing developmental cues with long days and high PAR supporting vegetative functions while shorter days and red:far-red light signals potentially triggering reproductive maturation including metabolic shift, water status with moderate deficit potentially advancing shift 2-5 days through ABA elevation and stress signaling, and nutritional status with adequate resources enabling normal timing while severe limitations potentially delaying through resource constraints affecting gene expression and enzyme synthesis. ||Cultivar genetic variation in shift characteristics shows early-ripening varieties displaying rapid complete shift over 4-7 days with dramatic gene expression changes and prompt metabolic transformation, mid-season cultivars showing 6-10 day transition period with progressive changes, and late cultivars exhibiting extended shift 8-14 days with gradual metabolic reorientation reflecting genetic differences in developmental programming and regulatory control. ||Physiological significance includes metabolic shift enabling transition from growth to ripening phase with resources redirected from structural development to storage and quality compound synthesis, carbon economy optimizing by catabolizing accumulated acids for energy rather than importing hexoses for respiration while simultaneously storing imported hexoses creating efficient dual metabolism, and developmental commitment where shift represents point-of-no-return with berry metabolism fundamentally reoriented toward ripening irreversibly even if environmental conditions later deteriorate. ||Quality implications include shift timing relative to other developmental processes affecting final composition with premature shift potentially causing inadequate acid accumulation producing low-acid fruit, delayed shift maintaining high acids potentially beneficial in warm regions or requiring extended ripening in cool climates, and coordination between acid metabolism shift and sugar accumulation onset critically determining whether appropriate sugar-acid balance achieved at harvest. ||Viticultural management affecting shift includes canopy management ensuring adequate photosynthesis providing resources for normal developmental progression, crop load optimization preventing excessive stress that could alter shift timing, irrigation management with moderate deficit potentially beneficial advancing shift slightly while severe deficit may disrupt, nutritional management ensuring adequate resources particularly nitrogen for enzyme synthesis supporting shift, and environmental monitoring tracking developmental progression enabling prediction of shift timing for harvest planning. ||Research applications include transcriptomic profiling revealing genome-wide expression changes during shift identifying regulatory networks, metabolomic analysis tracking metabolite dynamics showing substrate transitions, enzyme activity assays quantifying functional changes in metabolism confirming shift occurrence, and hormone manipulation studies with exogenous ABA or inhibitors revealing causal relationships between signals and metabolic reprogramming. ||Understanding metabolic shift provides insights into berry development biology revealing mechanisms of developmental transitions and enabling rational management strategies optimizing composition for quality wine production through informed viticultural practices targeting this critical physiological window.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 metabolism shift comprehensive || Terrier N, Glissant D, Grimplet J, Barrieu F, Abbal P, Couture C, Ageorges A, Atanassova R, Léon C, Renaudin JP, Dédaldéchamp F, Romieu C, Delrot S, Hamdi S (2005) Isogene specific oligo arrays reveal multifaceted changes in gene expression during grape berry development Plant Physiol 138:1617-1633 transcriptional changes during shift || Davies C, Boss PK, Robinson SP (1997) Treatment of grape berries, a nonclimacteric fruit with a synthetic auxin, retards ripening and alters the expression of developmentally regulated genes Plant Physiol 115:1155-1161 hormonal control of metabolism shift."
},

  "Metabolic_Pathway_Transition": {
  "definition": "A Metabolic_Pathway_Transition is an Acid_Metabolism_Shift comprising reorientation of the citric acid cycle from anaplerotic to oxidative mode, redirection of phosphoenolpyruvate metabolism from CO₂ fixation to decarboxylation, and reorganization of respiratory pathways toward organic acid catabolism.",
  "alternative_term": "pathway reorganization | central metabolism reorientation | TCA cycle functional shift | biosynthetic-to-catabolic conversion |+ Pfad-Reorganisation | Zentral-Metabolismus-Neuorientierung | TCA-Zyklus-funktionelle Verschiebung | biosynthetisch-zu-katabolis che-Umwandlung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Burgundy Chardonnay vineyard, metabolic pathway transition was characterized over 7 days in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 83) when PEPC activity declined from 16.5 to 4.8 units/g FW, NADP-malic enzyme increased from 4.2 to 28.5 units/g FW, pyruvate dehydrogenase rose from 11 to 19 units/g FW, isocitrate dehydrogenase maintained 32 units/g FW, berry organic acids plateaued at 24 g/L, respiratory quotient increased from 1.02 to 1.18 indicating enhanced organic acid respiration, under cool French conditions (daily high 22-25°C supporting gradual transition).",
  "editor_note": "Metabolic_Pathway_Transition is distinguished from Acid_Metabolism_Shift by representing specific pathway reorganization rather than overall metabolic reprogramming, from Respiratory_Substrate_Change by focusing on enzymatic pathways rather than substrate utilization, and from gene expression changes by representing functional activity rather than transcriptional control. ||PEPC declines 60-80%, malic enzyme increases 5-12 fold. ||Citric acid cycle shifts biosynthetic → oxidative. ||Duration 5-10 days BBCH 83. ||Metabolic_Pathway_Transition represents biochemical foundation enabling acid catabolism during ripening. || This transition occurs during veraison onset (BBCH 83), typically 1-6 days concurrent with transcriptional reprogramming and preceding active metabolic changes, and is characterized by citric acid cycle enzyme activities reorienting with oxidative enzymes (isocitrate dehydrogenase, α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase) maintaining or increasing 15-35% while biosynthetic citrate synthase in anaplerotic mode declining 25-50%, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase activity decreasing 60-80% eliminating primary CO₂ fixation pathway, malic enzyme activity increasing 5-12 fold establishing decarboxylation pathway dominance, and pyruvate metabolism shifting from predominantly biosynthetic uses toward oxidative citric acid cycle entry through pyruvate dehydrogenase complex with activity potentially increasing 30-60% supporting acid-derived pyruvate oxidation. ||Citric acid cycle reorganization involves functional transition from TCA cycle operating in biosynthetic mode during green berry growth (producing intermediates for amino acid synthesis, providing carbon skeletons for secondary metabolism, generating reducing equivalents for biosynthesis) toward purely oxidative catabolism during ripening (completely oxidizing acetyl-CoA and malate to CO₂, maximizing ATP production, minimal intermediate withdrawal), enzyme activity patterns showing isocitrate dehydrogenase (IDH) maintaining or increasing from 18-35 units/g to 22-45 units/g ensuring oxidative flux through rate-limiting step, α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase similarly sustained or elevated 15-32 units/g supporting continued oxidation, malate dehydrogenase showing complex regulation with activity 25-55 units/g potentially shifting from biosynthetic (cytoplasmic, producing malate for storage) to oxidative (mitochondrial, consuming malate from catabolism), and aconitase maintaining activity 20-40 units/g ensuring citrate-isocitrate interconversion supporting cycle flux. ||Phosphoenolpyruvate metabolism redirection demonstrates PEPC (phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase) declining from green berry peak 12-28 units/g to post-transition 3-10 units/g representing major reduction in carboxylation reaction PEP + CO₂ → oxaloacetate that during green berry growth fixes CO₂ and produces malate precursor, pyruvate kinase potentially adjusting though activity measurements variable across studies with some showing increases supporting glycolytic flux while others showing stability, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (PEPCK) potentially involved in some grape varieties catalyzing reverse reaction oxaloacetate → PEP + CO₂ though role controversial with evidence suggesting minor contribution compared to malic enzyme, and net effect of PEPC decline eliminating major anabolic pathway redirecting PEP toward pyruvate kinase and subsequently pyruvate metabolism rather than oxaloacetate and malate synthesis. ||Malic enzyme pathway establishment includes NADP-malic enzyme increasing from 2-6 units/g to 15-45 units/g representing major induction of oxidative decarboxylation pathway malate → pyruvate + CO₂, NAD-malic enzyme showing parallel increase from 1-4 units/g to 6-18 units/g contributing to total decarboxylation capacity, subcellular distribution with cytosolic isoforms dominant 65-80% providing primary site for malate oxidation, mitochondrial isoforms 20-35% potentially supporting anaplerotic or alternative functions, and kinetic properties with Km values 0.5-2.5 mM for malate and pH optimum 7.0-7.5 ensuring efficient catalysis in cytoplasmic environment enabling maximum flux during acid decline. ||Pyruvate metabolism reorganization shows pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC) potentially increasing activity 25-55% from 8-18 units/g to 12-28 units/g reflecting enhanced requirement for acetyl-CoA production from malic enzyme-derived pyruvate, mitochondrial pyruvate carrier facilitating enhanced pyruvate import from cytoplasm enabling oxidation, pyruvate entering citric acid cycle through acetyl-CoA representing major fate 70-85% of cytoplasmic pyruvate production during active acid decline, and minor alternative fates including transamination to alanine 8-15%, fermentation to lactate or ethanol under hypoxic conditions 5-12% particularly berry interior, and potential gluconeogenic uses <5% generally minimal during ripening. ||Respiratory chain adaptation involves Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase) maintaining or slightly increasing capacity ensuring efficient NADH oxidation from increased citric acid cycle flux, Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase) sustained activity supporting continued electron entry from FADH₂, Complexes III-IV (cytochrome bc₁ and cytochrome c oxidase) adequate capacity with measurements 12-28 units/g enabling efficient electron transport to oxygen, ATP synthase (Complex V) maintaining or increasing capacity 15-35 units/g ensuring ATP production keeps pace with enhanced respiratory substrate flux, and alternative oxidase potentially present providing overflow pathway under conditions of excess reducing equivalents though contribution generally minor in grape compared to some other fruits. ||Energy metabolism implications include ATP production transitioning from predominantly hexose-based (32 ATP per glucose complete oxidation) toward mixed substrate with organic acids contributing substantially (15 ATP per malate), total berry ATP synthesis rates relatively stable 50-90 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ before and after transition maintaining energy supply despite altered fuel sources, ATP utilization patterns adjusting with declining allocation to growth processes (cell division, wall synthesis) and increasing allocation to storage and quality metabolism (sugar transport, anthocyanin synthesis, aromatic compound production), and metabolic efficiency potentially improving as stored acids provide respiratory substrate without requiring import of hexoses exclusively for respiration enabling dual strategy of hexose storage and acid catabolism. ||Redox metabolism changes show NADH production from citric acid cycle potentially increasing 30-60% as oxidative mode dominates compared to biosynthetic mode where intermediates withdrawn, NADPH generation from NADP-malic enzyme providing substantial reductive capacity 2.5-5.0 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ supporting biosynthesis particularly anthocyanin and flavonoid synthesis in reds plus general antioxidant systems, NAD⁺/NADH and NADP⁺/NADPH ratios adjusting with ripening metabolism potentially showing NAD⁺/NADH declining slightly 8:1 to 5:1 reflecting enhanced oxidation while NADP⁺/NADPH may increase 2:1 to 4:1 as NADPH consumption for biosynthesis matches or exceeds malic enzyme production, and redox homeostasis maintained through multiple dehydrogenases, transhydrogenases, and antioxidant systems preventing excessive oxidation or reduction disrupting cellular function. ||Metabolite pool adjustments during transition include citric acid cycle intermediates showing complex dynamics with some (citrate, α-ketoglutarate) potentially declining 20-40% as biosynthetic withdrawal reduces and oxidative flux dominates, others (malate, succinate) showing path-dependent changes with malate declining through catabolism while succinate sometimes accumulating slightly, amino acid pools adjusting as citric acid cycle intermediate availability changes affecting biosynthesis particularly glutamate family from α-ketoglutarate and aspartate family from oxaloacetate potentially declining 15-35%, and organic phosphates (ATP, ADP, AMP) maintaining relatively stable ratios despite metabolic reorganization indicating energy charge homeostasis preserved throughout transition. ||Regulatory mechanisms coordinating transition include allosteric regulation with multiple enzymes responding to metabolite effectors (ATP, ADP, AMP, citrate, malate) enabling metabolic responsiveness, transcriptional control through ripening-specific factors coordinately activating catabolic genes while suppressing biosynthetic genes creating coordinated reprogramming, post-translational modifications particularly phosphorylation potentially affecting enzyme activities though modifications during grape transition incompletely characterized, and hormonal signals particularly ABA triggering regulatory cascades affecting multiple pathway components simultaneously enabling rapid coordinated transition. ||Environmental modulation of transition includes temperature affecting enzyme activities and reaction rates with warmer conditions 24-30°C potentially accelerating transition completion 2-4 days compared to cooler 18-24°C, oxygen availability affecting respiratory pathway flux with adequate O₂ essential for oxidative metabolism while hypoxia promoting fermentative alternatives, substrate availability with adequate photosynthesis providing resources for enzyme synthesis and metabolic function supporting normal transition, and stress conditions potentially disrupting transition timing or completeness through resource limitation or signaling perturbations. ||Cultivar variation in pathway transition demonstrates early-ripening varieties showing rapid transition 4-6 days with prompt enzyme activity changes and metabolite adjustments, mid-season cultivars displaying 6-9 day transition with progressive reorganization, and late varieties exhibiting extended transition 8-14 days with gradual shifts reflecting genetic differences in developmental control and metabolic flexibility. ||Physiological significance includes pathway transition enabling efficient resource utilization by catabolizing stored acids for energy while simultaneously storing imported sugars avoiding wasteful simultaneous synthesis and degradation, metabolic commitment representing developmental point-of-no-return with ripening metabolism established irreversibly, and energy economy optimizing by extracting ATP from accumulated acids supporting ripening processes without fully relying on imported hexose oxidation. ||Quality implications include transition completeness affecting acid decline capacity with inadequate transition potentially limiting acid reduction maintaining excessive acidity, timing relative to other processes determining compositional balance at harvest, and pathway efficiency affecting berry energy status potentially influencing secondary metabolism and quality compound synthesis. ||Research applications include enzyme activity profiling characterizing transition kinetics, metabolite flux analysis using isotope tracers quantifying pathway reorganization, transcriptomics revealing regulatory control, and metabolic modeling integrating data predicting transition dynamics enabling mechanistic understanding of ripening metabolism.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 pathway transition comprehensive || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis:a review Vitis 21:247-259 metabolic pathways || Hawker JS (1969) Changes in the activities of malic enzyme, malate dehydrogenase, phosphopyruvate carboxylase and pyruvate dehydrogenase during the development of a non-climacteric fruit:the grape Phytochem 8:9-23 enzyme activity transitions."
},

  "Respiratory_Substrate_Change": {
  "definition": "A Respiratory_Substrate_Change is an Acid_Metabolism_Shift consisting of the transition of berry respiration from predominantly hexose oxidation to mixed substrate utilization incorporating organic acid catabolism.",
  "alternative_term": "respiratory fuel transition | substrate utilization shift | hexose-to-acid respiration change | metabolic fuel switching |+ respiratorische Brennstoff-Übergang | Substrat-Verwendungs-Verschiebung | Hexose-zu-Säure-Atmungs-Änderung | metabolische Brennstoff-Umschaltung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Stellenbosch Chenin Blanc vineyard, respiratory substrate change was quantified over 12 days from late January to early February Year N+1 (BBCH 83-84) using gas exchange and isotope studies when respiratory quotient increased from 1.03 to 1.24, ¹³C-malate tracer showing 48% of respiratory CO₂ from malate (from 18% pre-veraison), berry O₂ consumption 1.65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, combined malic enzyme 52 units/g FW, malate declining from 11.2 to 8.1 g/L, under warm South African conditions (daily high 28-32°C).",
  "editor_note": "Respiratory_Substrate_Change is distinguished from Metabolic_Pathway_Transition by representing substrate utilization rather than enzymatic reorganization, from Acid_Metabolism_Shift by focusing on respiratory fuel preference rather than overall metabolism, and from Respiratory_Malate_Consumption by showing transition rather than ongoing process. ||RQ increases 0.95-1.05 → 1.08-1.32. ||Malate contribution 35-60% respiratory CO₂ during ripening. ||Duration 6-12 days BBCH 83-84. ||Respiratory_Substrate_Change represents fundamental alteration in berry energy metabolism during ripening. || This substrate change occurs during veraison onset through mid-veraison (BBCH 83-84), typically 2-8 days post-metabolic pathway transition initiation, and is characterized by respiratory quotient increasing from 0.92-1.05 (green berry indicating primarily carbohydrate oxidation) to 1.08-1.32 (ripening indicating substantial organic acid contribution) reflecting altered CO₂:O₂ stoichiometry, malate contribution to respiratory CO₂ production increasing from <15-25% (green berry where malate synthesized not catabolized) to 35-60% (early-mid ripening) based on isotope tracer studies and mass balance calculations, hexose contribution declining from 70-90% to 40-60% of respiratory substrate not through reduced absolute hexose oxidation but through enhanced acid oxidation increasing total flux, and total berry respiration rates maintained or slightly elevated 1.0-2.4 μmol O₂ g⁻¹ h⁻¹ despite substrate transition indicating metabolic continuity with altered fuel preference. ||Biochemical basis of substrate change includes enhanced availability of organic acids as respiratory substrate through mobilization of vacuolar stores via tonoplast transport providing cytoplasmic and mitochondrial access, malic enzyme pathway establishment creating efficient decarboxylation route converting malate to pyruvate then acetyl-CoA via pyruvate dehydrogenase feeding citric acid cycle, citric acid cycle reorganization enabling complete malate oxidation through both direct entry via malate dehydrogenase and indirect via malic enzyme-pyruvate pathway, and continued hexose availability through concurrent sugar import 1.5-3.5% Brix per week providing alternative substrate creating metabolic flexibility. ||Isotope tracer evidence for substrate change demonstrates ¹³C-glucose labeling showing declining proportion of respiratory CO₂ derived from exogenous glucose 75-85% (green berry) to 45-65% (ripening) indicating reduced relative glucose contribution, ¹³C-malate labeling revealing increasing proportion of CO₂ from malate 12-20% (green berry primarily from TCA cycle oxidation of endogenous malate) to 40-70% (ripening from enhanced catabolism), ¹⁴C-organic acid studies confirming rapid turnover with half-life declining from 24-48 hours (green berry slow catabolism) to 8-18 hours (ripening enhanced oxidation), and position-specific labeling distinguishing between complete oxidation (all carbons to CO₂) versus partial oxidation or biosynthetic uses revealing ripening shows predominantly complete oxidation pattern maximizing energy extraction. ||Respiratory quotient dynamics provide key evidence with RQ = molar CO₂ produced / molar O₂ consumed theoretically 1.0 for carbohydrate (C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6 O₂ → 6 CO₂ + 6 H₂O), RQ ~1.33 for organic acids like malate (C₄H₆O₅ + 3 O₂ → 4 CO₂ + 3 H₂O) due to oxygen already present in acid molecules, measured berry RQ increasing from 0.95-1.05 (green berry slightly below 1.0 possibly indicating some lipid biosynthesis consuming CO₂) to 1.10-1.30 (ripening elevated RQ consistent with 40-60% malate contribution), and RQ temporal pattern showing increase coinciding with veraison and active acid decline then potentially declining slightly toward harvest as malate depletes and hexose contribution increases relatively. ||Enzymatic capacity supporting substrate change includes glycolytic enzymes maintaining activity 12-35 units/g each (hexokinase, phosphofructokinase, pyruvate kinase) ensuring hexose catabolism continues, malic enzyme dramatically elevated 25-70 units/g combined NADP-ME and NAD-ME providing organic acid decarboxylation capacity, pyruvate dehydrogenase potentially increased 30-60% accommodating enhanced pyruvate flux from both hexose glycolysis and malic enzyme, citric acid cycle enzymes sustained or elevated supporting mixed substrate oxidation, and respiratory chain adequate capacity handling increased electron flux from combined hexose and acid catabolism with cytochrome oxidase 12-25 units/g ensuring terminal oxidation. ||Energy yield comparison shows hexose complete oxidation producing 32 ATP per glucose through glycolysis plus citric acid cycle plus oxidative phosphorylation representing efficient energy extraction, malate complete oxidation yielding ~15 ATP per malate through either direct TCA entry or malic enzyme then TCA representing moderately efficient substrate though lower per-carbon than glucose (malate 3.75 ATP per carbon versus glucose 5.33 ATP per carbon), mixed substrate utilization potentially optimizing energy economy by utilizing stored acids avoiding exclusive reliance on imported hexoses for respiratory needs, and ATP production rates 45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ maintained throughout substrate transition supporting continuous energy supply for ripening processes. ||Carbon flow implications include respiratory carbon loss from malate potentially 0.4-0.9 g glucose-equivalent per kg berries per day during peak acid decline (based on 3-7 μmol malate g⁻¹ h⁻¹ oxidation) representing substantial respiratory cost, concurrent carbon gain through sugar import 1.8-3.8 g glucose per kg per day far exceeding acid loss maintaining net carbon accumulation, net carbon balance positive throughout ripening despite enhanced respiratory losses enabling berry to simultaneously store sugars and catabolize acids, and carbon use efficiency potentially 65-85% (carbon stored / carbon imported) indicating moderate respiratory losses typical for ripening non-climacteric fruit. ||Substrate preference regulation involves potential hierarchical control with hexoses preferentially oxidized when abundantly available sparing acids, organic acids increasingly utilized as hexose availability moderate or acids accumulate creating metabolic pressure for catabolism, allosteric regulation of key enzymes with citrate inhibiting phosphofructokinase potentially coordinating glycolysis and TCA flux, and cellular energy status (ATP/ADP ratio, NADH/NAD⁺ ratio) providing feedback regulating both hexose and acid oxidation rates maintaining homeostasis. ||Compartmentation aspects show cytoplasmic hexose catabolism through glycolysis producing pyruvate and NADH, cytoplasmic organic acid catabolism via malic enzyme producing pyruvate, CO₂, and NADPH, mitochondrial oxidation of pyruvate from both sources through pyruvate dehydrogenase and citric acid cycle, mitochondrial direct malate oxidation via malate dehydrogenase and subsequent TCA reactions, and coordinated regulation between compartments ensuring balanced substrate flow and efficient energy production. ||Environmental influences on substrate change include temperature affecting respiratory rates and substrate preference with warmer conditions 26-32°C potentially enhancing organic acid oxidation disproportionately through kinetic effects on malic enzyme, oxygen availability essential for oxidative metabolism with adequate O₂ (>5-8% in berry tissue) supporting complete oxidation while hypoxia (<2-3%) promoting fermentative metabolism shifting substrate utilization, water status potentially affecting substrate availability and catabolism rates through effects on metabolite transport and enzyme activities, and nutrient status particularly nitrogen affecting respiratory enzyme capacity and thus potential substrate utilization rates. ||Cultivar genetic variation shows low-acid varieties exhibiting dramatic substrate change with organic acid contribution potentially reaching 65-80% of respiratory CO₂ during peak decline reflecting extensive acid mobilization, moderate cultivars displaying 45-65% acid contribution during peak, and high-acid varieties showing 35-55% contribution maintaining substantial hexose respiration even during active acid decline reflecting genetic differences in metabolic regulation and substrate preference. ||Physiological significance includes substrate change enabling efficient resource utilization by catabolizing stored acids for energy supporting ripening while simultaneously storing imported sugars avoiding wasteful sugar catabolism, metabolic flexibility providing resilience allowing berry to adjust substrate utilization based on availability and demands, and energy economy optimizing total energy extraction from available carbon sources maximizing ATP production per unit photosynthate invested. ||Quality implications include respiratory substrate directly affecting berry carbon budget with excessive acid catabolism representing yield loss while insufficient catabolism maintains undesirable high acids, coordination between substrate change and other ripening processes affecting final composition quality, and temperature sensitivity of substrate change contributing to vintage variation in final acid levels particularly in warm versus cool years. ||Viticultural management considerations include canopy photosynthesis ensuring adequate hexose supply supporting both storage and respiratory needs, temperature management through cluster exposure controlling respiratory rates and substrate preference affecting acid retention, and understanding substrate change informing carbon budget optimization for quality production. ||Research applications include respirometry measuring O₂ consumption and CO₂ production calculating RQ revealing substrate transitions, isotope tracer studies with labeled hexoses and organic acids quantifying relative contributions, metabolomic profiling tracking substrate pool dynamics, and enzyme activity assays confirming capacity for altered substrate utilization patterns during ripening.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Ruffner HP, Hawker JS, Hale CR (1976) Temperature and enzymic control of malate metabolism in berries of Vitis vinifera Phytochem 15:1877-1880 respiratory substrate || Sweetman C, Sadras VO, Hancock RD, Soole KL, Ford CM (2014) Metabolic effects of elevated temperature on organic acid degradation in ripening Vitis vinifera fruit J Exp Bot 65:5975-5988 substrate utilization || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 respiratory metabolism during ripening."
},

  "Acid_Balance_Adjustment": {
  "definition": "An Acid_Balance_Adjustment is an Acid_Metabolism_Shift characterized by the transition of berry organic acid composition from malate-dominated to tartrate-dominated through selective malate catabolism with tartaric acid remaining metabolically stable.",
  "alternative_term": "organic acid equilibrium shift | malate-tartrate balance adjustment | acid composition rebalancing | acid profile transformation |+ organische Säure-Gleichgewichts-Verschiebung | Malat-Tartrat-Balance-Anpassung | Säure-Kompositions-Neuausgleich | Säure-Profil-Transformation",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Côtes du Rhône Grenache vineyard, acid balance adjustment was tracked over 55 days from mid-August through October Year N+1 (BBCH 83-87) when malate declined from 10.8 g/L to 1.6 g/L (85% loss), tartaric acid decreased from 8.5 to 6.8 g/L (20% apparent decline primarily dilutional), malate:tartrate ratio shifted from 1.27:1 to 0.24:1, total TA declined from 19.3 to 5.4 g/L, pH increased from 2.98 to 3.68, under warm southern Rhône conditions (average daily high 28-32°C during ripening accelerating malate catabolism producing tartrate-dominant final composition typical for warm-climate Grenache).",
  "editor_note": "Acid_Balance_Adjustment is distinguished from Acid_Decline_Onset by representing progressive equilibrium shift rather than onset, from Malic_Acid_Decline_Start by focusing on compositional balance rather than absolute malate loss, and from pH_Increase_Start by representing acid ratio changes rather than pH effect. ||Malate:tartrate 1.2-2.5:1 → 0.15-0.8:1. ||Duration entire ripening 40-60 days BBCH 83-87. ||Tartrate metabolically stable, malate 70-95% loss. ||Final ratio cultivar/environment dependent. ||Acid_Balance_Adjustment represents fundamental compositional transformation determining wine acidity character. || This adjustment occurs throughout veraison and ripening (BBCH 83-87), beginning at veraison onset and continuing until harvest, and is characterized by malate:tartrate ratio declining from 1.2-2.5:1 (green berry malate-dominant) to 0.15-0.8:1 (harvest tartrate-dominant or balanced) representing fundamental compositional shift, total organic acids declining from 20-35 g/L (green berry) to 4-10 g/L (harvest) with malate loss 70-95% accounting for majority of reduction while tartrate loss <5-20% primarily dilutional, pH increasing from 2.7-3.1 (green berry) to 3.0-3.8 (harvest) reflecting net acid loss and proton consumption, and acid sensory character transforming from sharp tart (malate-driven) toward neutral or mild acidity (tartrate-dominated) affecting wine structure and flavor balance. ||Mechanisms driving selective adjustment include metabolic stability of tartaric acid with negligible enzymatic degradation in grape (unlike some other fruits where tartrate catabolized) creating persistent acid component, active malate catabolism through malic enzyme and citric acid cycle progressively depleting this component, lack of tartaric acid biosynthesis during ripening maintaining levels primarily through dilution from berry expansion, and differential compartmentation possibly contributing with tartrate potentially more strongly sequestered or complexed compared to malate affecting availability though evidence limited. ||Tartaric acid characteristics during adjustment show concentration declining modestly from 7-12 g/L (green berry) to 5-10 g/L (harvest) representing 15-35% apparent reduction primarily attributable to berry volume expansion 60-120% through water import rather than metabolic loss, berry tartrate content on per-berry basis relatively stable or slightly increasing (35-55 mg per berry green to 40-60 mg per berry harvest depending on size) confirming metabolic stability, vacuolar sequestration maintaining tartrate with minimal tonoplast efflux unlike malate where controlled release enables catabolism, and biochemical inertness in grape with no known degradation pathways contrasting with some other species where tartrate metabolized reflecting species-specific enzyme complement. ||Malic acid dynamics during adjustment demonstrate concentration declining dramatically from 9-16 g/L (green berry) to 1-6 g/L (harvest) representing 65-95% reduction through active catabolism, absolute malate content per berry declining from 45-85 mg to 8-35 mg confirming true catabolism not just dilution, vacuolar pools progressively depleted from 80-150 mM to 10-60 mM as tonoplast transport delivers substrate for cytoplasmic and mitochondrial oxidation, and respiratory consumption rates 0.18-0.55 g/L per day during active decline creating cumulative losses 6-12 g/L over 30-60 day ripening period accounting for observed depletion. ||Malate:tartrate ratio trajectory shows green berry values 1.3-2.5:1 reflecting active malate biosynthesis during growth phase when PEPC fixes CO₂ producing malate while tartrate synthesis minimal after initial berry development, veraison onset 0.8-1.8:1 as malate degradation initiates beginning selective loss, mid-ripening 0.4-1.2:1 during active malate decline approaching equilibrium, and harvest 0.15-0.8:1 (cultivar and conditions dependent) with low-acid varieties potentially <0.2:1 (tartrate-dominant) while high-acid cultivars maintaining 0.5-0.8:1 (balanced or moderate malate) reflecting genetic and environmental variation in final balance. ||Buffer capacity implications of adjustment include declining total buffer capacity as acids reduce from 16-24 mL to 8-14 mL of 0.1 N NaOH per 10 mL juice, shift from strong buffering (green berry high malate pKa₂ 5.11 near berry pH) toward weaker buffering (harvest lower tartrate pKa₂ 4.34 distant from pH 3.3-3.7) making harvest pH more labile, titratable acidity measurement affected by acid composition with malate as diprotic acid contributing two titratable H⁺ per molecule while tartrate also diprotic shows different titration curve affecting TA-pH relationship, and practical implications for winery pH adjustment where tartrate-dominant musts respond differently to additions compared to malate-rich musts. ||pH dynamics during adjustment show increase from 2.8-3.1 (green berry) to 3.2-3.7 (mid-ripening) to 3.0-3.8 (harvest cultivar-dependent) driven primarily by declining total acids particularly malate, relationship with acid concentration nonlinear following Henderson-Hasselbalch equation where pH change per unit acid loss accelerates as acids deplete, potassium effects potentially contributing with berry K⁺ accumulation from 1200-2000 mg/kg to 2000-3200 mg/kg correlating with pH increase r² = 0.70-0.88 though causation debated, and cultivar differences substantial with low-acid varieties reaching pH 3.6-3.9 while high-acid types maintaining 3.0-3.4 reflecting genetic variation in acid retention and balance. ||Sensory implications of adjustment include malate taste contribution as sharp tart distinct from tartaric acid more neutral acidity, high-malate fruit (>4-5 g/L) producing aggressive tartness sometimes described as green-apple character, balanced acid profiles (malate 2-4 g/L, tartrate 6-8 g/L) providing structure without excessive tartness desirable for many wine styles, tartrate-dominant profiles (malate <2 g/L, tartrate 5-9 g/L) offering mild acidity potentially bland if total TA also low but appropriate for low-acid styles, and acid-driven sensory changes throughout adjustment affecting harvest timing decisions requiring taste evaluation integrating analytical measures. ||Wine quality implications include final malate:tartrate ratio affecting wine character with balanced ratios 0.3-0.6:1 generally desirable for quality wines, very low ratios <0.2:1 potentially indicating over-deacidified fruit from warm conditions producing flat wines, higher ratios 0.6-1.0:1 in cool climates maintaining acid structure potentially beneficial for aging but requiring careful MLF management, MLF kinetics affected by malate levels with >3-4 g/L supporting rapid complete fermentation while <1.5-2 g/L potentially causing sluggish or stuck MLF complicating winemaking, and wine stability influenced by final pH with lower pH (<3.3) providing better microbial protection, color stability in reds, and oxidation resistance though excessive acidity undesirable. ||Malolactic fermentation considerations show bacteria (Oenococcus oeni) consume L-malate converting to L-lactate plus CO₂ reducing total acidity ~1-3 g/L and increasing pH 0.1-0.3 units, substrate requirement with adequate malate (>2-3 g/L) essential for reliable MLF while low malate (<1.5 g/L) may require nutrient additions or extended time, pH effects on bacterial growth with optimal 3.3-3.7 while <3.1 or >3.9 inhibitory affecting MLF success, and wine style implications with MLF often desirable reds (softening acid structure, adding complexity) but sometimes avoided whites (preserving acid freshness, fruit character) requiring appropriate grape acid balance at harvest. ||Environmental factors affecting adjustment include temperature strongly influencing malate catabolism rates with warm vintages producing more dramatic adjustment (lower final malate, lower ratios) while cool vintages maintaining higher malate and ratios, water availability potentially affecting through effects on berry expansion (diluting both acids) and metabolism (affecting catabolism rates), canopy microclimate with cluster exposure temperature differences creating spatial variation in adjustment across vineyard, and vintage variation substantial with warm years potentially showing final ratios 0.15-0.35:1 while cool years 0.45-0.80:1 reflecting cumulative temperature effects on adjustment process. ||Cultivar genetic differences demonstrate low-acid varieties (Grenache, Viognier) exhibiting dramatic adjustment to final ratios 0.12-0.30:1 with extensive malate loss, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Merlot) displaying ratios 0.25-0.55:1, and high-acid types (Riesling, Chenin Blanc) maintaining 0.45-0.85:1 reflecting genetic variation in maximum malic enzyme expression, catabolism rates, and acid retention set-points. ||Viticultural management targeting optimal adjustment includes canopy practices moderating cluster temperature slowing malate catabolism preserving acids important warm regions, irrigation management potentially affecting through cooling or metabolic effects, harvest timing decisions balancing acid decline trajectory against sugar accumulation and phenolic maturity requiring integrated maturity assessment, and site selection recognizing inherent thermal characteristics affect acid balance with cool sites naturally preserving while warm sites require intervention. ||Monitoring adjustment progression involves frequent analysis every 5-10 days during ripening tracking malate, tartrate, TA, and pH revealing trajectory, taste evaluation detecting sensory acid balance changes, spatial sampling across zones revealing heterogeneity, and historical data enabling comparison across seasons identifying typical patterns and vintage effects informing management decisions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 228-233 acid balance during ripening || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis:a review Vitis 21:247-259 acid composition || Boulton RB, Singleton VL, Bisson LF, Kunkee RE (1996) Principles and Practices of Winemaking pages 38-52 acid balance and wine quality implications."
},

  "Ripening": {
  "definition": "*A Ripening is a Berry_Development comprising sustained sugar accumulation, organic acid decline, berry softening, anthocyanin synthesis in red cultivars, and flavor-aroma compound biosynthesis from véraison onset through harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "berry maturation | fruit ripening | sugar-acid balance development | compositional maturation |+ Beeren-Reifung | Frucht-Reifung | Zucker-Säure-Balance-Entwicklung | kompositionelle Maturation",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, ripening was tracked over 68 days from early August through mid-October Year N+1 (BBCH 81-89) when berry Brix increased from 12.5° to 25.8° (13.3° gain, average 2.0% per week), titratable acidity declined from 16.8 to 5.6 g/L (67% reduction, average 0.23 g/L per day), pH increased from 3.08 to 3.52, berry firmness decreased from 3.8 to 0.7 N (82% softening), anthocyanin accumulated from 85 to 1240 mg/kg, total volatiles rose from 48 to 385 μg/kg, under warm California conditions (cumulative 1180 degree-days), enabling harvest at optimal phenolic and flavor maturity.",
  "editor_note": "Ripening is distinguished from Veraison by representing maturation phase (BBCH 81-89, 40-80 days) following veraison onset rather than the transition itself (BBCH 81-83, 7-14 days), encompasses complete sugar accumulation and acid decline rather than just onset, and includes late-stage processes like flavor development and physiological maturity absent during early veraison. ||Ripening represents coordinated progression of multiple parallel processes: sugar accumulation (dominant anabolic), acid decline (dominant catabolic), softening, color (reds), and flavor development. ||Final composition determines wine quality and style. ||Duration cultivar-dependent: early 40-55 days, mid-season 50-65 days, late 60-80 days. ||Temperature critically important: 25-30°C optimal, >35°C impairs. ||Ripening represents final major berry development phase defining harvest maturity and commercial value. || This ripening phase extends from veraison completion through harvest (BBCH 81-89), typically spanning 40-80 days depending on cultivar and environmental conditions (earlier maturing varieties 40-55 days, mid-season 50-65 days, late cultivars 60-80 days), and is characterized by berry Brix increasing from veraison establishment 11-16° to harvest maturity 18-30° representing 8-18° gain through sustained hexose import and vacuolar storage, titratable acidity declining from 12-20 g/L to final 4-10 g/L through preferential malic acid catabolism while tartaric acid remains relatively stable, berry pH increasing from 3.0-3.3 to 3.0-3.8 (cultivar-dependent) reflecting net organic acid loss, berry firmness declining 60-85% from veraison onset 2.5-4.5 N to harvest 0.4-1.2 N through cell wall pectin solubilization and turgor reduction creating characteristic soft ripe texture, anthocyanin accumulation in red cultivars from veraison levels 50-200 mg/kg reaching harvest maximum 400-1800 mg/kg (cultivar and conditions dependent) producing characteristic color intensity, and flavor-aroma volatiles accumulating 4-12 fold from veraison onset 25-65 μg/kg to harvest 100-650 μg/kg creating varietal character and sensory ripeness. ||Physiological basis of ripening involves fundamental metabolic reprogramming initiated at veraison and sustained throughout ripening with phloem unloading transitioning from symplastic to predominantly apoplastic (>85-95%) enabling high-flux sugar delivery, hexose transporter genes (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) collectively upregulated 100-300 fold above green berry levels creating import capacity 60-170 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ depending on phase and conditions, vacuolar hexose concentrations increasing from 400-700 mM to 1400-2200 mM combined glucose and fructose creating osmotic potential decline from -1.8 to -2.4 MPa to -2.6 to -3.6 MPa driving water import and berry expansion 50-120%, organic acid metabolism shifting from biosynthetic to catabolic mode with malic enzyme genes (VvME1, VvME2) upregulated 20-80 fold enabling malate respiratory consumption 0.15-0.55 g/L per day during active decline while tartaric acid metabolically stable showing only dilutional changes, cell wall modifying enzymes including polygalacturonase, pectinmethylesterase, and expansins progressively solubilizing pectins reducing berry firmness enabling characteristic ripe texture development, anthocyanin biosynthesis pathway genes (particularly PAL, CHS, UFGT) in reds upregulated 50-200 fold producing flavonoid accumulation 10-40 mg/kg per week during active coloration, and secondary metabolism intensifying with terpene synthases, ester-forming enzymes, and other flavor pathway genes activated producing characteristic varietal aromatics. ||Temporal progression of ripening demonstrates initial phase (BBCH 81-83, days 0-15 post-veraison) with accelerating sugar accumulation 1.2-2.5% Brix per week, moderate acid decline 0.18-0.35 g/L TA per day, continuing softening 15-35% firmness loss, and in reds beginning color development reaching 20-50% final anthocyanin, active ripening phase (BBCH 84-86, days 15-45) exhibiting peak sugar accumulation 2.5-5.0% Brix per week, maximum acid decline 0.30-0.65 g/L TA per day, softening largely completed, color development 50-95% final levels in reds, and flavor compound synthesis intensifying, and late ripening approaching harvest (BBCH 87-89, days 45-70) showing decelerating sugar accumulation 0.8-2.2% Brix per week as limits approached, continuing acid decline 0.10-0.30 g/L per day, firmness stabilizing at ripe levels, color reaching maximum in reds, and flavor complexity developing. ||Hormonal orchestration of ripening includes abscisic acid as master regulator with sustained elevated levels 1200-2800 ng/g throughout ripening maintaining coordinate expression of sugar transport, acid catabolism, softening, and color genes through ABA-responsive transcription factors, sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway creating feed-forward amplification enhancing ripening progression, declining growth hormones (gibberellin declining from 40-120 ng/g pre-veraison to <10-30 ng/g ripening, auxin similarly reduced) removing vegetative suppression allowing metabolic focus on maturation, and ethylene showing cultivar-dependent minor role with slight elevation 0.2-0.8 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in some varieties potentially fine-tuning ripening though grape generally non-climacteric with minimal ethylene requirement unlike climacteric fruits. ||Environmental factors critically affecting ripening include temperature showing strong influence with optimal 25-30°C supporting maximum rates of all processes, warm conditions 28-35°C accelerating ripening shortening duration 25-40% but risking excessive acid loss and unbalanced composition, cooler temperatures 18-24°C extending ripening 30-60% enabling flavor development and acid retention potentially beneficial for quality but requiring longer growing season, heat stress >35°C impairing ripening through metabolic disruption and potential berry damage, solar radiation affecting berry temperature and photosynthesis with adequate canopy light essential for source capacity while excessive cluster exposure in hot climates potentially detrimental through overheating, water availability with moderate deficit compatible or enhancing quality through concentration effects while severe deficit <-1.6 MPa impairing metabolism disrupting normal ripening progression, and cumulative growing degree-days strongly correlating with ripening progression (base 10°C) with typical requirements 900-1400 degree-days from veraison to harvest depending on cultivar. ||Cultivar genetic variation demonstrates early-ripening varieties (Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, Gewürztraminer) completing ripening 40-55 days post-veraison enabling cultivation in cool short-season regions, mid-season cultivars (Merlot, Syrah, Sauvignon Blanc) requiring 50-65 days representing majority commercial varieties, and late-ripening types (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo, Mourvèdre) needing 60-80 days restricting to warm long-season climates, with genetic differences in sugar accumulation capacity determining final Brix potential 18-30° cultivar-dependent, acid retention characteristics affecting final TA 4-10 g/L and pH 3.0-3.8, color intensity in reds varying 400-1800 mg/kg anthocyanin harvest levels, and flavor profiles reflecting variety-specific terpene, ester, and other volatile patterns creating distinctive sensory characteristics. ||Quality implications of ripening include sugar-acid balance at harvest critically determining wine style with ratios 20-35:1 (Brix:TA g/L) typical for quality wines, phenolic maturity in reds requiring tannin polymerization and seed browning synchronized with sugar-acid development often necessitating extended hang time beyond sugar maturity, flavor ripeness essential for quality requiring adequate volatile development particularly aromatic varieties where flavor may lag analytical maturity, physiological maturity indicated by seed browning, berry abscission ease, and stem lignification providing additional harvest timing cues beyond chemistry, and vintage variation substantial with warm years producing earlier faster ripening potentially challenging for achieving balanced maturity while cool years extending duration enabling flavor development but risking incomplete ripening in marginal climates. ||Harvest timing decisions integrate multiple ripening parameters including target sugar levels varying by wine style (table wines 20-24° Brix, fuller styles 22-26°, late harvest 24-32°), acceptable acid levels maintaining TA 5-8 g/L and pH 3.0-3.7 for most quality wines, phenolic assessment particularly reds evaluating tannin polymerization and seed maturation, flavor development through sensory evaluation detecting varietal character and ripeness, weather forecasts considering approaching adverse conditions (rain, frost) potentially necessitating earlier harvest, and market factors including winery capacity and labor availability affecting practical harvest windows. ||Viticultural management during ripening includes canopy maintenance ensuring continued photosynthesis supporting ripening processes, strategic leaf removal or shading managing cluster microclimate particularly warm regions where temperature moderation critical for balanced ripening, irrigation management providing adequate water without excess while potentially using deficit to enhance concentration and quality, disease control critical as high-sugar soft berries increasingly vulnerable to Botrytis, sour rot, and other pathogens requiring vigilant monitoring and intervention, bird and pest protection preventing crop losses particularly as sugars rise attracting wildlife, and harvest preparation including equipment readiness, labor scheduling, and winery coordination as ripening progression indicates approaching optimal maturity. ||Monitoring ripening progression involves regular berry sampling every 5-10 days tracking Brix, TA, pH, and malate revealing compositional trajectories, phenolic analysis in reds assessing tannin and anthocyanin development, sensory evaluation detecting flavor ripeness and balance, spatial sampling across vineyard zones revealing heterogeneity requiring selective management, and historical data compilation enabling vintage comparisons and predictive modeling improving management decisions and harvest timing optimization for achieving target quality parameters.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PO_0025502 ## fruit ripening stage | 0.9" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 221-256 ripening comprehensive || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 ripening dynamics || Kennedy JA, Matthews MA, Waterhouse AL (2002) Effect of maturity and vine water status on grape skin and wine flavonoids Amer J Enol Vitic 53:268-274 ripening and quality."
},

  "Sugar_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Accumulation is a Ripening consisting of sustained hexose import and vacuolar storage in mesocarp cells from véraison onset through harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "hexose storage | sweetness development | Brix increase | vacuolar sugar accumulation |+ Hexose-Speicherung | Süße-Entwicklung | Brix-Zunahme | vakuoläre Zucker-Akkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Chardonnay vineyard, sugar accumulation was tracked over 58 days from early August through late September Year N+1 (BBCH 83-89) when berry Brix increased from 8.2° to 24.6° (16.4° total gain, average 2.8% per week), showing initial phase 8.2° → 13.5° (days 0-14, 2.1%/week), active phase 13.5° → 22.8° (days 14-42, 3.8%/week peak), deceleration 22.8° → 24.6° (days 42-58, 1.3%/week), berry fresh weight 0.95 g → 1.88 g (98% expansion), vacuolar hexose 280 → 1620 mM, under typical California coastal conditions (daily high 23-28°C supporting sustained accumulation).",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Accumulation is distinguished from Sugar_Accumulation_Onset by representing entire accumulation process (40-70 days, 12-24° Brix gain) rather than onset (6-10 days, 5-8° Brix initial), encompasses both Active_Sugar_Accumulation and Peak_Sugar_Accumulation as organizational parent, and represents complete trajectory from veraison through harvest. ||Duration BBCH 83-89. ||Final levels: high-Brix 26-30°, moderate 22-26°, lower 18-24°. ||Dominant anabolic process of ripening. ||Sugar_Accumulation represents fundamental developmental process determining grape maturity and wine quality potential. || This accumulation extends throughout veraison and ripening phases (BBCH 83-89), typically beginning 0-3 days post-veraison onset and continuing 40-70 days until harvest, and is characterized by berry Brix increasing from veraison onset 6-10° to harvest 18-30° (cultivar and region dependent) representing 12-24° Brix total gain, total berry sugars rising from 80-140 g/L to 180-300 g/L constituting 100-180 g/L hexose accumulation, vacuolar glucose and fructose each increasing from 150-300 mM to 700-1100 mM creating combined concentrations 1400-2200 mM (25-40% w/v) dominating berry osmotic potential, and berry fresh weight expanding 50-120% from 0.8-1.4 g to 1.4-2.8 g through osmotic water import driven by sugar accumulation demonstrating tight coupling between hexose storage and berry development. ||Temporal pattern of accumulation demonstrates sigmoid progression with initial acceleration phase (days 0-12 post-veraison) showing 1.2-2.5% Brix per week as transport machinery activates, active accumulation phase (days 12-35) exhibiting peak rates 2.8-5.0% Brix per week when all pathway components operate maximally, deceleration phase (days 35-55) displaying declining rates 1.2-2.8% Brix per week as vacuolar concentrations approach equilibrium with phloem supply, and plateau phase approaching harvest (days 55-70) showing minimal increase <0.5-1.5% Brix per week as berry reaches cultivar-specific maximum indicating physiological maturity. ||Biochemical mechanisms enabling accumulation include phloem sucrose delivery from source leaves to berry providing substrate 150-400 mg sucrose per berry per day during peak (vine-level 120-350 g per vine per day), apoplastic unloading through plasmodesmata closure and cell wall invertase activity producing glucose and fructose from sucrose cleavage, hexose transporter-mediated uptake across plasma membrane with VvHT family members (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) collectively upregulated 100-300 fold above green berry providing import capacity 80-170 μmol combined hexoses g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during peak, tonoplast transport sequestering cytoplasmic hexoses into vacuoles maintaining concentration gradients enabling continued plasma membrane uptake, and vacuolar expansion from 85-90% to 95-97% of cell volume accommodating massive solute and water accumulation creating storage capacity 1.2-3.5 nL per mesocarp cell. ||Molecular regulation of accumulation involves abscisic acid signaling with sustained elevated levels 1200-2800 ng/g throughout ripening maintaining transporter gene expression and coordinating ripening processes, sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway where imported hexoses generate glucose-6-phosphate signals creating positive feedback enhancing transporter expression amplifying accumulation, declining growth hormones (gibberellin, auxin) removing vegetative suppression allowing metabolic focus on storage, and transcriptional control through ripening-specific transcription factors (VvMYB, VvNAC families) coordinately activating hundreds of genes including sugar transport, metabolism, and storage functions orchestrating comprehensive developmental program. ||Environmental factors critically affecting accumulation include temperature with optimal 26-30°C supporting maximum rates while cooler conditions 18-24°C reducing 30-50% through kinetic limitations and heat stress >32-35°C impairing 40-70% through enzyme denaturation and metabolic disruption, light operating primarily through source photosynthesis providing sucrose substrate with adequate canopy illumination essential for sustained accumulation, water status with moderate deficit compatible or potentially enhancing concentration through reduced berry expansion while severe deficit (<-1.5 MPa stem ψ) impairing 35-65% through impaired phloem delivery and metabolism, and nutritional status particularly nitrogen for enzyme synthesis and potassium for sugar-acid balance affecting accumulation capacity and final levels. ||Cultivar genetic variation demonstrates high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer, Sémillon potential 26-30° Brix) achieving rapid accumulation 4.2-5.5% Brix per week peak with high transporter expression and extended duration 45-55 days reaching maximum capacity, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon 22-26° Brix) showing 3.5-4.8% per week peak over 50-65 days achieving typical commercial levels, and lower-Brix types (Pinot Noir cool climates 20-24° Brix, table grapes 18-22° Brix) displaying 2.8-4.0% per week for 55-70 days reflecting genetic differences in transporter capacity, metabolic programming, and final sugar set-points. ||Osmotic consequences of accumulation include vacuolar osmotic potential declining from -1.4 to -2.0 MPa (veraison onset) to -2.6 to -3.6 MPa (harvest) creating strong water potential gradient, berry water potential following vacuolar sugar causing decline from -1.5 to -2.0 MPa to -2.2 to -3.2 MPa establishing gradient favoring water import from vine xylem (-0.5 to -1.2 MPa), and osmotically-driven water uptake causing berry expansion 60-130% despite declining growth rates illustrating hydraulic component of berry development where sugar accumulation drives size increase. ||Coordination with other ripening processes shows acid decline occurring simultaneously with sugar accumulation creating developing balance, berry softening largely completed by mid-accumulation period establishing characteristic ripe texture, color development in reds coordinated through common ABA signaling reaching completion during late accumulation, and flavor-aroma compound synthesis intensifying throughout accumulation with esters, terpenes, and volatiles accumulating creating integrated sensory ripeness. ||Carbon and energy budget implications demonstrate sugar accumulation representing net carbon import 120-220 g glucose-equivalent per kg berries over ripening period (based on 180-300 g/L final sugar), respiratory carbon loss through concurrent acid catabolism 15-35 g glucose-equivalent per kg berries representing moderate respiratory cost balanced by stored sugars, net carbon gain 100-185 g per kg berries enabling berry growth and quality compound synthesis, and energetics where imported hexoses partially respired (20-35% of import) providing ATP for transport and biosynthesis while majority (65-80%) accumulates in vacuoles creating efficient dual metabolism. ||Quality implications of accumulation include final sugar levels determining wine alcohol potential with each 1° Brix yielding approximately 0.55-0.60% ethanol post-fermentation, sugar-acid balance critically affecting wine style with ratios 20-35:1 (Brix:TA g/L) typical for quality wines, uniformity of accumulation across berries and clusters determining harvest maturity consistency affecting wine composition and requiring selective harvest if heterogeneous, timing of accumulation relative to phenolic and flavor development defining optimal harvest window requiring integration of multiple parameters, and accumulation rate patterns revealing environmental stress or management issues enabling diagnostic assessment and intervention. ||Harvest timing based on accumulation involves target sugar levels varying by style with table wines typically 20-24° Brix, fuller-bodied styles 22-26° Brix, late harvest or dessert wines 24-32° Brix depending on variety and region, weekly Brix sampling during ripening tracking rates and projecting harvest timing, integration with acid, pH, phenolic, and sensory parameters ensuring comprehensive maturity determination, and recognition that continued accumulation post-phenolic maturity may require earlier harvest accepting lower sugar to preserve balance particularly warm vintages. ||Viticultural management affecting accumulation includes crop load optimization with typical ratios 0.8-1.2 kg fruit per m² leaf area enabling adequate source capacity supporting target sugars without excessive competition, canopy management maintaining healthy productive foliage throughout ripening providing sustained photosynthesis, irrigation strategy with adequate water supporting continued accumulation without excess promoting vigor or berry dilution, disease control preventing infections that disrupt metabolism impairing accumulation, and harvest logistics preparing for optimal picking timing as accumulation trajectory indicates approaching maturity. ||Physiological limits to accumulation include maximum vacuolar concentrations ~2200-2600 mM approaching saturation potentially limiting further accumulation, membrane integrity constraints at extreme osmotic potentials <-3.6 MPa potentially compromising function, cell wall mechanical limits constraining vacuolar expansion beyond certain size, metabolic feedback regulation where high vacuolar sugar potentially inhibits further import through unknown mechanisms maintaining cultivar-specific set-points, and source photosynthesis capacity ultimately limiting total carbon available for accumulation determining yield-quality relationships. ||Research applications include transporter expression analysis revealing molecular control of accumulation, flux studies using isotope tracers quantifying import rates and metabolic partitioning, osmotic potential measurements characterizing thermodynamic driving forces, and modeling approaches integrating source-sink relationships predicting accumulation dynamics enabling precision viticulture optimization.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0034219 ## carbohydrate transmembrane transport | 0.75" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 221-228 sugar accumulation comprehensive || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 accumulation patterns || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 accumulation variation."
},

  "Active_Sugar_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "An Active_Sugar_Accumulation is a Sugar_Accumulation characterized by sustained operation of sugar transport machinery at elevated capacity producing the dominant fraction of total ripening sugar gain.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained hexose import | steady sweetening phase | prolonged sugar storage | consistent accumulation period |+ anhaltender Hexose-Import | stetige Süßungs-Phase | verlängerte Zucker-Speicherung | konsistente Akkumulations-Periode",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Mendoza Malbec vineyard, active sugar accumulation was tracked over 32 days from mid-February through mid-March Year N+1 (BBCH 84-86) when berry Brix increased from 15.8° to 25.2° (9.4° gain, average 2.9% per week), showing consistent daily rates 0.26-0.34% Brix per day (CV 12%), hexose import estimated 72-105 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ based on Brix trajectory, berry fresh weight 1.42 g → 1.95 g (37% expansion), under stable Argentine high-altitude conditions (daily high 26-29°C, moderate deficit stem ψ -1.15 MPa concentrating sugars while maintaining import).",
  "editor_note": "Active_Sugar_Accumulation is distinguished from Sugar_Accumulation_Onset by representing sustained phase (25-35 days, 7-13° Brix gain) rather than initial establishment (6-10 days, 5-8° Brix), from Peak_Sugar_Accumulation by showing steady rather than maximum rates (2.5-4.0% per week vs 3.5-5.0%), and from late accumulation by exhibiting consistent rates rather than deceleration. ||Duration days 12-40 post-veraison BBCH 84-86. ||Accounts for 50-70% total ripening sugar gain. ||Steady-state metabolism. ||Active_Sugar_Accumulation represents sustained sweetening phase achieving majority of commercial sugar levels. || This active accumulation occurs during mid-veraison through mid-ripening (BBCH 84-86), typically days 12-40 post-veraison onset spanning 25-35 days depending on cultivar and conditions, and is characterized by berry Brix increasing steadily from 13-19° at active onset to 21-27° at conclusion representing 7-13° gain during active period accounting for 50-70% of total ripening accumulation, daily Brix increase 0.18-0.35% per day (1.3-2.5% per week initially accelerating to 2.5-4.0% per week mid-active then moderating toward conclusion) showing relatively consistent rates compared to initial acceleration and final deceleration phases, hexose import rates sustained 45-120 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing mature transport capacity, and cumulative sugar gain 90-150 g/L over active period representing major contribution to final berry sweetness. ||Physiological characteristics during active accumulation include transporter gene expression maintained at elevated steady-state 80-120 fold above green berry (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6 collectively) with balance between synthesis and degradation sustaining high protein levels, enzyme activities stable with cell wall invertase 60-120 units/g fresh weight continuously cleaving phloem sucrose, membrane transport capacity 70-140 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ plasma membrane uptake and 55-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ tonoplast sequestration operating efficiently, hormonal regulation with ABA sustained 1400-2600 ng/g maintaining ripening program activation throughout active period, and metabolic integration where hexose import coordinated with partial respiration (25-35% of import oxidized) supporting ATP demands while majority (65-75%) accumulates ensuring efficient storage. ||Temporal stability during active accumulation demonstrates relatively constant day-to-day rates 0.20-0.38% Brix per day with <15-25% coefficient of variation over multi-week period indicating metabolic homeostasis, contrast with initial phase showing progressive acceleration as capacity establishes and final phase showing deceleration as limits approached, and environmental responsiveness maintaining rates within normal range under favorable conditions while moderating under stress demonstrating regulatory capacity preventing excessive fluctuation. ||Source-sink relationships during active period show sustained phloem delivery 180-350 mg sucrose per berry per day supported by canopy photosynthesis 12-25 g CO₂ fixed per vine per day producing adequate substrate, sink strength high with berry sugar demand dominant carbon sink receiving 70-85% of daily photosynthate, source capacity generally non-limiting under appropriate crop loads (0.8-1.2 kg fruit per m² leaf area) enabling sustained import, and balance between source supply and sink demand optimized through developmental programming and environmental acclimation maintaining steady accumulation without severe fluctuation. ||Cellular processes supporting sustained accumulation include vacuolar expansion continuing from 93-95% to 95-97% cell volume accommodating increasing solute loads, tonoplast membrane area increasing 40-80% over active period through proliferation supporting enhanced transport capacity, osmotic potential declining progressively -2.0 to -2.6 MPa → -2.4 to -3.2 MPa creating maintained water potential gradient favoring continued water import, and cell wall mechanical properties adjusting through expansin activity and polysaccharide modification enabling continued volume increase despite increasing turgor pressure. ||Environmental conditions supporting active accumulation include temperature optimum 25-30°C enabling maximum metabolic rates with this range producing fastest accumulation 3.0-4.5% Brix per week, moderate warmth 22-26°C supporting appropriate rates 2.2-3.5% per week achieving gradual progression, cooler conditions 18-22°C limiting to 1.5-2.5% per week extending duration to achieve final levels, heat stress 32-35°C potentially impairing 30-60% through enzyme impairment and membrane disruption, and cumulative heat during active period (growing degree-days) strongly correlating with total accumulation enabling predictive modeling. ||Water relations during active period demonstrate adequate vine water status essential with stem water potential -0.6 to -1.2 MPa supporting normal metabolism, moderate deficit -1.0 to -1.4 MPa generally compatible potentially enhancing concentration through reduced berry expansion with maintained import, severe deficit <-1.5 MPa impairing accumulation 35-65% through reduced phloem delivery and metabolic limitation, and irrigation timing strategically managing water availability balancing accumulation support against avoiding excess promoting vigor or dilution. ||Cultivar differences in active accumulation show rapid-accumulating varieties (Chardonnay, Gewürztraminer) displaying 3.5-4.8% Brix per week sustained 22-28 days achieving high final sugars efficiently, moderate cultivars (Merlot, Syrah) showing 2.8-4.0% per week over 28-35 days, and slower types (Nebbiolo, Carignan) exhibiting 2.2-3.2% per week extended 32-42 days reflecting genetic variation in transporter capacity and metabolic programming. ||Quality implications include active accumulation rates and duration determining whether target sugars achieved within available growing season, uniformity of active period across vineyard zones affecting harvest maturity consistency requiring zone-specific management, coordination between sugar accumulation and acid decline during active period establishing developing balance critical for wine style, and timing of active accumulation relative to phenolic maturity determining optimal harvest window particularly reds where tannin development must synchronize with sugar levels. ||Harvest timing considerations recognize active accumulation as critical period approaching maturity requiring increased monitoring frequency, weekly Brix sampling tracking rates enabling projection of harvest timing 2-3 weeks advance, integration with pH, TA, phenolic, and sensory assessment ensuring comprehensive maturity determination, and recognition that conclusion of active accumulation typically signals approaching harvest window requiring readiness. ||Viticultural management during active period includes maintaining canopy health ensuring sustained photosynthesis supporting continued accumulation, irrigation strategy providing adequate water without excess, disease control preventing infections disrupting metabolism, crop load management ensuring appropriate fruit-to-leaf ratios enabling adequate source capacity, and environmental monitoring tracking conditions affecting accumulation rates informing harvest planning. ||Metabolic efficiency during active period shows optimized carbon use with high proportion of imported hexoses (65-75%) accumulating versus respired (25-35%) representing efficient storage metabolism, ATP production from partial hexose oxidation supporting transport and biosynthesis costs estimated 15-25 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from hexose respiration plus 30-55 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from concurrent organic acid oxidation providing total 45-80 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ adequate for ripening demands, and energetic balance where combined sugar storage and acid catabolism creates metabolically efficient ripening strategy minimizing wasteful respiration while supporting necessary biosynthesis.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 223-227 sustained accumulation || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 accumulation dynamics || Ollat N, Gaudillère JP (1998) The effect of limiting leaf area during stage I of berry growth on development and composition of berries of Vitis vinifera L. cv. Cabernet Sauvignon Amer J Enol Vitic 49:251-258 sustained accumulation and source-sink."
},

  "Continuous_Sugar_Import": {
  "definition": "A Continuous_Sugar_Import is an Active_Sugar_Accumulation involving uninterrupted hexose flux from phloem unloading through cellular uptake into vacuolar storage without diurnal cessation.",
  "alternative_term": "uninterrupted hexose uptake | 24-hour sugar import | sustained substrate flux | constant sweetening |+ ununterbrochene Hexose-Aufnahme | 24-Stunden-Zucker-Import | anhaltender Substrat-Fluss | konstante Süßung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, continuous sugar import was characterized over 48-hour intensive monitoring during late August Year N+1 (BBCH 85, mid-active accumulation) showing daytime peak 88 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (12PM-4PM, berry temperature 31-34°C), evening 62 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (6PM-10PM, 26-28°C), nighttime sustained 42 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (12AM-4AM, 18-21°C, 48% of daytime rate), early morning 58 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (6AM-10AM, 22-26°C), demonstrating continuous 24-hour import without cessation, daily integrated 0.24% Brix per day.",
  "editor_note": "Continuous_Sugar_Import is distinguished from intermittent or episodic import by showing 24-hour flux without nocturnal cessation, from peak import by representing sustained (40-90 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ average) rather than maximum rates, and from initial import by showing established continuity rather than developing capacity. ||Nighttime flux 40-70% of daytime maintaining accumulation. ||Duration throughout active period BBCH 84-86. ||Essential for maximizing total accumulation. ||Continuous_Sugar_Import represents sustained metabolic process enabling efficient sweetness development. || This continuous import occurs during active accumulation period (BBCH 84-86), typically days 15-38 post-veraison spanning 20-30 days, and is characterized by 24-hour hexose uptake without nocturnal cessation at rates 40-90 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during daytime elevated to 50-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and reduced but maintained 25-60 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ nighttime representing 40-70% of daytime flux, daily integrated import 0.20-0.32% Brix per day (1.4-2.2% per week) accumulating continuously rather than episodically, phloem delivery maintained throughout diel cycle providing substrate availability 24 hours though mass flow rates potentially declining 30-50% nighttime as transpiration reduces, and cumulative effect where continuous import over 25-35 day period produces 6-11° Brix gain representing major contribution to final sweetness without interruption that could limit accumulation efficiency. ||Physiological basis for continuity includes phloem sap sucrose concentration maintained 350-600 mM throughout diel cycle providing substrate pool, apoplastic sucrose turnover rapid with half-life 4-12 minutes ensuring continuous cleavage by cell wall invertase producing glucose and fructose substrate for uptake, hexose transporter proteins present continuously in plasma membrane with densities 8-14% of total membrane protein not subject to rapid degradation maintaining import capacity 24 hours, and tonoplast transport capacity similarly sustained enabling vacuolar sequestration preventing cytoplasmic hexose accumulation that could reduce plasma membrane uptake gradient. ||Diel pattern characteristics demonstrate daytime peak import 60-130 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during hours 8AM-6PM when berry temperature optimal 24-32°C and phloem delivery maximum from active transpiration-driven mass flow, evening decline 45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ as temperature moderates and transpiration reduces but import continues, nighttime sustained flux 30-65 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ despite reduced phloem delivery and cooler temperature 16-24°C slowing kinetics indicating metabolic capacity exceeds substrate availability during night, and early morning recovery 40-75 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ as temperature increases and phloem delivery resumes demonstrating continuous 24-hour pattern without extended cessation periods. ||Molecular mechanisms enabling continuity include constitutive gene expression with VvHT transcript half-lives 8-14 hours requiring continuous transcription but steady-state levels maintained throughout diel cycle, protein stability with transporter half-lives 28-48 hours preventing rapid diurnal degradation maintaining functional capacity continuously, lack of strong diurnal transcriptional regulation unlike some genes showing circadian oscillation indicating ripening sugar transport prioritized over circadian control, and hormone signaling with ABA sustained 1600-2800 ng/g throughout 24-hour period maintaining transporter expression without nocturnal suppression. ||Substrate availability patterns show phloem sucrose delivery highest daytime 220-400 mg per berry per day declining nighttime to 120-240 mg per berry per day but remaining substantial supporting continued import, apoplastic hexose concentrations 180-350 mM daytime potentially declining to 120-250 mM nighttime but maintaining above threshold for transporter saturation (Km 1.5-10 mM depending on isoform), cytoplasmic hexose steady 60-100 mM throughout diel cycle through balance of plasma membrane import, metabolism, and tonoplast export maintaining homeostasis, and vacuolar accumulation progressive throughout 24 hours with concentrations rising 8-18 mM per day sustained day and night. ||Temperature effects on continuity demonstrate optimal import 26-30°C typically achieved midday enabling peak rates, cooler nighttime temperatures 16-24°C reducing rates 35-60% through kinetic effects on enzyme activities and membrane transport but not eliminating flux, and berry thermal mass plus nighttime atmospheric cooling creating diurnal temperature range 8-16°C modulating but not eliminating import maintaining continuity. ||Energetic considerations for continuous import include ATP requirements for membrane H⁺-pumps maintaining electrochemical gradients estimated 15-25 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹ must be met continuously, respiratory ATP production from concurrent acid oxidation 30-55 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ plus partial hexose respiration 15-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ providing 45-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ total adequate for transport and biosynthesis demands throughout diel cycle, and metabolic continuity where berry maintains active metabolism 24 hours supporting continuous import without nocturnal metabolic shutdown that would halt accumulation. ||Comparison with other fruits reveals grapes maintain continuous import unlike some climacteric fruits showing diurnal cessation, continuous pattern enabling efficient accumulation maximizing growing season utilization, and non-climacteric physiology with minimal ethylene involvement potentially contributing to sustained import without developmental interruption. ||Quality implications include continuous import enabling maximum total accumulation within available growing season achieving higher final sugars compared to hypothetical interrupted pattern, uniformity of import across 24-hour period reducing diurnal compositional variation potentially affecting berry heterogeneity, and efficiency where continuous process maximizes carbon use compared to episodic import requiring cyclic enzyme synthesis potentially wasting resources. ||Environmental factors affecting continuity include water status with adequate vine hydration essential for maintaining phloem delivery throughout diel cycle, severe deficit potentially disrupting continuity particularly nighttime when transpiration-driven flow minimal, temperature extremes with heat stress >35°C potentially disrupting daytime import or cool nights <12°C substantially reducing nighttime flux though rarely eliminating completely, and light operating primarily through source photosynthesis affecting substrate availability with adequate canopy function essential for sustained 24-hour sucrose supply. ||Viticultural management supporting continuity includes irrigation maintaining adequate vine water status throughout 24-hour period, canopy management ensuring sustained photosynthesis providing substrate, avoiding severe environmental stresses that could disrupt metabolic function, and recognizing continuous import as normal physiology not requiring intervention unless environmental conditions severely limiting.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 223-225 continuous accumulation || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 import dynamics || Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 transporter function enabling continuity."
},

  "Steady_Brix_Increase": {
  "definition": "A Steady_Brix_Increase is an Active_Sugar_Accumulation marked by uniform daily increments of berry soluble solids concentration.",
  "alternative_term": "consistent Brix progression | uniform soluble solids increase | predictable sweetening | stable sugar concentration rise |+ konsistente Brix-Progression | einheitliche lösliche Feststoff-Zunahme | vorhersagbare Süßung | stabile Zucker-Konzentrations-Anstieg",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Chianti Sangiovese vineyard, steady Brix increase was documented over 28 days in September Year N+1 (BBCH 85-86, active accumulation) when weekly Brix sampling showed consistent gains: 16.8° → 18.5° → 20.2° → 21.8° → 23.3° (average 1.7° per week, CV 8.5%), daily increment averaged 0.24% Brix (SD 0.032), linear regression r² = 0.94 enabling harvest forecast 18 days advance predicting 25° target within 2-day accuracy, under stable Tuscan autumn conditions (daily high 24-27°C, minimal variation).",
  "editor_note": "Steady_Brix_Increase is distinguished from initial acceleration by showing consistent (CV <12-20%) rather than increasing rates, from final deceleration by maintaining steady rather than declining rates, and from peak accumulation by representing sustained moderate (1.5-2.5% per week) rather than maximum (3.5-5.0% per week) rates. ||Duration 22-32 days BBCH 84-86. ||Linear relationship time-Brix r² >0.88. ||Predictive value for harvest timing. ||Steady_Brix_Increase represents normal healthy ripening pattern enabling management planning. || This steady increase occurs during active accumulation period (BBCH 84-86), typically days 14-38 post-veraison spanning 22-32 days, and is characterized by daily Brix increments 0.22-0.35% per day (1.5-2.5% per week) showing coefficient of variation <12-20% over multi-week measurement period indicating consistency, linear or gently curving regression relationship (r² > 0.88-0.96) between time and Brix demonstrating predictability, weekly sampling showing 1.8-3.2° Brix gain per week sustained over 3-5 consecutive weeks without dramatic fluctuation, and cumulative effect producing 7-12° Brix total increase during steady period representing 50-75% of total ripening gain achieved through consistent gradual accumulation. ||Statistical characteristics of steadiness include daily measurements showing normal distribution around mean daily increment with standard deviation <0.04-0.08% Brix per day, sequential measurements rarely differing >15-25% from running average indicating minimal day-to-day volatility, week-to-week comparison showing <18-28% variation in weekly gain rates demonstrating stability, and absence of extended plateaus (>3-5 days without measurable increase) or reversals (Brix decline) that would indicate metabolic dysfunction or severe environmental stress. ||Physiological basis for steadiness includes sustained transporter expression 85-115 fold above green berry with minimal day-to-day fluctuation maintaining stable import capacity, enzyme activities relatively constant with cell wall invertase 65-110 units/g fresh weight and transport proteins 75-135 μmol hexose uptake capacity g⁻¹ h⁻¹ showing <15-25% variation over measurement period, hormonal regulation with ABA 1500-2700 ng/g sustained without dramatic spikes or troughs providing stable ripening signal, and metabolic homeostasis where balance between import, respiration, and storage maintained through regulatory feedback preventing excessive fluctuation. ||Source-sink stability during steady period demonstrates photosynthesis rates relatively consistent 11-18 g CO₂ fixed per vine per day over multi-week period under favorable weather providing stable substrate supply, phloem delivery 180-320 mg sucrose per berry per day maintained within 25-40% range week-to-week, sink strength high with berry demand 70-85% of photosynthate relatively constant, and source-sink ratio stable through appropriate crop load (0.8-1.2 kg per m² leaf area) preventing source limitation that could disrupt steady accumulation. ||Environmental conditions supporting steadiness include stable moderate weather with temperatures 23-29°C range without extreme heat or cool spells producing consistent metabolic rates, adequate water availability maintaining stem water potential -0.7 to -1.3 MPa without severe fluctuation supporting stable phloem function, minimal disease or pest pressure preventing metabolic disruption, and absence of severe weather events (hail, extreme wind, excessive rain) that could directly damage berries or indirectly affect metabolism disrupting steady accumulation. ||Contrast with unsteady accumulation patterns includes initial acceleration phase showing increasing daily increments 0.12-0.20 → 0.28-0.38% Brix per day over 10-15 days as capacity develops representing developmental ramp-up not steady-state, final deceleration showing declining increments 0.25-0.32 → 0.08-0.15% per day as limits approached representing physiological constraint not steady accumulation, and stress-induced disruption showing erratic pattern with plateaus, reversals, or dramatic rate changes indicating abnormal metabolism requiring management attention. ||Predictive value of steadiness enables linear extrapolation from current Brix and steady rate projecting harvest date 2-4 weeks advance with reasonable accuracy ±3-7 days, degree-day models calibrated during steady period improving forecast precision, growers using steady period data to schedule labor, equipment, and winery capacity with confidence, and recognition that departure from steady pattern (acceleration, deceleration, plateau) signals changing conditions requiring management response or harvest timing adjustment. ||Quality implications include steady increase generally indicating healthy ripening with normal metabolism producing balanced compositional development, coordination between steady sugar increase and concurrent acid decline establishing appropriate sugar-acid balance developing predictably, uniformity across vineyard zones showing similar steady patterns indicating homogeneous ripening enabling single-pass harvest, and heterogeneity where some zones steady while others erratic revealing management issues or site variation requiring selective treatment. ||Cultivar differences in steadiness characteristics show some varieties displaying highly consistent patterns (Chardonnay, Merlot) enabling reliable forecasting, others showing greater variability (Pinot Noir particularly warm climates) requiring more frequent monitoring, and inherent rate differences with rapid cultivars showing higher daily increments 0.28-0.38% Brix per day while slower types 0.18-0.26% per day reflecting genetic variation in accumulation capacity. ||Temperature effects on steady rates demonstrate positive correlation with mean temperature during steady period explaining 60-80% of rate variation (r² = 0.60-0.80), cool vintages producing slower steady rates 1.2-2.0% Brix per week extending accumulation duration requiring patience, warm vintages showing faster rates 2.2-3.5% per week shortening period potentially requiring earlier harvest, and excessive heat disrupting steadiness through metabolic stress creating erratic patterns. ||Water management effects show adequate irrigation supporting steadiness through maintained phloem function and stable metabolism, deficit irrigation potentially slowing steady rate 15-30% through reduced berry expansion while maintaining or enhancing concentration, excessive water potentially disrupting steadiness through dilution effects or metabolic perturbation, and irrigation scheduling during steady period requiring balance between supporting accumulation and controlling berry size affecting concentration. ||Monitoring strategies during steady period include weekly Brix sampling minimum frequency with twice-weekly optimal for precise rate determination, spatial sampling across vineyard zones revealing uniformity or heterogeneity, temporal sampling tracking consistency enabling detection of departures from steady pattern indicating developing issues, and integration with other maturity parameters (pH, TA, phenolics, sensory) ensuring comprehensive assessment recognizing Brix alone insufficient for harvest decisions. ||Harvest timing decisions based on steady increase involve recognition that steady period typically concludes 1-3 weeks pre-harvest as deceleration begins, continued monitoring required as steadiness ends to determine actual harvest timing, target Brix achievement timing projected from steady period rates enabling advance planning, and flexibility to harvest earlier if environmental stress threatens to disrupt continued accumulation or later if phenolic maturity lags sugar development requiring extended ripening.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 ripening patterns || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 Brix increase dynamics || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 224-227 steady accumulation patterns."
},

  "Progressive_Sweetening": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Sweetening is an Active_Sugar_Accumulation characterized by sensory transformation from tart-acidic to sweet-balanced through cumulative hexose accumulation and concurrent acid decline.",
  "alternative_term": "gradual flavor development | cumulative taste transformation | sensory ripening progression | sugar-acid balance shift |+ graduelle Geschmacks-Entwicklung | kumulative Geschmacks-Transformation | sensorische Reifungs-Progression | Zucker-Säure-Balance-Verschiebung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Finger Lakes Riesling vineyard, progressive sweetening was evaluated over 35 days from mid-September through October Year N+1 (BBCH 85-87) through weekly taste panels when berries transitioned from tart-dominant (day 0: Brix 14.8°, TA 11.2 g/L, pH 3.06, ratio 1.32:1, taste:sharply tart) through balanced (day 21: Brix 19.6°, TA 8.4 g/L, pH 3.28, ratio 2.33:1, taste:sweet-tart harmonious) to sweet-forward (day 35: Brix 23.2°, TA 6.8 g/L, pH 3.42, ratio 3.41:1, taste:pleasantly sweet with crisp acidity, floral-fruity notes), enabling harvest at optimal balance for off-dry style.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Sweetening is distinguished from initial sweetening by showing gradual transition (30-40 days) rather than onset, from rapid sweetening by representing moderate-paced progression rather than accelerated rates, and from sugar accumulation by focusing on sensory perception rather than analytical measurement. ||Sugar:acid ratio 1.5-2.5:1 → 3.5-6.0:1. ||Taste: tart-dominant → balanced → sweet-forward. ||Duration BBCH 84-87. ||Sensory assessment critical. ||Progressive_Sweetening represents perceived ripening transformation defining harvest quality. || This progressive sweetening occurs throughout active ripening (BBCH 84-87), typically days 15-50 post-veraison spanning 30-40 days, and is characterized by taste evaluation showing decreasing tartness perception from dominant sharp acidity (pH 3.0-3.3, TA 10-16 g/L, Brix 13-18°) through balanced sweet-tart transition (pH 3.3-3.6, TA 6-10 g/L, Brix 19-23°) toward sweet-dominant ripe character (pH 3.4-3.8, TA 4-7 g/L, Brix 22-28°), sugar:acid ratio increasing from 1.5-2.5:1 (early active) through 2.5-4.0:1 (mid-active) to 3.5-6.0:1 (late active approaching harvest) representing fundamental balance shift, sensory sweetness threshold (~8-12° Brix) surpassed early in active period after which sweetness increasingly dominant taste component, and flavor complexity developing as esters, terpenes, and other volatiles accumulate 30-150 μg/kg total aromatics complementing sugar-acid balance creating integrated sensory ripeness. ||Biochemical basis of progressive sweetening includes hexose accumulation increasing vacuolar concentrations from 500-900 mM to 1400-2200 mM (glucose and fructose each 700-1100 mM) creating sweetness through activation of taste receptors particularly T1R2-T1R3 heterodimer responding to sugars, organic acid decline particularly malate reducing from 6-12 g/L to 2-5 g/L diminishing tartness as fewer acid molecules available to activate sour taste receptors (PKD channels responding to protons), pH increase from 3.1-3.4 to 3.4-3.7 reducing proton concentration further moderating sour perception, and flavor compound synthesis with esters (ethyl acetate, isoamyl acetate), terpenes (linalool, geraniol in aromatics), C6 aldehydes and alcohols (hexanal, hexanol) accumulating creating fruity floral aromas enhancing perceived sweetness through cross-modal sensory integration. ||Sensory perception dynamics demonstrate sweetness intensity increasing logarithmically with sugar concentration following psychophysical power law where doubling sugar produces <2-fold perceived sweetness increase, sourness decreasing as acid concentration declines and pH increases with malate loss particularly effective as malic acid more sour than tartaric at equivalent concentration, flavor development enhancing sweetness perception through multisensory integration where fruity aromas synergistically increase perceived sweetness even at constant sugar levels, and astringency from phenolics (particularly unripe reds) declining through tannin polymerization reducing harsh character allowing sweet-fruity notes to dominate sensory profile. ||Temporal trajectory of sweetening shows early active period (days 15-25) characterized by declining tartness as acids reduce while sweetness emerges but balance still acid-favored creating tart-sweet transition phase, mid-active period (days 25-38) displaying balanced sweet-tart character where neither dominates creating harmonious taste optimal for some styles, late active period (days 38-50) achieving sweetness dominance with reduced but adequate acidity creating characteristic ripe fruit taste suitable for harvest depending on style requirements, and varietal character increasingly expressed as flavor compounds accumulate differentiating cultivar-specific sensory signatures. ||Sugar:acid ratio as sweetness metric demonstrates ratios <2.0:1 (Brix:TA g/L) producing predominantly tart fruit inadequate for most uses, ratios 2.0-3.0:1 showing balanced character suitable for high-acid wine styles or fresh consumption of tart varieties, ratios 3.0-5.0:1 creating pleasant sweet-tart balance typical for quality table wine grapes, ratios >5.0:1 achieving very sweet character appropriate for late harvest styles or dessert wines or indicating over-deacidification in warm vintages potentially problematic, and target ratios varying by cultivar and style with high-acid varieties optimal 2.5-4.0:1 while lower-acid types 3.5-5.5:1. ||Cultivar variation in sweetening patterns shows aromatic varieties (Muscat, Gewürztraminer, Riesling) achieving pronounced sweetness perception through synergy between sugars, low acids, and intense floral-fruity aromas, neutral varieties (Chardonnay, Merlot) displaying sugar-driven sweetening with less aromatic contribution requiring higher absolute sugars for equivalent perceived sweetness, and phenolic-rich reds (Cabernet Sauvignon, Nebbiolo) potentially showing delayed sweetening perception until tannins polymerize reducing astringency masking sweetness. ||Quality implications for different uses include table grape breeding and selection prioritizing rapid progressive sweetening achieving 16-20° Brix with balanced acidity for fresh consumption, wine grapes requiring slower more balanced progression maintaining adequate acids (final TA 5-8 g/L) while achieving target sugars 20-26° Brix, late harvest or dessert wine production targeting extended ripening achieving very high sugars 26-35° Brix with maintained acids creating intense sweetness with balancing acidity, and raisins requiring progression to 24-30° Brix on vine or through post-harvest drying. ||Environmental effects on sweetening include warm conditions accelerating both sugar accumulation and acid decline potentially producing rapid sweetening but risk of excessive deacidification creating unbalanced fruit, cool conditions moderating sweetening maintaining higher acids potentially beneficial for acid retention but requiring longer season achieving target sugars, water status with deficit potentially enhancing sweetening perception through concentration effects reducing berry size, and canopy microclimate with sun exposure accelerating sweetening through enhanced berry temperature affecting both sugar and acid metabolism. ||Harvest timing based on progressive sweetening involves taste evaluation as critical assessment tool confirming analytical measures, recognition that perceived sweetness depends on sugar-acid balance not sugar alone requiring integrated assessment, sensory evaluation detecting flavor development complementing sweetness indicating true ripeness beyond just Brix, varietal character expression important particularly whites and aromatics where flavor ripeness may lag sugar requiring extended hang time, and consumer or winemaker preferences defining target sweetness profile varying by intended use and style. ||Viticultural management affecting progressive sweetening includes canopy management influencing cluster microclimate affecting sweetening rate through temperature and light effects, crop load adjustment ensuring adequate photosynthesis supporting both sugar accumulation and secondary metabolite synthesis contributing to perceived sweetness, irrigation strategy balancing adequate water for metabolism against deficit enhancing concentration, and harvest timing decisions integrating sensory sweetening assessment with analytical measures ensuring optimal balance achieved.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 224-228, 251-256 sensory development || Boulton RB, Singleton VL, Bisson LF, Kunkee RE (1996) Principles and Practices of Winemaking pages 53-58 taste and balance || Noble AC, Bursick GF (1984) The contribution of glycerol to perceived viscosity and sweetness in white wine Amer J Enol Vitic 35:110-112 sweetness perception."
},

  "Peak_Sugar_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Peak_Sugar_Accumulation is a Sugar_Accumulation marked by maximum velocity of hexose import and vacuolar storage during mid-to-late véraison with sugar transport pathway components at optimal capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum accumulation phase | fastest sweetening period | hexose import maximum | optimal loading phase |+ maximale Akkumulations-Phase | schnellste Süßungs-Periode | Hexose-Import-Maximum | optimale Beladungs-Phase",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Valley Shiraz vineyard, peak sugar accumulation was identified over 14 days in mid-February Year N+1 (BBCH 84-85) when berry Brix increased from 18.2° to 25.6° (7.4° gain, average 5.3% per week peak rate), hexose import calculated 128 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ based on Brix trajectory and berry volume, VvHT1 expression 142-fold, cell wall invertase 118 units/g FW, berry fresh weight 1.68 g → 1.95 g (16% expansion during peak), under optimal Australian conditions (daily high 28-31°C, adequate irrigation, healthy canopy supporting maximum photosynthesis).",
  "editor_note": "Peak_Sugar_Accumulation is distinguished from Active_Sugar_Accumulation by representing maximum (3.5-5.5% Brix per week) rather than sustained (2.5-4.0%) rates, from Sugar_Accumulation_Onset by showing established peak rather than initial phase, and from late accumulation by exhibiting maximum rather than declining rates. ||Duration 10-18 days BBCH 84-85. ||Accounts for 30-50% total ripening gain despite brief duration. ||Critical window. ||Peak_Sugar_Accumulation represents most intensive sweetening phase determining final sugar achievement. || This peak accumulation occurs during mid-to-late veraison (BBCH 84-85), typically days 18-32 post-veraison onset spanning 10-18 days depending on cultivar and environmental conditions, and is characterized by berry Brix increasing at maximum rates 3.5-5.5% per week (0.50-0.78% per day) compared to active phase average 2.5-4.0% per week and late phase 1.2-2.8% per week, hexose import reaching maximum velocity 90-170 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing full saturation of transport machinery, daily sugar gain 180-280 mg hexose per berry per day (depending on berry size 1.6-2.4 g) enabling 4-8° Brix increase over 12-16 day peak period, and cumulative contribution where peak phase though brief in duration accounts for 30-50% of total ripening sugar gain demonstrating concentrated intensive accumulation. ||Biochemical characteristics at peak include hexose transporter genes (VvHT1, VvHT2, VvHT3, VvHT5, VvHT6) expressed at absolute maximum 100-150 fold above green berry collectively providing capacity substantially exceeding average active phase levels, cell wall invertase activity 80-140 units/g fresh weight producing hexoses from phloem sucrose at maximum velocity matching or exceeding cellular uptake capacity, plasma membrane hexose uptake operating near Vmax 85-150 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with substrate concentrations well above Km ensuring kinetic saturation, tonoplast transport maximized 65-120 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ efficiently clearing cytoplasmic hexoses maintaining concentration gradients enabling continued plasma membrane uptake, and metabolic integration where partial hexose respiration 25-35% of import provides ATP supporting transport while majority 65-75% accumulates representing optimal storage efficiency. ||Source-sink dynamics at peak demonstrate phloem delivery maximized 250-450 mg sucrose per berry per day supported by canopy photosynthesis operating at seasonal maximum 15-28 g CO₂ fixed per vine per day under favorable conditions, sink strength at absolute maximum with berry demand overwhelming competing sinks receiving 75-90% of daily photosynthate, source-sink connectivity optimized through vascular development and phloem maturation enabling efficient translocation, and environmental conditions typically favorable during peak with moderate temperatures 25-30°C, adequate water, and high light supporting both source and sink processes. ||Cellular processes supporting peak include vacuolar expansion approaching maximum 95-97% cell volume creating storage capacity 1.8-3.2 nL per mesocarp cell, tonoplast membrane area at maximum following proliferation during earlier phases providing adequate surface for transport, osmotic potential declining most rapidly -0.22 to -0.32 MPa per week (from -2.0 to -2.6 MPa → -2.4 to -3.2 MPa over peak period) creating strong water potential gradient, turgor pressure maintained 0.3-0.6 MPa through balance of osmotic potential and cell wall resistance, and berry expansion continuing 12-22% during peak through osmotic water import demonstrating coupling between sugar accumulation and growth. ||Environmental factors producing peak conditions include temperature optimum 26-30°C enabling maximum enzyme activities and metabolic flux with this range occurring typically mid-to-late summer (northern hemisphere August, southern hemisphere February), photoperiod still long 13-15 hours providing extended photosynthesis period supporting substrate production, solar radiation high 20-30 MJ m⁻² per day saturating photosynthesis, water availability adequate with stem water potential -0.7 to -1.2 MPa supporting phloem function without severe stress, and absence of extreme weather events enabling uninterrupted accumulation during critical window. ||Hormonal regulation at peak shows ABA sustained at elevated plateau 1800-2800 ng/g maintaining maximum transporter expression and coordinating ripening processes, sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway with glucose-6-phosphate 35-65 μmol/g fresh weight creating strong feed-forward amplification, declining growth hormones having reached minimum maintaining metabolic focus on storage rather than structural development, and potential ethylene elevation slight 0.3-0.8 nL g⁻¹ h⁻¹ in some cultivars possibly fine-tuning ripening though grape generally non-climacteric with minimal ethylene effects. ||Cultivar variation in peak characteristics demonstrates high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer, Sémillon) achieving exceptional peak rates 4.8-6.2% Brix per week sustained 10-14 days with high transporter expression and efficient metabolism, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Merlot) showing 3.8-5.0% per week for 12-16 days representing typical commercial varieties, and lower-accumulation types (Pinot Noir cool climates, table grapes) displaying 3.0-4.2% per week over 14-20 days reflecting genetic differences in maximum capacity and duration. ||Quality implications of peak accumulation include timing and intensity determining whether target sugars achieved within available season particularly cool regions where growing season limited, duration of peak affecting total gain with extended peak beneficial for achieving high sugars while abbreviated peak may limit final levels, coordination between sugar peak and acid decline affecting final balance with simultaneous peaks producing rapid compositional change requiring careful harvest timing, and spatial variation in peak timing across vineyard creating maturity heterogeneity requiring zone-specific management or selective harvest. ||Harvest timing considerations recognize peak accumulation signals approaching maturity requiring increased monitoring, weekly sampling during peak critical for tracking rates and projecting harvest timing 1-2 weeks advance, recognition that conclusion of peak typically indicates 2-4 weeks to harvest as deceleration begins, and integration of peak sugar accumulation with phenolic and flavor maturity particularly reds where tannin development must synchronize with sugar levels. ||Viticultural management during peak includes maintaining optimal environmental conditions through irrigation supporting phloem function, canopy health ensuring continued photosynthesis, disease control preventing disruption, crop load ensuring adequate source capacity, avoiding severe environmental stresses during this critical window as impairment during peak disproportionately affects final sugar levels, and harvest preparation advancing as peak indicates approaching maturity. ||Metabolic efficiency at peak shows optimized carbon use with high proportion imported hexoses accumulating versus respired, ATP production from combined hexose and acid catabolism adequate for all ripening demands estimated 70-110 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹, and energetic balance where intensive metabolism during peak supported without excessive respiratory carbon loss representing efficient ripening strategy.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 223-228 peak accumulation || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 peak rates and variation || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 peak accumulation dynamics."
},

  "Maximum_Sugar_Loading_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Sugar_Loading_Rate is a Peak_Sugar_Accumulation marked by absolute highest velocity of hexose import with phloem delivery, invertase activity, membrane transport, and vacuolar sequestration all at saturating capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "peak hexose uptake velocity | fastest sugar import flux | maximum loading capacity | absolute accumulation maximum |+ Spitzen-Hexose-Aufnahme-Geschwindigkeit | schnellster Zucker-Import-Fluss | maximale Beladungs-Kapazität | absolutes Akkumulations-Maximum",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Zinfandel vineyard, maximum sugar loading rate was measured over 9 days in late August Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when hexose import reached 168 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ calculated from Brix trajectory, berry Brix increased from 20.8° to 26.2° (average 0.72% per day, 5.0% per week), cell wall invertase 128 units/g FW, VvHT1 expression 155-fold, vacuolar hexose rose from 1250 to 1680 mM (430 mM gain), berry fresh weight 2.08 g expanding 14%, under hot Napa conditions (daily high 32-36°C near heat stress threshold but sustained maximum briefly).",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Sugar_Loading_Rate is distinguished from Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate (Batch 34) by representing brief absolute maximum (100-180 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, 6-12 days) rather than sustained peak period, from average rates by showing maximum (0.55-0.85% Brix per day) rather than typical (0.22-0.35%), and conceptually similar to Peak_Sugar_Import_Rate providing alternative organizational perspective. ||Duration 6-12 days BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature optimum 26-30°C critical. ||Kinetic saturation achieved. ||Maximum_Sugar_Loading_Rate represents absolute capacity limit determining achievable sweetening under optimal conditions. || This maximum rate occurs during peak accumulation phase (BBCH 84-85), typically days 20-28 post-veraison for duration 6-12 days, and is characterized by hexose uptake reaching 100-180 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing full capacity of transport machinery, berry Brix increasing 0.55-0.85% per day (3.8-6.0% per week) creating steepest Brix trajectory, daily sugar gain 200-320 mg hexose per berry enabling 2.5-4.5° Brix increase over 6-10 day maximum period, and calculated sugar import flux 140-260 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ total (combining membrane uptake, metabolism, and accumulation) matching or exceeding apoplastic production from invertase indicating transport capacity adequate for maximum substrate delivery. ||Biochemical basis of maximum rate includes hexose transporter protein density reaching absolute maximum estimated 10-16% of total plasma membrane protein providing unprecedented facilitated diffusion capacity, cell wall invertase activity 90-150 units/g fresh weight producing hexoses from sucrose at rates 130-280 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ potentially exceeding cellular uptake capacity indicating enzyme saturation not limiting, apoplastic hexose concentrations 280-550 mM combined glucose and fructose creating strong driving force for membrane transport with concentrations far above transporter Km values 1.5-10 mM ensuring kinetic saturation, cytoplasmic hexose maintained 65-105 mM through rapid tonoplast clearing preventing accumulation that could reduce plasma membrane uptake gradient, and tonoplast transport 70-140 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ efficiently sequestering cytoplasmic hexoses maintaining compartmentation essential for continued import. ||Kinetic analysis at maximum rate demonstrates plasma membrane glucose transport Vmax 80-135 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ achieved during maximum with substrate saturation 92-98% (apoplastic glucose 140-280 mM far exceeding Km 1.5-3.0 mM), fructose transport Vmax similarly 70-120 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with saturation 90-96% (apoplastic fructose 140-270 mM exceeding Km 5-12 mM), combined uptake 150-255 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ limited by transporter density not substrate availability, and comparison with active phase average uptake 70-130 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ showing maximum represents 1.6-2.4 fold enhancement reflecting peak conditions. ||Phloem delivery supporting maximum rate shows sucrose mass flow 280-500 mg per berry per day enabled by transpiration-driven pressure flow, source photosynthesis 18-32 g CO₂ fixed per vine per day under optimal conditions producing abundant substrate, vine-level allocation 80-95% of photosynthate to fruit during maximum representing strong sink signal, and phloem sap sucrose concentration 450-750 mM maintained throughout diel cycle providing continuous substrate supply. ||Vacuolar dynamics during maximum show concentration rising 160-250 mM per week (glucose and fructose each 80-125 mM per week increase) representing most rapid accumulation, osmotic potential declining -0.25 to -0.35 MPa per week creating steepest gradient (from -2.2 to -2.8 MPa → -2.4 to -3.2 MPa over maximum period), water import 12-20% berry volume per week driven by osmotic gradient causing rapid berry expansion, and vacuole occupying 96-97% cell volume at maximum nearing absolute limit for mesocarp cells. ||Molecular mechanisms enabling maximum include gene expression at absolute ceiling 110-165 fold above green berry (VvHT1, VvHT2 combined) representing maximum transcriptional activation, protein synthesis rates 35-65 ng transporter protein per g berry per hour maintaining high levels despite turnover, post-translational modifications potentially optimizing transporter activity through phosphorylation or other changes though modifications in grape incompletely characterized, and regulatory signals including ABA 2000-3200 ng/g, hexose signaling with glucose-6-phosphate 45-75 μmol/g FW creating maximum feed-forward activation. ||Temperature optimum for maximum rate shows sharp dependence 26-30°C producing highest rates 140-200 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and 4.5-6.5% Brix per week, moderate warmth 23-26°C enabling 100-150 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and 3.2-4.8% per week still approaching maximum, cooler conditions 18-23°C limiting to 65-110 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and 2.2-3.5% per week through reduced kinetics, and heat stress >32-35°C impairing maximum by 35-65% through enzyme denaturation, membrane disruption, and metabolic dysfunction preventing achievement of true maximum. ||Diurnal variation at maximum shows midday peak 160-250 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ during hours 11AM-4PM when berry temperature optimal and phloem delivery maximum, morning and evening 110-180 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ as conditions moderate but remain favorable, nighttime sustained 70-120 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 45-65% of daytime maximum demonstrating continuous import even at reduced rates, and daily integrated maximum 0.60-0.90% Brix per day averaging diurnal cycle. ||Energy requirements at maximum include ATP demand for membrane H⁺-ATPases maintaining electrochemical gradients estimated 20-35 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹ must be met to support maximum transport, respiratory ATP production from combined hexose (20-40% of import oxidized = 25-65 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ oxidized producing 35-90 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹) plus organic acid catabolism (35-60 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹) providing total 70-150 μmol ATP g⁻¹ h⁻¹ adequate for transport and biosynthesis, and energetic efficiency where majority imported hexoses accumulate (60-80%) versus respired (20-40%) representing favorable storage ratio. ||Cultivar variation in maximum rate demonstrates high-capacity varieties achieving 160-220 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and 5.2-7.0% Brix per week sustained 7-11 days, moderate cultivars showing 120-170 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and 4.0-5.5% per week for 9-14 days, and lower-capacity types displaying 85-135 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ and 3.0-4.5% per week over 12-18 days reflecting genetic differences in transporter expression, enzyme capacity, and metabolic programming. ||Quality implications include maximum rate achievement critical for reaching target sugars within growing season particularly cool regions where season limited, duration of maximum affecting total sugar gain with extended maximum beneficial but also indicating potential for excessive sugars if not monitored, coordination between sugar maximum and acid decline potentially producing very rapid compositional change requiring careful harvest timing decisions, and failure to achieve expected maximum indicating environmental stress or management limitations requiring intervention or harvest timing adjustment. ||Harvest forecasting uses maximum rate measurements projecting final Brix achievement timing 10-16 days advance enabling advance planning, recognition that maximum typically concludes 2-3 weeks pre-harvest as deceleration begins, integration with acid, pH, phenolic monitoring ensuring comprehensive maturity determination, and flexibility to adjust harvest date based on actual versus projected maximum rate performance. ||Viticultural management during maximum prioritizes maintaining optimal conditions through adequate irrigation, canopy health, disease control, and environmental moderation, avoiding any severe stresses during this brief critical window as impairment dramatically affects final sugar, recognizing maximum as point of no return where berry committed to ripening trajectory determined by maximum rate achievement, and harvest preparation advancing as maximum signals approaching maturity requiring readiness within 2-4 weeks typical time from maximum completion to optimal harvest.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 223-228 maximum rates || Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 transporter capacity || Sweetman C, Deluc LG, Cramer GR, Ford CM, Soole KL (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits Phytochem 70:1329-1344 maximum loading dynamics."
},

  "Rapid_Brix_Elevation": {
  "definition": "A Rapid_Brix_Elevation is a Peak_Sugar_Accumulation characterized by maximum daily or weekly increments of refractometric soluble solids measurements.",
  "alternative_term": "steep Brix increase | fast soluble solids rise | accelerated sugar concentration | maximum Brix gradient |+ steiler Brix-Anstieg | schneller löslicher Feststoff-Anstieg | beschleunigte Zucker-Konzentration | maximaler Brix-Gradient",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Sonoma Chardonnay vineyard, rapid Brix elevation was documented over 12 days in early September Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when weekly sampling showed steep progression: 18.2° → 21.8° → 25.6° (average 3.7° per week, 0.53% per day), total 7.4° gain during rapid phase, linear regression slope 0.62° Brix per day (r² = 0.96), refractive index increase 0.00087 units per day, enabling harvest forecast 15 days advance projecting 26° target achieved within 8 days (actual 7 days, excellent accuracy), under warm California coastal conditions (daily high 26-30°C optimal).",
  "editor_note": "Rapid_Brix_Elevation is distinguished from Steady_Brix_Increase by showing maximum (0.52-0.88% per day) rather than moderate (0.22-0.35%) rates, from Rapid_Brix_Increase (Batch 34) by providing alternative perspective on same phenomenon, and from initial Brix increase by representing peak rather than early phase. ||Duration 8-16 days BBCH 84-85. ||Weekly gain 3.6-6.2° Brix. ||Steepest trajectory. ||Predictive value for harvest timing. ||Rapid_Brix_Elevation represents most dramatic sweetening period determining maturity achievement. || This rapid elevation occurs during peak accumulation phase (BBCH 84-85), typically days 19-30 post-veraison spanning 8-14 days, and is characterized by daily Brix increase 0.52-0.88% per day representing 2-3 fold enhancement over average active phase rates, weekly measurements showing 3.6-6.2° Brix gain per week creating steep trajectory visible in sequential sampling, berry Brix rising from 17-21° at rapid onset to 23-28° at conclusion over 10-15 day period representing 5-9° total increase during rapid phase, and refractive index increasing 0.00075-0.00123 units per day (corresponding to Brix change) reflecting altered light refraction through juice due to dissolved hexoses. ||Physical basis of Brix elevation includes total dissolved solids increasing primarily through hexose accumulation with glucose and fructose collectively contributing 85-95% of measured Brix, minor contribution from tartaric acid (5-9 g/L relatively stable) and other organic acids (declining 3-7 g/L malate), amino acids, phenolics, minerals collectively 12-25 g/L contributing 10-15% of total Brix measurement, refractive index relationship where each 1° Brix corresponds approximately to 10 g/L dissolved solids and refractive index increase 0.00014 at 20°C, and osmotic potential relationship where 1° Brix approximately equals -0.10 to -0.12 MPa osmotic potential contribution creating gradient driving water import. ||Measurement methodology for tracking rapid elevation includes portable digital refractometer field measurements accurate ±0.2° Brix enabling rapid assessment, laboratory bench refractometer providing ±0.05° accuracy for precise tracking, temperature compensation essential as refractive index varies 0.00025 per °C requiring correction to standard 20°C, sampling protocol collecting 20-50 berries randomly distributed across cluster zones ensuring representative measurement, and juice extraction through crushing and filtering providing clear sample free of particulates that could interfere with refraction measurement. ||Temporal characteristics during rapid phase show acceleration from active phase typical 0.24-0.38% Brix per day to rapid maximum 0.60-0.95% per day over 3-5 days as conditions optimize, sustained maximum rates 0.55-0.85% per day for 6-11 days while favorable conditions persist, then deceleration as substrates deplete or environmental conditions change transitioning toward late accumulation <0.35% per day, and total duration 8-16 days depending on cultivar and environment determining magnitude of rapid phase contribution to final sweetness. ||Biochemical mechanisms enabling rapid elevation reviewed from previous sections include maximum hexose import 100-180 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ producing sugar flux adequate for observed Brix increase, vacuolar accumulation 150-250 mM combined hexoses per week creating concentration changes underlying Brix measurement, water import 10-18% berry volume per week diluting sugars slightly but net effect strongly positive Brix increase as hexose accumulation far exceeds dilution, and respiratory consumption 20-35% of hexose import representing minor loss with 65-80% accumulating net contributing to Brix elevation. ||Environmental conditions producing rapid elevation include temperature optimum 26-30°C enabling maximum metabolic rates producing fastest elevation 5.0-7.0% Brix per week, moderate warmth 23-27°C supporting 3.8-5.5% per week approaching maximum, cooler conditions 18-24°C limiting to 2.5-4.0% per week extending duration required for achieving final levels, heat stress >32-35°C potentially impairing elevation 30-60% or causing irregular pattern, and stable favorable weather over 10-15 day period enabling sustained rapid elevation whereas variable conditions may produce irregular pattern. ||Cultivar genetic variation demonstrates high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer 26-30° potential, Sémillon 24-28°) achieving rapid elevation 5.5-7.5% Brix per week sustained 8-12 days, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon 22-26°) showing 4.2-6.0% per week for 10-14 days, and lower-Brix types (Pinot Noir cool climate 20-24°, table grapes 18-22°) displaying 3.2-5.0% per week over 12-18 days reflecting genetic differences in maximum capacity and duration determining elevation potential. ||Predictive modeling using rapid elevation data enables extrapolation from current Brix and measured rapid rate projecting harvest date 10-18 days advance, degree-day accumulation models calibrated during rapid phase improving forecast accuracy, recognition that rapid elevation typically concludes 1.5-3 weeks pre-harvest enabling harvest planning, and adjustment of projections if elevation rate changes indicating altered conditions requiring management response. ||Quality implications include rapid elevation timing and magnitude determining whether target sugars achieved within available growing season, excessive rapid elevation potentially producing higher-than-desired sugars requiring earlier harvest accepting lower phenolic development or later harvest risking over-ripeness, inadequate rapid elevation maintaining lower sugars potentially acceptable for lower-alcohol styles but problematic if target levels not achieved, and coordination between rapid Brix elevation and concurrent acid decline affecting final balance with simultaneous rapid changes producing compressed maturation window requiring precise harvest timing. ||Harvest timing decisions based on rapid elevation involve recognition that steepest Brix increase signals approaching critical maturity period, increased sampling frequency during rapid phase (2-3 times per week) essential for tracking trajectory accurately, target Brix achievement projection enabling advance harvest scheduling coordinating labor and logistics, integration with acid, pH, phenolic, flavor assessment ensuring comprehensive maturity beyond just Brix, and flexibility to harvest promptly when optimal parameters achieved as 3-5 day delay during rapid phase can produce 1.5-3° Brix increase substantially altering composition. ||Viticultural management during rapid elevation includes maintaining optimal conditions through irrigation supporting metabolism, canopy health ensuring continued photosynthesis, disease prevention protecting fruit during vulnerability to infection as sugars rise, avoiding environmental stresses that could disrupt rapid phase, and harvest preparation advancing as rapid elevation indicates imminent maturity. ||Comparison with other maturity indices shows Brix elevation correlates strongly with hexose accumulation (r² = 0.94-0.98) validating refractometry as sugar proxy, weaker correlation with acid decline (r² = 0.62-0.78) indicating independent though concurrent processes, moderate correlation with berry softening (r² = 0.70-0.85) as both result from ripening but through distinct mechanisms, and phenolic maturity correlation variable (r² = 0.45-0.75) particularly reds where tannin development may lag or lead sugar requiring integrated assessment. ||Regional patterns show warm regions typically experiencing briefer more intense rapid elevation 6-10 days due to accelerated metabolism, cool regions displaying more gradual elevation 12-18 days allowing extended flavor development potentially beneficial for quality, vintage variation substantial with warm years showing earlier more intense elevation while cool vintages exhibit delayed moderate elevation affecting harvest timing and final composition, and site variation within regions where warmer exposed positions undergo rapid elevation 4-8 days earlier than cooler shaded sites creating spatial heterogeneity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 224-227 rapid Brix increase || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 Brix elevation patterns || Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 rapid elevation dynamics."
},

  "Optimal_Sugar_Transport": {
  "definition": "An Optimal_Sugar_Transport is a Peak_Sugar_Accumulation involving synchronized operation of source photosynthesis, phloem translocation, invertase cleavage, membrane transport, and vacuolar sequestration producing maximum flux at minimal metabolic loss.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum transport efficiency | coordinated sugar flux | integrated hexose delivery | optimized accumulation pathway |+ maximale Transport-Effizienz | koordinierter Zucker-Fluss | integrierte Hexose-Lieferung | optimierter Akkumulations-Pfad",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Willamette Valley Pinot Noir vineyard, optimal sugar transport was characterized over 13 days in early September Year N+1 (BBCH 85) when source-to-sink efficiency calculated 79% (based on canopy photosynthesis 14.2 g CO₂ per vine per day, berry hexose accumulation 8.7 g glucose-equivalent per vine per day, respiratory losses 2.3 g), berry Brix increase 4.8% per week, hexose import 118 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, cell wall invertase 95 units/g FW, VvHT expression 128-fold, under ideal Oregon conditions (daily high 24-27°C, cool nights 13-16°C, adequate irrigation, healthy canopy).",
  "editor_note": "Optimal_Sugar_Transport is distinguished from Maximum_Sugar_Loading_Rate by emphasizing integrated efficiency (75-88% source-to-sink transfer) rather than absolute rate, from Active_Sugar_Loading by representing peak coordination rather than sustained operation, and from other transport classes by focusing on system-wide optimization rather than individual components. ||Duration 10-16 days BBCH 84-85. ||Temperature 26-30°C optimal. ||Metabolic efficiency maximized. ||Optimal_Sugar_Transport represents ideal integrated system performance determining maximum achievable sweetening efficiency. || This optimal transport occurs during peak accumulation phase (BBCH 84-85), typically days 18-30 post-veraison spanning 10-16 days, and is characterized by source-to-sink carbon transfer efficiency 75-88% (proportion of fixed CO₂ reaching berry vacuoles as hexoses) compared to active phase typical 65-80% and non-optimal conditions <60%, integrated pathway flux 110-190 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ berry accumulation representing seamless coordination from phloem delivery through vacuolar storage, metabolic losses minimized with respiratory hexose consumption 18-28% of import (optimal) compared to 25-35% typical representing efficient storage metabolism, and coordinated regulation where hormone signals, metabolite feedback, and environmental cues synchronize all pathway components optimizing total system performance rather than individual steps. ||Physiological integration at optimal includes source photosynthesis 16-30 g CO₂ fixed per vine per day producing sucrose at rates matching or exceeding sink demand preventing source limitation, phloem loading in leaves concentrating sucrose 450-750 mM in sieve tubes through active transport creating concentration gradient driving mass flow, long-distance transport through mature phloem delivering 250-450 mg sucrose per berry per day via pressure flow driven by transpiration and osmotic gradients, unloading in berry apoplast with >90% through apoplastic pathway (compared to <40% pre-veraison symplastic) enabling high flux, invertase cleavage rapid (turnover 3-8 minutes) preventing apoplastic sucrose accumulation that could feedback inhibit unloading, membrane uptake efficient with hexose transporters saturated (substrate concentrations 280-550 mM far exceeding Km 1.5-10 mM), tonoplast sequestration rapid (70-140 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹) preventing cytoplasmic accumulation maintaining gradients, and vacuolar accommodation through continued expansion (95-97% cell volume) providing capacity for massive accumulation. ||Molecular coordination at optimal involves transcriptional synchrony with sugar transport genes (VvHT family), invertase genes (VvcwINV), and regulatory factors coordinately expressed at maximum creating balanced pathway, post-transcriptional regulation ensuring mRNA stability and translation efficiency producing adequate protein levels for all components, enzyme activity coordination where invertase production matches transporter capacity preventing substrate limitation or excess, and compartmentation ensuring proper subcellular localization of transporters (plasma membrane 65-80%, tonoplast 15-30%) enabling efficient sequential uptake and sequestration. ||Hormone orchestration of optimal includes ABA 1900-3000 ng/g maintaining ripening program activation coordinating all pathway genes, sugar signaling through hexokinase pathway with glucose-6-phosphate 45-80 μmol/g FW creating feed-forward amplification enhancing transport gene expression, cross-talk between ABA and sugar signals synergistically activating transport machinery, declining growth hormones maintaining metabolic focus on storage rather than growth, and integrated signaling network ensuring coordinated response to developmental and environmental cues optimizing transport under prevailing conditions. ||Metabolic efficiency at optimal demonstrates ATP allocation optimized with 22-32% of berry ATP production supporting transport-related processes (H⁺-pumps, biosynthesis, protein turnover) compared to 28-38% non-optimal indicating efficient energy use, respiratory substrate utilization balanced between imported hexoses (20-28% respired optimal versus 25-35% typical) and concurrent organic acids providing adequate ATP without excessive sugar oxidation, carbon use efficiency 72-82% (hexose accumulated / CO₂ fixed) compared to 62-75% non-optimal representing superior conversion, and energetic coupling where ATP produced from partial substrate oxidation precisely matches transport and biosynthesis demands without excess wasteful respiration. ||Temperature optimum for transport shows narrow range 26-30°C producing highest efficiency with enzyme activities, membrane fluidity, metabolic rates all optimal, cooler temperatures 22-26°C reducing efficiency 15-30% through kinetic limitations slowing individual steps disrupting coordination, warmer temperatures 30-34°C initially enhancing but temperatures >32°C beginning impairment through enzyme denaturation and membrane perturbation, and temperature stability over optimal period important as fluctuations require metabolic readjustment potentially disrupting coordination temporarily reducing efficiency. ||Water relations supporting optimal require adequate vine water status stem water potential -0.6 to -1.2 MPa maintaining phloem turgor and transport function, moderate deficit -1.0 to -1.3 MPa potentially compatible or enhancing concentration without severely impairing flux, severe deficit <-1.5 MPa disrupting optimal through impaired phloem delivery and metabolic limitation reducing efficiency 35-65%, and irrigation timing strategically maintaining adequate hydration throughout optimal period maximizing efficiency. ||Nutritional influences on optimal show adequate nitrogen supporting enzyme synthesis with N-deficient vines showing 25-45% reduced transport capacity through translational limitation, potassium important for membrane function and pH regulation with adequate K⁺ essential for optimal transport though excess potentially problematic, phosphorus required for ATP synthesis supporting active transport with P limitation potentially impairing 20-40%, and general nutrient balance ensuring healthy vine function supporting optimal metabolism. ||Cultivar variation in achieving optimal demonstrates some varieties reliably reaching optimal efficiency under favorable conditions (Chardonnay, Merlot high-performing), others showing good but not maximum efficiency (Cabernet Sauvignon moderate), and some rarely achieving true optimal even under favorable conditions (Pinot Noir particularly warm climates) reflecting genetic differences in pathway coordination and metabolic integration. ||Environmental stability supporting optimal includes consistent moderate weather over 10-16 day period without extreme fluctuations enabling maintained coordination, adequate radiation 20-30 MJ m⁻² per day saturating photosynthesis without excess heat stress, moderate temperatures 24-30°C day and 16-22°C night providing optimal thermal regime, absence of severe weather events preventing physical damage or metabolic disruption, and pest/disease control maintaining healthy fruit capable of optimal function. ||Quality implications of optimal transport include achieving maximum final sugars within growing season through superior efficiency, balanced composition as optimal transport typically coordinates with appropriate acid decline and phenolic development, uniformity across vineyard where all zones achieve optimal producing consistent maturity enabling efficient harvest, and reduced environmental footprint as optimal efficiency maximizes yield per unit resource (water, nutrients, pesticides) invested representing sustainable production. ||Viticultural strategies promoting optimal include crop load management (0.8-1.2 kg fruit per m² leaf area) ensuring source capacity adequate supporting optimal flux, canopy management maintaining healthy productive foliage throughout optimal period, irrigation scheduling providing consistent adequate water without excess, nutritional management ensuring adequate but not excessive nutrient availability, disease/pest control preventing disruptions, and environmental monitoring identifying optimal conditions enabling harvest timing decisions capturing fruit at peak efficiency. ||Research applications include flux analysis using isotope tracers quantifying pathway efficiency, transporter activity assays measuring component capacities, transcriptomic profiling revealing coordinated gene expression, metabolomic analysis tracking pathway intermediates, and systems biology modeling integrating data predicting optimal conditions enabling precision viticulture targeting maximum efficiency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 156-162, 223-228 integrated transport || Ollat N, Gaudillère JP (1998) The effect of limiting leaf area during stage I of berry growth on development and composition of berries of Vitis vinifera L. cv. Cabernet Sauvignon Amer J Enol Vitic 49:251-258 source-sink efficiency || Patrick JW (1997) Phloem unloading:sieve element unloading and post-sieve element transport Annu Rev Plant Physiol Plant Mol Biol 48:191-222 transport integration."
},

  "Final_Sugar_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Final_Sugar_Accumulation is a Sugar_Accumulation characterized by decelerating hexose import and storage approaching cultivar-specific maximum sugar capacity during late ripening.",
  "alternative_term": "late-stage sugar import | decelerating accumulation | approaching sugar maximum | asymptotic sweetening |+ Spätphasen-Zucker-Import | dezelerierende Akkumulation | sich näherndes Zucker-Maximum | asymptotische Süßung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Bordeaux Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, final sugar accumulation was tracked over 32 days from mid-September through mid-October Year N+1 (BBCH 86-89) when berry Brix increased from 22.8° to 25.6° (2.8° gain, average 0.88% per week declining from 1.2% early to 0.6% late final phase), hexose import estimated declining from 58 to 28 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, berry fresh weight stable 1.92-1.98 g (minimal expansion), phenolic maturity achieved week 3 enabling harvest at optimal balance despite minimal continued sugar accumulation final week, under typical Bordeaux autumn conditions (daily high declining 24° to 18°C, canopy beginning senescence).",
  "editor_note": "Final_Sugar_Accumulation is distinguished from Peak_Sugar_Accumulation by showing declining rates (0.05-0.32% Brix per day progressive deceleration) rather than maximum (0.50-0.85%), from Active_Sugar_Accumulation by representing asymptotic approach (2-6° gain) rather than sustained accumulation (7-13° gain), and from Sugar_Plateau by showing continued though slowing accumulation rather than equilibrium. ||Duration 25-35 days BBCH 86-89. ||Accounts for 15-35% total ripening gain. ||Signals approaching maturity. ||Final_Sugar_Accumulation represents deceleration phase completing sugar accumulation trajectory. || This final accumulation occurs during late ripening approaching harvest (BBCH 86-89), typically days 35-65 post-veraison onset spanning 25-35 days, and is characterized by berry Brix increasing from 21-26° at phase onset to final harvest levels 23-30° representing 2-6° gain during final phase substantially less than peak accumulation 5-9° over similar duration, daily Brix increase declining progressively from 0.18-0.32% per day early final phase to 0.05-0.15% per day late phase representing 2-4 fold deceleration compared to peak rates 0.50-0.85% per day, hexose import rates declining from 50-90 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to 20-50 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ as vacuolar concentrations approach saturation, and cumulative sugar gain 80-140 g/L over final phase accounting for 15-35% of total ripening accumulation with declining marginal contribution as limits approached. ||Physiological basis for deceleration includes vacuolar hexose concentrations approaching maximum sustainable levels 1600-2400 mM combined glucose and fructose (cultivar-dependent) creating reduced concentration gradients diminishing thermodynamic driving force for continued import, osmotic potential reaching extreme values -2.8 to -3.8 MPa approaching cell tolerance limits potentially constraining further accumulation, cytoplasmic hexose potentially accumulating slightly 70-120 mM as tonoplast transport capacity saturates reducing plasma membrane uptake gradient, and phloem delivery potentially declining 20-40% as source photosynthesis decreases with advancing season and canopy senescence beginning reducing substrate availability. ||Molecular mechanisms during final phase show hexose transporter gene expression declining gradually from peak levels 100-150 fold to final 60-100 fold above green berry as ripening program begins downregulation, protein turnover potentially exceeding synthesis causing transporter density to decline 15-30% from peak reducing import capacity, post-translational modifications possibly reducing transporter activity though mechanisms in grape incompletely characterized, and potential feedback inhibition where high vacuolar hexose signals through unknown mechanisms to reduce transport gene expression or activity preventing excessive accumulation. ||Metabolic changes during final phase include increased proportion of imported hexoses respired rising from 20-30% during active phase to 30-45% during final phase as vacuolar storage becomes less favored, respiratory substrate shifting toward greater hexose contribution 45-65% of CO₂ production as organic acids deplete reducing alternative substrate availability, and energetic efficiency declining as higher proportion of import oxidized rather than stored representing less efficient carbon use but necessary for maintaining cellular ATP demands as acid catabolism wanes. ||Temporal pattern within final phase demonstrates early final (days 35-45, BBCH 86) showing moderate deceleration with Brix increase 0.15-0.28% per day and hexose import 40-75 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing transition from peak, mid-final (days 45-55, BBCH 87-88) exhibiting progressive slowing 0.08-0.18% Brix per day and 25-50 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ import as limits approached, and late final approaching harvest (days 55-65, BBCH 89) showing minimal accumulation 0.03-0.10% per day and 15-35 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ import asymptotically approaching plateau. ||Environmental influences on final accumulation include temperature effects persisting with warm conditions 26-32°C maintaining higher rates while cooler temperatures 18-24°C further reducing already declining rates potentially extending final phase duration, declining photoperiod and solar angle reducing source photosynthesis 20-40% compared to peak ripening limiting substrate availability accelerating rate decline, autumn cooling in late-ripening varieties potentially limiting accumulation through temperature effects on metabolism, water stress effects with late-season deficit potentially hastening approach to plateau through reduced berry expansion and phloem delivery, and canopy senescence particularly nitrogen-deficient vines showing earlier photosynthesis decline limiting late accumulation. ||Cultivar variation in final accumulation demonstrates high-Brix varieties maintaining higher rates longer with final phase rates 0.12-0.25% Brix per day achieving maximum 26-30° Brix, moderate cultivars showing 0.08-0.18% per day reaching 22-26° typical commercial levels, and lower-Brix types displaying 0.05-0.12% per day approaching 20-24° final levels reflecting genetic differences in maximum capacity and regulatory set-points determining when deceleration occurs and plateau achieved. ||Coordination with other late ripening processes shows acid decline continuing during final sugar accumulation maintaining 0.10-0.30 g/L TA per day loss creating developing sugar-acid balance, berry softening completed with firmness stabilized at ripe levels 0.4-1.2 N, color development in reds reaching maximum anthocyanin 600-1800 mg/kg with no further increase, flavor-aroma synthesis continuing with volatiles accumulating to final 150-750 μg/kg total creating characteristic varietal profiles, and seed maturation progressing with browning and hardening indicating physiological maturity independent of sugar levels. ||Quality implications of final accumulation include rate and duration determining final achievable Brix within growing season with early plateau potentially limiting maximum sugar in cool vintages, extended final phase enabling very high sugars >26-28° Brix beneficial for full-bodied or late-harvest styles but risking over-ripeness, coordination between final sugar accumulation and phenolic maturity particularly reds critical as tannin development may continue after sugar plateau requiring harvest timing decisions balancing parameters, and vintage variation substantial with warm years showing briefer final phase reaching plateau earlier while cool years exhibiting extended gradual accumulation potentially beneficial for flavor development. ||Harvest timing considerations during final phase recognize declining accumulation rates signal approaching maturity requiring increased monitoring frequency, target sugar achievement timing becomes more uncertain as rates slow necessitating flexibility in harvest scheduling, integration with acid levels particularly important as continued acid decline during final phase can produce unbalanced high-sugar low-acid fruit if harvest delayed excessively, phenolic and flavor assessment essential particularly reds where extended hang time during final phase may improve quality despite minimal sugar gain, and weather monitoring critical as late-season risks (rain, frost, disease) increase requiring harvest decisions balancing quality optimization against crop protection. ||Viticultural management during final phase includes maintaining canopy health supporting continued photosynthesis though senescence natural and inevitable, disease control particularly critical as high-sugar berries vulnerable to Botrytis and sour rot with infection risk increasing with autumn moisture, irrigation typically reduced or ceased allowing slight deficit potentially enhancing final concentration and triggering ripening completion, bird protection essential as peak sugar attractiveness to wildlife, and harvest logistics advancing as approaching plateau indicates imminent optimal harvest window requiring readiness. ||Physiological limits constraining final accumulation include maximum vacuolar solute concentration ~2200-2600 mM approaching saturation beyond which further accumulation thermodynamically unfavorable or physically impossible, cell wall and membrane mechanical limits at extreme osmotic potentials <-3.5 to -4.0 MPa potentially compromising integrity, metabolic feedback regulation where high sugar signals ripening completion downregulating transport machinery, and declining source capacity as photosynthesis wanes with advancing season fundamentally limiting substrate availability regardless of sink capacity. ||Research applications include transporter downregulation studies revealing molecular control of accumulation cessation, osmotic potential measurements characterizing thermodynamic limits, flux analysis quantifying changing import-respiration partitioning, and modeling approaches predicting plateau timing enabling harvest optimization based on accumulation trajectory analysis.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 226-228 final accumulation || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 deceleration phase || Matthews MA, Anderson MM (1988) Fruit ripening in Vitis vinifera L.:responses to seasonal water deficits Amer J Enol Vitic 39:313-320 late ripening dynamics."
},

  "Late_Stage_Sugar_Import": {
  "definition": "A Late_Stage_Sugar_Import is a Final_Sugar_Accumulation marked by progressively reduced hexose uptake flux from declining concentration gradients, reduced transporter expression, and approaching vacuolar saturation.",
  "alternative_term": "declining hexose uptake | diminishing sugar import | reduced import flux | downregulated sugar transport |+ abnehmende Hexose-Aufnahme | vermindernder Zucker-Import | reduzierter Import-Fluss | herunterregulierter Zucker-Transport",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Shiraz vineyard, late-stage sugar import was quantified over 26 days in late February through March Year N+1 (BBCH 87-89) when calculated hexose import declined from 62 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (early late-stage) to 32 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (final), VvHT1 expression decreased from 95-fold to 68-fold, berry Brix increased from 24.2° to 26.8° (2.6° gain decelerating), vacuolar hexose reached 2180 mM combined approaching cultivar maximum, under warm Australian late-summer conditions (daily high declining 32° to 26°C as autumn approached, canopy beginning senescence reducing source capacity).",
  "editor_note": "Late_Stage_Sugar_Import is distinguished from peak import by showing declining flux (18-85 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ progressive reduction) rather than maximum (100-180 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹), from active import by representing deceleration rather than sustained rates, and from cessation by showing continued though diminishing uptake rather than complete stop. ||Duration 22-30 days BBCH 86-89. ||Transporter expression declining 25-45% from peak. ||Thermodynamic and kinetic limitations. ||Late_Stage_Sugar_Import represents progressive import reduction approaching sugar equilibrium. || This late-stage import occurs during final accumulation period (BBCH 86-89), typically days 38-62 post-veraison spanning 22-30 days, and is characterized by plasma membrane hexose uptake declining progressively from early late-stage 45-85 μmol combined glucose and fructose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to final 18-45 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ representing 2-3 fold reduction compared to peak import 100-180 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, transporter gene expression declining from late-stage onset 70-110 fold above green berry to final 50-85 fold indicating downregulation of ripening program, vacuolar hexose concentrations approaching maximum 1700-2500 mM combined creating reduced thermodynamic driving force for continued uptake, and apoplastic-to-vacuolar concentration gradient declining from 15-30:1 (apoplastic 280-550 mM, vacuolar 500-900 mM peak accumulation) to 6-15:1 (apoplastic potentially declining 180-350 mM, vacuolar 1600-2400 mM late stage) reducing facilitated diffusion driving force. ||Molecular mechanisms limiting late-stage import include hexose transporter gene transcription declining 25-45% from peak levels as ripening program downregulates indicated by VvHT1, VvHT2 expression decreasing though remaining elevated above green berry baseline, mRNA stability potentially decreasing with shorter half-lives 5-9 hours versus 8-14 hours peak requiring higher transcription rates to maintain steady-state but transcription declining creating net reduction, protein synthesis rates declining 30-50% from peak as general translation slows with ripening maturation, transporter protein turnover potentially accelerating through ubiquitin-proteasome degradation removing older proteins faster than synthesis replaces causing density decline 20-40% from peak, and potential post-translational modifications (phosphorylation, ubiquitination) reducing activity or targeting degradation though modifications in grape transporters incompletely characterized. ||Kinetic limitations during late-stage import demonstrate cytoplasmic hexose concentrations potentially rising 75-125 mM (from 60-100 mM peak) as tonoplast transport saturates or vacuolar back-diffusion increases reducing plasma membrane concentration gradient and thus uptake rate even if transporter capacity unchanged, vacuolar hexose 1650-2450 mM approaching saturation reducing tonoplast gradient from vacuole-to-cytoplasm potentially causing slight back-flux 5-15 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ opposing continued uptake, and net import flux (plasma membrane uptake minus tonoplast back-flux minus respiratory consumption) declining to 15-40 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ net vacuolar accumulation representing 20-40% of peak net flux. ||Thermodynamic constraints include osmotic potential reaching -2.9 to -3.9 MPa (from -2.4 to -3.2 MPa peak) approaching cell tolerance limits potentially triggering regulatory mechanisms preventing further accumulation, water potential berry -2.5 to -3.5 MPa creating only small gradient versus vine xylem -0.8 to -1.5 MPa limiting water import that previously drove berry expansion enabling dilution-free sugar accumulation, turgor pressure declining to 0.2-0.4 MPa (from 0.3-0.6 MPa peak) as osmotic potential increases faster than water import can compensate potentially affecting membrane transport energetics, and approaching thermodynamic equilibrium between apoplastic and vacuolar hexose concentrations accounting for membrane potential and proton gradients reducing maximum achievable gradient limiting import capacity. ||Substrate availability effects show phloem sucrose delivery potentially declining 30-50% from peak 250-450 mg per berry per day to late-stage 150-280 mg per berry per day as source photosynthesis decreases with canopy senescence and declining photoperiod, apoplastic hexose concentrations potentially declining 35-50% from peak 280-550 mM to late-stage 180-350 mM as invertase substrate (sucrose) reduces, and reduced substrate availability limiting maximum possible uptake independent of transporter capacity creating substrate limitation rather than kinetic limitation particularly late final phase. ||Metabolic partitioning changes during late-stage import include increased proportion of imported hexoses entering respiratory pathways rising from 20-30% peak to 35-50% late-stage as vacuolar storage becomes thermodynamically less favored and cellular ATP demands persist, reduced net storage efficiency where each μmol hexose imported yields only 0.50-0.65 μmol vacuolar accumulation (late-stage) versus 0.65-0.80 μmol (peak) due to increased respiratory losses, and metabolic feedback where high cytoplasmic hexose potentially inhibits further uptake through hexokinase-mediated signaling creating negative feedback loop limiting excessive accumulation. ||Environmental modulation of late-stage import shows temperature continuing to affect rates with cooler autumn conditions 18-24°C further reducing already declining import 25-40% versus optimal 26-30°C, declining solar radiation and photoperiod reducing source photosynthesis 30-50% compared to mid-summer limiting substrate delivery independent of sink capacity, water deficit effects complex with moderate deficit potentially enhancing concentration but severe deficit impairing phloem delivery reducing import 30-60%, and canopy health with vigorous healthy vines maintaining higher late-stage import longer while stressed or nutrient-deficient vines showing earlier more severe import decline. ||Cultivar differences in late-stage import demonstrate high-Brix varieties maintaining higher absolute rates 35-70 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ late-stage enabling final 26-30° Brix achievement, moderate cultivars showing 25-55 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ reaching typical 22-26° levels, and lower-Brix types displaying 18-40 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ achieving 20-24° final reflecting genetic differences in transporter regulation, maximum vacuolar capacity, and metabolic set-points determining when import effectively ceases. ||Coordination with other processes shows late-stage sugar import declining while acid catabolism continues creating shifting sugar-acid balance, berry water import minimal or ceasing with size stabilization typical late ripening, and flavor-aroma synthesis continuing independently with volatiles accumulating despite declining sugar import indicating decoupled ripening processes. ||Quality implications include late-stage import rate determining final achievable Brix with early cessation potentially limiting maximum sugar problematic for high-alcohol styles, extended import enabling very high final sugars beneficial for some styles but requiring careful harvest timing avoiding over-ripeness, and import decline signaling approaching physiological maturity useful for harvest timing decisions. ||Viticultural factors affecting late-stage import include canopy management maintaining photosynthesis though senescence inevitable, irrigation typically minimal or ceased late season potentially beneficial for concentration but excessive deficit impairing phloem function reducing import, and nutritional status with adequate nitrogen supporting continued enzyme synthesis maintaining import longer while deficient vines showing earlier decline. ||Research methods quantifying late-stage import include flux studies using isotope tracers measuring declining uptake rates, gene expression analysis tracking transporter downregulation, enzyme activity assays revealing capacity changes, and metabolomic profiling characterizing compartment-specific hexose dynamics revealing kinetic and thermodynamic limitations.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Hayes MA, Davies C, Dry IB (2007) Isolation, functional characterization, and expression analysis of grapevine hexose transporters J Exp Bot 58:1985-1997 transporter regulation || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 226-228 late import || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 late-stage dynamics."
},

  "Approaching_Sugar_Maximum": {
  "definition": "An Approaching_Sugar_Maximum is a Final_Sugar_Accumulation characterized by asymptotic Brix trajectory toward cultivar-specific peak sweetness with gradually declining accumulation rate.",
  "alternative_term": "asymptotic sweetening | nearing maximum Brix | final approach to sugar capacity | decelerating toward equilibrium |+ asymptotische Süßung | sich näherndes Maximum-Brix | End-Annäherung zu Zucker-Kapazität | Dezeleration Richtung Gleichgewicht",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Mosel Riesling vineyard, approaching sugar maximum was modeled over 18 days in late September-October Year N+1 (BBCH 88-89) when berry Brix increased from 23.8° to 26.2° following exponential decay Brix(t) = 27.1 - 3.3×exp(-t/11.5) with fitted maximum Brix_max = 27.1° and time constant 11.5 days (r² = 0.94), half-time 8 days, daily increment declining from 0.18% to 0.05% per day, enabling harvest forecast of plateau achievement within 14 days (actual 12 days excellent agreement), under cool German autumn conditions (daily high 16-20°C extending gradual approach).",
  "editor_note": "Approaching_Sugar_Maximum is distinguished from Final_Sugar_Accumulation by focusing on asymptotic trajectory (exponential decay model) rather than overall late phase, from Sugar_Plateau by showing continued though minimal accumulation (<0.5-1.5° remaining) rather than equilibrium, and from peak accumulation by exhibiting clear deceleration (0.03-0.22% per day declining) rather than maximum rates. ||Duration 12-20 days BBCH 87-89. ||Time constant τ typically 8-18 days. ||Thermodynamic barriers approaching. ||Approaching_Sugar_Maximum represents measurable asymptotic approach enabling harvest timing prediction. || This approaching phase occurs during late-to-final ripening (BBCH 87-89), typically days 45-60 post-veraison spanning 12-20 days, and is characterized by berry Brix rising from 23-27° at approach onset to near-maximum 25-30° at conclusion representing 1.5-4.0° gain substantially reduced from earlier phases, daily Brix increase declining from 0.12-0.22% per day early approach to 0.03-0.08% per day late approach showing clear deceleration, asymptotic curve fitting showing r² >0.90-0.96 for exponential decay model Brix(t) = Brix_max - (Brix_max - Brix_0) × exp(-k×t) with rate constant k determining approach velocity, and time constant τ = 1/k typically 8-18 days indicating characteristic timescale for approaching 63% of remaining distance to maximum. ||Mathematical characterization of approach includes instantaneous accumulation rate dBrix/dt declining approximately linearly with distance from maximum (Brix_max - Brix_current) consistent with first-order kinetics, half-time to maximum (time to achieve 50% of remaining gain) typically 5-12 days from approach onset indicating rapid initial approach then slowing, 90% approach time (achieving 90% of final maximum) requiring 15-25 days demonstrating asymptotic nature where final increments require extended duration, and residual accumulation potential (Brix_max - Brix_current) declining from 3-6° approach onset to <0.5-1.5° late approach indicating most gain achieved early in approaching phase. ||Physiological basis for asymptotic approach includes vacuolar hexose concentrations 1750-2450 mM approaching saturation levels 2000-2600 mM cultivar-dependent creating increasingly unfavorable thermodynamics for continued accumulation, concentration gradients (apoplast-to-vacuole) declining progressively as vacuolar levels rise reducing driving force according to Fick's law where flux proportional to gradient, transporter capacity potentially declining but more importantly operating at progressively lower efficiency as substrate gradients reduce even if protein levels maintained, and metabolic equilibrium approaching where import rate equals respiratory consumption rate plus any export or interconversion with net vacuolar accumulation approaching zero. ||Thermodynamic analysis shows free energy change for hexose transport from apoplast (280-400 mM, pH 5.5-6.5) to vacuole (1800-2500 mM, pH 2.8-3.2) including membrane potential (-120 to -180 mV cytoplasm-negative) and pH gradient (4.5-5.0 units vacuole-acidic) calculating ΔG approaching zero or slightly positive late approach indicating thermodynamic barrier limiting further accumulation, osmotic work required for continued accumulation against concentration gradient increasing exponentially with vacuolar concentration following ΔG = RT ln(C_vacuole/C_apoplast) approaching or exceeding available cellular energy, and maximum achievable concentration gradient determined by coupling stoichiometry with H⁺-ATPase (ATP hydrolysis provides ~50 kJ/mol driving force enabling ~1000-fold gradient theoretically but practical limits lower due to inefficiencies). ||Molecular regulation during approach demonstrates transporter gene expression declining gradually VvHT1, VvHT2 from 80-120 fold to 55-90 fold above baseline as ripening program downregulates though levels remain substantial, protein degradation potentially accelerating with increasing ubiquitination targeting older transporters for proteasomal removal, post-translational modifications possibly reducing activity through phosphorylation at inhibitory sites or conformational changes reducing substrate affinity though mechanisms speculative in grape, and cellular signaling potentially detecting high vacuolar sugar triggering feedback inhibition through hexokinase-independent sensors in tonoplast or cytoplasm reducing transport gene expression or activity. ||Environmental factors affecting approach velocity include temperature with warmer conditions 26-30°C maintaining higher rates accelerating approach (shorter time constant) while cooler 18-24°C extending approach duration, declining source photosynthesis with autumn progression reducing substrate availability accelerating approach to plateau independent of thermodynamic limits as supply rather than demand becomes limiting, water status with late-season deficit potentially hastening approach through reduced phloem delivery and berry expansion while adequate water extending gradual approach, and canopy health with vigorous vines maintaining photosynthesis supporting slower asymptotic approach while senescent canopies forcing rapid approach as substrate depletes. ||Cultivar variation in approach characteristics shows high-Brix varieties (Gewürztraminer, Sémillon approaching 27-30° maximum) displaying extended gradual approach 16-24 days with time constant τ = 12-18 days indicating slow final accumulation continuing, moderate cultivars (Chardonnay, Merlot approaching 23-27° maximum) showing intermediate approach 12-18 days with τ = 8-14 days, and lower-Brix types (Pinot Noir cool climate approaching 21-25° maximum) exhibiting rapid approach 8-14 days with τ = 5-10 days reflecting genetic differences in maximum capacity and regulatory control determining approach kinetics. ||Predictive modeling using approach dynamics enables extrapolation from current trajectory fitting exponential decay model to estimate Brix_max and time to plateau within ±0.5-1.5° Brix and ±3-7 days accuracy, recognition that asymptotic approach means final 10% of accumulation requires 50-80% of total approach time informing harvest timing decisions, and understanding that factors disrupting approach (weather events, disease, stress) may prevent achieving theoretical maximum requiring harvest at current levels rather than waiting for completion. ||Quality implications include maximum sugar level determining wine alcohol potential with each 1° Brix yielding ~0.55-0.60% ethanol, approach timing relative to phenolic and flavor maturity affecting optimal harvest particularly reds where extended hang time during slow approach may improve quality despite minimal sugar gain, and recognition that asymptotic approach creates extended harvest window during late approach phase where 0.5-1.5° Brix difference over 7-14 days allows flexibility for integrating multiple maturity parameters. ||Harvest strategies during approach include monitoring approach trajectory through frequent sampling enabling maximum prediction and optimal timing determination, integrating sugar approach with acid plateau recognizing both processes asymptotic and coordinated, phenolic assessment particularly reds ensuring tannin maturity achieved during approach period, sensory evaluation detecting flavor development potentially continuing during slow sugar approach, and weather monitoring balancing quality optimization during extended approach against late-season risks (rain, disease, frost). ||Viticultural considerations include minimal intervention during approach as process physiologically determined and environmental manipulation limited effectiveness, disease control critical as high-sugar berries during extended approach vulnerable to infection, harvest preparation advancing as approach signals imminent maturity, and recognition that approach completion (plateau achievement) may occur on-vine or post-harvest during transport/processing with minimal practical difference if harvest timing appropriate.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 asymptotic approach || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 227-228 approaching maximum || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 approach dynamics and modeling."
},

  "Declining_Accumulation_Rate": {
  "definition": "A Declining_Accumulation_Rate is a Final_Sugar_Accumulation marked by progressive reduction in daily and weekly sugar gain velocity during the transition from active accumulation toward plateau.",
  "alternative_term": "decelerating sugar gain | slowing Brix increase | reducing accumulation velocity | progressive rate reduction |+ dezelerierende Zucker-Zunahme | verlangsamende Brix-Zunahme | reduzierende Akkumulations-Geschwindigkeit | progressive Raten-Reduktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Chianti Classico Sangiovese vineyard, declining accumulation rate was quantified over 28 days in September-October Year N+1 (BBCH 86-89) when weekly Brix measurements showed progressive decline: Week 1:1.8° gain (0.26% per day), Week 2:1.4° (0.20% per day), Week 3:0.9° (0.13% per day), Week 4:0.5° (0.07% per day), demonstrating consistent 22-36% week-over-week reduction, exponential fit dBrix/dt = 0.082 × (26.2 - Brix_current) predicting Brix_max 26.2° (actual harvest 25.8°), enabling harvest decision when rate <0.10% per day threshold achieved week 4, under typical Tuscan autumn conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Declining_Accumulation_Rate is distinguished from constant rates by showing negative second derivative d²Brix/dt² <0, from approaching maximum by focusing on rate measurement rather than distance-to-maximum, and from plateau by representing progressive decline rather than cessation. ||Quantitative metric: 0.25-0.40% → <0.05-0.12% Brix per day over 25-35 days. ||Week-over-week reduction typically 15-35%. ||Duration BBCH 86-89. ||Predictive value for harvest timing. ||Declining_Accumulation_Rate represents measurable kinetic deceleration enabling objective maturity assessment. || This declining rate occurs throughout final accumulation period (BBCH 86-89), typically days 35-65 post-veraison spanning entire late ripening 25-35 days, and is characterized by daily Brix increase declining continuously from early final 0.25-0.40% per day to late final <0.05-0.12% per day representing 3-6 fold reduction over phase, weekly Brix gain decreasing from 1.8-2.8° per week to <0.35-0.85° per week showing clear trajectory toward cessation, sequential measurements showing negative second derivative d²Brix/dt² < 0 confirming deceleration rather than constant or accelerating rates, and rate constant k in exponential model dBrix/dt = k × (Brix_max - Brix_current) estimated 0.055-0.125 day⁻¹ from curve fitting indicating characteristic decay timescale. ||Quantitative characteristics of rate decline include percentage reduction week-over-week typically 15-35% per week showing consistent proportional decrease, absolute reduction in weekly gain declining 0.3-0.8° Brix per week sequentially from peak to final, correlation between current Brix and accumulation rate showing strong negative relationship (r² = 0.82-0.94) where higher current Brix predicts lower future rate consistent with approaching saturation, and threshold detection where rates <0.10% per day or <0.7° per week generally indicate approaching plateau within 1-2 weeks useful for harvest timing. ||Physiological basis for rate decline includes declining concentration gradients as vacuolar hexose rises from 1200-1700 mM early final to 1800-2500 mM late final reducing thermodynamic driving force proportionally, transporter downregulation with gene expression declining 20-40% over final phase reducing import capacity, substrate limitation as phloem delivery decreases 30-50% with canopy senescence and declining photoperiod limiting supply independent of demand, and increasing respiratory consumption proportion rising from 25-35% to 35-50% of import reducing net accumulation efficiency amplifying rate decline beyond import reduction alone. ||Kinetic analysis demonstrates hexose import flux declining from 55-95 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ early final to 20-45 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ late final correlating with Brix rate decline, net vacuolar accumulation (import minus respiration minus other metabolism) declining 2.5-4.0 fold from 40-70 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ to 12-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ directly determining Brix increase rate, and Michaelis-Menten-like saturation kinetics where accumulation rate = Vmax × (Brix_max - Brix_current) / (Km + (Brix_max - Brix_current)) with Km ~2-4° Brix indicating half-saturation occurs when 2-4° below maximum. ||Temporal pattern within declining phase shows early deceleration (days 35-45, BBCH 86) with rates declining from 0.30-0.45% to 0.18-0.30% Brix per day representing initial slowdown, mid-deceleration (days 45-55, BBCH 87-88) exhibiting further reduction to 0.10-0.20% per day approaching threshold, and late deceleration (days 55-65, BBCH 89) showing minimal rates <0.05-0.12% per day indicating imminent plateau with some cultivars achieving complete cessation while others maintain minimal ongoing accumulation. ||Environmental modulation of decline trajectory includes temperature affecting both absolute rates and decline slope with warm conditions maintaining higher rates longer then declining more abruptly while cool conditions showing lower rates throughout with more gradual decline, declining solar radiation through autumn reducing source photosynthesis accelerating rate decline independent of berry capacity, water deficit potentially accelerating decline through reduced phloem delivery and metabolic impairment, and disease or environmental stress disrupting normal trajectory potentially causing premature plateau or irregular decline pattern. ||Cultivar genetic differences demonstrate high-Brix varieties maintaining higher absolute rates longer with decline from 0.35-0.50% to 0.08-0.15% Brix per day over 25-30 days, moderate cultivars showing decline from 0.25-0.40% to 0.05-0.12% over 22-28 days, and lower-Brix types displaying decline from 0.18-0.30% to 0.03-0.08% over 18-25 days reflecting variation in maximum capacity and regulatory set-points governing decline kinetics. ||Predictive value of rate decline includes linear extrapolation of declining rates enabling harvest date estimation with accuracy improving as plateau approached and trajectory stabilized, recognition that non-linear decline common requiring exponential or polynomial fitting for accurate prediction, threshold-based forecasting where detecting rates <0.10% per day triggers 7-14 day harvest window prediction, and integration with other maturity indicators improving forecast reliability beyond sugar alone. ||Quality implications include rate decline trajectory revealing ripening health with smooth gradual decline indicating normal physiology while erratic or premature plateau suggesting stress or dysfunction, coordination between sugar rate decline and continuing acid catabolism affecting final balance with excessive acid loss during extended sugar plateau potentially problematic, and rate decline providing objective quantitative metric for harvest decisions supplementing subjective assessments. ||Harvest timing strategies using rate decline involve establishing target minimum accumulation rate (typically 0.08-0.15% per day) below which harvest initiated, monitoring week-over-week rate reduction detecting accelerating decline signaling approaching plateau, integrating rate decline with absolute Brix achieving both minimum sweetness and declining trajectory ensuring near-maximum sugar, and flexibility recognizing that environmental factors may disrupt ideal trajectory requiring adaptive decisions. ||Monitoring techniques include frequent Brix sampling 2-3 times per week during late ripening enabling accurate rate calculation, statistical analysis calculating moving average rates reducing measurement noise improving trend detection, derivative analysis computing d²Brix/dt² confirming negative second derivative diagnostic of decline, and curve fitting to exponential or polynomial models enabling extrapolation and maximum Brix estimation. ||Viticultural management considerations recognize rate decline as physiologically determined and largely unresponsive to intervention, disease control maintaining berry health preventing disruption of normal decline trajectory, irrigation management typically minimal late season allowing natural ripening completion, and harvest logistics coordination with predicted plateau timing based on rate decline analysis ensuring readiness when optimal maturity achieved. ||Research applications include mathematical modeling of rate decline revealing underlying mechanisms and constraints, comparative studies across cultivars and environments identifying genetic and environmental controls, and predictive algorithm development enabling precision viticulture decision support systems optimizing harvest timing based on quantitative accumulation kinetics.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Coombe BG, McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics and environmental control of grape berry growth Australian J Grape Wine Res 6:73-83 rate decline dynamics || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 227-228 accumulation kinetics || Dai ZW, Ollat N, Gomès E, Decroocq S, Tandonnet JP, Bordenave L, Pieri P, Hilbert G, Kappel C, van Leeuwen C, Vivin P, Delrot S (2011) Ecophysiological, genetic, and molecular causes of variation in grape berry weight and composition Plant Physiol 155:519-532 quantitative rate analysis."
},

  "Sugar_Plateau": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Plateau is a Final_Sugar_Accumulation characterized by berry hexose concentration stabilized at cultivar-specific maximum with minimal or no net accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "sugar equilibrium | maximum sweetness achieved | Brix stabilization | accumulation cessation |+ Zucker-Gleichgewicht | maximale Süße erreicht | Brix-Stabilisierung | Akkumulations-Beendigung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Napa Cabernet Sauvignon vineyard, sugar plateau was confirmed over 19 days in late September-October Year N+1 (BBCH 89) when weekly Brix measurements showed stability: 25.2°, 25.4°, 25.6°, 25.3° (mean 25.4° ± 0.2°, CV 0.8%), vacuolar hexose 2150 mM combined, hexose import estimated 24 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ balanced by respiration 22 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹, enabling harvest timing optimization for phenolic maturity (achieved week 2) without concern for sugar loss, under warm Napa autumn conditions maintaining equilibrium without degradation.",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Plateau is distinguished from Approaching_Sugar_Maximum by showing achieved equilibrium (Brix variation <±0.3-0.8° over 7-14 days) rather than continuing approach, from declining rates by exhibiting effectively zero accumulation (dBrix/dt ≈ 0) rather than deceleration, and from sugar accumulation by representing cessation rather than ongoing process. ||Duration variable 7-21+ days BBCH 88-89. ||Cultivar maximum: high-Brix 26-30°, moderate 22-26°, lower 20-24°. ||Thermodynamic and regulatory equilibrium. ||Sugar_Plateau represents terminal equilibrium state defining physiological maturity ceiling for sweetness. || This plateau state occurs during late-to-harvest ripening (BBCH 88-89), typically days 55-75 post-veraison though timing highly variable, and is characterized by berry Brix stabilizing within narrow range ±0.3-0.8° over 7-14 day measurement period indicating effective cessation of net accumulation, daily Brix changes <0.03-0.06% representing measurement variability rather than true accumulation, vacuolar hexose concentrations 1900-2600 mM combined glucose and fructose (cultivar-dependent maximum) showing minimal variation <3-8% over plateau period, and hexose import flux approximately balanced by respiratory consumption plus any export creating steady-state where dBrix/dt ≈ 0 though instantaneous rates may fluctuate. ||Physiological basis of plateau includes vacuolar solute saturation approaching maximum sustainable concentration ~2000-2600 mM beyond which further accumulation thermodynamically unfavorable or physically impossible due to solubility limits, osmotic potential stabilized at extreme values -3.0 to -4.0 MPa near cellular tolerance limits preventing further concentration increases, concentration gradients (apoplast-to-vacuole) minimized to <5-10:1 (from 15-30:1 peak accumulation) providing insufficient driving force for significant net transport, transporter expression and activity downregulated to maintenance levels 50-80 fold above green berry (from peak 100-150 fold) adequate for replacing respiratory losses but insufficient for net accumulation, and metabolic equilibrium where import rate 18-35 μmol hexose g⁻¹ h⁻¹ approximately equals respiratory consumption 15-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ plus minor metabolic interconversions creating zero net vacuolar accumulation. ||Molecular mechanisms maintaining plateau include transporter gene expression stabilized at reduced steady-state with transcription rate balancing mRNA degradation, protein synthesis matching degradation maintaining constant transporter density though reduced from peak levels, lack of strong regulatory signals (ABA declining from peak 2000-3200 ng/g to plateau 1200-2000 ng/g, sugar signaling feedback potentially suppressing further induction), and cellular homeostatic mechanisms detecting high vacuolar sugar potentially triggering active suppression of transport machinery through unknown sensors and signaling pathways. ||Thermodynamic analysis at plateau shows free energy change for hexose transport ΔG ≈ 0 or slightly positive indicating thermodynamic equilibrium where forward transport (apoplast→vacuole) energetically unfavorable without coupling to ATP hydrolysis, maximum achievable gradient limited by H⁺-ATPase capacity with realistic coupling stoichiometry (1-2 H⁺ per hexose transported) and ATP availability constraining gradient to ~500-1500:1 theoretical maximum but practical plateau gradients only 5-10:1 suggesting additional kinetic or regulatory limitations beyond pure thermodynamics, and osmotic work calculation showing energy required for further accumulation W = RT × Δ(ln C) exceeding available cellular energy budget from concurrent metabolism. ||Metabolic steady-state characteristics include hexose import continuing at low rate 18-35 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ maintaining substrate for respiration, respiratory consumption 15-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ utilizing both imported hexoses and vacuolar reserves with dynamic exchange, potential minor export or interconversion 3-8 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ for biosynthesis (flavor compounds, cell wall precursors, secondary metabolites), and net accumulation <2-5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ effectively zero within measurement precision representing true equilibrium rather than kinetic slowdown. ||Environmental effects on plateau include temperature affecting absolute concentration achieved with warm conditions producing plateau at higher Brix 24-28° versus cool 20-24° through effects on accumulation kinetics during approach, water availability influencing concentration versus dilution with deficit potentially enhancing final Brix through reduced berry expansion while adequate water maintaining size with slightly lower concentration, source photosynthesis decline with canopy senescence potentially lowering plateau level if substrate depletion forces premature cessation before thermodynamic maximum achieved, and seasonal progression with late harvest potentially showing slight Brix decline 0.3-0.8° as berry water balance changes or degradation processes exceed minimal import. ||Cultivar genetic variation demonstrates high-Brix varieties achieving plateau 26-30° Brix corresponding to vacuolar hexose 2200-2600 mM near apparent saturation limits, moderate cultivars plateauing 22-26° Brix with 1800-2200 mM vacuolar concentrations, and lower-Brix types stabilizing 20-24° Brix at 1600-2000 mM reflecting genetic differences in maximum transporter capacity, vacuolar properties, and regulatory set-points determining when accumulation ceases. ||Temporal stability during plateau shows measurements over 7-21 days typically varying <±0.4° Brix (coefficient of variation <2-3%) indicating true equilibrium, occasional slight increases 0.2-0.5° over 7-10 days potentially representing measurement variability, temperature effects, or minor true accumulation, and rare decreases suggesting berry dehydration, degradation, or disease affecting measurement accuracy. ||Quality implications of plateau include maximum achievable sugar determining wine alcohol potential with cultivar and conditions setting ceiling independent of extended hang time, plateau achievement indicating physiological maturity useful for harvest timing though other parameters (phenolics, flavor, acid) may lag requiring integrated assessment, and plateau Brix serving as baseline for late-harvest or raisin production where further concentration requires dehydration rather than active accumulation. ||Harvest timing considerations at plateau recognize continued hang time beyond plateau achievement produces minimal sugar gain but may improve other quality parameters particularly phenolic and flavor maturity in reds, extended plateau period (2-4 weeks) creating flexible harvest window allowing optimization for non-sugar factors, weather risks increasing with extended hang time requiring balance between quality optimization and crop protection, and economic considerations where labor and winery capacity may necessitate harvest at plateau even if extended maturation potentially beneficial. ||Viticultural management during plateau includes minimal intervention as berry composition stable, disease control critical as high-sugar berries vulnerable during extended plateau, irrigation typically ceased allowing natural ripening completion and potentially slight concentration through dehydration, bird protection essential as peak sugar attractiveness maintained, and harvest logistics coordination recognizing plateau provides flexible timing within 2-4 week window. ||Exceptions to stable plateau include certain cultivars or conditions showing continued minimal accumulation 0.05-0.10% per day even at apparent plateau, disease or stress disrupting equilibrium causing decline, dehydration through transpiration or environmental stress concentrating sugars producing apparent Brix increase without net hexose accumulation, and measurement artifacts from temperature effects or sampling variability creating apparent fluctuation. ||Research applications include thermodynamic studies characterizing equilibrium conditions and limits, regulatory mechanism investigations revealing signals controlling plateau achievement, comparative analyses across genotypes identifying genetic determinants of maximum capacity, and modeling approaches predicting plateau timing and level enabling harvest optimization strategies for quality and alcohol management.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 plateau characteristics || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 227-228 sugar equilibrium || Ollat N, Gaudillère JP (1998) The effect of limiting leaf area during stage I of berry growth on development and composition of berries of Vitis vinifera L. cv. Cabernet Sauvignon Amer J Enol Vitic 49:251-258 plateau and equilibrium."
},

  "Sugar_Equilibrium": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Equilibrium is a Sugar_Plateau marked by hexose import flux balanced precisely against respiratory consumption, metabolic interconversion, and potential export with zero net vacuolar accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "hexose steady-state | sugar homeostasis | accumulation-consumption balance | dynamic equilibrium |+ Hexose-Gleichgewichtszustand | Zucker-Homöostase | Akkumulations-Konsum-Balance | dynamisches Gleichgewicht",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc vineyard, sugar equilibrium was characterized over 16 days in late March-April Year N+1 (BBCH 89) using isotope tracer studies when ¹³C-glucose uptake 26 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ measured but vacuolar concentration stable 1880 mM indicating equal efflux or respiration balancing import, berry Brix constant 22.6° ± 0.3° over measurement period, respiratory consumption calculated 23 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ from O₂ uptake, net vacuolar accumulation <1.5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ confirming equilibrium, under cool New Zealand autumn conditions (daily high 16-19°C maintaining stable metabolism).",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Equilibrium is distinguished from Sugar_Plateau by emphasizing dynamic steady-state (import = consumption + export) rather than static maximum, from Maximum_Sugar_Content by focusing on equilibrium process rather than achieved level, and from accumulation by representing zero net change (dC/dt ≈ 0) rather than positive flux. ||Vacuolar hexose 1900-2600 mM cultivar maximum. ||Import 18-35 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ balanced by consumption. ||Thermodynamic and kinetic equilibrium. ||Duration 2-6+ weeks potentially. ||Sugar_Equilibrium represents dynamic steady-state defining biochemical maturity endpoint. || This equilibrium state occurs during plateau period (BBCH 88-89), typically days 58-80 post-veraison though highly variable, and is characterized by vacuolar hexose concentrations constant 1900-2600 mM combined glucose and fructose (cultivar maximum) with fluctuations <±2-5% representing measurement variability and true equilibrium oscillation, plasma membrane hexose import 18-35 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ continuing to supply cellular metabolism, respiratory hexose consumption 15-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ utilizing imported plus vacuolar reserves maintaining energy production, and net change in vacuolar content dC/dt = (Import - Respiration - Export - Interconversion) ≈ 0 ± 1-3 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ within precision of measurement techniques. ||Thermodynamic equilibrium characteristics include electrochemical potential for hexose transport μ_hexose = μ°_hexose + RT ln([hexose]) equal across plasma membrane (apoplast ⇌ cytoplasm) and tonoplast (cytoplasm ⇌ vacuole) within energy available from coupled ion gradients, free energy change ΔG for hexose transport approaching zero ΔG = ΔG° + RT ln(C_product/C_substrate) + zFΔψ where electrochemical driving force balanced by concentration opposition, chemical potential gradient balanced by electrical potential gradient creating equilibrium distribution determined by coupling stoichiometry with H⁺ symport, and osmotic equilibrium where vacuolar osmotic potential -3.0 to -4.0 MPa balanced by turgor pressure 0.2-0.4 MPa plus apoplastic water potential creating stable cell volume without net water movement. ||Kinetic equilibrium properties demonstrate forward hexose transport rate (apoplast→cytoplasm→vacuole) approximately equal to reverse processes (vacuolar efflux, export, interconversion) creating bidirectional flux with zero net accumulation, transporter-mediated uptake Vforward = Vmax_forward × [hexose]_apoplast / (Km + [hexose]_apoplast) balanced by facilitated diffusion back-flux Vreverse = Vmax_reverse × [hexose]_vacuole / (Km + [hexose]_vacuole) where concentration-dependent rates equilibrate, and metabolic sink strength (respiration, biosynthesis) determining equilibrium concentration by consuming imported hexose maintaining gradient enabling continued import despite vacuolar saturation. ||Molecular basis of equilibrium includes transporter protein levels stabilized with synthesis matching degradation maintaining constant density 6-10% plasma membrane (from peak 10-16%), gene expression steady-state with transcription rate balancing mRNA decay yielding constant transcript levels 55-85 fold above baseline (from peak 100-150 fold), regulatory feedback where high vacuolar hexose potentially suppressing further transporter induction through hexokinase-independent sensors creating negative feedback maintaining equilibrium, and hormone signaling with ABA declining from ripening peak 2000-3200 ng/g to equilibrium 1200-2000 ng/g reducing ripening program activation while maintaining basal transporter expression. ||Metabolic flux at equilibrium shows hexose import 18-35 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ partitioned among respiratory consumption 15-30 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (50-85% of import), biosynthetic uses 3-8 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (8-20%) for flavor compounds, cell wall precursors, secondary metabolites, and potential export or interconversion 1-5 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ (3-12%) with net vacuolar accumulation <1-3 μmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ effectively zero, isotope tracer studies showing labeled hexose rapidly entering vacuole but equal unlabeled efflux creating dynamic exchange with constant total concentration, and respiratory quotient 1.05-1.25 indicating mixed substrate oxidation with hexoses contributing 50-75% and remaining acids 25-50% as malate depletes. ||Compartmental analysis reveals apoplastic hexose 180-350 mM (glucose 90-180 mM, fructose 90-170 mM) maintained by invertase activity balanced by cellular uptake, cytoplasmic hexose 70-120 mM steady through balance of plasma membrane import and tonoplast export plus metabolism, vacuolar hexose 1900-2600 mM (950-1300 mM each glucose and fructose approximately equimolar) representing storage pool at equilibrium maximum, and concentration ratios vacuole:cytoplasm:apoplast approximately 18:1:3 typical at equilibrium reflecting transporter distributions and energetics. ||Environmental perturbations to equilibrium include temperature changes causing transient disequilibrium with warmer temperatures increasing respiration potentially depleting vacuolar reserves slightly while cooler reducing metabolism allowing minor accumulation, water stress affecting cell volume and thus concentration with dehydration concentrating vacuolar hexose producing apparent Brix increase without net accumulation, substrate availability changes from declining source photosynthesis potentially reducing apoplastic hexose lowering equilibrium slightly as import cannot be maintained, and disease or stress disrupting normal metabolism potentially causing degradation exceeding import creating net loss and equilibrium decline. ||Recovery from perturbation demonstrates resilience with system returning to equilibrium within 2-5 days following transient temperature or water change, regulatory mechanisms adjusting import and respiration rates compensating for disturbances, and robust homeostasis maintaining constant vacuolar concentration despite environmental variability within normal range. ||Cultivar differences in equilibrium characteristics show high-Brix varieties achieving equilibrium at 2200-2600 mM vacuolar hexose corresponding to 26-30° Brix reflecting genetic maximum capacity, moderate cultivars equilibrating at 1800-2200 mM and 22-26° Brix, and lower types at 1600-2000 mM and 20-24° Brix, with equilibrium concentration likely determined by maximum transporter expression capacity, vacuolar properties (size, membrane area, pH regulation), and metabolic set-points governing downregulation triggers. ||Temporal stability shows equilibrium maintained for extended periods 2-6 weeks or longer if harvest delayed with berries remaining at constant composition, occasional slow drift toward slightly lower Brix 0.3-0.8° over 3-4 weeks potentially indicating senescence processes beginning to dominate over minimal import, and remarkable stability despite environmental fluctuation demonstrating robust homeostatic regulation maintaining maturity composition. ||Quality implications include equilibrium Brix defining maximum achievable alcohol potential for given cultivar and conditions, equilibrium representing physiological maturity ceiling where extended hang time produces minimal sugar change but may improve phenolics and flavor particularly reds, and equilibrium stability providing flexible harvest window 2-4 weeks where sugar composition constant enabling optimization of other parameters. ||Harvest timing at equilibrium recognizes sugar composition stable providing flexibility, other maturity indicators (acid, phenolics, flavor, seed color) potentially continuing to evolve during equilibrium requiring integrated assessment, weather and disease risks increasing with extended hang time requiring balance between quality optimization and crop protection, and economic factors (labor, winery capacity) often determining actual harvest timing within biologically suitable window. ||Viticultural management during equilibrium includes minimal intervention as composition stable, disease control essential preventing infections disrupting equilibrium, irrigation ceased allowing natural water balance potentially slight concentration, and monitoring other maturity parameters guiding final harvest decision beyond sugar alone. ||Research applications include thermodynamic studies characterizing equilibrium conditions and free energy changes, flux analysis using isotopes quantifying bidirectional exchange rates, regulatory mechanism investigations revealing signals maintaining homeostasis, and modeling approaches describing equilibrium as emergent property of integrated transport, metabolism, and regulatory networks enabling prediction and optimization.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 227-228 equilibrium state || Fondy BR, Geiger DR (1982) Diurnal pattern of translocation and carbohydrate metabolism in source leaves of Beta vulgaris L. Plant Physiol 70:671-676 equilibrium concepts applicable to grape || Walker RP, Famiani F (2018) Organic acids in fruits:metabolism, functions and contents Hort Rev 45:371-430 metabolic equilibrium in fruits."
},

  "Maximum_Sugar_Content": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Sugar_Content is a Sugar_Equilibrium characterized by cultivar-specific peak hexose concentration at the upper limit of berry sweetness attainable through active accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "peak berry sweetness | maximum Brix achievement | cultivar sugar ceiling | hexose concentration maximum |+ Spitzen-Beeren-Süße | maximale Brix-Erreichung | Kultivar-Zucker-Obergrenze | Hexose-Konzentrations-Maximum",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Barossa Valley Shiraz vineyard, maximum sugar content was achieved in late February Year N+1 (BBCH 89, 62 days post-veraison) when berry Brix stabilized 27.2° ± 0.4° over 18 days (plateau confirmed), total sugars 280 g/L (HPLC:glucose 142 g/L, fructose 138 g/L, ratio 1.03:1), vacuolar hexose estimated 2350 mM combined, osmotic potential -3.7 MPa, producing wine alcohol potential 15.0% (actual 14.6% post-fermentation), under hot Australian conditions (cumulative 1240 degree-days veraison-harvest) enabling high maximum typical for warm-climate Shiraz.",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Sugar_Content is distinguished from Sugar_Plateau by representing achieved concentration level (20-30° Brix cultivar-dependent) rather than equilibrium process, from Sugar_Equilibrium by focusing on content measurement rather than flux balance, and from approaching maximum by showing achieved ceiling rather than trajectory. ||Vacuolar hexose: high-Brix 2200-2600 mM, moderate 1800-2200 mM, lower 1600-2000 mM. ||Osmotic potential -3.0 to -4.2 MPa. ||Determines wine alcohol potential. ||Maximum_Sugar_Content represents cultivar-specific peak sweetness defining harvest maturity and quality potential. || This maximum content is typically achieved during late ripening plateau (BBCH 88-89), and is characterized by total berry sugars reaching cultivar-specific ceiling 180-310 g/L glucose-plus-fructose (corresponding to 20-30° Brix refractive index measurement depending on variety and conditions), vacuolar hexose concentrations at maximum sustainable levels 1600-2600 mM combined (800-1300 mM each glucose and fructose approximately equimolar ratio 0.95-1.05:1), refractive index stabilized at cultivar maximum corresponding to Brix 20-30° with high-Brix varieties achieving 26-30°, moderate cultivars 22-26°, and lower types 20-24°, and osmotic potential at extreme values -3.0 to -4.2 MPa representing near-cellular tolerance limits preventing further concentration increases. ||Biochemical composition at maximum includes glucose typically 90-155 g/L (8-14% w/v, 500-860 mM), fructose similarly 90-155 g/L (500-860 mM), combined hexoses 180-310 g/L (1000-1720 mM total, though vacuolar concentration higher 1600-2600 mM due to compartmentation), residual sucrose minimal <2-8 g/L as invertase activity maintains efficient cleavage, organic acids declined to final 4-10 g/L contributing minor proportion of total soluble solids compared to hexoses 85-95%, amino acids, phenolics, minerals collectively 8-18 g/L contributing remaining Brix measurement, and water content 72-82% fresh weight basis with solutes occupying 18-28% of berry mass. ||Molecular determinants of maximum include genetic regulation of hexose transporter expression with maximum induction levels determining import capacity ceiling, vacuolar properties (size, membrane area, pH regulation, osmotic tolerance) constraining maximum achievable concentration, metabolic capacity for maintaining cellular homeostasis at extreme osmotic potentials limiting how concentrated vacuole can become before cellular dysfunction, and regulatory set-points determining when downregulation triggered preventing excessive accumulation beyond safe physiological limits. ||Physiological limits constraining maximum demonstrate solubility limit for combined hexoses in aqueous solution approximately 2800-3200 mM (50-55% w/v) at berry temperature 15-30°C providing absolute physical ceiling well above biological maximum indicating other factors limiting, osmotic stress tolerance with most plant cells unable to maintain function at water potentials below -4.0 to -4.5 MPa setting practical limit, membrane integrity and function compromised at extreme osmotic potentials affecting transport, signaling, and cellular organization, and metabolic dysfunction if sugar concentrations interfere with enzyme activities or cellular processes constraining maximum to levels compatible with continued metabolism. ||Thermodynamic constraints include maximum achievable concentration gradient limited by coupling to available energy sources with H⁺-ATPase-driven symport theoretically enabling ~1000-fold gradients but practical limits much lower due to inefficiencies, equilibrium distribution determined by electrochemical potentials across membranes with maximum vacuolar concentration reflecting balance of transport energetics and osmotic back-pressure, and energy cost of maintaining extreme gradients requiring substantial ATP investment potentially limiting how high concentrations can rise before energetic costs exceed cellular capacity. ||Environmental effects on maximum achievable include temperature during ripening with warmer conditions 26-32°C generally enabling higher maximum 24-28° Brix versus cooler 18-24°C producing 20-24° Brix through effects on accumulation kinetics and duration, water availability affecting concentration versus dilution with deficit potentially enhancing maximum through reduced berry expansion 5-15% Brix increase while adequate water maintaining size with slightly lower concentration, solar radiation and canopy microclimate influencing berry temperature and source photosynthesis affecting both accumulation rate and final maximum achieved, and vintage variation substantial with warm years producing 2-5° Brix higher maximum than cool years for given cultivar reflecting cumulative environmental effects on accumulation trajectory. ||Cultivar genetic variation demonstrates remarkable range with high-Brix varieties: Gewürztraminer 27-30° maximum (2200-2600 mM vacuolar, 240-310 g/L total sugars), Sémillon 24-28° (2000-2400 mM, 210-280 g/L), Muscat 24-27° (2000-2300 mM, 210-270 g/L) || moderate cultivars: Chardonnay 22-26° (1800-2200 mM, 190-260 g/L), Cabernet Sauvignon 22-26° (1800-2200 mM, 190-260 g/L), Merlot 23-26° (1900-2200 mM, 200-260 g/L) || and lower-Brix types: Pinot Noir cool climates 20-24° (1600-2000 mM, 180-220 g/L), table grapes 18-22° (1400-1800 mM, 160-200 g/L) reflecting genetic differences in transporter capacity, ripening duration, and regulatory programming determining maximum. ||Wine quality implications include maximum sugar directly determining potential alcohol with conversion efficiency ~0.55-0.60% ethanol per 1° Brix yielding: 20° Brix → 11-12% alcohol, 24° Brix → 13.2-14.4% alcohol, 28° Brix → 15.4-16.8% alcohol affecting wine style, body, and stability, sugar-acid balance at maximum with typical ratios 25-35:1 (Brix:TA g/L) for quality wines requiring appropriate acid levels 5-8 g/L, residual sugar potential for off-dry or sweet styles depending on fermentation management with incomplete fermentation leaving 5-50+ g/L residual creating sweetness perception, and phenolic extraction during fermentation affected by alcohol level with higher sugar producing higher alcohol enhancing phenolic solubility particularly important reds. ||Harvest timing considerations include maximum sugar achievement indicating physiological maturity ceiling for sweetness, recognition that maximum may occur days-to-weeks before optimal phenolic or flavor maturity particularly reds requiring integrated assessment, flexibility in harvest timing during plateau period where maximum stable 2-4 weeks enabling optimization for non-sugar parameters, and economic factors where high-sugar grapes command premium prices in some markets incentivizing maximum achievement while other markets favor moderate sugars requiring earlier harvest. ||Viticultural strategies targeting maximum include cultivar selection matching genetic potential to climate and goals, crop load management with appropriate yields 6-12 kg per vine enabling adequate source capacity supporting maximum accumulation, canopy management maintaining healthy productive foliage throughout ripening, irrigation management with adequate water supporting metabolism while moderate deficit potentially enhancing concentration, disease control preserving berry health enabling normal ripening to maximum, and harvest timing flexibility capitalizing on plateau stability optimizing quality parameters beyond sugar alone. ||Measurement and verification of maximum employs refractometry measuring Brix providing standard industry metric, density measurement (pycnometry) determining specific gravity correlating with sugar concentration, HPLC analysis quantifying glucose and fructose separately confirming total hexose levels, osmometry directly measuring osmotic potential verifying extreme values characteristic of maximum, and sensory evaluation detecting sweetness intensity providing qualitative confirmation of high sugar levels. ||Exceptions and special cases include botrytized grapes (noble rot) achieving higher apparent Brix through dehydration rather than active accumulation potentially exceeding 30-40° through water loss concentrating sugars, late-harvest wines targeting very high sugars 28-35° requiring extended hang time plus potentially dehydration, ice wine production freezing grapes concentrating sugars in unfrozen portion potentially achieving 35-45° Brix, and raisin production completely desiccating berries achieving 55-70° Brix through extreme dehydration representing physical concentration not active accumulation. ||Research applications include genetic studies identifying QTLs and genes controlling maximum sugar capacity, physiological investigations characterizing limits and constraints, environmental manipulation studies optimizing conditions for maximum achievement, and breeding programs targeting specific sugar levels for different wine styles and markets ranging from moderate-alcohol table wines to high-alcohol full-bodied or dessert styles.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 227-228, 251-253 maximum sugar and quality || Boulton RB, Singleton VL, Bisson LF, Kunkee RE (1996) Principles and Practices of Winemaking pages 28-35 sugar content and fermentation || Conde C, Silva P, Fontes N, Dias ACP, Tavares RM, Sousa MJ, Agasse A, Delrot S, Gerós H (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development and fruit and wine quality Food Res Internat 40:1012-1018 maximum sugar and composition."
},

  "Brix_Stabilization": {
  "definition": "A Brix_Stabilization is a Sugar_Plateau exhibiting constant refractometric soluble solids readings within analytical precision providing the operative criterion for harvest maturity assessment.",
  "alternative_term": "plateau Brix | constant soluble solids | stable refractive index | maturity Brix achievement |+ Plateau-Brix | konstante lösliche Feststoffe | stabiler Brechungsindex | Reife-Brix-Erreichung",
  "example_of_usage": "In a Willamette Valley Pinot Noir vineyard, Brix stabilization was confirmed over 16 days in late September Year N+1 (BBCH 89) when twice-weekly refractometer measurements showed: 22.8°, 23.2°, 22.6°, 23.0°, 23.4°, 22.9° (mean 23.0° ± 0.3°, CV 1.3%), linear regression slope -0.008° per day (p = 0.62, not significant), confirming stability enabling harvest timing optimization for phenolic maturity (achieved day 12) and weather window (rain forecast day 18), under cool Oregon conditions maintaining stable plateau without degradation.",
  "editor_note": "Brix_Stabilization is distinguished from declining accumulation by showing constant measurement (variation <±0.3-0.6°, slope ≈ 0) rather than deceleration, from sugar equilibrium by representing refractometric observation rather than biochemical process, and from maximum content by focusing on stability detection rather than absolute level. ||Statistical criterion: CV <2-3%, p >0.05 for temporal trend. ||Duration typically 10-30 days plateau. ||Practical harvest timing indicator. ||Brix_Stabilization represents observable maturity signal enabling harvest optimization. || This stabilization occurs during plateau period (BBCH 88-89), typically days 55-75 post-veraison through harvest, and is characterized by sequential Brix measurements showing variation <±0.3-0.6° over 7-14 day period with coefficient of variation <2-3% indicating stability rather than continued accumulation or decline, daily Brix changes <0.03-0.05% representing measurement noise and true biological variability rather than directional trend, linear regression of Brix versus time showing slope not significantly different from zero (p >0.05) confirming no systematic change, and refractive index stabilized at final value 1.3330-1.3430 (20°C reference) corresponding to Brix 20-30° depending on cultivar and conditions. ||Measurement methodology for confirming stabilization includes refractometer sampling 2-3 times per week during late ripening detecting plateau onset, statistical analysis calculating mean and standard deviation over measurement period with SD <0.3° typically indicating stability, temporal trend analysis using linear or polynomial regression testing for significant slope with p-value threshold 0.05 determining stability versus continued change, and comparison with historical data for cultivar and site establishing expected plateau Brix enabling recognition when stabilization achieved. ||Biological basis of stabilization includes underlying sugar equilibrium with import balancing consumption creating constant vacuolar content reflected in stable Brix measurement, water balance stabilization with berry expansion ceased and transpiration balanced by minor import maintaining constant fresh weight and thus constant concentration, solute composition reaching final proportions with hexoses, acids, phenolics, minerals all at mature levels producing constant refractive index, and metabolic homeostasis where all ripening processes completed or continuing at maintenance rates without directional compositional changes. ||Refractometric principles relevant to stabilization demonstrate refractive index n = (speed of light in vacuum) / (speed of light in medium) affected by all dissolved solutes with sugars contributing 85-95% of measured Brix at maturity, Brix scale calibrated for pure sucrose solutions approximating grape juice but imperfectly as glucose, fructose, and other solutes have different refractive indices, temperature dependence requiring standardization to 20°C with correction factor ~0.00025 per °C deviation, and measurement precision typically ±0.1-0.2° Brix for quality refractometers with sample preparation (crushing, filtering) and technique (temperature control, calibration) critical for accuracy. ||Temporal characteristics of stabilization show transition from declining accumulation rates 0.08-0.15% Brix per day to stabilization <0.03% per day occurring over 5-10 day period, plateau duration typically 10-30 days before harvest though potentially extending 30-60 days if harvest delayed, and occasional slight drift toward lower Brix 0.2-0.5° over 3-4 weeks potentially indicating senescence or dehydration though often within measurement variability. ||Environmental factors affecting stabilization include temperature stability with consistent conditions maintaining stable Brix while fluctuations may cause apparent variability through differential effects on berry water balance, water availability with adequate irrigation maintaining constant berry hydration and thus Brix stability while deficit may concentrate sugars through dehydration producing apparent increase, rainfall potentially diluting berry content causing Brix decrease though typically minor <0.5-1.5° for moderate precipitation, and disease or stress disrupting stability through metabolic perturbation, degradation, or water balance changes. ||Cultivar differences in stabilization characteristics show some varieties achieving very stable plateau with Brix variation <±0.2° over 2-4 weeks (Chardonnay, Merlot), others showing more variability ±0.4-0.8° potentially reflecting subtle ongoing processes or measurement challenges (Pinot Noir particularly heterogeneous clusters), and high-Brix varieties often showing stable elevated plateau 26-30° while lower-Brix types plateau 20-24° with similar relative stability. ||Practical viticulture applications include Brix stabilization as key harvest timing indicator signaling physiological maturity achieved, combination with other parameters (pH, TA, phenolics, flavor, seed color) providing integrated maturity assessment, flexible harvest window during stable plateau enabling optimization for quality factors beyond sugar, and documentation through sampling records demonstrating maturity for quality control and regulatory compliance. ||Quality assurance uses stabilization confirmation through multiple measurements over time verifying true plateau versus transient pause in accumulation, spatial sampling across vineyard zones ensuring uniform stabilization or identifying heterogeneity requiring selective harvest, comparison with target Brix for intended wine style confirming appropriate level achieved (table wines 20-24°, fuller styles 22-26°, high-alcohol or late-harvest 24-30°+), and integration with contract specifications or winery requirements ensuring delivered fruit meets sugar criteria. ||Challenges and considerations include measurement variability from sampling (different berries, cluster positions, canopy zones), temperature effects requiring consistent sample handling and measurement conditions, timing of sampling with diurnal variation potentially affecting measurements taken at different times of day, and distinguishing true stability from transient plateau during deceleration phase requiring extended monitoring period confirming sustained stability. ||Harvest logistics planning uses stabilization detection triggering harvest preparation 1-2 weeks advance, coordination with other vineyard blocks and winery capacity scheduling based on maturity timing, weather monitoring balancing quality optimization during stable plateau against harvest risks (rain, disease, wildlife), and flexibility to adjust timing within stable window based on developing conditions or market factors. ||Economic implications include achievement of target Brix commanding premium prices in some markets particularly minimum thresholds for appellations or quality designations, high-Brix grapes potentially receiving bonuses for high-alcohol wine production, moderate-Brix grapes preferred for balanced lower-alcohol styles increasingly popular, and documentation of Brix stabilization supporting claims of optimal harvest timing and quality. ||Research applications include statistical methods for detecting stabilization objectively using time-series analysis and trend detection, modeling approaches predicting stabilization timing based on accumulation trajectory and environmental conditions, comparative studies across cultivars and environments identifying factors controlling plateau Brix and stability, and sensor technology development enabling continuous automated monitoring detecting stabilization without manual sampling.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry Amer J Enol Vitic 43:101-110 Brix plateau || Iland P, Bruer N, Edwards G, Weeks S, Wilkes E (2004) Chemical Analysis of Grapes and Wine:Techniques and Concepts Wine Promotions Adelaide pages 22-28 Brix measurement and interpretation || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pages 227-228 stabilization and harvest timing."
},

  "Acid_Reduction": {
  "definition": "An Acid_Reduction is a Ripening proceeding through respiratory consumption, enzymatic degradation, and dilution producing reduction of total organic acid content from 15–25 g/L at pre-véraison to 5–9 g/L at harvest, extending over 35–50 days post-véraison.",
  "alternative_term": "organic acid decline | berry acid decrease | ripening acid reduction | titratable acidity decline |+ Säure-Reduktion | organische Säure-Abnahme | Beeren-Säure-Abnahme | Reife-Säure-Reduktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay berries in Carneros, California during BBCH 85-89, acid reduction proceeds from 18.5 g/L titratable acidity at veraison to 6.2 g/L at harvest over 42 days, with malic acid declining from 9.8 to 2.1 g/L while tartaric acid remains stable at 5.5-5.8 g/L, resulting in pH increase from 2.95 to 3.45 under mean ripening temperatures of 22°C.",
  "editor_note": "Acid_Reduction is the parent class for all acid-related ripening processes under Ripening hierarchy. ||Distinguishes from Acid_Decline_Onset under Veraison which represents initial acid changes. ||Duration 35-50 days post-veraison. ||Subdivides into Active_Acid_Reduction, Malic_Acid_Degradation, Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization, and Final_Acid_Balance representing temporal progression and mechanistic pathways. ||Critical parameter is total titratable acidity decline from 15-25 to 5-9 g/L. || This process primarily involves the catabolism of L-malic acid, which decreases by 50-90% during ripening through mitochondrial respiration and gluconeogenic pathways, while L-tartaric acid remains relatively stable due to the absence of significant degradation pathways in grape berries, resulting in a shift in the malate-to-tartrate ratio from approximately 1.5-2.0 at veraison to 0.3-0.8 at maturity. ||The cellular mechanisms underlying acid reduction involve the activity of cytosolic and mitochondrial NADP-malic enzyme converting malate to pyruvate, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase facilitating gluconeogenesis from organic acids, and direct respiratory oxidation of malate through the tricarboxylic acid cycle, with these pathways collectively consuming 60-80% of the malate present at veraison. ||Temperature exerts profound influence on acid reduction rates, with warm conditions of 30-35°C accelerating malate degradation by 2-3 fold compared to cool conditions of 15-20°C, explaining the characteristically higher acidity retention in cool-climate viticulture regions such as Champagne, Burgundy, and the Mosel Valley compared to warm Mediterranean or continental climates. ||The process demonstrates significant cultivar variation, with varieties such as Riesling and Chenin Blanc exhibiting naturally high acid retention due to lower malic enzyme activity, while varieties such as Merlot and Grenache show rapid acid decline under warm conditions. ||Berry size and crop load influence acid reduction through dilution effects during the secondary growth phase, with larger berries typically showing greater apparent acid reduction due to volume increases of 50-100% between veraison and harvest. ||The vacuolar compartmentalization of organic acids, particularly the sequestration of tartaric acid in specialized idioblast cells, contributes to differential acid metabolism during ripening. ||Acid reduction directly impacts wine quality parameters including pH stability, microbial safety, aging potential, and sensory balance between sweetness and tartness. ||Viticultural practices such as leaf removal, irrigation management, and harvest timing are employed to modulate acid reduction rates and achieve desired sugar-acid balance at harvest. ||Research methodologies for monitoring acid reduction include titratable acidity measurements, HPLC quantification of individual organic acids, pH monitoring, and non-destructive spectroscopic techniques enabling real-time assessment of berry acid status throughout ripening.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006108 ## malate metabolic process | 0.80" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 265-280 || Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280 || Conde C et al (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development. Food Chemistry 1: 1-22"
},

  "Active_Acid_Reduction": {
  "definition": "An Active_Acid_Reduction is an Acid_Reduction realized through enzymatic degradation and respiratory consumption decreasing malic acid at 0.2–0.5 g/L per day, extending from 10–15 days post-véraison until 7–14 days pre-harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "dynamic acid catabolism | enzymatic acid decline | active malic acid consumption | ongoing acid reduction |+ aktive Säure-Reduktion | dynamischer Säure-Katabolismus | enzymatische Säure-Abnahme | aktiver Äpfelsäure-Abbau",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir berries in Willamette Valley, Oregon during BBCH 85-87, active acid reduction proceeds at 0.32 g/L per day over 25 days from day 12 to day 37 post-veraison, reducing titratable acidity from 14.2 to 6.2 g/L with malic acid declining from 7.8 to 2.6 g/L under mean temperatures of 19°C, while a late-season heat event of 35°C for 5 days accelerates reduction rate to 0.55 g/L per day.",
  "editor_note": "Active_Acid_Reduction is parent class under Acid_Reduction representing the dynamic enzymatic phase. ||Distinguishes from Final_Acid_Balance which represents equilibrium state. ||Duration 20-35 days during mid-to-late ripening. ||Contains subclasses Continuing_Acid_Decline, Malate_Degradation, and pH_Increase representing concurrent aspects of active reduction. ||Rate parameter 0.2-0.5 g/L per day distinguishes active from plateau phases. || This process encompasses the coordinated activity of multiple metabolic pathways including mitochondrial respiration of malate through the tricarboxylic acid cycle, cytosolic NADP-malic enzyme conversion of malate to pyruvate with CO2 release, and gluconeogenic recycling of malate carbon skeletons into hexose sugars, collectively accounting for the consumption of 4-8 g/L malic acid during the active reduction period spanning 20-35 days. ||The cellular biochemistry involves malate transport from vacuolar storage across the tonoplast membrane via specific malate channels, followed by cytosolic metabolism or mitochondrial import through the dicarboxylate carrier, with respiratory flux rates increasing 3-5 fold during active reduction compared to pre-veraison levels. ||Temperature sensitivity characterizes active acid reduction, with Q10 values of 2.0-2.5 indicating that enzymatic reaction rates approximately double for each 10°C temperature increase within the physiological range of 15-35°C, explaining accelerated acid loss during heat waves and the pronounced diurnal variation in malate metabolism linked to day-night temperature differentials. ||The process shows strong cultivar specificity, with high-acid varieties such as Riesling maintaining active reduction rates of 0.15-0.25 g/L per day compared to rapid-decline varieties such as Grenache showing rates of 0.4-0.6 g/L per day under equivalent thermal conditions. ||Hormonal regulation involves abscisic acid enhancement of malic enzyme gene expression and auxin modulation of vacuolar malate efflux, integrating acid reduction with broader ripening coordination. ||Berry position within the cluster influences active reduction rates through differential temperature exposure and vascular connection strength, with exposed exterior berries typically showing 15-25% faster acid decline than shaded interior berries. ||The process contributes substantially to berry carbon balance during ripening, with malate-derived carbon representing 5-10% of total respiratory substrate and contributing to the metabolic energy requirements of sugar accumulation and secondary metabolite synthesis. ||Monitoring active acid reduction through weekly titratable acidity measurements enables prediction of harvest acid levels and optimal picking decisions balancing sugar accumulation against acid retention for specific wine styles.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 268-275 || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis. Vitis 21: 346-358 || Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280"
},

  "Continuing_Acid_Decline": {
  "definition": "A Continuing_Acid_Decline is an Acid_Reduction defined by sustained day-over-day titratable acidity decreases of 0.1–0.3 g/L extending consistently over 25–40 days from early post-véraison through harvest approach.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained acid decrease | persistent acidity decline | ongoing titratable acidity reduction | continuous acid loss |+ fortlaufende Säure-Abnahme | anhaltender Säure-Rückgang | kontinuierliche Aciditäts-Reduktion | persistente Säure-Abnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sangiovese berries in Chianti Classico, Tuscany during BBCH 85-89, continuing acid decline proceeds consistently over 38 days from veraison to harvest, with titratable acidity decreasing from 16.8 to 5.9 g/L following a logarithmic decay curve with daily reductions averaging 0.29 g/L during weeks 1-3 and 0.12 g/L during weeks 4-5, correlating with 485 growing degree days accumulated above 10°C base temperature.",
  "editor_note": "Continuing_Acid_Decline is subclass of Active_Acid_Reduction representing temporal persistence of acid loss. ||Distinguishes from discrete events by emphasizing sustained nature. ||Duration 25-40 days spanning active ripening. ||Sibling to Malate_Degradation and pH_Increase which represent mechanistic and chemical aspects respectively. ||Key characteristic is consistent day-over-day negative acid balance throughout active ripening period. || This process reflects the cumulative effect of ongoing malate catabolism through respiratory and enzymatic pathways, maintaining negative acid balance as consumption rates exceed any residual biosynthetic activity, resulting in monotonic decline curves when titratable acidity is plotted against thermal time accumulation during ripening. ||The biochemical basis involves continuous flux of vacuolar malate through cytosolic and mitochondrial metabolic pathways, with steady-state enzyme activities of NADP-malic enzyme, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase, and mitochondrial malate dehydrogenase maintaining catabolism rates that collectively deplete 0.2-0.4 g/L malic acid equivalent per day throughout the active ripening window. ||Temperature integration determines the rate of continuing decline, with growing degree day accumulation correlating strongly with cumulative acid loss, enabling predictive modeling of harvest acidity based on thermal time calculations using base temperatures of 10°C and accumulated heat units of 300-500°C-days during the active reduction period. ||The process demonstrates asymptotic behavior as acid levels approach equilibrium values, with decline rates progressively decreasing from initial values of 0.4-0.5 g/L per day during early active reduction to 0.05-0.15 g/L per day as harvest approaches and substrate availability becomes limiting. ||Cultivar genetics influence the persistence of continuing decline, with varieties possessing high initial malic acid content such as Barbera and Sangiovese showing extended active decline periods of 35-45 days compared to low-acid varieties such as Viognier showing shorter periods of 20-28 days before reaching equilibrium. ||Diurnal patterns superimpose on the overall declining trend, with nighttime acid accumulation partially offsetting daytime respiratory losses, though net daily balance remains consistently negative throughout active ripening. ||Canopy management practices including leaf removal and shoot positioning influence continuing decline rates through modification of berry temperature exposure and resultant enzymatic activity levels. ||The consistency of continuing acid decline enables viticultural planning for harvest timing, with predictive equations incorporating initial acidity, temperature forecasts, and variety-specific decline coefficients achieving accuracy of plus-minus 0.5 g/L for harvest acidity prediction.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 270-275 || Coombe BG and McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics of grape berry growth and physiology of ripening. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 6: 131-135"
},

  "Malate_Degradation": {
  "definition": "A Malate_Degradation is an Acid_Reduction involving cytosolic NADP-malic enzyme, mitochondrial NAD-malic enzyme, and TCA cycle oxidation producing 60–90% reduction of L-malic acid from 8–15 g/L at véraison to 1–4 g/L at harvest over 30–45 days.",
  "alternative_term": "malic acid catabolism | malate breakdown | malic acid degradation | enzymatic malate consumption |+ Malat-Abbau | Äpfelsäure-Katabolismus | Äpfelsäure-Abbau | enzymatischer Malat-Abbau",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot berries in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux during BBCH 85-89, malate degradation reduces malic acid content from 11.2 g/L at veraison to 2.8 g/L at harvest over 40 days, representing 75% degradation with NADP-malic enzyme activity peaking at 2.8 µmol/min/g fresh weight at 20 days post-veraison under mean ripening temperatures of 24°C, while parallel tartaric acid levels remain stable at 5.2-5.5 g/L.",
  "editor_note": "Malate_Degradation is subclass of Active_Acid_Reduction representing the specific biochemical process of malic acid catabolism. ||Distinguishes from pH_Increase which is chemical consequence and from Continuing_Acid_Decline which describes temporal pattern. ||Parent to Malate_Respiratory_Consumption, Malic_Enzyme_Activity, and Progressive_Malate_Depletion under separate Malic_Acid_Degradation branch. ||Duration 30-45 days. ||Key parameter is 60-90% malic acid reduction. || This process represents the primary mechanism of acid reduction in grape berries, with malic acid serving as the predominant organic acid subject to metabolic turnover due to the presence of efficient degradation pathways absent for tartaric acid, fundamentally altering the organic acid profile from malate-dominated to tartrate-dominated composition during ripening progression. ||The cellular biochemistry initiates with malate efflux from vacuolar storage through ALMT-family aluminum-activated malate transporter channels and voltage-dependent anion channels, delivering substrate to cytosolic and mitochondrial enzyme systems, with vacuolar malate pools of 200-400 mM progressively depleted over the ripening period. ||Cytosolic NADP-malic enzyme catalyzes oxidative decarboxylation of malate to pyruvate with CO2 release and NADPH generation, representing the quantitatively dominant degradation pathway accounting for 50-70% of total malate catabolism, with enzyme activity increasing 3-5 fold between veraison and mid-ripening in response to developmental and hormonal signals. ||Mitochondrial metabolism contributes through NAD-malic enzyme and direct oxidation via malate dehydrogenase and the TCA cycle, generating ATP for cellular energy requirements while releasing malate-derived carbon as respiratory CO2. ||The gluconeogenic pathway diverts malate carbon toward hexose synthesis through phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase, contributing 10-20% of berry sugar accumulation from organic acid precursors and linking acid degradation to sugar metabolism. ||Temperature profoundly regulates malate degradation rates, with warm conditions of 30-35°C accelerating enzymatic activities and respiratory flux 2-3 fold compared to cool conditions of 15-20°C, establishing climate as the primary environmental determinant of final berry acidity. ||Cultivar variation in malate degradation reflects genetic differences in malic enzyme expression levels and activity, with high-acid varieties maintaining lower enzyme activities and correspondingly slower degradation rates throughout ripening.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry and other developing fruits. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280 || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis. Vitis 21: 346-358 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 268-272"
},

  "pH_Increase": {
  "definition": "A pH_Increase is an Acid_Reduction manifesting as elevation of berry juice pH from 2.6–3.0 at pre-véraison to 3.2–3.8 at harvest as a chemical consequence of malic acid catabolism.",
  "alternative_term": "juice pH elevation | acidity pH rise | ripening pH increase | hydrogen ion decrease |+ pH-Anstieg | Saft-pH-Erhöhung | Reife-pH-Zunahme | Aciditäts-pH-Anstieg",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon berries in Napa Valley, California during BBCH 85-89, pH increase proceeds from 2.88 at veraison to 3.62 at harvest over 45 days, with the 0.74 unit rise correlating with malic acid decline from 9.5 to 2.2 g/L and potassium increase from 22 to 38 mM, while titratable acidity decreases from 14.8 to 5.6 g/L, demonstrating the chemical linkage between acid catabolism and pH elevation.",
  "editor_note": "pH_Increase is subclass of Active_Acid_Reduction representing chemical consequence of acid catabolism. ||Distinguishes from Malate_Degradation which is biochemical cause and from Continuing_Acid_Decline which describes temporal pattern. ||Not subdivided further. ||Duration parallels active acid reduction at 25-40 days. ||Key parameter is pH rise of 0.4-0.8 units from 2.6-3.0 to 3.2-3.8. ||Important wine quality determinant. || This process reflects the fundamental relationship between organic acid concentration and hydrogen ion activity in the complex buffer system of grape juice, where the removal of malic acid molecules through enzymatic degradation eliminates both the undissociated acid and its conjugate base from the equilibrium, shifting pH upward according to Henderson-Hasselbalch relationships governing weak acid dissociation. ||The magnitude of pH increase during ripening typically spans 0.4-0.8 pH units, with the rate and extent determined by initial acid composition, degree of malic acid degradation, potassium accumulation affecting tartrate precipitation, and cultivar-specific organic acid profiles. ||Malic acid with pKa values of 3.40 and 5.11 contributes more strongly to juice acidity per gram than tartaric acid with pKa values of 2.98 and 4.34, meaning that malic acid degradation produces proportionally greater pH increase than equivalent tartaric acid removal, explaining the strong correlation between malate catabolism and pH elevation during ripening. ||Potassium accumulation during ripening, increasing from 15-25 to 25-40 mM, further elevates pH through formation of insoluble potassium bitartrate which precipitates tartaric acid from solution and reduces total tartrate contribution to acidity. ||Temperature influences pH increase indirectly through effects on malic acid degradation rates, with warm-climate berries typically achieving pH values 0.2-0.4 units higher than cool-climate equivalents due to accelerated malate catabolism. ||The viticultural significance of pH increase encompasses wine stability, color expression in red wines where higher pH shifts anthocyanin equilibria toward less colored forms, microbial stability with elevated pH increasing spoilage risk, and sulfur dioxide efficacy which decreases substantially above pH 3.5. ||Monitoring pH progression through ripening enables harvest timing decisions optimizing the balance between sugar accumulation and acid retention for specific wine style objectives.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 272-278 || Conde C et al (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development and ripening. Food Chemistry 1: 1-22 || Coombe BG (1987) Influence of temperature on composition and quality of grapes. Acta Horticulturae 206: 23-35"
},

  "Malic_Acid_Degradation": {
  "definition": "A Malic_Acid_Degradation is a Malate_Degradation comprising mitochondrial respiration, cytosolic enzyme activity, and gluconeogenic conversion of L-malate, reducing malic acid from 8–15 g/L at véraison to 1–4 g/L at harvest over 30–50 days.",
  "alternative_term": "malic acid breakdown process | L-malate catabolism | malic acid metabolic degradation | malate turnover |+ Äpfelsäure-Abbau | L-Malat-Katabolismus | Äpfelsäure-metabolischer-Abbau | Malat-Umsatz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling berries in Rheingau, Germany during BBCH 85-89, malic acid degradation reduces malate from 12.8 g/L at veraison to 6.2 g/L at harvest over 52 days, representing 52% degradation characteristic of this high-acid variety, with NADP-malic enzyme contributing approximately 60% of total degradation, mitochondrial respiration 25%, and gluconeogenesis 15%, under cool mean temperatures of 16°C that preserve higher residual acidity than warmer regions.",
  "editor_note": "Malic_Acid_Degradation is parent class under Acid_Reduction organizing biochemical mechanisms of malate catabolism. ||Distinguishes from Active_Acid_Reduction which emphasizes temporal dynamics. ||Contains subclasses Malate_Respiratory_Consumption, Malic_Enzyme_Activity, and Progressive_Malate_Depletion representing specific mechanisms and outcomes. ||Duration 30-50 days. ||Key parameter is 50-90% malic acid reduction depending on cultivar and climate. || This process class organizes the specific biochemical mechanisms including respiratory consumption of malate through the tricarboxylic acid cycle, NADP-malic enzyme catalyzed decarboxylation producing pyruvate and CO2, and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase mediated gluconeogenesis recycling malate carbon into hexose sugars, collectively accounting for the near-complete turnover of the berry malate pool during ripening. ||The subcellular organization involves coordinated transport and metabolism across multiple compartments, with vacuolar malate stores serving as the primary substrate reservoir, cytosolic enzymes providing the dominant degradation pathway, and mitochondrial metabolism contributing both catabolic capacity and energy generation through oxidative phosphorylation coupled to malate oxidation. ||Genetic regulation of malic acid degradation involves developmental activation of malic enzyme gene expression at veraison, hormonal modulation by abscisic acid enhancing enzyme activities, and cultivar-specific differences in regulatory element sequences determining the magnitude and timing of enzyme induction during ripening. ||The quantitative importance of malic acid degradation for berry carbon balance reflects the substantial carbon pool represented by malate, with complete degradation of 10 g/L malic acid releasing approximately 3.6 g carbon equivalent per liter of berry volume, contributing significantly to respiratory CO2 efflux and providing substrate for secondary metabolite biosynthesis during ripening. ||Environmental modulation occurs primarily through temperature effects on enzyme kinetics and respiratory rates, with degradation rates doubling for each 10°C temperature increase within the physiological range, establishing malic acid degradation as the primary temperature-responsive component of berry acid metabolism. ||The process demonstrates characteristic kinetics with initial rapid degradation during early ripening when enzyme activities peak and substrate concentrations remain high, transitioning to slower rates during late ripening as malate pools become depleted and enzyme activities decline.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280 || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis. Vitis 21: 346-358 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 268-275"
},

  "Malate_Respiratory_Consumption": {
  "definition": "A Malate_Respiratory_Consumption is a Malic_Acid_Degradation realized through mitochondrial oxidation of L-malate via the TCA cycle to CO₂ and H₂O with coupled ATP synthesis, accounting for 20–30% of total malic acid degradation.",
  "alternative_term": "mitochondrial malate oxidation | respiratory malate catabolism | malate TCA cycle oxidation | oxidative malate consumption |+ Malat-Atmungsverbrauch | mitochondriale Malat-Oxidation | respiratorischer Malat-Katabolismus | oxidativer Malat-Verbrauch",
  "example_of_usage": "In Shiraz berries in Barossa Valley, Australia during BBCH 87-89, malate respiratory consumption accounts for 28% of total malic acid degradation, oxidizing approximately 2.4 g/L malate through mitochondrial respiration over the 35-day ripening period, with respiratory rates peaking at 45 µL CO2/g fresh weight/hour during warm afternoon periods of 32°C and declining to 18 µL CO2/g fresh weight/hour during cool nights of 18°C.",
  "editor_note": "Malate_Respiratory_Consumption is subclass of Malic_Acid_Degradation representing mitochondrial oxidative pathway. ||Distinguishes from Malic_Enzyme_Activity which is primarily cytosolic decarboxylation. ||Sibling to Malic_Enzyme_Activity and Progressive_Malate_Depletion. ||Accounts for 20-30% of total malate catabolism. ||Important for energy provision during ripening. ||Temperature-sensitive with Q10 of 2.0-2.3. || This process involves malate transport across the inner mitochondrial membrane via the dicarboxylate carrier and subsequent oxidation through two primary pathways including direct conversion to oxaloacetate by mitochondrial malate dehydrogenase feeding into the TCA cycle, and oxidative decarboxylation by NAD-malic enzyme producing pyruvate which enters the cycle through pyruvate dehydrogenase. ||The quantitative contribution of respiratory consumption to total malate degradation varies with developmental stage and environmental conditions, representing 15-20% of malate flux during early ripening when cytosolic malic enzyme activity dominates, increasing to 30-40% during late ripening as cytosolic enzyme activities decline and mitochondrial respiration becomes proportionally more important. ||The energetic yield from complete malate oxidation generates approximately 15 ATP equivalents per malate molecule through oxidative phosphorylation, providing substantial energy for active transport processes including sugar loading, secondary metabolite biosynthesis, and maintenance of cellular integrity during the ripening period. ||Temperature strongly influences respiratory consumption rates, with Q10 values of 2.0-2.3 indicating near-doubling of mitochondrial malate oxidation for each 10°C increase, contributing to accelerated total acid decline under warm conditions through enhanced respiratory flux. ||The diurnal pattern of respiratory consumption shows peak rates during warm afternoon periods when mitochondrial activity is stimulated, with reduced nighttime rates allowing partial recovery of cytosolic malate pools through continued vacuolar efflux. ||Berry respiratory quotients during ripening reflect the mixed substrate utilization including malate oxidation, with RQ values of 0.9-1.1 indicating balanced carbohydrate and organic acid respiration. ||The coupling between malate respiratory consumption and other ripening processes includes provision of TCA cycle intermediates for amino acid biosynthesis and generation of reducing equivalents for secondary metabolite modification reactions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280 || Ruffner HP and Hawker JS (1977) Control of glycolysis in ripening berries of Vitis vinifera. Phytochemistry 16: 1171-1175 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 270-272"
},

  "Malic_Enzyme_Activity": {
  "definition": "A Malic_Enzyme_Activity is a Malic_Acid_Degradation realized through NADP- and NAD-dependent malic enzyme catalysis of L-malate oxidative decarboxylation to pyruvate with NAD(P)⁺ reduction and CO₂ release, accounting for 50–70% of total malate catabolism over 30–45 days post-véraison.",
  "alternative_term": "malic enzyme catalysis | NADP-malic enzyme function | malate decarboxylation activity | ME enzyme activity |+ Malic-Enzym-Aktivität | Äpfelsäure-Enzym-Katalyse | NADP-Malic-Enzym-Funktion | Malat-Decarboxylierungs-Aktivität",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grenache berries in Châteauneuf-du-Pape, Rhône Valley during BBCH 85-89, malic enzyme activity increases from 0.8 µmol/min/g fresh weight at veraison to peak activity of 4.2 µmol/min/g fresh weight at 18 days post-veraison, catalyzing degradation of 6.8 g/L malic acid representing 65% of total malate catabolism, with cytosolic NADP-malic enzyme contributing 85% of measured activity under warm ripening conditions averaging 28°C.",
  "editor_note": "Malic_Enzyme_Activity is subclass of Malic_Acid_Degradation representing the dominant enzymatic pathway. ||Distinguishes from Malate_Respiratory_Consumption which is mitochondrial TCA oxidation. ||Sibling to Malate_Respiratory_Consumption and Progressive_Malate_Depletion. ||Accounts for 50-70% of total malate catabolism. ||Peak activity 2-5 µmol/min/g fresh weight at mid-ripening. ||Key cultivar-differentiating parameter. || The cytosolic NADP-malic enzyme provides the primary degradation pathway, with enzyme activity increasing 3-6 fold between veraison and mid-ripening in response to developmental signals and abscisic acid induction, reaching peak activities of 2-5 µmol/min/g fresh weight before declining during late ripening as substrate becomes limiting. ||The biochemical mechanism involves sequential binding of malate and NADP+ to the enzyme active site, hydride transfer from malate C2 to NADP+ generating the intermediate oxaloacetate, and spontaneous or enzyme-assisted decarboxylation releasing CO2 and producing pyruvate as the stable product, with the overall reaction thermodynamically favorable and essentially irreversible under cellular conditions. ||Mitochondrial NAD-malic enzyme provides a secondary pathway with distinct kinetic properties and regulatory characteristics, contributing 10-20% of total malic enzyme flux with activity responsive to cellular energy status through adenylate regulation. ||The pyruvate produced by malic enzyme activity feeds into multiple downstream pathways including mitochondrial oxidation through pyruvate dehydrogenase, gluconeogenic reversal through pyruvate carboxylase, and amino acid biosynthesis through transamination, integrating malate degradation with broader cellular metabolism. ||Genetic variation in malic enzyme expression underlies cultivar differences in acid retention, with high-acid varieties such as Riesling showing lower enzyme induction and activity compared to rapid acid-decline varieties such as Grenache under equivalent conditions. ||Temperature modulation of malic enzyme activity occurs through both direct kinetic effects on catalytic rate and indirect effects on gene expression, with warm conditions stimulating both enzyme synthesis and activity to produce accelerated malate catabolism. ||The NADPH generated by cytosolic malic enzyme activity contributes to cellular reducing power for biosynthetic reactions including secondary metabolite modification and lipid synthesis during berry ripening.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280 || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis. Vitis 21: 346-358 || Or E et al (2000) Isolation of a NAD-dependent malic enzyme gene from grape berries. Plant Science 159: 1-9"
},

  "Progressive_Malate_Depletion": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Malate_Depletion is a Malic_Acid_Degradation exhibiting reduction of vacuolar malate concentration from 200–400 mM at véraison to 30–100 mM at harvest through sustained efflux and catabolism over 35–50 days post-véraison.",
  "alternative_term": "vacuolar malate reduction | malate pool decline | cumulative malate loss | berry malate exhaustion |+ progressive Malat-Erschöpfung | vakuoläre Malat-Reduktion | Malat-Pool-Abnahme | kumulative Malat-Verlust",
  "example_of_usage": "In Tempranillo berries in Ribera del Duero, Spain during BBCH 85-89, progressive malate depletion reduces vacuolar malate concentration from 340 mM at veraison to 65 mM at harvest over 42 days, representing 81% pool depletion with early-phase rates of 12 mM per day during the first 20 days declining to 4 mM per day during the final 22 days, corresponding to whole-berry malic acid reduction from 10.8 to 2.1 g/L under mean ripening temperatures of 25°C.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Malate_Depletion is subclass of Malic_Acid_Degradation representing the outcome measure of vacuolar pool reduction. ||Distinguishes from Malic_Enzyme_Activity and Malate_Respiratory_Consumption which are mechanistic pathways. ||Sibling class relationship with other Malic_Acid_Degradation subclasses. ||Duration 35-50 days. ||Key parameter is vacuolar concentration decline from 200-400 mM to 30-100 mM. ||Cultivar-diagnostic for acid retention potential. || This process reflects the net outcome of continuous malate export from vacuolar storage coupled with ongoing enzymatic degradation and respiratory consumption, with depletion kinetics following characteristic patterns determined by cultivar genetics, temperature regime, and initial malate pool size, typically exhibiting rapid early-phase depletion at rates of 8-15 mM per day transitioning to slower late-phase depletion at 2-5 mM per day as substrate becomes limiting. ||The vacuolar compartment serves as the primary malate reservoir, containing greater than 90% of total berry malate in dissociated form stabilized by the acidic vacuolar pH of 2.5-3.5, with efflux mediated by ALMT aluminum-activated malate transporter channels and voltage-dependent anion channels responding to cytosolic malate concentration gradients and membrane potential changes during ripening. ||The progression of depletion shows strong cultivar specificity, with high-acid varieties maintaining larger residual vacuolar pools through lower transport rates and reduced enzyme activities, while rapid-decline varieties achieve near-complete vacuolar depletion with final malate concentrations below 50 mM. ||Temperature integration determines depletion trajectory, with accumulated growing degree days correlating with fractional malate remaining, enabling prediction of harvest malate levels from thermal time accumulation and variety-specific depletion coefficients. ||The metabolic consequences of progressive depletion include shifting cellular carbon balance as malate contribution to respiratory substrate diminishes, altered cytosolic redox status as NADPH generation from malic enzyme declines, and modified vacuolar pH as buffer capacity decreases with malate removal. ||Berry-to-berry variation in depletion rates within clusters reflects differential temperature exposure and vascular connectivity, producing the heterogeneity in final acid composition that contributes to sample variation in harvest monitoring. ||The irreversible nature of depletion under normal ripening conditions, absent significant malate biosynthesis during post-veraison stages, establishes the monotonic decline characteristic that enables reliable prediction of harvest acidity from early-season measurements.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Sweetman C et al (2009) Regulation of malate metabolism in grape berry. Molecular Plant 2: 1270-1280 || Terrier N et al (2001) Changes in acidity and proton transport at the tonoplast of grape berries during development. Planta 213: 20-28 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 268-275"
},

  "Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization": {
  "definition": "A Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization is a Ripening exhibiting unchanged L-tartaric acid concentration of 5–10 g/L throughout the post-véraison maturation phase due to the absence of significant tartrate-degrading enzymatic activity in berry tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "tartrate stability | tartaric acid preservation | tartrate metabolic stability | tartaric acid maintenance |+ Weinsäure-Stabilisierung | Tartrat-Stabilität | Weinsäure-Erhaltung | Tartrat-metabolische-Stabilität",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Franc berries in Loire Valley, France during BBCH 81-89, tartaric acid stabilization maintains total berry tartrate content at 4.2-4.5 mg per berry throughout the 45-day ripening period, while volumetric concentration decreases from 9.2 to 6.8 g/L due to berry volume increase from 0.95 to 1.42 mL, with potassium bitartrate precipitation accounting for 18% apparent tartrate loss under harvest potassium levels of 42 mM.",
  "editor_note": "Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization is parent class under Acid_Reduction representing the contrasting metabolic fate of tartrate versus malate. ||Distinguishes from Malic_Acid_Degradation by emphasizing metabolic stability rather than catabolism. ||Contains subclasses Tartrate_Maintenance, Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level, and Acid_Balance_Achievement. ||Duration spans entire ripening period of 35-50 days. ||Key characteristic is absence of enzymatic degradation pathways for tartrate in grape berries. || This process reflects the unique biochemical status of tartaric acid among plant organic acids, as grapevines lack the tartrate-degrading enzymes present in some other plant species, rendering the tartrate pool metabolically inert once synthesized during the pre-veraison period spanning BBCH 71-81. ||The cellular basis of tartaric acid stabilization involves sequestration within vacuolar compartments of mesocarp parenchyma cells and specialized crystal idioblast cells, where the acidic vacuolar environment of pH 2.5-3.5 maintains tartrate in predominantly dissociated ionic forms that are not substrates for available metabolic enzymes. ||The concentration stability observed on a per-berry basis masks apparent concentration changes when expressed volumetrically, as berry expansion during the secondary growth phase of 50-100% volume increase produces dilution effects reducing tartaric acid concentration from 8-12 g/L at veraison to 5-8 g/L at harvest without actual tartrate catabolism occurring. ||Potassium accumulation during ripening, with berry potassium content increasing from 20-30 to 35-50 mM, results in formation of sparingly soluble potassium bitartrate crystals that precipitate within vacuolar compartments, effectively removing 10-25% of total tartrate from solution while the precipitated salt remains within berry tissues. ||Temperature exerts minimal direct influence on tartaric acid stability compared to its profound effects on malate degradation, though indirect effects through modulation of berry expansion rates and potassium accumulation patterns influence final tartrate concentrations at harvest. ||Cultivar variation in tartaric acid stabilization reflects genetic differences in initial tartrate biosynthesis capacity, berry size determining dilution effects, and potassium uptake efficiency influencing precipitation losses, with typical harvest concentrations ranging from 4-6 g/L in large-berried table grape varieties to 7-10 g/L in small-berried wine grape cultivars. ||The maintenance of stable tartaric acid levels throughout ripening establishes tartrate as the primary contributor to wine titratable acidity following malolactic fermentation, providing the structural acid backbone essential for wine stability, aging potential, and sensory balance. ||Viticultural practices influencing tartaric acid stabilization operate primarily through effects on berry size and potassium status rather than direct metabolic modulation, with irrigation management, crop load adjustment, and rootstock selection representing the primary management tools for optimizing harvest tartrate levels.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## viticulture-specific phenomenon (potassium bitartrate crystal formation in berry); no equivalent process in chemistry-focused OBO ontologies." ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 262-268 || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis. Vitis 21: 346-358 || DeBolt S et al (2006) L-Tartaric acid synthesis from vitamin C in higher plants. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences 103: 5608-5613"
},

  "Tartrate_Maintenance": {
  "definition": "A Tartrate_Maintenance is a Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization realized through vacuolar sequestration, absence of degradative enzyme activity, and limited membrane permeability preserving tartrate pools across the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "tartrate preservation | tartaric acid pool conservation | tartrate retention | tartaric acid maintenance process |+ Tartrat-Erhaltung | Weinsäure-Pool-Konservierung | Tartrat-Retention | Weinsäure-Bewahrung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc berries in Marlborough, New Zealand during BBCH 83-89, tartrate maintenance preserves total berry tartrate at 3.8-4.1 mg per berry over 40 days of ripening, with vacuolar tartrate concentration maintained at 185-195 mM despite berry volume increase from 0.82 to 1.35 mL, demonstrating the effectiveness of tonoplast sequestration mechanisms under cool maritime ripening conditions averaging 18°C.",
  "editor_note": "Tartrate_Maintenance is subclass of Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization representing the active physiological processes preserving tartrate pools. ||Distinguishes from Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level which describes the outcome measurement. ||Sibling to Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level and Acid_Balance_Achievement. ||Emphasizes vacuolar sequestration and absence of degradation pathways. ||Duration spans entire ripening period. || This process involves the continued function of tonoplast transport systems that originally accumulated tartrate during the pre-veraison biosynthetic period, maintaining vacuolar tartrate concentrations of 150-300 mM through active transport mechanisms that prevent passive efflux despite the substantial concentration gradient between vacuolar and cytosolic compartments. ||The molecular basis of tartrate maintenance reflects the evolutionary loss of tartrate-degrading enzyme systems in Vitis species, contrasting with some other plant families that possess tartrate dehydrogenase or related catabolic enzymes, rendering grape berry tartrate pools metabolically isolated from central carbon metabolism during ripening. ||Cellular compartmentalization contributes to tartrate maintenance through sequestration in specialized crystal idioblast cells containing calcium tartrate raphide crystals and potassium bitartrate druse crystals, with these crystalline forms representing 15-30% of total berry tartrate in a metabolically unavailable state that provides additional protection against potential degradation. ||The stability of tartrate maintenance under varying environmental conditions reflects the robustness of vacuolar sequestration mechanisms, with temperature extremes, water stress, and nutrient variation producing minimal effects on tartrate pool size compared to their substantial impacts on malate metabolism during ripening. ||Developmental regulation ensures tartrate maintenance through sustained expression of tonoplast transport proteins and vacuolar proton pumps that maintain the electrochemical gradients necessary for tartrate retention, with gene expression studies demonstrating continued activity of vacuolar ATPase and pyrophosphatase throughout the ripening period. ||The quantitative assessment of tartrate maintenance requires distinction between total tartrate content on a per-berry basis, which remains stable, and volumetric concentration, which decreases due to berry expansion, with research methodologies employing both metrics to accurately characterize tartrate dynamics during ripening. ||Berry-to-berry variation in tartrate maintenance within clusters reflects differences in initial tartrate accumulation, berry size progression, and localized potassium precipitation, contributing to the heterogeneity in final acid composition observed at harvest.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Terrier N et al (2001) Changes in acidity and proton transport at the tonoplast of grape berries during development. Planta 213: 20-28 || DeBolt S et al (2006) L-Tartaric acid synthesis from vitamin C in higher plants. PNAS 103: 5608-5613 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 262-265"
},

  "Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level": {
  "definition": "A Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level is a Tartrate_Maintenance defined by retention of total tartaric acid content within ±10–15% of véraison values, yielding harvest concentrations of 5–10 g/L.",
  "alternative_term": "constant tartrate concentration | stable tartaric acid content | maintained tartrate level | consistent tartaric acid |+ stabile Weinsäure-Konzentration | konstanter Tartrat-Gehalt | beständiger Weinsäure-Spiegel | stabiler Weinsäure-Level",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chenin Blanc berries in Vouvray, Loire Valley during BBCH 85-89, stable tartaric acid level maintains per-berry tartrate content at 4.8-5.2 mg throughout 42 days of ripening, while volumetric concentration decreases from 10.5 to 7.2 g/L due to berry expansion from 0.92 to 1.48 mL, with potassium bitartrate precipitation accounting for 12% of total tartrate under moderate potassium accumulation of 38 mM at harvest.",
  "editor_note": "Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level is subclass of Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization representing the quantitative measurement outcome. ||Distinguishes from Tartrate_Maintenance which describes physiological processes. ||Sibling to Tartrate_Maintenance and Acid_Balance_Achievement. ||Key parameter is plus-minus 10-15% variation in per-berry tartrate content. ||Important for harvest planning and wine style determination. || This stability manifests as consistent tartrate content when measured on a per-berry basis, with typical values of 3-6 mg tartaric acid per berry maintained from veraison through harvest despite the profound metabolic and compositional changes occurring in other berry components during ripening progression. ||The volumetric expression of stable tartaric acid levels requires interpretation accounting for berry expansion effects, as the 50-100% increase in berry volume during post-veraison growth produces apparent concentration decreases from 8-12 g/L at veraison to 5-8 g/L at harvest that do not represent actual tartrate loss but rather dilution within an expanding tissue volume. ||Potassium interactions modify the expression of stable tartaric acid levels through precipitation of potassium bitartrate crystals within vacuolar compartments, with the degree of precipitation dependent on berry potassium accumulation rates, temperature fluctuations affecting crystal solubility, and cultivar-specific differences in potassium uptake capacity, typically removing 10-25% of tartrate from the soluble pool while maintaining total berry tartrate content. ||The consistency of stable tartaric acid levels across diverse environmental conditions reflects the absence of temperature-responsive degradation pathways affecting tartrate metabolism, contrasting sharply with the 2-3 fold variation in malate degradation rates observed across the typical temperature range encountered during grape ripening seasons. ||Cultivar differences in stable tartaric acid levels primarily reflect genetic variation in pre-veraison tartrate biosynthesis capacity rather than ripening-phase metabolism, with high-acid varieties such as Riesling and Chenin Blanc typically maintaining higher tartrate levels of 7-10 g/L compared to lower-acid varieties such as Gewürztraminer showing levels of 4-6 g/L at equivalent maturity. ||The predictability of stable tartaric acid levels enables viticultural planning for harvest timing and wine style objectives, with tartrate measurements providing reliable baseline acidity values against which to assess malate reduction progress and optimal harvest windows for desired acid balance.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 262-268 || Conde C et al (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development and ripening. Food Chemistry 1: 1-22 || Ruffner HP (1982) Metabolism of tartaric and malic acids in Vitis. Vitis 21: 346-358"
},

  "Acid_Balance_Achievement": {
  "definition": "An Acid_Balance_Achievement is a Ripening manifesting as the compositional shift from malate-dominated at véraison to tartrate-dominated at harvest through differential catabolism of malic and tartaric acids over the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "organic acid equilibrium | acid composition balance | malate-tartrate balance | final acid profile establishment |+ Säure-Gleichgewichts-Erreichung | organische Säure-Balance | Malat-Tartrat-Gleichgewicht | Säureprofil-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Barbera berries in Piedmont, Italy during BBCH 85-89, acid balance achievement shifts the malate-to-tartrate ratio from 2.1 at veraison to 0.65 at harvest over 44 days, with malic acid declining from 12.5 to 4.8 g/L while tartaric acid remains stable at 7.2-7.5 g/L, producing final titratable acidity of 7.8 g/L and pH 3.28 characteristic of this high-acid variety under mean ripening temperatures of 23°C.",
  "editor_note": "Acid_Balance_Achievement is subclass of Tartaric_Acid_Stabilization representing the integrated outcome of differential acid metabolism. ||Distinguishes from individual acid processes by emphasizing compositional balance. ||Sibling to Tartrate_Maintenance and Stable_Tartaric_Acid_Level. ||Key parameter is malate-to-tartrate ratio shift from 1.5-2.5 to 0.2-0.8. ||Critical for harvest timing decisions. || This process reflects the integrated outcome of rapid malic acid degradation reducing malate content by 50-90% concurrent with stable tartaric acid maintenance, fundamentally altering the malate-to-tartrate ratio from 1.5-2.5 at veraison to 0.2-0.8 at harvest maturity across diverse cultivars and growing conditions. ||The biochemical basis of acid balance achievement involves the contrasting metabolic fates of the two primary grape organic acids, with malic acid serving as an active respiratory and gluconeogenic substrate subject to temperature-dependent enzymatic catabolism, while tartaric acid remains metabolically inert due to the absence of degradation pathways, producing predictable convergence toward tartrate-dominated acid profiles regardless of initial composition. ||Temperature regime profoundly influences acid balance achievement through differential effects on malate versus tartrate dynamics, with warm conditions accelerating malate degradation while leaving tartrate unaffected, producing lower final malate-to-tartrate ratios of 0.2-0.4 in warm climates compared to ratios of 0.6-1.0 in cool climates where malate degradation proceeds more slowly. ||The timing of acid balance achievement relative to sugar accumulation determines harvest decision windows, with optimal balance typically achieved when titratable acidity reaches 6-9 g/L concurrent with sugar levels of 22-26 Brix for dry wine production, though specific targets vary with intended wine style from high-acid sparkling base wines to lower-acid warm-climate table wines. ||Cultivar genetics influence acid balance achievement through effects on both initial acid composition at veraison and the rate of malate degradation during ripening, with varieties such as Barbera maintaining higher final malate content compared to varieties such as Grenache that achieve near-complete malate depletion under equivalent conditions. ||The achievement of appropriate acid balance represents a primary harvest quality criterion, with monitoring of titratable acidity, pH, and individual organic acid concentrations guiding picking decisions to optimize wine quality potential across diverse production objectives.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 275-280 || Coombe BG and McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics of grape berry growth and physiology of ripening. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 6: 131-135 || Conde C et al (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development. Food Chemistry 1: 1-22"
},

  "Final_Acid_Balance": {
  "definition": "A Final_Acid_Balance is an Acid_Balance_Achievement exhibiting stabilized titratable acidity at 5–9 g/L during the final 7–14 days pre-harvest as acid reduction processes approach equilibrium.",
  "alternative_term": "terminal acid equilibrium | harvest acid balance | mature acid composition | ripening acid endpoint |+ finale Säure-Balance | terminales Säure-Gleichgewicht | Ernte-Säure-Balance | reife Säure-Zusammensetzung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Viognier berries in Condrieu, Rhône Valley during BBCH 89, final acid balance stabilizes at titratable acidity of 5.4 g/L and pH 3.52 during the final 10 days before harvest, with malic acid equilibrating at 1.6 g/L and tartaric acid at 5.1 g/L, representing daily acid change of only 0.04 g/L compared to mid-ripening rates of 0.35 g/L, under late-season temperatures averaging 26°C.",
  "editor_note": "Final_Acid_Balance is parent class under Acid_Reduction representing the terminal equilibrium phase. ||Distinguishes from Active_Acid_Reduction which represents dynamic catabolism phase. ||Contains subclasses Mature_Berry_Acidity, Sugar_Acid_Ratio_Optimization, and Harvest_Acidity_Level. ||Duration 7-14 days at end of ripening. ||Key characteristic is asymptotic approach to stable acid levels with minimal daily change. || This process emerges as malic acid degradation rates decline asymptotically due to substrate depletion, with daily acid loss decreasing from active-phase rates of 0.2-0.5 g/L per day to equilibrium rates of 0.02-0.08 g/L per day as vacuolar malate pools approach minimum sustainable concentrations of 1-3 g/L in most cultivars. ||The attainment of final acid balance integrates the outcomes of malate catabolism and tartrate stability, producing characteristic harvest acid profiles comprising residual malate of 1-4 g/L and stable tartrate of 5-8 g/L that together constitute the 6-10 g/L titratable acidity typical of mature wine grapes across diverse growing regions. ||Temperature during the final ripening phase continues to influence the precise endpoint of acid balance, with warm conditions of 28-35°C driving malate to lower residual levels of 1-2 g/L compared to cool conditions of 15-20°C where final malate may stabilize at 3-5 g/L, producing the characteristic acidity differences between warm and cool climate wines. ||The pH at final acid balance typically ranges from 3.2-3.6 for white varieties and 3.3-3.8 for red varieties, reflecting the combined effects of organic acid composition, potassium content, and cultivar-specific buffering capacity, with pH providing critical information for winemaking decisions regarding acidification requirements, malolactic fermentation management, and sulfur dioxide additions. ||Cultivar variation in final acid balance reflects genetic differences in malate degradation endpoint, tartrate biosynthesis capacity, and potassium accumulation patterns, with high-acid varieties such as Riesling maintaining titratable acidity of 8-12 g/L at full maturity compared to low-acid varieties such as Viognier achieving balance at 5-7 g/L under equivalent conditions. ||The stability of final acid balance once achieved enables flexibility in harvest timing decisions, as the plateau phase allows picking windows of 7-14 days during which acid composition changes minimally while other quality parameters continue developing.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 275-280 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 43: 101-110 || Conde C et al (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development. Food Chemistry 1: 1-22"
},

  "Mature_Berry_Acidity": {
  "definition": "A Mature_Berry_Acidity is a Final_Acid_Balance defined by titratable acidity of 5–9 g/L and pH 3.2–3.8 integrating the outcomes of malate catabolism, tartrate stability, and potassium-mediated pH buffering.",
  "alternative_term": "ripe berry acid status | mature grape acidity | harvest-ready acid composition | fully ripe acid profile |+ reife Beeren-Acidität | Reife-Beeren-Säurestatus | erntereife Säure-Zusammensetzung | vollreifes Säureprofil",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling berries in Mosel Valley, Germany at BBCH 89, mature berry acidity is characterized by titratable acidity of 9.2 g/L, pH 3.08, malic acid of 5.8 g/L, and tartaric acid of 7.5 g/L, representing the high-acid profile typical of this variety under cool-climate conditions with mean ripening temperature of 15°C, providing optimal base material for production of off-dry to sweet wines with characteristic fresh acidity.",
  "editor_note": "Mature_Berry_Acidity is subclass of Final_Acid_Balance representing the quality state at ripening completion. ||Distinguishes from Harvest_Acidity_Level which emphasizes measurement for picking decisions. ||Sibling to Sugar_Acid_Ratio_Optimization and Harvest_Acidity_Level. ||Characterized by titratable acidity 5-9 g/L, pH 3.2-3.8, and equilibrium acid metabolism. ||Integrates temperature and cultivar effects on final composition. || This state represents the optimal acid status for wine production, characterized by residual malic acid of 1-4 g/L providing microbial substrate for potential malolactic fermentation, tartaric acid of 5-8 g/L constituting the primary structural acid for wine stability, and sufficient total acidity to ensure proper pH for antimicrobial protection, color stability in red wines, and fresh sensory character in the finished wine. ||The biochemical markers of mature berry acidity include completion of rapid-phase malate degradation with transition to equilibrium kinetics showing daily acid loss below 0.1 g/L, stable vacuolar pH reflecting exhaustion of readily catabolizable acid pools, and establishment of potassium-tartrate precipitation equilibrium determining final tartrate availability and pH buffering capacity. ||Temperature history during ripening determines the specific parameters of mature berry acidity, with warm-climate berries typically achieving maturity at lower titratable acidity of 5-7 g/L and higher pH of 3.5-3.8 compared to cool-climate berries maturing at titratable acidity of 7-10 g/L and pH of 3.1-3.4, reflecting the temperature sensitivity of malate degradation rates that establish final acid composition. ||Cultivar genetics interact with environmental conditions to determine mature berry acidity parameters, with inherently high-acid varieties such as Riesling, Chenin Blanc, and Barbera maintaining elevated acidity at maturity compared to lower-acid varieties such as Gewürztraminer, Viognier, and Grenache under equivalent growing conditions. ||The assessment of mature berry acidity requires integration of multiple analytical parameters including titratable acidity, pH, and individual organic acid concentrations, as these metrics provide complementary information about wine suitability, with titratable acidity predicting sourness perception, pH determining chemical and microbial stability, and organic acid composition indicating malolactic fermentation potential and wine aging trajectory.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 275-280 || Jackson RS (2020) Wine Science Principles and Applications 5th Ed Chapter 6 || Coombe BG and McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics of grape berry growth. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 6: 131-135"
},

  "Sugar_Acid_Ratio_Optimization": {
  "definition": "A Sugar_Acid_Ratio_Optimization is a Ripening defined by attainment of a Brix-to-tartaric-acid-equivalent ratio of 2.5–4.0 through coordinated sugar loading and acid reduction during the final ripening phase.",
  "alternative_term": "Brix-acidity balance | sugar-acid equilibrium | must balance optimization | sweetness-sourness ratio |+ Zucker-Säure-Verhältnis-Optimierung | Brix-Aciditäts-Balance | Most-Balance-Optimierung | Zucker-Säure-Gleichgewicht",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Gris berries in Alsace, France during BBCH 87-89, sugar acid ratio optimization progresses from 1.8 at early ripening through 2.9 at mid-ripening to optimal harvest ratio of 3.4 when Brix reaches 23.5 and titratable acidity declines to 6.9 g/L, with ratio increase of 0.04 per day during final two weeks enabling precise harvest timing for balanced dry wine production under mean temperatures of 20°C.",
  "editor_note": "Sugar_Acid_Ratio_Optimization is subclass of Final_Acid_Balance representing the integrative quality criterion. ||Distinguishes from individual sugar or acid measurements by emphasizing balance. ||Sibling to Mature_Berry_Acidity and Harvest_Acidity_Level. ||Key parameter is Brix-to-TA ratio of 2.5-4.0. ||Wine style dependent with lower ratios for sparkling and crisp wines, higher for full-bodied reds. || This process integrates the opposing trajectories of sugar accumulation increasing from 15-18 Brix at veraison to 22-28 Brix at harvest concurrent with titratable acidity decreasing from 15-25 g/L to 5-9 g/L, with the sugar-acid ratio increasing from initial values of 0.7-1.2 to harvest values of 2.5-4.5 over the 35-50 day post-veraison ripening period. ||The optimal sugar-acid ratio varies with intended wine style, ranging from lower ratios of 2.0-2.8 preferred for sparkling wine base material and crisp white wines, through intermediate ratios of 2.8-3.5 typical for balanced dry table wines, to higher ratios of 3.5-4.5 acceptable for full-bodied red wines and warm-climate productions where lower acidity is compensated by increased phenolic structure. ||Temperature profoundly influences sugar-acid ratio progression through differential effects on the component processes, with warm conditions accelerating both sugar accumulation and acid reduction but affecting acid loss proportionally more, producing rapid ratio increase and potential overshooting of optimal balance if harvest timing is delayed. ||Cultivar characteristics determine the achievable range of sugar-acid ratios at comparable maturity levels, with high-acid varieties such as Riesling capable of maintaining ratios below 3.0 at full phenolic ripeness compared to low-acid varieties such as Grenache where ratios may exceed 4.0 before optimal flavor development is achieved. ||Viticultural management of sugar-acid ratio optimization involves monitoring progression of both components through regular sampling, with predictive modeling using temperature forecasts enabling estimation of optimal harvest windows when target ratios will be achieved. ||The sugar-acid ratio provides a more integrative harvest criterion than either component alone, as it captures the balance determining sensory perception of wine harmony between sweetness and sourness that underlies consumer quality assessment.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 278-285 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 43: 101-110 || Jackson RS (2020) Wine Science Principles and Applications 5th Ed Chapter 6"
},

  "Harvest_Acidity_Level": {
  "definition": "A Harvest_Acidity_Level is a Final_Acid_Balance defined by titratable acidity and pH measurements at the point of commercial harvest, providing baseline parameters for subsequent vinification decisions.",
  "alternative_term": "picking acidity | harvest acid measurement | vintage acidity level | harvest titratable acidity |+ Ernte-Acidität | Lese-Säuregehalt | Ernte-Säure-Messung | Weinlese-Aciditäts-Level",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay berries in Champagne, France at BBCH 89 harvest, harvest acidity level measures titratable acidity of 10.8 g/L and pH 2.98, with malic acid at 7.2 g/L and tartaric acid at 6.5 g/L, representing the high-acid profile required for sparkling wine base material production, documented through sampling of 200 berries from 20 vines across five vineyard blocks with juice extraction at 65% yield for standardized analysis.",
  "editor_note": "Harvest_Acidity_Level is subclass of Final_Acid_Balance representing the specific measurement at picking. ||Distinguishes from Mature_Berry_Acidity which describes the biological state. ||Sibling to Mature_Berry_Acidity and Sugar_Acid_Ratio_Optimization. ||Key parameters are titratable acidity 5-10 g/L and pH 3.1-3.8. ||Critical for winemaking planning and quality documentation. ||Methodology-dependent requiring standardized protocols. || This metric encompasses titratable acidity values typically ranging from 5-10 g/L expressed as tartaric acid equivalents and pH values of 3.1-3.8, with the specific targets varying according to wine style objectives, regional regulations, and cultivar characteristics that define acceptable ranges for quality wine production in diverse viticultural contexts. ||The determination of harvest acidity level requires standardized analytical methodology including sample collection protocols specifying berry number, cluster position, and vineyard zone representation, juice extraction procedures ensuring consistent yield and minimal oxidation, and titrimetric analysis using sodium hydroxide titration to phenolphthalein endpoint or potentiometric endpoint detection for accurate quantification. ||Temperature conditions during the final ripening days significantly influence harvest acidity level through continued effects on malate degradation rates, with warm spells accelerating acid loss by 0.2-0.4 g/L per day compared to cool conditions maintaining near-equilibrium levels, necessitating frequent sampling during the pre-harvest period to capture optimal picking windows. ||The relationship between harvest acidity level and wine quality reflects the fundamental role of acidity in wine sensory balance, microbial stability, and aging potential, with insufficient acidity producing flat, unstable wines susceptible to spoilage while excessive acidity creates harsh, unbalanced wines requiring amelioration through deacidification or extended malolactic fermentation. ||Regional and regulatory considerations influence harvest acidity level targets, with cool-climate regions such as Champagne, Mosel, and Tasmania accepting or requiring higher acidity levels of 8-12 g/L for their characteristic wine styles compared to warm-climate regions such as Barossa, Napa, and Mendoza where lower levels of 5-7 g/L are typical and acceptable. ||Documentation of harvest acidity level provides essential traceability information for quality assurance programs, enabling correlation of vineyard conditions with wine quality outcomes and informing future viticultural decisions regarding harvest timing optimization for specific production objectives.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 278-285 || OIV (2021) Compendium of International Methods of Wine and Must Analysis || Iland P et al (2013) Chemical Analysis of Grapes and Wine Techniques and Concepts 2nd Ed"
},

  "Flavor_Development": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Development is a Ripening comprising biosynthesis, accumulation, and transformation of flavor and aroma compounds and their precursors over the 35–50 day post-véraison maturation phase.",
  "alternative_term": "flavor compound accumulation | berry flavor formation | grape flavor development | ripening flavor synthesis |+ Aromaentwicklung | Geschmacks-Entwicklung | Beeren-Aroma-Bildung | Reife-Aromasynthese",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc berries in Marlborough, New Zealand during BBCH 81-89, flavor development proceeds over 45 days with methoxypyrazine concentrations declining from 35 to 8 ng/L, volatile thiol precursors increasing from 50 to 280 µg/L, and total free volatiles accumulating to 850 µg/L at harvest, establishing the characteristic tropical and herbaceous flavor profile under cool maritime conditions averaging 18°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Development is parent class under Ripening representing all flavor-related biosynthetic processes. ||Distinguishes from Aroma_Development which focuses specifically on volatile aromatic compounds. ||Contains subclasses Precursor_Formation, Flavor_Compound_Synthesis, Flavor_Compound_Accumulation, and Flavor_Profile_Maturation. ||Duration 35-50 days post-veraison. ||Integrates amino acid, carbohydrate, lipid, and secondary metabolic pathways. || This process integrates multiple biosynthetic pathways including amino acid metabolism generating flavor-active compounds and precursors, carbohydrate-derived pathways producing furanones and related sweetness-associated volatiles, lipid oxidation yielding C6 aldehydes and alcohols contributing green and herbaceous notes, and specialized secondary metabolism generating terpenoids, norisoprenoids, and phenolic derivatives that constitute the aromatic signature of individual grape varieties. ||The temporal progression of flavor development follows characteristic patterns with early post-veraison accumulation of primary metabolites serving as biosynthetic precursors, mid-ripening activation of secondary metabolic pathways producing variety-specific flavor compounds, and late-ripening transformations including glycosylation, esterification, and oxidative modifications that modulate flavor compound availability and sensory impact in the mature berry. ||Cellular localization of flavor development processes varies among compound classes, with amino acid and organic acid metabolism occurring predominantly in mesocarp parenchyma cells, terpenoid and norisoprenoid synthesis concentrated in exocarp cells particularly in aromatic varieties, and phenolic compound accumulation distributed across skin and seed tissues with distinct compositional profiles reflecting tissue-specific enzyme expression. ||Temperature during ripening profoundly influences flavor development through effects on enzyme activities, precursor availability, and compound stability, with moderate temperatures of 20-25°C generally favoring balanced flavor accumulation while temperature extremes either accelerate degradation of heat-labile compounds or slow biosynthetic rates below optimal levels. ||Cultivar genetics establish the fundamental flavor development potential through variety-specific expression of biosynthetic enzymes, with aromatic varieties such as Muscat, Gewürztraminer, and Riesling showing elevated terpenoid pathway activity compared to neutral varieties such as Chardonnay and Pinot Noir where flavor complexity derives from different compound classes. ||Viticultural practices influence flavor development through effects on vine balance, canopy microclimate, and berry composition, with moderate water stress, appropriate crop load, and optimized light exposure generally enhancing flavor compound accumulation compared to excessive vigor or overcropping conditions. ||The relationship between flavor development and other ripening processes including sugar accumulation, acid reduction, and phenolic maturation reflects the integrated nature of berry metabolism, with carbon and nitrogen partitioning among competing biosynthetic pathways determining the final balance of flavor-active compounds at harvest. ||Research methodologies for assessing flavor development include gas chromatography-mass spectrometry quantification of volatile compounds, HPLC analysis of non-volatile precursors, and sensory evaluation techniques that correlate chemical composition with perceived flavor attributes in grapes and wines.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 285-310 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30 || Dunlevy JD et al (2009) A methyltransferase essential for the methoxypyrazine-derived flavour of wine. Plant Journal 59: 404-412"
},

  "Precursor_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Precursor_Formation is a Flavor_Development comprising biosynthesis and accumulation of metabolic intermediates and conjugated compounds serving as substrates for the release of flavor-active volatiles during vinification.",
  "alternative_term": "flavor precursor accumulation | aroma precursor synthesis | bound flavor formation | conjugate precursor development |+ Vorläufer-Bildung | Aroma-Vorläufer-Synthese | Aroma-Präkursor-Akkumulation | gebundene Aroma-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer berries in Alto Adige, Italy during BBCH 83-89, precursor formation accumulates total glycosidically-bound monoterpenes from 1.2 to 8.5 mg/L over 38 days, with bound linalool increasing from 0.3 to 2.8 mg/L and bound geraniol from 0.2 to 1.9 mg/L, representing 92% of total monoterpenoid content at harvest compared to 8% present as free volatiles, under warm-day cool-night conditions of 28°C/14°C.",
  "editor_note": "Precursor_Formation is parent class under Flavor_Development representing biosynthesis of conjugated and bound flavor compounds. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Compound_Synthesis which generates free volatiles. ||Contains subclasses Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis, Amino_Acid_Accumulation, and Precursor_Pool_Development. ||Key characteristic is accumulation of compounds requiring transformation for flavor release. ||Typically 80-95% of terpenoids exist as precursors. || This process involves the accumulation of diverse precursor classes including cysteine and glutathione conjugates of volatile thiols that generate tropical fruit aromas upon yeast-mediated cleavage during fermentation, glycosidically-bound monoterpenes and norisoprenoids that release floral and fruity volatiles through acid or enzyme hydrolysis, and amino acid pools that serve as substrates for Ehrlich pathway fermentation products and Maillard reaction participants during wine production and aging. ||The temporal progression of precursor formation shows characteristic accumulation patterns with initial synthesis of conjugating molecules including glutathione and UDP-glucose during early post-veraison stages, followed by active conjugate formation during mid-ripening as free volatile concentrations increase and glycosyltransferase activities peak, and continued accumulation through late ripening establishing the precursor pools that determine wine aromatic potential independent of free volatile concentrations at harvest. ||Cellular localization of precursor formation varies with compound class, with thiol precursors accumulating predominantly in mesocarp parenchyma cells where cysteine and glutathione conjugation occurs in cytosolic compartments, while glycosidic precursors concentrate in exocarp cells where monoterpene glycosyltransferases show highest expression and vacuolar sequestration protects conjugates from hydrolytic enzymes. ||The quantitative significance of precursor formation reflects the observation that 80-95% of total terpenoids and 60-90% of total volatile thiols exist in conjugated precursor forms at harvest, with free volatile concentrations representing only a fraction of total aromatic potential that can be released through appropriate winemaking interventions. ||Temperature during ripening influences precursor formation through effects on conjugating enzyme activities and precursor stability, with moderate conditions favoring balanced accumulation while high temperatures may accelerate precursor degradation or shift conjugation patterns affecting subsequent release efficiency. ||Cultivar genetics determine precursor formation capacity through variety-specific expression of glycosyltransferases, glutathione S-transferases, and related conjugating enzymes, with aromatic varieties showing 3-10 fold higher precursor concentrations than neutral varieties at equivalent ripeness levels.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Tominaga T et al (1998) Identification of cysteinylated aroma precursors in grape juice. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 46: 5215-5219 || Gunata Z et al (1985) The aroma of grapes. Extraction and determination of free and glycosidically bound fractions. Journal of Chromatography 331: 83-90 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 295-305"
},

  "Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis is a Precursor_Formation realized through glycosyltransferase-mediated conjugation of sugar moieties to terpenols and other aglycones, and glutathione-S-transferase-mediated conjugation of cysteine or glutathione to volatile thiol precursors.",
  "alternative_term": "glycoside precursor synthesis | bound volatile formation | conjugate biosynthesis | flavor glycosylation |+ Aromavorläufer-Synthese | Glycosid-Vorläufer-Bildung | gebundene Volatil-Biosynthese | Aroma-Glycosylierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Muscat of Alexandria berries in Rutherglen, Australia during BBCH 85-89, flavor precursor synthesis generates glycosidically-bound monoterpenes at rates of 0.15 mg/L per day during peak activity at 25 days post-veraison, with UDP-glucose monoterpenol glucosyltransferase activity reaching 45 nmol/min/g fresh weight in exocarp tissue, producing final bound linalool concentrations of 3.2 mg/L and bound geraniol of 2.4 mg/L under mean ripening temperatures of 26°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis is subclass of Precursor_Formation representing the specific enzymatic conjugation reactions. ||Distinguishes from Amino_Acid_Accumulation which provides nitrogen-containing precursors. ||Sibling to Amino_Acid_Accumulation and Precursor_Pool_Development. ||Key enzymes are glycosyltransferases and glutathione S-transferases. ||Produces stable conjugates for subsequent flavor release. || This process encompasses the activity of UDP-glucose-dependent glycosyltransferases that transfer glucose residues to monoterpene alcohols including linalool, geraniol, nerol, and citronellol, producing beta-glucoside conjugates that accumulate in vacuolar compartments where the acidic environment and absence of hydrolytic enzymes ensure precursor stability throughout ripening and harvest handling. ||The enzymatic mechanisms involve recognition of hydroxyl-bearing aglycone substrates by glycosyltransferase active sites, nucleophilic attack on UDP-glucose to form enzyme-glucoside intermediates, and transfer of the glucose moiety to the acceptor molecule with release of UDP as the leaving group, with reaction rates determined by enzyme expression levels, substrate availability, and cofactor concentrations that vary developmentally during berry maturation. ||Thiol precursor synthesis proceeds through glutathione S-transferase mediated conjugation of reduced glutathione to alpha-beta-unsaturated carbonyl compounds including mesityl oxide and related precursor aldehydes, followed by peptidase cleavage removing glutamate and glycine residues to generate cysteine conjugates that serve as the direct substrates for yeast carbon-sulfur lyase activity during fermentation. ||The cellular compartmentalization of flavor precursor synthesis involves cytosolic localization of most conjugating enzymes with subsequent transport of synthesized conjugates into vacuolar storage compartments through tonoplast-localized transporters, establishing the sequestered precursor pools that represent the dominant form of potential flavor compounds in ripe berries. ||Developmental regulation of precursor synthesis involves transcriptional activation of glycosyltransferase and glutathione S-transferase genes during the veraison-to-harvest period, with expression profiles showing variety-specific patterns that correlate with final precursor concentrations and distinguish aromatic from neutral cultivars at the molecular level. ||Temperature modulation of precursor synthesis reflects the thermal sensitivity of conjugating enzyme activities, with optimal synthesis rates at moderate temperatures of 20-28°C and reduced activity at temperature extremes that may limit precursor accumulation in climatically challenging vintages.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Bönisch F et al (2014) A UDP-glucose monoterpenol glucosyltransferase adds to the chemical diversity of the grapevine metabolome. Plant Physiology 165: 561-581 || Tominaga T et al (1998) Identification of cysteinylated aroma precursors. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 46: 5215-5219 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 298-302"
},

  "Amino_Acid_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "An Amino_Acid_Accumulation is a Precursor_Formation involving biosynthesis, protein turnover, and nitrogen remobilization from vegetative tissues elevating total amino nitrogen from 200–400 mg/L at véraison to 800–2000 mg/L at harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "free amino acid increase | berry nitrogen accumulation | amino acid pool development | yeast assimilable nitrogen accumulation |+ Aminosäure-Akkumulation | freie Aminosäure-Zunahme | Beeren-Stickstoff-Akkumulation | hefeverwertbarer Stickstoff-Anreicherung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay berries in Côte de Beaune, Burgundy during BBCH 83-89, amino acid accumulation increases total free amino acids from 320 to 1450 mg/L over 42 days, with proline increasing from 85 to 680 mg/L representing 47% of final total, arginine from 95 to 420 mg/L at 29%, and branched-chain amino acids from 18 to 85 mg/L, providing yeast assimilable nitrogen of 285 mg N/L under moderate vineyard nitrogen status and mean ripening temperature of 21°C.",
  "editor_note": "Amino_Acid_Accumulation is subclass of Precursor_Formation representing nitrogen-containing flavor precursor development. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis which involves conjugation reactions. ||Sibling to Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis and Precursor_Pool_Development. ||Key parameter is total amino nitrogen increase from 200-400 to 800-2000 mg/L. ||Proline typically 30-65% of total. ||Critical for fermentation performance. || This process involves the accumulation of diverse amino acid species with proline typically constituting 30-65% of total amino acids in ripe berries due to its role in osmotic adjustment and stress response, followed by arginine at 15-35% serving as the primary nitrogen storage form, glutamine and glutamate at 5-15% functioning as nitrogen assimilation intermediates, and the remaining amino acids including threonine, serine, alanine, and the branched-chain amino acids leucine, isoleucine, and valine contributing 10-25% collectively with particular significance as Ehrlich pathway substrates for higher alcohol production. ||The temporal progression of amino acid accumulation shows characteristic patterns with initial increases during early post-veraison driven by continued biosynthesis and nitrogen uptake, mid-ripening protein degradation contributing amino acids from turnover of photosynthetic and storage proteins, and late-ripening nitrogen remobilization from senescing leaves providing additional amino acid influx through phloem transport during the final weeks before harvest. ||Cellular distribution of accumulated amino acids involves cytosolic pools available for immediate metabolic utilization and vacuolar storage pools that buffer concentration fluctuations, with proline showing particularly strong vacuolar sequestration reflecting its role in osmotic regulation and stress protection during the dehydration associated with late-ripening berry concentration. ||Nitrogen fertilization and vineyard soil nitrogen status profoundly influence amino acid accumulation, with adequate nitrogen supply supporting accumulation to levels of 1500-2500 mg N/L considered optimal for fermentation performance, while nitrogen deficiency limits accumulation to potentially problematic levels below 500 mg N/L that may result in sluggish or incomplete fermentation. ||Cultivar variation in amino acid accumulation reflects genetic differences in nitrogen uptake efficiency, assimilation enzyme activities, and nitrogen partitioning between storage and metabolic pools, with varieties such as Riesling and Chardonnay typically showing higher total amino acid content than varieties such as Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot under equivalent nitrogen supply conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Bell SJ and Henschke PA (2005) Implications of nitrogen nutrition for grapes, fermentation and wine. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 11: 242-295 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 290-295 || Stines AP et al (1999) Proline and arginine accumulation in developing berries of Vitis vinifera. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 5: 14-23"
},

  "Precursor_Pool_Development": {
  "definition": "A Precursor_Pool_Development is a Precursor_Formation comprising the expansion of glycosidic, cysteinylated, and glutathionylated precursor reservoirs determining aromatic release potential during vinification.",
  "alternative_term": "bound flavor reservoir development | precursor pool expansion | conjugate pool accumulation | aromatic potential development |+ Vorläufer-Pool-Entwicklung | gebundenes Aroma-Reservoir-Entwicklung | Präkursor-Pool-Expansion | aromatisches Potential-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling berries in Rheingau, Germany during BBCH 81-89, precursor pool development establishes glycosidically-bound monoterpene pools increasing from 1.8 to 9.2 mg/L over 50 days, with bound linalool pool reaching 3.1 mg/L, bound alpha-terpineol 1.8 mg/L, and bound hotrienol precursors 0.9 mg/L, representing total aromatic potential 11-fold greater than free volatile concentrations of 0.82 mg/L at harvest under cool conditions averaging 16°C that favor precursor preservation.",
  "editor_note": "Precursor_Pool_Development is subclass of Precursor_Formation representing the cumulative establishment of precursor reservoirs. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis which describes individual reactions. ||Sibling to Flavor_Precursor_Synthesis and Amino_Acid_Accumulation. ||Integrates outputs of multiple biosynthetic pathways. ||Key parameter is total precursor pool size determining aromatic potential. ||Glycosidic precursors typically 2-15 mg/L in aromatic varieties. || This process integrates the outputs of multiple precursor biosynthetic pathways, with glycosidically-bound monoterpenes accumulating to pools of 2-15 mg/L in aromatic varieties representing 85-95% of total terpenoid content, cysteine-conjugated volatile thiol precursors reaching pools of 100-500 µg/L in Sauvignon Blanc and related varieties, and glycosidically-bound norisoprenoids including beta-damascenone and beta-ionone precursors accumulating to pools of 50-200 µg/L across diverse cultivars. ||The temporal dynamics of precursor pool development show variety-specific patterns with some cultivars exhibiting continuous linear accumulation throughout ripening while others demonstrate biphasic patterns with rapid early accumulation followed by plateau phases, reflecting differences in biosynthetic enzyme expression profiles and potential precursor turnover through hydrolytic or oxidative degradation. ||Cellular organization of precursor pools involves vacuolar sequestration as the primary storage mechanism, with tonoplast transport systems actively accumulating glycosidic conjugates against concentration gradients, establishing stable intracellular reservoirs protected from cytosolic glycosidase activities that would prematurely release volatile aglycones. ||The relationship between precursor pool size and wine aromatic intensity reflects the efficiency of subsequent release mechanisms, with larger pools generally correlating with greater aromatic potential though release efficiency varies with precursor structure, yeast strain capabilities, and winemaking conditions employed during vinification. ||Environmental factors including temperature, water status, and light exposure influence precursor pool development through effects on biosynthetic enzyme activities and precursor stability, with moderate stress conditions often enhancing accumulation compared to unstressed controls through activation of secondary metabolism pathways responsive to environmental signals. ||Viticultural practices targeting precursor pool development include canopy management to optimize light exposure of clusters, irrigation management to impose controlled water stress, and harvest timing to capture optimal precursor concentrations before potential late-season degradation, with these interventions collectively capable of modifying precursor pools by 50-200% relative to standard practices.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Gunata Z et al (1985) The aroma of grapes. Journal of Chromatography 331: 83-90 || Williams PJ et al (1989) Glycosidic precursors of varietal grape and wine flavor. In Flavor Chemistry Trends and Developments ACS Symposium Series 388: 35-48 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 295-305"
},

  "Flavor_Compound_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Compound_Synthesis is a Flavor_Development comprising enzymatic biosynthesis of free volatile flavor-active compounds including monoterpenoids, sesquiterpenoids, C13-norisoprenoids, methoxypyrazines, volatile thiols, esters, and lipid-derived C6 compounds in berry tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "volatile flavor biosynthesis | free flavor compound formation | flavor volatile synthesis | aroma compound biosynthesis |+ Aromaverbindungs-Synthese | flüchtige Aroma-Biosynthese | freie Aromaverbindungs-Bildung | Flavor-Volatil-Synthese",
  "example_of_usage": "In Muscat Blanc à Petits Grains berries in Frontignan, France during BBCH 83-89, flavor compound synthesis generates free monoterpenes increasing from 0.4 to 2.8 mg/L over 40 days, with free linalool reaching 1.2 mg/L, free geraniol 0.65 mg/L, and free nerol 0.35 mg/L, while concurrent glycosylation sequesters 85% of synthesized terpenoids as bound precursors, under Mediterranean conditions with mean temperature of 25°C and substantial diurnal variation.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Compound_Synthesis is parent class under Flavor_Development representing biosynthesis of free volatile compounds. ||Distinguishes from Precursor_Formation which generates conjugated forms. ||Contains subclasses Primary_Flavor_Formation, Secondary_Metabolite_Production, and Flavor_Pathway_Activation. ||Multiple pathways including MEP terpenoid, carotenoid cleavage, and amino acid-derived routes. ||Cultivar-specific expression determines synthesis capacity. || This process involves multiple biosynthetic pathways operating in distinct cellular compartments, with the methylerythritol phosphate pathway generating monoterpene precursors in plastids followed by modification reactions producing linalool, geraniol, nerol, and citronellol in cytosolic compartments, the carotenoid cleavage pathway generating norisoprenoid volatiles including beta-damascenone and beta-ionone through dioxygenase-mediated oxidation in chloroplasts and chromoplasts, and amino acid-derived pathways producing methoxypyrazines through O-methyltransferase activity in multiple cellular locations. ||The temporal progression of flavor compound synthesis shows compound-class-specific patterns with methoxypyrazines reaching maximum concentrations before veraison followed by progressive degradation during ripening, monoterpenes increasing throughout the post-veraison period with accumulation continuing until harvest in aromatic varieties, and C6 compounds showing complex dynamics reflecting the balance between lipoxygenase-mediated synthesis and oxidative degradation processes. ||Cultivar genetics fundamentally determine flavor compound synthesis capacity through variety-specific expression of biosynthetic enzymes, with aromatic varieties such as Muscat showing 10-100 fold higher monoterpene synthase expression than neutral varieties, Sauvignon Blanc demonstrating unique methoxypyrazine and thiol precursor synthesis capacity, and Cabernet Sauvignon expressing characteristic methoxypyrazine accumulation patterns distinct from aromatic cultivars. ||Environmental modulation of flavor compound synthesis occurs through temperature effects on enzyme activities and compound stability, light-mediated regulation of carotenoid and derived norisoprenoid synthesis, and water stress effects on secondary metabolism activation, with these factors interacting to produce the vintage variation and terroir expression characteristic of quality wine production. ||The partitioning between free volatile synthesis and conjugation to precursor forms represents a critical regulatory point determining flavor compound availability at harvest, with aromatic varieties typically maintaining 5-20% of terpenoids as free volatiles while neutral varieties may show less than 5% in free form.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation, genome organization and phylogeny of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Dunlevy JD et al (2009) A methyltransferase essential for methoxypyrazine-derived flavour. Plant Journal 59: 404-412 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 285-295"
},

  "Primary_Flavor_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Primary_Flavor_Formation is a Flavor_Compound_Synthesis comprising biosynthesis of flavor-active metabolites from carbohydrate, amino acid, and lipid pathways producing sugars, organic acids, and lipid-derived C6 volatiles as the foundational flavor matrix.",
  "alternative_term": "basic flavor compound synthesis | primary metabolite flavor formation | fundamental flavor biosynthesis | baseline flavor development |+ primäre Aromabildung | Grundaroma-Biosynthese | primäre Metabolit-Aromabildung | fundamentale Aroma-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Müller-Thurgau berries in Pfalz, Germany during BBCH 81-89, primary flavor formation establishes glucose accumulation from 45 to 115 g/L and fructose from 42 to 108 g/L over 45 days, organic acid reduction from 18.5 to 7.2 g/L titratable acidity, and C6 volatile synthesis with hexanal declining from 85 to 22 µg/L and trans-2-hexenal from 120 to 35 µg/L as berry maturity increases, establishing the sweet-tart-fresh flavor foundation under moderate continental conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Primary_Flavor_Formation is subclass of Flavor_Compound_Synthesis representing biosynthesis from primary metabolic pathways. ||Distinguishes from Secondary_Metabolite_Production which generates specialized compounds. ||Sibling to Secondary_Metabolite_Production and Flavor_Pathway_Activation. ||Includes sugars, organic acids, and lipid-derived C6 compounds. ||Establishes baseline flavor matrix for secondary metabolite overlay. || This process encompasses the continued accumulation of glucose and fructose to levels of 180-260 g/L at harvest providing the sweet taste component fundamental to ripe grape flavor perception, the modulation of malic and tartaric acid ratios determining the sourness and freshness characteristics, and the synthesis of C6 aldehydes and alcohols through lipoxygenase-mediated oxidation of membrane lipids generating hexanal, hexenal, and hexenol isomers that contribute green, grassy, and herbaceous notes particularly prominent in under-ripe or heavily processed berries. ||The biochemical pathways underlying primary flavor formation involve glycolytic and gluconeogenic carbon flux determining sugar accumulation rates, tricarboxylic acid cycle activity influencing organic acid pools, and membrane lipid turnover providing substrates for lipoxygenase and hydroperoxide lyase activities that generate C6 volatile compounds through oxidative cleavage of polyunsaturated fatty acids. ||Temporal dynamics of primary flavor formation show compound-specific patterns with sugar accumulation proceeding continuously throughout ripening following sigmoidal kinetics, organic acid reduction occurring primarily during early-to-mid ripening as previously described, and C6 compound synthesis showing complex patterns reflecting the balance between lipoxygenase activity and volatile degradation or conjugation processes. ||Environmental factors influence primary flavor formation through effects on carbon assimilation and partitioning, with adequate photosynthesis supporting sugar accumulation, temperature regulating organic acid metabolism, and oxidative conditions potentially enhancing lipid-derived volatile formation through increased lipoxygenase pathway flux. ||The contribution of primary flavor compounds to overall grape and wine flavor perception establishes the fundamental taste profile including sweetness, sourness, and basic aromatic character upon which the more complex secondary metabolite-derived flavors create variety-specific and terroir-expressive nuances distinguishing quality wines from ordinary productions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 250-265 || Kalua CM and Boss PK (2009) Evolution of volatile compounds during the development of Cabernet Sauvignon grapes. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 57: 3818-3830 || Conde C et al (2007) Biochemical changes throughout grape berry development. Food Chemistry 1: 1-22"
},

  "Secondary_Metabolite_Production": {
  "definition": "A Secondary_Metabolite_Production is a Flavor_Compound_Synthesis comprising biosynthesis of specialized flavor compounds from terpenoid, phenylpropanoid, and carotenoid pathways producing the variety-specific aromatic signature.",
  "alternative_term": "specialized metabolite synthesis | secondary flavor compound production | specialized volatile biosynthesis | terpenoid and phenolic production |+ Sekundärmetabolit-Produktion | spezialisierte Metabolit-Synthese | sekundäre Aromaverbindungs-Produktion | Terpenoid-und-Phenol-Biosynthese",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon berries in Margaret River, Australia during BBCH 79-89, secondary metabolite production shows methoxypyrazine concentrations peaking at 42 ng/L isobutyl-methoxypyrazine at BBCH 79 then declining to 8 ng/L at harvest through continued degradation, while beta-damascenone precursors increase from 15 to 85 µg/L and free norisoprenoids reach 12 µg/L, with total monoterpenes remaining low at 0.3 mg/L characteristic of this non-aromatic variety under warm maritime conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Secondary_Metabolite_Production is subclass of Flavor_Compound_Synthesis representing specialized pathway biosynthesis. ||Distinguishes from Primary_Flavor_Formation which derives from central metabolism. ||Sibling to Primary_Flavor_Formation and Flavor_Pathway_Activation. ||Includes terpenoids, norisoprenoids, methoxypyrazines, and phenolic volatiles. ||Cultivar-specific and environmentally responsive. ||Determines variety character. || This process involves the coordinated activity of specialized biosynthetic pathways with the methylerythritol phosphate pathway generating isopentenyl diphosphate and dimethylallyl diphosphate precursors for terpenoid synthesis in plastids, terpene synthases converting geranyl diphosphate to monoterpene scaffolds in cytosolic compartments, and carotenoid cleavage dioxygenases generating C13-norisoprenoid volatiles from beta-carotene and other carotenoid substrates in chromoplasts of ripening berries. ||The temporal regulation of secondary metabolite production shows characteristic induction during the veraison-to-harvest period, with monoterpene pathway genes activated 2-5 fold at veraison, norisoprenoid accumulation paralleling carotenoid degradation during color development and ripening, and methoxypyrazine synthesis reaching maximum before veraison followed by progressive catabolism during subsequent maturation. ||Cultivar genetics determine secondary metabolite production capacity through variety-specific expression of biosynthetic enzyme genes, with aromatic Muscat varieties expressing high levels of linalool synthase and geraniol synthase, Cabernet Sauvignon family varieties showing characteristic methoxypyrazine O-methyltransferase expression, and diverse varieties expressing different profiles of carotenoid cleavage dioxygenases generating distinct norisoprenoid signatures. ||Environmental modulation of secondary metabolite production occurs through light-mediated activation of terpenoid and carotenoid pathways, temperature effects on enzyme activities and compound stability, and water stress enhancement of secondary metabolism through activation of stress-responsive regulatory networks that upregulate specialized pathway gene expression. ||The ecological functions proposed for secondary metabolite production include attraction of seed dispersers through volatile signaling, defense against herbivores and pathogens through toxic or deterrent compounds, and protection against oxidative stress through antioxidant activities, though for viticulture the primary significance lies in the contribution to wine aromatic complexity and quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Mathieu S et al (2005) A carotenoid cleavage dioxygenase from Vitis vinifera L. Plant Journal 44: 612-621 || Dunlevy JD et al (2009) A methyltransferase essential for methoxypyrazine-derived flavour. Plant Journal 59: 404-412"
},

  "Flavor_Pathway_Activation": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Pathway_Activation is a Flavor_Compound_Synthesis manifesting as transcriptional upregulation of terpene synthases, carotenoid cleavage dioxygenases, O-methyltransferases, and related biosynthetic enzymes establishing flavor synthesis capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "flavor biosynthesis induction | secondary pathway activation | flavor enzyme induction | aroma pathway upregulation |+ Aroma-Stoffwechselweg-Aktivierung | Flavor-Biosynthese-Induktion | sekundärer Stoffwechselweg-Aktivierung | Aroma-Enzym-Induktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Moscato Giallo berries in Trentino, Italy during BBCH 81-85, flavor pathway activation induces linalool synthase gene expression 8.5-fold between pre-veraison and 14 days post-veraison, with corresponding enzyme activity increasing from 2.5 to 18.5 nmol/min/g fresh weight in exocarp tissue, enabling subsequent monoterpene accumulation that reaches 4.2 mg/L total terpenoids at harvest, with activation coinciding with ABA increase from 0.2 to 1.8 µg/g fresh weight during the same period.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Pathway_Activation is subclass of Flavor_Compound_Synthesis representing the regulatory initiation of biosynthetic capacity. ||Distinguishes from Primary_Flavor_Formation and Secondary_Metabolite_Production which describe compound synthesis. ||Sibling to those classes. ||Occurs during 7-14 days post-veraison. ||Involves transcriptional induction of terpene synthases, CCDs, and related enzymes. ||Cultivar-specific activation magnitude determines aromatic potential. || This process involves signal transduction cascades triggered by developmental cues at veraison including abscisic acid accumulation, ethylene signaling, and sugar sensing, with downstream transcription factor activation inducing coordinated expression of pathway genes within the 7-14 day period following veraison onset when biosynthetic capacity is established for subsequent flavor compound accumulation. ||The molecular mechanisms underlying flavor pathway activation include MYB and bHLH transcription factor binding to promoter elements of terpenoid pathway genes, hormone-responsive element activation linking ABA signaling to secondary metabolism induction, and chromatin remodeling events that transition flavor biosynthesis genes from repressed to transcriptionally active states during the developmental transition at veraison. ||Cultivar variation in flavor pathway activation reflects genetic differences in transcription factor expression, promoter element sequences, and signal transduction pathway sensitivity that collectively determine the magnitude and timing of biosynthetic gene induction, with aromatic varieties showing 5-20 fold higher induction of monoterpene synthase genes compared to neutral varieties during the veraison transition. ||Environmental modulation of flavor pathway activation occurs through light-responsive elements in terpenoid pathway gene promoters that enhance expression under appropriate irradiance conditions, temperature-sensitive regulatory mechanisms that may accelerate or delay pathway induction, and stress-responsive signaling pathways that activate secondary metabolism under conditions of water deficit, pathogen challenge, or oxidative stress. ||The relationship between pathway activation timing and final flavor compound concentrations reflects the integration of biosynthetic capacity with substrate availability and compound stability, with early activation in the ripening season potentially maximizing accumulation time while late activation may limit total synthesis despite equivalent enzyme activities due to shortened biosynthetic windows before harvest.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Castellarin SD et al (2011) Transcriptional regulation of anthocyanin biosynthesis in ripening fruits of grapevine. Plant Physiology 156: 1232-1246 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 285-295"
},

  "Flavor_Compound_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Compound_Accumulation is a Flavor_Development consisting of progressive concentration increase of flavor-active metabolites in berry tissues over the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "flavor metabolite accumulation | aroma compound build-up | volatile accumulation | flavor concentration increase |+ Aromaverbindungs-Akkumulation | Aroma-Metabolit-Anreicherung | Volatil-Akkumulation | Geschmacksstoff-Konzentrations-Zunahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In Torrontés berries in Cafayate, Argentina during BBCH 83-89, flavor compound accumulation increases total free monoterpenes from 0.6 to 4.8 mg/L and total bound monoterpenes from 2.1 to 12.5 mg/L over 42 days, with linalool accumulating from 0.25 to 1.85 mg/L free and 0.8 to 4.2 mg/L bound, representing net accumulation rates of 0.29 mg/L total monoterpenes per day during peak mid-ripening phase under high-altitude conditions at 1700 m elevation with intense solar radiation and cool nights of 12°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Compound_Accumulation is parent class under Flavor_Development representing quantitative increase in flavor metabolites. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Compound_Synthesis which describes biosynthetic processes. ||Contains subclasses Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up, Flavor_Intensity_Increase, and Flavor_Complexity_Development. ||Duration 35-50 days. ||Key characteristic is net positive balance between synthesis and degradation producing concentration increase. || This process integrates the net balance between ongoing biosynthesis generating new flavor compounds and potential losses through volatilization, oxidative degradation, and enzymatic transformation, with successful accumulation requiring that synthesis rates exceed loss rates to produce the monotonic increase in total flavor compound content characteristic of normal ripening progression. ||The cellular mechanisms supporting flavor compound accumulation involve vacuolar sequestration of both free volatiles and glycosidic precursors through tonoplast transport systems that actively import synthesized compounds against concentration gradients, establishing intracellular reservoirs protected from degradative processes occurring in cytosolic compartments where oxidases and other catabolic enzymes maintain activity throughout ripening. ||The temporal dynamics of flavor compound accumulation show compound-class-specific patterns with monoterpenes typically accumulating continuously throughout ripening in aromatic varieties, norisoprenoids showing accelerated accumulation during mid-to-late ripening coincident with carotenoid degradation, and methoxypyrazines uniquely demonstrating net decline rather than accumulation as degradation exceeds residual synthesis during the post-veraison period. ||Cultivar genetics profoundly influence flavor compound accumulation through effects on both biosynthetic capacity determining synthesis rates and transport efficiency affecting retention, with aromatic varieties such as Muscat achieving total monoterpene accumulation of 5-15 mg/L compared to neutral varieties such as Chardonnay accumulating less than 0.5 mg/L under equivalent conditions. ||Environmental factors modulate flavor compound accumulation through temperature effects on enzyme activities and compound volatility, light exposure influencing biosynthetic pathway activity, and water status affecting berry size and therefore concentration effects, with moderate conditions generally favoring optimal accumulation compared to environmental extremes that may either limit synthesis or accelerate degradation. ||The relationship between flavor compound accumulation and wine quality reflects the fundamental importance of adequate aromatic intensity for sensory impact, with research demonstrating threshold concentrations required for perception of individual compounds and synergistic interactions among accumulated compounds that enhance overall aromatic complexity beyond the sum of individual contributions. ||Viticultural practices targeting flavor compound accumulation include canopy management optimizing cluster microclimate, irrigation strategies balancing vine stress with metabolic function, and harvest timing decisions capturing optimal accumulation before potential late-season degradation compromises aromatic quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 285-310 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30 || Günata Z et al (1985) The aroma of grapes. Journal of Chromatography 331: 83-90"
},

  "Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up is a Flavor_Compound_Accumulation exhibiting daily net accumulation of 0.05–0.3 mg/L total flavor volatiles producing a monotonic upward trajectory in aromatic content from véraison through harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "continuous flavor accumulation | sustained aroma increase | incremental flavor development | ongoing volatile build-up |+ progressive Aroma-Aufbau | kontinuierliche Aroma-Akkumulation | anhaltende Geschmacks-Zunahme | schrittweise Volatil-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Viognier berries in Condrieu, Rhône Valley during BBCH 83-89, progressive flavor build-up increases total monoterpenes at consistent rates of 0.08 mg/L per day over 38 days, with free linalool progressing from 0.15 to 0.85 mg/L, free geraniol from 0.08 to 0.42 mg/L, and total bound terpenoids from 1.2 to 4.8 mg/L, demonstrating sustained accumulation without plateau under warm days of 30°C and moderate nights of 18°C that maintain biosynthetic enzyme activities throughout ripening.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up is subclass of Flavor_Compound_Accumulation representing the continuous nature of accumulation. ||Distinguishes from plateau or declining patterns. ||Sibling to Flavor_Intensity_Increase and Flavor_Complexity_Development. ||Key characteristic is sustained positive accumulation rates of 0.05-0.3 mg/L per day. ||Linear or accelerating trajectory throughout ripening. ||Predictive value for harvest timing. || This process reflects the sustained operation of flavor biosynthetic pathways at rates exceeding compound loss through volatilization and degradation, maintaining positive accumulation balance throughout ripening rather than reaching plateau phases or exhibiting decline that would indicate biosynthetic limitation or accelerated catabolism. ||The temporal characteristics of progressive flavor build-up show variety-specific accumulation curves, with aromatic varieties typically demonstrating linear or slightly accelerating accumulation patterns as biosynthetic enzyme activities increase during ripening, while neutral varieties may show more modest accumulation rates that plateau earlier in the ripening season due to lower biosynthetic capacity. ||Cellular mechanisms supporting progressive build-up involve continued induction of biosynthetic gene expression maintaining enzyme activities, efficient vacuolar transport sequestering synthesized compounds, and membrane integrity preventing excessive volatilization losses, with coordination among these processes ensuring sustained accumulation throughout the extended ripening period. ||The quantitative aspects of progressive flavor build-up vary substantially among compound classes, with monoterpenes in aromatic varieties showing accumulation of 0.1-0.4 mg/L per day during peak periods, norisoprenoid precursors accumulating at 2-8 µg/L per day, and amino acid-derived flavor precursors increasing at 20-50 mg/L per day reflecting the higher absolute concentrations of this compound class. ||Environmental conditions influence progressive build-up rates through temperature effects on biosynthetic enzyme activities, with optimal temperatures of 20-28°C supporting maximum accumulation rates while temperature extremes may reduce daily accumulation through either limited synthesis at cool temperatures or accelerated degradation at high temperatures. ||The consistency of progressive flavor build-up provides predictive value for harvest timing, with accumulation rate measurements during mid-ripening enabling estimation of final flavor compound concentrations at projected harvest dates, supporting quality optimization through informed picking decisions that capture optimal aromatic development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 295-305 || Marais J (1983) Terpenes in the aroma of grapes and wines. South African Journal of Enology and Viticulture 4: 49-58 || Wilson B et al (1984) Determination of free and bound monoterpenes in Muscat grapes. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 35: 95-100"
},

  "Flavor_Intensity_Increase": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Intensity_Increase is a Flavor_Compound_Accumulation manifesting as progressive elevation of flavor compound concentrations above sensory perception thresholds yielding pronounced varietal character at optimal maturity.",
  "alternative_term": "aromatic potency increase | flavor strength enhancement | sensory intensity development | aroma impact increase |+ Aroma-Intensitäts-Zunahme | Geschmacks-Stärke-Erhöhung | sensorische Intensitäts-Entwicklung | Aroma-Wirkung-Steigerung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer berries in Alsace, France during BBCH 85-89, flavor intensity increase elevates free linalool from 0.4 mg/L at 1.6-fold perception threshold to 2.2 mg/L at 8.8-fold threshold over 35 days, with total odor activity value of monoterpene fraction increasing from 12 to 85 threshold units, and trained panel intensity ratings progressing from 3.2 to 7.8 on 10-point scale for floral-rose character, demonstrating the sensory impact of continued accumulation under cool continental conditions averaging 19°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Intensity_Increase is subclass of Flavor_Compound_Accumulation representing sensory potency enhancement. ||Distinguishes from Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up which emphasizes quantity. ||Sibling to Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up and Flavor_Complexity_Development. ||Key parameter is odor activity value increase from sub-threshold to 2-10 fold supra-threshold. ||Relates concentration to perception threshold. ||Quality determinant for harvest timing. || This process reflects the relationship between absolute flavor compound concentrations and human sensory perception thresholds, with intensity increase occurring as compounds accumulate from sub-threshold levels of 10-50% of perception threshold at veraison to supra-threshold concentrations of 2-10 fold above threshold at harvest that generate clear sensory impact and varietal recognition. ||The sensory significance of flavor intensity increase varies among compound classes based on their respective perception thresholds, with potent odorants such as methoxypyrazines perceptible at nanogram-per-liter concentrations requiring only modest absolute accumulation for intensity impact, while less potent compounds such as certain monoterpene alcohols require milligram-per-liter accumulation to achieve equivalent sensory prominence. ||The measurement of flavor intensity increase integrates analytical quantification of compound concentrations with sensory evaluation methods including odor activity value calculations expressing concentration as multiples of perception threshold, trained panel assessments rating aromatic intensity on structured scales, and consumer studies correlating chemical composition with perceived quality attributes. ||Cultivar genetics determine the potential for flavor intensity increase through variety-specific biosynthetic capacities that establish maximum achievable compound concentrations, with aromatic varieties capable of producing intense floral, fruity, or spicy aromatics while neutral varieties develop more subtle aromatic profiles even at full physiological ripeness. ||Environmental and viticultural factors modulate flavor intensity increase through effects on both absolute accumulation and perception threshold modification, with berry composition factors including sugar content and pH influencing volatile release and perception in complex matrix effects that extend beyond simple concentration relationships. ||The optimization of flavor intensity increase represents a primary quality objective in premium wine grape production, with harvest timing decisions targeting concentration levels that maximize sensory impact while avoiding potential overripeness that may shift aromatic profiles toward less desirable dried fruit or oxidized characters.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Ferreira V et al (2000) Quantitative determination of the odorants of young red wines. Journal of the Science of Food and Agriculture 80: 1659-1667 || Guth H (1997) Quantitation and sensory studies of character impact odorants of different white wine varieties. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 45: 3027-3032 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 300-310"
},

  "Flavor_Complexity_Development": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Complexity_Development is a Flavor_Compound_Accumulation comprising concurrent accumulation of terpenoids, norisoprenoids, thiols, esters, and other volatile classes producing multifaceted aromatic profiles transcending simple varietal character.",
  "alternative_term": "aromatic complexity increase | flavor multidimensionality development | aroma diversification | complex flavor formation |+ Aroma-Komplexitäts-Entwicklung | Geschmacks-Vielschichtigkeit-Entwicklung | aromatische Diversifizierung | komplexe Aroma-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling berries in Wachau, Austria during BBCH 83-89, flavor complexity development establishes concurrent accumulation of free monoterpenes reaching 1.8 mg/L with 8 individual compounds above threshold, norisoprenoid precursors at 125 µg/L contributing 4 distinct aroma notes, and volatile thiol precursors at 185 µg/L providing 3 additional sensory dimensions, with trained panel complexity ratings increasing from 4.5 to 8.2 on 10-point scale as the number of identifiable aromatic notes increases from 6 to 14 over 48 days of ripening under cool conditions averaging 17°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Complexity_Development is subclass of Flavor_Compound_Accumulation representing diversification of aromatic profile. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Intensity_Increase which emphasizes potency. ||Sibling to Progressive_Flavor_Build_Up and Flavor_Intensity_Increase. ||Key characteristic is parallel accumulation of multiple compound classes. ||Measured by number of distinct aromatic notes and complexity indices. ||Quality differentiator for premium wines. || This process involves the parallel operation of multiple biosynthetic pathways each contributing distinct compound classes with characteristic sensory attributes, including floral notes from monoterpene alcohols, fruity-tropical character from volatile thiols and esters, spicy nuances from sesquiterpenes and phenolic derivatives, and complex background aromatics from norisoprenoids and lipid-derived compounds that collectively produce the layered sensory experience associated with quality wines. ||The temporal dynamics of flavor complexity development show compound-class-specific accumulation patterns that create evolving aromatic profiles throughout ripening, with early development of green-herbaceous character from C6 compounds and methoxypyrazines transitioning to floral-fruity dominance as monoterpenes and norisoprenoids accumulate during mid-to-late ripening, and final integration phases during the last weeks before harvest establishing the balanced complexity of optimally ripe fruit. ||Sensory evaluation of flavor complexity development employs multidimensional assessment methods including descriptive analysis mapping individual aromatic attributes, complexity indices integrating the number and balance of perceived notes, and trained panel ratings of overall aromatic complexity that correlate with wine quality potential and consumer preference. ||Cultivar genetics establish baseline complexity potential through variety-specific expression of multiple biosynthetic pathway genes, with certain varieties such as Riesling demonstrating inherent complexity through balanced accumulation of terpenoids, norisoprenoids, and volatile thiols, while other varieties may require specific terroir or viticultural conditions to achieve comparable aromatic multidimensionality. ||Environmental factors profoundly influence complexity development through differential effects on individual biosynthetic pathways, with the combination of adequate light exposure for terpenoid synthesis, moderate temperatures for norisoprenoid accumulation, and appropriate vine stress for thiol precursor formation creating the conditions necessary for optimal complexity development in premium vineyard sites.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30 || Ferreira V (2010) Volatile aroma compounds and wine sensory attributes. In Managing Wine Quality Vol 1 Woodhead Publishing pp 3-28 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 300-310"
},

  "Flavor_Profile_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Flavor_Profile_Maturation is a Flavor_Development consisting of the terminal qualitative refinement of accumulated flavor compounds during the final 10–21 days pre-harvest establishing the balanced varietal and terroir-expressive aromatic profile.",
  "alternative_term": "flavor profile completion | aromatic maturation | flavor character finalization | aroma profile ripening |+ Aromaprofil-Reifung | Geschmacksprofil-Vollendung | aromatische Reifung | Aroma-Charakter-Finalisierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir berries in Côte de Nuits, Burgundy during BBCH 87-89, flavor profile maturation refines the aromatic profile over the final 18 days before harvest, with methoxypyrazine declining from 12 to 4 ng/L eliminating green character, beta-damascenone increasing from 2.8 to 4.5 µg/L enhancing fruity complexity, and trained panel ratings for varietal typicity increasing from 6.2 to 8.5 while green-herbaceous scores decline from 4.8 to 1.5 on 10-point scales, establishing the characteristic red-fruit and earthy profile under mean temperatures of 22°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavor_Profile_Maturation is parent class under Flavor_Development representing the terminal qualitative refinement phase. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Compound_Accumulation which emphasizes quantity. ||Contains subclasses Mature_Flavor_Expression, Cultivar_Specific_Flavor, and Optimal_Flavor_Development. ||Duration 10-21 days before harvest. ||Emphasizes balance, harmony, and typicity rather than concentration. ||Primary harvest timing criterion. || This process involves subtle transformations in flavor compound composition including shifts in terpenoid profiles through interconversion reactions, modification of norisoprenoid balances through continued carotenoid degradation, and evolution of precursor-to-free-volatile ratios that determine immediate aromatic expression versus aromatic potential requiring winemaking intervention for release. ||The qualitative aspects of flavor profile maturation extend beyond simple concentration changes to encompass integration of disparate aromatic elements into cohesive sensory impressions, reduction of green-unripe character through continued methoxypyrazine degradation and C6 compound metabolism, and enhancement of ripe-fruit character through late-stage accumulation of ester and norisoprenoid compounds associated with optimal maturity. ||Sensory evaluation of flavor profile maturation employs holistic assessment methods including overall quality ratings, balance and harmony scores, and varietal typicity judgments that integrate multiple aromatic attributes into unified quality determinations, complementing analytical measurements of individual compound concentrations. ||The timing of flavor profile maturation relative to sugar accumulation and acid reduction varies among cultivars and growing conditions, with certain varieties achieving optimal flavor maturity coincident with target sugar levels while others may require extended hang-time for complete flavor development potentially at the cost of elevated sugar or reduced acidity. ||Environmental conditions during the final ripening phase critically influence flavor profile maturation, with moderate temperatures of 20-26°C favoring continued flavor refinement while excessive heat may accelerate degradation of heat-labile compounds or shift aromatic profiles toward overripe character before optimal balance is achieved. ||The assessment of flavor profile maturation status represents a primary criterion for harvest timing decisions in quality-focused viticulture, with sensory evaluation of berry samples often taking precedence over analytical measurements in determining optimal picking dates for premium wine production.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 305-315 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 43: 101-110 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30"
},

  "Mature_Flavor_Expression": {
  "definition": "A Mature_Flavor_Expression is a Flavor_Profile_Maturation defined by stabilized flavor compound composition at harvest-appropriate levels integrating varietal character, ripeness indicators, and site-specific nuances.",
  "alternative_term": "ripe flavor character | mature aromatic profile | harvest-ready flavor expression | optimal flavor state |+ reife Aroma-Expression | reifer Geschmacks-Charakter | erntereifes Aromaprofil | optimaler Aroma-Zustand",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner berries in Wagram, Austria at BBCH 89, mature flavor expression is characterized by total monoterpenes of 0.95 mg/L with citrus-floral balance, norisoprenoid precursors of 145 µg/L providing stone-fruit complexity, methoxypyrazine below detection threshold of 2 ng/L ensuring absence of green notes, and volatile thiol precursors of 210 µg/L contributing characteristic white pepper nuance, with trained panel overall quality rating of 8.4 on 10-point scale and varietal typicity score of 8.7 indicating achievement of optimal maturity under moderate continental conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Mature_Flavor_Expression is subclass of Flavor_Profile_Maturation representing the achieved quality state at ripening completion. ||Distinguishes from Optimal_Flavor_Development which emphasizes process optimization. ||Sibling to Cultivar_Specific_Flavor and Optimal_Flavor_Development. ||Characterized by specific compositional markers and sensory attributes. ||Integrates intensity, complexity, and balance. ||Harvest maturity indicator. || This state encompasses specific compositional markers including monoterpene concentrations of 1-5 mg/L in aromatic varieties providing characteristic floral-fruity impact, norisoprenoid levels of 50-200 µg/L contributing complexity and aging potential, minimal residual methoxypyrazine below 10-15 ng/L ensuring absence of green-unripe character, and balanced thiol precursor concentrations providing tropical fruit potential without excessive pungency in the finished wine. ||The sensory characteristics of mature flavor expression include predominance of ripe-fruit aromatics over green-herbaceous notes, integration of multiple aromatic elements into harmonious overall impression, appropriate intensity matching varietal expectations, and absence of overripe or degraded character indicating optimal harvest timing capture. ||Assessment of mature flavor expression employs multiple evaluation methods including trained panel sensory analysis rating specific aromatic attributes and overall quality, berry tasting protocols assessing flavor development through direct consumption of representative samples, and analytical profiling quantifying marker compounds associated with optimal maturity for specific cultivars and wine styles. ||Temperature history during the final ripening phase influences mature flavor expression through effects on late-stage biosynthesis and compound stability, with optimal conditions maintaining biosynthetic activities while avoiding thermal degradation that could compromise accumulated aromatic quality. ||The relationship between mature flavor expression and other ripeness parameters including sugar content, acidity, and phenolic development varies among cultivars and production objectives, with some varieties achieving optimal flavor expression coincident with target compositional values while others may require management decisions balancing competing quality factors for overall optimization.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 305-315 || Reynolds AG (2010) Managing Wine Quality Vol 1 Viticulture and Wine Quality Woodhead Publishing || Coombe BG and McCarthy MG (2000) Dynamics of grape berry growth. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 6: 131-135"
},

  "Cultivar_Specific_Flavor": {
  "definition": "A Cultivar_Specific_Flavor is a Flavor_Development manifesting as the genetically determined aromatic signature realized through variety-specific expression of flavor biosynthetic enzymes producing distinctive compound profiles enabling varietal identification.",
  "alternative_term": "varietal flavor character | variety-specific aroma | genetic flavor signature | cultivar aromatic identity |+ sortenspezifischer Geschmack | Rebsorten-Aroma-Charakter | genetische Aroma-Signatur | Kultivar-aromatische-Identität",
  "example_of_usage": "In Muscat Ottonel berries in Burgenland, Austria during BBCH 85-89, cultivar specific flavor develops through variety-characteristic accumulation of linalool to 1.8 mg/L and geraniol to 1.2 mg/L providing the distinctive Muscat floral character, with linalool-to-geraniol ratio of 1.5 typical for this variety, concurrent low methoxypyrazine of 3 ng/L distinguishing from Sauvignon-type varieties, and trained panel varietal typicity rating of 8.9 on 10-point scale confirming achievement of characteristic Muscat Ottonel expression under warm Pannonian conditions averaging 24°C.",
  "editor_note": "Cultivar_Specific_Flavor is subclass of Flavor_Profile_Maturation representing genetically-determined varietal character. ||Distinguishes from Mature_Flavor_Expression which describes general maturity. ||Sibling to Mature_Flavor_Expression and Optimal_Flavor_Development. ||Determined by variety-specific enzyme expression. ||Enables varietal identification. ||Typicity criterion for quality assessment. ||Modified but not determined by environment. || This phenomenon reflects the genetic architecture of flavor biosynthesis with variety-specific alleles of terpene synthases, O-methyltransferases, carotenoid cleavage dioxygenases, and related enzymes determining which compound classes accumulate to sensory-relevant concentrations, producing the floral-Muscat character of aromatic varieties through high monoterpene synthase expression, the herbaceous-tropical profile of Sauvignon Blanc through methoxypyrazine and thiol pathway activities, and the subtle stone-fruit nuances of Chardonnay through specific norisoprenoid accumulation patterns. ||The molecular basis of cultivar specific flavor involves transcriptional regulation through variety-specific promoter sequences and transcription factor expression, structural variation in enzyme-coding genes affecting catalytic activities and substrate specificities, and copy number variation in gene families that influences total biosynthetic capacity for individual compound classes. ||Sensory recognition of cultivar specific flavor enables variety identification through trained panel assessment and supports appellation regulations requiring varietal labeling accuracy, with experienced tasters achieving 70-90% correct identification rates for major varieties based on aromatic character alone, demonstrating the distinctiveness and reproducibility of varietal flavor signatures. ||Environmental modulation of cultivar specific flavor occurs through terroir effects that enhance, diminish, or modify the genetically-determined baseline profile, with certain sites and vintages producing particularly intense or characteristic varietal expression while others may yield atypical profiles requiring blending or stylistic adjustment to meet consumer expectations. ||The preservation of cultivar specific flavor through winemaking represents a primary quality objective in varietal wine production, with gentle processing, appropriate yeast selection, and careful oxidation management employed to maintain the distinctive aromatic signatures established during grape development rather than introducing winemaking-derived flavors that mask varietal character.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Ebeler SE and Thorngate JH (2009) Wine chemistry and flavor. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 57: 8098-8108 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30"
},

  "Optimal_Flavor_Development": {
  "definition": "An Optimal_Flavor_Development is a Flavor_Development bearing the disposition to produce maximum expression of desirable aromatic characteristics at harvest under given environmental, viticultural, and genetic conditions across the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "ideal flavor development | maximum flavor quality | optimal aromatic expression | peak flavor achievement |+ optimale Aromaentwicklung | ideale Geschmacksentwicklung | maximale Aroma-Qualität | Spitzen-Aroma-Erreichung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sémillon berries in Pessac-Léognan, Bordeaux during BBCH 85-89, optimal flavor development achieves free monoterpene concentration of 0.65 mg/L at 4.2-fold average perception threshold, norisoprenoid precursors of 165 µg/L providing 5 distinct aromatic notes, volatile thiol precursors of 320 µg/L enabling tropical-citrus complexity, with trained panel overall quality rating of 9.1 on 10-point scale, complexity score of 8.8, and varietal typicity of 8.6, representing near-ideal expression under exceptional vintage conditions with mean ripening temperature of 23°C, 15% vine water deficit, and 40% cluster-zone leaf removal optimizing light exposure.",
  "editor_note": "Optimal_Flavor_Development is subclass of Flavor_Profile_Maturation representing the quality ideal for flavor processes. ||Distinguishes from descriptive classes by emphasizing optimization. ||Sibling to Mature_Flavor_Expression and Cultivar_Specific_Flavor. ||Integrates intensity, complexity, balance, and typicity. ||Requires coordination of genetics, environment, and management. ||Benchmark for quality assessment. ||Vintage-dependent achievement. || This concept integrates multiple quality dimensions including sufficient flavor intensity exceeding perception thresholds by factors of 3-10 for key impact compounds, adequate complexity with 10-15 or more distinct aromatic notes contributing to overall impression, appropriate balance between fruity-floral and green-herbaceous elements favoring ripe character, and strong varietal typicity enabling clear identification and meeting consumer expectations for specific cultivars. ||The achievement of optimal flavor development requires coordination among environmental factors including moderate temperatures of 20-26°C supporting biosynthetic enzyme activities, adequate but not excessive light exposure promoting secondary metabolism without thermal stress, and appropriate vine water status imposing mild stress that enhances flavor compound accumulation without compromising photosynthetic capacity or berry physiological function. ||Viticultural practices supporting optimal flavor development encompass canopy management ensuring cluster microclimate optimization, crop load adjustment balancing vine capacity with fruit quality objectives, irrigation scheduling imposing controlled water deficit during the post-veraison period, and harvest timing capturing peak flavor quality before potential late-season degradation or overripeness shifts aromatic profiles away from optimal expression. ||The assessment of optimal flavor development employs integrated evaluation methods combining analytical quantification of marker compounds with sensory assessment of overall quality, with premium wine production requiring achievement of target values across multiple parameters rather than optimization of individual factors in isolation. ||Vintage variation in optimal flavor development potential reflects climatic differences affecting biosynthetic processes, with favorable years achieving near-ideal expression while challenging vintages may require management intervention or quality expectations adjustment to accommodate suboptimal development conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 305-315 || Reynolds AG (2010) Managing Wine Quality Vol 1 Viticulture and Wine Quality Woodhead Publishing || Jackson RS (2020) Wine Science Principles and Applications 5th Ed Chapter 6"
},

  "Aroma_Development": {
  "definition": "An Aroma_Development is a Ripening comprising biosynthesis, conjugation to precursor forms, and accumulation of volatile aromatic compounds responsible for olfactory perception of grape and wine character over the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "aromatic compound development | volatile aroma formation | olfactory compound synthesis | scent development |+ Aroma-Entwicklung | aromatische Verbindungs-Entwicklung | Duft-Entwicklung | olfaktorische Verbindungs-Synthese",
  "example_of_usage": "In Muscat à Petits Grains berries in Beaumes-de-Venise, Rhône Valley during BBCH 81-89, aroma development establishes total monoterpene content increasing from 1.2 to 8.5 mg/L over 45 days, with free volatiles rising from 0.3 to 1.8 mg/L and bound precursors from 0.9 to 6.7 mg/L, concurrent with norisoprenoid precursor accumulation from 25 to 145 µg/L, establishing the characteristic intense floral-grape Muscat aromatic profile under warm Mediterranean conditions averaging 26°C with substantial day-night temperature variation.",
  "editor_note": "Aroma_Development is parent class under Ripening representing all volatile aromatic compound processes. ||Distinguishes from Flavor_Development which encompasses broader sensory attributes including taste. ||Contains subclasses Aroma_Precursor_Formation, Volatile_Compound_Synthesis, Terpene_Accumulation, and Aroma_Profile_Maturation. ||Duration 35-50 days post-veraison. ||Emphasizes olfactory perception specifically. ||Cultivar-specific expression patterns determine aromatic potential. || This process encompasses the biosynthesis of diverse volatile compound classes including monoterpenoids contributing floral and citrus notes, sesquiterpenoids providing spicy and woody character, C13-norisoprenoids generating complex fruity and floral nuances, volatile thiols imparting tropical and passion fruit aromatics, esters contributing fruity sweetness, aldehydes and alcohols providing green and fatty notes, and methoxypyrazines generating herbaceous-vegetative character that collectively define the aromatic identity of individual grape varieties and vineyard sites. ||The distinction between aroma development and flavor development reflects sensory modality differences, with aroma specifically denoting volatile compounds perceived through olfactory receptors in the nasal epithelium either orthonasally during sniffing or retronasally during consumption, while flavor encompasses the broader integration of taste, aroma, and trigeminal sensations contributing to overall sensory experience. ||Cellular localization of aroma development processes shows tissue-specific patterns with monoterpenoid biosynthesis concentrated in exocarp cells where terpene synthase expression reaches highest levels, norisoprenoid generation associated with chromoplast-containing cells undergoing carotenoid degradation, and thiol precursor synthesis occurring predominantly in mesocarp parenchyma where cysteine conjugation machinery shows primary localization. ||The temporal progression of aroma development follows compound-class-specific trajectories with methoxypyrazines reaching maximum before veraison then declining, monoterpenes accumulating progressively throughout post-veraison ripening, and norisoprenoids showing late-ripening accumulation coincident with advanced carotenoid degradation during the final weeks before harvest. ||Cultivar genetics fundamentally determine aroma development potential through variety-specific expression of biosynthetic pathway genes, with aromatic varieties such as Muscat, Gewürztraminer, and Riesling demonstrating elevated monoterpenoid pathway activity, Sauvignon Blanc and related varieties showing distinctive thiol precursor synthesis capacity, and Cabernet family varieties expressing characteristic methoxypyrazine accumulation patterns. ||Environmental modulation of aroma development occurs through temperature effects on biosynthetic enzyme activities and compound volatility, light exposure influencing terpenoid and carotenoid pathway regulation, and water stress affecting secondary metabolism through stress-responsive pathway activation. ||The relationship between aroma development and wine quality reflects the fundamental importance of aromatic character for consumer perception and preference, with adequate aromatic intensity, complexity, and typicity representing primary quality criteria in premium wine grape production.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 285-310 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30 || Lund ST and Bohlmann J (2006) The molecular basis for wine grape quality. Annals of Botany 98: 985-1010"
},

  "Aroma_Precursor_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Aroma_Precursor_Formation is an Aroma_Development comprising enzymatic conjugation of volatile aromatic compounds with sugar moieties, amino acids, or other carrier molecules producing stable non-volatile precursor compounds.",
  "alternative_term": "bound aroma compound formation | glycosidic aroma precursor synthesis | conjugated volatile formation | aroma precursor biosynthesis |+ Aroma-Vorläufer-Bildung | gebundene Aroma-Verbindungs-Bildung | glycosidische Aroma-Vorläufer-Synthese | konjugierte Volatil-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Fernão Pires berries in Bucelas, Portugal during BBCH 83-89, aroma precursor formation accumulates glycosidically-bound monoterpenes from 1.5 to 7.2 mg/L over 40 days, with bound linalool increasing from 0.4 to 2.1 mg/L, bound alpha-terpineol from 0.3 to 1.4 mg/L, and thiol precursor cysteine-3-mercaptohexanol from 45 to 185 µg/L, representing 88% of total monoterpenoids and 94% of total thiols in conjugated precursor forms at harvest under Atlantic-influenced conditions averaging 22°C.",
  "editor_note": "Aroma_Precursor_Formation is parent class under Aroma_Development representing conjugation of volatiles to carrier molecules. ||Distinguishes from Volatile_Compound_Synthesis which generates free aromatics. ||Contains subclasses Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis, Bound_Aroma_Accumulation, and Precursor_Pool_Building. ||Typically 85-95% of monoterpenoids exist as bound precursors. ||Determines aromatic potential requiring winemaking release. || This process involves multiple conjugation mechanisms including glycosyltransferase-mediated attachment of glucose, rhamnose, arabinose, or apiose residues to monoterpenols, sesquiterpenols, and norisoprenoids forming glycosidic precursors, and glutathione S-transferase catalyzed conjugation of cysteine or glutathione to reactive carbonyls generating thiol precursors that will release volatile thiols through yeast metabolism during fermentation. ||The quantitative significance of aroma precursor formation reflects the observation that glycosidically-bound forms typically constitute 85-95% of total monoterpenoid content and 70-90% of total norisoprenoid content in ripe berries, with free volatile concentrations representing only a small fraction of the aromatic potential stored in conjugated precursor pools awaiting release through appropriate processing interventions. ||The cellular localization of aroma precursor formation involves cytosolic glycosyltransferase activities converting free terpenols to their glucosides followed by vacuolar transport and sequestration establishing stable intracellular reservoirs, with compartmentalization protecting precursors from hydrolytic enzymes that would prematurely release volatile aglycones compromising aromatic quality and stability. ||Temporal dynamics of precursor formation show progressive accumulation throughout the post-veraison period, with glycosyltransferase gene expression and enzyme activities increasing 3-8 fold between veraison and harvest in aromatic varieties, enabling continued conjugation of newly synthesized volatile compounds throughout the ripening window. ||Cultivar genetics determine precursor formation capacity through variety-specific expression of glycosyltransferase gene families, with Muscat and related aromatic varieties showing elevated expression of monoterpenol glucosyltransferases compared to neutral varieties, and Sauvignon Blanc demonstrating distinctive glutathione S-transferase expression enabling thiol precursor accumulation. ||Environmental factors modulate precursor formation through temperature effects on conjugating enzyme activities and substrate availability, with moderate conditions of 20-28°C generally supporting optimal precursor accumulation while temperature extremes may limit biosynthetic efficiency or accelerate precursor degradation. ||The relationship between precursor pool size and wine aromatic quality depends on subsequent release efficiency during vinification, with larger precursor pools providing greater aromatic potential that can be realized through appropriate enzyme additions, yeast strain selection, or extended skin contact during winemaking.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Gunata Z et al (1985) The aroma of grapes. Journal of Chromatography 331: 83-90 || Tominaga T et al (1998) Identification of cysteinylated aroma precursors. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 46: 5215-5219 || Williams PJ et al (1989) Glycosidic precursors of varietal grape and wine flavor. ACS Symposium Series 388: 35-48"
},

  "Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "A Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis is an Aroma_Precursor_Formation realized through UDP-glucose-dependent glycosyltransferase transfer of glucose residues to hydroxyl groups of monoterpenols, sesquiterpenols, and other volatile alcohols producing β-glucoside conjugates accounting for 85–95% of total terpenoid content at harvest.",
  "alternative_term": "monoterpenol glycosylation | terpene glucoside formation | glycosyltransferase-mediated conjugation | sugar-bound volatile synthesis |+ glycosidische Vorläufer-Synthese | Monoterpenol-Glycosylierung | Terpen-Glucosid-Bildung | Glycosyltransferase-vermittelte-Konjugation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Moscato Bianco berries in Asti, Piedmont during BBCH 85-89, glycosidic precursor synthesis generates monoterpene glucosides at rates of 0.12 mg/L per day during peak activity, with UDP-glucose linalool glucosyltransferase activity reaching 52 nmol/min/g fresh weight in exocarp tissue at 22 days post-veraison, producing bound linalool of 2.8 mg/L as monoglucoside and 0.9 mg/L as disaccharide forms, representing 91% of total linalool in glycosidic conjugates under warm Piedmont conditions averaging 25°C.",
  "editor_note": "Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis is subclass of Aroma_Precursor_Formation representing specific glycosyltransferase-mediated reactions. ||Distinguishes from thiol precursor formation using glutathione conjugation. ||Sibling to Bound_Aroma_Accumulation and Precursor_Pool_Building. ||Key enzymes are UDP-glucose-dependent glycosyltransferases. ||Produces mono-, di-, and tri-glycoside conjugates. ||Cultivar-specific expression determines capacity. || This process involves the recognition of diverse aglycone substrates by glycosyltransferase active sites, with broad-specificity enzymes accepting multiple terpenol substrates including linalool, geraniol, nerol, citronellol, and alpha-terpineol, enabling the glycosylation of the complete spectrum of monoterpene alcohols produced through terpenoid biosynthetic pathways in berry tissues. ||The biochemical mechanism proceeds through nucleophilic attack on UDP-glucose by the hydroxyl group of the acceptor terpenol, forming an enzyme-bound glucose ester intermediate followed by transfer to the aglycone with UDP release, with reaction rates determined by enzyme expression levels, substrate concentrations, and cofactor availability that vary developmentally and show cultivar-specific regulation patterns. ||Secondary glycosylation reactions further modify monoterpene glucosides through attachment of additional sugar residues including rhamnose, arabinose, and apiose by specific rhamnosyltransferases and related enzymes, generating disaccharide and trisaccharide glycosides that demonstrate enhanced stability and modified release characteristics compared to simple monoglucosides during subsequent hydrolysis. ||The cellular compartmentalization of glycosidic precursor synthesis involves cytosolic localization of most glycosyltransferase activities with subsequent transport of synthesized conjugates into vacuolar storage through tonoplast transporters, establishing protected precursor pools sequestered from cytosolic glycosidase activities that would prematurely hydrolyze glycosidic bonds releasing volatile aglycones. ||Cultivar genetics profoundly influence glycosidic precursor synthesis capacity through differential expression of glycosyltransferase genes, with aromatic varieties such as Muscat showing 5-15 fold higher glucosyltransferase expression and activity compared to neutral varieties such as Chardonnay, directly determining the accumulation capacity for glycosidically-bound terpenoids characteristic of aromatic grape varieties. ||Temperature during ripening modulates glycosidic precursor synthesis through effects on glycosyltransferase enzyme activities, with optimal synthesis rates at moderate temperatures of 22-28°C and reduced activity at temperature extremes that may limit precursor accumulation or shift the balance between free and bound volatile pools.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Bönisch F et al (2014) A UDP-glucose monoterpenol glucosyltransferase adds to the chemical diversity of the grapevine metabolome. Plant Physiology 165: 561-581 || Gunata Z et al (1985) The aroma of grapes. Journal of Chromatography 331: 83-90 || Williams PJ et al (1982) Use of C13 norisoprenoids as natural wine flavour precursors. ACS Symposium Series 388: 35-48"
},

  "Bound_Aroma_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Bound_Aroma_Accumulation is an Aroma_Development exhibiting monotonic increase in glycosidically conjugated aromatic compound concentrations through continued glycosyltransferase activity and stable vacuolar retention of preformed glycosides.",
  "alternative_term": "glycoside aroma accumulation | bound volatile increase | conjugated aroma build-up | precursor aroma accumulation |+ gebundene Aroma-Akkumulation | Glycosid-Aroma-Anreicherung | konjugierte Aroma-Aufbau | Vorläufer-Aroma-Akkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Irsai Olivér berries in Mátra, Hungary during BBCH 83-89, bound aroma accumulation increases glycosidically-bound monoterpenes from 2.2 to 9.8 mg/L over 42 days, with accumulation rates peaking at 0.25 mg/L per day during weeks 3-4 post-veraison, bound linalool reaching 3.2 mg/L, bound geraniol 2.1 mg/L, and bound nerol 1.4 mg/L, establishing aromatic potential 7.5-fold greater than free volatile content of 1.3 mg/L at harvest under continental conditions with warm days of 28°C and cool nights of 14°C.",
  "editor_note": "Bound_Aroma_Accumulation is subclass of Aroma_Precursor_Formation representing quantitative increase in conjugated aromatics. ||Distinguishes from Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis which describes reaction mechanism. ||Sibling to Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis and Precursor_Pool_Building. ||Bound forms typically 85-95% of total monoterpenoids. ||Accumulation continues throughout ripening. ||Determines aromatic potential for winemaking release. || This process reflects the net balance between ongoing glycosylation adding compounds to the bound pool and potential hydrolysis or degradation removing compounds, with successful accumulation requiring that conjugation rates substantially exceed any losses to maintain the positive accumulation trajectory characteristic of normal ripening progression in aromatic grape varieties. ||The quantitative aspects of bound aroma accumulation show variety-specific patterns, with aromatic varieties such as Muscat and Gewürztraminer accumulating bound monoterpene pools of 5-15 mg/L representing 85-95% of total terpenoid content, while neutral varieties such as Chardonnay and Pinot Noir accumulate substantially lower bound pools of 0.3-1.0 mg/L reflecting reduced glycosyltransferase expression and lower terpenoid biosynthetic capacity. ||Temporal dynamics of bound aroma accumulation demonstrate progressive increase throughout the post-veraison period, with accumulation rates typically highest during mid-ripening when both terpenoid biosynthesis and glycosyltransferase activities reach peak levels, followed by declining rates during late ripening as substrate availability decreases and enzyme activities wane approaching harvest maturity. ||The vacuolar sequestration mechanism supporting bound aroma accumulation involves active transport of glycosidic conjugates across the tonoplast membrane through ABC transporters and related systems, establishing concentration gradients with vacuolar glycoside levels of 2-10 mM representing 50-100 fold enrichment compared to cytosolic pools, ensuring stable storage protected from glycosidase activities maintaining precursor integrity throughout ripening and post-harvest handling. ||Environmental factors influence bound aroma accumulation through temperature effects on both terpenoid biosynthesis providing substrates and glycosyltransferase activities enabling conjugation, with moderate temperatures of 20-28°C generally supporting optimal accumulation while cool conditions may slow both processes and warm conditions may accelerate substrate volatilization reducing material available for glycosylation. ||The practical significance of bound aroma accumulation for winemaking reflects the requirement for precursor hydrolysis to release aromatic aglycones, with winemaker decisions regarding enzyme additions, yeast selection, and contact time determining the extent to which accumulated precursor pools are converted to sensory-active free volatiles in finished wines.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Wilson B et al (1984) Determination of free and bound monoterpenes in Muscat grapes. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 35: 95-100 || Gunata Z et al (1985) The aroma of grapes. Journal of Chromatography 331: 83-90 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 295-305"
},

  "Precursor_Pool_Building": {
  "definition": "A Precursor_Pool_Building is an Aroma_Precursor_Formation comprising cumulative establishment of bound aromatic compound reservoirs through integrated glycosylation, cysteine conjugation, and related precursor-forming reactions.",
  "alternative_term": "aromatic precursor reservoir development | bound aroma pool establishment | precursor capacity building | conjugate pool accumulation |+ Vorläufer-Pool-Aufbau | aromatische Vorläufer-Reservoir-Entwicklung | gebundener Aroma-Pool-Etablierung | Konjugat-Pool-Akkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Albariño berries in Rías Baixas, Galicia during BBCH 81-89, precursor pool building establishes glycosidically-bound monoterpene pools increasing from 1.8 to 6.5 mg/L, norisoprenoid precursor pools from 35 to 165 µg/L, and thiol precursor pools from 85 to 295 µg/L over 48 days, representing total aromatic potential 8.2-fold greater than free volatile content, with pool accumulation following biphasic pattern showing rapid increase during weeks 2-5 and plateau during final 2 weeks before harvest under cool Atlantic conditions averaging 19°C.",
  "editor_note": "Precursor_Pool_Building is subclass of Aroma_Precursor_Formation representing cumulative reservoir establishment. ||Distinguishes from individual precursor synthesis by emphasizing integrated accumulation. ||Sibling to Glycosidic_Precursor_Synthesis and Bound_Aroma_Accumulation. ||Integrates multiple precursor classes into composite potential. ||Pool size determines aromatic capacity for winemaking. ||Variety-specific accumulation trajectories. || This process integrates multiple precursor classes into composite aromatic potential, with glycosidically-bound monoterpenes contributing pools of 2-15 mg/L in aromatic varieties, glycosidically-bound norisoprenoids adding pools of 50-300 µg/L across diverse cultivars, and cysteine-conjugated volatile thiol precursors accumulating to pools of 100-500 µg/L in Sauvignon Blanc and related varieties, collectively establishing the raw material for aromatic expression during subsequent vinification. ||The dynamics of precursor pool building show variety-specific accumulation trajectories, with some cultivars demonstrating linear accumulation throughout ripening while others exhibit biphasic patterns with rapid early-phase accumulation followed by plateau phases during late ripening, reflecting genetic differences in biosynthetic capacity, substrate availability, and potential precursor turnover through degradative processes. ||Vacuolar storage capacity influences precursor pool building through the physical constraints on glycoside accumulation within finite intracellular compartments, with evidence suggesting that vacuolar transport saturation may limit maximum achievable pool sizes in some varieties, particularly during rapid accumulation phases when biosynthetic output may exceed transport and storage capacity. ||The relationship between precursor pool size at harvest and wine aromatic quality depends on multiple factors including release efficiency during winemaking, potential synergistic or masking interactions among released compounds, and threshold concentrations required for sensory perception, with larger pools generally correlating with greater aromatic potential though release optimization remains critical for converting precursor content to sensory impact. ||Environmental factors including temperature, light exposure, and water status influence precursor pool building through effects on both biosynthesis of free volatiles and subsequent conjugation reactions, with growing conditions affecting final pool sizes by 50-200% relative to baseline levels in controlled studies comparing different environmental treatments. ||Viticultural practices targeting precursor pool building include canopy management optimizing cluster microclimate for secondary metabolism, irrigation strategies imposing controlled water deficit that enhances precursor accumulation, and harvest timing decisions capturing maximum pool development before potential late-season degradation or dilution through continued berry expansion.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Williams PJ et al (1989) Glycosidic precursors of varietal grape and wine flavor. ACS Symposium Series 388: 35-48 || Tominaga T et al (1998) Identification of cysteinylated aroma precursors. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 46: 5215-5219 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 295-305"
},

  "Volatile_Compound_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "A Volatile_Compound_Synthesis is an Aroma_Development comprising enzymatic biosynthesis of free aromatic compounds including monoterpenes, sesquiterpenes, C13-norisoprenoids, volatile thiols, esters, aldehydes, and alcohols possessing vapor pressure sufficient for olfactory detection.",
  "alternative_term": "free volatile biosynthesis | aromatic volatile production | volatile aroma synthesis | free aroma compound formation |+ Volatil-Verbindungs-Synthese | freie Volatil-Biosynthese | aromatische Volatil-Produktion | freie Aroma-Verbindungs-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Scheurebe berries in Rheinhessen, Germany during BBCH 83-89, volatile compound synthesis generates free monoterpenes increasing from 0.2 to 1.4 mg/L over 45 days, with linalool synthase activity reaching 28 nmol/min/g fresh weight producing free linalool of 0.55 mg/L, concurrent norisoprenoid synthesis generating free beta-damascenone of 3.2 µg/L and beta-ionone of 1.8 µg/L, while C6 aldehyde content declines from 95 to 28 µg/L hexanal as green character diminishes with advancing ripeness under cool continental conditions averaging 18°C.",
  "editor_note": "Volatile_Compound_Synthesis is parent class under Aroma_Development representing biosynthesis of free aromatic volatiles. ||Distinguishes from Aroma_Precursor_Formation which generates conjugated forms. ||Contains subclasses Free_Volatile_Production, Ester_Formation, and Aldehyde_Synthesis. ||Multiple pathways including MEP terpenoid, carotenoid cleavage, and fatty acid oxidation. ||Cultivar-specific enzyme expression determines synthesis capacity. || This process involves multiple biosynthetic routes operating in distinct cellular compartments, with the methylerythritol phosphate pathway generating geranyl diphosphate precursor in plastids followed by terpene synthase conversion to monoterpene hydrocarbons and alcohols in cytosolic compartments, carotenoid cleavage dioxygenases generating norisoprenoid volatiles through oxidative degradation of carotenoid substrates in chromoplasts, and fatty acid metabolism producing C6 aldehydes and alcohols through lipoxygenase and hydroperoxide lyase sequential activities in various cellular locations. ||The temporal regulation of volatile compound synthesis shows compound-class-specific patterns, with monoterpene synthesis increasing progressively throughout post-veraison ripening as terpene synthase expression rises, norisoprenoid generation accelerating during mid-to-late ripening coincident with carotenoid degradation in coloring berries, and C6 volatile synthesis showing complex dynamics reflecting the balance between lipoxygenase pathway activity and aldehyde reduction or oxidation reactions that modify initially formed products. ||Cultivar genetics fundamentally determine volatile compound synthesis capacity through variety-specific expression of biosynthetic enzyme genes, with aromatic Muscat varieties expressing high levels of linalool synthase and geraniol synthase generating 10-100 fold higher monoterpene concentrations than neutral varieties, and Cabernet family varieties expressing characteristic O-methyltransferases producing methoxypyrazines distinctive to these cultivars. ||The partitioning between free volatile production and subsequent conjugation to precursor forms represents a critical regulatory point, with the balance between synthesis rates and glycosylation activities determining what fraction of produced volatiles remains in free, immediately aromatic form versus conjugated storage awaiting release during winemaking. ||Environmental modulation of volatile compound synthesis occurs through temperature effects on enzyme activities and substrate availability, light regulation of terpenoid and carotenoid pathway expression, and stress-responsive induction of secondary metabolism under water deficit or other environmental challenges that activate volatile biosynthetic pathways.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0044550 ## secondary metabolite biosynthetic process | 0.75", "skos:narrowMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0046184 ## aldehyde biosynthetic process | 0.8", "skos:narrowMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_1902655 ## aromatic primary alcohol biosynthetic process | 0.8" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Kalua CM and Boss PK (2009) Evolution of volatile compounds during development of Cabernet Sauvignon grapes. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 57: 3818-3830 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 285-295"
},

  "Free_Volatile_Production": {
  "definition": "A Free_Volatile_Production is a Volatile_Compound_Synthesis exhibiting unconjugated aromatic compounds in their non-glycosylated state contributing directly to the perceptible aroma of intact berries and freshly crushed juice.",
  "alternative_term": "unconjugated volatile synthesis | free aroma generation | immediate volatile production | non-glycosylated volatile formation |+ freie Volatil-Produktion | unkonjugierte Volatil-Synthese | freie Aroma-Erzeugung | unmittelbare Volatil-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Traminer berries in Südtirol, Italy during BBCH 85-89, free volatile production maintains unconjugated monoterpene content increasing from 0.15 to 0.95 mg/L over 38 days, representing 12% of total monoterpenoid content at harvest, with free linalool at 0.42 mg/L and free geraniol at 0.28 mg/L providing immediate floral-rose impact detectable in berry tasting, while the free-to-bound ratio remains relatively stable at 0.11-0.14 throughout ripening indicating balanced biosynthesis and conjugation rates under alpine conditions averaging 21°C.",
  "editor_note": "Free_Volatile_Production is subclass of Volatile_Compound_Synthesis representing unconjugated aromatic volatile generation. ||Distinguishes from Bound_Aroma_Accumulation which involves conjugated forms. ||Sibling to Ester_Formation and Aldehyde_Synthesis. ||Typically 5-15% of total monoterpenoids remain free. ||Provides immediate aromatic impact. ||Balance between synthesis and conjugation determines free pool size. || This process represents the fraction of total volatile biosynthesis that escapes conjugation to precursor forms, typically constituting 5-15% of total monoterpenoid content in aromatic varieties and varying proportions of other volatile classes depending on compound-specific glycosylation efficiencies and biosynthetic rates relative to conjugation capacity. ||The biochemical basis of free volatile production involves the kinetic competition between continued synthesis adding volatiles to the free pool and glycosyltransferase-mediated conjugation removing them, with free volatile concentrations representing the steady-state balance between these opposing processes rather than absolute accumulation without loss to conjugation pathways. ||Cellular mechanisms influencing free volatile production include subcellular compartmentalization separating sites of volatile synthesis from glycosyltransferase localization, membrane permeability determining volatile retention versus volatilization losses, and the relative expression levels of biosynthetic versus conjugating enzymes that establish the partitioning ratio between free and bound pools. ||The sensory significance of free volatile production reflects the immediate aromatic impact of these compounds in berry tasting and early-stage juice evaluation, with free volatiles providing the first olfactory impression encountered during harvest assessment and initial winemaking stages before precursor hydrolysis contributes additional aromatic complexity. ||Cultivar differences in free volatile production reflect genetic variation in both biosynthetic capacity and conjugation efficiency, with some aromatic varieties maintaining relatively high free-to-bound ratios of 0.15-0.25 while others show lower ratios of 0.05-0.10 despite equivalent total volatile content, suggesting variety-specific regulation of the partitioning between free and conjugated pools. ||Environmental factors including temperature and humidity influence free volatile production through effects on volatilization rates that deplete the free pool, with high temperatures and low humidity accelerating volatile loss and potentially reducing free volatile concentrations even when biosynthetic rates remain constant, necessitating consideration of environmental conditions when interpreting free volatile measurements during ripening assessment.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Wilson B et al (1984) Determination of free and bound monoterpenes in Muscat grapes. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 35: 95-100 || Marais J (1983) Terpenes in the aroma of grapes and wines. South African Journal of Enology and Viticulture 4: 49-58 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 290-295"
},

  "Ester_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Ester_Formation is a Volatile_Compound_Synthesis realized through alcohol acetyltransferase and related acyltransferase catalysis condensing alcohol and acyl-CoA substrates into volatile esters contributing fruity aromatic notes.",
  "alternative_term": "volatile ester biosynthesis | fruit ester formation | acyltransferase-mediated esterification | ester aroma synthesis |+ Ester-Bildung | flüchtige Ester-Biosynthese | Frucht-Ester-Formation | Acyltransferase-vermittelte-Veresterung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Malvasia Bianca berries in Friuli, Italy during BBCH 85-89, ester formation generates total volatile esters increasing from 45 to 185 µg/L over 35 days, with ethyl acetate rising from 18 to 65 µg/L, isoamyl acetate from 8 to 42 µg/L providing banana-fruity notes, and ethyl hexanoate from 5 to 28 µg/L contributing apple-fruity character, establishing the ester profile that will serve as template for fermentation-enhanced ester development under warm conditions averaging 25°C with significant diurnal temperature variation.",
  "editor_note": "Ester_Formation is subclass of Volatile_Compound_Synthesis representing acyltransferase-mediated ester biosynthesis. ||Distinguishes from fermentation-derived ester production by yeast. ||Sibling to Free_Volatile_Production and Aldehyde_Synthesis. ||Grape esters contribute 5-20% of final wine ester content. ||Provides fruity-sweet aromatic character. ||Progressive increase during ripening. || This process involves the enzymatic transfer of acyl groups from activated acyl-CoA donors to hydroxyl-bearing alcohol acceptors, with acetyl-CoA serving as the predominant acyl donor producing acetate esters such as ethyl acetate, hexyl acetate, and isoamyl acetate, while longer-chain acyl-CoAs generate ethyl esters of fatty acids including ethyl butanoate, ethyl hexanoate, and ethyl octanoate contributing fruity-tropical aromatic character. ||The substrate specificity of grape alcohol acyltransferases determines the ester profile produced during berry ripening, with these enzymes accepting diverse alcohol substrates including ethanol, higher alcohols derived from amino acid catabolism, and C6 alcohols from lipid oxidation, generating the complex mixture of esters characteristic of ripe grape aroma. ||The quantitative contribution of berry-derived esters to total wine ester content is relatively modest compared to fermentation-derived esters produced by yeast metabolism, with grape esters typically contributing 5-20% of final wine ester concentrations while providing important baseline aromatic character and serving as indicators of ripeness and fruit quality during harvest assessment. ||Temporal dynamics of ester formation show progressive increase during ripening coincident with alcohol substrate accumulation and acyltransferase enzyme expression, with ester concentrations typically rising 3-8 fold between veraison and harvest as both substrates and enzyme activities increase during berry maturation. ||Environmental factors influence ester formation through temperature effects on enzyme activities and substrate availability, with moderate temperatures of 20-26°C generally supporting optimal ester synthesis while temperature extremes may reduce enzyme function or alter substrate pools affecting ester production capacity. ||Cultivar variation in ester formation reflects genetic differences in acyltransferase expression and alcohol precursor accumulation, with some varieties producing more prominent ester-derived fruity character than others under equivalent ripening conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kalua CM and Boss PK (2009) Evolution of volatile compounds during development of Cabernet Sauvignon grapes. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 57: 3818-3830 || Dunlevy JD et al (2013) The production of flavour and aroma compounds in grape berries. In The Biochemistry of the Grape Berry Bentham Science pp 293-340 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 288-292"
},

  "Aldehyde_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "An Aldehyde_Synthesis is a Volatile_Compound_Synthesis realized through lipoxygenase-mediated oxidation of polyunsaturated fatty acids and hydroperoxide lyase cleavage producing C6 aldehydes hexanal and hexenal isomers contributing green-grassy aromatic character.",
  "alternative_term": "C6 aldehyde production | green volatile synthesis | lipoxygenase pathway aldehydes | hexanal biosynthesis |+ Aldehyd-Synthese | C6-Aldehyd-Produktion | Grün-Volatil-Synthese | Lipoxygenase-Stoffwechselweg-Aldehyde",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner berries in Kamptal, Austria during BBCH 79-89, aldehyde synthesis shows characteristic decline with hexanal decreasing from 125 µg/L at veraison to 18 µg/L at harvest over 48 days, trans-2-hexenal declining from 185 to 32 µg/L, and cis-3-hexenal from 95 to 12 µg/L, while corresponding C6 alcohols increase through aldehyde reduction, with trained panel green-herbaceous ratings declining from 6.8 to 2.2 on 10-point scale paralleling the analytical aldehyde reduction under cool conditions averaging 17°C.",
  "editor_note": "Aldehyde_Synthesis is subclass of Volatile_Compound_Synthesis representing lipoxygenase pathway volatile generation. ||Distinguishes from Ester_Formation which produces fruity volatiles. ||Sibling to Free_Volatile_Production and Ester_Formation. ||C6 aldehydes decline during ripening. ||Green character indicator. ||Maximum at veraison, minimum at harvest. ||Reduction to alcohols modifies sensory impact. || This process involves the sequential action of lipoxygenase enzymes oxidizing linoleic and linolenic acids at specific positions to form fatty acid hydroperoxides, followed by hydroperoxide lyase catalyzed cleavage producing C6 aldehyde fragments including hexanal from linoleic acid and cis-3-hexenal and trans-2-hexenal from linolenic acid that constitute the primary components of green leaf volatile character. ||The temporal dynamics of aldehyde synthesis show characteristic patterns during berry development, with C6 aldehyde concentrations reaching maximum levels during early berry development and the veraison transition when lipoxygenase activities are elevated and membrane lipid turnover provides abundant fatty acid substrates, followed by progressive decline during post-veraison ripening as aldehyde reduction to corresponding alcohols and continued degradation reduce overall aldehyde content. ||The sensory significance of aldehyde synthesis reflects the low perception thresholds for C6 aldehydes, with hexanal and hexenal isomers detectable at concentrations of 5-15 µg/L imparting distinctive green, grassy character that is desirable in some wine styles emphasizing freshness but considered negative in fully ripe fruit where residual green notes may indicate incomplete physiological maturity. ||Reduction of aldehydes to their corresponding C6 alcohols through alcohol dehydrogenase activity represents a key transformation during ripening, converting the intensely green-smelling aldehydes to softer-scented hexanol and hexenol compounds that contribute more subtle herbaceous nuance without the harsh green impact of aldehyde precursors. ||Environmental factors influence aldehyde synthesis through effects on membrane lipid composition and lipoxygenase pathway activities, with cool conditions and high humidity potentially maintaining elevated aldehyde levels longer into the ripening season, while warm, dry conditions may accelerate aldehyde decline through enhanced reduction and volatilization. ||The monitoring of C6 aldehyde concentrations during ripening provides useful indicators of physiological maturity, with low residual aldehyde levels correlating with advanced ripeness and reduced green character in harvested grapes and resulting wines.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kalua CM and Boss PK (2009) Evolution of volatile compounds during development of Cabernet Sauvignon grapes. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 57: 3818-3830 || Matsui K (2006) Green leaf volatiles: hydroperoxide lyase pathway of oxylipin metabolism. Current Opinion in Plant Biology 9: 274-280 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 288-290"
},

  "Terpene_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Terpene_Accumulation is an Aroma_Development consisting of progressive concentration increase of terpenoid compounds as both free volatiles and glycosidically bound precursors over the 35–50 day post-véraison phase, deriving from the methylerythritol phosphate pathway.",
  "alternative_term": "terpenoid accumulation | terpene build-up | monoterpene and sesquiterpene accumulation | terpenoid pool increase |+ Terpen-Akkumulation | Terpenoid-Anreicherung | Terpen-Aufbau | Monoterpen-und-Sesquiterpen-Akkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Muscat of Frontignan berries in Languedoc, France during BBCH 81-89, terpene accumulation increases total monoterpene content from 1.5 to 11.2 mg/L over 45 days, with free monoterpenes rising from 0.3 to 1.6 mg/L and bound monoterpenes from 1.2 to 9.6 mg/L, establishing a free-to-bound ratio of 0.17 at harvest, while concurrent sesquiterpene accumulation reaches 85 µg/L total including 12 µg/L farnesol, under warm Mediterranean conditions averaging 27°C with intense solar radiation.",
  "editor_note": "Terpene_Accumulation is parent class under Aroma_Development representing terpenoid compound increase. ||Distinguishes from Volatile_Compound_Synthesis which describes biosynthetic processes. ||Contains subclasses Monoterpene_Synthesis, Sesquiterpene_Production, and Terpene_Pool_Development. ||Aromatic varieties accumulate 5-15 mg/L versus 0.1-0.3 mg/L in neutral varieties. ||Includes both free volatiles and glycosidic precursors. ||80-95% typically in bound form. || This process integrates the biosynthesis of diverse terpenoid classes including monoterpenes comprising C10 compounds such as linalool, geraniol, nerol, citronellol, and alpha-terpineol that provide the dominant floral-fruity character of aromatic varieties, sesquiterpenes comprising C15 compounds such as rotundone, farnesol, and nerolidol contributing spicy and woody nuances, and trace quantities of diterpenes and other higher terpenoids that may contribute subtle aromatic background complexity. ||The quantitative aspects of terpene accumulation show dramatic cultivar variation, with aromatic Muscat varieties accumulating total monoterpene pools of 5-15 mg/L at harvest maturity representing 50-100 fold higher concentrations than neutral varieties such as Chardonnay or Pinot Noir that typically accumulate 0.1-0.3 mg/L total monoterpenes under equivalent conditions. ||Cellular localization of terpene accumulation demonstrates tissue-specific patterns, with monoterpene concentrations 5-20 fold higher in exocarp compared to mesocarp tissues reflecting the preferential expression of terpene synthase genes in skin cells, while sesquiterpene accumulation may show different tissue distribution patterns depending on specific compound and cultivar. ||The temporal dynamics of terpene accumulation follow progressive increase throughout post-veraison ripening, with accumulation rates typically highest during mid-ripening when terpene synthase gene expression reaches peak levels, followed by continued but declining accumulation during late ripening as enzyme activities wane and potential degradation or volatilization may partially offset continued synthesis. ||Temperature during ripening influences terpene accumulation through effects on biosynthetic enzyme activities, substrate availability, and compound stability, with moderate temperatures of 20-28°C generally supporting optimal accumulation while temperature extremes may reduce biosynthetic efficiency or accelerate volatile loss through increased vapor pressure. ||The partitioning between free and glycosidically-bound forms during terpene accumulation reflects the balance between synthesis rates and glycosyltransferase activities, with typical free-to-bound ratios of 0.05-0.20 indicating that 80-95% of accumulated terpenoids exist in conjugated precursor forms requiring hydrolysis for aromatic release. ||Viticultural practices influence terpene accumulation through effects on vine physiology and cluster microclimate, with moderate water stress, appropriate crop load, and optimized light exposure generally enhancing accumulation compared to conditions of excess vigor or resource limitation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Marais J (1983) Terpenes in the aroma of grapes and wines. South African Journal of Enology and Viticulture 4: 49-58 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 290-300"
},

  "Monoterpene_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "A Monoterpene_Synthesis is a Terpene_Accumulation realized through terpene synthase conversion of geranyl diphosphate into linalool, geraniol, nerol, citronellol, α-terpineol, and hotrienol contributing floral, citrus, and Muscat aromatic character.",
  "alternative_term": "monoterpenoid biosynthesis | C10 terpene synthesis | terpene synthase-mediated monoterpene production | linalool and geraniol synthesis |+ Monoterpen-Synthese | Monoterpenoid-Biosynthese | C10-Terpen-Synthese | Terpensynthase-vermittelte-Monoterpen-Produktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Orange Muscat berries in Rutherglen, Australia during BBCH 83-89, monoterpene synthesis generates total monoterpenes at rates reaching 0.28 mg/L per day during peak activity at 20-25 days post-veraison, with linalool synthase activity of 65 nmol/min/g fresh weight producing linalool accumulation to 3.5 mg/L total, geraniol synthase activity of 38 nmol/min/g generating geraniol to 2.2 mg/L, and alpha-terpineol formation reaching 1.1 mg/L through both direct synthesis and acid-catalyzed rearrangement of linalool under warm conditions averaging 26°C.",
  "editor_note": "Monoterpene_Synthesis is subclass of Terpene_Accumulation representing C10 terpenoid biosynthesis specifically. ||Distinguishes from Sesquiterpene_Production which generates C15 compounds. ||Sibling to Sesquiterpene_Production and Terpene_Pool_Development. ||Key enzymes include linalool synthase, geraniol synthase, alpha-terpineol synthase. ||MEP pathway provides GPP precursor. ||Variety-specific expression determines aromatic potential. || This process involves the ionization of geranyl diphosphate by terpene synthase enzymes generating carbocation intermediates that undergo cyclization, hydride shifts, and water capture reactions to produce the structurally diverse monoterpene products characteristic of individual enzyme specificities, with the Vitis vinifera genome encoding approximately 70 terpene synthase genes of which 30-40 are expressed in berry tissues with variety-specific expression patterns determining the monoterpene profile of individual cultivars. ||The subcellular organization of monoterpene synthesis involves geranyl diphosphate formation in plastids through the MEP pathway enzymes, potential transport of this precursor to cytosolic compartments where many terpene synthases appear localized, and subsequent modification reactions including hydroxylation, oxidation, and isomerization that generate the complete spectrum of monoterpene structures found in ripe grape berries. ||The dominant monoterpene synthase activities in aromatic varieties include linalool synthase generating the floral compound contributing rose-like and lavender notes, geraniol synthase producing the rose-geranium scented alcohol, and alpha-terpineol synthase creating the lilac-like tertiary alcohol that contributes to overall floral complexity, with these enzymes showing 5-20 fold higher expression in Muscat compared to neutral varieties. ||Developmental regulation of monoterpene synthesis involves transcriptional activation of terpene synthase genes during the veraison transition, with expression levels increasing 3-10 fold during the post-veraison period in aromatic varieties, reaching maximum during mid-ripening and declining during late ripening as berries approach harvest maturity. ||Environmental factors influence monoterpene synthesis through light-mediated regulation of MEP pathway and terpene synthase gene expression, temperature effects on enzyme activities with optimal synthesis at 22-28°C, and potential stress-responsive induction of specific synthase genes under water deficit or other environmental challenges. ||The relationship between monoterpene synthesis rates and final accumulation levels reflects the balance between production and subsequent glycosylation that sequesters 80-95% of synthesized monoterpenes in bound precursor forms, with variety-specific glycosyltransferase expression determining the partitioning between free and bound pools.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Lücker J et al (2004) Monoterpene biosynthesis in lemon. European Journal of Biochemistry 271: 2930-2938 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 290-295"
},

  "Sesquiterpene_Production": {
  "definition": "A Sesquiterpene_Production is a Terpene_Accumulation realized through sesquiterpene synthase conversion of farnesyl diphosphate into farnesol, nerolidol, α-farnesene, and rotundone, the latter conferring black pepper character on Syrah and related cultivars.",
  "alternative_term": "sesquiterpenoid biosynthesis | C15 terpene synthesis | rotundone production | farnesyl diphosphate-derived terpene synthesis |+ Sesquiterpen-Produktion | Sesquiterpenoid-Biosynthese | C15-Terpen-Synthese | Rotundon-Produktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Shiraz berries in Grampians, Victoria during BBCH 85-89, sesquiterpene production generates rotundone accumulating from below detection to 165 ng/L in berry skins over the final 28 days before harvest, with accumulation strongly enhanced by cool late-season temperatures averaging 16°C compared to warmer sites where rotundone reaches only 45 ng/L, concurrent with total sesquiterpene content of 95 µg/L including farnesol at 18 µg/L and nerolidol at 25 µg/L providing background spicy-woody complexity.",
  "editor_note": "Sesquiterpene_Production is subclass of Terpene_Accumulation representing C15 terpenoid biosynthesis. ||Distinguishes from Monoterpene_Synthesis which generates C10 compounds. ||Sibling to Monoterpene_Synthesis and Terpene_Pool_Development. ||Rotundone is key sensory-active compound in peppery varieties. ||Mevalonate pathway provides FPP precursor. ||Cool temperatures enhance rotundone accumulation. ||Skin-localized synthesis. || This process involves the ionization of farnesyl diphosphate followed by cyclization and rearrangement reactions generating the complex polycyclic structures characteristic of many sesquiterpenes, with the grapevine genome encoding multiple sesquiterpene synthase genes showing variety-specific expression patterns that determine the sesquiterpene profile contributing to cultivar-distinctive aromatic signatures beyond the dominant monoterpene character. ||The subcellular organization of sesquiterpene production differs from monoterpene synthesis, with farnesyl diphosphate formed through the cytosolic mevalonate pathway rather than the plastidial MEP pathway, and sesquiterpene synthase activities primarily localized in cytosolic compartments where substrate and enzyme colocalize for efficient product formation. ||The sensorially most significant sesquiterpene in grape and wine is rotundone, a bicyclic sesquiterpene ketone with extremely low perception threshold of approximately 16 ng/L in red wine providing intense black pepper spicy character, with rotundone synthase expression showing strong cultivar specificity concentrated in Shiraz, Durif, and related varieties while largely absent from non-peppery cultivars. ||Developmental regulation of sesquiterpene production shows variety-specific timing, with rotundone accumulation in Shiraz occurring primarily during late ripening in the final 3-4 weeks before harvest, reaching concentrations of 50-200 ng/L in berry skins that constitute the primary tissue site of rotundone synthesis and accumulation. ||Environmental factors profoundly influence sesquiterpene production, with cool temperatures during late ripening substantially enhancing rotundone accumulation in Shiraz to levels 3-5 fold higher than equivalent fruit ripened under warm conditions, explaining the strong site and vintage variation in peppery character expression observed in commercial wines. ||The tissue localization of sesquiterpene production concentrates in exocarp cells where sesquiterpene synthase expression shows highest levels, with sesquiterpene concentrations in skin tissue typically 10-50 fold higher than in mesocarp, suggesting that skin contact during winemaking significantly influences extraction and final wine sesquiterpene content.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Wood C et al (2008) From wine to pepper: rotundone, an obscure sesquiterpene, is a potent spicy aroma compound. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 56: 3738-3744 || Siebert TE et al (2008) Development of a stable isotope dilution analysis for the grape-derived compound rotundone. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 56: 3745-3748 || Drew DP et al (2016) Two key polymorphisms in a newly discovered sesquiterpene synthase gene. Phytochemistry 122: 204-215"
},

  "Terpene_Pool_Development": {
  "definition": "A Terpene_Pool_Development is a Terpene_Accumulation comprising the cumulative reservoir of free volatile and glycosidically conjugated terpenoids integrating the outputs of monoterpene and sesquiterpene biosynthetic pathways.",
  "alternative_term": "terpenoid pool establishment | terpene reservoir development | cumulative terpene accumulation | terpenoid capacity building |+ Terpen-Pool-Entwicklung | Terpenoid-Pool-Etablierung | Terpen-Reservoir-Entwicklung | kumulative Terpen-Akkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Zibbibo berries in Pantelleria, Sicily during BBCH 83-89, terpene pool development establishes total monoterpene pools increasing from 2.8 to 13.5 mg/L over 42 days, with free terpenoid pool reaching 1.9 mg/L and bound pool 11.6 mg/L representing 86% in precursor form, combined with sesquiterpene pool of 72 µg/L, establishing total terpenoid aromatic potential 7.1-fold greater than free volatile content under hot Mediterranean conditions with daytime temperatures exceeding 32°C moderated by maritime influence and cool nights of 18°C.",
  "editor_note": "Terpene_Pool_Development is subclass of Terpene_Accumulation representing cumulative terpenoid reservoir establishment. ||Distinguishes from individual synthesis processes by emphasizing integrated accumulation. ||Sibling to Monoterpene_Synthesis and Sesquiterpene_Production. ||Integrates mono- and sesqui-terpenes into composite potential. ||Bound fraction increases from 75-80% to 85-95% during ripening. ||Variety-specific trajectories reflect genetic capacity. || This process integrates multiple terpenoid compound classes into unified pool metrics, with total monoterpene pools comprising 2-15 mg/L in aromatic varieties distributed among linalool, geraniol, nerol, citronellol, alpha-terpineol, and related compounds, total sesquiterpene pools contributing 20-150 µg/L across various cultivars, and the combined free and bound fractions establishing the complete terpenoid potential available for immediate aromatic expression and subsequent precursor release. ||The dynamics of terpene pool development show variety-specific accumulation trajectories, with aromatic Muscat varieties demonstrating continuous linear accumulation throughout ripening achieving 10-15 mg/L total monoterpenes, while neutral varieties such as Chardonnay reach plateau levels of 0.2-0.4 mg/L by mid-ripening with minimal subsequent increase, reflecting fundamental genetic differences in biosynthetic capacity and pathway regulation. ||The balance between free and bound terpenoid pools evolves during ripening, with the bound fraction typically increasing from 75-80% at early post-veraison to 85-95% at harvest as glycosyltransferase activities conjugate newly synthesized terpenoids throughout the maturation period, establishing the precursor-dominated composition characteristic of ripe aromatic grapes. ||Environmental factors influence terpene pool development through effects on both biosynthetic rates and glycosylation efficiency, with moderate temperatures of 20-26°C and appropriate light exposure supporting optimal pool accumulation, while water stress may enhance terpenoid pathway activity through stress-responsive secondary metabolism induction. ||Viticultural practices targeting terpene pool development include canopy management optimizing cluster light exposure for enhanced terpene synthase expression, irrigation strategies imposing controlled water deficit that activates secondary metabolism, and harvest timing decisions capturing maximum pool development before potential late-season degradation or dilution through continued berry expansion. ||The relationship between terpene pool size at harvest and wine aromatic expression depends on subsequent release efficiency, with winemaking decisions regarding skin contact duration, enzyme additions, and yeast strain selection determining what fraction of accumulated potential is converted to sensory-active free volatiles in finished wines.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Wilson B et al (1984) Determination of free and bound monoterpenes in Muscat grapes. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 35: 95-100 || Williams PJ et al (1989) Glycosidic precursors of varietal grape and wine flavor. ACS Symposium Series 388: 35-48 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 295-305"
},

  "Aroma_Profile_Maturation": {
  "definition": "An Aroma_Profile_Maturation is an Aroma_Development consisting of qualitative refinement of accumulated volatile compounds and precursors during the final 10–21 days pre-harvest yielding the balanced varietal and terroir-expressive olfactory profile.",
  "alternative_term": "aromatic profile completion | scent profile maturation | olfactory character finalization | aroma balance achievement |+ Aromaprofil-Reifung | Duftprofil-Vollendung | olfaktorische Charakter-Finalisierung | Aroma-Balance-Erreichung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Petit Manseng berries in Jurançon, Pyrénées during BBCH 87-89, aroma profile maturation refines the aromatic character over the final 18 days, with monoterpene ratios shifting as linalool-to-alpha-terpineol ratio decreases from 3.2 to 2.1 through acid-catalyzed rearrangement, C6 aldehydes declining from 55 to 12 µg/L eliminating residual green character, and trained panel ratings for tropical-citrus character increasing from 5.8 to 8.2 while green-herbaceous scores decline from 4.2 to 1.8 on 10-point scales under late-harvest conditions with cool temperatures of 15°C.",
  "editor_note": "Aroma_Profile_Maturation is parent class under Aroma_Development representing terminal qualitative refinement phase. ||Distinguishes from Terpene_Accumulation which emphasizes quantitative increase. ||Contains subclasses Mature_Aroma_Expression, Cultivar_Typical_Aroma, and Optimal_Aroma_Development. ||Duration 10-21 days before harvest. ||Emphasizes balance, harmony, and typicity. ||Primary harvest timing criterion for aromatic quality. || This process involves subtle transformations in aromatic composition including shifts in monoterpene ratios through interconversion reactions such as acid-catalyzed linalool rearrangement to alpha-terpineol and geraniol-nerol isomerization, evolution of norisoprenoid profiles through continued carotenoid degradation generating late-ripening aromatic contributions, and progressive reduction of green-herbaceous character through declining C6 aldehyde content establishing the ripe-fruit-dominated aromatic balance characteristic of optimally mature grapes. ||The qualitative aspects of aroma profile maturation extend beyond simple concentration changes to encompass integration of disparate aromatic elements into cohesive olfactory impressions, development of complexity through accumulation of minor aromatic components that contribute nuance and depth, and achievement of varietal typicity enabling clear cultivar identification through characteristic scent signatures that define grape variety identity. ||Sensory evaluation of aroma profile maturation employs holistic assessment methods including overall aromatic quality ratings, harmony and balance scores integrating multiple scent attributes, and typicity judgments comparing observed profiles to variety benchmarks, complementing analytical measurements of individual compound concentrations that may not fully capture the perceptual integration underlying aromatic quality assessment. ||Environmental conditions during the final ripening phase critically influence aroma profile maturation, with moderate temperatures of 18-24°C favoring continued aromatic refinement and preservation of accumulated volatiles, while excessive heat may accelerate degradation of heat-labile compounds or shift aromatic profiles toward overripe character before optimal balance is achieved. ||The timing of aroma profile maturation relative to sugar accumulation and acid reduction varies among cultivars, with aromatic varieties often achieving optimal scent character coincident with traditional ripeness indicators while some cultivars may require extended hang-time or alternatively reach aromatic optimum before sugar targets are achieved, necessitating harvest timing decisions that balance multiple quality parameters.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 305-315 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30 || Coombe BG (1992) Research on development and ripening of the grape berry. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 43: 101-110"
},

  "Mature_Aroma_Expression": {
  "definition": "A Mature_Aroma_Expression is an Aroma_Profile_Maturation defined by stabilized volatile compound composition at harvest-appropriate levels integrating varietal character, ripeness indicators, and site-specific nuances.",
  "alternative_term": "ripe aroma character | mature olfactory profile | harvest-ready aromatic expression | optimal scent state |+ reife Aroma-Expression | reifer Duft-Charakter | erntereifes Aromaprofil | optimaler Duftzustand",
  "example_of_usage": "In Muscat Blanc à Petits Grains berries in Rutherglen, Australia at BBCH 89, mature aroma expression is characterized by total monoterpenes of 9.8 mg/L with linalool at 3.2 mg/L and geraniol at 2.1 mg/L providing intense floral-grape impact, norisoprenoid precursors of 165 µg/L contributing complexity, methoxypyrazine below 2 ng/L detection threshold, and C6 aldehydes at 18 µg/L indicating complete green character elimination, with trained panel aromatic intensity rating of 8.9 and overall quality of 8.6 on 10-point scales confirming achievement of optimal aromatic maturity.",
  "editor_note": "Mature_Aroma_Expression is subclass of Aroma_Profile_Maturation representing achieved quality state at ripening completion. ||Distinguishes from Optimal_Aroma_Development which emphasizes process optimization. ||Sibling to Cultivar_Typical_Aroma and Optimal_Aroma_Development. ||Characterized by specific compositional markers and sensory attributes. ||Integrates intensity, complexity, and balance. ||Harvest maturity indicator for aromatic quality. || This state encompasses specific compositional markers including monoterpene concentrations achieving variety-appropriate levels with aromatic cultivars showing 3-15 mg/L total terpenoids providing intense floral-fruity impact, norisoprenoid levels of 50-200 µg/L contributing complexity and background depth, minimal residual methoxypyrazine below variety-specific thresholds ensuring absence of excessive green character, and reduced C6 aldehyde content below 30 µg/L indicating completion of green-to-ripe aromatic transition. ||The sensory characteristics of mature aroma expression include predominance of ripe-fruit and floral aromatics over green-herbaceous notes, integration of multiple scent elements into harmonious overall impression without dominant off-characters, appropriate intensity matching varietal expectations with aromatic varieties showing pronounced but balanced scent profiles, and absence of overripe or degraded character indicating optimal harvest timing capture. ||The biochemical indicators of mature aroma expression include stabilization of terpene biosynthesis rates with daily accumulation declining to maintenance levels below 0.05 mg/L per day, completion of rapid-phase carotenoid degradation with norisoprenoid generation approaching equilibrium, and establishment of final free-to-bound terpenoid ratios of 0.08-0.18 representing mature partitioning between immediate aromatic expression and precursor potential. ||Temperature history during the final ripening phase influences mature aroma expression through effects on late-stage biosynthesis and compound stability, with cool conditions of 15-20°C during the final weeks preserving accumulated volatile compounds while warm conditions may accelerate degradation compromising optimal aromatic quality. ||Assessment of mature aroma expression requires integration of analytical quantification with sensory evaluation, as compositional measurements alone may not fully capture the perceptual qualities underlying aromatic maturity judgments that guide harvest timing decisions in quality-focused viticulture operations targeting optimal wine aromatic potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 305-315 || Marais J (1983) Terpenes in the aroma of grapes and wines. South African Journal of Enology and Viticulture 4: 49-58 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30"
},

  "Cultivar_Typical_Aroma": {
  "definition": "A Cultivar_Typical_Aroma is an Aroma_Development manifesting as the genetically determined olfactory signature realized through variety-specific expression of aromatic biosynthetic enzymes producing distinctive volatile profiles enabling varietal identification.",
  "alternative_term": "varietal aromatic character | variety-specific scent | genetic aroma signature | cultivar olfactory identity |+ sortentypisches Aroma | Rebsorten-Duft-Charakter | genetische Aroma-Signatur | Kultivar-olfaktorische-Identität",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer berries in Tramin, Alto Adige during BBCH 85-89, cultivar typical aroma develops through characteristic accumulation of linalool to 2.4 mg/L and distinctive cis-rose oxide to 85 µg/L providing the variety-defining lychee-rose character, with geraniol at 0.9 mg/L and citronellol at 0.4 mg/L contributing secondary floral complexity, trained panel varietal typicity rating of 9.2 on 10-point scale confirming achievement of characteristic Gewürztraminer aromatic expression recognizable by experienced tasters despite the warm vintage conditions averaging 25°C.",
  "editor_note": "Cultivar_Typical_Aroma is subclass of Aroma_Profile_Maturation representing genetically-determined varietal olfactory character. ||Distinguishes from Mature_Aroma_Expression which describes general maturity. ||Sibling to Mature_Aroma_Expression and Optimal_Aroma_Development. ||Determined by variety-specific enzyme expression. ||Enables varietal identification. ||Typicity criterion for quality assessment. ||Modified but not determined by environment. || This phenomenon reflects the genetic architecture of aromatic biosynthesis with variety-specific alleles of terpene synthases determining monoterpene profiles, unique expression patterns of O-methyltransferases establishing methoxypyrazine signatures in Sauvignon and Cabernet family varieties, variety-specific thiol precursor synthesis capacity creating tropical fruit potential in Sauvignon Blanc, and cultivar-distinctive carotenoid cleavage patterns generating characteristic norisoprenoid contributions to varietal complexity. ||The molecular basis of cultivar typical aroma involves transcriptional regulation through variety-specific promoter sequences controlling biosynthetic gene expression, structural variation in enzyme-coding genes affecting substrate specificity and product profiles, gene copy number variation influencing total biosynthetic capacity, and post-transcriptional regulatory mechanisms fine-tuning pathway outputs to establish the quantitative compound ratios that define varietal aromatic signatures. ||Sensory recognition of cultivar typical aroma enables variety identification through trained panel assessment and blind tasting exercises, with experienced evaluators achieving 75-95% correct identification rates for major aromatic varieties based on olfactory character alone, demonstrating the distinctiveness and reproducibility of varietal scent signatures despite substantial environmental and vintage variation that modifies but does not fundamentally alter genetic aromatic identity. ||The specific compounds defining cultivar typical aroma vary among varieties, with Muscat characterized by elevated linalool and geraniol providing floral-grape character, Gewürztraminer showing high linalool with distinctive rose oxide contribution, Riesling demonstrating balanced terpene profile with characteristic TDN petrol note development potential, and Sauvignon Blanc defined by methoxypyrazine herbaceous character combined with thiol-derived tropical fruit potential upon fermentation. ||Environmental and viticultural factors modulate but do not fundamentally determine cultivar typical aroma, with terroir effects capable of enhancing, diminishing, or subtly shifting the genetically-established baseline profile, while the essential varietal character remains recognizable across diverse growing conditions and vintage years.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Martin DM et al (2010) Functional annotation of the grapevine terpene synthase gene family. BMC Plant Biology 10: 226 || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30 || Ebeler SE and Thorngate JH (2009) Wine chemistry and flavor. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 57: 8098-8108"
},

  "Optimal_Aroma_Development": {
  "definition": "An Optimal_Aroma_Development is an Aroma_Development bearing the disposition to produce maximum expression of desirable olfactory characteristics at harvest under given environmental, viticultural, and genetic conditions across the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "ideal aroma development | maximum aromatic quality | optimal olfactory expression | peak scent achievement |+ optimale Aromaentwicklung | ideale Duft-Entwicklung | maximale aromatische Qualität | Spitzen-Duft-Erreichung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling berries in Wachau, Austria during BBCH 85-89, optimal aroma development achieves total monoterpene concentration of 2.8 mg/L at 6.5-fold average perception threshold with 8 individual terpenoids above detection, norisoprenoid precursors of 185 µg/L contributing 5 distinct scent notes including characteristic TDN precursor for aged petrol character, methoxypyrazine at 4 ng/L providing subtle herbaceous complexity without dominating green character, with trained panel overall aromatic quality rating of 9.3 on 10-point scale, complexity score of 8.9, and varietal typicity of 9.1, representing near-ideal expression under exceptional vintage conditions with mean ripening temperature of 19°C, 12% vine water deficit, and optimal canopy management achieving 35% cluster-zone leaf removal.",
  "editor_note": "Optimal_Aroma_Development is subclass of Aroma_Profile_Maturation representing the quality ideal for aromatic processes. ||Distinguishes from descriptive classes by emphasizing optimization. ||Sibling to Mature_Aroma_Expression and Cultivar_Typical_Aroma. ||Integrates intensity, complexity, balance, and typicity. ||Requires coordination of genetics, environment, and management. ||Benchmark for aromatic quality assessment. ||Vintage-dependent achievement. || This concept integrates multiple aromatic quality dimensions including sufficient intensity with key impact compounds exceeding perception thresholds by factors of 5-15 generating pronounced varietal character, adequate complexity with 12-18 or more distinct scent notes contributing to overall olfactory impression, appropriate balance between fruity-floral and green-herbaceous elements strongly favoring ripe character, and strong varietal typicity enabling clear cultivar identification and meeting consumer expectations for specific grape varieties. ||The achievement of optimal aroma development requires coordination among environmental factors including moderate temperatures of 18-25°C preserving accumulated volatiles while supporting continued biosynthesis, adequate but not excessive light exposure promoting terpenoid pathway expression without thermal stress, and appropriate vine water status imposing mild deficit that enhances secondary metabolism without compromising photosynthetic function or inducing excessive berry dehydration. ||Viticultural practices supporting optimal aroma development encompass canopy management ensuring cluster microclimate optimization for enhanced terpene accumulation, crop load adjustment balancing vine capacity with aromatic compound concentration objectives, irrigation scheduling imposing controlled water deficit during the post-veraison period that activates stress-responsive secondary metabolism, and harvest timing capturing peak aromatic quality before potential late-season degradation or overripeness shifts olfactory profiles away from optimal expression. ||Assessment of optimal aroma development employs integrated evaluation methods combining analytical quantification of marker compounds with sensory assessment of overall aromatic quality, recognizing that premium wine production requires achievement of target values across multiple parameters including intensity, complexity, balance, and typicity rather than optimization of individual factors in isolation. ||Vintage variation in optimal aroma development potential reflects climatic differences affecting biosynthetic processes, with favorable years achieving near-ideal aromatic expression while challenging vintages may require management intervention or quality expectations adjustment to accommodate suboptimal development conditions, with the consistency of achieving optimal development across vintages representing a hallmark of superior vineyard sites and management programs.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 305-315 || Reynolds AG (2010) Managing Wine Quality Vol 1 Viticulture and Wine Quality Woodhead Publishing || Robinson AL et al (2014) Origins of grape and wine aroma. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 65: 1-30"
},

  "Phenolic_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Phenolic_Maturation is a Ripening comprising quantitative accumulation, structural transformation, and qualitative refinement of anthocyanins, proanthocyanidins, flavonols, and hydroxycinnamic acids over the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "phenolic compound maturation | phenolic ripening | tannin and anthocyanin development | phenolic quality development |+ phenolische Reifung | Phenol-Verbindungs-Reifung | Tannin-und-Anthocyan-Entwicklung | phenolische Qualitäts-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon berries in Napa Valley, California during BBCH 81-89, phenolic maturation establishes total anthocyanin content increasing from 0.2 to 1.85 mg/g fresh weight over 48 days, skin tannin concentration rising from 1.2 to 3.8 mg/g skin, and seed tannin declining from 8.5 to 4.2 mg/g seed through oxidative browning, with total phenolic index increasing from 45 to 72 absorbance units while tannin-to-anthocyanin ratio decreases from 6.2 to 2.8 indicating progressive color and structural balance under warm conditions averaging 28°C.",
  "editor_note": "Phenolic_Maturation is parent class under Ripening representing all phenolic compound developmental processes. ||Contains subclasses Anthocyanin_Accumulation, Tannin_Polymerization, Skin_Phenolic_Development, and Seed_Phenolic_Maturation. ||Duration 35-50 days post-veraison. ||Integrates pigment accumulation, tannin modification, and copigmentation development. ||Critical for red wine quality assessment. ||Tissue-specific processes in skin and seed compartments. || This process integrates multiple biosynthetic and modification pathways operating in distinct berry tissues, with anthocyanin accumulation proceeding in exocarp hypodermal cells where flavonoid pathway enzymes show coordinated expression generating the red-blue-purple pigments responsible for berry and wine color, proanthocyanidin polymerization occurring in both skin and seed tissues producing the condensed tannins that contribute astringency and structure, and flavonol and hydroxycinnamic acid accumulation providing copigmentation cofactors and antioxidant capacity that modulate color expression and wine stability. ||The temporal progression of phenolic maturation shows compound-class-specific dynamics with anthocyanin accumulation initiating at veraison and continuing throughout ripening in red varieties, seed tannin biosynthesis largely complete before veraison with subsequent maturation involving oxidative browning and polymerization changes, and skin tannin accumulation continuing post-veraison with progressive structural modifications affecting extractability and sensory properties. ||Cellular localization demonstrates tissue-specific phenolic distribution with anthocyanins exclusively in vacuoles of hypodermal skin cells, seed tannins concentrated in outer integument and inner seed coat tissues, and skin tannins distributed across multiple exocarp cell layers with concentration gradients affecting extraction during winemaking. ||Temperature during ripening profoundly influences phenolic maturation through effects on biosynthetic enzyme activities, compound stability, and structural modification rates, with moderate temperatures of 20-28°C generally supporting optimal phenolic development while temperature extremes may limit anthocyanin accumulation through thermal degradation or reduce tannin quality through accelerated oxidation. ||Cultivar genetics fundamentally determine phenolic maturation potential through variety-specific expression of flavonoid pathway genes, with high-color varieties such as Alicante Bouschet and Petit Verdot accumulating anthocyanins to 2000-4000 mg/kg compared to lighter varieties such as Pinot Noir reaching 400-800 mg/kg, and thick-skinned varieties accumulating substantially higher skin tannin concentrations than thin-skinned cultivars under equivalent conditions. ||The relationship between phenolic maturation and wine quality reflects the fundamental importance of adequate color intensity, balanced astringency, and stable phenolic structure for red wine sensory appeal and longevity, with harvest timing decisions targeting optimal phenolic development frequently diverging from decisions based solely on sugar-acid balance, necessitating integrated assessment of multiple ripeness parameters. ||Viticultural practices influence phenolic maturation through effects on vine physiology, cluster microclimate, and berry composition, with moderate water deficit enhancing anthocyanin accumulation, appropriate crop load ensuring adequate phenolic concentration, and optimized light exposure promoting flavonoid pathway expression without inducing thermal degradation of accumulated pigments.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009718 ## anthocyanin-containing compound biosynthetic process | 0.80", "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010023 ## proanthocyanidin biosynthetic process | 0.70", "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0051555 ## flavonol biosynthetic process | 0.80" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 6 pp 310-340 || Kennedy JA et al (2006) Grape and wine phenolics. In Chemistry and Biology of Ellagitannins World Scientific pp 220-255 || Adams DO (2006) Phenolics and ripening in grape berries. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 249-256"
},

  "Anthocyanin_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "An Anthocyanin_Accumulation is a Phenolic_Maturation comprising biosynthesis and vacuolar deposition of cyanidin, delphinidin, peonidin, petunidin, and malvidin glycosides in berry skin cells over the 30–45 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "anthocyanin biosynthesis and deposition | berry pigment accumulation | color pigment accumulation | anthocyanin development |+ Anthocyan-Akkumulation | Anthocyan-Biosynthese-und-Einlagerung | Beeren-Pigment-Akkumulation | Farbpigment-Anreicherung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot berries in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux during BBCH 81-89, anthocyanin accumulation increases total anthocyanin content from 0.15 to 1.65 mg/g fresh weight over 42 days, with malvidin-3-glucoside accumulating to 0.82 mg/g representing 50% of total anthocyanins, petunidin-3-glucoside reaching 0.28 mg/g, and delphinidin-3-glucoside at 0.22 mg/g, establishing the characteristic Merlot color profile under moderate oceanic conditions averaging 24°C with beneficial diurnal temperature variation.",
  "editor_note": "Anthocyanin_Accumulation is parent class under Phenolic_Maturation representing pigment biosynthesis and deposition in skin. ||Contains subclasses Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis, Color_Intensity_Development, and Anthocyanin_Profile_Evolution. ||Duration 30-45 days post-veraison. ||Exclusive to hypodermal exocarp cells. ||Temperature and light sensitive. ||Cultivar-specific accumulation capacity ranges from 400 to 4000 mg/kg. || This process involves the final steps of the flavonoid biosynthetic pathway with anthocyanidin synthase converting leucoanthocyanidins to anthocyanidins, UDP-glucose flavonoid glucosyltransferase attaching glucose to form stable anthocyanin glucosides, and O-methyltransferases generating the methylated derivatives peonidin, petunidin, and malvidin from their respective unmethylated precursors cyanidin and delphinidin. ||The quantitative aspects of anthocyanin accumulation show dramatic cultivar variation, with deeply colored varieties such as Alicante Bouschet accumulating 2000-4000 mg/kg berry weight, moderately pigmented varieties such as Cabernet Sauvignon reaching 1000-2000 mg/kg, and lightly colored varieties such as Pinot Noir achieving 400-800 mg/kg under equivalent ripening conditions, reflecting genetic differences in pathway enzyme expression levels and regulatory factor activities. ||Cellular localization restricts anthocyanin accumulation to hypodermal cell layers of the exocarp where flavonoid pathway enzymes show coordinate expression, with synthesized anthocyanins transported into vacuolar compartments through glutathione S-transferase mediated mechanisms and tonoplast transporters, establishing the vacuolar pigment pools that confer berry color visible through the overlying epidermal cell layer. ||The temporal dynamics of anthocyanin accumulation show characteristic patterns with rapid initial accumulation during the first 2-3 weeks post-veraison when biosynthetic enzyme activities peak, continued but declining accumulation during mid-ripening, and potential plateau or slight decline during late ripening as degradation may partially offset continued synthesis in some varieties and conditions. ||Temperature profoundly influences anthocyanin accumulation, with optimal synthesis occurring at moderate temperatures of 20-25°C daytime and 15-18°C nighttime, while temperatures exceeding 35°C substantially inhibit accumulation through enzyme inactivation and accelerated pigment degradation, explaining the characteristic color deficiency observed in heat-affected vintages. ||Light exposure promotes anthocyanin accumulation through activation of MYB transcription factors that regulate flavonoid pathway gene expression, with appropriately exposed clusters showing 30-80% higher anthocyanin content than heavily shaded fruit, though excessive direct radiation may cause thermal damage that counteracts the positive light effects.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Boss PK et al (1996) Expression of anthocyanin biosynthesis pathway genes in red and white grapes. Plant Molecular Biology 32: 565-569 || Castellarin SD et al (2007) Colour variation in red grapevines. Planta 227: 895-908 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 310-325"
},

  "Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis is an Anthocyanin_Accumulation realized through sustained flavonoid pathway gene expression and biosynthetic enzyme activity producing daily increment of 20–80 mg/kg anthocyanin in berry skin cells.",
  "alternative_term": "continuous anthocyanin biosynthesis | sustained pigment synthesis | ongoing anthocyanin production | progressive pigment formation |+ progressive Anthocyan-Synthese | kontinuierliche Anthocyan-Biosynthese | anhaltende Pigment-Synthese | fortlaufende Anthocyan-Produktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Syrah berries in Côte-Rôtie, Rhône Valley during BBCH 83-89, progressive anthocyanin synthesis maintains accumulation rates of 45 mg/kg per day during the first 18 days post-veraison, declining to 28 mg/kg per day during days 18-30, and further decreasing to 12 mg/kg per day during the final 12 days, generating total accumulation from 0.18 to 1.92 mg/g fresh weight over 42 days with UFGT enzyme activity peaking at 85 nmol/min/g fresh weight at day 15 under moderate temperatures averaging 25°C.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis is subclass of Anthocyanin_Accumulation representing the sustained biosynthetic process. ||Distinguishes from Color_Intensity_Development which emphasizes visual outcome. ||Sibling to Color_Intensity_Development and Anthocyanin_Profile_Evolution. ||Synthesis rates of 20-80 mg/kg per day during active phase. ||MYB transcription factor regulated. ||Temperature sensitive with optimal at 20-26°C. || This process involves the coordinate expression and activity of multiple pathway enzymes including phenylalanine ammonia lyase initiating phenylpropanoid flux, chalcone synthase and chalcone isomerase generating the flavanone naringenin, flavanone 3-hydroxylase and flavonoid 3-prime-hydroxylase producing dihydroflavonols, dihydroflavonol reductase reducing these to leucoanthocyanidins, and anthocyanidin synthase catalyzing the final oxidation step generating colored anthocyanidins that are subsequently glucosylated and methylated to form stable vacuolar pigments. ||The temporal dynamics of progressive anthocyanin synthesis show characteristic phases with initial rapid synthesis during the first 14-21 days post-veraison when enzyme activities and substrate availability peak, sustained intermediate synthesis during mid-ripening maintaining accumulation rates of 25-50 mg/kg per day, and declining synthesis during late ripening as regulatory programs shift and potential degradation begins to offset continued production in some conditions. ||The transcriptional regulation of progressive anthocyanin synthesis involves MYB transcription factors including VvMYBA1 and VvMYBA2 that activate structural gene expression, with these regulatory genes themselves induced by developmental signals at veraison and modulated by environmental factors including light and temperature throughout the subsequent ripening period. ||Substrate availability influences progressive anthocyanin synthesis rates through competition with other branches of phenylpropanoid metabolism, with adequate carbon flux through the shikimate and phenylpropanoid pathways required to sustain anthocyanin production while simultaneously supporting proanthocyanidin synthesis and lignification occurring in parallel during berry ripening. ||Temperature modulation of progressive synthesis involves both direct effects on enzyme catalytic rates and indirect effects on regulatory gene expression, with optimal synthesis at moderate temperatures of 20-26°C daytime while high temperatures exceeding 30-35°C reduce synthesis through transcriptional repression of pathway genes and potential enzyme denaturation. ||The relationship between progressive synthesis rates and final anthocyanin content integrates biosynthetic capacity with potential degradation losses, with favorable conditions enabling continuous net accumulation while stress conditions may create periods of net loss that reduce final pigment concentrations below the potential established by maximum synthetic capacity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Boss PK et al (1996) Expression of anthocyanin biosynthesis pathway genes. Plant Molecular Biology 32: 565-569 || Kobayashi S et al (2002) Retrotransposon-induced mutations in grape skin color. Science 304: 982 || Castellarin SD et al (2007) Transcriptional regulation of anthocyanin biosynthesis. Plant Physiology 145: 1451-1469"
},

  "Color_Intensity_Development": {
  "definition": "A Color_Intensity_Development is an Anthocyanin_Accumulation manifesting as deepening saturation of red-purple-blue berry coloration through cumulative anthocyanin concentration combined with copigmentation interactions and pH-dependent chromophore equilibria.",
  "alternative_term": "berry color development | visual pigmentation increase | color saturation development | pigment intensity enhancement |+ Farbintensitäts-Entwicklung | Beeren-Farb-Entwicklung | visuelle Pigmentierungs-Zunahme | Farbsättigungs-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Petit Verdot berries in Margaret River, Australia during BBCH 81-89, color intensity development progresses from initial pink coloration with color density of 2.8 AU at veraison to deep purple-black with color density of 18.5 AU at harvest over 45 days, with CIELab lightness decreasing from 45 to 22, a* red coordinate increasing from 18 to 42, and b* blue coordinate shifting from +5 to -8 indicating blue hue development, paralleling anthocyanin increase from 0.25 to 2.85 mg/g and copigmentation enhancement contributing 42% of total color at optimal ripeness.",
  "editor_note": "Color_Intensity_Development is subclass of Anthocyanin_Accumulation representing visual color outcome. ||Distinguishes from Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis which describes biosynthetic process. ||Sibling to Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis and Anthocyanin_Profile_Evolution. ||Integrates anthocyanin concentration with copigmentation and pH effects. ||Spectrophotometric and colorimetric assessment. ||Threshold visibility at 50-100 mg/kg anthocyanins. || This process reflects the relationship between absolute anthocyanin concentration and perceived color intensity, with color development following characteristic patterns as pigment levels increase from threshold visibility of 50-100 mg/kg through moderate intensity at 500-800 mg/kg to deeply saturated color above 1500 mg/kg, though the precise concentration-intensity relationship varies with anthocyanin composition, copigmentation status, and vacuolar pH conditions affecting chromophore expression. ||The spectroscopic basis of color intensity development involves the pH-dependent equilibrium among anthocyanin structural forms, with the red flavylium cation predominating at low vacuolar pH of 2.5-3.5, the colorless carbinol pseudobase forming at higher pH, and quinoidal base forms contributing blue-purple hues, with the distribution among forms determining the hue and intensity of color expression at any given anthocyanin concentration. ||Copigmentation interactions enhance color intensity development through molecular stacking of anthocyanins with colorless copigments including flavonols, hydroxycinnamic acids, and other flavonoids, producing hyperchromic shifts that increase apparent color intensity by 30-50% beyond the contribution of anthocyanins alone, with copigment-to-anthocyanin ratios influencing the magnitude of this enhancement throughout ripening. ||The temporal progression of color intensity development shows variety-specific patterns with rapid initial color development during early post-veraison as anthocyanins first exceed visual threshold, continued intensity increase during mid-ripening paralleling anthocyanin accumulation, and potential intensity stabilization or decline during late ripening when degradation may reduce anthocyanin content or structural changes modify chromophore expression. ||Environmental factors influence color intensity development through effects on both anthocyanin accumulation and color expression, with excessive temperature reducing intensity through inhibition of synthesis and accelerated degradation, while appropriate light exposure enhances intensity through promotion of anthocyanin and copigment accumulation. ||Assessment of color intensity development employs multiple methods including visual scoring systems rating berry color on structured scales, spectrophotometric measurements of color density and hue at characteristic wavelengths, and colorimetric analysis using CIELab coordinates that quantify lightness, red-green balance, and yellow-blue balance providing comprehensive color characterization.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Boulton R (2001) The copigmentation of anthocyanins and its role in the color of red wine. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 52: 67-87 || Ribéreau-Gayon P et al (2006) Handbook of Enology Vol 2 The Chemistry of Wine 2nd Ed Wiley pp 141-205 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 315-322"
},

  "Anthocyanin_Profile_Evolution": {
  "definition": "An Anthocyanin_Profile_Evolution is an Anthocyanin_Accumulation exhibiting compositional shift from tri-hydroxylated delphinidin and petunidin derivatives toward methylated and acylated forms producing the mature anthocyanin profile influencing wine color stability and hue.",
  "alternative_term": "anthocyanin composition change | pigment profile development | anthocyanin ratio evolution | pigment species distribution change |+ Anthocyan-Profil-Evolution | Anthocyan-Zusammensetzungs-Änderung | Pigment-Profil-Entwicklung | Anthocyan-Verhältnis-Evolution",
  "example_of_usage": "In Tempranillo berries in Ribera del Duero, Spain during BBCH 83-89, anthocyanin profile evolution shifts malvidin-3-glucoside proportion from 42% at early post-veraison to 58% at harvest over 40 days, with concurrent increase in acylated forms from 18% to 35% of total anthocyanins, while delphinidin-3-glucoside decreases proportionally from 22% to 14% and cyanidin-3-glucoside from 8% to 4%, establishing the characteristic Tempranillo profile with high malvidin and substantial acylation under warm continental conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Anthocyanin_Profile_Evolution is subclass of Anthocyanin_Accumulation representing compositional changes among anthocyanin species. ||Distinguishes from total accumulation by emphasizing relative proportions. ||Sibling to Progressive_Anthocyanin_Synthesis and Color_Intensity_Development. ||Malvidin typically increases from 35-45% to 45-60%. ||Acylated forms increase during late ripening. ||Cultivar-specific profiles reflect genetic enzyme expression differences. || This process involves the continued activity of O-methyltransferases converting cyanidin to peonidin and delphinidin to petunidin and malvidin, with methylation typically increasing throughout ripening such that malvidin-3-glucoside proportion rises from 35-45% at early post-veraison to 45-60% at harvest in many varieties, establishing malvidin dominance characteristic of Vitis vinifera anthocyanin profiles. ||The biosynthetic basis of profile evolution reflects differential enzyme activities and substrate preferences, with flavonoid 3-prime-hydroxylase favoring tri-hydroxylated B-ring formation generating delphinidin precursors, flavonoid 3-prime-5-prime-hydroxylase competing for substrates, and subsequent O-methyltransferase activities determining the extent of methylation among accumulated anthocyanidins that establishes final profile proportions. ||Acylation represents an additional dimension of profile evolution, with anthocyanin acyltransferases attaching acetyl, p-coumaroyl, and caffeoyl groups to glucose residues of anthocyanin glucosides, typically increasing during late ripening such that acylated forms may comprise 20-50% of total anthocyanins at harvest in varieties expressing high acyltransferase activities. ||The cultivar-specific nature of anthocyanin profile evolution reflects genetic variation in pathway enzyme expression, with varieties such as Cabernet Sauvignon showing high malvidin proportions of 60-70% at maturity compared to varieties such as Pinot Noir maintaining higher cyanidin representation of 15-25%, and varieties such as Nebbiolo demonstrating distinctive profiles with elevated peonidin contribution reflecting reduced methyltransferase activities toward certain substrates. ||Environmental factors modulate anthocyanin profile evolution through differential effects on individual pathway enzymes, with temperature and light conditions influencing the relative activities of hydroxylases, methyltransferases, and acyltransferases that determine profile proportions independent of total anthocyanin accumulation. ||The enological significance of anthocyanin profile evolution relates to wine color properties, with malvidin-based anthocyanins showing greater color stability through enhanced participation in copigmentation and polymerization reactions compared to cyanidin derivatives, while acylated anthocyanins demonstrate improved stability under winemaking conditions due to intramolecular copigmentation protecting the chromophore from hydration.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Castellarin SD et al (2007) Colour variation in red grapevines. Planta 227: 895-908 || Fournier-Level A et al (2009) Quantitative genetic bases of anthocyanin variation in grape. BMC Plant Biology 9: 147 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 318-325"
},

  "Tannin_Polymerization": {
  "definition": "A Tannin_Polymerization is a Phenolic_Maturation comprising oxidative and enzymatic condensation of monomeric flavan-3-ol units including catechin, epicatechin, and galloylated derivatives generating polymeric tannin structures determining wine astringency, mouthfeel, and color stabilization capacity.",
  "alternative_term": "proanthocyanidin polymerization | condensed tannin polymer formation | tannin chain growth | tannin structural development |+ Tannin-Polymerisation | Proanthocyanidin-Polymerisation | kondensierte Tannin-Polymer-Bildung | Tannin-Ketten-Wachstum",
  "example_of_usage": "In Tannat berries in Madiran, France during BBCH 79-89, tannin polymerization modifies seed tannin mean degree of polymerization from 8.5 at veraison to 6.2 at harvest through oxidative cleavage concurrent with browning, while skin tannin mDP increases from 28 to 35 through continued condensation, with total condensed tannin content in skins increasing from 2.8 to 5.5 mg/g while seed tannin concentration per berry remains stable but extractability decreases 45% through structural modification under warm conditions averaging 26°C.",
  "editor_note": "Tannin_Polymerization is parent class under Phenolic_Maturation representing proanthocyanidin structural modification. ||Contains subclasses Tannin_Chain_Elongation, Condensation_Reactions, and Tannin_Structure_Maturation. ||Occurs in both skin and seed tissues with different dynamics. ||Seed mDP 5-12 decreases slightly || skin mDP 25-45 may increase. ||Influences astringency perception and color stability. ||Oxidative and acid-catalyzed mechanisms. || This process involves multiple reaction mechanisms including acid-catalyzed interflavonoid bond formation connecting C4 of one unit to C8 or C6 of another, oxidative coupling generating additional linkage types, and potential depolymerization through cleavage reactions that modify the mean degree of polymerization characterizing tannin populations in different berry tissues and at different developmental stages. ||The quantitative aspects of tannin polymerization show tissue-specific patterns, with seed tannins demonstrating mean degree of polymerization of 5-12 units at veraison decreasing slightly through oxidative modification during ripening, while skin tannins show mDP of 25-45 units that may increase modestly through continued polymerization during the post-veraison period. ||The biochemical basis of tannin polymerization involves both enzymatic and non-enzymatic mechanisms, with polyphenol oxidases and peroxidases potentially catalyzing oxidative coupling in the presence of oxygen, while acid-catalyzed condensation proceeds spontaneously under the acidic vacuolar conditions of pH 2.5-3.5 where proanthocyanidins accumulate. ||Structural changes accompanying polymerization include modification of interflavonoid linkage distribution, with A-type bonds forming through additional oxidative coupling between already-linked units, galloylation patterns evolving through continued esterification, and potential incorporation of anthocyanins into tannin polymers generating pigmented tannin species that contribute to wine color stability. ||The sensory significance of tannin polymerization relates to astringency perception, with highly polymerized tannins of mDP greater than 20-30 demonstrating greater astringent intensity but potentially softer quality compared to shorter oligomers, while the galloylation percentage influences both astringency intensity and quality contributing to the characteristic mouthfeel differences among grape varieties. ||Temperature during ripening influences tannin polymerization through effects on oxidative reaction rates and enzymatic activities, with warm conditions potentially accelerating polymerization and associated browning reactions particularly in seed tissues where oxidative modification is pronounced during ripening.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kennedy JA et al (2001) Changes in grape seed polyphenols during ripening. Phytochemistry 55: 77-85 || Downey MO et al (2003) Analysis of tannins in seeds and skins of Shiraz. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 9: 15-27 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 325-335"
},

  "Tannin_Chain_Elongation": {
  "definition": "A Tannin_Chain_Elongation is a Tannin_Polymerization comprising interflavonoid bond formation adding catechin, epicatechin, or epigallocatechin extension units to existing oligomeric and polymeric chains in berry skin tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "tannin polymer growth | proanthocyanidin chain extension | tannin length increase | polymer elongation |+ Tannin-Ketten-Verlängerung | Tannin-Polymer-Wachstum | Proanthocyanidin-Ketten-Extension | Tannin-Längen-Zunahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In Mourvèdre berries in Bandol, Provence during BBCH 85-89, tannin chain elongation increases skin tannin mean degree of polymerization from 26 to 38 over 35 days through continued condensation of epicatechin extension units, with phloroglucinolysis revealing extension unit composition of 72% epicatechin, 18% epigallocatechin, and 10% epicatechin-gallate, while terminal units show 65% epicatechin reflecting preferential chain initiation from this monomer under Mediterranean conditions averaging 27°C.",
  "editor_note": "Tannin_Chain_Elongation is subclass of Tannin_Polymerization representing polymer length increase through unit addition. ||Distinguishes from Condensation_Reactions which describes bonding mechanism. ||Sibling to Condensation_Reactions and Tannin_Structure_Maturation. ||Primarily active in skin tissues post-veraison. ||Assessed by mDP increase through phloroglucinolysis. ||Influences astringency intensity and quality. || This process involves the formation of C4-C8 or C4-C6 interflavonoid bonds through acid-catalyzed condensation, with carbocation intermediates generated at the C4 position of flavan-3-ol units attacking nucleophilic C6 or C8 positions of other units, creating the B-type procyanidin linkages that constitute the predominant bond type in grape proanthocyanidins. ||The dynamics of tannin chain elongation show tissue-specific patterns reflecting different biosynthetic and modification environments, with skin tannins demonstrating potential for continued elongation during post-veraison ripening as newly synthesized monomers become available for incorporation into existing polymers, while seed tannins show limited elongation after veraison when active proanthocyanidin biosynthesis largely ceases and subsequent modifications primarily involve oxidative reactions rather than chain extension. ||The quantitative assessment of chain elongation employs analytical methods including phloroglucinolysis and thiolysis that cleave interflavonoid bonds generating terminal and extension unit fragments whose ratio determines mean degree of polymerization, with chain elongation detected as increasing mDP values over time that distinguish active elongation from stable polymer populations. ||Substrate availability influences chain elongation rates through the requirement for continued flavan-3-ol monomer synthesis or release from other sources, with elongation potential limited when biosynthesis declines during late ripening or when monomers are preferentially diverted to other metabolic fates including glycosylation or oxidation rather than polymerization. ||The sensory significance of chain elongation relates to astringency properties, with longer tannin chains generally producing more intense but potentially softer astringency due to enhanced protein precipitation capacity combined with modified binding kinetics that influence the temporal development of astringent sensation in the mouth. ||Environmental factors including temperature and oxidative conditions modulate chain elongation through effects on reaction kinetics and competing processes, with moderate conditions favoring controlled elongation while oxidative stress may promote alternative modification pathways that reduce elongation efficiency.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kennedy JA and Jones GP (2001) Analysis of proanthocyanidin cleavage products following acid-catalysis in the presence of excess phloroglucinol. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 49: 1740-1746 || Downey MO et al (2003) Analysis of tannins in seeds and skins of Shiraz. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 9: 15-27 || Souquet JM et al (1996) Polymeric proanthocyanidins from grape skins. Phytochemistry 43: 509-512"
},

  "Condensation_Reactions": {
  "definition": "A Condensation_Reactions is a Tannin_Polymerization realized through acid-catalyzed C4–C8 and C4–C6 coupling producing B-type procyanidin linkages and oxidative coupling producing A-type C2–O–C7 linkages between flavan-3-ol units.",
  "alternative_term": "interflavonoid condensation | tannin bond formation | procyanidin coupling | flavanol condensation |+ Kondensationsreaktionen | Interflavanoid-Kondensation | Tannin-Bindungs-Bildung | Procyanidin-Kopplung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Monastrell berries in Jumilla, Spain during BBCH 83-89, condensation reactions generate B-type procyanidin linkages at rates sufficient to increase skin tannin mDP from 24 to 32 over 38 days, with C4-C8 bonds comprising 85% and C4-C6 bonds 15% of total interflavonoid linkages as determined by NMR analysis, while oxidative conditions promote A-type bond formation reaching 8% of total linkages by harvest under hot conditions averaging 32°C that enhance oxidative coupling.",
  "editor_note": "Condensation_Reactions is subclass of Tannin_Polymerization representing the specific bond-forming chemistry. ||Distinguishes from Tannin_Chain_Elongation which describes polymer growth outcome. ||Sibling to Tannin_Chain_Elongation and Tannin_Structure_Maturation. ||Includes acid-catalyzed B-type and oxidative A-type mechanisms. ||pH, temperature, and enzyme dependent. ||Continues during winemaking and aging. || This process involves multiple reaction mechanisms operating under the acidic vacuolar conditions of pH 2.5-3.5 where proanthocyanidins accumulate, with acid-catalyzed condensation proceeding through protonation of the C-ring hydroxyl generating carbocation intermediates at C4 that undergo electrophilic attack on electron-rich A-ring positions of other flavan-3-ol units to form new carbon-carbon bonds extending polymer chains. ||The stereochemistry of condensation reactions influences product structure, with the configuration at C4 determining whether 4-alpha or 4-beta linkages form, and the regioselectivity between C6 and C8 attack positions generating structural diversity within the polymer population that affects physical properties and biological activities. ||Oxidative condensation represents an alternative mechanism generating A-type proanthocyanidins through radical coupling processes potentially catalyzed by polyphenol oxidases or occurring spontaneously in the presence of oxygen, producing doubly-linked units with both C4-C8 and C2-O-C7 bonds that demonstrate enhanced resistance to acid-catalyzed cleavage and modified sensory properties compared to B-type polymers. ||The kinetics of condensation reactions depend on substrate concentration, pH, temperature, and potential enzymatic catalysis, with reaction rates increasing at lower pH where protonation equilibria favor carbocation formation, at elevated temperatures that provide activation energy for bond formation, and in the presence of enzymes that may facilitate electron transfer in oxidative coupling. ||Non-enzymatic condensation proceeds continuously in acidic vacuolar compartments throughout berry development and post-harvest handling, with reaction extent determined by the duration of contact between reactive intermediates and potential nucleophiles in the proanthocyanidin-rich storage pools. ||The practical significance of condensation reactions extends beyond the berry into winemaking and wine aging, where continued condensation modifies tannin structure and properties over time, contributing to the evolution of astringency and mouthfeel characteristics that distinguish young wines from aged productions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Haslam E (1980) In vino veritas: oligomeric procyanidins and the ageing of red wines. Phytochemistry 19: 2577-2582 || Es-Safi NE et al (1999) Competition between (+)-catechin and (-)-epicatechin in acetaldehyde-induced polymerization. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 47: 2088-2095 || Kennedy JA et al (2006) Grape and wine phenolics. In Chemistry and Biology of Ellagitannins World Scientific pp 220-255"
},

  "Tannin_Structure_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Tannin_Structure_Maturation is a Tannin_Polymerization comprising progressive modification of mean degree of polymerization, galloylation percentage, prodelphindin content, and subunit composition through polymerization, oxidation, and compositional change.",
  "alternative_term": "tannin structural evolution | proanthocyanidin structure development | tannin quality maturation | tannin compositional change |+ Tannin-Struktur-Reifung | Tannin-Struktur-Evolution | Proanthocyanidin-Struktur-Entwicklung | Tannin-Qualitäts-Reifung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Aglianico berries in Taurasi, Campania during BBCH 81-89, tannin structure maturation modifies skin tannin properties with mDP increasing from 25 to 34, galloylation remaining stable at 5.2-5.8%, and prodelphindin content at 32-35% over 48 days, while seed tannin structure shows mDP decline from 9.2 to 7.5, galloylation stable at 28-31%, and progressive browning reducing extractability by 52% as measured by protein precipitation assay, establishing the mature phenolic profile characteristic of this late-ripening variety under warm southern Italian conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Tannin_Structure_Maturation is subclass of Tannin_Polymerization representing comprehensive structural evolution. ||Distinguishes from individual modification processes by integrating multiple structural changes. ||Sibling to Tannin_Chain_Elongation and Condensation_Reactions. ||Encompasses mDP, galloylation, prodelphindin, and oxidation changes. ||Tissue-specific patterns in skin versus seed. ||Relates to astringency quality evolution. || This process encompasses multiple concurrent structural modifications including potential chain elongation through continued condensation increasing mean polymer length in skin tissues, oxidative browning particularly pronounced in seed tannins where quinone formation and subsequent reactions modify chromophore properties and reduce extractability, and shifts in the proportions of different extension and terminal units reflecting continued biosynthesis and potential selective degradation of specific structural forms. ||The galloylation percentage, representing the proportion of flavan-3-ol units bearing gallic acid ester substituents at the C3 position, typically remains relatively stable during ripening in most varieties though slight increases may occur through continued galloylation of existing polymers, with final galloylation levels of 15-35% in seeds and 2-8% in skins contributing to the astringency intensity and quality differences between tannins from these tissues. ||The prodelphindin content, reflecting units bearing trihydroxylated B-rings derived from epigallocatechin incorporation, shows tissue-specific patterns with skin tannins containing 20-40% prodelphindin units compared to seed tannins with typically less than 5%, contributing to differences in protein binding behavior and sensory properties between skin and seed tannin populations. ||Oxidative modification of tannin structure proceeds through polyphenol oxidase and peroxidase catalyzed reactions generating quinone intermediates that undergo nucleophilic addition, rearrangement, and polymerization, producing the characteristic browning of seed coat tissues during ripening and reducing tannin extractability through formation of oxidized polymers with modified solubility properties. ||The sensory significance of tannin structure maturation relates to the evolution of astringency quality, with mature tannin structures typically demonstrating softer, rounder astringency compared to harsh, aggressive character associated with immature seed tannins, reflecting structural changes that modify protein precipitation kinetics and oral sensation development during tasting.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kennedy JA et al (2001) Changes in grape seed polyphenols during ripening. Phytochemistry 55: 77-85 || Ristic R and Iland PG (2005) Relationships between seed and berry development of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 11: 43-58 || Adams DO (2006) Phenolics and ripening in grape berries. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 249-256"
},

  "Skin_Phenolic_Development": {
  "definition": "A Skin_Phenolic_Development is a Phenolic_Maturation comprising coordinated accumulation and structural modification of anthocyanins, proanthocyanidins, flavonols, and hydroxycinnamic acids in hypodermal and epidermal cell layers of the berry exocarp over the 35–50 day post-véraison phase.",
  "alternative_term": "exocarp phenolic development | skin tannin and anthocyanin development | berry skin phenolic maturation | skin polyphenol development |+ Haut-Phenol-Entwicklung | Exokarp-Phenol-Entwicklung | Beerenhaut-phenolische-Reifung | Haut-Polyphenol-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Nebbiolo berries in Barolo, Piedmont during BBCH 81-89, skin phenolic development establishes anthocyanin content increasing from 0.15 to 0.85 mg/g fresh weight, skin tannin concentration rising from 1.8 to 4.2 mg/g skin tissue with mDP increasing from 22 to 35, and flavonol content reaching 125 mg/kg dominated by quercetin-3-glucoside over 52 days, with phenolic extractability increasing 65% as assessed by model wine extraction under cool Piedmont conditions averaging 22°C.",
  "editor_note": "Skin_Phenolic_Development is parent class under Phenolic_Maturation representing exocarp-localized phenolic processes. ||Contains subclasses Skin_Tannin_Maturation, Flavonoid_Accumulation, and Skin_Phenolic_Profile. ||Distinguishes from Seed_Phenolic_Maturation by tissue localization. ||Integrates anthocyanin, tannin, and flavonol development. ||Duration 35-50 days. ||Light and water stress responsive. ||Extractability increases during ripening. || This process integrates multiple biosynthetic and modification pathways operating in distinct exocarp cell populations, with anthocyanin synthesis and accumulation restricted to hypodermal cells where vacuolar pigment deposition generates berry color, proanthocyanidin accumulation distributed across multiple skin cell layers with highest concentrations in outer hypodermal regions, and flavonol synthesis occurring primarily in epidermal cells where UV-protective functions are most relevant. ||The quantitative aspects of skin phenolic development show substantial cultivar variation, with thick-skinned varieties such as Cabernet Sauvignon and Tannat accumulating skin tannin concentrations of 3-6 mg/g skin tissue compared to thin-skinned varieties such as Pinot Noir reaching 1-3 mg/g, while anthocyanin concentrations vary independently based on variety-specific pigment biosynthetic capacity ranging from 0.5-4.0 mg/g fresh weight across diverse cultivars. ||The temporal dynamics of skin phenolic development demonstrate compound-class-specific patterns, with flavonol accumulation largely complete before veraison providing UV protection during early berry development, anthocyanin synthesis initiating at veraison and continuing throughout ripening in red varieties, and skin proanthocyanidin accumulation showing continued increase during post-veraison stages unlike seed tannins whose biosynthesis largely ceases before veraison. ||Environmental factors profoundly influence skin phenolic development, with light exposure essential for flavonol synthesis and beneficial for anthocyanin accumulation when not accompanied by excessive temperature, moderate water deficit enhancing both anthocyanin and tannin accumulation through berry size reduction and metabolic pathway activation, and temperature extremes potentially limiting anthocyanin synthesis while having lesser effects on tannin accumulation. ||The extractability of skin phenolics evolves during ripening through cell wall modification and membrane permeability changes, with increasing extractability of both anthocyanins and tannins during maturation facilitating color and tannin release during winemaking, though the precise extraction dynamics depend on vinification conditions including temperature, alcohol development, and maceration duration. ||Viticultural practices targeting skin phenolic development include canopy management optimizing cluster light exposure, irrigation strategies imposing controlled water deficit, and crop load adjustment ensuring adequate phenolic concentration per berry, with these interventions capable of modifying skin phenolic content by 30-100% relative to standard practices.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Downey MO et al (2006) Cultural practice and environmental impacts on the flavonoid composition of grapes and wine. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 257-268 || Adams DO (2006) Phenolics and ripening in grape berries. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 249-256 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 310-335"
},

  "Skin_Tannin_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Skin_Tannin_Maturation is a Skin_Phenolic_Development comprising accumulation, polymer chain elongation, and compositional modification of skin proanthocyanidins, yielding a mature tannin population with mean degree of polymerization of 25–45 units, prodelphindin content of 20–40%, and galloylation of 2–8%.",
  "alternative_term": "skin proanthocyanidin maturation | exocarp tannin development | skin condensed tannin evolution | berry skin tannin ripening |+ Haut-Tannin-Reifung | Exokarp-Proanthocyanidin-Reifung | Beerenhaut-kondensierte-Tannin-Evolution | Haut-Tannin-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sagrantino berries in Montefalco, Umbria during BBCH 83-89, skin tannin maturation increases skin tannin content from 2.4 to 5.8 mg/g skin tissue over 45 days, with mDP rising from 28 to 42, prodelphindin content stable at 35-38%, and galloylation at 4.5-5.2%, while extractability measured by model wine extraction increases from 45% to 78% of total skin tannin content, establishing the exceptionally high skin tannin concentration characteristic of this variety under warm central Italian conditions averaging 27°C.",
  "editor_note": "Skin_Tannin_Maturation is subclass of Skin_Phenolic_Development representing exocarp proanthocyanidin evolution specifically. ||Distinguishes from Seed_Tannin_Polymerization by tissue location and structural characteristics. ||Sibling to Flavonoid_Accumulation and Skin_Phenolic_Profile. ||Skin mDP 25-45 versus seed 5-12. ||Prodelphindin 20-40% versus seed less than 5%. ||Continues accumulating post-veraison unlike seed tannins. || This process involves continued proanthocyanidin biosynthesis during post-veraison ripening unlike seed tannins whose synthesis largely ceases before veraison, with ongoing expression of leucoanthocyanidin reductase and anthocyanidin reductase in skin tissues enabling accumulation increases of 30-80% between veraison and harvest in many varieties, establishing final skin tannin concentrations of 1-6 mg/g skin tissue depending on cultivar and growing conditions. ||The structural characteristics of skin tannin maturation reflect the distinctive biosynthetic environment of exocarp cells, with high expression of flavonoid 3-prime-5-prime-hydroxylase generating substantial epigallocatechin incorporation yielding the elevated prodelphindin percentages of 25-40% that exceed seed levels by 5-10 fold and contribute to enhanced protein precipitation capacity and specific sensory properties of skin-derived tannins. ||The temporal dynamics of skin tannin maturation show progressive accumulation throughout ripening with potential acceleration during late stages when berry dehydration may concentrate tannin content, while structural modifications including continued polymerization increasing mDP and potential oxidative changes modifying extractability occur concurrently with quantitative accumulation. ||Environmental factors influence skin tannin maturation through effects on both biosynthetic pathway activity and berry size determining concentration effects, with moderate water deficit enhancing skin tannin accumulation through reduced berry size and potential metabolic activation, while excessive stress may limit biosynthesis compromising final tannin content. ||The extractability of skin tannins evolves during maturation through cell wall softening and pectin solubilization that increases accessibility of vacuolar tannin pools to extracting solvents, with extraction efficiency typically increasing 40-80% between veraison and harvest as cellular barriers to tannin release progressively diminish. ||The enological significance of skin tannin maturation relates to wine structural properties, with skin tannins contributing substantial polymeric material that interacts with anthocyanins through copigmentation and covalent bonding, participates in color stabilization reactions, and provides mouthfeel characteristics described as softer and rounder compared to the more astringent character of seed-derived tannins.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Downey MO et al (2003) Analysis of tannins in seeds and skins of Shiraz grapes. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 9: 15-27 || Souquet JM et al (1996) Polymeric proanthocyanidins from grape skins. Phytochemistry 43: 509-512 || Kennedy JA et al (2006) Grape and wine phenolics. In Chemistry and Biology of Ellagitannins World Scientific pp 220-255"
},

  "Flavonoid_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Flavonoid_Accumulation is a Skin_Phenolic_Development comprising coordinated biosynthesis and deposition of flavonols, flavan-3-ols, and (in red cultivars) anthocyanins through flavonoid pathway gene expression in berry exocarp tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "skin flavonoid development | exocarp flavonoid synthesis | flavonol and flavan-3-ol accumulation | berry flavonoid accumulation |+ Flavonoid-Akkumulation | Haut-Flavonoid-Entwicklung | Exokarp-Flavonoid-Synthese | Flavonol-und-Flavan-3-ol-Anreicherung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sangiovese berries in Chianti Classico, Tuscany during BBCH 75-89, flavonoid accumulation establishes flavonol content reaching 145 mg/kg in sun-exposed clusters compared to 28 mg/kg in shaded fruit, with quercetin-3-glucoside at 85 mg/kg, quercetin-3-glucuronide at 35 mg/kg, and kaempferol-3-glucoside at 18 mg/kg, concurrent with skin proanthocyanidin accumulation to 3.2 mg/g and anthocyanin accumulation to 1.15 mg/g fresh weight by harvest under warm Tuscan conditions averaging 26°C.",
  "editor_note": "Flavonoid_Accumulation is subclass of Skin_Phenolic_Development representing comprehensive flavonoid compound increase in exocarp. ||Distinguishes from specific compound classes by integrating multiple flavonoid types. ||Sibling to Skin_Tannin_Maturation and Skin_Phenolic_Profile. ||Includes flavonols, flavan-3-ols, and anthocyanins. ||Light-responsive with UV-B induction of flavonols. ||Copigmentation function for color enhancement. || This process integrates multiple branches of flavonoid metabolism, with early pathway enzymes including chalcone synthase, chalcone isomerase, and flavanone 3-hydroxylase providing common intermediates that branch to flavonol synthase generating quercetin, kaempferol, and myricetin glycosides accumulating primarily in epidermal cells, to leucoanthocyanidin reductase and anthocyanidin reductase producing flavan-3-ols for proanthocyanidin synthesis, and to anthocyanidin synthase and subsequent enzymes generating anthocyanins in red variety hypodermal cells. ||The temporal dynamics of flavonoid accumulation show compound-class-specific patterns, with flavonol synthesis occurring primarily during early berry development before veraison in response to UV radiation exposure serving photoprotective functions, proanthocyanidin accumulation in skin tissues continuing through veraison and into post-veraison stages, and anthocyanin synthesis initiating at veraison and continuing throughout ripening as previously described. ||The quantitative aspects of flavonoid accumulation demonstrate substantial environmental responsiveness, with light exposure essential for flavonol induction through UV-B responsive regulatory elements in biosynthetic gene promoters, moderate water stress enhancing overall flavonoid accumulation through metabolic activation and berry size effects, and temperature influencing the balance among pathway branches with cool conditions favoring certain compound classes. ||Flavonol accumulation reaches characteristic levels of 50-200 mg/kg berry fresh weight in sun-exposed fruit compared to 10-30 mg/kg in heavily shaded clusters, with composition dominated by quercetin derivatives including quercetin-3-glucoside and quercetin-3-glucuronide in most varieties, while kaempferol and myricetin glycosides contribute varying proportions depending on hydroxylase expression patterns. ||The significance of flavonoid accumulation for wine quality extends beyond direct sensory contributions to include copigmentation effects where flavonols and other colorless flavonoids stack with anthocyanins enhancing color intensity by 30-50%, antioxidant capacity protecting both grape and wine from oxidative deterioration, and potential health benefits associated with flavonoid consumption that contribute to wine's position in dietary recommendations when consumed moderately.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Downey MO et al (2004) The effect of bunch shading on berry development and flavonoid accumulation in Shiraz grapes. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 10: 55-73 || Price SF et al (1995) Cluster sun exposure and quercetin in Pinot noir. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 46: 187-194 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 310-325"
},

  "Skin_Phenolic_Profile": {
  "definition": "A Skin_Phenolic_Profile is a Skin_Phenolic_Development defined by the relative proportions of anthocyanin, proanthocyanidin, flavonol, and hydroxycinnamic acid classes in the berry exocarp at harvest maturity.",
  "alternative_term": "exocarp phenolic composition | skin polyphenol profile | berry skin phenolic signature | skin phenolic fingerprint |+ Haut-Phenol-Profil | Exokarp-Phenol-Zusammensetzung | Beerenhaut-Polyphenol-Profil | Haut-phenolische-Signatur",
  "example_of_usage": "In Corvina berries in Valpolicella, Veneto at BBCH 89, skin phenolic profile is characterized by anthocyanin content of 0.95 mg/g with malvidin-3-glucoside at 42%, peonidin-3-glucoside at 28%, and cyanidin-3-glucoside at 18%, skin tannin of 2.8 mg/g with mDP 32 and prodelphindin 34%, and flavonol content of 95 mg/kg with quercetin derivatives dominating at 72%, establishing the distinctive profile that contributes to Amarone character when concentrated through appassimento drying under northern Italian conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Skin_Phenolic_Profile is subclass of Skin_Phenolic_Development representing the compositional outcome at maturity. ||Distinguishes from developmental processes by emphasizing final profile characterization. ||Sibling to Skin_Tannin_Maturation and Flavonoid_Accumulation. ||Integrates anthocyanin, tannin, and flavonol compositions. ||Cultivar-specific fingerprint. ||Guides extraction optimization during winemaking. || This concept encompasses the quantitative ratios among major phenolic classes including the anthocyanin-to-tannin ratio typically ranging from 0.3-0.8 in skin tissues depending on variety and ripeness, the flavonol-to-anthocyanin ratio of 0.05-0.20 that influences copigmentation capacity, and the relative proportions of individual compounds within each class that create variety-specific compositional fingerprints enabling cultivar discrimination through phenolic analysis. ||The cultivar-specific nature of skin phenolic profile reflects genetic differences in biosynthetic pathway regulation, with varieties such as Cabernet Sauvignon characterized by high malvidin-dominated anthocyanin profiles with substantial acylation, varieties such as Pinot Noir showing elevated cyanidin and peonidin contributions with minimal acylation, and varieties such as Nebbiolo demonstrating unique profiles with high peonidin proportions and distinctive tannin structures. ||The environmental modulation of skin phenolic profile occurs through differential effects on individual biosynthetic pathways, with light exposure preferentially enhancing flavonol accumulation relative to other flavonoids, temperature affecting anthocyanin-to-tannin ratios through differential temperature sensitivity of respective pathways, and water status influencing overall phenolic concentration while maintaining relatively stable compositional ratios within bounds established by genetic potential. ||The assessment of skin phenolic profile employs multiple analytical approaches including HPLC quantification of individual anthocyanins and flavonols, spectrophotometric determination of total phenolic classes, and advanced methods such as phloroglucinolysis for detailed tannin characterization, with these techniques providing comprehensive phenolic profiling that supports quality assessment and winemaking decisions. ||The practical significance of skin phenolic profile for winemaking relates to extraction optimization, with knowledge of phenolic composition guiding decisions regarding maceration duration, temperature management, and press fraction utilization to achieve desired wine style while managing potential quality-limiting factors such as excessive tannin extraction or inadequate color development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Mattivi F et al (2006) Metabolite profiling of grape. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 54: 7692-7702 || Downey MO et al (2006) Cultural practice and environmental impacts on flavonoid composition. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 257-268 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 320-335"
},

  "Seed_Phenolic_Maturation": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Phenolic_Maturation is a Phenolic_Maturation comprising oxidative browning, polymerization modification, and reduced extractability of pre-véraison-synthesized proanthocyanidins in grape seed tissues.",
  "alternative_term": "grape seed phenolic development | seed tannin maturation | seed polyphenol ripening | seed phenolic evolution |+ Samen-Phenol-Reifung | Traubenkern-phenolische-Entwicklung | Samen-Tannin-Reifung | Samen-Polyphenol-Reifung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Franc berries in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux during BBCH 81-89, seed phenolic maturation reduces extractable seed tannin from 8.2 to 3.5 mg/g seed over 42 days while total seed tannin per berry remains stable at 4.8-5.2 mg, with seed coat browning index increasing from 0.25 to 0.72 absorbance units at 420 nm, mDP declining from 10.5 to 8.2, and galloylation stable at 26-28%, establishing mature seed phenolic status with reduced extraction potential under moderate oceanic conditions averaging 24°C.",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Phenolic_Maturation is parent class under Phenolic_Maturation representing seed-localized phenolic processes. ||Contains subclasses Seed_Tannin_Polymerization, Seed_Browning, and Phenolic_Seed_Maturity. ||Distinguishes from Skin_Phenolic_Development by tissue localization and developmental trajectory. ||Biosynthesis complete before veraison || post-veraison involves oxidative modification. ||Extractability decreases 40-70% during ripening. || This process reflects the distinctive developmental trajectory of seed phenolics compared to skin tissues, with proanthocyanidin biosynthesis in seeds occurring predominantly before veraison during the seed coat development phase spanning BBCH 71-81, followed by cessation of active synthesis and initiation of post-synthetic maturation processes during the post-veraison period when oxidative modification becomes the dominant factor influencing seed phenolic properties. ||The quantitative aspects of seed phenolic maturation show characteristic patterns with total seed tannin content per berry remaining relatively stable during post-veraison while concentration per unit seed mass may decrease through seed size increase, and extractable tannin content declining substantially by 40-70% between veraison and harvest as oxidative modification reduces tannin solubility and availability for extraction during winemaking. ||The structural characteristics of seed tannins differ fundamentally from skin tannins, with seed proanthocyanidins showing lower mean degree of polymerization of 5-12 units compared to skin values of 25-45, minimal prodelphindin content typically below 5% compared to skin levels of 20-40%, and elevated galloylation percentages of 15-35% compared to skin values of 2-8%, contributing to the distinctive astringency properties associated with seed tannin extraction. ||Temperature during ripening influences seed phenolic maturation through effects on oxidative reaction rates, with warm conditions accelerating browning and extractability reduction while cool conditions may delay maturation requiring extended hang-time to achieve equivalent seed phenolic status. ||The enological significance of seed phenolic maturation relates to wine astringency management, with immature seed tannins contributing harsh, aggressive astringency considered negative for wine quality, while mature seed phenolics with reduced extractability contribute less aggressively to wine tannin content, making seed maturation assessment an important component of harvest timing decisions for red wine production seeking optimal phenolic balance.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kennedy JA et al (2000) Grape seed development germination and proanthocyanidin composition. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 48: 1490-1495 || Ristic R and Iland PG (2005) Relationships between seed and berry development of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 11: 43-58 || Adams DO (2006) Phenolics and ripening in grape berries. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 249-256"
},

  "Seed_Tannin_Polymerization": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Tannin_Polymerization is a Seed_Phenolic_Maturation realized through oxidative and acid-catalyzed reactions reducing mean degree of polymerization from 8–12 units at véraison to 5–9 units at harvest through oxidative cleavage concurrent with browning.",
  "alternative_term": "seed proanthocyanidin modification | seed tannin structural change | seed condensed tannin polymerization | seed tannin oxidative modification |+ Samen-Tannin-Polymerisation | Samen-Proanthocyanidin-Modifikation | Samen-Tannin-Struktur-Änderung | Samen-kondensierte-Tannin-Oxidation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Malbec berries in Mendoza, Argentina during BBCH 83-89, seed tannin polymerization modifies seed proanthocyanidin structure with mDP decreasing from 11.2 to 7.8 over 40 days through oxidative cleavage, extension unit composition shifting as epicatechin-gallate proportion decreases from 32% to 26% through preferential oxidation, and gel permeation chromatography revealing molecular weight distribution broadening with increased low-molecular-weight fraction indicating partial depolymerization concurrent with browning under warm high-altitude conditions averaging 28°C.",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Tannin_Polymerization is subclass of Seed_Phenolic_Maturation representing structural modification of seed proanthocyanidins. ||Distinguishes from Tannin_Polymerization under general category by seed-specific degradative character. ||Sibling to Seed_Browning and Phenolic_Seed_Maturity. ||mDP typically decreases from 8-12 to 5-9. ||Oxidative cleavage predominates over elongation. ||Temperature-dependent reaction rates. || This process differs from skin tannin polymerization in its predominantly degradative rather than elongative character, with seed tannins experiencing oxidative attack generating quinone intermediates that may undergo cleavage reactions reducing polymer chain length, cross-linking reactions generating insoluble polymeric material, and nucleophilic addition reactions incorporating other phenolic compounds into modified tannin structures. ||The biochemical mechanisms underlying seed tannin polymerization involve polyphenol oxidase and peroxidase catalyzed oxidation of catechol and pyrogallol groups on flavan-3-ol subunits generating reactive quinone species, with subsequent non-enzymatic reactions including intramolecular rearrangements, intermolecular cross-linking, and potential chain cleavage producing the structurally modified tannin populations that characterize mature seed tissues. ||The quantitative assessment of seed tannin polymerization employs analytical methods including phloroglucinolysis yielding mean degree of polymerization and subunit composition, gel permeation chromatography providing molecular weight distribution, and protein precipitation assays measuring functional tannin activity, with these techniques revealing the structural changes accompanying oxidative modification during seed maturation. ||The relationship between seed tannin polymerization and extractability reflects the formation of oxidatively modified polymers with reduced solubility in hydroalcoholic extraction media, with highly oxidized seed tannins showing decreased dissolution rates and reduced equilibrium solubility that limits their contribution to wine tannin content during standard maceration practices. ||Temperature during ripening influences seed tannin polymerization through effects on oxidative enzyme activities and non-enzymatic reaction rates, with warm conditions accelerating structural modification while cool conditions may preserve less modified tannin structures requiring longer ripening periods to achieve equivalent maturation status.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Kennedy JA et al (2001) Changes in grape seed polyphenols during ripening. Phytochemistry 55: 77-85 || Downey MO et al (2003) Analysis of tannins in seeds and skins of Shiraz. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 9: 15-27 || Cadot Y et al (2006) Anatomical histological and histochemical changes in grape seeds during development. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 54: 9206-9215"
},

  "Seed_Browning": {
  "definition": "A Seed_Browning is a Seed_Phenolic_Maturation manifesting as the progressive development of brown coloration in seed coat tissues through enzymatic and non-enzymatic oxidation of phenolic compounds yielding quinone polymers and melanin-like pigments.",
  "alternative_term": "seed coat oxidative browning | seed color development | seed oxidation | seed phenolic browning |+ Samen-Bräunung | Samenschalen-oxidative-Bräunung | Samen-Farbentwicklung | Samen-phenolische-Bräunung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grenache berries in Châteauneuf-du-Pape, Rhône Valley during BBCH 81-89, seed browning progresses from visual score 1.2 at veraison representing predominantly green seeds through score 2.8 at mid-ripening to score 3.8 indicating well-browned seeds at harvest over 45 days, with browning index at 420 nm increasing from 0.18 to 0.68 absorbance units, correlating with extractable tannin reduction from 9.5 to 3.8 mg/g seed as oxidative modification reduces tannin solubility under warm Mediterranean conditions averaging 29°C.",
  "editor_note": "Seed_Browning is subclass of Seed_Phenolic_Maturation representing the visible oxidative modification of seed coat. ||Distinguishes from Seed_Tannin_Polymerization by emphasizing color change as indicator. ||Sibling to Seed_Tannin_Polymerization and Phenolic_Seed_Maturity. ||Visual indicator of seed phenolic status. ||Correlates with extractability reduction. ||Assessed by color scoring and spectrophotometry at 420 nm. || This process involves the oxidation of colorless catechol and pyrogallol groups present on flavan-3-ol subunits of seed proanthocyanidins, with polyphenol oxidase catalyzing two-electron oxidation to ortho-quinones that undergo rapid non-enzymatic polymerization generating brown-colored products, while peroxidase activities contribute additional oxidative capacity in the presence of hydrogen peroxide generated during cellular metabolism. ||The temporal progression of seed browning shows characteristic patterns with initial browning visible at the chalazal end of seeds shortly after veraison where oxidative processes initiate, followed by progressive extension throughout the seed coat over the subsequent 4-6 weeks until uniform brown coloration indicates complete oxidative modification of surface phenolic compounds accessible to oxidative enzymes and atmospheric oxygen. ||The quantitative assessment of seed browning employs colorimetric methods including visual scoring on structured color scales ranging from 1 representing green through 4 representing dark brown, spectrophotometric measurement of absorbance at 420 nm providing objective browning indices, and digital image analysis enabling standardized color quantification that correlates with tannin extractability measurements. ||The relationship between seed browning and wine quality reflects the correlation between oxidative modification visible as browning and the reduced extractability of seed tannins that limits their contribution to wine astringency, with adequately browned seeds releasing 40-70% less tannin during standard maceration compared to green seeds, reducing the harsh astringent character associated with immature seed tannin extraction. ||Environmental factors influence seed browning rates through effects on oxidative enzyme activities and oxygen availability, with warm temperatures accelerating browning through enhanced enzyme kinetics while excessive heat may inactivate enzymes potentially slowing browning progression, and vineyard conditions affecting berry transpiration influencing oxygen diffusion into seed tissues.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Ristic R and Iland PG (2005) Relationships between seed and berry development of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 11: 43-58 || Kennedy JA et al (2000) Grape seed development germination and proanthocyanidin composition. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 48: 1490-1495 || Cadot Y et al (2006) Anatomical histological and histochemical changes in grape seeds. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry 54: 9206-9215"
},

  "Phenolic_Seed_Maturity": {
  "definition": "A Phenolic_Seed_Maturity is a Seed_Phenolic_Maturation defined by uniform brown seed coloration and tannin extractability reduced to 30–50% of initial levels indicating optimal seed ripeness.",
  "alternative_term": "seed tannin maturity | seed phenolic ripeness | mature seed phenolic status | optimal seed phenolic development |+ phenolische Samenreife | Samen-Tannin-Reife | Samen-phenolische-Reife | reifer Samen-phenolischer-Status",
  "example_of_usage": "In Touriga Nacional berries in Douro Valley, Portugal at BBCH 89, phenolic seed maturity is achieved with seed color score of 3.9 on 4-point scale indicating uniform dark brown appearance, seed texture crisp with clean separation from pulp, extractable tannin reduced to 3.2 mg/g seed representing 38% of veraison content, mDP at 7.5, and sensory evaluation confirming soft nutty character without harsh bitterness, establishing optimal seed phenolic status after 48 days post-veraison under warm continental-Mediterranean conditions averaging 28°C.",
  "editor_note": "Phenolic_Seed_Maturity is subclass of Seed_Phenolic_Maturation representing the achieved quality endpoint. ||Distinguishes from process-focused classes by emphasizing maturity status assessment. ||Sibling to Seed_Tannin_Polymerization and Seed_Browning. ||Integrates visual, tactile, analytical, and sensory indicators. ||Extractable tannin typically below 4-5 mg/g in mature seeds. ||Harvest timing criterion for quality wine production. || This state integrates multiple maturity indicators including visual assessment of seed coat color with mature seeds showing uniform dark brown appearance rated 3.5-4.0 on standard scales, tactile evaluation with mature seeds demonstrating crisp texture and easy separation from surrounding pulp tissue, analytical measurements confirming reduced extractable tannin content typically below 4-5 mg/g seed compared to 8-12 mg/g in immature seeds, and sensory evaluation of seed tannin astringency through chewing tests revealing softened rather than harsh bitter-astringent character in mature seeds. ||The biochemical characteristics of phenolic seed maturity encompass structural modifications including decreased mean degree of polymerization from initial values of 10-12 to mature values of 6-9 reflecting oxidative cleavage, formation of oxidatively cross-linked polymers with reduced solubility, and potential incorporation of anthocyanins or other phenolics into modified tannin structures through non-enzymatic condensation reactions during extended oxidative modification. ||The timing of phenolic seed maturity achievement varies among cultivars and environmental conditions, with some varieties reaching mature seed status 35-40 days post-veraison while others may require 50-60 days, and warm conditions generally accelerating maturation compared to cool seasons that may delay seed phenolic development requiring extended hang-time for optimal maturity. ||The practical assessment of phenolic seed maturity in vineyard sampling employs tactile and visual evaluation through the established protocol of cutting berries to expose seeds, evaluating color and texture, and potentially tasting seeds to assess astringency, with experienced viticulturists capable of reliably determining seed maturity status through these sensory methods that correlate with analytical measurements. ||The enological significance of phenolic seed maturity relates to wine quality optimization, with harvest of grapes possessing mature seeds reducing the risk of harsh tannin extraction during maceration, contributing to wines with balanced structure and approachable astringency compared to wines produced from grapes harvested before optimal seed maturation when aggressive seed tannins may compromise sensory quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Ristic R and Iland PG (2005) Relationships between seed and berry development of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 11: 43-58 || Kennedy JA et al (2001) Changes in grape seed polyphenols during ripening. Phytochemistry 55: 77-85 || Adams DO (2006) Phenolics and ripening in grape berries. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 249-256"
},

  "Leaf_Fall": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Fall is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising leaf senescence, abscission zone development, and physical detachment of mature leaves from the vine over a 4–8 week post-harvest period transitioning the vine from active vegetative function to winter dormancy.",
  "alternative_term": "autumn leaf drop | leaf abscission | defoliation | leaf shedding |+ Blattfall | Herbst-Blattabwurf | Entlaubung | Blattabszission",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in Rheingau, Germany during late October to early December, leaf fall progresses over 6 weeks following harvest, with basal leaf senescence initiating at day length of 10.5 hours in mid-October, chlorophyll degradation producing characteristic yellow coloration by late October, and complete defoliation achieved by early December when mean temperatures decline below 5°C, with 65-75% of leaf nitrogen successfully remobilized to perennial tissues before abscission under typical cool continental autumn conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Fall is parent class under Grapevine_Phenological_Process representing the complete annual leaf shedding process. ||Contains subclasses Leaf_Senescence, Petiole_Abscission, and Leaf_Detachment. ||Duration 4-8 weeks in late autumn. ||Photoperiod-triggered with temperature modulation. ||Integrates senescence, nutrient remobilization, and physical separation. ||Critical for nutrient conservation and dormancy transition. || This process represents the terminal phase of the annual leaf life cycle, with individual leaves typically surviving 120-180 days from emergence in spring through senescence and abscission in autumn, fulfilling their primary functions of photosynthetic carbon assimilation, transpirational water transport, and respiratory gas exchange before programmed disassembly and nutrient recovery precede physical separation from the supporting shoot. ||The physiological significance of leaf fall extends beyond simple tissue disposal to encompass critical resource conservation through remobilization of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, and other nutrients from senescing leaves into perennial woody tissues where storage reserves support winter survival and subsequent spring growth, with efficient nutrient recovery during senescence reducing the vine's dependence on soil nutrient uptake in the following season. ||The temporal coordination of leaf fall responds to environmental signals including decreasing photoperiod serving as the primary trigger for senescence initiation in most Vitis vinifera cultivars, declining temperatures accelerating chlorophyll degradation and abscission zone activation, and reduced soil moisture potentially hastening senescence under drought conditions that compromise continued leaf function. ||Cultivar variation in leaf fall timing reflects genetic differences in photoperiod sensitivity and temperature response thresholds, with early-maturing varieties such as Chasselas and Müller-Thurgau typically initiating senescence and leaf fall 2-4 weeks before late-maturing varieties such as Cabernet Sauvignon and Mourvèdre under equivalent environmental conditions. ||The progression of leaf fall within individual vines follows characteristic spatial patterns, with basal leaves on mature shoot portions senescing and falling first, followed by progressive acropetal advancement of senescence toward shoot tips, and lateral shoot leaves often persisting longer than main shoot leaves due to their more recent emergence and continued metabolic activity. ||Environmental factors beyond photoperiod and temperature influence leaf fall dynamics, with early autumn frost events potentially triggering rapid synchronous leaf fall through freeze damage bypassing normal senescence processes, extended warm autumns delaying senescence and prolonging the photosynthetic season in some years, and fungal diseases such as downy mildew potentially causing premature defoliation that disrupts normal nutrient remobilization. ||The completion of leaf fall marks a critical transition in the vine's annual cycle, with fully defoliated vines entering the dormant period characterized by minimal metabolic activity, maximum cold hardiness, and reliance on accumulated carbohydrate reserves that will sustain respiratory demands until photosynthesis resumes with new leaf emergence in the following spring.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned ## senescence is mapped at subclass level (Leaf_Senescence); fall as composite process has no generic equivalent" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 pp 85-95 || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of nitrogen in grapevine. Functional Plant Biology 31: 1141-1152 || Lim PO et al (2007) Leaf senescence. Annual Review of Plant Biology 58: 115-136"
},

  "Leaf_Senescence": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Senescence is a Leaf_Fall comprising controlled degradation of chloroplasts, proteins, nucleic acids, and membrane lipids in mature leaves enabling nutrient export to perennial vine tissues over a 3–6 week post-harvest period.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf aging | autumn leaf senescence | leaf yellowing | programmed leaf deterioration |+ Blattseneszenz | Blatt-Alterung | Herbst-Blattseneszenz | Blattvergilbung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in Napa Valley, California during October-November, leaf senescence progresses over 5 weeks with chlorophyll content declining from 450 to 45 µg/g fresh weight, nitrogen remobilization exporting 2.8 g N per vine to woody tissues representing 68% of leaf nitrogen content, and leaf color transitioning from green through yellow-orange to red-brown as anthocyanins accumulate concurrent with carotenoid exposure under warm autumn conditions averaging 18°C daytime and 8°C nighttime.",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Senescence is parent class under Leaf_Fall representing the controlled cellular dismantling program. ||Contains subclasses Leaf_Senescence_Initiation, Chlorophyll_Degradation, Nutrient_Remobilization, and Progressive_Leaf_Senescence. ||Duration 3-6 weeks. ||Genetically programmed process. ||Enables 50-80% nitrogen recovery. ||Photoperiod and temperature regulated. ||Precedes physical abscission. || This process represents a highly regulated genetic program rather than passive deterioration, with senescence-associated genes encoding proteases, lipases, nucleases, and chlorophyll-degrading enzymes activated in coordinated sequence to disassemble cellular components while maintaining membrane integrity sufficient for continued export of remobilized nutrients through the vascular system until late senescence stages. ||The biochemical events underlying leaf senescence begin with chloroplast dismantling as the quantitatively dominant process, with thylakoid membrane disassembly releasing chlorophyll for catabolism through the pheophytinase and pheophorbide oxygenase pathway, stromal proteins including Rubisco undergoing proteolytic degradation to release amino acids for export, and plastid lipids hydrolyzed to provide carbon skeletons for respiration and membrane maintenance during the senescence period. ||The nutrient remobilization function of leaf senescence enables recovery of 50-80% of leaf nitrogen, 40-60% of phosphorus, and 30-50% of potassium before abscission, with these nutrients transported through phloem connections to woody tissues including trunk, cordons, and roots where they accumulate as storage reserves supporting subsequent spring growth and reducing fertilizer requirements. ||The regulation of leaf senescence involves integration of developmental, hormonal, and environmental signals, with ethylene and abscisic acid promoting senescence progression, cytokinins delaying senescence through maintenance of chloroplast function, and the declining cytokinin-to-ethylene ratio during autumn creating conditions favoring senescence initiation and progression. ||Environmental factors modulating leaf senescence include photoperiod providing the primary timing signal through phytochrome-mediated perception of shortening day length, temperature influencing the rate of senescence progression with cool conditions accelerating chlorophyll degradation, and water availability affecting senescence timing with drought stress potentially inducing premature senescence through abscisic acid accumulation. ||The visible manifestation of leaf senescence appears as progressive color change from green through yellow as chlorophyll degrades revealing underlying carotenoid pigments, with some Vitis vinifera varieties additionally displaying red coloration through anthocyanin synthesis in senescing leaves that may serve photoprotective functions during the extended period of nutrient remobilization.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0010150 ## leaf senescence | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Lim PO et al (2007) Leaf senescence. Annual Review of Plant Biology 58: 115-136 || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of nitrogen in grapevine. Functional Plant Biology 31: 1141-1152 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 85-92"
},

  "Leaf_Senescence_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Senescence_Initiation is a Leaf_Senescence consisting of activation of senescence-associated gene expression and reprogramming of hormonal balance toward senescence-promoting states triggered by shortening photoperiod and declining temperatures.",
  "alternative_term": "senescence onset | senescence triggering | senescence induction | leaf aging initiation |+ Seneszenz-Initiierung | Seneszenz-Beginn | Seneszenz-Auslösung | Blatt-Alterungs-Initiierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines in Burgundy, France during early October, leaf senescence initiation occurs when photoperiod declines below 11.2 hours, with phytochrome-mediated signaling activating NAC transcription factor expression within 3-5 days, cytokinin-to-ethylene ratio declining from 2.5 to 0.8 over 10 days, and first visible chlorophyll degradation appearing 12-14 days after initiation trigger under cool autumn conditions with mean temperature of 12°C.",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Senescence_Initiation is subclass of Leaf_Senescence representing the developmental transition to senescence program. ||Distinguishes from progressive senescence by emphasizing triggering events. ||Sibling to Chlorophyll_Degradation, Nutrient_Remobilization, and Progressive_Leaf_Senescence. ||Photoperiod-triggered with temperature modulation. ||Involves hormonal reprogramming. ||Largely irreversible commitment. || This transition involves the integration of multiple environmental signals through photoreceptor systems, with phytochrome-mediated detection of declining red-to-far-red light ratios characteristic of shortening autumn days providing the primary trigger for senescence initiation in most Vitis vinifera cultivars, while temperature-sensing mechanisms involving membrane fluidity changes and cold-responsive transcription factors modulate the timing and rate of senescence entry. ||The molecular events marking senescence initiation include upregulation of senescence-associated genes encoding transcription factors such as NAC and WRKY family members that orchestrate downstream gene expression changes, activation of hormone biosynthesis and signaling pathways shifting the balance toward senescence-promoting ethylene and abscisic acid, and initial chloroplast-to-nucleus retrograde signaling that coordinates nuclear gene expression with chloroplast dismantling requirements. ||The hormonal reprogramming during senescence initiation involves declining cytokinin synthesis and sensitivity that removes the primary maintenance signal for photosynthetic function, increasing ethylene production through activation of ACC synthase and ACC oxidase genes, and accumulation of abscisic acid that promotes expression of genes involved in stress response and senescence progression. ||The timing of senescence initiation varies among cultivars reflecting genetic differences in photoperiod sensitivity, with day-length thresholds for senescence induction ranging from 11-12 hours in early-responding varieties to 9-10 hours in late-responding varieties, creating 2-4 week differences in senescence initiation timing among cultivars grown in the same location. ||Environmental factors beyond photoperiod influence senescence initiation timing, with unseasonably warm autumn temperatures potentially delaying initiation through maintained cytokinin activity, drought stress inducing premature initiation through abscisic acid accumulation independent of photoperiod signals, and nutrient deficiency particularly nitrogen limitation accelerating senescence initiation through reduced cytokinin synthesis capacity. ||The commitment point of senescence initiation represents a largely irreversible developmental transition, though early-stage senescence can be partially reversed by cytokinin application or removal of senescence-inducing conditions, with progression beyond initial stages establishing the full senescence program that will proceed through chlorophyll degradation and nutrient remobilization to completion.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lim PO et al (2007) Leaf senescence. Annual Review of Plant Biology 58: 115-136 || Guo Y and Gan S (2005) Leaf senescence: signals, execution and regulation. Current Topics in Developmental Biology 71: 83-112 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 86-88"
},

  "Chlorophyll_Degradation": {
  "definition": "A Chlorophyll_Degradation is a Leaf_Senescence realized through the pheophytinase–pheophorbide oxygenase pathway converting chlorophyll pigments to colorless linear tetrapyrrole catabolites and producing the green-to-yellow transition over 2–4 weeks.",
  "alternative_term": "chlorophyll catabolism | chlorophyll breakdown | leaf degreening | chlorophyll loss |+ Chlorophyll-Abbau | Chlorophyll-Katabolismus | Blatt-Entgrünung | Chlorophyll-Verlust",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Côte de Beaune, Burgundy during October-November, chlorophyll degradation reduces leaf chlorophyll content from 485 to 28 µg/g fresh weight over 25 days, with pheophorbide oxygenase activity peaking at 15 nmol/min/g fresh weight during mid-senescence, leaf color transitioning from green through yellow-green to uniform yellow, and carotenoid-to-chlorophyll ratio increasing from 0.25 to 4.8 as chlorophyll elimination reveals lutein and beta-carotene pigments under cool autumn conditions averaging 10°C.",
  "editor_note": "Chlorophyll_Degradation is subclass of Leaf_Senescence representing pigment catabolism specifically. ||Distinguishes from nutrient remobilization by focusing on chlorophyll pathway. ||Sibling to Leaf_Senescence_Initiation, Nutrient_Remobilization, and Progressive_Leaf_Senescence. ||Pheophytinase-pheophorbide oxygenase pathway. ||Duration 2-4 weeks. ||Produces yellow coloration through carotenoid exposure. || This process involves sequential enzymatic reactions beginning with chlorophyllase or pheophytinase removing the phytol tail from chlorophyll, followed by magnesium-dechelatase removing the central magnesium ion, pheophorbide a oxygenase opening the porphyrin macrocycle generating red chlorophyll catabolite, and red chlorophyll catabolite reductase reducing this intermediate to primary fluorescent chlorophyll catabolite that undergoes further modifications before vacuolar sequestration. ||The quantitative significance of chlorophyll degradation reflects the substantial chlorophyll content of mature grapevine leaves, typically 300-600 µg/g fresh weight comprising approximately 3-5% of total leaf dry weight, with complete degradation releasing this nitrogen-rich porphyrin pool for potential amino acid recovery while eliminating the phototoxic risk of free chlorophyll intermediates that could generate damaging reactive oxygen species under continued light exposure. ||The regulation of chlorophyll degradation involves transcriptional activation of catabolic enzyme genes by senescence-associated transcription factors, with stay-green mutants in other plant species demonstrating that chlorophyll retention can be achieved through reduced expression of specific pathway enzymes while other senescence processes continue, though such mutations have not been extensively characterized in grapevine. ||The temporal progression of chlorophyll degradation within individual leaves shows characteristic patterns, with degradation typically initiating in interveinal regions while areas adjacent to major veins retain chlorophyll longer due to continued photosynthate export demands, and complete chlorophyll loss achieved only in late senescence stages when phloem function declines and export requirements diminish. ||Environmental factors influence chlorophyll degradation rates, with cool temperatures of 5-15°C accelerating degradation through enhanced enzyme activities in the temperature-sensitive pheophorbide oxygenase reaction, while continued warm conditions may slow degradation maintaining green coloration longer into autumn. ||The visual progression of chlorophyll degradation produces the autumn color display characteristic of grapevine canopies, transitioning from uniform green through patchy yellow-green as degradation proceeds heterogeneously, to uniform yellow when chlorophyll is largely eliminated revealing carotenoid pigments, with some varieties additionally synthesizing anthocyanins producing red autumn coloration that serves photoprotective functions during the extended senescence period.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0033310 ## chlorophyll a catabolic process | 0.9" ],
  "definition_source": "Hörtensteiner S (2006) Chlorophyll degradation during senescence. Annual Review of Plant Biology 57: 55-77 || Pruzinská A et al (2005) Chlorophyll breakdown in senescent Arabidopsis leaves. Plant Physiology 139: 52-63 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 88-90"
},

  "Nutrient_Remobilization": {
  "definition": "A Nutrient_Remobilization is a Leaf_Senescence comprising phloem export of nitrogen, phosphorus, sulfur, and organic compounds from senescing leaves to trunk, cordons, and roots through systematic degradation of proteins, nucleic acids, and membrane lipids.",
  "alternative_term": "nutrient export | nutrient salvage | senescence nutrient recovery | nutrient resorption |+ Nährstoff-Remobilisierung | Nährstoff-Export | Seneszenz-Nährstoff-Rückgewinnung | Nährstoff-Resorption",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux during October-November, nutrient remobilization exports 3.2 g nitrogen per vine representing 72% of total leaf nitrogen content over 4 weeks, with glutamine and asparagine comprising 65% of exported amino acids, trunk nitrogen content increasing from 0.85% to 1.25% dry weight, and phosphorus remobilization achieving 58% recovery as measured by leaf nutrient analysis before and after senescence under mild oceanic autumn conditions with mean temperature of 14°C.",
  "editor_note": "Nutrient_Remobilization is subclass of Leaf_Senescence representing export of valuable nutrients to storage tissues. ||Distinguishes from degradation processes by emphasizing transport and conservation. ||Sibling to Leaf_Senescence_Initiation, Chlorophyll_Degradation, and Progressive_Leaf_Senescence. ||Recovers 50-80% of leaf nitrogen. ||Critical for vine nutrient economy. ||Requires maintained phloem function. || This process represents a critical adaptation for perennial plant nutrient economy, with efficient remobilization enabling recovery of 50-80% of leaf nitrogen representing 2-4 g N per mature vine, 40-60% of leaf phosphorus, 30-50% of potassium, and substantial proportions of sulfur, magnesium, and micronutrients that would otherwise be lost through leaf abscission and decomposition on the vineyard floor. ||The biochemical mechanisms of nutrient remobilization involve activation of proteases including cysteine proteases and aspartic proteases that degrade stromal and thylakoid proteins releasing amino acids, nucleases that hydrolyze DNA and RNA liberating nucleotides for phosphorus export, and phosphatases that cleave phosphate groups from organic molecules generating transportable inorganic phosphate. ||The nitrogen remobilization pathway proceeds through proteolytic degradation of Rubisco and other abundant leaf proteins to amino acids, conversion of amino acids to transport forms including glutamine and asparagine through glutamine synthetase and asparagine synthetase activities, and phloem loading of these transport amino acids for export to perennial tissues where storage proteins are synthesized in bark parenchyma cells. ||The temporal dynamics of nutrient remobilization show characteristic patterns, with nitrogen export initiating early in senescence while photosynthetic capacity remains partially intact to provide carbon skeletons and energy for amino acid synthesis, continuing through mid-senescence as protein degradation accelerates, and declining in late senescence as phloem function deteriorates and export capacity becomes limiting. ||Environmental factors influence remobilization efficiency, with gradual temperature decline favoring complete remobilization while sudden frost events may terminate senescence prematurely before export completion, and adequate soil moisture maintaining phloem hydration and transport function essential for continued nutrient export. ||The practical significance of nutrient remobilization for viticulture relates to vine nutrition management, with efficient remobilization reducing fertilizer requirements in subsequent seasons, while premature defoliation through disease, frost, or mechanical damage compromises nutrient recovery potentially affecting vine vigor and productivity in following years.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of nitrogen in grapevine. Functional Plant Biology 31: 1141-1152 || Masclaux-Daubresse C et al (2010) Nitrogen uptake, assimilation and remobilization in plants. Plant Physiology and Biochemistry 48: 203-212 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 90-92"
},

  "Progressive_Leaf_Senescence": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Leaf_Senescence is a Leaf_Senescence exhibiting sequential advancement of chlorophyll degradation, protein catabolism, and cellular dismantling through leaf tissues and from basal to distal canopy positions over 4–6 weeks.",
  "alternative_term": "gradual leaf senescence | sequential canopy senescence | advancing leaf senescence | senescence progression |+ progressive Blattseneszenz | fortschreitende Blattseneszenz | sequentielle Kronendach-Seneszenz | Seneszenz-Progression",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc vines in Marlborough, New Zealand during April-May, progressive leaf senescence advances from basal shoot positions where senescence initiates 3 weeks before distal positions, with canopy color transitioning from uniform green through heterogeneous yellow-green patchwork to complete yellow over 5 weeks, individual leaf senescence progressing from interveinal regions to complete lamina involvement over 12-15 days, and nitrogen remobilization continuing throughout the extended senescence period enabling 74% total recovery under cool maritime autumn conditions averaging 12°C.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Leaf_Senescence is subclass of Leaf_Senescence representing the gradual spatial and temporal advancement of senescence. ||Distinguishes from initiation by emphasizing progression patterns. ||Sibling to Leaf_Senescence_Initiation, Chlorophyll_Degradation, and Nutrient_Remobilization. ||Acropetal canopy progression. ||Within-leaf interveinal initiation. ||Duration 4-6 weeks. ||Enables extended nutrient recovery window. || This process exhibits characteristic spatial patterns within individual leaves, with senescence typically initiating in interveinal regions where mesophyll cells are most distant from vascular nutrient supply, progressively advancing toward the leaf margins and major veins, and ultimately encompassing the entire lamina while petiole tissues remain functional for continued nutrient export until late senescence stages. ||The acropetal progression of senescence across the vine canopy reflects developmental age differences among leaves, with basal leaves on mature shoot regions having emerged earliest in spring and thus being chronologically oldest initiating senescence first, followed by progressive involvement of more distal leaves, and lateral shoot leaves often senescing last due to their more recent emergence and continued metabolic activity. ||The temporal coordination of progressive senescence involves both autonomous leaf-age-dependent signals and systemic signals from other senescing tissues, with ethylene production by early-senescing basal leaves potentially accelerating senescence in adjacent leaves through gaseous diffusion, and resource competition creating sink-source relationships that influence senescence progression patterns. ||Environmental heterogeneity within vine canopies influences progressive senescence patterns, with shaded interior leaves often senescing earlier than well-exposed exterior leaves due to reduced photosynthetic contribution and lower cytokinin status, while leaves experiencing localized stress from disease, pest damage, or nutritional deficiency may initiate senescence independently of the whole-canopy progression. ||The functional significance of progressive rather than synchronous senescence relates to the extended time window available for nutrient remobilization, with gradual canopy senescence maintaining phloem export capacity from still-functional leaves while resources are being salvaged from senescing tissues, enabling more complete nutrient recovery than would occur with rapid synchronous senescence that might overwhelm transport capacity. ||The completion of progressive leaf senescence culminates in complete canopy yellowing followed by abscission zone activation and leaf fall, with the 4-6 week duration of visible senescence progression representing the final phase of the annual leaf life cycle before winter dormancy.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lim PO et al (2007) Leaf senescence. Annual Review of Plant Biology 58: 115-136 || Guo Y and Gan S (2005) Leaf senescence: signals, execution and regulation. Current Topics in Developmental Biology 71: 83-112 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 88-92"
},

  "Petiole_Abscission": {
  "definition": "A Petiole_Abscission is a Leaf_Fall comprising activation of the petiole abscission zone, cell wall degradation, and physical detachment of senescent leaves with concurrent wound sealing of the shoot scar over 1–2 weeks following senescence completion.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf stalk abscission | leaf detachment | petiole separation | leaf-shoot separation |+ Blattstiel-Abszission | Blattstiel-Trennung | Blatt-Ablösung | Blatt-Spross-Trennung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grenache vines in Châteauneuf-du-Pape, Rhône Valley during November-December, petiole abscission occurs 7-12 days after complete leaf yellowing, with abscission zone activation visible as a constriction ring at the petiole base, ethylene production in abscission zone tissue reaching 2.5 nL/g/h during active separation, cell wall degrading enzyme activity peaking at 3 days before detachment, and clean leaf scars with suberized protective layer formed within 48 hours of separation under cool Mediterranean autumn conditions averaging 8°C.",
  "editor_note": "Petiole_Abscission is parent class under Leaf_Fall representing physical leaf separation process. ||Contains subclasses Abscission_Zone_Formation, Abscission_Zone_Activation, Cell_Separation_Process, and Petiole_Abscission_Completion. ||Duration 1-2 weeks after senescence completion. ||Involves specialized abscission zone cells. ||Hormonal regulation through auxin and ethylene balance. ||Creates protective leaf scar. || This process represents the final phase of the leaf fall phenological sequence, occurring after nutrient remobilization has recovered the majority of transportable compounds from leaf tissues and senescence has progressed to the point where continued leaf attachment provides no further benefit to the vine. ||The anatomical basis of petiole abscission involves the abscission zone, a specialized region of small, cytoplasmically dense cells located at the junction of petiole and shoot that remains developmentally competent for separation throughout the leaf's life span, with activation of this zone in response to senescence-associated signals initiating the cell separation processes that culminate in leaf detachment. ||The physiological regulation of petiole abscission involves hormonal balance shifts, with declining auxin flux from senescing leaf blades removing the primary inhibition of abscission zone activation, increasing ethylene sensitivity in abscission zone cells enabling response to senescence-derived ethylene, and potential abscisic acid involvement in coordinating abscission with overall senescence progression. ||The protective functions of petiole abscission include formation of a protective layer on the shoot side of the abscission zone through suberization and lignification of cell walls in the separation region, creating a barrier against pathogen invasion and water loss at the leaf scar that would otherwise represent a vulnerable entry point during the extended dormant period. ||Environmental factors influence petiole abscission timing, with cool temperatures accelerating abscission zone activation after senescence completion, frost events potentially inducing rapid abscission through ice crystal damage to abscission zone cells, and maintained warm conditions delaying abscission such that senescent leaves may persist attached for extended periods before separation occurs. ||The completion of petiole abscission for all leaves on a vine marks the transition to full dormancy, with defoliated vines entering the winter period when all metabolic activity is supported by accumulated reserves and the absence of transpiring surfaces allows survival through periods of soil water unavailability in frozen or drought-affected conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009838 ## abscission | 0.80" ],
  "definition_source": "Roberts JA et al (2002) Abscission, dehiscence and other cell separation processes. Annual Review of Plant Biology 53: 131-158 || Patterson SE (2001) Cutting loose. Plant Physiology 126: 494-500 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed pp 92-95"
},

  "Abscission_Zone_Formation": {
  "definition": "An Abscission_Zone_Formation is a Petiole_Abscission comprising the developmental establishment of a specialized cellular region at the petiole base bearing the disposition for cell separation upon senescence signaling, characterized by reduced cell size, dense cytoplasm, and modified cell wall composition.",
  "alternative_term": "abscission zone development | separation zone establishment | abscission layer formation | separation layer differentiation |+ Abszissionszone-Bildung | Trennzone-Entwicklung | Abszissionsschicht-Bildung | Trennschicht-Differenzierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Tempranillo vines in Ribera del Duero, Spain, abscission zone formation establishes the 3-5 cell layer separation region at the petiole base during early leaf development in May, with zone cells showing 40% smaller diameter than adjacent cortical cells, 2.5-fold higher cytoplasmic density visible in histological sections, and maintained quiescence throughout the 150-day leaf lifespan until senescence-associated ethylene accumulation triggers activation in late October under continental climate conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Abscission_Zone_Formation is subclass of Petiole_Abscission representing developmental establishment of separation zone. ||Distinguishes from activation by emphasizing structural formation. ||Sibling to Abscission_Zone_Activation, Cell_Separation_Process, and Petiole_Abscission_Completion. ||Occurs during early leaf development. ||Creates quiescent competent zone. ||Auxin maintains quiescence during leaf function. || This process occurs during early leaf development as the primordial leaf emerges and the petiole differentiates, with abscission zone cells acquiring their distinctive characteristics through differential gene expression that establishes the cellular machinery for eventual separation while maintaining normal tissue function during the extended period between formation and activation. ||The anatomical characteristics of the formed abscission zone include several layers of small, isodiametric cells with dense cytoplasm and relatively thin cell walls positioned between the petiole vascular tissue and the shoot, with these cells representing a structural discontinuity that will become the plane of eventual separation once cell wall degradation is initiated. ||The cellular features distinguishing abscission zone cells from surrounding tissues include elevated receptor populations for ethylene and other hormones enabling rapid response to activation signals, pre-positioned inactive precursors of cell wall degrading enzymes that can be rapidly activated upon appropriate triggering, and modified middle lamella composition with reduced calcium cross-linking that facilitates eventual dissolution during the separation process. ||The maintenance of abscission zone quiescence during the leaf's functional lifespan involves auxin-mediated suppression of separation competence, with polar auxin transport through the petiole maintaining auxin concentrations in the abscission zone sufficient to prevent premature activation of cell separation processes, while the zone retains structural integrity and normal tissue function despite possessing the cellular machinery for eventual separation. ||The genetic regulation of abscission zone formation involves transcription factors that specify abscission zone cell identity during leaf development, with mutations affecting these factors potentially producing leaves that fail to abscise normally, though such mutations have been more extensively characterized in model species than in grapevine specifically.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Roberts JA et al (2002) Abscission, dehiscence and other cell separation processes. Annual Review of Plant Biology 53: 131-158 || Patterson SE (2001) Cutting loose. Plant Physiology 126: 494-500 || Addicott FT (1982) Abscission University of California Press Berkeley"
},

  "Abscission_Zone_Activation": {
  "definition": "An Abscission_Zone_Activation is a Petiole_Abscission realized through declining auxin flux and rising ethylene sensitivity triggering transcriptional reprogramming and cell wall-degrading enzyme synthesis in abscission zone cells, committing them to separation within 5–10 days.",
  "alternative_term": "separation zone activation | abscission triggering | abscission zone induction | separation layer activation |+ Abszissionszone-Aktivierung | Trennzone-Aktivierung | Abszissions-Auslösung | Trennschicht-Aktivierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Shiraz vines in Barossa Valley, Australia during May, abscission zone activation occurs when leaf blade auxin production declines below 50% of mid-season levels, with ethylene sensitivity increasing 4-fold in abscission zone cells within 48 hours, cellulase gene expression induced 8-fold and polygalacturonase expression 12-fold over 4 days, and visible constriction at the petiole base appearing 5-6 days after initial activation under cool autumn conditions averaging 14°C with ethylene accumulation reaching 3.2 nL/g/h in abscission zone tissue.",
  "editor_note": "Abscission_Zone_Activation is subclass of Petiole_Abscission representing physiological transition to active separation mode. ||Distinguishes from formation by emphasizing activation signals. ||Sibling to Abscission_Zone_Formation, Cell_Separation_Process, and Petiole_Abscission_Completion. ||Auxin decline and ethylene sensitivity increase required. ||Duration 5-10 days to completion. ||Irreversible commitment to separation. || This transition represents the critical control point determining abscission timing, with multiple signals converging on abscission zone cells to assess whether conditions favor leaf retention or separation, and the integration of these signals determining whether activation proceeds or quiescence is maintained. ||The hormonal basis of abscission zone activation involves the shifting auxin-to-ethylene balance, with auxin synthesized in active leaf tissues normally maintaining abscission zone quiescence through receptor-mediated suppression of ethylene sensitivity, and the declining auxin production characteristic of senescent tissues removing this suppression to enable ethylene response and subsequent activation of separation processes. ||The molecular events marking abscission zone activation include upregulation of ethylene receptor genes and ethylene-responsive transcription factors, induction of genes encoding cell wall degrading enzymes including cellulases, polygalacturonases, and xylanases, and activation of expansin genes that loosen cell wall structure facilitating subsequent enzymatic degradation. ||The temporal progression of abscission zone activation shows characteristic phases, with initial gene expression changes occurring within 24-48 hours of auxin decline, enzyme accumulation reaching effective levels over the subsequent 2-4 days, and active cell wall degradation proceeding during the final 2-4 days before physical separation occurs. ||Environmental factors modulate abscission zone activation timing, with ethylene production from senescing tissues providing the primary activation signal, cool temperatures enhancing ethylene sensitivity in abscission zone cells, and external ethylene exposure capable of inducing activation even in incompletely senescent leaves demonstrating the ethylene-dependent nature of the activation process. ||The practical significance of abscission zone activation timing relates to defoliation management in viticulture, with understanding of activation mechanisms enabling prediction of leaf fall timing and informing decisions regarding mechanical defoliation that may be employed for canopy management purposes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Roberts JA et al (2002) Abscission, dehiscence and other cell separation processes. Annual Review of Plant Biology 53: 131-158 || Bleecker AB and Patterson SE (1997) Last exit: senescence, abscission and meristem arrest in Arabidopsis. Plant Cell 9: 1169-1179 || Patterson SE (2001) Cutting loose. Plant Physiology 126: 494-500"
},

  "Cell_Separation_Process": {
  "definition": "A Cell_Separation_Process is a Petiole_Abscission realized through coordinated cellulase, polygalacturonase, and xylanase activity dissolving cell walls and middle lamellae in abscission zone cells over 3–5 days following activation.",
  "alternative_term": "cell wall dissolution | intercellular separation | abscission zone cell separation | cell detachment process |+ Zell-Trennungs-Prozess | Zellwand-Auflösung | interzelluläre Trennung | Abszissionszone-Zell-Separation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Mourvèdre vines in Bandol, Provence during November, cell separation process proceeds over 4 days following abscission zone activation, with polygalacturonase activity increasing from 0.8 to 28 nmol/min/g fresh weight, middle lamella dissolution visible histologically within 48 hours, cortical cell separation complete by day 3 while vascular strands persist until day 4, and final detachment occurring when wind gusts exceed 15 km/h providing sufficient mechanical force to sever remaining connections under cool Mediterranean autumn conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Cell_Separation_Process is subclass of Petiole_Abscission representing enzymatic cell wall degradation. Distinguishes from activation by emphasizing physical dissolution. ||Sibling to Abscission_Zone_Formation, Abscission_Zone_Activation, and Petiole_Abscission_Completion. Duration 3-5 days. Involves cellulases, polygalacturonases, xylanases, expansins. Outer-to-inner progression with vascular persistence. || This process involves the sequential degradation of cell wall components, with pectin hydrolysis by polygalacturonases dissolving the calcium-pectate-rich middle lamella that cements adjacent cells together, cellulase activity degrading cellulose microfibrils that provide structural strength to primary cell walls, and xylanase and other hemicellulase activities cleaving the matrix polysaccharides that cross-link cellulose within the cell wall architecture. ||The spatial progression of cell separation proceeds from the outer cortical regions of the abscission zone inward toward the vascular tissues, with peripheral cells separating first while vascular connections maintain leaf attachment until late stages when xylem and phloem elements are finally severed, explaining the observation that partially separated leaves may remain attached by vascular strands until mechanical stress completes detachment. ||The biochemical mechanisms involve secretion of cell wall degrading enzymes into the apoplastic space between abscission zone cells, with enzyme activities increasing 10-50 fold during the separation period compared to quiescent abscission zones, and optimal enzyme function at the slightly acidic apoplastic pH of 5.0-6.0 characteristic of this intercellular compartment. ||The role of expansins in cell separation involves loosening of cell wall structure through disruption of hydrogen bonds between cellulose microfibrils and matrix polysaccharides, creating access for hydrolytic enzymes to their substrates and facilitating the swelling and separation of loosened wall material under turgor pressure. ||Environmental factors influence cell separation rate, with adequate moisture maintaining turgor pressure that drives cell expansion and wall separation, cool temperatures enhancing enzyme activities in the temperature-sensitive polygalacturonase reaction, and wind or rain providing mechanical forces that accelerate separation of weakened tissues. ||The completion of cell separation creates a clean fracture surface at the leaf scar, with the shoot-side cells remaining attached to the stem and undergoing protective modifications while the leaf-side cells separate with the falling leaf.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0060867 ## fruit abscission | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Roberts JA et al (2002) Abscission, dehiscence and other cell separation processes. Annual Review of Plant Biology 53: 131-158 || Taylor JE and Whitelaw CA (2001) Signals in abscission. New Phytologist 151: 323-340 || Patterson SE (2001) Cutting loose. Plant Physiology 126: 494-500"
},

  "Petiole_Abscission_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Petiole_Abscission_Completion is a Petiole_Abscission comprising final severance of cellular connections, wound sealing of the leaf scar, and formation of a protective suberized and lignified layer persisting through the dormant season.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf fall completion | abscission finalization | leaf detachment completion | leaf scar formation |+ Blattstiel-Abszissions-Abschluss | Blattfall-Vervollständigung | Abszissions-Finalisierung | Blattnarben-Bildung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Touriga Nacional vines in Douro Valley, Portugal during late November, petiole abscission completion occurs following overnight temperatures of 2°C combined with morning wind gusts of 25 km/h, with leaf separation occurring at the enzyme-weakened abscission zone, callose deposition in phloem visible within 30 minutes of separation, suberization of leaf scar cells detectable within 24 hours, and complete protective layer established within 72 hours with suberized cell layers measuring 45-60 µm thickness providing durable wound protection through the dormant period.",
  "editor_note": "Petiole_Abscission_Completion is subclass of Petiole_Abscission representing final separation and wound sealing. ||Distinguishes from cell separation by emphasizing completion and protection. ||Sibling to Abscission_Zone_Formation, Abscission_Zone_Activation, and Cell_Separation_Process. ||Involves physical detachment and protective layer formation. ||Environmental triggers include wind and temperature. ||Creates sealed leaf scar. || This process represents the culmination of the abscission sequence, occurring when cell wall degradation has progressed sufficiently that leaf weight, wind forces, or rain impact provides adequate mechanical stress to sever remaining connections, with separation occurring at the structurally weakened plane created by cell wall dissolution in the abscission zone rather than through tissue rupture that would create irregular wound surfaces. ||The protective layer formation on the shoot side of the separation plane involves rapid physiological responses including callose deposition at sieve plates sealing phloem elements within minutes of separation, oxidative reactions generating quinones that provide antimicrobial protection at the wound surface, and subsequent suberization and lignification of cell walls in the separation layer creating a durable barrier against pathogen invasion and desiccation. ||The timing of abscission completion relative to environmental conditions influences vine vulnerability, with completion before the onset of freezing temperatures allowing adequate protective layer development while delayed abscission into freezing conditions may compromise wound healing responses, potentially creating entry points for winter trunk diseases. ||The leaf scar remaining after abscission completion displays characteristic anatomical features including the sealed vascular traces where xylem and phloem elements were severed, the suberized protective layer that forms the visible scar surface, and the underlying living bark tissues that remain connected to the vine's perennial vascular system. ||Environmental factors affecting abscission completion include wind speed providing mechanical force for final separation, precipitation that may simultaneously moisten tissues facilitating separation and provide physical impact force, and temperature affecting both the final enzymatic weakening of attachment and the wound healing responses following separation. ||The mass abscission events characteristic of late autumn occur when environmental conditions combine with advanced cell separation to trigger simultaneous leaf fall across large portions of the canopy, with cool nights followed by morning wind gusts commonly associated with major leaf fall events that can substantially defoliate vines within 24-48 hour periods.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Roberts JA et al (2002) Abscission, dehiscence and other cell separation processes. Annual Review of Plant Biology 53: 131-158 || Patterson SE (2001) Cutting loose. Plant Physiology 126: 494-500 || Addicott FT (1982) Abscission University of California Press Berkeley"
},

  "Leaf_Detachment": {
  "definition": "A Leaf_Detachment is a Leaf_Fall comprising the physical separation of senescing leaves from the vine following completion of abscission zone activation and cell separation.",
  "alternative_term": "leaf abscission completion | leaf separation | leaf shedding | autumn leaf fall |+ Blattabfall | Blattablösung | Laubfall | herbstlicher Blattfall",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vineyards of the Côte d'Or, Burgundy, leaf detachment typically commences in early November following completion of abscission zone activation, with 50% leaf fall achieved by mid-November when minimum temperatures consistently reach 2-4°C, and complete defoliation occurring by late November to early December under normal seasonal conditions corresponding to post-BBCH 97 developmental stage.",
  "editor_note": "Leaf_Detachment represents the final physical separation phase within the Leaf_Fall hierarchy, occurring after Petiole_Abscission processes have prepared the separation zone. ||Distinguished from Leaf_Senescence which encompasses biochemical degradation processes, and from Petiole_Abscission which specifically addresses abscission zone formation and activation. ||This parent class encompasses all temporal phases from initial to complete detachment, with duration typically spanning 3-6 weeks depending on cultivar and environmental conditions. ||Subdivides into Initial_Leaf_Detachment, Progressive_Leaf_Fall, Mass_Leaf_Fall, and Complete_Leaf_Detachment based on temporal progression and proportion of canopy affected. || This process occurs during late autumn, typically from late October through November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, when the abscission zone at the petiole base has undergone complete cell wall dissolution and middle lamella degradation, allowing mechanical separation of leaf tissue from shoot attachment points. ||The detachment process involves the final rupture of remaining vascular connections and residual cellular attachments that persisted through the cell separation phase, with actual leaf fall triggered by environmental factors including wind, rainfall, frost events, and gravitational forces acting on weakened attachment points. ||Physiologically, leaf detachment represents the culmination of programmed senescence processes that began 4-8 weeks earlier with chlorophyll degradation and nutrient remobilization, during which period the vine systematically recovered nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, and other mobile nutrients from leaf tissues for storage in permanent woody structures. ||The timing of leaf detachment varies considerably among cultivars, with early-ripening varieties such as Chasselas and Pinot Noir typically completing leaf fall 2-3 weeks before late-ripening cultivars like Cabernet Sauvignon and Grenache. ||Temperature plays a critical role in detachment timing, with accelerated leaf fall occurring when minimum temperatures drop below 5°C for consecutive nights, while mild autumn conditions can delay complete defoliation by several weeks. ||The process exhibits spatial patterns within the canopy, generally progressing from basal leaves that senesced earliest toward apical positions, though environmental exposure and shading history influence individual leaf detachment timing. ||From a viticultural perspective, the progression and completion of leaf detachment provides important indicators of vine dormancy preparation and carbohydrate reserve status, with delayed or incomplete leaf fall sometimes indicating nutritional imbalances or disease pressure that compromised normal senescence signaling. ||The physical mechanics of detachment involve separation at the abscission zone fracture plane, where specialized separation layer cells have dissolved their shared cell walls, leaving a clean break surface that rapidly suberizes to protect exposed shoot tissues from pathogen entry and desiccation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0009838 ## abscission | 0.75" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine Cambridge University Press || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of starch and N reserves in grapevine. Journal of Experimental Botany 55: 2165-2175"
},

  "Initial_Leaf_Detachment": {
  "definition": "An Initial_Leaf_Detachment is a Leaf_Detachment comprising the first leaves falling from the canopy following completion of abscission zone cell separation.",
  "alternative_term": "first leaf fall | early leaf detachment | beginning leaf abscission | initial defoliation |+ beginnender Blattfall | erster Blattabfall | frühe Blattablösung | initiale Entblätterung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vineyards of the Rheingau, Germany, initial leaf detachment commences during the last week of October when the first autumn frosts with temperatures of -1 to -2°C trigger separation of basal leaves representing approximately 10-12% of canopy leaf area, marking the onset of defoliation at post-BBCH 93 to early BBCH 95 developmental stage.",
  "editor_note": "Initial_Leaf_Detachment represents the first temporal phase of Leaf_Detachment, specifically encompassing the earliest 10-15% of leaf separation events. ||Distinguished from Progressive_Leaf_Fall which follows as detachment spreads through the canopy, and from Mass_Leaf_Fall which represents the period of most rapid defoliation. ||Occurs predominantly at basal canopy positions where senescence initiated earliest. ||Duration typically spans 5-10 days depending on weather conditions. ||Key indicators include first visible ground litter accumulation and initial exposure of basal shoot regions. || This phase typically begins in late October to early November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, when the oldest basal leaves that initiated senescence earliest have completed abscission zone activation and experience sufficient mechanical stress to trigger separation. ||The first detaching leaves are predominantly those at basal node positions that received reduced light penetration during the growing season and consequently initiated senescence programs 2-3 weeks before more exposed canopy positions. ||Anatomically, initial detachment occurs when the separation layer cells within the abscission zone have completed cell wall dissolution through the coordinated action of cellulases, polygalacturonases, and other hydrolytic enzymes, reducing attachment strength below the threshold where environmental forces can effect separation. ||The triggering events for initial leaf fall typically include the first significant autumn wind events, light frost exposure causing tissue damage that increases mechanical stress, or rainfall adding weight to weakened attachment points. ||Quantitatively, initial leaf detachment encompasses approximately the first 10-15% of total canopy leaf area, representing leaves from approximately 2-4 basal nodes on each shoot that underwent earliest senescence initiation. ||The process serves as an important phenological marker for viticulturists, indicating that dormancy preparation has progressed sufficiently for abscission zone maturation to reach completion at the most advanced positions. ||Physiologically, leaves undergoing initial detachment have typically completed nutrient remobilization processes, with nitrogen content reduced to 0.8-1.2% dry weight compared to 2.5-3.5% in fully functional summer leaves, and chlorophyll content degraded to less than 10% of maximum summer values. ||Temperature conditions during initial leaf detachment typically feature daytime maxima of 10-15°C and nighttime minima approaching or slightly below 5°C, creating the thermal environment that completes abscission zone enzyme activity while providing mechanical stress through frost-induced tissue changes. ||The spatial pattern of initial detachment provides diagnostic information about canopy senescence uniformity, with highly synchronous initial leaf fall indicating consistent vine nutrition and water status, while scattered or delayed initial detachment may suggest heterogeneous canopy conditions or stress factors that disrupted normal senescence signaling.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of starch and N reserves in grapevine. Journal of Experimental Botany 55: 2165-2175 || Wermelinger B, Koblet W (1990) Seasonal growth and nitrogen distribution in grapevine leaves. Vitis 29: 15-26"
},

  "Progressive_Leaf_Fall": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Leaf_Fall is a Leaf_Detachment exhibiting sequential advancement of leaf separation from earlier-senescing basal positions toward later-senescing apical and well-exposed positions over 2–4 weeks.",
  "alternative_term": "sequential leaf fall | advancing leaf detachment | gradual defoliation | continuing leaf abscission |+ fortschreitender Blattfall | sequentieller Blattfall | voranschreitende Entblätterung | gradueller Laubfall",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vineyards of the Mâconnais, Burgundy, progressive leaf fall advances acropetally through the canopy during November, with leaf detachment progressing from node positions 3-5 in the first week to positions 8-12 by mid-November, achieving approximately 60% total defoliation at a rate of 2-3 node positions per week under typical autumn temperatures of 6-10°C daytime maxima.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Leaf_Fall represents the main quantitative phase of Leaf_Detachment, encompassing 50-70% of total leaf area loss between Initial_Leaf_Detachment and Mass_Leaf_Fall. ||Distinguished by its directional acropetal pattern and steady advancement rate rather than the scattered nature of initial detachment or the rapid synchronous character of mass leaf fall. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 weeks depending on cultivar and temperature conditions. ||Characterized by progressive exposure of shoot architecture and systematic canopy transparency increase. || This phase encompasses the majority of canopy defoliation volume, typically representing 50-70% of total leaf area loss, and occurs during November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture as abscission zone maturation sequentially reaches completion at progressively younger leaf positions. ||The progressive pattern reflects the acropetal gradient of leaf initiation during spring growth, whereby basal leaves established earliest also initiate senescence programs earliest, creating a wave of abscission competence that advances up the shoot axis at a rate determined by senescence signal propagation and environmental conditions. ||Mechanistically, progressive leaf fall involves the sequential completion of cell separation processes at successive node positions, with each leaf's abscission zone requiring approximately 10-14 days from senescence initiation to achieve separation competence under typical autumn temperatures. ||The rate of progression varies considerably with temperature regime, accelerating during periods with consistent overnight minima below 5°C and daytime maxima of 8-12°C that favor both senescence advancement and abscission zone enzyme activity. ||Environmental events modulate the steady progression, with wind events or frost episodes causing synchronized detachment pulses within the general progressive trend, while calm mild conditions allow more gradual individual leaf separation. ||Cultivar differences significantly influence progression rate, with thin-leaved varieties such as Pinot Noir and Gamay typically completing progressive leaf fall within 2-3 weeks, while thick-leaved cultivars including Cabernet Sauvignon and Carignan may require 4-5 weeks for equivalent progression. ||The spatial pattern during progressive leaf fall creates characteristic canopy appearance changes, with increasing visibility of shoot architecture as leaf coverage retreats apically, providing viticultural indicators of dormancy preparation advancement. ||Physiologically, leaves detaching during progressive leaf fall have completed varying degrees of nutrient remobilization depending on their position in the senescence sequence, with earlier-detaching leaves showing more complete nitrogen and phosphorus recovery than later-detaching leaves that experienced abbreviated senescence periods. ||The progressive nature of leaf fall serves important vine functions, allowing extended periods for carbohydrate translocation to permanent structures and preventing sudden exposure of previously shaded tissues to environmental stress.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine Cambridge University Press || Holzapfel BP, Smith JP (2012) Developmental stage and climatic factors impact more on carbohydrate reserve dynamics than leaf area. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 18: 38-45"
},

  "Mass_Leaf_Fall": {
  "definition": "A Mass_Leaf_Fall is a Leaf_Detachment consisting of rapid synchronous separation of a substantial proportion of remaining canopy leaves within a compressed timeframe triggered by environmental events overcoming residual attachment strength.",
  "alternative_term": "rapid mass defoliation | synchronous leaf fall | bulk leaf detachment | simultaneous leaf shedding |+ Massenblattfall | synchroner Blattfall | schnelle Massenentblätterung | gleichzeitiger Laubfall",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Franc vineyards of Chinon, Loire Valley, a mass leaf fall event occurred on November 28 when overnight temperatures of -5°C followed by morning winds of 25-35 km/h triggered synchronous detachment of approximately 35% of remaining canopy leaves within 36 hours, reducing canopy leaf coverage from 45% to less than 15% and creating concentrated leaf litter accumulation beneath the trellis.",
  "editor_note": "Mass_Leaf_Fall represents a distinct event-driven phase within Leaf_Detachment characterized by rapid synchronous defoliation rather than gradual progression. ||Distinguished from Progressive_Leaf_Fall by its compressed timeframe and synchronous character, and from Complete_Leaf_Detachment which addresses final residual leaf removal. ||Triggering conditions typically involve frost events below -3°C combined with wind exposure. ||Can occur as single or multiple events during late autumn. ||Duration of individual mass fall events typically 24-72 hours. ||May account for 20-40% of total canopy defoliation in single episodes. || This phenomenon occurs most commonly during late November to early December in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, when significant frost events, strong wind episodes, or the combination of both create mechanical and physiological conditions that trigger widespread simultaneous leaf separation. ||Unlike the gradual progression characteristic of earlier leaf fall phases, mass leaf fall events can result in 20-40% of remaining canopy leaf area detaching within 24-72 hours, dramatically transforming vine appearance from partially foliated to nearly bare. ||The triggering conditions for mass leaf fall typically involve nighttime temperatures dropping to -3°C to -6°C that cause ice crystal formation within leaf tissues, disrupting cell membrane integrity and increasing leaf weight through ice accumulation while simultaneously making tissues brittle and more susceptible to mechanical separation. ||Wind events coinciding with or following frost exposure are particularly effective triggers, as the combination of weakened attachment points and mechanical stress creates conditions favoring synchronous detachment across multiple canopy positions regardless of their individual senescence advancement status. ||The phenomenon exhibits threshold behavior, with gradual accumulation of abscission zone maturation creating increasing proportions of leaves approaching detachment competence until environmental triggers release them simultaneously. ||Cultivar susceptibility to mass leaf fall events varies with leaf anatomical characteristics, with thin-leaved varieties showing greater frost sensitivity and more pronounced mass fall responses, while thick-leaved cultivars may retain damaged leaves longer due to more robust petiole construction. ||From a viticultural management perspective, mass leaf fall events provide convenient timing windows for winter pruning commencement, as the rapid canopy clearing exposes cane architecture and allows pruner assessment of wood maturity and bud positioning. ||The synchronous nature of mass leaf fall also creates concentrated leaf litter accumulation that influences vineyard floor management decisions regarding incorporation timing and disease pressure management for following seasons. ||Physiologically, leaves lost during mass leaf fall events may retain higher nutrient concentrations than those completing gradual progressive detachment, as the rapid separation can interrupt ongoing remobilization processes in less-advanced leaves.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Mills LJ, Ferguson JC, Keller M (2006) Cold-hardiness evaluation of grapevine buds and cane tissues. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 194-200"
},

  "Complete_Leaf_Detachment": {
  "definition": "A Complete_Leaf_Detachment is a Leaf_Detachment defined by the separation of all remaining leaves from the canopy yielding the bare-cane winter state.",
  "alternative_term": "full defoliation | complete leaf loss | total leaf fall | final leaf detachment |+ vollständiger Blattfall | komplette Entblätterung | totaler Laubfall | abgeschlossener Blattfall",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vineyards of Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux, complete leaf detachment was achieved by December 8 following a frost event of -4°C that triggered separation of the final 8% of canopy leaves consisting primarily of apical shoot leaves and late-formed lateral leaves, resulting in fully dormant bare-cane vine appearance at BBCH stage 97 with all abscission scars showing characteristic suberized protective layer formation.",
  "editor_note": "Complete_Leaf_Detachment represents the terminal phase of Leaf_Detachment, marking achievement of 100% defoliation and full dormant canopy appearance. ||Distinguished from Mass_Leaf_Fall which represents rapid synchronous events affecting substantial leaf proportions, while Complete_Leaf_Detachment specifically addresses final residual leaf removal regardless of mechanism. ||Corresponds to BBCH stage 97 achievement. ||Final detaching leaves typically located at apical positions and on lateral shoots. ||Duration variable depending on environmental forcing, ranging from gradual final progression to event-triggered completion. ||Marks optimal timing for winter pruning commencement and dormant vine assessment. || This phase encompasses the final 5-15% of leaf area removal, involving the last persistent leaves that either delayed senescence initiation due to favorable microclimate exposure or retained attachment despite completed abscission zone preparation. ||Complete leaf detachment typically occurs during December in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, finalizing the leaf fall process that began 4-8 weeks earlier with initial detachment of basal senesced leaves. ||The final detaching leaves are predominantly located at apical shoot positions that received optimal light exposure during the growing season and consequently maintained photosynthetic activity and chlorophyll retention longer than shaded canopy positions. ||Additionally, leaves on lateral shoots, water sprouts, and vigorous regrowth that initiated later in the growing season often represent the last leaves to complete detachment due to their delayed developmental timing relative to primary shoot leaves. ||Mechanistically, complete leaf detachment occurs through the same abscission zone separation processes as earlier phases, but may involve environmental forcing that overcomes incomplete abscission zone preparation in delayed leaves, particularly through severe frost damage that kills remaining leaf tissue and eliminates any physiological resistance to separation. ||The achievement of complete leaf detachment serves as an important phenological marker corresponding to BBCH stage 97, indicating that the vine has fully transitioned to winter dormancy status and has completed the annual cycle of deciduous leaf production and abscission. ||From a viticultural perspective, complete leaf detachment provides optimal conditions for winter pruning operations, dormant disease assessment, and vineyard structural maintenance, as the absence of foliage allows clear visualization of cane architecture and bud positioning. ||Delayed complete leaf detachment beyond typical timing may indicate cultivar characteristics, mild winter conditions, or nutritional factors that extended leaf functional lifespan. ||The completion of leaf detachment also marks the point at which vineyard floor organic matter inputs from the current season are finalized, influencing decisions regarding cover crop management and soil incorporation practices. ||The protective layer formed at abscission scars following complete leaf detachment consists of suberized cells that seal vascular tissues against winter desiccation and pathogen entry, completing the vine's preparation for dormant season survival.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Coombe BG, Dry PR (1992) Viticulture Volume 1 Resources 2nd Ed Winetitles Adelaide || Lorenz DH et al (1995) Growth stages of the grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine - BBCH-scale. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1: 100-103"
},

  "Dormancy": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy is a Grapevine_Phenological_Process comprising the suspension of visible growth and metabolic activity in meristematic tissues enabling survival under freezing and desiccating winter conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "winter dormancy | seasonal dormancy | growth cessation period | winter rest |+ Winterruhe | Dormanz | Vegetationsruhe | Ruheperiode",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vineyards of the Rheingau, Germany, the dormancy period extends from late November through mid-March, with vines entering endodormancy following exposure to temperatures below 10°C and short photoperiods of less than 12 hours, accumulating approximately 1200 chilling hours below 7.2°C for complete dormancy satisfaction, and remaining in ecodormancy until growing degree day accumulation triggers budbreak in early to mid-April.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy represents the highest-level process class within the dormancy hierarchy under Grapevine_Phenological_Process, encompassing all phases of growth suspension from induction through release. ||Distinguished from active growth phases by the absence of visible meristematic activity despite the presence of viable growing points. ||Subdivides into Dormancy_Induction, Endodormancy, Ecodormancy, and Dormancy_Release as sequential phases. ||Duration typically spans 4-6 months in temperate viticulture. ||Critical for winter survival and proper spring growth synchronization. || This complex physiological state encompasses a continuum of growth inhibition phases ranging from environmentally-induced dormancy induction through deep endodormancy to the environmentally-constrained ecodormancy that persists until conditions favor growth resumption in spring. ||The dormancy period in grapevine typically extends from late autumn through early spring, spanning approximately 4-6 months in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, during which buds remain in a quiescent state despite containing fully formed primordial shoots with leaf, tendril, and inflorescence primordia that were initiated during the previous growing season. ||Physiologically, dormancy involves profound changes in cellular metabolism, including accumulation of abscisic acid as a key regulatory hormone, decreased auxin and cytokinin activity, altered carbohydrate partitioning with starch accumulation in woody tissues, increased expression of dehydrin proteins that protect cellular structures during freezing, and modifications to membrane lipid composition that enhance freeze tolerance. ||The dormancy cycle is regulated by the interacting influences of photoperiod, temperature, and endogenous developmental programs, with short day length serving as the primary environmental signal initiating dormancy induction in autumn, chilling temperature accumulation required for dormancy release, and warming temperatures triggering growth resumption once dormancy has been satisfied. ||Cultivar differences in dormancy characteristics significantly influence viticultural adaptation, with cultivars originating from continental climates typically exhibiting deeper dormancy and higher chilling requirements than those from Mediterranean regions, affecting both winter hardiness and the timing of budbreak in spring. ||The dormancy period serves critical functions beyond winter survival, including synchronization of spring growth with favorable environmental conditions, prevention of premature budbreak during temporary warm periods, and provision of the rest period necessary for proper development of reproductive structures. ||Understanding dormancy physiology has become increasingly important in the context of climate change, as warming winters may provide insufficient chilling for complete dormancy satisfaction in some regions, potentially leading to erratic budbreak, reduced fruitfulness, and compromised vine performance.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:broadMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0022611 ## dormancy process | 0.90" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377"
},

  "Dormancy_Induction": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Induction is a Dormancy comprising perception of environmental signals and physiological transition from active growth to growth cessation and preparation for winter dormancy.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy onset | dormancy initiation | growth cessation induction | autumn dormancy entry |+ Dormanzeinleitung | Ruheinduktion | Dormanzinduktion | Vegetationsruhebeginn",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vineyards of Napa Valley, California, dormancy induction commences in late September when photoperiod decreases below 12.5 hours, with visible signs including cessation of shoot elongation, periderm browning advancing acropetally along shoots, and initial bud scale formation, progressing through October as night temperatures consistently fall below 10°C to achieve full dormancy establishment by early November.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Induction represents the first major phase within the Dormancy hierarchy, encompassing the transition from active growth to dormant state. ||Distinguished from Endodormancy which represents the established dormant condition, and from active growth phases by the progressive inhibition rather than absence of growth activity. ||Subdivides into Photoperiod_Response, Temperature_Acclimation, Growth_Cessation, and Dormancy_Establishment as component processes. ||Duration typically spans 6-10 weeks depending on cultivar and environmental conditions. ||Critical for establishing adequate cold hardiness before winter. || This critical period typically occurs during late summer through autumn, from August through October in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, as declining photoperiod and decreasing temperatures interact to activate the genetic and hormonal programs that progressively inhibit meristematic activity and redirect metabolism toward cold acclimation and reserve accumulation. ||The process is initiated primarily by photoperiod sensing, with the shortening day length below a cultivar-specific threshold serving as the most reliable environmental cue for upcoming winter conditions, detected through phytochrome-mediated pathways in leaf tissues that generate systemic signals affecting bud and cambial meristems. ||Temperature serves as a secondary but important modulating factor, with cool temperatures enhancing the dormancy induction response and warm temperatures potentially delaying the process, creating the risk of inadequate cold hardiness development when unseasonably warm autumn conditions occur. ||Physiologically, dormancy induction involves coordinated changes including cessation of shoot apical meristem activity, formation of terminal buds or shoot tip abscission, development of bud scales from modified leaves that provide physical protection, accumulation of abscisic acid which inhibits growth and promotes stress tolerance gene expression, and initiation of cold acclimation processes that progressively increase freezing tolerance. ||The hormonal transition during dormancy induction involves declining auxin and gibberellin levels that normally promote growth, increasing abscisic acid concentrations that inhibit cell division and elongation, and altered cytokinin transport from roots that affects bud activity. ||Carbohydrate metabolism shifts during induction from supporting active growth toward starch accumulation in woody tissues and synthesis of cryoprotective sugars including raffinose family oligosaccharides. ||The timing and completeness of dormancy induction significantly affects winter survival, with vines that fail to achieve adequate dormancy before severe cold exposure suffering increased cold injury, while premature or excessive dormancy induction may reduce photosynthetic capacity and reserve accumulation during favorable late-season conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0097436 ## entry into dormancy | 0.85" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Wake CMF, Fennell A (2000) Morphological, physiological and dormancy responses of three Vitis genotypes to short photoperiod. Physiologia Plantarum 109: 203-210"
},

  "Photoperiod_Response": {
  "definition": "A Photoperiod_Response is a Dormancy_Induction comprising detection of day-length change and transduction of this environmental information into developmental signals regulating dormancy induction and seasonal growth transitions.",
  "alternative_term": "daylength response | photoperiodic response | daylength sensing | photoperiod perception |+ Photoperioden-Reaktion | Tageslängenreaktion | photoperiodische Reaktion | Tageslängenwahrnehmung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines at latitude 47°N in the Willamette Valley, Oregon, photoperiod response initiates dormancy preparation when day length decreases below approximately 13.5 hours in mid-September, with phytochrome-mediated signaling in mature leaves triggering measurable increases in bud abscisic acid content within 2-3 weeks of critical photoperiod exposure and subsequent cessation of shoot elongation by early October.",
  "editor_note": "Photoperiod_Response represents a major component process within Dormancy_Induction, specifically addressing the detection and response to changing day length. ||Distinguished from Temperature_Acclimation which responds to thermal signals, though both processes interact during dormancy induction. ||Subdivides into Short_Day_Perception, Photoperiod_Signal_Transduction, and Growth_Inhibition_Initiation as sequential phases. ||The primary environmental trigger for dormancy induction in grapevine. ||Critical photoperiod thresholds vary with cultivar origin latitude. || This sophisticated sensory and signaling system enables vines to anticipate the approach of winter based on the highly reliable seasonal changes in photoperiod, initiating dormancy preparation well before potentially damaging cold temperatures occur. ||The detection of photoperiod occurs primarily in mature leaves through the photoreceptor phytochrome system, which exists in two interconvertible forms whose ratio changes with the relative durations of light and darkness, with the Pfr form produced during light exposure converting to the Pr form during extended dark periods characteristic of long nights. ||When night length exceeds a cultivar-specific critical threshold, typically corresponding to day lengths below 13-14 hours for most Vitis vinifera cultivars, the altered phytochrome signaling initiates cascades of gene expression changes that ultimately affect distant meristematic tissues including buds and cambium. ||The signal transduction pathway involves integration with circadian clock components that measure night length with remarkable precision, interactions with hormone biosynthesis and signaling pathways particularly involving abscisic acid and gibberellin, and long-distance transport of signaling molecules through the phloem from photoperception sites in leaves to responding tissues in buds and stems. ||The photoperiod response exhibits significant genotypic variation, with cultivars adapted to higher latitudes generally responding to longer critical day lengths than those from lower latitudes, reflecting evolutionary adaptation to the different relationships between photoperiod and the onset of cold conditions in different geographic regions. ||Environmental factors including temperature and plant water status can modulate the photoperiod response, with warm temperatures potentially delaying the response and water stress potentially enhancing sensitivity to short-day signals. ||The practical implications of photoperiod response for viticulture include understanding cultivar adaptation to different latitudes, predicting dormancy timing under changing climate conditions, and recognizing that artificial lighting or light pollution may potentially interfere with normal dormancy induction in affected vineyard areas.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Wake CMF, Fennell A (2000) Morphological, physiological and dormancy responses of three Vitis genotypes to short photoperiod. Physiologia Plantarum 109: 203-210 || Garner WW, Allard HA (1923) Further studies in photoperiodism. Journal of Agricultural Research 23: 871-920"
},

  "Short_Day_Perception": {
  "definition": "A Short_Day_Perception is a Photoperiod_Response realized through photoreceptor detection in leaf tissues of day length below the critical threshold signaling approaching winter conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "long night detection | critical daylength sensing | photoperiod detection | short photoperiod perception |+ Kurztagwahrnehmung | Langnacht-Erkennung | kritische Tageslängenerkennung | Kurzphotoperioden-Perzeption",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer vines in Alsace at latitude 48°N, short day perception occurs when night length exceeds approximately 11 hours in mid-September, with the mature leaves on mid-shoot positions serving as primary perception sites where phytochrome Pfr levels decline during the extended dark period below the threshold required to maintain growth-promoting gene expression, initiating the dormancy signaling cascade.",
  "editor_note": "Short_Day_Perception represents the initial sensory phase within Photoperiod_Response, specifically addressing the photoreceptor-mediated detection of critical night length. ||Distinguished from Photoperiod_Signal_Transduction which addresses downstream signaling events, and from Growth_Inhibition_Initiation which addresses the developmental response. ||Occurs in mature leaves rather than buds. ||Detection is technically of long nights rather than short days. ||Critical night length varies with cultivar origin latitude from approximately 10-12 hours. || This photobiological process occurs in mature, fully expanded leaves where phytochrome photoreceptors are concentrated, with detection depending on the duration of the dark period rather than the light period, making it technically a response to long nights rather than short days. ||The phytochrome system central to short day perception consists of photoreversible chromoproteins that exist in two forms, the red light-absorbing Pr form and the far-red light-absorbing Pfr form, with the Pfr form produced during daylight gradually reverting to the Pr form during darkness at a rate that allows measurement of night length. ||When the dark period exceeds the critical duration for a particular genotype, the resulting low Pfr/Pr ratio at dawn initiates the signaling cascade that leads to dormancy-related gene expression changes. ||The critical night length for Vitis vinifera cultivars generally falls between 10-12 hours, corresponding to day lengths of 12-14 hours, with variation among cultivars reflecting adaptation to different latitudes of origin where the relationship between photoperiod and the timing of winter cold differs. ||The perception process is remarkably sensitive, with plants capable of detecting differences in night length of less than 30 minutes, providing precise timing information for seasonal transitions. ||Multiple phytochrome genes are expressed in grapevine, including PHYA and PHYB homologs that may serve partially redundant and partially distinct functions in photoperiod perception. ||Light quality as well as quantity influences perception, with the red to far-red ratio at dusk and dawn providing additional temporal information through effects on phytochrome photoequilibrium. ||The anatomical localization of perception primarily in mature leaves necessitates signal transmission to distant responding tissues including buds, establishing the requirement for long-distance signaling mechanisms that connect perception sites with developmental response sites.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Wake CMF, Fennell A (2000) Morphological, physiological and dormancy responses of three Vitis genotypes to short photoperiod. Physiologia Plantarum 109: 203-210 || Borthwick HA, Hendricks SB (1960) Photoperiodism in plants. Science 132: 1223-1228"
},

  "Photoperiod_Signal_Transduction": {
  "definition": "A Photoperiod_Signal_Transduction is a Photoperiod_Response comprising conversion of the photoperiod perception event into systemic developmental signals reaching meristematic tissues in buds and cambium and producing growth cessation and dormancy establishment.",
  "alternative_term": "photoperiod signaling cascade | daylength signal transmission | photoperiodic signaling | dormancy signaling pathway |+ Photoperioden-Signaltransduktion | Tageslängen-Signalübertragung | photoperiodische Signalkaskade | Dormanz-Signalweg",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines, photoperiod signal transduction proceeds over 2-3 weeks following short day perception, with increased VvNCED expression in leaves elevating abscisic acid biosynthesis, altered VvFT homolog expression affecting mobile signal production, and subsequent detection of increased ABA and dormancy-associated transcripts in axillary buds indicating successful long-distance signal transmission from leaves to meristematic tissues.",
  "editor_note": "Photoperiod_Signal_Transduction represents the intermediate signaling phase within Photoperiod_Response, connecting Short_Day_Perception to Growth_Inhibition_Initiation. ||Distinguished from perception which addresses photoreceptor detection, and from growth inhibition which addresses the developmental outcome. ||Involves both intracellular signaling cascades and long-distance mobile signals. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 weeks as signals propagate and accumulate. ||Key molecular players include clock components, transcription factors, and hormones particularly ABA. || This complex signaling network operates across multiple scales from molecular interactions within perceiving cells to whole-plant hormone gradients that coordinate dormancy throughout the vine. ||The intracellular component of signal transduction involves interactions between phytochrome signaling and the circadian clock system, with clock components including homologs of CONSTANS, GIGANTEA, and other regulatory proteins integrating photoperiod information with endogenous rhythms to generate appropriately timed outputs. ||Transcription factor cascades activated by photoperiod signaling include members of the PHYTOCHROME INTERACTING FACTOR family whose activity is regulated by phytochrome-mediated degradation, and downstream factors that activate or repress target genes involved in growth, metabolism, and dormancy. ||The hormonal dimension of signal transduction involves changes in biosynthesis, transport, and sensitivity of multiple plant hormones, with increasing abscisic acid levels promoting dormancy and stress tolerance while declining gibberellin activity reduces growth promotion, creating the hormonal environment that favors dormancy establishment. ||Long-distance signaling from perception sites in leaves to responding meristems involves mobile signals transported through the phloem, potentially including small RNAs, transcription factors, and hormone precursors that communicate photoperiod status to distant tissues. ||The FLOWERING LOCUS T protein and its homologs, which serve as mobile flowering signals in annual plants, may play roles in mediating photoperiod information to grapevine buds, though their specific functions in perennial dormancy systems remain under investigation. ||Chromatin modifications including changes in histone acetylation and methylation contribute to the establishment of dormancy-related gene expression patterns that persist beyond the initial signal perception. ||The duration and intensity of short-day exposure affects signal strength, with prolonged exposure generally producing more robust dormancy responses than brief exposure near the critical threshold.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Cooke JE, Eriksson ME, Junttila O (2012) The dynamic nature of bud dormancy in trees: environmental control and molecular mechanisms. Plant Cell and Environment 35: 1707-1728"
},

  "Growth_Inhibition_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Inhibition_Initiation is a Photoperiod_Response marked by photoperiod-derived signals reaching sufficient strength to suppress meristematic activity producing the transition from growing to pre-dormant physiological status.",
  "alternative_term": "growth cessation onset | growth suppression initiation | meristem inhibition start | initial growth arrest |+ Wachstumshemmung-Initiierung | Wachstumseinstellung-Beginn | initiale Wachstumsunterdrückung | Meristem-Inhibierung-Start",
  "example_of_usage": "In Syrah vines in the Rhône Valley, growth inhibition initiation becomes measurable in early October approximately 3 weeks after critical photoperiod exposure, with shoot elongation rate declining from 2-3 cm per day to less than 0.5 cm per day, plastochron extending from 3-4 days to more than 7 days, and apical meristem cell division rate decreasing by approximately 60% as determined by mitotic index measurements.",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Inhibition_Initiation represents the functional outcome phase within Photoperiod_Response, marking the point where signaling produces measurable developmental effects. ||Distinguished from Photoperiod_Signal_Transduction which addresses upstream signaling, and from Growth_Cessation which represents complete growth stoppage. ||Represents beginning rather than completion of growth inhibition. ||Affects different meristems at different rates. ||Typically occurs 2-4 weeks after critical photoperiod exposure. ||Key indicators include declining elongation rate and extended plastochron. || This phase occurs when the accumulated signals from short day perception and subsequent transduction pathways reach threshold levels that overcome the growth-promoting activities maintained during the growing season, initiating measurable reductions in cell division and elongation in shoot apical meristems and cambium. ||The earliest manifestations of growth inhibition include slowing of shoot elongation rate, reduced plastochron as new leaf initiation declines, decreased internode length in newly forming stem segments, and subtle changes in apical meristem geometry as cell proliferation slows. ||At the cellular level, growth inhibition involves declining cyclin and cyclin-dependent kinase activity that reduces cell cycle progression, altered auxin transport and signaling that affects cell elongation, and increasing expression of growth-inhibiting transcription factors that suppress genes required for meristematic function. ||The hormonal basis of growth inhibition centers on the shifting balance between growth promoters and inhibitors, with rising abscisic acid levels directly inhibiting cell cycle progression and cell elongation, declining gibberellin activity reducing its growth-promoting effects, and altered cytokinin import from roots affecting bud meristem activity. ||The initiation of growth inhibition exhibits spatial patterns within the vine, typically affecting apical meristems before lateral positions and young leaves before mature ones, reflecting differential sensitivity of tissues at different developmental stages. ||Growth inhibition initiation does not represent complete cessation but rather the beginning of progressive reduction, with full growth cessation achieved through continued signaling and reinforcement during subsequent dormancy establishment. ||The timing of growth inhibition initiation relative to environmental conditions affects both the adequacy of cold hardiness development and the completeness of reserve accumulation for the following season.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223"
},

  "Temperature_Acclimation": {
  "definition": "A Temperature_Acclimation is a Dormancy_Induction comprising progressive development of freezing tolerance in vine tissues in response to declining autumn temperatures.",
  "alternative_term": "cold acclimation | cold hardening | frost hardening | freezing tolerance development |+ Temperatur-Akklimatisierung | Kälteabhärtung | Frostabhärtung | Kältetoleranz-Entwicklung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Mosel Valley, temperature acclimation progresses through autumn with initial acclimation at 10-15°C during October increasing bud cold hardiness from -5°C to -12°C, secondary hardening during November as temperatures fall to 0-5°C further increasing hardiness to -18°C, and maximum hardiness of -22°C achieved by late December following exposure to temperatures of -5 to -10°C during early winter.",
  "editor_note": "Temperature_Acclimation represents a major component process within Dormancy_Induction parallel to Photoperiod_Response, specifically addressing the thermal induction of cold hardiness. ||Distinguished from Photoperiod_Response which addresses daylength signals, though both processes interact synergistically during dormancy induction. ||Subdivides into Cold_Acclimation_Start, Freeze_Tolerance_Development, and Metabolic_Adjustment as component processes. ||Proceeds in stages requiring progressively lower temperatures. ||Maximum hardiness varies with cultivar from approximately -15 to -30°C in Vitis vinifera. || This adaptive response involves coordinated changes in cellular composition, gene expression, and metabolism that progressively enhance the ability of living tissues to withstand ice formation and the associated cellular stresses of dehydration, mechanical damage, and membrane disruption. ||The acclimation process proceeds in stages, with initial acclimation occurring at cool but non-freezing temperatures between 10-15°C involving transcriptional activation of cold-responsive genes, followed by further hardening at temperatures approaching freezing that induces additional protective mechanisms and maximum cold hardiness development at temperatures below freezing. ||The cellular changes during temperature acclimation include accumulation of compatible solutes including proline, raffinose family oligosaccharides, and other cryoprotective molecules that stabilize membranes and proteins during freezing, synthesis of dehydrin proteins that protect cellular structures during freeze-induced dehydration, and modifications to membrane lipid composition increasing unsaturated fatty acid content that maintains membrane fluidity at low temperatures. ||Gene expression changes during cold acclimation involve activation of CBF/DREB transcription factors that regulate large sets of cold-responsive genes, increased expression of genes encoding protective proteins and biosynthetic enzymes for cryoprotectants, and repression of genes associated with active growth. ||The interaction between temperature acclimation and photoperiod response is complex, with short days enhancing cold acclimation capacity even at warm temperatures and low temperatures being more effective at inducing hardiness after short-day pre-conditioning than before. ||Maximum cold hardiness in fully acclimated grapevine tissues can reach -20 to -25°C for hardy cultivars, compared to only -3 to -5°C for non-acclimated tissues, illustrating the dramatic protective effects of the acclimation process. ||The rate and extent of cold acclimation varies substantially among cultivars, contributing to differences in geographic adaptation and winter survival.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Mills LJ, Ferguson JC, Keller M (2006) Cold-hardiness evaluation of grapevine buds and cane tissues. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 194-200 || Xin Z, Browse J (2000) Cold comfort farm: the acclimation of plants to freezing temperatures. Plant Cell and Environment 23: 893-902"
},

  "Cold_Acclimation_Start": {
  "definition": "A Cold_Acclimation_Start is a Temperature_Acclimation comprising activation of molecular and cellular hardening processes upon initial exposure to cool but non-freezing autumn temperatures.",
  "alternative_term": "initial cold hardening | cold acclimation onset | first-stage hardening | early cold acclimation |+ Kälteabhärtungs-Beginn | initiale Kälteakklimatisierung | frühe Frostabhärtung | erste Abhärtungsphase",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Champagne, cold acclimation start commences in early October when mean daily temperatures fall below 12°C, with measurable increases in CBF transcription factor expression within 48 hours of initial cold exposure, initial accumulation of raffinose detected within one week, and bud cold hardiness improving from -4°C to -10°C within the first two weeks of cool temperature exposure at the onset of BBCH stage 91.",
  "editor_note": "Cold_Acclimation_Start represents the initial phase within Temperature_Acclimation, specifically addressing the first responses to cool autumn temperatures. ||Distinguished from Freeze_Tolerance_Development which addresses the more advanced stages of hardening at lower temperatures. ||Occurs at temperatures of 10-15°C before freezing exposure. ||Duration typically spans 2-3 weeks. ||Produces initial hardiness gains of 5-8°C. ||Enhanced by prior short-day exposure. ||Key molecular events include CBF activation and early cold-responsive gene expression. || This phase typically commences when ambient temperatures consistently fall below approximately 10-15°C, triggering the first transcriptional and metabolic responses that mark the beginning of the acclimation continuum. ||The earliest molecular events during cold acclimation start include rapid activation of CBF/DREB transcription factors within hours of cold exposure, increased expression of immediate early cold-responsive genes encoding signaling components and transcriptional regulators, and initial changes in membrane lipid desaturase activity that begin the shift toward more unsaturated membrane composition. ||Calcium signaling plays important roles in cold perception and early signal transduction, with cold-induced cytosolic calcium increases activating calcium-dependent protein kinases and other signaling components that contribute to downstream cold responses. ||The initial phase of acclimation produces relatively modest increases in cold hardiness, typically improving freezing tolerance by 5-8°C within the first 1-2 weeks, establishing the foundation for more substantial hardiness gains during subsequent acclimation stages at lower temperatures. ||Cellular changes during cold acclimation start include initial accumulation of compatible solutes as genes encoding biosynthetic enzymes are upregulated, early dehydrin protein synthesis, and subtle changes in protein complement as cold-induced genes begin expression while some growth-related genes are repressed. ||The effectiveness of cold acclimation start is enhanced by prior short-day exposure, with photoperiod pre-conditioning improving both the speed and magnitude of cold hardiness development at any given temperature, illustrating the integration of photoperiod and temperature signals in dormancy induction. ||The timing of cold acclimation start relative to the first freezing temperatures significantly affects vine survival, with early-acclimating genotypes and well-conditioned vines showing greater resilience to early cold events than late-acclimating or poorly conditioned vines.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Xin Z, Browse J (2000) Cold comfort farm: the acclimation of plants to freezing temperatures. Plant Cell and Environment 23: 893-902 || Thomashow MF (1999) Plant cold acclimation: freezing tolerance genes and regulatory mechanisms. Annual Review of Plant Physiology 50: 571-599"
},

  "Freeze_Tolerance_Development": {
  "definition": "A Freeze_Tolerance_Development is a Temperature_Acclimation realized through cellular composition and structural changes enabling tissue survival of extracellular ice formation.",
  "alternative_term": "progressive cold hardening | freeze hardiness acquisition | frost tolerance development | deep cold acclimation |+ Frosttoleranz-Entwicklung | progressive Kälteabhärtung | Frosthärte-Aufbau | tiefe Kälteakklimatisierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Franc vines in the Loire Valley, freeze tolerance development progresses through November and December with bud hardiness increasing from -10°C following initial acclimation to -15°C after exposure to temperatures of 5-8°C during early November, reaching -20°C following late November temperatures of 0-3°C, and achieving maximum hardiness of -23°C by late December following exposure to minimum temperatures of -5 to -8°C during early winter.",
  "editor_note": "Freeze_Tolerance_Development represents the progressive hardening phase within Temperature_Acclimation following Cold_Acclimation_Start. ||Distinguished from initial acclimation by the requirement for exposure to progressively lower temperatures and the substantially greater hardiness gains achieved. ||Duration spans 6-10 weeks through autumn into early winter. ||Produces major hardiness gains from approximately -10°C to -20 to -25°C depending on cultivar. ||Key mechanisms include cryoprotectant accumulation, membrane remodeling, and controlled extracellular ice formation tolerance. || This phase follows initial cold acclimation and proceeds through autumn and early winter as temperatures progressively decline, with each exposure to lower temperatures potentially inducing additional hardiness gains until maximum cold tolerance is achieved. ||The progressive nature of freeze tolerance development reflects the requirement for multiple rounds of gene expression and metabolic adjustment at successively lower temperatures, with each stage building upon the foundation established during previous acclimation. ||Cellular mechanisms underlying freeze tolerance include controlled ice formation in extracellular spaces rather than within cells, facilitated by ice nucleation active proteins and cell wall properties that favor extracellular ice crystal growth, combined with cellular dehydration tolerance as water moves osmotically to growing extracellular ice masses. ||The accumulation of cryoprotective molecules reaches maximum levels during this phase, with proline concentrations increasing 5-10 fold in cold-hardy tissues, raffinose family oligosaccharides accumulating to several percent of dry weight, and dehydrin proteins becoming major components of the soluble protein fraction. ||Membrane stabilization through lipid remodeling continues during freeze tolerance development, with the ratio of unsaturated to saturated fatty acids in membrane phospholipids increasing to maintain appropriate fluidity at sub-zero temperatures and prevent phase transitions that would damage cellular membranes. ||The extent of freeze tolerance development varies among tissue types within the vine, with primary bud tissues typically achieving hardiness of -20 to -25°C in well-adapted cultivars, secondary buds slightly hardier at -25 to -27°C, and cane phloem and xylem parenchyma achieving -25 to -30°C depending on cultivar genetics and acclimation conditions. ||The rate of freeze tolerance development depends on both genetic factors determining the capacity for hardiness and environmental factors including temperature regime, vine water status, and carbohydrate availability.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Mills LJ, Ferguson JC, Keller M (2006) Cold-hardiness evaluation of grapevine buds and cane tissues. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 57: 194-200 || Wisniewski M et al (2003) Observations of ice nucleation and propagation in plants using infrared thermography. Plant Physiology 133: 852-858"
},

  "Metabolic_Adjustment": {
  "definition": "A Metabolic_Adjustment is a Temperature_Acclimation comprising reprogramming of carbohydrate partitioning, respiratory pathway regulation, nitrogen metabolism, and secondary metabolism supporting cold hardiness development.",
  "alternative_term": "cold metabolic reprogramming | dormancy metabolism shift | acclimation metabolic adjustment | winter metabolic transition |+ metabolische Anpassung | Stoffwechsel-Umstellung | Kälte-Stoffwechselanpassung | Dormanz-Metabolismus-Änderung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines in Burgundy, metabolic adjustment during autumn cold acclimation includes starch accumulation in cane tissues reaching 8-12% of dry weight by December, proline concentrations in bud tissues increasing from 2 to 15 μmol per gram fresh weight, raffinose content rising from undetectable to 3-4% of soluble sugars, and respiratory rate declining by approximately 70% as tissues transition from active growth to dormant winter metabolism.",
  "editor_note": "Metabolic_Adjustment represents the metabolic dimension of Temperature_Acclimation, occurring in parallel with Cold_Acclimation_Start and Freeze_Tolerance_Development. ||Distinguished from purely structural or gene expression changes by its focus on metabolic pathway regulation and metabolite accumulation. ||Encompasses carbohydrate, nitrogen, respiratory, and secondary metabolism changes. ||Duration spans the entire acclimation period of 8-12 weeks. ||Key outcomes include starch reserve accumulation, cryoprotectant synthesis, and respiratory decline. || This metabolic remodeling reflects the fundamentally different requirements of dormant tissues compared to actively growing tissues, with emphasis shifting from supporting cell division and expansion toward accumulating protective compounds, maintaining minimal vital functions at low temperatures, and preserving reserves for spring growth resumption. ||Carbohydrate metabolism undergoes profound changes during metabolic adjustment, with starch accumulating in woody tissues as a winter reserve while simultaneously a portion of carbohydrate flux is redirected toward synthesis of raffinose family oligosaccharides and other cryoprotective sugars, and cold-induced invertases release hexoses from sucrose that contribute to osmotic adjustment and serve as substrates for respiration. ||Respiratory metabolism shifts toward increased capacity for alternative respiratory pathways that function at low temperatures and generate heat that may provide limited protection during freezing events, while the overall respiratory rate progressively declines as temperatures drop and tissues enter dormancy. ||Nitrogen metabolism during cold acclimation involves accumulation of free amino acids particularly proline which serves both as a compatible solute and a readily mobilizable nitrogen reserve, along with synthesis of cold-induced proteins including dehydrins, antifreeze proteins, and modified membrane proteins. ||Secondary metabolism contributes to cold acclimation through synthesis of phenolic compounds that may provide antioxidant protection during freeze-induced oxidative stress, and modifications to cell wall composition that affect ice propagation and cell mechanical properties during freezing. ||The regulation of metabolic adjustment involves complex transcriptional networks coordinated with the CBF pathway, hormonal signals particularly from abscisic acid, and metabolic feedback regulation, producing the integrated metabolic phenotype characteristic of cold-acclimated dormant tissues.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 5 Carbohydrate Supply and Reserve Storage || Xin Z, Browse J (2000) Cold comfort farm: the acclimation of plants to freezing temperatures. Plant Cell and Environment 23: 893-902 || Guy CL (1990) Cold acclimation and freezing stress tolerance: role of protein metabolism. Annual Review of Plant Physiology 41: 187-223"
},

  "Growth_Cessation": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Cessation is a Dormancy_Induction comprising the progressive decline of meristematic activity to complete inactivity producing the transition from the growth period to the dormant period.",
  "alternative_term": "growth termination | vegetative growth cessation | growth arrest | end of growth |+ Wachstumseinstellung | Wachstumsstopp | Vegetationsende | Wachstumsbeendigung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vineyards of the Côte de Beaune, Burgundy, growth cessation progresses through October with shoot elongation terminating by mid-October when day length falls below 11 hours, cambial activity ceasing by late October as mean temperatures drop below 10°C, and complete growth cessation achieved by early November at BBCH stage 91 when all meristematic activity has terminated and periderm browning has advanced to within 5 nodes of shoot tips.",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Cessation represents a major component process within Dormancy_Induction, specifically addressing the termination of all growth activities. ||Distinguished from Growth_Inhibition_Initiation which marks the beginning of growth decline, while Growth_Cessation represents complete termination. ||Subdivides into Shoot_Growth_Termination, Cambial_Activity_Decline, and Metabolic_Downregulation as component processes. ||Duration typically spans 4-6 weeks. ||Prerequisite for proper cold hardiness development and reserve accumulation. ||Corresponds to BBCH stages 91-93. || This process occurs during autumn, typically from September through November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, as the integrated effects of photoperiod response and temperature acclimation converge to terminate shoot elongation, arrest cambial activity, and reduce metabolic rates to winter maintenance levels. ||Growth cessation encompasses the coordinated shutdown of multiple growth centers including the shoot apical meristem which ceases producing new leaf and tendril primordia, the vascular cambium which terminates secondary xylem and phloem production, and the root system which reduces or ceases extension growth as soil temperatures decline. ||The process is regulated by the shifting hormonal balance characteristic of dormancy induction, with declining auxin and gibberellin levels removing growth promotion while increasing abscisic acid concentrations actively inhibit cell division and elongation in meristematic tissues. ||Morphological indicators of growth cessation include the termination of shoot elongation visible as static shoot tip position over successive observations, browning and hardening of shoot tips as they undergo lignification rather than continued extension, formation of terminal buds or abscission of immature shoot tips depending on cultivar and conditions, and the distinctive color change from green to brown as periderm development advances acropetally along shoots. ||The timing of growth cessation exhibits substantial variation among cultivars, with early-maturing varieties typically ceasing growth 2-4 weeks before late-maturing cultivars under equivalent environmental conditions, reflecting genetic differences in sensitivity to dormancy-inducing signals and the balance between vegetative vigor and dormancy tendency. ||Complete growth cessation is essential for proper cold hardiness development, as actively growing tissues are highly susceptible to freezing injury while dormant tissues with completed growth cessation achieve maximum cold tolerance. ||The relationship between harvest timing and growth cessation influences vine balance and subsequent season performance, with growth cessation before harvest allowing carbohydrate accumulation in reserves, while delayed cessation after harvest may compromise reserve status if photosynthetic capacity is reduced before growth terminates.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine Cambridge University Press"
},

  "Shoot_Growth_Termination": {
  "definition": "A Shoot_Growth_Termination is a Growth_Cessation comprising the complete cessation of shoot apical meristem activity and internode elongation.",
  "alternative_term": "shoot elongation cessation | apical growth termination | shoot extension termination | vegetative shoot growth end |+ Triebwachstums-Beendigung | Triebstreckungsstopp | apikale Wachstumsbeendigung | Triebverlängerungs-Ende",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in the Mâconnais, shoot growth termination occurs during the first half of October when shoot elongation rate declines to zero, with the shoot apical meristem becoming quiescent and shoot tips hardening from green to brown coloration, achieving complete termination approximately 3 weeks after mean daily temperatures consistently fall below 12°C, corresponding to the transition from BBCH 89 to BBCH 91.",
  "editor_note": "Shoot_Growth_Termination represents the shoot-specific component of Growth_Cessation, specifically addressing shoot apical meristem arrest and elongation cessation. ||Distinguished from Cambial_Activity_Decline which addresses secondary growth, and from the earlier Growth_Inhibition_Initiation which marks beginning rather than completion of growth decline. ||Timing varies with cultivar growth habit from determinate to indeterminate. ||Complete termination prerequisite for proper shoot maturation and cold hardiness. ||Duration of terminal phase typically spans 2-3 weeks. || This process typically occurs during October in Northern Hemisphere viticulture as the accumulated effects of short-day signaling and declining temperatures finally overcome any remaining growth potential in shoot meristems. ||The termination of shoot growth involves the arrest of cell division in the shoot apical meristem, cessation of cell elongation in the most recently formed internodes, and either the formation of a terminal resting bud or the abscission of the immature shoot tip depending on cultivar characteristics and environmental conditions. ||Prior to complete termination, shoot elongation rate progressively declines from peak values of 3-5 centimeters per day during rapid spring growth to less than 0.5 centimeters per day during late summer, eventually reaching zero as the terminal meristem becomes quiescent. ||The morphological changes accompanying shoot growth termination include hardening and browning of the shoot tip region as tissues that would have continued elongating instead undergo lignification and periderm development, cessation of new leaf primordium initiation at the shoot apex, and maturation of the most distal leaves that have already emerged but would not have fully expanded under continued growth conditions. ||Hormonal regulation of shoot growth termination involves the convergence of declining auxin transport from the shoot apex, reduced gibberellin biosynthesis and signaling, and increased abscisic acid accumulation that collectively create conditions incompatible with continued meristematic activity. ||The timing of shoot growth termination relative to other phenological events significantly affects vine performance, with termination before harvest allowing redirection of carbohydrates to fruit ripening and reserve accumulation, while very early termination may indicate stress conditions that prematurely limited growth, and very late termination may reflect excessive vigor or delayed dormancy induction that compromises cold hardiness. ||Cultivar differences in shoot growth termination timing range over several weeks, with determinate growth habit cultivars terminating earlier than indeterminate types under equivalent conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Pratt C (1974) Vegetative anatomy of cultivated grapes - a review. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 25: 131-150 || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine Cambridge University Press"
},

  "Cambial_Activity_Decline": {
  "definition": "A Cambial_Activity_Decline is a Growth_Cessation comprising the progressive reduction and cessation of vascular cambium function terminating secondary xylem and phloem production.",
  "alternative_term": "cambium cessation | secondary growth termination | cambial dormancy onset | vascular cambium decline |+ Kambiumaktivitäts-Rückgang | Sekundärwachstums-Ende | Kambium-Ruheeintritt | vaskuläre Kambium-Einstellung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in the Médoc, Bordeaux, cambial activity decline progresses through late October and November with cambial zone width decreasing from 10-12 cell layers in early October to 4-5 cell layers by late November, periclinal division frequency declining by approximately 80% over this period, and complete cambial dormancy achieved by early December when cross-sections show the characteristic narrow dormant cambium configuration.",
  "editor_note": "Cambial_Activity_Decline represents the secondary growth component of Growth_Cessation, specifically addressing vascular cambium function termination. ||Distinguished from Shoot_Growth_Termination which addresses primary shoot growth, and from Metabolic_Downregulation which addresses overall metabolic reduction. ||Involves reduction in cambial zone width and cessation of periclinal divisions. ||Duration typically spans 4-6 weeks. ||Complete cessation necessary for proper cold hardiness of stem tissues. ||Marks end of annual secondary growth increment. || This process occurs during late autumn, typically from October through November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, as the cambial meristem responds to the same photoperiod and temperature signals that drive overall dormancy induction by progressively reducing cell division rate until complete quiescence is achieved. ||The vascular cambium, a cylindrical meristem located between the secondary xylem and secondary phloem, produces xylem cells toward the interior and phloem cells toward the exterior through periclinal cell divisions, with the rate of cell production varying seasonally from maximum activity during spring and early summer to progressively reduced activity during late summer and autumn. ||During cambial activity decline, the rate of periclinal divisions in cambial initials progressively decreases, the width of the cambial zone narrows as fewer derivative cells are maintained in the division-competent state, and ultimately all cell division ceases leaving the cambium in a dormant condition with minimal cellular layers. ||The regulation of cambial activity decline involves declining auxin flux from shoots as shoot growth terminates, reduced cytokinin transport from roots as root activity decreases, and increased abscisic acid levels that directly inhibit cambial cell division, collectively creating the hormonal environment that favors cambial dormancy. ||Anatomically, the transition from active to dormant cambium is visible in cross-sections as a narrowing of the cambial zone from 8-12 cell layers during active growth to 3-5 cell layers in the dormant state, along with changes in cell morphology as cambial derivatives complete differentiation rather than continuing division. ||The timing of cambial activity decline relative to the onset of freezing temperatures affects both xylem vessel development and cold hardiness, as actively dividing cambial cells are highly susceptible to freezing injury while dormant cambium can survive temperatures that would kill active tissue. ||The cessation of cambial activity marks the end of the annual increment of secondary growth, with the final cells produced forming the outer boundary of that year's growth ring visible in cross-sections of woody stems.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 1 Grapevine Structure and Function || Esau K (1948) Phloem structure in the grapevine and its seasonal changes. Hilgardia 18: 217-296 || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine Cambridge University Press"
},

  "Metabolic_Downregulation": {
  "definition": "A Metabolic_Downregulation is a Growth_Cessation comprising coordinated reduction of photosynthesis, respiration, protein synthesis, and biosynthetic pathway activity accompanying the transition from active growth to winter dormancy.",
  "alternative_term": "metabolic reduction | metabolic decline | metabolic slowdown | dormancy metabolism | metabolische Herunterregulierung |+ Stoffwechsel-Reduktion | metabolischer Rückgang | Dormanz-Stoffwechsel",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Mosel Valley, metabolic downregulation progresses through autumn with whole-shoot respiration rates declining from 2.5 μmol CO2 per gram dry weight per hour in September to 0.6 μmol per gram per hour by late November, protein synthesis rates decreasing by approximately 75% over the same period, and overall metabolic activity reaching minimum winter levels by December when mean temperatures fall below 5°C.",
  "editor_note": "Metabolic_Downregulation represents the metabolic dimension of Growth_Cessation, specifically addressing the reduction in overall metabolic rates. ||Distinguished from Metabolic_Adjustment under Temperature_Acclimation which addresses qualitative metabolic changes for cold hardiness, while Metabolic_Downregulation addresses quantitative rate reductions. ||Encompasses photosynthesis, respiration, and biosynthetic pathway declines. ||Duration spans 6-10 weeks through autumn. ||Critical for energy conservation during the dormant period when photosynthetic input is absent. || This process occurs progressively through autumn as temperatures decline and day length shortens, with metabolic rates decreasing in parallel with the cessation of growth processes that normally consume the majority of metabolic output. ||The reduction in photosynthetic metabolism during metabolic downregulation reflects both the declining chlorophyll content in senescing leaves and the reduced requirement for photosynthate as growth cessation eliminates major carbon sinks, with net photosynthetic rate in remaining functional leaves declining by 50-70% from summer maximum values by late autumn. ||Respiratory metabolism decreases substantially during metabolic downregulation, with whole-plant respiration rates declining by 60-80% as temperature-dependent reaction rates slow and the metabolically active tissue mass decreases through leaf senescence, resulting in the characteristic low maintenance respiration of dormant vines. ||Protein synthesis rates decline dramatically during the transition to dormancy, with overall protein turnover decreasing as growth-related proteins are degraded and not replaced, while cold-induced proteins including dehydrins become relatively more prominent in the reduced protein complement of dormant tissues. ||Biosynthetic pathway activities generally decline during metabolic downregulation, though specific pathways involved in cold acclimation and cryoprotectant synthesis remain active or increase during the early phases before decreasing as dormancy deepens and temperatures continue falling. ||The enzymatic basis of metabolic downregulation involves both temperature-dependent reductions in reaction rates as temperatures approach and fall below optimal ranges, and regulatory changes in enzyme activity and gene expression that actively suppress metabolic capacity beyond what temperature alone would cause. ||The ecological significance of metabolic downregulation relates to energy conservation during the period when photosynthetic input is minimal and the vine must survive on stored reserves, with reduced metabolic rates minimizing reserve consumption and extending the period over which reserves can support vital functions. ||The extent of metabolic downregulation varies among tissue types, with woody stem tissues achieving very low metabolic rates characteristic of deep dormancy while root tissues in unfrozen soil may maintain somewhat higher activity levels throughout winter.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 5 Carbohydrate Supply and Reserve Storage || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of starch and N reserves in grapevine. Journal of Experimental Botany 55: 2165-2175 || Wample RL, Bary A (1992) Harvest date as a factor in carbohydrate storage and cold hardiness of Cabernet Sauvignon grapevines. Journal of the American Society for Horticultural Science 117: 32-36"
},

  "Dormancy_Establishment": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Establishment is a Dormancy_Induction comprising the achievement of the fully dormant state with complete growth cessation, maximum physiological preparation for winter survival, and the internal conditions requiring specific environmental cues for subsequent dormancy release.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy completion | full dormancy achievement | dormant state establishment | dormancy consolidation |+ Dormanz-Etablierung | Ruhestandsetablierung | vollständige Dormanz-Erreichung | Dormanz-Konsolidierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner vines in the Wachau, Austria, dormancy establishment is achieved by mid-November when bud scales have fully formed enclosing dormant meristems, shoot lignification has completed to within 3-4 nodes of tips, leaf abscission is complete, ABA concentrations in buds have reached maximum levels of 150-200 ng per gram fresh weight, and buds show no growth response to favorable temperatures indicating full endodormancy at BBCH stage 93.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Establishment represents the final phase of Dormancy_Induction, marking achievement of the fully dormant state. ||Distinguished from earlier induction phases by representing a stable state rather than transitional process, and from Endodormancy which represents the subsequent dormancy maintenance phase. ||Subdivides into Bud_Scale_Formation, ABA_Accumulation, and Deep_Dormancy_Entry as component processes. ||Corresponds to BBCH stage 93. ||Marks the beginning of the period requiring chilling for dormancy release. ||Critical for winter survival and proper spring growth resumption. || This phase occurs during late autumn, typically from late October through November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, as the accumulated effects of photoperiod response, temperature acclimation, and growth cessation converge to produce the stable dormant condition that will persist through winter. ||The establishment of dormancy involves the consolidation of multiple physiological changes including the complete arrest of all meristematic activity, the achievement of maximum cold hardiness appropriate to current acclimation conditions, the accumulation of abscisic acid to levels that actively maintain dormancy, and the developmental changes in bud structure that provide physical protection for dormant meristems. ||Morphological indicators of dormancy establishment include the completion of bud scale development providing physical protection for enclosed meristems, the full lignification of current-season shoots visible as complete browning of periderm to within a few nodes of shoot tips, the abscission or final senescence of remaining leaves, and the characteristic bare-cane winter appearance of fully dormant vines. ||At the molecular level, dormancy establishment involves the expression of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes including the DAM gene family that actively maintain the dormant state, chromatin modifications that establish dormancy-specific gene expression patterns, and the accumulation of dormancy markers including specific proteins and metabolites characteristic of the dormant condition. ||The transition from dormancy induction to established dormancy represents a qualitative shift from a process of becoming dormant to a state of being dormant, with the established dormancy being self-maintaining until environmental cues including chilling accumulation eventually lead to dormancy release. ||The timing and completeness of dormancy establishment significantly affects winter survival, with well-established dormancy providing maximum protection against mid-winter cold injury, while incomplete dormancy establishment leaves vines vulnerable to cold damage and may result in erratic budbreak in spring. ||Cultivar differences in dormancy establishment timing and depth contribute to regional adaptation, with cultivars showing earlier and deeper dormancy establishment being better suited to regions with severe winters.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377"
},

  "Bud_Scale_Formation": {
  "definition": "A Bud_Scale_Formation is a Dormancy_Establishment comprising the differentiation of outermost leaf primordia of dormant buds into specialized protective structures shielding enclosed meristematic tissues during winter dormancy.",
  "alternative_term": "bud scale development | scale leaf formation | protective scale development | dormant bud scale formation |+ Knospenschuppen-Bildung | Schuppenblatt-Entwicklung | Knospenschutz-Entwicklung | Winterknospen-Beschuppung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux, bud scale formation progresses during October and early November with outer scale primordia ceasing expansion and differentiating into protective scales by mid-October, dense trichome development on outer scale surfaces completing by late October, and full bud scale enclosure of dormant meristems achieved by early November when scales show characteristic brown coloration and tight overlapping arrangement typical of BBCH stage 93.",
  "editor_note": "Bud_Scale_Formation represents a morphological component of Dormancy_Establishment, specifically addressing the development of protective bud structures. ||Distinguished from normal leaf development by the alternative differentiation pathway producing protective rather than photosynthetic structures. ||Occurs in parallel with ABA_Accumulation and Deep_Dormancy_Entry during dormancy establishment. ||Typically involves 2-4 outer scales per bud. ||Provides physical protection against desiccation, freezing, and pathogens. ||Duration of active scale differentiation spans 3-4 weeks during autumn. || This process occurs during autumn as part of dormancy establishment, with bud scales developing from leaf primordia that would have formed foliage leaves under continued growth conditions but instead differentiate into the tough, often pubescent protective structures characteristic of dormant grapevine buds. ||The bud scales of Vitis vinifera are morphologically modified leaves that retain recognizable leaf-like features including a flattened blade-like structure and association with the node position, but exhibit distinctive specializations including thick cuticle development, dense trichome coverage particularly on outer scale surfaces, accumulation of phenolic compounds that provide antimicrobial protection, and the development of tight overlapping arrangement that seals the bud interior from environmental exposure. ||The developmental transition from leaf primordium to bud scale involves altered patterns of gene expression that suppress normal leaf blade expansion and promote the alternative developmental program leading to scale morphology, with this transition triggered by the same dormancy-inducing signals of short photoperiod and declining temperatures that drive overall dormancy establishment. ||The physical protection provided by bud scales includes reduction of water loss from enclosed tissues that would otherwise desiccate during winter, limitation of ice propagation into bud interior during freezing events, and exclusion of fungal pathogens and small invertebrates that might otherwise damage dormant meristems. ||The number of bud scales per dormant bud varies somewhat among cultivars and bud positions, typically ranging from 2-4 outer scales that provide the primary protective function, with the innermost protective structures transitioning toward leaf-like morphology representing an intermediate developmental state. ||Bud scale formation must be complete before severe winter conditions occur for adequate bud protection, with incomplete scale development leaving buds vulnerable to winter injury from desiccation, freezing, or pathogen invasion. ||The timing of bud scale formation correlates with other dormancy establishment processes, progressing in parallel with growth cessation and ABA accumulation during the final phase of dormancy induction.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Pratt C (1974) Vegetative anatomy of cultivated grapes - a review. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 25: 131-150 || Morrison JC (1991) Bud development in Vitis vinifera L. Botanical Gazette 152: 304-315 || Mullins MG, Bouquet A, Williams LE (1992) Biology of the Grapevine Cambridge University Press"
},

  "ABA_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "An ABA_Accumulation is a Dormancy_Establishment exhibiting elevated abscisic acid concentration in bud tissues through increased biosynthesis and decreased catabolism, supporting dormancy induction, maintenance, and cold hardiness.",
  "alternative_term": "abscisic acid accumulation | ABA buildup | dormancy hormone accumulation | abscisic acid increase |+ ABA-Akkumulation | Abscisinsäure-Anreicherung | Dormanzhormon-Akkumulation | ABA-Aufbau",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc vines in Marlborough, New Zealand, ABA accumulation in axillary buds progresses from baseline concentrations of 40-50 ng per gram fresh weight in February to 80-100 ng per gram by late March as photoperiod decreases below critical threshold, reaching maximum concentrations of 180-220 ng per gram fresh weight by late May coincident with full dormancy establishment, with NCED gene expression increasing 4-fold during this period.",
  "editor_note": "ABA_Accumulation represents the hormonal dimension of Dormancy_Establishment, specifically addressing the increase in abscisic acid that regulates dormancy. ||Distinguished from Metabolic_Adjustment which addresses broader metabolic changes, while ABA_Accumulation specifically addresses this key regulatory hormone. ||Involves increased NCED expression and decreased ABA catabolism. ||Typical maximum concentrations 150-250 ng per gram fresh weight in dormant buds. ||Duration spans 8-10 weeks during autumn. ||Subsequent ABA decline during chilling is associated with dormancy release. || This process occurs during autumn, typically from September through November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, with ABA levels in bud tissues increasing several-fold from growing season baseline values to reach maximum concentrations coincident with full dormancy establishment. ||The biosynthesis of ABA during dormancy induction involves increased expression and activity of 9-cis-epoxycarotenoid dioxygenase enzymes that catalyze the rate-limiting step in ABA production from carotenoid precursors, with NCED gene expression increasing in response to both short-day signals and low temperature exposure. ||The physiological functions of accumulated ABA during dormancy establishment include direct inhibition of cell division and elongation in meristematic tissues through effects on cell cycle regulators and expansion-related gene expression, promotion of storage compound accumulation by redirecting metabolism from growth toward reserve synthesis, induction of cold hardiness through activation of cold-responsive gene expression, and maintenance of the dormant state by preventing premature growth resumption in response to temporary favorable conditions. ||The regulation of ABA accumulation involves integration of multiple environmental signals, with short photoperiod and low temperatures both promoting ABA biosynthesis while also reducing ABA catabolism through decreased activity of ABA 8'-hydroxylase enzymes, resulting in net ABA accumulation that reflects both production and turnover rates. ||The concentration of ABA in dormant buds typically reaches values 3-5 times higher than in actively growing buds, with maximum concentrations of 150-250 nanograms per gram fresh weight in fully dormant buds of most Vitis vinifera cultivars. ||The subsequent decline in ABA concentration during chilling accumulation and dormancy release represents an important component of the transition from endodormancy to ecodormancy, with decreasing ABA levels permitting the eventual growth response to favorable spring temperatures. ||Cultivar differences in ABA accumulation patterns contribute to variation in dormancy depth and cold hardiness among genotypes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Zheng C et al (2015) Abscisic acid catabolism enhances dormancy release of grapevine buds. Plant Cell and Environment 38: 2490-2501 || Or E et al (2000) The transduction of the signal for grape bud dormancy breaking induced by hydrogen cyanamide may involve the SNF-like protein kinase. Plant Molecular Biology 43: 483-494"
},

  "Deep_Dormancy_Entry": {
  "definition": "A Deep_Dormancy_Entry is a Dormancy_Establishment comprising the transition of buds into the fully endodormant state with complete unresponsiveness to growth-promoting conditions and requirement for specific chilling exposure before growth resumption.",
  "alternative_term": "endodormancy entry | true dormancy establishment | deep rest entry | full dormancy achievement |+ Tiefschlaf-Eintritt | Endodormanz-Eintritt | volle Dormanz-Erreichung | tiefe Ruhe-Etablierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Zweigelt vines in Burgenland, Austria, deep dormancy entry is confirmed in mid-November when excised buds placed at 22°C with 16-hour photoperiod show no growth response after 4 weeks of observation, with parallel measurements showing maximum ABA concentrations of 200 ng per gram fresh weight, high VvDAM gene expression, and the beginning of chilling unit accumulation at field temperatures below 7.2°C marking the onset of the endodormancy period at BBCH stage 93.",
  "editor_note": "Deep_Dormancy_Entry represents the culminating phase of Dormancy_Establishment marking achievement of full endodormancy. ||Distinguished from earlier dormancy phases by the complete lack of growth response to favorable conditions, confirming transition from dormancy induction to established endodormancy. ||Characterized by high ABA, high DAM gene expression, and growth unresponsiveness. ||Marks beginning of chilling requirement period. ||Dormancy depth varies among cultivars from 400-1500 chilling hours required for release. ||Corresponds to full achievement of BBCH stage 93. || This transition typically occurs during November in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, marking the point at which buds have accumulated sufficient dormancy factors that even extended exposure to warm temperatures and optimal growing conditions fails to induce budbreak. ||The physiological basis of deep dormancy involves multiple reinforcing mechanisms including high concentrations of growth inhibitors particularly abscisic acid, low levels of growth promoters including cytokinins and gibberellins, chromatin modifications that silence growth-related genes, and the presence of dormancy-maintaining proteins that must be degraded before growth can resume. ||The molecular characteristics of deep dormancy include high expression of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes whose products actively maintain the dormant state, altered plasmodesmatal function that limits symplastic communication and signal transmission, and metabolic configurations that do not support the biosynthetic activities required for growth resumption. ||Testing for deep dormancy entry involves exposing buds to growth-promoting conditions and observing the failure of budbreak that confirms full endodormancy, with deeply dormant buds showing no growth response even after extended periods of favorable temperatures that would rapidly induce growth in non-dormant tissues. ||The depth of dormancy achieved during deep dormancy entry varies among cultivars, with some genotypes achieving very deep dormancy requiring 1000-1500 chilling hours for release while others achieve shallower dormancy requiring only 400-700 chilling hours, reflecting genetic variation in dormancy regulation. ||The transition into deep dormancy serves the ecological function of preventing premature growth resumption during temporary warm periods in autumn and early winter, which would expose sensitive growing tissues to subsequent freezing temperatures with potentially lethal consequences. ||Climate warming poses challenges to deep dormancy entry in some regions, as elevated autumn temperatures may delay or reduce dormancy depth, potentially leading to inadequate dormancy and erratic spring growth patterns.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223"
},

  "Endodormancy": {
  "definition": "An Endodormancy is a Dormancy comprising growth inhibition controlled by factors internal to the bud rendering buds incapable of growth under environmental conditions otherwise favorable for development.",
  "alternative_term": "true dormancy | rest | winter rest | internal dormancy |+ Endodormanz | echte Dormanz | Winterruhe | innere Dormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Côte d'Or, Burgundy, endodormancy extends from mid-November through late January, with buds showing no growth response when excised and placed under forcing conditions of 22°C and 16-hour photoperiod during December, requiring approximately 1000-1200 chilling hours below 7.2°C accumulated during this period before growth competence is restored and transition to ecodormancy occurs in late January to early February.",
  "editor_note": "Endodormancy represents the second major phase within the Dormancy hierarchy following Dormancy_Induction, characterized by internally-controlled growth inhibition. ||Distinguished from Ecodormancy where growth-competent buds are environmentally constrained, and from Dormancy_Induction which represents the transition into dormancy. ||Subdivides into Deep_Endodormancy, Chilling_Accumulation, Dormancy_Maintenance, and Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction as component phases. ||Duration typically spans 2-4 months depending on cultivar and chilling accumulation rate. ||Release requires cultivar-specific chilling accumulation typically ranging from 400-1500 hours below 7.2°C. || This dormancy phase, also termed true dormancy or rest in older literature, typically extends from late autumn through mid-winter in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, persisting until sufficient chilling exposure has satisfied the genetically determined chilling requirement and restored growth competence. ||The defining characteristic of endodormancy is the internal nature of growth inhibition, distinguishing it from ecodormancy where external environmental constraints prevent growth of otherwise competent buds, and from paradormancy where inhibitory signals from other plant parts suppress growth. ||The physiological basis of endodormancy involves multiple reinforcing mechanisms including elevated abscisic acid concentrations that directly inhibit cell cycle progression and growth-related gene expression, high expression of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes whose protein products actively maintain the dormant state, chromatin modifications that establish repressive configurations at growth-promoting gene loci, and altered cellular communication through modified plasmodesmatal function. ||During endodormancy, buds contain fully formed primordial shoots with leaf, tendril, and inflorescence primordia that developed during the previous growing season, but these structures remain arrested in development regardless of temperature, photoperiod, or nutrient availability until endodormancy is released through chilling accumulation. ||The ecological function of endodormancy is to prevent premature growth during temporary warm periods in autumn and winter that would expose sensitive growing tissues to subsequent lethal freezing, with the chilling requirement ensuring that growth does not resume until winter has sufficiently progressed that the probability of subsequent severe cold is reduced. ||The depth and duration of endodormancy vary substantially among cultivars, reflecting adaptation to different climatic regions, with cultivars from continental climates typically exhibiting deeper endodormancy requiring more chilling for release than cultivars from Mediterranean regions. ||Climate change poses significant challenges to endodormancy in many viticultural regions, as warming winters may provide insufficient chilling for complete dormancy release, potentially leading to delayed, erratic, or incomplete budbreak with consequences for vine productivity and fruit quality.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0097437 ## maintenance of dormancy | 0.70" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223"
},

  "Deep_Endodormancy": {
  "definition": "A Deep_Endodormancy is an Endodormancy exhibiting maximum dormancy intensity during early to mid-winter with internal growth-inhibition factors at peak strength and buds unresponsive to any growth-promoting stimuli.",
  "alternative_term": "maximum dormancy | deepest dormancy | peak dormancy | full endodormancy |+ tiefe Endodormanz | maximale Dormanz | Dormanz-Maximum | volle Endodormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in the Napa Valley, California, deep endodormancy occurs during December and early January when forcing tests show budbreak requiring more than 50 days at 22°C with many buds failing to break entirely, ABA concentrations in buds remain at maximum levels of 180-220 ng per gram fresh weight, and cold hardiness reaches seasonal maximum values of -18 to -20°C for primary buds, before chilling accumulation progressively begins reducing dormancy depth through January.",
  "editor_note": "Deep_Endodormancy represents the initial phase of maximum dormancy intensity within Endodormancy. ||Distinguished from later phases where chilling accumulation has begun reducing dormancy depth. ||Subdivides into Maximum_Dormancy_Depth, Growth_Inhibition_Maximum, and ABA_Maximum_Level as component characteristics. ||Duration typically spans 4-8 weeks during early winter. ||Characterized by longest forcing times and lowest budbreak percentages in forcing tests. ||Cold hardiness at seasonal maximum during this phase. || This phase typically occurs during December and early January in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, following the completion of dormancy establishment and before significant chilling accumulation has begun to reduce dormancy depth. ||During deep endodormancy, buds represent the most dormant condition achieved in the annual cycle, with all growth-inhibiting mechanisms operating at maximum intensity including peak abscisic acid concentrations, highest expression levels of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes, and most repressive chromatin configurations at growth-related loci. ||The practical definition of deep endodormancy relies on forcing tests showing that buds require the longest time to budbreak or completely fail to break when exposed to growth-promoting conditions, in contrast to earlier or later dormancy phases when forcing response is faster or more complete. ||The duration of deep endodormancy varies among cultivars in relation to their overall dormancy depth, with deeply dormant cultivars adapted to continental climates maintaining deep endodormancy for longer periods than shallowly dormant cultivars from Mediterranean regions. ||Physiologically, deep endodormancy is maintained by the convergence of multiple inhibitory factors that must be progressively dismantled through chilling exposure before growth competence can be restored, with the requirement for multiple changes explaining why dormancy release is gradual rather than abrupt. ||The metabolic state during deep endodormancy is characterized by minimal activity, with respiration rates at annual minimum values, protein synthesis essentially ceased except for maintenance functions, and cellular processes largely restricted to survival functions rather than growth preparation. ||Cold hardiness typically reaches maximum levels during deep endodormancy, reflecting the full expression of cold acclimation processes and the absence of any growth activity that would reduce freezing tolerance. ||The transition from deep endodormancy to progressive dormancy release begins as chilling accumulation starts to reduce dormancy depth, though this transition may not be externally visible and is detected through changes in forcing test response times.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46"
},

  "Maximum_Dormancy_Depth": {
  "definition": "A Maximum_Dormancy_Depth is a Deep_Endodormancy defined by the annual peak intensity of internal growth inhibition occurring in early winter prior to chilling-induced dormancy release.",
  "alternative_term": "peak dormancy intensity | deepest dormancy point | dormancy maximum | maximum rest depth |+ maximale Dormanztiefe | Dormanztiefe-Maximum | tiefster Ruhepunkt | Dormanz-Intensitätsmaximum",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Rheingau, Germany, maximum dormancy depth is reached in mid-December approximately 4 weeks after dormancy establishment, demonstrated by forcing tests requiring more than 60 days for 50% budbreak at 22°C, with this cultivar exhibiting characteristically deep dormancy that subsequently requires 1200-1400 chilling hours below 7.2°C for complete release, reflecting genetic adaptation to the continental climate of its central European origin.",
  "editor_note": "Maximum_Dormancy_Depth represents a quantitative characteristic within Deep_Endodormancy describing the peak intensity of dormancy. ||Distinguished from dormancy depth at other times which is either increasing during establishment or decreasing during chilling accumulation. ||Measured through forcing test response times and budbreak percentages. ||Cultivar variation substantial from approximately 400 to 1500+ chilling hours required for release. ||Timing typically early winter, 2-6 weeks after dormancy establishment completion. || This condition is quantified through forcing tests that measure the time required for budbreak or the percentage of buds breaking under standardized growth-promoting conditions, with maximum dormancy depth corresponding to the longest budbreak times and lowest budbreak percentages observed during the dormancy period. ||The timing of maximum dormancy depth varies among cultivars and is influenced by the rate of dormancy establishment during autumn, with early-dormant cultivars typically reaching maximum depth earlier than late-dormant cultivars, though all cultivars generally achieve maximum depth by early winter before substantial chilling accumulation has occurred. ||The physiological basis of maximum dormancy depth involves the convergent action of all dormancy-maintaining mechanisms at their peak effectiveness, including highest ABA concentrations, maximum expression of DAM genes, most extensive chromatin repression of growth genes, and lowest levels of growth-promoting hormones and their signaling components. ||From a practical perspective, maximum dormancy depth determines several important viticultural parameters including the minimum chilling requirement for adequate dormancy release, the susceptibility to inadequate chilling in warm winter climates, and the response to dormancy-breaking chemical treatments that are sometimes applied in regions with insufficient natural chilling. ||The concept of dormancy depth implies a quantitative continuum from deep to shallow dormancy, with the depth at any time reflecting the balance between dormancy-maintaining and dormancy-releasing factors, and maximum depth representing the point where maintaining factors are strongest relative to releasing factors. ||Cultivar differences in maximum dormancy depth are substantial, ranging from very deep dormancy in cultivars like Riesling and Cabernet Sauvignon that may require 1200-1500 chilling hours for release, to relatively shallow dormancy in cultivars like Sultana and Perlette that may require only 400-600 chilling hours. ||The maximum dormancy depth achieved in a given year can be influenced by environmental conditions during dormancy induction, with stress conditions or suboptimal acclimation potentially affecting the completeness of dormancy establishment and thus the depth achieved.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056"
},

  "Growth_Inhibition_Maximum": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Inhibition_Maximum is a Deep_Endodormancy realized through the convergent peak action of hormonal, transcriptional, and structural mechanisms preventing meristematic activity in buds.",
  "alternative_term": "peak growth suppression | maximum growth arrest | complete growth inhibition | full meristem arrest |+ Wachstumshemmungs-Maximum | maximale Wachstumsunterdrückung | vollständige Wachstumsinhibition | voller Meristem-Arrest",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer vines in Alsace, growth inhibition maximum is evident in mid-December when molecular analysis shows VvDAM1 and VvDAM2 expression at 8-10 fold higher levels than during active growth, CDK inhibitor ICK1 homolog expression elevated 5-fold, and complete absence of CYCLIN D expression in bud meristems, with these molecular markers of maximum inhibition coinciding with forcing test results showing zero budbreak after 30 days under optimal growth conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Inhibition_Maximum represents the functional dimension of Deep_Endodormancy describing peak inhibitory mechanism activity. ||Distinguished from Growth_Inhibition_Initiation which marks beginning of inhibition during dormancy induction. ||Encompasses transcriptional, hormonal, cell cycle, and structural inhibitory mechanisms. ||Characterized molecularly by peak DAM expression, CDK inhibitor accumulation, and growth gene silencing. ||Duration corresponds to deep endodormancy phase of 4-8 weeks. ||Release requires coordinated reversal through chilling-dependent processes. || This condition occurs during early winter coincident with maximum dormancy depth, representing the state in which all growth-inhibiting systems operate at their highest intensity before chilling accumulation begins the progressive dismantling of inhibitory mechanisms. ||At the molecular level, growth inhibition maximum involves peak expression of growth-repressing transcription factors including dormancy-associated MADS-box proteins that directly suppress growth-related gene transcription, maximum activity of growth-inhibiting hormonal pathways particularly ABA signaling, and the most extensive chromatin modifications that establish repressive configurations at loci encoding cell cycle regulators, hormone biosynthesis enzymes, and other growth-essential genes. ||The cell cycle arrest during growth inhibition maximum is maintained by multiple mechanisms including CDK inhibitor protein accumulation, absence of cyclins required for cell cycle progression, and chromatin-based silencing of genes encoding cell cycle machinery components. ||The hormonal dimension of growth inhibition maximum involves not only peak ABA concentrations and signaling but also minimum levels of growth-promoting hormones including cytokinins, gibberellins, and auxin, creating the most growth-suppressive hormonal environment of the annual cycle. ||Plasmodesmatal modifications contribute to growth inhibition maximum by restricting symplastic communication and limiting the movement of signaling molecules that might otherwise coordinate growth responses, effectively isolating dormant meristems from potential growth-promoting signals. ||The structural barriers to growth during this phase include the presence of callose deposits at plasmodesmata and potentially within phloem elements that restrict both symplastic and long-distance transport. ||The release from growth inhibition maximum requires the coordinated reversal of multiple inhibitory mechanisms through chilling-dependent processes, explaining why dormancy release is gradual and requires extended cold exposure rather than occurring as an abrupt transition.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Cooke JE, Eriksson ME, Junttila O (2012) The dynamic nature of bud dormancy in trees: environmental control and molecular mechanisms. Plant Cell and Environment 35: 1707-1728 || Vergara R et al (2017) VvDAM1 gene expression regulation during sweet cherry bud dormancy. Tree Genetics and Genomes 13: 106"
},

  "ABA_Maximum_Level": {
  "definition": "An ABA_Maximum_Level is a Deep_Endodormancy defined by peak abscisic acid concentration in bud tissues representing the hormonal culmination of autumn ABA accumulation.",
  "alternative_term": "peak ABA concentration | maximum abscisic acid | ABA peak | highest ABA level |+ ABA-Maximalgehalt | maximaler Abscisinsäure-Spiegel | ABA-Höchstwert | Abscisinsäure-Maximum",
  "example_of_usage": "In Tempranillo vines in Rioja, Spain, ABA maximum level is reached in early December at approximately 190-210 ng per gram fresh weight in primary buds, representing a 4-fold increase from September baseline values of 45-55 ng per gram, with this peak concentration maintained for approximately 3-4 weeks before chilling-induced catabolism progressively reduces ABA levels through January, coinciding with gradual dormancy depth reduction as measured by decreasing forcing time requirements.",
  "editor_note": "ABA_Maximum_Level represents the hormonal peak within Deep_Endodormancy specifically addressing abscisic acid concentration maximum. ||Distinguished from ABA_Accumulation which addresses the process of increasing ABA during dormancy establishment. ||Typical peak values 150-250 ng per gram fresh weight depending on cultivar. ||Duration of peak plateau typically 2-4 weeks before chilling-induced decline begins. ||Subsequent ABA reduction is a key component of dormancy release mechanism. || This peak concentration typically occurs during December in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, coincident with other indicators of maximum dormancy intensity, before chilling-dependent ABA catabolism begins reducing hormone levels as part of the dormancy release process. ||The quantitative values of ABA maximum level vary among cultivars but typically fall in the range of 150-250 nanograms per gram fresh weight in dormant buds, representing concentrations 3-5 fold higher than those present in actively growing buds during summer. ||The physiological significance of ABA maximum level relates to the multiple growth-inhibiting functions of this hormone, including direct inhibition of cell cycle progression through effects on CDK activity and cyclin expression, suppression of growth-related gene expression through ABA-responsive transcription factors, and promotion of storage and protective processes that characterize the dormant state. ||The achievement of ABA maximum level requires both active ABA biosynthesis through the NCED pathway that continues during early dormancy, and reduced ABA catabolism through decreased activity of ABA 8'-hydroxylase enzymes, with the balance between production and degradation determining the peak concentration achieved. ||The subsequent decline from ABA maximum level during chilling accumulation is an essential component of dormancy release, with chilling exposure activating ABA catabolic pathways and reducing biosynthetic gene expression, progressively lowering hormone concentrations toward levels compatible with growth resumption. ||The relationship between ABA maximum level and chilling requirement is complex, with some evidence suggesting that cultivars achieving higher ABA maximum levels may require more chilling for complete hormone reduction and dormancy release, though genetic variation in ABA sensitivity also affects this relationship. ||Environmental factors during dormancy induction can influence ABA maximum level, with stress conditions potentially elevating peak concentrations while suboptimal acclimation conditions might result in lower maximum levels.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Zheng C et al (2015) Abscisic acid catabolism enhances dormancy release of grapevine buds. Plant Cell and Environment 38: 2490-2501 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Or E et al (2000) The transduction of the signal for grape bud dormancy breaking induced by hydrogen cyanamide may involve the SNF-like protein kinase. Plant Molecular Biology 43: 483-494"
},

  "Chilling_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Chilling_Accumulation is an Endodormancy comprising the progressive satisfaction of the cultivar-specific chilling requirement through low-temperature exposure producing gradual reduction of dormancy depth and restoration of growth competence.",
  "alternative_term": "chilling hour accumulation | cold unit accumulation | chill accumulation | winter chilling |+ Kältestunden-Akkumulation | Chilling-Akkumulation | Kälteeinheiten-Ansammlung | Kältesumme",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Bordeaux, chilling accumulation progresses through winter with approximately 200 chilling hours accumulated by late December, 600 hours by mid-January, and the cultivar-specific requirement of approximately 900-1000 chilling hours satisfied by early February, as demonstrated by forcing tests showing budbreak time decreasing from more than 45 days in December to less than 20 days in February under identical 22°C forcing conditions, indicating progressive dormancy release through chilling accumulation.",
  "editor_note": "Chilling_Accumulation represents a major phase within Endodormancy addressing the progressive dormancy release through cold exposure. ||Distinguished from Deep_Endodormancy which precedes significant chilling accumulation, and from Dormancy_Release which marks completion of the process. ||Subdivides into Progressive_Chilling_Units, Dormancy_Depth_Reduction, and Cumulative_Cold_Exposure as component aspects. ||Duration spans most of winter from December through February typically. ||Effective temperature range approximately 0-7°C. ||Cultivar chilling requirements range from 400-1500+ hours. || This process occurs throughout the winter period, typically from December through February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, as cold temperatures induce the physiological changes that dismantle dormancy-maintaining mechanisms and prepare buds for eventual growth resumption. ||The quantification of chilling accumulation relies on models that integrate temperature exposure over time, with the simplest models counting hours below a threshold temperature, typically 7.2°C or 45°F based on research in deciduous fruit trees, while more sophisticated models apply different weights to different temperature ranges recognizing that moderately cold temperatures are most effective for dormancy release. ||The physiological changes occurring during chilling accumulation include progressive reduction in ABA concentration through increased catabolic enzyme activity, declining expression of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes, gradual removal of repressive chromatin marks from growth-related gene loci, and restoration of symplastic communication through callose degradation at plasmodesmata. ||The rate of chilling accumulation depends on temperature regime, with temperatures in the range of 0-7°C generally most effective for dormancy release, temperatures below -2°C being less effective or ineffective, and temperatures above 15°C potentially negating previously accumulated chilling in some models. ||The progress of chilling accumulation is not externally visible but can be tracked through periodic forcing tests that reveal progressively shorter times to budbreak as dormancy depth decreases with increasing chilling exposure. ||The completion of chilling accumulation, when the chilling requirement has been fully satisfied, marks the transition from endodormancy to ecodormancy, at which point buds have regained growth competence but remain quiescent due to unfavorable environmental temperatures rather than internal inhibition. ||Cultivar differences in chilling requirement significantly affect the duration of chilling accumulation, ranging from approximately 400 chilling hours for low-chill cultivars to more than 1500 hours for high-chill cultivars.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Richardson EA, Seeley SD, Walker DR (1974) A model for estimating the completion of rest for Redhaven and Elberta peach trees. HortScience 9: 331-332"
},

  "Progressive_Chilling_Units": {
  "definition": "A Progressive_Chilling_Units is a Chilling_Accumulation defined by incremental cold exposure quantified through temperature-based models tracking progress toward satisfaction of the cultivar-specific chilling requirement.",
  "alternative_term": "incremental chilling | chilling unit progression | accumulating chill hours | progressive cold units |+ progressive Kälteeinheiten | inkrementelle Chilling-Akkumulation | fortschreitende Kältestunden | zunehmende Kälteeinheiten",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chenin Blanc vines in the Loire Valley, progressive chilling units accumulate through winter following the Utah model, with approximately 150 units by December 15, 400 units by January 1, 750 units by January 20, and the cultivar requirement of approximately 1000 units satisfied by early February, with this progression tracked through weather station data showing effective chilling temperatures predominating during January when mean temperatures range from 2-6°C.",
  "editor_note": "Progressive_Chilling_Units represents the quantitative tracking aspect of Chilling_Accumulation. ||Distinguished from Cumulative_Cold_Exposure which addresses the physiological cold exposure, while Progressive_Chilling_Units specifically addresses model-based quantification. ||Various models include simple threshold counting, Utah model with temperature weighting, and dynamic model with two-step processing. ||Enables prediction of dormancy release timing. ||Cultivar requirements range from approximately 400-1500 units depending on model used and cultivar genetics. || This quantification approach provides a standardized method for comparing chilling status across different seasons, locations, and cultivars, enabling prediction of dormancy release timing and assessment of chilling adequacy in different viticultural environments. ||The simplest chilling unit models count hours at temperatures below a threshold, typically 7.2°C, with each hour contributing one chilling unit toward the total requirement, while more refined models recognize that different temperatures contribute differently to dormancy release. ||The Utah model and its derivatives assign weighted values to different temperature ranges, with temperatures between 2.5-9.4°C receiving full chilling credit, temperatures from 0-2.5°C and 9.4-12.4°C receiving partial credit, temperatures below 0°C receiving no credit, and temperatures above 15.9°C potentially negating previously accumulated chilling. ||The dynamic model, developed originally for Mediterranean climates, treats chilling as a two-step process involving initial cold exposure that creates an intermediate compound, followed by consolidation at moderate temperatures that converts the intermediate to a stable chilling unit, better accounting for the fluctuating temperatures common in mild winter regions. ||The progressive nature of chilling unit accumulation reflects the gradual physiological changes occurring during dormancy release, with each increment of chilling exposure contributing to the cumulative dismantling of dormancy-maintaining mechanisms until the threshold requirement is achieved. ||Monitoring progressive chilling units through the winter allows viticulturists to predict budbreak timing, assess risk of inadequate chilling in warm winters, and make decisions regarding dormancy-breaking treatments if natural chilling appears insufficient. ||The relationship between accumulated chilling units and forcing response provides validation of chilling models, with decreasing days to budbreak correlating with increasing chilling unit accumulation until the requirement is satisfied.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Richardson EA, Seeley SD, Walker DR (1974) A model for estimating the completion of rest for Redhaven and Elberta peach trees. HortScience 9: 331-332 || Fishman S, Erez A, Couvillon GA (1987) The temperature dependence of dormancy breaking in plants: mathematical analysis of a two-step model. Journal of Theoretical Biology 126: 309-321 || Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056"
},

  "Dormancy_Depth_Reduction": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Depth_Reduction is a Chilling_Accumulation manifesting as the progressive dismantling of dormancy-maintaining mechanisms and restoration of growth competence in endodormant buds.",
  "alternative_term": "decreasing dormancy depth | dormancy intensity decline | progressive dormancy release | dormancy weakening |+ Dormanztiefe-Reduktion | abnehmende Dormanzintensität | fortschreitende Dormanzlösung | Dormanz-Abschwächung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Gris vines in Oregon's Willamette Valley, dormancy depth reduction progresses through winter as demonstrated by forcing tests showing days to 50% budbreak decreasing from more than 55 days in early December before significant chilling accumulation, to 35 days by mid-January after 500 chilling hours, to 18 days by mid-February after 900 chilling hours, with this progressive reduction correlating with measured decreases in bud ABA concentration from 195 to 85 ng per gram fresh weight over the same period.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Depth_Reduction represents the functional outcome of Chilling_Accumulation describing the progressive decrease in dormancy intensity. ||Distinguished from Maximum_Dormancy_Depth which describes peak dormancy, and from Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction which marks completion of reduction. ||Measured through forcing test response showing decreasing budbreak time. ||Rate varies among cultivars and through the chilling period. ||Associated with declining ABA, decreasing DAM expression, and chromatin derepression. ||Duration spans most of winter chilling period. || This process occurs continuously through the winter as effective chilling temperatures induce the physiological changes that reduce internal growth inhibition, eventually reaching the point where dormancy is fully released and buds transition to the ecodormant state. ||The measurement of dormancy depth reduction relies on forcing tests conducted at intervals through winter, with decreasing time to budbreak and increasing percentage of buds breaking indicating progressive reduction in dormancy depth as chilling accumulates. ||The physiological mechanisms underlying dormancy depth reduction include decreased ABA concentration through activation of catabolic pathways particularly ABA 8'-hydroxylase, declining expression of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes, progressive removal of repressive histone modifications from growth-related gene promoters, and gradual restoration of symplastic connectivity through callose degradation at plasmodesmata. ||The relationship between chilling accumulation and dormancy depth reduction is generally continuous but not necessarily linear, with some evidence suggesting that dormancy depth decreases slowly during early chilling accumulation when inhibitory mechanisms are strongest, more rapidly during mid-winter as multiple mechanisms are simultaneously affected, and more slowly again as dormancy approaches full release. ||The rate of dormancy depth reduction varies among cultivars in relation to their chilling requirements and the intensity of their maximum dormancy, with high-chill cultivars showing slower reduction per unit of chilling than low-chill cultivars. ||Environmental factors beyond temperature can modulate dormancy depth reduction, with some evidence that photoperiod may influence the rate of reduction at equivalent chilling accumulation, and water stress potentially affecting dormancy status. ||The completion of dormancy depth reduction to the point of full dormancy release restores bud growth competence, though environmental temperatures typically continue to constrain actual growth until spring warming occurs.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Zheng C et al (2015) Abscisic acid catabolism enhances dormancy release of grapevine buds. Plant Cell and Environment 38: 2490-2501"
},

  "Cumulative_Cold_Exposure": {
  "definition": "A Cumulative_Cold_Exposure is a Chilling_Accumulation defined by the total physiologically effective low-temperature experience contributing to chilling-requirement satisfaction independent of the quantification model employed.",
  "alternative_term": "total cold exposure | integrated cold experience | accumulated cold | winter cold sum |+ kumulative Kälteexposition | Gesamtkälteeinwirkung | akkumulierte Kälte | Kältesummen-Exposition",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner vines in the Wachau, Austria, cumulative cold exposure builds through winter with total hours below 7.2°C reaching approximately 300 hours by late December, 700 hours by late January, and 1100 hours by late February, satisfying the cultivar requirement of approximately 1000-1100 hours, with this cumulative exposure achieved despite intermittent warm periods in January that temporarily interrupted but did not substantially reverse the dormancy release progress.",
  "editor_note": "Cumulative_Cold_Exposure represents the physiological integration aspect of Chilling_Accumulation emphasizing total effective cold experience. ||Distinguished from Progressive_Chilling_Units which addresses model-based quantification, while Cumulative_Cold_Exposure emphasizes the underlying physiological integration. ||Reflects the persistence of cold-induced changes allowing accumulation across variable temperature periods. ||Effective temperature range approximately 0-7°C. ||Total exposure requirements vary from approximately 400-1500 hours depending on cultivar. || This concept emphasizes the integrative nature of dormancy release as a process responding to total cold exposure over time rather than to any single temperature event, with buds effectively summing their cold experience from dormancy establishment through eventual dormancy release. ||The physiological basis of cumulative cold exposure effects involves temperature-sensitive processes that gradually modify dormancy-maintaining mechanisms, with low temperatures activating specific enzymatic and regulatory processes that are largely inactive at warmer temperatures, allowing these dormancy-releasing reactions to proceed only during cold periods. ||The cellular processes activated by cold exposure include increased expression and activity of ABA catabolic enzymes, chromatin remodeling complexes that remove repressive modifications from growth-related genes, and signaling pathways that downregulate dormancy-associated MADS-box gene expression. ||The cumulative nature of cold exposure effects reflects the persistence of physiological changes induced during each cold period, with modifications to ABA levels, chromatin state, and gene expression being maintained during subsequent warmer periods rather than immediately reversing, allowing the effects of multiple cold exposures to accumulate toward dormancy release. ||The effectiveness of cold exposure for dormancy release varies with temperature, with moderately cold temperatures in the range of 0-7°C generally most effective, very cold temperatures below -5°C being less effective or ineffective, and the integration of variable temperatures into effective exposure being addressed by various chilling models. ||The relationship between cumulative cold exposure and dormancy status is fundamentally quantitative, with insufficient exposure resulting in incomplete dormancy release that manifests as delayed, prolonged, or uneven budbreak, while adequate exposure ensures synchronous and timely spring growth resumption. ||Climate variability creates year-to-year variation in cumulative cold exposure that affects dormancy release timing and completeness, with warm winters potentially providing insufficient exposure for adequate dormancy release in some cultivar-region combinations.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056 || Campoy JA et al (2011) High temperatures and time to budbreak in low chill apricot. Environmental and Experimental Botany 73: 134-142"
},

  "Dormancy_Maintenance": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Maintenance is an Endodormancy comprising sustained preservation of the endodormant state through active physiological mechanisms preventing premature growth resumption until sufficient chilling has been accumulated.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy preservation | dormant state maintenance | sustained dormancy | dormancy persistence |+ Dormanz-Aufrechterhaltung | Ruheerhaltung | anhaltende Dormanz | Dormanz-Persistenz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in Napa Valley, dormancy maintenance persists through December and January as demonstrated by forcing tests showing continued growth inhibition with budbreak requiring more than 40 days at 22°C despite exposure to warm periods with temperatures exceeding 15°C for several consecutive days in early January, with the maintaining mechanisms only progressively weakening as chilling accumulates toward the cultivar requirement of approximately 900-1000 hours.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Maintenance represents a functional phase within Endodormancy addressing the active preservation of dormant state. ||Distinguished from Deep_Endodormancy which represents maximum dormancy intensity, and from Chilling_Accumulation which addresses progressive dormancy release. ||Subdivides into Sustained_Growth_Inhibition, Continued_Metabolic_Suppression, and Endodormancy_Persistence as component aspects. ||Duration spans most of endodormancy period from establishment through progressive release. ||Involves active regulatory mechanisms rather than passive quiescence. || This process operates throughout the endodormancy period, from dormancy establishment in late autumn until chilling-dependent dormancy release in late winter, ensuring that buds remain growth-incompetent during the period when environmental conditions would make growth resumption potentially lethal due to subsequent freezing exposure. ||The maintenance of dormancy is not a passive state but involves active regulatory processes that sustain growth inhibition, including continued expression of dormancy-associated MADS-box genes that repress growth-related transcription, ongoing ABA signaling that maintains cell cycle arrest, and the preservation of chromatin modifications that silence genes required for meristematic activity. ||The ecological function of dormancy maintenance is to prevent the vine from responding to temporary favorable conditions during winter, such as warm spells that might otherwise trigger growth in non-dormant buds, thereby protecting the vine from the catastrophic consequences of freeze damage to actively growing tissues. ||The effectiveness of dormancy maintenance varies through the endodormancy period, being strongest during deep endodormancy when all maintaining mechanisms operate at maximum intensity, and progressively weakening as chilling accumulation gradually dismantles inhibitory mechanisms and reduces dormancy depth. ||The robustness of dormancy maintenance against premature release has been selected through evolution in grapevine populations exposed to variable winter climates where temporary warm periods are common, with cultivars from continental climates typically showing more robust maintenance than those from Mediterranean regions where winters are milder and more predictable. ||Factors that can compromise dormancy maintenance include exposure to dormancy-breaking chemicals such as hydrogen cyanamide that artificially override maintaining mechanisms, severe dehydration stress that may disrupt normal hormonal and metabolic regulation, and potentially inadequate dormancy establishment that fails to fully activate maintaining mechanisms. ||The gradual transition from active dormancy maintenance to dormancy release competence represents the physiological basis for the chilling requirement, with each increment of chilling exposure reducing the strength of maintaining mechanisms until they can no longer prevent growth in response to favorable conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223"
},

  "Sustained_Growth_Inhibition": {
  "definition": "A Sustained_Growth_Inhibition is a Dormancy_Maintenance realized through the persistent operation of multiple growth-inhibiting mechanisms preventing cell division and elongation in bud meristems regardless of external conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "continuous growth suppression | persistent growth inhibition | maintained growth arrest | ongoing meristem inhibition |+ anhaltende Wachstumshemmung | kontinuierliche Wachstumsunterdrückung | persistierende Wachstumsinhibition | fortgesetzte Meristem-Hemmung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Rheingau, sustained growth inhibition persists through the endodormancy period from November through early February, with bud meristems showing no mitotic activity when examined histologically despite exposure to mid-January temperatures of 12-14°C for five consecutive days, demonstrating the robustness of internal inhibitory mechanisms that prevent growth response until approximately 1200 chilling hours have accumulated and dormancy maintenance mechanisms have been sufficiently dismantled.",
  "editor_note": "Sustained_Growth_Inhibition represents the growth-suppression aspect of Dormancy_Maintenance specifically addressing continuous meristem arrest. ||Distinguished from Growth_Inhibition_Maximum which represents peak inhibition intensity, while Sustained_Growth_Inhibition addresses the persistence of inhibition over time. ||Involves DAM gene expression, CDK inhibitors, hormonal suppression, and chromatin silencing. ||Strength varies with dormancy depth through the endodormancy period. ||Robustness against warm period response demonstrates internal control nature of endodormancy. || This sustained inhibition operates from dormancy establishment through dormancy release, ensuring that the fully formed primordial shoots within dormant buds remain arrested in development during the entire winter period when growth would be maladaptive. ||The molecular basis of sustained growth inhibition involves the continued activity of growth-suppressing regulatory systems including dormancy-associated MADS-box transcription factors that repress genes required for cell cycle progression and meristem function, CDK inhibitor proteins that block cyclin-dependent kinase activity essential for cell division, and chromatin-based silencing mechanisms that maintain growth genes in a transcriptionally inactive state. ||The hormonal component of sustained growth inhibition involves the maintenance of growth-suppressive hormone balances with elevated ABA levels that directly inhibit cell cycle progression and growth gene expression, reduced cytokinin signaling that normally promotes cell division, and limited auxin transport that would otherwise activate meristematic activity. ||The persistence of growth inhibition through temporary warm periods during winter demonstrates the robustness of maintaining mechanisms, with endodormant buds failing to respond to temperatures that would rapidly induce growth in ecodormant or non-dormant buds, illustrating the internal rather than environmental control of growth during endodormancy. ||The strength of sustained growth inhibition is not constant through endodormancy but varies with dormancy depth, being strongest during deep endodormancy and progressively weakening as chilling accumulation reduces the intensity of inhibitory mechanisms, eventually declining below the threshold required to prevent growth and allowing transition to ecodormancy. ||Cell biological features supporting sustained growth inhibition include restricted plasmodesmatal function that limits symplastic communication between dormant meristems and surrounding tissues, potentially isolating meristems from growth-promoting signals, and the maintenance of meristem cells in G0/G1 phase of the cell cycle where they are competent to resume division when inhibition is released but remain arrested as long as inhibitory mechanisms persist.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Cooke JE, Eriksson ME, Junttila O (2012) The dynamic nature of bud dormancy in trees: environmental control and molecular mechanisms. Plant Cell and Environment 35: 1707-1728 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
},

  "Continued_Metabolic_Suppression": {
  "definition": "A Continued_Metabolic_Suppression is a Dormancy_Maintenance exhibiting sustained reduction of respiration, protein synthesis, and biosynthetic pathway activity conserving carbohydrate reserves for spring growth resumption.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained metabolic reduction | persistent metabolic suppression | maintained metabolic dormancy | ongoing metabolic inhibition |+ fortgesetzte Stoffwechselunterdrückung | anhaltende metabolische Suppression | persistierende Stoffwechselhemmung | kontinuierliche metabolische Reduktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Champagne, continued metabolic suppression maintains bud respiration rates at 0.3-0.5 μmol CO2 per gram dry weight per hour throughout the December through February endodormancy period, representing only 15% of rates measured in actively growing buds during June, with this suppression persisting even during late January warm periods when ambient temperatures of 10-12°C would support much higher metabolic rates in non-dormant tissues.",
  "editor_note": "Continued_Metabolic_Suppression represents the metabolic dimension of Dormancy_Maintenance addressing sustained low metabolic rates. ||Distinguished from Metabolic_Downregulation during dormancy induction which establishes the suppressed state, while Continued_Metabolic_Suppression addresses persistence of this state through endodormancy. ||Encompasses respiration, protein synthesis, and biosynthetic pathway suppression. ||Reflects both temperature effects and active regulatory suppression. ||Duration spans entire endodormancy period. ||Critical for reserve conservation during winter. || This metabolic state persists from dormancy establishment in late autumn until dormancy release in late winter, with metabolic rates remaining at levels far below those characteristic of active growth throughout the period regardless of temporary temperature fluctuations that might otherwise stimulate metabolism in non-dormant tissues. ||The respiratory component of continued metabolic suppression involves maintenance of low respiration rates that minimize carbohydrate consumption during the extended period without photosynthetic input, with dormant bud respiration rates typically only 10-20% of rates in actively growing buds at equivalent temperatures, reflecting both temperature-dependent rate reductions and active regulatory suppression of respiratory capacity. ||Protein metabolism during continued metabolic suppression is characterized by minimal protein turnover with very low rates of both synthesis and degradation, maintaining the dormancy-related protein complement including dehydrins and other protective proteins while avoiding the energetic costs of active protein synthesis that would deplete reserves. ||The biosynthetic pathway suppression encompasses reduced activity of pathways for amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid synthesis that would support growth, with metabolic flux directed toward maintenance functions rather than biosynthetic production of growth substrates. ||The regulatory basis of continued metabolic suppression involves both the direct temperature effects on enzyme reaction rates that reduce metabolism during cold exposure, and active regulatory mechanisms including ABA-mediated suppression of metabolic gene expression and the absence of growth hormone signals that normally stimulate metabolic activity in support of development. ||The persistence of metabolic suppression during temporary warm periods demonstrates that metabolic downregulation during endodormancy reflects regulatory programming rather than simply temperature limitation, with dormant tissues failing to increase metabolism substantially even when temperatures would permit higher activity in non-dormant tissues. ||The gradual relief of metabolic suppression occurs in parallel with dormancy release, as chilling accumulation reduces dormancy depth and allows progressive metabolic reactivation in preparation for spring growth.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 5 Carbohydrate Supply and Reserve Storage || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of starch and N reserves in grapevine. Journal of Experimental Botany 55: 2165-2175 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
},

  "Endodormancy_Persistence": {
  "definition": "An Endodormancy_Persistence is a Dormancy_Maintenance characterized by continued internal growth inhibition resistant to release by favorable environmental conditions until satisfaction of the genetically determined chilling requirement.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained endodormancy | continued true dormancy | endodormancy continuation | persistent internal dormancy |+ Endodormanz-Persistenz | anhaltende Endodormanz | fortgesetzte echte Dormanz | persistierende innere Dormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Franc vines in the Loire Valley, endodormancy persistence is demonstrated through January when buds excised on January 15 after accumulation of only 600 chilling hours require 38 days for 50% budbreak under forcing conditions, compared to buds excised February 15 after 1000 chilling hours requiring only 15 days, illustrating the continued persistence of endodormancy at insufficient chilling levels and its eventual release as chilling accumulation satisfies the cultivar requirement of approximately 950 hours.",
  "editor_note": "Endodormancy_Persistence represents the temporal continuity aspect of Dormancy_Maintenance emphasizing resistance to premature release. ||Distinguished from Deep_Endodormancy which represents maximum dormancy intensity, while Endodormancy_Persistence addresses the duration and robustness of dormancy through the winter period. ||Measured through forcing test response showing continued growth inhibition. ||Duration determined by interaction of chilling requirement and chilling exposure. ||Provides ecological protection against false spring growth. || This persistence reflects the robustness of dormancy-maintaining mechanisms that have evolved to prevent premature growth during the unpredictable temperature fluctuations characteristic of temperate winters, ensuring that growth does not resume until winter has sufficiently progressed that subsequent severe cold is unlikely. ||The molecular basis of endodormancy persistence involves the stable maintenance of dormancy-related gene expression patterns including sustained DAM gene activity, persistent chromatin modifications that silence growth genes, and continued production of growth-inhibiting proteins and metabolites that accumulate faster than they are degraded under conditions of insufficient chilling. ||The concept of persistence emphasizes the resistance of endodormancy to release, distinguishing this phase from ecodormancy where growth is prevented by environmental limitation and would occur immediately upon exposure to favorable conditions, whereas endodormant buds fail to grow even under optimal forcing conditions until internal changes associated with chilling have released the dormant state. ||Testing for endodormancy persistence involves exposing buds to growth-promoting conditions and confirming continued growth inhibition, with persistent endodormancy indicated by extended times to budbreak or complete failure to break that demonstrates internal control of dormancy status. ||The duration of endodormancy persistence is determined by the interaction between chilling requirement genetics and environmental chilling exposure, with persistence continuing until accumulated chilling has sufficiently reduced dormancy depth that maintaining mechanisms can no longer prevent growth, at which point the transition to ecodormancy occurs. ||Factors affecting endodormancy persistence include cultivar genetics that determine both dormancy depth and chilling requirement, environmental conditions during dormancy induction that affect the completeness of dormancy establishment, and the rate of chilling accumulation during winter that determines how rapidly maintaining mechanisms are dismantled. ||The ecological significance of endodormancy persistence lies in protecting the vine from responding to false spring conditions, with more persistent dormancy providing greater protection against freeze damage following premature growth but also requiring more chilling for release and potentially delaying spring growth in regions with limited winter cold.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
},

  "Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction": {
  "definition": "A Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction is an Endodormancy comprising the achievement of sufficient cumulative cold exposure to fully release endodormancy and enable transition to environmentally controlled ecodormancy.",
  "alternative_term": "chilling fulfillment | chilling requirement completion | chill satisfaction | dormancy chilling achievement |+ Kältebedürfnis-Erfüllung | Chilling-Requirement-Befriedigung | Kälteanforderungs-Erfüllung | Kältebedarf-Deckung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux, chilling requirement satisfaction is achieved in early February when accumulated chilling hours reach the cultivar threshold of approximately 900-950 hours, confirmed by forcing tests showing 50% budbreak within 12 days at 22°C, ABA concentrations having declined to 60-70 ng per gram fresh weight, and subsequent field budbreak occurring uniformly within 10 days of sustained temperatures above 10°C in late March.",
  "editor_note": "Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction represents the culminating phase of Endodormancy marking achievement of full dormancy release competence. ||Distinguished from Chilling_Accumulation which addresses the progressive process, while Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction specifically marks threshold achievement. ||Subdivides into Adequate_Chilling_Achievement, Dormancy_Release_Competence, and Endodormancy_Completion as component aspects. ||Cultivar requirements range from approximately 400-1500 hours. ||Marks transition from endodormancy to ecodormancy. ||Critical for uniform spring budbreak. || This milestone typically occurs during late January to February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, when accumulated chilling hours or units reach the cultivar-specific threshold that has been genetically determined through adaptation to the climate of origin. ||The physiological basis of chilling requirement satisfaction involves the cumulative dismantling of dormancy-maintaining mechanisms through chilling-dependent processes, with sufficient chilling reducing ABA levels below inhibitory thresholds, decreasing DAM gene expression to levels compatible with growth, removing repressive chromatin modifications from growth gene promoters, and restoring cellular communication pathways required for growth coordination. ||The concept of satisfaction implies a threshold phenomenon where a specific amount of chilling must be accumulated before dormancy release occurs, though in practice the transition from endodormancy to ecodormancy appears gradual with dormancy depth progressively decreasing until it crosses the threshold where maintaining mechanisms can no longer prevent growth response to favorable conditions. ||The quantification of chilling requirement satisfaction depends on the chilling model employed, with requirements typically expressed as hours below 7.2°C ranging from approximately 400-600 hours for low-chill cultivars adapted to Mediterranean climates to 1200-1500 hours for high-chill cultivars from continental regions. ||The practical importance of chilling requirement satisfaction relates to the timing and uniformity of budbreak in spring, with fully satisfied chilling requirements producing rapid, synchronous budbreak when temperatures permit, while inadequately satisfied requirements result in delayed, prolonged, and uneven budbreak that complicates vineyard management and may reduce productivity. ||Climate change poses significant challenges to chilling requirement satisfaction in many viticultural regions, as warming winters may fail to provide sufficient chilling for complete dormancy release, particularly for high-chill cultivars in regions near the warm margin of their adaptive range. ||The verification of chilling requirement satisfaction through forcing tests shows rapid budbreak within 10-14 days under optimal conditions, contrasting with the extended times characteristic of insufficiently chilled buds still in endodormancy.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46"
},

  "Adequate_Chilling_Achievement": {
  "definition": "An Adequate_Chilling_Achievement is a Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction defined by accumulation of cold exposure sufficient for complete and uniform dormancy release without deficit compromising subsequent bud burst quality.",
  "alternative_term": "sufficient chilling accumulation | complete chilling fulfillment | full chill achievement | adequate cold accumulation |+ ausreichende Kälte-Erreichung | adäquate Chilling-Akkumulation | vollständige Kältebedürfnis-Erfüllung | hinreichende Kälteakkumulation",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Willamette Valley, Oregon, adequate chilling achievement occurs by late January when accumulated chilling hours of 1100-1200 exceed the cultivar requirement of approximately 1000 hours, ensuring complete dormancy release confirmed by forcing tests showing uniform budbreak within 10 days, and predicting the synchronous field budbreak within a 7-day window typically observed in this cultivar when spring temperatures become favorable.",
  "editor_note": "Adequate_Chilling_Achievement represents the quantitative sufficiency aspect of Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction. ||Distinguished from partial or marginal chilling that permits only incomplete dormancy release. ||Defined by chilling accumulation meeting or exceeding cultivar-specific requirement. ||Verified through forcing test response and physiological markers. ||Critical for budbreak uniformity and vigor. ||Margin above requirement affects budbreak timing. ||Subject to year-to-year variation with climate. || This condition is distinguished from partial or marginal chilling that may permit some degree of budbreak but results in the delayed, prolonged, and uneven growth characteristic of inadequate dormancy release. ||The quantitative definition of adequate chilling depends on cultivar-specific requirements, with adequacy achieved when accumulated chilling hours or units equal or exceed the genetic threshold, typically verified through forcing tests that demonstrate rapid and complete budbreak response indicating full restoration of growth competence. ||The physiological markers of adequate chilling achievement include ABA concentrations reduced to baseline levels compatible with growth, DAM gene expression declined to minimal levels, chromatin modifications removed from growth gene promoters restoring transcriptional competence, and metabolic systems prepared for the rapid activation required during budbreak. ||The practical importance of adequate chilling achievement for viticulture relates to the quality of spring growth, with adequate chilling producing the synchronous, vigorous budbreak desired for uniform crop development, while inadequate chilling causes the management challenges of extended budbreak period, variable shoot development, and potential yield reduction from poorly developed shoots. ||The margin of adequacy affects vineyard performance, with chilling substantially exceeding requirements potentially advancing budbreak timing and increasing frost risk in some environments, while chilling barely meeting requirements may result in acceptable but suboptimal budbreak uniformity. ||Climate variability creates year-to-year variation in chilling adequacy, with warm winters potentially failing to achieve adequate chilling particularly for high-requirement cultivars, while cold winters may substantially exceed requirements, allowing viticulturists to predict budbreak characteristics based on seasonal chilling accumulation relative to cultivar requirements. ||Management responses to anticipated inadequate chilling include application of dormancy-breaking chemicals and selection of cultural practices that maximize effective chilling exposure.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Campoy JA et al (2011) High temperatures and time to budbreak in low chill apricot. Environmental and Experimental Botany 73: 134-142"
},

  "Dormancy_Release_Competence": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Release_Competence is a Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction bearing the restored disposition for growth response to growth-promoting conditions following dismantling of internal endodormancy constraints.",
  "alternative_term": "growth competence restoration | budbreak readiness | dormancy release capacity | growth resumption competence |+ Dormanzlösungs-Kompetenz | Wachstumskompetenz-Wiederherstellung | Austriebsbereitschaft | Wachstumswiederaufnahme-Fähigkeit",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc vines in Marlborough, New Zealand, dormancy release competence is achieved by early August following accumulation of approximately 850 chilling hours, demonstrated by forcing tests showing complete budbreak within 11 days at 20°C, with competent buds subsequently responding rapidly to field warming in September, initiating visible bud swelling within 5-7 days of mean temperatures exceeding 10°C.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Release_Competence represents the functional capacity aspect of Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction describing restored growth potential. ||Distinguished from actual growth which requires favorable environmental conditions, while competence represents the potential for growth when conditions permit. ||Marks the endodormancy to ecodormancy transition. ||Verified through rapid forcing test response within 10-14 days. ||Involves completion of all chilling-dependent physiological changes. ||Uniformity of competence affects budbreak synchrony. || This competence represents a qualitative transition from the endodormant state where growth is impossible regardless of conditions to a growth-ready state where only environmental factors constrain actual growth initiation. ||The physiological basis of dormancy release competence involves the successful completion of chilling-dependent changes including reduction of ABA to non-inhibitory levels, silencing of DAM gene expression, removal of repressive chromatin marks from growth-related genes restoring their transcriptional responsiveness, and re-establishment of symplastic communication pathways that enable coordination of growth responses. ||The cellular characteristics of growth-competent buds include the presence of cell cycle regulators poised for activation, metabolic enzyme systems capable of rapid upregulation to support biosynthesis, and hormone receptor systems sensitized to respond to growth-promoting signals. ||The concept of competence distinguishes between the potential for growth and actual growth, with competent buds remaining quiescent during ecodormancy when environmental temperatures are insufficient for growth but capable of immediate response when conditions become favorable. ||Testing for dormancy release competence involves forcing assays that expose buds to optimal growth conditions and assess the speed and completeness of budbreak response, with competent buds showing rapid budbreak within 10-14 days while buds lacking competence due to incomplete dormancy release require extended periods or fail to break entirely. ||The achievement of dormancy release competence marks the transition from endodormancy to ecodormancy in the dormancy classification system, representing a fundamental change in the nature of growth control from internal inhibition to environmental limitation. ||The uniformity of competence achievement across buds on a vine affects the synchrony of subsequent budbreak, with simultaneous competence acquisition producing uniform budbreak while variable competence results in extended budbreak periods.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46"
},

  "Endodormancy_Completion": {
  "definition": "An Endodormancy_Completion is a Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction marking the termination of internally controlled dormancy and the onset of the ecodormant phase under environmental control.",
  "alternative_term": "endodormancy termination | true dormancy completion | endodormancy ending | internal dormancy completion |+ Endodormanz-Abschluss | Endodormanz-Beendigung | echte Dormanz-Ende | innere Dormanz-Abschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner vines in the Wachau, Austria, endodormancy completion occurs in early February when accumulated chilling of approximately 1100 hours has satisfied the cultivar requirement, confirmed by forcing tests showing budbreak within 12 days at 22°C, with subsequent field observations showing buds remaining in ecodormancy until late March warming triggers the transition through BBCH stage 01 to visible bud swelling at BBCH 05.",
  "editor_note": "Endodormancy_Completion represents the terminal transition of Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction marking the end of endodormancy phase. ||Distinguished from Dormancy_Release_Competence which describes the achieved capacity, while Endodormancy_Completion emphasizes the phase transition. ||Marks beginning of ecodormancy phase. ||Verified by forcing response less than 14 days. ||Timing affects budbreak date and frost risk. ||Molecular markers include low ABA, minimal DAM expression, and derepressed chromatin state. || This transition typically occurs during late January to February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, when cumulative chilling exposure has satisfied the genetically determined requirement and all physiological changes associated with dormancy release have been accomplished. ||The molecular markers of endodormancy completion include the reduction of ABA concentrations to levels characteristic of ecodormant or growing buds, cessation of DAM gene expression, removal of repressive chromatin modifications from growth gene promoters, and restoration of cellular communication pathways that were restricted during endodormancy. ||The physiological state following endodormancy completion is characterized by buds that are metabolically prepared for growth resumption, with cell cycle machinery poised for activation, biosynthetic enzyme systems ready for rapid upregulation, and hormone signaling systems sensitized to respond to the warming temperatures of spring. ||The verification of endodormancy completion relies on forcing tests demonstrating rapid budbreak response comparable to that of ecodormant reference material, with completion indicated by budbreak times of less than 14 days under optimal forcing conditions contrasting with the extended times characteristic of endodormant buds. ||The timing of endodormancy completion relative to the onset of spring warming significantly affects budbreak date and potential frost exposure, with early completion in warm winters potentially advancing budbreak into periods of frost risk, while late completion in cold winters may delay budbreak and shorten the growing season. ||The concept of completion emphasizes the discrete transition between dormancy phases, though in physiological reality the transition is gradual with dormancy depth continuously declining until it crosses the threshold defining endodormancy release. ||Following endodormancy completion, buds enter ecodormancy where they remain quiescent due to environmental temperature limitation rather than internal inhibition, awaiting the warming of spring to initiate visible growth.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223"
},

  "Ecodormancy": {
  "definition": "An Ecodormancy is a Dormancy comprising growth inhibition controlled by external environmental factors with buds bearing restored growth competence through completed chilling but remaining quiescent under unfavorable environmental conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "environmental dormancy | quiescence | imposed dormancy | temperature-limited dormancy |+ Ekodormanz | Umweltdormanz | erzwungene Ruhe | temperaturbedingte Dormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Côte d'Or, Burgundy, ecodormancy extends from early February when chilling requirements are satisfied through late March when spring warming triggers budbreak, with buds demonstrating growth competence through rapid budbreak within 10 days under forcing conditions at 22°C while remaining quiescent in the field where mean temperatures of 5-8°C during February and early March are insufficient to satisfy heat unit requirements for growth initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Ecodormancy represents the third major phase within the Dormancy hierarchy following Endodormancy, characterized by environmentally-controlled rather than internally-controlled growth inhibition. ||Distinguished from Endodormancy by the external nature of growth control and immediate growth response under forcing conditions. ||Subdivides into Ecodormancy_Transition, Environmental_Constraint, Conditional_Dormancy, and Quiescence_Maintenance as component phases. ||Duration varies from weeks to months depending on climate. ||Growth competent buds await heat accumulation for budbreak initiation. || This dormancy phase follows endodormancy and typically extends from late winter through early spring in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, persisting until warming temperatures satisfy the heat requirements for growth initiation and budbreak commences. ||The defining characteristic of ecodormancy is the external nature of growth control, distinguishing it from endodormancy where internal factors prevent growth regardless of environmental conditions, with ecodormant buds capable of immediate growth response when transferred to favorable conditions while endodormant buds remain inhibited even under optimal forcing. ||The physiological state during ecodormancy differs fundamentally from endodormancy in that all dormancy-maintaining mechanisms have been dismantled through chilling accumulation, growth-related genes have been derepressed and are competent for transcription, hormone balances have shifted toward growth-permissive configurations with low ABA and responsive cytokinin and gibberellin signaling, and cellular communication pathways have been restored enabling coordinated growth responses. ||The ecological function of ecodormancy is to delay growth until environmental conditions are reliably favorable, with temperature serving as the primary constraint that prevents budbreak during late winter when frost risk remains high despite the restoration of growth competence. ||The duration of ecodormancy varies substantially depending on climate, with longer ecodormancy periods in cold continental climates where spring warming is delayed, and shorter periods in Mediterranean climates where mild temperatures may follow closely after chilling completion. ||During ecodormancy, buds undergo preparatory changes for growth including gradual metabolic activation, accumulation of growth-related transcripts, and ultrastructural changes in meristematic cells that prepare for rapid division upon warming. ||The concept of heat unit or growing degree day accumulation during ecodormancy quantifies the temperature exposure required for budbreak initiation, with cultivar-specific heat requirements determining the timing of growth resumption relative to spring temperature patterns. ||The transition from ecodormancy to active growth is triggered when accumulated heat units satisfy the requirement for budbreak, initiating the visible swelling and eventual opening of buds that marks the beginning of the new growing season.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:relatedMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0097437 ## maintenance of dormancy | 0.70" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Ecodormancy_Transition": {
  "definition": "An Ecodormancy_Transition is an Ecodormancy comprising the physiological shift from internally controlled endodormancy to environmentally controlled ecodormancy following chilling requirement satisfaction with environmental temperatures remaining below the growth threshold.",
  "alternative_term": "endodormancy to ecodormancy transition | dormancy phase shift | dormancy type transition | quiescence onset |+ Ekodormanz-Übergang | Endodormanz-Ekodormanz-Wechsel | Dormanzphasen-Übergang | Ruhetyp-Transition",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Champagne, ecodormancy transition occurs during the first two weeks of February when accumulated chilling hours reach approximately 1000, demonstrated by forcing tests showing budbreak time decreasing from 35 days in late January to 12 days by mid-February, with this transition marking the shift from internal dormancy control to environmental temperature limitation that will persist until March warming initiates budbreak.",
  "editor_note": "Ecodormancy_Transition represents the phase shift from endodormancy to ecodormancy within the dormancy cycle. ||Distinguished from Chilling_Requirement_Satisfaction which marks the quantitative chilling achievement, while Ecodormancy_Transition emphasizes the qualitative change in dormancy control mechanism. ||Subdivides into Endodormancy_to_Ecodormancy_Shift, Environmental_Control_Onset, and Growth_Competence_Restoration as component aspects. ||Identified through forcing test response less than 14 days. ||Duration of transition phase typically spans 1-2 weeks. || This transition typically occurs during late January to February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, marking a fundamental change in the nature of dormancy from a state where growth is impossible regardless of conditions to a state where growth is merely delayed by unfavorable environment. ||The transition involves the completion of all chilling-dependent physiological changes including reduction of ABA to non-inhibitory levels, cessation of DAM gene expression, removal of repressive chromatin modifications from growth gene promoters, and restoration of symplastic communication through callose degradation at plasmodesmata, collectively restoring the capacity for growth that was suspended during endodormancy. ||The practical identification of ecodormancy transition relies on forcing tests that demonstrate rapid budbreak response indicating growth competence, with the transition point defined as the time when forcing response times decrease to less than approximately 14 days under optimal conditions, contrasting with the extended times characteristic of endodormant buds. ||The transition is not instantaneous but represents the crossing of a threshold where dormancy-maintaining mechanisms have been sufficiently weakened that they can no longer prevent growth under favorable conditions, with individual buds potentially crossing this threshold at slightly different times creating a brief period of transition heterogeneity across the vine. ||Environmental conditions during ecodormancy transition affect subsequent budbreak characteristics, with continued cold exposure during early ecodormancy potentially improving budbreak uniformity while premature warming might advance budbreak into periods of elevated frost risk. ||The metabolic state following ecodormancy transition involves gradual reactivation of biosynthetic pathways in preparation for growth, though full metabolic activation awaits the warming temperatures that will trigger budbreak, with ecodormant buds maintaining intermediate metabolic rates between the minimal activity of deep endodormancy and the high activity of actively growing tissues.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46"
},

  "Endodormancy_to_Ecodormancy_Shift": {
  "definition": "An Endodormancy_to_Ecodormancy_Shift is an Ecodormancy_Transition marking the specific change of dormancy control from internal physiological inhibition to external environmental limitation upon completion of chilling-dependent dormancy release.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy phase transition | endodormancy exit | ecodormancy entry | dormancy control shift |+ Endodormanz-Ekodormanz-Wechsel | Dormanzphasen-Transition | Endodormanz-Austritt | Ekodormanz-Eintritt",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Mosel Valley, the endodormancy to ecodormancy shift occurs in late January to early February when accumulated chilling of approximately 1200 hours has satisfied the cultivar requirement, verified by forcing test response decreasing below 14 days and ABA concentrations declining to 70-80 ng per gram fresh weight, with buds subsequently remaining in ecodormancy until late March warming triggers budbreak initiation at BBCH stage 01.",
  "editor_note": "Endodormancy_to_Ecodormancy_Shift represents the discrete transition point within Ecodormancy_Transition marking the change in dormancy control source. ||Distinguished from gradual Dormancy_Depth_Reduction by representing the threshold crossing rather than continuous change. ||Defined by forcing response less than 14 days and molecular markers including low ABA and minimal DAM expression. ||Timing determined by chilling requirement satisfaction. ||Critical boundary in dormancy classification system. || This shift constitutes a discrete change in dormancy classification despite the gradual nature of the underlying physiological changes, defining the boundary between two fundamentally different dormancy states based on the source of growth inhibition. ||The physiological basis of the shift involves the cumulative effects of chilling exposure having reduced all dormancy-maintaining mechanisms below the threshold required to prevent growth, with ABA concentrations, DAM gene expression, and chromatin repression all declining to levels compatible with growth response to favorable conditions. ||The timing of the shift is determined by the interaction between cultivar-specific chilling requirements and environmental chilling accumulation, occurring earlier in warm winters with rapid chilling accumulation for low-chill cultivars and later in cold winters for high-chill cultivars, with typical timing ranging from mid-January to late February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture depending on these factors. ||The verification of shift completion relies on forcing tests demonstrating that buds have acquired the capacity for rapid growth response, with shifted buds breaking within 10-14 days under optimal forcing conditions compared to the extended times or failure to break characteristic of buds that remain in endodormancy. ||The practical significance of shift timing relates to frost risk management, with earlier shifts in warm winters creating longer ecodormancy periods during which premature warming could trigger vulnerable early growth, while later shifts in cold winters reduce this risk but may delay spring growth initiation. ||The molecular markers of shift completion include reduced ABA to less than approximately 80 ng per gram fresh weight, DAM gene expression declined to less than 20% of maximum endodormancy levels, and restoration of growth gene transcriptional competence verified through expression analysis of cell cycle and meristem function genes.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Zheng C et al (2015) Abscisic acid catabolism enhances dormancy release of grapevine buds. Plant Cell and Environment 38: 2490-2501"
},

  "Environmental_Control_Onset": {
  "definition": "An Environmental_Control_Onset is an Ecodormancy_Transition comprising the establishment of temperature, moisture, and other external variables as the primary determinants of bud growth status following dismantling of internal dormancy constraints.",
  "alternative_term": "environmental regulation onset | exogenous control establishment | external factor dominance | environmental growth control |+ Umweltkontroll-Beginn | exogene Kontroll-Etablierung | Umweltfaktoren-Dominanz | externe Wachstumskontrolle",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer vines in Alsace, environmental control onset occurs in early February following chilling requirement satisfaction, after which budbreak timing becomes predictable from temperature accumulation models, with growing degree day accumulation above 10°C base temperature tracked from this point and budbreak occurring when approximately 150-180 GDD have accumulated, typically in late March to early April depending on spring temperature patterns.",
  "editor_note": "Environmental_Control_Onset represents the regulatory transition aspect of Ecodormancy_Transition marking the shift to external growth control. ||Distinguished from internal control characteristic of endodormancy. ||Enables temperature-based budbreak prediction through heat unit models. ||Primary controlling factor is temperature with secondary moisture effects. ||Creates vulnerability to premature growth from early warming. ||Coincides with chilling requirement satisfaction timing. || This transition occurs coincident with the endodormancy to ecodormancy shift, as the dismantling of internal growth inhibition transfers control of bud quiescence from endogenous regulatory mechanisms to exogenous environmental conditions. ||The practical consequence of environmental control onset is that bud growth status becomes predictable from environmental monitoring, with temperature-based models able to forecast budbreak timing based on heat unit accumulation, in contrast to the endodormancy period when internal factors override environmental influences and make growth unpredictable from environmental data alone. ||The temperature component of environmental control involves the requirement for heat unit accumulation above a base temperature threshold, typically 10°C for grapevine, with budbreak initiation requiring cultivar-specific accumulations typically ranging from 100-300 growing degree days following the onset of environmental control. ||The responsiveness to environmental signals during this period reflects the restored sensitivity of growth-regulatory pathways to external cues, with temperature affecting the activity of growth-promoting hormones, the rate of metabolic processes supporting growth, and the expression of genes required for cell division and expansion in meristematic tissues. ||The moisture component of environmental control relates to the requirement for adequate water availability to support the cellular expansion and metabolic activity associated with growth resumption, though moisture limitation is typically less important than temperature limitation in most viticultural environments during early spring. ||The onset of environmental control represents a vulnerable period for the vine, as growth-competent buds may respond prematurely to temporary warm conditions, initiating growth that is subsequently damaged by frost when temperatures return to winter levels, highlighting the ecological risk associated with the transition from robust internal control to more responsive environmental control.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216"
},

  "Growth_Competence_Restoration": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Competence_Restoration is an Ecodormancy_Transition realized through the re-establishment of cellular and molecular prerequisites for meristematic activity and developmental growth following endodormancy completion.",
  "alternative_term": "growth capacity restoration | meristem competence recovery | developmental competence restoration | growth potential re-establishment |+ Wachstumskompetenz-Wiederherstellung | Meristem-Kompetenz-Erholung | Entwicklungskompetenz-Restauration | Wachstumspotential-Wiedererrichtung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Bordeaux, growth competence restoration is completed by early February following accumulation of approximately 950 chilling hours, demonstrated by excised buds achieving visible bud swelling within 8 days and full budbreak within 12 days under forcing conditions at 22°C, with restored competence verified through detection of cell cycle gene transcripts including CYCLIN D and CDK expression potential in meristematic tissues.",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Competence_Restoration represents the functional capacity aspect of Ecodormancy_Transition describing the re-establishment of growth potential. ||Distinguished from Dormancy_Release_Competence which describes the achieved state, while Growth_Competence_Restoration emphasizes the process of capacity recovery. ||Encompasses cell cycle, hormonal, metabolic, and connectivity restoration. ||Verified by forcing test response within 10-14 days. ||Heterogeneity among buds affects subsequent budbreak uniformity. || This restoration is achieved through the cumulative effects of chilling exposure that progressively dismantle dormancy-maintaining mechanisms and re-establish growth-permissive conditions within bud tissues. ||The cellular basis of growth competence restoration involves the re-establishment of cell cycle competence in meristematic cells, with restoration of cyclin and CDK expression potential, degradation of CDK inhibitor proteins that blocked cell cycle progression during dormancy, and chromatin remodeling that makes cell cycle gene promoters accessible for transcription upon growth signal reception. ||The hormonal dimension of competence restoration involves the re-establishment of hormone signaling systems that transduce environmental cues into growth responses, including sensitization of cytokinin and gibberellin receptors, restoration of auxin polar transport capacity, and reduction of ABA signaling that inhibited growth during dormancy. ||The metabolic preparedness component of growth competence restoration encompasses the restoration of biosynthetic pathway capacity to support the rapid synthesis of proteins, nucleic acids, cell wall materials, and membranes required for cell division and expansion, with metabolic enzyme systems poised for rapid activation upon growth initiation. ||The symplastic connectivity restoration through callose degradation at plasmodesmata re-establishes the cell-to-cell communication required for coordinated growth responses across meristematic tissues. ||The verification of growth competence restoration relies on forcing tests demonstrating rapid and complete budbreak under optimal conditions, with fully competent buds achieving visible growth within 10-14 days at 22°C in contrast to the extended times characteristic of incompletely restored buds. ||The timing of competence restoration varies among buds on a vine, potentially creating heterogeneity that affects subsequent budbreak uniformity, with factors including bud position, light exposure history, and local microenvironment influencing the rate of restoration at individual bud positions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Cooke JE, Eriksson ME, Junttila O (2012) The dynamic nature of bud dormancy in trees: environmental control and molecular mechanisms. Plant Cell and Environment 35: 1707-1728"
},

  "Environmental_Constraint": {
  "definition": "An Environmental_Constraint is an Ecodormancy comprising the external factors preventing growth initiation in growth-competent buds, primarily temperature limitation and secondarily moisture limitation, during late winter and early spring.",
  "alternative_term": "environmental limitation | external growth constraint | environmental growth inhibition | climatic constraint |+ Umweltbeschränkung | externe Wachstumsbeschränkung | umweltbedingte Wachstumshemmung | klimatische Beschränkung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in the Médoc, Bordeaux, environmental constraint maintains bud quiescence from early February when chilling requirements are satisfied through late March when spring warming releases constraint, with mean February temperatures of 7-9°C remaining below the 10°C base temperature threshold and preventing budbreak despite fully restored growth competence, until sustained March warming provides sufficient growing degree day accumulation for growth initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Environmental_Constraint represents the external limitation phase within Ecodormancy addressing factors that prevent growth in competent buds. ||Distinguished from internal inhibition characteristic of endodormancy. ||Subdivides into Temperature_Limitation, Moisture_Limitation, and Conditional_Growth_Suppression as component factors. ||Primary constraint is temperature below approximately 10°C base. ||Duration from dormancy release through budbreak initiation. ||Progressive release through spring warming and heat accumulation. || This constraint operates from the completion of dormancy release through budbreak initiation, representing the interval during which growth-competent buds await environmental conditions permissive for development. ||The temperature component of environmental constraint is quantified through the concept of base temperature below which metabolic and developmental processes cannot proceed at rates sufficient for growth, typically 10°C for grapevine, with temperatures below this threshold effectively preventing growth regardless of bud competence. ||The molecular basis of temperature constraint involves the temperature-dependence of enzyme activities required for biosynthesis and energy metabolism, the requirement for adequate ATP production to support anabolic processes, and the temperature sensitivity of hormone signaling pathways that transduce environmental signals into developmental responses. ||The practical effect of temperature constraint is to delay budbreak until accumulated warmth has satisfied the heat requirement for growth initiation, with this delay providing protection against frost damage by preventing premature growth during the period when late frosts remain likely. ||The intensity of environmental constraint varies with ambient conditions, with continuous cold maintaining strong constraint while warming periods reduce constraint and may trigger partial growth responses if sustained, creating the characteristic fluctuating bud development often observed during transitional spring weather. ||The moisture constraint component relates to the requirement for adequate soil water availability to support the cellular expansion and transpiration associated with active growth, though moisture limitation during early spring is uncommon in most viticultural regions where winter precipitation has recharged soil water reserves. ||The release of environmental constraint occurs progressively as spring warming provides increasing heat unit accumulation, eventually crossing the threshold for budbreak initiation when accumulated growing degree days satisfy the cultivar-specific heat requirement.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216"
},

  "Temperature_Limitation": {
  "definition": "A Temperature_Limitation is an Environmental_Constraint defined by ambient temperatures below the threshold required for growth-supporting metabolic and developmental processes preventing bud burst initiation in growth-competent buds.",
  "alternative_term": "thermal limitation | cold constraint | temperature growth limitation | thermal growth inhibition |+ Temperaturbeschränkung | thermische Limitation | Kältebeschränkung | temperaturbedingte Wachstumshemmung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Gris vines in Oregon's Willamette Valley, temperature limitation maintains ecodormancy from early February through late March, with February mean temperatures of 6-8°C providing minimal growing degree day accumulation above the 10°C base temperature, March warming gradually increasing GDD accumulation to approximately 80 units by month end, and budbreak occurring in early April when accumulated GDD reach the cultivar threshold of approximately 120-150 units.",
  "editor_note": "Temperature_Limitation represents the primary environmental constraint within Environmental_Constraint specifically addressing thermal control of ecodormancy. ||Distinguished from Moisture_Limitation which addresses water-related constraints. ||Operates through temperature-dependence of metabolic reaction rates. ||Base temperature approximately 10°C for grapevine. ||Quantified through growing degree day accumulation. ||Release progressive with spring warming. ||Cultivar heat requirements typically 100-300 GDD for budbreak. || This temperature-based control mechanism operates through the fundamental temperature-dependence of biological reaction rates, with temperatures below approximately 10°C being insufficient to support the sustained metabolic activity required for cell division, expansion, and the coordinated developmental processes of budbreak. ||The biochemical basis of temperature limitation involves the temperature-dependence of enzyme catalysis according to Arrhenius kinetics, with reaction rates declining exponentially as temperature decreases below optima, eventually reaching levels insufficient to sustain net biosynthesis and growth even when all regulatory constraints have been removed. ||The cellular processes limited by low temperature include mitochondrial respiration required for ATP production, protein synthesis requiring coordinated ribosome function, cell wall biosynthesis involving multiple enzymatic steps, and membrane biogenesis necessary for cell expansion, all of which must proceed at adequate rates for growth to occur. ||The concept of base temperature defines the threshold below which these processes cannot support growth, with grapevine typically exhibiting a base temperature near 10°C though some variation exists among cultivars and the effective base temperature may differ for different developmental processes. ||The quantification of temperature limitation uses growing degree day accumulation above the base temperature, with each degree above threshold contributing to the cumulative heat exposure required for budbreak, typically 100-300 growing degree days depending on cultivar and environmental history. ||The release from temperature limitation occurs progressively as spring warming increases the frequency and duration of above-threshold temperatures, accumulating growing degree days until the cultivar-specific requirement is satisfied and budbreak commences. ||The non-linear nature of temperature responses means that a few warm days can contribute substantially to heat accumulation, while extended cool periods contribute little, making budbreak timing sensitive to temperature variability during late winter and early spring.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || Moncur MW et al (1989) Base temperatures for budbreak and leaf appearance of grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 40: 21-26"
},

  "Moisture_Limitation": {
  "definition": "A Moisture_Limitation is an Environmental_Constraint defined by soil water availability insufficient to support cellular expansion and metabolic activity associated with growth initiation in growth-competent buds.",
  "alternative_term": "water limitation | moisture constraint | drought limitation | water deficit constraint |+ Feuchtebeschränkung | Wasserlimitation | Trockenheitsbeschränkung | Wasserdefizit-Beschränkung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Tempranillo vines in central Spain during a dry winter, moisture limitation contributed to delayed budbreak in early April despite adequate heat accumulation, with soil water content declining to 15% of field capacity by late March due to below-average winter precipitation, pre-dawn leaf water potential of -0.5 MPa indicating mild water stress, and irrigation application required to relieve moisture constraint and enable normal budbreak progression.",
  "editor_note": "Moisture_Limitation represents a secondary environmental constraint within Environmental_Constraint addressing water-related growth limitation. ||Distinguished from Temperature_Limitation which is the primary ecodormancy constraint. ||Typically less important than temperature in most regions due to winter precipitation. ||Significant mainly in winter-drought regions, shallow soils, or abnormally dry years. ||Detected through soil moisture and vine water potential monitoring. ||Pre-dawn water potential more negative than -0.3 MPa indicates potential limitation. || The physiological basis of moisture limitation relates to the fundamental requirement for water in cellular expansion, with cell enlargement depending on turgor pressure generated by water uptake, and inadequate water availability preventing the turgor development necessary for cell wall extension and growth. ||The metabolic dimension of moisture limitation involves the requirement for adequate water status to maintain enzyme function, support transpiration-driven nutrient uptake, and enable the biochemical reactions of biosynthesis that depend on aqueous cellular environments. ||In most viticultural regions, moisture limitation during ecodormancy is uncommon because winter precipitation typically recharges soil water reserves, providing adequate moisture for early spring growth even in regions with summer drought stress, with dormant vines having minimal water requirements that are easily met by residual soil moisture. ||The situations where moisture limitation becomes significant during ecodormancy include regions with winter drought patterns, particularly Mediterranean climates with irregular precipitation, vineyards on sandy or shallow soils with low water holding capacity, and years with abnormally low winter precipitation that fails to adequately recharge soil water reserves. ||The interaction between temperature and moisture limitation can affect budbreak timing, with adequate moisture enabling rapid growth response when temperature constraint is released, while moisture deficit may delay or limit growth even when temperatures become favorable, though this interaction is rarely significant in well-managed vineyards with appropriate site selection. ||The detection of moisture limitation during ecodormancy involves monitoring soil water status and vine water potential, with pre-dawn water potential values more negative than -0.3 to -0.4 MPa potentially indicating moisture stress that could affect budbreak, though such values are uncommon during the typically wet late winter period in most grape-growing regions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 3 Water Relations and Nutrient Uptake || Williams LE, Baeza P (2007) Relationships among ambient temperature and vapor pressure deficit and leaf and stem water potentials of fully irrigated, field-grown grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 58: 173-181 || Schultz HR (2003) Differences in hydraulic architecture account for near-isohydric and anisohydric behaviour of two field-grown Vitis vinifera L. cultivars during drought. Plant Cell and Environment 26: 1393-1405"
},

  "Conditional_Growth_Suppression": {
  "definition": "A Conditional_Growth_Suppression is an Ecodormancy bearing the disposition for immediate growth resumption upon provision of favorable environmental conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "reversible growth suppression | environment-dependent inhibition | conditional quiescence | reversible dormancy |+ bedingte Wachstumsunterdrückung | reversible Wachstumshemmung | umweltabhängige Inhibition | bedingte Ruhe",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc vines in Marlborough, New Zealand, conditional growth suppression maintains ecodormancy through August and early September, with the conditional nature demonstrated by forcing test response showing budbreak within 11 days at 20°C and by field observations of partial bud swelling during warm periods in late August followed by growth arrest when cool conditions return, illustrating the reversible environment-dependent nature of suppression during ecodormancy.",
  "editor_note": "Conditional_Growth_Suppression represents the reversible nature of growth inhibition within Environmental_Constraint. ||Distinguished from unconditional suppression during endodormancy which persists regardless of conditions. ||Demonstrated by immediate growth response to favorable forcing conditions. ||Creates frost vulnerability due to potential premature growth during warm periods. ||Intensity varies continuously with temperature conditions. ||Transition to growth when favorable conditions persist sufficiently for heat unit accumulation. || This conditional nature distinguishes ecodormancy fundamentally from endodormancy, where growth suppression persists regardless of environmental conditions until internal changes associated with chilling release the dormant state. ||The mechanistic basis of conditional suppression involves the absence of internal inhibitory mechanisms, with growth-competent buds poised for immediate response to favorable signals, and suppression depending entirely on environmental temperatures being insufficient to support the metabolic rates required for growth processes. ||The reversibility of conditional suppression is demonstrated through forcing tests where transfer of ecodormant buds to favorable temperature immediately initiates growth processes leading to budbreak within 10-14 days, in contrast to endodormant buds where forcing conditions fail to reverse internal inhibition and budbreak requires extended periods or does not occur. ||The practical implications of conditional growth suppression relate to frost vulnerability, as the reversible nature of suppression means that temporary warm periods during late winter can trigger partial or complete growth initiation that is then damaged when temperatures return to suppressive levels, representing a significant difference from the more robust suppression during endodormancy that protects against such false spring responses. ||The intensity of conditional suppression varies continuously with environmental conditions, with strong suppression during cold periods, weakening suppression during mild conditions, and no suppression when temperatures exceed the threshold for growth support, creating the dynamic response to weather variability characteristic of the ecodormancy period. ||The transition from conditional to active growth occurs when favorable conditions persist long enough to accumulate sufficient heat units for budbreak initiation, at which point the previously suppressed growth processes proceed to visible developmental changes marking the end of dormancy and beginning of the new growing season.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Conditional_Dormancy": {
  "definition": "A Conditional_Dormancy is an Ecodormancy bearing the disposition for reversible transition between quiescence and active growth in response to changes in environmental favorability.",
  "alternative_term": "environment-dependent dormancy | conditional quiescence | weather-dependent dormancy | facultative dormancy |+ bedingte Dormanz | umweltabhängige Dormanz | konditionale Ruhe | fakultative Dormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chenin Blanc vines in the Loire Valley, conditional dormancy persists from early February through late March, with the conditional nature demonstrated by partial bud swelling during mid-February warm periods with temperatures of 12-15°C followed by growth arrest when temperatures return to 5-8°C, and eventual budbreak occurring in late March when sustained warming provides sufficient heat accumulation for irreversible growth commitment.",
  "editor_note": "Conditional_Dormancy represents a characteristic state within Ecodormancy describing the environment-dependent nature of growth control. ||Distinguished from unconditional endodormancy by the reversible, environment-responsive nature of quiescence. ||Subdivides into Environment_Dependent_Quiescence, Reversible_Growth_Suppression, and Weather_Responsive_Dormancy as component aspects. ||Duration varies with climate from weeks to months. ||Creates weather-dependent budbreak timing variability. ||Characterized by absence of internal inhibitory mechanisms. || This conditional nature fundamentally distinguishes ecodormancy from the unconditional growth inhibition of endodormancy, where internal factors prevent growth regardless of environmental conditions until chilling-dependent release processes have been completed. ||The physiological basis of conditional dormancy involves the absence of internal growth-inhibiting mechanisms that were active during endodormancy, leaving environmental factors as the sole determinants of bud behavior, with growth-competent buds responding dynamically to temperature fluctuations and other environmental variables throughout the ecodormancy period. ||The conditionality is manifest in the immediate reversibility of quiescence, with buds transitioning toward growth when conditions become favorable and reverting to quiescence when conditions become unfavorable, creating the dynamic relationship between bud status and environment that characterizes the late winter and early spring period. ||The practical implications of conditional dormancy for viticulture relate to the variable and weather-dependent nature of budbreak timing, with warm late winters potentially advancing budbreak into periods of frost risk while cold springs may delay growth beyond optimal timing, creating management challenges that are absent during the more predictable endodormancy period. ||The molecular state during conditional dormancy reflects the completion of dormancy release, with low ABA concentrations, minimal DAM gene expression, derepressed growth gene promoters, and restored hormone signaling systems that enable rapid response to growth-promoting conditions when they occur. ||The duration of conditional dormancy varies with climate, extending for longer periods in cold continental regions where spring warming is delayed and for shorter periods in Mediterranean climates where mild temperatures follow closely after chilling completion, with the transition from conditional dormancy to active growth occurring when sustained favorable conditions accumulate sufficient heat units to trigger budbreak initiation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Environment_Dependent_Quiescence": {
  "definition": "An Environment_Dependent_Quiescence is an Ecodormancy bearing the disposition for immediate transition to active development upon environmental shift to growth-favorable conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "environmentally-imposed quiescence | external condition dependent dormancy | environment-controlled inactivity | exogenous quiescence |+ umweltabhängige Ruhe | extern bedingte Quieszenz | umweltkontrollierte Inaktivität | exogene Ruhe",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Willamette Valley, Oregon, environment dependent quiescence maintains bud inactivity from early February through mid-March, with quiescence entirely dependent on temperatures remaining below 10°C as demonstrated by immediate growth initiation when single-node cuttings are transferred to 22°C forcing conditions, achieving visible bud swelling within 5 days and full budbreak within 10 days, illustrating the absence of internal barriers to growth.",
  "editor_note": "Environment_Dependent_Quiescence represents the externally-determined inactive state within Conditional_Dormancy. ||Distinguished from internally-determined endodormancy by complete dependence on environmental factors. ||Demonstrated by immediate forcing response without delay. ||Temperature is the primary determining factor with base threshold approximately 10°C. ||Metabolic activity continues at low levels during quiescence. ||Transition to growth requires sustained favorable conditions and heat unit accumulation. || This quiescence differs fundamentally from the dormancy of endodormancy in being externally imposed rather than internally generated, with no physiological barriers to growth existing within the bud itself and quiescence depending entirely on the environmental context. ||The temperature-dependence of quiescence reflects the fundamental requirement for adequate warmth to support the metabolic processes of growth, with temperatures below approximately 10°C being insufficient to sustain the enzyme activities, biosynthetic reactions, and cellular processes required for cell division and expansion regardless of the growth competence of bud tissues. ||The immediate responsiveness of environment dependent quiescence to changing conditions is demonstrated by forcing experiments, where transfer of ecodormant buds to warm conditions immediately initiates growth processes without the delay characteristic of endodormant material, and by field observations showing partial growth responses during warm spells followed by return to quiescence when temperatures decline. ||The ecological function of environment dependent quiescence is to synchronize growth resumption with reliably favorable conditions, with temperature serving as an indicator of seasonal progression that correlates with reduced frost risk and adequate conditions for sustained growth, though this synchronization is imperfect and vulnerable to unseasonable weather patterns. ||The metabolic state during quiescence involves minimal but not absent activity, with some respiratory metabolism continuing at rates determined by temperature, gradual accumulation of growth-related transcripts and proteins in preparation for growth, and maintenance of cellular structures in a state ready for rapid activation when conditions permit. ||The transition from quiescence to active growth occurs when environmental conditions become and remain favorable long enough to trigger irreversible commitment to budbreak, typically requiring accumulation of 100-300 growing degree days above the base temperature threshold.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46"
},

  "Reversible_Growth_Suppression": {
  "definition": "A Reversible_Growth_Suppression is an Ecodormancy bearing the disposition for immediate reversal of growth suppression upon provision of favorable conditions, in contrast to chilling-dependent release of endodormancy.",
  "alternative_term": "reversible dormancy | reversible growth inhibition | conditional suppression | temporary growth arrest |+ reversible Wachstumsunterdrückung | reversible Dormanz | bedingte Unterdrückung | vorübergehender Wachstumsstopp",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Burgundy, reversible growth suppression is demonstrated during February and March when warm periods with temperatures of 14-16°C induce visible bud swelling to BBCH stage 01-03, followed by growth arrest and maintenance of swollen bud state when temperatures return to 4-7°C, with this reversible pattern continuing until sustained April warming provides irreversible commitment to budbreak progression through BBCH stage 05 and beyond.",
  "editor_note": "Reversible_Growth_Suppression represents the reversibility characteristic within Conditional_Dormancy. ||Distinguished from irreversible endodormancy suppression that persists regardless of conditions. ||Demonstrated by immediate forcing response and field stop-and-start growth patterns. ||Reflects absence of stable internal growth barriers. ||Creates frost vulnerability from premature growth response. ||Transition to irreversible growth after green tip emergence typically at BBCH 07-09. || This reversibility reflects the absence of stable internal barriers to growth during ecodormancy, with growth suppression depending entirely on the immediate environmental context rather than on persistent physiological states that require time and specific conditions for removal. ||The cellular basis of reversibility involves the maintenance of growth-ready cellular states during ecodormancy, with cell cycle machinery poised for activation, biosynthetic enzyme systems prepared for rapid upregulation, and hormone signaling pathways sensitized to respond to growth-promoting conditions, enabling immediate growth response when suppressive conditions are relieved. ||The practical demonstration of reversibility uses forcing tests that expose ecodormant buds to optimal growth conditions and measure the speed of growth response, with reversible suppression indicated by rapid budbreak within 10-14 days contrasting with the extended times or failure characteristic of the irreversible suppression of endodormancy. ||The field manifestation of reversibility includes the partial growth responses commonly observed during warm periods in late winter, with buds initiating swelling or other early growth stages during favorable conditions and arresting development when temperatures return to suppressive levels, creating the stop-and-start growth pattern characteristic of transitional spring weather. ||The ecological implications of reversible suppression relate to frost vulnerability, as the capacity for immediate growth response to warming creates the risk that temporary favorable conditions will trigger growth that is subsequently damaged by return to cold temperatures, a risk that is absent during endodormancy when irreversible suppression protects against such responses. ||The transition from reversible suppression to committed growth occurs when favorable conditions persist long enough to pass a point of no return in the budbreak process, after which growth continues even if conditions subsequently become unfavorable, typically occurring after visible bud swelling has progressed to green tip emergence.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Weather_Responsive_Dormancy": {
  "definition": "A Weather_Responsive_Dormancy is an Ecodormancy exhibiting continuous modulation of bud activity in response to prevailing meteorological conditions with growth activity rising during favorable weather and falling during unfavorable weather.",
  "alternative_term": "weather-dependent dormancy | meteorologically responsive quiescence | climate-responsive dormancy | weather-driven dormancy |+ wetterabhängige Dormanz | meteorologisch responsive Ruhe | klimaabhängige Dormanz | wettergesteuerte Dormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Rheingau, weather responsive dormancy during February and March creates year-to-year budbreak timing variation of 2-3 weeks depending on spring temperature patterns, with warm springs providing rapid heat accumulation and early budbreak in late March, cool springs delaying heat accumulation and budbreak until mid-April, and this weather responsiveness quantified through growing degree day tracking that enables budbreak prediction within approximately 5 days accuracy when initiated from late February.",
  "editor_note": "Weather_Responsive_Dormancy represents the dynamic weather-bud relationship within Conditional_Dormancy. ||Distinguished from weather-independent endodormancy status. ||Creates year-to-year budbreak timing variability of 2-4 weeks typically. ||Quantified through growing degree day accumulation models. ||Complicates budbreak prediction beyond short-term weather forecasts. ||Response timescales range from immediate metabolic effects to developmental progress over weeks. ||Base temperature typically 10°C with requirements of 100-300 GDD for budbreak. || This responsiveness creates the characteristic weather-dependent variability in budbreak timing and progression observed during late winter and early spring, contrasting with the weather-independent dormancy of endodormancy where bud status is determined by internal factors regardless of external conditions. ||The physiological basis of weather responsiveness involves the absence of buffering internal regulatory mechanisms, leaving bud physiology directly coupled to environmental temperature through the fundamental temperature-dependence of metabolic reaction rates, with warming accelerating growth-related processes and cooling decelerating them in direct proportion to temperature effects on enzyme activities and cellular processes. ||The time-scale of weather responsiveness ranges from immediate biochemical responses to temperature changes affecting metabolic rates, through short-term responses over days affecting gene expression and protein accumulation, to longer-term developmental responses over weeks determining progress toward budbreak, with all these timescales contributing to the overall relationship between weather and bud status. ||The practical consequences of weather responsive dormancy for viticulture include the difficulty of predicting budbreak timing more than a few weeks in advance due to dependence on future weather patterns, the need for flexible frost protection strategies that can respond to weather-driven variation in bud developmental stage, and the potential for weather extremes to advance or delay budbreak outside normal timing windows. ||The quantitative relationship between weather and dormancy status is captured by growing degree day models that integrate temperature exposure over time, with accumulated heat units providing a measure of progress toward budbreak that accounts for the varying intensity of growth-promoting conditions experienced during different weather patterns. ||The transition from weather responsive dormancy to active growth represents the point where accumulated weather-driven progress has satisfied the thermal requirement for budbreak, typically occurring after 100-300 growing degree days have accumulated above the base temperature following completion of chilling requirement.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Moncur MW et al (1989) Base temperatures for budbreak and leaf appearance of grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 40: 21-26"
},

  "Quiescence_Maintenance": {
  "definition": "A Quiescence_Maintenance is an Ecodormancy comprising sustained preservation of the ecodormant state through ongoing environmental limitation of growth in the absence of internal inhibitory mechanisms.",
  "alternative_term": "sustained quiescence | maintained dormant state | continued environmental dormancy | persistent ecodormancy |+ Quieszenz-Aufrechterhaltung | anhaltende Ruhe | fortgesetzte Umweltdormanz | persistierende Ekodormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Franc vines in Chinon, Loire Valley, quiescence maintenance extends from early February when chilling requirements are satisfied through late March when spring warming triggers budbreak, with quiescence maintained by mean temperatures of 6-9°C during February and early March that are insufficient to support growth despite fully restored bud competence, and terminating when late March temperatures consistently exceed 10°C and accumulated growing degree days reach the threshold for budbreak initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Quiescence_Maintenance represents the sustained inactive state within Ecodormancy during the period between dormancy release and budbreak. ||Distinguished from active Dormancy_Maintenance during endodormancy by passive rather than active inhibition. ||Subdivides into Sustained_Environmental_Inhibition, Low_Temperature_Constraint, and Pre_Budbreak_Quiescence as component aspects. ||Duration varies from weeks to months with climate. ||Involves gradual preparatory changes despite maintained inactivity. ||Terminates with spring warming and heat unit accumulation. || This maintenance phase extends from the completion of endodormancy release through the onset of sustained favorable conditions that trigger budbreak, encompassing the period of waiting during which growth-competent buds remain inactive due solely to environmental inadequacy for growth support. ||The mechanistic basis of quiescence maintenance differs fundamentally from endodormancy maintenance in involving no active regulatory suppression, with quiescence being a passive consequence of environmental limitation rather than an actively maintained physiological state, and with growth occurring immediately when environmental limitation is removed without requiring any release process. ||The temperature basis of quiescence maintenance involves the continuous operation of thermal limitation on growth processes, with temperatures below the approximately 10°C base threshold being insufficient to support the sustained metabolic activity required for net biosynthesis and development, effectively preventing growth regardless of bud competence. ||The duration of quiescence maintenance varies substantially with climate and season, ranging from a few weeks in mild Mediterranean climates to several months in cold continental regions, and varying year-to-year within regions depending on the timing of spring warming relative to chilling completion. ||The metabolic state during maintained quiescence involves continued low-level activity that gradually prepares buds for growth, with slow accumulation of growth-related transcripts and proteins, gradual metabolic reactivation within the constraints imposed by temperature, and maintenance of cellular integrity and viability throughout the quiescent period. ||The termination of quiescence maintenance occurs when environmental limitation is removed through sustained warming that provides sufficient heat accumulation for budbreak initiation, marking the transition from dormancy to active growth that begins the new growing season.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Sustained_Environmental_Inhibition": {
  "definition": "A Sustained_Environmental_Inhibition is a Quiescence_Maintenance realized through the continuous operation of unfavorable temperature and related environmental factors below thresholds required for growth support.",
  "alternative_term": "continuous environmental suppression | persistent external inhibition | maintained environmental constraint | ongoing thermal inhibition |+ anhaltende Umwelthemmung | kontinuierliche externe Suppression | persistierende Umweltbeschränkung | fortgesetzte thermische Inhibition",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner vines in the Wachau, Austria, sustained environmental inhibition maintains quiescence from early February through mid-March, with continuous inhibition by mean temperatures of 3-7°C preventing any visible growth activity despite fully competent buds, interrupted briefly by a late February warm period with temperatures of 13-15°C that induced slight bud swelling before inhibition was re-established by return to cold conditions, and finally released by sustained March warming that accumulated sufficient growing degree days for budbreak initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Sustained_Environmental_Inhibition represents the continuous suppression aspect of Quiescence_Maintenance. ||Distinguished from active internal inhibition by dependence solely on environmental conditions. ||Temperature is the primary inhibitory factor with threshold approximately 10°C. ||Continuity depends on consistency of unfavorable conditions. ||Hidden preparatory changes occur despite apparent inactivity. ||Release occurs through sustained warming and heat unit accumulation. ||Duration varies with climate and seasonal weather patterns. || This inhibition operates from the completion of endodormancy through budbreak, maintaining bud quiescence through the continuous inadequacy of environmental conditions for growth rather than through any active suppression mechanism within the bud. ||The temperature basis of sustained inhibition involves the fundamental requirement for adequate warmth to support the metabolic processes underlying growth, with sustained temperatures below approximately 10°C preventing the enzyme activities, biosynthetic reactions, and cellular processes required for cell division and expansion regardless of the growth readiness of bud tissues. ||The continuity of environmental inhibition depends on the consistency of unfavorable conditions, with uninterrupted cold maintaining uninterrupted quiescence, while interruptions by warm periods create temporary relief from inhibition that may trigger partial growth responses before inhibition is re-established upon return to cold conditions. ||The cellular state under sustained inhibition reflects the poised readiness for growth characteristic of ecodormancy, with cell cycle machinery prepared for activation, biosynthetic capacity available for upregulation, and hormone response systems sensitized for growth signal transduction, all awaiting only the relief of environmental inhibition to proceed. ||The gradual changes occurring under sustained inhibition include slow accumulation of growth-related gene products, progressive metabolic reactivation within temperature-imposed limits, and ultrastructural changes in meristematic cells preparing for division, representing the hidden progress toward budbreak that occurs even during apparent inactivity. ||The release from sustained inhibition occurs when environmental conditions improve sufficiently to support growth processes, with the transition from inhibition to active growth being determined by heat unit accumulation above the base temperature threshold reaching the level required for budbreak initiation.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216"
},

  "Low_Temperature_Constraint": {
  "definition": "A Low_Temperature_Constraint is a Sustained_Environmental_Inhibition defined by ambient temperatures below the threshold required for growth-supporting metabolic activity preventing bud burst initiation in growth-competent buds.",
  "alternative_term": "cold temperature limitation | thermal growth constraint | low temperature inhibition | cold constraint |+ Tieftemperatur-Beschränkung | thermische Wachstumsbeschränkung | Kälte-Limitation | Niedertemperatur-Hemmung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux, low temperature constraint maintains ecodormancy from early February through late March, with mean February temperatures of 7-9°C providing strong constraint that prevents budbreak despite restored growth competence, constraint gradually weakening through March as mean temperatures increase to 10-12°C allowing growing degree day accumulation, and constraint fully relieved by late March when sustained temperatures of 12-15°C provide the heat accumulation required for budbreak initiation at BBCH stage 05.",
  "editor_note": "Low_Temperature_Constraint represents the specific thermal limitation within Quiescence_Maintenance. ||Base temperature threshold approximately 10°C for grapevine. ||Constraint intensity varies continuously with temperature from strong at low temperatures to absent above threshold. ||Quantified through heat deficit and growing degree day concepts. ||Diurnal and seasonal variation affects constraint intensity. ||Relief through warming and heat unit accumulation. ||Primary determining factor for ecodormancy duration and budbreak timing. || This temperature-based control operates throughout the ecodormancy period as the primary factor determining bud status, with the constraint intensity varying continuously with ambient temperature from strong constraint at low temperatures to weak or absent constraint at temperatures above the growth threshold. ||The biochemical basis of low temperature constraint involves the fundamental temperature-dependence of enzyme-catalyzed reactions following Arrhenius kinetics, with reaction rates declining exponentially as temperature decreases, eventually falling below levels sufficient to sustain net biosynthesis and the coordinated cellular processes required for growth and development. ||The threshold temperature below which constraint effectively prevents growth, termed the base temperature, is approximately 10°C for grapevine budbreak, though some variation exists among cultivars and the effective threshold may differ slightly for different component processes of budbreak. ||The quantification of low temperature constraint uses the concept of heat deficit, representing the cumulative shortfall of temperature below the growth-supporting threshold, with constraint being relieved as warming provides temperatures above this threshold and allows accumulation of the growing degree days required for budbreak. ||The diurnal and seasonal variation in temperature creates corresponding variation in constraint intensity, with constraint being strongest during cold nights and winter conditions, and weakening during warm days and as seasonal warming progresses, creating the gradual relief of constraint that eventually permits budbreak. ||The interaction between low temperature constraint and bud developmental status affects budbreak characteristics, with buds that have accumulated some heat units during intermittent warming being closer to the budbreak threshold and requiring less additional warming for growth initiation than buds that have experienced consistently cold conditions throughout ecodormancy.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Moncur MW et al (1989) Base temperatures for budbreak and leaf appearance of grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 40: 21-26 || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Pre_Budbreak_Quiescence": {
  "definition": "A Pre_Budbreak_Quiescence is an Ecodormancy comprising the final ecodormant phase immediately preceding bud burst with growth-competent buds bearing accumulated but not yet sufficient heat exposure for growth initiation.",
  "alternative_term": "late ecodormancy | pre-growth quiescence | imminent budbreak state | near-budbreak dormancy |+ Vor-Austrieb-Ruhe | späte Ekodormanz | Kurz-vor-Austrieb-Quieszenz | austriebsnahe Dormanz",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Côte d'Or, Burgundy, pre budbreak quiescence extends through the final two weeks of March when accumulated growing degree days have reached 80-120 units toward the approximately 150-unit threshold for budbreak, with buds showing subtle swelling at BBCH stage 01, scale margins beginning to separate, and internal examination revealing enlarged meristematic zones with cells preparing for division, before transition to active budbreak occurs in early April when accumulated GDD cross the threshold.",
  "editor_note": "Pre_Budbreak_Quiescence represents the final transitional phase within Quiescence_Maintenance immediately before visible growth. ||Distinguished from earlier quiescence by advanced preparatory state and proximity to growth threshold. ||Characterized by elevated metabolic activity, increased gene expression, and hormonal changes preparing for growth. ||Subtle visible changes may include bud swelling at BBCH 00-01. ||Duration typically 1-3 weeks depending on warming rate. ||Transition to active growth when heat unit threshold is crossed. || This phase typically occurs during the final 1-3 weeks before budbreak when warming temperatures are providing increasing heat unit accumulation but the threshold for visible growth has not yet been crossed, with buds in an advanced state of readiness that will transition to active growth upon receipt of relatively small additional heat input. ||The physiological state during pre budbreak quiescence involves advanced preparation for growth, with metabolic activity substantially elevated above deep dormancy levels, growth-related gene expression increased, protein synthesis accelerated in preparation for the demands of cell division and expansion, and cellular ultrastructure modified toward the actively dividing configuration characteristic of growing meristems. ||The hormonal changes during pre budbreak quiescence include declining ABA to minimal levels, increasing cytokinin activity as root function increases with soil warming, elevated gibberellin signaling preparing for cell elongation, and sensitized auxin transport systems ready to establish the polar gradients required for organized growth. ||The visual appearance during pre budbreak quiescence may include subtle changes such as slight bud swelling, color changes in bud scales, or emergence of woolly trichomes at scale margins, representing the earliest externally visible signs of the internal changes preparing for growth, corresponding to BBCH stages 00-01. ||The transition from pre budbreak quiescence to active budbreak occurs when accumulated heat units cross the threshold for growth commitment, typically after 100-300 growing degree days depending on cultivar, at which point visible bud swelling accelerates and the irreversible process of budbreak commences with progression through subsequent BBCH stages. ||The duration of pre budbreak quiescence varies with the rate of heat accumulation, being compressed during rapid spring warming and extended during gradual or interrupted warming patterns.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lorenz DH et al (1995) Growth stages of the grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine - BBCH-scale. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1: 100-103"
},

  "Dormancy_Release": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Release is a Dormancy comprising the terminal phase of the dormancy cycle realized through completion of chilling requirements, restoration of bud competence, and response to warming temperatures producing the transition from winter dormancy to active spring growth.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy termination | dormancy ending | dormancy break | growth resumption |+ Dormanzlösung | Dormanzbeendigung | Dormanzbruch | Wachstumswiederaufnahme",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Côte d'Or, Burgundy, dormancy release proceeds through February and March with chilling completion achieved by early February after approximately 1100 chilling hours, followed by progressive heat accumulation through February and March reaching approximately 150 growing degree days by late March, with visible budbreak commencing in early April as the final stage of dormancy release marks the transition to active growth at BBCH stage 05.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Release represents the fourth and final major phase within the Dormancy hierarchy, encompassing all processes leading to growth resumption. ||Distinguished from Ecodormancy which represents maintained quiescence, while Dormancy_Release specifically addresses the termination of dormancy and transition to growth. ||Subdivides into Chilling_Completion, Bud_Competence_Restoration, Heat_Accumulation_Response, and Dormancy_Break as component phases. ||Timing determined by sequential chilling and heat requirement satisfaction. ||Corresponds to transition from BBCH 00 through BBCH 09. || This process encompasses the final events of dormancy termination occurring during late winter and early spring, integrating the completion of endodormancy release through chilling satisfaction with the subsequent ecodormancy release through heat accumulation to achieve the fully growth-competent and growth-active state. ||The physiological basis of dormancy release involves the completion of all chilling-dependent changes that dismantle endodormancy maintaining mechanisms, followed by the heat-dependent activation of growth processes that overcomes the environmental constraints of ecodormancy, culminating in the visible developmental changes of budbreak. ||The molecular markers of dormancy release completion include ABA concentrations reduced to levels characteristic of growing tissues, DAM gene expression at minimal or undetectable levels, growth gene promoters fully derepressed and transcriptionally active, and cell cycle machinery engaged in active progression through division cycles. ||The timing of dormancy release is determined by the sequential satisfaction of chilling and heat requirements, with chilling completion typically occurring during late January to February and heat accumulation proceeding through late winter and early spring until the threshold for budbreak is reached, typically after 100-300 growing degree days above the base temperature. ||The practical importance of dormancy release timing relates to the synchronization of growth with favorable environmental conditions, with optimal release timing balancing the benefits of early growth initiation against the risks of frost damage to emerging shoots, and with release timing variability among cultivars contributing to their adaptation to different climatic regions. ||The consequences of incomplete or abnormal dormancy release include delayed, prolonged, or uneven budbreak that complicates vineyard management, reduced shoot vigor from inadequate chilling, and potential yield impacts from poorly developed shoots, highlighting the importance of adequate dormancy release for vineyard productivity. ||Climate change poses challenges to dormancy release in many regions through effects on both chilling accumulation and heat accumulation timing, potentially disrupting the evolved synchronization between dormancy release and optimal growth conditions.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lang GA et al (1987) Endo-, para-, and ecodormancy: physiological terminology and classification for dormancy research. HortScience 22: 371-377 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Chilling_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Chilling_Completion is a Dormancy_Release marking the full satisfaction of the chilling requirement and the dismantling of all dormancy-maintaining mechanisms enabling unrestricted growth response to favorable conditions.",
  "alternative_term": "chilling fulfillment | chill requirement completion | full chilling achievement | chilling satisfaction | Chilling-Abschluss |+ Kältebedürfnis-Vollendung | vollständige Kälteerfüllung | Chilling-Befriedigung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Rheingau, Germany, chilling completion occurs in late January to early February when accumulated chilling hours reach the cultivar requirement of approximately 1200-1400 hours, verified by forcing tests showing budbreak within 10 days at 22°C and greater than 95% bud break success rate, marking the definitive end of endodormancy and enabling subsequent response to spring warming for budbreak initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Chilling_Completion represents the first component phase of Dormancy_Release marking definitive endodormancy termination. ||Distinguished from Chilling_Accumulation which addresses the progressive process, while Chilling_Completion specifically marks full requirement satisfaction. ||Subdivides into Chilling_Requirement_Met, Full_Chill_Accumulation, and Competence_Achievement as component aspects. ||Verified by forcing test response less than 14 days with high success rate. ||Cultivar requirements range from approximately 400-1500 hours. ||Timing typically late January to February in Northern Hemisphere. || This milestone typically occurs during late January to February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, representing the point at which the genetically determined chilling requirement has been met or exceeded through accumulated winter cold exposure. ||The physiological significance of chilling completion lies in the full restoration of growth capacity, with all internal barriers to growth having been removed through the chilling-dependent reduction of ABA, silencing of DAM genes, derepression of growth gene chromatin, and restoration of cellular communication pathways that were restricted during endodormancy. ||The verification of chilling completion relies on forcing tests demonstrating rapid and complete budbreak response, with completed chilling indicated by budbreak times of less than 10-14 days under optimal forcing conditions and high percentages of buds successfully breaking, contrasting with the extended times and incomplete response characteristic of insufficient chilling. ||The quantification of chilling completion uses accumulated chilling hours or units according to various models, with completion defined as achieving or exceeding the cultivar-specific requirement that typically ranges from 400-600 hours for low-chill cultivars to 1200-1500 hours for high-chill cultivars when using the simple hours-below-7.2°C model. ||The margin by which chilling exceeds the minimum requirement affects subsequent growth characteristics, with substantial excess chilling potentially advancing budbreak timing while barely adequate chilling may result in acceptable but suboptimal budbreak uniformity. ||The timing of chilling completion relative to subsequent warming patterns determines the duration of ecodormancy and influences budbreak timing, with early chilling completion in warm winters creating extended ecodormancy periods while late completion in cold winters may be followed rapidly by warming that triggers immediate budbreak. ||The consequences of incomplete chilling, where the requirement is not fully satisfied, include the delayed, prolonged, and uneven budbreak characteristic of inadequate dormancy release that can significantly impact vineyard productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "skos:closeMatch # http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0097438 ## exit from dormancy | 0.85" ],
  "definition_source": "Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lavee S, May P (1997) Dormancy of grapevine buds - facts and speculation. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 3: 31-46"
},

  "Chilling_Requirement_Met": {
  "definition": "A Chilling_Requirement_Met is a Chilling_Completion defined by accumulated cold exposure equal to the genetically determined threshold for complete dormancy release.",
  "alternative_term": "chilling threshold reached | chill requirement satisfied | chilling quota achieved | dormancy chilling fulfilled |+ Kältebedarf-Erfüllung | Chilling-Schwelle-erreicht | Kälteanforderung-befriedigt | Dormanz-Kältequote-erreicht",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Bordeaux, chilling requirement met is achieved in early February when accumulated chilling hours of approximately 950 reach the cultivar threshold, demonstrated by forcing test response decreasing from 25 days in mid-January to 12 days by February 10, indicating that the chilling requirement has been satisfied and buds have transitioned from residual endodormancy to fully released ecodormancy status.",
  "editor_note": "Chilling_Requirement_Met represents the threshold achievement aspect of Chilling_Completion marking exact requirement satisfaction. ||Distinguished from progressive Chilling_Accumulation by representing the specific threshold crossing point. ||Defined by accumulated chilling equaling cultivar-specific requirement. ||Verified through forcing test response approaching minimum times. ||Requirements vary from approximately 400-1500 hours depending on cultivar origin. ||Critical transition point from partial to complete dormancy release. || This threshold achievement typically occurs during late January to February in Northern Hemisphere viticulture when cumulative chilling hours or units reach the cultivar-specific requirement through the integration of winter cold exposure over time. ||The physiological meaning of requirement satisfaction involves the completion of all chilling-dependent processes that progressively dismantle dormancy-maintaining mechanisms, with the requirement threshold representing the cumulative exposure needed to reduce ABA below inhibitory levels, silence DAM gene expression, remove chromatin repression from growth genes, and restore cellular communication pathways to degrees compatible with unrestricted growth response. ||The verification that the requirement has been met relies on forcing tests demonstrating the rapid budbreak response characteristic of fully released dormancy, with requirement satisfaction indicated by forcing times decreasing below approximately 14 days and approaching the minimum times characteristic of fully ecodormant material with no residual endodormancy constraints. ||The quantification of requirement satisfaction depends on the chilling model employed, with requirements typically expressed as hours below 7.2°C ranging from approximately 400-600 hours for low-chill cultivars adapted to mild winter climates to 1200-1500 hours for high-chill cultivars from continental regions, though more sophisticated models using temperature weighting or dynamic calculations may express requirements in different units. ||The practical determination of when requirements are met involves tracking chilling accumulation through winter and comparing accumulated units to known cultivar requirements, enabling prediction of when dormancy release will be complete and subsequent heat accumulation can effectively drive progress toward budbreak. ||The consequences of requirements not being met include the persistence of residual endodormancy that prolongs forcing response times, reduces budbreak uniformity, and may cause the delayed and erratic budbreak characteristic of inadequate chilling in warm winter climates.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Richardson EA, Seeley SD, Walker DR (1974) A model for estimating the completion of rest for Redhaven and Elberta peach trees. HortScience 9: 331-332"
},

  "Full_Chill_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Full_Chill_Accumulation is a Chilling_Completion comprising the integrated cumulative cold exposure from dormancy establishment through requirement satisfaction yielding total satisfaction of the chilling requirement.",
  "alternative_term": "complete chilling accumulation | total chill accumulation | cumulative chilling | integrated cold exposure |+ vollständige Kälteakkumulation | komplette Chilling-Ansammlung | kumulative Kälteeinwirkung | integrierte Kälteexposition",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in the Médoc, Bordeaux, full chill accumulation is achieved by late January when integrated cold exposure reaches approximately 1000 chilling hours, with accumulation proceeding from approximately 200 hours by late November through 600 hours by early January to full accumulation by January 25, tracked using the hours-below-7.2°C model and verified by forcing tests showing budbreak within 11 days indicating complete dormancy release.",
  "editor_note": "Full_Chill_Accumulation represents the quantitative completeness aspect of Chilling_Completion addressing total integrated cold exposure. ||Distinguished from partial accumulation during endodormancy by representing requirement satisfaction. ||Quantified through various models from simple hour counting to dynamic calculations. ||Effective temperature range approximately 0-7°C. ||Seasonal progression from slow autumn accumulation through winter completion. ||Verified by forcing test minimum response times. || This comprehensive accumulation reflects the summation of effective cold exposure according to temperature-dependent effectiveness functions, with the full accumulation representing the total chilling credit acquired through winter that equals or exceeds the genetically determined requirement for complete dormancy release. ||The physiological basis of full accumulation involves the progressive and persistent effects of cold exposure on dormancy-maintaining mechanisms, with each increment of effective chilling contributing to the cumulative reduction of ABA through catabolic activation, the progressive silencing of DAM gene expression, and the gradual removal of repressive chromatin modifications, with full accumulation representing the completion of these cumulative changes. ||The quantification of full accumulation depends on the chilling model employed, with simple models summing hours below a threshold temperature to yield totals typically ranging from 400-1500 hours depending on cultivar, while more sophisticated models apply temperature-dependent weighting functions or dynamic calculations that account for the varying effectiveness of different temperatures and potential negation by warm exposure. ||The temperature range most effective for chill accumulation in grapevine spans approximately 0-7°C, with temperatures in this range providing maximum contribution to accumulated chilling, temperatures below freezing being less effective or ineffective, and temperatures above approximately 15°C potentially negating previously accumulated chilling in some model formulations. ||The seasonal pattern of chill accumulation typically shows slow initial accumulation during autumn as temperatures fluctuate around effectiveness thresholds, accelerating accumulation during consistent winter cold, and eventual completion when cumulative effective exposure reaches the requirement threshold. ||The verification of full accumulation relies on forcing tests confirming rapid budbreak response, with full accumulation demonstrated by the minimum forcing times and maximum budbreak percentages characteristic of completely released dormancy.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Richardson EA, Seeley SD, Walker DR (1974) A model for estimating the completion of rest for Redhaven and Elberta peach trees. HortScience 9: 331-332 || Fishman S, Erez A, Couvillon GA (1987) The temperature dependence of dormancy breaking in plants: mathematical analysis of a two-step model. Journal of Theoretical Biology 126: 309-321 || Dokoozlian NK (1999) Chilling temperature and duration interact on the budbreak of Perlette grapevine cuttings. HortScience 34: 1054-1056"
},

  "Competence_Achievement": {
  "definition": "A Competence_Achievement is a Dormancy_Release bearing the restored disposition for complete growth response to growth-promoting conditions following dismantling of internal endodormancy constraints.",
  "alternative_term": "growth competence achievement | competence restoration completion | full competence attainment | growth capacity achievement |+ Kompetenz-Erreichung | Wachstumskompetenz-Erlangung | vollständige Kompetenz-Wiederherstellung | Wachstumsfähigkeits-Erreichung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Gewürztraminer vines in Alsace, competence achievement is confirmed in early February when forcing tests show budbreak within 10 days at 22°C with 98% success rate, ABA concentrations have declined to 55 ng per gram fresh weight, and transcript analysis confirms minimal VvDAM expression with restored CYCLIN D expression potential, indicating full restoration of growth capacity following completion of chilling requirement at approximately 1100 hours.",
  "editor_note": "Competence_Achievement represents the functional capacity outcome of Chilling_Completion describing restored growth ability. ||Distinguished from Dormancy_Release_Competence during endodormancy by representing verified complete competence. ||Confirmed by forcing response less than 14 days with greater than 95% success. ||Molecular markers include baseline ABA, minimal DAM, and restored growth gene responsiveness. ||Timing coincides with chilling requirement satisfaction. ||Uniformity across buds affects subsequent budbreak synchrony. || This achievement marks the functional completion of dormancy release from the perspective of bud capability, establishing the growth-ready state that will enable rapid response to subsequent heat accumulation and eventual budbreak initiation. ||The physiological basis of competence achievement involves the completion of all cellular and molecular changes required for growth capacity, including restoration of cell cycle competence through cyclin and CDK expression potential, re-establishment of hormone signaling sensitivity enabling response to growth-promoting signals, restoration of metabolic enzyme systems capable of supporting biosynthesis, and recovery of symplastic communication enabling coordinated growth responses. ||The verification of competence achievement relies on forcing tests that demonstrate the capacity for rapid and complete budbreak, with achievement confirmed when forcing response times have decreased to minimum values of approximately 10-14 days and budbreak percentages have reached maximum levels of greater than 95% under optimal conditions. ||The molecular markers of competence achievement include ABA concentrations at baseline levels below approximately 60-80 ng per gram fresh weight, DAM gene expression at minimal or undetectable levels, and growth gene promoters showing full transcriptional responsiveness to activating signals. ||The timing of competence achievement coincides with chilling requirement satisfaction, occurring during late January to February for most cultivars in Northern Hemisphere viticulture, and marking the transition from the internally-constrained state of endodormancy to the environmentally-constrained state of ecodormancy. ||The uniformity of competence achievement across buds on a vine affects subsequent budbreak synchrony, with simultaneous achievement of competence at all bud positions promoting uniform budbreak while variable achievement may contribute to extended or uneven budbreak patterns.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Cooke JE, Eriksson ME, Junttila O (2012) The dynamic nature of bud dormancy in trees: environmental control and molecular mechanisms. Plant Cell and Environment 35: 1707-1728"
},

  "Bud_Competence_Restoration": {
  "definition": "A Bud_Competence_Restoration is a Competence_Achievement realized through re-establishment of cellular, molecular, and physiological capacities required for meristematic activity and developmental growth upon environmental signaling.",
  "alternative_term": "bud growth competence restoration | meristem competence recovery | bud capacity re-establishment | dormant bud reactivation potential |+ Knospenkompetenz-Wiederherstellung | Meristemkompetenz-Erholung | Knospen-Kapazitäts-Wiedererrichtung | Knospenwachstumsfähigkeit-Restauration",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Champagne, bud competence restoration is completed by mid-February following accumulation of approximately 1000 chilling hours, with restoration verified through forcing tests showing budbreak within 11 days, molecular analysis confirming restored CYCLIN D and CDK expression potential, and ultrastructural examination showing meristematic cells with characteristics of division-ready G1 phase including prominent nucleoli and dispersed chromatin.",
  "editor_note": "Bud_Competence_Restoration represents the second component phase of Dormancy_Release addressing comprehensive re-establishment of growth capability. ||Distinguished from Competence_Achievement which marks the endpoint, while Bud_Competence_Restoration addresses the process encompassing cellular, hormonal, metabolic, and connectivity dimensions. ||Subdivides into Growth_Capacity_Restoration, Metabolic_Reactivation_Potential, and Budbreak_Readiness as component aspects. ||Verified through forcing tests and molecular markers. ||Completeness affects subsequent growth vigor and uniformity. || This restoration process occurs through the final phases of endodormancy and early ecodormancy as chilling-dependent changes complete the dismantling of dormancy-maintaining mechanisms and prepare buds for growth response to spring warming. ||The cellular dimension of competence restoration involves the re-establishment of cell cycle readiness in meristematic cells, with restoration of cyclin expression potential, degradation of CDK inhibitors that blocked division during dormancy, and chromatin remodeling that makes cell cycle gene promoters accessible for transcription upon growth signal reception. ||The hormonal dimension encompasses the restoration of growth hormone signaling systems, including sensitization of cytokinin receptors that promote cell division, restoration of gibberellin response capacity that enables cell elongation, and re-establishment of auxin polar transport that organizes growth patterns, while ABA signaling capacity that inhibited growth during dormancy becomes reduced. ||The metabolic dimension involves the restoration of biosynthetic pathway capacity to support the rapid synthesis of proteins, nucleic acids, cell wall materials, and membranes required for growth, with enzyme systems prepared for rapid activation upon growth initiation even while remaining at low activity during ecodormant quiescence. ||The connectivity dimension addresses the restoration of symplastic communication through callose degradation at plasmodesmata, re-establishing the cell-to-cell signaling required for coordinated growth responses across meristematic tissues. ||The verification of competence restoration relies on forcing tests demonstrating rapid budbreak, with restored competence indicated by budbreak times below 14 days and high success rates, and on molecular markers confirming the completion of dormancy-releasing changes at the gene expression level. ||The completeness of competence restoration affects the quality of subsequent growth, with full restoration supporting vigorous uniform budbreak while incomplete restoration may result in weak or delayed growth.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Growth_Capacity_Restoration": {
  "definition": "A Growth_Capacity_Restoration is a Bud_Competence_Restoration realized through re-establishment of cell cycle machinery, growth-related gene expression potential, and cellular structures required for developmental growth.",
  "alternative_term": "growth potential restoration | developmental capacity recovery | meristem growth capacity re-establishment | growth competence recovery |+ Wachstumskapazitäts-Wiederherstellung | Entwicklungskapazitäts-Erholung | Meristem-Wachstumsfähigkeits-Wiedererrichtung | Wachstumspotential-Restauration",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Gris vines in Oregon, growth capacity restoration is completed by early February following accumulation of 1000 chilling hours, demonstrated by forcing tests showing visible bud swelling within 5 days and full budbreak within 10 days at 22°C, with capacity restoration confirmed through transcript analysis showing restored expression potential of CYCLIN D, EXPANSIN, and cell wall biosynthesis genes in response to growth-promoting conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Growth_Capacity_Restoration represents the fundamental cellular capacity aspect of Bud_Competence_Restoration. ||Distinguished from Metabolic_Reactivation_Potential which addresses metabolic preparation, while Growth_Capacity_Restoration focuses on cell cycle and growth machinery restoration. ||Encompasses cell cycle, gene expression, structural, and hormonal signaling dimensions. ||Verified through forcing response and molecular markers. ||Completeness determines subsequent growth vigor. || This restoration occurs progressively during the final phases of chilling accumulation as dormancy-maintaining mechanisms are dismantled, reaching completion when all components required for growth have been restored to functional status. ||The cell cycle dimension of capacity restoration involves the re-establishment of division competence through restoration of cyclin expression potential enabling cell cycle progression, degradation of CDK inhibitor proteins that maintained G0/G1 arrest during dormancy, and chromatin derepression of cell cycle genes allowing their transcription upon appropriate signaling. ||The gene expression dimension encompasses the broader restoration of growth-related transcriptional programs, with derepression of genes encoding biosynthetic enzymes, structural proteins, and regulatory factors required for cell division and expansion, enabling rapid gene expression responses to growth-promoting signals. ||The structural dimension involves restoration of cellular infrastructure supporting growth, including re-organization of cytoskeleton for division and expansion, preparation of endomembrane systems for secretory activity supporting cell wall deposition, and maintenance of mitochondria and plastids in states ready for the increased energy and biosynthetic demands of growth. ||The hormonal signaling dimension addresses the restoration of growth hormone response capacity, with sensitization of receptor systems for cytokinins, gibberellins, and auxin that transduce growth-promoting signals into cellular responses. ||The verification of capacity restoration uses forcing tests demonstrating rapid growth response, with restored capacity indicated by short times to visible bud swelling and subsequent budbreak progression, and molecular markers confirming the restoration of growth gene expression potential through transcript analysis or chromatin accessibility assays. ||The completeness of capacity restoration determines the vigor of subsequent growth, with full restoration supporting rapid synchronous budbreak while partial restoration may limit growth potential.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Rohde A, Bhalerao RP (2007) Plant dormancy in the perennial context. Trends in Plant Science 12: 217-223 || Cooke JE, Eriksson ME, Junttila O (2012) The dynamic nature of bud dormancy in trees: environmental control and molecular mechanisms. Plant Cell and Environment 35: 1707-1728 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
},

  "Metabolic_Reactivation_Potential": {
  "definition": "A Metabolic_Reactivation_Potential is a Bud_Competence_Restoration bearing the disposition for rapid upregulation of biosynthetic pathways and energy metabolism upon bud burst and early shoot growth.",
  "alternative_term": "metabolic activation readiness | metabolic reactivation capacity | metabolism upregulation potential | biosynthetic reactivation readiness |+ metabolisches Reaktivierungspotential | Stoffwechsel-Aktivierungsbereitschaft | Metabolismus-Hochregulierungs-Kapazität | biosynthetische Reaktivierungsbereitschaft",
  "example_of_usage": "In Sauvignon Blanc vines in Marlborough, New Zealand, metabolic reactivation potential is established by early August following chilling completion, demonstrated by rapid respiratory upregulation from 0.4 to 2.5 μmol CO2 per gram dry weight per hour within 48 hours of transfer to 20°C forcing conditions, with concurrent upregulation of amino acid and nucleotide synthesis pathway enzyme activities indicating prepared metabolic systems capable of supporting the biosynthetic demands of budbreak.",
  "editor_note": "Metabolic_Reactivation_Potential represents the metabolic preparedness aspect of Bud_Competence_Restoration. ||Distinguished from Growth_Capacity_Restoration which addresses cellular growth machinery, while Metabolic_Reactivation_Potential specifically addresses metabolic system readiness. ||Encompasses biosynthetic, energy, nitrogen, and regulatory dimensions. ||Temperature-dependent activation links warming to growth initiation. ||Verified through rapid metabolic upregulation upon warming. ||Supports the intensive demands of budbreak and early growth. || This potential is established through the chilling-dependent changes that dismantle dormancy while simultaneously preparing metabolic systems for reactivation, creating a poised state where metabolism can rapidly increase upon receipt of growth-promoting temperature signals. ||The biosynthetic dimension of reactivation potential involves the preparation of pathways for amino acid, nucleotide, lipid, and carbohydrate synthesis that will support the intensive biosynthetic demands of cell division and expansion during budbreak, with enzyme systems maintained in states capable of rapid activation even while operating at low levels during ecodormant quiescence. ||The energy metabolism dimension encompasses the preparation of respiratory pathways for the increased ATP production required during growth, with mitochondrial systems maintained in states capable of rapid upregulation and the availability of carbohydrate reserves ensuring substrate supply for elevated respiration. ||The nitrogen metabolism dimension addresses the preparation for mobilization of stored nitrogen reserves and increased amino acid synthesis required for the protein production supporting growth, with nitrogen remobilization pathways prepared for activation when growth signals are received. ||The regulatory dimension involves the restoration of metabolic regulatory systems that coordinate pathway activities in response to growth demands, including the hormone signaling connections between growth signals and metabolic activation, and the transcriptional programs that upregulate metabolic gene expression during growth initiation. ||The temperature-dependence of metabolic reactivation creates the link between warming and growth initiation, with increasing temperatures progressively activating metabolic systems according to their temperature response characteristics, eventually reaching activity levels sufficient to support sustained growth when heat accumulation satisfies the requirement for budbreak. ||The verification of reactivation potential involves demonstrating rapid metabolic upregulation upon warming, with potential confirmed by the speed of respiratory and biosynthetic responses to growth-promoting temperatures in forcing experiments.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 5 Carbohydrate Supply and Reserve Storage || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of starch and N reserves in grapevine. Journal of Experimental Botany 55: 2165-2175 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
},

  "Budbreak_Readiness": {
  "definition": "A Budbreak_Readiness is a Dormancy_Release bearing the disposition for bud burst initiation upon adequate heat accumulation following completion of dormancy release processes.",
  "alternative_term": "budbreak preparedness | growth initiation readiness | pre-budbreak competence | bud activation readiness |+ Austriebsbereitschaft | Knospenaustritts-Vorbereitung | Wachstumsinitiierungs-Bereitschaft | Knospenaktivierungs-Bereitschaft",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner vines in the Wachau, Austria, budbreak readiness is achieved by mid-February following satisfaction of the approximately 1100 chilling hour requirement, with ready buds demonstrating forcing response within 9 days at 22°C, ultrastructural examination showing meristem cells with prominent nucleoli and dispersed chromatin characteristic of division readiness, and subsequent field budbreak occurring predictably within 5 days of accumulated growing degree days reaching 130 units above the 10°C base temperature in late March.",
  "editor_note": "Budbreak_Readiness represents the complete preparedness state within Bud_Competence_Restoration describing fully prepared buds awaiting heat accumulation. ||Distinguished from earlier competence states by representing complete preparation for imminent growth. ||Encompasses cellular, molecular, hormonal, and structural readiness dimensions. ||Enables predictable budbreak response to heat accumulation. ||Transition to active growth when GDD requirement satisfied, typically 100-300 units. ||Corresponds to late BBCH 00 immediately preceding visible bud swelling. || This state of readiness is achieved when chilling requirements have been satisfied, growth capacity has been restored, and metabolic systems have been prepared for reactivation, establishing the complete preparation for growth that characterizes the ecodormant bud following endodormancy release. ||The cellular dimension of readiness involves meristematic cells poised at the G1/S boundary of the cell cycle prepared to initiate DNA replication and subsequent division upon appropriate signaling, with all cell cycle components present and functional awaiting activation. ||The molecular dimension encompasses the full complement of growth-related gene transcripts and proteins accumulated in preparation for growth, with transcription factors poised to activate growth programs and biosynthetic enzymes ready for rapid upregulation. ||The hormonal dimension involves the growth-permissive hormone balance established through dormancy release, with low ABA removing inhibition, sensitized cytokinin and gibberellin signaling prepared to transduce growth signals, and auxin transport systems ready to establish the polar gradients organizing growth. ||The structural dimension addresses the ultrastructural preparation of meristematic cells for division, including prominent nucleoli indicating ribosome biogenesis capacity, dispersed chromatin indicating transcriptional readiness, and organized cytoskeleton prepared for division and expansion. ||The practical significance of budbreak readiness relates to the predictability of subsequent development, with ready buds responding uniformly and predictably to heat accumulation according to growing degree day models, enabling accurate prediction of budbreak timing from temperature forecasts. ||The transition from readiness to active budbreak occurs when accumulated heat units satisfy the cultivar-specific requirement, typically 100-300 growing degree days above the base temperature, at which point visible bud swelling commences marking the initiation of the new growing season.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lorenz DH et al (1995) Growth stages of the grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine - BBCH-scale. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1: 100-103"
},

  "Heat_Accumulation_Response": {
  "definition": "A Heat_Accumulation_Response is a Dormancy_Release comprising the temperature-dependent progression toward bud burst in growth-competent buds through accumulating thermal exposure following endodormancy completion.",
  "alternative_term": "thermal accumulation response | heat unit response | temperature-driven budbreak progression | warming response |+ Wärmeakkumulations-Reaktion | thermische Akkumulationsantwort | Wärmeeinheiten-Reaktion | temperaturgetriebene Austriebsprogression",
  "example_of_usage": "In Merlot vines in Saint-Émilion, Bordeaux, heat accumulation response drives budbreak progression through March and early April, with growing degree days above the 10°C base temperature accumulating from approximately 20 GDD by March 10 through 80 GDD by March 25 to the cultivar threshold of approximately 140 GDD by April 5, at which point visible bud swelling at BBCH stage 05 indicates successful completion of heat-driven budbreak initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Heat_Accumulation_Response represents the third component phase of Dormancy_Release addressing temperature-driven progression to budbreak. ||Distinguished from Chilling_Completion which addresses endodormancy release, while Heat_Accumulation_Response addresses the subsequent ecodormancy release through warming. ||Subdivides into Growing_Degree_Day_Accumulation, Temperature_Sum_Response, and Heat_Unit_Requirement as component aspects. ||Base temperature approximately 10°C for grapevine. ||Cultivar heat requirements typically 100-300 GDD. ||Enables budbreak timing prediction from temperature data. || This process operates during late winter and early spring as the primary driver of budbreak timing in ecodormant buds, with the rate of progress toward budbreak determined by the intensity and duration of temperatures above the base threshold for growth-related metabolic activity. ||The physiological basis of heat accumulation response involves the temperature-dependence of metabolic and developmental processes that prepare for and execute budbreak, with warming temperatures progressively activating enzyme systems, accelerating biosynthetic reactions, and enabling the cellular processes of division and expansion that constitute visible growth. ||The quantification of heat accumulation uses growing degree day or heat unit models that integrate effective temperature exposure over time, with each degree above the base temperature contributing to cumulative heat accumulation according to model-specific algorithms, and budbreak occurring when accumulated units reach the cultivar-specific threshold requirement. ||The base temperature for heat accumulation in grapevine is approximately 10°C, below which temperatures contribute minimally or not at all to progress toward budbreak, while temperatures above this threshold contribute in proportion to their elevation above the base according to most simple linear models. ||The cultivar-specific heat requirement for budbreak typically ranges from 100-300 growing degree days depending on genotype, with early-budbreak cultivars generally requiring less heat accumulation than late-budbreak cultivars, creating the characteristic spread of budbreak timing among cultivars in mixed plantings. ||The interaction between heat accumulation and prior chilling affects response characteristics, with adequately chilled buds responding efficiently to heat accumulation while inadequately chilled buds may show delayed or reduced response reflecting residual endodormancy constraints. ||The practical application of heat accumulation models enables prediction of budbreak timing from temperature forecasts, supporting vineyard management decisions regarding frost protection, early season pest management, and scheduling of cultural operations relative to expected growth stage progression.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || Moncur MW et al (1989) Base temperatures for budbreak and leaf appearance of grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 40: 21-26 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle"
},

  "Growing_Degree_Day_Accumulation": {
  "definition": "A Growing_Degree_Day_Accumulation is a Heat_Accumulation_Response defined by progressive summation of daily temperature contributions above the base temperature threshold according to established calculation methods.",
  "alternative_term": "GDD accumulation | heat sum accumulation | thermal time accumulation | degree day summation |+ Wachstumsgradtag-Akkumulation | GDD-Akkumulation | Wärmesummen-Akkumulation | Gradtag-Summierung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Noir vines of the Côte d'Or, Burgundy, growing degree day accumulation proceeds through March with daily contributions varying from 0-2 GDD during cool periods with mean temperatures of 8-12°C to 5-8 GDD during warm periods with mean temperatures of 15-18°C, with cumulative GDD reaching the cultivar threshold of approximately 150 units by late March to early April depending on seasonal temperature patterns, triggering budbreak initiation at BBCH stage 05.",
  "editor_note": "Growing_Degree_Day_Accumulation represents the quantitative tracking method within Heat_Accumulation_Response. ||Distinguished from Temperature_Sum_Response which addresses the physiological integration, while Growing_Degree_Day_Accumulation specifically addresses the calculation methodology. ||Base temperature typically 10°C. ||Daily accumulation rate varies with temperature from 0 to 10+ GDD. ||Cumulative thresholds for budbreak typically 100-300 GDD depending on cultivar. ||Enables budbreak prediction from temperature monitoring. || This accumulation process operates continuously during the ecodormancy period following chilling completion, with each day's temperature regime contributing to the cumulative heat total that drives progress toward growth initiation. ||The calculation of growing degree days employs various methods that integrate temperature above the base threshold, with the simplest approach calculating the difference between daily mean temperature and base temperature when this difference is positive, while more sophisticated methods use hourly temperatures or apply corrections for temperature fluctuation patterns. ||The base temperature for growing degree day calculation in grapevine budbreak models is typically set at 10°C, representing the threshold below which metabolic activity is insufficient to support meaningful progress toward growth, though some models employ slightly different base temperatures based on regional calibration or cultivar-specific optimization. ||The daily accumulation rate varies with temperature regime, with warm spring days contributing substantially to the growing total while cool days near the base temperature contribute minimally, creating the weather-dependent variability in accumulation rate that affects budbreak timing prediction accuracy. ||The cumulative nature of growing degree day accumulation reflects the integration of temperature effects over time, with the developmental progress achieved during warm periods being retained during subsequent cool periods rather than being lost, allowing gradual progress toward budbreak even when temperatures fluctuate around the base threshold. ||The relationship between accumulated growing degree days and developmental stage is approximately linear for budbreak prediction, with cultivar-specific thresholds typically falling in the range of 100-300 GDD for the transition from dormant bud to visible bud swelling at BBCH stage 05. ||The practical application of growing degree day accumulation involves tracking cumulative heat units through spring and comparing to cultivar thresholds to predict budbreak timing, enabling proactive management decisions regarding frost protection deployment and early season cultural operations.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Moncur MW et al (1989) Base temperatures for budbreak and leaf appearance of grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 40: 21-26 || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || McMaster GS, Wilhelm WW (1997) Growing degree-days: one equation, two interpretations. Agricultural and Forest Meteorology 87: 291-300"
},

  "Temperature_Sum_Response": {
  "definition": "A Temperature_Sum_Response is a Heat_Accumulation_Response comprising physiological integration of cumulative thermal exposure driving developmental progress through preparatory and early growth stages culminating in visible bud swelling.",
  "alternative_term": "thermal sum response | cumulative temperature response | heat integration response | temperature accumulation response |+ Temperatursummen-Reaktion | kumulative Temperaturantwort | Wärmeintegrations-Reaktion | Temperaturakkumulations-Reaktion",
  "example_of_usage": "In Riesling vines in the Rheingau, Germany, temperature sum response drives developmental progress through March and April, with physiological advancement toward budbreak proceeding in proportion to accumulated warmth above 10°C, meristematic activation increasing progressively as GDD accumulate from 50 units in mid-March to 120 units by early April, and visible budbreak occurring when the response threshold of approximately 140-160 GDD is reached corresponding to sufficient cellular and metabolic preparation for growth initiation.",
  "editor_note": "Temperature_Sum_Response represents the physiological integration aspect of Heat_Accumulation_Response. ||Distinguished from Growing_Degree_Day_Accumulation which addresses calculation methodology, while Temperature_Sum_Response addresses the underlying biological response to accumulated warmth. ||Response approximately proportional to heat accumulation within normal temperature range. ||Cumulative nature reflects persistence of developmental progress. ||Cultivar variation in response efficiency affects budbreak timing. ||Interaction with dormancy status affects response characteristics. || This response reflects the fundamental temperature-dependence of biological processes underlying budbreak, with warming temperatures accelerating metabolic reactions, gene expression programs, and cellular activities according to their characteristic temperature response functions. ||The physiological basis of temperature sum response involves the integration of temperature effects across multiple cellular and molecular processes including respiratory metabolism providing energy for growth preparation, biosynthetic pathways producing materials for cell division and expansion, gene expression programs activating growth-related transcription, and cell cycle progression advancing meristematic cells toward division. ||The response to accumulated temperature is approximately proportional within the range of temperatures typically experienced during spring, with developmental progress increasing in rough proportion to heat exposure above the base threshold, though the relationship becomes non-linear at temperature extremes where very high temperatures may inhibit rather than promote development. ||The cumulative nature of temperature sum response reflects the persistence of developmental progress achieved during warm periods, with changes in gene expression, protein accumulation, and cellular preparation being maintained rather than reversed during subsequent cool periods, allowing gradual advancement toward budbreak even under fluctuating temperature conditions. ||The cultivar variation in temperature sum response reflects genetic differences in the thermal requirements for budbreak, with early-budbreak cultivars showing more rapid response to accumulated temperature and reaching the budbreak threshold with less total heat exposure than late-budbreak cultivars. ||The interaction between temperature sum response and dormancy status affects response efficiency, with fully released buds showing efficient response to heat accumulation while incompletely released buds may show delayed or reduced response due to residual internal constraints. ||The practical significance of temperature sum response lies in its predictability, enabling forecast of budbreak timing from temperature accumulation that supports vineyard management planning.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || Bonhomme R (2000) Bases and limits to using degree-day units. European Journal of Agronomy 13: 1-10"
},

  "Heat_Unit_Requirement": {
  "definition": "A Heat_Unit_Requirement is a Heat_Accumulation_Response defined by the cultivar-specific threshold of accumulated thermal exposure above the base temperature required for bud burst initiation.",
  "alternative_term": "thermal requirement for budbreak | heat accumulation threshold | GDD requirement | budbreak heat threshold |+ Wärmeeinheiten-Bedarf | thermische Anforderung für Austrieb | Wärmeakkumulations-Schwelle | GDD-Anforderung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chardonnay vines in Champagne, the heat unit requirement for budbreak is approximately 120-140 growing degree days above the 10°C base temperature, with this threshold consistently predicting budbreak timing within approximately 5 days accuracy when applied to accumulated GDD data, enabling vineyard managers to anticipate budbreak in late March to early April and plan frost protection deployment and early season spray programs accordingly.",
  "editor_note": "Heat_Unit_Requirement represents the threshold parameter within Heat_Accumulation_Response defining cultivar-specific budbreak thermal needs. ||Distinguished from Heat_Accumulation_Response process by representing the specific threshold value rather than the response mechanism. ||Cultivar requirements typically range from 100-300 GDD with 10°C base. ||Genetically determined with reasonable stability across environments. ||Interaction with chilling adequacy affects requirement expression. ||Enables predictive modeling of budbreak timing for management planning. || This requirement represents a genetically determined characteristic that varies among cultivars and contributes to the differences in budbreak timing observed among genotypes grown in the same environment. ||The quantification of heat unit requirement uses accumulated growing degree days or equivalent thermal units, with cultivar-specific thresholds typically ranging from approximately 100 GDD for early-budbreak cultivars to 300 GDD or more for late-budbreak cultivars when calculated using a 10°C base temperature. ||The physiological meaning of the heat unit requirement reflects the total thermal exposure needed to complete all preparatory processes for growth initiation, including metabolic activation to levels supporting biosynthesis, accumulation of growth-related gene products and proteins, and cellular preparations for division and expansion in meristematic tissues. ||The determination of heat unit requirements for specific cultivars involves experimental observation of budbreak timing in relation to measured temperature accumulation, with requirements established through correlation of GDD accumulation at the time of budbreak across multiple seasons and locations. ||The stability of heat unit requirements enables their use in predictive models, with cultivar-specific thresholds providing reasonably consistent budbreak timing predictions when applied to temperature accumulation data, though some variation occurs due to interactions with prior chilling adequacy, vine physiological status, and local microclimate factors. ||The interaction between heat unit requirement and chilling completion affects budbreak characteristics, with the heat requirement being most relevant following complete chilling satisfaction, while inadequate chilling may increase the apparent heat requirement or produce erratic response that deviates from model predictions. ||The practical application of heat unit requirements supports budbreak timing prediction for vineyard management, with threshold values for common cultivars available in viticultural literature and decision support systems that enable planning of early season operations relative to expected phenological development.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Moncur MW et al (1989) Base temperatures for budbreak and leaf appearance of grapevines. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 40: 21-26 || Parker AK et al (2011) General phenological model to characterise the timing of flowering and veraison of Vitis vinifera L. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 17: 206-216 || Duchêne E, Schneider C (2005) Grapevine and climatic changes: a glance at the situation in Alsace. Agronomy for Sustainable Development 25: 93-99"
},

  "Dormancy_Break": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Break is a Dormancy comprising the terminal event of the dormancy cycle realized through accumulated heat exposure triggering the irreversible transition from ecodormant quiescence to active growth.",
  "alternative_term": "budbreak initiation | dormancy termination | growth commencement | dormancy ending |+ Dormanzbruch | Austriebsbeginn | Dormanzbeendigung | Wachstumsbeginn",
  "example_of_usage": "In Cabernet Sauvignon vines in the Médoc, Bordeaux, dormancy break occurs in early to mid-April when accumulated growing degree days reach the cultivar threshold of approximately 160-180 GDD following complete chilling satisfaction in February, with visible bud swelling appearing at BBCH stage 05 within 3-5 days of threshold achievement and progression to green tip emergence at BBCH stage 07 within 7-10 days, marking the irreversible transition to active growth.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Break represents the fourth and final component phase of Dormancy_Release marking the actual transition to active growth. ||Distinguished from earlier phases by representing the irreversible growth initiation rather than preparation. ||Subdivides into Active_Growth_Resumption, Bud_Swelling_Initiation, and Dormancy_Exit_Completion as component aspects. ||Visible as bud swelling at BBCH 05-07. ||Timing determined by heat threshold achievement following chilling. ||Creates frost vulnerability requiring protection management. ||Synchrony affects subsequent shoot uniformity. || This transition occurs when heat accumulation has satisfied the cultivar-specific requirement following complete chilling satisfaction, representing the culmination of the dormancy release process in the actual initiation of growth. ||The physiological basis of dormancy break involves the crossing of developmental thresholds where accumulated metabolic activity, biosynthetic production, and cellular preparation reach levels sufficient to support sustained growth, with the system transitioning from preparatory activity to active developmental progression. ||The irreversibility of dormancy break distinguishes it from the reversible quiescence of earlier ecodormancy, with buds that have passed the break point continuing developmental progression even if temperatures subsequently decline, in contrast to pre-break buds that return to quiescence during cool periods. ||The visible manifestation of dormancy break is bud swelling, where the enclosed primordial shoot begins expansion that separates bud scales and produces the characteristic appearance of swollen buds transitioning to green tip emergence, corresponding to BBCH stages 05 through 07. ||The timing of dormancy break is determined by the achievement of heat accumulation thresholds following chilling completion, with the specific timing varying among cultivars, seasons, and sites according to the interaction of genetically determined requirements with environmental temperature patterns. ||The synchrony of dormancy break across buds on a vine affects the uniformity of subsequent shoot development, with simultaneous break producing uniform shoot populations while extended break periods create the shoot heterogeneity that complicates canopy management. ||The vulnerability following dormancy break relates to the cold sensitivity of actively growing tissues, with broken buds and emerging shoots being highly susceptible to frost damage that can significantly impact vine productivity, making accurate prediction of dormancy break timing essential for frost protection management.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235 || Lorenz DH et al (1995) Growth stages of the grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine - BBCH-scale. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1: 100-103"
},

  "Active_Growth_Resumption": {
  "definition": "An Active_Growth_Resumption is a Dormancy_Break comprising activation of cell division in meristematic tissues, onset of cell expansion driving visible bud swelling, and metabolic upregulation supporting biosynthetic production for growth.",
  "alternative_term": "growth reactivation | developmental resumption | growth re-initiation | active growth commencement |+ aktive Wachstumswiederaufnahme | Wachstumsreaktivierung | Entwicklungswiederaufnahme | aktiver Wachstumsbeginn",
  "example_of_usage": "In Pinot Gris vines in Alsace, active growth resumption commences in early April when meristematic cell division resumes following heat accumulation of approximately 130 GDD, with cell cycle progression detected through increased mitotic index within 48 hours of visible bud swelling at BBCH stage 05, respiratory rates increasing 5-fold from ecodormant levels within 72 hours, and rapid shoot elongation of 2-3 cm per day achieved within 10-14 days as growth systems reach full activation.",
  "editor_note": "Active_Growth_Resumption represents the functional reactivation aspect of Dormancy_Break describing the return to active developmental growth. ||Distinguished from Budbreak_Readiness which describes preparation, while Active_Growth_Resumption describes the actual growth activity. ||Encompasses cellular, metabolic, hormonal, and gene expression activation. ||Rate accelerates following initiation through positive feedback. ||Creates environmental vulnerability requiring management attention. ||Marks functional end of dormancy from growth perspective. || This resumption marks the functional end of dormancy from the perspective of growth activity, representing the point at which the vine transitions from the quiescent survival mode of winter to the active developmental mode of the growing season. ||The cellular basis of growth resumption involves the re-entry of meristematic cells into active cell cycle progression, with cells that were arrested in G1 phase during dormancy advancing through S phase DNA replication and subsequent division, producing the new cells that will constitute the expanding shoot. ||The metabolic dimension of growth resumption encompasses the dramatic upregulation of respiratory activity providing ATP for growth, biosynthetic pathway activation producing the amino acids, nucleotides, lipids, and carbohydrates required for cell production, and the mobilization of stored reserves from woody tissues to supply the demanding sink activity of growing buds. ||The hormonal changes accompanying growth resumption include increased cytokinin activity promoting cell division, elevated gibberellin signaling driving cell elongation, and establishment of auxin polar transport gradients that organize the spatial patterns of growth within the expanding shoot. ||The gene expression dimension involves the activation of growth-related transcriptional programs including cell cycle genes, cell wall biosynthesis genes, and developmental regulators that coordinate the organized growth of shoot structures. ||The rate of growth resumption accelerates following initiation as positive feedback loops between growth activity and resource mobilization become established, with initial slow growth transitioning to rapid expansion as metabolic and transport systems achieve full activation. ||The environmental sensitivity following growth resumption creates management implications, as the actively growing tissues are highly vulnerable to environmental stresses including frost, drought, and pest damage that can significantly impact shoot development and vine productivity.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Zapata C et al (2004) Partitioning and mobilization of starch and N reserves in grapevine. Journal of Experimental Botany 55: 2165-2175 || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
},

  "Bud_Swelling_Initiation": {
  "definition": "A Bud_Swelling_Initiation is an Active_Growth_Resumption manifesting as the first externally visible enlargement of dormant buds through expansion of the enclosed primordial shoot producing visible separation of bud scales.",
  "alternative_term": "bud swell onset | visible budbreak beginning | bud enlargement initiation | early bud swelling |+ Knospenschwellungs-Initiierung | Knospenschwellungsbeginn | sichtbarer Austriebsbeginn | frühe Knospenvergrößerung",
  "example_of_usage": "In Grüner Veltliner vines in the Wachau, Austria, bud swelling initiation is observed in late March when accumulated GDD reach approximately 120 units, with buds showing visible enlargement and scale separation at BBCH stage 05 within 3-4 days of threshold achievement, woolly trichomes becoming visible at scale margins within 5-6 days, and progression to green tip emergence at BBCH stage 07 occurring within 8-12 days depending on subsequent temperature conditions.",
  "editor_note": "Bud_Swelling_Initiation represents the first visible developmental event within Dormancy_Break. ||Distinguished from internal growth resumption by representing the externally observable morphological change. ||Corresponds to BBCH stage 05. ||Driven by cell expansion and turgor development in primordial shoot. ||Rate varies with temperature following initiation. ||Synchrony indicates uniformity of dormancy release. ||Marks transition to increased frost sensitivity requiring protection attention. || This morphological change marks the transition from the externally static appearance of dormant buds to the dynamic developmental progression of budbreak, serving as the practical field indicator that dormancy has been broken and active growth has commenced. ||The cellular basis of bud swelling involves the initiation of cell expansion in the primordial shoot enclosed within bud scales, driven by turgor pressure generated through osmotic water uptake into enlarging cells, with cell wall loosening enabling the increase in cell volume that produces macroscopic bud enlargement. ||The anatomical changes during bud swelling initiation include the expansion of primordial leaves and internodes that were formed during the previous growing season and remained quiescent through dormancy, separation of bud scales as the expanding shoot pushes against them, and the appearance of woolly trichomes at scale margins as protective structures become visible through widening scale gaps. ||The temporal position of bud swelling initiation corresponds to BBCH stage 05 in the standardized grapevine phenological scale, representing the first stage of visible development following the dormant winter period at BBCH 00 and preceding the green tip emergence at BBCH 07 that follows as development progresses. ||The rate of bud swelling following initiation varies with temperature, with warm conditions accelerating expansion and producing rapid progression through subsequent developmental stages, while cool conditions slow expansion and may extend the bud swell phase over days to weeks. ||The synchrony of bud swelling initiation across a vine or vineyard provides important information about dormancy status and subsequent growth uniformity, with simultaneous initiation indicating uniform dormancy release while extended initiation periods suggest variable dormancy satisfaction or response heterogeneity. ||The vulnerability during bud swelling initiation relates to the increasing frost sensitivity as buds transition from the relatively hardy dormant state to the frost-sensitive swollen state, with lethal temperatures rising from approximately -15°C for dormant buds to -4 to -6°C for swelling buds.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al (1995) Growth stages of the grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine - BBCH-scale. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1: 100-103 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Pratt C (1974) Vegetative anatomy of cultivated grapes - a review. American Journal of Enology and Viticulture 25: 131-150"
},

  "Dormancy_Exit_Completion": {
  "definition": "A Dormancy_Exit_Completion is a Dormancy_Break marking the definitive termination of the dormancy cycle confirmed by visible green tissue emergence beyond the dormancy break threshold.",
  "alternative_term": "dormancy termination completion | full dormancy exit | complete dormancy ending | dormancy cycle completion |+ Dormanzaustritts-Vollendung | vollständiger Dormanzaustritt | komplette Dormanzbeendigung | Dormanzzyklus-Abschluss",
  "example_of_usage": "In Chenin Blanc vines in the Loire Valley, dormancy exit completion is achieved in mid-April approximately 8 days after bud swelling initiation, with green tip emergence at BBCH stage 07 confirming irreversible transition to active growth, accumulated GDD of approximately 180 units representing sufficient heat exposure for complete dormancy exit, and subsequent shoot development proceeding at rates of 3-5 cm per day as the vine enters the rapid growth phase of the new growing season.",
  "editor_note": "Dormancy_Exit_Completion represents the terminal event of Dormancy_Break and the entire Dormancy cycle marking definitive transition to active growth. ||Distinguished from Bud_Swelling_Initiation by representing complete rather than initial transition. ||Corresponds to BBCH stage 07 green tip emergence. ||Represents irreversible commitment to growth. ||Timing typically 5-10 days after bud swelling initiation. ||Maximum frost sensitivity at this stage requiring vigilant protection. ||Marks beginning of new annual growth cycle. || This completion represents the final stage of dormancy release, occurring when developmental progress has advanced from bud swelling through scale separation to the emergence of green shoot tissue that demonstrates committed growth progression. ||The morphological indicator of dormancy exit completion is green tip emergence corresponding to BBCH stage 07, where the expanding primordial shoot has pushed sufficiently through separating bud scales to expose the green tissue of emerging leaves, representing a clear visual confirmation that active growth is underway. ||The physiological state at dormancy exit completion involves fully active cell division in meristematic tissues, established patterns of cell expansion driving shoot elongation, mobilization of reserves from woody tissues providing resources for growth, and the hormonal and metabolic systems supporting sustained developmental activity. ||The irreversibility at dormancy exit completion distinguishes this stage from earlier phases where return to quiescence was possible, with green tip emergence representing commitment to growth that will continue regardless of subsequent temperature fluctuations, though growth rate will vary with environmental conditions. ||The timing of dormancy exit completion typically follows bud swelling initiation by 5-10 days depending on temperature, with warm conditions accelerating progression while cool conditions extend the interval, and the specific timing being predictable from continued heat accumulation following the initial budbreak threshold. ||The significance of dormancy exit completion for vineyard management relates to the confirmation of successful dormancy release and the establishment of the developmental trajectory for the new season, with uniform completion across a vineyard indicating consistent dormancy satisfaction and predicting uniform subsequent development. ||The frost sensitivity at dormancy exit completion is substantially elevated relative to earlier stages, with green tip tissue being damaged at temperatures of -2 to -3°C compared to -4 to -6°C for swelling buds and -15°C or below for dormant buds, making frost protection particularly critical during this vulnerable transition period.",
  "has_curation_status": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000122",
  "external_mapping": [ "no_mapping_assigned" ],
  "definition_source": "Lorenz DH et al (1995) Growth stages of the grapevine: Phenological growth stages of the grapevine - BBCH-scale. Australian Journal of Grape and Wine Research 1: 100-103 || Keller M (2020) The Science of Grapevines 3rd Ed Chapter 2 Phenology and Growth Cycle || Fennell A (2004) Freezing tolerance and injury in grapevines. Journal of Crop Improvement 10: 201-235"
}

} );
